अंशु
<u>'''Aṃśu.'''</u>--I. Name of a protégé of the Aśvins in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1/> 2. '''[[धानंजय्य|Dhānaṃjayya]],''' pupil of '''Amāvāsya [[शाण्डिल्यायन|Śāṇḍilyāyana]],''' according to the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1/><br>

अंहसस्-पति
<u>'''Aṃhasas-pati.'''</u>--This is the name of the intercalary month in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (vii. 30; xxii. 31). See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

अक्र
<u>'''Akra.'''</u>--In several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_3/> this word means, according to Geldner,<ref name=fx2_ve1_3/> ‘horse.’ Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_3/> suggests that ‘riding horse’ is the precise sense. ''Cf.'' '''[[अश्व|Aśva]].'''<br>

अक्ष
<u>'''1. Akṣa,'''</u> ‘axle,’ is a part of a chariot often referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_4/> and later. It was apparently<ref name=fx2_ve1_4/> fastened to the body of the chariot ('''[[कोश|Kośa]]''') by straps (''akṣā-nah,'' lit. ‘tied to the axle,’ though this word is also<ref name=fx3_ve1_4/> rendered ‘horse’). The heating of the axle and the danger of its breaking were known.<ref name=fx4_ve1_4/> The part of the axle round which the nave of the wheel revolved was called [[आणि|Āṇi]], ‘pin.’ <br>

अक्ष
<u>'''2. Akṣa.'''</u>--This word occurs frequently, from the Rigveda onwards, both in the singular and plural, meaning ‘die’ and ‘dice.’ Dicing, along with horse-racing, was one of the main amusements of the Vedic Indian; but, despite the frequent mention of the game in the literature, there is considerable difficulty in obtaining any clear picture of the mode in which it was played.<br><br>(1) ''The Material.''--The dice appear normally to have been made of Vibhīdaka nuts. Such dice are alluded to in both the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_5/> and the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_5/> hence being called ‘brown’ (''[[बभ्रु|babhru]]''), and ‘born on a windy spot.’<ref name=fx3_ve1_5/> In the ritual game of dice at the Agnyādheya and the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]] ceremonies the material of the dice is not specified, but it is possible that occasionally gold imitations of Vibhīdaka nuts were used.<ref name=fx4_ve1_5/> There is no clear trace in the Vedic literature of the later use of cowries as dice.<ref name=fx5_ve1_5/><br><br>(2) ''The Number.''--In the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_5/> the dicer is described as ‘leader of a great horde’ (''senānīr mahato gaṇasya''), and in another passage<ref name=fx7_ve1_5/> the number is given as ''tri-pañcāśaḥ,'' an expression which has been variously interpreted. Ludwig,<ref name=fx8_ve1_5/> Weber,<ref name=fx9_ve1_5/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx10_ve1_5/> render it as fifteen, which is grammatically hardly possible. Roth<ref name=fx11_ve1_5/> and Grassmann<ref name=fx12_ve1_5/> render it as ‘consisting of fifty-three.’ Lüders<ref name=fx13_ve1_5/> takes it as ‘consisting of one hundred and fifty,’ but he points out that this may be merely a vague expression for a large number. For a small number Zimmer<ref name=fx14_ve1_5/> cites a reference in the Rigveda<ref name=fx15_ve1_5/> to one who fears ‘him who holds four’ (''caturaś cid dadamānāt''), but the sense of that passage is dependent on the view taken of the method of playing the game.<br><br>(3) ''The Method of Play.''--In several passages of the later  Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas lists are given of expressions connected with dicing. The names are [[कृत|Kṛta]], Tretā, [[द्वापर|Dvāpara]], Āskanda, and Abhibhū in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx16_ve1_5/> In the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx17_ve1_5/> among the victims at the Puruṣamedha, the ''[[कितव|kitava]]'' is offered to the Akṣarāja, the ''ādinava-[[दर्श|darśa]]'' to the [[कृत|Kṛta]], the ''kalpin'' to the Tretā, the ''adhi-kalpin'' to the [[द्वापर|Dvāpara]], the ''[[सभा-स्थाणु|sabhā-sthāṇu]]'' to the Āskanda. The lists in the parallel version of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] are ''[[कितव|kitava]], [[सभाविन्|sabhāvin]], ādinavadarśa, bahiḥ-sad,'' and ''[[सभा-स्थाणु|sabhā-sthāṇu]],''<ref name=fx18_ve1_5/> and Aksarāja, [[कृत|Kṛta]], Tretā, [[द्वापर|Dvāpara]], and Kali. From the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx19_ve1_5/> it appears that another name of Kali was Abhibhū, and the parallel lists in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] and Vājasaneyi Saṃhitās suggest that Abhibhū and Akṣarāja are identical, though both appear in the late [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] list. The names of some of these throws go back even to the Rigveda and the Atharvaveda. Kali occurs in the latter,<ref name=fx20_ve1_5/> and Lüders<ref name=fx21_ve1_5/> shows that in a considerable number of passages in the former [[कृत|Kṛta]] means a ‘throw’ (not ‘a stake’<ref name=fx22_ve1_5/> or ‘what is won’<ref name=fx23_ve1_5/> and this sense is clearly found in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx24_ve1_5/> Moreover, that there were more throws (''ayāḥ'') than one is proved by a passage in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx25_ve1_5/> when the gods are compared to throws as giving or destroying wealth.<br><br>The nature of the throws is obscure. The St. Petersburg Dictionary conjectures that the names given above were applied either to dice marked 4, 3, 2, or 1, or to the sides of the dice so marked, and the latter interpretation is supported by some late commentators.<ref name=fx26_ve1_5/> But there is no evidence for the former interpretation, and, as regards the latter, the shape of the Vibhīdaka nuts,<ref name=fx27_ve1_5/> used as dice, forbids any side being properly on the top. Light is thrown on the expressions by the descrip-  tion of a ritual game<ref name=fx28_ve1_5/> at the Agnyādheya and at the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]] ceremonies. The details are not certain,<ref name=fx29_ve1_5/> but it is clear that the game consisted in securing even numbers of dice, usually a number divisible by four, the [[कृत|Kṛta]], the other three throws then being the Tretā, when three remained over after division by four; the [[द्वापर|Dvāpara]], when two was the remainder; and the Kali, when one remained. If five were the dividing number, then the throw which showed no remainder was Kali, the [[कृत|Kṛta]] was that when four was left, and so on. The dice had no numerals marked on them, the only question being what was the total number of the dice themselves.<br><br>There is no reason to doubt that the game as played in the Rigveda was based on the same principle, though the details must remain doubtful. The number of dice used was certainly large,<ref name=fx30_ve1_5/> and the reference to throwing fours,<ref name=fx31_ve1_5/> and losing by one, points to the use of the [[कृत|Kṛta]] as the winning throw. The Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx32_ve1_5/> on the other hand, possibly knew of the Kali as the winning throw. In one respect the ordinary game must have differed from the ritual game. In the latter the players merely pick out the number of dice required--no doubt to avoid ominous errors, such as must have happened if a real game had been played. In the secular game the dice were thrown,<ref name=fx33_ve1_5/> perhaps on the principle suggested by Lüders:<ref name=fx34_ve1_5/> the one throwing a certain number on the place of playing, and the other then throwing a number to make up with those already thrown a multiple of four or five. This theory, at any rate, accounts for the later stress laid on the power of computation in a player, as in the Nala.<br><br>No board appears to have been used, but a depression on which  the dice were thrown (''[[अधि-देवन|adhi-devana]], [[देवन|devana]],''<ref name=fx35_ve1_5/> ''[[इरिण|iriṇa]]''<ref name=fx36_ve1_5/> ), was made in the ground. No dice box was used, but reference is made to a case for keeping dice in (''[[अक्ष|akṣa]]-[[वपन|vapana]]''<ref name=fx37_ve1_5/> The throw was called ''[[ग्रह|graha]]''<ref name=fx38_ve1_5/> or earlier ''[[ग्राभ|grābha]].''<ref name=fx39_ve1_5/> The stake is called ''vij.''<ref name=fx40_ve1_5/> Serious losses could be made at dicing: in the Rigveda a dicer laments the loss of all his property, including his wife.<ref name=fx41_ve1_5/> Lüders<ref name=fx42_ve1_5/> finds a different form of the game referred to in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx43_ve1_5/><br>

अक्ष
<u>'''3. Akṣa.'''</u>--In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vii. 3, 1) this word seems to denote the nut of the Vibhīdaka (''Terminalia bellerica'').<br>

अक्षत
<u>'''Akṣata'''</u> or '''Akṣita.'''--In one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_7/> dealing with the '''[[जायान्य|Jāyānya]],''' mention is made of a remedy for sores designated both Akṣita and Sukṣata, or, according to the reading of the Kauṣika [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], [[अक्षत|Akṣata]] and Sukṣata, while Sāyaṇa has Akṣita and Sukṣita. Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve1_7/> renders ‘not caused by cutting’ and ‘caused by cutting.’ Formerly<ref name=fx3_ve1_7/> he suggested ‘tumour’ or ‘boil.’ Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve1_7/> thinks that two varieties of [[जायान्य|Jāyānya]] are meant. Ludwig<ref name=fx5_ve1_7/> reads with Sāyana ''akṣita,'' which he renders by ‘not firmly established’ in the invalid. Zimmer<ref name=fx6_ve1_7/> finds in it a disease [[क्षत|Kṣata]]. <br>

अक्षा-वपन
<u>'''Akṣā-vapana.'''</u> See '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]].'''<br>

अक्षु
<u>'''Akṣu.'''</u>--The word occurs in two passages of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_9/> and one of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_9/> Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_9/> renders it by ‘net,’ while Bo7htlingk<ref name=fx4_ve1_9/> suggests ‘axle of a car.’ Geldner<ref name=fx5_ve1_9/> sees in it a stake or pole used with a fishermen's net ('''[[जाल|Jāla]]'''),<ref name=fx6_ve1_9/> the pole of a wagon,<ref name=fx7_ve1_9/> and the pole of a house, whether vertical or horizontal, he leaves uncertain (see '''[[वंश|Vaṃśa]]''').<ref name=fx8_ve1_9/> Bloomfield<ref name=fx9_ve1_9/> takes it as a covering of wickerwork stretched across a beam and sloping down to both sides--like a thatched roof, and this best explains the epithet ‘thousand-eyed’ (''i.e.,'' with countless holes) ascribed to it. In the other Atharvaveda passage<ref name=fx10_ve1_9/> he accepts the sense ‘net,’ and doubts if the word in the Rigveda is not an adjective (''a-kṣu'') as it is taken by Sāyaṇa. See also '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].'''<br>

अगस्ति
<u>'''Agasti.'''</u>--This form of '''Agastya's''' name occurs once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_10/> where he appears as a favourite of [[मित्र|Mitra]] and Varuṇa.<br>

अगस्त्य
<u>'''Agastya.'''</u>--This is the name of a sage, of mythical character, who plays a great part in the later literature. He was a '''[[मान|Māna]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_11/> and therefore is called '''[[मान्य|Mānya]]'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_11/> and son of [[मान|Māna]], and only once is there a reference<ref name=fx3_ve1_11/> to the legend prevalent in latter times that he was a son of [[मित्र|Mitra]] and Varuṇa.<br><br>His greatest feat was the reconciliation of Indra and the Maruts after Indra had been annoyed at his proposing to give the Maruts an offering to the exclusion of Indra. This feat is the subject of three hymns of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_11/> and is often referred  to in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx5_ve1_11/> though the exact details and significance of the legend are variously treated by Oldenberg,<ref name=fx6_ve1_11/> Sieg,<ref name=fx7_ve1_11/> Hertel,<ref name=fx8_ve1_11/> and von Schroeder.<ref name=fx9_ve1_11/><br><br>He also appears in a strange dialogue with [[लोपामुद्रा|Lopāmudrā]] in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx10_ve1_11/> which appears to show him as an ascetic who finally yields to temptation. Von '''Schroeder'''<ref name=fx11_ve1_11/> regards it as a ritual drama of vegetation magic.<br><br>In another passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx12_ve1_11/> he appears as helping in the Aśvins’ gift of a leg to [[विश्पला|Viśpalā]]. Sāyaṇa holds that be was the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of '''[[खेल|Khela]],''' and Sieg<ref name=fx13_ve1_11/> accepts this view, while Pischel<ref name=fx14_ve1_11/> thinks that [[खेल|Khela]] is a deity, Vivasvant.<br><br>Geldner<ref name=fx15_ve1_11/> shows from the Rigveda<ref name=fx16_ve1_11/> that [[अगस्त्य|Agastya]], as brother of [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]--both being miraculous sons of [[मित्र|Mitra]] and Varuṇa-introduces '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]''' to the '''Tṛtsus.''' There are two other references to [[अगस्त्य|Agastya]] in the Rigveda, the one<ref name=fx17_ve1_11/> including him in a long list of persons, the other alluding to his sister's sons (''nadbhyaḥ''),<ref name=fx18_ve1_11/> apparently '''[[बन्धु|Bandhu]],''' etc. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx19_ve1_11/> he appears as connected with witchcraft, and in a long list of sages.<ref name=fx20_ve1_11/> In the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx21_ve1_11/> cows, with a peculiar mark on their ears (''viṣṭya-karṇyaḥ''), are associated with him.<br>

अगर
<u>'''Agara.'''</u>--This rare word is found as ‘house’ in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_12/> <br>

अग्नि-दग्ध
<u>'''Agni-dagdha.'''</u>--This epithet (‘burnt with fire’)<ref name=fx1_ve1_13/> applies to the dead who were burned on the funeral pyre. This is one of the two normal methods of disposing of the dead, the other being burial (''an-agnidagdhāḥ,'' ‘not burnt with fire’).<ref name=fx2_ve1_13/> The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_13/> adds two further modes of disposal to those-viz., casting out (''paroptāḥ''), and the exposure of the dead (''uddhitāḥ''). The exact sense of these expressions is doubtful. Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve1_13/> considers that the former is a parallel to the Iranian practice of casting out the dead to be devoured by beasts, and that the latter refers to the old who are exposed when helpless.<ref name=fx5_ve1_13/> Whitney<ref name=fx6_ve1_13/> refers the latter expression to the exposure of the dead body on a raised platform of some sort.<br><br>Burial was clearly not rare in the Rigvedic period: a whole hymn<ref name=fx7_ve1_13/> describes the ritual attending it. The dead man was buried apparently in full attire, with his bow in his hand, and probably at one time his wife was immolated to accompany him, in accordance with a practice common among savage tribes. But in the Vedic period both customs appear in a modified form: the son takes the bow from the hand of the dead man, and the widow is led away from her dead husband by his brother or other nearest kinsman. A stone is set between the dead and the living to separate them. In the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx8_ve1_13/> but not in the Rigveda, a coffin (''[[वृक्ष|vṛkṣa]]'') is alluded to. In both Saṃhitās<ref name=fx9_ve1_13/> occur other allusions to the ‘house of earth’ (''[[भूमि|bhūmi]]-[[गृह|gṛha]]''). To remove the apparent discrepancy between burning and burial, by assuming that the references to burial are to the burial of the burned bones, as does Oldenberg,<ref name=fx10_ve1_13/> is unnecessary and improbable, as burning and burial subsisted side by side in Greece for many years.<br><br>Burning was, however, equally usual, and it grew steadily in frequency, for in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx11_ve1_13/> the adornment  of the body of the dead with curd ('''[[आमिक्षा|Āmikṣā]]'''), clothes, and ornaments, in order to win the next world, is referred to as something erroneous and wrong, and in the funeral Mantras of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx12_ve1_13/> only burning seems to be contemplated; the verses which refer to burial here really alluding to the burial of the ashes in the burying-ground (''[[श्मशान|śmaśāna]]'').<ref name=fx13_ve1_13/> The body was wrapped in fat,<ref name=fx14_ve1_13/> as we learn from the funeral hymn in the Rigveda, a goat being apparently burned with it,<ref name=fx15_ve1_13/> to act as a guide on the way to the next world. According to the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx16_ve1_13/> a draft-ox was burned presumably for the dead to ride with in the next world. It was expected that the dead would revive with his whole body and all his limbs (''sarva-tanūḥ sāṅgaḥ''),<ref name=fx17_ve1_13/> although it is also said<ref name=fx18_ve1_13/> that the eye goes to the sun, the breath to the wind, and so forth.<br><br>Before burial or burning, the corpse was washed,<ref name=fx19_ve1_13/> a clog (''[[कूदी|kūdī]]'') being tied to the foot to prevent the deceased returning to earth.<ref name=fx20_ve1_13/><br>

अग्नि-भू काश्यप
<u>'''Agni-bhū Kāśyapa'''</u> is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_14/><br>

अग्नि-शाल
<u>'''Agni-śāla.'''</u>--This term, which designates part of the sacrificial  apparatus,<ref name=fx1_ve1_15/> is applied in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_15/> to a part of an ordinary house, presumably the central hall where the fireplace was.<br>

अघा
<u>'''Aghā.'''</u>--In the wedding hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_16/> it is said that cows are slain in the Aghās, and the wedding takes place at the '''Arjunīs''' (dual). The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_16/> has the ordinary '''[[मघास्|Maghās]]''' instead. It is impossible to resist the conclusion that the reading of the Rigveda was deliberately altered because of the connection of the slaughter of kine with sin (''agha'')--possibly, too, with a further desire to emphasize the contrast with ''[[अघ्न्या|aghnyā]],'' a name for ‘cow.’ Moreover, in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_16/> occurs the formula ‘Svāhā to the [[मघास्|Maghās]], Svāhā to the Anaghās.’ See also '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

अघाश्व
<u>'''Aghāśva.'''</u>--The name of a serpent in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_17/><br>

अ-घ्न्या
<u>'''A-ghnyā.'''</u>--See '''[[मांस|Māṃsa]].'''<br>

अङ्क
<u>'''Aṅka.'''</u>--The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_19/> and [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_19/> refer to two Aṅkas and two Nyaṅkas as parts of a chariot. The meaning of these terms is quite obscure. The commentators refer them to the sides or wheels. Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_19/> compares the Greek <ref name=fx4_ve1_19/> and thinks that the Aṅkau were the upper border of the body of the chariot (''[[कोश|kośa]], [[वन्धुर|vandhura]]''), and the Nyaṅkau the lower rims for greater security. Oldenberg<ref name=fx5_ve1_19/> confesses that the exact sense is impossible to make out, but considers that the terms at once refer to parts of the chariot and to divinities, while Bo7htlingk<ref name=fx6_ve1_19/> takes the term as referring to divinities alone. <br>

अङ्ग
<u>'''Aṅga.'''</u>--The name occurs only once in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_20/> in connection with the '''Gandhāris, Mūjavants,''' and '''Magadhas,''' as distinct peoples. They appear also in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_20/> in the compound name ''[[अङ्ग|Aṅga]]-magadhāḥ.'' As in later times they were settled on the Sone and Ganges,<ref name=fx3_ve1_20/> their earlier seat was presumably there also. See also '''[[वङ्ग|Vaṅga]].'''<br>

अङ्ग वैरोचन
<u>'''Aṅga Vairocana.'''</u>--He is included in the list of anointed kings in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_21/> His [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] was '''Udamaya,''' an [[आत्रेय|Ātreya]].<br>

अङ्गारावक्षयण
<u>'''Aṅgārāvakṣayaṇa.'''</u>--A word of doubtful meaning found in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_22/> It is rendered ‘tongs’ by Max Müller and Bo7htlingk in their translations. The St. Petersburg Dictionary explains it as ‘a vessel in which coals are extinguished,’ and Monier-Williams as ‘an instrument for extinguishing coals.’ The smaller St. Petersburg Dictionary renders the word ‘coal-shovel or tongs.’ ''Cf.'' '''Ulmukāvakṣayaṇa.'''<br>

अङ्गिरस्
<u>'''Aṅgiras.'''</u>--The Aṅgirases appear in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_23/> as semimythical beings, and no really historical character can be assigned even to those passages<ref name=fx2_ve1_23/> which recognize a father of the race, [[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]. Later, however, there were definite families of Aṅgirases, to whose ritual practices (''ayana, dvirātra'') references are made.<ref name=fx3_ve1_23/><br>

अङ्गुष्ठ
<u>'''Aṅguṣṭha.'''</u>--As a measure of size this word appears in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 12; vi. 17). <br>

अ-च्युत्
<u>'''A-cyut.'''</u>--He acted as [[प्रतिहर्तृ|Pratihartṛ]] at the Sattra celebrated by the Vibhindukīyas and described in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_25/><br>

अज
<u>'''Aja, Ajā.'''</u>--This is the ordinary name for goat in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_26/> and the later literature. The goat is also called '''[[बस्त|Basta]], [[छाग|Chāga]], Chagala.''' Goats and sheep (''ajāvayaḥ'') are very frequently mentioned together.<ref name=fx2_ve1_26/> The female goat is spoken of as producing two or three kids,<ref name=fx3_ve1_26/> and goat's milk is well known.<ref name=fx4_ve1_26/> The goat as representative of Pūṣan plays an important part in the ritual of burial.<ref name=fx5_ve1_26/> The occupation of a goatherd (''ajapāla'') was a recognized one, being distinguished from that of a cowherd and of a shepherd.<ref name=fx6_ve1_26/><br>

अज
<u>'''Aja.'''</u>--The Ajas are named in one verse of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_27/> as having been defeated by the '''Tṛtsus''' under '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]].''' They are there mentioned with the '''Yakṣus''' and '''Śigrus,''' and Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_27/> conjectures that they formed part of a confederacy under [[भेद|Bheda]] against [[सुदास्|Sudās]]. The name has been regarded as a sign of totemism,<ref name=fx3_ve1_27/> but this is very uncertain, and it is impossible to say if they were or were not Āryans.<br>

अजकव
<u>'''Ajakava.'''</u>--This name of a poisonous scorpion occurs once in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_28/><br>

अज-गर
<u>'''Aja-gara'''</u> (‘goat-swallower’) occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_29/> and in the list of animals at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_29/> or horse sacrifice, as the  name of the boa-constrictor. Elsewhere<ref name=fx3_ve1_29/> it is called [[वाहस|Vāhasa]]. It denotes a person at the snake feast in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_29/><br>

अज-मीढ
<u>'''Aja-mīḍha.'''</u>--The Ājamīḍhas, or descendants of [[अजमीढ|Ajamīḍha]], are referred to in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_30/> Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_30/> and Oldenberg<ref name=fx3_ve1_30/> deduce from the use of this patronymic that [[अजमीढ|Ajamīḍha]] was the seer of that hymn.<br>

अज-शृङ्गी
<u>'''Aja-śṛṅgī.'''</u>--This plant (‘goat's horn’), equated by the commentator with [[विषाणिन्|Viṣāṇin]] (the ''Odina pinnata''), is celebrated as a demon-destroyer in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_31/> Its other name is '''[[अराटकी|Arāṭakī]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_31/> Weber<ref name=fx3_ve1_31/> suggests that it is the ''Prosopis spicigera'' or ''Mimosa suma.''<br>

अजात-शत्रु
<u>'''Ajāta-śatru.'''</u>--He is mentioned as a King of Kāśī (Kāśya) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve1_32/> and [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_32/> Upaniṣads, where he instructs the proud [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] [[बालाकि|Bālāki]] as to the real nature of the self. He is not to be identified with the Ajātasattu of the Buddhist texts.<ref name=fx3_ve1_32/><br>

अज्ञात-यक्ष्म
<u>'''Ajñāta-yakṣma,'''</u> the ‘unknown sickness,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_33/> Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_33/> and [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx3_ve1_33/> It is referred to in connection with [[राजयक्ष्म|Rājayakṣma]]. Grohmann<ref name=fx4_ve1_33/> thinks that the two are different forms of disease, hypertrophy and atrophy, the purpose of the spell in the Rigveda being thus the removal of all disease. From the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_33/> he deduces its identity with '''[[बलास|Balāsa]].''' Zimmer,<ref name=fx6_ve1_33/> however, points out that this  conclusion is unjustified, leaving the disease unidentified, which seems to accord with its name.<br>

अजिन
<u>'''Ajina.'''</u>--This word denotes generally the skin of an animal-''e.g.,'' a gazelle,<ref name=fx1_ve1_34/> as well as that of a goat ('''Aja''').<ref name=fx2_ve1_34/> The use of skins as clothing is shown by the adjective ‘clothed in skins’ (''[[अजिन|ajina]]-vāsin'') in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_34/> and the furrier's trade is mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx4_ve1_34/> The Maruts also wear deer-skins,<ref name=fx5_ve1_34/> and the wild ascetics (''muni'') of a late Rigveda hymn<ref name=fx6_ve1_34/> seem to be clad in skins ('''Mala''').<br>

अजिर
<u>'''Ajira.'''</u>--He was [[सुब्रह्मण्य|Subrahmaṇya]] priest at the snake festival of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_35/><br>

अजीगर्त सौयवस
<u>'''Ajīgarta Sauyavasa.'''</u>--This is the name given to the father of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]''' in the famous legend of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_36/> perhaps invented for the occasion, as Weber<ref name=fx2_ve1_36/> suggests.<br>

अ-ज्येयता
<u>'''A-jyeyatā.'''</u> See '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].'''<br>

अणीचिन् मौन
<u>'''Aṇīcin Mauna.'''</u>--He is mentioned as an authority on ritual, and contemporary with '''[[जाबाल|Jābāla]]''' and '''[[चित्र|Citra]] [[गौश्रायणि|Gauśrāyaṇi]]''' or '''[[गौश्र|Gauśra]],''' in the '''[[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]]''' [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_38/><br>

अणु
<u>'''Aṇu.'''</u>--This is the designation in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_39/> and the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_39/> of a cultivated grain, '''apparently''' the ''Panicum miliaceum.''<br>

अतिथि
<u>'''Atithi'''</u> (‘guest’).--A hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_40/> celebrates in detail the merits of hospitality. The guest should be fed before  the host eats, water should be offered to him, and so forth. The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_40/> also lays stress on hospitality, using the expression ‘one whose deity is his guest’ (''[[अतिथि|atithi]]-deva''). In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx3_ve1_40/> it is said that only the good are deemed worthy of receiving hospitality. The guest-offering forms a regular part of the ritual,<ref name=fx4_ve1_40/> and cows were regularly slain in honour of guests.<ref name=fx5_ve1_40/><br>

अतिथि-ग्व
<u>'''Atithi-gva.'''</u>--This name occurs frequently in the Rigveda, apparently applying, in nearly all cases, to the same king, otherwise called '''Divodāsa.''' The identity of the two persons has been denied by Bergaigne,<ref name=fx1_ve1_41/> but is certainly proved by a number of passages, when the two names occur together,<ref name=fx2_ve1_41/> in connection with the defeat of '''[[शम्बर|Śambara]].''' In other passages<ref name=fx3_ve1_41/> [[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]] is said to have assisted Indra in slaying [[पर्णय|Parṇaya]] and [[करञ्ज|Karañja]]. Sometimes he is only vaguely referred to, while once<ref name=fx5_ve1_41/> he is mentioned as an enemy of [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] and Yadu. Again<ref name=fx6_ve1_41/> [[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]] is coupled with '''[[आयु|Āyu]]''' and '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]]''' as defeated by '''[[तूर्वयाण|Tūrvayāṇa]].'''<br><br>A different [[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]] appears to be referred to in a Dānastuti<ref name=fx7_ve1_41/> (‘Praise of Gifts’), where his son, '''[[इन्द्रोत|Indrota]],''' is mentioned.<br><br>Roth<ref name=fx8_ve1_41/> distinguishes three Atithigvas--the [[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]] Divodāsa, the enemy of [[पर्णय|Parṇaya]] and [[करञ्ज|Karañja]], and the enemy of [[तूर्वयाण|Tūrvayāṇa]]. But the various passages can be reconciled, especially if it is admitted that [[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]] Divodāsa was already an ancient hero in the earliest hymns, and was becoming almost mythical.<br><br><ref name=fx4_ve1_41/><br>

अति-धन्वन् शौनक
<u>'''Ati-[[धन्वन्|dhanvan]] Śaunaka.'''</u>--He is mentioned as a teacher in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_42/> and the Vaṃsa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_42/> <br>

अ-तृणाद
<u>'''A-tṛṇāda.'''</u>--This term (‘not eating grass’) was applied, according to the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]], to a newborn calf.<ref name=fx1_ve1_43/><br>

अत्क
<u>'''1. Atka.'''</u>--This word occurs frequently in the Rigveda, but its sense is doubtful. Roth, Grassmann, Ludwig, Zimmer,<ref name=fx1_ve1_44/> and others render it as ‘garment’ in several passages,<ref name=fx2_ve1_44/> when the expressions ‘put on’ (''vyā'' or ''prati muñc'') or ‘put off’ (''muñc'') are used of it, and when it is said to be ‘woven’ (''vyuta'')<ref name=fx3_ve1_44/> or ‘wellfitting’ (''surabhi'').<ref name=fx4_ve1_44/> On the other hand, Pischel<ref name=fx5_ve1_44/> denies that this sense occurs, and otherwise explains the passages. He takes the term to mean ‘axe’ in four places.<ref name=fx6_ve1_44/><br>

अत्क
<u>'''2. Atka.'''</u>--In two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_45/> this word is regarded as a proper name by Roth, Grassmann, and Ludwig. But Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_45/> explains it in these passages as the ‘armour of a warrior as a whole,’ and Pischel<ref name=fx3_ve1_45/> thinks that in both cases an ‘axe’ is meant.<br>

अत्य्-अंहस् आरुणि
<u>'''Aty-aṃhas Āruṇi.'''</u>--According to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 10, 9, 3-5), this teacher sent a pupil to question '''[[प्लक्ष|Plakṣa]] Dayyāṃpati''' as to the Sāvitra (a form of Agni). For this impertinence his pupil was severely rebuked.<br>

अत्य्-अराति जानं-तपि
<u>'''Aty-arāti Jānaṃ-tapi,'''</u> though not a prince, was taught the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]] by '''[[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]] Satyahavya,''' and thereupon conquered the earth. When [[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]] reminded him of his indebtedness, and claimed a great reward, the warrior replied irascibly that he intended to conquer the '''Uttara Kurus,''' and that [[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]] would then become King of the Earth, Atyarāti himself being his general (''[[सेना|senā]]-pati''). [[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]] replied that as no mortal man could conquer the Uttara Kurus he was cheated of his reward.  He consequently procured Atyarāti's defeat and death at the hands of '''[[अमित्रतपन शुष्मिण शैब्य|Amitratapana Śuṣmiṇa Śaibya]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_47/><br>

अत्रि
<u>'''Atri.'''</u>--Neither Atri himself nor the Atris can claim any historical reality,<ref name=fx1_ve1_48/> beyond the fact that Maṇḍala V. of the Rigveda is attributed, no doubt correctly, to the family of the Atris.<ref name=fx2_ve1_48/> The Atris as a family probably stood in close relations with the '''Priyamedhas'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_48/> and '''Kaṇvas,'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_48/> perhaps also with the '''Gotamas'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_48/> and '''Kākṣīvatas.'''<ref name=fx6_ve1_48/> The mention of both the '''[[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]]''' and the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]''' in one hymn<ref name=fx7_ve1_48/> of the fifth Maṇḍala seems to justify the presumption that the family was spread over a wide extent of territory.<br>

अथरी
<u>'''Atharī.'''</u>--This word occurs only in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_49/> and the sense is doubtful. Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve1_49/> followed by most interpreters, renders it ‘point of a lance,’ but Pischel<ref name=fx3_ve1_49/> thinks that it means ‘an elephant.’<br>

अथर्वन्
<u>'''Atharvan.'''</u>--The name in the singular denotes the head of a semi-divine family of mythical priests,<ref name=fx1_ve1_50/> of whom nothing historical can be said. In the plural the family as a whole is meant. In a few places an actual family seems to be referred to. Thus, for instance, they are mentioned as recipients of gifts in the Dānastuti<ref name=fx2_ve1_50/> (‘Praise of Gifts’), of '''Aśvattha's'''  generosity; their use of milk mingled with honey in the ritual is referred to;<ref name=fx3_ve1_50/> and a cow that miscarries (''ava-tokā'') from accident is dedicated to the Atharvans, according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_50/><br>

अथर्वाणः
<u>'''Atharvāṇaḥ.'''</u>--This expression<ref name=fx1_ve1_51/> is used with '''Aṅgirasaḥ,''' to denote the Atharvaveda. The compound '''[[अथर्वाङ्गिरसः|Atharvāṅgirasaḥ]]''' is employed in the same sense.<br>

अथर्वाङ्गिरसः
<u>'''Atharvāṅgirasaḥ.'''</u>--This is the collective name of the Atharvaveda in several passages<ref name=fx1_ve1_52/> of the later Brāhmaṇas. It occurs once in the Atharvaveda itself,<ref name=fx2_ve1_52/> while the term Atharvaveda is not found before the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period.<ref name=fx3_ve1_52/> The compound seems, according to Bloomfield,<ref name=fx4_ve1_52/> to denote the two elements which make up the Atharvaveda. The former part refers to the auspicious practices of the Veda (''bheṣajāni'');<ref name=fx5_ve1_52/> the latter to its hostile witchcraft, the ''yātu''<ref name=fx6_ve1_52/> or ''abhi-cāra.''<ref name=fx7_ve1_52/> This theory is supported by the names of the two mythic personages '''[[घोर आङ्गिरस|Ghora Āṅgirasa]]''' and '''[[भिषज् आथर्वण|Bhiṣaj Ātharvaṇa]],''' as well as by the connection of [[अथर्वाणः|Atharvāṇaḥ]] and '''Ātharvaṇāni''' with healing (''[[भेषज|bheṣaja]]'') in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx8_ve1_52/> Moreover, the term ''bhesajā'' (‘remedies’) designates in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx9_ve1_52/> that Veda itself, while in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx10_ve1_52/> ''yātu'' (‘sorcery’) conveys the same meaning. The evidence, however, being by no means convincing, it remains probable that there existed no clear differentiation between the two sages as responsible for the Atharvaveda as a whole. <br>

अ-दृष्ट
<u>'''A-dṛṣṭa.'''</u>--‘The unseen’ is a term used in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_53/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_53/> to designate a species of vermin. The sun is also described as ‘the slayer of the unseen’ (''[[अदृष्ट|adṛṣṭa]]-han''),<ref name=fx3_ve1_53/> and as a counterpart a ‘seen’ (''[[दृष्ट|dṛṣṭa]]'') is mentioned.<ref name=fx4_ve1_53/> In one passage<ref name=fx5_ve1_53/> the epithets ‘seen’ and ‘unseen’ are applied to the worm ('''[[कृमि|Kṛmi]]'''), their use being no doubt due to the widespread theory of diseases being due to worms, whether discernable by examination or not.<ref name=fx6_ve1_53/><br>

अद्म-सद्
<u>'''Adma-sad.'''</u>--This expression (''lit.'' ‘sitting at the meal’), found several times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_54/> is usually rendered ‘guest at the feast,’ but Geldner<ref name=fx2_ve1_54/> adduces reasons to show that it means ‘a fly,’ so called because of its settling on food.<br>

अद्रि
<u>'''Adri.'''</u>--Zimmer<ref name=fx1_ve1_55/> deduces from the use of this word (‘rock,’ ‘stone’) in a passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_55/> that sling-stones were used in Vedic fighting. But the passage is mythical, referring to Indra's aid, and cannot be used with any certainty as evidence for human war. More probably it merely denotes Indra's bolt. See also '''[[अशनि|Aśani]].'''<br>

अधि-देवन
<u>'''Adhi-devana.'''</u>--The place where the dice were thrown is thus designated in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_56/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_56/> according to Lüders.<ref name=fx3_ve1_56/> Roth,<ref name=fx4_ve1_56/> followed by Whitney, takes it to mean ‘gambling-board.’ See '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]].'''<br>

अधि-राज
<u>'''Adhi-rāja.'''</u>--The word occurs fairly often throughout the early literature,<ref name=fx1_ve1_57/> denoting ‘overlord’ among kings or princes.  In no passage is it clear that a real over-king is meant, as the word ''[[राजन्|rājan]]'' may mean king or merely prince, a person of royal blood. On the whole it seems most probable that the word connotes no more than ‘king’ as opposed to ‘prince.’<br>

अधि-षवण
<u>'''Adhi-ṣavaṇa.'''</u>--The two Adhiṣavaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_58/> are usually understood, as by Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_58/> and Zimmer,<ref name=fx3_ve1_58/> to designate the two boards between which the Soma was pressed. Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx4_ve1_58/> however, shows from the ritual that the boards were not placed one over the other, but were placed one behind the other, the two serving as a foundation upon which the Soma was pressed by a stone. This theory seems to account best for the etymological sense of the name ‘over-press,’ as well as for the use of the word as an adjective (‘used for pressing ''upon''’). But according to the procedure as witnessed by Haug<ref name=fx5_ve1_58/> in the Deccan, the shoots of the plant are first placed on the skin, one of the boards being then laid over them and pounded with a stone. The shoots are then taken out and placed upon the board, the second board being then laid over them.<br>

अधी¤-वास
<u>'''Adhī¤-vāsa.'''</u>--This word<ref name=fx1_ve1_59/> denotes the ‘upper garment’ of the Vedic Indian. Its exact nature is not described, but as the king in the ritual set forth in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_59/> puts on first an undergarment, then a garment, and finally an upper garment, it presumably denotes some sort of cloak or mantle.<br>

अध्याण्डा
<u>'''Adhyāṇḍā.'''</u>--This is a plant mentioned with many others in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 8, 1, 16). <br>

अध्रि-गु
<u>'''Adhri-gu.'''</u>--This is the name of a man twice referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_61/> as a protégé of the Aśvins and of Indra respectively.<br>

अध्वर्यु
<u>'''Adhvaryu.'''</u>--In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_62/> Hillebrandt<ref name=fx2_ve1_62/> thinks that the five Adhvaryus who are mentioned do not designate actual priests, but refer to the five planets which move about in the heavens like the [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]] priests on the sacrificial ground. See also '''[[ग्रह|Graha]].'''<br>

अन्-अग्नि-दग्ध
<u>'''An-agni-dagdha,'''</u> ‘not burnt with fire.’ See '''[[अग्नि-दग्ध|Agni-dagdha]],''' ‘burnt with fire.’<br>

अनड्-वाह्
<u>'''Anaḍ-vāh'''</u> (lit. ‘cart-drawer’).--This is the common<ref name=fx1_ve1_64/> name of oxen as employed for drawing carts ('''Anas'''). Such oxen were normally castrated,<ref name=fx2_ve1_64/> though not always. Female draft cattle were also used (''anaḍuhī''), but rarely.<ref name=fx3_ve1_64/> See also '''Gō.'''<br>

अनस्
<u>'''Anas.'''</u>--This is the term<ref name=fx1_ve1_65/> used to designate the draft wagon, as opposed to the chariot (''[[रथ|ratha]]'') for war or sport, with which it is sometimes expressly contrasted,<ref name=fx2_ve1_65/> though Indra is once said to be ‘seated in a wagon’ (''anar-[[विश्|viś]]'')<ref name=fx3_ve1_65/> instead of on a chariot. Though Uṣas, Goddess of Dawn, sometimes rides on a chariot (''[[रथ|ratha]]''), the wagon is her characteristic vehicle.<ref name=fx4_ve1_65/> Of its construction we know little. The bridal wagon on which Sūryā, the daughter of the Sun, was borne in the marriage hymn in the Rigveda had a covering ('''[[छदिस्|Chadis]]''').<ref name=fx5_ve1_65/> The axle-box ('''Kha''') is also  mentioned.<ref name=fx6_ve1_65/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_65/> [[विपथ|Vipatha]] appears to denote a rough vehicle used for bad tracks. The wagon was usually drawn by oxen ('''[[अनड्वाह्|Anaḍvāh]]'''), as in wedding processions.<ref name=fx8_ve1_65/> The wagon of Dawn is described as drawn by ruddy cows or bulls.<ref name=fx9_ve1_65/><br>

अनास्
<u>'''Anās.'''</u> See '''[[दस्यु|Dasyu]].'''<br>

अनितभा
<u>'''Anitabhā'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_67/> is taken by Max Müller<ref name=fx2_ve1_67/> to denote some river.<br>

अनु
<u>'''Anu, Ānava.'''</u>--Grassmann and Roth<ref name=fx1_ve1_68/> see in these words designations of people foreign to the Aryans. But it is clear<ref name=fx2_ve1_68/> that they denote a special people, the Anus, who are mentioned with the '''Yadus, Turvaśas, Druhyus,''' and '''Pūrus,'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_68/> with the Druhyus,<ref name=fx4_ve1_68/> and with the Turvaśas, Yadus, and Druhyus.<ref name=fx5_ve1_68/> It is also a fair conclusion from their mention in a passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_68/> that they dwelt on the [[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]]. The inference that the Bhṛgus were connected with this tribe is much more doubtful,<ref name=fx7_ve1_68/> for it rests solely on the fact that in one place<ref name=fx8_ve1_68/> the Bhṛgus and Druhyus are mentioned together, and not Anus and Druhyus. [[आनव|Ānava]] is used as an epithet of Agni,<ref name=fx9_ve1_68/> but also in the sense of ‘Anu prince,’<ref name=fx10_ve1_68/> in one case in conjunction with [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]].<ref name=fx11_ve1_68/><br>

अनु-क्षत्तृ
<u>'''Anu-kṣattṛ.'''</u>--This word occurs in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha,<ref name=fx1_ve1_69/> and means, according to Mahīdhara,<ref name=fx2_ve1_69/> ‘an attendant on the door-keeper,’ and, according to Sāyaṇa, ‘an attendant on the charioteer’ (''[[सारथि|sārathi]]''). See also '''[[क्षत्तृ|Kṣattṛ]].'''(**  3) On [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], ''loc. cit.'' <br>

अनु-चर
<u>'''Anu-cara.'''</u>--This is a general expression<ref name=fx1_ve1_70/> for an ‘attendant’ (the feminine being Anucarī),<ref name=fx2_ve1_70/> but it is not often used.<br>

अनु-मति
<u>'''Anu-mati.'''</u> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

अनु-राधा
<u>'''Anu-rādhā.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

अनु-वक्तृ सत्य सात्य-कीर्त
<u>'''Anu-vaktṛ Satya Sātya-kīrta'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 5, 4).<br>

अनुव्या-ख्यान
<u>'''Anuvyā-khyāna'''</u> is a species of writing referred to in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_74/> Śaṅkara interprets it as ‘explanation of the Mantras.’ As the term, in the plural, follows '''Sūtras,''' this interpretation is reasonable. Sieg,<ref name=fx2_ve1_74/> however, equates the word with '''[[अन्वाख्यान|Anvākhyāna]],''' ‘supplementary narrative.’<br>

अनु-शासन
<u>'''Anu-śāsana'''</u> in the plural denotes in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xi. 5, 6, 8) some form of literature; according to Sāyaṇa, the Vedāṅgas.<br>

अनु-शिख
<u>'''Anu-śikha'''</u> is the name of the [[पोतृ|Potṛ]] at the snake festival in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_76/><br>

अन्ते-वासिन्
<u>'''Ante-vāsin,'''</u> ‘dwelling near,’ is the epithet of the '''Brahmacārin''' who lives in the house of his teacher. The expression does not occur before the late [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] period.<ref name=fx1_ve1_77/> Secrecy is often enjoined on others than Antevāsins.<ref name=fx2_ve1_77/><br>

अन्ध्र
<u>'''Andhra'''</u> is the name of a people, and is mentioned with the '''Puṇḍras, Śabaras, Pulindas,''' and '''Mūtibas,''' as being the outcasts resulting from the refusal of the fifty eldest sons of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' to accept his adoption of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_78/> It may fairly be deduced  from this statement that these people were recognized as nonAryan, as the Andhras certainly seem to have been.<ref name=fx2_ve1_78/><br>

अन्यतः-प्लक्षा
<u>'''Anyataḥ-plakṣā'''</u> (‘with wave-leafed fig-trees on one side only’) is the name of a lake in [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]] according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_79/> where it occurs in the story of [[पुरूरवस्|Purūravas]] and Urvaśī. Pischel<ref name=fx2_ve1_79/> places it somewhere in Sirmor.<br>

अन्य-वाप
<u>'''Anya-vāpa'''</u> (‘sowing for others’).--The cuckoo is so called<ref name=fx1_ve1_80/> from its habit of depositing its eggs in the nests of other birds<br>

अन्वा-ख्यान
<u>'''Anvā-khyāna.'''</u>--From the literal translation (‘after-story’) the meaning of ‘supplementary narrative’ seems to follow. In two<ref name=fx1_ve1_81/> of its three occurrences in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] this sense is hardly felt, the expression being used to indicate a subsequent portion of the book itself. But in the third<ref name=fx2_ve1_81/> passage it is distinguished from the '''[[इतिहास|Itihāsa]]''' (‘story’) proper, and there must mean ‘supplementary narrative.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[अनुव्याख्यान|Anuvyākhyāna]].'''<br>

अप-चित्
<u>'''Apa-cit.'''</u>--This word occurs several times in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_82/> It is held by Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve1_82/> Zimmer,<ref name=fx3_ve1_82/> and others to denote an insect whose sting produced swellings, etc. (''glau''). But Bloomfield<ref name=fx4_ve1_82/> shows that the disease, scrofulous swellings, is what is really meant, as is shown by the rendering (''gaṇḍa-mālā,'' ‘inflammation of the glands of the neck’) of Keśava and Sāyaṇa, and by the parallelism of the later disease, ''apacī,'' the derivation being from ''apa'' and ''ci,'' ‘to pick off.’ <br>

अप-श्रय
<u>'''Apa-śraya.'''</u> See '''Upaśraya.'''<br>

अप-स्कम्भ
<u>'''Apa-skambha.'''</u>--The word occurs only in one passage of the Atharvaveda, where the tip of it is mentioned as poisoned. Roth<ref name=fx1_ve1_84/> suggests that the fastening of the arrow-point to the shaft is meant. Whitney<ref name=fx2_ve1_84/> inclines to this version, but suggests corruption of text. Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_84/> follows Roth. Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve1_84/> renders the word by ‘barb.’ Bloomfield<ref name=fx5_ve1_84/> thinks it means ‘tearing (arrow),’ a sense deduced from the etymology.<br>

अपाच्यस्
<u>'''Apācyas.'''</u>--The kings of the ‘Westerners’ are referred to in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 14) in connection with those of the '''Nīcyas.'''<br>

अपान
<u>'''Apāna.'''</u>--The word appears repeatedly in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_86/> and later as one of the vital breaths ('''[[प्राण|Prāṇa]]'''), usually with [[प्राण|Prāṇa]], and often with one or more of the other three. Its original sense<ref name=fx2_ve1_86/> appears to have been ‘inspiration.’ Its connection with the lower part of the body (''[[नाभि|nābhi]],'' ‘navel’), which is found already in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_86/> is not unnatural.<br>

अपा-मार्ग
<u>'''Apā-mārga.'''</u>--A plant (''Achyranthes aspera'') used frequently<ref name=fx1_ve1_87/> in witchcraft practices, and for medical purposes, especially against '''[[क्षेत्रिय|Kṣetriya]].''' It is described in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_87/> as ‘revertive’ (''[[पुनः-सर|punaḥ-sara]]''), either, as Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_87/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve1_87/> think, because of its having reverted leaves (a view also accepted by Whitney<ref name=fx5_ve1_87/> ),  or because, as Bloomfield<ref name=fx6_ve1_87/> holds, it wards off a spell by causing it to recoil on its user.<br>

अप-लम्ब
<u>'''Apa-lamba.'''</u>--By this word<ref name=fx1_ve1_88/> is denoted a brake or drag, let down (from ''lamb,'' ‘hang down’) to check the speed of a wagon.<br>

अपाष्ठ
<u>'''Apāṣṭha.'''</u>--This word occurs twice in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_89/> denoting the barb of an arrow.<br>

अपि-शर्वर
<u>'''Api-śarvara.'''</u> See '''Anan.'''<br>

अपी
<u>'''Apī.'''</u>--Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve1_91/> finds an [[अपी|Apī]] whose sons are described as not performing sacrifice (''a-yajña-sāc'') and as breakers of the law of [[मित्र|Mitra]]-Varuṇa in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_91/> Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_91/> and Grassmann take the expression used (''apyaḥ putrāḥ'') as referring to the sons of the waters.<br>

अपूप
<u>'''Apūpa'''</u> is the general word from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_92/> onwards for a cake, which might be mixed with ghee (''ghṛtavant''),<ref name=fx2_ve1_92/> or be made of rice (''[[व्रीहि|vrīhi]]''),<ref name=fx3_ve1_92/> or of barley (''yava'').<ref name=fx4_ve1_92/> In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_92/> there is a difference of interpretation. Max Müller renders it as ‘hive,’ Bo7htlingk as ‘honeycomb,’ Little<ref name=fx6_ve1_92/> as ‘cake.’<br>

अप्नवान
<u>'''Apnavāna'''</u> appears only twice in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_93/> as an ancient sage, coupled with the Bhṛgus, to whose family Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_93/> conjectures him to have belonged. <br>

अ-प्रति-रथ
<u>'''A-prati-ratha'''</u> (‘he who has no match in fight’) is the name of an obviously invented [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], to whom is ascribed by the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_94/> and Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_94/> the composition of a Rigveda hymn<ref name=fx3_ve1_94/> celebrating Indra as the invincible warrior.<br>

अप्वा
<u>'''Apvā.'''</u>--A disease affecting the stomach,<ref name=fx1_ve1_95/> possibly dysentery, as suggested by Zimmer,<ref name=fx2_ve1_95/> on the ground that the disease is invoked to confound the enemy.<ref name=fx3_ve1_95/> Weber<ref name=fx4_ve1_95/> considers that it is diarrhœa induced by fear, as often in the Epic.<ref name=fx5_ve1_95/> This view is supported by Bloomfield,<ref name=fx6_ve1_95/> and was apparently that of [[यास्क|Yāska]].<ref name=fx7_ve1_95/><br>

अप्सस्
<u>'''Apsas.'''</u>--This word usually refers to the body, meaning ‘front part.’<ref name=fx1_ve1_96/> In one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_96/> however, the adjective ‘with a long front part’ (''[[दीर्घाप्सस्|dīrghāpsas]]'') is applied to the chariot ('''[[रथ|Ratha]]''').<br>

अभि-क्रोशक
<u>'''Abhi-krośaka'''</u> designates one of the victims in the Puruṣamedha, meaning, perhaps, ‘herald.’ The commentator Mahīdhara<ref name=fx1_ve1_97/> renders it as ‘reviler’ (''nindaka'').<br>

अभि-जित्
<u>'''Abhi-jit.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

अभि-पित्व
<u>'''Abhi-pitva.'''</u> See '''Ahan.'''<br>

अभि-प्रतारिन् काक्ष-सेनि
<u>'''Abhi-pratārin Kākṣa-seni'''</u> is mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_100/> the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_100/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_100/> as engaged in discussions on philosophy. The Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_100/> further reports that his sons divided the property amongst themselves while he was yet alive. He was a Kuru and a prince. <br>

अभि-प्रश्निन्
<u>'''Abhi-praśnin.'''</u>--This term occurs after '''Praśnin,''' and followed by '''Praśnavivāka''' in the list of victims for the Puruṣamedha given in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_101/> and the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve1_101/> The commentators, Sāyaṇa and Mahīdhara, see in it merely a reference to an inquisitive man. But there can be little doubt that the term must have had a legal reference of some sort-perhaps indicating the defendant as opposed to plaintiff and judge.<br>

अभि-श्री
<u>'''Abhi-śrī'''</u> (‘admixture’).--This word<ref name=fx1_ve1_102/> designates the milk used to mingle with the Soma juice before it was offered.<br>

अभि-षवणी
<u>'''Abhi-ṣavaṇī.'''</u>--Zimmer<ref name=fx1_ve1_103/> renders the expression in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_103/> as a pressing instrument, but it appears to be merely an adjective, (waters) ‘used in pressing.’<ref name=fx3_ve1_103/><br>

अभि-षेक
<u>'''Abhi-ṣeka'''</u> (‘besprinkling’).--The Vedic king was consecrated after his election with an elaborate ritual, which is fully described in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_104/> Pañcaviṃśa,<ref name=fx2_ve1_104/> Śatapatha,<ref name=fx3_ve1_104/> and [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx4_ve1_104/> and for which the Mantras are given in the Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx5_ve1_104/> The consecration took place by sprinkling with water (''abhiṣecanīyā āpaḥ'').<ref name=fx6_ve1_104/> Only kings could be consecrated, the people not being worthy of it (''anabhiṣecanīyāḥ'').<ref name=fx7_ve1_104/> The sprinkler (''abhiṣektṛ'') is mentioned in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha.<ref name=fx8_ve1_104/> The [[अभिषेक|Abhiṣeka]] is an essential part of the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]],''' or sacrifice of royal inauguration, being the second of its component members.(**  9 ''Cf.'' Hillebrandt, ''Rituallitteratur,'' 143-147; Eggeling, ''Sacred Books of the East,'' 41, xxvi; Weber, ''Über den [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]].'' <br>

अभीशु
<u>'''Abhīśu'''</u> is a common Vedic word<ref name=fx1_ve1_105/> denoting the ‘reins’ or ‘bridle’ of the chariot horses. The use of the plural is due to the fact that two or four horses, possibly five (''daśābhīśu'' ‘tenbridled’),<ref name=fx2_ve1_105/> were yoked to the car.<br>

अभ्य्-अग्नि ऐतशायन
<u>'''Abhy-agni Aitaśāyana.'''</u>--This man was, according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_106/> unfortunate enough to quarrel with his father, '''[[ऐतश|Aitaśa]].''' The result was that he and his progeny were called the worst of the '''Aurvas.''' In the version of the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_106/> the '''Aitaśāyana Ājāneyas''' take the place of the Abhyagnis and the '''Bhṛgus''' of the '''Aurvas,''' the latter being probably a branch of the former family.<br>

अभ्या-वर्तिन् चायमान
<u>'''Abhyā-vartin Cāyamāna'''</u> appears in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_107/> and as conqueror of the Vṛcīvants under the leader '''[[वरशिख|Varaśikha]].''' It is probable though not absolutely certain, that he is identical with the '''[[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]] [[दैववात|Daivavāta]],''' mentioned in the same hymn<ref name=fx2_ve1_107/> as having the '''Turvaśas''' and '''Vṛcīvants''' defeated for him by Indra. In this case he would be prince (''[[सम्राज्|samrāj]]'') of the Sṛñjayas. [[दैववात|Daivavāta]] is mentioned elsewhere<ref name=fx3_ve1_107/> as a worshipper of Agni.<br><br>Abhyāvartin is also referred to as a [[पार्थव|Pārthava]]. Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve1_107/> and Hillebrandt<ref name=fx5_ve1_107/> maintained that he is thus a Parthian, the latter using the evidence of the two places mentioned in the description<ref name=fx6_ve1_107/> of Daivavāta's victories, '''[[हरियूपीया|Hariyūpīyā]]''' and '''[[यव्यावती|Yavyāvatī]],''' as proofs for the western position of Abhyāvartin's people in Arachosia, in Iran. But Zimmer<ref name=fx7_ve1_107/> is probably right in holding that the name [[पार्थव|Pārthava]] merely means ‘a descendant of [[पृथु|Pṛthu]],’ and that its similarity to the Iranian Parthians is only on a par with the numerous other points of identity between the Indian and Iranian cultures. <br>

अ-भ्रातरः
<u>'''A-bhrātaraḥ'''</u> (‘brotherless’).--The lot of girls without brothers is referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_108/> as unsatisfactory--apparently they became prostitutes. The [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_108/> expressly forbids marriage with a brotherless maiden, probably because of the risk of her being made a ''[[पुत्रिका|putrikā]]'' (‘adoptive daughter’) by her father--that is, any son of hers being counted as belonging to her father's, instead of to her husband's, family. See '''[[अयोगू|Ayogū]].'''<br>

अभ्रि
<u>'''Abhri'''</u> (‘spade’) is a Vedic word<ref name=fx1_ve1_109/> of frequent occurrence. Various possible materials and forms are enumerated in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_109/> It may be made of bamboo or of the wood of [[विकङ्कत|Vikaṅkata]] or [[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]]. It may be a span or a cubit in size. It is hollow, and either one or both edges are sharp. From this it would appear that the handle was made of some wood, but the head of some metal.<br>

अमत्र
<u>'''Amatra'''</u> was a vessel into which the Soma, after being pressed, was poured,<ref name=fx1_ve1_110/> and out of which the libation to the god was made.<ref name=fx2_ve1_110/><br>

अमला
<u>'''Amalā.'''</u>--This plant<ref name=fx1_ve1_111/> is probably the ''Emblica officinalis,'' or Myrobalan tree; also called '''[[आमलक|Āmalaka]],''' or '''Āmalakā.'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_111/><br>

अमा-जुर्
<u>'''Amā-jur'''</u> is an epithet<ref name=fx1_ve1_112/> denoting maidens ‘who grow old at home’ without finding husbands, or, as they are elsewhere called, ‘who sit with their father’ (''[[पितृ|pitṛ]]-ṣad''). A well-known example of such was [[घोषा|Ghoṣā]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_112/> <br>

अमा-वास्य शाण्दिल्यायन
<u>'''Amā-vāsya Śāṇdilyāyana'''</u> is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_113/> as the teacher of '''[[अंशु|Aṃśu]] [[धानंजय्य|Dhānaṃjayya]].'''<br>

अमित्र-तपन शुष्मिण शैब्य
<u>'''Amitra-tapana Śuṣmiṇa Śaibya'''</u> is the name of him who killed '''[[अत्य्अराति जानंतपि|Atyarāti Jānaṃtapi]],''' according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 23).<br>

अ-मूला
<u>'''A-mūlā'''</u> (‘without root’) is the name in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_115/> of a plant (''Methonica superba''), which was used for poisoning arrows. Bloomfield,<ref name=fx2_ve1_115/> however, renders it as ‘movable property.’<br>

अम्बरीष
<u>'''Ambarīṣa'''</u> is mentioned as a [[वार्षागिर|Vārṣāgira]] in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_116/> along with '''[[ऋज्राश्व|Ṛjrāśva]], [[सहदेव|Sahadeva]], [[सुराधस्|Surādhas]],''' and '''[[भयमान|Bhayamāna]].'''<br>

अम्बष्ठ
<u>'''Ambaṣṭha.'''</u> See '''[[आम्बष्ठ्य|Āmbaṣṭhya]].'''<br>

अय
<u>'''Aya.'''</u> See '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]].'''<br>

अयस्
<u>'''Ayas.'''</u>--The exact metal denoted by this word when used by itself, as always in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_119/> is uncertain. As favouring the sense of ‘bronze’ rather than that of ‘iron’ may perhaps be cited with Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_119/> the fact that Agni is called ''ayo-[[दंष्ट्र|daṃṣṭra]],'' ‘with teeth of Ayas,’<ref name=fx3_ve1_119/> with reference to the colour of his flames, and that the car-seat of [[मित्र|Mitra]] and Varuṇa is called ''ayaḥ-sthūṇa,''<ref name=fx4_ve1_119/> ‘with pillars of Ayas’ at the setting of the sun.<ref name=fx5_ve1_119/> Moreover, in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx6_ve1_119/> Ayas is enumerated in a list of six metals: gold (''[[हिरण्य|hiraṇya]]''), Ayas, [[श्याम|Śyāma]], Loha, lead (''[[सीस|sīsa]]''), tin (''[[त्रपु|trapu]]''). Here ''[[श्याम|śyāma]]'' (‘swarthy’) and ''loha'' (‘red’) must mean ‘iron’ and ‘copper’ respectively; ''ayas'' would therefore seem to mean ‘bronze.’ In many passages in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_119/> and  other books, the Ayas is divided into two species--the ''[[श्याम|śyāma]]'' (‘iron’) and the ''[[लोहित|lohita]]'' (‘copper’ or ‘bronze’). In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_119/> a distinction is drawn between Ayas and ''[[लोहायस|lohāyasa]],'' which may either be a distinction between iron and copper as understood by Eggeling,<ref name=fx9_ve1_119/> or between copper and bronze as held by Schrader.<ref name=fx10_ve1_119/> In one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx11_ve1_119/> the sense of iron seems certain. Possibly, too, the arrow of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx12_ve1_119/> which had a tip of Ayas (''yasyā ayo mukham''), was pointed with iron. Copper, however, is conceivable, and bronze quite likely.<br><br>Iron is called ''[[श्याम|śyāma]] ayas'' or ''[[श्याम|śyāma]]'' alone.<ref name=fx13_ve1_119/> See also '''[[कार्ष्णायस|Kārṣṇāyasa]].''' Copper is '''[[लोहायस|Lohāyasa]]''' or '''[[लोहितायस|Lohitāyasa]].'''<br><br>The smelting (''dhmā'' ‘to blow’) of the metal is frequently referred to. The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx14_ve1_119/> states that if ‘well smelted’ (''bahu-dhmātam'') it is like gold, referring evidently to bronze. A heater of Ayas is mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx15_ve1_119/> and bowls of Ayas are also spoken of.<ref name=fx16_ve1_119/><br>

अय-स्थूण
<u>'''Aya-sthūṇa.'''</u>--He was Gṛhapati (‘householder,’ the sacrificer at sacrificial sessions) of those whose [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]] was Śaulvāyana, and taught the latter the proper mode of using certain spoons.<ref name=fx1_ve1_120/><br>

अयास्य आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Ayāsya Āṅgirasa.'''</u>--This sage appears to be mentioned in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_121/> and the Anukramaṇī ascribes to him several hymns of the Rigveda (ix. 44-46; x. 67; 68). In the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] tradition he was Udgātṛ at the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]] or Royal Inauguration Sacrifice, at which [[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]] was to have been slain, and his Udgītha ([[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]] chant) is referred to elsewhere.<ref name=fx3_ve1_121/> He is also referred to several times as a ritual(**  2) [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], vii. 16.  authority.<ref name=fx4_ve1_121/> In the Vaṃśas, or Genealogies of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_121/> he is named as the pupil of Ābhūti [[त्वाष्ट्र|Tvāṣṭra]].<br>

अयोगू
<u>'''Ayogū'''</u> is a word of quite doubtful meaning, found in the list of victims in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_122/> It may, like the late ''[[आयोगव|āyogava]],'' denote a member of a mixed caste (theoretically a descendant of a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] by a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] wife).<ref name=fx2_ve1_122/> Weber<ref name=fx3_ve1_122/> rendered it as ‘unchaste woman.’<ref name=fx4_ve1_122/> Zimmer thinks it denotes a brotherless maiden who is exposed to the dangers of prostitution (''cf. [[आयोगव|āyogava]]'').<br>

अर
<u>'''Ara.'''</u> See '''[[रथ|Ratha]].'''<br>

अरटु
<u>'''Araṭu.'''</u>--A plant<ref name=fx1_ve1_124/> (''Colosanthes Indica'') from the wood of which the axle of a chariot was sometimes made.<ref name=fx2_ve1_124/><br>

अरण्य
<u>'''Araṇya.'''</u>--This term denotes the uncultivated land--not necessarily forest land--beyond the village. It is contrasted with home (''amā''),<ref name=fx1_ve1_125/> and with the plough land (''[[कृषि|kṛṣi]]''),<ref name=fx2_ve1_125/> being spoken of as apart (''tiras'') from men.<ref name=fx3_ve1_125/> It is also contrasted with the '''[[ग्राम|Grāma]],'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_125/> and it is the place where thieves live.<ref name=fx5_ve1_125/> The character of the forest is described in a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_125/> to the forest spirit (Araṇyānī). The dead are carried there for burial,<ref name=fx7_ve1_125/> and hermits live there.<ref name=fx8_ve1_125/> Forest fires were common.<ref name=fx9_ve1_125/> <br>

अरत्नि
<u>'''Aratni.'''</u>--This word, which primarily means ‘elbow,’ occurs frequently from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_126/> onwards as denoting a measure of length (‘ell’ or ‘cubit’), the distance from the elbow to the tip of the hand. The exact length nowhere appears from the early texts.<br>

अ-राजानः
<u>'''A-rājānaḥ,'''</u> ‘not princes,’ is a term used to describe persons in two passages of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_127/> and in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_127/> Weber<ref name=fx3_ve1_127/> also finds them mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_127/> and thinks that they--'''Sūtas''' (‘charioteers’) and '''Grāmaṇīs''' (‘troop-leaders’) there referred to--were called thus because, while not themselves princes, they assisted in the consecration of princes.<br>

अराटकी
<u>'''Arāṭakī'''</u> is a plant mentioned once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_128/> and apparently identical with the '''[[अजशृङ्गी|Ajaśṛṅgī]].''' ''Cf.'' also '''[[अरटु|Araṭu]].'''<br>

अराड दात्रेय शौनक
<u>'''Arāḍa [[दात्रेय|Dātreya]] Śaunaka.'''</u>--He is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_129/> as the pupil of '''[[दृति ऐन्द्रोत|Dṛti Aindrota]] [[शौनक|Śaunaka]].'''<br>

अरित्र
<u>'''Aritra'''</u> denotes the ‘oar’ by which boats were propelled. The Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_130/> and the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_130/> speak of a vessel with a hundred oars, and a boat (''nau'') is said to be ‘propelled by oars’ (''[[अरित्र|aritra]]-paraṇa'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_130/> In two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_130/> the term, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, denotes a part of a chariot. The rower of a boat is called ''aritṛ.''<ref name=fx5_ve1_130/> See '''Nau.''' <br>

अरिं-दम सन-श्रुत
<u>'''Ariṃ-dama Sana-śruta'''</u> is mentioned as a [[महाराज|Mahārāja]] in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], vii. 34.<br>

अरिम्-एजय
<u>'''Arim-ejaya'''</u> is mentioned as one who served as [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]] at the snake feast celebrated in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_132/><br>

अरुण आट
<u>'''Aruṇa Āṭa'''</u> was Achāvāka at the snake feast in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxv. 15).<br>

अरुण औपवेशि गौतम
<u>'''Aruṇa [[औपवेशि|Aupaveśi]] Gautama'''</u> is the full style<ref name=fx1_ve1_134/> of a teacher, who is repeatedly referred to in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve1_134/> and Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx3_ve1_134/> and whose son was the famous '''[[उद्दालक आरुणि|Uddālaka Āruṇi]].''' He was a pupil of Upaveśa,<ref name=fx4_ve1_134/> and a contemporary of the prince '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]],''' by whom he was instructed. ''Cf.'' '''Āruṇa.'''<br>

अरुन्धती
<u>'''1. Arundhatī'''</u> is the name of a plant celebrated in several passages of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_135/> as possessing healing properties in case of wounds, as a febrifuge, and as inducing cows to give milk. The plant was a climber which attached itself to trees like the '''[[प्लक्ष|Plakṣa]], [[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]], [[न्यग्रोध|Nyagrodha]],''' and '''[[पर्ण|Parṇa]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_135/> It was of golden colour (''[[हिरण्य|hiraṇya]]-varṇā''), and had a hairy stem (''lomaśavakṣaṇā'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_135/> It was also called [[सिलाची|Silācī]], and the '''[[लाक्षा|Lākṣā]]''' appears to have been a product of it.<ref name=fx4_ve1_135/><br>

अरुन्धती
<u>'''2. Arundhatī,'''</u> as the name of a star, is often referred to in the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] literature, but only once in a late Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve1_136/> <br>

अर्क
<u>'''Arka,'''</u> as the name of the tree ''Colotropis gigantea,'' is perhaps found in one obscure passage of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_137/><br>

अर्गल
<u>'''Argala.'''</u>--The word which is usual later to denote the wooden pin of a door is found in the Śāṇkhāyana Āraṇyaka (ii. 16) in the compound ''argaleṣīke'' to denote the pin and bar of the door of a cow-pen. ''Cf.'' '''[[इषीका|Iṣīkā]].'''<br>

अर्गल-काहोडि
<u>'''Argala-Kāhoḍi'''</u> is mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Samhitā (xxv. 7) as a teacher. The name may, however, be [[अर्यल|Aryala]], as suggested in the St. Petersburg Dictionary, ''s.v.,'' and as read by v. Schroeder in his edition. The Kapiṣṭhala (xxxix. 5) has Ayala. See below.<br>

अर्चन्त्
<u>'''Arcant'''</u> is possibly, as Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve1_140/> thinks, the name of the author of a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_140/> ; but the word may be merely the ordinary participle ‘praising.’<br>

अर्चनानस्
<u>'''Arcanānas.'''</u>--In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_141/> the gods MitraVaruṇa are besought to protect [[अर्चनानस्|Arcanānas]]. He is also invoked with '''[[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]]''' and several other ancestors enumerated in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_141/> He appears as father of [[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]] in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_141/> The later tradition makes him play a part in the legend of his son's wedding, which Sieg<ref name=fx4_ve1_141/> endeavours to show is known to the Rigveda.<br>

अर्चा
<u>'''Arcā.'''</u> See '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].'''<br>

अर्जुनी
<u>'''Arjunī'''</u> is, in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_143/> the name of the '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]]''' (‘lunar mansion’), elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve1_143/> called [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]]. It occurs in the marriage hymn, with '''[[अघा|Aghā]]''' for '''[[मघा|Maghā]],''' and, like that word, is apparently a deliberate modification. <br>

अर्बुद
<u>'''Arbuda'''</u> is mentioned as Grāvastut priest at the snake festival described in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_144/> He is obviously the same mythical figure as [[अर्बुद|Arbuda]] Kādraveya, a seer spoken of in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_144/> and [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx3_ve1_144/> as a maker of Mantras.<br>

अर्य
<u>'''Arya.'''</u>--This word is not common in the older literature, in places where the quantity of the first vowel is fixed as short, except in a mere adjectival sense. Geldner,<ref name=fx1_ve1_145/> indeed, contends that no other sense is anywhere needed; but Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_145/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_145/> agree in thinking that in several passages of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve1_145/> the word has the same sense as '''[[आर्य|Ārya]],''' and this appears probable. Whether it is necessary to ascribe this sense to the word in the compound ''arya-[[पत्नी|patnī]]''<ref name=fx5_ve1_145/> applied to the waters set free by Indra, is more doubtful. The commentator, Mahīdhara,<ref name=fx6_ve1_145/> suggests that the word means a '''[[वैश्य|Vaiśya]],''' not an '''[[आर्य|Ārya]]''' generally. This view is supported by the explanation in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve1_145/> of one of the passages of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx8_ve1_145/> But though the use of Arya to denote a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] became common later, it is not clear that it was original.<br>

अर्यम्णः पन्था
<u>'''Aryamṇaḥ Panthā,'''</u> ‘Aryaman's Way,’ an expression which occurs in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx1_ve1_146/> denotes, according to Weber,<ref name=fx2_ve1_146/> ‘the milky way,’ but, according to Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx3_ve1_146/> ‘the ecliptic.’ <br>

अर्यल
<u>'''Aryala.'''</u>--Those at whose snake feast the Gṛhapati was [[अर्यल|Aryala]], and the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] was '''[[आरुणि|Āruṇi]]''' are mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxiii. 1, 5). See also '''[[अर्गल|Argala]].'''<br>

अर्वन्त्
<u>'''Arvant.'''</u> See '''[[अश्व|Aśva]].'''<br>

अर्शस्
<u>'''Arśas'''</u> is the name of a disease mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_149/> with consumption and other ailments. It appears to designate ‘hæmorrhoids,’ as in the later medical literature.<br>

अलज
<u>'''Alaja'''</u> designates some kind of bird--one of the victims in the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_150/> or Horse Sacrifice.<br>

अलजि
<u>'''Alaji'''</u> is the name of a disease in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_151/> The later ''alajī'' denotes an eye-disease--a discharge at the junction of the cornea and the sclerotica.<br>

अलम्म पारिजानत
<u>'''Alamma Pārijānata'''</u> is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 4, 11; 10, 8) as a sage.<br>

अलसाला
<u>'''Alasālā.'''</u>--This word occurring only in one passage of the Atharvaveda (vi. 16, 4) is said to denote a grain-creeper.<br>

अलाण्डु
<u>'''Alāṇḍu.'''</u>--This is the reading in the text of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_154/> of the name of a species of worm. Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve1_154/> shows reason to adopt the reading Algaṇḍu as the correct form of the word.<br>

अलाबु
<u>'''Alābu.'''</u>--The bottle-gourd (''Lagenaria vulgaris''). Vessels made of it are referred to in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_155/><br>

अलाय्य
<u>'''Alāyya'''</u> is a word occurring in an obscure verse of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_156/> and appearing to be a proper name. Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx2_ve1_156/> however, amends the text so as to remove the name. The St. Petersburg Dictionary suggests that it refers to Indra. Pischel<ref name=fx3_ve1_156/> holds that  it is the name of a person whose axe was stolen, and for whom the hymn was written as a spell for the recovery of the axe.<br>

अलिक्लव
<u>'''Aliklava'''</u> is a kind of carrion bird mentioned in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_157/><br>

अलिन
<u>'''Alina'''</u> is the name of a people mentioned once only in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_158/> Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_158/> thought that the Alinas were allies--possibly a subdivision--of the '''Tṛtsus.''' Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve1_158/> more probably thinks that they were defeated by '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' together with the '''Pakthas, [[भलानस्|Bhalānas]], Śivas,''' and '''Viṣāṇins,''' with whom they are mentioned, at the '''[[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]];''' and Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve1_158/> suggests that they lived to the north-east of Kafiristan.<br>

अलीकयु वाचस्-पत्य
<u>'''Alīkayu Vācas-patya'''</u> is twice mentioned as an authority in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxvi. 5; xxviii. 4).<br>

अल्प-शयु
<u>'''Alpa-śayu'''</u> is a kind of insect mentioned in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_160/><br>

अवका
<u>'''Avakā'''</u> is an aquatic plant (''Blyxa octandra'') frequently referred to in the Atharvaveda as well as in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve1_161/> and Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_161/> The Gandharvas are said to eat it.<ref name=fx4_ve1_161/> Its later name is ''śaivala,'' and it is identical with the '''[[शीपाल|Śīpāla]].'''(**  1) viii. 7, 9; 37, 8-10.(**  5) With which it is glossed in Āśvalāyana [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], ii. 8; iv. 4. ''Cf.'' Bloomfield, ''Proceedings of the American Oriental Society,'' October, 1890, xli.-xliii.; ''American Journal of Philology,'' 11, 349; Zimmer, ''Altindisches Leben,'' 71.<br>

अवत
<u>'''Avata,'''</u> a word occurring several times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_162/> denotes a well, artificially made (''khan'' ‘to dig’) in contrast with a spring  (''utsa''), though the latter expression is also applied to an artificial well. Such wells were covered by the makers,<ref name=fx2_ve1_162/> and are described as unfailing (''a-kṣita'') and full of water.<ref name=fx3_ve1_162/> The water was raised by a wheel (''[[चक्र|cakra]]'') of stone, to which was fastened a strap (''[[वरत्रा|varatrā]]''), with a pail (''[[कोश|kośa]]'')<ref name=fx4_ve1_162/> attached to it. When raised it was poured (''siñc'') into buckets (''[[आहाव|āhāva]]'') of wood.<ref name=fx5_ve1_162/> Sometimes those wells appear to have been used for irrigation purposes, the water being led off into broad channels (''sārmī suṣirā'').<ref name=fx6_ve1_162/><br>

अवत्सार
<u>'''Avatsāra'''</u> is mentioned as a seer in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_163/> as a priest in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_163/> and as [[प्रास्रवण|Prāsravaṇa]] (or [[प्राश्रवण|Prāśravaṇa]]), son of [[प्रस्रवण|Prasravaṇa]], in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_163/> A hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_163/> is incorrectly ascribed to him in the Anukramaṇī.<br>

अ-वध्यता
<u>'''A-vadhyatā.'''</u> See '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].'''<br>

अवस
<u>'''Avasa'''</u> in the adjective ''an-[[अवस|avasa]]'' in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_165/> may mean ‘drag.’<br>

अव-स्कव
<u>'''Ava-skava.'''</u>--A kind of worm, mentioned along with others in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_166/><br>

अवात
<u>'''Avāta.'''</u> See '''[[वात|Vāta]].'''<br>

अवि
<u>'''Avi.'''</u>--‘Sheep’ are repeatedly mentioned in the Rigveda, and later, often in conjunction with goats (''aja''). The wolf (''[[वृक|vṛka]]'') was their great enemy,<ref name=fx1_ve1_168/> and they were tended by shepherds.<ref name=fx2_ve1_168/>  Sheep as well as kine were captured from the enemy.<ref name=fx3_ve1_168/> The Soma sieve was made of sheep's wool, and is repeatedly referred to (''avi, meṣī, avya, avyaya'').<ref name=fx4_ve1_168/> Considerable herds must have existed, as [[ऋज्राश्व|Ṛjrāśva]] is said<ref name=fx5_ve1_168/> to have slain one hundred rams, and in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’)<ref name=fx6_ve1_168/> a hundred sheep are mentioned as a gift. The (''[[मेष|meṣa]],''<ref name=fx7_ve1_168/> ''vṛṣṇi''<ref name=fx8_ve1_168/> ) ram was sometimes castrated (''[[पेत्व|petva]]'').<ref name=fx9_ve1_168/> The main use of sheep was their wool; hence the expression ‘woolly’ (''[[ऊर्णावती|ūrṇāvatī]]'')<ref name=fx10_ve1_168/> is employed to designate a sheep. In the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx11_ve1_168/> the ram is described as ‘woolly,’ and as ‘the skin of beasts, quadruped and biped,’ with reference to the use of its wool as clothing for men and shelter for animals. Pūṣan is said<ref name=fx12_ve1_168/> to weave raiment from the wool of sheep. Normally the sheep stayed out at pasture; in an obscure passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx13_ve1_168/> reference appears to be made to rams in stall. [[गन्धार|Gandhāra]]<ref name=fx14_ve1_168/> ewes were famous for their wool. Pischel<ref name=fx15_ve1_168/> considers that the '''[[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]]'''<ref name=fx16_ve1_168/> was named from its richness in sheep, ''[[परुस्|parus]]''<ref name=fx17_ve1_168/> denoting the ‘flocks’ of wool.<br>

अशनि
<u>'''Aśani.'''</u>--Zimmer<ref name=fx1_ve1_169/> cites this word from the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_169/> as denoting a sling stone, and compares a similar use of '''Adri.'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_169/> In either case, however, the weapons are mythical, being used in descriptions of Indra's deeds. Schrader<ref name=fx4_ve1_169/> also cites ''aśan'' in this sense, but no Vedic passage requires this sense.<br>

अश्म-गन्धा
<u>'''Aśma-gandhā'''</u> (‘rock-smell’) is a plant mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_170/> probably identical with the late ''aśvagandhā,'' ‘horse-smell’ (''Physalis flexuosa''). <br>

अश्व
<u>'''Aśva'''</u> is the commonest word for ‘horse’ in the Vedic literature. The horse is also called ‘the runner’ (''atya''), ‘the swift’ (''[[अर्वन्त्|arvant]]''), ‘the strong,’ for pulling (''[[वाजिन्|vājin]]''), ‘the runner’ (''[[सप्ति|sapti]]''), and ‘the speeding’ (''haya''). The mare is termed ''aśvā, atyā, arvatī, vaḍavā,'' etc. Horses of various colour were known, dun (''[[हरित|harita]], hari''), ruddy (''aruṇa, aruṣa, [[पिशङ्ग|piśaṅga]], [[रोहित|rohita]]''), dark brown (''[[श्याव|śyāva]]''), white (''śveta''), etc. A white horse with black ears is mentioned in the Atharvaveda as of special value.<ref name=fx1_ve1_171/> Horses were highly prized,<ref name=fx2_ve1_171/> and were not rare, as Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_171/> thought, for as many as four hundred mares are mentioned in one Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’).<ref name=fx4_ve1_171/> They were on occasion ornamented with pearls and gold.<ref name=fx5_ve1_171/><br><br>Mares were preferred for drawing chariots because of their swiftness and sureness.<ref name=fx6_ve1_171/> They were also used for drawing carts, but were not ordinarily so employed.<ref name=fx7_ve1_171/> No mention is made of riding in battle, but for other purposes it was not unknown.<ref name=fx8_ve1_171/><br><br>Horses were often kept in stalls,<ref name=fx9_ve1_171/> and fed there.<ref name=fx10_ve1_171/> But they were also allowed to go out to grass,<ref name=fx11_ve1_171/> and were then hobbled.<ref name=fx12_ve1_171/> They were watered to cool them after racing.<ref name=fx13_ve1_171/> Their attendants  are frequently referred to (''[[अश्व|aśva]]-pāla,''<ref name=fx14_ve1_171/> ''[[अश्व|aśva]]-pa,''<ref name=fx15_ve1_171/> ''[[अश्व-पति|aśva-pati]]'').<ref name=fx16_ve1_171/> Stallions were frequently castrated (''vadhri'').<ref name=fx17_ve1_171/><br><br>Besides reins (''raśmayaḥ''), reference is made to halters (''aśvābhidhānī''),<ref name=fx18_ve1_171/> and whips (''aśvājani'').<ref name=fx19_ve1_171/> See also '''[[रथ|Ratha]].'''<br><br>Horses from the Indus were of special value,<ref name=fx20_ve1_171/> as also horses from the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].'''<br>

अश्व-तर
<u>'''Aśva-tara, [[अश्व|Aśva]]-tarī'''</u> are respectively the masculine and feminine name of ‘mule.’ These animals are mentioned frequently from the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_172/> onwards. They were known not to be fruitful,<ref name=fx2_ve1_172/> and were probably considered inferior to horses,<ref name=fx3_ve1_172/> but a mule-car was quite common.<ref name=fx4_ve1_172/><br>

अश्व-त्थ
<u>'''1. Aśva-ttha'''</u> (‘horse-stand’) is one of India's greatest trees, the ''Ficus religiosa,'' later called ''[[पिप्पल|pippala]]''<ref name=fx1_ve1_173/> (now Peepal). Vessels made of the wood of the [[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]] are mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_173/> and the tree itself is constantly referred to later.<ref name=fx3_ve1_173/> Its hard wood formed the upper of the two pieces of wood used for kindling fire, the lower being of '''[[शमी|Śamī]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_173/> It planted its roots in shoots of other trees, especially the '''[[खदिर|Khadira]],''' and destroyed them;<ref name=fx5_ve1_173/> hence it is called ‘the destroyer’ (''vaibādha''). Its berries  are referred to as sweet, and as eaten by birds.<ref name=fx6_ve1_173/> The gods are said to sit under it in the third heaven.<ref name=fx7_ve1_173/> It and '''[[न्यग्रोध|Nyagrodha]]''' are styled the ‘crested ones’ (''śikhaṇḍin'').<ref name=fx8_ve1_173/><br>

अश्व-त्थ
<u>'''2. Aśva-ttha.'''</u>--This prince is celebrated in a Dānastuti<ref name=fx1_ve1_174/> as having given gifts to [[पायु|Pāyu]]. He is identified with '''Divodāsa''' by Griffith,<ref name=fx2_ve1_174/> but it is impossible to be certain of this identification.<br>

अश्व-दावन्
<u>'''Aśva-dāvan.'''</u>--Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve1_175/> finds a prince of this name in a passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_175/> where a gift of fifty horses is mentioned, but the word appears to be an epithet of Indra (‘bestower of horses’).<br>

अश्व-पति
<u>'''Aśva-pati'''</u> (‘lord of horses’) is a name of a prince of the '''Kekayas,''' who instructed '''Prācīnaśāla''' and other Brahmins.<ref name=fx1_ve1_176/><br>

अश्व-मेध
<u>'''Aśva-medha'''</u> (‘offering a horse-sacrifice’) is a prince mentioned in a hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_177/> which contains a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) of '''Tryaruṇa,''' and to which three verses have been added in praise of [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]]. See also '''Āśvamedha.'''<br>

अश्व-युजौ
<u>'''Aśva-yujau.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

अश्वल
<u>'''Aśvala,'''</u> the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest of '''[[जनक|Janaka]],''' King of '''[[विदेह|Videha]],''' appears as an authority in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iii. 1, 2. 10).<br>

अश्व-वार
<u>'''Aśva-vāra, [[अश्व|Aśva]]-vāla'''</u> (‘hair of a horse's tail’).--The former form occurs in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_180/> the latter in the  [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_180/> and Kapiṣṭhala Saṃhitās<ref name=fx3_ve1_180/> and Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_180/> denoting a species of reed (''Saccharum spontaneum'').<br>

अश्व-सूक्ति
<u>'''Aśva-sūkti'''</u> is the name of a seer to whom the Rigveda Anukramaṇī ascribes two hymns of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_181/> The [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_181/> knows a Sāman of [[अश्वसूक्ति|Aśvasūkti]].<br>

अश्विनी
<u>'''Aśvinī.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

अषाढ कैशिन्
<u>'''Aṣāḍha Kaiśin'''</u> is the name of a man referred to in a corrupt and obscure passage of the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_183/> as connected with the defeat of the '''Pañcālas''' by the '''Kuntis.'''<br>

अषाढ उत्तर पाराशर्य
<u>'''Aṣāḍha Uttara Pārāśarya'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] or Genealogy in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 41, 1).<br>

अषाढा
<u>'''Aṣāḍhā.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

अषाढि सौश्रोमतेय
<u>'''Aṣāḍhi Sauśromateya'''</u> was a man who is stated in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vi. 2, 1, 37) to have died because the heads for the sacrifice in connection with the laying of the bricks of the fire-altar had been obtained in an improper manner.<br>

अष्टक
<u>'''Aṣṭaka'''</u> is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_187/> as one of the sons of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]].'''<br>

अष्टका
<u>'''Aṣṭakā.'''</u> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

अष्ट-कर्णी
<u>'''Aṣṭa-karṇī'''</u> is an expression which occurs in one passage of the Ṛigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_189/> and which Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_189/> was at first inclined to interpret  as a proper name. There can, however, be no doubt that it means a cow, not a man, as suggested by Grassmann. The exact reason why a cow should be so described is uncertain. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_189/> was later inclined to see in it the sense ‘having pierced ears,’ similar epithets being at a later period known to Pāṇini<ref name=fx4_ve1_189/> (''bhinna-karṇa, chinna-karṇa''). Grassmann's more obvious rendering, ‘having the sign for (the number) 8 marked on the ear,’ is supported by the similar epithets, ‘having the mark of a lute on the ear’ (''[[कर्करि|karkari]]-karṇyaḥ''), ‘having the mark of a sickle on the ear’ (''[[दात्र|dātra]]-karṇyaḥ''), ‘having the mark of a stake on the ear’ (''sthūṇākarṇyaḥ''), ‘having the ears bored’ (''chidra-karṇyaḥ''), and ''viṣtyakarṇyaḥ,'' given in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx5_ve1_189/> The simple meaning, ‘with marked ears,’ is, however, supported by the same passage of the Maitrāyaṇī, where the verb ''akṣ'' occurs in the sense ‘to mark.’ In the Atharvaveda the mark used is the Mithuna, no doubt as a magical device to secure fertility.<br><br>The marking of ears was apparently a regular practice. It is twice referred to in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx6_ve1_189/> The mark is termed ''[[लक्ष्मन्|lakṣman]],''<ref name=fx7_ve1_189/> and was made with a copper-knife<ref name=fx8_ve1_189/> (''[[लोहित|lohita]]''). The Maitrayaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx9_ve1_189/> forbids the use of an arrow-shaft (''[[तेजन|tejana]]''), or of iron, but permits that of a stem of sugar-cane (''[[इक्षु|ikṣu]]-kāṇḍa'') or copper.<br>

अष्टा-दंष्ट्र वैरूप
<u>'''Aṣṭā-[[दंष्ट्र|daṃṣṭra]] Vairūpa.'''</u>--To him the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 9, 21) ascribes two Sāmans.<br>

अष्ट्रा
<u>'''Aṣṭrā'''</u> is the plougher's ‘goad,’ the badge of agriculture. It is mentioned several times in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_191/><br>

असमाति राथ-प्रौष्ठ
<u>'''Asamāti Rātha-prauṣṭha.'''</u>--The story of the quarrel between Asamāti, the [[इक्ष्वाकु|Ikṣvāku]] prince of the [[रथप्रोष्ठ|Rathaproṣṭha]] family, and  his priests, the Gaupāyanas, is found only in the later Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_192/> It appears to be based on a misreading of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_192/> where ''asamāti'' is merely an adjective. The later story is that the king was induced to abandon his family priests by two Asuras, [[किरात|Kirāta]] and [[आकुलि|Ākuli]], who by their magic compassed the death of [[सुबन्धु|Subandhu]], one of the brother priests, and that the others revived him by the use of the hymns (Rigveda, x. 57-60).<br>

असि
<u>'''Asi'''</u> usually denotes the sacrificial knife,<ref name=fx1_ve1_193/> but occasionally appears to mean a knife used in war.<ref name=fx2_ve1_193/> Mention is made of a sheath (''vavri'')<ref name=fx3_ve1_193/> to which a belt (''[[वाल|vāla]]'')<ref name=fx4_ve1_193/> was attached. The word ''asi-[[धारा|dhārā]]''<ref name=fx5_ve1_193/> also denotes ‘sheath.’<br>

असिक्नी
<u>'''Asiknī'''</u> (‘black’) is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_194/> of the river known later as [[चन्द्र|Candra]]-bhāgā, and to the Greeks as Akesines, now the Chenab in the Punjab.<br>

असित
<u>'''1. Asita'''</u> is a name of the ‘black snake,’ referred to in the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_195/><br>

असित
<u>'''2. Asita.'''</u>--(''a'') A mythical sage of this name figures as a magician in the Atharvaveda in conjunction with '''Gaya'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_196/> or with '''[[जमद्अग्नि|Jamadagni]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_196/> In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_196/> he appears as  [[असित|Asita]] [[धान्व|Dhānva]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_196/> and as [[दैवल|Daivala]] or [[देवल|Devala]] in the Pañcaviṃsa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_196/> and [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx6_ve1_196/><br><br>(''b'') '''[[असित|Asita]] [[वार्ष-गण|Vārṣa-gaṇa]]''' is a pupil of '''[[हरित कश्यप|Harita Kaśyapa]]''' according to the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] or Genealogy in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1b_ve1_196/><br>

असित-मृग
<u>'''Asita-mṛga'''</u> is the designation in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_197/> of a family of the '''Kaśyapas''' who were excluded from a sacrifice by '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]],''' but who took away the conduct of the offering from the '''Bhūtavīras,''' whom the king employed. In the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_197/> and the Ṣaḍviṃsa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_197/> the Asitamṛgas are called ‘sons of the Kaśyapas,’ and one is mentioned as '''Kusurubindu'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_197/> '''[[औद्दालकि|Auddālaki]].'''<br>

असुर-विद्या
<u>'''Asura-vidyā,'''</u> ‘the science of the Asuras,’ the term used in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] and Āśvalāyana<ref name=fx1_ve1_198/> Śrauta Sūtras as the equivalent of the term ''māyā'' employed in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_198/> clearly means ‘magic,’ as it is rendered by Professor Eggeling.<ref name=fx3_ve1_198/><br>

अस्तृ
<u>'''Astṛ,'''</u> ‘shooter,’ is a term frequently used in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_199/> and Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_199/> for the archer who fought from the chariot.<br>

अहन्
<u>'''Ahan,'''</u> ‘day.’ Like other peoples, the Indians used night as a general expression of time as well as day, but by no means predominantly.<ref name=fx1_ve1_200/> Night is also termed the dark (''[[कृष्ण|kṛṣṇa]]''), as  opposed to the light (''arjuna''), day.<ref name=fx2_ve1_200/> Aho-rātra<ref name=fx3_ve1_200/> is a regular term for ‘day and night’ combined.<br><br>The day itself is variously divided. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_200/> a division into ‘the rising sun’ (''udyan sūryaḥ''), ‘the coming together of the cows’ (''[[सं-गव|saṃ-gava]]''), ‘midday’ (''[[मध्यं-दिन|madhyaṃ-dina]]''), ‘afternoon’ (''aparāhṇa''), and ‘sunset’ (''astaṃ-yan'') is found. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_200/> the same series appears with ‘early’ (''[[प्रातर्|prātar]]'') and ‘evening’ (''sāyāhna'') substituted for the first and last members, while a shorter list gives ''[[प्रातर्|prātar]], [[संगव|saṃgava]], sāyam.'' In the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx6_ve1_200/> there is the series ‘dawn’ ''(uṣas), [[संगव|saṃgava]], [[मध्यंदिन|madhyaṃdina]],'' and ''aparāhṇa.''<br><br>The morning is also, according to Zimmer, called ''[[अपि-शर्वर|api-śarvara]],''<ref name=fx7_ve1_200/> as the time when the dark is just past. It is named ''[[स्वसर|svasara]],''<ref name=fx8_ve1_200/> as the time when the cows are feeding, before the first milking at the ''[[संगव|saṃgava]],'' or when the birds are awakening.<ref name=fx9_ve1_200/> It is also called ''[[प्र-पित्व|pra-pitva]],''<ref name=fx10_ve1_200/> according to Zimmer.<ref name=fx11_ve1_200/> But Geldner<ref name=fx12_ve1_200/> points out that that term refers to the late midday, which also is called ''[[अपि-शर्वर|api-śarvara]],'' as bordering on the coming night, being the time when day is hastening to its close, as in a race. From another point of view, evening is called ''[[अभि-पित्व|abhi-pitva]],''<ref name=fx13_ve1_200/> the time when all come to rest. Or again, morning and evening are denoted as the dawning of the sun (''uditā sūryasya''), or its setting (''[[नि-म्रुच्|ni-mruc]]''). The midday is regularly ''madhyam ahnām,''<ref name=fx14_ve1_200/> ''madhye,''<ref name=fx15_ve1_200/> or ''[[मध्यंदिन|madhyaṃdina]]. [[संगव|Saṃgava]]''<ref name=fx16_ve1_200/> is the forenoon, between the early morning (''[[प्रातर्|prātar]]'') and midday (''[[मध्यंदिन|madhyaṃdina]]'').<br><br>The divisions of time less than the day are seldom precisely given. In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx17_ve1_200/> however, a day and  night make up 30 ''muhūrtas;'' 1 ''[[मुहूर्त|muhūrta]]'' = 15 ''kṣipra;'' 1 ''kṣipra'' = 15 ''etarhi;'' 1 ''etarhi'' = 15 ''idāni;'' 1 ''idāni'' = 15 breathings; 1 breathing = 1 spiration; 1 spiration = 1 twinkling (''nimeṣa''), etc. In the Sāṅkhāyana Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx18_ve1_200/> the series is ''dhvaṃsayo, nimeṣāḥ, kāṣṭhāḥ, kalāḥ, kṣanā, muhūrtā, ahorātrāḥ.'' A thirtyfold division of day as well as of night is seen in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx19_ve1_200/> by Zimmer, who compares the Babylonian sixtyfold division of the day and night. But the expression used-thirty Yojanas--is too vague and obscure--Bergaigne<ref name=fx20_ve1_200/> refers it to the firmament--to build any theory upon with safety.<br><br>The longer divisions of time are regularly ‘half month’ (''ardha-[[मास|māsa]]''), ‘month’ (''[[मास|māsa]]''), ‘season’ (''[[ऋतु|ṛtu]]''), and ‘year’ (''[[संवत्सर|saṃvatsara]]''), which often<ref name=fx21_ve1_200/> occur in this sequence after ''ahorātrāṇi'' (‘days and nights’).<br>

अहल्या मैत्रेयी
<u>'''Ahalyā Maitreyī'''</u> is practically a mythical name, the existence of the lady whose story is alluded to in several Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_201/> being derived from the epithet of Indra, ‘lover of Ahalyā’ (''ahalyāyai [[जार|jāra]]'').<br>

अहि
<u>'''Ahi.'''</u>--This word occurs frequently from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_202/> onwards to denote ‘snake.’ Reference is several times<ref name=fx2_ve1_202/> made to its casting its slough. Mention is also made of the serpent's peculiar movement,<ref name=fx3_ve1_202/> which earns for it the designation<ref name=fx4_ve1_202/> of ‘the toothed rope’ (''datvatī rajjuḥ''). The poisonous character  of its bite is spoken of,<ref name=fx5_ve1_202/> as well as the torpidity of the reptile in winter, when it creeps into the earth.<ref name=fx6_ve1_202/> The cast skin is used as an amulet against highwaymen.<ref name=fx7_ve1_202/> Mention is made of a mythical horse, [[पैद्व|Paidva]], which the Aśvins gave to Pedu as a protection against snakes,<ref name=fx8_ve1_202/> and which is invoked as a destroyer of serpents.<ref name=fx9_ve1_202/> The ichneumon (''[[नकुल|nakula]]'') is regarded as their deadly enemy, and as immune against their poison through the use of a healing plant,<ref name=fx10_ve1_202/> while men kill them with sticks<ref name=fx11_ve1_202/> or strike off their heads.<ref name=fx12_ve1_202/><br><br>Many species of snakes are mentioned: see '''[[अघाश्व|Aghāśva]], [[अजगर|Ajagara]], [[असित|Asita]], [[कङ्कपर्वन्|Kaṅkaparvan]], [[करिक्रत|Karikrata]], [[कल्माषग्रीव|Kalmāṣagrīva]], [[कसर्णील|Kasarṇīla]], [[कुम्भीनस|Kumbhīnasa]], [[तिरश्चराजि|Tiraścarāji]], [[तैमात|Taimāta]], [[दर्वि|Darvi]], [[दशोनसि|Daśonasi]], [[पुष्करसाद|Puṣkarasāda]], [[पृदाकु|Pṛdāku]], [[लोहिताहि|Lohitāhi]], [[शर्कोट|Śarkoṭa]], [[श्वित्र|Śvitra]], [[सर्प|Sarpa]].'''<br>

अहीना आश्वत्थ्य
<u>'''Ahīnā Āśvatthya'''</u> was a sage (''muni'') who achieved immortality by knowledge of a certain rite (''sāvitram'').<ref name=fx1_ve1_203/><br>

आकुलि
<u>'''Ākuli.'''</u>--This mythical priest plays, together with '''[[किरात|Kirāta]],''' a part in the later tale of '''Asamāti''' and the '''Gaupāyanas.'''<br>

आक्ताक्ष्य
<u>'''Āktākṣya'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher who had peculiar views on the fire ritual (''agni-citi''), which are rejected in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_205/><br>

आ-क्रमण
<u>'''Ā-kramaṇa.'''</u>--In the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]^1 (i. 3) this word is used with the specific sense of ‘steps to climb trees.’ <br>

आखु
<u>'''Ākhu.'''</u>--The exact sense of this word is uncertain. Zimmer<ref name=fx1_ve1_207/> renders it ‘mole,’ while Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_207/> prefers ‘mouse’ or ‘rat.’ It is frequently mentioned in the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx3_ve1_207/> and is known to the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_207/> where, however, the word is regarded by Pischel<ref name=fx5_ve1_207/> as having acquired the secondary sense of ‘thief.’ This is denied by Hillebrandt.<ref name=fx6_ve1_207/><br>

आ-ख्यान
<u>'''Ā-khyāna.'''</u>--In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_208/> we hear of the Śaunaḥśepa [[आख्यान|Ākhyāna]], ‘the story of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]],'''’ which is told by the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest at the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]] (‘royal inauguration’). The series of stories<ref name=fx2_ve1_208/> used at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) during the year while the sacrificial horse is allowed to wander at its will is called the ‘cyclic’ (''pari-plavam''). The [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_208/> mentions also [[आख्यान|Ākhyāna]]-vids (‘men versed in tales’), who tell the Sauparṇa legend, elswhere<ref name=fx4_ve1_208/> known as a '''[[व्याख्यान|Vyākhyāna]].''' [[यास्क|Yāska]], in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_208/> frequently uses the term, sometimes in a pregnant sense as denoting the doctrine of the Aitihāsikas or traditional interpreters of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx6_ve1_208/><br>

आ-ख्यायिका
<u>'''Ā-khyāyikā.'''</u>--This word occurs apparently but once in the Vedic literature, in the late [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx1_ve1_209/> where its significance is doubtful.<br>

आगस्त्य
<u>'''Āgastya'''</u> appears as a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] (iii. 1, 1) and [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] (vii. 2) Āraṇyakas. <br>

आग्नि-वेशि शत्रि
<u>'''Āgni-veśi Śatri.'''</u>--A prince of this name appears to be referred to in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_211/><br>

आग्नि-वेश्य
<u>'''Āgni-veśya.'''</u>--Several teachers of this name are mentioned in the Vaṃśas or Genealogies of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]. In the Mādhyandina recension<ref name=fx1_ve1_212/> [[आग्निवेश्य|Āgniveśya]] is a pupil of '''[[सैतव|Saitava]].''' In the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension he is a pupil of '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]]''' and '''[[आनभिम्लात|Ānabhimlāta]]''' in one [[वंश|Vaṃśa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_212/> and of '''[[गार्ग्य|Gārgya]]''' in the second [[वंश|Vaṃśa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_212/><br>

आ-घाटि
<u>'''Ā-ghāṭi'''</u> is a musical instrument, the ‘cymbal,’ used to accompany dancing. It is known to the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_213/> and Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_213/><br>

आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Āṅgirasa'''</u> is a title denoting a claim to be of the family of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]],''' borne by many sages and teachers, like '''[[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]], [[आजीगर्ति|Ājīgarti]], [[च्यवन|Cyavana]], Ayāsya, [[संवर्त|Saṃvarta]], Sudhanvan,''' etc.<br>

आज-केशिन्
<u>'''Āja-keśin'''</u> is the name of a family in which, according to the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 9, 3), '''Baka''' used violence against Indra.<br>

आजनि
<u>'''Ājani.'''</u>--This word is used to denote a ‘goad’ in the Atharvaveda (iii. 25, 5).<br>

आजात-शत्रव
<u>'''Ājāta-śatrava.'''</u> See '''Bhadrasena.'''<br>

आजि
<u>'''Āji'''</u> is constantly used in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_218/> and the later literature to express the sense of ‘a race,’ and only seldom denotes ‘a battle.’ '''Horse'''-racing was one of the favourite amusements of the '''Vedic''' Indian,<ref name=fx2_ve1_218/> the other being dicing  ('''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]]'''). The racecourse, called [[काष्ठा|Kāṣṭhā]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_218/> or [[आजि|Āji]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_218/> itself, appears from the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_218/> to have been a quasi-circular one to a mark (''[[कार्ष्मन्|kārṣman]]''<ref name=fx6_ve1_218/> ) and back again. In the Rigveda the course is described as broad (''urvī'') and the distance as measured out (''apāvṛktā aratnayaḥ'').<ref name=fx7_ve1_218/> Prizes (''[[धन|dhana]]'') were offered (''dhā''),<ref name=fx8_ve1_218/> and eagerly competed for. Other words for victory and the prize are ''kāra''<ref name=fx9_ve1_218/> and ''bhara;''<ref name=fx10_ve1_218/> and to ‘run a race’ is described by the expressions ''ājim aj, i, dhāv, sṛ.''<ref name=fx11_ve1_218/> The person who instituted a race is referred to as ''[[आजि|āji]]-sṛt,''<ref name=fx12_ve1_218/> and Indra is called ''[[आजि|āji]]-kṛt''<ref name=fx13_ve1_218/> (‘race-maker’), and ''[[आजि|āji]]-pati''<ref name=fx14_ve1_218/> (‘lord of the race’).<br><br>The swift steeds (''[[वाजिन्|vājin]], atya'') used for the races were often washed and adorned.<ref name=fx15_ve1_218/> According to Pischel<ref name=fx16_ve1_218/> the name of one swift mare is preserved--viz., [[विश्पला|Viśpalā]],<ref name=fx17_ve1_218/> whose broken leg was replaced by the Aśvins in a race; but the interpretation is very doubtful. Geldner<ref name=fx18_ve1_218/> has also found a comic picture of a horse-chariot race in the [[मुद्गल|Mudgala]] hymn in the Rigveda, but Bloomfield<ref name=fx19_ve1_218/> has shown that that interpretation is unsound. Pischel<ref name=fx20_ve1_218/> also seeks to show that races were run in honour of gods, but the evidence for the theory is inadequate.<ref name=fx21_ve1_218/>  A formal race, however, is a feature of the ritual of the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]] or royal consecration.<ref name=fx22_ve1_218/><br>

आजीगर्ति
<u>'''Ājīgarti.'''</u>--See '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]],''' who bears this patronymic in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_219/> He is called an [[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]] in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve1_219/><br>

आज्य
<u>'''Ājya.'''</u> See '''[[घृत|Ghṛta]].'''<br>

आञ्जन
<u>'''Āñjana.'''</u>--A salve frequently referred to in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_221/> which came from Mount '''Trikakubh'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_221/> in the Himālaya, and was used to anoint the eyes.<ref name=fx3_ve1_221/> The region of the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_221/> is also given as a possible place of origin, and the ointment is declared as potent to remove jaundice, '''[[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]], [[जायान्य|Jāyānya]],''' and other diseases.<ref name=fx5_ve1_221/> A female ointment-maker is mentioned in the list of victims of the '''Puruṣamedha''' (‘human sacrifice’).<ref name=fx6_ve1_221/><br>

आटिकी
<u>'''Āṭikī'''</u> is the name of the wife of '''Uṣasti''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 10, 1).<br>

अट्णार
<u>'''Aṭṇāra.'''</u>--Patronymic of '''Para.'''<br>

आडम्बर
<u>'''Āḍambara'''</u> was a kind of ‘drum.’ A ‘drummer’ (''āḍambarāghāta'') is mentioned in the list of victims at the [[पुरुष|Puruṣa]]-[[मेध|medha]] (‘human sacrifice’) in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_224/> <br>

आणि
<u>'''Āṇi.'''</u>--This word, which is found in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_225/> but rarely later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_225/> appears to be best taken with Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_225/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve1_225/> as denoting the part of the axle of the chariot which is inserted into the nave of the wheel. Sāyaṇa renders it as lynch-pin, and this sense is accepted by Leumann,<ref name=fx5_ve1_225/> being apparently also found in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx6_ve1_225/> In one place in the Rigveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_225/> the word appears by synecdoche to denote the whole chariot, but the passage is, according to Geldner,<ref name=fx8_ve1_225/> completely obscure.<br>

आण्डीक
<u>'''Āṇḍīka'''</u> (‘bearing eggs’) is a term found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_226/> denoting an edible plant, apparently with fruit or leaves of egg shape (''āṇḍa''), akin to the lotus.<br>

आता
<u>'''Ātā.'''</u>--The framework of the door of a house appears to be denoted by the plural of this word in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_227/> (though in all passages there it is used only by synecdoche of the doors of the sky), and in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve1_227/> Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_227/> compares the Latin ''antae,'' to which the word etymologically corresponds.<ref name=fx4_ve1_227/><br>

आति
<u>'''Āti,'''</u> an aquatic bird. The Apsarases in the legend of [[पुरूरवस्|Purūravas]] and Urvaśī appear to him like Ātis, probably swans.<ref name=fx1_ve1_228/> The birds appear also in the list of animals in the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’),<ref name=fx2_ve1_228/> where Mahīdhara<ref name=fx3_ve1_228/> renders them as the  later Āḍī (''Turdus ginginianus''), and Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx4_ve1_228/> quotes a view, according to which the [[आति|Āti]] was the [[चाष|Cāṣa]], or blue jay (''Coracias indica'').<br>

आतिथि-ग्व
<u>'''Ātithi-gva.'''</u>--Patronymic of '''[[इन्द्रोत|Indrota]].'''<br>

आत्रेय
<u>'''Ātreya'''</u> is the patronymic of a pupil of [[माण्टि|Māṇṭi]] in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_230/> An [[आत्रेय|Ātreya]] appears as a [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of '''[[अङ्ग|Aṅga]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_230/> An [[आत्रेय|Ātreya]] was regularly the priest in certain rites,<ref name=fx3_ve1_230/> and an Ātreyī occurs in an obscure passage in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_230/><br>

आत्रेयी-पुत्र
<u>'''Ātreyī-putra'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[गौतमीपुत्र|Gautamīputra]]''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]], or Genealogy, in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 2, in both versions).<br>

आथर्वण
<u>'''Ātharvaṇa,'''</u> a patronymic formed from the name of the mythic [[अथर्वन्|Atharvan]], is found normally in the plural neuter as a designation of the hymns of the Atharvans. This use appears in the late nineteenth book of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_232/> and in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_232/> In the singular the expression [[आथर्वण|Ātharvaṇa]] (Veda), though not occurring till the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_232/> is earlier than the term ‘Atharvaveda,’ which is first found in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx4_ve1_232/> In the [[निदान|Nidāna]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_232/> Ātharvaṇikas, or ‘followers of the Atharvaveda,’ appear.<br><br>Specific but mainly mythical Ātharvaṇas are '''Kabandha, [[बृहद्दिव|Bṛhaddiva]], [[भिषज्|Bhiṣaj]], Dadhyaṅc,''' and '''Vicārin.''' <br>

आ-दर्श
<u>'''Ā-darśa,'''</u> ‘mirror,’ is a term found only in the Upaniṣads<ref name=fx1_ve1_233/> and Āraṇyakas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_233/><br>

आदार
<u>'''Ādāra'''</u> was a kind of plant which was prescribed as a substitute for '''Soma.'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_234/> It is identified in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_234/> with '''[[पूतीक|Pūtīka]].'''<br>

आनन्द-ज चान्धनायन
<u>'''Ānanda-ja Cāndhanāyana'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[शाम्ब|Śāmba]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_235/><br>

आनभि-म्लात
<u>'''Ānabhi-mlāta'''</u> is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]], or Genealogy, in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_236/> as a pupil of [[आनभिम्लात|Ānabhimlāta]].<br>

आनव
<u>'''Ānava.'''</u> See '''Anu.'''<br>

आनूक
<u>'''Ānūka.'''</u>--Geldner<ref name=fx1_ve1_238/> thinks that in its solitary occurrence in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_238/> this word means an ornament. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_238/> takes it adverbially, and so do Ludwig and Oldenberg.<br>

आपया
<u>'''Āpayā'''</u> is the name of a river mentioned once only in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_239/> when it occurs between the '''[[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]]''' and the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].''' Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_239/> was inclined to identify it with the Āpagā as a name for the Ganges, but Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_239/> correctly places it near the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]], either as the small tributary which flows past Thānesar or the modern Indramatī farther west, while Pischel<ref name=fx4_ve1_239/> assigns it to '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]],''' of which the [[आपया|Āpayā]] is mentioned as a famous river in the Mahābhārata.<ref name=fx5_ve1_239/> <br>

आबयु
<u>'''Ābayu'''</u> is apparently the name of a plant in the Atharvaveda;<ref name=fx1_ve1_240/> the mustard plant<ref name=fx2_ve1_240/> may have been meant, but the sense is quite uncertain.<ref name=fx3_ve1_240/><br>

आभि-प्रतारिण
<u>'''Ābhi-pratāriṇa.'''</u>--Patronymic of '''Vṛddhadyumna.'''<br>

आ भूति त्वाष्ट्र
<u>'''Ā [[भूति|bhūti]] Tvāṣṭra'''</u> is mentioned in two Vaṃśas, or Genealogies, of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_242/> as a pupil of '''Viśvarūpa [[त्वाष्ट्र|Tvāṣṭra]],''' both teachers being no doubt equally mythical.<br>

आमलक
<u>'''Āmalaka'''</u> (neuter), a common word later, is found in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vii. 3, 1), denoting the Myrobalan fruit. ''Cf.'' '''[[अमला|Amalā]].'''<br>

आमिक्षा
<u>'''Āmikṣā'''</u> designates a mess of clotted curds. It is not known to the Rigveda, but occurs in all the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_244/> Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve1_244/> etc., and is associated with the [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx3_ve1_244/><br>

आम्ब
<u>'''Āmba'''</u> denotes in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_245/> and [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_245/> Saṃhitās a grain, called '''[[नाम्ब|Nāmba]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_245/><br>

आम्बष्ठ्य
<u>'''Āmbaṣṭhya'''</u> is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 21) as a king, whose priest for the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]], or royal inauguration, was '''[[नारद|Nārada]].''' Presumably the name is local, meaning ‘King of  the Ambaṣṭhas,’ as interpreted in the St. Petersburg Dictionary. Later the term [[अम्बष्ठ|Ambaṣṭha]] denotes ‘a man of mingled [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] and [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] parentage by father and mother’ respectively.<br>

आ-यतन
<u>'''Ā-yatana.'''</u>--The general sense of ‘abode’ or ‘home’ appears to be limited in one passage of the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vii. 24, 2) to the sense of ‘holy place,’ ‘sanctuary,’ which is found in the epic.<br>

आयवस
<u>'''Āyavasa'''</u> is mentioned apparently as a king in a corrupt and unintelligible verse of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_248/><br>

आयु
<u>'''Āyu'''</u> appears in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_249/> with '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]]''' and '''[[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]]''' as having been defeated, with Indra's aid, by '''[[तूर्वयाण|Tūrvayāṇa]],''' who is believed by Pischel<ref name=fx2_ve1_249/> to have been King of the '''Pakthas.''' Possibly he is elsewhere<ref name=fx3_ve1_249/> referred to as victorious, by Indra's aid, over '''[[वेश|Veśa]].''' Elsewhere he is quite mythical.<ref name=fx4_ve1_249/><br>

आयुत
<u>'''Āyuta.'''</u> See '''[[घृत|Ghṛta]].'''<br>

आ-युध
<u>'''Ā-yudha,'''</u> ‘weapon,’ in its widest sense covers the whole of a Kṣatriya's warlike equipment, which in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_251/> is summed up as horse-chariot (''[[अश्व|aśva]]-[[रथ|ratha]]''), bow and arrows (''[[इषु|iṣu]]-dhanva''), and corselet (''[[कवच|kavaca]]''). As the bow and arrow (''[[इषु|iṣu]], [[धन्वन्|dhanvan]]'') were essential as the main weapons of the Vedic fighter, they are probably meant when [[आयुध|Āyudha]] is used specifically of weapons, as often from the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_251/> onwards. The battle hymn in the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_251/> confirms this view, as it presents to us the warrior armed with bow and arrow on his chariot, and clad in armour ('''[[वर्मन्|Varman]]'''), with a guard ('''[[हस्तघ्न|Hastaghna]]''') on the left arm to avoid the friction of the bow-string. The corselet was not a single solid piece of metal, but consisted of many pieces fitted together (''syūta'');<ref name=fx4_ve1_251/> it may  have been made either of metal plates or, as is more likely, of some stiff material plated with metal. In addition the warrior wore a helmet ('''[[शिप्रा|Śiprā]]'''). There is no trace of the use of a shield, nor is there any clear record of the employment of greaves or other guard for the feet.<ref name=fx5_ve1_251/> Skill in the use of weapons is referred to in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx6_ve1_251/><br><br>It is doubtful whether sling stones ('''Adri, [[अशनि|Aśani]]''') were in ordinary use. The hook (''aṅkuśa'')<ref name=fx7_ve1_251/> also is merely a divine weapon, and the axe (''[[स्वधिति|svadhiti]],''<ref name=fx8_ve1_251/> ''[[वाशी|vāśī]], [[परशु|paraśu]]'') does not occur in mortal combats. For the use of the spear see '''[[ऋष्टि|Ṛṣṭi]], [[रम्भिणी|Rambhiṇī]], [[शक्ति|Śakti]], [[शरु|Śaru]];''' of the sword, '''Asi, [[कृति|Kṛti]].''' Neither weapon can be considered ordinary in warfare, nor was the club ('''[[वज्र|Vajra]]''') used. For the modes of warfare see '''[[संग्राम|Saṃgrāma]].'''<br>

आयोगव
<u>'''Āyogava.--Marutta Āvi-kṣita,'''</u> the [[आयोगव|Āyogava]] king, is mentioned as a sacrificer in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_252/> where also a [[गाथा|Gāthā]] (‘stanza’) celebrating his sacrifice is cited. ''Cf.'' '''[[अयोगू|Ayogū]].'''<br>

आरङ्गर
<u>'''Āraṅgara'''</u> is one of the names of the bee found in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_253/> Other names are '''[[सरह्|Sarah]]''' and '''[[भृङ्गा|Bhṛṅgā]].'''<br>

आरा
<u>'''Ārā,'''</u> a word later<ref name=fx1_ve1_254/> known as an ‘awl’ or ‘gimlet,’ occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_254/> only to designate a weapon of Pūṣan, with whose pastoral character its later use for piercing leather is consistent. ''Cf.'' '''[[वाशी|Vāśī]].'''<br>

आराढि
<u>'''Ārāḍhi.'''</u>--Patronymic of '''Saujāta.''' ''Cf.'' '''Arāḍa.''' <br>

आरुण औप-वेशि
<u>'''Āruṇa Aupa-veśi.'''</u>--So the manuscripts let us read the former word in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā, but this is doubtless an error for '''Aruṇa.'''<br>

आरुणि
<u>'''Āruṇi'''</u> is the patronymic normally referring to '''Uddālaka,''' son of '''Aruṇa [[औपवेशि|Aupaveśi]].''' Uddālaka is probably also meant by [[आरुणि|Āruṇi]] Yaśasvin, who occurs as a teacher of the Subrahmaṇyā (a kind of recitation) in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_257/> Āruṇis are referred to both in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_257/> and in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_257/> as well as in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx4_ve1_257/><br>

आरुणेय
<u>'''Āruṇeya.'''</u>--An epithet of '''[[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]],''' indicating his descent from '''[[उद्दालक आरुणि|Uddālaka Āruṇi]]''' and '''Aruṇa [[औपवेशि|Aupaveśi]].''' It is apparently confined to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_258/> and Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_258/> in which [[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]] plays a great part.<br>

आर्क्ष
<u>'''Ārkṣa.'''</u>--Patronymic of '''Śrutarvan''' and of '''Āśvamedha.'''<br>

आर्जीक
<u>'''Ārjīka'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_260/> and '''Ārjīkīya'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_260/> (masc.), '''Ārjīkīyā'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_260/> (fem.).--The two masculine forms probably denote the people or land, while the feminine word designates the river of the land. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx4_ve1_260/> locates the country in or near Kaśmir, as Arrian<ref name=fx5_ve1_260/> mentions Arsaces, brother of Abhisares, who presumably took his name from his people, and Abhisāra bordered on Kaśmir. Pischel<ref name=fx6_ve1_260/> accepts [[आर्जीक|Ārjīka]] as designating a country, which he, however, thinks cannot be identified. But neither Roth<ref name=fx7_ve1_260/> nor Zimmer<ref name=fx8_ve1_260/> recognizes the word as a proper name. On the other hand, all authorities agree in regarding Ārjīkīyā as the name of a  river. '''Roth'''<ref name=fx9_ve1_260/> does so in one passage<ref name=fx10_ve1_260/> only, elsewhere seeing references to Soma vessels; but it seems necessary to treat the word alike in all passages containing it. Zimmer does not locate the river, and Pischel denies the possibility of its identification. Hillebrandt thinks it may have been the Upper Indus, or the '''[[वितस्ता|Vitastā]]''' (the Jhelum), or some other stream. Grassmann follows [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx11_ve1_260/> in identifying it with the the '''[[विपाश्|Vipāś]]''' (Beäs), but this is rendered improbable by the position of the name in the hymn in praise of rivers (''nadīstuti'').<ref name=fx12_ve1_260/> Brunnhofer<ref name=fx13_ve1_260/> identifies it with the Arghesan, a tributary of the Arghanab.<br>

आर्जुनेय
<u>'''Ārjuneya.'''</u>--In the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_261/> this name occurs as the patronymic of '''[[कौत्स|Kautsa]].'''<br>

आर्तभागी-पुत्र
<u>'''Ārtabhāgī-putra'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[शौङ्गी-पुत्र|Śauṅgī-putra]]''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] or Genealogy in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_262/> Ārtabhāga is a patronymic of Jaratkārava in the same [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_262/><br>

आर्तव
<u>'''Ārtava.'''</u>--This expression denotes a portion of the year consisting of more seasons than one. But it does not bear the exact sense of ‘half-year,’ as suggested by Zimmer.<ref name=fx1_ve1_263/> This is shown by the fact that it occurs regularly in the plural, not in the dual. In the Atharvaveda it occurs between seasons and years (''[[हायन|hāyana]]''),<ref name=fx2_ve1_263/> but also in the combinations, ‘seasons, Ārtavas, months, years,;<ref name=fx3_ve1_263/> ‘half-months, months, Ārtavas, seasons’;<ref name=fx4_ve1_263/>  ‘seasons, Ārtavas, months, half-months, days and nights, day’;<ref name=fx5_ve1_263/> and in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā ‘months, seasons, Ārtavas, the year,’<ref name=fx6_ve1_263/> or simply with the seasons.<ref name=fx7_ve1_263/><br>

आर्त्नी
<u>'''Ārtnī'''</u> denotes the end of the bow to which the bow-string (''[[ज्या|jyā]]'') was attached.<ref name=fx1_ve1_264/> The string was not normally kept fastened to both ends of the bow, but when an arrow was to be shot it was strung taut.<ref name=fx2_ve1_264/> On the other hand, the legend of the death of Viṣṇu, told in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx3_ve1_264/> and Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx4_ve1_264/> expressly contemplates his leaning on his strung bow, which cleaves his head by the sudden springing apart of the two ends when the bow-string is gnawed through.<br>

आर्य
<u>'''Ārya'''</u> is the normal designation in the Vedic literature from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_265/> onwards of an Āryan, a member of the three upper classes, '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]],''' or '''[[वैश्य|Vaiśya]],''' as the formal division is given in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_265/> The [[आर्य|Ārya]] stands in opposition to the '''[[दास|Dāsa]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_265/> but also to the '''[[शूद्र|Śūdra]].''' Sometimes<ref name=fx4_ve1_265/> the expression is restricted to the [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] caste,  the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] and the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] receiving special designations; but this use is not common, and it is often uncertain also whether '''Arya''' is not meant. The phrase Śūdrāryau<ref name=fx5_ve1_265/> is especially ambiguous, but appears to have denoted originally the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] and the Āryan, for in the Mahāvrata ceremony the fight between a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] and an [[आर्य|Ārya]] is represented in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] as one between a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] and a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]], though the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] treats it as a fight between a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] and a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]].<br><br>The word [[आर्य|Ārya]] (fem. Āryā or Ārī) also occurs frequently used as an adjective to describe the Āryan classes (''viśaḥ''),<ref name=fx6_ve1_265/> or name (''[[नामन्|nāman]]''),<ref name=fx7_ve1_265/> or caste (''[[वर्ण|varṇa]]''),<ref name=fx8_ve1_265/> or dwellings (''[[धामन्|dhāman]]'');<ref name=fx9_ve1_265/> or again reference is made to the Āryan supremacy (''[[व्रत|vrata]]'')<ref name=fx10_ve1_265/> being extended over the land. Āryan foes (''vṛtra'')<ref name=fx11_ve1_265/> are referred to beside [[दास|Dāsa]] foes, and there are many<ref name=fx12_ve1_265/> references to war of Āryan versus Āryan, as well as to war of Āryan against [[दास|Dāsa]]. From this it can be fairly deduced that even by the time of the Rigveda the Āryan communities had advanced far beyond the stage of simple conquest of the aborigines. In the later Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas the wars alluded to seem mainly Āryan wars, no doubt in consequence of the fusion of [[आर्य|Ārya]] and [[दास|Dāsa]] into one community.<br><br>Weber<ref name=fx13_ve1_265/> considers that the five peoples known to the Rigveda were the Āryans and the four peoples of the quarters (''[[दिश्|diś]]'') of the earth, but this is doubtful. Āryan speech (''[[वाच्|vāc]]'')<ref name=fx14_ve1_265/> is specially referred to in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] and [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyakas. <br>

आर्य
<u>'''Ārya.'''</u> See '''[[माल्य|Mālya]].'''<br>

अर्ष्टि-षेण
<u>'''Arṣṭi-ṣeṇa.'''</u>--Patronymic of '''Devāpi.'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_267/><br>

आल
<u>'''Āla'''</u> appears to mean ‘weed’ in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_268/> and to form part of three other words,<ref name=fx2_ve1_268/> denoting, according to Sāyaṇa, grass-creepers (''[[सस्य|sasya]]-vallī'')--viz., [[अलसाला|Alasālā]], Silañjālā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_268/> and [[नीलागलसाल|Nīlāgalasāla]]. Whitney,<ref name=fx4_ve1_268/> however, does not think that the words can be given any determinate sense.<br>

आलम्बायनी-पुत्र
<u>'''Ālambāyanī-putra'''</u> is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] or Genealogy of the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 2) as a pupil of '''[[आलम्बी-पुत्र|Ālambī-putra]].''' In the Mādhyandina recension (vi. 4, 32) the relation is reversed, for there he is teacher of [[आलम्बी-पुत्र|Ālambī-putra]] and pupil of '''[[जायन्ती-पुत्र|Jāyantī-putra]].'''<br>

आलम्बी-पुत्र
<u>'''Ālambī-putra'''</u> is a pupil of '''[[जायन्ती-पुत्र|Jāyantī-putra]]''' according to a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 2), but of '''[[आलम्बायनी-पुत्र|Ālambāyanī-putra]]''' according to the Mādhyandina (vi. 4, 32).<br>

आलिगी
<u>'''Āligī'''</u> is the name of a kind of serpent in the Atharvaveda (v. 13, 7). ''Cf.'' '''[[विलिगी|Viligī]].'''<br>

आ-वसथ
<u>'''Ā-vasatha'''</u> (‘dwelling’).--The precise sense<ref name=fx1_ve1_272/> of this term appears to be a place for the reception of guests, especially Brāhmaṇas and others on the occasion of feasts and sacrifices (somewhat like the modern meaning of [[धर्म|Dharma]]-[[शाला|śālā]] as a resthouse for pilgrims), a use derived from the more general sense of ‘abode.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_272/> <br>

आविक
<u>'''Āvika'''</u> (‘coming from the sheep,’ ''avi'') is a term for ‘wool,’ which occurs first in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 3, 6). ''Cf.'' '''Avi.'''<br>

अवि-क्षित
<u>'''Avi-kṣita.'''</u>--Patronymic of '''Marutta,'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_274/> the '''[[आयोगव|Āyogava]].'''<br>

आ-शरीक
<u>'''Ā-śarīka'''</u> appears to denote a disease in a hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_275/> celebrating the powers of the '''Jaṅgida''' plant. Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_275/> thinks that it merely denotes the pain in the limbs accompanying fever. Whitney<ref name=fx3_ve1_275/> suggests taking the word as merely an epithet.<br>

आ-शिर्
<u>'''Ā-śir'''</u> (‘admixture’) denotes the mixing, and more especially the milk mixed with the juice, of the Soma before it was offered to the gods. In this sense it is not rare from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_276/> onwards. Not milk alone was employed for this purpose. The epithet ‘having three admixtures’ applied to Soma<ref name=fx2_ve1_276/> is explained by the other epithets, ‘mixed with milk’ (''[[गवाशिर्|gavāśir]]''), ‘mixed with curds’ (''[[दध्य्-आशिर्|dadhy-āśir]]''), and ‘mixed with grain’ (''[[यवाशिर्|yavāśir]]'')--all referring to Soma.<br>

आशी-विष
<u>'''Āśī-viṣa,'''</u> occurring only in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_277/> is understood by Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_277/> as designating a particular kind of snake, and perhaps means ‘having poison (''[[विष|viṣa]]'') in its fangs’ (''āśī'').<br>

आशु
<u>'''Āśu,'''</u> the ‘swift,’ is frequently used without '''[[अश्व|Aśva]]''' to denote the chariot steed from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_278/> onwards. <br>

आशुं-ग
<u>'''Āśuṃ-ga'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_279/> seems to denote some sort of animal. It is qualified by the word ‘young’ (''[[शिशुक|śiśuka]]''), and Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_279/> suggests that it may mean a bird (‘swift-flying’), or that the expression denotes ‘a foal going to its dam’ (''[[आशु|āśu]]-ga''). Sāyaṇa, however, reads the accompanying word as ''[[शुशुक|śuśuka]],'' which he assumes to denote an animal. Bloomfield<ref name=fx3_ve1_279/> renders the two words ‘a swift (''[[आशुंग|āśuṃga]]'') foal (''[[शिशुक|śiśuka]]''),’ thus agreeing with one of Roth's suggestions in sense, though not in the explanation of Aśuṃga.<br>

आ-श्रम
<u>'''Ā-śrama'''</u> (‘resting-place’) does not occur in any [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] which can be regarded as pre-Buddhistic. Its earliest use as denoting the stages of a Hindu's life is found in the Śvetāśvatara [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_280/> In one passage<ref name=fx2_ve1_280/> of the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] reference is made only to the '''Brahmacārin''' and householder, to whom, as a reward for study, the procreation of children, the practice of Yoga, abstention from injury to living creatures, and sacrifices, freedom from transmigration are promised. In another place<ref name=fx3_ve1_280/> three states are contemplated, but not as consecutive. The Brahmacārin may either become a householder or become an anchorite, or remain in his teacher's house all his life. Similarly, reference<ref name=fx4_ve1_280/> is made to the death of the anchorite in the forest, or the sacrifice in the village. In contrast with all three<ref name=fx5_ve1_280/> is the man who stands fast in [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] (Brahmasaṃstha). In the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_280/> the knower of the Ātman is contrasted with those who (1) study, or (2) sacrifice and give alms, or (3) are anchorites, and in another place<ref name=fx7_ve1_280/> with those who sacrifice and make benefactions, and those who practice asceticism. This position of superiority to, and distinction from, the Āśramas became later a fourth<ref name=fx8_ve1_280/> [[आश्रम|Āśrama]],  the '''Gṛhastha,''' or householder, who was in the second stage, being required to pass not only into the stage of '''Vānaprastha,''' but also that of the Sannyāsin ('''[[भिक्षु|Bhikṣu]], [[परिव्राजक|Parivrājaka]]'''). The first stage, that of the '''Brahmacārin,''' was still obligatory, but was no longer allowed to remain a permanent one, as was originally possible.<br><br>''Cf.'' Deussen, ''Philosophy of the Upanishads,'' 60, 367 ''et seq.''<br>

आ-श्रेषा
<u>'''Ā-śreṣā, Ā-śleṣā.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

आश्व-घ्न
<u>'''Āśva-ghna.'''</u>--This name occurs in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_282/> in a very obscure hymn, where it appears to denote a prince who had made offerings to Indra, and who may, as Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_282/> thinks, have been called '''Vitaraṇa.'''<br>

अश्वतर आश्वि
<u>'''Aśvatara Āśvi,'''</u> or '''Āśvatarāśvi.'''--These two expressions are used<ref name=fx1_ve1_283/> as patronymics of '''Buḍila,''' denoting, according to Sāyaṇa,<ref name=fx2_ve1_283/> that he was son of [[अश्व|Aśva]], and descendant of [[अश्वतर|Aśvatara]].<br>

अश्व-त्थ्य
<u>'''Aśva-tthya.'''</u>--Patronymic of Ahīnā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_284/><br>

अश्व-मेध
<u>'''Aśva-medha'''</u> is the patronymic of an unnamed prince, who occurs in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) in the Rigveda (viii. 68, 15. 16).<br>

आश्व-वाल
<u>'''Āśva-vāla.'''</u>--From this adjective (‘made of horse-tail grass’), applied to a strew (''[[प्रस्तर|prastara]]'') in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 4, 1, 17; 6, 3, 10), follows the existence of the Aśvavāla grass (''Saccharum spontaneum'').<br>

आश्व-सूक्ति
<u>'''Āśva-sūkti'''</u> is mentioned in [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xix. 4, 2, ''et seq.'') as an author of Sāmans (Soma chants) along with '''Gausūkti.''' <br>

आश्विन
<u>'''Āśvina,'''</u> or '''Āśvīna,''' designates, in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_288/> and two Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve1_288/> the length of journey made in a day by a horseman (''aśvin''). The exact distance is not defined. In the Atharva it appears to exceed five leagues, being mentioned immediately after a distance of three or five '''Yojanas;''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] the heavenly world is placed at a distance of a thousand '''Āśvinas.'''<br>

आषाधि सौश्रोमतेय
<u>'''Āṣādhi Sauśromateya.'''</u>--According to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_289/> he was ruined because the heads were put on at the Agniciti in a certain manner, and not correctly.<br>

आष्ट्रा
<u>'''Āṣṭrā'''</u> seems in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xxxvii. 1) to denote the ploughman's goad.<br>

आष्ट्री
<u>'''Āṣṭrī.'''</u>--In the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_291/> the word seems to denote a fireplace. The evil bird is entreated not to settle there on the hearth.<br>

आसङ्ग प्लायोगि
<u>'''Āsaṅga Plāyogi'''</u> is a king who appears in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_292/> as a generous patron. Owing, however, to the addition of a curious phallic verse to the hymn, and its early misunderstanding,<ref name=fx2_ve1_292/> a legend was invented that he lost his manhood and became a woman, but by the intercession of '''[[मेध्यातिथि|Medhyātithi]]''' was transformed into a man, much to the delight of his wife, '''[[शश्वती|Śaśvatī]],''' whose existence is based on a misunderstanding of the phrase ‘every woman’ (''[[शश्वती|śaśvatī]] [[नारी|nārī]]'') in the added verse.<ref name=fx3_ve1_292/> Another misunderstanding  of the Dānastuti<ref name=fx4_ve1_292/> gives him a son [[स्वनद्-रथ|Svanad-ratha]], really a mere epithet, and makes him a descendant of Yadu.<br>

आ-सन्दी
<u>'''Ā-sandī.'''</u>--This is a generic term for a seat of some sort, occurring frequently in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_293/> and Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_293/> but not in the Rigveda. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_293/> the settle brought for the '''[[व्रात्य|Vrātya]]''' is described at length. It had two feet, lengths wise and cross-pieces, forward and cross-cords, showing that it was made of wood and also cording. It was also covered with a cushion ('''[[आस्तरण|Āstaraṇa]]''') and a pillow ('''[[उपबर्हण|Upabarhaṇa]]'''), had a seat ('''[[आसाद|Āsāda]]''') and a support ('''Upaśraya'''). Similar seats are described in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_293/> and the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_293/> The seat for the king at the royal consecration is described in very similar terms in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx6_ve1_293/> where the height of the feet is placed at a span, and the lengthwise and cross-pieces are each to be a cubit, while the interwoven part (''[[विवयन|vivayana]]'') is to be of [[मुञ्ज|Muñja]] grass, and the seat of [[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]] wood. In another passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_293/> Lanman seems to take the seat meant as a ‘long reclining chair.’ There also a cushion ('''[[उपधान|Upadhāna]]''') and coverlet ('''Upavāsana''') are mentioned. The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] repeatedly describes the [[आसन्दी|Āsandī]] in terms showing that it was an elaborate seat. In one place<ref name=fx8_ve1_293/> it is said to be made of [[खदिर|Khadira]] wood, perforated (''vi-tṛṇṇā''), and joined with straps (''[[वर्ध्र|vardhra]]-yutā'') like that of the Bhāratas. At the [[सौत्रामणी|Sautrāmaṇī]] rite<ref name=fx9_ve1_293/> (an Indra sacrifice) the seat is of [[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]] wood, is knee-high, and of unlimited width and depth, and is covered with plaited reed-work. The  imperial seat<ref name=fx10_ve1_293/> is to be shoulder-high, of [[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]] wood, and wound all over with cords of Balvaja grass (''Eleusina indica''). Elsewhere<ref name=fx11_ve1_293/> the seat is a span high, a cubit in width and depth, of [[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]] wood, and covered with reed-grass cords, and daubed with clay.<br>

आसन्दी-वन्त्
<u>'''Āsandī-vant,'''</u> ‘possessing the throne,’ is the title of the royal city of '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]] [[पारिक्षित|Pārikṣita]],''' in which the horse, for his famous [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], was bound. The authorities both cite a [[गाथा|Gāthā]] for the fact, but they differ as to the priest who celebrated the rite. In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_294/> he is stated to have been [[इन्द्रोत दैवाप शौनक|Indrota <a class="pada_vei" href="दैवाप">Daivāpa]] Śaunaka», but in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_294/> '''[[तुर कावषेय|Tura Kāvaṣeya]].'''<br>

आ-साद
<u>'''Ā-sāda,'''</u> ‘seat,’ occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_295/> as a description of part of the settle ('''[[आसन्दी|Āsandī]]''') of the '''[[व्रात्य|Vrātya]].''' It seems best to regard it with Whitney<ref name=fx2_ve1_295/> as the seat proper; Aufrecht,<ref name=fx3_ve1_295/> Zimmer,<ref name=fx4_ve1_295/> and Roth<ref name=fx5_ve1_295/> render it as the ‘cushion for the seat,’ but that is sufficiently described by the word '''[[आस्तरण|Āstaraṇa]].'''<br>

आसुरायण
<u>'''Āsurāyaṇa'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[त्रैवणि|Traivaṇi]]''' in the first two Vaṃśas<ref name=fx1_ve1_296/> (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] in both recensions, but as a pupil of '''[[आसुरि|Āsuri]]''' in the third [[वंश|Vaṃśa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_296/><br>

आसुरि
<u>'''Āsuri'''</u> occurs in the first two Vaṃśas<ref name=fx1_ve1_297/> (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] as a pupil of '''[[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]]''' and teacher of '''[[औपजन्धनि|Aupajandhani]],''' but in the third<ref name=fx2_ve1_297/> as a pupil of '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]]''' and teacher of '''[[आसुरायण|Āsurāyaṇa]].''' He appears as a  ritual authority in the first four books of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_297/> and as an authority on dogmatic, specially noted for his insistence on truth, in the last book.<ref name=fx4_ve1_297/><br>

आसुरि-वासिन्
<u>'''Āsuri-vāsin'''</u> is a name of '''[[प्राश्नी-पुत्र|Prāśnī-putra]]''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 2, in both recensions).<br>

आ-सेचन
<u>'''Ā-secana'''</u> designates a vessel to hold liquids, such as meat juice (''[[यूषन्|yūṣan]]'')<ref name=fx1_ve1_299/> or ghee.<ref name=fx2_ve1_299/> Of its shape and make we know nothing.<br>

आ-स्तरण
<u>'''Ā-staraṇa'''</u> denotes the coverlet of the settle ('''[[आसन्दी|Āsandī]]''') of the '''[[व्रात्य|Vrātya]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_300/> A tiger's skin serves as the coverlet of the king's seat in the royal consecration ([[राजसूय|Rājasūya]]).<ref name=fx2_ve1_300/> In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_300/> the word used is '''[[उपस्तरण|Upastaraṇa]].'''<br>

आस्त्र-बुध्न
<u>'''Āstra-budhna'''</u> is the name of a man whom Indra is said in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_301/> to have assisted. It is not clear whether '''Venya,''' who is mentioned in the same line, was his friend<ref name=fx2_ve1_301/> or his enemy,<ref name=fx3_ve1_301/> whom Indra saved or defeated for him.<br>

आ-स्थातृ
<u>'''Ā-sthātṛ.'''</u>--The warrior in the chariot is once thus designated (as ‘standing on the car’) in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_302/> Normally he is named '''[[रथिन्|Rathin]]''' or '''[[रथेष्ठा|Ratheṣṭhā]].''' <br>

आ-स्राव
<u>'''Ā-srāva'''</u> (‘discharge’) denotes a disease, thrice referred to in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_303/> the precise nature of which is uncertain. The Scholiast<ref name=fx2_ve1_303/> in one place interprets it as painful urination (''mūtrātisāra''), while Lanman<ref name=fx3_ve1_303/> suggests diabetes. Bloomfield<ref name=fx4_ve1_303/> takes it to be diarrhœa, and Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve1_303/> argues that as the remedy is called ‘wound healer’ (''arus-srāṇa''), the sense is ‘the flux from unhealed wounds.’ Whitney<ref name=fx6_ve1_303/> renders it ‘flux,’ and questions Bloomfield's rendering. Ludwig<ref name=fx7_ve1_303/> translates it vaguely by ‘sickness’ and ‘cold.’<br>

आहनस्या
<u>'''Āhanasyā'''</u> (‘unchaste’).--This word in the plural (‘lascivious verses’) denotes a section (xx. 136) of the Kuntāpa hymns of the Atharvaveda, which are of an obscene character.<ref name=fx1_ve1_304/><br>

आ-हाव
<u>'''Ā-hāva'''</u> denotes a pail or bucket, especially in conjunction with a well ('''[[अवत|Avata]]''').<ref name=fx1_ve1_305/><br>

आह्नेय
<u>'''Āhneya.'''</u>--Patronymic of '''Sauca''' ([[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka, ii. 12).<br>

इक्षु
<u>'''Ikṣu,'''</u> the generic name for the sugar-cane, is first found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_307/> and the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve1_307/> Whether it grew wild, or was cultivated, does not appear from the references. <br>

इक्ष्वाकु
<u>'''Ikṣvāku.'''</u>--In the Rigveda this name occurs but once,<ref name=fx1_ve1_308/> and in a doubtful context. It is clear, however, that it denotes a prince; later interpretations make '''Asamāti,''' whose name is read into the hymn, an [[इक्ष्वाकु|Ikṣvāku]] prince.<ref name=fx2_ve1_308/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_308/> also the name is found in only one passage, where it is uncertain whether a descendant of [[इक्ष्वाकु|Ikṣvāku]], or [[इक्ष्वाकु|Ikṣvāku]] himself, is referred to; in either case he seems to be regarded as an ancient hero. In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_308/> mention is made of '''Tryaruṇa [[त्रैधात्व|Traidhātva]]''' [[ऐक्ष्वाक|Aikṣvāka]], who is identical with the '''Tryaruṇa [[त्रैवृष्ण|Traivṛṣṇa]]''' of the Bṛhaddevatā,<ref name=fx5_ve1_308/> and with '''Tryaruṇa [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]]''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx6_ve1_308/> The connection of [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] with the Ikṣvākus is confirmed by the fact that '''[[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]]''' was an [[ऐक्ष्वाक|Aikṣvāka]], according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx7_ve1_308/> Thus the [[इक्ष्वाकु|Ikṣvāku]] line was originally a line of princes of the Pūrus. Zimmer<ref name=fx8_ve1_308/> places them on the upper Indus, but they may well have been somewhat further east.<ref name=fx9_ve1_308/> Later [[इक्ष्वाकु|Ikṣvāku]] is connected with Ayodhyā<br>

इट
<u>'''1. Iṭa.'''</u>--This word occurs twice in the Atharvaveda. in the first passage<ref name=fx1_ve1_309/> it seems to denote a bulrush of the sort that dies in a year; in the second<ref name=fx2_ve1_309/> it refers to the reed work of the house.<br>

इट
<u>'''2. Iṭa'''</u> appears as a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] and a protégé of Indra in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_310/> Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve1_310/> however, thinks that the word is really part of a verb (''iṭ'') meaning ‘to err, wander’ (cp. ''aṭ''), and  that the name is a mere misunderstanding. It is already so regarded in the Anukramaṇī, but not apparently in the Bṛhaddevatā.<ref name=fx3_ve1_310/><br>

इटन्त् काव्य
<u>'''Iṭant Kāvya'''</u> is the name of a sage, contemporary with '''[[केशिन् दार्भ्य|Keśin Dārbhya]],''' in the Kauṣitaki [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_311/> He is also mentioned as Iḍhant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_311/><br>

इतिहास
<u>'''Itihāsa,'''</u> as a kind of literature, is repeatedly mentioned along with '''[[पुराण|Purāṇa]]''' in the later texts of the Vedic period. The earliest reference to both occurs in the late fifteenth book of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_312/> [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] then appears in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_312/> the Jaiminīya,<ref name=fx3_ve1_312/> Bṛhadāraṇyaka,<ref name=fx4_ve1_312/> and Chāndogya Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx5_ve1_312/> In the latter it is expressly declared with [[पुराण|Purāṇa]] to make up the fifth Veda, while the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_312/> makes the [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] a Veda and the [[पुराण|Purāṇa]] a Veda. The [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]]-veda and the [[पुराण|Purāṇa]]-veda appear also in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx7_ve1_312/> while the Śatapatha<ref name=fx8_ve1_312/> identifies the [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] as well as the [[पुराण|Purāṇa]] with the Veda. In one passage '''[[अन्वाख्यान|Anvākhyāna]]''' and [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] are distinguished<ref name=fx9_ve1_312/> as different classes of works, but the exact point of distinction is obscure; probably the former was supplementary. The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx10_ve1_312/> mentions Itihāsas and Purāṇas in the plural.<br><br>There is nothing to show in the older literature what distinction there was, if any, between [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] and [[पुराण|Purāṇa]]; and the late literature,<ref name=fx11_ve1_312/> which has been elaborately examined by Sieg,<ref name=fx12_ve1_312/> yields no consistent result. Geldner<ref name=fx13_ve1_312/> has conjectured that there existed a single work, the [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]]-[[पुराण|purāṇa]], a collection  of the old legends of all sorts, heroic, cosmogonic, genealogical; but though a work called [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]], and another called [[पुराण|Purāṇa]], were probably known to Patañjali,<ref name=fx14_ve1_312/> the inaccuracy of Geldner's view is proved by the fact that [[यास्क|Yāska]] shows no sign of having known any such work. To him the [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] may be a part of the [[मन्त्र|Mantra]] literature itself,<ref name=fx15_ve1_312/> Aitihāsikas being merely people who interpret the Rigveda by seeing in it legends where others see myths.<ref name=fx16_ve1_312/> The fact, however, that the use of the compound form is rare, and that [[यास्क|Yāska]] regularly has [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]],<ref name=fx17_ve1_312/> not [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]]-[[पुराण|purāṇa]], is against the theory of there ever having been one work.<br><br>The relation of [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] to '''[[आख्यान|Ākhyāna]]''' is also uncertain. Sieg<ref name=fx18_ve1_312/> considers that the words [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] and [[पुराण|Purāṇa]] referred to the great body of mythology, legendary history, and cosmogonic legend available to the Vedic poets, and roughly classed as a fifth Veda, though not definitely and finally fixed. Thus, Anvākhyānas, '''Anuvyākhyānas,''' and '''Vyākhyānas''' could arise, and separate Ākhyānas could still exist outside the cycle, while an [[आख्यान|Ākhyāna]] could also be a part of the [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]]-[[पुराण|purāṇa]]. He also suggests that the word [[आख्यान|Ākhyāna]] has special reference to the form of the narrative. Oldenberg,<ref name=fx19_ve1_312/> following Windisch,<ref name=fx20_ve1_312/> and followed by Geldner,<ref name=fx21_ve1_312/> Sieg, and others, has found in the [[आख्यान|Ākhyāna]] form a mixture of prose and verse, alternating as the narrative was concerned with the mere accessory parts of the tale, or with the chief points, at which the poetic form was naturally produced to correspond with the stress of the emotion. This theory has been severely criticized by Hertel<ref name=fx22_ve1_312/> and von Schroeder.<ref name=fx23_ve1_312/> These scholars, in accordance with older suggestions of Max Müller<ref name=fx24_ve1_312/> and Lévi,<ref name=fx25_ve1_312/> see in the  so-called [[आख्यान|Ākhyāna]] hymns of the Rigveda, in which Oldenberg finds actual specimens of the supposed literary genus, though the prose has been lost, actual remains of ritual dramas. Elsewhere<ref name=fx26_ve1_312/> it has been suggested that the hymns in question are merely literary dialogues.<br>

इद्
<u>'''Id-, Idā-, Idu- Vatsara.'''</u> See '''[[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]].'''<br>

इन्द्र-गोप
<u>'''Indra-gopa'''</u> (‘protected by Indra’), masc., is a designation of the cochineal insect in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 3, 6).<br>

इन्द्र-द्युम्न भाल्लवेय वैयाघ्र-पद्य
<u>'''Indra-[[द्युम्न|dyumna]] [[भाल्लवेय|Bhāllaveya]] Vaiyāghra-padya'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher who with others was unable to agree as to the nature of Agni Vaiśvānara, and who was instructed by '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]] [[कैकेय|Kaikeya]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_315/> As [[भाल्लवेय|Bhāllaveya]] he is cited several times in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_315/> on ritual points.<br>

इन्द्र-भू काश्यप
<u>'''Indra-bhū Kāśyapa'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[मित्रभू काश्यप|Mitrabhū Kāśyapa]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_316/><br>

इन्द्रोत
<u>'''1. Indrota'''</u> is twice mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_317/> in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Liberality’) as a giver of gifts. In the second passage he has the epithet [[आतिथिग्व|Ātithigva]], which shows conclusively that he was a son of [[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]], as Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_317/> holds, and not of [[ऋक्ष|Ṛkṣa]], as Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_317/> states.<br>

इन्द्रोत दैवाप शौनक
<u>'''2. Indrota [[दैवाप|Daivāpa]] Śaunaka'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_318/> as the priest who officiated at the horse  sacrifice of '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]],''' although this honour is attributed in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_318/> to '''[[तुर कावषेय|Tura Kāvaṣeya]].''' He also appears in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_318/> as a pupil of '''Śruta,''' and is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_318/> He cannot be connected in any way with '''Devāpi,''' who occurs in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx5_ve1_318/><br>

इभ
<u>'''1. Ibha'''</u> is a word of somewhat doubtful sense and interpretation. It is found only in the Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_319/> and especially in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_319/> According to Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_319/> and Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve1_319/> the sense is ‘retainer,’ and Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve1_319/> thinks that it includes not only dependants and servants, but also the royal family and the youthful cadets of the chief families. In the opinion of Pischel and Geldner<ref name=fx6_ve1_319/> it denotes ‘elephant.’ This view is supported by the authority of the commentators Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx7_ve1_319/> and Mahīdhara;<ref name=fx8_ve1_319/> the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx9_ve1_319/> too, gives ‘elephant’ as one of the senses of the word. Megasthenes<ref name=fx10_ve1_319/> and Nearchos<ref name=fx11_ve1_319/> tell us that elephants were a royal prerogative, and the derivative word '''[[इभ्य|Ibhya]]''' may thus be naturally explained as denoting merely ‘rich’ (lit., ‘possessor of elephants’).<ref name=fx12_ve1_319/><br>

इभ
<u>'''2. Ibha'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_320/> appears certainly to be intended as an abbreviation of the proper name '''[[स्मद्इभ|Smadibha]].''' <br>

इभ्य
<u>'''Ibhya'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_321/> in the plural, when a king is said to devour his Ibhyas as the fire the forest; and twice in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_321/> in one passage as the first member of a compound, and in the other as either a proper name or an adjective. Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve1_321/> Ludwig,<ref name=fx4_ve1_321/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve1_321/> interpret the word as ‘retainers’ in the Rigveda, but in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] Roth thinks it means ‘rich.’ Pischel and Geldner<ref name=fx6_ve1_321/> accept the sense in all passages. Bo7htlingk in his translation of the Chāndogya treats the word as simply a proper name, ‘Ibhya's village’ (''[[इभ्य|ibhya]]-[[ग्राम|grāma]]'') and ‘Ibhya.’<br>

इरिण
<u>'''Iriṇa'''</u> (neut.) occurs not rarely in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_322/> and Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve1_322/> in the sense of ‘a cleft in the ground,’ usually natural (''sva-[[कृत|kṛta]]''). The same meaning is also, as Pischel<ref name=fx3_ve1_322/> shows, to be ascribed to it in three passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_322/> in one<ref name=fx5_ve1_322/> of which the hole is referred to as ‘made by water’ (''apā kṛtam''). In another passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_322/> the word refers to the place on which the dice are thrown. Hence Pischel<ref name=fx7_ve1_322/> concludes that the dicing-board must have been so called because it contained holes into which the dice had to be thrown if possible. Lüders,<ref name=fx8_ve1_322/> however, points out that this assumption is not necessary; the dice ('''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]]''') were merely thrown on a space dug out, which could be called '''[[इरिण|Iriṇa]],''' as being a hole in the ground, though not a natural one. This view is supported by the commentary of Sāyaṇa,<ref name=fx9_ve1_322/> as well as by [[दुर्ग|Durga]] in his note on the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx10_ve1_322/> <br>

इष श्यावाश्वि
<u>'''Iṣa Śyāvāśvi'''</u> is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (‘list of teachers’) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iv. 16, 1) as a pupil of [[अगस्त्य|Agastya]].<br>

इषीका
<u>'''Iṣīkā,'''</u> ‘a stalk of reed grass,’ occurs frequently from the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_324/> onwards, often as an emblem of fragility. In the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve1_324/> it seems to denote the pin fixed in the bar of a pen to keep cattle in (''argaleṣīke,'' ‘bolt and pin’). A basket (''[[शूर्प|śūrpa]]'') of [[इषीका|Iṣīkā]] is referred to in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_324/><br>

इषु
<u>'''Iṣu'''</u> is the usual name for ‘arrow’ from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_325/> onwards. Other names are '''[[शर्य|Śarya]], Śārī,''' and '''[[बाण|Bāṇa]].''' In the hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_325/> which gives a catalogue of armour, two kinds of arrows are distinctly referred to: the one is poisoned (''ālāktā''), and has a head of horn (''ruru-śīrṣṇī''); the other is copper-, bronze-, or iron-headed (''ayo-mukham''). Poisoned (''digdhā'') arrows are also referred to in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve1_325/> The arrows were feathered.<ref name=fx4_ve1_325/> The parts of an arrow are enumerated in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_325/> as the shaft (''[[शल्य|śalya]]''), the feather-socket (''[[पर्ण-धि|parṇa-dhi]]''), the point (''[[शृङ्ग|śṛṅga]]''), the neck of the point in which the shaft is fixed (''[[कुल्मल|kulmala]]''), and the '''[[अपस्कम्भ|Apaskambha]]''' and '''[[अपाष्ठ|Apāṣṭha]],''' which are of more doubtful significance. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_325/> the parts of an arrow are given as the point (''anīka''), the ''[[शल्य|śalya]], [[तेजन|tejana]],'' and the feathers (''parṇāni''), where ''[[शल्य|śalya]]'' and ''[[तेजन|tejana]]'' must apparently mean the upper and lower parts of the shaft, since it is reasonable to suppose that the arrow is described as a whole consecutively. So in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_325/> the arrow of Kāma is described as having feathers, a shaft  (''[[शल्य|śalya]]''), and a firm fastening (''[[कुल्मल|kulmala]]'').<ref name=fx8_ve1_325/> The arrow was shot from the ear, and so is described in the Rigveda<ref name=fx9_ve1_325/> as ‘having the ear for its place of birth.’<br><br>As a measure of length, the [[इषु|Iṣu]] was five spans, say three feet.<ref name=fx10_ve1_325/> A regular profession of arrow-making existed (''[[इषु|iṣu]]-kṛt,''<ref name=fx11_ve1_325/> ''[[इषु|iṣu]]-kāra'').<ref name=fx12_ve1_325/><br>

इषु त्रि-काण्डा
<u>'''Iṣu Tri-kāṇḍā'''</u> is the name given in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_326/> to some constellation, perhaps Orion's girdle. It is mentioned with '''[[मृग|Mṛga]], [[मृगव्याध|Mṛgavyādha]],''' and '''[[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]].'''<br>

इषु-धि
<u>'''Iṣu-dhi'''</u> (‘arrow-holder’) is the name of the quiver which was carried by every bowman. The word is common from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_327/> onwards. No trace is to be found in Vedic literature of the later practice of carrying two quivers.<ref name=fx2_ve1_327/> According to Pischel,<ref name=fx3_ve1_327/> the curious expression ''[[इषु|iṣu]]-kṛt'' in the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_327/> means quiver.<br>

ईषा
<u>'''Īṣā'''</u> denotes the ‘pole of a chariot.’ Normally the chariot had one pole (''ekeṣaḥ''),<ref name=fx1_ve1_328/> but sometimes two poles are referred to.<ref name=fx2_ve1_328/> The word is often<ref name=fx3_ve1_328/> compounded with '''Yuga,''' ‘yoke,’ into which it was fastened (see '''Kha'''), and tied with ropes.<ref name=fx4_ve1_328/> Exactly how it was attached to the chariot we do not know.<ref name=fx5_ve1_328/> See also '''[[रथ|Ratha]].''' <br>

उक्षन्
<u>'''Ukṣan.'''</u> See '''Go.'''<br>

उक्षण्यायन
<u>'''Ukṣaṇyāyana'''</u> is mentioned in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_330/> along with '''[[हरयाण|Harayāṇa]]''' and '''[[सुषामन्|Suṣāman]].''' Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_330/> thinks that all three are identical. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_330/> finds a reference to [[उक्षन्|Ukṣan]] himself in the verb ''ukṣaṇyati''<ref name=fx4_ve1_330/> and in the adjective ''ukṣaṇyu.''<ref name=fx5_ve1_330/><br>

उक्ष्णो-रन्ध्र काव्य
<u>'''Ukṣṇo-[[रन्ध्र|randhra]] Kāvya'''</u> is mentioned as a seer in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 9, 19).<ref name=fx1_ve1_331/><br>

उखा
<u>'''Ukhā'''</u> is the regular word or a ‘cooking pot,’ usually mentioned in connexion with sacrifice, from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_332/> onwards. It was made of clay (''mṛṇ-mayī'').<ref name=fx2_ve1_332/> See also '''[[स्थाली|Sthālī]].'''<br>

उग्र
<u>'''Ugra'''</u> in one passage of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_333/> seems to have a technical force, denoting ‘man in authority,’ or according to Max Müller's rendering, ‘policeman.’ Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_333/> compares a passage in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_333/> where, however, the word has simply the general sense of ‘mighty man.’ Bo7htlingk,<ref name=fx4_ve1_333/> in his rendering of the [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]], treats the word as merely adjectival.<br>

उग्र-देव
<u>'''Ugra-deva'''</u> is mentioned with '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]]''' and '''Yadu''' in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_334/> apparently as a powerful protector. The name occurs also in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_334/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx3_ve1_334/> where he is styled '''[[राजनि|Rājani]]''' and called a leper (''[[किलास|kilāsa]]''). <br>

उग्र-सेन
<u>'''Ugra-sena'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 5, 4, 3), and in a [[गाथा|Gāthā]] there cited as being, with '''[[भीमसेन|Bhīmasena]]''' and '''[[श्रुतसेन|Śrutasena]],''' a Pārikṣitīya and a brother of '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]].''' The brothers were cleansed by the horse sacrifice from sin.<br>

उच्चैः-श्रवस् कौपयेय
<u>'''Uccaiḥ-śravas Kaupayeya'''</u> appears in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 29, 1-3) as a king of the '''Kurus''' and as maternal uncle of '''[[केशिन्|Keśin]].''' His connexion with the Kurus is borne out by the fact that '''[[उपमश्रवस्|Upamaśravas]]''' was son of '''Kuruśravaṇa,''' the names being strikingly similar.<br>

उच्-छीर्षक
<u>'''Uc-chīrṣaka.'''</u>--This word, occurring in the description of the couch (''[[पर्य्अङ्क|paryaṅka]]'') in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_337/> (i. 5), apparently denotes a cushion for the head. See also '''[[आसन्दी|Āsandī]].'''<br>

उत्तर कुरु
<u>'''Uttara Kuru.'''</u>--The Uttara Kurus, who play a mythical part in the Epic and later literature, are still a historical people in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_338/> where they are located beyond the Himālaya (''pareṇa Himavantam''). In another passage,<ref name=fx2_ve1_338/> however, the country of the Uttara Kurus is stated by '''[[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]] [[सात्यहव्य|Sātyahavya]]''' to be a land of the gods (''deva-[[क्षेत्र|kṣetra]]''), but '''[[जानंतपि|Jānaṃtapi]] Atyarāti''' was anxious to conquer it, so that it is still not wholly mythical. It is reasonable to accept Zimmer's view that the northern Kurus were settled in Kaśmīr, especially as '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]]''' is the region where tribes advancing from Kaśmīr might naturally be found. ''Cf.'' '''[[उद्ईच्यस्|Udīcyas]].'''<br>

उत्तर मद्र
<u>'''Uttara Madra'''</u> is the name of a tribe mentioned with the '''Uttara Kurus''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_339/> as living beyond the Himālaya. Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_339/> points out that in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_339/> '''[[काम्बोज|Kāmboja]] [[औपमन्यव|Aupamanyava]]''' is a pupil of '''Madragāra,''' and thence  infers that Kambojas and Madras were not far distant in space. This conclusion is perfectly reasonable in view of the probable position of the Kāmbojas.<ref name=fx4_ve1_339/><br>

उत्-तान आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Ut-tāna Āṅgirasa'''</u> is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_340/> as a quasi-mythical person who received all good things, and yet was not harmed, as he was really a form of the earth, according to Sāyaṇa's<ref name=fx2_ve1_340/> explanation. His name occurs also in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_340/> the Pancaviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_340/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx5_ve1_340/><br>

उदग्-अयन
<u>'''Udag-ayana.'''</u> See '''[[सूर्य|Sūrya]].'''<br>

उद्-अङ्क शौल्बायन
<u>'''Ud-[[अङ्क|aṅka]] Śaulbāyana.'''</u>--His views on [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], which he identified with the vital airs (''[[प्राण|prāṇa]]''), are mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 1, 3). He would thus have been a contemporary of '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' of [[विदेह|Videha]]. He is also mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vii. 5, 4, 2) as holding that the Daśarātra ceremony was the prosperity or best part of the Sattra (‘sacrificial session’).<br>

उद्-अञ्चन
<u>'''Ud-añcana.'''</u>--This word, occurring only metaphorically in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_343/> means a ‘pail’ or ‘bucket’ in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_343/><br>

उदमय आत्रेय
<u>'''Udamaya Ātreya'''</u> is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 22) as [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], or domestic priest, of '''[[अङ्ग वैरोचन|Aṅga Vairocana]].'''<br>

उदर शाण्डिल्य
<u>'''Udara Śāṇḍilya'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_345/> and as a pupil of '''[[अतिधन्वन् शौनक|Atidhanvan Śaunaka]]''' in the '''[[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_345/><br>

उदल
<u>'''Udala,'''</u> a [[वैश्वामित्र|Vaiśvāmitra]], is mentioned in the Pañcaviṃsa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 11, 33) as the seer of a Sāman. <br>

उद्-आज
<u>'''Ud-āja'''</u> is the word used in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_347/> to denote the share of the booty of war taken by the king after a victory (''saṃgrāmaṃ jitvā''). This interpretation, which is that of Delbrück,<ref name=fx2_ve1_347/> is clearly correct, as against the older version, ‘march out,’ given by von Schroeder<ref name=fx3_ve1_347/> and accepted by Bo7htlingk.<ref name=fx4_ve1_347/> The [[उद्आज|Udāja]] thus corresponds precisely with the Homeric  This sense also suits Nirāja, the variant of both the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_347/> and the Kapiṣṭhala<ref name=fx6_ve1_347/> Saṃhitās.<br>

उदान
<u>'''Udāna'''</u> is usually the fifth of the vital breaths ('''[[प्राण|Prāṇa]]''') when five are enumerated.<ref name=fx1_ve1_348/> Sometimes<ref name=fx2_ve1_348/> it appears as the second, coming after [[प्राण|Prāṇa]], and followed by [[व्य्आन|Vyāna]] or [[समान|Samāna]]. Again,<ref name=fx3_ve1_348/> it is found simply opposed to [[प्राण|Prāṇa]], or it simply follows [[प्राण|Prāṇa]] and [[अपान|Apāna]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_348/> In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_348/> it is treated as the breath that consumes food, a notion traceable in the later Upaniṣads,<ref name=fx6_ve1_348/> while it is also regarded as the wind that rises up by the throat,<ref name=fx7_ve1_348/> and leads the spirit forth at death.<ref name=fx8_ve1_348/><br>

उद्-ईच्यस्
<u>'''Ud-īcyas.'''</u>--The Brāhmaṇas of the northern parts are referred to in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_349/> as engaging, with '''[[स्वैदायन|Svaidāyana]] [[शौनक|Śaunaka]]''' as their spokesman, in a dispute with the Kurupañcāla [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] '''[[उद्दालक आरुणि|Uddālaka Āruṇi]],''' and as vanquishing him. Their relation to the Kurupañcālas appears also from the fact that in  the same [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_349/> reference is made to the speech of the north being similar to that of the Kurupañcālas. The speech of the Northerners was also celebrated for purity; hence Brāhmaṇas used to go to the north for purposes of study, according to the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_349/> while in the Buddhist texts the school of Takṣaśilā (in [[गन्धार|Gandhāra]]) is famous as a resort of students.<ref name=fx4_ve1_349/> Possibly, too, Sanskrit was specially developed in Kaśmīr, as suggested by Franke.<ref name=fx5_ve1_349/> See also '''Kuru.'''<br>

उदुम्बर
<u>'''Udumbara.'''</u>--This name of the ''Ficus glomerata'' does not occur in the Rigveda, but is often found from the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_350/> onwards. For ritual purposes of all kinds its wood was constantly used. The sacrificial post (''[[यूप|yūpa]]'')<ref name=fx2_ve1_350/> and the sacrificial ladle<ref name=fx3_ve1_350/> were made of it, and amulets of [[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]] are mentioned.<ref name=fx4_ve1_350/> Its wood, like that of other kinds of figtree-'''[[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]], [[न्यग्रोध|Nyagrodha]],''' and '''[[प्लक्ष|Plakṣa]]'''--was considered suitable for employment at the sacrifice.<ref name=fx5_ve1_350/> The sweetness of its fruit is referred to in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx6_ve1_350/> where it is put on the same level as '''[[मधु|Madhu]].''' It is there also spoken of as ripening three times a year.<ref name=fx7_ve1_350/> A forest of [[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]] trees is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx8_ve1_350/><br>

उद्दालक आरुणि
<u>'''Uddālaka Āruṇi.'''</u>--Uddālaka, son of Aruṇa, is one of the most prominent teachers of the Vedic period. He was a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] of the Kurupañcālas, according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_351/> This statement is confirmed by the fact that he was teacher of '''Proti [[कौसुरुबिन्दि|Kausurubindi]]''' of Kauśāmbī,<ref name=fx2_ve1_351/> and that his son  '''Svetaketu''' is found disputing among the Pañcālas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_351/> He was a pupil of Aruṇa, his father,<ref name=fx4_ve1_351/> as well as of [[पतञ्चल काप्य|Patañcala Kāpya]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_351/> of [[मद्र|Madra]], while he was the teacher of the famous [[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_351/> [[वाजसनेय|Vājasaneya]] and of [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]],<ref name=fx7_ve1_351/> although the former is represented elsewhere<ref name=fx8_ve1_351/> as having silenced him. He overcame in argument [[प्राचीनयोग्य|Prācīnayogya]] [[शौचेय|Śauceya]],<ref name=fx9_ve1_351/> and apparently also [[भद्रसेन आजातशत्रव|Bhadrasena Ājātaśatrava]],<ref name=fx10_ve1_351/> though the text here seems to read the name as Āraṇi. He was a [[गौतम|Gautama]],<ref name=fx11_ve1_351/> and is often alluded to as such. As an authority on questions of ritual and philosophy, he is repeatedly referred to by his patronymic name [[आरुणि|Āruṇi]] in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx12_ve1_351/> the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx13_ve1_351/> the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx14_ve1_351/> and occasionally in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]],<ref name=fx15_ve1_351/> the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]],<ref name=fx16_ve1_351/> and the Ṣaḍviṃśa<ref name=fx17_ve1_351/> Brāhmaṇas, as well as the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx18_ve1_351/> In the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā he is not mentioned, according to Geldner,<ref name=fx19_ve1_351/> but only his father Aruṇa; his name does not occur, according to Weber,<ref name=fx20_ve1_351/> in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]], but in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx21_ve1_351/> he is, as [[आरुणि|Āruṇi]], known as a contemporary of '''[[दिवोदास भैमसेनि|Divodāsa Bhaimaseni]],''' and in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx22_ve1_351/> he is mentioned as serving '''[[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]] [[चैकितानेय|Caikitāneya]].''' In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] tradition he seldom appears. There is an allusion in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx23_ve1_351/> to Kusurubinda [[औद्दालकि|Auddālaki]], and according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx24_ve1_351/> [[नचिकेतस्|Naciketas]] was a son of [[वाजश्रवस|Vājaśravasa]] [[गौतम|Gautama]], who  is made out to be Uddālaka by Sāyaṇa.<ref name=fx25_ve1_351/> But the episode of [[नचिकेतस्|Naciketas]], being somewhat unreal, cannot be regarded as of historical value in proving relationship. Aruṇa is known to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā. A real son of Uddālaka was the famous '''[[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]],''' who is expressly reported by Āpastamba<ref name=fx26_ve1_351/> to have been in his time an Avara or later authority, a statement of importance for the date of [[आरुणि|Āruṇi]].<br>

उद्दालकायन
<u>'''Uddālakāyana'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of [[जाबालायन|Jābālāyana]] in the second [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) contained in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 6, 2).<br>

उद्र
<u>'''Udra'''</u> is the name of an animal occurring only in the list of sacrificial victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] given in the Saṃhitās of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_353/> According to Mahīdhara<ref name=fx2_ve1_353/> it was a crab; but as the commentary on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_353/> calls it a watercat, there can be no doubt that it was an otter.<br>

उद्धि
<u>'''Uddhi'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_354/> denotes some part of a chariot, probably the seat,<ref name=fx2_ve1_354/> but, according to Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve1_354/> the frame resting on the axle.<br>

उप-केतु
<u>'''Upa-ketu'''</u> is the name of a man mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xiii. 1).<br>

उप-कोसल कामलायन
<u>'''Upa-[[कोसल|kosala]] Kāmalāyana'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher and a pupil of '''[[सत्यकाम|Satyakāma]] [[जाबाल|Jābāla]]''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 10, 1; 14, 1). <br>

उप-क्वस
<u>'''Upa-kvasa'''</u> is the name in the Atharvaveda (vi. 50, 2) of a noxious insect injurious to seed. Sāyaṇa, however, reads the word as a plural adjective (''a-pakvasaḥ = a-dagdāḥ''), but the Paippalāda recension supports the form ''upakvasaḥ.''<br><br>''Cf.'' Zimmer, ''Altindisches Leben,'' 237; Bloomfield, ''Hymns of the Atharvaveda,'' 486; Whitney's Translation of the Atharvaveda, 318.<br>

उप-गु सौश्रवस
<u>'''Upa-gu Sauśravasa'''</u> is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 6, 8) as [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of '''[[कुत्स औरव|Kutsa Aurava]],''' by whom he was murdered because of his paying homage to Indra.<br><br>''Cf.'' Hillebrandt, ''Vedische Mythologie,'' 3, 268; Hopkins, ''Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences,'' 15, 57.<br>

उप-चित्
<u>'''Upa-cit'''</u> occurs in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_359/> as the name of a disease, which Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_359/> renders as ‘swelling,’ and which Bloomfield<ref name=fx3_ve1_359/> identifies with '''[[अपचित्|Apacit]].'''<br>

उप-जिह्विका
<u>'''Upa-jihvikā, Upa-jīkā, Upa-dīkā'''</u> are all forms of one word denoting a species of ant.<ref name=fx1_ve1_360/> To these ants is attributed in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_360/> the power of penetrating to water which possesses curative properties. They were accordingly used in all sorts of spells against poisoning. The belief in their healing qualities was no doubt due to the well-known properties of the earth of ant-heaps which contains their water.<br>

उप-धान
<u>'''Upa-dhāna'''</u> denotes the ‘cushion’ of a seat ('''[[आसन्दी|Āsandī]]''') in the Atharvaveda (xiv. 2, 65). It corresponds to the '''[[उपबर्हण|Upabarhaṇa]]''' of other texts. <br>

उप-धि
<u>'''Upa-dhi'''</u> occurs once each in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_362/> and the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_362/> in conjunction with '''[[प्रधि|Pradhi]],''' denoting part of the wheel of a chariot. It is impossible to decide exactly what part is meant. Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve1_362/> Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve1_362/> and Bloomfield,<ref name=fx5_ve1_362/> agree in thinking that the word denotes the spokes collectively. Whitney,<ref name=fx6_ve1_362/> considering this improbable, prefers to see in it the designation of a solid wheel, [[प्रधि|Pradhi]] being presumably the rim and [[उपधि|Upadhi]] the rest. Other possibilities<ref name=fx7_ve1_362/> are that the [[उपधि|Upadhi]] is a rim beneath the felly, or the felly itself as compared with the tire (ordinarily '''Pavi''').<br>

उप-निषद्
<u>'''Upa-niṣad'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_363/> normally denotes the ‘secret sense’ of some word or text, sometimes the ‘secret rule’ of the mendicant. But in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_363/> it is already used in the plural as the designation of a class of writings, no doubt actually existing and similar to the Upaniṣads in the nature of their subject-matter and its treatment. Similarly the sections of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] end with the words ''ity [[उपनिषद्|upaniṣad]].'' The [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx3_ve1_363/> commences its third part with the title ‘The [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] of the Saṃhitā,’ and the title occurs also in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx4_ve1_363/> The exact primary sense of the expression is doubtful. The natural derivation, adopted by Max Müller<ref name=fx5_ve1_363/> and usual ever since, makes the word mean firstly a session of pupils, hence secret doctrine, and secondly the title of a work on secret doctrine. Oldenberg,<ref name=fx6_ve1_363/> however, traces the use of the word to the earlier  sense of ‘worship’ (''cf. upāsana''). Deussen<ref name=fx7_ve1_363/> considers the original sense to have been ‘secret word,’ next ‘secret text,’ and then ‘secret import,’ but this order of meaning is improbable. Hopkins<ref name=fx8_ve1_363/> suggests that [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] denotes a subsidiary treatise, but this sense does not account naturally for the common use as ‘secret meaning,’ which is far more frequent than any other.<br>

उप-पति
<u>'''Upa-pati,'''</u> ‘the gallant,’ is mentioned with the [[जार|Jāra]], ‘lover,’ in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_364/> as a victim in the human sacrifice (''puruṣamedha'').<br>

उप-बर्हण
<u>'''Upa-barhaṇa'''</u> denotes a ‘pillow’ or ‘cushion,’ especially of a seat (''[[आसन्दी|āsandī]]''), occurring in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_365/> the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_365/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_365/> The feminine Upabarhaṇī is found in the Rigveda with the same sense, but used metaphorically of the earth.<br>

उप-मन्थनी
<u>'''Upa-manthanī'''</u> is used in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_366/> to denote ‘churning sticks.’ In the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_366/> the ‘churner’ (''upamanthitṛ'') is included in the list of victims at the human sacrifice (''puruṣamedha''), and the verb ''upa-manth'' is often used of churning or mixing fluids.<ref name=fx3_ve1_366/><br>

उप-मन्यु
<u>'''Upa-manyu'''</u> is, according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx1_ve1_367/> the name of a person in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_367/> but is more probably explained by Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_367/> as a mere epithet. <br>

उपम-श्रवस्
<u>'''Upama-śravas'''</u> is mentioned in a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_368/> as a son of '''Kuruśravaṇa,''' and grandson of '''[[मेधातिथि|Medhātithi]].''' The exact force of the reference to him in however, uncertain. According to the Bṛhaddevatā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_368/> followed by Ludwig,<ref name=fx3_ve1_368/> and by Lanman,<ref name=fx4_ve1_368/> the poet in the hymn consoles [[उपमश्रवस्|Upamaśravas]] for the death of his grandfather, [[मेधातिथि|Medhātithi]]. Geldner,<ref name=fx5_ve1_368/> on the other hand, thinks that the poet, who was '''[[कवष|Kavaṣa]] [[ऐलूष|Ailūṣa]],''' was ill-treated by his patron's son, [[उपमश्रवस्|Upamaśravas]], and cast into a ditch or well, where he uttered his complaint and appeal for mercy. But of this there is no adequate evidence, and the tradition of the Bṛhaddevatā seems sound.<br>

उप-मित्
<u>'''Upa-mit'''</u> occurs twice in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_369/> and once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_369/> as the designation of some part of a house. The passages in the Rigveda leave little doubt that the word means an upright pillar. As it is, in the Atharvaveda, coupled with '''[[परिमित्|Parimit]]''' and '''[[प्रतिमित्|Pratimit]],''' the conclusion is natural that the latter word denotes the beams supporting the [[उपमित्|Upamit]], presumably by leaning against it at an angle, while '''[[परिमित्|Parimit]]''' denotes the beams connecting the Upamits horizontally. These interpretations, however, can only be conjectural. See also '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].'''<br>

उपर
<u>'''Upara,'''</u> which, according to Pischel,<ref name=fx1_ve1_370/> means ‘stone’ in general, is the technical name of the stone on which the Soma plant was laid in order to be pounded for the extraction of the juice by other stones (''adri, grāvan''). The word is rare, occurring only thrice in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_370/> and once in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve1_370/> <br>

उपल-प्रक्षिणी
<u>'''Upala-prakṣiṇī'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_371/> where it designates the occupation of a woman, as opposed to that of her son, who is a poet (''[[कारु|kāru]]''), and to that of his father, who is a physician (''[[भिषज्|bhiṣaj]]''). [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_371/> renders the word by ‘maker of groats’ (''[[सक्तु|saktu]]-kārikā''), and Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve1_371/> Grassmann,<ref name=fx4_ve1_371/> Zimmer,<ref name=fx5_ve1_371/> as well as others, connect it with the operation of grinding corn. Pischel,<ref name=fx6_ve1_371/> however, who points out that corn was not ground between two stones, but beaten on a stone with a pestle (''[[दृषद्|dṛṣad]]''), considers that [[उपल-प्रक्षिणी|Upala-prakṣiṇī]] denotes a woman that assisted at the crushing of Soma (''cf.'' '''[[उपर|Upara]]'''). Von Schroeder,<ref name=fx7_ve1_371/> who more correctly points out that there is no objection to regarding ''upala'' as the mortar in which the corn was placed and then beaten with the pestle, renders the word literally as ‘one who fills the (lower) stone (with corn).’<br>

उपला
<u>'''Upalā'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_372/> may denote the upper and smaller ‘stone,’ which was used as a pestle with the '''[[दृषद्|Dṛṣad]]''' as the mortar, whereas '''[[उपर|Upara]]''' in the Saṃhitās denotes rather the mortar, and [[दृषद्|Dṛṣad]] the pestle. But see '''[[दृषद्|Dṛṣad]].'''<br>

उप-वाक
<u>'''Upa-vāka'''</u> occurs in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_373/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve1_373/> as a description of a species of grain, the ''Wrightia antidysenterica,'' known later as Indra-yava. The commentator Mahīdhara<ref name=fx3_ve1_373/> simply glosses it with the more general term '''Yava.'''  According to the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā, it formed the essential element of gruel (''[[करम्भ|karambha]]''), and [[उपवाक|Upavāka]] groats (''saktavaḥ'') are mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_373/><br>

उप-वेशि
<u>'''Upa-veśi'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of '''Kuśri''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 3, in both recensions). See also '''[[औपवेशि|Aupaveśi]].'''<br>

उप-श्री
<u>'''Upa-[[श्री|śrī]], Upa-śraya,'''</u> are two readings of the same term. The former is found in one recension of the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_375/> while the latter is probably the reading of the other recension of the [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_375/> and certainly the reading in one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_375/> though the text has ''apaśrayaḥ,'' which is accepted as possible by Roth.<ref name=fx4_ve1_375/> In both cases the term clearly means something connected with a couch ('''[[आसन्दी|Āsandī]]''' in the Atharvaveda, '''[[पर्य्अङ्क|Paryaṅka]]''' in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]). Aufrecht,<ref name=fx5_ve1_375/> Roth,<ref name=fx6_ve1_375/> and Max Müller<ref name=fx7_ve1_375/> render it as ‘coverlet’ or ‘cushion,’ but Whitney<ref name=fx8_ve1_375/> seems evidently right in holding that it must mean a ‘support’ or something similar.<br>

उप-स्तरण
<u>'''Upa-staraṇa'''</u> denotes in the description of the couch ('''[[पर्य्अङ्क|Paryaṅka]]''') in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_376/> a ‘coverlet,’ and has this sense, used metaphorically, in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_376/> also. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_376/> it seems to have the same meaning. Whitney,<ref name=fx4_ve1_376/> however, renders it ‘couch,’ though he translates<ref name=fx5_ve1_376/> the parallel word '''[[आस्तरण|Āstaraṇa]]''' in another passage<ref name=fx6_ve1_376/> by ‘cushion.’ <br>

उप-स्ति
<u>'''Upa-sti'''</u> denotes both in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_377/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_377/> a ‘dependent,’ just as later in the Epic<ref name=fx3_ve1_377/> the subordination of the [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] to the two superior castes is expressed by the verb ''upa-sthā,'' ‘stand under,’ ‘support.’ The word also appears, with the same sense, in the form of Sti, but only in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx4_ve1_377/> The exact nature of the dependence connoted by the term is quite uncertain. Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve1_377/> conjectures that the ‘dependents’ were the members of defeated Aryan tribes who became clients of the king, as among the Greeks, Romans, and Germans, the term possibly including persons who had lost their freedom through dicing.<ref name=fx6_ve1_377/> The evidence of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_377/> shows that among the Upastis were included the chariot-makers (''[[रथ-कार|ratha-kāra]]''), the smiths (''[[तक्षन्|takṣan]]''), and the charioteers (''[[सूत|sūta]]''), and troop-leaders (''[[ग्राम|grāma]]-ṇī''), while the Rigveda passages negative the possibility of the ‘subjects’ (''sti'') being the whole people. It is therefore fair to assume that they were the clients proper of the king, not servile, but attached in a special relation to him as opposed to the ordinary population. They may well have included among them not only the classes suggested by Zimmer, but also higher elements, such as refugees from other clans, as well as ambitious men who sought advancement in the royal service. Indeed, the [[सूत|Sūta]] and the Grāmaṇī were, as such, officers of the king's household--kingmakers, not themselves kings, as they are described in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx8_ve1_377/> The use of the word in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx9_ve1_377/> the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx10_ve1_377/> and the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]],<ref name=fx11_ve1_377/> is purely metaphorical, as well as in the one passage of the Rigveda in which it occurs. In the Paippalāda recension of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx12_ve1_377/> [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]], [[शूद्र|Śūdra]], and [[आर्य|Ārya]] are referred to as Upastis, perhaps in the general sense of ‘subject.’ <br>

उप-स्तुत
<u>'''Upa-stuta'''</u> is mentioned several times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_378/> always as a sage of old, and usually in connexion with [[कण्व|Kaṇva]], who was aided or favoured by Agni, the Aśvins, and other gods. The Upastutas, sons of [[वृष्टिहव्य|Vṛṣṭihavya]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_378/> are mentioned as singers<ref name=fx3_ve1_378/><br>

उप-ह्वर
<u>'''Upa-hvara'''</u> denotes, in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_379/> according to Geldner,<ref name=fx2_ve1_379/> the body of a chariot (''upa-stha'').<br>

उपानस
<u>'''Upānasa'''</u> is in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_380/> opposed to '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]],''' and must mean something like ‘the body of the wagon,’ though Sāyaṇa suggests that it signifies either a ‘granary’ or a ‘wagon full of grain.’ In the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_380/> where the word occurs only once, its sense is doubtful. Pischel<ref name=fx3_ve1_380/> explains the form which occurs there not as an adjective, but as an infinitive.<br>

उपा-नह्
<u>'''Upā-nah'''</u> is the regular word for a ‘sandal’ or ‘shoe’ from the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_381/> onwards. Boarskin is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_381/> as a material of which shoes were made. The combination ‘staff and sandals’ (''daṇḍopānaha'') occurs as early as the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_381/><br>

उपावि जान-श्रुतेय
<u>'''Upāvi [[जान|Jāna]]-śruteya'''</u> is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 25, 15) as an authority on the Upasads (a kind of Soma ceremony).<br>

उपोदिति गौपालेय
<u>'''Upoditi Gaupāleya'''</u> is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xii. 13, 11) as a seer of Sāmans.<br>

उभया-दन्त्
<u>'''Ubhayā-dant,'''</u> ‘having incisors in both jaws,’ is an expression employed to distinguish, among domestic animals, the horse,  the ass, etc., from the goat, the sheep, and cattle. The distinction occurs in a late hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_384/> and is several times alluded to in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve1_384/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_384/> In one passage of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve1_384/> man is classed with the horse as ''[[उभया-दन्त्|ubhayā-dant]].'' The opposite is ''anyato-dant,'' ‘having incisors in one jaw only,’ a term regularly applied to cattle,<ref name=fx5_ve1_384/> the eight incisors of which are, in fact, limited to the lower jaw. The ass is styled ''[[उभया-दन्त्|ubhayā-dant]]'' in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx6_ve1_384/> In one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx7_ve1_384/> however, the epithet is applied to a ram; but the sense here is that a marvel occurs, just as in the Rigveda<ref name=fx8_ve1_384/> a ram destroys a lioness. Bloomfield<ref name=fx9_ve1_384/> suggests in the Atharvaveda passage another reading which would mean ‘horse.’ A parallel division of animals is that of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]]<ref name=fx10_ve1_384/> and Vājasaneyi Saṃhitās<ref name=fx11_ve1_384/> into ‘whole-hoofed’ (''eka-[[शफ|śapha]]'') and ‘small’ (''kṣudra'').<br><br>Zimmer<ref name=fx12_ve1_384/> seeks to show from the Greek <ref name=fx13_ve1_384/> and the Latin ''ambidens''<ref name=fx14_ve1_384/> that the Indo-European was familiar with the division of the five sacrificial animals into the two classes of man and horse on the one hand, and cattle, sheep, and goats on the other. But this supposition is not necessary.<br>

उरा
<u>'''Urā'''</u> as a name for ‘sheep’ is confined to the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_385/> It is curious that in one of its two occurrences the wolf should be referred to as terrifying sheep, and that the epithet of the wolf, ''[[उरा|urā]]-mathi,'' ‘killing sheep,’ should occur once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_385/> both references being in one book of the Saṃhitā, a fact which suggests a dialectical origin of the word ''[[उरा|urā]].'' See also '''Avi.''' <br>

उरु-कक्ष
<u>'''Uru-kakṣa'''</u> occurs in only one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_386/> where the sense of the word is much disputed. The reading of the text is ''uruḥ kakṣo na gāṅgyaḥ,'' which may refer to a man, [[उरुकक्ष|Urukakṣa]], ‘dwelling on the Ganges,’<ref name=fx2_ve1_386/> or to a man, son of [[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]], or to a wood so called,<ref name=fx3_ve1_386/> or may simply denote the ‘broad thicket on the Ganges.’<ref name=fx4_ve1_386/><br>

उरु-क्षय
<u>'''Uru-kṣaya.'''</u>--A family of Urukṣayas, singers and worshippers of Agni, is referred to in one hymn of the Rigveda (x. 118, 8. 9).<br><br>''Cf.'' Ludwig, Translation of the Rigveda, 3, 167.<br>

उरुञ्जिरा
<u>'''Uruñjirā'''</u> is given in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (ix. 26) as one of the names of the river '''[[विपाश्|Vipāś]]''' (now Beäs).<br>

उर्वरा
<u>'''Urvarā'''</u> is with '''[[क्षेत्र|Kṣetra]]''' the regular expression, from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_389/> onwards, denoting a piece of ‘ploughland’ (). Fertile (''apnasvatī'') fields<ref name=fx2_ve1_389/> are spoken of as well as waste fields (''ārtanā'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_389/> Intensive cultivation by means of irrigation is clearly referred to both in the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_389/> and in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx5_ve1_389/> while allusion is also made to the use of manure.<ref name=fx6_ve1_389/> The fields (''[[क्षेत्र|kṣetra]]'') were carefully measured according to the Rigveda.<ref name=fx7_ve1_389/> This fact points clearly to individual ownership in land for the plough, a conclusion supported by the reference of Apālā, in a hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx8_ve1_389/> to her father's field (''[[उर्वरा|urvarā]]''), which is put on the same level as his head of hair as a personal possession. Consistent with this are the epithets ‘winning fields’ (''[[उर्वरा|urvarā]]-sā, [[उर्वरा|urvarā]]-jit, [[क्षेत्र|kṣetra]]-sā''),<ref name=fx9_ve1_389/> while ‘lord of fields’ used of a god<ref name=fx10_ve1_389/> is presumably a transfer of a human epithet (''[[उर्वरा|urvarā]]-pati''). Moreover, fields are spoken of in the same  connexion as children,<ref name=fx11_ve1_389/> and the conquest of fields (''kṣetrāṇi saṃ-ji'') is often referred to in the Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx12_ve1_389/> Very probably, as suggested by Pischel,<ref name=fx13_ve1_389/> the ploughland was bounded by grass land (perhaps denoted by '''[[खिल|Khila]], Khilya''') which in all likelihood would be joint property on the analogy of property elsewhere. There is no trace in Vedic literature of communal property in the sense of ownership by a community of any sort,<ref name=fx14_ve1_389/> nor is there mention of communal cultivation. Individual property in land seems also presumed later on. In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx15_ve1_389/> the things given as examples of wealth include fields and houses (''āyatanāni''). The Greek evidence<ref name=fx16_ve1_389/> also points to individual ownership. The precise nature of the ownership is of course not determined by the expression ‘individual ownership.’ The legal relationship of the head of a family and its members is nowhere explained, and can only be conjectured (see '''[[पितृ|Pitṛ]]'''). Very often a family may have lived together with undivided shares in the land. The rules about the inheritance of landed property do not occur before the Sūtras.<ref name=fx17_ve1_389/> In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx18_ve1_389/> the giving of land as a fee to priests is mentioned, but with reproof: land was no doubt even then a very special kind of property, not lightly to be given away or parted with.<ref name=fx19_ve1_389/> <br><br>On the relation of the owners of land to the king and others see '''[[ग्राम|Grāma]];''' on its cultivation see '''[[कृषि|Kṛṣi]].'''<br>

उर्वारू
<u>'''Urvārū,'''</u> f., '''Urvāruka,''' n., ‘cucumber.’ The former<ref name=fx1_ve1_390/> of these words denotes the plant, the latter<ref name=fx2_ve1_390/> the fruit, but both are very rare. The passages all seem to refer to the fact that the stem of the plant becomes loosened when the fruit is ripe.<ref name=fx3_ve1_390/> The fruit is also called Urvāru in a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_390/><br>

उल
<u>'''Ula'''</u> is the name of some unknown wild animal, perhaps, as Whitney<ref name=fx1_ve1_391/> suggests, the ‘jackal.’ It is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_391/> and later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx3_ve1_391/> but not definitely identified by the commentators.<br>

उल वार्ष्णि-वृद्ध
<u>'''Ula Vārṣṇi-vṛddha'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 4).<br>

उलप
<u>'''Ulapa'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_393/> is the name of a species of grass referred to in the Rigveda and the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve1_393/><br>

उलुक्य जान-श्रुतेय
<u>'''Ulukya [[जान|Jāna]]-śruteya'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 6, 3). <br>

उलूक
<u>'''Ulūka'''</u> is the ordinary word for ‘owl’ from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_395/> onwards. The bird was noted for its cry,<ref name=fx2_ve1_395/> and was deemed the harbinger of ill-fortune (''nairṛta'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_395/> Owls were offered at the horse sacrifice to the forest trees,<ref name=fx4_ve1_395/> no doubt because they roosted there.<br>

उलूखल
<u>'''Ulūkhala'''</u> is the regular expression for ‘mortar’ from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_396/> onwards, occurring frequently also in the compound<ref name=fx2_ve1_396/> Ulūkala-[[मुसल|musala]], ‘mortar and pestle.’ The exact construction of the vessel is quite unkown till we reach the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period.<br>

उल्का
<u>'''Ulkā'''</u> regularly denotes a meteor from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_397/> onwards. In the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve1_397/> it also signifies a ‘firebrand.’ The much rarer form Ulkuṣī<ref name=fx3_ve1_397/> has both senses.<br>

उल्मुक
<u>'''Ulmuka'''</u> is the common word in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_398/> for ‘firebrand,’ from which a coal (''aṅgāra'')<ref name=fx2_ve1_398/> could be taken.<br>

उल्मुकवक्षयण
<u>'''Ulmukavakṣayaṇa'''</u> is an expression that occurs several times in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_399/> signifying a ‘means of extinguishing (''ava-kṣayaṇa'') a firebrand,’ or possibly more precisely ‘tongs.’ Compare '''[[अङ्गारावक्षयण|Aṅgārāvakṣayaṇa]].''' <br>

उशनस् काव्य
<u>'''Uśanas Kāvya'''</u> is an ancient seer, already a half-mythical figure in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_400/> where he is often mentioned, especially as associated with [[कुत्स|Kutsa]] and Indra. Later on<ref name=fx2_ve1_400/> he becomes the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of the Asuras in their contests with the gods. A variant of his name is Kavi Uśanas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_400/> He appears in the Brāhmaṇas as a teacher also.<ref name=fx4_ve1_400/><br>

उशना
<u>'''Uśanā'''</u> occurs in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 4, 3, 13; iv. 2, 5, 15) as the name of a plant from which Soma was prepared.<br>

उशीनर
<u>'''Uśīnara'''</u>--In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Brāhmaṇā<ref name=fx1_ve1_402/> the Kuru-Pañcālas are mentioned as dwelling together in the ‘Middle Country’ with the Vaśas and the Uśīnaras. In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_402/> also the Uśīnaras are associated with the Kuru-Pañcālas and Vaśas, but in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_402/> the Uśīnaras and Vaśas are regarded as northerners. In the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_402/> the people is alluded to in one passage by reference to their queen, Uśīnarāṇī. Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve1_402/> thinks that the Uśīnaras earlier lived farther to the north-west, but for this there is no clear evidence. His theory is based merely on the fact that the Anukramaṇī (Index) of the Rigveda ascribes one hymn<ref name=fx6_ve1_402/> to [[शिबि|Śibi]] Auśīnara, and that the Śibis were known to Alexander's followers as ,<ref name=fx7_ve1_402/> living between the Indus and the Akesines (Chenab). But this is in no way conclusive, as the Śibis, at any rate in Epic times,<ref name=fx8_ve1_402/> occupied the land to the north of [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]], and there is no reason whatever to show that in the Vedic period the Uśīnaras were farther west than the ‘Middle Country.’ <br>

उष
<u>'''Uṣa,'''</u> ‘salt ground,’ occurs as a variant of [[ऊष|Ūṣa]] in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (i. 6, 3).<br>

उषस्त चाक्रायण
<u>'''Uṣasta Cākrāyaṇa'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka (iii. 5, 1) and Chāndogya (i. 10, 1; 11, 1) Upaniṣads, the name in the latter work appearing as Uṣasti.<br>

उष्टि
<u>'''Uṣṭi, Uṣṭra.'''</u>--Both of these words, of which the former is quite rare,<ref name=fx1_ve1_405/> must have the same sense. Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_405/> and Aufrecht<ref name=fx3_ve1_405/> hold that in the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_405/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx5_ve1_405/> the sense is ‘humped bull’ or ‘buffalo,’ but the former thinks that in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx6_ve1_405/> the sense is doubtful, and ‘camel’ may be meant. Hopkins<ref name=fx7_ve1_405/> is decidedly of opinion that the sense in every case is ‘camel.’ The animal was used as a beast of burden yoked in fours.<ref name=fx8_ve1_405/><br>

उष्णीष
<u>'''Uṣṇīṣa'''</u> denotes the ‘turban’ worn by Vedic Indians, men and women<ref name=fx1_ve1_406/> alike. The Vrātya's turban is expressly referred to in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_406/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_406/> A turban was also worn at the [[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_406/> and the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_406/> ceremonies by the king as a token of his position.<br>

उष्यल
<u>'''Uṣyala'''</u> occurs once in the description of the couch or the bridal car in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_407/> where it seems to mean the four ‘frame-pieces.’ The form is doubtful: ''uṣpala'' is possible.<ref name=fx2_ve1_407/> <br>

उस्र
<u>'''Usra,'''</u> m.; '''Usrā,''' f.; '''Usrika,''' m.; '''Usriya,''' m.; '''Usriyā,''' f. All these words denote a ‘bull’ or a ‘cow,’ occurring frequently in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_408/> and sometimes later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_408/> but usually with some reference to the morning light. In some passages the sense is doubtful. See '''Go.'''<br>

ऊर्जयन्त् औपमन्यव
<u>'''Ūrjayant Aupamanyava'''</u> is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_409/> as a pupil of '''[[भानुमन्त् औपमन्यव|Bhānumant Aupamanyava]].'''<br>

ऊर्जयन्ती
<u>'''Ūrjayantī'''</u> is regarded by Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve1_410/> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_410/> as the name of a fort, the stronghold of '''[[नार्मर|Nārmara]].''' The verse is, however, quite unintelligible.<ref name=fx3_ve1_410/><br>

ऊर्जव्य
<u>'''Ūrjavya,'''</u> a word occurring only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_411/> is taken by Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_411/> to be the name of a sacrificer. Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve1_411/> however, regards the word as an adjective meaning ‘rich in strength,’ and this is the more probable interpretation.<br>

ऊर्ण-नाभी
<u>'''Ūrṇa-nābhī,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_412/> '''Ūrṇa-vābhi, [[ऊर्णा|Ūrṇā]]-vant''' are all names of the spider in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas in allusion to the insect's spinning threads of wool, as it were. <br>

ऊर्णा
<u>'''Ūrṇā,'''</u> ‘wool,’ is very frequently mentioned from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_413/> onwards. The [[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]] country was famous for its wool,<ref name=fx2_ve1_413/> like [[गन्धार|Gandhāra]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_413/> for its sheep. The term for the separate tufts was ''[[पर्वन्|parvan]]''<ref name=fx4_ve1_413/> or ''[[परुस्|parus]].''<ref name=fx5_ve1_413/> ‘Soft as wool’ (''ūrṇa-mradas'')<ref name=fx6_ve1_413/> is not a rare epithet. The sheep is called ‘woolly’ (''[[ऊर्णावती|ūrṇāvatī]]'').<ref name=fx7_ve1_413/> ‘Woollen thread’ (''[[ऊर्णा|ūrṇā]]-[[सूत्र|sūtra]]'') is repeatedly referred to in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx8_ve1_413/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx9_ve1_413/> The word ''[[ऊर्णा|ūrṇā]]'' was not restricted to the sense of sheep's wool,<ref name=fx10_ve1_413/> but might denote goat's hair also.<ref name=fx11_ve1_413/><br>

ऊर्णा-वती
<u>'''Ūrṇā-vatī.'''</u>--In the hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_414/> which celebrates the rivers Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_414/> finds a reference to an affluent of the Indus called [[ऊर्णावती|Ūrṇāvatī]]. This interpretation, however, seems certainly wrong. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_414/> renders the word merely as ‘woolly,’ and Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve1_414/> rejects Ludwig's explanation on the ground that it throws the structure of the hymn into confusion. Pischel<ref name=fx5_ve1_414/> makes the word an epithet of the Indus, ‘rich in sheep.’<br>

ऊर्दर
<u>'''Ūrdara.'''</u>--This word occurs once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_415/> when reference is made to filling Indra with Soma as one fills an  [[ऊर्दर|Ūrdara]] with grain ('''Yava'''). Sāyaṇa renders it granāry, but Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_415/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_415/> seem more correct in simply making it a measure for holding grain, or ‘garner.’<br>

ऊल
<u>'''Ūla'''</u> is a variant of '''Ula.'''<br>

ऊष
<u>'''Ūṣa'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_417/> and Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve1_417/> denotes salt ground suited for cattle. ''Cf.'' '''[[उष|Uṣa]].'''<br>

ऋक्ष
<u>'''1. Ṛkṣa,'''</u> ‘bear,’ is found only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_418/> and seldom later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_418/> the animal having evidently been scarce in the regions occupied by the Vedic Indians. Not more frequent<ref name=fx3_ve1_418/> is the use of the word in the plural to denote the ‘seven bears,’ later called the ‘seven [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]],’<ref name=fx4_ve1_418/> the constellation of the ‘Great Bear’ (, ''ursa'').<br>

ऋक्ष
<u>'''2. Ṛkṣa'''</u> is the name of a patron mentioned in one verse of a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_419/> his son being referred to in the next verse as '''[[आर्क्ष|Ārkṣa]].'''<br>

ऋक्षाका
<u>'''Ṛkṣākā'''</u> is a word occurring once in an obscure passage of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_420/> The sense is quite unknown. Weber<ref name=fx2_ve1_420/> thinks it refers to the ‘milky way,’ but his view rests on no evidence. Whitney<ref name=fx3_ve1_420/> despairs of the passage. <br>

ऋक्षीका
<u>'''Ṛkṣīkā,'''</u> a word found in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_421/> the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_421/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_421/> appears to denote a demon. Harisvāmin, however, in his commentary on the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], connects the word with '''[[ऋक्ष|Ṛkṣa]],''' as meaning ‘bear.’<br>

ऋग्-वेद
<u>'''Ṛg-veda,'''</u> the formal name of the collection of Ṛcs, first appears in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx1_ve1_422/> and thereafter frequently in the Āraṇyakas<ref name=fx2_ve1_422/> and Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx3_ve1_422/><br>

ऋजिश्वन्
<u>'''Ṛjiśvan'''</u> is mentioned several times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_423/> but always in a vague manner, as if very ancient. He assists Indra in fights against demoniac figures like [[पिप्रु|Pipru]] and the dusky brood (''[[कृष्ण|kṛṣṇa]]-garbhāḥ''). According to Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve1_423/> he was called Auśija's son,<ref name=fx3_ve1_423/> but this is doubtful. He is twice<ref name=fx4_ve1_423/> clearly called [[वैदथिन|Vaidathina]], or descendant of Vidathin.<br>

ऋजूनस्
<u>'''Ṛjūnas'''</u> is mentioned once only in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_424/> along with six other Soma sacrificers.<br>

ऋज्राश्व
<u>'''Ṛjrāśva'''</u> appears in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_425/> as one of the '''Vārṣāgiras,''' along with '''[[अम्बरीष|Ambarīṣa]], [[सुराधस्|Surādhas]], [[सहदेव|Sahadeva]],''' and '''[[भयमान|Bhayamāna]],''' and as apparently victorious in a race. Elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve1_425/> in the  Rigveda he is celebrated as having been blinded by his father for slaying one hundred rams for a she-wolf, and as having been restored to sight by the Aśvins, a legend of quite obscure meaning.<br><br>''Cf.'' Macdonell, ''Vedic Mythology,'' p. 52.<br>

ऋण
<u>'''Ṛṇa,'''</u> ‘debt,’ is repeatedly mentioned from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_426/> onwards, having apparently been a normal condition among the Vedic Indians. Reference is often made<ref name=fx2_ve1_426/> to debts contracted at dicing. To pay off a debt was called ''ṛṇaṃ saṃ-nī.''<ref name=fx3_ve1_426/> Allusion is made to debt contracted without intention of payment.<ref name=fx4_ve1_426/><br><br>The result of non-payment of a debt might be very serious: the dicer might fall into slavery.<ref name=fx5_ve1_426/> Debtors, like other malefactors, such as thieves, were frequently bound by their creditors to posts (''[[द्रु-पद|dru-pada]]''),<ref name=fx6_ve1_426/> presumably as a means of putting pressure on them or their friends to pay up the debt.<br><br>The amount of interest payable is impossible to make out. In one passage of the Rigveda and Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_426/> an eighth (''[[शफ|śapha]]'') and a sixteenth (''[[कला|kalā]]'') are mentioned as paid, but it is quite uncertain whether interest or an instalment of the principal is meant. Presumably the interest would be paid in kind.<br><br>How far a debt was a heritable interest or obligation does not appear. The [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_426/> regards three hymns of the  Atharvaveda<ref name=fx9_ve1_426/> as applicable to the occasion of the payment of a debt after the creditor's decease. For the payment of a debt. by a relation of the debtor the evidence is still less clear.<ref name=fx10_ve1_426/><br><br>Zimmer<ref name=fx11_ve1_426/> thinks that payments of debt were made in the presence of witnesses who could be appealed to in case of dispute. This conclusion is, however, very uncertain, resting solely on a vague verse in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx12_ve1_426/><br>

ऋणं-चय
<u>'''Ṛṇaṃ-caya,'''</u> a prince of the '''Ruśamas,''' is celebrated in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) of the Rigveda (v. 30, 12. 14) for his generosity to a poet named '''[[बभ्रु|Babhru]].'''<br><br>''Cf.'' Zimmer, ''Altindisches Leben,'' 129; Bṛhadevatā, ed. Macdonell, 2, 169, 174.<br>

ऋतु
<u>'''Ṛtu,'''</u> ‘season,’ is a term repeatedly mentioned from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_428/> onwards, Three seasons of the year are often alluded to,<ref name=fx2_ve1_428/> but the names are not usually specified. In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_428/> spring (''[[वसन्त|vasanta]]''), summer (''[[ग्रीष्म|grīṣma]]''), and autumn (''[[शरद्|śarad]]'') are given. The Rigveda knows also the rainy season (''[[प्रा-वृष्|prā-vṛṣ]]'') and the winter (''[[हिमा|himā]], [[हेमन्त|hemanta]]''). A more usual<ref name=fx4_ve1_428/> division (not found in the Rigveda) is into five seasons,  ''[[वसन्त|vasanta]], [[ग्रीष्म|grīṣma]], varṣā, [[शरद्|śarad]], hemama-siśira,'' but occasionally the five are otherwise divided, ''varṣā-[[शरद्|śarad]]'' being made one season.<ref name=fx5_ve1_428/> Sometimes six<ref name=fx6_ve1_428/> seasons are reckoned, ''[[हेमन्त|hemanta]]'' and ''[[शिशिर|śiśira]]'' being divided, so that the six seasons can be made parallel to the twelve months of the year. A still more artificial arrangement<ref name=fx7_ve1_428/> makes the seasons seven, possibly by reckoning the intercalary month as a season, as Weber and Zimmer<ref name=fx8_ve1_428/> hold, or more probably because of the predilection for the number seven, as Roth<ref name=fx9_ve1_428/> suggests. Occasionally the word ''[[ऋतु|ṛtu]]'' is applied to the months.<ref name=fx10_ve1_428/> The last season, according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx11_ve1_428/> is ''[[हेमन्त|hemanta]].''<br><br>The growth of the division of the seasons from three to five is rightly explained by Zimmer<ref name=fx12_ve1_428/> as indicating the advance of the Vedic Indians towards the east. It is not Rigvedic, but dominates the later Saṃhitās. Traces of an earlier division of the year into winter and summer do not appear clearly in the Rigveda, where the appropriate words ''[[हिमा|himā]]'' and ''[[समा|samā]]'' are merely general appellations of the year, and where ''[[शरद्|śarad]]''<ref name=fx13_ve1_428/> is commoner than either as a designation of the year, because it denotes the harvest, a time of overwhelming importance to a young agricultural people. The division of the year in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx14_ve1_428/> into two periods of six months is merely formal, and in no way an indication of old tradition. <br>

ऋतु-पर्ण
<u>'''Ṛtu-parṇa'''</u> appears in a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]-like passage of the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_429/> as son of [[भङ्गाश्विन|Bhaṅgāśvina]] and king of [[शफाल|Śaphāla]]. In the Āpastamba Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_429/> are mentioned [[ऋतुपर्ण|Ṛtuparṇa]]-Kayovadhī Bhaṅgyaśvinau.<br>

ऋत्व्-इज्
<u>'''Ṛtv-ij'''</u> is the regular term for ‘sacrificial priest,’ covering all the different kinds of priests employed at the sacrifice. It appears certain that all the priests were Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_430/> The number of priests officiating at a sacrifice with different functions was almost certainly seven. The oldest list, occurring in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_430/> enumerates their names as [[होतृ|Hotṛ]], [[पोतृ|Potṛ]], [[नेष्टृ|Neṣṭṛ]], Agnīdh, [[प्रशास्तृ|Praśāstṛ]], [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]], [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], besides the institutor of the sacrifice. The number of seven probably explains the phrase ‘seven Hotṛs’ occurring so frequently in the Rigveda, and is most likely connected with that of the mythical ‘seven [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]].’ It may be compared with the eight of Iran.<ref name=fx3_ve1_430/> The chief of the seven priests was the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]], who was the singer of the hymns, and in the early times their composer also. The [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]] performed the practical work of the sacrifice, and accompanied his performance with muttered formulas of prayer and deprecation of evil. His chief assistance was derived from the Agnīdh, the two performing the smaller sacrifices without other help in practical matters. The [[प्रशास्तृ|Praśāstṛ]], Upavaktṛ, or Maitrāvaruṇa, as he was variously called, appeared only in the greater sacrifices as giving instructions to the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]], and as entrusted with certain litanies. The [[पोतृ|Potṛ]], [[नेष्टृ|Neṣṭṛ]], and [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] belonged to the ritual of the Soma sacrifice, the latter being later styled [[ब्राह्मणाच्छंसिन्|Brāhmaṇācchaṃsin]] to distinguish him from the priest who in the later  ritual acted as supervisor. Other priests referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_430/> are the singers of Sāmans or chants, the Udgātṛ and his assistant the [[प्रस्तोतृ|Prastotṛ]], while the [[प्रतिहर्तृ|Pratihartṛ]], another assistant, though not mentioned, may quite well have been known. Their functions undoubtedly represent a later stage of the ritual, the development of the elaborate series of sacrificial calls on the one hand, and on the other the use of long hymns addressed to the Soma plant. Other priests, such as the Achāvāka,<ref name=fx5_ve1_430/> the Grāvastut, the Unnetṛ, and the [[सुब्रह्मण्य|Subrahmaṇya]], were known later in the developed ritual of the Brāhmaṇas, making in all sixteen priests, who were technically and artificially classed in four groups<ref name=fx6_ve1_430/> [[होतृ|Hotṛ]], Maitrāvaruṇa, Achāvāka, and Grāvastut; Udgātṛ, [[प्रस्तोतृ|Prastotṛ]], [[प्रतिहर्तृ|Pratihartṛ]], and [[सुब्रह्मण्य|Subrahmaṇya]]; [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]], Pratisthātṛ, [[नेष्टृ|Neṣṭṛ]], and Unnetṛ; [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], [[ब्राह्मणाच्छंसिन्|Brāhmaṇācchaṃsin]], Agnīdhra, and Petṛ.<br><br>Apart from all these priests was the '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]],''' who was the spiritual adviser of the king in all his religious duties. Geldner<ref name=fx7_ve1_430/> holds that, as a rule, when the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] actually took part in one of the great sacrifices he played the part of the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], in the sense of the priest who superintended the whole conduct of the ritual. He sees evidence for this view in a considerable number of passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx8_ve1_430/> and the later literature,<ref name=fx9_ve1_430/> where [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] and [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] were combined or identified. Oldenberg,<ref name=fx10_ve1_430/> however, more correctly points out  that in the earlier period this was not the case: the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] was then normally the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]], the singer of the most important of the songs; it was only later that the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], who in the capacity of overseer of the rite is not known to the Rigveda, acquired the function of general supervision hitherto exercised by the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], who was ''ex officio'' skilled in the use of magic and in guarding the king by spells which could also be applied to guarding the sacrifice from evil demons. With this agrees the fact that Agni, pre-eminently<ref name=fx11_ve1_430/> the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of men, is also a [[होतृ|Hotṛ]], and that the two divine Hotṛs of the Āprī hymns are called<ref name=fx12_ve1_430/> the divine Purohitas. On the other hand, the rule is explicitly recognized in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx13_ve1_430/> that a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] should have a [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] as a [[पुरोहित|Purohita]]; and in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx14_ve1_430/> the [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] family have a special claim to the office of [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]]-[[पुरोहित|Purohita]], perhaps an indication that it was they who first as Purohitas exchanged the function of Hotṛs for that of Brahmans in the sacrificial ritual.<br><br>The sacrifices were performed for an individual in the great majority of cases. The Sattra,<ref name=fx15_ve1_430/> or prolonged sacrificial session, was, however, performed for the common benefit of the priests taking part in it, though its advantageous results could only be secured if all the members actually engaged were consecrated (''dīkṣita''). Sacrifices for a people as such were unknown. The sacrifice for the king was, it is true, intended to bring about the prosperity of his people also; but it is characteristic that the prayer<ref name=fx16_ve1_430/> for welfare includes by name only the priest and the king, referring to the people indirectly in connexion with the prosperity of their cattle and agriculture. <br>

ऋश्य
<u>'''Ṛśya'''</u>--This is the correct<ref name=fx1_ve1_431/> spelling of a word that occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_431/> and the later literature<ref name=fx3_ve1_431/> meaning ‘stag,’ the feminine being '''[[रोहित्|Rohit]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_431/> Apparently deer were caught in pits (''[[ऋश्य|ṛśya]]-da'').<ref name=fx5_ve1_431/> The procreative power of the stag (''ārśya vṛṣṇya'') was celebrated.<ref name=fx6_ve1_431/><br>

ऋषभ
<u>'''1. Ṛṣabha'''</u> is the common name of the ‘bull’ from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_432/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve1_432/> See also '''Go.'''<br>

ऋषभ
<u>'''2. Ṛṣabha,'''</u> king of the Śviknas, appears in the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_433/> with the patronymic [[याज्ञतुर|Yājñatura]], as one of those who performed an [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] or horse sacrifice. He is also mentioned there<ref name=fx2_ve1_433/> as having probably been the source of a saying of '''Gaurīviti Śāktya's.'''<br>

ऋषभ
<u>'''3. Ṛṣabha'''</u> is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 17) as a son of [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]].<br>

ऋषि
<u>'''Ṛṣi,'''</u> ‘seer,’ is primarily a composer of hymns to the gods. In the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_435/> reference is often made to previous singers and to contemporary poets. Old poems were inherited and refurbished by members of the composer's family,<ref name=fx2_ve1_435/> but the great aim of the singers was to produce new and approved hymns.<ref name=fx3_ve1_435/> It is not till the time of the Brāhmaṇas that the  composition of hymns appears to have fallen into disuse,<ref name=fx4_ve1_435/> though poetry was still produced, for example, in the form of '''Gāthās,''' which the priests were required to compose themselves<ref name=fx5_ve1_435/> and sing to the accompaniment of the lute at the sacrifice. The [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] was the most exalted of Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx6_ve1_435/> and his skill, which is often compared with that of a carpenter,<ref name=fx7_ve1_435/> was regarded as heaven-sent.<ref name=fx8_ve1_435/> The [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], whether as [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] or as [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] (see '''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]]'''), was a singer.<ref name=fx9_ve1_435/> No doubt the [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]] were normally<ref name=fx10_ve1_435/> attached to the houses of the great, the petty kings of Vedic times, or the nobles of the royal household. Nor need it be doubted that occasionally<ref name=fx11_ve1_435/> the princes themselves essayed poetry: a [[राजन्यर्षि|Rājanyarṣi]], the prototype of the later Rājarṣi or ‘royal seer,’ who appears in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx12_ve1_435/> though he must be mythical as Oldenberg<ref name=fx13_ve1_435/> points out, indicates that kings cultivated poetry<ref name=fx14_ve1_435/> just as later they engaged in philosophic disputations.<ref name=fx15_ve1_435/> Normally, however, the poetical function is Brahminical, Viśāmitra and others not being kings, but merely Brāhmaṇas, in the Rigveda.<br><br>In the later literature the [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]] are the poets of the hymns preserved in the Saṃhitās. a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] being regularly<ref name=fx16_ve1_435/> cited when a Vedic Saṃhitā is quoted. Moreover, the [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]] become the representatives of a sacred past, and are regarded as holy sages,  whose deeds are narrated as if they were the deeds of gods or Asuras.<ref name=fx17_ve1_435/> They are typified by a particular group of seven,<ref name=fx18_ve1_435/> mentioned four times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx19_ve1_435/> several times in the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx20_ve1_435/> and enumerated in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx21_ve1_435/> as [[गोतम|Gotama]], [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]], [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]], [[जमद्अग्नि|Jamadagni]], [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]], [[कश्यप|Kaśyapa]], and Atri. In the Rigveda itself [[कुत्स|Kutsa]],<ref name=fx22_ve1_435/> Atri,<ref name=fx23_ve1_435/> [[रेभ|Rebha]],<ref name=fx24_ve1_435/> [[अगस्त्य|Agastya]],<ref name=fx25_ve1_435/> the Kuśikas,<ref name=fx26_ve1_435/> [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]],<ref name=fx27_ve1_435/> [[व्य्अश्व|Vyaśva]],<ref name=fx28_ve1_435/> and others appear as [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]]; and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx29_ve1_435/> contains a long list, including [[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]], Agastī, [[जमद्अग्नि|Jamadagni]], Atri, [[कश्यप|Kaśyapa]], [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]], [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]], Gaviṣṭhira, [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]], [[कुत्स|Kutsa]], [[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]], [[कण्व|Kaṇva]], [[मेधातिथि|Medhātithi]], [[त्रिशोक|Triśoka]], [[उशना|Uśanā]] [[काव्य|Kāvya]], [[गोतम|Gotama]], and [[मुद्गल|Mudgala]].<br><br>Competition among the bards appears to have been known. This is one of the sides of the riddle poetry ('''[[ब्रह्मोद्य|Brahmodya]]''') that forms a distinctive feature<ref name=fx30_ve1_435/> of the Vedic ritual of the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice. In the [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] period such competitions were quite frequent. The most famous was that of [[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]], which was held at the court of [[जनक|Janaka]] of [[विदेह|Videha]], as detailed in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx31_ve1_435/> and which was a source of annoyance to '''[[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]]''' of '''Kāśī.'''<ref name=fx32_ve1_435/> According to an analogous practice, a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], like '''Uddālaka Aruṇi,''' would go about disputing with all he came across, and compete with them for a prize of money.<ref name=fx33_ve1_435/><br>

ऋषिस्
<u>'''Ṛṣis.'''</u>--The term ‘Seven Ṛṣis’ denotes the ‘Great Bear’ (see 1. '''[[ऋक्ष|Ṛkṣa]]''') in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_436/> and occasionally  later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_436/> This is probably a secondary use, instead of the seven Ṛkṣas, brought about by the frequent mention of the seven [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]].<br>

ऋष्टि
<u>'''Ṛṣṭi'''</u> is a term frequently employed in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_437/> to designate a weapon held in the hands of the Maruts, and doubtless meant to indicate lightning. That it denotes a spear in mortal warfare, as Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_437/> thinks, is not shown by a single passage.<ref name=fx3_ve1_437/><br>

ऋष्टि-षेण
<u>'''Ṛṣṭi-ṣeṇa'''</u> is mentioned in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_438/> as an explanation of the patronymic '''Ārṣṭiṣeṇa,''' but nothing else is known of him.<br>

ऋष्य-शृङ्ग
<u>'''Ṛṣya-śṛṅga'''</u> appears as a teacher, pupil of Kāśyapa, and as bearing the patronymic Kāśyapa in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] Brahmaṇa<ref name=fx1_ve1_439/> and in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_439/> The more correct spelling of the name is [[ऋश्य|Ṛśya]]-[[शृङ्ग|śṛṅga]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_439/><br>

एक-द्यू
<u>'''Eka-dyū'''</u> is mentioned as a poet in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_440/><br>

एक-यवन् गां-दम
<u>'''Eka-yavan Gāṃ-dama'''</u> is a man mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_441/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_441/> <br>

एक-राज्
<u>'''Eka-rāj,'''</u> ‘sole ruler,’ ‘monarch,’ seems to mean no more than ‘king.’ In the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_442/> the term is used metaphorically only. But it is found with the literal sense in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_442/> as well as in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve1_442/><br>

एकायन
<u>'''Ekāyana'''</u> denotes some object of study in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_443/> The St. Petersburg Dictionary renders it ‘doctrine (''ayana'') of unity’ (''eka''), ‘monotheism,’ while Max Müller prefers ‘ethics,’ and Monier-Williams in his Dicitionary ‘worldly wisdom.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_443/><br>

एकाष्टका
<u>'''Ekāṣṭakā.'''</u>--That [[अष्टका|Aṣṭakā]] is the eighth day after the full moon appears clearly from the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_444/> [[एकाष्टका|Ekāṣṭakā]], or ‘sole [[अष्टका|Aṣṭakā]],’ must denote not merely any [[अष्टका|Aṣṭakā]], but some particular one. Sāyaṇa, in his commentary on the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_444/> in which a whole hymn celebrates the [[एकाष्टका|Ekāṣṭakā]], fixes the date meant by the term as the eighth day in the dark half of the month of Māgha (January--February). The [[एकाष्टका|Ekāṣṭakā]], is declared in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_444/> to be the time for the consecration (''dīkṣā'') of those who are going to perform a year long sacrifice. See also '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

एजत्क
<u>'''Ejatka'''</u> is the name of an insect in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_445/><br>

एडक
<u>'''Eḍaka'''</u> appears to denote a ‘vicious ram’ in the Śatapatha<ref name=fx1_ve1_446/> and Jaiminīya<ref name=fx2_ve1_446/> Brāhmaṇas. <br>

एणी
<u>'''Eṇī'''</u> denotes the ‘female antelope’ in the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_447/> perhaps as the feminine of '''Eta.'''<br>

एत
<u>'''Eta'''</u> in the plural (''etāḥ'') denotes the steeds of the Maruts, being a swift species of deer, which are mentioned several times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_448/> and the skins of which are also said to be worn by the Maruts on their shoulders.<ref name=fx2_ve1_448/> The epithet ''pṛthubudhna,'' once applied to them in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_448/> and variously interpreted as ‘broad-hoofed,’<ref name=fx4_ve1_448/> ‘broad-chested,’<ref name=fx5_ve1_448/> and ‘broad in the hinder part,’<ref name=fx6_ve1_448/> seems to indicate that they were not gazelles.<ref name=fx7_ve1_448/><br>

एतश
<u>'''1. Etaśa'''</u> is in several passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_449/> according to Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_449/> the name of a protégé whom Indra helped against the sun-god [[सूर्य|Sūrya]]. But in all these passages [[एतश|Etaśa]] seems merely to designate the horse of the sun.<ref name=fx3_ve1_449/><br>

एतश
<u>'''2. Etaśa'''</u> is in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_450/> the name of a sage who is said to have cursed his children because they interrupted him in the midst of a rite; hence the Aitaśāyanas (descendants of [[एतश|Etaśa]]) are declared to be the worst of the Bhṛgus. The same story appears in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Brāhmaṇā<ref name=fx2_ve1_450/> where, however, the sage's name is [[ऐतश|Aitaśa]], and the Aitaśāyanas are described as the worst of the Aurvas.<br>

एदिधिषुः-पति
<u>'''Edidhiṣuḥ-pati'''</u> is a term occurring only in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_451/> where the commentator Mahīdhara interprets it as  meaning the ‘husband of a younger sister married before the elder sister.’ Though this sense is probably correct, the form is doubtless, as Delbrück<ref name=fx2_ve1_451/> points out, corrupt. See '''[[दिधिषूपति|Didhiṣūpati]].'''<br>

एरण्ड
<u>'''Eraṇḍa,'''</u> the castor-oil plant (''Ricinus communis''), is first mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (xii. 8).<br>

एवावद
<u>'''Evāvada'''</u> is regarded by Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve1_453/> in a very obscure passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_453/> as the name of a singer beside '''[[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]], [[मनस|Manasa]],''' and '''[[यजत|Yajata]].''' The commentator Sāyaṇa also interprets the word as a proper name. Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve1_453/> however, considers it to be an adjective meaning ‘truthful.’<br>

ऐकादशाक्ष मानु-तन्तव्य
<u>'''Aikādaśākṣa Mānu-tantavya'''</u> appears in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_454/> as a king who observed the rule of sacrificing when the sun had risen (''udita-homin''), and as a contemporary of '''[[नगरिन् जान-श्रुतेय|Nagarin <a class="pada_vei" href="जान">Jāna]]-śruteya».'''<br>

ऐक्ष्वाक
<u>'''Aikṣvāka,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[इक्ष्वाकु|Ikṣvāku]],’ is the patronymic borne by '''[[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_455/> Another [[ऐक्ष्वाक|Aikṣvāka]] is Vārṣṇi, a teacher mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_455/> A king '''[[हरिश्चन्द्र वैधस|Hariścandra Vaidhasa]]''' [[ऐक्ष्वाक|Aikṣvāka]] is known to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_455/> and '''Tryaruṇa''' is an [[ऐक्ष्वाक|Aikṣvāka]] in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_455/><br>

ऐतरेय
<u>'''Aitareya,'''</u> perhaps a patronymic from Itara, though the commentator Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx1_ve1_456/> regards the word as a metronymic from  Itarā, is an epithet of '''Mahidāsa''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve1_456/> and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_456/><br>

ऐतश
<u>'''Aitaśa, Aitaśāyana.'''</u> See '''[[एतश|Etaśa]], Etaśāyana.''' The Aitaśapralāpa, or ‘Discourse of [[ऐतश|Aitaśa]],’ is a part of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_457/><br>

ऐति-हासिक
<u>'''Aiti-hāsika.'''</u>--This term was applied to the people who explained the Vedic hymns by treating them as legendary history ('''[[इतिहास|Itihāsa]]'''), as Sieg<ref name=fx1_ve1_458/> shows by the passages of the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_458/> where their views are opposed to those of the '''Nairuktas,''' who relied rather on etymology. Sieg<ref name=fx3_ve1_458/> also seems right in finding them in the Naidānas of the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]:<ref name=fx4_ve1_458/> it is possible that their textbook was called the [[निदान|Nidāna]].<br>

ऐभावत
<u>'''Aibhāvata,'''</u> ‘descendant of Ibhāvant,’ is the patronymic of '''Pratīdarśa.'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_459/><br>

ऐरावत
<u>'''Airāvata,'''</u> ‘son of Irāvant,’ is the patronymic of [[धृतराष्ट्र|Dhṛtarāṣṭra]], as a snake demon,<ref name=fx1_ve1_460/> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_460/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_460/><br>

ऐलूष
<u>'''Ailūṣa,'''</u> ‘descendant of Ilūṣa,’ is the patronymic of '''[[कवष|Kavaṣa]].'''<br>

ऐष-कृत
<u>'''Aiṣa-kṛta.'''</u> See '''Śitibāhu.''' <br>

ऐषा-वीर
<u>'''Aiṣā-vīra.'''</u>--The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] once<ref name=fx1_ve1_463/> refers to the Aiṣā-vīras as officiating at a sacrifice, with the implication that they were bad sacrificers. Sāyaṇa regards the word as a proper name (‘descendants of Eṣavīra’), denoting the members of a despised family. But Roth may be right in explaining the word both in the passage mentioned above and elsewhere as meaning ‘weak’<ref name=fx2_ve1_463/> or ‘insignificant man.’<ref name=fx3_ve1_463/><br>

ऐषुमत
<u>'''Aiṣumata,'''</u> ‘descendant of Iṣumant,’ is the patronymic of '''Trāta''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_464/><br>

ओगण
<u>'''Ogaṇa'''</u> is a word occurring only once, as a plural, in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_465/> where it appears to indicate persons hostile to the seer of the hymn, and apparently opposed to the Āryan religion. Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_465/> regards the terms as the proper name of a people, but Pischel<ref name=fx3_ve1_465/> thinks that it is merely an adjective meaning ‘weak’ (''[[ओगण|ogaṇa]] = ava-gaṇa''), as in Pāli.<br>

ओतु
<u>'''Otu'''</u> in Vedic literature<ref name=fx1_ve1_466/> denotes the ‘woof’ in weaving and corresponds to '''[[तन्तु|Tantu]],''' ‘the warp,’ the roots ''vā,''<ref name=fx2_ve1_466/> ‘to weave,’ and ''tan,''<ref name=fx3_ve1_466/> to stretch,’ from which these two terms are derived, being used in parallel senses. In the process of weaving a shuttle ('''[[तसर|Tasara]]''') was used. The ‘weaver’ is termed ''vāya,''<ref name=fx4_ve1_466/> and the ‘loom’ ''veman.''<ref name=fx5_ve1_466/> A wooden peg ('''[[मयूख|Mayūkha]]''') was used to  stretch the web on, while lead was employed as a weight to extend it.<ref name=fx6_ve1_466/><br><br>The work of weaving was probably the special care of women.<ref name=fx7_ve1_466/> A metaphor in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx8_ve1_466/> personifies Night and Day as two sisters weaving the web of the year, the nights serving as warp, the days as woof.<br>

ओदन
<u>'''Odana'''</u> is a common expression<ref name=fx1_ve1_467/> denoting a mess, usually of grain cooked with milk (''[[क्षीर|kṣīra]]-pākam odanam'').<ref name=fx2_ve1_467/> Special varieties are mentioned, such as the ‘milk-mess’ (''[[क्षीरौदन|kṣīraudana]]''),<ref name=fx3_ve1_467/> the ‘curd-mess’ (''dadhy-[[ओदन|odana]]''),<ref name=fx4_ve1_467/> the ‘bean-mess’ (''mudgaudana''),<ref name=fx5_ve1_467/> the ‘sesame-mess’ (''tilaudana''),<ref name=fx6_ve1_467/> the ‘water-mess’ (''udaudana''),<ref name=fx7_ve1_467/> the ‘meat-mess’ (''[[मांसौदन|māṃsaudana]]''),<ref name=fx8_ve1_467/> the ‘ghee-mess’ (''ghṛtaudana''),<ref name=fx9_ve1_467/> etc.<br>

ओपश
<u>'''Opaśa'''</u> is a word of somewhat doubtful sense, occurring in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_468/> the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_468/> and occasionally later.<ref name=fx3_ve1_468/> It probably means a ‘plait’ as used in dressing the hair, especially of women,<ref name=fx4_ve1_468/> but apparently, in earlier times,<ref name=fx5_ve1_468/> of men also. The goddess [[सिनीवाली|Sinīvālī]] is called ''svaupaśā,''<ref name=fx6_ve1_468/> an epithet of doubtful sense, from which Zimmer<ref name=fx7_ve1_468/> conjectures that the wearing of  false plaits of hair was not unknown in Vedic times. What was the difference between the braic referred to in the epithets ''[[पृथु|pṛthu]] ṣṭuka,''<ref name=fx8_ve1_468/> ‘having broad braids,’ and ''viṣita-ṣṭuka,''<ref name=fx9_ve1_468/> ‘having loosened braids,’ and the [[ओपश|Opaśa]] cannot be made out from the evidence available. Geldner<ref name=fx10_ve1_468/> thinks that the original sense was ‘horn,’ and that when the word applies to Indra<ref name=fx11_ve1_468/> it means ‘diadem.’<br>

ओषधि
<u>'''Oṣadhi.'''</u>--Roughly speaking, the vegetable world is divided in Vedic literature<ref name=fx1_ve1_469/> between [[ओषधि|Oṣadhi]] or '''[[वीरुध्|Vīrudh]]''' ‘plants’ and '''Vana''' or '''[[वृक्ष|Vṛkṣa]]''' ‘trees.’ [[ओषधि|Oṣadhi]] is employed in opposition to [[वीरुध्|Vīrudh]] to denote plants as possessing a healing power or some other quality useful to men, while [[वीरुध्|Vīrudh]] is rather a generic term for minor vegetable growths, but sometimes,<ref name=fx2_ve1_469/> when occurring beside [[ओषधि|Oṣadhi]], signifies those plants which do not possess medicinal properties.<br><br>A list of the minor parts of which a plant is made up is given in the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx3_ve1_469/> It comprises the root (''[[मूल|mūla]]''), the panicle (''tūla''), the stem (''kāṇḍa''), the twig (''[[वल्श|valśa]]''), the flower (''[[पुष्प|puṣpa]]''), and the fruit (''[[फल|phala]]''), while trees<ref name=fx4_ve1_469/> have, in addition, a corona (''skandha''), branches (''[[शाखा|śākhā]]''), and leaves (''[[पर्ण|parṇa]]''). The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_469/> gives an elaborate, though not very intelligible, division of plants into those which expand (''pra-stṛṇatīḥ''), are bushy (''stambinīḥ''), have only one sheath (''eka-śuṅgāḥ''), are creepers (''pra-tanvatīḥ''), have many stalks (''aṃśumatīḥ''), are  jointed (''kāṇḍinīḥ''), or have spreading branches (''vi-śākhāḥ''). In the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_469/> plants are termed ‘fruitful’ (''phalinīḥ''), ‘blossoming’ (''puṣpavatīḥ''), and ‘having flowers’ (''pra-sūvarīḥ'').<br>

औक्ष-गन्धि
<u>'''Aukṣa-gandhi'''</u> (‘having the smell of bull's grease’) appears in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_470/> as the name of an Apsaras, beside other names, of which '''Guggulū''' and '''Naladī''' clearly indicate plants. This name, therefore, presumably also denotes some sort of fragrant plant. Aukṣa in the same Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_470/> means ‘bull's grease’ (from ''akṣan,'' ‘bull’).<br>

औग्र-सैन्य
<u>'''Augra-sainya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[उग्रसेन|Ugrasena]],’ is the patronymic of King '''Yuddhāmśrauṣṭi''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 21).<br>

औदन्य
<u>'''Audanya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Udanya or [[ओदन|Odana]],’ is the patronymic in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_472/> of Muṇḍibha, who is credited with inventing an expiation for the crime of slaying a Brahmin. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_472/> the name appears in the form of Audanyava.<br>

औदमय
<u>'''Audamaya'''</u> is Weber's<ref name=fx1_ve1_473/> reading of the name of the [[आत्रेय|Ātreya]], who was [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of '''[[अङ्ग वैरोचन|Aṅga Vairocana]],''' according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_473/> Aufrecht, however, in his edition more probably takes the correct form of the name to be '''Udamaya.''' <br>

औद-वाहि
<u>'''Auda-vāhi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Udavāha,’ appears in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_474/> as a teacher of [[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]].<br>

औद्-उम्बरायण
<u>'''Aud-umbarāyaṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]],’ is the patronymic of a grammarian in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (i. 1).<br>

औद्-दालकि
<u>'''Aud-dālaki,'''</u> ‘descendant of Uddālaka,’ is the patronymic of the teacher variously called '''Asurbinda'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_476/> or '''Kusurubinda,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_476/> and of '''[[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_476/><br>

औद्-भारि
<u>'''Aud-bhāri,'''</u> ‘descendant of Udbhāra,’ is the patronymic in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xi. 8, 4. 6) of '''Khaṇḍika,''' teacher of '''[[केशिन्|Keśin]].'''<br>

औप-जन्धनि
<u>'''Aupa-jandhani,'''</u> ‘descendant of Upajandhana,’ is the patronymic of a teacher mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_478/> as a pupil of '''[[आसुरि|Āsuri]],''' and also<ref name=fx2_ve1_478/> as a pupil of '''[[सायकायन|Sāyakāyana]].'''<br>

औप-तस्विनि
<u>'''Aupa-tasvini,'''</u> ‘descendant of Upatasvina,’ is the patronymic of '''[[राम|Rāma]]''' in the Śatapatha '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]''' (iv. 6, 1. 7).<br>

औप-मन्यव
<u>'''Aupa-manyava,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[उपमन्यु|Upamanyu]],’ is the patronymic of various persons: see '''[[काम्बोज|Kāmboja]], Prācīnaśāla, [[महाशाल|Mahāśāla]].''' The best known bearer of the name is the grammarian who disagreed with the onomatopetic theory of the derivation of names, and who is mentioned by [[यास्क|Yāska]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_480/> An Aupamanyavīputra occurs in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_480/> as a teacher. <br>

औपर
<u>'''Aupara,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[उपर|Upara]],’ is the patronymic of '''[[दण्ड|Daṇḍa]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vi. 2, 9, 4).<br>

औप-वेशि
<u>'''Aupa-veśi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Upaveśa,’ is the patronymic borne by '''Aruṇa,''' father of Uddālaka.<ref name=fx1_ve1_482/><br>

औपस्वती-पुत्र
<u>'''Aupasvatī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Upasvant’(?), is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[पाराशरीपुत्र|Pārāśarīputra]]''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_483/><br>

औपावि
<u>'''Aupāvi'''</u> (‘descendant of Upāva’) '''[[जान-श्रुतेय|Jāna-śruteya]]''' (‘descendant of Janaśruti’), appears in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_484/> and the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_484/> as a sacrificer who used to offer the [[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]] sacrifice and ascend to the other world.<br>

औपोदिति
<u>'''Aupoditi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Upodita,’ is the patronymic applied in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_485/> to '''Tumiñja,''' and in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_485/> to '''[[गौपालायन|Gaupālāyana]],''' son of '''Vyāghrapad,''' [[स्थपति|Sthapati]] (‘general’) of the Kurus. In the form of Aupoditeya, a metronymic from Upoditā, the name is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_485/> where the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] text calls him Tumiñja Aupoditeya [[वैयाघ्रपद्य|Vaiyāghrapadya]].<br>

और्ण-वाभ
<u>'''Aurṇa-vābha,'''</u> ‘descendant of Ūrṇavābhi.’ (1) This is the name of a pupil of '''[[कौण्डिन्य|Kauṇḍinya]]''' mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_486/> (2) A teacher of this name is frequently referred to in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]. His explanations in two passages<ref name=fx2_ve1_486/> agree with those of the Nairuktas  or etymological school of interpreters of the Rigveda. In other passages<ref name=fx3_ve1_486/> he appears rather to belong to the school of the Aitihāsikas, who relied on traditional legends. He was thus probably, as Sieg<ref name=fx4_ve1_486/> suggests, an eclectic.<br>

और्व
<u>'''Aurva,'''</u> ‘descendant of Uru or Urva,’ appears in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_487/> in close connexion with '''[[भृगु|Bhṛgu]],''' being probably a [[भृगु|Bhṛgu]] himself. As in one passage of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_487/> the descendants of [[ऐतश|Aitaśa]] are called the worst of the Aurvas, while the parallel version of the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_487/> calls them the worst of the Bhṛgus, the Aurvas must have been a branch of the larger family of the Bhṛgus. [[और्व|Aurva]] himself is said in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve1_487/> to have received offspring from Atri. In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_487/> two Aurvas are referred to as authorities. See also '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]].'''<br>

औलान
<u>'''Aulāna'''</u> is a word occurring in a single passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_488/> where it may possibly be a patronymic of '''[[शंतनु|Śaṃtanu]]''' as a ‘descendant of Ula.’ Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve1_488/> however, conjectures that the reading should be ‘Kaulāna.’ Sieg<ref name=fx3_ve1_488/> regards [[औलान|Aulāna]] as a later descendant<ref name=fx4_ve1_488/> of [[शंतनु|Śaṃtanu]], who utilized the story of Devāpi's rain-making as an introduction to his rain hymn.<br>

औलुण्ड्य
<u>'''Auluṇḍya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Uluṇḍa,’ is the patronymic of '''Supratīta''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_489/> <br>

औशिज
<u>'''Auśija,'''</u> ‘descendant of Uśij,’ is a patronymic clearly applied to '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]]''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_490/> It is also applied to '''[[ऋजिश्वन्|Ṛjiśvan]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_490/> but Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve1_490/> thinks that the correct reading of the passage in question is ''auśijasyarjiśvā,'' ‘Ṛjiśvan, son of [[औशिज|Auśija]].’ In one verse<ref name=fx4_ve1_490/> [[औशिज|Auśija]] and [[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]] are both mentioned, but in such a way that two different persons must apparently be meant. In other passages where the patronymic occurs alone, it is doubtful who is meant, or whether a proper name at all is intended.<ref name=fx5_ve1_490/> [[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]] [[औशिज|Auśija]] appears also in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_490/> and elsewhere.<br>

औष्ट्राक्षि
<u>'''Auṣṭrākṣi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Uṣṭrākṣa,’ occurs as the patronymic of '''Sāti''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_491/><br>

कंस
<u>'''Kaṃsa,'''</u> a word denoting a ‘pot or vessel of metal,’ occurs in the Atharvaveda and elsewhere.<ref name=fx1_ve1_492/><br>

ककर
<u>'''Kakara'''</u> occurs in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_493/> as the name of a victim at the horse sacrifice ([[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]]). It probably denotes some ‘sort of bird,’ as rendered by the commentator Mahīdhara.<ref name=fx2_ve1_493/><br>

ककुठ
<u>'''Kakuṭha,'''</u> a word occurring in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_494/> presumably denotes some kind of animal. According to Bo7htlingk,<ref name=fx2_ve1_494/> it is identical with '''[[कक्कट|Kakkaṭa]].''' <br>

ककुह
<u>'''Kakuha,'''</u> a word occurring several times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_495/> is understood by Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_495/> to designate part of a chariot, perhaps the seat. Ludwig,<ref name=fx3_ve1_495/> again, regards it in one passage<ref name=fx4_ve1_495/> as the proper name of a Yādava prince who took spoil from '''[[तिरिन्दिर|Tirindira]],''' the '''[[पर्शु|Parśu]],''' but this view is hardly probable.<ref name=fx5_ve1_495/> It is, on the whole, most likely that the word always means ‘chief,’ ‘pre-eminent,’ being applied as an epithet to horses, chariots, princes, etc.<ref name=fx6_ve1_495/> This is the only sense given by Grassmann,<ref name=fx7_ve1_495/> and later adopted by Roth.<ref name=fx8_ve1_495/><br>

कक्कट
<u>'''Kakkaṭa'''</u> denotes the ‘crab’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_496/> being a Prākritized form of Karkaṭa, which is common in the later literature.<ref name=fx2_ve1_496/> Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve1_496/> however, takes the word to mean a bird, and compares '''[[ककर|Kakara]].''' See also '''[[ककुठ|Kakuṭha]].'''<br>

कक्ष
<u>'''Kakṣa'''</u> is the name of two men mentioned as teachers in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]. One is [[कक्ष|Kakṣa]] [[वारक्य|Vārakya]], pupil of '''[[प्रोष्ठपद|Proṣṭhapada]] [[वारक्य|Vārakya]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_497/> and the other [[कक्ष|Kakṣa]] Vārāki<ref name=fx2_ve1_497/> or Vārakyā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_497/> pupil of '''[[दक्ष कात्यायनि आत्रेय|Dakṣa <a class="pada_vei" href="कात्यायनि">Kātyāyani]] Ātreya».''' See also '''[[उरुकक्ष|Urukakṣa]].'''<br>

कक्षीवन्त्
<u>'''Kakṣīvant'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] mentioned frequently in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_498/> and occasionally elsewhere.<ref name=fx2_ve1_498/> He appears to have been a descendant of a female slave named Uśij.<ref name=fx3_ve1_498/> He must have been a '''[[पज्र|Pajra]]''' by family, as he bears the epithet [[पज्रिय|Pajriya]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_498/>  and his descendants are called Pajras.<ref name=fx5_ve1_498/> In a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_498/> he celebrates the prince '''[[स्वनय भाव्य|Svanaya Bhāvya]],''' who dwelt on the '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]''' (Indus), as having bestowed magnificent gifts on him; and the list of Nārāśaṃsas (‘Praises of Heroes’) in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx7_ve1_498/> mentions one by [[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]] [[औशिज|Auśija]] in honour of Svanaya [[भावयव्य|Bhāvayavya]]. In his old age he obtained as a wife the maiden '''[[वृचया|Vṛcayā]].'''<ref name=fx8_ve1_498/> He appears to have lived to be a hundred,<ref name=fx9_ve1_498/> the typical length of life in the Vedas. He seems always to be thought of as belonging to the past, and in a hymn of the fourth book of the Rigveda<ref name=fx10_ve1_498/> he is mentioned with the semi-mythical '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]]''' and '''Kavi Uśanas.''' Later, also, he is a teacher of bygone days.<ref name=fx11_ve1_498/><br><br>In Vedic literature he is not connected with '''[[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]]''' beyond being once mentioned along with him in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx12_ve1_498/> But in the Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx13_ve1_498/> he appears as a son of [[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]] by a slave woman, Uśij.<br><br>Weber<ref name=fx14_ve1_498/> considers that [[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]] was originally a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]], not a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], quoting in favour of this view the fact that he is mentioned beside kings like '''[[पर आट्णार|Para Āṭṇāra]], [[वीतहव्य|Vītahavya]] [[श्रायस|Śrāyasa]],''' and '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] Paurukutsya.'''<ref name=fx15_ve1_498/> But that these are all kings is an unnecessary assumption: these persons are mentioned in the passages in question undoubtedly only as famous men of old, to whom are ascribed mythical sacrificial performances, and who thus gained numerous sons.<br>

कङ्क
<u>'''Kaṅka'''</u> is the name of a bird, usually taken to mean ‘heron,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_499/> but, at any rate in some passages, rather denoting some bird of prey.<ref name=fx2_ve1_499/> It first appears in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx3_ve1_499/> <br>

कङ्कत
<u>'''Kaṅkata'''</u> is the name of an animal mentioned once in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_500/> According to Sāyaṇa it is a destructive beast; perhaps, as Grassmann renders it, a ‘scorpion.’<br>

कङ्कतीय
<u>'''Kaṅkatīya'''</u> is the name of a family said in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_501/> to have learned from '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]]''' the piling up of the sacrificial firse (''agni-cayana.'') In the Āpastamba Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_501/> a Kaṅkati [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], no doubt the textbook of the school, is referred to. It may have been identical with the Chāgaleya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], cited in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_501/><br>

कङ्क-पर्वन्
<u>'''Kaṅka-parvan'''</u> (‘heron-jointed’?), a term occurring once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_502/> is applied to a snake, meaning perhaps ‘scorpion.’ As the Paippalāda recension has a different reading (''[[अङ्ग|aṅga]]-parvaṇaḥ''), the passage may be corrupt.<br>

कट
<u>'''Kaṭa'''</u> denotes a ‘mat,’ which was ‘made of reeds’ (''vaitasa''). The maker of mats from reeds (''[[बिदल-कारी|bidala-kārī]]'') is mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_503/> and the process of splitting reeds for the purpose is referred to in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve1_503/><br><br>^1) [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā. v. 3, 12, 2. ''Cf.'' Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], xiii. 3, 1, 3.<br>

कण्टकी-कारी
<u>'''Kaṇṭakī-kārī,'''</u> ‘worker in thorns,’ is one of the victims at the human sacrifice (Puruṣamedha) in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_504/> No doubt the thorns were cut up and used to plait mats ('''[[कट|Kaṭa]]''') or to stuff cushions. <br>

कण्व
<u>'''Kaṇva'''</u> is the name of an ancient [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] repeatedly referred to in the Rigveda and later.<ref name=fx1_ve1_505/> His sons and descendants,<ref name=fx2_ve1_505/> the Kaṇvas, are also often mentioned, especially in the eighth book of the Rigveda, the authorship of that book, as well as of part of the first, being attributed to this family. A descendant of [[कण्व|Kaṇva]] is also denoted by the name in the singular, either alone<ref name=fx3_ve1_505/> or accompanied by a patronymic, as [[कण्व|Kaṇva]] [[नार्षद|Nārṣada]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_505/> and [[कण्व|Kaṇva]] [[श्रायस|Śrāyasa]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_505/> besides in the plural the Kaṇvas Sauśravasas.<ref name=fx6_ve1_505/> The [[कण्व|Kaṇva]] family appears to have been connected with the Atri family,<ref name=fx7_ve1_505/> but not to have been of great importance.<ref name=fx8_ve1_505/> In one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx9_ve1_505/> they seem to be definitely regarded with hostility.<br>

कथा
<u>'''Kathā.'''</u>--The later use of this word<ref name=fx1_ve1_506/> in the sense of a ‘philosophical discussion’ appears in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_506/><br>

कद्रू
<u>'''Kadrū,'''</u> a word occurring only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_507/> is interpreted by Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_507/> as the name of a priest, but it more probably means a Soma vessel.<ref name=fx3_ve1_507/> <br>

कनक्नक
<u>'''Kanaknaka,'''</u> a word occurring once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_508/> either denotes a poison or is an adjective qualifying ''[[काण्डा-विष|kāṇḍā-viṣa]],'' a species of poison.<br>

कना
<u>'''Kanā, Kanyā.'''</u>--Both these words, of which the former is very rare,<ref name=fx1_ve1_509/> while the latter is the normal term from the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_509/> onwards, denote ‘maiden’ or ‘young woman.’ It is doubtful whether Kanīnakā (accented on the final syllable) has this meaning,<ref name=fx3_ve1_509/> or only denotes the pupil of the eye,<ref name=fx4_ve1_509/> which is the sense of ''kanīnakā'' or ''kanīnikā'' (both accented on the antepenultimate) in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas. See also '''[[स्त्री|Strī]].'''<br>

कपना
<u>'''Kapanā,'''</u> from its solitary occurrence in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_510/> appears to mean a ‘worm’ that destroys the leaves of trees, and is so interpreted in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_510/><br>

कपर्द
<u>'''Kaparda,'''</u> ‘braid,’ '''Kapardin,''' ‘wearing braids.’ These words refer to the Vedic custom of wearing the hair in braids or plaits. Thus a maiden is said to have her hair in four plaits (''catuṣ-kapardā''),<ref name=fx1_ve1_511/> and the goddess [[सिनीवाली|Sinīvālī]] is described as ‘wearing fair braids’ (''su-kapardā'').<ref name=fx2_ve1_511/> Men also wore their hair in this style, for both Rudra<ref name=fx3_ve1_511/> and Pūṣan<ref name=fx4_ve1_511/> are said to have done so, while the '''Vasiṣṭhas'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_511/> were distinguished by wearing their hair in a plait on the right (''[[दक्षिणतस्-कपर्द|dakṣiṇatas-kaparda]]''). The opposite was to wear one's hair ‘plain’ (''[[पुलस्ति|pulasti]]'').<ref name=fx6_ve1_511/> See also '''[[ओपश|Opaśa]].''' <br>

कपि
<u>'''1. Kapi,'''</u> ‘monkey,’ occurs only once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_512/> with reference to Vṛṣā-kapi, the ‘Man-ape,’ in the dialogue of Indra and Indrāṇī in the presence of Vṛṣākapi. There the ape is termed the ‘tawny’ (''[[हरित|harita]]''). In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_512/> the monkey is mentioned several times as hairy, and an enemy of dogs. That the ape was tamed appears from its position in the Vṛṣākapi hymn, and from the mention, in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_512/> of a '''Mayu''' as belonging to the forest. See also '''Mayu, [[मर्कट|Markaṭa]],''' and '''[[पुरुष हस्तिन्|Puruṣa Hastin]].'''<br>

कपि
<u>'''2. Kapi'''</u> is, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, another name for [[लुश|Luśa]] [[खार्गलि|Khārgali]] in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xxx. 2), but the name appears rather to be '''Luśākapi.'''<br>

कपिञ्जल
<u>'''Kapiñjala,'''</u> the name of the ‘francoline partridge’ or ‘hazelcock,’ is found in all the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_514/> and occasionally later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_514/><br>

कपिल
<u>'''Kapila'''</u> appears in the Śvetāśvatara [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_515/> as a teacher, according to Weber<ref name=fx2_ve1_515/> and Garbe,<ref name=fx3_ve1_515/> who think that the expression ''[[कपिल|kapila]] ṛṣiḥ'' there refers to the founder of the Sāṅkhya philosophy. But this is doubtful.<ref name=fx4_ve1_515/> <br>

कपि-वन भौवायन
<u>'''Kapi-vana Bhauvāyana'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_516/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_516/> A rite called Kapivana's Dvyaha (‘ceremony lasting two days’) is also referred to in the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_516/><br>

कपोत
<u>'''Kapota'''</u> is the name of a bird, probably the ‘pigeon’ (its sense in the later language), occurring from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_517/> It is associated in some passages<ref name=fx2_ve1_517/> with the owl ('''[[उलूक|Ulūka]]''') as a messenger of Nirṛti (‘dissolution,’ ‘misfortune’). This aspect of the pigeon as a bird of evil omen is probably based on an ancient belief which is also found beyond the confines of India.<ref name=fx3_ve1_517/><br>

कबन्ध आथर्वण
<u>'''Kabandha Ātharvaṇa'''</u> is mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_518/> along with '''[[सुधन्वन् आङ्गिरस|Sudhanvan Āṅgirasa]],''' as a teacher, but is semi-mythical. His son was '''[[विचारिन् काबन्धि|Vicārin Kābandhi]].'''<br>

कम-द्यू
<u>'''Kama-dyū'''</u> appears once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_519/> as the wife of '''[[विमद|Vimada]].''' She is probably identical with the ‘maiden’ (''yoṣā'') of '''[[पुरुमित्र|Purumitra]],''' no doubt his daughter. She is elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve1_519/> referred to in connexion with [[विमद|Vimada]], who appears to have taken her for his bride against the will of her father.<br>

कम्बल
<u>'''Kambala'''</u> denotes in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_520/> a ‘woollen coverlet’ or ‘blanket.’ <br>

कम्बोज
<u>'''Kamboja.--Yāska,'''</u> in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_521/> refers to the speech of the Kambojas as differing from that of the other Āryas. The Kambojas were later settled to the north-west of the Indus, and are known as Kambujiya in the old Persian inscriptions. A teacher, '''[[काम्बोज|Kāmboja]] [[औपमन्यव|Aupamanyava]],''' pupil of '''Madragāra,''' is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_521/> This points to a possible connexion of the Madras, or more probably the '''Uttara Madras,''' with the Kambojas, who probably had Iranian as well as Indian affinities.<br>

करञ्ज
<u>'''Karañja,'''</u> a word which in the Sūtras and later denotes the tree ''Pongamia glabra,'' occurs only twice in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_522/> as the name of a foe of Indra, but whether a demon or a man<ref name=fx2_ve1_522/> is intended remains uncertain.<br>

करम्भ
<u>'''Karambha'''</u> is the name, from the Rigveda onwards,<ref name=fx1_ve1_523/> of a kind of porridge made of grain ('''Yava'''), which was unhusked, parched slightly, and kneaded.<ref name=fx2_ve1_523/> It was the especial sacrificial portion of Pūṣan, no doubt in his capacity of an agricultural deity. Karmabha was also made of barley ('''[[उपवाक|Upavāka]]''')<ref name=fx3_ve1_523/> or of sesame ('''[[तिर्य|Tirya]]''').<ref name=fx4_ve1_523/> <br>

करिक्रत
<u>'''Karikrata'''</u> denotes, according to Zimmer,<ref name=fx1_ve1_524/> a snake in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_524/><br>

करीर
<u>'''Karīra,'''</u> the name of a leafless shrub, ''Capparis aphylla,'' or its fruit, first appears in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_525/><br>

करीष
<u>'''Karīṣa'''</u> denotes ‘dry cow dung’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_526/> The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_526/> shows that the value of the natural manure of animals in the fields was appreciated.<br>

कर्कन्धु
<u>'''1. Karkandhu'''</u> is the ordinary word for ‘jujube,’ the tree (''Zizyphus jujuba'') and the fruit, from the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_527/> The berry is red (''[[रोहित|rohita]]'').<ref name=fx2_ve1_527/> Compare '''[[कुवल|Kuvala]]''' and '''[[बदर|Badara]],''' which denote the fruit.<br>

कर्कन्धु
<u>'''2. Karkandhu'''</u> is only the name borne by a protégé of the Aśvins in the Rigveda (i. 112, 6). Its identity with the word for jujube indicates that the latter, though not otherwise mentioned there, was known at the time of the Rigveda.<br>

कर्करि
<u>'''Karkari,'''</u> a musical instrument, probably the ‘lute,’ occurs from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_529/> The Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_529/> mentions cattle branded on the ears with a mark resembling a lute (''[[कर्करि|karkari]]-karṇyaḥ''). <br>

कर्की
<u>'''Karkī'''</u> may denote in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_530/> a white cow,’ according to the suggestion of Roth.<ref name=fx2_ve1_530/><br>

कर्ण-शोभन
<u>'''Karṇa-śobhana'''</u> denotes an ‘ornament for the ear’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_531/> apparently for the use of men. Some deity is called ‘gold-eared’ in another passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_531/> Hopkins<ref name=fx3_ve1_531/> considers the use of ear-rings later than that of necklets and wristlets.<br>

कर्ण-श्रवस् आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Karṇa-śravas Āṅgirasa'''</u> is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 11, 14) as a seer of Sāmans or chants, the same tale being told of him as of '''Dāvasu.'''<br>

कर्मार
<u>'''Karmāra,'''</u> the ‘smith,’ is several times mentioned with approval in the Vedic Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_533/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_533/> smiths appear with fishermen (''dhīvānaḥ'') and chariot-builders (''rathakārāḥ''), all being classified as clever workers (''manīṣiṇaḥ''): possibly a quasi-caste of smiths was already developing from the guild organization that probably existed.<ref name=fx3_ve1_533/><br><br>Little is known of the smith's methods of work and of his tools. No doubt he smelted (''dhmā'') the ore in the fire; hence he is called ''[[ध्मातृ|dhmātṛ]],'' the ‘smelter.’<ref name=fx4_ve1_533/> Mention is also made of  his bellows of birds' feathers.<ref name=fx5_ve1_533/> He made metal vessels (''[[घर्म|gharma]] ayasmaya'')<ref name=fx6_ve1_533/> to be put on the fire: even the Soma cup could occasionally be made of hammered metal (''ayo-hata'').<ref name=fx7_ve1_533/><br>

कर्वर
<u>'''Karvara,'''</u> a word found in one passage of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_534/> seems to mean some kind of fish<ref name=fx2_ve1_534/> caught by a fisherman (''[[पौञ्जिष्ठ|pauñjiṣṭha]]'').<br>

कर्षू
<u>'''Karṣū,'''</u> a rare word found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_535/> denotes a ‘furrow’ or ‘trench.’<br>

कलविङ्क
<u>'''Kalaviṅka,'''</u> a name of the ‘sparrow,’ is found in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_536/> and occasionally later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_536/><br>

कलश
<u>'''Kalaśa'''</u> is, from the Rigveda onwards,<ref name=fx1_ve1_537/> a common word for ‘pot’ or ‘jar,’ probably either formed of a gourd or made of clay (unburnt or baked), as we know that both kinds of pot were in use.<ref name=fx2_ve1_537/> The wooden Soma tub (''[[द्रोण|droṇa]]-[[कलश|kalaśa]]'') is frequently referred to in the ritual. See also '''[[कोश|Kośa]].''' <br>

कला
<u>'''Kalā'''</u> denotes a fractional part, normally ‘one-sixteenth,’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_538/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_538/> It is often mentioned in connexion with '''[[शफ|Śapha]],''' ‘one-eighth.’<br>

कलि
<u>'''1. Kali.'''</u> See '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]].'''<br>

कलि
<u>'''2. Kali'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda, twice in the singular<ref name=fx1_ve1_540/> as the name of a protégé of the Aśvins, and once in the plural.<ref name=fx2_ve1_540/> The persons meant in the latter passage seem to be different from the former one. The Kalis are once mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_540/> beside the Gandharvas.<ref name=fx4_ve1_540/><br>

कल्प
<u>'''Kalpa'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (ii. 10) seems to denote [[कल्प|Kalpa]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<br>

कल्माष-ग्रीव
<u>'''Kalmāṣa-grīva'''</u> (‘speckled-neck’) is the name of a snake in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_542/><br>

कल्याण
<u>'''Kalyāṇa'''</u> is the name, in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_543/> of an [[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]] who saw the Aurṇāyava Sāman. <br>

कवच
<u>'''Kavaca'''</u> denotes a ‘corselet’ or ‘breastplate’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_544/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_544/> There is nothing to show whether it was made of metal, but that it was so is quite possible (see '''[[वर्मन्|Varman]]'''). The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_544/> refers to a ‘corselet-strap’ (''[[कवच|kavaca]]-[[पाश|pāśa]]''), which may point to a linen corselet such as those known to Herodotus.<ref name=fx4_ve1_544/><br>

कवष
<u>'''Kavaṣa'''</u> is mentioned in a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_545/> as one of those whom, together with the '''[[द्रुह्यु|Druhyu]]''' king, Indra overthrew for the '''Tṛtsus.''' The Anukramaṇī (Index) also attributes to him the authorship of several hymns of the Rigveda, including two (x. 32. 33) that deal with a prince '''Kuruśravaṇa''' and his descendant '''[[उपमश्रवस्|Upamaśravas]].''' There seems no reason to doubt this attribution, which is accepted by both Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_545/> and Geldner.<ref name=fx3_ve1_545/> The former holds that [[कवष|Kavaṣa]] was the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of the joint tribes named '''[[वैकर्ण|Vaikarṇa]],''' in whom he sees the KuruKrivi ([[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]]) peoples, and that [[कवष|Kavaṣa]] in that capacity is mentioned in the Rigveda as representative of those peoples. He also suggests that the language of Rigveda x. 33, 4 is best explained by the reduced position in which the Kuru-Krivis found themselves on their defeat by the Tṛtsus. Ludwig,<ref name=fx4_ve1_545/> on the other hand, thinks that [[कवष|Kavaṣa]] was the priest of the five peoples. Geldner<ref name=fx5_ve1_545/> holds that [[कवष|Kavaṣa]] was the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of Kuruśravaṇa, by whose son, [[उपमश्रवस्|Upamaśravas]], he was ill-treated, and that he composed Rigveda x. 33 to deprecate the anger of his royal master. Hopkins<ref name=fx6_ve1_545/> thinks that he was a king.<br><br>In the Brāhmaṇas of the Rigveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_545/> mention is made of  [[कवष|Kavaṣa]] [[ऐलूष|Ailūṣa]], who was a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] born of a female slave, and was reproached on this ground by the other [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]]. He is possibly identical with the [[कवष|Kavaṣa]] of the Rigveda.<br>

कश
<u>'''Kaśa'''</u> is the name of an unknown animal mentioned as a victim at the horse sacrifice in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_546/><br>

कशीका
<u>'''Kaśīkā'''</u> is name of an animal mentioned once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_547/> and interpreted as ‘weasel’ by the commentator Sāyaṇa. Fick<ref name=fx2_ve1_547/> suggests that the meaning is ‘pole-cat.’ Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve1_547/> takes it as ‘female ichneumon.’<br>

कशिपु
<u>'''Kaśipu'''</u> denotes a ‘mat’ or ‘cushion’ made, according to the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_548/> by women from reeds (''[[नड|naḍa]]''), which they crushed for the purpose by means of stones. On the other hand, the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_548/> refers to a mat as made of gold.<br>

कशु
<u>'''Kaśu'''</u> is the name of a prince mentioned in the Rigveda with the patronymic [[चैद्य|Caidya]], or descendant of '''Cedi,''' as a generous patron of the singer, who praises the liberality of the Cedis. Neither this king nor the Cedis appear again in Vedic literature.<br><br>^1) viii. 5, 37. ''Cf.'' Zimmer, ''Altindisches Leben,'' 129.<br>

कशो-जू
<u>'''Kaśo-jū'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda (i. 112, 14) either as a proper name or as an epithet of '''Divodāsa.''' The sense of the word is quite uncertain.<br>

कश्यप
<u>'''Kaśyapa,'''</u> a word denoting ‘tortoise,’ occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_551/> and often later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_551/> <br>

कश्यप
<u>'''Kaśyapa'''</u> is the name of a sage who is mentioned only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_552/> but is a common figure in the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve1_552/> He is always of a mythical character, as belonging to the distant past. According to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_552/> he anointed King '''[[विश्वकर्मन् भौवन|Viśvakarman Bhauvana]],''' and in the Upaniṣads<ref name=fx4_ve1_552/> he is mentioned as a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]]. The Kaśyapas appear in connexion with '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_552/><br>

कश्यप नैध्रुवि
<u>'''Kaśyapa Naidhruvi'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_553/><br>

कष्कष
<u>'''Kaṣkaṣa'''</u> designates a kind of worm in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_554/><br>

कसर्णील
<u>'''Kasarṇīla'''</u> is the name of a kind of snake in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_555/> It occurs also in the form Kasarṇīra, personified as the seer Kasarṇīra Kādraveya in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Sāṃhita.<ref name=fx2_ve1_555/><br>

क-स्तम्भी
<u>'''Ka-stambhī'''</u> denotes in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_556/> a piece of wood used as a prop for the end of a wagon-pole to rest on.<br>

कहोड कौषीतकि
<u>'''Kahoḍa Kauṣītaki'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_557/> or '''Kauṣītakeya'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_557/> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_557/> the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_557/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx1_ve1_557/> as a teacher, contemporary with [[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]]. ''Cf.'' '''[[काहोडि|Kāhoḍi]].''' <br>

काकम्बीर
<u>'''Kākambīra'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_558/> of a useful tree of some kind.<br>

काक्ष-सेनि
<u>'''Kākṣa-seni'''</u> is the patronymic (‘son of '''Kakṣasena’''') of '''Abhipratārin''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 1, 12).<br>

काक्षीवत
<u>'''Kākṣīvata.'''</u> See '''[[नोधस्|Nodhas]].'''<br>

काठक
<u>'''Kāṭhaka,'''</u> the name of the recension of the Black [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] belonging to the school of the Kaṭhas, is mentioned in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_561/> of [[यास्क|Yāska]] and in the Anupada [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_561/> The Saṃhitā which bears the name has been in part edited by L. v. Schroeder.<ref name=fx3_ve1_561/><br>

काण्ठे-विद्धि
<u>'''Kāṇṭhe-viddhi'''</u> (‘descendant of Kaṇṭheviddha’) is mentioned as a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_562/><br>

काण्ड-वीणा
<u>'''Kāṇḍa-vīṇā,'''</u> the name of a musical instrument, a kind of lute made out of joints of reed, which is mentioned as used at the Mahāvrata ceremony in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_563/><br>

काण्ड्विय
<u>'''Kāṇḍviya'''</u> is mentioned as an Udgātṛ in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 10, 2).<br>

काण्व
<u>'''Kāṇva.'''</u> See '''[[कण्व|Kaṇva]]:''' among others, '''Devātithi, [[मेधातिथि|Medhātithi]], [[वत्स|Vatsa]],''' were prominent members of the [[कण्व|Kaṇva]] family. <br>

काण्वी-पुत्र
<u>'''Kāṇvī-putra'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[कापीपुत्र|Kāpīputra]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_566/><br>

काण्वायन
<u>'''Kāṇvāyana'''</u> (‘descendant of Kaṇva’) and '''Kāṇvyāyana''' (‘descendant of Kāṇvya’) are patronymics occurring in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_567/> and the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_567/> respectively.<br>

कात्यायनि
<u>'''Kātyāyani.'''</u> See '''Dakṣa.'''<br>

कात्यायनी
<u>'''Kātyāyanī'''</u> is the name of one of the two wives of '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_569/><br>

कात्यायनी-पुत्र
<u>'''Kātyāyanī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of [[कात्यायनी|Kātyāyanī]],’ is mentioned in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_570/> as a pupil of '''[[गोतमीपुत्र|Gotamīputra]]''' and of '''[[कौशिकीपुत्र|Kauśikīputra]].''' A [[जातूकर्ण्य|Jātūkarṇya]] [[कात्यायनीपुत्र|Kātyāyanīputra]] is named as a teacher in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx2_ve1_570/><br>

कानान्ध
<u>'''Kānāndha'''</u> is mentioned in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] xxi. 10) as son of '''[[वध्र्य्अश्व|Vadhryaśva]].'''<br>

कानीत
<u>'''Kānīta'''</u> is the patronymic (‘son of Kanīta’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_572/> of '''[[पृथुश्रवस्|Pṛthuśravas]].'''<br>

कानीन
<u>'''Kānīna'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_573/> apparently denotes the ‘son of a maiden.’ See '''Pati.''' <br>

काण्डा-विष
<u>'''Kāṇḍā-viṣa'''</u> in the Atharvaveda (x. 4, 22) denotes some kind of poison. ''Cf.'' '''[[कनक्नक|Kanaknaka]].'''<br>

कापटव सु-नीथ
<u>'''Kāpaṭava Su-nītha'''</u> is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_575/> as a pupil of '''Sutemanas [[शाण्डिल्यायन|Śāṇḍilyāyana]].'''<br>

कापिलेय
<u>'''Kāpileya.'''</u>--The Kāpileyas and the '''Bābhravas''' are mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_576/> as descendants of '''[[देवरात|Devarāta]] [[वैश्वामित्र|Vaiśvāmitra]],''' the adoptive name of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]].'''<br>

कापी-पुत्र
<u>'''Kāpī-putra'''</u> (‘son of Kāpī’) is mentioned in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 1) as a pupil of '''[[आत्रेयीपुत्र|Ātreyīputra]].'''<br>

कापेय
<u>'''Kāpeya'''</u> (‘descendant of Kapi’). The Kāpeyas are mentioned as priests of '''[[चित्ररथ|Citraratha]]''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_578/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_578/> See also '''[[शौनक|Śaunaka]].'''<br>

काप्य
<u>'''Kāpya'''</u> (‘descendant of Kapi’) is the patronymic of [[सनक|Sanaka]] and [[नवक|Navaka]], two obviously fictitious persons who served at the Sattra (‘sacrificial session’) of the Vibhindukīyas in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_579/> It is also the patronymic of Patañcala in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka Upanisad.<ref name=fx2_ve1_579/> See also '''Kaiśerya.'''<br>

काबन्धि
<u>'''Kābandhi'''</u> (‘descendant of Kabandha’) is the patronymic of '''Vicārin''' in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 2, 9. 18).<br>

काम-प्रि
<u>'''Kāma-pri'''</u> (descendant of Kāmapra’) is the patronymic of '''Marutta''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 21). In the St. Petersburg Dictionary it is suggested that the reading in this passage should be ''kāmapre,'' ‘fulfilling desires,’ as an epithet of the sacrifice (''yajñe''). <br>

कामलायन
<u>'''Kāmalāyana'''</u> (‘descendant of Kamala’) is the patronymic of '''Upakosala''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 10, 1).<br>

काम्पील
<u>'''Kāmpīla.'''</u>--In one passage of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_583/> the epithet [[काम्पील|Kāmpīla]]-vāsinī is applied to a woman, perhaps the king's [[महिषी|Mahiṣī]] or chief wife, whose duty it was to sleep beside the slaughtered animal at the horse sacrifice ([[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]]). The exact interpretation of the passage is very uncertain, but both Weber<ref name=fx2_ve1_583/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_583/> agree in regarding [[काम्पील|Kāmpīla]] as the name of the town known as Kāmpīlya in the later literature, and the capital of [[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] in [[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]].<br>

काम्बोज
<u>'''Kāmboja'''</u> (‘native of '''[[कम्बोज|Kamboja]]'''’) '''[[औपमन्यव|Aupamanyava]]''' (‘descendant of Upamanyu’) is mentioned as a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_584/><br>

कारपचव
<u>'''Kārapacava'''</u> is the name in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_585/> of a place on the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]].'''<br>

कारस्कर
<u>'''Kāraskara'''</u> is the name of a people mentioned in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_586/> and the Āpastamba<ref name=fx2_ve1_586/> and Hiraṇyakeśi<ref name=fx3_ve1_586/> Sūtras. <br>

कारि
<u>'''Kāri'''</u> is the name of one of the victims of the human sacrifice (Puruṣamedha) in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_587/> and is there dedicated to ‘laughter.’ The commentator Mahīdhara<ref name=fx2_ve1_587/> interprets the word as ‘worker’ (''karaṇa-śīla''), but the St. Petersburg Dictionary suggests that it means a ‘jubilant’ person (as derived from the root ''kṛ,'' ‘to praise’).<br>

कारीरदि
<u>'''Kārīradi'''</u> is the name of persons mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 4, 4) as holding a special view of the Udgītha ([[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]] Chant).<br>

कारु
<u>'''Kāru,'''</u> ‘poet,’ is a word almost confined to the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_589/> There is evidence that the poet was regarded as a professional man, just as much as the physician ('''[[भिषज्|Bhiṣaj]]''').<ref name=fx2_ve1_589/> The poets, no doubt, mainly lived at the courts of princes amid their retainers,<ref name=fx3_ve1_589/> though they would probably also sing the praises of rich merchants. There was probably no essential connexion between the priest and the poet. Though the priest was often a poet, yet poetry can hardly have been restricted to the priestly caste. Indeed, at the horse sacrifice ([[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]]) the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_589/> expressly requires that one of the singers of panegyrics should be a [[राजन्य|Rājanya]], while the other was a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], both singing verses of their own composition. The Anukramaṇī (Index) in several cases<ref name=fx5_ve1_589/> attributes hymns of the Rigveda to princes; and even though this may often be merely the same sort of procedure<ref name=fx6_ve1_589/> as has made Śūdraka the author of the Mṛcchakaṭikā, or Harṣa of the Ratnāvalī, and has given us royal teachers of the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] doctrine,<ref name=fx7_ve1_589/> still the Indian tradition evidently saw nothing odd in the idea of nonBrāhmaṇas as poets. Most of the non-sacred poetry has,  however, disappeared, for the epic is a product, as it stands, of a later period. See also '''[[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]].'''<br>

कारोतर
<u>'''Kārotara'''</u> appears to denote in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_590/> and occasionally later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_590/> a ‘filter’ or ‘sieve’ for purifying the liquor called '''[[सुरा|Surā]].'''<br>

कारोती
<u>'''Kārotī'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ix. 5, 2, 15) as a place, or perhaps a river, where '''[[तुर कावषेय|Tura Kāvaṣeya]]''' made a fire-altar--that is, as a seat of the fire-cult ''par excellence.''<br>

कार्शकेयी-पुत्र
<u>'''Kārśakeyī-putra'''</u> (‘son of Kārśakeyī’) is the name of a man mentioned in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]. In the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] (vi. 5, 2) recension he is a pupil of '''[[प्राचीनयोगीपुत्र|Prācīnayogīputra]];''' in the Mādhyaṃdina (vi. 4, 33) recension his teacher's name is '''[[प्राश्नीपुत्र|Prāśnīputra]] [[आसुरिवासिन्|Āsurivāsin]].'''<br>

कार्ष्णायस
<u>'''Kārṣṇāyasa'''</u> (‘black metal’), a word found in the Upaniṣads,<ref name=fx1_ve1_593/> must clearly mean ‘iron.’ See '''Ayas.'''<br>

कार्ष्मन्
<u>'''Kārṣman,'''</u> a word meaning literally ‘furrow,’ and found only in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_594/> is the designation of the goal in the chariot race. The competitor probably turned round it and came back to the starting-place.<ref name=fx2_ve1_594/><br>

कार्ष्मर्य
<u>'''Kārṣmarya'''</u> is the name of a tree (''Gmelina arborea'') which is often alluded to in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_595/> the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_595/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_595/> <br>

काल
<u>'''Kāla,'''</u> the generic expression for ‘time,’ first occurs in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_596/> where, however, it is used only once, in the late tenth book. It is known to the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_596/> where [[काल|Kāla]] has already developed the sense of time as fate. The word is frequent in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx3_ve1_596/> superseding the earlier use of '''[[ऋतु|Ṛtu]].''' The more general division of time is into ‘past’ (''bhūta''), ‘present’ (''bhavat''), and ‘future’ (''bhaviṣyat'').<ref name=fx4_ve1_596/> For other divisons see '''Ahan, [[मास|Māsa]], [[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]].'''<br>

कालका
<u>'''Kālakā'''</u> is the name of one of the victims at the horse sacrifice ([[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]]) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_597/> variously identified with a bird<ref name=fx2_ve1_597/> or a chameleon.<ref name=fx3_ve1_597/><br>

काल-काञ्ज
<u>'''Kāla-kāñja.'''</u>--In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_598/> mention is made of the Kālakāñjas as being in the sky. Both Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_598/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_598/> hold that some constellation is meant. But as the defeat of the Kālakāñjas is one of Indra's exploits,<ref name=fx4_ve1_598/> it is doubtful whether any stress can be laid on that interpretation of the passage in the Atharvaveda. Whitney<ref name=fx5_ve1_598/> suggests that the three stars of Orion are meant, Bloomfield<ref name=fx6_ve1_598/> that the galaxy or the stars in general are intended. <br>

कावषेय
<u>'''Kāvaṣeya'''</u> (‘descendant of Kavaṣa’) is the constant patronymic of '''Tura.''' The Kāvaṣeyas are also mentioned as teachers of philosophical points in the Rigveda Āraṇyakas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_599/><br>

काव्य
<u>'''Kāvya'''</u> (‘descendant of Kavi’) is the constant<ref name=fx1_ve1_600/> patronymic of '''Uśanas.''' In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] it is also applied to '''Iḍhat'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_600/> and '''Ukṣṇorandhra.'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_600/><br>

काश
<u>'''Kāśa.'''</u>--Roth<ref name=fx1_ve1_601/> finds this word, which denotes a species of grass (''Saccharum spontaneum'') used for mats, etc., in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_601/> but the reading is uncertain. The word has this sense in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx3_ve1_601/><br>

काशि
<u>'''Kāśi, Kāśya.'''</u>--The name [[काशि|Kāśi]] denotes (in the plural<ref name=fx1_ve1_602/>) the people of [[काशि|Kāśi]] (Benares), and Kāśya, the king of [[काशि|Kāśi]]. The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_602/> tells of '''[[धृतराष्ट्र|Dhṛtarāṣṭra]],''' king of [[काशि|Kāśi]], who was defeated by '''[[शतानीक सात्राजित|Śatānīka Sātrājita]],''' with the result that the Kāśis, down to the time of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], gave up the kindling of the sacred fire. [[सात्राजित|Sātrājita]] was a '''[[भरत|Bharata]].''' We hear also of '''[[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]]''' as a king of [[काशि|Kāśi]];<ref name=fx3_ve1_602/> and no doubt '''Bhadrasena Ajātaśatrava,''' a contemporary of '''Uddālaka,''' was also a king of [[काशि|Kāśi]].<br><br>The Kāśis and '''Videhas''' were closely connected, as was natural in view of their geographical position. The compound name [[काशि|Kāśi]]-[[विदेह|Videha]] occurs in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]];<ref name=fx4_ve1_602/> in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_602/> '''Gārgī''' describes [[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]] as either a [[काशि|Kāśi]] or a [[विदेह|Videha]] king. The [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_602/>  mentions one [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] as acting for the kings of [[काशि|Kāśi]], [[कोसल|Kosala]], and [[विदेह|Videha]]; and the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx7_ve1_602/> mentions [[काशि|Kāśi]] and [[विदेह|Videha]] in close proximity. Weber,<ref name=fx8_ve1_602/> indeed, throws out the suggestion that the Kāśis and the Videhas together constitute the '''Uśīnaras,''' whose name is very rare in Vedic literature.<br><br>As [[कोसल|Kosala]] and [[विदेह|Videha]] were in close connexion, [[काशि|Kāśi]] and [[कोसल|Kosala]] are found combined in the compound name KāśiKauśalyas of the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx9_ve1_602/><br><br>Though [[काशि|Kāśi]] is a late word, it is quite possible that the town is older, as the river '''[[वरणावती|Varaṇāvatī]]''' referred to in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx10_ve1_602/> may be connected with the later Vārāṇasī (Benares).<br><br>It is significant that while the Kāśis, Kosalas, and Videhas were united, any relations which the Kuru-Pañcala peoples may have had with them were hostile. It is a fair conclusion that between these two great groups of peoples there did exist some political conflict as well as probably a difference of culture in some degree. The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx11_ve1_602/> in the story of the advance of Āryan civilization over [[कोसल|Kosala]] and [[विदेह|Videha]], preserves a clear tradition of this time, and a piece of evidence that in the Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] country lay the real centre of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] culture (see also '''Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]]'''). That the [[कोसल|Kosala]]-Videhas were originally settlers of older date than the Kuru-Pañcālas is reasonably obvious from their geographical position, but the true [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] culture appears to have been brought to them from the Kuru-Pañcala country. It is very probable that the East was less Āryan than the West, and that it was less completely reduced under Brahmin spiritual supremacy, as the movement of Buddhism was Eastern, and the Buddhist texts<ref name=fx12_ve1_602/> reveal a position in which the Kṣatriyas rank above Brāhmaṇas. With this agrees the fact that the later Vedic texts<ref name=fx13_ve1_602/> display  towards the people of [[मगध|Magadha]] a marked antipathy, which may be reasonably explained by that people's lack of orthodoxy, and which may perhaps be traced as far back as the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx14_ve1_602/> It is, of course, possible that the [[कोसल|Kosala]]-Videhas and Kāśis actually were merely offshoots of the tribes later known as the Kuru-Pañcālas, and that they by reason of distance and less complete subjugation of the aborigines lost their Brahminical culture. This hypothesis, however, appears less likely, though it might be supported by a literal interpretation of the legend of the Aryan migration in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx15_ve1_602/><br>

कास्यप
<u>'''Kāsyapa'''</u> (‘descendant of Kaśyapa’) is a common patronymic,<ref name=fx1_ve1_603/> and is applied specially to '''Ṛśyaśṛṅga, Devataras [[श्यावसायन|Śyāvasāyana]], [[शूष वाह्नेय|Śūṣa Vāhneya]].'''<br>

काश्यपी-बालाक्या-माठरी-पुत्र
<u>'''Kāśyapī-bālākyā-[[माठरी|māṭharī]]-putra'''</u> (‘son of Kāśyapī, Bālākyā, and Māṭharī’). This curious name is given in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_604/> to a teacher, pupil of '''[[कौत्सीपुत्र|Kautsīputra]].'''<br>

काषायण
<u>'''Kāṣāyaṇa'''</u> is mentioned in the second [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] as a teacher, pupil of [[सायकायन|Sāyakāyana]] according to the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] (iv. 6, 2), of [[सौकरायण|Saukarāyaṇa]] according to the Mādhyaṃdina recension (iv. 5, 27).<br>

काष्ठा
<u>'''Kāṣṭhā'''</u> seems to have the sense in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_606/> of ‘course’ for a chariot race. It also means in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_606/> and later<ref name=fx3_ve1_606/> ‘goal,’ either like the '''[[कार्ष्मन्|Kārṣman]]''' the turning place, or the final goal (''paramā [[काष्ठा|kāṣṭhā]]''). <br>

कास्
<u>'''Kās, Kāsa, Kāsā, Kāsikā.'''</u>--All these four forms<ref name=fx1_ve1_607/> of the same word denote ‘cough,’ which is mentioned in the Atharvaveda as accompanying a headache,<ref name=fx2_ve1_607/> as a symptom in fever ('''[[तक्मन्|Takman]]'''),<ref name=fx3_ve1_607/> and as an independent disease.<ref name=fx4_ve1_607/><br>

काहोडि
<u>'''Kāhoḍi'''</u> (‘descendant of Kahoḍa’) is the patronymic of '''[[अर्गल|Argala]]''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xxv. 5).<br>

किंशुक
<u>'''Kiṃśuka'''</u> is the name of a tree (''Butea frondosa'') mentioned in the wedding hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_609/> the bridal car being described as adorned with its blossoms (''su-[[किंशुक|kiṃśuka]]'').<br>

किकि-दीवि
<u>'''Kiki-dīvi'''</u> denotes some kind of bird, perhaps the blue jay.<ref name=fx1_ve1_610/> According to the commentator, it means ‘partridge’ (''tittiri'') in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve1_610/><br>

कितव
<u>'''Kitava,'''</u> ‘the gambler,’ is frequently referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_611/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_611/> A father is represented as chastising his son for gambling.<ref name=fx3_ve1_611/> The gambler seems at times to have fallen, along with his family, into servitude, presumably by selling himself to pay his debts.<ref name=fx4_ve1_611/> Technical names<ref name=fx5_ve1_611/> for different sorts of gamblers given in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās are Ādinava-[[दर्श|darśa]],  Kalpin, Adhi-kalpin, and [[सभा-स्थाणु|Sabhā-sthāṇu]]. None of these can be safely<ref name=fx6_ve1_611/> explained, though the last has usually<ref name=fx7_ve1_611/> been taken as a satirical name derived from the gambler's devotion to the dicing place ('''[[सभा|Sabhā]]'''), ‘pillar of the dicing hall.’ The first literally means ‘seeing ill-luck,’<ref name=fx8_ve1_611/> and may refer to the quickness of the dicer to note an error on the part of his antagonist, or to his eagerness to see the defeat of his rival.<br>

किं-पुरुष
<u>'''Kiṃ-puruṣa,'''</u> lit. ‘what sort of man,’ appears in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_612/> to designate the ‘ape,’ which is a mimic man. Possibly the same sense should be seen in the passage of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_612/> where it occurs, and where Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_612/> assumes it to refer to a contemptible man. Max Müller<ref name=fx4_ve1_612/> renders it ‘savage.’<br>

कियाम्बु
<u>'''Kiyāmbu'''</u> is the name of one of the water-plants which are to grow, according to a funeral hymn in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_613/> on the place where the body of the dead was burned. The word seems to mean ‘having some water,’ possibly by popular etymology.<ref name=fx2_ve1_613/><br>

किरात
<u>'''1. Kirāta'''</u> is a name applied to a people living in the caves of the mountains, as appears clearly from the dedication of the [[किरात|Kirāta]] to the caves (''guhā'') in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_614/> and from the reference in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_614/> to a [[किरात|Kirāta]] girl (''[[कैरातिका|kairātikā]]''), who digs a remedy on the ridges of the mountains.  Later<ref name=fx3_ve1_614/> the people called Kirātas were located in Eastern Nepal, but the name seems to have been applied to any hill folk, no doubt aborigines, though the [[मानव|Mānava]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] Śāstra<ref name=fx4_ve1_614/> regards them as degraded Kṣatriyas.<br>

किरात
<u>'''2. Kirāta.'''</u>--In the story of '''Asamāti''' there appear, as the two priests who are opposed to the '''Gaupāyanas,''' [[किरात|Kirāta]] and '''Akuli''' according to the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_615/> or [[किलात|Kilāta]] and [[आकुलि|Ākuli]] according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_615/> No doubt the name is chosen, not as that of a historic person, but as a suitable designation of a hostile priest; for it is probably identical with the name of the mountaineers described in the preceding article.<br>

किलात
<u>'''Kilāta'''</u> is the form of the name 2. '''[[किरात|Kirāta]]''' that appears in the Śatapatha, Śāṭyāyanaka, and Jaiminīya Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_616/><br>

किलास
<u>'''Kilāsa'''</u> is the name of a disease, ‘white leprosy,’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_617/> and the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā, etc.<ref name=fx2_ve1_617/> It resulted in the appearance of grey (''[[पलित|palita]]'') and white (''[[शुक्ल|śukla]], śveta'') spots all over the skin. Haug gave the same sense to ''alasa'' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_617/> but this is doubtful. The fem. Kilāsī is taken by Max Müller to mean a ‘spotted deer’ in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx4_ve1_617/> <br>

कीकट
<u>'''Kīkaṭa.'''</u>--The name of this people occurs only in one passage of the Rigveda, where they appear as hostile to the singer and as under the leadership of '''[[प्रमगन्द|Pramaganda]].''' [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_618/> declares that [[कीकट|Kīkaṭa]] was the name of a non-Āryan country, and later<ref name=fx3_ve1_618/> [[कीकट|Kīkaṭa]] is given as a synonym of [[मगध|Magadha]]. Hence Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve1_618/> concludes that the Kīkaṭas were a non-Āryan people living in the country later known as [[मगध|Magadha]]. Weber<ref name=fx5_ve1_618/> holds that this people were located in [[मगध|Magadha]], but were Āryan, though at variance with other Āryan tribes, perhaps because of heretical tendencies, for [[मगध|Magadha]] was later a seat of Buddhism. But the identification is uncertain, and is doubted by Oldenberg<ref name=fx6_ve1_618/> and Hillebrandt.<ref name=fx7_ve1_618/><br><br>^1 iii. 53, 14.<br>

कीट
<u>'''Kīṭa'''</u> is the name of a species of worm mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_619/> and frequently in the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx2_ve1_619/><br>

कीनाश
<u>'''Kīnāśa,'''</u> a name of the ploughman or cultivator of the soil, is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_620/> and the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve1_620/> See '''[[कृषि|Kṛṣi]].'''<br>

कीरि
<u>'''Kīri'''</u> is in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_621/> a regular designation of the ‘poet.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]].'''<br>

कीर्शा
<u>'''Kīrśā,'''</u> the name of some kind of animal, or perhaps bird, is mentioned in the list of victims for the horse sacrifice ([[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]]) in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_622/> <br>

कीलाल
<u>'''Kīlāla,'''</u> a word denoting a ‘sweet drink,’ is found in all the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_623/> but not in the Rigveda. As the [[सुरा-कार|Surā-kāra]], ‘maker of [[सुरा|Surā]],’ is dedicated in the list of victims in the human sacrifice<ref name=fx2_ve1_623/> (Puruṣamedha) to [[कीलाल|Kīlāla]], it must have been a drink of somewhat the same nature as the '''[[सुरा|Surā]]''' itself, possibly, as Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_623/> suggests, a kind of rum.<br>

कीश्मील
<u>'''Kīśmīla'''</u> denotes, according to Bo7htlingk,<ref name=fx1_ve1_624/> a certain disease in the Paippalāda recension of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_624/><br>

कीस्त
<u>'''Kīsta'''</u> in two passages of the '''Rigveda'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_625/> means ‘poet,’ like '''[[कीरि|Kīri]].'''<br>

कुक्कुट
<u>'''Kukkuṭa,'''</u> ‘cock,’ occurs in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_626/> only.<ref name=fx2_ve1_626/><br>

कुटरु
<u>'''Kuṭaru'''</u> is, according to the commentator Mahīdhara,<ref name=fx1_ve1_627/> synonymous with '''[[कुक्कुट|Kukkuṭa]],''' ‘cock.’ The word is found in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās only.<ref name=fx2_ve1_627/><br>

कुण्ड-पायिन्
<u>'''Kuṇḍa-pāyin'''</u> (‘drinking from a jug’) is the name of a teacher mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_628/> and in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve1_628/> <br>

कुण्ड-पाय्य
<u>'''Kuṇḍa-pāyya'''</u> (‘descendant of Kuṇḍapāyin’) is a patronymic connected with a man named '''[[शृङ्गवृष्|Śṛṅgavṛṣ]]''' in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_629/><br>

कुण्डृणाची
<u>'''Kuṇḍṛṇācī'''</u> is the name of an animal of unknown character occurring in the lists of victims at the horse sacrifice ([[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]]) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_630/> The word also occurs in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_630/> in which a bird would seem to be intended, though Sāyaṇa interprets it as meaning ‘with crooked flight’ (''kuṭila-gatyā''). In his commentary on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_630/> he takes the word to denote the houselizard (''[[गृह|gṛha]]-godhikā'').<br>

कुत्स
<u>'''Kutsa'''</u> is the name of a hero frequently mentioned in the Rigveda, which, however, gives practically no information about him, for he was no doubt already a figure of the mythic past. He is several times<ref name=fx1_ve1_631/> called [[आर्जुनेय|Ārjuneya]], ‘descendant of Arjuna,’ and is usually<ref name=fx2_ve1_631/> associated with Indra in the exploit of defeating the demon Śuṣṇa and winning the sun. He is said<ref name=fx3_ve1_631/> to have defeated '''[[स्मद्इभ|Smadibha]], [[तुग्र|Tugra]],''' and the '''Vetasus,''' but, on the other hand, he is several times<ref name=fx4_ve1_631/> mentioned with '''[[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]]''' and '''[[आयु|Āyu]]''' as being vanquished by Indra, his defeat in one passage<ref name=fx5_ve1_631/> being attributed to '''[[तूर्वयाण|Tūrvayāṇa]].''' Elsewhere<ref name=fx6_ve1_631/> he appears with [[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]] as a friend of Indra's. In the later literature he is seldom<ref name=fx7_ve1_631/> mentioned except in connexion with the myth of his binding Indra, which is found in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx8_ve1_631/> and which is based on an obscure verse in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx9_ve1_631/> <br><br>The Kutsas, or descendants of [[कुत्स|Kutsa]], are mentioned in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx10_ve1_631/><br>

कुत्स औरव
<u>'''Kutsa Aurava'''</u> (‘son of Uru’) is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_632/> as having murdered his domestic priest (''[[पुरोहित|purohita]]''), '''[[उपगु सौश्रवस|Upagu Sauśravasa]],''' because the father of the latter insisted on paying homage to Indra. This fact may be compared with the hostility to Indra of '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]]''' according to certain passages of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_632/><br>

कुन्ति
<u>'''Kunti.'''</u>--The Kuntis are referred to in an obscure and corrupt passage of the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_633/> as having defeated the '''Pañcālas.'''<br>

कुबेर वारक्य
<u>'''Kubera Vārakya'''</u> is mentioned in a list of teachers in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 41, 1) as a pupil of '''[[जयन्त|Jayanta]] [[वारक्य|Vārakya]].'''<br>

कुभा
<u>'''Kubhā'''</u> is the name of a river mentioned twice in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_635/> and no doubt identical with the modern Kabul river, the Greek .<br>

कुभ्र
<u>'''Kubhra'''</u> is the name of some animal in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (ii. 5, 3). <br>

कु-मुद
<u>'''Ku-muda'''</u> is the name of a plant mentioned with other water plants in one passage of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_637/> It is no doubt the white water-lily (''Nymphœa esculenta''), being the name of that plant in post-Vedic Sanskrit also.<br>

कुम्ब
<u>'''Kumba'''</u> is mentioned with '''[[ओपश|Opaśa]]''' and '''[[कुरीर|Kurīra]]''' as an ornament of women's hair in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_638/> Geldner<ref name=fx2_ve1_638/> thinks that, like those two words, it originally meant ‘horn,’ but this is very doubtful. Indian tradition<ref name=fx3_ve1_638/> simply regards the term as denoting a female adornment connected with the dressing of the hair.<br>

कुम्ब्या
<u>'''Kumbyā'''</u> or '''Kumvyā''' is a word mentioned after Ṛc, [[यजुस्|Yajus]], Sāman, and [[गाथा|Gāthā]] in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_639/> to denote a form of speech. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve1_639/> it appears as one of the forms of measured speech together with Ṛc and [[गाथा|Gāthā]]. The precise meaning of the term is unknown. Weber<ref name=fx3_ve1_639/> suggests the sense ‘refrain.’<br>

कुम्भ
<u>'''Kumbha'''</u> is a word of frequent occurrence in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_640/> as well as later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_640/> and denotes a ‘pot.’ Usually no doubt made of clay, it was easily broken.<ref name=fx3_ve1_640/> See also '''[[उखा|Ukhā]].'''<br>

कुम्भी-नस
<u>'''Kumbhī-nasa'''</u> (‘pot-nosed’) is the name of an animal mentioned in the list of victims at the horse sacrifice ([[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]]) in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_641/> Possibly some sort of snake is meant, as in the later literature. <br>

कुय-वाच्
<u>'''Kuya-vāc'''</u> (‘evil-speaking’) appears in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_642/> to denote a demon slain by Indra, probably as a personification of the barbarian opponents of the Āryans. The expression ''[[मृध्र-वाच्|mṛdhra-vāc]]'' (‘speaking insultingly’) is similarly used of barbarians in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_642/><br>

कुरीर
<u>'''Kurīra,'''</u> like '''[[ओपश|Opaśa]]''' and '''[[कुम्ब|Kumba]],''' denotes some sort of female head ornament in the description of the bride's adornment in the wedding hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_643/> and in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_643/> According to the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx3_ve1_643/> the goddess [[सिनीवाली|Sinīvālī]] is described by the epithets ''su-kapardā, [[सु-कुरीर|su-kurīra]], sv-opaśā,'' as wearing a beautiful head-dress.<br><br>According to Geldner,<ref name=fx4_ve1_643/> the word originally meant ‘horn’; but this is uncertain, as this sense is not required in any passage in which the term occurs.<ref name=fx5_ve1_643/><br>

कुरीरिन्
<u>'''Kurīrin'''</u> (‘having a '''[[कुरीर|Kurīra]]'''’) is a word occurring in an ambiguous passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_644/> in which it may be taken either as a noun meaning a ‘crested animal,’ perhaps as Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_644/> suggests the ‘peacock,’ or as an epithet of the word '''Aja,''' ‘goat,’ in which case it might mean ‘horned.’ But even in the latter alternative a metaphorical application of the word seems sufficient, just as in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_644/> '''[[ओपश|Opaśa]]''' is used of the horns of cattle, and thus renders unnecessary the adoption of Geldner's<ref name=fx4_ve1_644/> view that the original meaning of '''[[कुरीर|Kurīra]]''' is ‘horn.’ <br>

कुरु
<u>'''Kuru.'''</u>--The Kurus appear as by far the most important people in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] literature. There is clear evidence that it was in the country of the Kurus, or the allied KuruPañcālas, that the great Brāhmaṇas were composed.<ref name=fx1_ve1_645/> The Kurus are comparatively seldom mentioned alone, their name being usually coupled with that of the Pañcālas on account of the intimate connexion of the two peoples. The Kuru-Pañcālas are often expressly referred to as a united nation.<ref name=fx2_ve1_645/> In the land of the Kuru-Pañcālas speech is said to have its particular home;<ref name=fx3_ve1_645/> the mode of sacrifice among the Kuru-Pañcālas is proclaimed to be the best;<ref name=fx4_ve1_645/> the Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] kings perform the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]] or royal sacrifice;<ref name=fx5_ve1_645/> their princes march forth on raids in the dewy season, and return in the hot season.<ref name=fx6_ve1_645/> Later on the Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] Brahmins are famous in the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx7_ve1_645/> Weber<ref name=fx8_ve1_645/> and Grierson<ref name=fx9_ve1_645/> have sought to find traces in Vedic literature of a breach between the two tribes, the latter scholar seeing therein a confirmation of the theory that the Kurus belonged to the later stream of immigrants into India, who were specially Brahminical, as opposed to the Pañcālas, who were anti-Brahminical. In support of this view, Weber refers to the story in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx10_ve1_645/> of a dispute between '''[[वक दाल्भ्य|Vaka Dālbhya]]''' and '''[[धृतराष्ट्र वैचित्रवीर्य|Dhṛtarāṣṭra Vaicitravīrya]],''' the former being held to be by origin a [[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]], while the latter is held  to be a Kuru. But there is no trace of a quarrel between Kurus and Pañcālas in the passage in question, which merely preserves the record of a dispute on a ritual matter between a priest and a prince: the same passage refers to the Naimiṣīya sacrifice among the Kuru-Pañcālas, and emphasizes the close connexion of the two peoples.<ref name=fx11_ve1_645/> Secondly, Weber conjectures in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx12_ve1_645/> that '''[[सुभद्रिका|Subhadrikā]]''' of '''Kāmpila''' was the chief queen of the king of a tribe living in the neighbourhood of the clan, for whose king the horse sacrifice described in the Saṃhitā was performed. But the interpretation of this passage by Weber is open to grave doubt;<ref name=fx13_ve1_645/> and in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Saṃhitā<ref name=fx14_ve1_645/> a passage used at the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]] shows that the Kuru-Pañcālas had actually one king. Moreover, there is the evidence of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx15_ve1_645/> that the old name of the Pañcālas was '''[[क्रिवि|Krivi]].''' This word looks very like a variant of Kuru, and Zimmer<ref name=fx16_ve1_645/> plausibly conjectures that the Kurus and Krivis formed the '''[[वैकर्ण|Vaikarṇa]]'''<ref name=fx17_ve1_645/> of the Rigveda, especially as both peoples are found about the [[सिन्धु|Sindhu]] and the [[असिक्नी|Asiknī]].<ref name=fx18_ve1_645/><br><br>The Kurus alone are chiefly mentioned in connexion with the locality which they occupied, '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]],''' We are told, however, of a domestic priest ('''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]]''') in the service of both the Kurus and the '''Sṛñjayas,'''<ref name=fx19_ve1_645/> who must therefore at one time have been closely connected.<ref name=fx20_ve1_645/> In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] reference is made to the Kurus being saved by a mare (''aśvā''),<ref name=fx21_ve1_645/> and to some disaster which befel them owing to a hailstorm.<ref name=fx22_ve1_645/> In the Sūtras, again, a ceremony ([[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]]) of the Kurus is mentioned.<ref name=fx23_ve1_645/> There also a curse, which was pronounced on them and led to their being driven from [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]], is alluded to.<ref name=fx24_ve1_645/>  This possibly adumbrates the misfortunes of the Kauravas in the epic tradition.<br><br>In the Rigveda the Kurus do not appear under that name as a people. But mention is made of a prince, '''Kuruśravaṇa''' (‘Glory of the Kurus’),<ref name=fx25_ve1_645/> and of a '''[[पाकस्थामन् कौरयाण|Pākasthāman Kaurayāṇa]].'''<ref name=fx26_ve1_645/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx27_ve1_645/> there occurs as a king of the Kurus '''[[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]],''' whose son, '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]],''' is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx28_ve1_645/> as one of the great performers of the horse sacrifice.<br><br>It is a probable conjecture of Oldenberg's<ref name=fx29_ve1_645/> that the Kuru people, as known later, included some of the tribes referred to by other names in the Rigveda. Kuruśravaṇa, shown by his name to be connected with the Kurus, is in the Rigveda called [[त्रासदस्यव|Trāsadasyava]], ‘descendant of '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]],'''’ who is well known as a king of the '''Pūrus.''' Moreover, it is likely that the [[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]]'''Bharatas,''' who appear in the Rigveda as enemies of the Pūtus, later coalesced with them to form the Kuru people.<ref name=fx30_ve1_645/> Since the Bharatas appear so prominently in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] texts as a great people of the past, while the later literature ignores them in its list of nations, it is difficult to avoid the conclusion that they became merged in some other tribe. Moreover, there is evidence that the Bharatas occupied the territory in which the Kurus were later found. Two of them are spoken of in a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx31_ve1_645/> as having kindled fire on the '''[[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]],''' the '''[[आपया|Āpayā]],''' and the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]'''--that is to say, in the sacred places of the later [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]]. Similarly, the goddess Bhāratī (‘belonging to the Bharatas’) is constantly mentioned in the Āprī (‘propitiatory’) hymns together with [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].<ref name=fx32_ve1_645/> Again, according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], one [[भरत|Bharata]] king was victorious over the Kāśis,<ref name=fx33_ve1_645/> and another made offerings to [[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]] and [[यमुना|Yamunā]],<ref name=fx34_ve1_645/> while raids of the Bharatas against the '''Satvants''' are mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx35_ve1_645/> Nor is it  without importance that the Bharatas appear as a variant for the Kuru Pañcālas in a passage of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx36_ve1_645/> and that in the list of the great performers of the horse sacrifice the names of one Kuru and two [[भरत|Bharata]] princes are given without any mention of the people over which they ruled, while in other cases that information is specifically given.<ref name=fx37_ve1_645/><br><br>The territory of the Kuru-Pañcālas is declared in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] to be the middle country ('''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]]''').<ref name=fx38_ve1_645/> A group of the Kuru people still remained further north--the '''Uttara Kurus''' beyond the Himālaya. It appears from a passage of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] that the speech of the Northerners-that is, presumably, the Northern Kurus--and of the KuruPañcālas was similar, and regarded as specially pure.<ref name=fx39_ve1_645/> There seems little doubt that the Brahminical culture was developed in the country of the Kuru-Pañcālas, and that it spread thence east, south, and west. Traces of this are seen in the [[व्रात्य|Vrātya]] Stomas (sacrifices for the admission of non-Brahminical Āryans) of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx40_ve1_645/> and in the fact that in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka it is unusual for a Brahmin to dwell in the territory of '''[[मगध|Magadha]].'''<ref name=fx41_ve1_645/> The repeated mention of KuruPañcāla Brahmins is another indication of their missionary activity.<ref name=fx42_ve1_645/><br><br>The geographical position of the Kuru-Pañcālas renders it probable that they were later immigrants into India than the '''[[कोसल|Kosala]]-[[विदेह|Videha]]''' or the '''Kāśis,'''<ref name=fx43_ve1_645/> who must have been pushed  into their more eastward territories by a new wave of Āryan settlers from the west. But there is no evidence in Vedic literature to show in what relation of time the immigration of the latter peoples stood to that of their neighbours on the west. It has, however, been conjectured,<ref name=fx44_ve1_645/> mainly on the ground of later linguistic phenomena, which have no cogency for the Vedic period, that the Kurus were later immigrants, who, coming by a new route, thrust themselves between the original Āryan tribes which were already in occupation of the country from east to west. ''Cf.'' also '''[[कृत्वन्|Kṛtvan]].''' For other Kuru princes see '''[[कौरव्य|Kauravya]].'''<br>

कुरु-क्षेत्र
<u>'''Kuru-kṣetra'''</u> (‘land of the Kurus’) is always regarded in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] texts<ref name=fx1_ve1_646/> as a particularly sacred country. Within its boundaries flowed the rivers '''[[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]]''' and '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],''' as well as the '''[[आपया|Āpayā]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_646/> Here, too, was situated '''[[शर्यणावन्त्|Śaryaṇāvant]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_646/> which  appears to have been a lake, like that known to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] by the name of '''[[अन्यतः-प्लक्षा|Anyataḥ-plakṣā]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_646/> According to Pischel, there was also in [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]] a stream called '''[[पस्त्या|Pastyā]],'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_646/> which he sees in certain passages of the Rigveda. The boundaries of [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]] are given in a passage of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx6_ve1_646/> as being [[खाण्डव|Khāṇḍava]] on the south, the [[तूर्घ्न|Tūrghna]] on the north, and the [[परीणह्|Parīṇah]] on the west. Roughly speaking, it corresponded to the modern Sirhind.<br>

कुरुङ्ग
<u>'''Kuruṅga'''</u> is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_647/> as a prince and a patron. Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_647/> suggests that he was a king of the '''Anus,''' but for this theory there seems no good ground. As the '''Turvaśas''' are mentioned in the same verse, he may possibly have been one of their kings. The name suggests a connexion with the '''Kurus,''' and it may be noted that in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_647/> the Turvaśas are connected with the '''Pañcālas (Krivis).'''<br>

कुरु
<u>'''Kuru'''</u>-[[श्रवण|śravaṇa]] '''[[त्रासदस्यव|Trāsadasyava]]''' is alluded to as dead in a hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_648/> which refers also to his son '''[[उपमश्रवस्|Upamaśravas]],''' and his father '''[[मित्रातिथि|Mitrātithi]].''' In another hymn<ref name=fx2_ve1_648/> he is mentioned as still alive. His name connects him on the one hand with the '''Kurus,''' and on the other with '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]]''' and the '''Pūrus.'''<br>

कुरूरु
<u>'''Kurūru,'''</u> apparently the name of a species of worm, is mentioned twice in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_649/> <br>

कुर्कुर
<u>'''Kurkura'''</u> is an onomatopoetic name for the dog in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_650/> See also '''[[श्वन्|Śvan]].'''<br>

कुल
<u>'''Kula, Kula-pā.'''</u>--As an uncompounded word, Kula does not occur before the period of the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_651/> It denotes the ‘home’ or ‘house of the family,’ and by metonymy the family itself, as connected with the home. The Kula-pā (lit. ‘house protector’), or chief of the family, is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_651/> as inferior to and attendant on the '''[[व्राजपति|Vrājapati]]''' in war, the latter being perhaps the leader of the village contingent of the clan. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_651/> a girl is ironically called Kulapā, because she is left without a husband in the world, and has only Yama (the god of death) for a spouse.<br><br>The use of the term Kula points clearly to a system of individual families, each no doubt consisting of several members under the headship of the father or eldest brother, whose Kula the dwelling is. As distinct from '''[[गोत्र|Gotra]],''' Kula seems to mean the family in the narrower sense of the members who still live in one house, the undivided family. ''Cf.'' '''[[गृह|Gṛha]], [[ग्राम|Grāma]], Jana, [[विश्|Viś]].'''<br>

कुलाल
<u>'''Kulāla,'''</u> the word denoting a ‘potter,’ occurs in the [[शतरुद्रिय|Śatarudriya]], or litany to Rudra in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_652/><br>

कुलिश
<u>'''Kuliśa,'''</u> ‘axe,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda as used for the making of chariots,<ref name=fx1_ve1_653/> and also in warfare,<ref name=fx2_ve1_653/> while the Atharvaveda refers to its employment in cutting down trees.<ref name=fx3_ve1_653/> <br>

कुलीकय
<u>'''Kulīkaya'''</u> is the form in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_654/> of the name of an animal, apparently a kind of fish, as explained by Mahīdhara in his commentary, which is called Kulīpaya in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_654/> and [[पुरीकय|Purīkaya]] in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_654/> variants probably due to the faulty tradition of an unfamiliar. name.<br>

कुलीका
<u>'''Kulīkā'''</u> is the name of a bird mentioned in the list of victims at the horse sacrifice in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_655/> The Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_655/> has [[पुलीका|Pulīkā]] instead.<br>

कुलुङ्ग
<u>'''Kuluṅga'''</u> is the name of an animal, perhaps a gazelle, mentioned in the list of victims at the horse sacrifice in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_656/><br>

कुल्मल
<u>'''Kulmala'''</u> seems, in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_657/> the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_657/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_657/> to denote the neck of an arrow in which the shaft is fixed.<br>

कुमल-बर्हिस्
<u>'''Kumala-barhis'''</u> is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xv. 3, 21) as the seer of a Sāman or Chant.<br>

कुमार हारित
<u>'''Kumāra Hārita'''</u> is mentioned in the first [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_659/> as a pupil of '''[[गालव|Gālava]].'''<br>

कुल्माष
<u>'''Kulmāṣa,'''</u> a word mentioned by the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_660/> in the plural, is interpreted by the commentator as ‘bad beans’ (''kutsitā māṣāḥ''), a version adopted by Bo7htlingk in his  Dictionary.<ref name=fx2_ve1_660/> Little<ref name=fx3_ve1_660/> renders it ‘sour gruel’ in accordance with the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_660/><br>

कुल्या
<u>'''Kulyā'''</u> in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_661/> according to Muir,<ref name=fx2_ve1_661/> possibly refers to artificial watercourses flowing into a reservoir (''[[ह्रद|hrada]]''). See '''[[अवत|Avata]].'''<br>

कुवय
<u>'''Kuvaya.'''</u> See '''Kvayi.'''<br>

कुवल
<u>'''Kuvala'''</u> is a name of the jujube fruit (''Zizyphus jujuba'') occurring frequently in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_663/> and Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve1_663/> in connexion with '''[[कर्कन्धु|Karkandhu]]''' and '''[[बदर|Badara]].''' See also '''Kola.'''<br>

कुश
<u>'''Kuśa,'''</u> a word later denoting the ‘sacred grass’ (''Poa cynosuroides''), is taken by the St. Petersburg Dictionary to mean simply ‘grass’ in the passages of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] in which it occurs.<br><br>^1) ii. 5, 2, 15; iii. 1, 2, 16; v. 3, 2, 7, etc. Kuśā and Kuśī occur in Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā, iv. 5, 7; Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], iii. 6, 2, 9; [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], i. 5, 10, 1. 2, 7, apparently denoting pins of wood or metal, used as a mark in a special mode of recitation.<br>

कु-सर
<u>'''Ku-sara'''</u> is mentioned with '''[[शर|Śara]]''' and other grasses in one hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_665/> as affording lurking places for serpents.<br>

कुशिक
<u>'''Kuśika'''</u> is the probably mythical forefather<ref name=fx1_ve1_666/> of the Kuśikas, and especially the father of the most important member of that family, '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_666/> The Kuśikas are repeatedly referred  to in the third Maṇḍala of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_666/> and figure in the legend of [[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]] in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_666/> They were clearly a family of priests who attached themselves to the service of the princes of the '''Bharatas.''' They were especially devoted to the worship of Indra; hence he is styled [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] even in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx5_ve1_666/><br>

कुश्रि वाज-श्रवस
<u>'''Kuśri [[वाज|Vāja]]-śravasa'''</u> appears as a teacher concerned with the lore of the sacred fire in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_667/> and in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_667/> he is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[वाजश्रवस्|Vājaśravas]].''' It is not clear whether he is identical with the Kuśri of the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka<ref name=fx3_ve1_667/> in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension, and of the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] in the tenth book of the Śatapatha,<ref name=fx4_ve1_667/> who is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[यज्ञवचस् राजस्तम्बायन|Yajñavacas Rājastambāyana]].'''<br>

कु-षण्ड
<u>'''Ku-ṣaṇḍa'''</u> is mentioned with '''[[षण्ड|Ṣaṇḍa]]''' as a priest at the snake festival described in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_668/><br>

कुषीतक
<u>'''1. Kuṣītaka'''</u> denotes, according to the commentary on the one passage of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_669/> in which it is found, the sea crow (''[[सम्उद्र|samudra]]-kāka'')<br>

कुषीतक साम-श्रवस
<u>'''2. Kuṣītaka Sāma-śravasa'''</u> is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_670/> as the Gṛhapati, or householder at a sacrificial session, of the Kauṣītakis. <br>

कुषुम्भक
<u>'''Kuṣumbhaka'''</u> seems in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_671/> to mean a poisonous insect, Kuṣumbha in th Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_671/> clearly having the sense of a poison bag. Sāyaṇa renders it as ‘ichneumon’ (''[[नकुल|nakula]]'').<br>

कुष्ठ
<u>'''1. Kuṣṭha'''</u> is the name of a plant (''Costus speciosus'' or ''arabicus'')<ref name=fx1_ve1_672/> which is prominent in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_672/> It grew especially on the mountains, along with the Soma, on the high peaks of the Himālaya (''[[हिमवन्त्|Himavant]]'') where the eagles nest, and was thence brought east to men.<ref name=fx3_ve1_672/> Like Soma, it is said to have grown in the third heaven under the famous '''[[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]]''' tree, where the gods were wont to assemble, and thence it was brought in a golden ship.<ref name=fx4_ve1_672/> As a remedy, it held the highest place among herbs, being called by the auspicious names [[नघ-मार|Nagha-māra]] and Naghā-riṣa, and styled the offspring of Jīvala and Jīvalā, the ‘lively’ ones.<ref name=fx5_ve1_672/> It cured headache (''[[शीर्षामय|śīrṣāmaya]]''), diseases of the eyes, bodily affliction,<ref name=fx6_ve1_672/> but especially fever--hence called ‘feverdestroyer’ (''takma-nāśana'')--and consumption ('''[[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]]'''). From its general properties it was also named ‘all-healing’ (''viśvabheṣaja'').<ref name=fx7_ve1_672/> Its aromatic qualities were apparently known, as it is classed with ‘salve’ ('''[[आञ्जन|Āñjana]]''') and ‘nard’ ('''[[नलद|Nalada]]''').<ref name=fx8_ve1_672/><br>

कुष्ठ
<u>'''2. Kuṣṭha.'''</u>--In one passage of the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_673/> there is a series of fractions, '''[[कला|Kalā]], [[कुष्ठ|Kuṣṭha]], [[शफ|Śapha]], Pad,''' which appear to denote one-sixteenth, one-twelfth, one-eighth, and one-fourth respectively. <br>

कुसीदिन्
<u>'''Kusīdin'''</u> is a designation of the ‘usurer’ found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_674/> and the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_674/> and often in the Sūtras. Jolly,<ref name=fx3_ve1_674/> referring doubtless to the expression ''kusīda apratītta,''<ref name=fx4_ve1_674/> ‘a loan not yet repaid,’ occurring in connexion with ''an-[[ऋण|ṛṇa]],'' ‘free from debt,’ appears to be right in taking Kusīda to have the sense of ‘loan’ in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā. The rate of interest on loans is not specified before the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period.<ref name=fx5_ve1_674/> ''Cf.'' '''[[ऋण|Ṛṇa]].'''<br>

कुसुरुबिन्द औद्दलकि
<u>'''Kusurubinda Auddalaki'''</u> appears as an authority on ritual matters in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_675/> the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_675/> the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_675/> and the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_675/> He may have been the brother of '''[[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]],''' as suggested by Weber.<ref name=fx5_ve1_675/><br>

कुहू
<u>'''Kuhū.'''</u> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

कूचक्र
<u>'''Kūcakra'''</u> is a word occurring only once in an obscure verse of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_677/> where Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_677/> suggests that it has the sense of the wheel by which water is raised from a well. Much more probable is the interpretation of Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve1_677/> who understands it to mean the female breast.<br>

कूट
<u>'''Kūṭa,'''</u> a word found in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_678/> the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_678/> and the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx3_ve1_678/> is of doubtful signification. On the whole,  the most probable sense is hammer,<ref name=fx4_ve1_678/> which suits every passage adequately. The St. Petersburg Dictionary renders it ‘horn,’ which is the sense accepted by Whitney<ref name=fx5_ve1_678/> for the Atharvaveda passage where it occurs. Geldner<ref name=fx6_ve1_678/> thinks that it means ‘trap.’<br>

कूदी
<u>'''Kūdī,'''</u> written also Kūṭī in the manuscripts, occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_679/> and the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_679/> denoting a twig--identified by the scholiast with '''Badarī,''' the jujube--which was tied to the bodies of the dead to efface their traces, presumably in order to render the return of the spirit to the old home difficult.<br>

कूप
<u>'''Kūpa'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_680/> and later literature<ref name=fx2_ve1_680/> denoting an artificial hollow in the earth, or pit. In some cases they must have been deep, as [[त्रित|Trita]] in the myth is said to have fallen into one from which he could not escape unaided.<ref name=fx3_ve1_680/><br>

कूबर
<u>'''Kūbara'''</u> in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (ii. 1, 11) and '''Kūbarī''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iv. 6, 9, 11. 12) and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxvii. 6) denote the pole of a cart.<br>

कूर्च
<u>'''Kūrca'''</u> is found in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_682/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_682/> denoting a bundle of grass used as a seat. In one passage of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_682/> a golden [[कूर्च|Kūrca]] is referred to. <br>

कूर्म
<u>'''Kūrma,'''</u> the ‘tortoise,’ is mentioned frequently in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_683/> and Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve1_683/> but nothing is said of its characteristics. See also '''[[कश्यप|Kaśyapa]].'''<br>

कूशाम्ब स्वायव लातव्य
<u>'''Kūśāmba [[स्वायव|Svāyava]] Lātavya'''</u> is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_684/> as a priest. His name apparently means<ref name=fx2_ve1_684/> Kūśāmba,<ref name=fx3_ve1_684/> of the [[लातव्य|Lātavya]] clan, son of Svāyu.<br>

कृकलास
<u>'''Kṛkalāsa'''</u> denotes the ‘chameleon’ mentioned in the list of sacrificial victims at the horse sacrifice in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_685/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_685/> The female chameleon, Kṛkalāsī, is also referred to in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_685/> See '''[[गोधा|Godhā]]''' and '''[[शयण्डक|Śayaṇḍaka]].'''<br>

कृक-वाकु
<u>'''Kṛka-vāku,'''</u> the ‘cock,’ being named in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_686/> with sheep, goats, and other domesticated animals, was presumably tamed.<ref name=fx2_ve1_686/> In the list of victims at the horse sacrifice in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_686/> it appears as dedicated to Savitṛ: [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_686/> explains this by the fact that it declares the time of day (''kālānuvāda''). The commentator Mahīdhara<ref name=fx5_ve1_686/> explains the name by ''tāmra-cūḍa,'' ‘red-crested.’ It is of course onomatopoetic (‘calling kṛka’).<ref name=fx6_ve1_686/> See also '''[[कुक्कुट|Kukkuṭa]].''' <br>

कृत
<u>'''Kṛta.'''</u> See 2. '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]]''' and 2. '''Yuga.'''<br>

कृति
<u>'''Kṛti.'''</u>--From one passage in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_688/> where the Maruts are described as having Kṛtis, Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_688/> concludes that the word means a dagger used in war. But there is no evidence that [[कृति|Kṛti]] was ever a human weapon. See '''Asi.'''<br>

कृत्तिकास्
<u>'''Kṛttikās.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

कृत्वन्
<u>'''Kṛtvan.'''</u>--In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_690/> the word [[कृत्वन्|Kṛtvan]] in the plural is mentioned with the '''Ārjīkas''' and the five peoples. Pischel<ref name=fx2_ve1_690/> thinks that it means a people, and Sāyaṇa expressly says that the Kṛtvans designate a country.<ref name=fx3_ve1_690/> The name in that case would point to some connexion with the '''Kurus''' or '''Krivis.''' Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx4_ve1_690/> however, thinks that the word is an adjective which qualifies Ārjīkas and designates this people as magicians, being applied to them by an opponent. In favour of this view, he quotes Hiouen Thsang's statement<ref name=fx5_ve1_690/> that the neighbouring kings held the base Kaśmīrians in such scorn as to refuse all alliance with them, and to give them the name of Ki-li-to, or Kṛtyas. He suggests that the Ārjīkas settled in Kasmīr in ancient times already had the same evil reputation as their successors in later days.<br>

कृप
<u>'''Kṛpa'''</u> is mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_691/> along with [[रुशम|Ruśama]] and '''[[श्यावक|Śyāvaka]],''' as a protégé of Indra.<br>

कृमि
<u>'''Kṛmi,'''</u> ‘worm.’ In the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_692/> and especially in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_692/> worms play a considerable part. They are  regarded as poisonous, and are spoken of as found in the mountains, in forests, in waters, in plants, and in the human body. In accordance with widespread primitive ideas, they are considered to be the causes of disease in men and animals. The Atharvaveda contains three hymns<ref name=fx2_ve1_692/> as charms directed against them. The first of these hymns is of a general character, the second is meant to destroy worms in cattle, and the third is intended to cure children of worms. When found in men, worms are said to have their place in the head and ribs,<ref name=fx3_ve1_692/> and to creep into the eyes, nose, and teeth.<ref name=fx4_ve1_692/> They are described as dark brown, but white in the fore part of the body, with black ears, and as having three heads.<ref name=fx5_ve1_692/> They are given many specific names: '''[[अलाण्डु|Alāṇḍu]], [[एजत्क|Ejatka]], [[कष्कष|Kaṣkaṣa]], [[कीट|Kīṭa]], [[कुरूरु|Kurūru]], [[नीलङ्गु|Nīlaṅgu]], [[येवाष|Yevāṣa]], [[वघा|Vaghā]], [[वृक्षसर्पी|Vṛkṣasarpī]], [[शलुन|Śaluna]], [[शवर्त|Śavarta]], [[शिपवित्नुक|Śipavitnuka]], [[स्तेग|Stega]].'''<br>

कृमुक
<u>'''Kṛmuka'''</u> is the name in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_693/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_693/> of a species of wood used for fuel.<ref name=fx3_ve1_693/><br>

कृश
<u>'''Kṛśa'''</u> is mentioned with '''[[संवर्त|Saṃvarta]]''' as a pious sacrificer to Indra in one of the [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymns of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_694/> and in another<ref name=fx2_ve1_694/> as a speaker of truth, while a third is traditionally<ref name=fx3_ve1_694/> ascribed to his authorship. He seems also to be mentioned with '''[[शयु|Śayu]]''' as a protégé of the Aśvins in another hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_694/> but here the word may merely denote the ‘feeble man.’<ref name=fx5_ve1_694/> <br>

कृशन
<u>'''Kṛśana,'''</u> ‘pearl.’ In the Rigveda pearls are mentioned as adorning the car of Savitṛ<ref name=fx1_ve1_695/> as well as being used for the adornment of a horse.<ref name=fx2_ve1_695/> Hence the horse is spoken of as the ‘pearled one’ (''kṛśanāvant'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_695/> The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_695/> also refers to pearls, and mentions that ‘pearl shell’ (''śañkhaḥ kṛśanaḥ'') won from the sea was used as an amulet.<ref name=fx5_ve1_695/> The Nighaṇṭu<ref name=fx6_ve1_695/> renders the word as ‘gold.’<br>

कृशानु
<u>'''Kṛśānu'''</u> appears in the Rigveda as a mythological personage.<ref name=fx1_ve1_696/> In one verse,<ref name=fx2_ve1_696/> however, Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_696/> sees in this word the name of a bowman, but there seems no reason to dissociate this passage from the rest.<br>

कृषि
<u>'''Kṛṣi,'''</u> ‘ploughing.’ The cultivation of the soil was no doubt known to the Indians before they separated from the Iranians, as is indicated by the identity of the expressions ''yavaṃ kṛṣ'' and ''[[सस्य|sasya]]'' in the Rigveda with ''yao karesh'' and ''hahya'' in the Avesta, referring to the ploughing in of the seed and to the grain which resulted.<ref name=fx1_ve1_697/> But it is not without significance that the expressions for ploughing occur mainly in the first<ref name=fx2_ve1_697/> and tenth<ref name=fx3_ve1_697/> books of the Rigveda, and only rarely in the so-called ‘family’ books (ii.-vii.).<ref name=fx4_ve1_697/> In the Atharvaveda '''Pṛthī [[वैन्य|Vainya]]''' is credited with the origination of ploughing,<ref name=fx5_ve1_697/> and even in the Rigveda the Aśvins are spoken of as concerned with the sowing of grain by means of the plough.<ref name=fx6_ve1_697/> In the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas ploughing is repeatedly referred to.<ref name=fx7_ve1_697/> <br><br>Even in the Rigveda<ref name=fx8_ve1_697/> there is clear proof of the importance attached to agriculture. In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx9_ve1_697/> the '''Vrātyas,''' Hindus without the pale of Brahminism, are described as not cultivating the soil.<br><br>The plough land was called '''[[उर्वरा|Urvarā]]''' or '''[[क्षेत्र|Kṣetra]];''' manure ('''[[शकन्|Śakan]], [[करीष|Karīṣa]]''') was used, and irrigation was practised ('''[[खनित्र|Khanitra]]'''). The plough ('''[[लाङ्गल|Lāṅgala]], [[सीर|Sīra]]''') was drawn by oxen, teams of six, eight, or even twelve being employed.<ref name=fx10_ve1_697/> The operations of agriculture are neatly summed up in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx11_ve1_697/> as ‘ploughing, sowing, reaping, and threshing’ (''kṛṣantaḥ, vapantaḥ, lunantaḥ, mṛṇantaḥ''). The ripe grain was cut with a sickle ('''[[दात्र|Dātra]], Sṛṇi'''), bound into bundles<ref name=fx12_ve1_697/> ('''[[पर्ष|Parṣa]]'''), and beaten out on the floor of the granary ('''[[खल|Khala]]''').<ref name=fx13_ve1_697/> The grain was then separated from the straw and refuse either by a sieve ('''Titau''') or a winnowing fan ('''[[शूर्प|Śūrpa]]''').<ref name=fx14_ve1_697/> The winnower was called '''Dhānyākṛt,'''<ref name=fx15_ve1_697/> and the grain was measured in a vessel called '''Urdara.'''<ref name=fx16_ve1_697/><br><br>The Rigveda leaves us in doubt as to the kind of grain grown, for '''Yava''' is a word of doubtful signification, and '''[[धाना|Dhānā]]''' is also vague. In the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx17_ve1_697/> things are different. Rice ('''[[व्रीहि|Vrīhi]]''') appears, Yava means barley, with a species styled '''[[उपवाक|Upavāka]].''' Beans ('''[[मुद्ग|Mudga]], [[माष|Māṣa]]'''), sesamum ('''Tila'''), and other grains ('''[[अणु|Aṇu]], [[खल्व|Khalva]], [[गोधूम|Godhūma]], [[नीवार|Nīvāra]], [[प्रियङ्गु|Priyaṅgu]], [[मसूर|Masūra]], [[श्यामाक|Śyāmāka]]''') are mentioned, while cucumbers ('''[[उर्वारू|Urvārū]], Uryārūka''') were known. It is uncertain whether fruit trees ('''[[वृक्ष|Vṛkṣa]]''') were cultivated, or merely grew wild;<ref name=fx18_ve1_697/> but frequent mention is made of the jujube ('''[[कर्कन्धु|Karkandhu]], [[कुवल|Kuvala]], [[बदर|Badara]].''').<br><br>The seasons for agriculture are briefly summed up in a passage of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā:<ref name=fx19_ve1_697/> barley ripened in summer, being no doubt sown, as in modern India, in winter; rice  ripened in autumn, being sown in the beginning of the rains; beans and sesamum, planted at the time of the summer rains, ripened in the winter and the cool season. There were two harvests ('''[[सस्य|Sasya]]''') a year according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā;<ref name=fx20_ve1_697/> the winter crop was ripe by the month of [[चैत्र|Caitra]] (March-April) according to the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx21_ve1_697/><br><br>The farmer had plenty of trouble of his own: moles destroyed the seed, birds and various kinds of reptiles ('''[[उपक्वस|Upakvasa]], [[जभ्य|Jabhya]], [[तर्द|Tarda]], [[पतङ्ग|Pataṅga]]''') injured the young shoots, excessive rain or drought might damage the crops. The Atharvaveda contains spells to prevent these evils.<ref name=fx22_ve1_697/><br>

कृष्टि
<u>'''Kṛṣṭi'''</u> denotes ‘people’ in general from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_698/> onwards. Its common and regular use in this sense appears to show that the Āryans, when they invaded India, were already agriculturists, though the employment of the words referring to ploughing mentioned under '''[[कृषि|Kṛṣi]]''' indicates that not all of the people devoted themselves equally to that occupation. Indra and Agni are ''par excellence'' the lords of men ([[कृष्टि|Kṛṣṭi]]).<ref name=fx2_ve1_698/> Sometimes the word is further defined by the addition of an adjective meaning ‘belonging to mankind,’ ‘of men’ (''mānuṣīḥ,''<ref name=fx3_ve1_698/> ''mānavīḥ'').<ref name=fx4_ve1_698/><br><br>Special mention is frequently<ref name=fx5_ve1_698/> made of the ‘five peoples’ (''pañca kṛṣṭayaḥ''). The exact sense of this expression is doubtful. See '''Panca Janāsaḥ.'''<br>

कृष्ण
<u>'''1. Kṛṣṇa'''</u> (‘black’) denotes a dark-coloured animal or bird. In some passages,<ref name=fx1_ve1_699/> as the context shows, an antelope is certainly  meant. In a few others<ref name=fx2_ve1_699/> a bird of prey seems indicated. See also '''[[कृष्णाजिन|Kṛṣṇājina]].'''<br>

कृष्ण
<u>'''2. Kṛṣṇa'''</u> appears as the name of a seer in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_700/> Tradition assigns to him or to [[विश्वक|Viśvaka]], son of [[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]] (''Kārṣṇi''), the authorship of the following hymn.<ref name=fx2_ve1_700/> The word Kṛṣṇiya may be a patronymic<ref name=fx3_ve1_700/> formed from the same name in two other hymns of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_700/> where the Aśvins are said to have restored '''Viṣṇāpū''' to [[विश्वक|Viśvaka]] Kṛṣṇya. In that case [[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]] would seem to be the grandfather of Viṣṇāpū. This [[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]] may be identical with [[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]] [[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]] mentioned in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_700/><br>

कृष्ण देवकी-पुत्र
<u>'''3. Kṛṣṇa Devakī-putra'''</u> is mentioned in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_701/> as a pupil of the mythical '''[[घोर आङ्गिरस|Ghora Āṅgirasa]].''' Tradition,<ref name=fx2_ve1_701/> and several modern writers like Grierson, Garbe, and von Schroeder, recognize in him the hero [[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]], who later is deified. In their view he is a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] teacher of morals, as opposed to Brahminism.<ref name=fx3_ve1_701/> This is extremely doubtful. It appears better either to regard the coincidence of name as accidental, or to suppose that the reference is a piece of Euhemerism. To identify this [[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]] with the preceding, as does the St. Petersburg Dictionary, seems to be quite groundless.<br>

कृष्ण हारीत
<u>'''4. Kṛṣṇa Hārīta'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve1_702/> The [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve1_702/> has Kṛtsna in the parallel passage. <br>

कृष्ण-दत्त लौहितय
<u>'''Kṛṣṇa-datta Lauhitaya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1) as a pupil of '''[[श्यामसुजयन्त लौहित्य|Śyāmasujayanta Lauhitya]].'''<br>

कृष्ण-धृति सात्यकि
<u>'''Kṛṣṇa-dhṛti Sātyaki'''</u> (‘descendant of Satyaka’) is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1) as a pupil of '''[[सत्यश्रवस्|Satyaśravas]].'''<br>

कृष्ण-रात लौहित्य
<u>'''Kṛṣṇa-rāta Lauhitya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1) as a pupil of '''Śyāmaiajayanta [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]].'''<br>

कृष्णल
<u>'''Kṛṣṇala'''</u> denotes the berry of the ''Abrus precatorius,'' used as a weight according to the later authorities, one [[माष|Māṣa]] (‘bean’) being equated to four Kṛṣṇalas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_706/> In the sense of a weight it occurs in the Taittirīva<ref name=fx2_ve1_706/> and other Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx3_ve1_706/> and later.<ref name=fx4_ve1_706/><br>

कृष्णाजिन
<u>'''Kṛṣṇājina'''</u> is the skin (''[[अजिन|ajina]]'') of the black antelope ('''[[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]].''') It is repeatedly referred to in the later Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_707/> with regard to its ritual use.<br>

कृष्णायस
<u>'''Kṛṣṇāyasa'''</u> (‘black metal’), ‘iron,’ is referred to in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 1, 6). See also '''Ayas''' and '''[[कार्ष्णायस|Kārṣṇāyasa]].'''<br>

कृसर
<u>'''Kṛsara,'''</u> a term denoting a mess of rice and sesamum, often mentioned in the Sūtras, occurs in the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_709/><br>

केकय
<u>'''Kekaya'''</u> is the name of a tribe which in later days, and probably also in Vedic times, was settled in the north-west,  oetween the '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]''' (Indus) and '''[[वितस्ता|Vitastā]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_710/> In the Vedic texts the Kekayas are mentioned indirectly only in the name of their prince '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]] [[कैकेय|Kaikeya]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_710/><br>

केतु
<u>'''1. Ketu'''</u> is a term which Weber<ref name=fx1_ve1_711/> understands in the sense of ‘meteor’ or ‘comet’ in the late Adbhuta [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<br>

केतु वाज्य
<u>'''2. Ketu Vājya'''</u> (‘descendant of Vāja’) is mentioned as a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_712/><br>

केवर्त
<u>'''Kevarta, Kaivarta'''</u> are two variant forms denoting ‘fisherman’ in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_713/> and [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_713/> lists of victims at the Puruṣamedha, or human sacrifice.<br>

केश
<u>'''Keśa,'''</u> ‘hair of the head,’ is repeatedly mentioned in the later Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_714/> The hair was a matter of great care to the Vedic Indian, and several hymns of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_714/> are directed to securing its plentiful growth. Cutting or shaving (''vap'') the hair is often referred to.<ref name=fx3_ve1_714/> For a man to wear long hair was considered effeminate.<ref name=fx4_ve1_714/> As to modes of dressing the hair see '''[[ओपश|Opaśa]]''' and '''[[कपर्द|Kaparda]];''' as to the beard see '''[[श्मश्रु|Śmaśru]].'''<br>

केशिन्
<u>'''1. Keśin'''</u> is the name of a people occurring in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_715/> where their king is mentioned as learning from '''Khaṇḍika''' the atonement for a bad omen at the sacrifice. <br>

केशिन् दार्भ्य
<u>'''2. Keśin Dārbhya'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_716/> or '''[[दाल्भ्य|Dālbhya]]'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_716/> (‘descendant of Darbha’) is a somewhat enigmatic figure. According to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_716/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] Brāhmana<ref name=fx4_ve1_716/> he was a king, sister's son of '''Uccaiḥśravas,''' according to the latter authority. His people were the '''Pañcālas,''' of whom the Keśins must therefore have been a branch, and who are said to have been threefold (''tryanīka'').<ref name=fx5_ve1_716/> A story is told of his having a ritual dispute with '''[[षण्डिक|Ṣaṇḍika]]''' in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx6_ve1_716/> this appears in another form in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_716/> He was a contemporary of a fellow sage, '''[[केशिन् सात्यकामि|Keśin Sātyakāmi]],''' according to the Maitrāyaṇī<ref name=fx7_ve1_716/> and [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_716/> Saṃhitās. The [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx9_ve1_716/> attributes to him a Sāman or chant, and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx10_ve1_716/> tells how he was taught by a golden bird.<br><br>In view of the fact that the early literature always refers to [[दार्भ्य|Dārbhya]] as a sage, it seems doubtful whether the commentator is right in thinking that the Śatapatha refers to a king and a people, when a sage alone may well be meant, while the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] is of no great authority. The latter work may have assumed that the reference in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx11_ve1_716/> to the [[केशिन्|Keśin]] people signifies kingship, but this is hardly necessary.<br>

केशिन् सात्य-कामि
<u>'''3. Keśin Sātya-kāmi'''</u> (‘descendant of Satyakāma’) is mentioned as a teacher and contemporary of '''[[केशिन् दार्भ्य|Keśin Dārbhya]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] (ii. 6, 2, 3) and Maitrāyaṇī (i. 6, 5) Saṃhitās. <br>

केसर-प्राबन्धा
<u>'''Kesara-prābandhā.'''</u>--In the list of the crimes of the '''Vaitahavyas''' narrated in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_718/> is the cooking of the last she-goat (''caramājām'') of [[केसरप्राबन्धा|Kesaraprābandhā]], who may presumably be deemed to have been a woman, ‘having braided hair.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_718/> Ludwig,<ref name=fx3_ve1_718/> followed by Whitney,<ref name=fx4_ve1_718/> appears to amend the passage (''carama-jām'') as meaning ‘the last-born calf’ of [[केसरप्राबन्धा|Kesaraprābandhā]], a cow. But this interpretation does not suit the name so well.<br>

कैकेय
<u>'''Kaikeya,'''</u> ‘king of the Kekayas,’ is an epithet of '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_719/><br>

कैरात
<u>'''Kairāta'''</u> is the name of a snake in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_720/>--possibly, but not probably, the modern Karait.<br>

कैरातिका
<u>'''Kairātikā,'''</u> a ‘maiden of the '''[[किरात|Kirāta]]''' people,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda (x. 4, 14) as digging up roots for medicinal use.<br>

कैरिशि
<u>'''Kairiśi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Kiriśa,’ is the patronymic of '''Sutvan''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 28).<br>

कैवर्त
<u>'''Kaivarta.'''</u> See '''[[केवर्त|Kevarta]].'''<br>

कैशिनी
<u>'''Kaiśinī.'''</u>--The ''Kaiśinyaḥ prajāḥ,'' ‘offspring or people<ref name=fx1_ve1_724/> of [[केशिन्|Keśin]],’ are mentioned in an obscure passage of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_724/> either as still existing at the date of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_724/> or as extinct.<br>

कैशोर्य
<u>'''Kaiśorya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Kaiśori,’ is the patronymic of '''[[काप्य|Kāpya]]''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_725/> <br>

कोक
<u>'''1. Koka,'''</u> a word occurring in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_726/> and the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_726/> seems to denote the ‘cuckoo.’ In all the three passages in which it is found, Sāyaṇa explains it as the '''[[चक्रवाक|Cakravāka]].''' Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_726/> renders it in the Atharvaveda passages as a certain destructive parasitic animal. ''Cf.'' '''[[अन्यवाप|Anyavāpa]].'''<br>

कोक
<u>'''2. Koka'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 5, 4, 17) as a son of the [[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] king, '''[[सात्रासाह|Sātrāsāha]].'''<br>

कोकिल
<u>'''Kokila,'''</u> a very frequent word in the Epic and later, denoting the cuckoo, is only inferred for the Vedic period from its being the name of a [[राजपुत्र|Rājaputra]] in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Anukramaṇī.<ref name=fx1_ve1_728/><br>

कोणेय
<u>'''Koṇeya, Kauṇeya.'''</u> See '''Rajana.'''<br>

कोल
<u>'''Kola,'''</u> another form of '''[[कुवल|Kuvala]],''' the ''Zizyphus jujuba,'' is mentioned in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vii. 3, 1).<br>

कोश
<u>'''1. Kośa'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_731/> for the ‘bucket’ used in drawing water by means of a rope from a well ('''[[अवत|Avata]]'''). In the ritual<ref name=fx2_ve1_731/> it denotes a large vessel to hold Soma, as opposed to '''[[कलश|Kalaśa]].'''<br>

कोस
<u>'''2. Kosa'''</u> denotes the body of a chariot.<ref name=fx1_ve1_732/> Presumably it was fastened to the axles, but it was probably not very secure, as the body of Pūṣan's chariot is said not to fall.<ref name=fx2_ve1_732/> The ropes<ref name=fx3_ve1_732/> used to fasten the [[कोश|Kośa]] are perhaps referred to in the word ''akṣā-nah.''<ref name=fx4_ve1_732/> By synecdoche this word also denotes the whole chariot.<ref name=fx5_ve1_732/> See also '''[[वन्धुर|Vandhura]], [[रथ|Ratha]].''' <br>

कोश
<u>'''3. Kośa.'''</u>--The exact sense of this word in '''[[कोश|Kośa]]-kārī,''' the designation of a female victim at the Puruṣamedha, or human sacrifice,<ref name=fx1_ve1_733/> is uncertain. It may be ‘sheath.’<br>

कोष
<u>'''Koṣa.'''</u>--The Koṣas appear as a priestly family in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], where one of them, '''[[सुश्रवस्|Suśravas]],''' is mentioned by name.<ref name=fx2_ve1_734/><br><br>^1 x. 5, 5, 8.<br>

कोसल
<u>'''Kosala'''</u> is the name of a people not occurring in the earliest Vedic literature. In the story of the spread of Āryan culture told in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_735/> the [[कोसल|Kosala]]-Videhas, as the offspring of '''[[विदेघ|Videgha]] [[माथव|Māthava]],''' appear as falling later than the Kuru-Pañcālas under the influence of Brahminism. The same passage gives the '''[[सदानीरा|Sadānīrā]]''' as the boundary of the two peoples--[[कोसल|Kosala]] and [[विदेह|Videha]]. Elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve1_735/> the [[कौसल्य|Kausalya]], or [[कोसल|Kosala]] king, '''[[पर आट्णार|Para Āṭṇāra]] [[हैरण्यनाभ|Hairaṇyanābha]],''' is described as having performed the great [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice. Connexion with '''[[काशि|Kāśi]]''' and '''[[विदेह|Videha]]''' appears also from a passage of the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_735/> Weber<ref name=fx4_ve1_735/> points out that Āśvalāyana, who was very probably a descendant of '''[[अश्वल|Aśvala]],''' the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest of [[विदेह|Videha]], is called a [[कोसल|Kosala]] in the [[प्रश्न|Praśna]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_735/> The later distinction of North and South [[कोसल|Kosala]] is unknown to both Vedic and Buddhist literature.<ref name=fx6_ve1_735/><br><br>[[कोसल|Kosala]] lay to the north-east of the Ganges, and corresponded roughly to the modern Oudh.<br>

कौकूस्त
<u>'''Kaukūsta'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_736/> as a giver of a Daksiṇā, or gift to the priests officiating at a sacrifice. The [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension reads the name '''Kaükthasta.'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_736/> <br>

कौणेय
<u>'''Kauṇeya.'''</u> See '''Rajana.'''<br>

कौण्ठ-रव्य
<u>'''Kauṇṭha-ravya'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_738/> and [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyakas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_738/><br>

कौण्डिनी
<u>'''Kauṇḍinī.'''</u> See '''[[पाराशरीकौण्डिनीपुत्र|Pārāśarīkauṇḍinīputra]].'''<br>

कौण्डिन्य
<u>'''Kauṇḍinya'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]]''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_740/> See also '''Vidarbhīkauṇḍinya,''' and the following.<br>

कौण्डिन्यायन
<u>'''Kauṇḍinyāyana'''</u> is mentioned in the first [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_741/> as a pupil of [[कौण्डिन्य|Kauṇḍinya]], pupil of [[कौण्डिन्य|Kauṇḍinya]] and [[आग्निवेश्य|Āgniveśya]]; in the second<ref name=fx2_ve1_741/> as a pupil of the two Kauṇḍinyas, pupil of [[कौण्डिन्य|Kauṇḍinya]] and [[आग्निवेश्य|Āgniveśya]]. Neither [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] is of much value.<ref name=fx3_ve1_741/><br>

कौतस्त
<u>'''Kautasta,'''</u> a word occurring once in the dual, is apparently a patronymic of '''[[अरिम्एजय|Arimejaya]]''' and '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]],''' two [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]] priests at the snake sacrifice described in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_742/><br>

कौत्स
<u>'''Kautsa'''</u> (‘descendant of Kutsa’) is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_743/> as a pupil of '''[[माहित्थि|Māhitthi]].''' A [[कौत्स|Kautsa]] is also attacked in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_743/> as denying the value of the Vedas, and there is a strong ritual tradition of hostility to the Kautsas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_743/> <br>

कौत्सी-पुत्र
<u>'''Kautsī-putra'''</u> (‘son of a female descendant of '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]]'''’) is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[बौधीपुत्र|Baudhīputra]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] in the Mādhyaṃdina recension (vi. 4, 31).<br>

कौपयेय
<u>'''Kaupayeya'''</u> is the patronymic of '''Uccaiḥśravas.'''<br>

कौम्भ्य
<u>'''Kaumbhya'''</u> (‘descendant of Kumbhya’) is the patronymic of '''[[बभ्रु|Babhru]]'''<br>

कौरम
<u>'''Kaurama.'''</u> See '''[[कौरव|Kaurava]].'''<br>

कौरयाण
<u>'''Kaurayāṇa'''</u> is apparently a patronymic of '''Pākasthāman''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_748/> Hopkins<ref name=fx2_ve1_748/> suggests that Kaurāyaṇa may be meant.<br>

कौरव
<u>'''Kaurava'''</u> is the reading of the text of the Khilas<ref name=fx1_ve1_749/> and of some manuscripts of the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_749/> for the [[कौरम|Kaurama]] of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_749/> who appears in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) as a generous donor among the '''Ruśamas.'''<br>

कौरव्य
<u>'''Kauravya'''</u> (‘belonging to the '''Kurus’'''). A man of the Kuru people, is described in the Atharvaveda as enjoying prosperity with his wife under the rule of King '''[[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_750/> Mention is also made of the [[कौरव्य|Kauravya]] king '''[[बल्हिक प्रातिपीय|Balhika Prātipīya]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_750/> and in the later legend '''Ārṣṭiṣeṇa''' and '''Devāpi''' are alleged to have been Kauravyas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_750/><br>

कौरव्यायणी-पुत्र
<u>'''Kauravyāyaṇī-putra'''</u> (‘son of a female descendant of '''Kuru'''’) is mentioned as a teacher in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (v. 1, 1). <br>

कौरु-पञ्चाल
<u>'''Kauru-pañcāla,'''</u> ‘belonging to the Kuru-Pañcālas,’ is an epithet of '''[[आरुणि|Āruṇi]]''' in the Śatapatha Brāhmana (xi. 4, 1, 2), and a practice of those tribes is designated by this word in the same work (i. 7, 2, 8).<br>

कौलकावती
<u>'''Kaulakāvatī'''</u> are two persons mentioned in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (ii. 1, 3) as having given advice, in the capacity of priests, to '''[[रथप्रोत दार्भ्य|Rathaprota Dārbhya]].'''<br>

कौलाल
<u>'''Kaulāla'''</u> is a word denoting a hereditary potter (‘son of a ''[[कुलाल|kulāla]]'' or potter’) according to the commentator Mahīdhara on the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_754/> The other Samhitās<ref name=fx2_ve1_754/> have '''[[कुलाल|Kulāla]].'''<br>

कौलितर
<u>'''Kaulitara'''</u> is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_755/> as a '''[[दास|Dāsa]].''' Apparently the name is an epithet of '''[[शम्बर|Śambara]],''' meaning ‘son of Kulitara’: this points to [[शम्बर|Śambara]] having been a terrestrial foe, and not a mere demon.<ref name=fx2_ve1_755/><br>

कौलीक
<u>'''Kaulīka,'''</u> like '''[[कुलीका|Kulīkā]],''' is the name of some sort of bird in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_756/><br>

कौशाम्बेय
<u>'''Kauśāmbeya'''</u> is the patronymic (‘descendant of Kuśāmba’) of a teacher '''Proti''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_757/> according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary: a view supported by the fact that '''Kūśāmba''' actually occurs as the name of a man in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_757/> It is, however, possible that the word means a ‘native of the town Kauśāmbī’ as understood by Harisvāmin in his commentary on the Śatapatha Brāhmana.<ref name=fx3_ve1_757/> <br>

कौशिक
<u>'''Kauśika'''</u> is an epithet of Indra as ‘connected with the Kuśikas,’ and also of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' as ‘son of [[कुशिक|Kuśika]].’<ref name=fx1_ve1_758/> A teacher named [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[कौण्डिन्य|Kauṇḍinya]]''' in the first two Vaṃśias (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_758/><br>

कौशिकायनि
<u>'''Kauśikāyani'''</u> (‘descendant of Kauśika’) is mentioned as a teacher and a pupil of '''[[घृतकौशिक|Ghṛtakauśika]]''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_759/><br>

कौशिकी-पुत्र
<u>'''Kauśikī-putra'''</u> (‘son of a female descendant of Kuśika’) is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 1) as a pupil of '''[[आलम्बीपुत्र|Ālambīputra]]''' and '''[[वैयाघ्रपदीपुत्र|Vaiyāghrapadīputra]].'''<br>

कौश्रेय
<u>'''Kauśreya'''</u> (‘descendant of Kuśri’) is the patronymic of '''Somadakṣa''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xx. 8; xxi. 9).<br>

कौषारव
<u>'''Kauṣārava'''</u> (‘descendant of Kuṣāru’) is the patronymic of '''[[मैत्रेय|Maitreya]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 28).<br>

कौषीतकि
<u>'''Kauṣītaki'''</u> (‘descendant of Kuṣītaka’) is the patronymic of a teacher, or series of teachers, to whom the doctrines set forth in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_763/> and in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx2_ve1_763/> and the Śrauta and [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] Sūtras,<ref name=fx3_ve1_763/> are referred. He is rarely mentioned elsewhere.<ref name=fx4_ve1_763/> The doctrine of [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] is called the Kauṣītaka.<ref name=fx5_ve1_763/> The pupils of [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] are known as the Kauṣītakis in the [[निदान|Nidāna]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx6_ve1_763/> and in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve1_763/>  they with [[कुषीतक|Kuṣītaka]] are stated to have been cursed by '''Luśākapi.''' Elsewhere<ref name=fx8_ve1_763/> they are called Kauṣītakins. If the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx9_ve1_763/> can be trusted, there were among them at least two leading teachers, '''Kahoḍa''' and '''Sarvajit,''' the former of whom is mentioned elsewhere.<ref name=fx10_ve1_763/><br>

कौष्य
<u>'''Kauṣya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[कोष|Koṣa]],’ is the patronymic of '''[[सुश्रवस्|Suśravas]].'''<br>

कौसल्य
<u>'''Kausalya,'''</u> ‘prince of [[कोसल|Kosala]],’ is the designation of '''[[पर आट्णार|Para Āṭṇāra]]''' in the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_765/> and of '''[[हिरण्यनाभ|Hiraṇyanābha]]''' in the Sāṅkhāvana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_765/> Āśvalāyana is styled [[कौसल्य|Kausalya]], as ‘belonging to the [[कोसल|Kosala]] country,’ in the [[प्रश्न|Praśna]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_765/> and the Kaśī-Kausalyāḥ, or the ‘Kāśis and people of [[कोसल|Kosala]],’ are mentioned in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_765/><br>

कौसित
<u>'''Kausita'''</u> appears in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (ii. 1, 11) in connexion with the demon Kusitāyin as the name of a lake. The [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (x. 5) has Kausida instead.<br>

कौसुरुबिन्दि
<u>'''Kausurubindi,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Kusurubinda,'''’ is the patronymic of '''Proti [[कौशाम्बेय|Kauśāmbeya]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xii. 2, 2, 13). In the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 4, 24) the form is Kausuravindu.<br>

कौहड
<u>'''Kauhaḍa,'''</u> ‘descendant of Kohaḍa,’ is the patronymic of a teacher, '''Mitravinda,''' mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_768/> as well as of '''[[श्रवणदत्त|Śravaṇadatta]].'''<br>

क्रतु-जित् जानकि
<u>'''Kratu-jit Jānaki'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[जनक|Janaka]]'''’) is mentioned in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_769/> as the priest of '''Rajana [[कौणेय|Kauṇeya]].''' See also '''Kratuvid.''' <br>

क्रतु-विद् जानकि
<u>'''Kratu-vid Jānaki'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[जनक|Janaka]]'''’) is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 34) as having learned a certain doctrine regarding Soma from Agni.<br>

क्रय
<u>'''Kraya,'''</u> ‘sale,’ is a word which does not actually occur in the Rigveda, though the verb ''krī,'' from which this noun is derived, is found there.<ref name=fx1_ve1_771/> Both noun and verb are common in the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve1_771/> Sale appears to have regularly consisted in barter in the Rigveda:<ref name=fx3_ve1_771/> ten cows are regarded as a possible price for an (image of) Indra to be used as a fetish, while elsewhere not a hundred, nor a thousand, nor a myriad are considered as an adequate price (''[[शुल्क|śulka]]'') for the purchase of Indra.<ref name=fx4_ve1_771/> The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_771/> mentions, as possible objects of commerce, garments (''[[दूर्श|dūrśa]]''), coverlets (''[[पवस्त|pavasta]]''), and goatskins (''[[अजिन|ajina]]''). The haggling of the market was already familiar in the days of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx6_ve1_771/> and a characteristic hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_771/> is directed to procuring success in trade. The ‘price’ was called '''[[वस्न|Vasna]],''' and the ‘merchant’ '''[[वणिज्|Vaṇij]].''' his greed being well known.<ref name=fx8_ve1_771/><br><br>There is little evidence of a standard of value in currency having been adopted. When no specific mention is made of the standard, the unit was probably the cow.<ref name=fx9_ve1_771/> In a considerable number of passages of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx10_ve1_771/> and elsewhere,<ref name=fx11_ve1_771/> however, the expression ''hiraṇyaṃ śata-mānam'' suggests that there must have been some standard other than  cows, though it might in all these passages be rendered as ‘gold worth a hundred cows.’ But the use of the '''[[कृष्णल|Kṛṣṇala]]''' as a measure of weight<ref name=fx12_ve1_771/> suggests that the meaning is ‘gold weighing a hundred Kṛṣṇalas,’ and this seems the more probable explanation. This unit seems not to be known in the Rigveda, where the meaning of the term '''[[मना|Manā]],''' which occurs once, is mysterious, and where necklets ('''[[निष्क|Niṣka]]''') seem to have been one of the more portable forms of wealth, like jewellery in modern India, and may perhaps have served as a means of exchange.<br>

क्रवण
<u>'''Kravaṇa,'''</u> a word occurring only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_772/> is understood by Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_772/> as the name of the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest or the sacrificer. Roth considered it an adjective without at first<ref name=fx3_ve1_772/> assigning a sense, but afterwards<ref name=fx4_ve1_772/> as meaning ‘timid.’ Sāyaṇa interprets it as ‘worshipping.’ Oldenberg<ref name=fx5_ve1_772/> considers the meaning uncertain, suggesting as possible ‘the slayer of the victim.’<br>

क्रव्य
<u>'''Kravya,'''</u> ‘raw flesh,’ is never mentioned in Vedic literature as eaten by men. Demons alone are spoken of as consuming it,<ref name=fx1_ve1_773/> apart from Agni being called ''kravyād,'' ‘eating raw flesh,’ as consumer of the bodies of the dead.<ref name=fx2_ve1_773/> The man who in the Rigveda is compelled by starvation to eat dog's flesh, nevertheless cooks it.<ref name=fx3_ve1_773/><br>

क्रातु-जातेय
<u>'''Krātu-jāteya'''</u> is a patronymic of '''[[राम क्रातुजातेय|Rāma Krātujāteya]] [[वैयाघ्रपद्य|Vaiyāghrapadya]]''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 2; iv. 16, 1).<br>

क्रिमि
<u>'''Krimi.'''</u> See '''[[कृमि|Kṛmi]].''' <br>

क्रिवि
<u>'''Krivi'''</u> is asserted in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_776/> to have been the older name of the '''Pañcālas.''' This statement is supported by the name of the king there mentioned, '''[[क्रैव्य|Kraivya]] [[पाञ्चाल|Pāñcāla]],''' The Krivis appear in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_776/> as settled on the '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]''' and the '''[[असिक्नी|Asiknī]].''' It is a plausible conjecture of Zimmer's<ref name=fx3_ve1_776/> that with the '''Kurus''' they made up the '''[[वैकर्ण|Vaikarṇa]]''' people.<ref name=fx4_ve1_776/> The importance of the Pañcālas, and the insignificance of the Krivis, may be explained in part by the fact that the later Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] alliance included the '''Bharatas.''' It is also probable, as Oldenberg<ref name=fx5_ve1_776/> suggests, from the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx6_ve1_776/> that the '''Turvaśas''' were included in the Pañcālas, and as the latter name indicates, probably other tribes also. Or, if Hopkins' view<ref name=fx7_ve1_776/> is accepted that [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] was king of the Yadus, the latter may in part have been allied with the Krivis to form the Pañcālas.<br>

क्रीत वैत-होत्र
<u>'''Krīta Vaita-hotra'''</u> (‘descendant of Vītahotra’) is mentioned in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iv. 2, 6) in connexion with the '''Kurus.'''<br>

क्रुञ्च्
<u>'''1. Kruñc,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_778/> '''Kruñca,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_778/> '''[[क्रौञ्च|Krauñca]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_778/> are variant forms denoting the ‘curlew’ or ‘snipe.’ To it is attributed in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_778/>  the faculty, later assigned to the '''[[हंस|Haṃsa]],''' of extracting milk from water when the two fluids are mixed.<ref name=fx4_ve1_778/><br>

क्रुन्च् आङ्गिरस
<u>'''2. Krunc Āṅgirasa'''</u> is in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_779/> the name of the seer of a Sāman or Chant called the [[क्रौञ्च|Krauñca]]. It is doubtless invented to explain the name of the Chant on the ordinary principle that Sāmans are called after their authors, though this rule has many exceptions.<ref name=fx2_ve1_779/><br>

क्रुमु
<u>'''Krumu'''</u> is the name of a stream mentioned twice in the Rigveda--once in the fifth book<ref name=fx1_ve1_780/> and once in the last, in the [[नदी|Nadī]]-[[स्तुति|stuti]], or ‘praise of rivers.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_780/> There can be little doubt that this river is identical with the modern Kurum, a western tributary of the Indus.<ref name=fx3_ve1_780/><br>

क्रुमुक
<u>'''Krumuka'''</u> as the name of ‘wood’ appears to be a variant form of [[कृमुक|Kṛmuka]].<br><br>^1) [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā, v. 1, 9, 3; [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], i. 4, 7, 3.<br>

क्रैव्य। पाञ्चाल
<u>'''Kraivya. Pāñcāla,'''</u> the king of the '''Krivis,'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_782/> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_782/> as having performed the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, on the '''[[परिवक्रा|Parivakrā]].''' Eggeling,<ref name=fx3_ve1_782/> however, takes the word as a proper name, ‘Kraivya, the [[पाञ्चाल|Pāñcāla]] king.’<br>

क्रोश
<u>'''Krośa,'''</u> as a measure of distance (lit. ‘a shout,’ as expressing the range of the voice), is found in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_783/> <br>

क्रोष्टृ
<u>'''Kroṣṭṛ'''</u> (lit. ‘howler’), the ‘jackal,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_784/> as by nature cowardly compared with the wild boar ('''[[वराह|Varāha]]'''). In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_784/> it is spoken of as devouring corpses. The word also occurs in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_784/> where the commentator glosses it with [[सृगाल|Sṛgāla]], another name of the jackal. See also '''[[लोपाश|Lopāśa]].'''<br>

क्रौञ्च
<u>'''1. Krauñca.'''</u> See '''[[क्रुञ्च्|Kruñc]].'''<br>

क्रौञ्च
<u>'''2. Krauñca,'''</u> as the name of a mountain, occurs only in the latest Vedic literature.<ref name=fx1_ve1_786/><br>

क्रौञ्चिकी-पुत्र
<u>'''Krauñcikī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of [[क्रौञ्च|Krauñca]],’ is mentioned as a pupil of '''Vaiṭṭabhatīputra'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_787/> in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_787/><br>

क्रौष्टुकि
<u>'''Krauṣṭuki,'''</u> ‘descendant of Kroṣṭuka,’ is mentioned as a grammarian in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_788/> the Bṛhaddevatā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_788/> and the [[छन्दस्|Chandas]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_788/> but as an astrologer in a Pariśiṣṭa of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx4_ve1_788/><br>

क्वयी
<u>'''Kvayī'''</u> is the name of some species of bird in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_789/> occurring in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice. The form in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_789/> is [[कुवय|Kuvaya]]. <br>

क्वल
<u>'''Kvala'''</u> is a substance, perhaps<ref name=fx1_ve1_790/> identical with '''[[कुवल|Kuvala]],''' the fruit of the jujube, used to coagulate milk according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve1_790/><br>

क्षत
<u>'''Kṣata'''</u> is regarded by Zimmer<ref name=fx1_ve1_791/> as denoting a special disease (a sort of ''Phthisis pulmonalis'') in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_791/> but the word is probably only an adjective.<ref name=fx3_ve1_791/><br>

क्षत्तृ
<u>'''Kṣattṛ'''</u> is a word of frequent occurrence in the later Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas, denoting a member of the royal entourage, but the sense is somewhat uncertain. In the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_792/> it is used of a god as the ‘distributor’ of good things to his worshippers; the same sense seems to be found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_792/> and elsewhere.<ref name=fx3_ve1_792/> In one passage of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve1_792/> the interpretation ‘doorkeeper’ is given by the commentator Mahīdhara, a sense which seems possible in other passages,<ref name=fx5_ve1_792/> while Sāyaṇa ascribes to it in one passage of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_792/> the more dignified meaning of ''antaḥpurādhyakṣa,'' ‘a chamberlain.’ In other passages,<ref name=fx7_ve1_792/> again, the sense of ‘charioteer’ is not unlikely. Later the [[क्षत्तृ|Kṣattṛ]] was regarded as a man of mixed caste.<ref name=fx8_ve1_792/> <br>

क्षत्र
<u>'''1. Kṣatra,'''</u> in the general sense of ‘dominion,’ ‘rule,’ ‘power,’ as exercised by gods and men, occurs frequently from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_793/> onwards. The word is also found in the concrete sense of ‘rulers’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_793/> and later;<ref name=fx3_ve1_793/> but in no case does it in the Rigveda certainly<ref name=fx4_ve1_793/> mean what it regularly denotes in the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx5_ve1_793/> the ruling class as opposed to the priests ('''[[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]]'''), the subject people ('''[[विश्|Viś]], [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]'''), and the servile class ('''[[शूद्र|Śūdra]]'''). See also '''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]].''' A [[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]]-pati is several times mentioned<ref name=fx6_ve1_793/> as an equivalent of ‘king.’<br>

क्षत्र
<u>'''2. Kṣatra'''</u> seems to be the name of a man mentioned with others, including '''[[मनस|Manasa]], [[यजत|Yajata]],''' and '''[[अवत्सार|Avatsāra]],''' in one quite obscure passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_794/><br>

क्षत्र-विद्या
<u>'''Kṣatra-vidyā,'''</u> ‘the science of the ruling class,’ is mentioned in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_795/> Śaṅkara glosses the term with ''dhanur-veda,'' ‘the science of the bow,’ which is the most probable sense.<ref name=fx2_ve1_795/><br>

क्षत्रिय
<u>'''Kṣatriya.'''</u>--As the origin of caste, the relation of the castes, intermarriage, and cognate matters may most conveniently be discussed under '''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]],''' this article will be confined to determining, as far as possible, the real character of the class called Kṣatriyas, or collectively '''[[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]].'''<br><br>The evidence of the Jātakas<ref name=fx1_ve1_796/> points to the word Khattiya  denoting the members of the old Āryan nobility who had led the tribes to conquest, '''as well''' as those families of the aborigines who had managed to maintain their princely status in spite of the conquest. In the epic<ref name=fx2_ve1_796/> also the term [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] seems to include these persons, but it has probably a wider signification than Khattiya, and would cover all the royal military vassals and feudal chiefs, expressing, in fact, pretty much the same as the ''barones'' of early English history. Neither in the Jātakas<ref name=fx3_ve1_796/> nor in the epic<ref name=fx4_ve1_796/> is the term co-extensive with all warriors; the army contains many besides the Kṣatriyas, who are the leaders or officers, rather than the rank and file.<br><br>In the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx5_ve1_796/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx6_ve1_796/> the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] stands as a definite member of the social body, distinct from the priest, the subject people, and the slaves, '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]],''' and '''[[शूद्र|Śūdra]].''' It is significant that [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] is a variant to [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]], and an earlier one. Hence it is reasonable to suppose that the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] and [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] are both of similar origin, being princely or connected with royalty. Moreover, the early use of [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] in the Rigveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_796/> is exclusively connected with royal authority or divine authority.<br><br>It is impossible to say exactly what persons would be included in the term [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]. That it covered the royal house and the various branches of the royal family may be regarded as certain. It, no doubt, also included the nobles and their families: this would explain the occasional opposition of [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] and [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]], as in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx8_ve1_796/> where a [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] asks a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] for a place for sacrifice (''deva-yajana''). Thus, when strictly applied, [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] would have a wider denotation than [[राजन्य|Rājanya]]. As a rule, however, the two expressions are identical, and both are used as evidence in what follows. That [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] ever included the mere fighting  man has not been proved: in the Rigveda<ref name=fx9_ve1_796/> and later<ref name=fx10_ve1_796/> others than Kṣatriyas regularly fought; but possibly if the nobles had retinues as the kings had, [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] would embrace those retainers who had military functions. The term did not apply to all members of the royal entourage; for example, the '''Grāmaṇī''' was usually a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]].<br><br>The connexion of the Kṣatriyas with the Brahmins was very close. The prosperity of the two is repeatedly asserted<ref name=fx11_ve1_796/> to be indissolubly associated, especially in the relation of king ('''[[राजन्|Rājan]]''') and domestic priest ('''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]]'''). Sometimes there was feud between [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] and Brahmin.<ref name=fx12_ve1_796/> His management of the sacrifice then gave the Brahmin power to ruin the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] by embroiling him with the people<ref name=fx13_ve1_796/> or with other Kṣatriyas.<ref name=fx14_ve1_796/><br><br>Towards the common people, on the other hand, the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] stood in a relation of well-nigh unquestioned superiority.<ref name=fx15_ve1_796/> There are, however, references to occasional feuds between  the people and the nobles,<ref name=fx16_ve1_796/> in which no doubt the inferior numbers of the latter were compensated by their superior arms and prowess. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx17_ve1_796/> the [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] is described as tributary to another (''anyasya bali-kṛt''), to be devoured by another (''anyasyādya''), and to be oppressed at will (''yathākāma-jyeya''). Probably these epithets apply most strictly to the relation of the king and his people, but the passage shows that the people were greatly at the mercy of the nobles. No doubt the king granted to them the right, which may have been hereditary, to be supported by the common people, whose feudal superiors they thus became. In return for these privileges the Kṣatriyas had probably duties of protection to perform, as well as some judicial functions, to judge from an obscure passage of the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx18_ve1_796/><br><br>The main duty of the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] in the small states<ref name=fx19_ve1_796/> of the Vedic period was readiness for war. The bow is thus his special attribute,<ref name=fx20_ve1_796/> just as the goad is that of the agriculturist; for the bow is the main weapon of the Veda. Whether the Kṣatriyas paid much attention to mental occupations is uncertain. In the latest stratum of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] literature there are references to learned princes like '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' of '''[[विदेह|Videha]],''' who is said to have become a Brahmin (''brahmā''), apparently in the sense that he had the full knowledge which a Brahmin possessed.<ref name=fx21_ve1_796/> Other learned Kṣatriyas of this period were  '''[[प्रवाहण जैवलि|Pravāhaṇa Jaivali]],'''<ref name=fx22_ve1_796/> '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]] [[कैकेय|Kaikeya]],'''<ref name=fx23_ve1_796/> and [[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]].<ref name=fx24_ve1_796/> Garbe,<ref name=fx25_ve1_796/> Grierson,<ref name=fx26_ve1_796/> and others believe they are justified in holding the view that the Ksatriyas developed a special philosophy of their own as opposed to Brahminism, which appears later as Bhakti, or Faith. On the other hand, there is clear evidence<ref name=fx27_ve1_796/> that the opinion of Ksatriyas on such topics were held in little respect, and it must be remembered that to attribute wisdom to a king was a delicate and effective piece of flattery. There are earlier references to royal sages (''[[राजन्यर्षि|rājanyarṣi]]''),<ref name=fx28_ve1_796/> but it is very doubtful if much stress can be laid on them, and none can be laid on the later tradition of Sāyaṇa.<ref name=fx29_ve1_796/> Again, the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx30_ve1_796/> gives a tradition relating how '''Devāpi,''' a king's son, became the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of his younger brother '''[[शंतनु|Śaṃtanu]];''' but it is very doubtful if the story can really be traced with Sieg<ref name=fx31_ve1_796/> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx32_ve1_796/> itself. In any case, the stories refer only to a few selected Kṣatriyas of high rank, while there is no evidence that the average [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] was concerned with intellectual pursuits. Nor is there any reference to Kṣatriyas engaging in agriculture or in trade or commerce. It may be assumed that the duties of administration and war were adequate to absorb his attention. On the other hand, we do hear of a [[राजन्य|Rājanya]]  as a lute player and singer at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] or horse sacrifice.<ref name=fx33_ve1_796/><br><br>Of the training and education of a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] we have no record; presumably, as in fact if not in theory later on, he was mainly instructed in the art of war, the science of the bow, and the rudimentary administrative functions which would devolve on him. At this early state of the development of the nobility which appears to be represented in the Rigveda, it was probably not unusual or impossible for a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] to become a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]; at least, this assumption best explains the phrase<ref name=fx34_ve1_796/> ‘claiming falsely a Kṣatriya's rank’ (''kṣatriyaṃ mithuyā dhārayantam'').<br><br>The king and the Kṣatriyas must have stood in a particularly close relation. The former being the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] ''par excellence,'' it is to him rather than to the ordinary [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] that we must refer passages like that in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx35_ve1_796/> where it is said that the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]], with the consent of the clansmen, gives a settlement to a man: clearly a parallel to the rule found among many peoples that the chief, but only with the consent of the people, can make a grant of unoccupied land. In the same [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx36_ve1_796/> it is said that a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] consecrates a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]], a clear reference, as the commentator explains, to the practice of the old king consecrating the prince (''kumāra'') who is to succeed him; and again,<ref name=fx37_ve1_796/> the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] and the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] are regarded as alone complete in contrast with other people, the parallel with the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] here suggesting that the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] ''par excellence'' is meant. On the other hand, the king is sometimes contrasted with the [[राजन्य|Rājanya]].<ref name=fx38_ve1_796/><br><br>The [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] literature contains elaborate rules<ref name=fx39_ve1_796/> for the educa-  tion and occupations of Kṣatriyas, but their contents cannot always be traced in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] literature, and their value is questionable.<br>

क्ष-पावन्
<u>'''Kṣa-pāvan,'''</u> ‘protector of the earth,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_797/> is an epithet of a king,<ref name=fx2_ve1_797/> or denotes a king<ref name=fx3_ve1_797/> in the Rigveda. The word is significant, as showing the function of the king as the protector of the tribal territory.<br>

क्षिति
<u>'''Kṣiti'''</u> is in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_798/> a regular word for ‘dwelling,’ and in particular the ''kṣitir [[ध्रुवा|dhruvā]],'' ‘the secure dwelling,’ is mentioned<ref name=fx2_ve1_798/> in a context that shows it, to be equivalent to the '''[[वृजन|Vṛjana]]''' or '''[[ग्राम|Grāma]]''' regarded as a stronghold. From this sense is developed that of the peoples occupying the settlements,<ref name=fx3_ve1_798/> and in particular the five peoples<ref name=fx4_ve1_798/> (for whom see '''Pañca Janāsaḥ''').<br>

क्षिप्त
<u>'''Kṣipta,'''</u> ‘a wound’ (caused by shooting), or ‘bruise’ (caused by throwing), is mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_799/> together with a remedy for it, the '''Pippalī.'''<br>

क्षिप्र-श्येन
<u>'''Kṣipra-śyena,'''</u> ‘swift falcon,’ is the name of a bird in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iii. 14, 11) and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] x. 5, 2, 10).<br>

क्षीर
<u>'''Kṣīra,'''</u> ‘milk,’ also called '''Go''' or '''[[पयस्|Payas]],''' played a large part in the economy of the Vedic Indians.<ref name=fx1_ve1_801/> It was taken warm (''[[पक्व|pakva]]''  as it came from the cow,<ref name=fx2_ve1_801/> or was used with grain to make a ‘mess cooked with milk’ (''[[क्षीर|kṣīra]]-pākam odanam'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_801/> It was also used for mixing with Soma ('''[[अभिश्री|Abhiśrī]], [[आशिर्|Āśir]]'''). From it butter ('''[[घृत|Ghṛta]]''') was made. Milk was also curdled, the '''Pūtīkā''' and '''[[क्वल|Kvala]]''' plants, among others, being used for the purpose.<ref name=fx4_ve1_801/> The curdled milk ('''[[दधि|Dadhi]]''') was undoubtedly used for food; and a kind of cheese is perhaps referred to in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx5_ve1_801/> Goat's milk (''aja-[[क्षीर|kṣīra]]'') is also mentioned.<ref name=fx6_ve1_801/><br>

क्षीरौदन
<u>'''Kṣīraudana,'''</u> ‘rice cooked with milk,’ is mentioned frequently in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 5, 3, 4; xi. 5, 7, 5, etc.).<br>

क्षुद्र-सूक्तस्
<u>'''Kṣudra-sūktas,'''</u> ‘makers of short hymns,’ is the name given in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve1_803/> to the authors of certain hymns of the Rigveda. ''Cf.'' '''[[महासूक्त|Mahāsūkta]].'''<br>

क्षुम्प
<u>'''Kṣumpa'''</u> is a word occurring only in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_804/> where it seems to mean a ‘bush.’ The [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_804/> identifies it with the Ahichatraka, a ‘mushroom.’<br>

क्षुर
<u>'''Kṣura'''</u> occurs three times in the Rigveda. The word appears to have the general sense of ‘blade’<ref name=fx1_ve1_805/> in one passage,<ref name=fx2_ve1_805/> possibly also in another,<ref name=fx3_ve1_805/> where it is said that the hare swallowed a  [[क्षुर|Kṣura]], and where the sense ‘blade’ is adequate. In the third passage<ref name=fx4_ve1_805/> there seems to be a reference to the sharpening of a razor on a grindstone<ref name=fx5_ve1_805/> (''bhurijos,'' the dual denoting precisely, as Pischel<ref name=fx6_ve1_805/> points out, the two sides of the apparatus, between which the stone revolved like the modern grindstone). But Muir,<ref name=fx7_ve1_805/> following another view of Roth,<ref name=fx8_ve1_805/> adopts the sense ‘the edge of scissors,’ which, however, hardly suits the other passage, one in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx9_ve1_805/> where a [[क्षुर|Kṣura]] is described as moving about on the ''bhurijos,''<ref name=fx10_ve1_805/> as the tongue on the lip. The meaning ‘razor’ is perfectly clear in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx11_ve1_805/> where shaving by means of it is mentioned; in many other passages<ref name=fx12_ve1_805/> either sense is adequate. A ''kṣuro bhṛjvān'' occurs in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]:<ref name=fx13_ve1_805/> it seems to denote, as Bloomfield<ref name=fx14_ve1_805/> suggests, a razor with a strop (in the shape of a small grinding apparatus). [[क्षुर|Kṣura]]-[[धारा|dhārā]]<ref name=fx15_ve1_805/> denotes ‘the edge of a razor,’ like ''kṣurasya [[धारा|dhārā]].''<ref name=fx16_ve1_805/> In the Upaniṣads<ref name=fx17_ve1_805/> a razor-case ([[क्षुर|Kṣura]]-dhāna) is mentioned. See also '''[[श्मश्रु|Śmaśru]].'''<br>

क्षेत्र
<u>'''Kṣetra,'''</u> ‘field.’ The use of this word in the Rigveda points clearly to the existence of separate fields<ref name=fx1_ve1_806/> carefully measured off,<ref name=fx2_ve1_806/> though in some passages the meaning is less definite,  indicating cultivated land generally.<ref name=fx3_ve1_806/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_806/> and later the sense of a separate field is clearly marked, though the more general use is also found.<ref name=fx5_ve1_806/> The deity Kṣetrasya Pati,<ref name=fx6_ve1_806/> ‘Lord of the Field,’ should probably be understood as the god presiding over each field, just as Vāstoṣ Pati presides over each dwelling.<ref name=fx7_ve1_806/> It is a fair conclusion from the evidence that the system of separate holdings already existed in early Vedic times.^8 See also '''[[उर्वरा|Urvarā]], Khilya.'''<br>

क्षेत्रिय
<u>'''Kṣetriya'''</u> is a disease which is mentioned several times in the Atharvaveda, and against which three hymns are specially directed.<ref name=fx1_ve1_807/> It is also mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_807/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_807/> The commentators on the Atharvaveda agree in taking it to be a hereditary disease. The word may mean ‘organic,’<ref name=fx4_ve1_807/> or possibly ‘produced in the field,’ as a theory of its origin. What disease is really intended is quite uncertain. Weber<ref name=fx5_ve1_807/> considered that the aim of the [[अथर्वन्|Atharvan]] hymns was to drive away injury threatening the fields, but this is improbable. Bloomfield<ref name=fx6_ve1_807/> suggests ‘scrofula’ or ‘syphilis.’ The remedies mentioned throw no light on the symptoms. <br>

क्षेम-धृत्वन् पौण्डरीक
<u>'''Kṣema-dhṛtvan Pauṇḍarīka'''</u> (‘descendant of Puṇḍarīka’) is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_808/> as having sacrificed on the bank of the river '''[[सुदामन्|Sudāman]].'''<br>

क्षैमि
<u>'''Kṣaimi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Kṣema,’ is the patronymic of '''Sudakṣiṇa''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 6, 3; 7, 1, etc.; 8, 6).<br>

क्षोणी
<u>'''Kṣoṇī.'''</u>--This word, when used in the plural, denotes, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary and Ludwig,<ref name=fx1_ve1_810/> in several passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_810/> the free retainers of the king. Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve1_810/> at one time thought it referred to the wives of the king, pointing to polygamy; but later<ref name=fx4_ve1_810/> he concluded that it means certain divine wives.<br>

क्षौम
<u>'''Kṣauma,'''</u> ‘a linen garment,’ is mentioned in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iii. 6, 7, etc.) and in the Sūtras.<br>

क्ष्विङ्का
<u>'''Kṣviṅkā'''</u> is mentioned once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_812/> as a bird of '''prey.''' The word also occurs in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_812/> where the commentary absurdly explains it as ‘a red-mouthed female ape’ (''rakta-mukhī vānarī''). <br>

ख
<u>'''Kha'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_813/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_813/> the hole in the nave of the wheel in which the axle is inserted. There was a difference, it seems, in the size of the hole in the wheel of a cart ('''Anas''') and of a chariot ('''[[रथ|Ratha]]''').<ref name=fx3_ve1_813/> See also 1. '''Yuga.'''<br>

खङ्ग
<u>'''Khaṅga.'''</u> See '''[[खड्ग|Khaḍga]].'''<br>

खड्ग
<u>'''Khaḍga'''</u> is the reading in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_815/> of the name of an animal which, in the text of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_815/> variously appears as [[खङ्ग|Khaṅga]] and [[खड्ग|Khaḍga]]. The rhinoceros seems clearly to be meant.<ref name=fx3_ve1_815/> In the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_815/> a rhinoceros hide is mentioned as the covering of a chariot.<br>

खण्डिक औद्भारि
<u>'''Khaṇḍika Audbhāri'''</u> (‘descendant of Udbhāra’) is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_816/> as a teacher of '''[[केशिन्|Keśin]],''' and in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_816/> as having been defeated by [[केशिन्|Keśin]] as a sacrificer. A Khāṇḍika appears in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_816/> as an enemy of [[केशिन्|Keśin]].<br>

खदिर
<u>'''Khadira'''</u> is mentioned frequently from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_817/> onwards<ref name=fx2_ve1_817/> as a tree with hard wood<ref name=fx3_ve1_817/> --the ''Acacia catechu.'' The '''[[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]]''' is referred to as engrafting itself upon it in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_817/>  and from it the climbing plant '''[[अरुन्धती|Arundhatī]]''' is said to have sprung.<ref name=fx5_ve1_817/> The ''[[स्रुव|sruva]]'' or sacrificial ladle is spoken of as having been made from it,<ref name=fx6_ve1_817/> no doubt because of its hardness. It is in the same passage also said to have sprung from the sap (''rasa'') of the Gāyatrī. There is no clear reference to Catechu having been prepared from its core,<ref name=fx7_ve1_817/> as it was later. The core (''sāra'') was used for making amulets.<ref name=fx8_ve1_817/><br>

ख-द्योत
<u>'''Kha-dyota'''</u> (‘sky-illuminator’), ‘the firefly,’ is mentioned in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 7, 3. 5).<br>

खनित्र
<u>'''Khanitra,'''</u> a ‘shovel’ or ‘spade’ for digging, is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_819/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_819/><br>

खनित्रिम
<u>'''Khanitrima,'''</u> ‘produced by digging,’ as an epithet of ''āpaḥ,'' ‘waters,’ clearly refers to artificial water channels used for irrigation, as practised in the times of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_820/> and the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_820/><br>

खर
<u>'''Khara,'''</u> ‘ass,’ is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx1_ve1_821/> where a team of asses is alluded to. Probably the passages in the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_821/> where the word is used to denote an earth mound on which the sacrificial vessels were placed, presuppose the sense of ‘ass,’ the mound being shaped in this form.<ref name=fx3_ve1_821/> <br>

खर्गला
<u>'''Khargalā'''</u> is an ‘owl’ or other nocturnal bird mentioned in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_822/><br>

खर्जूर
<u>'''Kharjūra'''</u> is the name of a tree (''Phœnix silvestris'') which is mentioned in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_823/><br>

खल
<u>'''Khala,'''</u> the ‘threshing-floor,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_824/> and the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_824/> See '''[[कृषि|Kṛṣi]].'''<br>

खल-कुल
<u>'''Khala-kula'''</u> is a word occurring in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_825/> where Sāyaṇa glosses it by Kulattha, a kind of pulse (''Dolichos uniflorus'').<br>

खल्व
<u>'''Khalva'''</u> is some sort of grain or leguminous plant, perhaps, as Weber<ref name=fx1_ve1_826/> thinks, the ''Phaselus radiatus.'' It is mentioned with other grains of all sorts in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_826/> and as being crushed with the '''[[दृषद्|Dṛṣad]]''' in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve1_826/> It occurs also in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_826/> where Śaṅkara glosses it with ''niṣpāva.''<br>

खाण्डव
<u>'''Khāṇḍava'''</u> is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve1_827/> as one of the boundaries of '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]].''' There seems no reason to doubt its identity with the famous [[खाण्डव|Khāṇḍava]] forest of the Mahābhārata. The name occurs also in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_827/> and the Śāṭyāyanaka.<ref name=fx3_ve1_827/> <br>

खादि
<u>'''Khādi'''</u> occurs frequently in the Rigveda denoting either anklets<ref name=fx1_ve1_828/> or armlets,<ref name=fx2_ve1_828/> or sometimes rings on the hands.<ref name=fx3_ve1_828/> Max Müller<ref name=fx4_ve1_828/> considers that the word means quoits, the later [[चक्र|Cakra]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_828/> The rings were sometimes of gold.<ref name=fx6_ve1_828/><br>

खारी
<u>'''Khārī'''</u> designates a measure of Soma in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_829/><br>

खार्गलि
<u>'''Khārgali,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[खर्गला|Khargalā]] or [[खृगल|Khṛgala]],’ is the metronymic or patronymic of Luśākapi.<ref name=fx1_ve1_830/><br>

खिल
<u>'''1. Khila,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_831/> '''Khilya'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_831/> appear to have the same meaning. According to Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve1_831/> these terms denote the waste land lying between cultivated fields; but he admits that this sense does not suit the passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_831/> in which it is said that the god places the worshipper on an unbroken Khilya (''abhinne khilye''), and he accordingly conjectures the reading ''akhilyabhinne,'' ‘land unbroken by barren strips.’ Pischel<ref name=fx5_ve1_831/> thinks that the meaning intended is broad lands, which were used for the pasturing of the cattle of the community, and were not broken up by cultivated fields. Oldenberg,<ref name=fx6_ve1_831/> however, points out that the sense is rather the land which lay between cultivated fields, but which need not be deemed to have been unfertile, as Roth thought. This agrees with the fact that in Vedic times separate fields were already known: see '''[[क्षेत्र|Kṣetra]].''' <br>

खिल
<u>'''2. Khila'''</u> as a designation of certain hymns appended to the received text of the Rigveda occurs only in the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period.<ref name=fx1_ve1_832/> The term is a metaphorical application of the preceding word, ‘a space not filled up,’ ‘a supplement.’<br>

खृगल
<u>'''Khṛgala,'''</u> or, as the Paippalāda recension of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_833/> has it, Khugila, is an obscure expression found in two passages only--once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_833/> and once in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_833/> In the former the meaning ‘crutch’ seems required; in the latter Sāyaṇa glosses it by ‘armour’ (''tanu-trāṇa''), but the sense is quite uncertain.<br>

खेल
<u>'''Khela'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_834/> where Pischel<ref name=fx2_ve1_834/> considers that a god, Vivasvant, is meant, and that races were run in his honour, explaining thus the phrase ''ājā khelasya,'' as ‘in the race of [[खेल|Khela]].’ Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_834/> thinks that a man is meant, and Sieg,<ref name=fx4_ve1_834/> following Sāyaṇa, sees in him a king whose [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] was [[अगस्त्य|Agastya]]. See also '''[[अंशु|Aṃśu]].'''<br>

गङ्गा
<u>'''Gaṅgā,'''</u> the modern Ganges, is mentioned directly in the Rigveda only once, in the [[नदी|Nadī]]-[[स्तुति|stuti]] or ‘Praise of Rivers.’<ref name=fx1_ve1_835/> But it is also referred to in the derivative form ''gāṅgyaḥ'' as an epithet of '''[[उरुकक्ष|Urukakṣa]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_835/> The name of this river does not occur<br><br><ref name=fx2_ve1_835/>  in the other Saṃhitā, but appears in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_835/> where victories of '''[[भरत|Bharata]] [[दौःषन्ति|Dauḥṣanti]]''' on both [[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]] and '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]''' are referred to, and in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx5_ve1_835/> especial honour is assigned to those who dwell between the [[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]] and the [[यमुना|Yamunā]], this being. To doubt, the region in which that text originated. The identification of the [[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]] with the Apayā<ref name=fx6_ve1_835/> made by Ludwig<ref name=fx7_ve1_835/> must be rejected: see '''[[आपया|Āpayā]].'''<br>

गज
<u>'''Gaja,'''</u> the common name of the elephant in Epic<ref name=fx1_ve1_836/> and later Sanskrit, is only found in the late Adbhuta [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_836/> See '''[[हस्तिन्|Hastin]].'''<br>

गणक
<u>'''Gaṇaka,'''</u> ‘an astrologer,’ occurs in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha, or human sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_837/> See also [[नक्षत्रदर्श|Nakṣatradarśa]].<br>

गन्धर्वायण बालेय
<u>'''Gandharvāyaṇa Bāleya'''</u> (‘descendant of Bali’) '''[[आग्निवेश्य|Āgniveśya]]''' is mentioned as a [[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xx. 25).<br>

गन्धार
<u>'''Gandhāra'''</u> is a later form of the name of the people called '''[[गन्धारि|Gandhāri]]''' in the Rigveda and Atharvaveda. In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_839/> the Gandhāras are referred to as being distant from the writer. See also '''[[गान्धार|Gāndhāra]].''' <br>

गन्धारि
<u>'''Gandhāri'''</u> is the name of a people in the north-west of India. In the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_840/> the good wool of the sheep of the Gandhāris is referred to. The Gandhāris are also mentioned with the '''Mūjavants, Angas,''' and '''Magadhas''' in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_840/> Gandhāris<ref name=fx3_ve1_840/> or Gāndhāris<ref name=fx4_ve1_840/> are also spoken of in the Śrauta Sūtras.<ref name=fx5_ve1_840/> Zimmer<ref name=fx6_ve1_840/> considers that they were settled in Vedic times on the south bank of the '''[[कुभा|Kubhā]]''' up to its mouth in the Indus, and for some distance down the east side of the Indus itself. They later formed a portion of the Persian empire, and detachments of Gandarians accompanied Xerxes in his expedition against Greece.<ref name=fx7_ve1_840/><br>

गभस्ति
<u>'''Gabhasti'''</u> denotes, according to Roth,<ref name=fx1_ve1_841/> the pole of a chariot in the epithet ''[[स्यूम-गभस्ति|syūma-gabhasti]],'' ‘having reins as a pole,’ used of the car of the gods in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_841/> and independently in the plural in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_841/> The meaning is, however, doubtful.<ref name=fx4_ve1_841/> Roth<ref name=fx5_ve1_841/> himself suggests that ''[[स्यूम-गभस्ति|syūma-gabhasti]]'' may refer to a sort of double reins.<br>

गय
<u>'''1. Gaya,'''</u> ‘house,’ is a common word in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_842/> and sometimes occurs later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_842/> As its sense includes the inmates as well as their belongings, it is equivalent to ‘household.’<br>

गय प्लात
<u>'''2. Gaya Plāta'''</u> (‘son of Plati’) is referred to in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_843/> two hymns of which he clearly claims to have composed, and which are attributed to him in the Sarvānukramaṇī and the  [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_843/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_843/> he appears with [[असित|Asita]] and [[कश्यप|Kaśyapa]] as a half-mythical magician.<ref name=fx4_ve1_843/><br>

गर
<u>'''1. Gara,'''</u> ‘poison,’ is referred to in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_844/> in the compound ''gara-gīrṇa,'' ‘poisoned.’ In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_844/> it means simply a ‘fluid.’<br>

गर
<u>'''2. Gara'''</u> is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_845/> as the author of a Sāman or Chant, and as a friend of Indra.<br>

गर्ग
<u>'''Garga'''</u> is the name of a sage who is not mentioned in any of the Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_846/> but his descendants, the ''Gargāḥ Prāvareyāḥ,'' are referred to in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve1_846/> [[गर्ग|Garga]] himself does not occur till the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period.<ref name=fx3_ve1_846/><br>

गर्गर
<u>'''Gargara,'''</u> apparently the designation of a musical instrument, is mentioned once in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_847/><br>

गर्त
<u>'''Garta'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_848/> primarily denotes the seat of the chariot on which the archer sat. It seems to have been of considerable  size, being described as ''bṛhant,''<ref name=fx2_ve1_848/> ‘large.’ The word then comes to denote the chariot<ref name=fx3_ve1_848/> itself, either really or metaphorically.<ref name=fx4_ve1_848/><br>

गर्दभ
<u>'''Gardabha,'''</u> ‘the ass,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_849/> as inferior to the horse. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā he again appears as inferior to the horse,<ref name=fx2_ve1_849/> but at the same time as the best bearer of burdens (''bhāra-bhāritama'') among animals.<ref name=fx3_ve1_849/> The same authority styles the ass ''[[द्वि-रेतस्|dvi-retas]],'' ‘having double seed,’<ref name=fx4_ve1_849/> in allusion to his breeding with the mare as well as the she-ass. The smallness of the young of the ass, and his capacity for eating, are both referred to.<ref name=fx5_ve1_849/> The disagreeable cry of the animal is mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx6_ve1_849/> and in allusion to this the term ‘ass’ is applied opprobriously to a singer in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx7_ve1_849/> A hundred asses are spoken of as a gift to a singer in a [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymn.<ref name=fx8_ve1_849/> The mule (''[[अश्वतर|aśvatara]]'') is the offspring of an ass and a mare, the latter, like the ass, being called ''[[द्विरेतस्|dviretas]],''<ref name=fx9_ve1_849/> ‘receiving double seed,’ for similar reasons. The male ass is often also termed '''[[रासभ|Rāsabha]].''' The female ass, Gardabhī, is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx10_ve1_849/> and the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx11_ve1_849/><br>

गर्दभी-मुख
<u>'''Gardabhī-mukha'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_850/> <br>

गर्दभी-विपीत
<u>'''Gardabhī-vipīta,'''</u> or '''Gardabhī-vibhīta,''' is the name of a teacher who was a [[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]] and a contemporary of '''[[जनक|Janaka]],''' mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].(**  1) iv. 1, 11 (Mādhyaṃdina = iv. 1, 5 [[काण्व|Kāṇva]]).<br>

गर्मुत्
<u>'''Garmut'''</u> is the name of a kind of wild bean mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_852/> The [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_852/> has the form Ganmut, which is probably a false reading. The adjective ''gārmuta,'' ‘made from the [[गर्मुत्|Garmut]] bean,’ is found in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx3_ve1_852/><br>

गलुन्त
<u>'''Galunta'''</u> is a word occurring only once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_853/> apparently in the sense of ‘swelling,’<ref name=fx2_ve1_853/> but Whitney<ref name=fx3_ve1_853/> translates it by ‘neck.’<br>

गलूनस आर्क्षाकायण
<u>'''Galūnasa Ārkṣākāyaṇa'''</u> (‘descendant of Ṛkṣāka’) is mentioned as a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 38, 4).<br>

गवय
<u>'''Gavaya,'''</u> the name of a species of ox (''Bos gavacus'') occurs frequently from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_855/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve1_855/> It is mentioned with '''[[गौर|Gaura]]''' and '''[[महिष|Mahiṣa]]''' in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_855/> where also a wild [[गवय|Gavaya]] is spoken of.<ref name=fx4_ve1_855/><br>

गवाशिर्
<u>'''Gavāśir,'''</u> ‘mixed with milk,’ is a frequent epithet of '''Soma''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_856/> <br>

गव्-इष्टि
<u>'''Gav-iṣṭi'''</u> (lit. ‘desire of cows’) in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_857/> denotes ‘conflict’ or ‘battle,’ evidently with reference to cattle raids. [[गव्या|Gavyā]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_857/> is similarly used.<br>

गवि-ष्ठिर आत्रेय
<u>'''Gavi-ṣṭhira Ātreya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''Atri'''’) is mentioned as a '''[[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]],''' or seer, in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_858/> and the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_858/><br>

गवीधुका
<u>'''Gavīdhukā,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_859/> '''Gavedhukā,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_859/> is the name of a species of grass (''Coix barbata''). It is also referred to in the adjectival forms ''gāvīdhuka''<ref name=fx3_ve1_859/> and ''gāvedhuka.''<ref name=fx4_ve1_859/> It was boiled with rice<ref name=fx5_ve1_859/> (''gavīdhukāyavāgā'') or barley<ref name=fx6_ve1_859/> (''gavedhukā-saktavaḥ'') in preparing gruel.<br>

गव्य
<u>'''Gavya.'''</u> See '''[[गव्यूति|Gavyūti]].'''<br>

गव्या
<u>'''Gavyā.'''</u> See '''[[गव्इष्टि|Gaviṣṭi]].'''<br>

गव्यूति
<u>'''Gavyūti'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_862/> means, according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve1_862/> grass land for the pasturing of cattle, in which sense [[गव्य|Gavya]] is also found.<ref name=fx3_ve1_862/> Thence it derives the sense of a measure of distance found in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_862/> Geldner, on the other hand, takes the original meaning to be ‘road,’ real<ref name=fx6_ve1_862/> or metaphorical,<ref name=fx7_ve1_862/> thence a measure of distance,<ref name=fx8_ve1_862/> and finally ‘land.’<ref name=fx9_ve1_862/>(**  5) ''Vedische Studien,'' 2, 290, 291. <br>

गाङ्ग्य
<u>'''Gāṅgya,'''</u> ‘being on the Ganges,’ is the epithet of '''[[उरुकक्ष|Urukakṣa]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_863/> or of a thicket<ref name=fx2_ve1_863/> in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve1_863/><br>

गाङ्ग्यायनि
<u>'''Gāṅgyāyani,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[गाङ्ग्य|Gāṅgya]],’ occurs as the patronymic of '''[[चित्र|Citra]]''' in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_864/><br>

गातु
<u>'''Gātu.'''</u> See '''[[गाथा|Gāthā]].'''<br>

गाथा
<u>'''Gāthā'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_866/> usually means only ‘song,’ ‘verse,’ like [[गातु|Gātu]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_866/> In one passage,<ref name=fx3_ve1_866/> however, it already has a more special sense, as it is classed with '''[[नाराशंसी|Nārāśaṃsī]]''' and '''[[रैभी|Raibhī]],''' a collocation repeatedly found later.<ref name=fx4_ve1_866/> The commentators identify the three terms with certain verses of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx5_ve1_866/> but Oldenberg<ref name=fx6_ve1_866/> has shown that this identification is incorrect for the Rigveda. Gāthās are often mentioned elsewhere,<ref name=fx7_ve1_866/> and are referred to as metrical in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx8_ve1_866/> where the '''Ṛc, [[कुम्ब्या|Kumbyā]],''' and [[गाथा|Gāthā]] are classed as forms of verse. The [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx9_ve1_866/> distinguishes between Ṛc and [[गाथा|Gāthā]] as divine and human respectively. According to the usage of the  Brāhmaṇas and the liturgical literature, as stated by the St. Petersburg Dictionary, the Gāthās are, though religious in content, distinguished from Ṛc, [[यजुस्|Yajus]], and Sāman as nonVedic--that is, are not Mantras. This view is consistent with the fact that the phrase '''[[यज्ञ-गाथा|Yajña-gāthā]],''' meaning a verse summarizing a sacrificial usage, is not rare. The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx10_ve1_866/> preserves several Gāthās, which generally accord with this description as epitomizing the sacrifices of famous kings, and the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx11_ve1_866/> states that a [[गाथा|Gāthā]] is sung at a wedding. Sometimes<ref name=fx12_ve1_866/> [[गाथा|Gāthā]] is qualified as [[नाराशंसी|Nārāśaṃsī]], where it must be a eulogy of a generous donor.<br>

गाथिन्
<u>'''Gāthin'''</u> is mentioned as the son of '''[[कुशिक|Kuśika]]''' and father of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' in the Sarvānukramaṇī. It is difficult to say whether this tradition is correct; it derives some support from the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 18), where reference is made to the divine lore (''[[दैव|daiva]] veda'') of the Gāthins, which is said to be shared by '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]''' as a result of his adoption by '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]].''' See '''[[गाथिन|Gāthina]].'''<br>

गाथिन
<u>'''Gāthina.'''</u>--The sons of [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] are described in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_868/> as Gāthinas, or descendants of [[गाथिन्|Gāthin]], who, according to tradition, was their grandfather;<ref name=fx2_ve1_868/> and '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' himself is styled [[गाथिन|Gāthina]] in the Sarvānukramaṇī. <br>

गां-दम
<u>'''Gāṃ-dama'''</u> is the form in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_869/> of the name of '''Ekayāvan,''' which in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_869/> is read as Kāṃdama.<br>

गान्धार
<u>'''Gāndhāra,'''</u> ‘a king of Gandhāra’ named '''[[नग्नजित्|Nagnajit]],''' is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_870/> In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_870/> he or some descendant figures as '''[[स्वर्जित् नाग्नजित|Svarjit Nāgnajita]]''' or [[नग्नजित्|Nagnajit]], and as giving an opinion on the ritual, which is rejected with the observation that the author was merely a princely person (''[[राजन्य-बन्धु|rājanya-bandhu]]'').<br>

गार्गी वाचक्नवी
<u>'''Gārgī Vācaknavī'''</u> is referred to in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_871/> as a female contemporary and rival of '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]].'''<br>

गार्गी-पुत्र
<u>'''Gārgī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of Gargī,’ occurs as the name of three teachers in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 30). The earliest of these three was the pupil of '''[[बाडेयीपुत्र|Bāḍeyīputra]]''' and the teacher of the second [[गार्गीपुत्र|Gārgīputra]]. The latter was the teacher of '''[[पाराशरीकौण्डिनीपुत्र|Pārāśarīkauṇḍinīputra]],''' the teacher of the third [[गार्गीपुत्र|Gārgīputra]].<br>

गार्ग्य
<u>'''Gārgya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[गर्ग|Garga]],’ is the patronymic of '''[[बालाकि|Bālāki]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve1_873/> and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_873/> Upaniṣads. Two Gārgyas are mentioned in the second [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]:<ref name=fx3_ve1_873/> one of them is the pupil of [[गार्ग्य|Gārgya]], who again is the pupil of [[गौतम|Gautama]]. Others occur in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx4_ve1_873/> and in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_873/> as well as later in the ritual Sūtras. Thus the family was evidently long connected with the development of liturgy and grammar. <br>

गार्ग्यायण
<u>'''Gārgyāyaṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[गार्ग्य|Gārgya]],’ is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[उद्दालकायन|Uddālakāyana]]''' in the second [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 6, 2 [[काण्व|Kāṇva]]).<br>

गार्ग्यायणि
<u>'''Gārgyāyaṇi,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[गार्ग्य|Gārgya]],’ is a variant reading for '''[[गाङ्ग्यायनि|Gāṅgyāyani]]''' as the patronymic of '''[[चित्र|Citra]]''' in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 1).<br>

गालव
<u>'''Gālava'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of '''Vidarbhīkauṇḍinya''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_876/> It is possibly the same man that is referred to regarding a point of ritual in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx2_ve1_876/> A grammarian of this name is mentioned in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_876/><br>

गिरि
<u>'''Giri,'''</u> ‘mountain’ or ‘height,’ is a word that occurs repeatedly in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_877/> Thus reference is made to the trees on the hills, hence called ‘tree-haired’ (''[[वृक्ष|vṛkṣa]]-keśāḥ''),<ref name=fx2_ve1_877/> and to the streams proceeding from the hills to the sea (''[[सम्उद्र|samudra]]'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_877/> The term is frequently coupled with the adjectival ''[[पर्वत|parvata]].''<ref name=fx4_ve1_877/> The Rigveda mentions the waters from the hills,<ref name=fx5_ve1_877/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_877/> refers to the snowy mountains. Actual names of mountains, as '''[[मूजवन्त्|Mūjavant]], [[त्रिककुद्|Trikakud]], [[हिमवन्त्|Himavant]],''' are very rare. References to '''[[क्रौञ्च|Krauñca]], [[महामेरु|Mahāmeru]],''' and '''Maināga,''' are confined to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka, while '''[[नावप्रभ्रंशन|Nāvaprabhraṃśana]]''' can no longer be considered a proper name.<ref name=fx7_ve1_877/><br>

गिरि-क्षित् औच्चा-मन्यव
<u>'''Giri-kṣit Auccā-manyava,'''</u> ‘descendant of Uccāmanyu,’ is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 5, 7) as a contemporary of '''Abhipratārin Kākṣaseṇi''' <br>

गिरि-ज बाभ्रव्य
<u>'''Giri-ja Bābhravya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[बभ्रु|Babhru]],’ is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 1) as having been taught by '''Śrauta''' the method of dividing the sacrificial animal (''paśor vibhakti'').<br>

गुग्गुलु
<u>'''Guggulu,'''</u> ‘bdellium,’ is referred to in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_880/> as produced by the [[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_880/> and by the sea. The latter source presumably alludes, as Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_880/> assumes, to seaborne trade, bdellium being the gum of a tree, not a product of the sea. It is, however, possible that in this passage some other substance may be meant. The word in this form also occurs elsewhere in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_880/> and later;<ref name=fx5_ve1_880/> it is often<ref name=fx6_ve1_880/> mentioned in the older form of '''[[गुल्गुलु|Gulgulu]],''' between which and [[गुग्गुलु|Guggulu]] the manuscripts constantly vary<br>

गुङ्गु
<u>'''Guṅgu.'''</u>--The descendants of [[गुङ्गु|Guṅgu]] are referred to as Guṅgus in a hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_881/> apparently as friends of '''[[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]].''' Possibly a people may be meant.<br>

गुप्त
<u>'''Gupta'''</u> is the name in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42) of '''[[वैपश्चित|Vaipaścita]] [[दार्ढजयन्ति|Dārḍhajayanti]] [[गुप्त|Gupta]] [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]].''' All the three other names being patronymics show that he was descended from the families of Vipaścit, [[दृढजयन्त|Dṛḍhajayanta]], and [[लोहित|Lohita]].<br>

गुल्गुलु
<u>'''Gulgulu.'''</u> See '''[[गुग्गुलु|Guggulu]].'''<br>

गृत्स-मद
<u>'''Gṛtsa-mada'''</u> is the name of a seer to whom the Sarvānukramaṇī attributes the authorship of the second Maṇḍala of the Rigveda. This tradition is supported by the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Brāh-  maṇa<ref name=fx1_ve1_884/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Araṇyaka.<ref name=fx2_ve1_884/> The [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_884/> speaks of him as a '''[[भार्गव|Bhārgava]],''' ‘descendant of [[भृगु|Bhṛgu]],’ with a variant '''[[बाभ्रव|Bābhrava]],''' ‘descendant of [[बभ्रु|Babhru]],’ but the later tradition keeps to the former patronymic.<ref name=fx4_ve1_884/> The Gṛtsamadas are often mentioned in the second Maṇḍala of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx5_ve1_884/> and are also called Śunahotras,<ref name=fx6_ve1_884/> but never Gārtsamadas or Śaunahotras, and [[गृत्समद|Gṛtsamada]] himself never occurs there.<ref name=fx7_ve1_884/><br>

गृध्र
<u>'''Gṛdhra,'''</u> ‘the vulture,’ is often mentioned from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_885/> downwards.<ref name=fx2_ve1_885/> The swiftness of its flight<ref name=fx3_ve1_885/> and its fondness for devouring carrion are especially noticed.<ref name=fx4_ve1_885/> More generally the word is used to designate any bird of prey, the eagle ('''[[श्येन|Śyena]]''') being classed as the chief of the Gṛdhras.<ref name=fx5_ve1_885/><br>

गृष्टि
<u>'''Gṛṣṭi,'''</u> ‘a young cow,’ which has only calved once, occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_886/> and the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_886/> as well as in the later [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] literature.<ref name=fx3_ve1_886/><br>

गृह
<u>'''Gṛha'''</u> is used in the singular,<ref name=fx1_ve1_887/> or oftener in the plural,<ref name=fx2_ve1_887/> to denote the ‘house’ of the Vedic Indian. '''Dama''' or '''Dam''' has  the same sense, while '''[[पस्त्या|Pastyā]]''' and '''[[हर्म्य|Harmya]]''' denote more especially the home with its surroundings, the family settlement. The house held not only the family, which might be of considerable size, but also the cattle<ref name=fx3_ve1_887/> and the sheep<ref name=fx4_ve1_887/> at night. It was composed of several rooms, as the use of the plural indicates, and it could be securely shut up.<ref name=fx5_ve1_887/> The door ('''[[द्वार्|Dvār]], Dvāra''') is often referred to, and from it the house is called '''[[दुरोण|Duroṇa]].''' In every house the fire was kept burning.<ref name=fx6_ve1_887/><br><br>Very little is known of the structure of the house. Presumably stone was not used,<ref name=fx7_ve1_887/> and houses were, as in Megasthenes' time,<ref name=fx8_ve1_887/> built of wood. The hymns of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx9_ve1_887/> give some information about the construction of a house, but the details are extremely obscure, for most of the expressions used do not recur in any context in which their sense is clear. According to Zimmer,<ref name=fx10_ve1_887/> four pillars ('''[[उपमित्|Upamit]]''') were set up on a good site, and against them beams were leant at an angle as props ('''[[प्रतिमित्|Pratimit]]'''). The upright pillars were connected by cross beams ('''[[परिमित्|Parimit]]''') resting upon them. The roof was formed of ribs of bamboo cane (''[[वंश|vaṃśa]]''),<ref name=fx11_ve1_887/> a ridge called '''[[विषूवन्त्|Viṣūvant]],''' and a net ('''[[अक्षु|Akṣu]]'''), which may mean a thatched covering<ref name=fx12_ve1_887/> over the bamboo ribs. The walls were filled up with grass in bundles (''[[पलद|palada]]''), and the whole structure was held together with ties of  various sorts (''nahana, prāṇāha, [[संदंश|saṃdaṃśa]], pariṣvañjalya'').<ref name=fx13_ve1_887/> In connexion with the house, mention is made of four terms which, though primarily sacrificial in meaning, seem to designate parts of the building: [[हविर्धान|Havirdhāna]], ‘oblation-holder’; [[अग्निशाल|Agniśāla]],<ref name=fx14_ve1_887/> ‘fireplace’; Patnīnāṃ [[सदन|Sadana]], ‘wives’ room’; and [[सदस्|Sadas]], ‘sitting room.’ Slings or hanging vessels ('''[[शिक्य|Śikya]]''') are also mentioned.<ref name=fx15_ve1_887/> Reedwork (''[[इट|iṭa]]'') is spoken of, no doubt as part of the finishing of the walls of the house.<ref name=fx16_ve1_887/> The sides are called '''[[पक्ष|Pakṣa]].''' The door with its framework was named '''[[आता|Ātā]].'''<br>

गृह-प
<u>'''Gṛha-pa'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_888/> or '''[[गृह|Gṛha]]-pati'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_888/> is the regular name, from the Rigveda onwards, of the householder as master of the house. Similarly the mistress is called [[गृह|Gṛha]]-[[पत्नी|patnī]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_888/> For the powers and position of the Gṛhapati see '''[[पितृ|Pitṛ]].'''<br>

गृह्य
<u>'''Gṛhya'''</u> denotes the members of the house or family in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].(**  1) ii. 5, 2, 14; 3, 16; 6, 2, 4; iii. 4, 1, 6; xii. 4, 1, 4. ''Cf. gṛhāḥ,'' i. 7, 4; 12.<br>

गैरि-क्षित
<u>'''Gairi-kṣita,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Girikṣit,'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]]''' in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_890/> and of the '''Yaskas''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve1_890/><br>

गो
<u>'''1. Go'''</u> (''a''), ‘ox’ or ‘cow.’<ref name=fx1_ve1_891/> These were among the chief sources of wealth to the Vedic Indian, and are repeatedly  referred to from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve1_891/> The milk ('''[[क्षीर|Kṣīra]]''') was either drunk fresh or made into butter ('''[[घृत|Ghṛta]]''') or curds ('''[[दधि|Dadhi]]'''), or was mixed with '''Soma''' or used for cooking with grain ('''[[क्षीरौदन|Kṣīraudana]]'''). The cows were milked thrice a day, early (''[[प्रातर्|prātar]]-doha''), in the forenoon ('''[[संगव|Saṃgava]]'''), and in the evening (''sāyaṃ-doha'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_891/> Thrice a day they were driven out to graze, according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_891/> (''prātaḥ, saṃgave, sāyam''). The first milking was productive, the last two scanty.<ref name=fx3_ve1_891/> According to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_891/> among the Bharatas the herds in the evening are in the '''[[गोष्ठ|Goṣṭha]],''' at midday in the '''Saṃgavīnī.''' This passage Sāyaṇa expands by saying that the herds go home to the [[शाला|Śālā]], or house for animals, at night so far as they consist of animals giving milk, while the others stayed out in the [[गोष्ठ|Goṣṭha]], or open pasturage; but both were together in the cattle-shed during the heat of the day. The time before the [[संगव|Saṃgava]], when the cows were grazing freely on the pastureland, was called '''[[स्वसर|Svasara]].'''<ref name=fx6_ve1_891/> When the cows were out feeding they were separated from the calves, which were, however, allowed to join them at the [[संगव|Saṃgava]],<ref name=fx7_ve1_891/> and sometimes in the evening.<ref name=fx8_ve1_891/><br><br>While grazing the cattle were under the care of a herdsman ('''[[गोपा|Gopā]], Gopāla''') armed with a goad,<ref name=fx9_ve1_891/> but they were liable to all sorts of dangers, such as being lost, falling into pits, breaking limbs,<ref name=fx10_ve1_891/>  and being stolen. The marking of the ears of cattle was repeatedly adopted, no doubt, to indicate ownership.<ref name=fx11_ve1_891/><br><br>Large herds of cattle were well-known, as is shown by the Dānastutis, or ‘praises of gifts,’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx12_ve1_891/> even when allowances are made for the exaggeration of priestly gratitude. The importance attached to the possession of cattle is shown<ref name=fx13_ve1_891/> by the numerous passages in which the gods are asked to prosper them, and by the repeated prayers<ref name=fx14_ve1_891/> for wealth in kine. Hence, too, forays for cattle ('''[[गव्इष्टि|Gaviṣṭi]]''') were well known; the [[भरत|Bharata]] host is called the ‘horde desiring cows’ (''gavyan grāmaḥ'') in the Rigveda;<ref name=fx15_ve1_891/> and a verbal root ''gup,''<ref name=fx16_ve1_891/> ‘to protect,’ was evolved as early as the Rigveda from the denominative ''go-pāya,'' ‘to guard cows.’ The Vedic poets<ref name=fx17_ve1_891/> do not hesitate to compare their songs with the lowing of cows, or to liken the choir of the singing Apsarases to cows.<ref name=fx18_ve1_891/><br><br>The cattle of the Vedic period were of many colours: red (''[[रोहित|rohita]]''), light (''[[शुक्र|śukra]]''), dappled (''pṛśni''), even black (''[[कृष्ण|kṛṣṇa]]'').<ref name=fx19_ve1_891/> Zimmer<ref name=fx20_ve1_891/> sees a reference to cows with blazes on the face in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx21_ve1_891/> but this is uncertain.<br><br>Oxen were regularly used for ploughing or for drawing wagons (''[[अनड्वाह्|anaḍvāh]]''), in which case they were, it seems, usually castrated.<ref name=fx22_ve1_891/> Cows were not properly used for drawing carts, hough they at times did so.<ref name=fx23_ve1_891/> The flesh of both cows and bulls was sometimes eaten ('''Māmsa'''). Cattle were certainly the  objects of individual ownership, and they formed one of the standards of exchange and valuation (see '''[[क्रय|Kraya]]''').<br><br>(''b'') The term '''Go''' is often applied to express the products of the cow. It frequently means the milk,<ref name=fx1b_ve1_891/> but rarely the flesh<ref name=fx2b_ve1_891/> of the animal. In many passages it designates leather used as the material of various objects, as a bowstring,<ref name=fx3b_ve1_891/> or a sling,<ref name=fx4b_ve1_891/> or thongs to fasten part of the chariot,<ref name=fx5b_ve1_891/> or reins,<ref name=fx6b_ve1_891/> or the lash of a whip.<ref name=fx7b_ve1_891/> See also '''[[चर्मन्|Carman]],''' with which Go is sometimes synonymous.<ref name=fx8b_ve1_891/><br><br>(''c'') '''Gāvaḥ''' means the stars of heaven in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1c_ve1_891/> according to Roth.<ref name=fx2c_ve1_891/><br>

गो आङ्गिरस
<u>'''2. Go Āṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]'''’) is the reputed author of a Sāman or Chant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_892/> There is little doubt that he is mythical.<ref name=fx2_ve1_892/><br>

गो-घात
<u>'''Go-ghāta,'''</u> ‘a cow-killer,’ is enumerated in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha, or human sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_893/> See '''[[मांस|Māṃsa]].'''<br>

गोतम
<u>'''Gotama'''</u> is mentioned several times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_894/> but never in such a way as to denote personal authorship of any hymn.<ref name=fx2_ve1_894/> It seems clear that he was closely connected with the  Aṅgirases, for the Gotamas frequently refer to '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_894/> That he bore the patronymic [[राहूगण|Rāhūgaṇa]] is rendered probable by one hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_894/> and is assumed in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_894/> where he appears as the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], or domestic priest, of '''[[माथव|Māthava]] [[विदेघ|Videgha]],''' and as a bearer of Vedic civilization. He is also mentioned in the same [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_894/> as a contemporary of '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' of '''[[विदेह|Videha]],''' and '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]],''' and as the author of a [[स्तोम|Stoma]].<ref name=fx7_ve1_894/> He occurs, moreover, in two passages of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx8_ve1_894/><br><br>The Gotamas are mentioned in several passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx9_ve1_894/> '''[[वामदेव|Vāmadeva]]''' and '''[[नोधस्|Nodhas]]''' being specified as sons of [[गोतम|Gotama]]. They include the '''Vājaśravases.''' See also '''[[गौतम|Gautama]].'''<br>

गोतमी-पुत्र
<u>'''Gotamī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of Gotamī,’ is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[भारद्वाजी-पुत्र|Bhāradvājī-putra]]''' in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 1). See also '''[[गौतमी-पुत्र|Gautamī-putra]].'''<br>

गोत्र
<u>'''Gotra'''</u> occurs several times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_896/> in the account of the mythic exploits of Indra. Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_896/> interprets the word as ‘cowstall,’ while Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve1_896/> thinks ‘herd’ is meant. The latter sense seems to explain best the employment which the term shows in the later literature as denoting the ‘family’ or ‘clan,’ and which is found in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_896/><br><br>In the [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] Sūtras<ref name=fx5_ve1_896/> stress is laid on the prohibition of  marriage within a [[गोत्र|Gotra]], or with a Sapiṇḍa of the mother of the bridegroom--that is to say, roughly, with agnates and cognates. Senart<ref name=fx6_ve1_896/> has emphasized this fact as a basis of caste, on the ground that marriage within a ''curia, phratria,'' or caste ('''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]]''') was Indo-European, as was marriage outside the circle of agnates and cognates. But there is no evidence at all<ref name=fx7_ve1_896/> to prove that this practice was Indo-European, while in India the Śatapatha<ref name=fx8_ve1_896/> expressly recognizes marriage within the third or fourth degree on either side. According to Sāyaṇa, the Kāṇvas accepted marriage in the third degree, the Saurāṣṭras only in the fourth, while the scholiast on the Vajrasūcī<ref name=fx9_ve1_896/> adḍs to the Kāṇvas the Andhras and the Dākṣiṇātyas, and remarks that the Vājasaneyins forbade marriage with the daughter of the mother's brother. All apparently allowed marriage with the daughter of a paternal uncle, which later was quite excluded. Change of [[गोत्र|Gotra]] was quite possible, as in the case of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]''' and '''[[गृत्समद|Gṛtsamada]],''' who, once an Aṅgirasa, became a [[भार्गव|Bhārgava]].<ref name=fx10_ve1_896/><br>

गो-दान
<u>'''Go-dāna'''</u> appears to mean ‘the whiskers’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_897/> where the person, being consecrated, first shaves off the right and then the left ‘whisker.’ Later on the Godānavidhi, or ceremony of shaving the head, is a regular part of the initiation of a youth on the attainment of manhood and on marriage;<ref name=fx2_ve1_897/> but though the ceremony is recognized in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_897/> the name<ref name=fx4_ve1_897/> does not occur there. <br>

गोधा
<u>'''Godhā.'''</u>--(''a'') The sense of ‘bowstring’ seems certain in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_898/> and possible in another.<ref name=fx2_ve1_898/> Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_898/> also adopts this meaning in the only passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_898/> where the word occurs.<br><br>(''b'') In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1b_ve1_898/> the sense of ‘musical instrument’ is recognized by Roth and by Hillebrandt<ref name=fx2b_ve1_898/> for this word.<br><br>(''c'') Elsewhere<ref name=fx1c_ve1_898/> an animal seems to be meant, perhaps the ‘crocodile,’ as Ludwig<ref name=fx2c_ve1_898/> and Weber<ref name=fx3c_ve1_898/> think; perhaps a large ‘lizard,’ as Roth and Zimmer<ref name=fx4c_ve1_898/> assume. An animal is probably also meant in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx5_ve1_898/><br>

गो-धूम
<u>'''Go-dhūma,'''</u> ‘wheat,’ is frequently referred to in the plural in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_899/> and Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve1_899/> and is expressly distinguished from ‘rice’ ('''[[व्रीहि|Vrīhi]]''') or ‘barley’ ('''Yava''').<ref name=fx3_ve1_899/> ‘Groats’ (''saktavaḥ'') made of this grain are also mentioned.<ref name=fx4_ve1_899/> The word occurs in the singular in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_899/><br>

गो-पति
<u>'''Go-pati,'''</u> ‘lord of cows,’ is freely used in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_900/> to denote any lord or master, a natural usage considering that cattle formed the main species of wealth. <br>

गोप-वन
<u>'''Gopa-vana'''</u> is the name of a poet of the race of Atri in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_901/> See '''[[गौपवन|Gaupavana]].'''<br>

गो-पा
<u>'''Go-pā'''</u> and '''Go-pāla,''' ‘protector of cows,’ occur in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_902/> and later, but the former is usually metaphorical in sense, applying to any protector, while the latter has the literal force of ‘cow-herd.’<br>

गो-बल
<u>'''Go-bala'''</u> (‘ox-strength’) '''[[वार्ष्ण|Vārṣṇa]]''' (‘descendant of Vṛṣṇi’) is mentioned as a teacher in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (iii. 11, 9, 3) and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 6, 1).<br>

गो-मती
<u>'''Go-matī,'''</u> ‘possessing cows,’ is mentioned as a river in the [[नदी|Nadī]]-[[स्तुति|stuti]], or ‘Praise of Rivers,’ in the tenth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_904/> In that hymn a river flowing into the Indus must be meant, and its identification<ref name=fx2_ve1_904/> with the Gomal, a western tributary of the Indus, cannot be doubted. In one other passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_904/> the accentuation of Gomati shows that a river is meant. It is possible that in a third passage<ref name=fx4_ve1_904/> the reading should be changed to ''gomatír'' from ''gómatīr.'' Geldner<ref name=fx5_ve1_904/> suggests that in the two last passages the Gumti, or rather its four upper arms (hence the use of the plural) is meant: this accords well with the later use of the name and with the general probability of the river here intended being in '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]],''' as the centre of Vedic civilization.<ref name=fx6_ve1_904/> <br>

गो-मायु
<u>'''Go-māyu,'''</u> ‘lowing like a cow,’ does not occur as the name of the ‘jackal’ till the late Adbhuta [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_905/><br>

गो-मृग
<u>'''Go-mṛga,'''</u> a species of ox, now called Gayal (''Bos gavaeus''), is mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_906/> and Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_906/> In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_906/> it is declared to be neither a wild nor a tame animal; this presumably means that it was semidomesticated, or perhaps that it was both tamed and found wild. With the name of this animal may be compared the [[मृग|Mṛga]] [[महिष|Mahiṣa]], which is clearly mentioned as wild in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx4_ve1_906/> See also '''Gayava.'''<br>

गोलत्तिका
<u>'''Golattikā'''</u> is the name of some unknown animal in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_907/><br>

गो-विकर्तन
<u>'''Go-vikartana'''</u> (‘cow-butcher’) designates the ‘huntsman’ in the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 3, 1, 10).<ref name=fx1_ve1_908/> See '''[[गोघात|Goghāta]].'''<br>

गो-व्यच
<u>'''Go-vyaca.'''</u> See '''Vyaca.'''<br>

गोशर्य
<u>'''Gośarya'''</u> is the name of a protégé of the Aśvins in the Rigveda (viii. 8, 20; 49, 1; 50, 10).<br>

गो-श्रु जाबाल
<u>'''Go-śru Jābāla'''</u> is mentioned as a sage in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 7, 7).<br>

गो-श्रुति वैयाघ्र-पद्य
<u>'''Go-śruti Vaiyāghra-padya'''</u> (‘descendant of Vyāghrapad’) is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[सत्यकाम|Satyakāma]]''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (v. 2, 3). In the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (ix. 7) the name appears as Gośruta. <br>

गो-षादी
<u>'''Go-ṣādī'''</u> (‘sitting on a cow’) is the name of a bird in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_913/><br>

गो-षूक्तिन्
<u>'''Go-ṣūktin'''</u> is mentioned in the Sarvānukramaṇī as the author of Rigveda viii. 14 and 15, and a Sāman or Chant of his seems to be referred to in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xix. 4, 9), under the title of Gauṣūkta. But see '''[[गौषूक्ति|Gauṣūkti]].'''<br>

गो-ष्ठ
<u>'''Go-ṣṭha,'''</u> ‘standing-place for cows,’ denotes not so much a ‘cowstall’ as the ‘grazing ground of cows,’ as Geldner<ref name=fx1_ve1_915/> shows from a passage of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_915/> and from a note of Mahīdhara on the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx3_ve1_915/> This sense suits adequately all the passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_915/> where it occurs, and it greatly improves the interpretation of a hymn of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx5_ve1_915/> besides being acceptable elsewhere.<ref name=fx6_ve1_915/> See also '''Go.'''<br>

गौतम
<u>'''Gautama,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[गोतम|Gotama]],’ is a common patronymic, being applied to '''Aruṇa,'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_916/> '''[[उद्दालक आरुणि|Uddālaka Āruṇi]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_916/> '''Kuśri,'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_916/> '''Sāti,'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_916/> '''[[हारिद्रुमत|Hāridrumata]].'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_916/><br><br>Several Gautamas are mentioned in the Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] as pupils of '''[[आग्निवेश्य|Āgniveśya]],'''<ref name=fx6_ve1_916/> of '''[[सैतव|Saitava]]''' and '''[[प्राचीनयोग्य|Prācīnayogya]],'''<ref name=fx7_ve1_916/> of '''[[सैतव|Saitava]],'''<ref name=fx8_ve1_916/> of '''Bhārad-  [[वाज|vāja]],'''<ref name=fx9_ve1_916/> of '''[[गौतम|Gautama]],'''<ref name=fx10_ve1_916/> and of '''[[वात्स्य|Vātsya]].'''<ref name=fx11_ve1_916/> A [[गौतम|Gautama]] is also referred to elsewhere.<br>

गौतमी-पुत्र
<u>'''Gautamī-putra'''</u> (‘son of a female descendant of Gotama’) is mentioned in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 2) as a pupil of '''[[भारद्वाजीपुत्र|Bhāradvājīputra]].''' In the Mādhyaṃdina (vi. 4, 31) a [[गौतमीपुत्र|Gautamīputra]] is a pupil of '''[[आत्रेयीपुत्र|Ātreyīputra]],''' pupil of a [[गौतमीपुत्र|Gautamīputra]], pupil of '''[[वात्सीपुत्र|Vātsīputra]].''' See also '''[[गोतमीपुत्र|Gotamīputra]].'''<br>

गौप-वन
<u>'''Gaupa-vana'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[गोपवन|Gopavana]]'''’) is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[पौतिमाष्य|Pautimāṣya]]''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 6, 1; iv. 6, 1).<br>

गौपायन
<u>'''Gaupāyana'''</u> (‘descendant of Gopa’). The Gaupāyanas appear in the legend of '''Asamāti, [[किरात|Kirāta]],''' and '''[[आकुलि|Ākuli]],''' which is first met with in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_919/><br>

गौपालायन
<u>'''Gaupālāyana'''</u> (‘descendant of Gopāla’) is the patronymic of '''Śucivṛkṣa''' in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_920/> It is also the patronymic of '''[[औपोदिति|Aupoditi]],''' [[स्थपति|Sthapati]] of the '''Kurus,''' in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_920/> and, as Gaupāleya, of Upoditi or [[औपोदिति|Aupoditi]] in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_920/><br>

गौर
<u>'''Gaura,'''</u> a species of ox (''Bos gaurus''), is frequently mentioned with the '''[[गवय|Gavaya]]''' from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_921/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve1_921/> As the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_921/> expressly mentions wild (''āraṇya'') Gauras, they  must usually have been tame. The female, Gaurī, is also often referred to.<ref name=fx4_ve1_921/> The compound term [[गौर|Gaura]]-[[मृग|mṛga]] (‘the [[गौर|Gaura]] wild beast’) is sometimes met with.<ref name=fx5_ve1_921/><br>

गौरि-वीति शाक्त्य
<u>'''Gauri-vīti Śāktya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[शक्ति|Śakti]]'''’) or '''Gaurīviti,''' as the name is also spelt,<ref name=fx1_ve1_922/> is the [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], or Seer, of a hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_922/> and is frequently mentioned in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_922/> According to the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_922/> he was [[प्रस्तोतृ|Prastotṛ]] at the Sattra, or sacrificial session, celebrated by the '''Vibhindukīyas''' and mentioned in that [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<br>

गौश्र
<u>'''Gauśra'''</u> (‘descendant of Guśri’) is the name of a teacher mentioned in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xvi. 9; xxiii. 5). See '''[[गौश्ल|Gauśla]].'''<br>

गौश्रायणि
<u>'''Gauśrāyaṇi'''</u> (‘descendant of Gauśra’) is the patronymic of a teacher, '''[[चित्र|Citra]],''' in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxiii. 5).<br>

गौश्ल
<u>'''Gauśla,'''</u> a variant of '''[[गौश्र|Gauśra]],''' is the name of a teacher represented as in disagreement with '''Buḍila Āśvatara Āśvi''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_925/><br>

गौ-षूक्ति
<u>'''Gau-ṣūkti'''</u> is the name of a pupil of '''[[इष श्यावाश्वि|Iṣa Śyāvāśvi]]''' according to the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_926/> in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers). It is also the name, in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_926/>  of a teacher who appears to have been needlessly invented to explain the Gauṣūkta Sāman (chant), which is really the Sāman of '''[[गोषूक्तिन्|Goṣūktin]].'''<br>

ग्रह
<u>'''Graha'''</u> (‘seizing’) is a term applied to the sun in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_927/> most probably not in the later sense of ‘planet,’ but to denote a power exercising magical influence.<ref name=fx2_ve1_927/> The sense of ‘planet’ seems first to occur in the later literature, as in the Maitrāyaṇī [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_927/> The question whether the planets were known to the Vedic Indians is involved in obscurity. Oldenberg<ref name=fx4_ve1_927/> recognizes them in the Ādityas, whose number is, he believes, seven; sun, moon, and the five planets. But this view, though it cannot be said to be impossible or even unlikely, is not susceptible of proof, and has been rejected by Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx5_ve1_927/> Pischel,<ref name=fx6_ve1_927/> von Schroeder,<ref name=fx7_ve1_927/> Macdonell,<ref name=fx8_ve1_927/> and Bloomfield,<ref name=fx9_ve1_927/> among others. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx10_ve1_927/> sees the planets in the five Adhvaryus mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx11_ve1_927/> but this is a mere conjecture. The five bulls (''ukṣāṇaḥ'') in another passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx12_ve1_927/> have received a similar interpretation with equal uncertainty,<ref name=fx13_ve1_927/> and [[दुर्ग|Durga]], in his commentary on the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx14_ve1_927/> even explains the term ''bhūmija,'' ‘earth-born,’ which is only mentioned by [[यास्क|Yāska]], as meaning the planet Mars.<ref name=fx15_ve1_927/> Thibaut,<ref name=fx16_ve1_927/> who is generally sceptical as to the mention of planets in the Veda, thinks that [[बृहस्पति|Bṛhaspati]] there refers to Jupiter; but this is extremely improbable, though in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx17_ve1_927/> [[बृहस्पति|Bṛhaspati]] is made the regent of [[तिष्य|Tiṣya]]. A reference to the  planets is much more probable in the seven suns (''[[सप्त सूर्याः|sapta sūryāḥ]]'') of the late [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx18_ve1_927/> On the other hand, Ludwig's efforts to find the five planets with the sun, the moon, and the twenty-seven Nakṣatras (lunar mansions) in the Rigveda, as corresponding to the number thirty-four used in connexion with light<ref name=fx19_ve1_927/> (''jyotis'') and the ribs of the sacrificial horse,<ref name=fx20_ve1_927/> is farfetched. See also '''[[शुक्र|Śukra]], [[मन्थिन्|Manthin]], Vena.'''<br>

ग्राभ
<u>'''Grābha'''</u> (lit. ‘grasping’) designates the ‘throw’ of dice in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_928/> See also '''[[ग्लह|Glaha]].'''<br>

ग्राम
<u>'''Grāma.'''</u>--The primitive sense of this word, which occurs frequently from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_929/> onwards, appears to have been ‘village.’ The Vedic Indians must have dwelt in villages which were scattered over the country, some close together,<ref name=fx2_ve1_929/> some far apart, and were connected by roads.<ref name=fx3_ve1_929/> The village is regularly contrasted with the forest (''[[अरण्य|araṇya]]''), and its animals and plants with those that lived or grew wild in the woods.<ref name=fx4_ve1_929/> The villages contained cattle, horses, and other domestic animals, as well as men.<ref name=fx5_ve1_929/> Grain was also stored in them.<ref name=fx6_ve1_929/> In the evening the cattle regularly returned thither from the forest.<ref name=fx7_ve1_929/> The villages were probably open, though perhaps a fort ('''Pur''') might on  occasion be built inside.<ref name=fx8_ve1_929/> Presumably they consisted of detached houses with enclosures, but no details are to be found in Vedic literature. Large villages (''mahāgrāmāḥ'') were known.<ref name=fx9_ve1_929/><br><br>The relation of the villagers is difficult to ascertain with precision. In several passages<ref name=fx10_ve1_929/> the word occurs with what appears to be the derivative sense of ‘body of men.’ This sense presumably started from the use of the word to denote the ‘village folk,’ as when '''[[शर्यात|Śaryāta]] [[मानव|Mānava]]''' is said in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx11_ve1_929/> to have wandered about with his ‘village’ (''grāmeṇa''); but, as Zimmer<ref name=fx12_ve1_929/> observes, this restricted sense nowhere appears clearly in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx13_ve1_929/> where indeed the ‘folk’ (''jana'')<ref name=fx14_ve1_929/> of the Bharatas is in one passage<ref name=fx15_ve1_929/> called the ‘horde seeking cows’ (''gavyan grāmaḥ''). Zimmer<ref name=fx16_ve1_929/> tends to regard the [[ग्राम|Grāma]] as a clan, and as standing midway between the family and the tribe ('''[[विश्|Viś]]'''). The [[ग्राम|Grāma]] may, however, perhaps be regarded more correctly<ref name=fx17_ve1_929/> as an aggregate of several families, not necessarily forming a clan, but only part of a clan ('''[[विश्|Viś]]'''), as is often the case at the present day.<ref name=fx18_ve1_929/><br><br>Vedic literature tells us very little about the social economy of the village. There is nothing to show that the community as such held land. What little evidence there is indicates that individual tenure of land was known (see '''[[उर्वरा|Urvarā]], [[क्षेत्र|Kṣetra]]'''), but this, in effect though not in law, presumably meant tenure by a family rather than by an individual person. The expression  ‘desirous of a village’ (''[[ग्राम|grāma]]-kāma''), which occurs frequently in the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx19_ve1_929/> points, however, to the practice of the king's granting to his favourites his royal prerogatives over villages so far as fiscal matters were concerned. Later<ref name=fx20_ve1_929/> the idea developed that the king was owner of all the land, and parallel with that idea the view that the holders of such grants were landlords. But of either idea there is no vestige in Vedic literature beyond the word ''[[ग्राम|grāma]]-kāma,'' which much more probably refers to the grant of regalia than to the grant of land, as Teutonic parallels show.<ref name=fx21_ve1_929/> Such grants probably tended to depress the position of the actual cultivators, and to turn them into tenants, but they can hardly have had this effect to any appreciable extent in early times.<br><br>The village does not appear to have been a unit for legal purposes in early days,<ref name=fx22_ve1_929/> and it can hardly be said to have been a political unit. The village no doubt, as later, included in its members various menials, besides the cultivating owners, and also the Brāhmaṇas and Kṣatriyas who might hold interest in it by royal grant or usage without actually cultivating land, such as chariot-makers ('''[[रथ-कार|Ratha-kāra]]'''), carpenters ('''[[तक्षन्|Takṣan]]'''), smiths ('''[[कर्मार|Karmāra]]'''), and others, but they did not presumably, in any sense, form part of the brotherhood.<ref name=fx23_ve1_929/> All alike were politically subject to the king, and bound to render him food or service or other tribute, unless he had transferred his rights to  others of the royal family or household, as was no doubt often the case, either in whole or part. The king's share in a village is referred to as early as the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx24_ve1_929/><br><br>At the head of the village was the [[ग्राम|Grāma]]-ṇī, or ‘leader of the village,’ who is referred to in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx25_ve1_929/> and often in the later Saṃhitās and in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx26_ve1_929/> The exact meaning of the title is not certain. By Zimmer<ref name=fx27_ve1_929/> the Grāmaṇī is regarded as having had military functions only, and he is certainly often connected with the '''[[सेनानी|Senānī]],''' or ‘leader of an army.’ But there is no reason so to restrict the sense: presumably the Grāmaṇī was the head of the village both for civil purposes and for military operations. He is ranked in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx28_ve1_929/> as inferior to the '''[[सूत|Sūta]],''' or ‘charioteer,’ with whom, however, he is associated<ref name=fx29_ve1_929/> as one of the '''Ratnins,''' the ‘jewels’ of the royal establishment. The post was especially valuable to a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]], who, if he attained it, was at the summit of prosperity (''gataśrī'').<ref name=fx30_ve1_929/> The Grāmaṇī's connexion with the royal person seems to point to his having been a nominee of the king rather than a popularly elected officer. But the post may have been sometimes hereditary, and sometimes nominated or elective: there is no decisive evidence available. The use of the singular presents difficulties: possibly the Grāmaṇī of the village or city where the royal residence was situated was specially honoured and influential.<ref name=fx31_ve1_929/> <br>

ग्राम्य-वादिन्
<u>'''Grāmya-vādin'''</u> apparently means a ‘village judge’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_930/> His '''[[सभा|Sabhā]],''' ‘court,’ is mentioned in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<br>

ग्राह
<u>'''Grāha,'''</u> ‘the seizer,’ is the name of a disease in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_931/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_931/> it perhaps means ‘paralysis’ of the thigh.<ref name=fx3_ve1_931/><br>

ग्राहि
<u>'''Grāhi,'''</u> ‘the seizer,’ appears in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_932/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_932/> as a female demon of disease. Her son is sleep (''[[स्वप्न|svapna]]'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_932/><br>

ग्रीष्म
<u>'''Grīṣma.'''</u> See '''[[ऋतु|Ṛtu]].'''<br>

ग्रैव्य
<u>'''Graivya,'''</u> in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_934/> appears to denote ‘tumours on the neck’ (''grīvāḥ'').<br>

ग्लह
<u>'''Glaha'''</u> denotes the ‘throw’ at dice, like '''[[ग्राभ|Grābha]],''' of which it is a later form, occurring in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_935/><br>

ग्लाव मैत्रेय
<u>'''Glāva Maitreya'''</u> (‘descendant of Maitrī’) is mentioned in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_936/> where he is said to be the same as '''[[वक दाल्भ्य|Vaka Dālbhya]].''' He appears as Pratistotṛ at the snake festival of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_936/> and is referred to in the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_936/> <br>

ग्लौ
<u>'''Glau'''</u> occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_937/> and in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_937/> as the name of some symptom of a disease, probably, as Bloomfield<ref name=fx3_ve1_937/> thinks, ‘boils.’ In the one passage of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhita,<ref name=fx4_ve1_937/> where it is found the sense is obscure, some part of the sacrificial victim being perhaps meant.<ref name=fx5_ve1_937/><br><br>''Cf.'' '''[[गलुन्त|Galunta]].'''<br>

घर्म
<u>'''Gharma'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_938/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_938/> the pot used for heating milk, especially for the offering to the Aśvins. It hence often<ref name=fx3_ve1_938/> denotes the hot milk itself, or some other hot drink.<br>

घास
<u>'''Ghāsa'''</u> means ‘fodder’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_939/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_939/> In the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_939/> Ghāsi is used of the fodder of the horse victim at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]].<br>

घृणीवन्त्
<u>'''Ghṛṇīvant'''</u> is the name of some animal in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_940/> In the parallel passage of the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_940/> Ghṛṇāvant is the reading. Elsewhere the word is adjectival.<ref name=fx3_ve1_940/> <br>

घृत
<u>'''Ghṛta,'''</u> the modern Ghee or ‘clarified butter,’ is repeatedly mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_941/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_941/> both as in ordinary use and as a customary form of sacrifice. According to a citation in Sāyaṇa's commentary on the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_941/> the distinction between [[घृत|Ghṛta]] and '''[[सर्पिस्|Sarpis]]''' consisted in the latter being butter fully melted, while the former was butter melted and hardened (''ghanī-bhūta''), but this distinction cannot be pressed. Because the butter was thrown into the fire, Agni is styled ‘butter-faced’ (''[[घृत|ghṛta]]-pratīka''),<ref name=fx4_ve1_941/> ‘butter-backed’ (''[[घृत|ghṛta]]-pṛṣṭha''),<ref name=fx5_ve1_941/> and ‘propitiated with butter’ (''[[घृत|ghṛta]]-prasatta''),<ref name=fx6_ve1_941/> and ‘found of butter’ (''[[घृत|ghṛta]]-prī'').<ref name=fx7_ve1_941/> Water was used to purify the butter: the waters were therefore called ‘butter-cleansing’ (''[[घृत|ghṛta]]-pū'').<ref name=fx8_ve1_941/> In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]^9 it is said that [[आज्य|Ājya]], [[घृत|Ghṛta]], [[आयुत|Āyuta]], and [[नवनीत|Navanīta]] pertain to gods, men, Pitṛs, and embryos respectively.<br>

घृत-कौशिक
<u>'''Ghṛta-kauśika'''</u> is mentioned in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_942/> as a pupil of '''[[पाराशर्यायण|Pārāśaryāyaṇa]].'''<br>

घोर आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Ghora Āṅgirasa'''</u> is the name of a mythical teacher in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_943/> and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_943/> where he is teacher of the strange '''[[कृष्ण देवकीपुत्र|Kṛṣṇa Devakīputra]].''' That the name is certainly a mere figment is shown by the fact that this ‘dread descendant of the Aṅgirases’ has a counterpart in '''[[भिषज् आथर्वण|Bhiṣaj Ātharvaṇa]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_943/> ‘the healing descendant of the Atharvans,’ while in the Rigveda Sūtras<ref name=fx4_ve1_943/> the ''Atharvāṇo vedaḥ'' is connected  with ''bheṣajam'' and the ''Āṅgiraso vedaḥ'' with ''ghoram.'' He is accordingly a personification of the dark side of the practice of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx5_ve1_943/> He is also mentioned in the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] section of the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx6_ve1_943/><br>

घोष
<u>'''Ghoṣa.'''</u> See '''[[घोषा|Ghoṣā]].'''<br>

घोषवन्त्
<u>'''Ghoṣavant.'''</u> See '''[[स्वर|Svara]].'''<br>

घोषा
<u>'''Ghoṣā'''</u> is mentioned as a protégée of the Aśvins in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_946/> probably as the recipient of a husband, who is perhaps referred to in another passage<ref name=fx2_ve1_946/> as Arjuna, though this is not likely. Sāyaṇa finds a reference there to a skin disease, which is considered in the later tradition of the Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx3_ve1_946/> to have been the cause of her remaining unwed, but this view is not tenable. According to Sāyaṇa, her son, Suhastya, is alluded to in an obscure verse of the Rigveda;<ref name=fx4_ve1_946/> Oldenberg,<ref name=fx5_ve1_946/> however, here sees a reference to [[घोषा|Ghoṣā]] herself, while Pischel<ref name=fx6_ve1_946/> thinks that the form (''ghoṣe'') is not a noun at all, but verbal.<br>

चक
<u>'''Caka'''</u> is mentioned with [[पिशङ्ग|Piśaṅga]] as one of the two Unnetṛ priests at the snake festival in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_947/> <br>

चक्र
<u>'''Cakra,'''</u> the ‘wheel’ of a chariot or wagon, is repeatedly mentioned from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_948/> onwards, often in a metaphorical sense. The wheel was fixed on the axle ('''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]]''') when the chariot was required for use; this required considerable strength, as is shown by a reference in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_948/> The wheel consisted normally of spokes ('''Ara'''), and a nave ('''[[नाभि|Nābhi]]'''),<ref name=fx3_ve1_948/> in the opening ('''Kha''') of which the end of the axle ('''[[आणि|Āṇi]]''') was inserted. An indication of the importance attached to the strength of the wheel is the celebration of the car of the god Pūṣan as having a wheel that suffers no damage.<ref name=fx4_ve1_948/> The usual number of wheels was two,<ref name=fx5_ve1_948/> but in seven passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_948/> a chariot is called ‘three-wheeled,’ in a few others ‘sevenwheeled,’<ref name=fx7_ve1_948/> while in one of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx8_ve1_948/> it is styled ‘eightwheeled.’ Zimmer<ref name=fx9_ve1_948/> argues that these epithets do not refer to real chariots, pointing out that in all the passages where ''tri-[[चक्र|cakra]],'' ‘three-wheeled,’ occurs there is a mythical reference. On the other hand, Weber<ref name=fx10_ve1_948/> thinks that there might have been chariots with three wheels, one being in the centre between the two occupants. This is not very conclusive; at any rate, the seven-wheeled and the eight-wheeled chariots can hardly be regarded as indicating the existence of real vehicles with that number of wheels.<br><br>In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx11_ve1_948/> the potter's wheel (''kaulālacakra'') is referred to.<br>

चक्र-वाक
<u>'''Cakra-vāka'''</u> is the name, apparently derived from the nature of its cry, of a species of gander (''Anas casarca''), the modern Chakwā, as it is called in Hindī, or Brahmany duck in English.<ref name=fx1_ve1_949/> It is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_949/> and in the list of victims at the  [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_949/> while in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_949/> it already appears as the type of conjugal fidelity, its characteristic in the classical literature.<br>

चक्षुस्
<u>'''Cakṣus,'''</u> ‘eye.’ The ‘evil eye’ (''ghoraṃ [[चक्षुस्|cakṣus]]'') was well known in the Atharvaveda, which contains spells to counteract its influence.<ref name=fx1_ve1_950/> As remedies against it are mentioned salve from Mount '''Trikakubh'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_950/> and the '''[[जङ्गिड|Jaṅgiḍa]]''' plant.<ref name=fx3_ve1_950/> In the wedding ceremony the wife is entreated not to have the evil eye (''aghoracakṣus'').<ref name=fx4_ve1_950/> The structure of the eye, and its division into white (''[[शुक्ल|śukla]]''), dark (''[[कृष्ण|kṛṣṇa]]''), and the pupil (''kanīn ikā'') are repeatedly referred to in the later Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx5_ve1_950/> The desease '''[[अलजि|Alaji]]''' appears to have been an affection of the eyes.<br>

चण्डाल
<u>'''Caṇḍāla,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_951/> '''[[चाण्डाल|Cāṇḍāla]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_951/> are the variant forms of the name of a despised caste, which in origin was probably a tribal body,<ref name=fx3_ve1_951/> but which in the Brahminical theory was the offspring of [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] athers and Brahmin mothers.<ref name=fx4_ve1_951/> The references to the caste in he [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās and in the Upaniṣads show clearly hat it was a degraded one, but they yield no particulars. <br>

चतुष्-पद्
<u>'''Catuṣ-pad,'''</u> ‘quadruped,’ is a regular name for animals from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_952/> onwards, being frequently contrasted with '''Dvipad,''' ‘biped.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_952/> Catuṣ-[[पाद|pāda]], as an adjective applying to ''paśavaḥ,'' ‘animals,’ is also found.<ref name=fx3_ve1_952/><br>

चन्द्र
<u>'''1. Candra,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_953/> '''[[चन्द्र|Candra]]-mas,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_953/> are the names of the ‘moon,’ the latter occurring from the Rigveda onwards, but the former being first used in this sense by the Atharvaveda. Very little is said about the moon in Vedic literature, except as identified with '''Soma,'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_953/> both alike being described as waxing and waning. Reference is, however, made to the regular changes of the moon, and to its alternation with the sun,<ref name=fx5_ve1_953/> to which it, as Soma, is declared in the Rigveda to be married.<ref name=fx6_ve1_953/> Mention is also made of its disappearance at the time of new moon,<ref name=fx7_ve1_953/> and of its birth from the light of the sun.<ref name=fx8_ve1_953/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx9_ve1_953/> reference is made to demons eclipsing the moon (''grahāś cāndramāsāḥ'').<br><br>For the phases of the moon, and the month as a measure of time, see '''[[मास|Māsa]].''' For the moon and its mansions, see '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br><br>^4) Rv. x. 55, 5. ''Cf.'' Av. x. 8, 32.<br>

चन्द्र
<u>'''2. Candra'''</u> appears to denote ‘gold’ in a certain number of passages from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_954/> <br>

चप्य
<u>'''Capya'''</u> is found in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_955/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_955/> as the name of a sacrificial vessel.<br>

चमस
<u>'''Camasa'''</u> denotes a ‘drinking vessel,’ usually as employed for holding '''Soma''' at the sacrifice. It is frequently mentioned from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_956/> It was made of wood (''[[वृक्ष|vṛkṣa]]''),<ref name=fx2_ve1_956/> and is hence called ''dru.''<ref name=fx3_ve1_956/> According to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_956/> it was made of '''[[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]]''' wood.<br>

चमू
<u>'''Camū'''</u> is a term of somewhat doubtful sense occurring repeatedly in the Rigveda, and connected with the preparation of Soma. Zimmer<ref name=fx1_ve1_957/> considers that in the dual it denotes the two boards between which, in his opinion, the Soma was crushed (''cf.'' '''[[अधिषवण|Adhiṣavaṇa]]'''). Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve1_957/> however, appears to be right in taking the normal sense to designate a vessel into which the Soma was poured from the press, and Hillebrandt<ref name=fx3_ve1_957/> shows clearly that when it occurs in the plural<ref name=fx4_ve1_957/> it always has this sense, corresponding to the [[ग्रह|Graha]]-pātras of the later ritual, and that sometimes it is so used in the singular<ref name=fx5_ve1_957/> or dual<ref name=fx6_ve1_957/> also. In some cases,<ref name=fx7_ve1_957/> however, he recognizes its use as denoting the mortar in which the Soma was pressed: he may be right here, as this mode of preparation was probably Indo-Iranian.<ref name=fx8_ve1_957/><br><br>In a derivative sense [[चमू|Camū]] appears in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx9_ve1_957/> to denote a trough, either of solid stone or consisting of  bricks, used by the Eastern people to protect the body of the dead from contact with the earth, like modern stone-lined graves or vaults.<br>

चरक
<u>'''Caraka'''</u> primarily denotes a ‘wandering student,’ a sense actually found in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_958/> More especially it denotes the members of a school of the Black [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]], the practices of which are several times referred to with disapproval in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_958/> In the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_958/> the [[चरक|Caraka]] teacher (''Carakācārya'') is enumerated among the sacrificial victims at the Puruṣamedha, or human sacrifice. His dedication there to ill-doing is a clear hint of a ritual feud.<br>

चरक-ब्राह्मण
<u>'''Caraka-brāhmaṇa'''</u> is the name of a work from which Sāyaṇa quotes in his commentary on the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_959/><br>

चराचर
<u>'''Carācara'''</u> (‘running about’), a term found classed with '''[[सरीसृप|Sarīsṛpa]]''' in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_960/> must apparently denote some kind of animal.<br>

चरु
<u>'''Caru'''</u> designates a ‘kettle’ or ‘pot’ from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_961/> It had a lid (''apidhāna'') and hooks (''[[अङ्क|aṅka]]'') by which it could be hung over a fire.<ref name=fx2_ve1_961/> It was made of iron or bronze<ref name=fx3_ve1_961/>  (''ayasmaya''). The word is also secondarily used<ref name=fx4_ve1_961/> to denote the contents of the pot, the mess of grain which was cooked in it.<br>

चर्मन्
<u>'''Carman,'''</u> denoting ‘hide’ in general, is a common expression from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_962/> The oxhide was turned to many uses, such as the manufacture of bowstrings, slings, and reins (see '''Go'''). It was especially often employed to place above the boards<ref name=fx2_ve1_962/> on which the Soma was pressed with the stones.<ref name=fx3_ve1_962/> It was possibly also used for making skin bags.<ref name=fx4_ve1_962/> Carmaṇya denotes leather-work generally in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_962/><br><br>The art of tanning hides (''mlā'') was known as early as the Rigveda,<ref name=fx6_ve1_962/> where also the word for ‘tanner’ (''carmamna'') occurs.<ref name=fx7_ve1_962/> Details of the process are lacking, but the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_962/> refers to stretching out a hide with pegs (''śañkubhiḥ''), and the Rigveda<ref name=fx9_ve1_962/> mentions the wetting of the hide.<br>

चर्षणि
<u>'''Carṣaṇi,'''</u> used in the plural, denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_963/> ‘men’ in general or ‘people,’ conceived either as active beings<ref name=fx2_ve1_963/> or as cultivators<ref name=fx3_ve1_963/> in opposition to nomads. The expression ‘king of men’ (''rājā carṣaṇīnām'') is frequently found.<ref name=fx4_ve1_963/> The ‘people’ are  also mentioned in connexion with war.<ref name=fx5_ve1_963/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_963/> ‘animals’ (''[[पशु|paśu]]'') and ‘men’ (''[[चर्षणि|carṣaṇi]]'') are spoken of together.<br><br>For the five ''carṣaṇayaḥ,''<ref name=fx7_ve1_963/> see '''Pañca Janāsaḥ.'''<br>

चषाल
<u>'''Caṣāla,'''</u> the mortar-shaped top-piece of the sacrificial post ('''[[यूप|Yūpa]]'''), is mentioned from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_964/> In one passage of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_964/> it is directed to be made of wheaten dough (''gaudhūma'').<br>

चाक्र
<u>'''Cākra'''</u> is the name of a man, variously styled [[रेवोत्तरस्|Revottaras]] [[स्थपति|Sthapati]] [[पाटव|Pāṭava]] [[चाक्र|Cākra]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_965/> and [[रेवोत्तरस्|Revottaras]] [[पाटव|Pāṭava]] [[चाक्र|Cākra]] [[स्थपति|Sthapati]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_965/> who is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] only. He is there said to have been expelled by the '''Sṛñjayas,''' but to have restored to them their prince '''[[दुष्टरीतु|Duṣṭarītu]]''' despite the opposition of the [[कौरव्य|Kauravya]] king '''[[बल्हिक प्रातिपीय|Balhika Prātipīya]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_965/> He must have been a sage rather than a warrior, as the first passage of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_965/> shows him in the capacity of a teacher only. ''Cf.'' '''[[स्थपति|Sthapati]].'''<br>

चाक्रायण
<u>'''Cākrāyaṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[चक्र|Cakra]],’ is the patronymic of '''Uṣasta''' or '''Uṣasti.'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_966/><br>

चाण्डाल
<u>'''Cāṇḍāla.'''</u> See '''[[चण्डाल|Caṇḍāla]].'''<br>

चाक्षुष
<u>'''Cākṣuṣa,'''</u> a word occurring once only in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_968/> is, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, a patronymic (of Suyāman, a personification). Whitney<ref name=fx2_ve1_968/> treats it as probably a simple adjective (‘of sight’). <br>

चातुर्-मास्य
<u>'''Cātur-māsya,'''</u> ‘four-monthly,’ denotes the festival of the Vedic ritual held at the beginning of the three seasons of four months each, into which the Vedic year was artificially divided.<ref name=fx1_ve1_969/> It is clear that the sacrifices commenced with the beginning of each season,<ref name=fx2_ve1_969/> and it is certain that the first of them, the Vaiśvadeva, coincided with the Phālgunī full moon,<ref name=fx3_ve1_969/> the second, the Varuṇa-praghāsas, with the Āṣāḍhī full moon,<ref name=fx4_ve1_969/> and the third, the Sāka-[[मेध|medha]], with the Kārttikī full moon.<ref name=fx5_ve1_969/> There were, however, two alternative datings: the festivals could also be held in the Caitrī, the Śrāvaṇī, and Āgrahāyaṇī (Mārgaśīrṣī) full moons,<ref name=fx6_ve1_969/> or in the Vaiśākhī, Bhādrapadī, and Pauṣī full moons.<ref name=fx7_ve1_969/> Neither of the later datings is found in a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] text, but each may well have been known early, since the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx8_ve1_969/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx9_ve1_969/> both recognize the full moon in the month [[चैत्र|Caitra]] as an alternative to the full moon in the month Phālguna, for the beginning of the year.<br><br>Jacobi considers that the commencement of the year with the full moon in the asterism [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]], which is supported by other evidence,<ref name=fx10_ve1_969/> indicates that the year at one time began with the winter solstice with the moon in [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]], corresponding to the summer solstice when the sun was in [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]]. These astronomical conditions, he believes, existed in the time of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx11_ve1_969/> and prevailed in the fourth millennium B.C. The alternative  dates would then indicate periods when the winter solstice coincided with the Caitrī or the Vaiśākhī full moon. But Oldenberg<ref name=fx12_ve1_969/> and Thibaut<ref name=fx13_ve1_969/> seem clearly right in holding that the coincidence of Phālgunī with the beginning of spring,<ref name=fx14_ve1_969/> which is certain, is fatal to this view, and that there is no difficulty in regarding this date as consistent with the date of the winter solstice in the new moon of Māgha, which is given by the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx15_ve1_969/> and which forms the basis of the calculations of the [[ज्योतिष|Jyotiṣa]].<ref name=fx16_ve1_969/> The full moon in Phālguna would be placed about one month and a half after the winter solstice, or, say, in the first week of February, which date, according to Thibaut, may reasonably be deemed to mark the beginning of a new season in India about 800 B.C. At the same time it must be remembered that the date was necessarily artificial, inasmuch as the year was divided into three seasons, each of four months, and the Indian year does not in fact consist of three equal seasons. The variations of the other datings would then not be unnatural if any school wished to defer its spring festival, the Vaiśvadeva, to the time when spring had really manifested itself. See also '''[[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]].'''<br>

चान्धनायन
<u>'''Cāndhanāyana'''</u> is the patronymic of '''Ānandaja''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_970/><br>

चायमान
<u>'''Cāyamāna'''</u> is the patronymic in the Rigveda (vi. 27, 5. 8) of '''Abhyāvartin.''' <br>

चाष
<u>'''Cāṣa,'''</u> the ‘blue woodpecker’ (''Coracias indica''), is mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_972/> as well as in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_972/><br>

चिच्चिक
<u>'''Ciccika'''</u> is a bird mentioned with the equally unknown '''[[वृषारव|Vṛṣārava]]''' in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_973/> It may perhaps be compared with the Ciṭaka mentioned by Dārila in his commentary on the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_973/><br>

चित्र
<u>'''Citra'''</u> is the name of several persons. (''a'') The Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_974/> contains a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) of a prince [[चित्र|Citra]]. The later legend<ref name=fx2_ve1_974/> attributes this panegyric to [[सोभरि|Sobhari]], and describes [[चित्र|Citra]] as king of the rats.<br><br>(''b'') [[चित्र|Citra]] [[गाङ्ग्यायनि|Gāṅgyāyani]] or Gārgyāyaṃ is mentioned in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_974/> as a contemporary of '''[[आरुणि|Āruṇi]]''' and '''[[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]].'''<br><br>(''c'') [[चित्र|Citra]] [[गौश्रायणि|Gauśrāyaṇi]] is mentioned as a teacher in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1b_ve1_974/><br>

चित्र-रथ
<u>'''Citra-ratha'''</u> (‘having a brilliant car’) is the name of two persons.<br><br>(''a'') It designates an Āryan prince, who, with Arṇa, was defeated by Indra for the [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]]-Yadus on the '''[[सरयु|Sarayu]]''' (perhaps the modern Sarju in Oudh), according to the Rigveda (iv. 30, 18). The locality would accord with the close connexion of [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] and '''[[क्रिवि|Krivi]]''' or '''[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]].''' <br><br>(''b'') [[चित्ररथ|Citraratha]] is also the name of a king for whom the '''Kāpeyas''' performed a special kind of sacrifice (''dvirātra''), with the result, according to the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_975/> that in the [[चैत्ररथि|Caitrarathi]] family only one member was a [[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]]-pati, the rest dependents. Apparently this must mean that the Caitrarathis were distinguished from other families of princes by the fact that the chief of the clan received a markedly higher position than in most cases, in which probably the heads of the family were rather an oligarchy than a monarch and his dependents. See '''[[राजन्|Rājan]].'''<br>

चित्रा
<u>'''Citrā.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

चिल्वटि
<u>'''Cilvaṭi'''</u> is the name of an unknown animal in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 2, 7).<br>

चीपुद्रु
<u>'''Cīpudru'''</u> designates some substance mentioned in a hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_978/> as of use in healing. The commentator Sāyaṇa reads Cīpadru, and explains the word as a kind of tree. This interpretation is supported by the fact that the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_978/> refers to the employment of splinters of [[पलाश|Palāśa]] wood in the ritual application of this hymn.<ref name=fx3_ve1_978/> Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve1_978/> suggests that the form of the word should be Cīpuḍu.<br>

चुमुरि
<u>'''Cumuri'''</u> is the name of an enemy of '''[[दभीति|Dabhīti]],''' for whom he, along with his friend '''[[धुनि|Dhuni]],''' is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_979/> as having been defeated by Indra. Elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve1_979/> the two are spoken of, along with '''[[शम्बर|Śambara]], [[पिप्रु|Pipru]],''' and Śuṣṇa, as having been crushed by Indra, who destroyed their castles. It is impossible to say whether real men or demons are meant, but in favour of  a man being denoted by [[चुमुरि|Cumuri]] is the form of the name, which seems not to be Āryan.<ref name=fx3_ve1_979/><br>

चूड भागवित्ति
<u>'''Cūḍa Bhāgavitti'''</u> (‘descendant of Bhagavitta’) is mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka Upaṇiṣad<ref name=fx1_ve1_980/> as a pupil of '''[[मधुक पैङ्ग्य|Madhuka Paiṅgya]].'''<br>

चूर्ण
<u>'''Cūrṇa'''</u> appears to denote an aromatic powder in the phrase ''[[चूर्ण|cūrṇa]]-[[हस्त|hasta]],'' used of the Apsarases in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 4).<br>

चेदि
<u>'''Cedi'''</u> is the name of a people who, with their king '''[[कशु|Kaśu]],''' the [[चैद्य|Caidya]], are mentioned only in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’), occurring at the end of one hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_982/> where their generosity is celebrated as unsurpassed. They occur later in the Epic with the '''Matsyas,''' and lived in Bandela Khaṇḍa (Bundelkhand).<ref name=fx2_ve1_982/> In Vedic times they were probably situated in much the same locality.<br>

चेलक शाण्डिल्यायन
<u>'''Celaka Śāṇḍilyāyana'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]]'''’) is mentioned as a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 4, 5, 3).<br>

चैकितानेय
<u>'''Caikitāneya'''</u> (‘descendant of Cekitāna’) is mentioned as a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_984/> The Caikitāneyas are also referred to there<ref name=fx2_ve1_984/> in connexion with the Sāman which they worshipped. '''Brahmadatta''' [[चैकितानेय|Caikitāneya]] is brought into connexion with the Sāman in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_984/> and '''[[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]]''' [[चैकितानेय|Caikitāneya]] is known to the Ṣaḍviṃśa<ref name=fx4_ve1_984/> and [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx5_ve1_984/> The word is a patronymic, formed from  Caikitāna, according to Śaṅkara,<ref name=fx6_ve1_984/> but more probably from Cekitāna,<ref name=fx7_ve1_984/> a name found in the Epic.<br>

चैकितायन
<u>'''Caikitāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Cikitāyana<ref name=fx1_ve1_985/> or Cekita,’<ref name=fx2_ve1_985/> is the patronymic of '''[[दाल्भ्य|Dālbhya]]''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_985/><br>

चैत्र
<u>'''Caitra'''</u> is the patronymic of '''[[यज्ञसेन|Yajñasena]]''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xxi. 4).<br>

चैत्र-रथि
<u>'''Caitra-rathi.'''</u> See '''[[चित्ररथ|Citraratha]]''' and '''Satyādhivāka.'''<br>

चैत्रियायण
<u>'''Caitriyāyaṇa'''</u> is the patronymic or metronymic of the teacher '''[[यज्ञसेन|Yajñasena]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (v. 3, 8, 1).<br>

चैद्य
<u>'''Caidya.'''</u> See '''Cedi.'''<br>

चैलकि
<u>'''Cailaki,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Celaka,'''’ is the patronymic of Jīvala in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 3, 1, 34).<br>

चोर
<u>'''Cora,'''</u> ‘thief,’ is only found in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka, a late work, in its last book (x. 65). The Vedic terms are '''[[तस्कर|Taskara]] [[तायु|Tāyu]], [[स्तेन|Stena]],''' and '''[[परिपन्थिन्|Paripanthin]].'''<br>

च्यवतान मारुताश्व
<u>'''Cyavatāna Mārutāśva'''</u> (‘descendant of Marutāśva’) is apparently the name of a prince in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’), in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_992/> Two distinct persons may, however, be meant.<br>

च्यवन
<u>'''Cyavana,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_993/> '''Cyavāna,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_993/> are variant forms of the name of an ancient [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], or seer. The Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_993/> represents him as an old decrepit man, to whom the Aśvins restored youth and strength, making him acceptable to his wife, and a husband of maidens.  The legend is given in another form in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_993/> where [[च्यवन|Cyavana]] is described as wedding [[सुकन्या|Sukanyā]], the daughter of '''[[शर्यात|Śaryāta]].''' He is there called a [[भृगु|Bhṛgu]] or [[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]], and is represented as having been rejuvenated by immersion in a pond--the first occurrence of a motive, later very common in Oriental literature. Another legend about Cyavāna is apparently alluded to in an obscure hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx5_ve1_993/> where he seems to be opposed to the '''[[पक्थ|Paktha]]''' prince '''[[तूर्वयाण|Tūrvayāṇa]],''' an Indra worshipper, while Cyavāna seems to have been specially connected with the Aśvins. This explanation of the hymn, suggested by Pischel,<ref name=fx6_ve1_993/> is corroborated by the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx7_ve1_993/> which relates that '''Vidanvant,''' another son of [[भृगु|Bhṛgu]], supported [[च्यवन|Cyavana]] against Indra, who was angry with him for sacrificing to the Aśvins; it is also noteworthy that the Aśvins appear in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_993/> as obtaining a share in the sacrifice on the suggestion of [[सुकन्या|Sukanyā]]. But a reconciliation of Indra and [[च्यवन|Cyavana]] must have taken place, because the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx9_ve1_993/> relates the inauguration of '''[[शार्यात|Śāryāta]]''' by [[च्यवन|Cyavana]] with the great Indra consecration (''aindreṇa mahābhiṣekeṇa''). In the Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇā<ref name=fx10_ve1_993/> [[च्यवन|Cyavana]] is mentioned as a seer of Sāmans or Chants.<br>

छग
<u>'''Chaga'''</u> is the name of the ‘goat’ in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (v. 6, 22, 1). ''Cf.'' '''Aja''' and '''[[छाग|Chāga]].'''<br>

छदिस्
<u>'''Chadis'''</u> is used once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_995/> and not rarely later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_995/> to denote the covering of a wagon or the thatch of a house, or  something analogous to these. Weber<ref name=fx3_ve1_995/> thinks that in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_995/> the word designates a constellation, and Whitney,<ref name=fx5_ve1_995/> who does not decide whether that interpretation is necessary, suggests that the constellation  Aquarii may be meant, sicne the next verse mentions '''[[विचृतौ|Vicṛtau]],''' which is the constellation  and  Scorpionis, and is not far from Aquarius. See also '''[[छर्दिस्|Chardis]].'''<br>

छन्दस्
<u>'''1. Chandas'''</u> in the Rigveda usually denotes a ‘song of praise’ or ‘hymn.’<ref name=fx1_ve1_996/> The original sense of the word, as derived from the verb ''chand,'' ‘to please,’ was probably ‘attractive spell,’ ‘magic hymn,’<ref name=fx2_ve1_996/> which prevailed on the gods. In a very late hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_996/> as well as in one of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_996/> the word is mentioned in the plural (''chandāṃsi''), beside Ṛc (''ṛcaḥ''), Sāman (''sāmāni''), and [[यजुस्|Yajus]], and seems to retain its original meaning, not improbably with reference to the magical subject-matter of the Atharvaveda. From denoting a (metrical) hymn it comes to mean ‘metre’ in a very late verse of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx5_ve1_996/> in which the ‘Gāyatrī, the Triṣṭubh, and all (''sarvā'') the metres (''chandāṃsi'') are mentioned. In the later Saṃhitās three<ref name=fx6_ve1_996/> or seven<ref name=fx7_ve1_996/> metres are enumerated, and in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_996/> eight. By the time of the Rigveda Prātiśākhya<ref name=fx9_ve1_996/> the metres were subjected to a detailed examination, though much earlier references are found to the number of syllables in the several metres.<ref name=fx10_ve1_996/> Later the word definitely denotes a Vedic text generally, as in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx11_ve1_996/> <br>

छन्दस्
<u>'''2. Chandas'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_997/> in the adjectival compound ''[[बृहच्-छन्दस्|bṛhac-chandas]],'' which is used of a house, and must mean ‘having a large roof.’ Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve1_997/> accepts the reading as correct, but Whitney<ref name=fx3_ve1_997/> considers emendation to '''[[छदिस्|Chadis]]''' necessary.<br>

छन्दो-ग
<u>'''Chando-ga,'''</u> ‘metre-singing,’ is the term applied to reciters of the Sāmans, no doubt because these chants were sung according to their order in the Chandaārcika of the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]]. It is only found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_998/> and often in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve1_998/><br>

छर्दिस्
<u>'''Chardis'''</u> occurs often in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_999/> and occasionally later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_999/> denoting a secure dwelling-place. The word appears to be incorrectly written, because the metre shows that the first syllable is always short. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_999/> accordingly suggested that '''[[छदिस्|Chadis]]''' should be read instead. But [[छदिस्|Chadis]] means ‘roof,’ while [[छर्दिस्|Chardis]] never has that sense. Bartholomae<ref name=fx4_ve1_999/> is therefore probably right in suggesting some other form, such as Chaḍis.<br>

छाग
<u>'''Chāga,'''</u> ‘goat,’ is found in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1000/> and not rarely later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1000/> See '''Aja''' and '''[[छग|Chaga]].''' <br>

जगत्
<u>'''Jagat,'''</u> ‘moving,’ is applied sometimes in the Atharvaveda, and later to the domestic animals in particular, as opposed to wild animals (''śvapad'').<ref name=fx1_ve1_1001/> Occasionally the cow is mentioned separately, when the word ''[[जगत्|jagat]]'' covers the rest of the domesticated animals.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1001/><br>

जङ्गिड
<u>'''Jaṅgiḍa'''</u> is the name of a healing plant mentioned in the hymns of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1002/> It was used as an amulet against the diseases, or symptoms of disease, '''[[तक्मन्|Takman]], [[बलास|Balāsa]], [[आशरीक|Āśarīka]], Viśarīka, [[पृष्ट्य्आमय|Pṛṣṭyāmaya]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1002/> fevers and rheumatic pains, '''[[विष्कन्ध|Viṣkandha]]''' and '''[[संस्कन्ध|Saṃskandha]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1002/> '''[[जम्भ|Jambha]],''' and so on. But it is also regarded as a specific against all diseases, and as the best of healing powers.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1002/> It is said to be produced from the juices (''rasa'') of ploughing (''[[कृषि|kṛṣi]]''),<ref name=fx5_ve1_1002/> but this need only mean that it grew in cultivated land, not that it was itself cultivated. What plant the name designates is quite uncertain, for it disappears in the later literature. Caland<ref name=fx6_ve1_1002/> takes it in the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] to be the ''Terminalia arjuneya.''<br>

जतू
<u>'''Jatū,'''</u> the ‘bat,’ occurs in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1003/> and is mentioned as one of the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1003/> <br>

जन
<u>'''Jana,'''</u> besides meaning ‘man’ as an individual, with a tendency to the collective sense, commonly denotes a ‘people’ or ‘tribe’ in the Rigveda and later. Thus, the ‘five tribes’ ('''Panca Janāḥ''' or '''Janāsaḥ''') are frequently referred to, and in one hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1004/> the ‘people of Yadu’ (''[[याद्व|yādva]] jana'') and the '''Yadus''' (''yādvāḥ'') are synonymous. Again, the king (''[[राजन्|rājan]]'') is described as ‘protector (''[[गोपा|gopā]]'') of the people (''janasya''),’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1004/> and there are other references to king and Jana.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1004/> The people of the '''Bharatas''' (''[[भारत|bhārata]] jana'') is also mentioned;<ref name=fx4_ve1_1004/> there is no ground to assume with Hopkins<ref name=fx5_ve1_1004/> that Jana in this case means a clan or horde ('''[[ग्राम|Grāma]]'''), as distinguished from a people.<br><br>It is difficult to say exactly how a people was divided. Zimmer<ref name=fx6_ve1_1004/> argues from a passage in the Rigveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_1004/> that a people was divided into cantons ('''[[विश्|Viś]]'''), cantons into joint families or clans, or village communities ('''[[ग्राम|Grāma]], [[वृजन|Vṛjana]]'''), and these again into single families. He thinks that the four divisions are reflected in the passage in question. by Jana, [[विश्|Viś]], [[जन्मन्|Janman]], and Putrāḥ, or sons, and argues that each village community was originally founded on relationship. But it is very doubtful whether this precise division of the people can be pressed. The division of the Jana into several [[विश्|Viś]] may be regarded as probable, for it is supported by the evidence of another passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1004/> which mentions the [[विश्|Viś]] as a unit of the fighting men, and thus shows that, as in Homeric times and in ancient Germany, relationship was deemed a good principle of military arrangement. But the subdivision of the [[विश्|Viś]] into several Grāmas is very doubtful. Zimmer<ref name=fx9_ve1_1004/> admits that neither [[ग्राम|Grāma]]<ref name=fx10_ve1_1004/>  nor '''[[वृजन|Vṛjana]]'''<ref name=fx11_ve1_1004/> has the special sense of a subdivision of the [[विश्|Viś]] when used for war, for both words only denote generally an armed host. He finds other designations of the village host in '''Vrā'''<ref name=fx12_ve1_1004/> and in '''Vrāja,'''<ref name=fx13_ve1_1004/> but it is sufficient to say that the former passage is of extremely doubtful import,<ref name=fx14_ve1_1004/> and that the latter has no reference to war at all. It is therefore impossible to state in what exact relation the [[ग्राम|Grāma]] in Vedic times stood to the [[विश्|Viś]] or to the family (Kula or [[गोत्र|Gotra]]). The confusion is increased by the vagueness of the sense of both [[ग्राम|Grāma]] and [[विश्|Viś]]. If the latter be regarded as a local division, then no doubt the [[ग्राम|Grāma]] must have been a part of a district; but if a [[विश्|Viś]] was a unit of relationship, then a [[ग्राम|Grāma]] may have contained families of different Viśes, or may have sometimes coincided with a [[विश्|Viś]], or have contained only a part of a [[विश्|Viś]]. But in any case the original state of affairs must have been greatly modified by the rise of the system of caste, and the substitution of a hierarchical for a political point of view. The elements of the people were represented by the family--either as an individual family inhabiting one home ('''Kula'''), and consisting often, no doubt, of a joint family of brothers, or as a patriarchal family of sons who still lived with their father--and by the clan, the later '''[[गोत्र|Gotra]],''' which included all those who claimed a common ancestor. The [[गोत्र|Gotra]] may be regarded as roughly corresponding to the Latin ''gens'' and the Greek , and possibly the [[विश्|Viś]] may be the equivalent of the ''curia'' and, and the Jana of the ''tribus'' and  or .<ref name=fx15_ve1_1004/> These three divisions may also be seen in the [[विश्|Viś]], Zantu, and Daqyu of the Iranian world, where the use of [[विश्|Viś]] suggests that in the Indian [[विश्|Viś]] a relationship based on blood rather than locality is meant--and perhaps even in the ''vicus, pagus,'' and ''civitas'' of the old German polity described in the Germania<ref name=fx16_ve1_1004/> of Tacitus. The family in some form appears as the third element of the Jana in a passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx17_ve1_1004/> where the house (''[[गृह|gṛha]]'') is  contrasted with the Jana and the [[विश्|Viś]]. Possibly, too, another passage<ref name=fx18_ve1_1004/> contrasts the ''adhvara,'' or family sacrifice, with that of the Jana or [[विश्|Viś]], rather than, as Zimmer<ref name=fx19_ve1_1004/> thinks, the village with the two larger units. But it is significant of the particularism of the Vedic Indians that while the king maintained a fire which might be regarded as the sacred fire of the tribe, there is no sure trace<ref name=fx20_ve1_1004/> of any intermediate cult between that of the king and that of the individual householder. The real elements in the state are the [[गोत्र|Gotra]] and the Jana, just as ultimately the ''gens'' and ''tribus,'' the  and  are alone important. It may be that [[विश्|Viś]] sometimes represents in the older texts what later was known as the [[गोत्र|Gotra]]. See '''[[विश्|Viś]].'''<br><br>This appears clearly when the constitution of society in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] period is considered. The tribe or people still exists, and is presupposed, but the division into [[विश्|Viś]] disappears. The real division is now the separate castes ('''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]]'''), but the numerous sections into which each of them is divided appear to be based in part on the ancient [[गोत्र|Gotra]].<br>

जन शार्करक्ष्य
<u>'''2. Jana Śārkarakṣya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''Śarkarakṣa'''’) is mentioned as a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 6, 1, 1 ''et seq.'') and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (v. 11, 1; 15, 1). He was a contemporary of '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]] [[कैकेय|Kaikeya]],''' and of '''Aruṇa [[औपवेशि|Aupaveśi]]''' and his son '''[[उद्दालक आरुणि|Uddālaka Āruṇi]].'''<br>

जनक
<u>'''Janaka,'''</u> king of [[विदेह|Videha]], plays a considerable part in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1006/> and the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1006/> as well as in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1006/> and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1006/> He was a contemporary of '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]] [[वाज|Vāja]]-  saneya,'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1006/> of '''[[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]] [[आरुणेय|Āruṇeya]],''' and of other sages.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1006/> He had become famous for his generosity and his interest in the discussion of the nature of [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], as ultimate basis of reality, in the life-time of '''[[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]]''' of [[काशि|Kāśi]].<ref name=fx7_ve1_1006/> It is significant that he maintained a close intercourse with the Brahmins of the Kuru-Pañcālas, such as [[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]] and [[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]]; for this indicates that the home of the philosophy of the Upaniṣads was in the Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] country rather than in the east. There is a statement in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_1006/> that he became a Brahmin (''brahmā''). This does not, however, signify a change of caste, but merely that in knowledge he became a Brahmin (see '''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]'''). [[जनक|Janaka]] is occasionally mentioned in later texts: in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx9_ve1_1006/> he has already become quite mythical; in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx10_ve1_1006/> a ''sapta-rātra'' or seven nights' rite is ascribed to him.<br><br>It is natural to attempt to date [[जनक|Janaka]] by his being a contemporary of [[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]], and by identifying the latter with the Ajātasattu of the Pāli texts:<ref name=fx11_ve1_1006/> this would make the end of the sixth century B.C. the approximate date of [[जनक|Janaka]].<ref name=fx12_ve1_1006/> But it is very doubtful whether this identification can be supported: [[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]] was king of [[काशि|Kāśi]], whereas Ajātasattu was king of [[मगध|Magadha]], and his only connexion with [[काशि|Kāśi]] was through his marriage with the daughter of Pasenadi of [[कोसल|Kosala]].<ref name=fx13_ve1_1006/> Moreover, the acceptance of this chronology would be difficult to reconcile with the history of the development of thought; for it would make the rise of Buddhism contemporaneous with the Upaniṣads, whereas it is reasonably certain that the older Upaniṣads preceded Buddhism.<ref name=fx14_ve1_1006/> Nor do the Vedic texts know anything of Bimbisāra or Pasenadi, or any of the other princes famed in Buddhist records. <br><br>The identification<ref name=fx15_ve1_1006/> of [[जनक|Janaka]] of [[विदेह|Videha]] and the father of [[सीता|Sītā]] is less open to objection, but it cannot be proved, and is somewhat doubtful. In the Sūtras [[जनक|Janaka]] appears as an ancient king who knew of a time when wifely honour was less respected than later.<ref name=fx16_ve1_1006/><br>

जनता
<u>'''Janatā,'''</u> a word frequently found in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1007/> and the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1007/> denotes the people as a community (''cf.'' '''[[सभा|Sabhā]]''') or as a religious unit.<br>

जन-पद
<u>'''Jana-pada'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas denotes both the ‘people,’ as opposed to the king,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1008/> and the ‘land’ or ‘relam.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1008/> The ‘subjects’ are also denoted by the adjectival ''[[जानपद|jānapada]].''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1008/><br>

जनम्-एजय
<u>'''1. Janam-ejaya'''</u> (‘man-impelling’) is the name of a king, a '''[[पारिक्षित|Pārikṣita]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1009/> famous towards the end of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] period. He is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1009/> as owning horses which when wearied were refreshed with sweet drinks, and as a performer of the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1009/> His capital, according to a [[गाथा|Gāthā]] quoted in the Śatapatha<ref name=fx4_ve1_1009/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1009/> was '''[[आसन्दीवन्त्|Āsandīvant]].''' His brothers '''[[उग्रसेन|Ugrasena]], [[भीमसेन|Bhīmasena]],''' and '''[[श्रुतसेन|Śrutasena]]''' are mentioned as having  by the horse sacrifice purified themselves from sin. The priest who performed the sacrifice for him was '''[[इन्द्रोत|Indrota]] Daivāpi [[शौनक|Śaunaka]].'''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1009/> On the other hand the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx7_ve1_1009/> which also mentions his [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], names '''[[तुर कावषेय|Tura Kāvaṣeya]]''' as his priest. It also contains an obscure tale stating that at one sacrifice of his he did not employ the '''Kaśyapas,''' but the '''Bhūtavīras,''' being, however, induced by the '''Asitamṛgas''' to have recourse to the Kaśyapas again.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1009/> He was a '''Kuru''' prince; see '''[[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]].''' The Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx9_ve1_1009/> tells an absurd tale about him, evidently as of an ancient hero.<br>

जनम्-एजय
<u>'''2. Janam-ejaya'''</u> is in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1010/> the name of a priest who officiated at the snake sacrifice.<br>

जन-श्रुत
<u>'''Jana-śruta'''</u> (‘famed among men’) '''[[काण्ड्विय|Kāṇḍviya]]''' is the name of a pupil of '''Hṛtsvāśaya,''' mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 2), and of [[वारक्य|Vārakya]], a pupil of '''[[जयन्त|Jayanta]],''' referred to in the same [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 41, 1; iv. 17, 1). ''Cf.'' '''[[जानश्रुति|Jānaśruti]].'''<br>

जनि
<u>'''Jani, Janī.'''</u>--These words appear to denote ‘wife,’ usually applying to her in relation to her husband ('''Pati'''). The more general sense of ‘woman’ is doubtful; for when Uṣas is called a fair '''Janī,'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1012/> ‘wife’ may be meant, and the other passage<ref name=fx2_ve1_1012/> cited for this sense by Delbrück,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1012/> which refers to the begetting of childern, seems to demand the sense of ‘wives.’ Since the words usually appear in the plural,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1012/> it is possible they may  refer not to ‘wives’ proper, but to Hetairai. This is, however, rendered unlikely because the Rigveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_1012/> uses the phrase ''patyur janitvam,'' denoting ‘wifehood to a husband,’ as well as the expression ''janayo na patnīḥ,''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1012/> ‘like wives (who are) mistresses,’<ref name=fx7_ve1_1012/> besides containing passages in which the word has reference to marriage.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1012/> The singular occurs in the dialogue of Yama and Yamī.<ref name=fx9_ve1_1012/><br>

जनितृ
<u>'''Janitṛ'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1013/> and '''Janitrī'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1013/> are frequent words, in the Rigveda and later, for ‘father’ and ‘mother’ regarded as the ‘begetter’ and the ‘bearer’ respectively of the child. See '''[[पितृ|Pitṛ]], [[मातृ|Mātṛ]].'''<br>

जन्तु
<u>'''Jantu,'''</u> besides the general sense of ‘man,’ has also in a few passages<ref name=fx1_ve1_1014/> the more restricted sense of ‘follower’ or ‘subject.’ The ‘followers of '''[[श्वैत्रेय|Śvaitreya]]'''’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1014/> may be compared with the ‘subjects (''viśaḥ'') of '''[[तृणस्कन्द|Tṛṇaskanda]].'''’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1014/><br>

जन्मन्
<u>'''Janman'''</u> appears to have the sense of ‘relations’ in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1015/> being used collectively in the second of them.<br>

जन्य
<u>'''Janya'''</u> has in the Rigveda (iv. 38, 6) and the Atharvaveda (xi. 8, 1) the special sense of bridesman.’<br>

जबाला
<u>'''Jabālā'''</u> is the name of the mother of an illegitimate son, '''[[सत्यकाम|Satyakāma]],''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 4, 1. 2. 4). <br>

जभ्य
<u>'''Jabhya,'''</u> ‘snapper,’ denotes in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1018/> an insect destructive to grain.<br>

जमद्-अग्नि
<u>'''Jamad-agni'''</u> is one of the somewhat mythical sages of the Rigveda, where he is frequently mentioned. In some passages<ref name=fx1_ve1_1019/> his name occurs in such a way as to indicate that he is the author of the hymn; once<ref name=fx2_ve1_1019/> he is thus associated with '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]].''' In other passages<ref name=fx3_ve1_1019/> he is merely referred to, and the Jamadagnis are mentioned once.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1019/> In the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1019/> as well as the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx6_ve1_1019/> and the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1019/> he is quite a frequent figure. Here he appears as a friend of [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_1019/> and a rival of '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]].'''<ref name=fx9_ve1_1019/> He owed his prosperity to his ''catūrātra,'' or ‘four-night’ ritual, with which his family were also very successful.<ref name=fx10_ve1_1019/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx11_ve1_1019/> [[जमद्अग्नि|Jamadagni]] is connected with '''Atri''' and '''[[कण्व|Kaṇva]],''' as well as '''[[असित|Asita]]''' and '''Vitahavya.''' He was [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]] priest at the proposed sacrifice of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]].'''<ref name=fx12_ve1_1019/><br>

जम्भ
<u>'''Jambha'''</u> occurs twice in the Atharvaveda as the name of a disease or a demon of disease. In one passage<ref name=fx1_ve1_1020/> it is said to be cured by the '''[[जङ्गिड|Jaṅgiḍa]]''' plant; in the other<ref name=fx2_ve1_1020/> it is described as ''samhanuḥ,'' ‘bringing the jaws together.’ Weber<ref name=fx3_ve1_1020/> argued from  the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1020/> that it was a child's ailment, especially ‘teething.’ Bloomfield<ref name=fx5_ve1_1020/> considers it to mean ‘convulsions,’ while Caland<ref name=fx6_ve1_1020/> thinks it denotes ‘tetanus.’ Whitney<ref name=fx7_ve1_1020/> decides for ‘lockjaw’ or ‘convulsions.’<br>

जम्भक
<u>'''Jambhaka,'''</u> as the name of a demon, presumably identical with the demon causing '''[[जम्भ|Jambha]],''' is mentioned in the [[वाज|Vāja]] saneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1021/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1021/><br>

जयक लौहित्य
<u>'''Jayaka Lauhitya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1) as a pupil of '''[[यशस्विन् जयन्त लौहित्य|Yaśasvin <a class="pada_vei" href="जयन्त">Jayanta]] Lauhitya».'''<br>

जयन्त
<u>'''Jayanta'''</u> is the name of several teachers in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]:<br><br>(''a'') [[जयन्त|Jayanta]] [[पाराशर्य|Pārāśarya]] (‘descendant of '''[[पराशर|Parāśara]]'''’) is mentioned as a pupil of '''Vipaścit''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers).<ref name=fx1_ve1_1023/><br><br>(''b'') [[जयन्त|Jayanta]] [[वारक्य|Vārakya]] (‘descendant of Varaka’) appears in the same [[वंश|Vaṃśa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1023/> as a pupil of '''[[कुबेर वारक्य|Kubera Vārakya]].''' His grandtather is also mentioned there as a pupil of '''[[कंस|Kaṃsa]] [[वारक्य|Vārakya]].'''<br><br>(''c'') A [[जयन्त|Jayanta]] [[वारक्य|Vārakya]], pupil of '''[[सुयज्ञ शाण्डिल्य|Suyajña Śāṇḍilya]],''' perhaps identical with the preceding, is found in another [[वंश|Vaṃśa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1023/><br><br>(''d'') [[जयन्त|Jayanta]] is a name of '''Yaśasvin [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1023/><br><br>See also '''Dakṣa [[जयन्त|Jayanta]]''' [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]].<br>

जरा-बोध
<u>'''Jarā-bodha,'''</u> a word occurring only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1024/> is of doubtful meaning. It is held by Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_1024/> to be the name of  a seer. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_1024/> regards it as a mere adjective meaning ‘attending to the invocation,’ which is perhaps the most probable interpretation. Oldenburg,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1024/> however, thinks that the word is a proper name, the literal sense being ‘alert in old age.’<br>

जरायु
<u>'''Jarāyu'''</u> is found once in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1025/> in the sense of a ‘serpent's skin.’ Usually<ref name=fx2_ve1_1025/> it denotes the outer covering (chorion) of the embryo, as opposed to the ''ulva,'' the inner covering (amnion).<br><br>Living things are occasionally classified according to their mode of origin. In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1025/> they are divided into ''(a) āṇḍa-ja,'' ‘egg-born’; ''(b) [[जीव-ज|jīva-ja]],'' ‘born alive,’ or born from the womb; ''(c) udbhij-ja,'' ‘propagated by sprouts.’ In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx4_ve1_1025/> the division is fourfold: ''(a) āṇḍa-ja; (b) [[जारु|jāru]]-ja,'' that is, ''[[जरायु|jarāyu]]-ja'' (found in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1025/> and needlessly read here by Bo7htlingk);<ref name=fx6_ve1_1025/> ''(c) udbhij-ja;'' and ''(d) svcda-ja,'' ‘sweat-born,’ explained as ‘insects.’<br>

जरितृ
<u>'''1. Jaritṛ'''</u> is the regular term in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1026/> and occasionally later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1026/> for a singer of hymns of praise or worshipper.<br>

जरितृ
<u>'''2. Jaritṛ.'''</u> According to Sieg,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1027/> mention is made in one hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1027/> of [[जरितृ|Jaritṛ]], one of the Śārṅgas. That hymn he seeks to bring into connexion with the epic<ref name=fx3_ve1_1027/> tradition  of the [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] Mandapāla, who wedded Jaritā, a female [[शार्ङ्ग|Śārṅga]] bird--apparently a hen sparrow (''caṭakā'')--and had four sons. These being abandoned by him and exposed to the danger of being consumed by a forest fire, prayed to Agni with the hymn Rigveda x. 142. This interpretation is very doubtful, though Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx4_ve1_1027/> appears to have adopted it.<br>

जरूथ
<u>'''Jarūtha,'''</u> mentioned in three passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1028/> appears to denote a '''demon''' defeated by Agni.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1028/> Ludwig, however, followed by Griffith,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1028/> sees in him a foe slain in a battle in which '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]],''' the traditional author of the seventh Maṇḍala of the Rigveda, was [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], or domestic priest.<br>

जर्तिल
<u>'''Jartila,'''</u> ‘wild sesamum,’ is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (v. 4, 3, 2) as an unsuitable sacrificial offering. In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ix. 1, 1, 3) sesamum seeds are regarded as combining the qualities of cultivation (viz., edibility) with those of wild growth (because they are produced on unploughed land).<br>

जर्वर
<u>'''Jarvara'''</u> was Gṛhapati or ‘householder’ at the snake festival described in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1030/><br>

जल जातूकर्ण्य
<u>'''Jala Jātūkarṇya'''</u> (‘descendant of Jātūkarṇa’), is mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xvi. 29, 6) as having obtained the position of [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], or domestic priest, of the three peoples or kings of '''[[काशि|Kāśi]], [[विदेह|Videha]],''' and '''[[कोसल|Kosala]].'''<br>

जलाष-भेषज
<u>'''Jalāṣa-bheṣaja,'''</u> ‘whose remedy is Jalāṣa,’ is an epithet of Rudra in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1032/> and the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1032/> The word  '''[[जालाष|Jālāṣa]]''' occurs in a hymn of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1032/> where it denotes a remedy, perhaps, for a tumour or boil.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1032/> The commentator on this passage and the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1032/> regard [[जालाष|Jālāṣa]] as meaning ‘urine,’ which seems a probable interpretation.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1032/> But Geldner<ref name=fx7_ve1_1032/> thinks that rain-water, conceived as urine, is meant; and the Naighaṇṭuka<ref name=fx8_ve1_1032/> identifies ''jalāṣa'' and ''udaka'' ‘water.’<br>

जष
<u>'''Jaṣa'''</u> is the name of some aquatic animal or fish in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1033/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1033/> The commentary on the latter text explains it by ''[[मकर|makara]],'' probably meaning ‘dolphin.’ The word also occurs in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1033/><br><br>''Cf.'' '''[[झष|Jhaṣa]].'''<br>

जहका
<u>'''Jahakā,'''</u> the ‘polecat,’ is mentioned as a victim at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1034/> Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx2_ve1_1034/> thinks it means a jackal living in holes (''vila-vāsī kroṣṭā'').<br>

जह्नु
<u>'''Jahnu'''</u> occurs only in the plural in the legend of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]],''' who is said to have obtained, as [[देवरात|Devarāta]], both the lordship of the Jahnus and the divine lore of the Gāthins.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1035/> A '''[[जाह्नव|Jāhnava]],''' or descendant of [[जह्नु|Jahnu]], was, according to the Pañcaviṃśa  [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1035/> '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]],''' who is said, by means of a certain ''catū-rātra'' or ‘four-night’ ritual, to have secured the kingdom for the Jahnus in their conflict with the '''Vṛcīvants.''' He is here described as a king. Again, in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1035/> [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] is addressed as a ''[[राज-पुत्र|rāja-putra]],'' ‘prince,’ and ''Bharatarṣabha,'' ‘bull of the Bharatas.’ It is therefore clear that the Brāhmaṇas, though not the Saṃhitās, saw in him at once a priest and a prince by origin, though there is no trace whatever of their seeing in him a prince who won Brahmanhood as in the version of the later texts.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1035/><br><br>A Jahnāvī is mentioned twice in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1035/> being either the wife of [[जह्नु|Jahnu]], or, as Sāyaṇa thinks, the race of [[जह्नु|Jahnu]]. The family must clearly once have been a great one, later merged in the Bharatas.<br>

जात शाकायन्य
<u>'''Jāta Śākāyanya'''</u> (‘descendant of Śāka’) is mentioned as a ritual authority and contemporary of '''[[शङ्ख|Śaṅkha]]''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xxii. 7).<br>

जात-रूप
<u>'''Jāta-rūpa,'''</u> ‘possessing native beauty,’ is the name of ‘gold’ in the later Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_1037/> and the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1037/><br>

जाति
<u>'''Jāti,'''</u> which in the Pāli<ref name=fx1_ve1_1038/> texts is the word denoting ‘caste,’ does not occur at all in the early Vedic literature; when it is found, as in the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1038/> it has only the sense of ‘family’ (for which ''cf.'' '''Kula, [[गोत्र|Gotra]],''' and '''[[विश्|Viś]]'''). For the influence of the family system on the growth of caste, see '''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]].''' To assume that it was the basis of caste, as does  Senart,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1038/> is difficult in face of the late appearance of words for family and of stress on family.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1038/><br>

जातू-कर्ण्य
<u>'''Jātū-karṇya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Jātūkarṇa,'''’ is the patronymic of several persons.<br><br>(''a'') A pupil of '''[[आसुरायण|Āsurāyaṇa]]''' and '''[[यास्क|Yāska]]''' bears this name in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1039/> In the Mādhyaṃdina<ref name=fx2_ve1_1039/> he is a pupil of '''[[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]].'''<br><br>(''b'') A [[कात्यायनी-पुत्र|Kātyāyanī-putra]], ‘son of [[कात्यायनी|Kātyāyanī]],’ bears this name in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1039/><br><br>(''c'') A [[जातूकर्ण्य|Jātūkarṇya]] is mentioned in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1039/> as a contemporary of '''[[अलीकयु वाचस्पत्य|Alīkayu Vācaspatya]]''' and other sages.<br><br>(''d'') [[जातूकर्ण्य|Jātūkarṇya]] is in the Sūtras<ref name=fx5_ve1_1039/> frequently a patronymic of teachers whose identity cannot be determined. The same person or different persons may here be meant.<br>

जातू-ष्ठिर
<u>'''Jātū-ṣṭhira'''</u> occurs in one verse of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1040/> where Sāyaṇa and Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_1040/> interpret the word as a proper name. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_1040/> renders it as an adjective meaning ‘naturally powerful.’<ref name=fx4_ve1_1040/><br>

जान
<u>'''Jāna,'''</u> ‘descendant of Jana,’ is the patronymic of '''Vṛśa''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1041/> and apparently in the Śāṭyāyanaka.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1041/> <br>

जानक
<u>'''Jānaka,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[जनक|Janaka]],’ is the patronymic of '''Kratuvid''' in some MSS. of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1042/> In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1042/> the name appears instead as '''[[क्रतुजित् जानकि|Kratujit Jānaki]].''' [[जानक|Jānaka]] is also, according to some manuscripts of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1042/> the patronymic of '''Āyasthūṇa,''' but is here no doubt a misreading of '''[[जानकि|Jānaki]].'''<br>

जानकि
<u>'''Jānaki,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[जनक|Janaka]],’ is the patronymic of '''Kratujit''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1043/> of '''Kratuvid''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1043/> and of '''Āyasthūṇa''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1043/> where he is mentioned as a pupil of '''[[चूड भागवित्ति|Cūḍa Bhāgavitti]],''' and as teacher of '''[[सत्यकाम|Satyakāma]] [[जाबाल|Jābāla]].'''<br>

जानं-तपि
<u>'''Jānaṃ-tapi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Janaṃtapa,’ is the patronymic of '''Atyarāti''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 23).<br>

जान-पद
<u>'''Jāna-pada.'''</u> See '''[[जनपद|Janapada]].'''<br>

जान-श्रुति
<u>'''Jāna-śruti,'''</u> ‘descendant of Jānaśruta,’ is the patronymic of '''Pautrāyaṇa''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 1, 1; 2, 1).<br>

जान-श्रुतेय
<u>'''Jāna-śruteya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Jānaśruti’ or of ‘Janaśrutā.’ is the patronymic or metronymic of several persons--'''Upāvi'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1047/> or '''[[औपावि|Aupāvi]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1047/> '''Ulukya,'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1047/> '''Nagarin,'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1047/> and '''[[सायक|Sāyaka]].'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1047/><br>

जाबाल
<u>'''Jābāla,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Jabāla,'''’ is the metronymic of '''[[महाशाल|Mahāśāla]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1048/> and '''[[सत्यकाम|Satyakāma]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1048/> [[जाबाल|Jābāla]] is also mentioned as a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1048/> which refers to the  Jābālas<ref name=fx4_ve1_1048/> as well. The [[जाबाल|Jābāla]] Gṛhapatis are spoken of in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_1048/><br>

जाबालायन
<u>'''Jābālāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[जाबाल|Jābāla]],’ is the patronymic of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[माध्यंदिनायन|Mādhyaṃdināyana]],''' who is mentioned in the second [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 6, 2).<br>

जामदग्निय
<u>'''Jāmadagniya'''</u> is the patronymic of two ‘descendants of Jamadagni’ in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1050/> It appears from the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1050/> that the '''Aurvas''' are meant, and that Jamadagni's descendants were ever prosperous.<br>

जामातृ
<u>'''Jāmātṛ'''</u> is a rare word denoting ‘son-in-law’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1051/> where also occurs the word '''[[विजामातृ|Vijāmātṛ]],''' denoting an ‘unsatisfactory son-in-law,’ as one who does not pay a sufficient price, or one who, having other defects, must purchase a bride. Friendly relations between son-in-law and father-in-law are referred to in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1051/><br>

जामि
<u>'''Jāmi,'''</u> a word which appears originally to have meant ‘related in blood,’ is not rarely used as an epithet of ‘sister’ ('''[[स्वसृ|Svasṛ]]'''), and sometimes even denotes ‘sister’ itself, the emphasis being on the blood-relationship.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1052/> So it appears in a passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1052/> where ‘brotherless sisters’  (''abhrātara iva jāmayaḥ'') are referred to. The word is similarly used in the dispute occurring in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1052/> as to the precedence of [[राका|Rākā]], or of the wives of the gods, in a certain rite. One party is there described as holding that the sister should be preferred (''jāmyai vai pūrva-peyam'')--apparently at a ceremonial family meal--to the wife, presumably as being of one blood with the husband, while the wife is not (being ''anyodaryā,'' ‘of another womb’).<ref name=fx4_ve1_1052/> In the neuter<ref name=fx5_ve1_1052/> the word means ‘relationship,’ like ''[[जामि|jāmi]]-tva,'' which also occurs in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1052/><br>

जामि-शंस
<u>'''Jāmi-śaṃsa,'''</u> the ‘imprecation by a sister’ or ‘relation,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1053/> showing that family disputes were not rare. This is also indicated by the word '''[[भ्रातृव्य|Bhrātṛvya]],''' which, while properly meaning ‘father's brother's son,’ regularly denotes simply ‘enemy.’<br>

जाम्बिल
<u>'''Jāmbila,'''</u> ‘hollow of the knee,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1054/> occurs once in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1054/> The word also occurs in the form of Jāmbīla in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_1054/> and the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1054/> Mahīdhara, in his commentary on the latter text, interprets the word as ‘knee-pan,’ which he says is so named because of its resemblance to the citron, ''jāmbīra.''<br>

जायन्ती-पुत्र
<u>'''Jāyantī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of Jāyantī,’ is mentioned in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1055/> as a pupil of '''[[माण्डूकायनीपुत्र|Māṇḍūkāyanīputra]].'''<br>

जाया
<u>'''Jāyā'''</u> regularly denotes ‘wife,’ and, as opposed to '''[[पत्नी|Patnī]],''' wife as an object of marital affection, the source of the continuance  of the race.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1056/> So it is used of the wife of the gambler, and of the wife of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] in the Rigveda;<ref name=fx2_ve1_1056/> it is also frequently combined with '''Pati,''' ‘husband,’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1056/> both there and in the later literature.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1056/> [[पत्नी|Patnī]], on the other hand, is used to denote the wife as partner in the sacrifice;<ref name=fx5_ve1_1056/> when no share in it is assigned to her, she is called [[जाया|Jāyā]].<ref name=fx6_ve1_1056/> The distinction is, of course, merely relative; hence one text<ref name=fx7_ve1_1056/> calls Manu's wife [[जाया|Jāyā]], another<ref name=fx8_ve1_1056/> [[पत्नी|Patnī]]. Later on [[जाया|Jāyā]] is superseded by [[दार|Dāra]].<br>

जायान्य
<u>'''Jāyānya,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1057/> '''Jāyenya,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1057/> are variant forms of the name of a disease mentioned in the Atharvaveda and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā. In one passage of the former text<ref name=fx3_ve1_1057/> it is mentioned with jaundice (''harimā'') and pains in the limbs (''[[अङ्ग|aṅga]]-bhedo visalpakaḥ''). Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve1_1057/> thinks these are its symptoms, and identifies it with a kind of [[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]], or disease of the lungs. Bloomfield<ref name=fx5_ve1_1057/> prefers to identify it with syphilis, in accordance with certain indications in the ritual of the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx6_ve1_1057/> Roth conjectures ‘gout,’ but Whitney<ref name=fx7_ve1_1057/> leaves the nature of the disease doubtful.<br>

जार
<u>'''Jāra,'''</u> ‘lover,’ has no sinister sense in the early texts<ref name=fx1_ve1_1058/> generally, where the word applies to any lover. But it seems probable that the [[जार|Jāra]] at the Puruṣamedha, or human sacrifice,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1058/>  must be regarded as an illegitimate lover; this sense also appears in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1058/> and Indra is styled the lover of '''Ahalyā,''' wife of '''[[गौतम|Gautama]]'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1058/><br>

जारत्-कारव
<u>'''Jārat-kārava'''</u> (‘descendant of Jaratkāru’) '''Ārtabhāga''' (‘descendant of Ṛtabhāga’) is the name of a teacher mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (vii. 20) and the Bṛhadāranyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iii. 2, 1, in both recensions).<br>

जारु
<u>'''Jāru.'''</u> See '''[[जरायु|Jarāyu]].'''<br>

जाल
<u>'''Jāla'''</u> occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1061/> and the Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve1_1061/> in the sense of ‘net.’ Jālaka is used in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1061/> of a reticulated membrane resembling a woven covering.<br>

जालाष
<u>'''Jālāṣa.'''</u> See '''Jalāṣa,''' which is read by Sāyaṇa in the Atharvaveda (vi. 57, 2) for [[जालाष|Jālāṣa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1062/><br>

जाष्कमद
<u>'''Jāṣkamada'''</u> is the name of an unknown animal in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1063/><br>

जास्-पति
<u>'''Jās-pati'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1064/> in the sense of the ‘head of the family.’ The abstract formed from this word, Jās-patya, apparently denoting ‘lordship of children,’ is also found there.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1064/><br>

जाहुष
<u>'''Jāhuṣa'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1065/> of a protégé of the Aśvins. <br>

जाह्नव
<u>'''Jāhnava,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[जह्नु|Jahnu]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1066/> This fact is of some importance as disproving Aufrecht's theory<ref name=fx2_ve1_1066/> that the Jahnus were the clan of '''Ajīgarta''' the father of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]].'''<br>

जित्वन् शैलिनि
<u>'''Jitvan Śailini'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1067/> a contemporary of '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' and '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]].''' He held that speech (''[[वाच्|vāc]]'') was [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]].<br>

जिह्वावन्त् बाध्योग
<u>'''Jihvāvant Bādhyoga'''</u> is the name, in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1068/> of a teacher, pupil of '''[[असित|Asita]] Vārṣāgaṇa.'''<br>

जीव-गृभ्
<u>'''Jīva-gṛbh,'''</u> ‘seizing alive,’ is, according to Roth,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1069/> the term for a police official in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1069/> But although this sense is rendered possible by the mention of '''[[मध्यमशी|Madhyamaśī]],''' perhaps ‘arbitrator,’ in the same passage,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1069/> it is neither necessary nor probable.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1069/><br>

जीव-ज
<u>'''Jīva-ja.'''</u> See '''[[जरायु|Jarāyu]].'''<br>

जीवन्त्
<u>'''Jīvant'''</u> appears to denote a certain plant in one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1071/> where the edition of Roth and Whitney has the unjustified emendation '''Jīvala.'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1071/> <br>

जीवल चल्लकि
<u>'''Jīvala Callaki,'''</u> ‘descendant of Celaka,’ is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1072/> as reproving '''[[तक्षन्|Takṣan]].'''<br>

जुहू
<u>'''Juhū'''</u> is the regular name in the Rigveda and later for the tongue-shaped ladle in which butter was offered to the gods.(**  1) Rv. viii. 44, 5; x. 21, 3; Av. xviii. 4, 5. 6, etc.<br>

जूर्णि
<u>'''Jūrṇi,'''</u> ‘firebrand,’ is regarded by Zimmer<ref name=fx1_ve1_1074/> as one of the weapons of the Vedic Indians. But since it is only mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1074/> as a weapon used by demons, its employment in normal war cannot be safely assumed.<br>

जूर्णी
<u>'''Jūrṇī'''</u> is one of the names given to serpents in a hymn of the Atharvaveda (ii. 24, 5), perhaps from their habit of casting their slough. See '''Ahi.'''<br>

जेतृ
<u>'''Jetṛ.'''</u> See '''Sṛṇi.'''<br>

जैत्रायण सहो-जित्
<u>'''Jaitrāyaṇa Saho-jit'''</u> is apparently in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1077/> the name of a prince who celebrated the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]], or ‘royal consecration.’ Von Schroeder<ref name=fx2_ve1_1077/> quotes in support of Jaitrāyaṇa as a proper name the derivative Jaitrāyaṇi, ‘descendant of Jaitra,’ formed according to the Gaṇa ''karṇādi,'' which is referred to by Pāṇini;<ref name=fx3_ve1_1077/> but it should be noted that in the parallel passage of the Kapiṣṭhala Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve1_1077/> the reading is different, and no proper personal name appears, the subject being Indra, the god. This reading seems much more probable, for the verse should be general, and suit every king performing the rite. <br>

जैमिनि
<u>'''Jaimini'''</u> does not appear till the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1078/> But a Jaiminīya Saṃhitā of the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]] is extant, and has been edited and discussed by Caland;<ref name=fx2_ve1_1078/> and a Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], of which a special section is the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1078/> is known and has formed the subject of several articles by Oertel.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1078/><br>

जैवन्तायन
<u>'''Jaivantāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Jīvanta,’ is mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1079/> as a teacher, with '''[[शौनक|Śaunaka]]''' and '''[[रैभ्य|Raibhya]],''' of '''[[रौहिणायन|Rauhiṇāyana]].'''<br>

जैवल
<u>'''Jaivala'''</u> or '''Jaivali,''' ‘descendant of Jīvala,’ is the patronymic of '''Pravāhaṇa''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve1_1080/> and Chāndogya Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1080/> Jaivali, the king, in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1080/> is the same person.<br>

ज्ञातृ
<u>'''Jñātṛ'''</u> occurs in two passages of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1081/> and one of the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve1_1081/> with a somewhat obscure sense. Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_1081/> conjectures not unnaturally that the word is a technical term taken from law, meaning ‘witness.’ The reference is, perhaps, to a custom of carrying on transactions of business before witnesses as practised in other primitive societies.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1081/> Roth<ref name=fx5_ve1_1081/> suggests that the word has the sense of  ‘surety.’ But Bloomfield<ref name=fx6_ve1_1081/> and Whitney<ref name=fx7_ve1_1081/> ignore these interpretations.<br>

ज्ञाति
<u>'''Jñāti'''</u> (masc.), a word which originally seems to have meant ‘acquaintance,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1082/> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1082/> and later<ref name=fx3_ve1_1082/> a ‘relation,’ apparently one who was connected by blood on the father's side, though the passages do not necessarily require the limitation. But this sense follows naturally enough from the patriarchal basis of Vedic society.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1082/><br>

ज्या
<u>'''Jyā'''</u> is the regular word for ‘bowstring’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1083/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1083/> The making of bowstrings was a special craft, as is shown by the occurrence of the [[ज्या|Jyā]]-kāra, or ‘maker of bowstrings,’ among the victims at the Puruṣamedha, or human sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1083/> The bowstring consisted of a thong of ox-hide.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1083/> It was not usually kept taut,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1083/> but was specially tightened when the bow was to be used.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1083/> The sound of the bowstring (''[[ज्या|jyā]]-[[घोष|ghoṣa]]'') is referred to in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1083/><br><br>''Cf.'' '''[[आर्त्नी|Ārtnī]].''' <br>

ज्याका
<u>'''Jyākā'''</u> means ‘bowstring,’ with a contemptuous sense, in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1084/> and in the simple sense in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1084/><br>

ज्या-पाश
<u>'''Jyā-pāśa'''</u> means ‘bowstring’ in the Atharvaveda (xi. 10, 22).<br>

ज्या-ह्रोड
<u>'''Jyā-hroḍa'''</u> occurs in the description of the arms of the '''[[व्रात्य|Vrātya]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1086/> and is also mentioned in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1086/> The sense is somewhat obscure, for one [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] describes it as a ‘bow not meant for use’ (''ayogyaṃ [[धनुस्|dhanus]]''),<ref name=fx3_ve1_1086/> while the other speaks of it as a ‘bow without an arrow’ (''dhanuṣka aniṣu'').<ref name=fx4_ve1_1086/> Some sort of a bow, therefore, seems to be meant.<br>

ज्येष्ठ
<u>'''Jyeṣṭha,'''</u> ordinarily meaning ‘greatest,’ has further the specific sense of ‘eldest’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1087/> brother in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1087/> It also means the eldest among sons, which is another side of the same sense.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1087/><br>

ज्येष्ठ-घ्नी
<u>'''Jyeṣṭha-ghnī,'''</u> ‘slaying the eldest,’ is the name of a '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]],''' or lunar mansion, usually called '''[[ज्येष्ठा|Jyeṣṭhā]],''' in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1088/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1088/> It is Antares or ''Cor Scipionis.''<br>

ज्येष्ठा
<u>'''Jyeṣṭhā.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].''' <br>

ज्यैष्ठिनेय
<u>'''Jyaiṣṭhineya'''</u> denotes, in combination with '''[[ज्येष्ठ|Jyeṣṭha]],''' the eldest,’ a ‘son of the father's first wife’ (''[[ज्येष्ठा|jyeṣṭhā]]''), in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1090/><br>

ज्योतिष
<u>'''Jyotiṣa,'''</u> ‘astronomy.’ It is important to note that no reference to any work on astronomy occurs in the Saṃhitās or Brāhmaṇas. The text which claims to represent the astronomical science of the Veda has been edited by Weber,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1091/> and has frequently been discussed since.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1091/> Its date is unknown, but is undoubtedly late, as is shown alike by the contents and form of the work.<br>

ज्वालायन
<u>'''Jvālāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Jvāla,’ is the name of a man, a pupil of '''[[गौषूक्ति|Gauṣūkti]],''' mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iv. 16, 1), in a list of teachers.<br>

झष
<u>'''Jhaṣa'''</u> is mentioned in the story of Manu told in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1093/> where it means a ‘great fish’ (''[[महा-मत्स्य|mahā-matsya]]'') according to the commentator. Eggeling<ref name=fx2_ve1_1093/> suggests that a horned fish is meant, because in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_1093/> the Iḍā, or personified libation, is represented as a cow, and this may have brought in the idea of a horned fish in the later form of an old legend. But ''cf.'' '''[[जष|Jaṣa]].''' <br>

तकवान
<u>'''Takavāna'''</u> appears to be a patronymic from Taku,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1094/> and to be the name of a seer in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1094/> presumably a descendant of Taku [[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]], for his name occurs in a group of hymns composed by the Kākṣīvatas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1094/><br>

तक्मन्
<u>'''Takman'''</u> is a disease repeatedly mentioned in the Atharvaveda, but later not known under this name. It is the subject of five hymns<ref name=fx1_ve1_1095/> of the Atharvaveda, and is often mentioned elsewhere.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1095/> Weber<ref name=fx3_ve1_1095/> first identified it with ‘fever,’ and Grohmann<ref name=fx4_ve1_1095/> showed that all the symptoms pointed to that ailment.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1095/> Reference is made to the alternate hot and shivering fits of the patient,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1095/> to the yellow colour of the jaundice which accompanies the fever,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1095/> and to its peculiar periodicity. The words used to describe its varieties are ''anye-dyuḥ,''<ref name=fx8_ve1_1095/> ''ubhaya-dyuḥ,''<ref name=fx9_ve1_1095/> ''[[तृतीयक|tṛtīyaka]],''<ref name=fx10_ve1_1095/> ''vi-tṛtīya,''<ref name=fx11_ve1_1095/> and ''sadaṃ-di,''<ref name=fx12_ve1_1095/> the exact sense of most of which terms is somewhat uncertain. It is agreed<ref name=fx13_ve1_1095/> that the first epithet designates the fever known as ''quotidianus,'' which recurs each day at the same hour, though the word is curious (lit.  ‘on the other--''i.e.,'' next, day’). The ''ubhaya-dyuḥ'' (‘on both days’) variety appears to mean a disease recurring for two successive days, the third being free; this corresponds to the ''rhythmus quartanus complicatus.''<ref name=fx14_ve1_1095/> But Sāyaṇa considers that it means a fever recurring on the third day, the ‘tertian.’ The ''[[तृतीयक|tṛtīyaka]],'' however, must be the ‘tertian’ fever,<ref name=fx15_ve1_1095/> though Zimmer<ref name=fx16_ve1_1095/> suggests that it may mean a fever which is fatal at the third paroxysm. Grohmann<ref name=fx17_ve1_1095/> regards the ''vi-[[तृतीयक|tṛtīyaka]]'' as equivalent to the ''tertiana duplicata,'' a common form in southern countries, in which the fever occurs daily, but with a correspondence in point of time or severity of attack on alternate days. Bloomfield<ref name=fx18_ve1_1095/> suggests that it is identical with the ''ubhaya-dyuḥ'' variety. The ''sadaṃ-di''<ref name=fx19_ve1_1095/> type appears to be the kind later known as ''saṃtata-jvara'' (‘continuous fever’), in which there are attacks of several days’ duration, with an interval followed by a fresh period of attack. Fever occurred at different seasons, in the autumn (''[[शारद|śārada]]''), in the hot weather (''graiṣma''), in the rains (''vārṣika''),<ref name=fx20_ve1_1095/> but was especially prevalent in the first, as is indicated by the epithet ''viśva-[[शारद|śārada]],'' ‘occurring every autumn.’<ref name=fx21_ve1_1095/><br><br>The disease is said to arise when Agni enters the waters.<ref name=fx22_ve1_1095/> From this Weber<ref name=fx23_ve1_1095/> deduced that it was considered to be the result of a chill supervening on heat, or the influence of heat on marshy land. Grohmann<ref name=fx24_ve1_1095/> preferred to see in this connexion of the origin of the disease with Agni's entering the waters<ref name=fx25_ve1_1095/> an allusion to the fact that fever arises in the rainy season, the time when Agni, as lightning, descends to earth with the rain. Zimmer.<ref name=fx26_ve1_1095/> who accepts this view, further refers to the prevalence  of fever in the Terai, and interprets ''vanya,'' an epithet of fever found in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx27_ve1_1095/> as meaning ‘sprung from the forest,’ pointing out that fever is mentioned as prevalent among the '''Mūjavants''' and '''Mahāvṛṣas,''' two mountain tribes of the western Himālaya.<ref name=fx28_ve1_1095/> There is no trace of fever having been observed to be caused by the bite of the ''anopheles'' mosquito, which breeds in stagnant water: this theory has without reason been held to be known to classical Indian medicine.<ref name=fx29_ve1_1095/><br><br>Among the symptoms of [[तक्मन्|Takman]], or among complications accompanying it, are mentioned ‘itch’ ('''[[पामन्|Pāman]]'''), ‘headache’ (''śīrṣa-śoka''),<ref name=fx30_ve1_1095/> ‘cough’ ('''Kāsikā'''), and ‘consumption,’ or perhaps some form of itch ('''[[बलास|Balāsa]]''').<br><br>It is perhaps significant that the [[तक्मन्|Takman]] does not appear until the Atharvaveda. It is quite possible that the Vedic Āryans, when first settled in India, did not know the disease, which would take some generations to become endemic and recognized as dangerous. What remedies they used against it is quite uncertain, for the Atharvaveda mentions only spells and the '''[[कुष्ठ|Kuṣṭha]],''' which can hardly have been an effective remedy, though still used in later times. Fever must, even in the [[अथर्वन्|Atharvan]] period, have claimed many victims, or it would not be mentioned so prominently.<br>

तक्वन्
<u>'''Takvan,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1096/> '''Takvarī,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1096/> seem in the Rigveda to denote a ‘swiftflying bird.’ Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx3_ve1_1096/> explains [[तक्वन्|Takvan]] as a swift steed.<br>

तक्षक वैशालेय
<u>'''Takṣaka Vaiśāleya'''</u> (‘descendant of Viśālā’) is a mythical figure, mentioned as the son of [[विराज्|Virāj]] in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1097/> and as [[ब्राह्मणाच्छंसिन्|Brāhmaṇācchaṃsin]] priest at the snake sacrifice in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1097/> <br>

तक्षन्
<u>'''1. Takṣan,'''</u> ‘carpenter,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1098/> and often later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1098/> He was employed to do all sorts of work in wood, such as the making of chariots ('''[[रथ|Ratha]]''') and wagons ('''Anas'''). Carved work of a finer type seems also to have fallen to his lot.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1098/> The axe (''[[कुलिश|kuliśa]],''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1098/> ''[[परशु|paraśu]]'')<ref name=fx5_ve1_1098/> is mentioned as one of his tools, and perhaps the '''[[भुरिज्|Bhurij]],''' a word which is, however, uncertain in sense. In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_1098/> reference seems to be made to the pains of the carpenter in bending over his work. That the carpenters were a low caste, or formed a separate class of the people, is certainly not true of Vedic times.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1098/><br>

तक्षन्
<u>'''2. Takṣan'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1099/> as a teacher whose view of a certain formula was not accepted by '''Jīvala [[चैलकि|Cailaki]].'''<br>

तक्षन्
<u>'''3. Takṣan.'''</u> See '''[[बृबु|Bṛbu]].'''<br>

तण्डुल
<u>'''Taṇḍula,'''</u> ‘grain,’ especially ‘rice grain,’ is mentioned very often in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1101/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1101/> but not in the Rigveda. This accords with the fact that rice cultivation seems hardly known in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1101/> Husked (''karṇa'') and unhusked (''akarṇa'') rice is referred to in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1101/> <br>

तत
<u>'''Tata,'''</u> ‘dada,’ is the pet name for ‘father’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1102/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1102/> ''Cf.'' '''[[तात|Tāta]]''' and '''[[पितृ|Pitṛ]].'''<br>

ततामह
<u>'''Tatāmaha,'''</u> ‘grandfather,’ is found in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1103/><br>

तनय
<u>'''Tanaya,'''</u> n., denotes ‘offspring,’ ‘descendants’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1104/> where also it is often used adjectivally with '''Toka.'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1104/> There seems no ground for the view<ref name=fx3_ve1_1104/> that ''toka'' means ‘sons,’ ‘children,’ and ''[[तनय|tanaya]]'' ‘grandchildren.’<br>

तन्ति
<u>'''Tanti'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1105/> where Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_1105/> renders the plural of the word by ‘files’ of calves. But it seems rather to have the sense which it has in the later literature, of ‘cords,’ here used to fasten the calves.<br>

तन्तु
<u>'''Tantu'''</u> appears properly to mean ‘thread,’ and in particular the ‘warp’ of a piece of weaving, as opposed to '''Otu,''' the ‘woof.’ Both senses are found in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1106/> In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1106/> the ‘warp’ is called ''anuchāda,'' the ‘woof’ ''[[पर्य्आस|paryāsa]],'' the ''tantavaḥ'' being the ‘threads.’ In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1106/>  on the other hand, the ‘warp’ is ''[[प्राचीन-तान|prācīna-tāna]],'' the ‘woof’ ''otu.'' The threads or cords of the throne ('''Pary ṅka''') are referred to in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1106/><br><br>In the Rigveda the word is used only metaphorically, and this is its most frequent use even in the Brāhmanas.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1106/> See also '''[[वाण|Vāṇa]].'''<br>

तन्त्र
<u>'''Tantra'''</u> means, like '''[[तन्तु|Tantu]],''' the ‘warp’ of a piece of weaving, or more generally the ‘web’ itself. It is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1107/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1107/><br>

तपस्
<u>'''Tapas, Tapasya.'''</u> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

तपो-नित्य
<u>'''Tapo-nitya'''</u> (‘constant in penance’) [[पौरु-शिष्टि|Pauru-śiṣṭi]] (‘descendant of Puruśiṣṭa’) is the name of a teacher in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 9, 1) who believed in the value of penance (''[[तपस्|tapas]]'').<br>

तयादर
<u>'''Tayādara'''</u> is the name of an animal only mentioned in the adjectival form ''[[तायादर|tāyādara]]'' along with '''[[परस्वन्त्|Parasvant]],''' ‘wild ass’(?) in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1110/><br>

तरक्षु
<u>'''Tarakṣu,'''</u> the ‘hyæna,’ is mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1111/> <br>

तरन्त
<u>'''Taranta'''</u> appears, along with '''Purumīḍha,''' as a patron of '''[[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]]''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1112/> In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1112/> and other Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx3_ve1_1112/> he, together with Purumīḍha, is described as receiving gifts from '''[[ध्वस्र|Dhvasra]]'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1112/> and '''[[पुरुषन्ति|Puruṣanti]];''' but since the receipt of gifts was forbidden to Kṣatriyas, they for the nonce became [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]], and composed a passage in honour of the donors.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1112/> He, like Purumīḍha, was a [[वैदद्अश्वि|Vaidadaśvi]], or son of Vidadaśva.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1112/><br>

तरु
<u>'''Taru,'''</u> the usual term for ‘tree’ in classical Sanskrit, never occurs in Vedic literature, except perhaps in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1113/> where Sāyaṇa finds it, and where it can be so translated. But the form (''tarubhiḥ'') is probably to be interpreted otherwise.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1113/><br>

तरुक्ष
<u>'''Tarukṣa'''</u> is the name of a man in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1114/> who is mentioned along with '''[[बल्बूथ|Balbūtha]],''' the '''[[दास|Dāsa]],''' in a [[दान|Dāna]]-[[स्तुति|stuti]], or ‘Praise of Gifts.’<br>

तर्कु
<u>'''Tarku,'''</u> ‘spindle,’ is known only in Vedic literature from the mention of it in Yāska's [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (ii. 1) as an example of the transposition of letters, the word being derived, according to him, from the root ''kart,'' ‘to spin.’ <br>

तर्द
<u>'''Tarda,'''</u> ‘borer,’ occurs in a hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1116/> enumerating insects that injure grain. Whitney<ref name=fx2_ve1_1116/> suggests that a kind of mouse or rat may be meant. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_1116/> thought a bird was denoted.<br>

तर्द्मन्
<u>'''Tardman'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1117/> applies to the hole in the yoke ('''Yuga'''). In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1117/> it designates a hole in a skin.<br>

तर्य
<u>'''Tarya'''</u> is, according to Sāyaṇa, the name of a man in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1118/> But the verse is hopelessly obscure.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1118/><br>

तलाश
<u>'''Talāśa'''</u> is the name of a tree in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1119/> Whitney<ref name=fx2_ve1_1119/> suggests that it may be the same as ''tālīśa (Flacourtia cataphracta).''<br>

तल्प
<u>'''Talpa'''</u> is the regular term for ‘bed’ or ‘couch’ from the Rigveda and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1120/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1120/> One made of '''[[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]]''' wood is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1120/> The violation of the bed of a Guru, or teacher, is already mentioned in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_1120/> while the adjective ''talpya,'' ‘born in the nuptial couch,’ denotes ‘legitimate’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_1120/> <br>

तलव
<u>'''Talava'''</u> in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha, or human sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1121/> denotes a ‘musician’ of some kind.<br>

तष्टृ
<u>'''Taṣṭṛ'''</u> is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1122/> in the sense of ‘carpenter,’ like '''[[तक्षन्|Takṣan]],''' which is from the same root ''takṣ,'' ‘to fashion.’<br>

तसर
<u>'''Tasara'''</u> denotes the weaver's ‘shuttle’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1123/> and the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1123/><br>

तस्कर
<u>'''Taskara'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1124/> and frequently later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1124/> denoting ‘thief’ or ‘robber.’ It appears to be practically synonymous with '''[[स्तेन|Stena]],''' in connexion with which it is often mentioned.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1124/> The [[स्तेन|Stena]] and the [[तस्कर|Taskara]] are contrasted in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve1_1124/> with the '''[[मलिम्लु|Malimlu]],''' who is a burglar or house-breaker, while they are highwaymen, or, as the Rigveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_1124/> puts it, ‘men who haunt the woods and risk their lives’ (''tanū-tyajā vanar-gū''). In another passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1124/> however, the dog is told to bark at the [[तस्कर|Taskara]] or the [[स्तेन|Stena]], which clearly points to an attempt at house-breaking. The thief goes about at night,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1124/> and knows the paths<ref name=fx8_ve1_1124/> on which he attacks his victim. In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx9_ve1_1124/> the use of cords is mentioned, but whether to bind the thieves when captured, or to bind the  victim, is not clear.<ref name=fx10_ve1_1124/> The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx11_ve1_1124/> refers to the [[स्तेन|Stena]] and the [[तस्कर|Taskara]] as cattle and horse thieves.<ref name=fx12_ve1_1124/><br>

तायु
<u>'''Tāyu'''</u> was another name for thief, perhaps of a less distinguished and more domestic character than the highwayman, for though he is referred to as a cattle-thief,<ref name=fx13_ve1_1125/> he is also alluded to as a stealer of clothes (''[[वस्त्र|vastra]]-mathi'')<ref name=fx14_ve1_1125/> and as a debtor.<ref name=fx15_ve1_1125/> In one passage the Tāyus are said to disappear at the coming of dawn (which is elsewhere called ''yāvayad-dveṣas,'' ‘driving away hostile beings,’ and ''ṛta-pā,'' ‘guardian of order’), like the stars of heaven (''[[नक्षत्र|nakṣatra]]'').<ref name=fx16_ve1_1125/><br><br>In the [[शतरुद्रिय|Śatarudriya]] litany of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx17_ve1_1125/> Rudra is called lord of assailers (''ā-vyādhin''), thieves (''[[स्तेन|stena]]''), robbers (''[[तस्कर|taskara]]''), pickpockets (''stāyu''), stealers (''muṣṇant''), and cutters (''vi-kṛnta''); and designations of sharpers (''gṛtsa'') and bands (''gaṇa, [[व्रात|vrāta]]''), apparently of robbers, are mentioned.<ref name=fx18_ve1_1125/> It is therefore not surprising that the Rigveda<ref name=fx19_ve1_1125/> should contain many prayers for safety at home or on the way, or that the Atharvaveda should devote several hymns to night<ref name=fx20_ve1_1125/> chiefly for protection against the evil doings of thieves and robbers.<br><br>Pischel<ref name=fx21_ve1_1125/> suggests that in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx22_ve1_1125/> '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]''' is represented as a burglar, but the admits that, since [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] was attacking the house of his father Varuṇa, he was only seeking to obtain what he may have regarded as his own. But the interpretation of the hymn is not certain.<ref name=fx23_ve1_1125/><br><br>Sāyaṇa's explanation of one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx24_ve1_1125/> as  referring to professional cattle-trackers, like the Khojis of the Panjab, seems quite probable.<ref name=fx25_ve1_1125/><br><br>The punishment of thieves appears primarily to have been left to the action of the robbed. The practice of binding them in stocks<ref name=fx26_ve1_1125/> seems clearly referred to. But later, at any rate-and in all probability earlier also, as in othe countries--a more severe penalty could be exacted, and death inflicted by the king.<ref name=fx27_ve1_1125/> There is no hint in Vedic literature of the mode of conviction; a fire ordeal is not known to the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx28_ve1_1125/> and the ordeal known to the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx29_ve1_1125/> is not said to be used in the case of theft. No doubt the stolen property was recovered by the person robbed if he could obtain it. Nothing is known as to what happened if the property had passed from the actual thief into the possession of another person.<br>

तस्तुव
<u>'''Tastuva,'''</u> or '''Tasruva,''' as the Paippalāda recension has it, is the name of a remedy against snake poison, and is mentioned along with '''[[ताबुव|Tābuva]]''' in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1126/> <br>

ताजद्-भङ्ग
<u>'''Tājad-bhaṅga'''</u> (‘easily broken’) is apparently the name of a tree or plant in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1127/> The [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1127/> treats it as a compound word, and its commentator makes it out to be the castor-oil plant (''[[एरण्ड|eraṇḍa]]''). Whitney,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1127/> however, treats the expression as two separate words, and thinks that the passage means ‘may they be broken suddenly (''tājat'') like hemp (''bhañga'').’<br>

ताण्ड
<u>'''Tāṇḍa'''</u> seems to be the name of a sage to whose school belonged the [[ताण्ड|Tāṇḍa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] mentioned in the Lāṭyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1128/><br>

ताण्ड-विन्द
<u>'''Tāṇḍa-vinda,'''</u> or '''[[ताण्ड|Tāṇḍa]]-vindava,''' is the name of a teacher mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1129/><br>

ताण्डि
<u>'''Tāṇḍi'''</u> occurs as the name of a pupil of '''[[बादरायण|Bādarāyaṇa]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the Sāmavidhāna [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1130/><br>

ताण्ड्य
<u>'''Tāṇḍya'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1131/> quoted on a point bearing on the Agniciti, or piling of the sacred fire. He is also mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1131/> The [[ताण्ड्य|Tāṇḍya]] [[महाब्राह्मण|Mahābrāhmaṇa]] or [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1131/> of the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]] represents the school of the Tāṇḍins. <br>

तात
<u>'''Tāta,'''</u> apparently ‘dada's boy,’ an affectionate term of address by a father (''cf.'' '''Tata''') to a son, is found in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1132/> occurring in the vocative only. But in the sense of ‘father,’ through confusion with Tata, it occurs also as early as the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1132/><br>

तादुरी
<u>'''Tādurī'''</u> is mentioned in a verse of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1133/> together with the female frog ('''Maṇḍūkī'''). Some similar animal must be meant,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1133/> but Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1133/> with the commentator [[दुर्ग|Durga]] on the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_1133/> regards the word as an adjective describing the frog.<br>

तान्व
<u>'''1. Tānva'''</u> in an obscure passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1134/> seems to mean a ‘legitimate son,’ who is said not to leave the heritage (''[[रिक्थ|riktha]]'') of his father to his sister (''[[जामि|jāmi]]''). The exact meaning is probably unascertainable,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1134/> but the passage may convey a statement of what was no doubt the fact, that the daughter had no share in the paternal inheritance; her brother had to provide for her during her life if she remained unmarried, but she had no independent portion.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1134/> (See '''[[दाय|Dāya]].''')<br>

तान्व
<u>'''2. Tānva'''</u> appears to be a patronymic, ‘descendant of Tanva,’ in a verse of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1135/> Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_1135/> thinks that it is the patronymic of '''[[दुःशीम|Duḥśīma]],''' who is mentioned in the preceding verse, but this is uncertain. <br>

तापस
<u>'''1. Tāpasa,'''</u> ‘ascetic,’ is not found in Vedic literature till the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1136/><br>

तापस
<u>'''2. Tāpasa'''</u> is a name of '''Datta''' who was [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest at the snake festival described in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxv. 15).<br>

ताबुव
<u>'''Tābuva'''</u> is the name in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1138/> of a remedy against snake poison. The Paippalāda recension has Tāvuca instead. Weber<ref name=fx2_ve1_1138/> thinks that the original form was Tāthuva, from the root ''sthā,'' ‘stand,’ and that it meant ‘stopping’; but this is hardly probable.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1138/><br>

तायादर
<u>'''Tāyādara,'''</u> ‘belonging to the '''[[तयादर|Tayādara]]'''’ (Av. vi. 72, 2).<br>

तायु
<u>'''Tāyu,'''</u> ‘thief,’ is mentioned several times in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1140/> See '''[[तस्कर|Taskara]].'''<br>

तारका
<u>'''Tārakā'''</u> is found several times in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1141/> denoting a star. The masculine form Tāraka occurs in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1141/><br>

तारुक्ष्य
<u>'''Tārukṣya'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1142/> and [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyakas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1142/> In the former passage [[तार्क्ष्य|Tārkṣya]] is a variant reading, and in the latter [[तार्क्ष्य|Tārkṣya]] is read, but this is probably only due to confusion with [[तार्क्ष्य|Tārkṣya]], the reputed author of a Rigvedic hymn.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1142/> <br>

तार्क्ष्य
<u>'''Tārkṣya'''</u> is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1143/> as a divine steed, apparently the sun conceived as a horse.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1143/> But Foy,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1143/> judging by the name, apparently a patronymic of '''[[तृक्षि|Tṛkṣi]],''' who is known from the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1143/> onwards as a descendant of '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]],''' thinks that a real steed, the property of [[तृक्षि|Tṛkṣi]], is meant; but this is not very probable.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1143/> See also '''[[तारुक्ष्य|Tārukṣya]].'''<br>

तार्प्य
<u>'''Tārpya'''</u> denotes, in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1144/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1144/> a garment made of some material, the nature of which is uncertain. The commentators on the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1144/> suggest that a linen garment, or one thrice soaked in ghee, or one made of the ''tṛpā'' or of the ''triparṇa'' plant, is meant: it is doubtful whether the sense was known even to the author of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] himself. Goldstücker's<ref name=fx4_ve1_1144/> rendering of the word is ‘silken garment,’ which Eggeling<ref name=fx5_ve1_1144/> is inclined to accept.^6<br>

तार्ष्टाघ
<u>'''Tārṣṭāgha,'''</u> a species of tree, is mentioned in the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1145/> while the adjective formed from it, ''tārṣṭāghī,'' ‘derived from the [[तार्ष्टाघ|Tārṣṭāgha]] tree,’ is found in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1145/> Weber<ref name=fx3_ve1_1145/> thinks that the ''[[सर्षप|sarṣapa]],'' or mustard plant, is meant. <br>

तितü
<u>'''Titaü'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1146/> is found once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1146/> denoting a ‘sieve,’ or perhaps ‘winnowing fan,’ which was used for purifying corn (''[[सक्तु|saktu]]'').<br>

तित्तिर
<u>'''Tittira, Tittiri,'''</u> is the name of the partridge in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1147/> and the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1147/> being presumably an onomatopoetic formation. The bird is described as having variegated plumage (''bahu-rūpa''). It is usually associated with the '''[[कपिञ्जल|Kapiñjala]]''' and '''[[कलविङ्क|Kalaviṅka]].'''<br>

तिथि
<u>'''Tithi,'''</u> as the name of a lunar day, the thirtieth part of a lunar month of rather over twenty-seven days, is only found in the later Sūtras,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1148/> being completely unknown to the Brāhmaṇas, in which the only day is the natural one.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1148/> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

तिमिर्घ दौरे-श्रुत
<u>'''Timirgha Daure-śruta'''</u> (‘descendant of Dūreśruta’) is mentioned as Agnīdh (‘fire-kindling’) priest at the snake sacrifice described in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1149/><br>

तिरश्च
<u>'''Tiraśca'''</u> is read in some manuscripts of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1150/> in the description of the Vrātya's throne ('''[[आसन्दी|Āsandī]]'''), meaning ‘the cross-pieces.’ But the reading should be ''tiraścye,'' which is adjectival, and is used in the same sense. <br>

तिरश्च-राजि
<u>'''Tiraśca-rāji,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1151/> '''Tiraści-rāji,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1151/> '''Tiraścīna-rāji,'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1151/> are variant forms of a name for ‘snake’ (lit., ‘striped across’), found in the later Saṃhitās.<br>

तिरश्ची
<u>'''Tiraścī'''</u> is, according to the Anukramaṇī, the author of a Rigvedic hymn<ref name=fx1_ve1_1152/> in which he appeals to Indra to hear his call. The [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1152/> adopts this view of the name, and mentions a [[तिरश्ची|Tiraścī]] [[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]]. But Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_1152/> thinks that the word is not a proper name at all.<br>

तिरश्चीन-वंश
<u>'''Tiraścīna-vaṃśa,'''</u> ‘cross-beam,’ is used to denote a ‘beehive’ in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1153/> See also '''[[वंश|Vaṃśa]].'''<br>

तिरिन्दिर
<u>'''Tirindira'''</u> is mentioned in a Dānastuti, or ‘Praise of Gifts,’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1154/> as having, along with '''[[पर्शु|Parśu]],''' bestowed gifts on the singer. In the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1154/> this statement is represented by a tale that the [[कण्व|Kaṇva]] [[वत्स|Vatsa]] obtained a gift from [[तिरिन्दिर|Tirindira]] [[पारशव्य|Pāraśavya]], [[तिरिन्दिर|Tirindira]] and [[पर्शु|Parśu]] being in this version thus treated as one and the same man. Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve1_1154/> sees in the Rigvedic passage a proof that the Yadus had gained a victory over [[तिरिन्दिर|Tirindira]], and gave a part of the booty to the singers; but there is no proof whatever of the correctness of this interpretation, which Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve1_1154/> shows to be most unlikely. Yadu princes must be meant by [[तिरिन्दिर|Tirindira]] and  [[पर्शु|Parśu]], though Weber<ref name=fx5_ve1_1154/> thinks that the singers were Yadus, not the princes. The latter he holds to have been Iranian (''cf.'', and see '''[[पर्शु|Parśu]]'''), and he thinks that in this there is evidence of continual close relations between India and Iran. This is perfectly possible, but the evidence for it is rather slight.(**  6 For the recent controversy as to Iranian names found at Boghaz-kio7i, ''cf.'' Jacobi, ''Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society,'' 1909, 721 ''et seq.;'' Oldenberg, ''ibid.,'' 1095-1100; Keith, ''ibid.,'' 1100-1106; Sayce, ''ibid.,'' 1106, 1107; Kennedy, ''ibid.,'' 1107-1119. Hillebrandt, ''Vedische Mythologie,'' 1, 94 ''et seq.,'' argues in favour of an early connexion of Iranians and Indians in Arachosia, where he places part of the action of the Rigveda. Hopkins, ''Journal of the American Oriental Society,'' 17, 16, 277, holds that traces of Iranian connexion are signs of late date; Arnold, ''ibid.,'' 18, 205 ''et seq.,'' opposes this view.<br>

तिरीट
<u>'''Tirīṭa'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1155/> is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1155/> in the adjectival derivative ''tirīṭin'' used of a demon, and presumably meaning ‘adorned with a tiara.’<br>

तिर्य
<u>'''Tirya'''</u> occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1156/> as an epithet of '''[[करम्भ|Karambha]],''' ‘gruel.’ It is probably equivalent to ''tilya,'' ‘made of sesamum,’ as rendered by Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_1156/> and Whitney,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1156/> but ''tiriya'' is read by Roth<ref name=fx4_ve1_1156/> in the Rāja-nighaṇṭu as a kind of rice.<br>

तिर्यञ्च् आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Tiryañc Āṅgirasa'''</u> is mentioned as a seer of Sāmans, or Chants, in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1157/> The name is doubtless feigned. <br>

तिल
<u>'''Tila'''</u> denotes in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1158/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1158/> the sesamum plant, and particularly its grains, from which a rich oil ('''[[तैल|Taila]]''') was extracted. It is often<ref name=fx3_ve1_1158/> mentioned in connexion with '''[[माष|Māṣa]],''' ‘kidney bean.’ The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve1_1158/> attributes the bean and the sesamum to the winter (''[[हेमन्त|hemanta]]'') and the cool (''[[शिशिर|śiśira]]'') seasons. The stalk of the sesamum plant (''tila-piñjī,''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1158/> ''til-piñja''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1158/>) was used for fuel, and the seed was boiled in the form of porridge (''tilaudana''<ref name=fx7_ve1_1158/>) for food.<br>

तिल्वक
<u>'''Tilvaka'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1159/> as a tree (''Symplocos racemosa''), near which it is inauspicious to construct a grave. The adjectival derivative ''tailvaka,'' ‘made of the wood of the [[तिल्वक|Tilvaka]],’ is found in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1159/> and is employed to describe the ''[[यूप|yūpa]],'' or sacrificial post, in the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1159/><br>

तिष्य
<u>'''Tiṣya'''</u> occurs twice in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1160/> apparently as the name of a star,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1160/> though Sāyaṇa takes it to mean the sun. It is doubtless identical with the Avestan Tistrya. Later it is the name of a lunar mansion: see '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

तिसृ-धन्व
<u>'''Tisṛ-dhanva,'''</u> ‘a bow with three (arrows),’ is mentioned as a gift to the priest at the sacrifice in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1161/> and in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1161/> <br>

तुग्र
<u>'''Tugra'''</u> appears in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1162/> as the name of the father of '''[[भुज्यु|Bhujyu]],''' a protégé of the Aśvins, who is accordingly called [[तुग्र्य|Tugrya]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1162/> or [[तौग्र्य|Taugrya]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1162/> A different [[तुग्र|Tugra]] seems to be referred to in other passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1162/> as an enemy of Indra.<br>

तुग्र्य
<u>'''Tugrya'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda as a patronymic of '''[[भुज्यु|Bhujyu]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1163/> but also in a passage<ref name=fx2_ve1_1163/> in which no reference to [[भुज्यु|Bhujyu]] appears to be meant, and in which it may mean ‘a man of the house of [[तुग्र|Tugra]].’ A similar sense seems to occur in the locative plural feminine in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1163/> where (supplying ''vikṣu'') the meaning must be ‘among the Tugrians.’ This explanation may also apply to the epithet of Indra<ref name=fx4_ve1_1163/> or Soma,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1163/> ''tugryā-vṛdh,'' ‘rejoicing among the Tugrians.’<br>

तुच्
<u>'''Tuc'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1164/> occasionally occurs denoting ‘children.’ Tuj occurs rather more often in the same sense.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1164/> ''Cf.'' '''[[तनय|Tanaya]]''' and '''Toka.'''<br>

तुजि
<u>'''Tuji'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1165/> of a protégé of Indra, who in another hymn<ref name=fx2_ve1_1165/> appears to be called [[तूतुजि|Tūtuji]].<br>

तुमिञ्ज औपोदिति
<u>'''Tumiñja Aupoditi'''</u> is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (i. 7, 2, 1) as a [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest at a Sattra, or ‘sacrificial session,’ and as having been engaged in a discussion with '''[[सुश्रवस्|Suśravas]].''' <br>

तुर कावषेय
<u>'''Tura Kāvaṣeya'''</u> is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the tenth book of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1167/> as the source of the doctrine set forth in that book, and as separated, in the succession of teachers, from '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]]''' by '''Yajñavacas''' and '''Kuśri.''' In the same [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1167/> he is quoted by [[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]] as having erected a fire-altar on the '''[[कारोती|Kārotī]].''' In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1167/> he appears as a [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], or ‘domestic priest,’ of '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]] [[पारिक्षित|Pārikṣita]],''' whom he consecrated king. In the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1167/> and a [[खिल|Khila]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1167/> he appears as an ancient sage. Oldenberg,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1167/> no doubt rightly, assigns him to the end of the Vedic period. He is probably<ref name=fx7_ve1_1167/> identical with Tura, the ''[[देव-मुनि|deva-muni]],'' ‘saint of the gods,’ who is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx8_ve1_1167/><br>

तुर-श्रवस्
<u>'''Tura-śravas'''</u> is the name of a seer mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1168/> as having pleased Indra by two Sāmans (Chants) of his composition. Indra in return appears to have given him the oblation of the '''Pārāvatas''' on the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]].'''<br>

तुर्य-वाह्
<u>'''Turya-vāh,'''</u> masc.; '''Turyauhī,''' fem., ‘a four-year-old ox or cow,’ is mentioned in the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1169/><br>

तुर्व
<u>'''Turva'''</u> occurs only once in the Rigveda (x. 62, 10), doubtless as a name of the '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]]''' people or king. <br>

तुर्वश
<u>'''Turvaśa'''</u> occurs frequently in the Rigveda as the name of a man or of a people, usually in connexion with '''Yadu.''' The two words usually occur in the singular without any connecting particle, ''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] Yadu'' or ''Yadu [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]].''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1171/> In a plural form the name [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] occurs once with the Yadus,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1171/> and once alone<ref name=fx4_ve1_1171/> in a hymn in which the singular has already been used. In one passage<ref name=fx5_ve1_1171/> the dual ''Turvaśā-Yadū'' actually occurs, and in another<ref name=fx6_ve1_1171/> ''Yadus Turvaś ca,'' ‘Yadu and [[तुर्व|Turva]].’ In other passages<ref name=fx7_ve1_1171/> [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] appears alone, while in one<ref name=fx8_ve1_1171/> [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] and [[याद्व|Yādva]] occur.<br><br>From these facts Hopkins<ref name=fx9_ve1_1171/> deduces the erroneousness of the ordinary view,<ref name=fx10_ve1_1171/> according to which [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] is the name of a tribe, the singular denoting the king, and regards [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] as the name of the Yadu king. But the evidence for this is not conclusive. Without laying any stress on the argument based on the theory<ref name=fx11_ve1_1171/> that the ‘five peoples’ of the Rigveda are the '''Anus, Druhyus,''' Turvaśas, Yadus, and '''Pūrus,''' it is perfectly reasonable to hold that the Turvaśas and Yadus were two distinct though closely allied tribes. Such they evidently were to the seers of the hymns which mention in the dual the ''Turvaśā-Yadū'' and speak of ''Yadus Turvaś ca.'' This explanation also suits best the use of the plural of [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] in two Rigvedic hymns.<br><br>In the Rigveda the chief exploit of [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] was his participation in the war against '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' by whom he was defeated.<ref name=fx12_ve1_1171/> Hopkins<ref name=fx13_ve1_1171/> suggests that he may have been named [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] because of his fleet (''tura'') escape from the battle. His escape(**  1 i. 36, 18; 54, 6; 174, 9; vi. 20, 12; 45, 1; viii. 4, 7; 7, 18; 9, 14; 45, 27; x. 49, 8. In vii. 18, 6, [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] is joined with [[यक्षु|Yakṣu]], apparently a contemptuous variant of Yadu (Hopkins, ''Journal of the American Oriental Society,'' 15, 261). ''Cf.'' '''[[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]].'''  may have been assisted by Indra, for in some passages<ref name=fx14_ve1_1171/> Indra's aid to [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] (and) Yadu is referred to; it is also significant that the Anu, and apparently the [[द्रुह्यु|Druhyu]], kings are mentioned as having been drowned in the defeat, but not the [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] and Yadu kings, and that [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] appears in the eighth book of the Rigveda as a worshipper of Indra with the Anu prince, the successor, presumably, of the one who was drowned.<ref name=fx15_ve1_1171/> Griffith,<ref name=fx16_ve1_1171/> however, proposes to refer these passages to a defeat by [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] and Yadu of Arṇa and [[चित्ररथ|Citraratha]] on the '''[[सरयु|Sarayu]];'''<ref name=fx17_ve1_1171/> but the evidence for this is quite inadequate.<br><br>Two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx18_ve1_1171/> seem to refer to an attack by [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] and Yadu on '''Divodāsa,''' the father of [[सुदास्|Sudās]]. It is reasonable to suppose that this was an attack of the two peoples on Divodāsa, for there is some improbability of the references being to the [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]], who was concerned in the attack on [[सुदास्|Sudās]], the son.<br><br>Zimmer<ref name=fx19_ve1_1171/> considers that the Turvaśas were also called '''Vṛcīvants.''' This view is based on a hymn<ref name=fx20_ve1_1171/> in which reference is made to the defeat of the Vṛcīvants on the '''[[यव्यावती|Yavyāvatī]]''' and '''[[हरियूपीया|Hariyūpīyā]]''' in aid of Daivarāta, and of [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] in aid of '''[[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]],''' the latter being elsewhere<ref name=fx21_ve1_1171/> clearly the son of [[देवरात|Devarāta]]. But as this evidence for the identification of the Turvaśas with the Vṛcīvants is not clear, it seems sufficient<ref name=fx22_ve1_1171/> to assume that they were allies.<br><br>Later, in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx23_ve1_1171/> the Turvaśas appear as allies of the Pañcālas, [[तौर्वश|Taurvaśa]] horses, thirty-three in number, and armed men, to the number of 6,000, being mentioned.<ref name=fx24_ve1_1171/> But otherwise the name disappears: this lends  probability to Oldenberge's conjecture<ref name=fx25_ve1_1171/> that the Turvaśas became merged in the '''[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]]''' people. Hopkins<ref name=fx26_ve1_1171/> considers that in the Śatapatha passage the horses were merely named from the family of [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]]; but this view is less likely, since it ignores the difficulty involved in the reference to the men.<br><br>It is impossible to be certain regarding the home of the Turvaśas at the time of their conflict with [[सुदास्|Sudās]]. They apparently crossed the '''[[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]],'''<ref name=fx27_ve1_1171/> but from which side is disputed. The view of Pischel<ref name=fx28_ve1_1171/> and Geldner,<ref name=fx29_ve1_1171/> that they advanced from the west towards the east, where the '''Bharatas''' were (see '''Kuru'''), is the more probable.<br>

तुर्वीति
<u>'''Turvīti'''</u> is mentioned several times in the Rigveda, both in association with [[वय्य|Vayya]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1172/> and alone.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1172/> In three passages<ref name=fx3_ve1_1172/> reference is made to Indra aiding him over a flood. Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve1_1172/> has conjectured that he was king of the Turvaśas and Yadus. But there is no sufficient evidence for this view, though presumably he was of the [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] tribe.<br>

तुला
<u>'''Tulā,'''</u> ‘scales,’ is mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1173/> The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1173/> also speaks of the balance in connexion with the weighing of a man's good and evil deeds in the next and in this world. This differs very considerably from the later balance<ref name=fx3_ve1_1173/> ordeal, in which a man was weighed twice, and was pronounced guilty or innocent according as, on the second occasion, he was more or less heavy than on the  first. It is not possible to read the later practice into the earlier.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1173/><br>

तुष
<u>'''Tuṣa,'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1174/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1174/> regularly denotes the ‘husk’ of grain, often used for a fire.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1174/><br>

तूणव
<u>'''Tūṇava'''</u> denotes in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1175/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve1_1175/> a musical instrument of wood, probably the ‘flute.’ A ‘fluteblower’ is enumerated among the victims of the Puruṣamedha, or ‘human sacrifice.’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1175/><br>

तूतुजि
<u>'''Tūtuji.'''</u> See '''Tuji.'''<br>

तूपर
<u>'''Tūpara,'''</u> ‘hornless,’ is a frequent description of animals intended for the sacrifice, especially of the goat, in the Atharvaveda and later.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1177/><br>

तूर्घ्न
<u>'''Tūrghna'''</u> is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyak (v. 1) as the northern part of [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1178/> Its exact position, however, cannot be ascertained.<br>

तूर्णाश
<u>'''Tūrṇāśa,'''</u> in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1179/> seems to denote a ‘mountain torrent.’ <br>

तूर्वयाण
<u>'''Tūrvayāṇa'''</u> is the name of a prince mentioned in the Rigveda. He appears by name in two passages,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1180/> and is clearly alluded to in a third,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1180/> as an enemy of '''[[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]], [[आयु|Āyu]],''' and '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]].''' With this accords the fact that the '''Pakthas''' were opposed in the battle of the ten kings to the Tṛtsus,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1180/> and that [[तूर्वयाण|Tūrvayāṇa]]  is shown by another passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1180/> to have been a prince of the Pakthas. He is there represented as having been a protégé of Indra, who aided him against '''Cyavāna''' and his guardians, the Maruts. It is not probable that he is identical with '''[[सुश्रवस्|Suśravas]].'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1180/><br>

तूष
<u>'''Tūṣa'''</u> is found in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_1181/> denoting the ‘fringe’ or ‘trimming’ of a garment.<br>

तृक्षि
<u>'''Tṛkṣi'''</u> is, in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1182/> the name of a prince who was a [[त्रासदस्यव|Trāsadasyava]], ‘descendant of '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]].'''’ He also appears with the [[द्रुह्यु|Druhyu]] and the [[पूरु|Pūru]] peoples in another hymn.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1182/> It has been conjectured, but it is not probable, that the steed '''[[तार्क्ष्य|Tārkṣya]]''' (as ‘belonging to Tṛkṣi’) was his.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1182/><br>

तृण
<u>'''Tṛṇa,'''</u> ‘grass,’ is often mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1183/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1183/> It was used as straw to roof in a house or hut.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1183/> <br>

तृण-जलायुक
<u>'''Tṛṇa-jalāyuka,'''</u> ‘caterpillar,’ is mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 2, 4).<br>

तृण-स्कन्द
<u>'''Tṛṇa-skanda'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1185/> as the name of a prince, his subjects (''viśaḥ'') being referred to.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1185/> The word may originally have meant ‘grasshopper.’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1185/><br>

तृतीयक
<u>'''Tṛtīyaka,'''</u> ‘the tertian (fever),’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda (i. 25, 4; v. 22, 13; xix. 39, 10). See '''[[तक्मन्|Takman]].'''<br>

तृत्सु
<u>'''Tṛtsu'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda, once in the singular<ref name=fx1_ve1_1187/> and several times in the plural,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1187/> as a proper name. The Tṛtsus were clearly helpers of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' in the great battle against the ten kings, '''[[शिम्यु|Śimyu]],''' the '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]],''' the '''[[द्रुह्यु|Druhyu]], [[कवष|Kavaṣa]],''' the '''[[पूरु|Pūru]],''' the '''Anu, [[भेद|Bheda]], [[शम्बर|Śambara]],''' the two '''Vaikarṇas,''' and perhaps the '''Yadu,''' who led with them as allies<ref name=fx3_ve1_1187/> the '''Matsyas, Pakthas, [[भलानस्|Bhalānas]], Alinas, Viṣāṇins, Śivas, Ajas, Śigrus,''' and perhaps Yakṣus.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1187/> The defeat of the ten kings is celebrated in one  hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1187/> and is evidently alluded to in two others.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1187/> The great battle took place on the '''[[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]],''' but there was also a fight on the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]''' with [[भेद|Bheda]], the Ajas, Śigrus, and Yakṣus. As the [[यमुना|Yamunā]] and the Parusṇī represent opposite ends of the territory of the Tṛtsus (for we cannot with Hopkins<ref name=fx7_ve1_1187/> safely identify the streams), it is difficult to see exactly how the ten kings could be confederated, but it should be noted that the references to the ten kings occur in the two later hymns,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1187/> and not in the hymn<ref name=fx5_ve1_1187/> describing the battle itself; besides, absolute numerical accuracy cannot be insisted upon.<br><br>It is difficult exactly to determine the character of the Tṛtsus; especially in their relation to the Bharatas, who under Viśvāmitra's guidance are represented as prospering and as advancing to the '''[[विपाश्|Vipāś]]''' and '''[[शुतुद्री|Śutudrī]].'''<ref name=fx8_ve1_1187/> Roth ingeniously brought this into connexion with the defeat of his enemies by [[सुदास्|Sudās]], which is celebrated in the seventh book of the Rigveda--a book attributed to the [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] family--and thought that there was a reference in one verse<ref name=fx9_ve1_1187/> to the defeat of the Bharatas by [[सुदास्|Sudās]]. But it seems certain that the verse is mistranslated, and that the Bharatas are really represented as victors with [[सुदास्|Sudās]].<ref name=fx10_ve1_1187/> Ludwig<ref name=fx11_ve1_1187/> accordingly identifies the Tṛtsus and the Bharatas. Oldenberg,<ref name=fx12_ve1_1187/> after accepting this view at first,<ref name=fx13_ve1_1187/> later expressed the opinion that the Tṛtsus were the priests of the [[भरत|Bharata]] people, and therefore identical with the Vasiṣṭhas. This view is supported by the fact that in one passage<ref name=fx14_ve1_1187/> the Tṛtsus are clearly described as wearing their hair in the peculiar manner affected by the Vasiṣṭhas,<ref name=fx15_ve1_1187/> and would in that passage thus seem to represent the Vasiṣṭhas.  But Geldner<ref name=fx16_ve1_1187/> has suggested with great probability that [[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]], who is once mentioned in the singular,<ref name=fx17_ve1_1187/> means the [[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]] king--that is, [[सुदास्|Sudās]].<ref name=fx18_ve1_1187/> This explanation alone justifies the description<ref name=fx19_ve1_1187/> of the Bharatas as ''Tṛtsūnāṃ viśaḥ,''<ref name=fx20_ve1_1187/> ‘subjects of the Tṛtsus,’ meaning the [[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]] [[गोत्र|Gotra]] or family, for the people could not be said to be subjects of a body of priests. The Vasiṣṭhas might be called Tṛtsus because of their close connexion with the royal house of that people. The reverse process is also quite possible, but is rendered improbable by the fact that the '''Pratṛdaḥ''' are referred to as receiving [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]].<ref name=fx21_ve1_1187/> This name of the [[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]] dynasty is probably older than its connexion with [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] in the time of [[सुदास्|Sudās]], a conclusion supported by the name of '''[[प्रतर्दन|Pratardana]],''' who is mentioned later as a descendant of Divodāsa,<ref name=fx22_ve1_1187/> an ancestor of [[सुदास्|Sudās]]. The [[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]] dynasty could therefore hardly have been referred to as Vasiṣṭhas. For the further history of the dynasty and its relation with [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] and [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]], see '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]].'''<br><br>If the Tṛtsus and their subjects, the Bharatas, were in the Rigvedic period at war with the tribes on either side of the territory between the [[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]] and the [[यमुना|Yamunā]], it is clear<ref name=fx23_ve1_1187/> that later on they coalesced with the Pūrus and probably others of those tribes to form the '''Kuru''' people. Already in the Rigveda<ref name=fx24_ve1_1187/> the Tṛtsus are allied with the '''Sṛñjayas,''' and in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx25_ve1_1187/> one [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] serves both Kurus and Sṛñjayas. <br><br>Hillebrandt<ref name=fx26_ve1_1187/> considers that the Tṛtsus cannot be identified with the Bharatas, but that [[सुदास्|Sudās]] and the Bharatas represent an invading body, which, however, became allied with the Tṛtsus and the [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] priests. He also thinks that the Rigveda reveals a time when '''Divodāsa,''' the grandfather or ancestor of [[सुदास्|Sudās]], was living in Arachosia, on the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],''' and warring against the '''Paṇis,''' whom he identifies with the Parnians. But this conjecture<ref name=fx27_ve1_1187/> cannot be regarded as probable. In the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]<ref name=fx28_ve1_1187/> it is not necessary to see any other river than the later [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]], in the middle country, which flowed within the boundaries of the Tṛtsus: it is also significant that there are references<ref name=fx29_ve1_1187/> to contests between '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] Yadu''' and [[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]] or Divodāsa. Thus there is no reason to doubt that Divodāsa and the Bharatas were in the middle country, and not in Iran.<br>

तृष्ट
<u>'''Tṛṣṭa'''</u> is mentioned in the Maitrāyaṇī<ref name=fx1_ve1_1188/> and [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve1_1188/> as being along with '''Varutri''' the priest of the Asuras.<br>

तृष्टामा
<u>'''Tṛṣṭāmā'''</u> is mentioned as a stream in the [[नदी|Nadī]]-[[स्तुति|stuti]], or ‘praise of rivers,’ in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1189/> There seems to be no means of identifying it.<br>

तेजन
<u>'''Tejana'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1190/> a rod or staff of reed used for measuring a field. In the Atharvaveda the sense of ‘bamboo’ is found twice,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1190/> the bamboo being specified in the  second passage as ‘of the spring’ (''vāsantika''); more particularly it denotes the shaft of an arrow,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1190/> a sense often found in later Vedic texts.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1190/><br>

तेजनी
<u>'''Tejanī'''</u> denotes in the later Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas a bundle of reeds,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1191/> and in some cases such a bundle twisted into a rope,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1191/> for the two ends of the [[तेजनी|Tejanī]] are mentioned.<br>

तेजस्
<u>'''Tejas'''</u> is regarded by Schrader<ref name=fx1_ve1_1192/> as having in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1192/> the specific sense of ‘axe.’ But in all the passages the sense of the ‘bolt’ of the god is adequate.<br>

तैत्तिरीय
<u>'''Taittirīya'''</u> is the name of one of the divisions of the Black [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]], which is, however, not found thus described until the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1193/> The school is represented by a Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1193/> a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1193/> and an Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1193/> besides an [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_1193/> which forms a part of the Āraṇyaka.<br>

तैमात
<u>'''Taimāta'''</u> is twice mentioned as a species of snake in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1194/> <br>

तैल
<u>'''Taila,'''</u> ‘sesamum oil,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1195/> where<ref name=fx2_ve1_1195/> reference is made to keeping such oil in jars. In the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1195/> reference is made to anointing with sesamum oil.<br>

तोक
<u>'''Toka'''</u> denotes ‘children’ or ‘descendants’ generally in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1196/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1196/> The word is often joined with '''[[तनय|Tanaya]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1196/><br>

तोक्मन्
<u>'''Tokman,'''</u> neut., denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1197/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1197/> the green shoots of any kind of grain. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1197/> reference is made to the shoots of rice (''[[व्रीहि|vrīhi]]''), large rice (''mahāvrīhi''), panic seed (''[[प्रियङ्गु|priyaṅgu]]''), and barley (''yava'').<br>

तोत्त्र
<u>'''Tottra,'''</u> a ‘goad’ for driving cattle, is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xii. 4, 1, 10).<br>

तोद
<u>'''Toda'''</u> appears once to denote a ‘goad’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1199/> but more often<ref name=fx2_ve1_1199/> it is an agent noun meaning ‘impeller.’ Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve1_1199/> considers that in one passage<ref name=fx4_ve1_1199/> the sense is ‘wielder of the rod of punishment’ (later ''[[दण्ड|daṇḍa]]-dhara'')--that is, ‘prince.’ <br>

तौग्र्य
<u>'''Taugrya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[तुग्र|Tugra]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[भुज्यु|Bhujyu]]''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1200/><br>

तौदी
<u>'''Taudī'''</u> in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1201/> appears to denote a plant.<br>

तौर्वश
<u>'''Taurvaśa.'''</u> See '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]].'''<br>

तौल
<u>'''Taula,'''</u> the reading of the text of the Atharvaveda (i. 7, 2), and a form which is otherwise unknown and cannot be satisfactorily explained, must doubtless be meant for '''[[तैल|Taila]].'''<br>

तौविलिका
<u>'''Tauvilikā,'''</u> occurring once in a hymn of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1204/> is a word of quite uncertain sense. Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_1204/> thinks it means some kind of beast; Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_1204/> and Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve1_1204/> regard it as a sort of plant; Sāyaṇa explains it as a disease-causing demon, while Bloomfield<ref name=fx5_ve1_1204/> leaves the sense doubtful.<br>

त्रपु
<u>'''Trapu'''</u> denotes ‘tin’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1205/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1205/> Its quality of being easily smelted, which Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_1205/> thinks is indicated by the name (as derived from the root ''trap,'' ‘be ashamed’), is clearly alluded to in the Atharvaveda passage. <br>

त्रस-दस्यु
<u>'''Trasa-dasyu,'''</u> son of '''[[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1206/> is mentioned in the Rigveda as king of the Pūrus.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1206/> He was born to [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]] by his wife, '''[[पुरुकुत्सानी|Purukutsānī]],''' at a time of great distress;<ref name=fx3_ve1_1206/> this, according to Sāyaṇa, refers to Purukutsa's captivity: possibly his death is really meant. [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] was also a descendant of Girikṣit,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1206/> and [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]] was a descendant of [[दुर्गह|Durgaha]]. The genealogy, therefore, appears to be: [[दुर्गह|Durgaha]], Girikṣit, [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]], [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]]. [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] was the ancestor of '''[[तृक्षि|Tṛkṣi]],'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1206/> and, according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1206/> had a son [[हिरणिन्|Hiraṇin]]. Trasadasyu's chronological position is determined by the fact that his father, [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]], was a contemporary of [[सुदास्|Sudās]], either as an opponent<ref name=fx7_ve1_1206/> or as a friend.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1206/> That [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]] was an enemy of [[सुदास्|Sudās]] is more probable, because the latter's predecessor, Divodāsa, was apparently<ref name=fx9_ve1_1206/> at enmity with the Pūrus, and in the battle of the ten kings Pūrus were ranged against [[सुदास्|Sudās]] and the Tṛtsus. [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] himself seems to have been an energetic king. His people, the Pūrus, were settled on the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],'''<ref name=fx10_ve1_1206/> which was, no doubt, the stream in the middle country, that locality according well with the later union of the Pūrus with the '''Kuru''' people, who inhabited that country. This union is exemplified in the person of '''Kuruśravaṇa,''' who is called [[त्रासदस्यव|Trāsadasyava]], ‘descendant of [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]],’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx11_ve1_1206/> whose father was '''[[मित्रातिथि|Mitrātithi]],''' and whose son was '''[[उपमश्रवस्|Upamaśravas]].''' The relation of [[मित्रातिथि|Mitrātithi]] to [[तृक्षि|Tṛkṣi]] does not appear.<br><br>Another descendant of [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] was '''Tryaruṇa [[त्रैवृष्ण|Traivṛṣṇa]],''' who is simply called [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx12_ve1_1206/>  He was not only a ‘descendant of Trivṛṣan,’ but, according to the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx13_ve1_1206/> he was also [[त्रैधात्व|Traidhātva]], ‘descendant of Tridhātu.’ The order of these two predecessors of Tryaruṇa cannot be determined in any way from Vedic literature. According to the later tradition,<ref name=fx14_ve1_1206/> a prince named Tridhanvan preceded Tryaruṇa in the succession. Vedic tradition further fails to show in what precise relation [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] stood to Trivṛṣan or Tryaruṇa.<br><br>Trasdasyu [[पौरुकुत्स|Paurukutsa]] appears in several Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx15_ve1_1206/> as a famous sacrificer of ancient times, together with '''[[पर आट्णार|Para Āṭṇāra]], [[वीतहव्य|Vītahavya]] [[श्रायस|Śrāyasa]],''' and '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]] [[औशिज|Auśija]],''' who in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx16_ve1_1206/> are called ‘ancient great kings’ (''pūrve mahārājāḥ'').<br>

त्रात ऐषुमत
<u>'''Trāta Aiṣumata'''</u> (‘descendant of Iṣumant’) is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1207/> as a pupil of '''Nigaḍa [[पार्णवल्कि|Pārṇavalki]].'''<br>

त्रायमाणा
<u>'''Trāyamāṇā'''</u> denotes in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1208/> a plant of an unknown species. The word is possibly only an epithet, retaining its participial sense of ‘preserving,’ though this interpretation is not favoured by the accent.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1208/><br>

त्रासदस्यव
<u>'''Trāsadasyava,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]],'''’ is the patronymic in the Rigveda of '''[[तृक्षि|Tṛkṣi]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1209/> and of '''Kuruśravaṇa.'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1209/> The  word is also applied to Agni as ‘protector of, or worshipped by, Trasadasyu’ and his line.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1209/><br>

त्रि-ककुद्
<u>'''Tri-kakud'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1210/> or '''Tri-kakubh,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1210/> ‘having three peaks,’ occurs in the Atharvaveda and later as the name of a mountain in the Himālaya, the modern Trikota. From it came the salve ([[आञ्जन|Āñjana]]),<ref name=fx3_ve1_1210/> which tradition made out to be derived from Vṛtra's eye.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1210/><br>

त्रि-कद्रुक
<u>'''Tri-kadruka,'''</u> a term used in the plural only, appears to denote three vessels of some kind for holding Soma.<br><br>^1 i. 32, 3; ii. 11, 17; 15, 1; 22, 1; x. 14, 16.<br>

त्रि-खर्व
<u>'''Tri-kharva'''</u> is the name of a school of priests mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 8, 3) as practising a special rite with success.<br>

त्रित
<u>'''Trita'''</u> is clearly a god<ref name=fx1_ve1_1213/> in Vedic literature, but [[यास्क|Yāska]] in one passage of the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1213/> already explains the name as that of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] or seer.<br>

त्रि-पुर
<u>'''Tri-pura,'''</u> ‘a threefold stronghold,’ is alluded to in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_1214/> as a secure protection. But as the passages are mythical no stress can be laid on them as evidence for the existence of forts with three concentric walls. <br>

त्रि-प्लक्ष
<u>'''Tri-plakṣa,'''</u> masc. plur., ‘the three fig-trees,’ is the name of the place where the '''[[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]]''' disappeared, near the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]],''' according to the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1215/><br>

त्रिय्-अवि
<u>'''Triy-avi.'''</u> See '''[[त्र्य्अवि|Tryavi]].'''<br>

त्रि-युग
<u>'''Tri-yuga,'''</u> neut., is an expression occurring in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1217/> where it is said that the plants (''[[ओषधि|oṣadhi]]'') were born ‘three ages’ before the gods (''devebhyas triyugaṃ purā''). The commentator on the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1217/> thinks that the ages here meant are the Yugas of the later Indian chronology, the sense of the passage being that the plants were born in the first Yuga. The author of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1217/> understands three seasons--spring, the rains, and autumn--to be meant in the verse, taking the two words ''triyugaṃ purā'' separately as ‘formerly, in the three seasons.’ The vague sense ‘three ages’ is quite adequate: the use of ‘three’ in such cases is a favourite feature in folklore. ''Cf.'' '''Yuga.'''<br>

त्रि-वत्स
<u>'''Tri-vatsa,'''</u> ‘three years old,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1218/> is an expression applied to cattle in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1218/><br>

त्रि-वृत्
<u>'''Tri-vṛt,'''</u> ‘threefold,’ is the designation of an amulet in the Atharvaveda (v. 28, 2. 4).<br>

त्रि-वेद कृष्ण-रात लौहित्य
<u>'''Tri-veda [[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]]-rāta Lauhitya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[श्यामजयन्त लौहित्य|Śyāmajayanta Lauhitya]],''' according to a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1). <br>

त्रि-शङ्कु
<u>'''Tri-śaṅku'''</u> is in Vedic literature the name of a sage mentioned as a teacher in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1221/> There is no trace of the later legend by which he becomes the victim of '''Vasiṣṭha's''' curse and the object of '''Viśvāmitra's''' solicitude, being eventually fixed in the sky as a constellation.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1221/> The confusion of the chronology in the tales of [[त्रिशङ्कु|Triśaṅku]] is a good example of the worthlessness of the supposed epic tradition.<br>

त्रि-शोक
<u>'''Tri-śoka'''</u> is the name of an ancient mythical seer who is mentioned both in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1222/> and the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1222/> A Sāman, or chant, named after him is referred to in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1222/><br>

त्रै-ककुद
<u>'''Trai-kakuda.'''</u> See '''[[त्रिककुद्|Trikakud]].'''<br>

त्रैतन
<u>'''Traitana'''</u> appears in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1224/> as a '''[[दास|Dāsa]],''' an enemy of '''[[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]],''' who seems to have engaged him in single combat and defeated him. The St. Petersburg Dictionary suggests that he is rather a supernatural being allied to [[त्रित|Trita]] (''cf.'' the Avestan Thrita and Thraetaona).<ref name=fx2_ve1_1224/><br>

त्रै-धात्व
<u>'''Trai-dhātva'''</u> (‘descendant of Tridhātu,’) is the patronymic of '''Tryaruṇa''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 3, 12).<br>

त्रै-पद
<u>'''Trai-pada,'''</u> neut., occurs as a measure of distance, ‘threequarters’ of a '''[[योजन|Yojana]],''' in the Pañcāviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], where half a [[योजन|Yojana]] is termed '''[[गव्यूति|Gavyūti]]''' and a quarter '''[[क्रोश|Krośa]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1226/> <br>

त्रैवणि
<u>'''Traivaṇi'''</u> is mentioned as a pupil of '''Aupacandhani''' or '''[[औपजन्धनि|Aupajandhani]]''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1227/> In the Mādhyaṃdina recension<ref name=fx2_ve1_1227/> his name occurs twice in the second [[वंश|Vaṃśa]], in both cases as a pupil of [[औपजन्धनि|Aupajandhani]].<br>

त्रै-वृष्ण
<u>'''Trai-vṛṣṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of Trivṛṣan,’ is the patronymic of '''Trayaruṇa''' in the Rigveda (v. 27, 1).<br>

त्र्य्-अरुण त्रै-वृष्ण त्रसदस्यु
<u>'''Try-aruṇa [[त्रै-वृष्ण|Trai-vṛṣṇa]] Trasadasyu'''</u> is the name of a prince whose generosity to a singer is celebrated in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1229/> In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1229/> he appears as '''Tryaruṇa [[त्रैधात्व|Traidhātva]] [[ऐक्ष्वाक|Aikṣvāka]],''' and is the hero of the following story. He was out in his chariot with his [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], or domestic priest, '''[[वृश जान|Vṛśa Jāna]],''' and by excessive speed in driving killed a Brahmin boy. This sin was atoned for by the Purohita's using his Vārśa Sāman (chant). The [[शाट्यायन|Śāṭyāyana]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], cited by Sāyaṇa,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1229/> elaborates the tale. As Vṛśa had held the reins, king and priest accused each other of the murder. The Ikṣvākus being consulted threw the responsibility for the crime on Vṛśa, who thereupon revived the boy by the Vārśa Sāman. In consequence of this unfairness of theirs--being Kṣatriyas they were partial to a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]--Agni's glow ceased to burn in their houses. In response to their appeal to restore it, Vṛśa came to them, saw the Piśācī (demoness), who, in the form of Trasadasyu's wife, had stolen the glow, and succeeded in restoring it to Agni. This version with some variations occurs also in the Bṛhaddevatā,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1229/> which connects the story with a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1229/> Sieg's attempt<ref name=fx6_ve1_1229/> to show that the hymn really refers to this tale is not at all successful.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1229/> <br><br>It is clear that [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] must here mean ‘descendant of [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]],’ and not King [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] himself. The difference of the patronymics, [[त्रैवृष्ण|Traivṛṣṇa]] and [[त्रैधात्व|Traidhātva]], by which he is referred to can best be explained by assuming that there were two kings, Trivṛṣan and Tridhātu (or possibly Tridhanvan), from whom Tryaruṇa was descended.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1229/> The connexion with the Ikṣvākus is important (see '''[[इक्ष्वाकु|Ikṣvāku]]''').<br>

त्र्य्-अवि
<u>'''Try-avi'''</u> designates a calf eighteen months old<ref name=fx1_ve1_1230/> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1230/> and later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1230/><br>

त्र्य्-आशिर्
<u>'''Try-āśir,'''</u> ‘with three admixtures,’ is an epithet of Soma in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1231/> According to Sāyaṇa this means mixed with curds ('''[[दधि|Dadhi]]'''), meal ('''[[सक्तु|Saktu]]'''), and milk ('''[[पयस्|Payas]]'''). More accurately it would seem<ref name=fx2_ve1_1231/> to denote the milk (''[[गवाशिर्|gavāśir]]''), the barley (''[[यवाशिर्|yavāśir]]''), and the curds (''[[दध्य्आशिर्|dadhyāśir]]''), which were used to mix with the Soma.<br>

त्वच्
<u>'''Tvac,'''</u> ‘skin,’ ‘hide,’ (''a'') denotes specially in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1232/> the hide used in the process of extracting the '''Soma''' juice from the plant. The Soma was pounded with stones (''adri'') upon the skin laid on the pressing boards (''adhiṣavaṇe phalake''),<ref name=fx2_ve1_1232/> which, however, are not mentioned in the Rigveda. Or if a pestle and mortar were used, the skin was still placed underneath them to catch the drops of juice, not above, as Pischel<ref name=fx3_ve1_1232/> thought. <br><br>(''b'') Tvac also denotes the rind of the Soma plant that remains after the juice has been extracted.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1232/><br><br>(''c'') Metaphorically the term ''kṛṣṇā tvac,'' ‘the black skins,’ is applied to the aboriginal enemies of the invading Āryans.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1232/><br>

त्वष्टृ
<u>'''Tvaṣṭṛ'''</u> is employed once in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1233/> to denote a ‘carpenter,’ with a deliberate play on the name of the god [[त्वष्टृ|Tvaṣṭṛ]]. He is there mentioned as using an axe (''[[स्वधिति|svadhiti]]'') to fashion (from wood) ‘a well-made form’ (''rūpaṃ sukṛtam''). See '''[[तष्टृ|Taṣṭṛ]].'''<br>

त्वाष्ट्र
<u>'''Tvāṣṭra,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[त्वष्टृ|Tvaṣṭṛ]],’ is the patronymic, in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1234/> of the mythical teacher '''Ābhūti.'''<br>

त्सरु
<u>'''Tsaru,'''</u>--(''a'') This word seems to denote some sort of crawling animal in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1235/><br><br>(''b'') In the later literature the word means a ‘handle,’ as of a beaker ('''[[चमस|Camasa]]''').<ref name=fx1b_ve1_1235/> In this sense also it seems to occur in the description of the plough ('''[[लाङ्गल|Lāṅgala]]''') in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1235/> and the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1235/> <br>

त्सारिन्
<u>'''Tsārin'''</u> denotes, in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1236/> a ‘hunter’ engaged in the chase of the ''takva'' (an unknown beast), according to Ludwig and Max Müller.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1236/> But this explanation is quite conjectural.<br>

दंश
<u>'''Daṃśa'''</u> (lit., ‘biter’), ‘gad-fly,’ is mentioned in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 9, 3; 10, 2).<br>

दंष्ट्र
<u>'''Daṃṣṭra,'''</u> denoting a prominent tooth, ‘tusk,’ or ‘fang’ of an animal, occurs often from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1238/><br>

दक्ष कात्यायनि आत्रेय
<u>'''Dakṣa [[कात्यायनि|Kātyāyani]] Ātreya'''</u> (‘descendant of Atri’) is mentioned in the Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 41, 1; iv. 17, 1) as a pupil of '''[[शङ्ख बाभ्रव्य|Śaṅkha Bābhravya]].'''<br>

दक्ष जयन्त लौहित्य
<u>'''Dakṣa [[जयन्त|Jayanta]] Lauhitya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1) as a pupil of '''[[कृष्णरात लौहित्य|Kṛṣṇarāta Lauhitya]].'''<br>

दक्ष पार्वति
<u>'''Dakṣa Pārvati'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[पर्वत|Parvata]]'''’) is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1241/> as having performed a certain rite which his descendants, the Dākṣāyaṇas, still maintained, thus enjoying royal dignity down to the time of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] itself. He appears in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1241/> also.<br>

दक्षिणतस्-कपर्द
<u>'''Dakṣiṇatas-kaparda'''</u> is an epithet of the '''Vasiṣṭhas''' in the Rigveda (vii. 33, 1) referring to their mode of ‘wearing the hair in a braid on the right side.’ See '''[[कपर्द|Kaparda]].''' <br>

दक्षिणा
<u>'''Dakṣiṇā'''</u> appears repeatedly in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1243/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1243/> as the designation of the gift presented to priests at the sacrifice, apparently because a cow--a prolific (''[[दक्षिणा|dakṣiṇā]]'') one--was the usual ‘fee’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1243/> on such an occasion.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1243/> The later [[दान|Dāna]]-stutis, or ‘Praises of Gifts,’ in the Rigveda immensely exaggerate these donations, and the exaggeration grows in the Brāhmaṇas. It is important to notice that these enumerations of gifts in the main include nothing but articles of personal property, such as kine, horses, buffaloes, or camels (''uṣṭra''), ornaments, and so forth, but not land.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1243/> Reference is, however, made in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_1243/> to land as a [[दक्षिणा|Dakṣiṇā]], but with disapproval, probably because the land came to be regarded as inalienable without the consent of the clansmen.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1243/><br>

दक्षिणा-पथ
<u>'''Dakṣiṇā-patha'''</u> (lit., ‘the road to the south’), ‘the south country,’ is found, probably as a designation of the Deccan, as early as the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1244/> coupled with  Surāṣṭra. A similar expression is ''[[दक्षिणा|dakṣiṇā]] padā,'' ‘with southward foot,’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1244/> referring to the place where the exile (''[[परा-वृज्|parā-vṛj]]'') goes on being expelled. This no doubt simply means ‘the south’ beyond the limits of the recognized Āryan world, which even as late as the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1244/> appears as bounded by the Vindhyas on the south.<br>

दक्षिणा-प्रष्टि
<u>'''Dakṣiṇā-praṣṭi'''</u> denotes ‘the side horse on the right.’ It appears from two passages of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1245/> that there were at times four horses yoked to the chariot, the right and the left yoke horse (''[[दक्षिणा-युग्य|dakṣiṇā-yugya]], savyā-yugya'') in the middle, flanked by one on each side, the two latter of course not being fastened to the yoke at all, but presumably by traces alongside of the yoke horses. See '''[[रथ|Ratha]].'''<br>

दक्षिणायन
<u>'''Dakṣiṇāyana.'''</u> See '''[[सूर्य|Sūrya]].'''<br>

दक्षिणा-युग्य
<u>'''Dakṣiṇā-yugya,'''</u> ‘the yoke horse on the right,’ is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 1, 4, 6; 4, 3, 8; ix. 4, 2, 11). See '''[[रथ|Ratha]].'''<br>

दण्ड
<u>'''Daṇḍa,'''</u> ‘staff.’ (''a'') This word is often mentioned in the ordinary sense; for example, when used for driving cattle<ref name=fx1_ve1_1248/> (''go-ajanāsaḥ''), or as a weapon.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1248/> A staff was given to a man on consecration for driving away demons, according to the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1248/> The staff also played a part in the initiation (''upanayana'') of a youth on attaining manhood.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1248/> In a modified sense the word is used to denote the handle of a ladle or similar implement.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1248/> <br><br>(''b'') The ‘staff’ as the symbol of temporal power, implying punishment, is applied by the king (''rāja-preṣito daṇḍaḥ'').<ref name=fx1b_ve1_1248/> The king, in modern phraseology, was the source of criminal law; and he clearly retained this branch of law in his own hands even in later times.<ref name=fx2b_ve1_1248/> The punishment of the non-guilty (''a-daṇḍya'') is given as one of the characteristics of the nonBrahminical '''Vrātyas''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3b_ve1_1248/> See also '''[[धर्म|Dharma]].'''<br>

दण्ड औपर
<u>'''Daṇḍa Aupara'''</u> (‘descendant of Upara’) is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vi. 2, 9, 4) and the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iii. 8, 7) as having performed a certain rite.<br>

दण्डन
<u>'''Daṇḍana'''</u> occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1250/> among other names of ‘reed’ or ‘cane.’<br>

दत्त तापस
<u>'''Datta Tāpasa'''</u> was [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest at the snake festival described in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1251/><br>

दधि
<u>'''Dadhi,'''</u> ‘sour milk,’ is repeatedly mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1252/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1252/> The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1252/> mentions in order '''Ghrta''' (‘clarified butter’), [[दधि|Dadhi]], '''[[मस्तु|Mastu]],''' which Eggeling<ref name=fx4_ve1_1252/> renders ‘whey,’ and '''[[आमिक्षा|Āmikṣā]],''' ‘curds.’ [[दधि|Dadhi]] often has the meaning of ‘curds’ also. It was used for mixing with '''Soma.'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1252/><br>

दध्यञ्च् आथर्वण
<u>'''Dadhyañc Ātharvaṇa'''</u> is a purely mythical sage. In the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1253/> he is clearly a divinity of some kind, but in the later  Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve1_1253/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx3_ve1_1253/> he is metamorphosed into a teacher. In the Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmana<ref name=fx4_ve1_1253/> he is by oversight called an [[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]].<br>

दध्य्-आशिर्
<u>'''Dadhy-āśir.'''</u> See '''[[दधि|Dadhi]]''' and '''Soma.'''<br>

दन्त्
<u>'''Dant, Danta,'''</u> ‘tooth,’ is frequently mentioned from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1255/> Cleansing (''dhāv'') the teeth was an ordinary act, especially in preparation for a sacrifice, and accompanied bathing, shaving of the hair and beard (''[[केश|keśa]]-[[श्मश्रु|śmaśru]]''), and the cutting of the nails.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1255/> A hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1255/> celebrates the appearance of the first two teeth of a child, though its exact interpretation is doubtful.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1255/> In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1255/> there is a reference to a child's first teeth falling out. The word seems in the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_1255/> once to denote an elephant's tusk. Whether dentistry was practised is doubtful. The occurrence in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx7_ve1_1255/> of '''[[हिरण्य-दन्त्|Hiraṇya-dant]],''' ‘gold-toothed,’ as the name of a man, is perhaps significant, especially as it is certain that the stopping of teeth with gold was known at Rome as early as the legislation of the Twelve Tables.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1255/><br>

दभीति
<u>'''Dabhīti'''</u> appears several times in the Rigveda as a hero or sage. Indra overcomes on his behalf '''[[चुमुरि|Cumuri]]''' and '''[[धुनि|Dhuni]];'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1256/>  he pressed Soma for Indra,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1256/> who rewarded him.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1256/> For him 30,000 '''Dāsas''' were sent to sleep,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1256/> and for him the '''Dasyus''' were bound without cords.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1256/> [[दभीति|Dabhīti]] also appears, with '''[[तुर्वीति|Turvīti]],''' as a protégé of the Aśvins.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1256/> There seems no reason to deny that he was a real person.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1256/><br>

दम
<u>'''Dama,'''</u> ‘house,’ is a word that occurs several times in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1257/> It denotes, according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1257/> the place in which a man wields uncontrolled power (from the root ''dam,'' ‘control’).<br>

दम्-पति
<u>'''Dam-pati'''</u> denotes ‘the master of the house’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1258/> in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1258/> but is more often used in the dual to designate ‘the master and the mistress,’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1258/> an expression that may legitimately be deemed to show the high status of women at the time of the Rigveda. See '''[[स्त्री|Strī]].'''<br>

दर्भ
<u>'''Darbha'''</u> is the name of a grass in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1259/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1259/> In the Atharvaveda it is used for the calming of anger (''manyuśamana''),<ref name=fx3_ve1_1259/> and as an amulet for protection against the scattering of one's hair or the striking of one's breast.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1259/> It is also said to be ‘rich in roots’ (''bhūri-[[मूल|mūla]]''),<ref name=fx5_ve1_1259/> to possess a thousand leaves (''sahasra-[[पर्ण|parṇa]]'') and a hundred stalks (''śata-kāṇḍa'').<ref name=fx6_ve1_1259/> <br>

दर्वि
<u>'''Darvi,'''</u> or '''Darvī,''' properly denotes a ‘ladle,’ in which sense it is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1260/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1260/> But the word also means a serpent's ‘hood’ in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1260/> though Zimmer regards it as the name of a serpent.<br><br>^4 ''Altindisches Leben,'' 95, where he takes '''[[करिक्रत|Karikrata]]''' also as the name of a snake.<br>

दर्विदा
<u>'''Darvidā,'''</u> the ‘woodpecker,’ is mentioned as a victim at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1261/> ''Cf.'' '''[[दार्व्आघात|Dārvāghāta]].'''<br>

दर्श
<u>'''Darśa'''</u> (‘appearance’) denotes the new moon day,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1262/> usually in opposition to the day of full moon (''[[पूर्ण-मास|pūrṇa-māsa]]'').<ref name=fx2_ve1_1262/> Most frequently the word occurs in the compound<ref name=fx3_ve1_1262/> ''[[दर्श|darśa]]-pūrṇamāsau,'' ‘new and full moon,’ the days of special ritual importance.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1262/> The order of the first two words here is worthy of note, for it distinctly suggests, though it does not conclusively prove, that the month was reckoned from new moon to new moon, not from full moon to full moon. See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

दश-ग्व
<u>'''Daśa-gva'''</u> appears in one hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1263/> as the name of a person who was assisted by Indra. The other references in that work,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1263/> however, clearly show the mythical character of the Daśagvas, and of any individual among them. <br>

दशतयी
<u>'''Daśatayī'''</u> in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1264/> frequently denotes the text of the Rigveda as divided into ten Maṇḍalas.<br>

दश-द्यु
<u>'''Daśa-dyu'''</u> appears twice in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1265/> as the name of a hero, but nothing can be made out regarding him or his relation to '''[[वेतसु|Vetasu]],''' who is mentioned in one passage along with him.<br>

दशन्
<u>'''Daśan,'''</u> ‘ten,’ forms the basis of the numerical system of the Vedic Indians, as it does of the Āryan people generally. But it is characteristic of India<ref name=fx1_ve1_1266/> that there should be found at a very early period long series of names for very high numerals, whereas the Āryan knowledge did not go beyond 1,000. In the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1266/> the list is 1; 10; 100; 1,000; 10,000 (''ayuta''); 100,000 (''niyuta''); 1,000,000 (''prayuta''); 10,000,000 (''[[अर्बुद|arbuda]]''); 100,000,000 (''nyarbuda''); 1,000,000,000 (''[[सम्उद्र|samudra]]''); 10,000,000,000 (''madhya''); 100,000,000,000 (''anta''); 1,000,000,000,000 (''parārdha''). In the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_1266/> the list is the same, but ''niyuta'' and ''prayuta'' exchange places, and after ''nyarbuda'' a new figure (''badva'') intervenes, thus increasing ''[[सम्उद्र|samudra]]'' to 10,000,000,000, and so on. The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā has in two places<ref name=fx4_ve1_1266/> exactly the same list as the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā. The Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx5_ve1_1266/> has the list ''ayuta, prayuta,'' then ''ayuta'' again, ''[[अर्बुद|arbuda]], nyarbuda, [[सम्उद्र|samudra]], madhya, anta, parārdha.'' The [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_1266/> has the Vājasaneyi list up to ''nyarbuda'' inclusive, then follow ''nikharvaka, badva, akṣita,'' and apparently ''go'' = 1,000,000,000,000. The Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve1_1266/> list  replaces ''nikharvaka'' by ''nikharva, badva'' by ''padma,'' and ends with ''akṣitir vyomāntaḥ.'' The [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_1266/> continues the series after ''nyarbuda'' with ''nikharvāda, [[सम्उद्र|samudra]], salila, antya, ananta'' (= 10 billions).<br><br>But beyond ''ayuta''<ref name=fx9_ve1_1266/> none of these numbers has any vitality. ''Badva,'' indeed, occurs in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx10_ve1_1266/> but it cannot there have any precise numerical sense;<ref name=fx11_ve1_1266/> and later on the names of these high numerals are very much confused.<br><br>An arithmetical progression of some interest is found in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx12_ve1_1266/> where occurs a list of sacrificial gifts in which each successive figure doubles the amount of the preceding one. It begins with ''[[द्वादश|dvādaśa]]-mānaṃ hiraṇyam,'' ‘gold to the value of 12’ (the unit being uncertain, but probably the '''[[कृष्णल|Kṛṣṇala]]'''),<ref name=fx13_ve1_1266/> followed by ‘to the value of 24, 48, 96, 192, 384, 768, 1,536, 3072,’ then ''dve aṣṭāviṃśati-śata-māne,'' which must mean 2×128×24 (the last unit being not a single ''[[मान|māna]],'' but a number of 24 ''mānas'') = 6,144, then 12,288, 24,576, 49,152, 98,304, 196,608, 393, 216. With these large numbers may be compared the minute theoretical subdivision of time found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx14_ve1_1266/> where a day is divided into 15 ''muhūrtas''--1 ''[[मुहूर्त|muhūrta]]'' = 15 ''kṣipras,'' 1 ''kṣipra'' = 15 ''etarhis,'' 1 ''etarhi'' = 15 ''idānis,'' 1 ''idāni'' = 15 ''prāṇas.'' The [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx15_ve1_1266/> has a decimal division of the day into 15 ''muhūrtas''-1 ''[[मुहूर्त|muhūrta]]'' = 10 ''nimeṣas,'' 1 ''nimeṣa'' = 10 ''dhvaṃsis.''<br><br>Few fractions are mentioned in Vedic literature. ''Ardha, [[पाद|pāda]], [[शफ|śapha]],'' and ''[[कला|kalā]]'' denote (1/2), (1/4), (1/8), (1/16) respectively, but only  the first two are common. ''Tṛtīya'' denotes the third part.<ref name=fx16_ve1_1266/> In the Rigveda<ref name=fx17_ve1_1266/> Indra and Viṣṇu are said to have divided 1,000 by 3, though how they did so is uncertain. ''Tri-pād'' denotes ‘three-fourths.’<ref name=fx18_ve1_1266/><br><br>There is no clear evidence that the Indians of the Vedic period had any knowledge of numerical figures, though it is perfectly possible.<ref name=fx19_ve1_1266/><br>

दश-पुरुषं-राज्य
<u>'''Daśa-puruṣaṃ-rājya,'''</u> occurring in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1267/> doubtless<ref name=fx2_ve1_1267/> means ‘sovereignty inherited through ten ancestors,’ a striking case of hereditary rule. Weber<ref name=fx3_ve1_1267/> once rendered the word as the ‘kingdom<ref name=fx4_ve1_1267/> of Daśapuru,’ comparing the Daśapura of Kālidāsa's Meghadūta<ref name=fx5_ve1_1267/> and the Daśārṇa of the ‘middle country.’<br>

दश-मास्य
<u>'''Daśa-māsya,'''</u> ‘ten months old,’ describes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1268/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1268/> the embryo immediately before birth. See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

दशमी
<u>'''Daśamī'''</u> denotes in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1269/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1269/> the period of life between 90 and 100 years  which the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1269/> calls the ''daśama yuga,'' ‘the tenth stage of life.’ Longevity seems not to have been rare among the Vedic Indians, for the desire to live a ‘hundred autumns’ (''śaradaḥ śatam'') is constantly expressed.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1269/> '''[[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]]''' is said to have lived 100 years,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1269/> and '''[[महिदास ऐतरेय|Mahidāsa Aitareya]]''' is credited with 116.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1269/> Onesikritos<ref name=fx7_ve1_1269/> reported that they sometimes lived 130 years, a statement with which corresponds the wish expressed in the Jātaka<ref name=fx8_ve1_1269/> for a life of 120 years. Probably the number was always rather imaginary than real, but the comparative brevity of modern life in India<ref name=fx9_ve1_1269/> may be accounted for by the cumulative effect of fever, which is hardly known to the Rigveda. See '''[[तक्मन्|Takman]].'''<br>

दश-वृक्ष
<u>'''Daśa-vṛkṣa'''</u> is the name of a tree, according to Roth,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1270/> in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1270/> But Whitney<ref name=fx3_ve1_1270/> treats the word as a mere adjective meaning ‘of ten trees.’<br>

दश-व्रज
<u>'''Daśa-vraja'''</u> is the name of a protégé of the Aśvins in the Rigveda (viii. 8, 20; 49, 1; 50, 9).<br>

दश-शिप्र
<u>'''Daśa-śipra'''</u> is the name of a sacrificer mentioned in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1272/><br>

दशा
<u>'''Daśā'''</u> denotes the ‘fringe’ or ‘border’ of a garment (''vāsaḥ'') in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1273/> The word also occurs in the compound ''[[दशा|daśā]]-[[पवित्र|pavitra]],''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1273/> which means ‘a filtering cloth with a fringe.’ <br>

दशोणि
<u>'''Daśoṇi'''</u> appears in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1274/> apparently as a favourite of Indra and as opposed to the '''Paṇis,''' who fell in hundreds for his benefit. The view of Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_1274/> that he is here the priest of the Paṇis is very improbable. Elsewhere his name is simply mentioned.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1274/> See also '''[[दशोण्य|Daśoṇya]].'''<br>

दशोण्य
<u>'''Daśoṇya'''</u> is the name of a sacrificer mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1275/> along with '''[[दशशिप्र|Daśaśipra]]''' and others. Whether he is identical with '''[[दशोणि|Daśoṇi]]''' cannot be decided.<br>

दशोनसि
<u>'''Daśonasi'''</u> is the name of a kind of snake in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1276/> The reading of the Paippalāda recension is Naśonaśī.<br>

दस्यवे वृक
<u>'''Dasyave vṛka,'''</u> ‘wolf to the '''[[दस्यु|Dasyu]],'''’ is the name of a man mentioned four times in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1277/> In one hymn<ref name=fx2_ve1_1277/> he is called a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], but in two others<ref name=fx3_ve1_1277/> he is clearly a prince victorious over the Dasyus, and a generous patron of the singer. It is hardly necessary to assume different persons,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1277/> for the term [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] is not altogether inconsistent with royalty. He was son of '''[[पूतक्रतु|Pūtakratu]]'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1277/> and '''[[पूतक्रता|Pūtakratā]],'''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1277/> his wife.<br>

दस्यवे सह
<u>'''Dasyave saha'''</u> is, according to Roth,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1278/> the name of a man or a clan in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1278/> But he admits that the words may  be an epithet of Agni. This is the interpretation given to them by Oldenberg.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1278/><br>

दस्यु
<u>'''Dasyu,'''</u> a word of somewhat doubtful origin, is in many passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1279/> clearly applied to superhuman enemies. On the other hand, there are several passages in which human foes, probably the aborigines, are thus designated. This may be regarded as certain in those passages where the [[दस्यु|Dasyu]] is opposed to the Āryan, who defeats him with the aid of the gods.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1279/> The great difference between the Dasyus and the Āryans was their religion: the former are styled ‘not sacrificing,’ ‘devoid of rites,’ ‘addicted to strange vows,’ ‘godhating,’ and so forth.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1279/> As compared with the '''[[दास|Dāsa]],''' they are less distinctively a people: no clans (''viśaḥ'') of the Dasyus are mentioned, and while Indra's ''[[दस्यु|dasyu]]-hatya,'' ‘slaughter of the Dasyus,’ is often spoken of, there is no corresponding use of ''[[दास|dāsa]]-hatya.'' That the Dasyus were real people is, however, shown by the epithet ''[[अनास्|anās]]'' applied to them in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1279/> The sense of this word is not absolutely certain: the Pada text and Sāyaṇa both take it to mean ‘without face’ (''an-ās''),<ref name=fx6_ve1_1279/> but the other rendering, ‘noseles’ (''a-nās''), is quite possible,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1279/>(**  4 Rv. i. 51, 5, 6; 103, 4; x. 95, 7; 99, 7; 105, 11. ''Cf. [[दस्यु|dasyu]]-han.'' ‘Dasyuslaying,’ i. 100, 12; vi. 45, 24; viii. 76, 11; 77, 3; x. 47, 4 (all of Indra); vi. 16, 15; viii. 39, 8 (of Agni), etc.  and would accord well with the flat-nosed aborigines of the Dravidian<ref name=fx8_ve1_1279/> type, whose language still persists among the Brahuis, who are found in the north-west. This interpretation would receive some support from Vṛtra's being called ‘broken-nosed’ if this were a correct explanation of the obscure word ''rujānās.''<ref name=fx9_ve1_1279/><br><br>The other epithet of the Dasyus is ''[[मृध्र-वाच्|mṛdhra-vāc]],'' which occurs with ''[[अनास्|anās]],''<ref name=fx10_ve1_1279/> and which has been rendered<ref name=fx11_ve1_1279/> ‘of stammering, or unintelligible speech.’ This version is by no means certain, and since the epithet is elsewhere<ref name=fx12_ve1_1279/> applied to Āryans, its correct meaning is more probably ‘of hostile speech.’<br><br>[[दस्यु|Dasyu]] corresponds with the Iranian ''daṅhu, daqyu,'' which denotes a ‘province.’ Zimmer<ref name=fx13_ve1_1279/> thinks that the original meaning was ‘enemy,’ whence the Iranians developed the sense of ‘hostile country,’ ‘conquered country,’ ‘province,’ while the Indians, retaining the signification of ‘enemy,’ extended it to include demon foes. Roth<ref name=fx14_ve1_1279/> considers that the meaning of human enemy is a transfer from the strife of gods  and demons. Lassen<ref name=fx15_ve1_1279/> attempted to onnect the contrast ''daqyu: [[दस्यु|dasyu]]'' with that of ''daeva: deva,'' and to see in it a result of the religious differences which, according to Haug's theory, had separated the Iranians and the Indians. The word may have originally meant ‘ravaged land’<ref name=fx16_ve1_1279/> as a result of invasion; hence ‘enemies’ country,' then ‘hostile people,’ who as human foes were more usually called by the cognate name of '''[[दास|Dāsa]].'''<br><br>Individual Dasyus are '''[[चुमुरि|Cumuri]], [[शम्बर|Śambara]], Śuṣṇa,''' etc.<br><br>In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx17_ve1_1279/> the word has, as later,<ref name=fx18_ve1_1279/> the sense of uncivilized peoples generally.<br>

दाक्षायण
<u>'''Dākṣāyaṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of Dakṣa.’ The Dākṣāyaṇas are mentioned in the Atharvaveda and the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1280/> as having given gold to '''Śatānīka.''' In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1280/> the word is actually used to denote ‘gold.’ The Dākṣāyaṇas appear there<ref name=fx3_ve1_1280/> as a race of princes who, because of performing a certain rite, prospered down to the time of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] itself.<br>

दात्यौह
<u>'''Dātyauha,'''</u> a ‘gallinule,’ is mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or horse sacrifice, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1281/> The  word is clearly a variant of ''dātyūha,'' which occurs in the epics and law books.<br>

दात्र
<u>'''Dātra'''</u> (‘cutter’), denoting a ‘sickle,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1282/> Cows ‘with sickle-shaped marks on their ears’ (''[[दात्र|dātra]]-karṇyaḥ'') are referred to in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1282/> Otherwise the expression is only found later, occurring in the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] and epic literature.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1282/> See also '''Sṛṇi.'''<br>

दात्रेय
<u>'''Dātreya'''</u> is the patronymic of '''Arāḍa [[शौनक|Śaunaka]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1283/> Possibly [[दार्तेय|Dārteya]], ‘descendant of [[दृति|Dṛti]],’ should be read,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1283/> but the word may have the same derivation as the latter form with metathesis.<br>

दाधीच
<u>'''Dādhīca,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Dadhyanc,'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[च्यवन|Cyavana]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 6).<br>

दान
<u>'''1. Dāna,'''</u> ‘giving,’ ‘gift,’ is a word of frequent occurrence in the Rigveda, especially in the [[दान|Dāna]]-stutis<ref name=fx1_ve1_1285/> (‘Praises of Gifts’) of generous patrons (see '''[[दक्षिणा|Dakṣiṇā]]'''). One of the characteristics of the '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]''' is his right to receive gifts, which it is obligatory on the other castes to present.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1285/> The gift of a daughter (''kanyāyā dānam'') was a form of marriage<ref name=fx3_ve1_1285/> (see '''[[विवाह|Vivāha]]'''), because in it the girl was ‘given’ away by her father or brother.<br>

दान
<u>'''2. Dāna'''</u> (‘distribution’)<ref name=fx1_ve1_1286/> seems in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1286/> to be a designation of the sacrificial feast to which  the god is invited (''cf.'' ). In one passage<ref name=fx3_ve1_1286/> Sāyaṇa thinks that it denotes the ''mada-jalāni,'' ‘drops of water falling from the temples of a rutting elephant,’<ref name=fx4_ve1_1286/> but this is doubtful. In another passage<ref name=fx5_ve1_1286/> Roth thinks that ‘pasture land’ is meant.<br>

दान
<u>'''3. Dāna'''</u> is in three passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1287/> held by Roth to designate a chariot horse.<br>

दामन्
<u>'''Dāman,'''</u> a ‘rope’ or ‘girdle,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1288/> is often mentioned in the Rigveda and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1288/> Reference is made to the rope of the sacrificial horse,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1288/> as well as to the practice of tying calves with ropes.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1288/> The word occurs in the sense of a ‘band’ of horse hair in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_1288/><br>

दाय
<u>'''Dāya'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1289/> only in the sense of ‘reward’ of exertion (''śrama''), but later it means ‘inheritance’--that is, a father's property which is to be divided among his sons either during his lifetime or after his death. The passages all negative the idea that the property of the family was legally family property: it is clear that it was the property of the head of the house, usually the father, and that the other members of the family only had moral claims upon it which the father could ignore, though he might be coerced by his sons if they were physically stronger.<br><br>Thus '''Manu''' is said in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1289/> to have divided his property among his sons. He omitted '''[[नाभानेदिष्ठ|Nābhānediṣṭha]],'''  whom he afterwards taught how to appease the Aṅgirases, and to procure cows. This is a significant indication that the property he divided was movable property, rather than land ('''[[उर्वरा|Urvarā]]'''). In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1289/> the division is said to have been made during Manu's lifetime by his sons, who left only their aged father to [[नाभानेदिष्ठ|Nābhānediṣṭha]]. According to the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_1289/> again, four sons divided the inheritance while their old father, Abhipratārin, was still alive. It is, of course, possible to regard [[दाय|Dāya]] as denoting the heritable property of the family, but the developed ''patria potestas'' of the father, which was early very marked, as shown by the legend of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]],''' is inconsistent with the view that the sons were legally owners with their father, unless and until. they actually insisted on a division of the property.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1289/> Probably-there is no evidence of any decisive character--land was not divided at first, but no doubt its disposal began to follow the analogy of cattle and other movable property as soon as the available supply of arable land became limited.<br><br>As for the method of division, it is clear from the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx6_ve1_1289/> that the elder son was usually preferred; perhaps  this was always the case after death. During the father's lifetime another might be preferred, as appears from a passage of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx7_ve1_1289/> Women were excluded from partition or inheritance, according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_1289/> and the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx9_ve1_1289/> They were, no doubt, supported by their brothers; but if they had none they might be reduced to prostitution.<ref name=fx10_ve1_1289/> Detailed rules of inheritance appear in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx11_ve1_1289/><br><br>The heir is called Dayada,<ref name=fx12_ve1_1289/> ‘receiver (''ā-da'') of inheritance.’<br>

दार
<u>'''Dāra,'''</u> ‘wife,’ is found in the Sūtras (usually as a plural masculine), and once (as a singular) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1290/><br>

दारु
<u>'''Dāru,'''</u> ‘wood,’ is frequently mentioned in the Rigveda and later,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1291/> denoting amongst other things the pole of a chariot,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1291/> logs as fuel,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1291/> the wooden parts of a car,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1291/> possibly wooden stocks,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1291/> and so forth.<br>

दार्ढ-जयन्ति
<u>'''Dārḍha-jayanti,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[दृढजयन्त|Dṛḍhajayanta]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[वैपश्चित|Vaipaścita]] [[गुप्त|Gupta]] [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]]''' and of '''[[वैपश्चित|Vaipaścita]] [[दृढजयन्त|Dṛḍhajayanta]] [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]]''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1).<br>

दार्तेय
<u>'''Dārteya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[दृति|Dṛti]].'''’ The Dārteyas are mentioned as authorities on sacrificial matters in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1293/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1293/> <br>

दार्भ्य
<u>'''Dārbhya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[दर्भ|Darbha]],’ is mentioned in a verse of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1294/> Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_1294/> identifies him with '''[[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]],''' but the Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx3_ve1_1294/> with '''Rathavīti.''' The same patronymic is frequently<ref name=fx4_ve1_1294/> connected with '''[[केशिन्|Keśin]],''' and is also applied to '''Rathaprota.'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1294/> See also '''[[दाल्भ्य|Dālbhya]].'''<br>

दार्व्-आघात
<u>'''Dārv-āghāta,'''</u> the ‘woodpecker,’ is included in the list of sacrificial victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or ‘horse sacrifice,’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1295/><br>

दार्व्-आहार
<u>'''Dārv-āhāra,'''</u> a ‘gatherer of wood,’ is included in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha, or ‘human sacrifice,’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1296/><br>

दाल्भि
<u>'''Dālbhi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Dalbha,’ is the patronymic of '''Vaka''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (x. 6).<br>

दाल्भ्य
<u>'''Dālbhya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Dalbha,’ is a variant of '''[[दार्भ्य|Dārbhya]].''' It is the patronymic of (''a'') '''[[केशिन्|Keśin]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]];<ref name=fx1_ve1_1298/> (''b'') '''[[चैकितायन|Caikitāyana]]''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1298/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]];<ref name=fx3_ve1_1298/> (''c'') '''Vaka''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1298/> and the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1298/> <br>

दाव
<u>'''Dāva,'''</u> ‘forest fire,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1299/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1299/> In the latter work such fires are referred to as occurring in spring. According to Sieg,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1299/> a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1299/> describes a forest fire. Watchers were employed to guard against surprise from such conflagrations (''[[दाव|dāva]]-pa'').<ref name=fx5_ve1_1299/><br>

दाव-सु आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Dāva-su Āṅgirasa,'''</u> a seer of Sāmans, or chants, is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1300/><br>

दाश
<u>'''Dāśa,'''</u> ‘fisherman,’ is mentioned in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha, or ‘human sacrifice,’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1301/> ''Cf.'' '''[[धैवर|Dhaivara]].'''<br>

दाशतय
<u>'''Dāśataya,'''</u> ‘belonging to the (Rigveda text) divided into ten (books),’ is an epithet of Adhyāya, ‘section,’ in the [[निदान|Nidāna]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1302/> The feminine form of the word is also found in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1302/> and later<ref name=fx3_ve1_1302/><br>

दाश-राज्ञ
<u>'''Dāśa-rājña'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1303/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1303/> of '''Sudās'''' famous ‘battle with the ten kings.’ It is somewhat difficult to make out exactly who the kings were (see '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]]'''), but the number is probably a round one, and cannot be pressed. The actual battle hymn<ref name=fx3_ve1_1303/> does not contain  the word, and the passages in which it is found may reasonably be considered late.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1303/><br>

दाशर्म
<u>'''Dāśarma'''</u> appears in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1304/> as a teacher and a contemporary of '''[[आरुणि|Āruṇi]].'''<br>

दास
<u>'''Dāsa,'''</u> like '''[[दस्यु|Dasyu]],''' sometimes denotes enemies of a demoniac character in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1305/> but in many passages<ref name=fx2_ve1_1305/> the word refers to human foes of the Āryans. The Dāsas are described as having forts (''puraḥ''),<ref name=fx3_ve1_1305/> and their clans (''viśaḥ'') are mentioned.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1305/> It is possible that the forts, which are called ‘autumnal’ (''śaradīḥ''),<ref name=fx5_ve1_1305/> may be mythical, but it is not essential, for the epithet may allude to their being resorted to in the autumn season. The [[दास|Dāsa]] colour ('''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]]''')<ref name=fx6_ve1_1305/> is probably an allusion to the black skin of the aborigines, which is also directly mentioned.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1305/> The aborigines (as Dasyus) are called ''[[अनास्|anās]],'' ‘noseless’(?),<ref name=fx8_ve1_1305/> and ''[[मृध्र-वाच्|mṛdhra-vāc]],'' ‘of hostile speech,’<ref name=fx9_ve1_1305/> and are probably meant by the phallus-worshippers (''śiśna-devāḥ,'' ‘whose deity is a phallus’) of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx10_ve1_1305/> It is significant that constant  reference is made to the differences in religion between Ārva and [[दास|Dāsa]] or [[दस्यु|Dasyu]].<ref name=fx11_ve1_1305/><br><br>Since the Dāsas were in many cases reduced to slavery, the word [[दास|Dāsa]] has the sense of ‘slave’ in several passages of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx12_ve1_1305/> Dāsī, the feminine, always has this sense from the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx13_ve1_1305/> onwards. Aboriginal women were, no doubt, the usual slaves, for on their husbands being slain in battle they would naturally have been taken as servants. They would sometimes also become concubines; thus '''[[कवष|Kavaṣa]]''' was taunted with being the son of a female slave (''dāsyāḥ putraḥ'') in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx14_ve1_1305/><br><br>Ludwig<ref name=fx15_ve1_1305/> considers that in some passages<ref name=fx16_ve1_1305/> [[दास|Dāsa]] is applied, in the sense of ‘enemy,’ to Āryan foes, but this is uncertain. Zimmer<ref name=fx17_ve1_1305/> and Meyer<ref name=fx18_ve1_1305/> think that [[दास|Dāsa]]<ref name=fx19_ve1_1305/> originally meant ‘enemy’ in general, later developing in Iran into the name of the Dahae<ref name=fx20_ve1_1305/> of the Caspian steppes, and in India into a designation of the aborigines. On the other hand, Hillebrandt<ref name=fx21_ve1_1305/> argues that, as the Dāsas and the Paṇis are mentioned together,<ref name=fx22_ve1_1305/> they must be deemed to be closely related tribes, identifying  the Paṇis with the Parnians and the Dāsas of the Rigveda with the Dahae. This view, of course, necessitates a transfer of the scenes of the Rigveda, where Dāsas are prominent, and especially those in which Divodāsa--‘the heavenly Dāsa’--plays an important part,<ref name=fx23_ve1_1305/> to the far west. Hillebrandt justifies this by regarding the scene of the sixth book of the Rigveda as quite different from that of the seventh and third, in which [[सुदास्|Sudās]], the Bharatas, [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]], and [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] appear. The [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] of the sixth book he locates in Arachosia, that of the seventh in the ‘Middle Country.’ It is, however, extremely doubtful whether this theory can be upheld. That Divodāsa should have been a [[दास|Dāsa]], and yet have fought against other Dāsas, is not in itself likely, especially when his son [[सुदास्|Sudās]] appears as a protagonist of Āryan civilization. It also seems unreasonable to seek in Arachosia for the river '''Sarasvati,''' which it is natural to locate in the ‘Middle Country.’<br><br>The wealth of the Dāsas was no doubt considerable,<ref name=fx24_ve1_1305/> but in civilization there is no reason to suppose that they were ever equal to the invaders.<ref name=fx25_ve1_1305/> Leading Dāsas were '''Ilībiśa, [[चुमुरि|Cumuri]]''' and '''[[धुनि|Dhuni]], [[पिप्रु|Pipru]], [[वर्चिन्|Varcin]], [[शम्बर|Śambara]].''' For names of aboriginal tribes, see '''[[किरात|Kirāta]], [[कीकट|Kīkaṭa]], [[चण्डाल|Caṇḍāla]], [[पर्णक|Parṇaka]], Śiṃyu.'''<br>

दास-वेश
<u>'''Dāsa-veśa,'''</u> occurring only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1306/> probably designates a [[दास|Dāsa]] named '''[[वेश|Veśa]].''' Sāyaṇa's interpretation of the word as ‘destruction of foes’ can hardly be correct. <br>

दास्य
<u>'''Dāsya'''</u> occurs once in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 2. 30 Mādhyaṃdina = 23 [[काण्व|Kāṇva]]) in the sense of ‘slavery.’<br>

दित्य-वाह्
<u>'''Ditya-vāh,'''</u> m.; '''Dityauhī,''' f., ‘a two-year-old bull or cow.’ is mentioned in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmanas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1308/><br>

दिद्यु
<u>'''Didyu, Didyut,'''</u> both<ref name=fx1_ve1_1309/> denote in the Rigveda ‘missile,’ ‘arrow,’ whether divine or human.<br>

दिधिषु
<u>'''Didhiṣu'''</u> in the Rigveda denotes a ‘wooer.’ It is applied<ref name=fx1_ve1_1310/> to the relative, probably brother-in-law,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1310/> who takes the place of the husband at the funeral rite, and who, as in the Hebraic levirate, is to beget a child by the brother's wife if there is no son.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1310/> Hillebrandt<ref name=fx4_ve1_1310/> and Lanman<ref name=fx5_ve1_1310/> consider that the word originally meant only ‘wooer,’ and applied to the king who, after the chief queen had lain beside the dead victim in the Puruṣamedha or ‘human sacrifice,’ claimed her again; but this view is hardly plausible.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1310/> The term is also applied to the god Pūṣan<ref name=fx7_ve1_1310/> as the wooer of his mother, apparently Sūryā.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1310/><br>

दिधिषू-पति
<u>'''Didhiṣū-pati'''</u> occurs in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1311/> and Kapiṣṭhala Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1311/> as well as in the Āpastamba,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1311/> [[गौतम|Gautama]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_1311/> and [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]  [[धर्म|Dharma]] Sūtras,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1311/> in lists of people who have committed sin (''enas''). The traditional rendering<ref name=fx6_ve1_1311/> is ‘husband of a woman married a second time’; Manu<ref name=fx7_ve1_1311/> seems to apply the term to the brother-in-law who is ‘married’ to his sister-in-law after his brother's death for the purpose of begetting a child, if he displays conjugal affection to her (''anurajyate kāmataḥ'').<ref name=fx8_ve1_1311/> This sense would be possible, since '''[[दिधिषु|Didhiṣu]]''' denotes a ‘wooer,’ and a widow could be regarded as a ‘wooer’ when able to control her own choice of a spouse. But another tradition<ref name=fx9_ve1_1311/> holds that Didhiṣū means the elder sister whose younger sister has married before her. This view is supported by a passage in the [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx10_ve1_1311/> and by the use of the word ''agredidhiṣū-pati,''<ref name=fx11_ve1_1311/> which must mean the ‘husband of a younger sister married before the elder.’ In this case also Didhiṣū would mean ‘wooer,’ the elder sister being so called because, if her parents do not arrange a marriage for her, she is, according to Viṣṇu,<ref name=fx12_ve1_1311/> to make her own choice of a husband (''kuryāt svayaṃvaram''). See also '''[[एदिधिषुःपति|Edidhiṣuḥpati]]''' and '''[[दैधिषव्य|Daidhiṣavya]].'''<br>

दिव्
<u>'''Div,'''</u> ‘sky.’ The world as a whole is regarded as divided into the three domains of ‘earth,’ ‘air’ or ‘atmosphere,’ and ‘heaven’ or ‘sky’ (''div''),<ref name=fx1_ve1_1312/> or alternatively into ‘heaven and earth’ (''dyāvā-[[पृथिवी|pṛthivī]]''),<ref name=fx2_ve1_1312/> which two are then considered as comprising the universe, the atmosphere being included in the sky. Lightning, wind, and rain belong to the atmosphere, solar and  similar phenomena to the sky. In some passages<ref name=fx3_ve1_1312/> the vault (''[[नाक|nāka]]'') of the sky is added after the usual triad, and before the celestial light (''svar, jyotis'').<br><br>The threefold division of the universe is reflected in a threefold division of the three elements--earth, air, and sky. Thus a highest (''uttama,''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1312/> ''uttara,''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1312/> ''pārya''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1312/> ), a middle, and a lowest heaven are specified.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1312/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_1312/> the three heavens are distinguished as ‘rich in water’ (''udanvatī''), as ''[[पीलुमती|pīlumatī]]'' (of uncertain meaning), and as the ''pradyaus,'' where the Fathers sit. Heaven is frequently called ''vyoman'' as well as ''rocana''<ref name=fx8_ve1_1312/> (properly the ‘luminous space’ of heaven), and the dividing firmament which separates the visible upper world from the highest heaven is called, besides ''[[नाक|nāka]],'' ‘vault,’ ''sānu,'' ‘summit,’ ''viṣṭap,'' ‘surface,’ and ''pṛṣṭha,'' ‘ridge,’ and even ‘ridge of the vault,’<ref name=fx9_ve1_1312/> or ‘summit of the vault.’<ref name=fx10_ve1_1312/><br><br>Similarly three atmospheres (''[[रजस्|rajas]]''), or oftener two, are alluded to,<ref name=fx11_ve1_1312/> but the division here is merely artificial. In one passage<ref name=fx12_ve1_1312/> six ''rajāṃsi,'' ‘regions,’ are referred to, the heavens and the earths no doubt being meant. The usual name for the atmosphere is ''antarikṣa.''<br><br>The three earths are equally artificial, the origin of the triad being probably the use of ''[[पृथिवी|pṛthivī]]'' in the plural<ref name=fx13_ve1_1312/> to denote the three divisions of the universe (just as ''pitarau,'' ‘two fathers,’ denotes ‘father and mother’).<ref name=fx14_ve1_1312/> The earth is called ''kṣam, kṣā, gmā,'' or designated by the epithets ''mahī,'' ‘the great,’ ''[[पृथिवी|pṛthivī]]'' or ''urvī,'' ‘the broad,’ ''uttānā,'' ‘the extended,’ and is regularly contrasted as ''idam,'' ‘this world here,’ with the upper sphere.<ref name=fx15_ve1_1312/>  The shape of the earth is compared with a wheel in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx16_ve1_1312/> and is expressly called ‘circular’ (''pari-maṇḍala'') in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx17_ve1_1312/> When earth is conjoined with heaven, the two are conceived as great bowls (''camvā'') turned towards each other.<ref name=fx18_ve1_1312/> In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx19_ve1_1312/> the two are regarded as halves of an egg. The distance of heaven from the earth is given by the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx20_ve1_1312/> as a thousand days' journey for the sun-bird, by the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx21_ve1_1312/> as a thousand days' journey for a horse, while the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx22_ve1_1312/> whimsically estimates the distance as equivalent to a thousand cows standing one on the top of the other.<br><br>According to Zimmer,<ref name=fx23_ve1_1312/> the Vedic poets conceived the atmosphere to be above the earth in its upper division only, but below it in its lower stratum. The evidence,<ref name=fx24_ve1_1312/> however, for the latter assumption is quite insufficient.<ref name=fx25_ve1_1312/> The theory of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx26_ve1_1312/> is that the sun merely reverses its bright side at night, turning its light on the stars and the moon while it retraverses its course to the east; and it has been shown<ref name=fx25_ve1_1312/> that this is probably the doctrine of the Rigveda also.<ref name=fx27_ve1_1312/> literature. The Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] See also '''[[सूर्य|Sūrya]]''' and '''Candramās.''' For the Vedic knowledge of the planets, see '''[[ग्रह|Graha]].'''<br><br>There is no geographical division of the earth in Vedic literature. The Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx28_ve1_1312/> states that the centre of the earth is a span north of the '''[[प्लक्ष|Plakṣa]] Prāsravaṇā,''' and that the centre of the sky is the constellation of the seven [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]], the Great Bear. For the quarters, see '''[[दिश्|Diś]].''' <br>

दिवोदास अतिथिग्व
<u>'''Divodāsa Atithigva'''</u> is one of the leading princes of the early Vedic age. He was a son of [[वध्र्य्अश्व|Vadhryaśva]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1313/> and father, or more probably grandfather, of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' the famous king of the '''[[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]]''' family, among the '''Bharatas.''' Probably [[पिजवन|Pijavana]] was the son and [[सुदास्|Sudās]] the grandson. Divodāsa was naturally a '''[[भरत|Bharata]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1313/> and, like [[सुदास्|Sudās]], was an opponent of the '''Turvaśas''' and '''Yadus.'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1313/> His great enemy was '''[[शम्बर|Śambara]],''' the '''[[दास|Dāsa]],''' who was apparently chief of a mountain people,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1313/> and whom he repeatedly defeated.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1313/> He was also, it seems, like his father [[वध्र्य्अश्व|Vadhryaśva]],<ref name=fx6_ve1_1313/> an energetic supporter of the fire ritual, for Agni is once called by his name in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1313/> On the other hand, he was defeated, with '''[[आयु|Āyu]]''' and '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]],''' by Indra's aid. In several passages he seems closely connected with the singer family, the '''Bharadvājas.'''<ref name=fx8_ve1_1313/><br><br>From one passage,<ref name=fx9_ve1_1313/> where Divodāsa is said to have fought against the '''Paṇis,''' the '''Pārāvatas,''' and '''[[बृसय|Bṛsaya]],''' Hillebrandt<ref name=fx10_ve1_1313/> has inferred that he was engaged in conflicts with the tribes of Arachosia, and interpreting the name as the ‘heavenly Dāsa’<ref name=fx11_ve1_1313/> conjectures that he was himself a [[दास|Dāsa]]. This conclusion is not probable, for the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' on which the battle in question took place, and which can hardly be the Haraqaiti of Arachosia, would naturally designate the later [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]], while the Pārāvatas are mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx12_ve1_1313/> as in the east, about the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]].''' Bergaigne's  opinion<ref name=fx13_ve1_1313/> that Divodāsa and [[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]] were different people cannot be supported in view of the complete parallelism in the acts of the two persons.<ref name=fx14_ve1_1313/> See also '''[[प्रतर्दन|Pratardana]].'''<br><br>The people of Divodāsa are referred to in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx15_ve1_1313/><br>

दिवो-दास भैम-सेनि
<u>'''Divo-[[दास|dāsa]] Bhaima-seni'''</u> (‘descendant of Bhīmasena’) is mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1314/> as a contemporary of '''[[आरुणि|Āruṇi]].'''<br>

दिव्य
<u>'''Divya,'''</u> ‘ordeal,’ is a term not found until the later literature, but several references to the practice of ordeals have been seen in Vedic literature. The fire ordeal seen in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1315/> by Schlagintweit,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1315/> Weber,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1315/> Ludwig,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1315/> Zimmer,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1315/> and others, has been disproved by Grill,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1315/> Bloomfield,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1315/> and Whitney.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1315/> But such an ordeal appears in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx9_ve1_1315/> and an ordeal with a glowing axe<ref name=fx10_ve1_1315/> occurs in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] as applied in an accusation of theft. Geldner<ref name=fx11_ve1_1315/> suggests that this usage is referred to even in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx12_ve1_1315/> but this is most improbable.<ref name=fx13_ve1_1315/> Ludwig<ref name=fx14_ve1_1315/> and Griffith<ref name=fx15_ve1_1315/> discover in another  passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx16_ve1_1315/> references to '''Dīrghatamas'''' having been subjected to the fire and water ordeals, but this view cannot be supported. According to Weber,<ref name=fx17_ve1_1315/> the ‘balance’ ordeal is referred to in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx18_ve1_1315/> but see '''[[तुला|Tulā]].'''<br>

दिव्य श्वन्
<u>'''Divya Śvan,'''</u> the ‘divine dog,’ in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1316/> appears to denote Canis major or Sirius. But Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve1_1316/> thinks that the two divine dogs referred to in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_1316/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1316/> are the sun and moon, and that the sun is meant in the Atharvaveda.<br>

दिश्
<u>'''Diś,'''</u> ‘direction,’ is a word very frequently used in the Rigveda and later<ref name=fx1_ve1_1317/> to denote a quarter of the sky. As a general rule, four quarters are mentioned--east, south, west, north.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1317/> But the number of the ‘directions’ is sometimes increased up to ten by the addition to these four of various others. The five points include the zenith (''ūrdhvā'');<ref name=fx3_ve1_1317/> the six, the zenith and the nadir (''ūrdhvā'' and ''avācī'');<ref name=fx4_ve1_1317/> the seven, the zenith, the ground on which one stands (''[[ध्रुवा|dhruvā]]''), and the air (''antarikṣa'') between these two (''vyadhvā'');<ref name=fx5_ve1_1317/> the eight include the intermediate quarters (S.E., S.W., N.E., N.W.);<ref name=fx6_ve1_1317/> the nine add to these the zenith;<ref name=fx7_ve1_1317/> the ten, zenith and nadir.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1317/> The number  five is sometimes made up by the ground beneath the observer's feet (''[[ध्रुवा|dhruvā]]''),<ref name=fx9_ve1_1317/> and the number six by that point (''[[ध्रुवा|dhruvā]]'') and the zenith (''ūrdhvā'');<ref name=fx10_ve1_1317/> the ‘lofty’ (''bṛhatī'')<ref name=fx11_ve1_1317/> sometimes taking the place of the ‘vertical’ (''ūrdhvā'').<br>

दीर्घ-तमस्
<u>'''Dīrgha-tamas'''</u> (‘long darkness’) '''[[मामतेय|Māmateya]]''' (‘son of Mamatā’) '''Aucathya''' (‘son of Ucatha’) is mentioned as a singer in one hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1318/> and is referred to in several passages<ref name=fx2_ve1_1318/> by his metronymic, [[मामतेय|Māmateya]], alone. He is said, both in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1318/> and in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1318/> to have attained the tenth decade of life. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1318/> he appears as the priest of '''[[भरत|Bharata]].''' The Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx5_ve1_1318/> contains a preposterous legend made up of fragments of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1318/> according to which [[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]] was born blind, but recovered his sight; in old age he was thrown into a river by his servants, one of whom, '''[[त्रैतन|Traitana]],''' attacked him, but killed himself instead. Carried down by the stream, he was cast up in the [[अङ्ग|Aṅga]] country, where he married Uśij, a slave girl, and begot '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]].''' The two legends here combined are not even consistent, for the second ignores Dīrghatamas' recovery of sight. To attach any historical importance to them, as does Pargiter,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1318/> would seem to be unwise. <br>

दीर्घ-नीथ
<u>'''Dīrgha-nītha'''</u> appears to be the proper name of a sacrificer in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1319/><br>

दीर्घ-श्रवस्
<u>'''Dīrgha-śravas'''</u> (‘far-famed’) is the name of a royal seer who, according to the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1320/> having been banished from his kingdom, and suffering from actual hunger, ‘saw’ a certain Sāman (chant), and thus obtained food. In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1320/> an [[औशिज|Auśija]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1320/> a merchant (''[[वणिज्|vaṇij]]''), is mentioned as ''[[दीर्घ-श्रवस्|dīrgha-śravas]],'' which may be a proper name, as Sāyaṇa holds, or an adjective, as it is understood by Roth.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1320/><br>

दीर्घाप्सस्
<u>'''Dīrghāpsas,'''</u> used in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1321/> as an epithet of a chariot, means, according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1321/> ‘having a long front part.’<br>

दीर्घायुत्व
<u>'''Dīrghāyutva,'''</u> ‘longevity,’ is a constant object of the prayers of the Vedic Indians,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1322/> and length of life is never deprecated in the Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas, while the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1322/> is full of spells intended to prolong existence (''āyuṣyāṇi'').<br>

दीर्घारण्य
<u>'''Dīrghāraṇya,'''</u> ‘wide tract of forest,’ in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1323/> and Śatapatha<ref name=fx2_ve1_1323/> Brāhmanas refers to the extensive jungles which  must clearly then have covered Northern India. In one of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] passages<ref name=fx3_ve1_1323/> it is said that in the east the villages are close together and frequent, while in the west there are forests.<br>

दीव्
<u>'''Dīv'''</u> (fem.) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1324/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1324/> denotes the ‘game of dice.’ See '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]].'''<br>

दुघा
<u>'''Dughā,'''</u> ‘yielding milk,’ denotes ‘cow’ in a few passages in the Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1325/><br>

दुन्दुभि
<u>'''Dundubhi,'''</u> apparently an onomatopoetic word, means ‘drum,’ as used in both war and peace. It is often mentioned from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1326/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1326/> A special sort of drum was the ‘earth drum,’ made by digging a hole in the ground and covering it with a hide. This was employed in the Mahāvrata, a rite performed at the winter solstice, for the purpose of driving away influences hostile to the return of the sun.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1326/> A ‘drumbeater’ is included in the list of sacrificial victims at the Puruṣamedha or ‘human sacrifice.’<ref name=fx4_ve1_1326/><br>

दुर्
<u>'''Dur'''</u> is used several times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1327/> to denote ‘door,’ both literally and metaphorically. <br>

दुरोण
<u>'''Duroṇa'''</u> is used in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1328/> and sometimes later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1328/> to denote ‘home,’ both literally and metaphorically. See '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].'''<br>

दुर्-ग
<u>'''Dur-ga,'''</u> ‘hard to approach,’ occurs in the Rigveda as a neuter substantive only, sometimes in the sense of ‘fort,’ ‘stronghold.’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1329/> ''Cf.'' '''Pur.'''<br>

दुर्-गह
<u>'''Dur-gaha'''</u> is mentioned in a hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1330/> where his grandsons are lauded for their generosity, though Sāyaṇa renders the word adjectivally.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1330/> In another passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1330/> however, Sāyaṇa sees in the epithet [[दौर्गह|Daurgaha]] a description of '''[[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]]''' as Durgaha's son, who was either captured by the enemy or slain, and whose wife, '''[[पुरुकुत्सानी|Purukutsānī]],''' then obtained a son, '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]],''' to restore the line; he also quotes a story, not found in the Bṛhaddevatā,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1330/> to support this interpretation. On the other hand, the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1330/> seems to take [[दौर्गह|Daurgaha]] as meaning a horse. Sieg<ref name=fx6_ve1_1330/> thinks that the same sense should be adopted in the Rigveda passage, which he interprets as referring to the sacrifice of a horse, [[दौर्गह|Daurgaha]], by King [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]] to gain a son; he also sees in Dadhikrāvan, with Pischel<ref name=fx7_ve1_1330/> and Ludwig,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1330/> a real horse, the charger of [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]]. The Śatapatha Brāhmaṇa's interpretation of [[दौर्गह|Daurgaha]] is, however, doubtful, and cannot be regarded as receiving support from the case of Dadhikrāvan, who was probably a divinity, and not a real horse at all.<ref name=fx9_ve1_1330/> <br>

दुर्-णामन्
<u>'''Dur-ṇāman,'''</u> ‘of evil name,’ is the designation in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1331/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1331/> of a demon causing disease, or the disease itself. The [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1331/> explains the words as meaning a ‘worm,’ an interpretation which accords with the widespread belief in disease-causing worms.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1331/> Later Durnāman denotes ‘hæmorrhoids.’<ref name=fx5_ve1_1331/><br>

दुर्-मुख
<u>'''Dur-mukha,'''</u> ‘ugly-faced,’ is the name, in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1332/> of a [[पाञ्चाल|Pāñcāla]], that is, [[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] king, who conquered the world, and whose priest was '''[[बृहद्उक्थ|Bṛhaduktha]].'''<br>

दुर्य
<u>'''Durya,'''</u> ‘belonging to the door or house,’ appears in several passages of the Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1333/> as a plural substantive denoting the ‘door-posts,’ or more generally ‘dwelling.’<br>

दुर्योण
<u>'''Duryoṇa'''</u> occurs a few times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1334/> in the sense of ‘house.’<br>

दुर्-वराह
<u>'''Dur-varāha'''</u> probably denotes a ‘wild boar.’ It is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1335/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1335/><br>

दुला
<u>'''Dulā.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] ([[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]]).'''<br>

दुश्-चर्मन्
<u>'''Duś-carman,'''</u> ‘afflicted with a skin disease,’ occurs in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1337/> and [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1337/> The disease meant is probably leprosy, the usual name of which is '''[[किलास|Kilāsa]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1337/> <br>

दुः-शासु
<u>'''Duḥ-śāsu'''</u> is possibly a proper name in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1338/> and would then denote an enemy of '''Kuruśravaṇa.''' Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_1338/> thinks that he was a '''[[पर्शु|Parśu]]''' or Persian, but this is most improbable, and the word may simply be an adjective meaning ‘malignant.’<br>

दुः-शीम
<u>'''Duḥ-śīma'''</u> is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1339/> as a generous donor, his patronymic perhaps being '''[[तान्व|Tānva]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1339/><br>

दुष्-टरीतु
<u>'''Duṣ-ṭarītu,'''</u> ‘hard to defeat,’ is the name of a king of the '''Sṛñjayas,''' who was deposed from a principality that had existed for ten generations, but was re-instated by '''[[चाक्र|Cākra]] [[स्थपति|Sthapati]]''' in spite of the resistance of '''[[बल्हिक प्रातिपीय|Balhika Prātipīya]],''' according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1340/><br>

दुः-षन्त
<u>'''Duḥ-ṣanta.'''</u> See '''[[दौःषन्ति|Dauḥṣanti]].'''<br>

दुहितृ
<u>'''Duhitṛ'''</u> is the regular designation of ‘daughter’ from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1342/> The word appears to be derived from ''duh,'' ‘milk,’ in the sense of one who nourishes a child, rather than as the ‘milker’ of the primitive family or the suckling.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1342/> See also '''[[स्त्री|Strī]], Pati, [[पितृ|Pitṛ]], [[भ्रातृ|Bhrātṛ]].'''<br>

दूत
<u>'''Dūta,'''</u> ‘messenger’ or envoy,' is found several times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1343/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1343/> used metaphorically. The '''[[सूत|Sūta]]''' seems to have performed the duties later assigned to the [[दूत|Dūta]]. <br>

दूर्वा
<u>'''Dūrvā,'''</u> a species of grass (''Panicum dactylon''), is mentioned frequently from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1344/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1344/> It grew in damp ground.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1344/> A simile occurring in the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1344/> seems to indicate that the ears lay horizontal with the stem. ''Cf.'' '''[[पाकदूर्वा|Pākadūrvā]].'''<br>

दूर्श
<u>'''Dūrśa,'''</u> denoting some kind of garment, is mentioned twice in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1345/> Weber<ref name=fx2_ve1_1345/> thinks that it was worn by the aborigines.<br>

दूषीका
<u>'''Dūṣīkā,'''</u> ‘rheum of the eyes,’ is mentioned as a disease in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1346/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1346/><br>

दृढ-च्युत् आगस्ति
<u>'''Dṛḍha-cyut Āgasti'''</u> (‘descendant of Agastya’) is mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1347/> as having been Udgātṛ priest at the Sattra (‘sacrificial session’) of the Vibhindukīyas.<br>

दृढ-जयन्त
<u>'''Dṛḍha-jayanta.'''</u> See '''Vipaścit''' and '''[[वैपश्चित|Vaipaścita]].'''<br>

दृति
<u>'''1. Dṛti,'''</u> a ‘leather bag to hold fluids,’ is frequently mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1349/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1349/> In one passage<ref name=fx3_ve1_1349/> it is called ''dhmāta,'' ‘inflated,’ the man afflicted with dropsy being compared with such a bag. Milk ('''[[क्षीर|Kṣīra]]''') and intoxicating liquor ('''[[सुरा|Surā]]''') are mentioned as kept in bags.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1349/> <br>

दृति ऐन्द्रोत
<u>'''2. Dṛti Aindrota'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[इन्द्रोत|Indrota]]'''’) is mentioned in the Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1350/> as a contemporary of '''[[अभिप्रतारिन् काक्षसेनि|Abhipratārin Kākṣaseni]]''' and as a pupil of '''[[इन्द्रोत|Indrota]] [[दैवाप|Daivāpa]]''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Jaīminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1350/> Possibly the same [[दृति|Dṛti]] is meant in the compound [[दृति|Dṛti]]-Vātavantau, which is found in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1350/> The former is here said to have continued, after the Mahāvrata was over, the sacrificial session in which both had been engaged, with the result that his descendants prospered more than the Vātavatas.<br>

दृप्त-बालाकि गार्ग्य
<u>'''Dṛpta-[[बालाकि|bālāki]] Gārgya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[गर्ग|Garga]]'''’) is the name of a teacher who is mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 1, 1) as a contemporary of '''[[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]]''' of '''[[काशि|Kāśi]].'''<br>

दृभीक
<u>'''Dṛbhīka'''</u> is the name of a man<ref name=fx1_ve1_1352/> or a demon,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1352/> who, according to the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1352/> was slain by Indra.<br>

दृशान भार्गव
<u>'''Dṛśāna Bhārgava'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[भृगु|Bhṛgu]]'''’) is mentioned as a seer in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1353/><br>

दृषद्
<u>'''Dṛṣad'''</u> appears in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1354/> and Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1354/> to denote not a millstone,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1354/> but merely a stone used to pound grain, which was placed on another stone as a support. When used later<ref name=fx4_ve1_1354/>  in connexion with '''[[उपला|Upalā]],''' the lower and the upper millstone, or mortar and pestle may be meant; but this is not certain. Eggeling<ref name=fx5_ve1_1354/> renders them as the large and small millstones. See also '''[[उपर|Upara]]''' and '''[[उपला|Upalā]].'''<br>

दृषद्वती
<u>'''Dṛṣadvatī,'''</u> ‘stony,’ is the name of a river which flows into the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' after running for a time parallel to it. It is mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1355/> along with the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] and the '''[[आपया|Āpayā]],''' as the scene of action of the [[भरत|Bharata]] princes. In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1355/> and later<ref name=fx3_ve1_1355/> the [[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]] and the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] are the scene of special sacrifices. In Manu<ref name=fx4_ve1_1355/> these two rivers form the western boundary of the Middle Country.<br>

दृष्ट
<u>'''Dṛṣṭa.'''</u> See '''[[अदृष्ट|Adṛṣṭa]].'''<br>

देवक मान्यमान
<u>'''Devaka Mānyamāna'''</u> (‘descendant of Manyamāna’) appears in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1357/> as an opponent of the Tṛtsus, and as connected with [[शम्बर|Śambara]]. Possibly, however, as Grassmann suggests, the words should be understood as denoting [[शम्बर|Śambara]], ‘who deemed himself a god,’ ''devaka'' being used contemptuously.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1357/><br>

देवकी-पुत्र
<u>'''Devakī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of Devakī,’ is the metronymic of '''[[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]]''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1358/> According to the Epic,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1358/> a Devaka was father of Devakī, Kṛṣṇa's mother; the St. Petersburg Dictionary suggests that he was the ‘king of the Gandharvas’, also referred to in the Epic.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1358/> <br>

देव-जन-विद्या
<u>'''Deva-jana-vidyā,'''</u> ‘knowledge of divine beings,’ is one of the sciences enumerated in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1359/> and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1359/><br>

देव-तरस् श्यावसायन काश्यप
<u>'''Deva-taras [[श्यावसायन|Śyāvasāyana]] Kāśyapa'''</u> (‘descendant of Kaśyapa’) is mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1360/> as a pupil of '''Rsyasṛṅga.''' In the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1360/> as Śāvasāyana, he is a pupil of his father [[शवस्|Śavas]], who again was a pupil of Kāśyapa.<br>

देवत्या
<u>'''Devatyā'''</u> occurs in the text of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1361/> where it must, if the reading is correct, denote some animal.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1361/> But the reading should no doubt be ''[[रोहिणी|rohiṇī]]-devatyās,'' ‘having the red one as deity.’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1361/><br>

देवन
<u>'''Devana'''</u> is mentioned once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1362/> in connexion with dicing. The word must designate the place on which the dice are thrown (elsewhere called '''[[अधिदेवन|Adhidevana]]'''), and it is so explained by [[दुर्ग|Durga]] in his commentary on the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1362/><br>

देव-नक्षत्र
<u>'''Deva-nakṣatra,'''</u> ‘asterism of the gods,’ is the name applied in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1363/> to the first fourteen lunar mansions, which are said to be south, while the others are called [[यमनक्षत्र|Yamanakṣatra]], ‘asterisms of Yama,’ and are said to be north. See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

देव-भाग श्रौतर्ष
<u>'''Deva-bhāga Śrautarṣa'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1364/> as the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], or ‘domestic priest,’ of both the  '''Sṛñjayas''' and the '''Kurus.''' In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1364/> he is said to have taught '''[[गिरिज बाभ्रव्य|Girija Bābhravya]]''' the science of the dissection of the sacrificial animal (''pasor vibhakti''). In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1364/> he is an authority on the Sāvitra Agni.<br>

देव-मलिम्लुच्
<u>'''Deva-malimluc,'''</u> ‘robber of the gods,’ is the epithet of Rahasya,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1365/> who is said in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1365/> to have slain the pious '''Vaikhānasas''' at '''[[मुनिमरण|Munimaraṇa]]''' (‘saint's death’). He was apparently an Asura, but may have been a real person.<br>

देव-मुनि
<u>'''Deva-muni,'''</u> ‘divine saint,’ is the epithet of '''Tura''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxv. 14, 5). The name is given in the Anukramaṇī to the author of a hymn of the Rigveda (x. 146).<br>

देव-राजन्
<u>'''Deva-rājan'''</u> apparently denotes a king of Brahminical descent in the phrase ‘Sāmans of Devarājans’ in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xviii. 10, 5). ''Cf.'' '''[[राजन्यर्षि|Rājanyarṣi]]''' and '''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]].'''<br>

देव-रात
<u>'''Deva-rāta'''</u> (‘god-given’) '''[[वैश्वामित्र|Vaiśvāmitra]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]'''’) is the name given to [[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]] after his adoption by [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1368/><br>

देवल
<u>'''Devala'''</u> is mentioned as a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xxii. 11). See also '''[[दैवल|Daivala]].'''<br>

देववन्त्
<u>'''Devavant'''</u> is mentioned in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1370/> as the ancestor of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' apparently his grandfather; or if '''[[पिजवन|Pijavana]]''' be accepted as Sudās' father, and '''Divodāsa''' as his grandfather, then his great-great-grandfather, and father of '''[[वध्र्य्अश्व|Vadhryaśva]].''' The succession in the latter case would then be [[देववन्त्|Devavant]], [[वध्र्य्अश्व|Vadhryaśva]], Divodāsa, [[पिजवन|Pijavana]], [[सुदास्|Sudās]]. <br>

देव-वात
<u>'''Deva-vāta'''</u> (‘desired of the gods’) is the name of a '''[[भरत|Bharata]]''' prince in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1371/> where he is mentioned as sacrificing on the '''[[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]], [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],''' and '''[[आपया|Āpayā]].'''<br>

देव-विद्या
<u>'''Deva-vidyā,'''</u> ‘knowledge of the gods,’ is one of the sciences enumerated in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vii. 1, 2, 4; 2, 1; 7, 1).<br>

देव-श्रवस्
<u>'''Deva-śravas'''</u> is the name of a '''[[भरत|Bharata]]''' prince who with '''[[देववात|Devavāta]]''' appears as a sacrificer on the '''[[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]], [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],''' and '''[[आपया|Āpayā]]''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1373/><br>

देवातिथि काण्व
<u>'''Devātithi Kāṇva'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[कण्व|Kaṇva]]'''’) is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1374/> as the seer of a Sāman (chant) by which he turned pumpkins into cows for himself and his son when they were starving in the desert, whither they had been driven by rivals. He is also the reputed author of a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1374/><br>

देवापि आर्ष्टिषेण
<u>'''Devāpi Ārṣṭiṣeṇa'''</u> (‘descendant of Ṛṣṭiṣeṇa’) is mentioned in a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1375/> and in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1375/> According to the latter source there were two brothers, '''Devāpi''' and '''Śantanu,''' princes of the Kurus. The elder was Devāpi, but Śantanu got himself anointed king, whereupon no rain fell for twelve years. The drought being attributed by the Brahmins to his having superseded his elder brother, Śantanu offered the kingdom to Devāpi. The latter, however, refused, but acting as [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], or domestic priest, for his brother, obtained rain. The Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx3_ve1_1375/> tells much the same tale, but adds that the reason for Devāpi's exclusion from the throne was the fact that he suffered from a skin disease. The Epic and later legends further  develop the story, presenting two somewhat discrepant accounts. According to the one version,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1375/> the ground of Devāpi's being passed over was leprosy, while in the other his devoting himself to asceticism in his youth was the cause of his brother's taking his place. The Epic,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1375/> moreover, treats him as a son of Pratīpa, and names as his brothers Bāhlīka<ref name=fx6_ve1_1375/> and Āṛṣṭiṣeṇa,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1375/> who is a new figure developed from the patronymic of Devāpi Possibly Sieg<ref name=fx8_ve1_1375/> is right in holding that two stories, those of Devāpi, Pratīpa's son, and of Devāpi, Ṛṣṭiṣeṇa's son, have been confused; but in any case it is impossible to extract history from them.<ref name=fx9_ve1_1375/><br><br>The Rigvedic hymn certainly appears to represent Devāpi as sacrificing for Śantanu, who seems to be called '''[[औलान|Aulāna]].'''<ref name=fx10_ve1_1375/> But there is no trace in it of the brotherhood of the two men, nor is there anything to show that Devāpi was not a Brahmin, but a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]. Sieg,<ref name=fx11_ve1_1375/> who interprets the hymn by the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]], thinks that he was a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]], but on this occasion was enabled by the favour of [[बृहस्पति|Bṛhaspati]] to officiate as priest, and that the hymn shows clear recognition of the unusual character of his action; but this view seems very improbable.<br>

देवृ
<u>'''Devṛ'''</u> is a rare word denoting the wife's ‘brother-in-law’ (that is, the husband's brother). He is included with the sisters of the husband among those over whom the wife of the husband--his elder brother--rules;<ref name=fx1_ve1_1376/> at the same time the wife is to be devoted to him,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1376/> and friendly to him.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1376/> After the death  of the husband the [[देवृ|Devṛ]] could perform the duty of begetting a son for him.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1376/> No word occurs for the wife's brother corresponding to [[देवृ|Devṛ]].<br>

देश
<u>'''Deśa,'''</u> ‘land,’ is a word that does not come into use till the time of the Upaniṣads and Sūtras,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1377/> excepting one occurrence in the latest period of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1377/> literature, and one in a much-discussed passage of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1377/> where the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' is mentioned as having five tributaries. This passage militates against the view that [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] was a name of the Indus, because the use of [[देश|Deśa]] here seems to indicate<ref name=fx4_ve1_1377/> that the seer of the verse placed the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] in the [[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]] or ‘Middle Country,’ to which all the geographical data of the Yajurvedas point.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1377/><br>

देही
<u>'''Dehī'''</u> in two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1378/> refers to defences thrown up against an enemy, apparently earthworks or dikes. ''Cf.'' '''Pur.'''<br>

दैधिषव्य
<u>'''Daidhiṣavya'''</u> is mentioned in a [[मन्त्र|Mantra]] of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1379/> Apparently the word (as derived from '''Didhiṣū''') denotes the son of a younger sister married before the elder sister,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1379/> rather than the son of a woman twice married, the explanation of the St. Petersburg Dictionary. <br>

दैयांपाति
<u>'''Daiyāṃpāti,'''</u> ‘descendant of Dayāṃpāta,’ is the name of a teacher of the east, who was instructed by '''[[शाण्डिल्यायन|Śāṇḍilyāyana]],''' according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ix. 5, 1, 14), in the lore of the construction of the fire-altar. The same patronymic is given, in the form of Dayyāṃpāti, to '''[[प्लक्ष|Plakṣa]],''' the contemporary of '''Atyaṃhas''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 10, 9, 3-5).<br>

दैव
<u>'''1. Daiva'''</u> (masc.) appears in the list of sciences in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1381/> where Śaṅkara explains it as ''utpātajñāna,'' apparently the ‘knowledge of portents.’ The St. Petersburg Dictionary suggests that the word is here used adjectivally, and this view is followed by Little<ref name=fx2_ve1_1381/> and by Bo7htlingk in his translation.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1381/><br>

दैव
<u>'''2. Daiva'''</u> is the patronymic of the mythical [[अथर्वन्|Atharvan]] in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1382/><br>

दैवल
<u>'''Daivala,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[देवल|Devala]],’ is the patronymic of '''[[असित|Asita]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 11, 18).<br>

दैव-वात
<u>'''Daiva-vāta,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[देववात|Devavāta]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]],''' probably the [[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]] king, in the Rigveda. He is mentioned<ref name=fx1_ve1_1384/> as a devotee of the fire cult, and as victorious over the '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]]''' king and the '''Vṛcīvants.'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1384/> According to Zimmer,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1384/> his name was '''[[अभ्यावर्तिन् चायमान|Abhyāvartin Cāyamāna]] [[पार्थव|Pārthava]]''' (‘descendant of Pṛthu’), but Hillebrandt<ref name=fx4_ve1_1384/> recognizes this as doubtful, though he none the less places the Sṛñjayas to the west of the Indus with '''Divodāsa.''' What is more important is to note that the name suggests connexion with the [[भरत|Bharata]] '''[[देववात|Devavāta]],''' and as '''Kurus''' and Sṛñjayas were closely connected<ref name=fx5_ve1_1384/> this is not immaterial. <br>

दैवाप
<u>'''Daivāpa,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Devāpi,'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[इन्द्रोत|Indrota]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1385/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1385/> No connexion can be traced with the Devāpi of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1385/><br>

दैवावृध
<u>'''Daivāvṛdha,'''</u> ‘descendant of Devāvṛdha,’ is the patronymic of '''[[बभ्रु|Babhru]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 34).<br>

दैवो-दासि
<u>'''Daivo-dāsi,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Divodāsa,'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[प्रतर्दन|Pratardana]]''' in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1387/> and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1387/> It is impossible to ascertain whether the famous Divodāsa is meant.<br>

दोषा
<u>'''Doṣā,'''</u> ‘evening,’ is frequently referred to from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1388/> onwards,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1388/> usually as contrasted with ''uṣas,'' ‘dawn.’ In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1388/> the word is contrasted with ''[[प्रातर्|prātar]],'' ‘early.’ See also '''Ahan.'''<br>

दोह
<u>'''Doha,'''</u> ‘milking,’ is a common word in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1389/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1389/> Reference is made in the Sūtras<ref name=fx3_ve1_1389/> to the ''sāyaṃ-doha,'' ‘evening milking,’ and the ''[[प्रातर्|prātar]]-doha,'' ‘morning milking.’ Dohana has the same sense.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1389/> See also '''Go.'''<br>

दौरे-श्रवस्
<u>'''Daure-śravas,'''</u> ‘descendant of Dūreśravas,’ is the patronymic of the priest '''[[पृथुश्रवस्|Pṛthuśravas]],''' who officiated at the snake sacrifice described in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxv. 15, 3). <br>

दौरे-श्रुत
<u>'''Daure-śruta,'''</u> ‘descendant of Dūreśruta,’ is the patronymic of the priest '''Timirgha,''' who officiated at the snake sacrifice described in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxv. 15, 3).<br>

दौर्-गह
<u>'''Daur-gaha.'''</u> See '''[[दुर्गह|Durgaha]].'''<br>

दौः-षन्ति
<u>'''Dauḥ-ṣanti'''</u> (‘descendant of Duḥṣanta’) is the patronymic of [[भरत|Bharata]] in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] (viii. 23) and Śatapatha (xiii. 5, 4, 11) Brāhmaṇas.<br>

द्युतान मारुत
<u>'''Dyutāna Māruta'''</u> (‘descendant of the Maruts’) is the name of a divine being invoked in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1394/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1394/> and also mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1394/> In the Śatapatha<ref name=fx4_ve1_1394/> [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] the name is explained to mean Vāyu, while in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1394/> he seems to be regarded as the author of a Sāman (chant). He is treated as a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] by the Anukramaṇī, which credits him with the authorship of a hymn of the Rigveda (viii. 96).<br>

द्युम्न
<u>'''Dyumna,'''</u> according to Pischel,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1395/> denotes ‘raft’ in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1395/><br>

द्यूत
<u>'''Dyūta,'''</u> ‘dicing,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1396/> and the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1396/> See '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]].'''<br>

द्योतन
<u>'''Dyotana'''</u> is, according to Sāyaṇa, the name of a prince in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1397/> This is probably correct, though the word may also<ref name=fx2_ve1_1397/> be interpreted as denoting ‘glorification’ but it is not clear what relation existed between [[द्योतन|Dyotana]] and the other persons mentioned in the same passage, '''[[वेतसु|Vetasu]], [[दशोणि|Daśoṇi]], [[तूतुजि|Tūtuji]],''' and '''[[तुग्र|Tugra]].''' <br>

द्रप्स
<u>'''Drapsa'''</u> is a common word from the Rigveda onwards<ref name=fx1_ve1_1398/> for a ‘drop’: according to Sāyaṇa,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1398/> a ‘thick drop’ as opposed to ''stoka,'' a ‘small drop.’ Hence there frequently occurs the expression ''dadḥi-[[द्रप्स|drapsa]],''’ ‘drop of curds.’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1398/> In the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1398/> the word normally denotes the thick drops of Soma or the Soma itself.<br><br>In two passages<ref name=fx5_ve1_1398/> Roth<ref name=fx6_ve1_1398/> sees the sense of ‘banner,’ which is adopted by Oldenberg.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1398/> Geldner,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1398/> on the other hand, considers that ‘dust’ is meant, but this interpretation is not very probable. Max Müller<ref name=fx9_ve1_1398/> renders the word ‘rain-drop’ in one of the passages.<br>

द्रापि
<u>'''Drāpi'''</u> occurs several times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1399/> in the sense of ‘mantle’ or ‘cloak.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1399/> Sāyaṇa, however, renders the word by ‘coat of mail’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1399/> (''[[कवच|kavaca]]''). This seems needless, but none of the passages are very decisive one way or the other.<br>

द्रु
<u>'''Dru'''</u> denotes a vessel made of wood,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1400/> and in particular the vessel used at the Soma sacrifice,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1400/> perhaps, as Hillebrandt<ref name=fx3_ve1_1400/> suggests, to catch the Soma juice when running through the sieve. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1400/> the word simply means ‘wood.’ <br>

द्रु-घण
<u>'''Dru-ghaṇa'''</u> is found in the [[मुद्गल|Mudgala]] hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1401/> and in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1401/> The sense is uncertain. [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1401/> renders it as a ‘''ghana'' made of wood,’ probably, as Roth<ref name=fx4_ve1_1401/> takes it, meaning a ‘club of wood.’ Geldner<ref name=fx5_ve1_1401/> thinks that it was a wooden bull used by [[मुद्गल|Mudgala]] as a substitute for a second bull when he wanted to join in a race. But this interpretation of the legend is very improbable.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1401/> Whitney<ref name=fx7_ve1_1401/> translates the word as ‘tree-smiter’ in the Atharvaveda, quoting Sāyaṇa, who explains it as a ‘cutting instrument,’ so called because trees are struck with it.<br>

द्रु-पद
<u>'''Dru-pada,'''</u> a ‘wooden pillar’ or ‘post,’ is several times referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1402/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1402/> [[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]] was bound to three posts for sacrifice.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1402/> Thieves, there is some evidence to show, were tied to posts as a penalty for stealing.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1402/><br>

द्रुम
<u>'''Druma,'''</u> ‘tree,’ is not found until the later period in the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 11) and the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (iv. 19; v. 26; ix. 23).<br>

द्रुवय
<u>'''Druvaya,'''</u> ‘wooden,’ is used in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1404/> as an epithet of the drum.<br>

द्रु-हन्
<u>'''Dru-han,'''</u> ‘wood-cutter,’ seems to be meant by the word ''druhantara'' in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1405/> where it is usually taken as ''druhaṃtara,'' ‘fiend-overpowering.’ But as an epithet of ''[[परशु|paraśu]],'' ‘axe,’ the other sense (‘mighty wood-cutter’)<ref name=fx2_ve1_1405/> is more probable.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1405/> <br>

द्रुह्यु
<u>'''Druhyu'''</u> is the name of a people mentioned several times in the Rigveda. In one passage<ref name=fx1_ve1_1406/> it occurs, in the plural, with the '''Yadus, Turvaśas, Anus,''' and '''Pūrus,''' suggesting that these are the famous five peoples of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1406/> Again, the [[द्रुह्यु|Druhyu]] king shared in the defeat of his allies by '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' and appears to have perished in the waters.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1406/> In a second passage [[द्रुह्यु|Druhyu]], Anu, [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]], and Yadu are all mentioned in the singular,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1406/> while in another [[पूरु|Pūru]] and [[द्रुह्यु|Druhyu]] occur.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1406/> From the tribal grouping it is probable that the Druhyus were a north-western people,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1406/> and the later tradition of the Epic connects [[गान्धार|Gāndhāra]] and [[द्रुह्यु|Druhyu]].<ref name=fx7_ve1_1406/><br>

द्रोण
<u>'''Droṇa'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1407/> a ‘wooden trough,’ and more specifically it designates in the plural vessels used for holding Soma.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1407/> The great wooden reservoir for Soma is called a [[द्रोण|Droṇa]]-[[कलश|kalaśa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1407/> The altar was sometimes made in the form of a [[द्रोण|Droṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1407/><br>

द्रोणाहाव
<u>'''Droṇāhāva'''</u> is used as an epithet of '''[[अवत|Avata]],''' ‘well,’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1408/> apparently in the sense of ‘having wooden buckets’ with reference to the drawing up of water.<br>

द्वादश
<u>'''Dvādaśa,'''</u> ‘consisting of twelve,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1409/> is used of the year in the Rigveda (vii. 103, 9). See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

द्वापर
<u>'''Dvāpara.'''</u> See '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]]''' and '''Yuga.''' <br>

द्वार्
<u>'''Dvār'''</u> is frequently used from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1411/> onwards<ref name=fx2_ve1_1411/> to denote the ‘door’ of a house. The later form, Dvāra, has the same sense.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1411/> ''Cf.'' '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].''' The ‘door-fastener’ is called Dvārapidhāna in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1411/><br>

द्वार-प
<u>'''Dvāra-pa,'''</u> ‘door-keeper,’ is only found in a metaphorical sense in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 30), where Viṣṇu is called the ‘doorkeeper’ of the gods, and in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iii. 13, 6).<br>

द्वि-गत् भार्गव
<u>'''Dvi-gat Bhārgava'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[भृगु|Bhṛgu]]'''’) is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 9) as the seer of a Sāman or Chant, by means of which he twice went to the heavenly world.<br>

द्वि-ज
<u>'''Dvi-ja,'''</u> ‘twice-born,’ as an epithet of the Āryans generally, or of the Brahmins in particular, is not found in Vedic literature except in a quite obscure verse of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1414/><br>

द्वि-पाद्
<u>'''Dvi-pād,'''</u> ‘two-footed,’ ‘biped,’ denotes man, as opposed to quadrupeds, from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1415/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1415/><br>

द्वि-बन्धु
<u>'''Dvi-bandhu'''</u> is in an obscure hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1416/> according to Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_1416/> and Grassmann,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1416/> the name of a man, while Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve1_1416/> renders it as a simple adjective meaning ‘of double kinship.’ <br>

द्वि-राज
<u>'''Dvi-rāja'''</u> (neut,), ‘conflict between two kings,’ or ‘battle,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda (v. 20, 9). ''Cf.'' '''[[दाशराज्ञ|Dāśarājña]].'''<br>

द्वि-रेतस्
<u>'''Dvi-retas,'''</u> ‘having double seed,’ is an epithet of both the ass<ref name=fx1_ve1_1418/> and the mare.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1418/><br>

द्वीप
<u>'''Dvīpa,'''</u> ‘island,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1419/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1419/> But there is no reason to imagine that the islands referred to were other than sandbanks in the great rivers, Indus or Ganges.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1419/> Vedic literature knows nothing of the system of geography according to which the earth consists of four, seven, or thirteen Dvīpas grouped round Mount Meru.<br>

द्वीपिन्
<u>'''Dvīpin,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1420/> ‘panther’ or ‘leopard,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1420/> and the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1420/><br>

द्वैत-वन
<u>'''Dvaita-vana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Dvitavana,’ is the patronymic of '''Dhvasan,''' the king of the '''Matsyas,''' whose [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or ‘horse sacrifice,’ is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 5, 4, 9).<br>

द्व्य्-ओपश
<u>'''Dvy-opaśa.'''</u> See '''[[ओपश|Opaśa]].''' <br>

धन
<u>'''Dhana,'''</u> ‘prize,’ is often found in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1423/> probably the prize in racing rather than the ‘booty’ in battle. It also denotes<ref name=fx2_ve1_1423/> the ‘stake’ at dicing. In some passages it possibly means the ‘contest’ itself.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1423/> More generally it denotes ‘wealth’ or ‘gift.’<ref name=fx4_ve1_1423/> But it sometimes expresses ‘booty,’<ref name=fx5_ve1_1423/> probably from the notion of ‘wealth’ rather than of ‘prize.’<br>

धन-धानी
<u>'''Dhana-dhānī,'''</u> a ‘treasure house,’ is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (x. 67).<br>

धनिष्ठा
<u>'''Dhaniṣṭhā'''</u> (‘very rich’), used in the plural, is the later name<ref name=fx1_ve1_1425/> of the lunar mansion '''([[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]]) Śraviṣṭhā.'''<br>

धनु
<u>'''Dhanu'''</u> (fem.), ‘sandbank,’ occurs several times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1426/> but only metaphorically of the clouds in the atmosphere. Dhanū is found in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1426/> where it seems to denote a sandbag used to prevent bleeding.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1426/> ''Cf.'' '''[[धन्वन्|Dhanvan]].'''<br>

धनुस्
<u>'''Dhanus,'''</u> the ‘bow,’ frequently mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1427/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1427/> was the chief weapon of the Vedic Indian.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1427/> The last act of the funeral rite included the removal of the bow from  the right hand of the dead man.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1427/> The weapon was composed of a stout staff bent into a curved shape (''vakra''),<ref name=fx5_ve1_1427/> and of a bowstring ('''[[ज्या|Jyā]]''') made of a strip of cowhide<ref name=fx6_ve1_1427/> which joined the ends. The tips of the bow, when the string was fastened, were called '''[[आर्त्नी|Ārtnī]].''' Relaxed when not in actual use, the bow was specially strung up when needed for shooting.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1427/> The stages of the process are given in detail in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā:<ref name=fx8_ve1_1427/> the stringing (''ā-tan'') of the bow, the placing (''[[प्रति-धा|prati-dhā]]'') of the arrow, the bending (''ā-yam'') of the bow, and the shooting (''as''). The arrow was discharged from the ear,<ref name=fx9_ve1_1427/> and is hence called ''karṇa-yoni,''<ref name=fx10_ve1_1427/> ‘having the ear as its point of origin.’<ref name=fx10_ve1_1427/> The making of bows was a regular profession (''dhanuṣ-kāra,''<ref name=fx11_ve1_1427/> ''dhanuṣ-kṛt'').<ref name=fx12_ve1_1427/> For the arrow see '''[[इषु|Iṣu]],''' and for the handguard '''[[हस्तघ्न|Hastaghna]].'''<br>

धन्वन्
<u>'''1. Dhanvan,'''</u> ‘bow,’ is found frequently in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1428/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1428/> It also occurs in the compounds ''[[इषु|iṣu]]-dhanva,'' ‘bow and arrow,’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1428/> ''[[आज्य|ājya]]-dhanva,''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1428/> ‘having clarified butter for its bow,’<ref name=fx5_ve1_1428/> ''adhijya-dhanva,'' ‘bow with string fixed,’ etc. ''Cf.'' '''[[धनुस्|Dhanus]].'''<br>

धन्वन्
<u>'''2. Dhanvan,'''</u> ‘desert,’ is repeatedly mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1429/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1429/> Death from thirst in the desert was not rare,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1429/> and  the value of a spring in the desert was fully appreciated.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1429/> The great desert east of the '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]''' (Indus) and the '''[[शुतुद्री|Śutudrī]]''' (Sutlej) is possibly referred to in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1429/><br>

धमनि
<u>'''Dhamani,'''</u> ‘reed,’ appears to denote ‘pipe’ in a passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1430/> and in a citation appearing in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1430/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1430/> it denotes, perhaps, ‘artery’ or ‘vein,’ or more generally ‘intestinal channel,’ being coupled in some passages<ref name=fx4_ve1_1430/> with '''[[हिरा|Hirā]].'''<br>

धरुण
<u>'''Dharuṇa'''</u> in one passage of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (viii. 51) denotes a ‘sucking calf.’<br>

धर्म
<u>'''Dharma,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1432/> '''Dharman,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1432/> are the regular words, the latter in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1432/> and both later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1432/> for ‘law’ or ‘custom.’ But there is very little evidence in the early literature as to the administration of justice or the code of law followed. On the other hand, the [[धर्म|Dharma]] Sūtras<ref name=fx3_ve1_1432/> contain full particulars.<br><br>(1) ''Criminal Law.''--The crimes recognized in Vedic literature vary greatly in importance, while there is no distinction adopted in principle between real crimes and what now are regarded as fanciful bodily defects or infringements of merely  conventional practices.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1432/> The crimes enumerated include the slaying of an embryo (''bhrūṇa''),<ref name=fx5_ve1_1432/> the slaying of a man (''[[वीर|vīra]]''),<ref name=fx6_ve1_1432/> and  the slaying of a Brahmin,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1432/> a much more serious crime. Treachery is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_1432/> as being punishable by death, as it was punished later.<ref name=fx9_ve1_1432/> But there is no trace of an organized criminal justice vested either in the king or in the people. There still seems to have prevailed the system of wergeld ('''[[वैर|Vaira]]'''), which indicates that criminal justice remained in the hands of those who were wronged. In the Sūtras,<ref name=fx10_ve1_1432/> on the other hand, the king's peace is recognized as infringed by crimes, a penalty being paid to him, or, according to the Brahminical textbooks, to the Brahmins. It may there-  fore reasonably be conjectured that the royal power of jurisdiction steadily increased; the references in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] to the king as wielding punishment ('''[[दण्ड|Daṇḍa]]''') confirm this supposition. Whether, as the analogy of other systems suggests, the king was assisted in his judicial duties, as he undoubtedly was later, by assessors, presumably of the Brahmin caste, cannot be made out clearly.<ref name=fx11_ve1_1432/><br><br>The procedure adopted in deciding cases is quite uncertain. In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx12_ve1_1432/> the ordeal of the red-hot axe is mentioned as applied in an accusation of theft. It must apparently be understood to have been inflicted by the direction of the king. But no other judicial ordeal is known to Vedic literature (see '''[[दिव्य|Divya]]'''). The punishment of theft was in some cases at least death, probably when the thief was taken redhanded;<ref name=fx13_ve1_1432/> in other cases binding to posts was the penalty,<ref name=fx14_ve1_1432/> presumably accompanied by the return of the stolen goods. In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx15_ve1_1432/> the list of sins given as apparently equal in wickedness is stealing gold, drinking spirits, defiling a Guru's bed, and the murder of a Brahmin.<br><br>(2) ''Civil Law.''--There is little recorded as to civil law in Vedic literature. The relations of the family and the question of family property are dealt with under '''[[उर्वरा|Urvarā]], [[क्षेत्र|Kṣetra]], Pati;''' succession and partition of property are treated under '''[[दाय|Dāya]].''' As regards the transfer of chattels--for land as transferable ''inter vivos'' is hardly yet recognized, save exceptionally as a sacrificial fee ('''[[दक्षिणा|Dakṣiṇā]]'''), and then disapproved<ref name=fx16_ve1_1432/> --the recognized modes are gift ('''[[दान|Dāna]]''') and barter or sale ('''[[क्रय|Kraya]]'''), which includes exchange. Original acquisition of land was no doubt brought  about by occupation and apportionment among the tribesmen,<ref name=fx17_ve1_1432/> while chattels were acquired by taking possession of them, provided that they were found on one's own land or on unoccupied land, and did not belong to any other person originally. The Sūtras<ref name=fx18_ve1_1432/> contain rules for the disposal of lost property, which tend to give it to the king, with the deduction of a percentage for the finder, unless the latter is a Brahmin, who keeps it all. As for contract, save in regard to moneylending (for which see '''[[ऋण|Ṛṇa]]'''), practically nothing is to be gathered from Vedic literature, doubtless because of the primitive conditions prevailing in that early period. Much of the labour, which would in a more developed society have been done by workers for hire, would be performed by slaves (''cf.'' '''[[दास|Dāsa]], [[शूद्र|Śūdra]]'''), while the technical workers of the village--of whom long lists are given in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx19_ve1_1432/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx20_ve1_1432/> --may have been recompensed not by any sum based on each piece of work done, but by fixed allowances, much as the village servants are in modern times.<ref name=fx21_ve1_1432/> But this must remain a matter of conjecture, and it is uncertain what exact status the carpenter or smith held in the village. Similarly it is impossible to trace in the early literature any legal theory or practice as to torts, but rules as to penalties for insults appear in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx22_ve1_1432/><br><br>Very little is recorded as to procedure. The list<ref name=fx23_ve1_1432/> of victims at the Puruṣamedha, or ‘horse sacrifice,’ includes a ''praśnin,'' an ''[[अभि-प्रश्निन्|abhi-praśnin]],'' and a ''[[प्रश्न|praśna]]-vivāka,'' in whom it is not unreasonable to see the plaintiff, the defendant, and the arbitrator or judge: the terms may refer to what is probably an early  form of judicial procedure, a voluntary arbitration. The same idea may be conveyed by the word ''[[मध्यम-शी|madhyama-śī]],'' ‘lying in the midst,’ which occurs in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx24_ve1_1432/> and which Roth,<ref name=fx25_ve1_1432/> followed by Zimmer,<ref name=fx26_ve1_1432/> understood to mean an arbitrator or judge, the expression being derived from the judge acting with other judicial persons,<ref name=fx27_ve1_1432/> and being surrounded by the assembly of the people. But this interpretation is uncertain; Whitney<ref name=fx28_ve1_1432/> thinks that the word merely alludes to a chief round whom his men encamp. The king is later the chief civil judge, and may presumably have been so earlier, no doubt in conjunction with the elders of the tribe, but for this we are reduced to conjecture.<ref name=fx29_ve1_1432/><br><br>The use of witnesses as evidence is uncertain (see '''[[ज्ञातृ|Jñātṛ]]'''), and the ordeal is not recorded as deciding any civil matter except the dispute between '''[[वत्स|Vatsa]]''' and his rival as to the true Brahminical descent of the former, which was settled by his walking unharmed through the flame of a fire.<ref name=fx30_ve1_1432/> But it is probable on analogy that the ordeal may have been used for the purpose of deciding disputes. Whether the oath was so used cannot be certainly shown. It appears, however, that a Brahmin was preferred in legal matters to a non-Brahmin.<ref name=fx31_ve1_1432/><br><br>There are very few references to police officials: no doubt the king employed some of his dependents to execute sentences and arrest offenders (see '''Ugra, [[जीवगृभ्|Jīvagṛbh]]''').<br><br>(3) ''Morality.''--It is convenient to notice under this head  several points bearing on the moral condition of the people: (''a'') the exposure of children; (''b'') the exposure of the aged; (''c'') prostitution; (''d'') adultery; (''e'') incest.<br><br>(''a'') The exposure of girl infants is asserted by Zimmer<ref name=fx32_ve1_1432/> on the strength of a passage in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx33_ve1_1432/> but it seems clear that the passage has been misunderstood,<ref name=fx34_ve1_1432/> and that it refers merely to laying the child aside, not exposing it, while a boy was lifted up. It is, however, true that the birth of a girl was not at all popular, not an unnatural sentiment in an early society, and paralleled among other Āryan peoples.<ref name=fx35_ve1_1432/><br><br>(''b'') The exposure of the aged is also inferred by Zimmer<ref name=fx36_ve1_1432/> from a passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx37_ve1_1432/> and from the mention of persons exposed (''ud-hitāḥ'') in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx38_ve1_1432/> The latter passage may well refer merely to the bodies being exposed after death to the elements (as is done by the Parsis). The former passage merely refers to the individual case of some person who may have been cast out, and proves absolutely nothing as to a habitual or recognized custom, nor can such a custom be inferred from, ''e.g.,'' the legend of '''Cyavāna.'''<br><br>(''c'') That prostitution existed in Rigvedic times is certain, but its extent is disputed. Brotherless girls were frequently reduced to becoming prostitutes;<ref name=fx39_ve1_1432/> the putting away of an illegitimate child is referred to in the Rigveda;<ref name=fx40_ve1_1432/> besides the  terms ''[[पुंश्चली|puṃścalī]]''<ref name=fx41_ve1_1432/> and ''[[महानग्नी|mahānagnī]],''<ref name=fx42_ve1_1432/> which undoubtedly mean ‘harlot,’ there are other clear references to prostitution;<ref name=fx43_ve1_1432/> and expressions like ''kumārī-[[पुत्र|putra]],'' ‘son of a maiden,’<ref name=fx44_ve1_1432/> and the ‘son of an unmarried girl’ (''agrū''), spoken of in the Rigveda<ref name=fx45_ve1_1432/> as exposed and attacked by animals, point in the same direction. The Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx46_ve1_1432/> seems to recognize prostitution as a profession. Pischel<ref name=fx47_ve1_1432/> sees many references to Hetairai in the Rigveda, which as Geldner<ref name=fx48_ve1_1432/> insists reflects in its imagery the court life of Indian princes. But the correctness of the view of these two scholars on this point is not by any means certain.<ref name=fx49_ve1_1432/><br><br>(''d'') Adultery was generally regarded among Āryan peoples as a serious offence against the husband of the woman affected. We accordingly find in the legal literature of India traces of the rule that an adulterer can be slain with impunity if taken in the act.<ref name=fx50_ve1_1432/> Weber,<ref name=fx51_ve1_1432/> however, has adduced some material indicating an indifference to these matters in Vedic times, and Ludwig<ref name=fx52_ve1_1432/> has adopted the same view. But, as Delbrück<ref name=fx53_ve1_1432/> has clearly shown, the evidence is not convincing; the cited prescriptions<ref name=fx54_ve1_1432/> forbidding connexion with another man's wife during a certain rite do not imply that such connexion would otherwise be allowed: the ritual of the Varuṇa-praghāsas,<ref name=fx55_ve1_1432/> when a wife names her lover or lovers, seems originally to have been a solemn means of banishing the evil brought on a family by a wife's fall; '''Yājñavalkya's''' famous saying<ref name=fx56_ve1_1432/> that no one  cares whether a wife is ‘unchaste’ (''paraḥ-puṃsā'') or not is a mere mistranslation,<ref name=fx57_ve1_1432/> the expression ''paraḥ-puṃsā'' really meaning ‘removed from the male persons.’ And the uncertainty asserted in some passages<ref name=fx58_ve1_1432/> as to origin from a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] is not a sign of doubtful descent, but is due to the fact that Ṛṣihood was a difficult matter to ascertain. None the less woman's position was lowered by the prevalence of polygamy, and such stories as that of Ahalyā and Indra<ref name=fx59_ve1_1432/> are not compatible with a very high standard of morality. A similar conclusion is pointed to by references in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx60_ve1_1432/> to relations between the [[आर्य|Ārya]] man and the [[शूद्रा|Śūdrā]] woman, and by a spell given in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx61_ve1_1432/> to expiate relations with the wife of a [[श्रोत्रिय|Śrotriya]] (Brahmin theologian).<br><br>(''e'') Incest was recognized in the marriage of brother and sister as appears from the legend of Yama and Yamī in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx62_ve1_1432/> which clearly shows that such a marriage was not approved by the feeling of the Vedic age. There is also another hymn<ref name=fx63_ve1_1432/> in which reference to such intercourse appears to be made. Mention is further made in the Rigveda<ref name=fx64_ve1_1432/> to the wedlock of Prajāpati and his daughter, which is, however, interpreted mythologically in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx65_ve1_1432/> an interpretation which may be correct. That incest, however, actually did take place is clear from the Atharvaveda;<ref name=fx66_ve1_1432/> but even though the mythological interpretation of the passage were not justified, no conclusion could be drawn from the hymn as to the normal occurrence of such relations.<br>

धव
<u>'''1. Dhava'''</u> is the name of a tree (''Grislea tormentosa'') mentioned, together with the '''[[प्लक्ष|Plakṣa]], [[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]],''' and '''Khādira,''' in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1433/> <br>

धव
<u>'''2. Dhava,'''</u> ‘man,’ is not found before the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1434/> The word clearly owes its existence merely to ''[[विधवा|vidhavā]],'' ‘widow,’ wrongly interpreted as ''vi-dhavā,'' ‘without a husband.’<br>

धवित्र
<u>'''Dhavitra,'''</u> occurring in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1435/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1435/> denotes a ‘fan’ of hide or leather for blowing the sacrificial fire.<br>

धानं-जय्य
<u>'''Dhānaṃ-jayya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Dhanaṃ-jaya,'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[अंशु|Aṃśu]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1436/><br>

धाना
<u>'''Dhānā,'''</u> always used in the plural, and frequently referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1437/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1437/> means ‘grains of corn.’ They were sometimes parched (''bhṛjj''),<ref name=fx3_ve1_1437/> and were regularly mixed with Soma.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1437/><br>

धान्य
<u>'''Dhānya'''</u> (neut.), a derivative from the preceding word,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1438/> denotes ‘grain’ in general. It is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1438/> and later.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1438/> According to the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_1438/> there are ten cultivated (''grāmyāṇi'') kinds of grain: rice and barley (''vrīhiyavāḥ''), sesamum and beans (''tila-māṣāḥ''), Panicum Miliaceum and Italicum (''[[अणु|aṇu]]-priyaṅgavaḥ''), maize (''godhūmāḥ''), lentils (''masūrāḥ''), Khalvāḥ and Dolichos uniflorus (''[[खल|khala]]-kulāḥ''). The  horse is called ‘corn-eating’ (''dhānyāda'') in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1438/> and Śatapatha<ref name=fx6_ve1_1438/> Brāhmaṇas, and men are mentioned as ‘purifying corn’ (''dhānyā-kṛt'') in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1438/>(**  7 Lit., ‘preparing corn.’<br>

धान्व
<u>'''Dhānva'''</u> is the patronymic of '''[[असित|Asita]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1439/> In the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1439/> the form of the name is Dhānvana.<br>

धामन्
<u>'''Dhāman'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1440/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1440/> ‘dwelling’ and ‘house,’ or sometimes<ref name=fx3_ve1_1440/> its inmates. The word is also<ref name=fx4_ve1_1440/> found in the sense of ‘ordinance,’ ‘law,’ expressing much the same as '''Dharman,''' especially in conjunction<ref name=fx5_ve1_1440/> with Rta, ‘eternal order.’ Hillebrandt<ref name=fx6_ve1_1440/> sees in one passage<ref name=fx7_ve1_1440/> the sense of '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

धारा
<u>'''Dhārā'''</u> denotes the ‘edge’ of a weapon,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1441/> as of an axe (''[[स्वधिति|svadhiti]]''),<ref name=fx2_ve1_1441/> or of a razor (''[[क्षुर|kṣura]]'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_1441/> See also '''Asi.'''<br>

धिषणा
<u>'''Dhiṣaṇā,'''</u> according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, denotes<ref name=fx1_ve1_1442/> an implement used in preparing the Soma, ‘bowl’ or ‘vat,’ and by metonymy also the Soma draught itself.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1442/> The dual, by  a metaphor,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1442/> also expresses the ‘two worlds,’ heaven and earth.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1442/> Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1442/> however, thinks that the word properly means earth,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1442/> in the dual heaven and earth,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1442/> in the plural the triad, earth, atmosphere, and heaven,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1442/> while in some passages<ref name=fx9_ve1_1442/> [[धिषणा|Dhiṣaṇā]] denotes the Vedi, the excavated ground used as an altar. This is not, however, certain, while it seems clear that the Vājasaneyi<ref name=fx10_ve1_1442/> and [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]]<ref name=fx11_ve1_1442/> Saṃhitās understand the Dhiṣaṇās (dual) to be the planks over which the pressing of the Soma took place (''[[अधिषवण|adhiṣavaṇa]]-phalake'').<ref name=fx12_ve1_1442/> Pischel<ref name=fx13_ve1_1442/> sees in [[धिषणा|Dhiṣaṇā]] a goddess of wealth akin to Aditi and the earth.<br>

धी
<u>'''Dhī,'''</u> ‘thought,’ is used several times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1443/> to denote the ‘prayer’ or ‘hymn of praise’ of the singer. One poet speaks of himself as ‘weaving’ such a prayer,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1443/> while another refers to his ‘ancient ancestral hymn,’ which he refurbishes presumably for use.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1443/><br>

धीति
<u>'''Dhīti'''</u> has in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1444/> practically the same sense as '''[[धी|Dhī]],''' ‘prayer,’ or ‘hymn of praise.’<br>

धीर शात-पर्णेय
<u>'''Dhīra Śāta-parṇeya'''</u> (‘descendant of Śataparṇa’) is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 3, 3, 1) as a pupil of '''[[महाशाल|Mahāśāla]].''' <br>

धीवन्
<u>'''Dhīvan'''</u> occurs in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1446/> where it may either be taken with Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1446/> Bloomfield,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1446/> and Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve1_1446/> as an epithet of ‘chariot-builders’ (''[[रथ|ratha]]-kārāḥ''), meaning ‘clever,’ or be construed with the scholiast as denoting ‘fishermen’ (''dhīvara''). The Paippalāda recension has ''takṣāṇaḥ,'' ‘carpenters.’<br>

धुङ्क्षा
<u>'''Dhuṅkṣā'''</u> is the name of some sort of bird in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or ‘horse sacrifice,’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1447/> See also '''[[धूङ्क्ष्णा|Dhūṅkṣṇā]]''' and '''[[ध्वाङ्क्ष|Dhvāṅkṣa]].'''<br>

धुनि
<u>'''Dhuni'''</u> is the name of a foe of Indra, normally mentioned along with '''[[चुमुरि|Cumuri]]''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1448/> He and [[चुमुरि|Cumuri]] seem to have been opposed to '''[[दभीति|Dabhīti]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1448/> His name is probably that of an aboriginal chief.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1448/><br>

धुर्
<u>'''Dhur'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1449/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1449/> denotes, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, that part of the yoke which is placed on the shoulders of the animals drawing the chariot or cart, whence they are called ''dhūr-ṣāh,'' ‘yoke-bearing,’ in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1449/> In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1449/> the sense is uncertain: Roth<ref name=fx5_ve1_1449/> takes it to mean the pin at either end of the axle ('''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]]''') which goes through the nave of the wheel, and would thus be equivalent to '''[[आणि|Āṇi]],''' and Oldenberg<ref name=fx6_ve1_1449/>  seems to adopt the same view. Monier Williams<ref name=fx7_ve1_1449/> seems to think that ‘load’ is meant, but this is not probable. It is possible that Dhur has the sense of ‘pole,’<ref name=fx8_ve1_1449/> and then more generally still the pole and the axle together regarded as the drawing part of the chariot: this might explain the use in the doubtful passage of the Rigveda.<br>

धूङ्क्ष्णा
<u>'''Dhūṅkṣṇā'''</u> is the form in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1450/> of the name of the bird elsewhere found as '''[[धुङ्क्षा|Dhuṅkṣā]].''' It is glossed as ‘white crow’ (''śveta-kākī'').<br>

धूम-केतु
<u>'''Dhūma-ketu,'''</u> ‘smoke-bannered,’ is an epithet of [[मृत्यु|Mṛtyu]], ‘death,’ in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1451/> Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve1_1451/> thinks that a comet is meant, but Whitney<ref name=fx3_ve1_1451/> considers this extremely improbable. Lanman<ref name=fx4_ve1_1451/> plausibly suggests that the smoke of the funeral pile is referred to.<br>

धूम्र
<u>'''Dhūmra'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (i. 8, 21, 1) denotes ‘camel’ according to Bo7htlingk's Dictionary.<br>

धूर्-षद्
<u>'''Dhūr-ṣad'''</u> means, according to Roth,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1453/> ‘standing under the yoke’ and so ‘burden-bearing,’ and thus metaphorically ‘promoting,’ in the passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1453/> where it occurs. More probable, however, is the view<ref name=fx3_ve1_1453/> that it means ‘sitting on the pole,’ that is, ‘charioteer,’ with reference to the fact that  to get near his horses the charioteer might well go forward and sit on the pole or even on the yoke.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1453/><br>

धृत-राष्ट्र
<u>'''1. Dhṛta-rāṣṭra'''</u> (‘having his kingdom firmly established’) is the name of a snake demon with the patronymic '''[[ऐरावत|Airāvata]],''' ‘descendant of '''Irāvant,'''’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1454/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1454/><br>

धृतराष्ट्र वैचित्र-वीर्य
<u>'''2. Dhṛtarāṣṭra Vaicitra-vīrya'''</u> (‘descendant of Vicitravīrya’) is mentioned in a passage of the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1455/> which is, unhappily, far from intelligible. But there is no ground for supposing that he was a Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] king; he seems rather to have lived at some distance from the KuruPañcālas. There is no good reason to deny his identity<ref name=fx2_ve1_1455/> with the [[धृतराष्ट्र|Dhṛtarāṣṭra]] of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1455/> king of '''[[काशि|Kāśi]],''' who was defeated, when he attempted to offer a horse sacrifice, by '''[[सात्राजित|Sātrājita]] Śatānīka.''' The fact that the latter was a '''[[भरत|Bharata]]''' also points to Dhṛtarāṣṭra's not having been a Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] at all. In the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā he appears as having a dispute with '''Vaka [[दाल्भि|Dālbhi]];''' but even assuming that the latter was a [[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]], there is nothing to hint that the former was a Kuru or that this dispute is a sign of an early hostility of Kuru and [[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1455/> It is true that in the Epic '''Śantanu''' and Vicitravīrya and [[धृतराष्ट्र|Dhṛtarāṣṭra]] himself are all connected, but this connexion seems to be due, as so often in the Epic, to a confused derangement of great figures of the past.<br>

धृष्टि
<u>'''Dhṛṣṭi,'''</u> found in the dual in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1456/> the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1456/> and the Sūtras,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1456/> seems to denote ‘firetongs.’ <br>

धेना
<u>'''Dhenā'''</u> denotes a ‘milch cow,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1457/> or in the plural, ‘draughts of milk.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1457/> In two passages<ref name=fx3_ve1_1457/> Roth<ref name=fx4_ve1_1457/> takes the word to mean ‘mare,’ and in another the ‘team’ of Vāyu's chariot. Benfey,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1457/> on the other hand, renders it ‘lips’ in one passage,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1457/> with Sāyaṇa and with Durga's commentary on the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx8_ve1_1457/> Geldner<ref name=fx9_ve1_1457/> assigns to the word the senses of ‘lips,’<ref name=fx10_ve1_1457/> ‘speech,’<ref name=fx11_ve1_1457/> ‘cow,’<ref name=fx12_ve1_1457/> ‘beloved,’<ref name=fx13_ve1_1457/> and ‘streams.’<ref name=fx14_ve1_1457/>(**  5) Rv. i. 2, 3.<br>

धेनु
<u>'''Dhenu'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1458/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1458/> means ‘milch cow,’ which is often mentioned with special reference to the production of milk,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1458/> and is contrasted with the ‘bull’ (''[[वृषभ|vṛṣabha]],''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1458/> ''[[पुमांस्|pumāṃs]],''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1458/> ''[[अनड्वाह्|anaḍvāh]]'').<ref name=fx6_ve1_1458/> In the plural<ref name=fx7_ve1_1458/> the word denotes ‘draughts of milk.’ The derivative, ''dhenukā,'' means merely ‘female.’<ref name=fx8_ve1_1458/><br>

धेनु-ष्टरी
<u>'''Dhenu-ṣṭarī'''</u> in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] (xiii. 6) and Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (ii. 5, 4) denotes a cow which has ceased to give milk.<br>

धैवर
<u>'''Dhaivara'''</u> means a ‘fisherman,’ as a member of a caste,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1460/> in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha, or ‘human sacrifice,’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1460/> ''Cf.'' '''Dhīvara.''' <br>

ध्मातृ
<u>'''Dhmātṛ'''</u> (lit. ‘blower’) occurs twice in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1461/> in the two forms, ''dhmātā,'' nom. ‘smelter,’ and ''dhmātarī,'' which, according to the Padapāṭha, stands for ''dhmātari,'' a locative probably meaning ‘in the smelting furnace.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1461/> Geldner,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1461/> Bartholomae,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1461/> and Oldenburg<ref name=fx5_ve1_1461/> regard the latter form as a locative infinitive, ‘in the smelting.’ Ludwig<ref name=fx6_ve1_1461/> and Neisser<ref name=fx7_ve1_1461/> think ''dhmātarī'' is a nom. sing. masc. used in the same sense as ''dhmātā.'' Smelting is also clearly referred to,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1461/> and the smelter is described as using the wings of birds (''[[पर्ण|parṇa]] śakunānām'') to fan the flame.<ref name=fx9_ve1_1461/> That the art was widely applied is shown by the fact that reference is made to arrows with points of '''Ayas,'''<ref name=fx10_ve1_1461/> to kettles which were fashioned of the same metal and could be placed upon a fire,<ref name=fx11_ve1_1461/> and to Soma cups of beaten Ayas.<ref name=fx12_ve1_1461/><br>

ध्राजि
<u>'''Dhrāji'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1462/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1462/> denotes the ‘sweep’ of the wind, referring no doubt to the violent gales which often blow in India devastating the forests, and which figure in the descriptions of the Maruts, or storm gods.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1462/><br>

ध्रुव
<u>'''Dhruva'''</u> in the Sūtras<ref name=fx1_ve1_1463/> denotes the pole star, being mentioned in connexion with the marriage ritual, in which the star is pointed out to the bride as an emblem of constancy. In the  Maitrāyaṇī [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1463/> a late work, the movement of the [[ध्रुव|Dhruva]] (''dhruvasya pracalanam'') is mentioned, but this can hardly be interpreted as referring to an actual observed motion of the nominal pole star,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1463/> but rather to an extraordinary event, such as a destruction of the world, as Cowell understood the expression.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1463/> Jacobi<ref name=fx5_ve1_1463/> sees in the motion of the [[ध्रुव|Dhruva]] the possibility of fixing a date, on the ground that the only star which could have been deemed a pole star, as ‘immovable,’ was one (''a'' Draconis) of the third millenium B.C. But this attempt to extract chronology from the name of the star is of very doubtful validity.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1463/><br>

ध्रुवा
<u>'''Dhruvā,'''</u> ‘fixed,’ as an epithet of '''[[दिश्|Diś]],''' ‘cardinal point,’ denotes the ground under one's feet.(**  1) Av. iii. 27, 5; xii. 3, 59; xv. 6, 1; [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], viii. 14 (''cf.'' '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]]'''); Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]], iii. 9, 25, etc.<br>

ध्वज
<u>'''Dhvaja'''</u> occurs twice in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1465/> in the sense of ‘banner’ used in battle. It is characteristic of Vedic fighting that in both passages reference is made to arrows being discharged and falling on the banners.<br>

ध्वन्य
<u>'''Dhvanya'''</u> is apparently the name of a patron, son of '''Lakṣmaṇa,''' in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1466/> <br>

ध्वसन् द्वैत-वन
<u>'''Dhvasan Dvaita-vana'''</u> (‘descendant of Dvitavana’) is the name in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1467/> of the king of the '''Matsyas''' who celebrated an [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or ‘horse sacrifice,’ near the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].'''<br>

ध्वसन्ति
<u>'''Dhvasanti'''</u> is in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1468/> mentioned together with '''[[पुरुषन्ति|Puruṣanti]]''' as having been aided by the Aśvins. There can be no doubt that this is the longer form of the name '''[[ध्वस्र|Dhvasra]],''' which is found with [[पुरुषन्ति|Puruṣanti]] both in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1468/> and in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1468/><br>

ध्वस्र
<u>'''Dhvasra'''</u> is named with '''[[पुरुषन्ति|Puruṣanti]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1469/> as giving gifts to '''[[तरन्त|Taranta]]''' and '''Purumīḍha.''' These two, being kings, could not<ref name=fx2_ve1_1469/> properly accept gifts which Brāhmaṇas alone could accept, but by becoming authors of a verse of the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1469/> they qualified themselves to accept them. The verse mentions the names in the dual as ''Dhvasrayoḥ Puruṣantyoḥ,'' ‘from the two, [[ध्वस्र|Dhvasra]] and [[पुरुषन्ति|Puruṣanti]].’<ref name=fx4_ve1_1469/> In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1469/> the names occur in the dual as ''Dhvasre Puruṣantī,'' a reading which is confirmed by the [[निदान|Nidāna]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx6_ve1_1469/> The former is necessarily a feminine form, though Sāyaṇa, in his comment on the passage, explains it as really an irregular masculine. According to Roth,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1469/> the feminine is a corruption based on the dual form in the verse of the Rigveda mentioned above; but the names may be those of women,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1469/> as Benfey<ref name=fx9_ve1_1469/>  inclines to believe. Weber<ref name=fx10_ve1_1469/> suggests that the two were demons, but this is, as Sieg<ref name=fx11_ve1_1469/> shows, quite unnecessary. [[ध्वस्र|Dhvasra]] is no doubt identical with '''[[ध्वसन्ति|Dhvasanti]].'''<br>

ध्वाङ्क्ष
<u>'''Dhvāṅkṣa,'''</u> ‘crow,’ is mentioned twice in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1470/> and in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1470/> Possibly the same bird is meant by the words '''[[धुङ्क्षा|Dhuṅkṣā]]''' and '''Dhūṅksnā.'''<br>

ध्वान्त
<u>'''Dhvānta'''</u> is the name of some wind in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1471/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1471/><br>

नकुल
<u>'''Nakula,'''</u> ‘ichneumon,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1472/> as being able to cut a snake in two and then join it up again. Its knowledge<ref name=fx2_ve1_1472/> of a remedy against snake poison is also mentioned. The animal figures in the list of sacrificial victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or ‘horse sacrifice,’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1472/> <br>

नक्त
<u>'''Nakta,'''</u> ‘night,’ is found frequently in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1473/> and sometimes later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1473/> usually in the adverbial form ''naktaṃ,'' ‘by night’<br>

नक्षत्र
<u>'''Nakṣatra'''</u> is a word of obscure origin and derivation. The Indian interpreters already show a great divergence of opinion as to its primary meaning. The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1474/> resolves it into ''na-[[क्षत्र|kṣatra]]'' (‘no power’), explaining it by a legend. The [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1474/> refers it to the root ''nakṣ,'' ‘obtain,’ following the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1474/> Aufrecht<ref name=fx4_ve1_1474/> and Weber<ref name=fx5_ve1_1474/> derived it from ''[[नक्त|nakta]]-tra,'' ‘guardian of night,’ and more recently<ref name=fx6_ve1_1474/> the derivation from ''nak-[[क्षत्र|kṣatra]],'' ‘having rule over night,’ seems to be gaining acceptance. The generic meaning of the word therefore seems to be ‘star.’<br><br>''The Nakṣatras as Stars in the Rigveda and Later.''--The sense of ‘star’ appears to be adequate for all or nearly all the passages in which [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] occurs in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1474/> The same sense occurs in the later Saṃhitās also: the sun and the Nakṣatras are mentioned together,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1474/> or the sun, the moon, and the Nakṣatras,<ref name=fx9_ve1_1474/> or the moon and the Nakṣatras,<ref name=fx10_ve1_1474/> or the Nakṣatras alone;<ref name=fx11_ve1_1474/>  but there is no necessity to attribute to the word the sense of ‘lunar mansion’ in these passages.<br><br>On the other hand, the names of at least three of the Nakṣatras in the later sense occur in the Rigveda. [[तिष्य|Tiṣya]],<ref name=fx12_ve1_1474/> however, does not seem to be mentioned as a lunar mansion. With '''Aghās''' (plur.) and '''[[अर्जुनी|Arjunī]]''' (dual)<ref name=fx13_ve1_1474/> the case is different: it seems probable that they are the later lunar mansions called [[मघास्|Maghās]] (plur.) and [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]] (dual). The names appear to have been deliberately changed in the Rigveda, and it must be remembered that the hymn in which they occur, the wedding hymn of Sūryā, has no claim to great age.<ref name=fx14_ve1_1474/> Ludwig<ref name=fx15_ve1_1474/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx16_ve1_1474/> have seen other references to the Nakṣatras as 27 in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx17_ve1_1474/> but these seem most improbable. Nor do the adjectives ''[[रेवती|revatī]]'' (‘rich’) and ''punarvasā'' (‘bringing wealth again’) in another hymn<ref name=fx18_ve1_1474/> appear to refer to the Nakṣatras.<br><br>''The Nakṣatras as Lunar Mansions.''--In several passages of the later Saṃhitās the connexion of the moon and the Nakṣatras is conceived of as a marriage union. Thus in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]]<ref name=fx19_ve1_1474/> and [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx20_ve1_1474/> it is expressly stated that Soma was wedded to the mansions, but dwelt only with [[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]]; the others being angry, he had ultimately to undertake to live with them all equally. Weber<ref name=fx21_ve1_1474/> hence deduced that the Nakṣatras were regarded as of equal extent, but this is to press the texts unduly, except in the sense of approximate equality. The number of the mansions is not stated as 27 in the story told in the two Saṃhitās: the Taittīriya has 33, and the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] no  number; but 27 appears as their number in the list which is found in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx22_ve1_1474/> and elsewhere.<ref name=fx23_ve1_1474/> The number 28 is much less well attested: in one passage of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx24_ve1_1474/> [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]] is practically marked as a new comer, though in a later book,<ref name=fx25_ve1_1474/> in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx26_ve1_1474/> and in the Atharvaveda list,<ref name=fx27_ve1_1474/> it has found acceptance. It is perfectly possible that 28 is the earlier number, and that [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]] dropped out because it was faint, or too far north, or because 27 was a more mystic (3×3×3) number: it is significant that the Chinese Sieou and the Arabic Manāzil are 28 in number.<ref name=fx28_ve1_1474/> Weber,<ref name=fx29_ve1_1474/> however, believes that 27 is the older number in India.<br><br>The meaning of the number is easily explained when it is remembered that a periodic month occupies something between 27 and 28 days, more nearly the former number. Such a month is in fact recognized in the Lāṭyāyana<ref name=fx30_ve1_1474/> and [[निदान|Nidāna]] Sūtras<ref name=fx31_ve1_1474/> as consisting of 27 days, 12 months making a year of 324 days, a [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] year, or with an intercalary month, a year of 351 days. The [[निदान|Nidāna]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx32_ve1_1474/> makes an attempt to introduce the [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] reckoning into the civil or solar (''sāvana'') year of 360 days, for it holds that the sun spends 13(1/3) days in each [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] (13(1/3)×27 = 360). But the month of 27 or 28 days plays no part in the chronological calculations of the Veda.<ref name=fx33_ve1_1474/><br><br>''The Names of the Nakṣatras.''--In addition to the two mentioned in the Rigveda, the earlier Atharvaveda<ref name=fx34_ve1_1474/> gives the  names of [[ज्येष्ठघ्नी|Jyeṣṭhaghnī]]<ref name=fx35_ve1_1474/> (the later [[ज्येष्ठा|Jyeṣṭhā]]) and [[विचृतौ|Vicṛtau]],<ref name=fx36_ve1_1474/> which are mentioned as in close connexion, and of Revatīs (plural) and [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]].<ref name=fx37_ve1_1474/> With reference to possible times for the ceremony of the Agnyādhāna, or ‘laying of the sacred fires,’ the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx38_ve1_1474/> the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx39_ve1_1474/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx40_ve1_1474/> mention the Nakṣatras called [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]], [[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]], Phalgunyas, [[हस्त|Hasta]]; the latter [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] adds [[पुनर्वसू|Punarvasū]], and in an additional remark<ref name=fx41_ve1_1474/> excludes Pūrve [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]] in favour of Uttare [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]]. The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx42_ve1_1474/> adds [[मृगशीर्ष|Mṛgaśīrṣa]] and [[चित्रा|Citrā]] as possibilities. On the other hand, [[पुनर्वसू|Punarvasū]] is recommended by all authorities<ref name=fx43_ve1_1474/> as suitable for the Punarādheya, ‘relaying of the sacred fires,’ which takes place if the first fire has failed to effect the aim of its existence, the prosperity of the sacrificer.<ref name=fx44_ve1_1474/> The [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx45_ve1_1474/> however, allows Anurādhās also.<br><br>In the ceremony of the Agnicayana, or ‘piling of the firealtar,’ the bricks are assumed to be equal in number to the Nakṣatras. The bricks number 756, and they are equated to 27 Nakṣatras multiplied by 27 secondary Nakṣatras, reckoned as 720 (instead of 729), with the addition of 36 days, the length of an intercalary month. Nothing can be usefully derived from this piece of priestly nonsense.<ref name=fx46_ve1_1474/> But in connexion with this ceremony the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx47_ve1_1474/> enumerate the 27  Nakṣatras, and these lists<ref name=fx48_ve1_1474/> may be given ''in extenso'' as follows:<C1>''[[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.'' <C2>''Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhita.'' <C3>''[[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.''<C1>1. [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]] (fem. plur.) ... <C2>[[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]] ... ... ... <C3>[[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]]<C1>2. [[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]] ... ... ... <C2>[[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]] ... ... ... <C3>[[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]]<C1>3. [[मृगशीर्ष|Mṛgaśīrṣa]] (neut.) ... <C2>Invagā ... ... ... <C3>Invakā<C1>4. [[आर्द्रा|Ārdrā]] ... ... ... <C2>[[बाहु|Bāhu]] ... ... ... <C3>[[बाहु|Bāhu]]<C1>5. [[पुनर्वसू|Punarvasū]] (dual) ... <C2>[[पुनर्वसु|Punarvasu]] (sing.) ... ... <C3>[[पुनर्वसु|Punarvasu]]<C1>6. [[तिष्य|Tiṣya]] ... ... ... <C2>[[तिष्य|Tiṣya]] ... ... ... <C3>[[तिष्य|Tiṣya]]<C1>7. [[आश्रेषास्|Āśreṣās]] (fem. plur.) ... <C2>Āśleṣās(plur.; Pada Aśleṣā) <C3>Āśleṣās (or Aśleṣās)<C1>8. [[मघास्|Maghās]] (fem. plur.) ... <C2>[[मघास्|Maghās]] ... ... ... <C3>[[मघास्|Maghās]]<C1>9. [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]] (fem. dual) ... <C2>Phalgunīs (plur.) ... ... <C3>Phalgunis<C1>10. [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]] (fem. dual) ...<C2>Phalgunīs (plur.) ... ... <C3>Uttarāḥa Phalgunīs<C1>11. [[हस्त|Hasta]] ... ... ... <C2>[[हस्त|Hasta]] ... ... ... <C3>Hastau (dual)<C1>12. [[चित्रा|Citrā]] ... ... ... <C2>[[चित्रा|Citrā]] ... ... ... <C3>[[चित्रा|Citrā]]<C1>13. [[स्वाती|Svātī]] ... ... ... <C2>[[निष्ट्य|Niṣṭya]] (neut.) ... ... <C3>Niṣṭyā<C1>14. [[विशाखे|Viśākhe]] (fem. dual) ... <C2>Viśākha (neut. sing.) ... <C3>Viśākhā (fem. sing.)<C1>15. [[अनूराधास्|Anūrādhās]] (plur.) ... <C2>Anūrādhā (Pada Anu-[[अनूराधास्|Anūrādhās]] (masc. rādhā) <C3>[[अनूराधास्|Anūrādhās]] (masc. plur.)<C1>16. [[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]] ... ... ... <C2>[[ज्येष्ठा|Jyeṣṭhā]] ... ... ... <C3>[[ज्येष्ठा|Jyeṣṭhā]]<C1>17. [[विचृतौ|Vicṛtau]] ... ... ... <C2>[[मूल|Mūla]] (neut.) ... ... <C3>[[मूल|Mūla]]<C1>18. Aṣāḍhās (fem. plur.) ... <C2>Aṣāḍhās ... ... ... <C3>Aṣāḍhās<C1>19. Aṣāḍhās (fem. plur.) ... <C2>Aṣāḍhās ... ... ...<C3>Uttarā Aṣāḍhās<C1>20. <C2>[[अभिजित्|Abhijit]] ... ... ...<C1>21. [[श्रोणा|Śroṇā]] ... ... ... <C2>[[श्रोणा|Śroṇā]] ... ... ... <C3>[[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]]<C1>22. [[श्रविष्ठास्|Śraviṣṭhās]] (plur.) ... <C2>[[श्रविष्ठास्|Śraviṣṭhās]] ... ... ... <C3>[[श्रविष्ठास्|Śraviṣṭhās]]<C1>23. [[शतभिषज्|Śatabhiṣaj]] ... ... <C2>[[शतभिषज्|Śatabhiṣaj]] ... ... ... <C3>[[शतभिषज्|Śatabhiṣaj]]<C1>24. Proṣṭhapadās (masc. plur.) <C2>Proṣṭhapadās ... ... <C3>Proṣṭhapadās<C1>25. Proṣṭhapadās(masc. plur.) <C2>Proṣṭhapadās ... ... <C3>Uttare Proṣṭhapadās<C1>26. [[रेवती|Revatī]] ... ... ... <C2>[[रेवती|Revatī]] ... ... ... <C3>[[रेवती|Revatī]]<C1>27. [[अश्वयुजौ|Aśvayujau]] (dual) ... <C2>[[अश्वयुजौ|Aśvayujau]] ... ... ... <C3>[[अश्वयुजौ|Aśvayujau]]<C1>28. [[अपभरणीस्|Apabharaṇīs]] (fem. plur.) <C2>Bharaṇīs ... ... ... <C3>[[अपभरणीस्|Apabharaṇīs]]<br><br>The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Brahmaṇa<ref name=fx49_ve1_1474/> has a list of the Nakṣatras which agrees generally with the list of the Saṃhitās. It runs as follows: [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]], [[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]], Invakās, Bāhū (dual), [[तिष्य|Tiṣya]], Āśleṣās, [[मघास्|Maghās]], Pūrve [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]], Uttare [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]], [[हस्त|Hasta]], [[चित्रा|Citrā]], Niṣṭyā, [[विशाखे|Viśākhe]], [[अनूराधास्|Anūrādhās]], [[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]], Mūlabarhaṇī, Pūrvā Aṣāḍhās, Uttarā Aṣāḍhās, [[श्रोणा|Śroṇā]], [[श्रविष्ठास्|Śraviṣṭhās]], [[शतभिषज्|Śatabhiṣaj]], Pūrve Proṣṭhapadās, Uttare Proṣṭhapadās, [[रेवती|Revatī]], [[अश्वयुजौ|Aśvayujau]], [[अपभरणीस्|Apabharaṇīs]]. In a later book,<ref name=fx50_ve1_1474/> however, the list grows to 28,  and the full moon is inserted after number 14, and the new moon after number 28, as an attempt to bring the Nākṣatra (lunar) month into accordance with the Sāvana (solar) month of 30 days. The names in this second list are as in the Saṃhitās with the following exceptions. The seven stars of the [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]] are named as Ambā, [[दुला|Dulā]], [[नितत्नी|Nitatnī]], Abhrayantī, Meghayantī, Varṣayantī, Cupuṇīkā, names found also in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]]<ref name=fx51_ve1_1474/> and [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx52_ve1_1474/> Beside [[मृगशीर्ष|Mṛgaśīrṣa]], Invakās are also mentioned.<ref name=fx53_ve1_1474/> Then come [[आर्द्रा|Ārdrā]], [[पुनर्वसू|Punarvasū]], [[तिष्य|Tiṣya]], [[आश्रेषास्|Āśreṣās]], [[मघास्|Maghās]] (beside which Anaghās, Agadās, and Arundhatīs are also mentioned), Phalgunyas (but elsewhere in the dual, Phalgunyau),<ref name=fx54_ve1_1474/> Phalgunyas, [[हस्त|Hasta]], [[चित्रा|Citrā]], Niṣṭyā, [[विशाखे|Viśākhe]], [[अनूराधास्|Anūrādhās]], [[ज्येष्ठा|Jyeṣṭhā]], [[मूल|Mūla]], Aṣāḍhās, Aṣāḍhās, [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]], Śronā, [[श्रविष्ठास्|Śraviṣṭhās]], [[शतभिषज्|Śatabhiṣaj]], Proṣṭhapadās, Proṣṭhapadās, [[रेवती|Revatī]], [[अश्वयुजौ|Aśvayujau]], Bharaṇyas, but also [[अपभरणीस्|Apabharaṇīs]].<ref name=fx55_ve1_1474/> [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]], which occurs also in an earlier part of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx56_ve1_1474/> is perhaps interpolated. But Weber's<ref name=fx57_ve1_1474/> argument that [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]] is out of place in this list because [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] is here mentioned as the 28th [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]], loses some force from the fact (of course unknown to him) that the list in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx58_ve1_1474/> contains 28 Nakṣatras, including [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]], and adds [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] at the end as another.<br><br>In another passage<ref name=fx59_ve1_1474/> the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] divides the Nakṣatras into two sets, the Deva Nakṣatras and the Yama Nakṣatras, being 1-14 and 15-27 (with the omission of [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]]) respectively. This division corresponds with one in the third book of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx60_ve1_1474/> where the days of the light half of the month and those of the dark half are equated with the Nakṣatras. The [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] treats the former series as south, the latter as north; but this has no relation to facts, and can only be regarded as a ritual absurdity.<br><br>The late nineteenth book of the Atharvaveda contains a list<ref name=fx61_ve1_1474/> of the Nakṣatras, including [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]]. The names here  given are: [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]], [[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]], [[मृगशिरस्|Mṛgaśiras]], [[आर्द्रा|Ārdrā]], [[पुनर्वसू|Punarvasū]], [[पुष्य|Puṣya]], Āśleṣās, [[मघास्|Maghās]], Pūrvā Phalgunyau (''sic''),<ref name=fx62_ve1_1474/> [[हस्त|Hasta]], [[चित्रा|Citrā]], Svāti (masc.),<ref name=fx63_ve1_1474/> [[विशाखे|Viśākhe]], [[अनुराधा|Anurādhā]],<ref name=fx64_ve1_1474/> [[ज्येष्ठा|Jyeṣṭhā]], [[मूल|Mūla]], Pūrvā Aṣāḍhās,<ref name=fx65_ve1_1474/> Uttarā Aṣāḍhās, [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]], [[श्रवण|Śravaṇa]], [[श्रविष्ठास्|Śraviṣṭhās]], [[शतभिषज्|Śatabhiṣaj]], Dvayā Proṣṭhapadā, [[रेवती|Revatī]], [[अश्वयुजौ|Aśvayujau]], Bharaṇyas.<br><br>''The Position of the Nakṣatras.''--There is nothing definite in Vedic literature regarding the position of most of the Nakṣatras, but the later astronomy precisely locates all of them, and its statements agree on the whole satisfactorily with what is said in the earlier texts, though Weber<ref name=fx66_ve1_1474/> was inclined to doubt this. The determinations adopted below are due to Whitney<ref name=fx67_ve1_1474/> in his notes on the [[सूर्य|Sūrya]] Siddhānta.<br>

कृत्तिकास्
<u>'''1. Kṛttikās'''</u> are unquestionably  Tauri, etc., the Pleiades. The names of the seven stars forming this constellation, and given above from [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] texts,<ref name=fx68_ve1_1475/> include three--''abhrayantī,'' ‘forming clouds’; ''meghayantī,'' ‘making cloudy’; ''varṣayantī,'' ‘causing rain’--which clearly refer to the rainy Pleiades. The word ''kṛttikā'' possibly means ‘web,’ from the root ''kṛt,'' ‘spin.’<br>

रोहिणी
<u>'''2. Rohiṇī,'''</u> ‘ruddy,’ is the name of the conspicuously reddish star, ''a'' Tauri or Aldebaran, and denotes the group of the Hyades,  Tauri. Its identification seems absolutely assured by the legend of Prajāpati in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx69_ve1_1476/> He is there represented as pursuing his daughter with incestuous intention, and as having been shot with an arrow ('''[[इषु त्रिकाण्डा|Iṣu Trikāṇḍā]],''' ‘the belt of Orion’) by the ‘huntsman’ ('''[[मृगव्याध|Mṛgavyādha]],''' ‘Sirius’). Prajāpati is clearly Orion ([[मृगशिरस्|Mṛgaśiras]] being the name of the little group of stars in Orion's head).<br>

मृगशीर्ष
<u>'''3. Mṛgaśīrṣa'''</u> or '''[[मृगशिरस्|Mṛgaśiras]],''' also called Invakā or Invagā,  seems to be the faint stars , Orionis. They are called Andhakā, ‘blind,’ in the Śāntikalpa of the Atharvaveda, probably because of their dimness.<ref name=fx70_ve1_1477/><br>

आर्द्रा
<u>'''4. Ārdrā,'''</u> ‘moist,’ is the name of the brilliant star,  Orionis. But the names by which it is styled, in the plural as Ārdrās in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx71_ve1_1478/> and the Nakṣatrakalpa,<ref name=fx72_ve1_1478/> and in the dual as Bāhū, in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx73_ve1_1478/> point to a constellation of two or more stars, and it may be noted<ref name=fx74_ve1_1478/> that the corresponding Chinese Sieou includes the seven brilliant stars composing the shoulders, the belt, and the knees of Orion.<br>

पुनर्वसू
<u>'''5. Punarvasū,'''</u> ‘the two that give wealth again,’ denotes the two stars,  and  Geminorum, on the heads of Castor and Pollux. The name is no doubt connected with the beneficent character of the Aśvins, who correspond to the Dioscuri.<ref name=fx75_ve1_1479/><br>

तिष्य
<u>'''6. Tiṣya'''</u> or '''[[पुष्य|Puṣya]]''' includes the somewhat faint group in the body of the Crab, , and  Cancri. The singular is rather curious, as primarily one star would seem to have been meant. and none of the group is at all prominent.<ref name=fx76_ve1_1480/><br>

आश्रेषास्
<u>'''7. Āśreṣās'''</u> or '''Āśleṣās,''' which in some texts<ref name=fx77_ve1_1481/> is certainly to be read Aśreṣās or Aśleṣas, denotes , and perhaps also , Hydræ. The word means ‘embracer,’ a name which admirably fits the constellation.<br>

मघास्
<u>'''8. Maghās,'''</u> the ‘bounties,’ are the Sickle, or , Leonis. The variants '''Anaghā,''' the ‘sinless one,’ etc., clearly refer to the auspicious influence of the constellation.(**  9, 10. '''[[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]], Phalgunyau, Phalgū,'''<ref name=fx78_ve1_1482/> '''Phalgunīs, Phalgunyas,''' is really a-double constellation, divided into Pūrve, ‘former,’ and Uttare, ‘latter.’ The former is  and  Leonis, the latter  and 93 Leonis. According to Weber, the word denotes, like '''[[अर्जुनी|Arjunī]],''' the variant of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx79_ve1_1482/> a ‘brightcoloured’ constellation. <br>

हस्त
<u>'''11. Hasta,'''</u> ‘hand,’ is made up of the five conspicuous stars () in Corvus, a number which the word itself suggests. According to Geldner,<ref name=fx80_ve1_1483/> the ‘five bulls’ of the Rigveda are this constellation.<br>

चित्रा
<u>'''12. Citrā,'''</u> ‘bright,’ is the beautiful star,  Virginis. It is mentioned in a legend of Indra in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx81_ve1_1484/> and in that of the ‘two divine dogs’ (''divyau śvānau'') in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx82_ve1_1484/><br>

स्वाती
<u>'''13. Svātī'''</u> or '''Niṣṭyā''' is later clearly the brilliant star Arcturus or  Bootis, its place in the north being assured by the notice in the Śāntikalpa,<ref name=fx83_ve1_1485/> where it is said to be ‘ever traversing the northern way’ (''nityam uttara-mārgagam''). The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx84_ve1_1485/> however, constructs an asterismal Prajāpati, giving him [[चित्रा|Citrā]] (''a'' Virginis) for head, [[हस्त|Hasta]] (Corvus) for hand, the [[विशाखे|Viśākhe]] (''a'' and  Libræ) for thighs, and the Anurādhās (, and  Scorpionis) for standing place, with Niṣṭyā for heart. But Arcturus, being 30º out, spoils this figure, while, on the other hand, the Arabic and Chinese systems have respectively, instead of Arcturus, , and  Virginis and  Virginis, which would well fit into the Prajāpati figure. But in spite of the force of this argument of Weber's,<ref name=fx85_ve1_1485/> Whitney<ref name=fx86_ve1_1485/> is not certain that Niṣṭyā here must mean a star in Virgo, pointing out that the name Niṣṭyā, ‘outcast,’ suggests the separation of this [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] from the others in question.<br>

विशाखे
<u>'''14. Viśākhe'''</u> is the couple of stars  and  Libræ. This mansion is later called Rādhā according to the Amarakośa, and it is curious that in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx87_ve1_1486/> the expression ''rādho [[विशाखे|Viśākhe]],'' ‘the [[विशाखे|Viśākhe]] are prosperity,’ should occur. But probably Rādhā is merely an invention due to the name of the next [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]], [[अनुराधा|Anurādhā]], wrongly conceived as meaning ‘that which is after or follows Rādhā.’<ref name=fx88_ve1_1486/><br>

अनूराधास्
<u>'''15. Anūrādhās'''</u> or '''[[अनुराधा|Anurādhā]],''' ‘propitious,’ is , and  (perhaps also ) Scorpionis. <br>

रोहिणी
<u>'''16. Rohiṇī,'''</u> ‘ruddy’; '''[[ज्येष्ठघ्नी|Jyeṣṭhaghnī]],''' ‘slaying the eldest’; or '''[[ज्येष्ठा|Jyeṣṭhā]],''' ‘eldest,’ is the name of the constellation , and  Scorpionis, of which the central star, , is the brilliant reddish Antares (or Cor Scorpionis).<br>

विचृतौ
