अभिजित्
<u>'''20. Abhijit'''</u> is the brilliant star  Lyræ with its two companions  and . Its location in 60º north latitude is completely discordant with the position of the corresponding Arabian and Chinese asterisms. This fact is considered by Oldenberg<ref name=fx90_ve1_1490/> to support the view that it was a later addition to the system; its occurrence, however, as early as the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx91_ve1_1490/> which he does not note, somewhat invalidates<ref name=fx92_ve1_1490/> that view. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx93_ve1_1490/> [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]] is said to be ‘over Aṣāḍhās, under [[श्रोणा|Śroṇā]],’ which Weber<ref name=fx94_ve1_1490/> held to refer to its position in space, inferring thence that its Vedic position corresponded to that of the Arab Manāzil and the Chinese Sieou--viz., , Capricorni. But Whitney<ref name=fx95_ve1_1490/> argues effectively that the words ‘over’ and ‘under’ really refer to the place of [[अभिजित्|Abhijit]] in the list, ‘after’ Aṣāḍhās and ‘before’ [[श्रोणा|Śroṇā]].<br>

श्रोणा
<u>'''21. Śroṇā,'''</u> ‘lame,’ or '''[[श्रवण|Śravaṇa]],''' ‘ear,’ denotes the bright star Aquilæ with  below and  above it. Weber<ref name=fx96_ve1_1491/> very need-  lessly thinks that the name [[श्रवण|Śravaṇa]] suggested two ears and the head between. It is quite out of correspondence with the Manāzil and the Sieou, and is clearly an Indian invention.<ref name=fx97_ve1_1491/><br>

श्रविष्ठास्
<u>'''22. Śraviṣṭhās,'''</u> ‘most famous,’ or later '''Dhaniṣṭhās,'''<ref name=fx98_ve1_1492/> ‘most wealthy,’ is the diamond-shaped group, , and , in the Dolphin, perhaps also  in the same constellation. Like the preceding [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]], it is out of harmony with the Manāzil and Sieou.<br>

शतभिषज्
<u>'''23. Śatabhiṣaj'''</u> or '''Śatabhiṣa,'''<ref name=fx99_ve1_1493/> ‘having a hundred physicians,’ seems to be  Aquarii with the others around it vaguely conceived as numbering a hundred.(**  24, 25. '''[[प्रोष्ठ|Proṣṭha]]-padās''' (fem. plur.), ‘feet of a stool,’ or later '''Bhadra-padās,'''<ref name=fx100_ve1_1493/> ‘auspicious feet,’ a double asterism forming a square, the former (''pūrva'') consisting of  and  Pegasi, the latter (''uttara'') of  Pegasi and  Andromedæ.<br>

रेवती
<u>'''26. Revatī,'''</u> ‘wealthy,’ denotes a large number of stars (later 32), of which  Piscium, close upon the ecliptic where it was crossed by the equator of about 570 A.D., is given as the southernmost.<br>

अश्व-युजौ
<u>'''27. Aśva-yujau,'''</u> ‘the two horse-harnessers,’ denotes the stars and  Arietis. Aśvinyau<ref name=fx101_ve1_1495/> and [[अश्विनी|Aśvinī]]<ref name=fx102_ve1_1495/> are later names.<br>

भरणीस्
<u>'''28. Apabharaṇīs, Bharaṇīs,'''</u> or '''Bharaṇyas,''' ‘the bearers,’ is the name of the small triangle in the northern part of the Ram known as Musca or 35, 39, and 41 Arietis.<br><br>''The Nakṣatras and the Months.''--In the Brāhmaṇas the [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] names are regularly used to denote dates. This is done in two ways. The name, if not already a feminine, may be turned into a feminine and compounded with ''[[पूर्ण-मास|pūrṇa-māsa]],'' ‘the full moon,’ as in ''Tiṣyā-[[पूर्णमास|pūrṇamāsa]],'' ‘the full moon in the [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] [[तिष्य|Tiṣya]].’<ref name=fx103_ve1_1496/> Much more often, however, it is turned into a derivative adjective, used with ''[[पौर्णमासी|paurṇamāsī]],'' ‘the full  moon (night),’ or with ''amāvāsyā,'' ‘the new moon (night),’ as in ''Phālgunī [[पौर्णमासी|paurṇamāsī]],'' ‘the full-moon night in the [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] Phalgunī’;<ref name=fx104_ve1_1496/> or, as is usual in the Sūtras, the [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] adjective alone is used to denote the full-moon night. The month itself is called by a name derived<ref name=fx105_ve1_1496/> from that of a [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]], but only Phālguna,<ref name=fx106_ve1_1496/> [[चैत्र|Caitra]],<ref name=fx107_ve1_1496/> Vaiśākha,<ref name=fx108_ve1_1496/> Taiṣya,<ref name=fx109_ve1_1496/> Māgha<ref name=fx110_ve1_1496/> occur in the Brāhmaṇas, the complete list later being Phālguna, [[चैत्र|Caitra]], Vaiśākha, Jyaiṣṭha, Āṣāḍha, Śrāvaṇa, Prauṣṭhapada, Āśvayuja, Kārttika, Mārgaśīrṣa, Taiṣya, Māgha. Strictly speaking, these should be lunar months, but the use of a lunar year was clearly very restricted: we have seen that as early as the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] there was a tendency to equate lunar months with the twelve months of thirty days which made up the solar year (see '''[[मास|Māsa]]''').<br><br>''The Nakṣatras and Chronology.''--(1) An endeavour has been made to ascertain from the names of the months the period at which the systematic employment of those names was introduced. Sir William Jones<ref name=fx111_ve1_1496/> refers to this possibility, and Bentley, by the gratuitous assumption that Śrāvaṇa always marked the summer solstice, concluded that the names of the months did not date before B.C. 1181. Weber<ref name=fx112_ve1_1496/> considered that there was a possibility of fixing a date by this means, but Whitney<ref name=fx113_ve1_1496/> has convincingly shown that it is an impossible feat, and Thibaut<ref name=fx114_ve1_1496/> concurs in this view. Twelve became fixed as the number of the months because of the desire, evident in the Brāhmaṇas, somehow or other to harmonize lunar with solar time; but the selection of twelve Nakṣatras out of twenty-seven as connected with the night of full moon can have no chronological significance, because full moon at  no period occurred in those twelve only, but has at all periods occurred in every one of the twenty-seven at regularly recurrent intervals.<br><br>(2) All the lists of the Nakṣatras begin with Kṛttīkās. It is only fair to suppose that there was some special reason for this fact. Now the later list of the Nakṣatras begins with [[अश्विनी|Aśvinī]], and it was unquestionably rearranged because at the time of its adoption the vernal equinox coincided with the star  Piscium on the border of [[रेवती|Revatī]] and [[अश्विनी|Aśvinī]],<ref name=fx115_ve1_1496/> say in the course of the sixth century A.D. Weber<ref name=fx116_ve1_1496/> has therefore accepted the view that the [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]] were chosen for a similar reason, and the date at which that [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] coincided with the vernal equinox has been estimated at some period in the third millennium B.C.<ref name=fx117_ve1_1496/> A very grave objection to this view is its assumption that the sun, and not the moon, was then regarded as connected with the Nakṣatras; and both Thibaut<ref name=fx118_ve1_1496/> and Oldenberg<ref name=fx119_ve1_1496/> have pronounced decidedly against the idea of connecting the equinox with the [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]]. Jacobi<ref name=fx120_ve1_1496/> has contended that in the Rigveda<ref name=fx121_ve1_1496/> the commencement of the rains and the summer solstice mark the beginning of the new year and the end of the old, and that further the new year began with the summer solstice in [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]].<ref name=fx121_ve1_1496/> He has also referred to the distinction of the two sets of Deva and Yama Nakṣatras in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx122_ve1_1496/> as supporting his view of the connexion of the sun and the Nakṣatras. But this view is far from satisfactory: the Rigveda passages cannot yield the sense required except by translating the word ''[[द्वादश|dvādaśa]]''<ref name=fx123_ve1_1496/> as ‘the twelfth (month)’ instead of ‘consisting of twelve parts,’ that is, ‘year,’ the accepted  interpretation; and the division of the Nakṣatras is not at all satisfactorily explained by a supposed connexion with the sun. It may further be mentioned that even if the [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] of [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]] be deemed to have been chosen because of its coincidence with the vernal equinox, both Whitney<ref name=fx124_ve1_1496/> and Thibaut<ref name=fx125_ve1_1496/> are prepared to regard it as no more than a careless variant of the date given by the [[ज्योतिष|Jyotiṣa]], which puts the winter solstice in Māgha.<br><br>(3) The winter solstice in Māgha is assured by a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] text, for the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx126_ve1_1496/> expressly places it in the new moon of Māgha (''māghasyāmāvāsyāyām''). It is not very important whether we take this with the commentators<ref name=fx127_ve1_1496/> as the new moon in the middle of a month commencing with the day after full moon in Taiṣa, or, which is much more likely, as the new moon beginning the month and preceding full moon in Māgha. The datum gives a certain possibility of fixing an epoch in the following way. If the end of [[रेवती|Revatī]] marked the vernal equinox at one period, then the precession of the equinoxes would enable us to calculate at what point of time the vernal equinox was in a position corresponding to the winter solstice in Māgha, when the solstitial colure cut the ecliptic at the beginning of [[श्रविष्ठास्|Śraviṣṭhās]]. This would be, on the strict theory, in the third quarter of Bharaṇī, 6(3/4) asterisms removed from [[श्रविष्ठास्|Śraviṣṭhās]], and the difference between that and the beginning of [[अश्विनी|Aśvinī]]=  1(3/4) asterisms = 23(1/3)º (27 asterisms being = 360º). Taking the starting-point at 499 A.D., the assured period of [[वराह|Varāha]] Mihira, Jones<ref name=fx128_ve1_1496/> arrived at the date B. C. 1181 for the vernal equinox corresponding to the winter solstice in Māgha--that is, on the basis of 1º = 72 years as the precession. Pratt<ref name=fx129_ve1_1496/> arrived at precisely the same date, taking the same rate of precession and adopting as his basis the ascertained position in the Siddhāntas of the junction star<ref name=fx130_ve1_1496/> of [[मघा|Maghā]],  Leonis or Regulus. Davis<ref name=fx131_ve1_1496/> and Colebrooke<ref name=fx132_ve1_1496/> arrived at a different date, B.C. 1391, by taking as the basis of their calculation the junction star of [[चित्रा|Citrā]], which happens to be of uncertain position, varying as much as 3º in the different textbooks. But though the twelfth century has received a certain currency as the epoch of the observation in the [[ज्योतिष|Jyotiṣa]],<ref name=fx133_ve1_1496/> it is of very doubtful value. As Whitney points out, it is impossible to say that the earlier asterisms coincided in position with the later asterisms of 13(1/3)º extent each. They were not chosen as equal divisions, but as groups of stars which stood in conjunction with the moon; and the result of subsequently making them strictly equal divisions was to throw the principal stars of the later groups altogether out of their asterisms.<ref name=fx134_ve1_1496/> Nor can we say that the star  Piscium early formed the eastern boundary of [[रेवती|Revatī]]; it may possibly not even have been in that asterism at all, for it is far remote from the Chinese and Arabic asterisms corresponding to [[रेवती|Revatī]]. Added to all this, and to the uncertainty of the starting-point-582 A.D., 560 A.D., or 491 A.D. being variants<ref name=fx135_ve1_1496/> --is the fact that the place of the equinox is not a matter accurately determinable by mere observation, and that the Hindu astronomers of the Vedic period cannot be deemed to have been very accurate observers, since they made no precise determination of the  number of days of the year, which even in the [[ज्योतिष|Jyotiṣa]] they do not determine more precisely than as 366 days, and even the [[सूर्य|Sūrya]] Siddhānta<ref name=fx136_ve1_1496/> does not know the precession of the equinoxes. It is therefore only fair to allow a thousand years for possible errors,<ref name=fx137_ve1_1496/> and the only probable conclusion to be drawn from the datum of the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] is that it was recording an observation which must have been made some centuries B.C., in itself a result quite in harmony with the probable date of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] literature,<ref name=fx138_ve1_1496/> say B.C. 800-600.<br><br>(4) Another chronological argument has been derived from the fact that there is a considerable amount of evidence for Phālguna having been regarded as the beginning of the year, since the full moon in [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]] is often described as the ‘mouth (''mukham'') of the year.’<ref name=fx139_ve1_1496/> Jacobi<ref name=fx140_ve1_1496/> considers that this  was due to the fact that the year was reckoned from the winter solstice, which would coincide with the month of Phālguna about B.C. 4000. Oldenberg<ref name=fx141_ve1_1496/> and Thibaut,<ref name=fx142_ve1_1496/> on the other hand, maintain that the choice of Phālguna as the ‘mouth’ of the year was due to its being the first month of spring. This view is favoured by the fact that there is distinct evidence<ref name=fx143_ve1_1496/> of the correspondence of Phālguna and the beginning of spring: as we have seen above in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], the new moon in Māgha is placed at the winter solstice,<ref name=fx144_ve1_1496/> which puts the full moon of [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]] at a month and a half after the winter solstice, or in the first week of February, a date not in itself improbable for about B.C. 800, and corresponding with the February 7 of the ''veris initium'' in the Roman Calendar. This fact accords with the only natural division of the year into three periods of four months, as the rainy season lasts from June 7-10 to October 7-10, and it is certain that the second set of four months dates from the beginning of the rains (see '''[[चातुर्मास्य|Cāturmāsya]]'''). Tilak,<ref name=fx145_ve1_1496/> on the other hand, holds that the winter solstice coincided with Māghī full moon at the time of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (B.C. 2350), and had coincided with Phālgunī and Caitrī in early periods--viz., B.C. 4000-2500, and B.C. 60004000.<br><br>(5) The passages of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx146_ve1_1496/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx147_ve1_1496/> which treat the full moon in Phālguna as the beginning of the year, give as an alternative the full moon in [[चैत्र|Caitra]]. Probably the latter month was chosen so as to secure that the initial day should fall well within the season of spring,<ref name=fx148_ve1_1496/> and was not, as Jacobi believes, a relic of a period  when the winter solstice corresponded with [[चैत्र|Caitra]]. Another alternative is the [[एकाष्टका|Ekāṣṭakā]], interpreted by the commentators as the eighth day after the full moon in [[मघास्|Maghās]], a time which might, as being the last quarter of the waning half of the old year, well be considered as representing the end of the year. A fourth alternative is the fourth day before full moon; the full moon meant must be that of [[चैत्र|Caitra]], as Ālekhana quoted by Āpastamba held, not of Māgha, as Āśmarathya, Laugākṣi and the Mīmāṃsists believed, and as Tilak believes.<ref name=fx149_ve1_1496/><br><br>(6) Others, again, according to the [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] ritual, began the year with the month Mārgaśīrṣa, as is shown by its other name Āgrahāyaṇa<ref name=fx150_ve1_1496/> (‘belonging to the commencement of the year’). Jacobi and Tilak<ref name=fx151_ve1_1496/> think that this one denoted the autumn equinox in [[मृगशिरस्|Mṛgaśiras]], corresponding to the winter solstice in [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]]. But, as Thibaut<ref name=fx152_ve1_1496/> shows clearly, it was selected as the beginning of a year that was taken to commence with autumn, just as some took the spring to commence with [[चैत्र|Caitra]] instead of Phālguna.<ref name=fx153_ve1_1496/><br><br>(7) Jacobi has also argued, with the support of Bühler,<ref name=fx154_ve1_1496/> from the terms given for the beginning of Vedic study in the [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] Sūtras, on the principle that study commenced with the rains (as in the Buddhist ''vassā'') which mark the summer solstice. He concludes that if Bhādrapada appears as the date of commencing study in some texts, it was fixed thus because at one time Proṣṭhapadās (the early name of Bhadrapadās) coincided with the summer solstice, this having been the case when the winter solstice was in Phālguna. But Whitney<ref name=fx155_ve1_1496/> has pointed out that this argument is utterly illegitimate; we cannot say that there was any necessary connexion between the rains and learning--a month like Śrāvaṇa might be preferred  because of its connexion with the word [[श्रवण|Śravaṇa]], ‘ear’--and in view of the precession of the equinoxes, we must assume that Bhādrapada was kept because of its traditional coincidence with the beginning of the rains after it had ceased actually so to coincide.<ref name=fx156_ve1_1496/><br><br>''The Origin of the Nakṣatras.''--As we have seen, there is no evidence showing the process by which the Nakṣatras may  have originated in India. They are mentioned only as stars in the earlier parts of the Rigveda, then the names of three of them are found in the latest parts of that Saṃhitā, and finally in the later Atharvaveda and in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās the full list appears. It may also be noted that the Vedic Indians show (see '''[[ग्रह|Graha]]''') a remarkably small knowledge of the other astronomical phenomena; the discovery of a series of 27 lunar mansions by them would therefore be rather surprising. On the other hand, the nature of such an operation is not very complicated; it consists merely in selecting a star or a star group with which the moon is in conjunction. It is thus impossible ''a priori'' to deny that the Vedic Indians could have invented for themselves a lunar Zodiac.<ref name=fx157_ve1_1496/><br><br>But the question is complicated by the fact that there exist two similar sets of 28 stars or star groups in Arabia and in China, the Manāzil and the Sieou. The use of the Manāzil in Arabia is consistent and effective; the calendar is regulated by them, and the position of the asterisms corresponds best with the positions required for a lunar Zodiac. The Indians might therefore have borrowed the system from Arabia, but that is a mere possibility, because the evidence for the existence of the Manāzil is long posterior to that for the existence of the Nakṣatras, while again the Mazzaroth or Mazzaloth of the Old Testament<ref name=fx158_ve1_1496/> may really be the lunar mansions.<ref name=fx159_ve1_1496/> That the Arabian system is borrowed from India, as Burgess<ref name=fx160_ve1_1496/> held, is, on the other hand, not at all probable.<br><br>Biot, the eminent Chinese scholar, in a series of papers published by him between 1839 and 1861,<ref name=fx161_ve1_1496/> attempted to prove  the derivation of the [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] from the Chinese Sieou. The latter he did not regard as being in origin lunar mansions at all. He thought that they were equatorial stars used, as in modern astronomy, as a standard to which planets or other stars observed in the neighbourhood can be eferred; they were, as regards twenty-four of them, selecte about B.C. 2357 on account of their proximity to the equator, and of their having the same right ascension as certain circumpolar stars which had attracted the attention of Chinese observers. Four more were added in B.C. 1100 in order to mark the equinoxes and solstices of the period. He held that the list of stars commenced with Mao (= [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]]), which was at the vernal equinox in B.C. 2357. Weber,<ref name=fx162_ve1_1496/> in an elaborate essay of 1860, disputed this theory, and endeavoured to show that the Chinese literary evidence for the Sieou was late, dating not even from before the third century B.C. The last point does not appear<ref name=fx163_ve1_1496/> to be correct, but his objections against the basis of Biot's theory were reinforced by Whitney,<ref name=fx164_ve1_1496/> who insisted that Biot's supposition of the Sieou's not having been ultimately derived from a system of lunar mansions, was untenable. This is admitted by the latest defender of the hypothesis of borrowing from China, Léopold de Saussure,<ref name=fx165_ve1_1496/> , but his arguments in favour of a Chinese origin for the Indian lunar mansions have been refuted by Oldenberg,<ref name=fx166_ve1_1496/> who has also pointed out<ref name=fx167_ve1_1496/> that the series does not begin with Mao (= [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]]).<br><br>There remains only the possibility that a common source for all the three sets--[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]], Manāzil, and Sieou--may be found in Babylonia. Hommel<ref name=fx168_ve1_1496/> has endeavoured to show that recent research has established in Babylonia the existence of a lunar zodiac of twenty-four members headed by the  Pleiades (= [[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]]); but Thibaut's researches<ref name=fx169_ve1_1496/> are not favourable to this claim. On the other hand, Weber,<ref name=fx170_ve1_1496/> Whitney,<ref name=fx171_ve1_1496/> Zimmer,<ref name=fx172_ve1_1496/> and Oldenberg<ref name=fx173_ve1_1496/> all incline to the view that in Babylonia is to be found the origin of the system, and this must for the present be regarded as the most probable view, for there are other traces of Babylonian influence in Vedic literature, such as the legend of the flood, perhaps the Ādityas,<ref name=fx174_ve1_1496/> and possibly the word '''[[मना|Manā]].''' <br>

नक्षत्र-दर्श
<u>'''Nakṣatra-darśa'''</u> (‘gazer at the lunar mansions’), an ‘astrologer,’ is mentioned in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha, or ‘human sacrifice,’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1497/> A notice in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1497/> indicates that that work regarded the practice of choosing a particular [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] under which to set up the sacrificial fires as an idle one, because it decides in favour of choosing the sun as one's [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].<br>

नक्षत्र-विद्या
<u>'''Nakṣatra-vidyā,'''</u> the ‘science of the lunar mansions,’ ‘astronomy,’ is mentioned with other sciences in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vii. 1, 2. 4; 2, 1; 7, 1).<br>

नख
<u>'''Nakha'''</u> denotes either the ‘nail’ of a man,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1499/> or the ‘claw’ of a wild beast, such as a tiger.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1499/> The trimming (''nikṛntana'')<ref name=fx3_ve1_1499/> of the nails was a regular part of the toilet of the Vedic Indian, especially on occasions of special sanctity, when it accompanied the cleansing of the teeth.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1499/> <br>

न-ग
<u>'''Na-ga'''</u> (‘not moving’), ‘mountain,’ is a word occurring only in a late book of the Atharvaveda (xix. 8, 1), and then in the Sūtras.<br>

नगर
<u>'''Nagara'''</u> is in early Vedic literature found only in the derivative adjective, used as a proper name, '''Nagarin,''' but it appears in the sense of ‘town’ in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (i. 11, 18; 31, 4), and frequently in the later language.<br>

नगरिन् जान-श्रुतेय
<u>'''Nagarin [[जान|Jāna]]-śruteya'''</u> (‘descendant of Janaśruti’) is mentioned as a priest in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 30), and as [[नगरिन् जानश्रुतेय|Nagarin Jānaśruteya]] [[काण्ड्विय|Kāṇḍviya]] in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 2).<br>

नग्न-जित्
<u>'''Nagna-jit,'''</u> King of '''[[गन्धार|Gandhāra]],''' is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1503/> as having been consecrated by '''[[पर्वत|Parvata]]''' and '''[[नारद|Nārada]].''' The same king is mentioned with his son '''Svarjit''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1503/> where a remark attributed to one of them on a ritual topic is treated with contempt.<br>

नग्ना
<u>'''Nagnā.'''</u> See '''[[धर्म|Dharma]].'''<br>

नघ-मार
<u>'''Nagha-māra'''</u> and '''Naghā-riṣa.''' See 1. '''[[कुष्ठ|Kuṣṭha]].'''<br>

न-चिकेतस्
<u>'''Na-ciketas'''</u> occurs in the well-known legend of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1506/> (where he is a [[गोतम|Gotama]], the son of '''[[वाजश्रवस|Vājaśravasa]]'''), and in the Kaṭha [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1506/> His historical reality is extremely doubtful: in the [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] he is called son of [[आरुणि|Āruṇi]] [[औद्दालकि|Auddālaki]] or [[वाजश्रवस|Vājaśravasa]], an impossible attribution, and one due only to a desire to give [[नचिकेतस्|Naciketas]] a connexion with the famous [[आरुणि|Āruṇi]]. <br>

नड
<u>'''1. Naḍa,'''</u> ‘reed,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1507/> as growing in lakes, and in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1507/> is described as ''vārṣika,'' ‘produced in the rains.’ Reeds were used, after being split, for making mats, a work carried out by women.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1507/> They are frequently mentioned elsewhere.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1507/> See also '''Nada.'''<br>

नड नैषध
<u>'''2. Naḍa Naiṣadha'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1508/> where he seems to be<ref name=fx2_ve1_1508/> a human king who is compared with Yama, the god of death, because of his conquests. Being there identified with the southern sacrificial fire, he was presumably a king of the south, just as Yama is connected with the south.<br>

नड्वला
<u>'''Naḍvalā,'''</u> a ‘reed bed,’ is mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xxx. 16) and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 4, 12, 1).<br>

नद
<u>'''Nada'''</u> is found in several passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1510/> but its sense is still obscure. It is identified by Pischel<ref name=fx2_ve1_1510/> with '''[[नड|Naḍa]],''' being explained by him in one passage<ref name=fx3_ve1_1510/> as a reed boat, which is split, and over which the waters go; in another<ref name=fx4_ve1_1510/> as a reed whip, of which the sharp points (''karṇa'') are used to urge horses on; and in others<ref name=fx5_ve1_1510/> again as figuratively designating the penis. Roth<ref name=fx6_ve1_1510/> takes the sense to be ‘bull’ (either literally or meta-  phorically) in all passages. Once at least<ref name=fx7_ve1_1510/> the ‘neigher’ (from the root ''nad,'' ‘sound’) seems to be meant with reference to Indra's horse. In the phrase ''nadasya karṇaiḥ''^8 the sense is, perhaps, ‘through the ears of the (side) horse’ (that is, by their being ready to hear the word of command) of their chariot, the Maruts ‘hasten on with their swift steeds’ (''turayanta āśubhiḥ'').<br>

नदी
<u>'''Nadī,'''</u> ‘stream,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1511/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1511/> Reference is made to shallows (''gādha'')<ref name=fx3_ve1_1511/> in the river's bed, to the opposite bank (''[[पार|pāra]]''),<ref name=fx4_ve1_1511/> and to the bathing of horses in streams.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1511/> Rivers are also mentioned in close connexion with mountains.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1511/> The title [[नदी|Nadī]]-pati, ‘lord of rivers,’<ref name=fx7_ve1_1511/> is once used to express ‘ocean’ or ‘sea-water.’<br>

नना
<u>'''Nanā'''</u> is a familiar name for mother, parallel with '''Tata,''' for father, with which it is found in a verse of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1512/> describing the occupations of the parents of the poet.<br>

ननान्दृ
<u>'''Nanāndṛ'''</u> is a word occurring only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1513/> where it denotes, according to Sāyaṇa, the ‘husband's sister,’ over whom the wife is to rule. This interpretation is confirmed by the fact that the same position is ascribed to the husband's sister--no doubt while unmarried and living in her brother's care--by the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1513/> <br>

नपात्
<u>'''Napāt'''</u> in Vedic literature apparently has both the wider sense of ‘descendant,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1514/> and the narrower one of ‘grandson’ in the Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1514/> In the Brāhmaṇas the word seems hardly to have the sense of ‘descendant’ at all, while it denotes not only ‘grandson,’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1514/> but also ‘great-grandson’ in the sequence ‘sons, grandsons, great-grandsons’ (''putrān, pautrān, naptṝn'').<ref name=fx4_ve1_1514/> ‘Grandson’ is also expressed by [[पौत्र|Pautra]] (‘son's son’) in the Atharvaveda and later,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1514/> while the sense of ‘great-grandson’ is accurately conveyed as early as the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_1514/> by [[प्र-णपात्|Pra-ṇapāt]], used beside [[नपात्|Napāt]], ‘grandson.’ Naptī, the feminine, is practically limited to the Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1514/> and denotes ‘daughter.’ The use in the Veda throws no light on the original use of the word.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1514/><br>

नप्त्री
<u>'''Naptrī,'''</u> as feminine of '''[[नपात्|Napāt]],''' is found in the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]], Āraṇya (v. 13).<br>

नभ(स्) नभस्य
<u>'''Nabha(s) Nabhasya.'''</u> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

नभाक
<u>'''Nabhāka'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] who is referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1517/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1517/> The Anukramaṇī (Index) attributes to '''[[नाभाक|Nābhāka]]''' the composition of several hymns of the Rigveda (viii. 39-42). <br>

नभ्य
<u>'''Nabhya,'''</u> the ‘nave’ of the wheel, is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1518/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1518/> See also '''[[नाभि|Nābhi]].'''<br>

नमी साप्य
<u>'''Namī Sāpya'''</u> is the name of a man in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1519/> Weber<ref name=fx2_ve1_1519/> thinks that he is mentioned as a priest, but the passages suit a king better, and in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1519/> he appears as [[नमी साप्य|Namī Sāpya]], ''Vaidcho rājā,'' ‘King of [[विदेह|Videha]].’ In one passage<ref name=fx4_ve1_1519/> he is represented as engaged in the contest against Namuci.<br>

नर
<u>'''Nara, Nṛ.'''</u>--The general name for ‘man’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1520/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1520/> is [[नृ|Nṛ]], while Nara<ref name=fx3_ve1_1520/> is found occasionally in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1520/><br>

नराची
<u>'''Narācī'''</u> occurs once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1521/> perhaps meaning a poisonous plant.<br>

नर्य
<u>'''Narya'''</u> (‘manly’) is in two passages of the Rigveda (i. 54, 6; 112, 9) understood by the commentator Sāyaṇa as the proper name of a man. See also '''[[नार्य|Nārya]].''' <br>

नलद
<u>'''Nalada,'''</u> ‘nard’ (''Nardastachys Jatamansi'') is a plant mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1523/> in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1523/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1523/> Āraṇyakas (where it is mentioned as used for a garland), as well as in the Sūtras. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1523/> the feminine form of the word, Naladī, occurs as the name of an Apsaras, or celestial nymph.<br>

नवक
<u>'''Navaka'''</u> is mentioned as having wished for a wife at the Sattra of the '''Vibhindukīyas''' in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1524/><br>

नव-ग्व
<u>'''Nava-gva'''</u> occurs in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1525/> as a man, an [[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]] in the highest degree (''Aṅgirastama''),<ref name=fx2_ve1_1525/> apparently being the type of the Navagvas,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1525/> who appear as a mystic race of olden times, coupled with, and conceived probably as related to, the Aṅgirases. They are often associated with the '''Daśagvas.'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1525/><br>

नव-नीत
<u>'''Nava-nīta,'''</u> ‘fresh butter,’ is mentioned frequently in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1526/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1526/> According to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1526/> this is the kind of butter which is fitted for anointing an embryo (''garbha''), while the gods receive '''[[आज्य|Ājya]],''' men fragrant ghee ('''[[घृत|Ghṛta]]'''), and the fathers '''[[आयुत|Āyuta]].''' Elsewhere<ref name=fx4_ve1_1526/> it is contrasted with [[घृत|Ghṛta]] and '''[[सर्पिस्|Sarpis]].''' <br>

नव-वास्त्व
<u>'''Nava-vāstva'''</u> appears in three passages of the Rigveda. In one<ref name=fx1_ve1_1527/> he seems to be a protégé of Agni; in another<ref name=fx2_ve1_1527/> as perhaps a son of '''Uśanas''' and favourite of Indra, but in the last he seems to be defeated, or even slain, by Indra.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1527/> But he may be a mythic figure altogether. ''Cf.'' also '''[[बृहद्रथ|Bṛhadratha]].'''<br>

नह्
<u>'''Nah'''</u> has been taken by Roth<ref name=fx1_ve1_1528/> and Grassmann<ref name=fx2_ve1_1528/> to be the stem, meaning ‘bond,’ of the dative form ''nadbhyas,'' which occurs once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1528/> and which Sieg<ref name=fx4_ve1_1528/> thinks means ‘sister's sons.’ But the sense of this dative is probably rather ‘to the grandsons.’<ref name=fx5_ve1_1528/><br>

नहुस्
<u>'''Nahus'''</u> occurs several times in the Rigveda, but the exact sense is not certain. Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve1_1529/> sees in the [[नहुस्|Nahus]] a tribe on the '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]''' (Indus)<ref name=fx2_ve1_1529/> or '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1529/> rich in horses,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1529/> allied with the '''Bharatas''' and '''Śimyus,'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1529/> connected with '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]]''' and the '''Vārṣāgiras,'''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1529/> and having as kings '''[[मशर्शार|Maśarśāra]]''' and '''[[आयवस|Āyavasa]].'''<ref name=fx7_ve1_1529/> Roth,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1529/> on the other hand, sees in [[नहुस्|Nahus]] the general sense of ‘neighbour’ as opposed to a member of one's own people ('''[[विश्|Viś]]'''); this interpretation is supported by the occurrence of the phrase ''nahuṣo nahuṣṭara,''<ref name=fx9_ve1_1529/> ‘closer than a neighbour.’ Nahuṣa has the same sense as [[नहुस्|Nahus]] in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx10_ve1_1529/> but in  one it seems to be intended for the proper name of a man.<ref name=fx11_ve1_1529/> Possibly [[नहुस्|Nahus]] was originally a man like Manu.<ref name=fx12_ve1_1529/><br>

नाक
<u>'''1. Nāka'''</u> denotes the ‘firmament’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1530/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1530/> It is often used with the epithet ‘highest’ (''uttama'')<ref name=fx3_ve1_1530/> or ‘third’ (''tṛtīya'')<ref name=fx4_ve1_1530/> referring to the threefold division of heaven, parallel to the threefold division of earth, atmosphere, and sky ('''Div'''). The [[नाक|Nāka]] is said to be on the third ridge (''pṛṣṭha''), above the luminous space (''rocana'') of the sky.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1530/> Elsewhere<ref name=fx6_ve1_1530/> the series earth, atmosphere, sky, and the firmament (''[[नाक|nāka]]''), heaven (''svar''), the celestial light (''jyotis''), occurs. The word ''[[नाक|nāka]]'' is explained in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx7_ve1_1530/> as derived from ''na,'' ‘not,’ and ''aka,'' ‘pain,’ because those who go there are free from sorrow.<br>

नाक
<u>'''2. Nāka'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1531/> Presumably he is identical with [[नाक|Nāka]] [[मौद्गल्य|Maudgalya]] (‘descendant of Mudgala’), who is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1531/> the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1531/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1531/> <br>

नाक्र
<u>'''Nākra'''</u> is the name of an aquatic animal included among the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or ‘horse sacrifice,’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1532/> Perhaps the animal meant is the crocodile, which later is called Nakra.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1532/><br>

नाग
<u>'''Nāga'''</u> appears once in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1533/> in the form ''[[महानाग|mahānāga]],'' where ‘great snake’ or ‘great elephant’ may be meant. In the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1533/> and in a citation found in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1533/> the sense of ‘elephant’ is clearly intended. In the Sūtras<ref name=fx4_ve1_1533/> the mythic [[नाग|Nāga]] already occurs.<br>

नाग्न-जित
<u>'''Nāgna-jita,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[नग्नजित्|Nagnajit]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Svarjit''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 1, 4, 10).<br>

नाचिकेत
<u>'''Nāciketa,'''</u> ‘connected with '''[[नचिकेतस्|Naciketas]],'''’ is the title of a narrative (''upākhyāna'') in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1535/> The word is also applied as an epithet to a special fire in that [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1535/> and in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1535/><br>

नाड-पित्
<u>'''Nāḍa-pit'''</u> occurs in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1536/> as the birthplace of '''[[भरत|Bharata]].''' The word may, however, be read as Nāḍa-pitī, the name of Bharata's mother,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1536/> but this is less probable. <br>

नाडी
<u>'''1. Nāḍī'''</u> denotes a ‘vein’ or ‘artery’ in the human body in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1537/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1537/> a natural extension of the literal sense of ‘reed.’<br>

नाडी
<u>'''2. Nāḍī'''</u> means a musical instrument, a ‘reed flute,’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1538/> as well as the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1538/> where in one passage it is mentioned along with the '''[[तूणव|Tūṇava]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1538/><br>

नाडी
<u>'''3. Nāḍī'''</u> in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1539/> seems to mean the box of the chariot wheel.<br>

नाडीका
<u>'''Nāḍīkā'''</u> occurs once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1540/> where the sense seems clearly to be ‘wind-pipe,’ with a reference also to the ‘shaft of an arrow’ made of reed.<br>

नाथ
<u>'''Nātha'''</u> in Vedic literature<ref name=fx1_ve1_1541/> appears only as a neuter meaning ‘protection,’ and is of rare occurrence.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1541/> Generally, too, very little appears in Vedic literature of practices such as those which produced Anglo-Saxon society or the Roman ''patronatus.''<br>

नापित
<u>'''Nāpita,'''</u> ‘barber,’ is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1542/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1542/> But the older word is [[वप्तृ|Vaptṛ]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1542/> a derivative of  ''vap,'' ‘shave,’ with forms of which verb shaving is referred to as early as the Rigveda.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1542/> The dead were shaved before burial.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1542/><br>

नाभाक
<u>'''Nābhāka,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[नभाक|Nabhāka]],’ is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], or seer, in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1543/> The Anukramaṇī (Index) ascribes three or four hymns of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1543/> to him. According to Ludwig,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1543/> the man was an [[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_1543/> not a [[कण्व|Kaṇva]].<br>

नाभा-नेदिष्ठ
<u>'''Nābhā-nediṣṭha'''</u> (‘nearest in descent’) '''[[मानव|Mānava]]''' (‘descendant of Manu’) is famous in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_1544/> for the way in which he was treated when his father '''Manu''' divided his property among his sons, or they divided it: [[नाभानेदिष्ठ|Nābhānediṣṭha]] was left out, but was solaced by obtaining, through his father's advice, cows from the Aṅgirases, a feat which is regarded in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1544/> as on a level with the exploits of other seers who celebrated their patrons in hymns, and as giving rise to the hymn, Rigveda x. 62. Nābhānediṣṭha's hymn is repeatedly mentioned in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1544/> but beyond its authorship nothing is recorded of him. In the Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve1_1544/> itself he seems to be spoken of as a poet in one passage, which is, however, of quite uncertain meaning.<br><br>[[नाभानेदिष्ठ|Nābhānediṣṭha]] is etymologically connected in all probability with Nabānazdiṣta in the Avesta, which refers to the Fravaṣi of the paoiryō-ṭkaēsha and the Fravaṣi of the Nabānazdiṣta. Lassen<ref name=fx5_ve1_1544/> saw in the legend a reminiscence of an Indo-Iranian split; but Roth<ref name=fx6_ve1_1544/> showed conclusively that this was impossible, and that [[नाभानेदिष्ठ|Nābhānediṣṭha]] meant simply ‘nearest in birth,’ and  Weber<ref name=fx7_ve1_1544/> admits that the connexion of the words is not one of borrowing on either side, but that in the Avesta it has kept its original sense of ‘nearest relation,’ while in the Rigveda it has become a proper name.<br>

नाभि
<u>'''1. Nābhi'''</u> develops from the literal sense of ‘navel’ the figurative meaning of ‘relationship,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1545/> or, concretely, ‘relation.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1545/><br>

नाभि
<u>'''2. Nābhi,'''</u> ‘nave’ of a chariot wheel, is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1546/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1546/> See also '''[[रथ|Ratha]],''' and ''cf.'' '''[[नभ्य|Nabhya]].'''<br>

नाम-धेय
<u>'''Nāma-dheya,'''</u> ‘name,’ is found in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1547/> and often in the later language.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1547/> See '''[[नामन्|Nāman]].'''<br>

नामन्
<u>'''Nāman,'''</u> ‘name,’ is a common word from the Rigveda onwards. The [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] Sūtras<ref name=fx1_ve1_1548/> give elaborate rules for the formation of the names of children, but more important is the distinction between the secret (''guhya'') and the ordinary name, though the rules as to the secret name are not at all consistent. The secret name is already recognized in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1548/> and is referred to in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1548/> one secret name, that of Arjuna for Indra, being given in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1548/> It is to be noted that the rule as to giving the  designation of a [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] (lunar asterism) as the secret name or otherwise is not illustrated by a single recorded name of a teacher in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1548/><br><br>The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_1548/> several times mentions the adoption of a second name with a view to securing success, and also refers to the adoption of another name for purposes of distinction.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1548/><br><br>In actual practice two names are usually found in the Brāhmaṇas, the second being a patronymic or a metronymic, as in '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]] [[औशिज|Auśija]]'''<ref name=fx8_ve1_1548/> (if the story of the slave woman Uśij as his mother is correct), or '''[[बृहद्उक्थ|Bṛhaduktha]] Vāmneya,'''<ref name=fx9_ve1_1548/> ‘son of Vāmnī,’ though the relationship may, of course, be not direct parentage, but more remote descent.<ref name=fx10_ve1_1548/> Three names are less common--for example, '''[[कूशाम्ब स्वायव लातव्य|Kūśāmba <a class="pada_vei" href="स्वायव">Svāyava]] Lātavya»,'''<ref name=fx11_ve1_1548/> ‘son of Svāyu, of the [[लातव्य|Lātavya]] (son of Latu) family,’ or '''[[देवतरस् श्यावसायन काश्यप|Devataras <a class="pada_vei" href="श्यावसायन">Śyāvasāyana]] Kāśyapa»,'''<ref name=fx12_ve1_1548/> where the patronymic and the [[गोत्र|Gotra]] name are both found. In other cases the names probably have a local reference--''e.g.,'' '''[[कौशाम्बेय|Kauśāmbeya]]''' and '''[[गाङ्ग्य|Gāṅgya]].''' Frequently the patronymic only is given, as '''[[भार्गव|Bhārgava]], [[मौद्गल्य|Maudgalya]],''' etc., or two patronymics are used. The simple name is often used for the patronymic--''e.g.,'' '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]].'''<ref name=fx13_ve1_1548/> In a few cases the name of the wife is formed from the husband's name,<ref name=fx14_ve1_1548/> as '''Uśīnarāṇī, [[पुरुकुत्सानी|Purukutsānī]], Mudgalānī.'''<br>

नाम्ब
<u>'''Nāmba'''</u> is the name of a kind of grain mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1549/> [[आम्ब|Āmba]] is the form of the word in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1549/> and the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1549/> <br>

नाय
<u>'''Nāya'''</u> in two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1550/> is, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, probably a proper name. Sāyaṇa takes the word to mean ‘leader,’ while Pischel<ref name=fx2_ve1_1550/> considers it a gerund with passive sense.<br>

नारद
<u>'''Nārada'''</u> is the name of a mythical seer mentioned several times in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1551/> In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] he appears in conjunction with '''[[पर्वत|Parvata]]''' as priest of '''Hariścandra,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1551/> as teaching '''[[सोमक साहदेव्य|Somaka Sāhadevya]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1551/> and as anointing '''Āmbāṣṭhya''' and '''Yudhāṃśrauṣṭi.'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1551/> In the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx5_ve1_1551/> he is mentioned as a teacher, and in the Sāmavidhāna [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve1_1551/> as a pupil of [[बृहस्पति|Bṛhaspati]]. In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx7_ve1_1551/> he is coupled with [[सनत्कुमार|Sanatkumāra]].<br>

नाराशंसी
<u>'''Nārāśaṃsī'''</u> (scil. Ṛc), ‘(verse) celebrating men,’ is mentioned as early as the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1552/> and is distinguished from '''[[गाथा|Gāthā]]''' in a number of passages in the later literature.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1552/> The [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1552/> while distinguishing the two, asserts that both are false (''anṛtam''). It is hardly probable that the two were absolutely distinct, for the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1552/> has the phrase ‘a [[गाथा|Gāthā]] celebrating men’ (''[[नाराशंसी|nārāśaṃsī]]''). What such verses were may be seen from the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_1552/> which enumerates the ''Nārāśaṃsāni'' at the Puruṣamedha, or ‘human  sacrifice.’ They may legitimately be reckoned as a source of the epic.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1552/><br><br>The term [[नाराशंसी|Nārāśaṃsī]] is restricted in some passages<ref name=fx7_ve1_1552/> to a particular group of three verses of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1552/> but Oldenberg<ref name=fx9_ve1_1552/> must be right in holding that the restricted sense is not to be read into the Rigveda.<ref name=fx10_ve1_1552/> Not even in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx11_ve1_1552/> is the technical sense certain, and the Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx12_ve1_1552/> gives the word a general application.<br>

नारी
<u>'''Nārī,'''</u> ‘woman,’ occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1553/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1553/> The word seems in the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1553/> to have a distinct reference to a woman as a wife, because it occurs in several passages with distinct reference to matrimonial relations,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1553/> and in the later Vedic literature, where it is not common, it sometimes<ref name=fx4_ve1_1553/> has that sense. Delbrück,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1553/> however, thinks that it does not indicate marital relations, but merely the woman as the sexual complement of the man.<br>

नार्मर
<u>'''Nārmara'''</u> occurs once in a corrupt verse of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1554/> Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_1554/> regards the word as the proper name of the prince of a fort, '''[[ऊर्जयन्ती|Ūrjayantī]],''' but Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_1554/> as that of a demon. <br>

नार्मिणी
<u>'''Nārmiṇī'''</u> is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1555/> as an epithet of '''Pur,''' ‘fort’: it must apparently either be a proper name of the fort,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1555/> or mean ‘belonging to Narmin or Narmiṇa,’ some prince.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1555/><br>

नार्य
<u>'''Nārya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[नर्य|Narya]],’''' is the name of a generous donor in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1556/><br>

नार्षद
<u>'''Nārṣada,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[नृषद्|Nṛṣad]],’ is the patronymic of [[कण्व|Kaṇva]] (''i.e.,'' a descendant of [[कण्व|Kaṇva]]) in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1557/> and in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1557/> where probably the same man is referred to in another passage<ref name=fx3_ve1_1557/> as a protégé of the Aśvins, and perhaps as the husband of '''Ruśatī.''' But in a third passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1557/> the name seems applied to a demon, though this is not certain.<br>

नाव-प्रभ्रंशन
<u>'''Nāva-prabhraṃśana,'''</u> the ‘sliding down of the ship,’ is read in Whitney and Roth's text of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1558/> and has been connected by Weber<ref name=fx2_ve1_1558/> and others<ref name=fx3_ve1_1558/> with [[मनोर् अवसर्पण|Manor Avasarpaṇa]], the name in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1558/> of the northern mountain on which Manu's ship settled on the subsidence of the deluge. But both Bloomfield<ref name=fx5_ve1_1558/> and Whitney<ref name=fx6_ve1_1558/> point out that this interpretation is highly improbable, and this view is accepted by  Macdonell.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1558/> The expression is analyzed as ''na ava-prabhraṃśana'' by the Pada text and the commentator alike, and is never found elsewhere with reference to the descent of a boat or ship.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1558/><br>

नावा
<u>'''Nāvā,'''</u> ‘ship,’ occurs once in the Rigveda (i. 97, 8). See '''Nau.'''<br>

नावाज
<u>'''Nāvāja'''</u> (‘ship-propeller’), a ‘boatman,’ is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 3, 3, 5).<br>

नाव्या
<u>'''Nāvyā'''</u> is found several times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1561/> and the later literature<ref name=fx2_ve1_1561/> in the sense of a ‘navigable stream.’<br>

नाहुष
<u>'''Nāhuṣa,'''</u> like '''[[नहुस्|Nahus]],''' means, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, in some passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1562/> ‘neighbouring’ as an adjective, and once<ref name=fx2_ve1_1562/> as a substantive ‘neighbour.’ If, on the other hand, [[नहुस्|Nahus]] is taken as a proper name, then [[नाहुष|Nāhuṣa]] no doubt denotes ‘belonging to the [[नहुस्|Nahus]] people,’ and, as a substantive, ‘King of the [[नहुस्|Nahus]].’<br>

निकोथक भाय-जात्य
<u>'''Nikothaka Bhāya-jātya'''</u> (‘descendant of Bhayajāta’) is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1563/> as a pupil of '''Pratithi.'''<br>

निगद पार्ण-वल्कि
<u>'''Nigada Pārṇa-valki'''</u> (‘descendant of Parṇavalka’) is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1564/> as a pupil of Giriśarman. <br>

नि-गुत्
<u>'''Ni-gut'''</u> occurs in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1565/> where Sāyaṇa takes it to mean ‘enemy,’ a possible interpretation. Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_1565/> suggests that non-Āryan foes are meant.<br>

निगुस्थ
<u>'''Nigustha'''</u> is a term of unknown meaning applied in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xvi. 29, 6) to the peoples of [[काशि|Kāśi]], [[विदेह|Videha]], and [[कोसल|Kosala]].<br>

नि-तत्नी
<u>'''1. Ni-tatnī,'''</u> ‘striking downwards,’ occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1567/> as the name of an unknown plant which was used as a means of restoring the hair.<br>

नि-तत्नी
<u>'''2. Ni-tatnī'''</u> is the name of one of the seven '''[[कृत्तिकास्|Kṛttikās]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 1, 4, 1). See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

नि-तान मारुत
<u>'''Ni-tāna Māruta'''</u> is the name of a man in the '''[[काठक|Kāṭhaka]]''' Saṃhitā (xxv. 10).<br>

नि-दाघ
<u>'''Ni-dāgha'''</u> (‘burning down’), ‘summer,’ is the name of one of the seasons in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 8, 1, 4). See '''[[नैदाघ|Naidāgha]].'''<br>

नि-दान
<u>'''Ni-dāna'''</u> is the name of a [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], which is referred to in the Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1571/> apparently as containing a quotation from the [[भाल्लवि|Bhāllavi]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]. The quotation cannot be verified in the existing text of the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1571/> <br>

नि-धा
<u>'''Ni-dhā,'''</u> ‘net,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1572/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1572/><br>

नि-धि
<u>'''Ni-dhi'''</u> means primarily ‘(place of) deposit,’ ‘store,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1573/> and then ‘treasure’ generally.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1573/> In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1573/> [[निधि|Nidhi]] denotes some sort of science.<br>

नि-नाह्य
<u>'''Ni-nāhya'''</u> denotes in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 9, 2, 8) a ‘water jar,’ so called, according to the commentator, because it was buried in the ground.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1574/> Eggeling<ref name=fx2_ve1_1574/> explains it as ‘a vessel or cistern dug into the ground for keeping water cool.’<br>

निन्दिताश्व
<u>'''Ninditāśva'''</u> (‘possessing contemptible steeds’) is the name of a patron in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1575/> The name may suggest connexion with Iran, but such a reference is not at all necessary.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1575/> Sāyaṇa ingeniously turns the name--probably a nickname-into a compliment by rendering it ‘one who puts to shame the horses of his rivals.’<br>

नि-पाद
<u>'''Ni-pāda'''</u> in the Rigveda (v. 83, 7) denotes ‘low ground,’. ‘valley,’ as opposed to ‘hill’ (''udvat''). ''Cf.'' '''[[निवत्|Nivat]].'''<br>

नि-म्रुच्
<u>'''Ni-mruc,'''</u> ‘sunset,’ is repeatedly mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1577/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1577/> as a division of time. <br>

निर्-अष्ट
<u>'''Nir-aṣṭa,'''</u> ‘castrated,’ is found in some of the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1578/> as applied to oxen, and in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1578/> to horses.<br>

निर्-आल
<u>'''Nir-āla'''</u> occurs once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1579/> where Sāyaṇa regards it as the name of a disease. Bloomfield,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1579/> with the Padapāṭha, explains it as two words, understanding ''nir'' as an elliptical imperative, ‘(go) out,’ with the vocative ''[[आल|āla]],'' a kind of weed. Whitney<ref name=fx3_ve1_1579/> at first took ''[[आल|āla]]'' to be a verbal form, but finally came to the conclusion that the expression is one word, ''[[निर्आल|nirāla]],'' of unknown sense.<br>

निरुक्त
<u>'''Nirukta,'''</u> ‘explanation’ of a word or passage, is found in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (viii. 3, 3), but does not appear as the name of a work before the later Upaniṣads. It is, however, probable that Yāska's [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] is not later than the rise of Buddhism. ''Cf.'' '''[[निर्वचन|Nirvacana]].'''<br><br>''Cf.'' Weber, ''Indische Studien,'' 1, 13, 17; 3, 260 ''et seq.; Indian Literature,'' 25, 26, 41, 42, etc.; Macdonell, ''Sanskrit Literature,'' 269, 270; Keith, ''[[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka,'' 24, 25; Roth, ''[[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],'' xv. ''et seq.''<br>

निर्-यास
<u>'''Nir-yāsa'''</u> denotes the ‘exudation’ of trees. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (ii. 1, 5, 4) it is tabooed as food because of its red colour.<br>

निर्-वचन
<u>'''Nir-vacana'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve1_1582/> and the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1582/> means ‘explanation,’ especially etymological. ''Cf.'' '''[[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].'''<br>

नि-वत्
<u>'''Ni-vat'''</u> denotes ‘valley’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1583/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1583/> <br>

निवान्य-वत्सा
<u>'''Nivānya-vatsā'''</u> and '''Nivānyā''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1584/> denotes a ‘cow with a calf to which she has to be won over,’ that is, with a calf substituted for one of her own which has died. Nivānyā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1584/> is a contracted form of the compound term. Similar expressions are ''abhivānya-vatsā,''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1584/> ''abhivānyā,''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1584/> ''vānyā,''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1584/> and ''apivānya-vatsā.''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1584/><br>

नि-विद्
<u>'''Ni-vid'''</u> denotes a brief invocation of the deity that is invited in a liturgy in honour of the god. The Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_1585/> repeatedly mention Nivids as inserted in the Śastras (recitations), and the '''Khilas''' of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1585/> preserve among them a set of Nivids. But it is doubtful<ref name=fx3_ve1_1585/> whether the habit of using such brief formulas--the [[निविद्|Nivid]] is usually not more than a Pada or quarter-verse in length--is known to the Rigveda, though it has been seen even there,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1585/> and the word [[निविद्|Nivid]] is several times found in that Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1585/> but hardly in the technical sense of the Brāhmaṇas. In the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx6_ve1_1585/> the technical sense is common.<br>

निविद्-धान
<u>'''Nivid-dhāna,'''</u> ‘containing a [[निविद्|Nivid]],’ is found several times as an epithet of a hymn or verse in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1586/> <br>

नि-वेशन
<u>'''Ni-veśana,'''</u> ‘dwelling,’ occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1587/> and the Sūtras. In the latter<ref name=fx2_ve1_1587/> the word is sometimes contrasted with '''[[गृह|Gṛha]]''' as the resting-place of animals.<br>

नि-षङ्गथि
<u>'''Ni-ṣaṅgathi'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1588/> or '''Niṣaṅga-dhi'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1588/> is found in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās. If the second form of the word is correct, the sense may be ‘sheath of a sword’ (''niṣaṅga''), as it is taken by the St. Petersburg Dictionary, but probably the first form is the correct one, the word then having the same meaning as '''[[निषङ्गिन्|Niṣaṅgin]].'''<br>

नि-षङ्गिन्
<u>'''Ni-ṣaṅgin'''</u> is found three times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1589/> where, owing to its following in one passage<ref name=fx2_ve1_1589/> the words ''sudhanvāna iṣumanto,'' ‘having good bows and arrows,’ the sense of ''niṣaṅginaḥ'' as ‘having quivers’ seems quite certain. In the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_1589/> it is taken by the commentator Mahīdhara to mean ‘having a sword,’ a sense which is quite possible both there and in the other passages<ref name=fx4_ve1_1589/> where it occurs. But the word far more probably means ‘having a quiver,’ for the bow was the Vedic weapon, not the sword ('''Asi''').<br>

नि-षाद
<u>'''Ni-ṣāda'''</u> is found in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1590/> The word seems to denote not so much a particular tribe, but to be the general term for the non-Āryan tribes who were not under Āryan control, as the Śūdras were, for [[औपमन्यव|Aupamanyava]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1590/> took the five peoples (''pañca janāḥ'') to be the four castes (''catvāro  varṇāḥ'') and the Niṣādas, and the commentator Mahīdhara explains the word where it occurs in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_1590/> as meaning a Bhilla, or Bhīl. A village of Niṣādas is mentioned in the Lāṭyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_1590/> and a [[निषाद|Niṣāda]] '''[[स्थपति|Sthapati]],''' a leader of some kind, is referred to in the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1590/> and in a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] cited by the scholiast on that passage. Weber<ref name=fx6_ve1_1590/> thinks that the Niṣādas were the settled aborigines (form ''ni,'' ‘down,’ and ''sad,'' ‘settle’), a view supported by the fact that the ritual of the Viśvajit sacrifice<ref name=fx7_ve1_1590/> requires a temporary residence with Niṣādas; for the Niṣādas who would permit an Āryan to reside temporarily amongst them must have been partially amenable to Āryan influence. But the name might easily be applied to the whole body of aborigines outside the Āryan organization. Von Schroeder<ref name=fx8_ve1_1590/> thinks that the Niṣādas were most probably identical with the Nysæans, who, according to the Greek account, sent an embassy to Alexander when he was in the territory of the Aśvakas, but this identification is doubtful.<br>

निष्क
<u>'''Niṣka'''</u> is frequently found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1591/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1591/> denoting a gold ornament worn on the neck, as is shown by the two epithets ''[[निष्क|niṣka]]-kaṇṭha''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1591/> and ''[[निष्क|niṣka]]-grīva,''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1591/> ‘having a gold ornament on the neck.’ A [[निष्क|Niṣka]] of silver is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_1591/> As early as the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_1591/> traces are seen of the  use of Niṣkas as a sort of currency, for a singer celebrates the receipt of a hundred Niṣkas and a hundred steeds: he could hardly require the Niṣkas merely for purposes of personal adornment. Later the use of Niṣkas as currency is quite clear.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1591/> ''Cf.'' also '''[[कृष्णल|Kṛṣṇala]].'''<br>

निष्किरीय
<u>'''Niṣkirīya'''</u> is the name of a school of priests who are mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1592/> as holding a Sattra, or ‘sacrificial session.’<br>

निष्ट्य
<u>'''Niṣṭya'''</u> means in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1593/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1593/> an outsider or stranger. Hence the constellation usually known as Svāti (see '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]]''') is named Niṣṭyā in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1593/> because it occupies a position markedly away from the ecliptic.<br>

निहाका
<u>'''Nihākā'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1594/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1594/> appears to denote some phenomenon of a storm, perhaps the ‘whirlwind.’<br>

नीक्षण
<u>'''Nīkṣaṇa.'''</u> See '''[[नेक्षण|Nekṣaṇa]].'''<br>

नीच्य
<u>'''Nīcya'''</u> (‘living below’) is a designation of certain nations of the west. The Nīcyas are mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 14) as distinguished from the people of '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]],''' and no doubt mean the inhabitants of the Indus and Panjab regions. <br>

नीथ
<u>'''Nītha'''</u> (‘leading’), neut., means musical ‘mode’ and then ‘hymn of praise.’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1597/> The feminine form Nīthā occurs once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1597/> meaning ‘artifice.’<br>

नीनाह
<u>'''Nīnāha,'''</u> a word occurring once in the Atharvaveda (xix. 57, 4), seems to denote a ‘girdle’ or something similar, as derived from the verb ''nah,'' ‘fasten.’<br>

नीपातिथि
<u>'''Nīpātithi'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1599/> as the name of a man to whom a hymn<ref name=fx2_ve1_1599/> is ascribed by the Anukramaṇī (Index). A Sāman, or Chant, of his is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1599/><br>

नीलङ्गु
<u>'''Nīlaṅgu'''</u> is the name of a species of ‘worm’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1600/> in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or ‘horse sacrifice.’<br>

नील-शीर्ष्णी
<u>'''Nīla-śīrṣṇī,'''</u> ‘black-headed,’ is the name of an unknown animal in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or ‘horse sacrifice,’ in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1601/><br>

नीलागलसाल
<u>'''Nīlāgalasāla,'''</u> or, as the Paippalāda version reads, '''Nīlākalasālā,''' is the name, according to the commentator, of a graincreeper in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1602/> <br>

नीवार
<u>'''Nīvāra,'''</u> ‘wild rice,’ is mentioned in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1603/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1603/><br>

नीवि
<u>'''Nīvi'''</u> is the name of the ‘undergarment,’ probably a simple apron of cloth, worn by both men and women, but especially by the latter. It is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1604/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1604/><br>

नीहार
<u>'''Nīhāra,'''</u> ‘mist,’ occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1605/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1605/><br>

नृ
<u>'''Nṛ.'''</u> See '''Nara.'''<br>

नृति
<u>'''Nṛti'''</u> in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1607/> seems to mean a bag of skin. But though the Paippalāda recension has the same text, it is clear that we must read '''[[दृति|Dṛti]]''' with Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_1607/> and Whitney.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1607/> Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve1_1607/> renders the word ‘dancer,’ which makes no sense in the context.<br>

नृतू
<u>'''Nṛtū'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1608/> denoting a female ‘dancer.’ In another passage<ref name=fx2_ve1_1608/> [[नृति|Nṛti]] is found coupled with ''hāsa,'' ‘laughter,’ in the description of the funeral ritual; but though it is clear that a joyful celebration is meant (like the Irish ‘wake’ or the  old-fashioned feasting in Scotland after a funeral), it is difficult to be certain that actual dancing is here meant. Dancing is, however, often referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1608/> and later. Nṛttagīta, ‘dance and song,’ are mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1608/> as found in the sixth world. See also '''[[शैलूष|Śailūṣa]].'''<br>

नृ-पति
<u>'''Nṛ-pati,'''</u> ‘lord of men,’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1609/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1609/> denotes a ‘king’ or a man of the ruling class ('''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]''').<br>

नृ-मेध
<u>'''Nṛ-medha,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1610/> '''[[नृ|Nṛ]]-medhas,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1610/> is the name of a protégé of Agni in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1610/> where he also appears with '''Sumedhas''' in a hymn that Griffith<ref name=fx4_ve1_1610/> with justice declares to be unintelligible. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1610/> he is an unsuccessful rival of '''[[परुच्छेप|Parucchepa]],''' and in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1610/> he is an [[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]] and a seer of Sāmans (Chants).<br>

नृ-षद्
<u>'''Nṛ-ṣad,'''</u> ‘sitting among men,’ is the name of the father of '''[[कण्व|Kaṇva]]''' in the Rigveda (x. 31, 11). ''Cf.'' '''[[नार्षद|Nārṣada]].'''<br>

नेक्षण
<u>'''Nekṣaṇa'''</u> occurs once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1612/> where a ‘spit’ seems to be meant. In the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1612/> [[नीक्षण|Nīkṣaṇa]] occurs, and must have the same sense; Oldenberg<ref name=fx3_ve1_1612/> inclines to think that this word refers to the ‘inspection’ of food, to see if it is ready (as from ''ni-īkṣ,'' ‘look into’). <br>

नेमि
<u>'''Nemi'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1613/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1613/> the ‘felly’ of a chariot wheel. It was required to be of good wood (''su-drū''),<ref name=fx3_ve1_1613/> and was bent into shape.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1613/> ''Cf.'' '''[[रथ|Ratha]].'''<br>

नेष्टृ
<u>'''Neṣṭṛ,'''</u> the name of one of the chief priests at the Soma sacrifice, occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1614/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1614/> See '''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]].'''<br>

नैचा-शाख
<u>'''Naicā-śākha'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1615/> where Sāyaṇa renders it as ‘of low origin,’ but elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve1_1615/> he explains it as the name of a place. The former sense is accepted by Grassmann and Ludwig in their versions, and by Zimmer,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1615/> but Hillebrandt<ref name=fx4_ve1_1615/> points out that the reference is rather to the ‘low-branched’ Soma plant. ''Cf.'' '''[[कीकट|Kīkaṭa]]''' and '''[[प्रमगन्द|Pramaganda]].'''<br>

नैचु-दार
<u>'''Naicu-dāra'''</u> occurs in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1616/> meaning ‘composed of the wood of the Nicudāra.’ What tree is meant by the latter name is unknown.<br>

नैतन्धव
<u>'''Naitandhava'''</u> is mentioned as a place on the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1617/> and the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1617/><br>

नै-दाघ
<u>'''Nai-dāgha'''</u> is the name of the ‘summer’ season in the later Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1618/> ''Cf.'' '''[[ऋतु|Ṛtu]]''' and '''[[निदाघ|Nidāgha]].''' <br>

नै-दान
<u>'''Nai-dāna'''</u> is a term applied in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1619/> to a class of Vedic interpreters. Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_1619/> takes the Naidānas to be ‘etymologists,’ but Sieg<ref name=fx3_ve1_1619/> thinks they are the same as the '''Aitihāsikas''' or ‘legendarists.’<ref name=fx4_ve1_1619/><br>

नै-ध्रुवि
<u>'''Nai-dhruvi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Nidhruva,’ is the patronymic of '''[[कश्यप|Kaśyapa]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1620/><br>

नैमिशि
<u>'''Naimiśi'''</u> is the epithet of '''Śitibāhu [[ऐषकृत|Aiṣakṛta]]''' in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1621/> It is probably to be taken as an indication that Śitibāhu came from the Naimiśa forest.<br>

नैमिशीय
<u>'''Naimiśīya,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1622/> '''Naimiṣīya'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1622/> denotes the dwellers in the Naimiśa forest. They are mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1622/> and the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1622/> being clearly of special sanctity. Hence in the Epic the Mahābhārata is said to have been recited to the [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]] dwelling in the Naimiṣa forest.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1622/><br>

नैर्-उक्त
<u>'''Nair-ukta'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1623/> in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1623/> denotes a man who knows the true etymology of words, and explains their meaning accordingly. Yāska's [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] is the classic work of this school, and forms a commentary on an earlier [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]], the so-called Naighaṇṭuka, a glossary consisting of five collections of Vedic words. <br>

नै-षाद
<u>'''Nai-ṣāda,'''</u> a ‘man of [[निषाद|Niṣāda]],’ is mentioned in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxv. 15) and the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xxx. 8).<br>

नैषिध
<u>'''Naiṣidha'''</u> is the reading in the Śata atha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 3, 2, 1. 2) of the epithet of '''[[नड|Naḍa]],''' a king of the south. The later form of the name is Naiṣadha; the St. Petersburg Dictionarv suggests that its original form was Naiḥṣidha.<br>

नोधस्
<u>'''Nodhas'''</u> is the name of a poet who is mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1626/> and to whom certain of its hymns are ascribed.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1626/> In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1626/> he is called '''[[काक्षीवत|Kākṣīvata]],''' a ‘descendant of '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]].'''’ Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve1_1626/> regards him as contemporary with the defeat of '''[[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]].''' He was a '''[[गोतम|Gotama]].'''<ref name=fx5_ve1_1626/><br>

नौ
<u>'''Nau'''</u> is the regular word in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1627/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1627/> for a ‘boat’ or ‘ship.’ In the great majority of cases the ship was merely a boat for crossing rivers, though no doubt a large boat was needed for crossing many of the broad rivers of the Panjab as well as the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]''' and '''[[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]].''' Often no doubt the Nau was a mere dug-out canoe (''[[दारु|dāru]]'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_1627/> It is certainly against the theory<ref name=fx4_ve1_1627/> of the existence in Vedic times of an extensive sea trade that there is no mention of any of the parts of a ship, such as masts and sails, except the oar ('''[[अरित्र|Aritra]]'''), Yet there are some allusions indicating a trade more extensive than that implied by boats used for crossing rivers. The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_1627/> compares the ruin of a kingdom where Brahmins are oppressed to the  sinking of a ship which is leaking (''bhinnā''); though the language here employed can be made to fit the theory that the ship was only a canoe, it cannot naturally be so interpreted. Moreover, there is mention made in the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_1627/> of men who go to the ocean ('''[[सम्उद्र|Samudra]]''') eager for gain (''saniṣyavaḥ''). It is not altogether satisfactory to restrict such references with Zimmer<ref name=fx7_ve1_1627/> to the broad stream of the Indus after the union of that river with the tributaries of the Panjab. In the Rigveda<ref name=fx8_ve1_1627/> too it is said that the Aśvins rescued '''[[भुज्यु|Bhujyu]]''' in the ocean with a ship of a hundred oars (''śatāritra''). It is not easy to refuse to recognize here the existence of larger vessels with many oars used for sea voyages. The [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx9_ve1_1627/> at any rate, clearly refers to maritime navigation. See also '''[[सम्उद्र|Samudra]].'''<br>

न्यग्-रोध
<u>'''Nyag-rodha,'''</u> ‘growing downwards,’ is the name of the ''Ficus indica,'' a tree remarkable for sending down from its branches fibres which take root and form new stems. Though the tree is not mentioned by name in the Rigveda, it appears to have been known, as Pischel<ref name=fx1_ve1_1628/> has shown from a hymn<ref name=fx2_ve1_1628/> in which its characteristics may be recognized. It is frequently mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1628/> and the later literature.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1628/> The sacrificial bowls ('''[[चमस|Camasa]]''') were made of its wood.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1628/> It was doubtless of the greatest importance, as in modern times, to the Vedic village. The sister tree, the '''[[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]]''' (''Ficus religiosa''), already occurs in the Rigveda.<br>

न्य्-अङ्क
<u>'''Ny-aṅka'''</u> in the dual denotes in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1629/> and [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1629/> some part of the chariot, parallel with '''[[अङ्क|Aṅka]].''' The [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1629/> has Nyaṅkū, the dual of [[न्यङ्कु|Nyaṅku]]. <br>

न्यङ्कु
<u>'''Nyaṅku'''</u> is the name of an animal in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or ‘horse sacrifice,’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1630/> It seems clear that a kind a ‘gazelle’ is meant, but the commentary on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1630/> suggests ‘bear’ (''[[ऋक्ष|ṛkṣa]]'') as a variant rendering.<br>

न्य्-अस्तिका
<u>'''Ny-astikā'''</u> seems in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1631/> to denote a plant of some kind, identified by the scholiast with the Śaṅkhapuṣpikā (''Andropogon aciculatus'').<br>

न्य्-ओचनी
<u>'''Ny-ocanī'''</u> is found in the marriage hymn of the Rigveda (x. 85, 6), where some kind of ornament worn by women seems to be meant. The commentator Sāyaṇa interprets it as ‘female slave.’<br>

पक्ति
<u>'''Pakti'''</u> denotes a cooked object, probably a kind of ‘cake,’ in the Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1633/> One who cooks food is called '''Paktṛ.'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1633/><br>

पक्थ
<u>'''Paktha'''</u> is the name of a people in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1634/> where they appear as one of the tribes that opposed<ref name=fx2_ve1_1634/> the '''[[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]]-Bharatas''' in the '''[[दाशराज्ञ|Dāśarājña]].''' or ‘battle of the ten kings.’ Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_1634/> compares  them with the tribe of  and their country , mentioned as in the north-west of India by Herodotus,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1634/> and with the modern Pakhthūn in Eastern Afghanistan, holding that they were a northern tribe; this is probable, since the Bharatas seem to have occupied the [[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]], or ‘Middle Land.’ In three passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_1634/> a [[पक्थ|Paktha]] is referred to as a protégé of the Aśvins. The second connects him with '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]],''' whose tribe, the '''Pūrus,''' were aided by the Pakthas in their unsuccessful onslaught on '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]].''' In the third passage he seems specified as '''Tūrvāyaṇa,''' and appears as an opponent of '''Cyavāna.'''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1634/> Probably, therefore, [[पक्थ|Paktha]] in all cases denotes the king of the [[पक्थ|Paktha]] people.<br>

पक्व
<u>'''Pakva,'''</u> ‘cooked,’ is used substantively as meaning ‘cooked food’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1635/> or ‘cooked milk.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1635/> The word is also used of ‘baked’ bricks.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1635/><br>

पक्ष
<u>'''Pakṣa'''</u> is, in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1636/> applied to some part of a house, either the ‘side posts,’ according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1636/> Zimmer,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1636/> and Grill,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1636/> or ‘sides,’ as understood by Whitney<ref name=fx5_ve1_1636/> and Bloomfield.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1636/> The description of the roof ('''[[छदिस्|Chadis]]''') in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_1636/> as ''catuṣ-[[पक्ष|pakṣa]],'' ‘four-sided,’ tells in favour of the second explanation. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_1636/> [[पक्ष|Pakṣa]] is used of the sides of a chariot. For [[पक्ष|Pakṣa]] as the ‘half’ of a month, see '''[[मास|Māsa]].''' <br>

पक्षस्
<u>'''Pakṣas'''</u> is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1637/> and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1637/> meaning the ‘sides’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1637/> of a chariot. In the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve1_1637/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1637/> it is used of the sides of a hut or chamber ('''[[शाला|Śālā]]'''). In the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx6_ve1_1637/> it means the ‘wing’ of a door. In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve1_1637/> the ‘half’ of an army is so named, and in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_1637/> it means the ‘half’ of a month, or ‘fortnight.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[पक्ष|Pakṣa]].'''<br>

पक्षिन्
<u>'''Pakṣin'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1638/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1638/> denotes a ‘winged’ creature, more particularly a ‘bird.’<br>

पङ्क्ति
<u>'''Paṅkti,'''</u> originally a ‘set of five,’ denotes as early as the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1639/> a ‘series’ generally. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve1_1639/> the word is used of the series of a man's ancestors whom he purifies by certain conduct.<br>

पचत
<u>'''Pacata,'''</u> like '''[[पक्ति|Pakti]],''' denotes ‘cooked food’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1640/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1640/><br>

पचन
<u>'''Pacana'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1641/> and the Śatapatha Brāhamaṇa<ref name=fx2_ve1_1641/> denotes a ‘vessel for cooking’ food. <br>

पज्र
<u>'''Pajra'''</u> is the name of the family from which '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]]''' sprang ('''[[पज्रिय|Pajriya]]'''). It is mentioned several times in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1642/> According to Pischel,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1642/> the epithet ''[[पृक्ष-याम|pṛkṣa-yāma]]''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1642/> applied to them means ‘carrying out brilliant sacrificial performances,’ which won for them '''Śrutaratha's''' generosity. In two passages<ref name=fx4_ve1_1642/> Roth<ref name=fx5_ve1_1642/> sees a [[पज्र|Pajra]] called Sāmaṅ. This is uncertain, but in any case a [[पज्र|Pajra]] seems clearly alluded to. Elsewhere<ref name=fx6_ve1_1642/> it is very doubtful whether the word is a proper name at all. In the [[शाट्यायन|Śāṭyāyana]]<ref name=fx7_ve1_1642/> the Pajras are declared to be Aṅgirases.<br>

पज्रा
<u>'''Pajrā'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1643/> where Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_1643/> sees in the word the name of the wife of the sacrificer, '''[[पज्र|Pajra]],''' while Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_1643/> takes it to be an epithet (‘stout’) of the Soma plant. The sense is thus uncertain.<br>

पज्रिय
<u>'''Pajriya'''</u> ‘descendant of [[पज्र|Pajra]],’ is the patronymic<ref name=fx1_ve1_1644/> of '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]]''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1644/><br>

पञ्च-जनाः
<u>'''Pañca-janāḥ,'''</u> the ‘five peoples,’ are mentioned under various names in Vedic literature.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1645/> Who are meant by the five is very uncertain. The [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1645/> explains the five to be gods, men, Gandharvas and Apsarases, snakes, and the Fathers.  [[औपमन्यव|Aupamanyava]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1645/> held that the four castes ('''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]]''') and the '''Niṣādas''' made up the five, and Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx4_ve1_1645/> is of the same opinion. [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1645/> thinks that the five are the Gandharvas, fathers, gods, Asuras, and Rakṣases. No one of these explanations can be regarded as probable. Roth<ref name=fx6_ve1_1645/> and Geldner<ref name=fx7_ve1_1645/> think that all the peoples of the earth are méant: just as there are four quarters ('''[[दिश्|Diś]]'''), there are peoples at the four quarters (N. E. S. W.), with the Āryan folk in the middle. Zimmer<ref name=fx8_ve1_1645/> opposes this view on the ground that the inclusion of all peoples in one expression is not in harmony with the distinction so often made between Āryan and [[दास|Dāsa]]; that neither ''janāsaḥ,'' ‘men,’<ref name=fx9_ve1_1645/> nor ''mānuṣāḥ,'' ‘people,’<ref name=fx10_ve1_1645/> could be used of non-Āryans; that the Soma is referred to as being among the five tribes;<ref name=fx11_ve1_1645/> that the five tribes are mentioned as on the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],'''<ref name=fx12_ve1_1645/> and that Indra is ''[[पाञ्चजन्य|pāñcajanya]],''<ref name=fx13_ve1_1645/> ‘belonging to the five peoples.’ He concludes that Āryans alone are meant, and in particular the five tribes of the '''Anus, Druhyus, Yadus, Turvaśas,''' and '''Pūrus,''' who are all mentioned together in one or perhaps two hymns of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx14_ve1_1645/> and four of whom occur in another hymn.<ref name=fx15_ve1_1645/> But he admits that the expression might easily be used more generally later. Hopkins<ref name=fx16_ve1_1645/> has combated Zimmer's view, but his own opinion rests mainly on his theory that there was no people named [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]], but only a king of the Yadus called [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]], and that theory is not very probable. <br><br>In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx17_ve1_1645/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx18_ve1_1645/> the five peoples are opposed to the Bharatas, and in the former work<ref name=fx19_ve1_1645/> seven peoples are alluded to.<br>

पञ्च-दशी
<u>'''Pañca-daśī,'''</u> ‘the fifteenth day of the month,’ is already mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 5, 10, 5).<br>

पञ्च-नद
<u>'''Pañca-nada,'''</u> ‘having five streams,’ is not found until the epic period as the name of the Panjāb, which has no designation in the earlier literature. The importance of the Panjāb as the home<ref name=fx1_ve1_1647/> of the Rigveda has been greatly diminished by recent research, Hopkins,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1647/> Pischel,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1647/> and Geldner<ref name=fx4_ve1_1647/> having on different grounds shown reason for believing that the Rigveda, at least in great part, was composed farther east, in the '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]],''' which admittedly was the home of the later Vedic culture. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx5_ve1_1647/> considers that the Rigveda belongs in part to the Panjāb, or rather to Arachosia, and in part to the Middle Country. See also '''Kuru, [[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]].'''<br>

पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण
<u>'''Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa.'''</u> See '''Tāṇdya.'''<br>

पञ्चाल
<u>'''Pañcāla'''</u> is the later name<ref name=fx1_ve1_1649/> of the people called '''[[क्रिवि|Krivi]]''' in the Rigveda. The Pañcālas are rarely referred to except in connexion with the '''Kurus,''' and the kings of the Kuru-Pañcālas are mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1649/> In the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_1649/> the Pañcālas appear as the people of '''[[केशिन्|Keśin]] [[दाल्भ्य|Dālbhya]].'''  In the Upaniṣads and later<ref name=fx4_ve1_1649/> the Brahmins of the Pañcālas figure as taking part in philosophical and philological discussions. The Saṃhitopaniṣad [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1649/> makes mention of the [[प्राच्य|Prācya]]-Pañcālas.<br><br>The Pañcālas, no doubt, included other tribes besides the Krivis. The name seems to refer to five tribes, and it has been suggested<ref name=fx6_ve1_1649/> that the Pañcālas represent the five tribes of the Rigveda, but the suggestion is not very probable. There is no trace in Vedic literature of the Epic division of the Pañcālas into northern (''uttara'') and southern (''dakṣiṇa''). The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve1_1649/> mentions their town '''[[परिचक्रा|Paricakrā]];''' other towns to which allusion seems to be made were '''[[काम्पील|Kāmpīla]]''' and kauśāmbī.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1649/> Of their kings and chiefs, as distinguished from kings of the Kuru-Pañcālas, we hear of '''[[क्रैव्य|Kraivya]], [[दुर्मुख|Durmukha]], [[प्रवाहण जैवलि|Pravāhaṇa Jaivali]],''' and '''Śona.'''<br>

पञ्चाल-चण्ड
<u>'''Pañcāla-caṇḍa'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1650/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1650/> Āraṇyakas.<br>

पञ्चावि
<u>'''Pañcāvi'''</u> occurs several times in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1651/> in the sense of ‘aged five lamb-periods’ (of six months), that is, ‘thirty months old.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1651/><br>

पञ्चौदन
<u>'''Pañcaudana'''</u> is an adjective in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1652/> meaning ‘prepared with five rice-messes.’ The cooking of five rice dishes is referred to in the same Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1652/> <br>

पटल
<u>'''Paṭala'''</u> as early as the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1653/> denotes ‘section’ of a work, a sense occurring in the Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve1_1653/> and later.<br>

पठर्वन्
<u>'''Paṭharvan'''</u> appears to be the name of a man in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1654/> According to Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1654/> however, the word is Paṭharu, and is the name of a fort which was saved by a rain-storm from being set on fire.<br>

पड्गृभि
<u>'''Paḍgṛbhi,'''</u> ‘seizing by the foot,’<ref name=fx1_ve1_1655/> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1655/> of either a man<ref name=fx3_ve1_1655/> or a demon. See also '''[[पड्बीश|Paḍbīśa]].'''<br>

पड्-बीश
<u>'''Paḍ-bīśa,'''</u> the ‘foot-fetter’ of a horse in five passages, two in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1656/> and one each in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1656/> the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve1_1656/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1656/> Elsewhere<ref name=fx5_ve1_1656/> its uses are metaphorical. According to Roth,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1656/> the literal sense is ‘foot-fastening’ (''paḍ'' being = ''pad,'' ‘foot,’ and ''bīśa,'' written ''vīśa'' in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā, being connected with the Latin ''vincire,'' ‘bind’). Pischel<ref name=fx7_ve1_1656/> objects that the sense of ‘foot-fastening’ involves the absurdity, in the [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] passages, of a fine horse from the '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]''' (Indus) being spoken of as tearing up the peg to which it is fastened. He suggests instead the meaning of ‘hobble,’ which must be right.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1656/> <br>

पण
<u>'''Paṇa,'''</u> with '''[[प्रतिपण|Pratipaṇa]],''' is found in a hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1657/> denoting the process of bargaining and selling. The root ''paṇ,'' from which the word is derived, is employed in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1657/> while Paṇana in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1657/> denotes ‘trafficking.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[वणिज्|Vaṇij]].'''<br>

पणि
<u>'''Paṇi'''</u> in the Rigveda appears to denote a person who is rich, but who does not give offerings to the gods, or bestow '''Dakṣiṇās''' on the priests, and who is therefore an object of intense dislike to the composers of the Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1658/> Hence the gods are asked to attack the Paṇis, who are also referred to as being defeated with slaughter.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1658/> The [[पणि|Paṇi]] is opposed to the pious sacrificer as a niggard,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1658/> and is spoken of as a wolf,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1658/> the symbol of enmity. In some passages<ref name=fx5_ve1_1658/> the Paṇis definitely appear as mythological figures, demons who withhold the cows or waters of heaven, and to whom Saramā goes on a mission from Indra.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1658/> Among the Paṇis '''[[बृबु|Bṛbu]]''' was apparently important. In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_1658/> they are described as '''Bekanāṭas,''' or ‘usurers’ (?). In another<ref name=fx8_ve1_1658/> they are called '''Dasyus,''' and styled ''[[मृध्र-वाच्|mṛdhra-vāc]],'' probably ‘of hostile speech,’ and ''grathin,'' a word of uncertain meaning. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx9_ve1_1658/> thinks that the latter epithet refers to the continuous flow of a speech which  is not understood, and that ''[[मृध्र-वाच्|mṛdhra-vāc]]'' means ‘śpeaking an enemy's speech,’ though not necessarily with reference to non-Āryans.<ref name=fx10_ve1_1658/> In two passages<ref name=fx11_ve1_1658/> the Paṇis appear as '''Dāsas,''' and in one<ref name=fx12_ve1_1658/> a [[पणि|Paṇi]] is mentioned in connexion with wergeld ('''[[वैर|Vaira]]'''), being apparently regarded as equal to a man merely in the price put on his life, but in other respects as inferior.<br><br>It is difficult to be certain exactly who a [[पणि|Paṇi]] was. Roth<ref name=fx13_ve1_1658/> thinks that the word is derived from ''paṇ,'' ‘barter,’ and that the [[पणि|Paṇi]] is properly the man who will give nothing without return, hence the niggard, who neither worships the gods nor rewards their priests. This view is accepted by Zimmer<ref name=fx14_ve1_1658/> and by Ludwig.<ref name=fx15_ve1_1658/> The latter scholar thinks the apparent references to fights with Paṇis are to be explained by their having been aboriginal traders who went in caravans--as in Arabia and Northern Africa--prepared to fight, if need be, to protect their goods against attacks which the Āryans would naturally deem quite justified. He supports this explanation by the references to the Paṇis as Dasyus and Dāsas. It is, however, hardly necessary to do more than regard the Paṇis generally as non-worshippers of the gods favoured by the singers; the term is wide enough to cover either the aborigines or hostile Āryan tribes, as well as demons. Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx16_ve1_1658/> however, thinks that a real tribe is meant, the Parnians of Strabo, and that they were associated with the Dahae ('''[[दास|Dāsa]]'''). Moreover, he finds them associated in one passage<ref name=fx17_ve1_1658/> with the '''Pārāvatas,''' whom  he identifies with the  of Ptolemy,<ref name=fx18_ve1_1658/> and with '''Bṛṣaya,''' whom he connects with  of Arrian;<ref name=fx19_ve1_1658/> he also considers that the frequent<ref name=fx20_ve1_1658/> mention of the Paṇis as opponents of '''Divodāsa''' shows that the latter was on the Arachosian Haraqaiti ('''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''') fighting against the Parnians and Dahae, as well as other Iranian tribes. But the identification of [[पणि|Paṇi]] and the Parnians is needless, especially as the root ''paṇ,'' which is found also in the Greek , shows a satisfactory derivation, while the transfer of Divodāsa to the Haraqaiti is improbable. See also '''Divodāsa''' and '''[[बेकनाट|Bekanāṭa]].'''<br>

पण्डित
<u>'''Paṇḍita,'''</u> a ‘learned man,’ is not found until the [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] period.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1659/><br>

पतङ्ग
<u>'''1. Pataṅga,'''</u> ‘flying,’ denotes a ‘winged insect’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1660/> and the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1660/><br>

पतङ्ग प्राजापत्य
<u>'''2. Pataṅga Prājāpatya'''</u> (‘descendant of Prajāpati’) is credited by the Anukramaṇī (Index) with the authorship of a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1661/> in which [[पतङ्ग|Pataṅga]] means the ‘sun-bird.’ He is also mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1661/><br>

पतञ्चल काप्य
<u>'''Patañcala Kāpya'''</u> is the name of a sage mentioned twice in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1662/> According to Weber,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1662/> his  name is reminiscent of '''[[कपिल|Kapila]]''' and Patañjali of the ŚāṅkhyaYoga system, but this suggestion may be regarded as quite improbable.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1662/><br>

पतत्रिन्
<u>'''Patatrin'''</u> denotes a ‘flying creature’ generally in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1663/> or more particularly a ‘bird’ in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1663/><br>

पताका
<u>'''Patākā,'''</u> ‘banner,’ is not found until the Adbhuta [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1664/> Its Vedic equivalent is '''[[ध्वज|Dhvaja]].'''<br>

पति
<u>'''Pati, Patnī.'''</u>--Under these words denoting primarily, as the evidence collected in the St. Petersburg Dictionary shows, ‘lord’ and ‘lady,’ and so ‘husband’ and ‘wife,’ it is convenient to consider the marital relations of the Vedic community.<br><br>''Child Marriage.''--Marriage in the early Vedic texts appears essentially as a union of two persons of full development. This is shown by the numerous references<ref name=fx1_ve1_1665/> to unmarried girls who grow old in the house of their fathers (''[[अमा-जुर्|amā-jur]]''), and who adorn themselves in desire of marriage, as well as to the paraphernalia of spells and potions used in the Atharvavedic tradition<ref name=fx2_ve1_1665/> to compel the love of man or woman respectively, while even the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1665/> itself seems to present us with a spell by which a  lover seeks to send all the household to sleep when he visits his beloved. Child wives first occur regularly in the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period, though it is still uncertain to what extent the rule of marriage before puberty there obtained.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1665/> The marriage ritual also quite clearly presumes that the marriage is a real and not a nominal one: an essential feature is the taking of the bride to her husband's home, and the ensuing cohabitation.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1665/><br><br>''Limitations on Marriage.''--It is difficult to say with certainty within what limits marriage was allowed. The dialogue of Yama and Yamī in the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_1665/> seems clearly to point to a prohibition of the marriage of brother and sister. It can hardly be said, as Weber<ref name=fx7_ve1_1665/> thinks, to point to a practice that was once in use and later became antiquated. In the Gobhila [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_1665/> and the [[धर्म|Dharma]] Sūtras<ref name=fx9_ve1_1665/> are found prohibitions against marriage in the '''[[गोत्र|Gotra]]''' (‘family’) or within six degrees on the mother's or father's side, but in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx10_ve1_1665/> marriage is allowed in the third or fourth generation, the former being allowed, according to Harisvamin,<ref name=fx11_ve1_1665/> by the Kāṇvas, and the second by the Saurāṣṭras, while the Dākṣiṇātyas allowed marriage with the daughter of the mother's brother or the son of the father's sister, but presumably not with the daughter of the mother's sister or the son of the father's brother. The prohibition of marriage within the [[गोत्र|Gotra]] cannot then have existed,<ref name=fx12_ve1_1665/> though naturally marriages  outside the [[गोत्र|Gotra]] were frequent.<ref name=fx13_ve1_1665/> Similarity of caste was also not an essential to marriage, as hypergamy was permitted even by the [[धर्म|Dharma]] Sūtras,<ref name=fx14_ve1_1665/> so that a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] could marry wives of any lower caste, a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] wives of the two lowest castes as well as of his own caste, a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] a [[शूद्रा|Śūdrā]] as well as a Vaiśyā, although the [[शूद्रा|Śūdrā]] marriages were later disapproved ''in toto.'' Instances of such intermarriage are common in the Epic, and are viewed as normal in the Bṛhaddevatā.<ref name=fx15_ve1_1665/><br><br>It was considered proper that the younger brothers and sisters should not anticipate their elders by marrying before them. The later Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx16_ve1_1665/> present a series of names expressive of such anticipation, censuring as sinful those who bear them. These terms are the ''pari-vividāna,''<ref name=fx17_ve1_1665/> or perhaps ''agre-dadhus,''<ref name=fx18_ve1_1665/> the man who, though a younger brother, marries before his elder brother, the latter being then called the ''[[परिवित्त|parivitta]];''<ref name=fx19_ve1_1665/> the ''agre-[[दिधिषु|didhiṣu]],''<ref name=fx20_ve1_1665/> the man who weds a younger daughter while her elder sister is still unmarried; and the '''[[दिधिषू-पति|Didhiṣū-pati]],'''<ref name=fx21_ve1_1665/> who is the husband of the latter. The passages do not explicitly say that the exact order of birth must always be followed, but the mention of the terms shows that the order was often broken.<br><br>''Widow Remarriage.''--The remarriage of a widow was  apparently permitted. This seems originally to have taken the form of the marriage of the widow to the brother or other nearest kinsman of the dead man in order to produce children. At any rate, the ceremony is apparently alluded to in a funeral hymn of the Rigveda;<ref name=fx22_ve1_1665/> for the alternative explanation, which sees in the verse a reference to the ritual of the Puruṣamendha (‘human sacrifice’), although accepted by Hillebrandt<ref name=fx23_ve1_1665/> and Delbrück,<ref name=fx24_ve1_1665/> is not at all probable, while the ordinary view is supported by the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] evidence.<ref name=fx25_ve1_1665/> Moreover, another passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx26_ve1_1665/> clearly refers to the marriage of the widow and the husband's brother (''[[देवृ|devṛ]]''), which constitutes what the Indians later knew as Niyoga.<ref name=fx27_ve1_1665/> This custom was probably not followed except in cases where no son was already born. This custom was hardly remarriage in the strict sense, since the brother might--so far as appears--be already married himself. In the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx28_ve1_1665/> a verse refers to a charm which would secure the reunion, in the next world, of a wife and her second husband. Though, as Delbrück<ref name=fx29_ve1_1665/> thinks, this very possibly refers to a case in which the first husband was still alive,<ref name=fx30_ve1_1665/> but was impotent or had lost caste (''patita''),<ref name=fx31_ve1_1665/> still it is certain that the later [[धर्म|Dharma]] Sūtras<ref name=fx32_ve1_1665/> began to recognize ordinary remarriage in case of the death of the first husband.  Pischel<ref name=fx33_ve1_1665/> finds some evidence in the Rigveda<ref name=fx34_ve1_1665/> to the effect that a woman could remarry if her husband disappeared and could not be found or heard of.<br><br>''Polygamy.''--A Vedic Indian could have more than one wife. This is proved clearly by many passages in the Rigveda;<ref name=fx35_ve1_1665/> Manu, according to the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx36_ve1_1665/> had ten wives; and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx37_ve1_1665/> explains polygamy by a characteristic legend. Moreover, the king regularly has four wives attributed to him, the [[महिषी|Mahiṣī]],<ref name=fx38_ve1_1665/> the Parivṛktī,<ref name=fx39_ve1_1665/> the [[वावाता|Vāvātā]],<ref name=fx40_ve1_1665/> and the [[पालागली|Pālāgalī]].<ref name=fx41_ve1_1665/> The [[महिषी|Mahiṣī]] appears to be the chief wife, being the first one married according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx42_ve1_1665/> The Parivṛktī, ‘the neglected,’ is explained by Weber<ref name=fx43_ve1_1665/> and Pischel<ref name=fx44_ve1_1665/> as one that has had no son. The [[वावाता|Vāvātā]] is ‘the favourite,’ while the [[पालागली|Pālāgalī]] is, according to Weber, the daughter of the last of the court officials. The names are curious, and not very intelligible, but the evidence points to the wife first wedded alone being a wife in the fullest sense. This view is supported by the fact emphasized by  Delbrück,<ref name=fx45_ve1_1665/> that in the sacrifice the [[पत्नी|Patnī]] is usually mentioned in the singular, apparent exceptions being due to some mythological reason.<ref name=fx46_ve1_1665/> Zimmer<ref name=fx47_ve1_1665/> is of opinion that polygamy is dying out in the Rigvedic period, monogamy being developed from pologamy; Weber,<ref name=fx48_ve1_1665/> however, thinks that polygamy is secondary, a view that is supported by more recent anthropology.<ref name=fx49_ve1_1665/><br><br>''Polyandry.''--On the other hand, polyandry is not Vedic.<ref name=fx50_ve1_1665/> There is no passage containing any clear reference to such a custom. The most that can be said is that in the Rigveda<ref name=fx51_ve1_1665/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx52_ve1_1665/> verses are occasionally found in which husbands are mentioned in relation to a single wife. It is difficult to be certain of the correct explanation of each separate instance of this mode of expression; but even if Weber's<ref name=fx53_ve1_1665/> view, that the plural is here used ''majestatis causā,'' is not accepted, Delbrück's<ref name=fx54_ve1_1665/> explanation by mythology is probably right. In other passages<ref name=fx55_ve1_1665/> the plural is simply generic.<br><br>''Marital Relations.''--Despite polygamy, however, there is ample evidence that the marriage tie was not, as Weber<ref name=fx56_ve1_1665/> has suggested, lightly regarded as far as the fidelity of the wife was concerned. There is, however, little trace of the husband's being expected to be faithful as a matter of morality. Several  passages,<ref name=fx57_ve1_1665/> indeed, forbid, with reference to ritual abstinence, intercourse with the ''[[स्त्री|strī]]'' of another. This may imply that adultery on the husband's part was otherwise regarded as venial. But as the word ''[[स्त्री|strī]]'' includes all the ‘womenfolk,’ daughters and slaves, as well as wife, the conclusion can hardly be drawn that intercourse with another man's ‘wife’ was normally regarded with indifference.<ref name=fx58_ve1_1665/> The curious ritual of the Varuṇapraghāsās,<ref name=fx59_ve1_1665/> in which the wife of the sacrificer is questioned as to her lovers, is shown by Delbrück<ref name=fx60_ve1_1665/> to be a part of a rite meant to expiate unchastity on the part of a wife, not as a normal question for a sacrificer to put to his own wife. Again, Yājñavalkya's doctrine in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx61_ve1_1665/> which seems to assert that no one cares if a wife is unchaste (''paraḥ-puṃsā'') or not, really means that no one cares if the wife is away from the men who are sacrificing, as the wives of the gods are apart from them during the particular rite in question. Monogamy is also evidently approved,<ref name=fx62_ve1_1665/> so that some higher idea of morality was in course of formation. On the other hand, no Vedic text gives us the rule well known to other Indo-Germanic<ref name=fx63_ve1_1665/> peoples that the adulterer taken in the act can be killed with impunity, though the later legal literature has traces of this rule.<ref name=fx64_ve1_1665/> There is also abundant evidence that the standard of ordinary sexual morality was not high.<br><br>''Hetairai.''--In the Rigveda<ref name=fx65_ve1_1665/> there are many references to illegitimate love and to the abandonment of the offspring of  such unions,<ref name=fx66_ve1_1665/> especially in the case of a protégé of Indra, often mentioned as the ''parāvṛkta'' or ''[[परावृज्|parāvṛj]].''<ref name=fx67_ve1_1665/> The ‘son of a maiden’ (''kumārī-[[पुत्र|putra]]'') is already spoken of in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx68_ve1_1665/> Such a person appears with a metronymic in the [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] period:<ref name=fx69_ve1_1665/> this custom may be the origin of metronymics such as those which make up a great part of the lists of teachers (Vaṃśas) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx70_ve1_1665/> The Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx71_ve1_1665/> refers to illicit unions of [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] and [[आर्य|Ārya]], both male and female, besides giving in its list of victims at the Puruṣamedha, or ‘human sacrifice,’ several whose designations apparently mean ‘courtesan’ (''atītvarī'')<ref name=fx72_ve1_1665/> and ‘procuress of abortion’ (''atiṣkadvarī''),<ref name=fx73_ve1_1665/> while the ‘dyeing woman’ (''[[रजयित्री|rajayitrī]]'') is dedicated to sensuality.<ref name=fx74_ve1_1665/> Pischel and Geldner also see many references to Hetairai in other passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx75_ve1_1665/> especially where mention is made of Uṣas, the goddess of Dawn, who in their view is the characteristic Hetaira. At any rate, there is little doubt that the ‘dancer’ (''[[नृतू|nṛtū]]'') referred to in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx76_ve1_1665/> was a Hetaira. When women are referred to as going to the '''[[समन|Samana]],''' or ‘place of meeting,’ Hetairai are probably also meant.<ref name=fx77_ve1_1665/> Grave cases of immorality are alluded to in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx78_ve1_1665/> The love of father and daughter, as shown in the myth of Prajāpati,<ref name=fx79_ve1_1665/> is evidently censured, but the actual existence of this form of incest is recognized in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx80_ve1_1665/> Girls who had lost their  natural protectors--father or brother<ref name=fx81_ve1_1665/> --were apt to be reduced to live by immorality.<br><br>''Forms of Marriage.''--The state of society revealed in the Vedic age seems to point to considerable freedom on the part of both man and woman in selecting a wife or a husband. At any rate, it is not clear that either the father or the mother controlled the marriage of son or daughter of mature age,<ref name=fx82_ve1_1665/> though no doubt the parents or parent often arranged a suitable match.<ref name=fx83_ve1_1665/> The marriage was frequently arranged through an intermediary, the ‘wooer’ (''vara''),<ref name=fx84_ve1_1665/> presumably after those concerned had in effect come to an agreement. The sale of a daughter was not unknown,<ref name=fx85_ve1_1665/> but a certain amount of discredit would seem to have attached to it,<ref name=fx86_ve1_1665/> and sons-in-law in such cases were sometimes stingy. On the other hand, dowries were not infrequently given, especially no doubt when damsels Suffered from bodily defects.<ref name=fx87_ve1_1665/> Occasionally marriages by  capture may have taken place, but only as knightly feats, as when '''[[विमद|Vimada]]''' carried off '''Purumitra's''' daughter against her father's wish, but very possibly with her own consent.<ref name=fx88_ve1_1665/> The later law-books and the Epic describe in much detail various forms of marriage, but they all seem reducible to three types: (''a'') that which is based on mutual consent, the ''prājāpatya'' (‘connected with Prajāpati’); (''b'') that in which a price is paid for the bride, the ''āsura'' (‘Asura-like’), ''ārṣa'' (‘connected with the Ṛṣis’), ''brāhma'' (‘relating to Brahman’), or ''[[दैव|daiva]]'' (‘divine’); (''c'') those which consist in stealing the bride, the ''kṣātra'' (‘warrior-like’) or the ''rākṣasa'' (‘demon-like’) mode, of all of which traces are found in Vedic literature.<ref name=fx89_ve1_1665/> For instance, the gift of a maiden for services rendered or other object is exemplified in the story of '''[[च्यवन|Cyavana]]''' in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx90_ve1_1665/> and in that of '''[[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]]''' in the Bṛhaddevatā.<ref name=fx91_ve1_1665/><br><br>''Wedding Ceremony.''--In normal marriages the bridal was celebrated by an elaborate ceremony which bears in essentials and details the strongest resemblance to the form observed by other Indo-Germanic as well as non-Indo-Germanic peoples,<ref name=fx92_ve1_1665/> and which was destined to secure the stability and fruitfulness of the union. The ceremony commenced at the bride's house,<ref name=fx93_ve1_1665/> to which the bridegroom with his friends and relations repaired, and in which he met the friends and relations of the bride.<ref name=fx94_ve1_1665/> A cow or cows were slain for the entertainment of the guests.<ref name=fx95_ve1_1665/> The bridegroom having caused the bride to mount a stone, formally grasped her hand, and led her round the household  fire.<ref name=fx96_ve1_1665/> This act constituted the marriage, the husband hence being called ‘he who takes by the hand’ (''[[हस्त|hasta]]-[[ग्राभ|grābha]]'').<ref name=fx97_ve1_1665/> The festivities being over,<ref name=fx98_ve1_1665/> the bridegroom took the bride to his home on a car in a marriage procession,<ref name=fx99_ve1_1665/> all to the accompaniment of suitable stanzas. Then followed cohabitation.<ref name=fx100_ve1_1665/><br><br>''Wife's Property and Status.''--We have very little information as to the legal relations of wife and husband after marriage. It may be assumed that the husband appropriated the wife's dowry, if any, as well as her earnings, if any: even in the Epic<ref name=fx101_ve1_1665/> the rise of the recognition of women's property as their own (''[[स्त्री|strī]]-[[धन|dhana]]'') is only slow. That the husband was absolute master of a wife as of a slave is not probable, though he doubtless exercised the same power of correction as was expressly allowed in the eighteenth century by English law. The poetical ideal<ref name=fx102_ve1_1665/> of the family was decidedly high, and we have no reason to doubt that it was often actually fulfilled. Moreover, the wife on her marriage was at once given an honoured position in the house; she is emphatically mistress in her husband's home, exercising authority over her fatherin-law, her husband's brothers, and her unmarried sisters.<ref name=fx103_ve1_1665/> No doubt the case contemplated is one in which the eldest son  of a family has become its head owing to the decrepitude<ref name=fx104_ve1_1665/> of the parents, his wife then taking the place of the mistress of the joint family while the brothers and sisters are still unmarried. It is not inconsistent with the great stress elsewhere<ref name=fx105_ve1_1665/> laid on the respect due to a father-in-law, who then is probably regarded as still in full possession of his faculties, and controls the house while his son continues to live with him. The respect would no doubt equally apply if the son had set up a separate family of his own.<ref name=fx106_ve1_1665/><br><br>Moreover, the wife was a regular participator in the offerings of the husband. In this connexion the term '''[[पत्नी|Patnī]]''' regularly applies to her in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx107_ve1_1665/> where '''[[जाया|Jāyā]]''' designates her in her conjugal capacity, not in that of sharer in the sacrifice. In this respect her position gradually deteriorated: thus the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx108_ve1_1665/> describes a certain ceremony in which the wife (''[[जाया|jāyā]]'') alone offered the oblation in former times, while later a priest might do so instead. The same [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] shows other traces of a lowering in the position of women, probably due to the growing sense of the importance of ceremonial priority.<ref name=fx109_ve1_1665/> So in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx110_ve1_1665/> women generally are classed with dice and drink as three chief evils, and woman is declared to be ‘untruth,’<ref name=fx111_ve1_1665/> and connected with Nirṛti, ‘calamity.’<ref name=fx112_ve1_1665/> A woman too, according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx113_ve1_1665/> is inferior even to a bad man, and a sarcastic reference is made in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx114_ve1_1665/> to her power of  getting things from her husband by cajolery at night. On the other hand must be set the encomia on woman: a woman is half her husband,<ref name=fx115_ve1_1665/> and completes him;<ref name=fx116_ve1_1665/> and in the Rigveda<ref name=fx117_ve1_1665/> attacks on women mingle with the general assumption of their good qualities. None the less, the Brāhmaṇas clearly indicate a gradual decline in their position, which is evident from the rule that requires the wife to eat after her husband.<ref name=fx118_ve1_1665/> Scolds were also known: the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx119_ve1_1665/> praises the wife ‘who does not answer back’ (''aprativādinī''). Women bore no part in political life: men go to the assembly, not women, the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx120_ve1_1665/> expressly says. On the other hand, with the advance of education, women shared in the intellectual interests of the day, as is exemplified by Yājñavalkya's<ref name=fx121_ve1_1665/> two wives, of whom one was interested in his philosophical discussions, the other not. Other women are also referred to in the Upaniṣads as teachers, but whether they were married is not certain.<ref name=fx122_ve1_1665/><br><br>But the main object of a woman's marriage was the production of children, this being repeatedly asserted in the Rigveda and later.<ref name=fx123_ve1_1665/> The desire for offspring, as was natural in a society which mainly counted relationship through the father, took the form of a wish for a son to perform the necessary funeral rites for the father, and to continue his line. It was no doubt possible to adopt a son, but in the Rigveda<ref name=fx124_ve1_1665/> this custom is plainly viewed as unsatisfactory. The practice  is recognized,<ref name=fx125_ve1_1665/> as we have seen above of Niyoga, in the appointment of a brother to beget children with the wife of a dead man, or perhaps of a man who is childless. ‘Sonlessness’ (''avīratā'') is placed on the same level as lack of property (''amati''), and Agni is besought to protect from it.<ref name=fx126_ve1_1665/> The birth of a daughter was certainly not specially welcome: the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx127_ve1_1665/> in one hymn distinctly invokes the birth of a son, and deprecates that of a daughter, while the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx128_ve1_1665/> contains an old verse which says that a daughter is a misery (''kṛpaṇam''), while a son is a light in the highest heaven (''jyotir ha putraḥ parame vyoman''). But there is no proof that the Vedic Indians practised the exposure of female children. This conclusion, deduced from certain passages in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx129_ve1_1665/> by Zimmer<ref name=fx130_ve1_1665/> and Delbrück,<ref name=fx131_ve1_1665/> has been disproved by Bo7htlingk.<br><br>''Child Life.''--No doubt the care of a child was left to the mother, but we learn little from the earlier literature<ref name=fx132_ve1_1665/> of the life of the young. The length of the period of pregnancy is frequently placed at ten (doubtless lunar) months.<ref name=fx133_ve1_1665/> On birth the child was first fed with milk or ghee, and then given the breast.<ref name=fx134_ve1_1665/> On the eighth day after birth  the infant was washed.<ref name=fx135_ve1_1665/> The cutting of the teeth was also a solemn occasion,<ref name=fx136_ve1_1665/> and is the subject of a hymn in the Atharvaveda. Reference is also made to children's learning to speak, which the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx137_ve1_1665/> ascribes to the end of the first year of life. The [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx138_ve1_1665/> asserts that the words '''Tata''' and '''[[तात|Tāta]],''' onomatopoetic words like ‘dada,’<ref name=fx139_ve1_1665/> are the first words of a child's speech, giving therein perhaps an unfair prominence to the father. The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx140_ve1_1665/> further contains at least one hymn for the ceremony of the first shaving of the young man's beard. The giving of a name was also an occasion of importance, a second one being often added.<ref name=fx141_ve1_1665/><br><br>''Satī.''--On the death of her husband, in some cases the widow burned herself or was burned by his relations.<ref name=fx142_ve1_1665/> This is clearly implied in the reference to this ancient custom in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx143_ve1_1665/> On the other hand, the Rigveda does not contemplate the custom anywhere, but on the contrary considers the widow as married apparently to the brother of the dead man.<ref name=fx144_ve1_1665/> The custom of Suttee would therefore appear buring the Vedic age to have been in abeyance, at least as a general rule. At all times the practice seems to have been mainly usual among families of the warrior class, to judge from the other Indo-Germanic parallels.<ref name=fx145_ve1_1665/> In other classes  the survival of wives was more necessary, and the remarriage of widows, whether prohibited or allowed in the texts, is proof that there were widows who could be remarried.<ref name=fx146_ve1_1665/><br>

पत्ति
<u>'''Patti'''</u> is used in the Atharvaveda (vii. 62, 1) to designate the ‘foot soldier’ in war as opposed to the '''[[रथिन्|Rathin]],''' ‘charioteer,’ the latter defeating (''ji'') the former. One of the epithets of Rudra in the [[शतरुद्रिय|Śatarudriya]] liturgy of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xvi. 19) is ‘lord of footmen’ (''pattīnāṃ pati'').<br>

पत्नी
<u>'''Patnī.'''</u> See '''Pati.''' A part of the house is the ''Patnīnāṃ [[सदन|Sadana]],'' mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1667/> presumably the women's quarters. The phrase is borrowed from the ''Patnīśāla,'' ‘hut for the wife,’ of the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1667/> ritual.<br>

पथिन् सौभर
<u>'''Pathin Saubhara'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[सोभरि|Sobhari]]'''’) is mentioned in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1668/> as the pupil of '''[[अयास्य आङ्गिरस|Ayāsya Āṅgirasa]].'''<br>

पथि-कृत्
<u>'''Pathi-kṛt,'''</u> ‘path-maker,’ is not a rare epithet in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1669/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1669/> showing clearly the importance naturally attached in primitive times to the finding of roads. The frequency  with which the epithet is applied to Agni<ref name=fx3_ve1_1669/> suggests that there is here an allusion to fire burning the primæval forest and rendering advance possible. The god Pūṣan is ''[[पथि-कृत्|pathi-kṛt]],'' as guarding the flocks.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1669/> The [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_1669/> or seers, as ‘path-makers,’ may be compared with the Roman Pontifices.<br>

पद्
<u>'''Pad'''</u> in the Atharvaveda (xix. 6, 2) and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xi. 3, 2, 3) denotes a ‘quarter.’ This sense is derived from the primary meaning of ‘foot,’ which as applied to quadrupeds would represent ‘one-fourth.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[पाद|Pāda]].'''<br>

पद
<u>'''Pada'''</u> in the sense of ‘quarter of a stanza’ is found as early as the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1671/> and often later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1671/> In the Brāhmaṇas it also denotes a ‘word’ as opposed to a ‘letter’ ('''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]]''').<ref name=fx3_ve1_1671/><br>

पदि
<u>'''Padi'''</u> is found once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1672/> where, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, the word probably designates some kind of animal. [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1672/> explains it as equivalent to ''gantu,'' ‘a moving creature,’ but [[दुर्ग|Durga]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1672/> as meaning ‘bird.’ The passage may refer to catching the Padi in a net (''? [[मुक्षीजा|mukṣījā]]'').<ref name=fx4_ve1_1672/><br>

पयस्
<u>'''Payas'''</u> denotes the ‘milk’ of the cow in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1673/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1673/> More generally it has also the sense of ‘sap’ or ‘fluid’  found in plants,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1673/> and giving them life and strength. In other passages it denotes the ‘water’ of heaven.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1673/> A vow to live for a time on milk alone occurs in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_1673/><br>

पयस्या
<u>'''Payasyā'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve1_1674/> denotes curds, said to consist of a mixture of sour milk and hot or cold fresh milk.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1674/><br>

पर आट्णार
<u>'''Para Āṭṇāra'''</u> (‘descendant of Aṭṇāra’) appears in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1675/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve1_1675/> as one of the ancient great kings who won sons by performing a particular sacrifice. In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1675/> he is styled [[हैरण्यनाभ|Hairaṇyanābha]], ‘descendant of [[हिरण्यनाभ|Hiraṇyanābha]],’ and in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1675/> he is called Para Āhlāra [[वैदेह|Vaideha]], a fact testifying to the close connexion of '''[[कोसल|Kosala]]''' and '''[[विदेह|Videha]].''' A '''[[यज्ञ-गाथा|Yajña-gāthā]],''' or ‘sacrificial verse,’ there<ref name=fx5_ve1_1675/> cited mentions '''[[हिरण्यनाभ|Hiraṇyanābha]] [[कौसल्य|Kausalya]]''' in connexion with Para.<br>

परम-ज्या
<u>'''Parama-jyā,'''</u> ‘of supreme power,’ is understood by Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve1_1676/> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1676/> as the proper name of a great man among the '''Yadus.''' But it is doubtful whether the word is more than an epithet.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1676/> <br>

परशु
<u>'''Paraśu'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1677/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1677/> denotes the axe of the woodcutter. Of its form we know nothing. A red-hot axe was used in a form of ordeal ('''[[दिव्य|Divya]]''') applied in accusations of theft.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1677/> See also '''[[पर्शु|Parśu]].'''<br>

परश्वन्
<u>'''Paraśvan.'''</u> See '''[[परस्वन्त्|Parasvant]].'''<br>

परस्वन्त्
<u>'''Parasvant'''</u> denotes a large wild animal which Roth<ref name=fx1_ve1_1679/> conjectures to be the wild ass. It is mentioned in the Vṛṣākapi hymn<ref name=fx2_ve1_1679/> of the Rigveda, twice in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1679/> and in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1679/> in all of which passages the sense of ‘wild ass’ is satisfactory. More doubtful is the meaning of the word ''paraśvā(n)'' in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_1679/> where the commentary explains it as ‘serpent.’ It is, of course, quite possible that the word has nothing to do with ''[[परस्वन्त्|parasvant]].'' Bühler<ref name=fx6_ve1_1679/> suggests connexion with the Pāli ''palāsāda,'' ‘rhinoceros.’<br>

परा-वृज्
<u>'''Parā-vṛj'''</u> is a term found in four passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1680/> in all of which it refers to a person in a forlorn condition, while one<ref name=fx2_ve1_1680/> of them also speaks of him as going south. Sāyaṇa's<ref name=fx3_ve1_1680/> view that the word is a proper name is most unlikely, while Grassmann's<ref name=fx4_ve1_1680/> explanation of it as ‘cripple’ is still less probable.  Roth's<ref name=fx5_ve1_1680/> interpretation of it as ‘exile’ seems clearly right in the passage which refers to the [[परावृज्|Parāvṛj]] as going south. Zimmer<ref name=fx6_ve1_1680/> accepts Roth's view for this passage, but in the others sees a reference to the child of a maiden exposed by her and in danger of being eaten by insects (''vamrī''). This view is supported by the fact that ''parāvṛkta'' seems to have the same sense,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1680/> and is accepted by Oldenberg.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1680/><br>

पराशर
<u>'''Parāśara'''</u> is mentioned with '''[[शतयातु|Śatayātu]]''' and '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]''' in the Rigvedic hymn celebrating '''Sudās''''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1681/> victory over the ten kings. According to the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1681/> he was a son of [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]], but the Epic version makes him a son of '''[[शक्ति|Śakti]]''' and grandson of [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]. Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve1_1681/> thinks that he is mentioned in the Rigveda along with [[शतयातु|Śatayātu]], perhaps his uncle, and his grandfather [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]], as the three sages who approached Indra and won his favour for [[सुदास्|Sudās]]. He is erroneously credited with the authorship of certain hymns of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1681/> by the Anukramaṇī (Index).<br>

परि-क्षित्
<u>'''Pari-kṣit'''</u> appears in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1682/> as a king in whose realm, that of the Kurus, prosperity and peace abound. The verses in which he is celebrated are later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1682/> called ''Pārikṣityaḥ,'' and the Brāhmaṇas explain that Agni is ''[[परि-क्षित्|pari-kṣit]]'' because he dwells among men. Hence Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_1682/> and Bloomfield<ref name=fx4_ve1_1682/> regard [[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]] in the Atharvaveda not as a human king at all. This may be correct, but it is not certain. Both Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve1_1682/> and  Oldenberg<ref name=fx6_ve1_1682/> recognize [[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]] as a real king, a view supported by the fact that in the later Vedic literature King '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]]''' bears the patronymic '''[[पारिक्षित|Pārikṣita]].''' If this be so, [[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]] belonged to the later period, since the [[अथर्वन्|Atharvan]] passage in which his name occurs is certainly late, and none of the other Saṃhitās know [[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]] at all. The Epic<ref name=fx7_ve1_1682/> makes him grandfather of Pratiśravas and great-grandfather of Pratīpa, and Zimmer,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1682/> probably with justice, compares the [[प्रातिसुत्वन|Prātisutvana]] and Pratīpa found in another late [[अथर्वन्|Atharvan]] passage.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1682/> But '''Devāpi''' and '''Śantanu''' cannot be brought into connexion with Pratīpa.<ref name=fx9_ve1_1682/><br>

परि-घ
<u>'''Pari-gha'''</u> denotes an iron bolt or bar in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 24, 6. 10. 15) as often later.<br>

परि-चक्रा
<u>'''Pari-cakrā'''</u> is according to one reading the name of a '''[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]]''' town mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1684/> and identified by Weber<ref name=fx2_ve1_1684/> with the later Ekacakrā, which was near '''[[काम्पील|Kāmpīla]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1684/> There is a various reading [[परिवक्रा|Parivakrā]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1684/><br>

परि-चर
<u>'''Pari-cara'''</u> is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1685/> in the sense of ‘attendant.’ In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1685/> ''pari-caraṇa'' has the same sense metaphorically, the other two Vedas (Sāma and Yajur) being said to be subsidiary to the Rigveda.<br>

परि-चर्मण्य
<u>'''Pari-carmaṇya'''</u> denotes a thong of leather in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vi. 12) and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (ii. 1).<br>

परि-तक्म्या
<u>'''Pari-takmyā'''</u> in a number of passages of the '''Rigveda'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1687/> denotes ‘night’ according to the St. Petersburg '''Dictionary.'''  Sieg<ref name=fx2_ve1_1687/> thinks that in one place<ref name=fx3_ve1_1687/> at least the word signifies the decisive point of the race, something like the sense of '''[[प्रपित्व|Prapitva]].''' But this is very doubtful.<br>

परि-दा
<u>'''Pari-dā'''</u> in a few passages of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1688/> has the sense of ‘giving oneself up to the mercy or protection of another.’<br>

परि-धान
<u>'''Pari-dhāna'''</u> denotes ‘garment,’ probably ‘under garment,’ in the Atharvaveda (viii. 2, 16) and the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 1, 10). A garment of saffron is mentioned in the Śānkhāyana Āraṇyaka (xi. 4).<br>

परि-पद्
<u>'''Pari-pad'''</u> seems in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1690/> to denote a pitfall used to capture lions.<br>

परि-पन्थिन्
<u>'''Pari-panthin,'''</u> ‘besetting the path,’ denotes ‘robber’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1691/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1691/> ''Cf.'' '''[[तस्कर|Taskara]], [[तायु|Tāyu]], [[स्तेन|Stena]].'''<br>

परि-पवन
<u>'''Pari-pavana'''</u> signifies in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (iv. 9. 10) an instrument for winnowing grain.<br>

परि-मित्
<u>'''Pari-mit'''</u> occurs once in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1693/> in the description of a house, meaning perhaps the ‘crossbeams’ connecting the vertical posts.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1693/> ''Cf.'' '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].'''<br>

परि-मोष
<u>'''Pari-moṣa'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1694/> signifies ‘theft,’ and ''parimoṣin'' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1694/> ‘thief.’ <br>

परि-रथ्य
<u>'''Pari-rathya'''</u> occurs once in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1695/> meaning either ‘road’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1695/> or a part of the chariot, perhaps as Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve1_1695/> and Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve1_1695/> render it, the ‘rim.’<br>

परि-वक्रा
<u>'''Pari-vakrā'''</u> is the reading accepted in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 5, 4, 7) by the scholiast instead of the variant '''[[परिचक्रा|Paricakrā]],''' which is supported by the Epic Ekacakrā.<br>

परि-वत्सर
<u>'''Pari-vatsara'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1697/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1697/> a ‘full year.’ It is often mentioned with other names of year (see '''[[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]]'''), and in the later five year cycle counts as the second year.<br>

परि-वाप
<u>'''Pari-vāpa'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1698/> and Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve1_1698/> denotes ‘fried grains of rice.’<br>

परि-वित्त
<u>'''Pari-vitta'''</u> denotes an ‘elder brother who is not married when his younger brother is.’ The term occurs in the list of sinful persons in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1699/> as well as in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1699/> where Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve1_1699/> needlessly proposes to read ''parivettā,'' the ‘younger brother who marries before his eldest brother.’ The name for the younger brother in the older texts is Parivividāna.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1699/> <br>

परि-वृक्ता
<u>'''Pari-vṛktā, Pari-vṛktī, Pari-vṛttī,'''</u> are variant forms of the name of the rejected one among the royal wives. See '''Pati.'''<br>

परि-वेष्टृ
<u>'''Pari-veṣṭṛ'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1701/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1701/> denotes an ‘attendant,’ more especially one who serves up food, a ‘waiter.’ The feminine form Pariveṣṭrī signifies a ‘female attendant’ or ‘handmaid.’<ref name=fx3_ve1_1701/><br>

परि-व्राजक
<u>'''Pari-vrājaka'''</u> (lit., ‘wandering about’) denotes in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (i. 14; ii. 8) a ‘mendicant monk.’<br>

परि-षद्
<u>'''Pari-ṣad'''</u> (lit., ‘sitting around’) denotes in the Upaniṣads<ref name=fx1_ve1_1703/> an ‘assemblage’ of advisers in questions of philosophy, and the Gobhila [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1703/> refers to a teacher with his [[परिषद्|Pariṣad]] or ‘council.’ In the later literature the word denotes a body of advisers on religious topics, but also the assessors of a judge, or the council of ministers of a prince.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1703/> But in none of these senses is the word found in the early literature, though the institutions indicated by it must have existed at least in embryo.<br>

परि-ष्कन्द
<u>'''Pari-ṣkanda'''</u> (lit., ‘leaping around’) occurs in the '''[[व्रात्य|Vrātya]]''' hymn of the Atharvaveda (xv. 2, 1 ''et seq.'') denoting, in the dual, the two footmen running beside a chariot.<br>

परि-ष्यन्द
<u>'''Pari-ṣyanda'''</u> (with water ‘flowing around’) in two passages of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ix. 1, 19; xiv. 3, 1, 14) denotes a sandbank or island in a river. <br>

परि-सारक
<u>'''Pari-sāraka'''</u> is the name of a place, an island formed by the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' ‘flowing around’ it, according to a story in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 19).<br>

परि-स्रुत्
<u>'''Pari-srut'''</u> is the name of a drink which is mentioned first in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1707/> and which was distinct from both '''[[सुरा|Surā]]''' and '''Soma,'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1707/> but was intoxicating. According to Mahīdhara,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1707/> the liquor was made from flowers ('''[[पुष्प|Puṣpa]]'''). Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve1_1707/> thinks that it was the family drink, and this is supported by the fact that in the Atharvaveda it twice occurs as a household beverage.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1707/> Hillebrandt<ref name=fx6_ve1_1707/> is of opinion that it was very much the same as [[सुरा|Surā]].<br>

परी-णह्
<u>'''1. Parī-ṇah'''</u> appears to denote a ‘box’ or something similar in the Atharvaveda (xix. 48, 1).<br>

परी-णह्
<u>'''2. Parī-ṇah'''</u> is the name of a place in '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]]''' mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1709/> the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1709/> and the Sūtras.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1709/><br>

परी-शास
<u>'''Parī-śāsa'''</u> is the name of an instrument of the nature of tongs, used to lift the sacrificial kettle off the fire.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1710/><br>

परुच्-छेप
<u>'''Paruc-chepa'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] to whom the Anukramaṇī (Index) attributes a series of hymns<ref name=fx1_ve1_1711/> in the Rigveda, and whose  authorship is asserted in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1711/> and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1711/> Brāhmaṇas, as well as in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1711/> In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx5_ve1_1711/> he appears as a rival of '''Nṛmedhas.'''<br>

परुष
<u>'''Paruṣa'''</u> seems to mean ‘reed’ in the Atharvaveda (viii. 8, 4) and ‘arrow’ in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xiv. 22, 20).<br>

परुष्णी
<u>'''Paruṣṇī'''</u> is the name of a river which is mentioned in the [[नदी|Nadī]]-[[स्तुति|stuti]] (‘Praise of Rivers’),<ref name=fx1_ve1_1713/> and in the song of Sudās’ victory over the ten kings,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1713/> which seems to have been made decisive by the rise of the river drowning the fugitives.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1713/> In these passages and one of the eighth book of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1713/> where it is called a ‘great stream’ (''mahenadi''), the name is certainly that of the river later called Ravi (Irāvatī), as recognized by [[यास्क|Yāska]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_1713/> Pischel<ref name=fx6_ve1_1713/> sees a reference to it in two other passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1713/> where ‘wool’ (''ūṛṇā'') is connected with the word ''[[परुष्णी|paruṣṇī]],'' and the allusion to the river is accepted by Max Müller<ref name=fx8_ve1_1713/> and Oldenberg,<ref name=fx9_ve1_1713/> though they are not fully agreed as to the exact sense of the passages in question. Pischel suggests that the name is derived from the ‘flocks’ (''[[परुस्|parus]]'') of wool, not from the bends of the river, as understood by the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx5_ve1_1713/> or from its reeds, as Roth<ref name=fx10_ve1_1713/> suggests. <br><br>The mention of the [[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]] and the [[यमुना|Yamunā]] in the hymn celebrating the victory of [[सुदास्|Sudās]] has given rise to the conjectures of Hopkins,<ref name=fx11_ve1_1713/> that the [[यमुना|Yamunā]] in that hymn is merely another name for the [[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]], and of Geldner,<ref name=fx12_ve1_1713/> that the [[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]] there is merely a tributary of the [[यमुना|Yamunā]] (Jumna). But neither interpretation is either essential or even probable. The hymn is a condensed one, and may well be taken as celebrating two great victories of [[सुदास्|Sudās]]. There is a doubtful reference to the [[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]] in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx13_ve1_1713/><br>

परुस्
<u>'''Parus'''</u> means first a ‘limb’ or ‘member’ of the body,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1714/> and is then applied metaphorically to the divisions of the sacrifice<ref name=fx2_ve1_1714/> or of the year<ref name=fx3_ve1_1714/> (''cf.'' '''[[पर्वन्|Parvan]]''').<br>

पर्ण
<u>'''1. Parṇa'''</u> denotes the ‘wing’ of a bird in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1715/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1715/> It also means the ‘feather’ of an arrow in a late passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1715/> and more often later;<ref name=fx4_ve1_1715/> and the ‘leaf’ of a tree from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1715/><br>

पर्ण
<u>'''2. Parṇa'''</u> denotes the tree ''Butea frondosa,'' later usually called '''[[पलाश|Palāśa]].''' It occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1716/> in connexion with the '''[[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]],''' and with that tree as well as the '''[[न्यग्रोध|Nyagrodha]]''' in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1716/> which mentions both amulets<ref name=fx3_ve1_1716/> and the cover of sacrificial dishes<ref name=fx4_ve1_1716/> as made from its wood. Its use for the  making of sacrificial implements like the ladle (''[[जुहू|juhū]]''),<ref name=fx5_ve1_1716/> or sacrificial posts,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1716/> or the small ladle called ''[[स्रुव|sruva]],''<ref name=fx7_ve1_1716/> is mentioned. The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx8_ve1_1716/> ascribes its origin to the loss of a feather by the Gāyatrī when winning the Soma. The tree is also often mentioned elsewhere.<ref name=fx9_ve1_1716/> Reference too is sometimes made to its bark (''[[पर्ण|parṇa]]-[[वल्क|valka]]'').<ref name=fx10_ve1_1716/><br>

पर्णक
<u>'''Parṇaka'''</u> is the name of a man included in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1717/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1717/> According to Mahīdhara,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1717/> a Bhilla is meant--''i.e.,'' presumably a wild hillman, for he glosses '''[[निषाद|Niṣāda]]''' in the same way.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1717/> Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx5_ve1_1717/> explains the word as meaning ‘one who catches fish by putting over the water a ''[[पर्ण|parṇa]]'' with poison,’ but this is apparently a mere etymological guess. Weber's<ref name=fx6_ve1_1717/> rendering of the term as referring to a savage ‘wearing feathers’ is ingenious, but uncertain.<br>

पर्ण-धि
<u>'''Parṇa-dhi'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1718/> denotes the part of the shaft in which the feather of the arrow is fastened.<br>

पर्णय
<u>'''Parṇaya'''</u> is the name in two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1719/> either of a hero, as Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_1719/> thinks, or of a demon<ref name=fx3_ve1_1719/> overcome by Indra. <br>

पर्य्-अङ्क
<u>'''Pary-aṅka'''</u> is the name of the seat of the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1720/> It seems to correspond to what is elsewhere called '''Āsandi;'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1720/> as used in the [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]], it can, however, hardly mean a long seat for reclining on, but rather a throne.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1720/><br>

पर्य्-आस
<u>'''Pary-āsa'''</u> is used in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 1, 2, 18) to denote the woof of cloth, the warp being called ''anuchāda.''<br>

पर्वत
<u>'''1. Parvata'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1722/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1722/> is conjoined with ''giri'' in the sense of ‘hill’ or ‘mountain.’ From the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1722/> onwards<ref name=fx4_ve1_1722/> it is common in this sense as connected with the waters of rivers which flow in the hills.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1722/> The legend of the mountains having wings is already found in the Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1722/> In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx7_ve1_1722/> are mentioned the southern (''dakṣiṇa'') and the northern (''uttara'') mountains, evidently in allusion to the Himālaya and the Vindhya ranges. The plants (''[[ओषधि|oṣadhi]]'') and aromatic products (''añjana'') of the mountains are referred to in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1722/> and their mineral treasures in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx9_ve1_1722/><br>

पर्वत
<u>'''2. Parvata'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1723/> denotes, according to Ludwing,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1723/> a sacrificer whose generosity is praised. But it is probable that the god [[पर्वत|Parvata]], the spirit of the mountain, is meant.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1723/> <br>

पर्वत
<u>'''3. Parvata'''</u> is mentioned several times in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1724/> along with '''[[नारद|Nārada]].''' The Anukramaṇī (Index) attributes to him the authorship of several hymns of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1724/><br>

पर्वन्
<u>'''Parvan'''</u> denotes the knots of the reed or the joints of a plant,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1725/> and more generally a part or limb of the body.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1725/> It also designates a period of time, probably with reference to the breaks in the month at new and full moon.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1725/> In one passage<ref name=fx4_ve1_1725/> Geldner<ref name=fx5_ve1_1725/> thinks the word indicates a song section of the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]].<br>

पर्शान
<u>'''Parśāna,'''</u> ‘hollow,’ is mentioned several times in the Rigveda (vii. 104, 5; viii. 7, 34; 45, 41).<br>

पर्शु
<u>'''1. Parśu'''</u> denotes ‘rib’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1727/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1727/> ''Cf.'' '''[[शरीर|Śarīra]].'''<br>

पर्शु
<u>'''2. Parśu'''</u> seems in some passages<ref name=fx1_ve1_1728/> to denote a ‘sickle,’ being apparently a variant of '''[[परशु|Paraśu]].''' <br>

पर्शु
<u>'''3. Parśu'''</u> in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1729/> is explained in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1729/> as meaning the sides of a cistern (''[[कूप|kūpa]]'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_1729/> But the sense of ‘ribs’ is quite adequate there.<br>

पर्शु
<u>'''4. Parśu'''</u> occurs in one passage in a Dānastuti (‘praise of gifts’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1730/> as the name of a man. It is not certain that he is identical with '''[[तिरिन्दिर|Tirindira]],''' but the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1730/> mentions [[तिरिन्दिर|Tirindira]] [[पारशव्य|Pāraśavya]] as the patron of '''[[वत्स|Vatsa]] [[काण्व|Kāṇva]].''' In another passage occurring in the Vṛṣākapi hymn,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1730/> [[पर्शु|Parśu]] [[मानवी|Mānavī]] occurs, apparently as a woman, daughter of Manu, but who is meant it is quite impossible to say. Excepting these two, there are no other occurrences in which the word has with any probability the value of a proper name in the Rigveda.<br><br>Ludwig,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1730/> however, sees in several other places an allusion to the Parśus. Thus in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_1730/> he finds a reference to the defeat of '''Kuruśravaṇa''' by the Parśus; in another<ref name=fx6_ve1_1730/> he finds a reference to the Pṛthus and Parśus--''i.e.,'' the Parthians and the Persians. He also sees the Parthians in '''[[पार्थव|Pārthava]],''' a name found in one hymn.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1730/> The same view is taken by Weber,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1730/> who holds that historical connexions with the  Persians are referred to. But Zimmer<ref name=fx9_ve1_1730/> points out that this conclusion is not justified; the Parśus were known to Pāṇini<ref name=fx10_ve1_1730/> as a warrior tribe; the Pāraśavas were a tribe in south-west '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]];''' and the ''Periplus''<ref name=fx11_ve1_1730/> knows a tribe of Parthoi in north India. At most the only conclusion to be drawn is that the Indians and Iranians were early connected, as was of course the case. Actual historical contact cannot be asserted with any degree of probability.<br>

पर्ष
<u>'''Parṣa'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1731/> denoting in the plural ‘sheaves’ strewn over the threshing floor. ''Cf.'' '''[[खल|Khala]].'''<br>

पलद
<u>'''Palada'''</u> occurs twice in one hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1732/> in the description of a house. It seems to mean bundles of straw or reeds used to thatch the house and render the sides wind and weather proof.<br>

पलस्ति
<u>'''Palasti.'''</u> See '''[[पलित|Palita]].'''<br>

पलाल
<u>'''Palāla'''</u> is found with Anu-[[पलाल|palāla]] in the Atharvaveda (viii. 6, 2) as the name of a demon. The meaning of the word is ‘straw,’ in which sense it occurs in the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (lxxx. 27), while the feminine form, Palālī, is found in the Atharvaveda itself (ii. 8, 3) as the straw of barley ('''Yava''').<br>

पलाव
<u>'''Palāva'''</u> is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1735/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1735/> in the sense of ‘chaff.’ <br>

पलाश
<u>'''Palāśa,'''</u> like '''[[पर्ण|Parṇa]],''' denotes ‘leaf’ in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1736/> It also<ref name=fx2_ve1_1736/> designates the tree ''Butea frondosa,'' of which [[पर्ण|Parṇa]] is the early name.<br>

पलित
<u>'''Palita,'''</u> ‘grey-haired,’ occurs frequently from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1737/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1737/> It is the distinctive sign of old age. Those who, like certain descendants of '''[[जमद्अग्नि|Jamadagni]],''' do not grow old,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1737/> are said not to become grey-haired, while '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]]''' is described as having in his old age become thin and grey-haired.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1737/> The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1737/> in one passage observes that grey hairs appear first on the head, and elsewhere<ref name=fx6_ve1_1737/> alludes to the hair on the arms having become grey.<br>

पल्पूलन
<u>'''Palpūlana'''</u> is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1738/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1738/> apparently meaning, properly, ‘lye,’ or water impregnated with some biting substance for washing clothes. In the [[अथर्वन्|Atharvan]] passage urine seems to be meant.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1738/> The verb ''palpūlaya,'' ‘to wash with alkaline water,’ occurs in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1738/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]];<ref name=fx4_ve1_1738/> and the Sūtras refer to hides (''[[चर्मन्|carman]]'')<ref name=fx5_ve1_1738/> and garments<ref name=fx6_ve1_1738/> so washed. ''Cf.'' also '''[[वासःपल्पूली|Vāsaḥpalpūlī]].'''<br>

पल्लि-गुप्त लौहित्य
<u>'''Palli-[[गुप्त|gupta]] Lauhitya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (‘list of teachers’) in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1) as a pupil of '''[[श्यामजयन्त लौहित्य|Śyāmajayanta Lauhitya]].'''  The name is obviously a late one, for Palli is not found in the early literature, and the name of the [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]] family is otherwise known in post-Vedic works only.<br>

पवन
<u>'''Pavana'''</u> (‘purifier’) in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1740/> denotes an instrument for purifying grain from husks, etc.; either a ‘sieve’ or a ‘winnowing basket’ may be meant. In the Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve1_1740/> it is mentioned as used for cleaning the bones of the dead after cremation.<br>

पवमान
<u>'''Pavamāna'''</u> is a term very frequently applied in the Rigveda to the Soma ‘purifying itself’ by running through the sieve. Later it appears in a few passages<ref name=fx1_ve1_1741/> in the sense of ‘wind’ (as a purifier).<br>

पवस्त
<u>'''Pavasta'''</u> in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1742/> apparently denotes ‘covers.’<br>

पवि
<u>'''Pavi'''</u> denotes the ‘tire’ of the wheel of a chariot in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1743/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1743/> Reference is made<ref name=fx3_ve1_1743/> to the necessity for fastening it on firmly, and the epithet ''su-pavi,'' ‘having a good tire,’ is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1743/> with ''su-[[नाभि|nābhi]],'' ‘having a good nave,’ and ''su-[[चक्र|cakra]],'' ‘having a good wheel.’ The tires were, of course, of metal,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1743/> and being sharp,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1743/> could serve on occasion as weapons.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1743/> The St. Petersburg Dictionary in one passage of  the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx8_ve1_1743/> takes Pavi to mean a metal rim on the stone for pounding Soma, but this seems improbable, because no such metal attachment is elsewhere alluded to. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx9_ve1_1743/> seems clearly right in accepting the sense of ‘sharp edge’ in this passage, especially as the stones in the Rigveda<ref name=fx10_ve1_1743/> are, in allusion to their rolling action, styled ‘rims without horses and without chariots’ (''anaśvāsaḥ pavayo 'rathāḥ'').<br><br>The [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx11_ve1_1743/> ascribes to Pavi the sense of arrow (''[[शल्य|śalya]]''), but this is very uncertain. The St. Petersburg Dictionary cites for this use two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx12_ve1_1743/> but in one the secondary sense of sharp-edged weapon with reference to the bolt of Indra is quite likely, and in the other, where the expression ''vāṇasya pavi'' occurs, the sharp-edged pounding-stone of the ‘reed,’<ref name=fx13_ve1_1743/> meaning the stalk of the Soma plant, may be meant. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx14_ve1_1743/> thinks a reference to the shape of the Soma plant is intended. Pavī-nasa, the name of a demon mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx15_ve1_1743/> seems to throw no light on this point, for while the St. Petersburg Dictionary takes it to mean ‘whose nose is like a spearhead,’ it is translated as ‘rim-nosed’ (presumably in allusion to the curved shape of the nose) by Whitney.<ref name=fx16_ve1_1743/><br>

पवित्र
<u>'''Pavitra'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1744/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1744/> the sieve used for purifying the Soma, the only mode of purifying it certainly<ref name=fx3_ve1_1744/> known to the Rigveda. It seems clearly<ref name=fx4_ve1_1744/> to have been made of  sheep's wool, whether woven or plaited is not certain, for the expressions used are too vague to be decisive, though Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve1_1744/> thinks ''hvarāṃsi''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1744/> points to plaiting.<br>

पवीर
<u>'''Pavīra,'''</u> according to the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1745/> denotes a ‘lance.’ The epithet derived from this word, ''pavīravant'' or ''pavīrava,'' which is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1745/> and the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1745/> is used of the plough, apparently in the sense of ‘having a metal share.’ The same epithet occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1745/> applied to a man, in the sense of ‘having a goad’ or ‘having a spear.’<br>

पवीरु
<u>'''Pavīru'''</u> appears in a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1746/> as a '''[[रुशम|Ruśama]],''' being a prince or at least a wealthy noble.<br>

पशु
<u>'''Paśu'''</u> means ‘animal’ generally, including man. There is frequent mention<ref name=fx1_ve1_1747/> of the five sacrificial animals--the horse, the cow, the sheep, the goat, and man. Seven such domestic animals are spoken of in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1747/> and later;<ref name=fx3_ve1_1747/> probably, as Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve1_1747/> observes, merely as a sacred mystic number, not, as the commentator<ref name=fx5_ve1_1747/> explains, the usual five with the ass and the camel added. Animals are also referred to as ''ubhayadant''  and ''anyatodant.'' They are further<ref name=fx6_ve1_1747/> classified as those which take hold with the hand (''hastādānāḥ''), man (''[[पुरुष|puruṣa]]''), elephant (''[[हस्तिन्|hastin]]''), and ape (''[[मर्कट|markaṭa]]''), and those which grasp by the mouth (''mukhādānāḥ''). Another division is that of biped (''[[द्विपाद्|dvipād]]'') and quadruped (''catuṣpād'').<ref name=fx7_ve1_1747/> Man is a biped;<ref name=fx8_ve1_1747/> he is the first (''prathama'') of the beasts;<ref name=fx9_ve1_1747/> he alone of animals lives a hundred years (''śatāyus''),<ref name=fx10_ve1_1747/> and he is king of the animals.<ref name=fx11_ve1_1747/> He possesses speech (''[[वाच्|vāc]]'') in conjunction with the other animals.<ref name=fx12_ve1_1747/> In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx13_ve1_1747/> an elaborate distinction is drawn between vegetables, animals, and man in point of intellect.<br><br>Of animals apart from man a threefold division is offered in the Rigveda<ref name=fx14_ve1_1747/> --into those of the air (''vāyavya''), those of the jungle (''āraṇya''), and those of the village (''grāmya''), or tame animals. The division into ''āraṇya'' and ''grāmya'' animals is quite common.<ref name=fx15_ve1_1747/> In the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx16_ve1_1747/> is found a division into ''eka-[[शफ|śapha]],'' ‘whole-hoofed’; ''kṣudra,'' ‘small’; and ''āraṇya,'' ‘wild,’ the two former classes denoting the tame animals.<ref name=fx16_ve1_1747/> The horse and the ass are ''eka-[[शफ|śapha]];''<ref name=fx17_ve1_1747/> the ''kṣudra'' are the sheep, the goat, and the ox: this distinction being parallel to that of ''ubhayadant'' and ''anyatodant.''<ref name=fx18_ve1_1747/> Zimmer<ref name=fx19_ve1_1747/> sees in a passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx20_ve1_1747/> a division of wild animals (''āraṇya'') into five classes: (1) those of the jungle described as the ‘dread beasts  which are in the wood’ (''mṛgā bhīmā vane hitāḥ''); (2) winged creatures, represented by the '''[[हंस|Haṃsa]],''' ‘gander,’ '''[[सुपर्ण|Suparṇa]],''' ‘eagle,’ '''[[शकुन|Śakuna]],''' ‘bird’; (3) amphibia--'''[[शिंशुमार|Śiṃśumāra]],''' ‘alligator,’ and '''[[अजगर|Ajagara]],''' ‘crocodile’ (?); (4) ‘fish,’ '''[[पुरीकय|Purīkaya]], [[जष|Jaṣa]],''' and '''[[मत्स्य|Matsya]];''' (5) insects and worms (described as ''rajasāḥ''). But this division is more ingenious than probable, and it is ignored by both Bloomfield<ref name=fx21_ve1_1747/> and Whitney.<ref name=fx22_ve1_1747/><br>

पशु-प
<u>'''Paśu-pa'''</u> denotes ‘herdsman’ in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1748/> Metaphorically the term is applied to Pūṣan.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1748/><br>

पष्ठ-वाह्
<u>'''1. Paṣṭha-vāh'''</u> occurs in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1749/> meaning an ox, four years old, according to the commentators. This qualification is, however, very doubtful, for Paṣṭhauhī, ‘cow,’ a word occurring quite frequently,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1749/> is in one passage<ref name=fx3_ve1_1749/> accompanied by the adjective ''prathama-garbhāḥ,'' ‘having a first calf,’ which disproves the theory of the age adopted by the commentators.<br>

पष्ठ-वाह्
<u>'''2. Paṣṭha-vāh'''</u> is mentioned as a seer of Sāmans in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1750/><br>

पस्त्य-सद्
<u>'''Pastya-sad'''</u> (‘sitting in the house’) occurs in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1751/> where the sense seems to be ‘inmate,’ ‘companion.’ <br>

पस्त्या
<u>'''Pastyā'''</u> (fem. pl.) is a word occurring in several passages of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1752/> Roth<ref name=fx2_ve1_1752/> ascribes to it the meaning of ‘house’ or ‘dwelling,’ in the wide sense of the term, as well as that of the ‘family’ living in the house; and this view is accepted by Zimmer.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1752/> On the other hand, Pischel<ref name=fx4_ve1_1752/> finds in two of the passages<ref name=fx5_ve1_1752/> usually referred to [[पस्त्या|Pastyā]] the neuter Pastya, which appears in '''[[पस्त्य-सद्|Pastya-sad]]''' and in '''[[पस्त्या-वन्त्|Pastyā-vant]]''' (where the length of the second syllable is not primitive¤), and which is certainly found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve1_1752/> in the metaphorical sense of ‘dwelling,’ ascribed to it in the Naighaṇṭuka.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1752/> In the other passages<ref name=fx8_ve1_1752/> he thinks the word means ‘rivers’ or ‘waters’; in particular, where Soma in the middle of the Pastyās<ref name=fx9_ve1_1752/> is spoken of, the sees a reference to '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]],''' with its several rivers,<ref name=fx10_ve1_1752/> '''[[आपया|Āpayā]], [[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]],''' and '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' (''cf.'' 2. '''[[पस्त्यावन्त्|Pastyāvant]]'''). In some passages<ref name=fx11_ve1_1752/> he sees in [[पस्त्या|Pastyā]] the proper name of a stream, just as [[सिन्धु|Sindhu]] primarily means ‘river,’ then the ‘Indus.’<br>

पस्त्या-वन्त्
<u>'''1. Pastyā-vant,'''</u> explained in the Pada text as Pastya-vant, occurs in several passages of the Rigveda. In two of them<ref name=fx1_ve1_1753/>  a rich householder seems meant, and in the two others reference to a ‘house’ is clear.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1753/><br>

पस्त्या-वन्त्
<u>'''2. Pastyā-vant'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1754/> in the locative parallel with '''Suṣoma, [[शर्यणावन्त्|Śaryaṇāvant]],''' and '''[[आर्जीक|Ārjīka]].''' It must apparently denote a place, as Pischel<ref name=fx2_ve1_1754/> argues, probably corresponding to the locality ‘in the middle of the streams’ (''madhye pastyānām''), elsewhere<ref name=fx3_ve1_1754/> referred to as the home of Soma. Pischel<ref name=fx4_ve1_1754/> suggests that Patiāla is meant, though he does not lay any stress on the similarity of name. In the north of Patiāla there are hills where the Soma might have grown. Roth<ref name=fx5_ve1_1754/> thought that something connected with the Soma press was meant.<br>

पांसु
<u>'''Pāṃsu'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1755/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1755/> denotes ‘dust’ or ‘sand,’ usually in the plural. Among the portents enumerated in the Adbhuta [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1755/> is a rain of dust or sand (''pāṃsuvarṣa''), a phenomenon not rare in India.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1755/><br>

पाक-दूर्वा
<u>'''Pāka-dūrvā'''</u> is, in a verse of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1756/> included with '''[[कियाम्बु|Kiyāmbu]]''' and '''[[व्यल्कशा|Vyalkaśā]]''' among the plants used for growing on the spot where the corpse of the dead man has been consumed with fire.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1756/> The verse is repeated in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx3_ve1_1756/>  with the variant Kyāmbu. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1756/> the word is read Śāṇḍadūrvā. [[पाकदूर्वा|Pākadūrvā]] is probably, as Sāyaṇa-understands it, ''paripakva-[[दूर्वा|dūrvā]],'' ‘ripe or edible millet.’ Śāṇḍadūrvā is explained by the commentator<ref name=fx5_ve1_1756/> in various ways, as millet ‘having egg-shaped roots’ (''i.e., sāṇḍa,'' not ''[[शाण्ड|śāṇḍa]]''), or as ‘having long joints,’ with the additional remark that it was called ''bṛhaddūrvā,'' ‘large millet.’ In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka, on the other hand, the commentary explains [[पाकदूर्वा|Pākadūrvā]] as small millet.<br>

पाक-स्थामन् कौरयाण
<u>'''Pāka-sthāman Kaurayāṇa'''</u> is celebrated as a generous donor  in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1757/> Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve1_1757/> suggests, without much reason, that he may have been a king of the '''Anus.'''<br>

पाकरु
<u>'''Pākaru'''</u> is mentioned as a disease, together with '''[[विषूचिका|Viṣūcikā]]''' and '''[[अर्शस्|Arśas]],''' ‘hæmorrhoids,’ in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1758/> Its nature is unknown; the etymology<ref name=fx2_ve1_1758/> points to the sense of ‘developed sores,’ ‘ulcers.’<br>

पाङ्क्त्र
<u>'''Pāṅktra'''</u> is the name of an animal mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], or ‘horse-sacrifice,’ in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1759/> The ‘field-rat’ seems to be meant.<br>

पाञ्च-जन्य
<u>'''Pāñca-janya,'''</u> ‘relating to the five peoples.’ See '''[[पञ्चजनाः|Pañcajanāḥ]].'''<br>

पाञ्चाल
<u>'''Pāñcāla'''</u> means a ‘king of the [[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] people,’ and is applied to '''[[दुर्मुख|Durmukha]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1761/> and to '''Śoṇa''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1761/> The term is also found in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1761/> See also '''[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]].''' <br>

पाञ्चि
<u>'''Pāñci,'''</u> ‘descendant of Pañcan,’ is the name of a teacher mentioned with disapproval in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1762/><br>

पाटव
<u>'''Pāṭava,'''</u> ‘descendant of Paṭu,’ is a patronymic of '''[[चाक्र|Cākra]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xii. 8, 1, 17; 9, 3, 1).<br>

पाटा
<u>'''Pāṭā'''</u> is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1764/> and in the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1764/> It is assumed by the commentator to be identical with the later Pāṭhā, the plant ''Clypea hernandifolia,'' which was much used medicinally, and is still so used at the present day according to Roth.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1764/> Very possibly the word should be read as Pāṭhā.<br>

पाणि-घ्न
<u>'''Pāṇi-ghna,'''</u> ‘hand-clapper,’ is enumerated among the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1765/> Presumably a man who drives away birds from the fields by making a noise is intended.<br>

पाण्ड्व
<u>'''Pāṇḍva'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 3, 5, 21) denotes an uncoloured woollen garment.<br>

पातल्य
<u>'''Pātalya'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1767/> meaning some part of the chariot. What it was is quite uncertain. Hopkins<ref name=fx2_ve1_1767/> suggests that, as in the Epic, it was possibly a piece of wood on the axle to hold the pole of the car. <br>

पात्र
<u>'''Pātra,'''</u> primarily a ‘drinking vessel’ (from ''pā,'' ‘to drink’) denotes a vessel generally both in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1768/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1768/> It was made either of wood<ref name=fx3_ve1_1768/> or clay.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1768/> In some passages<ref name=fx5_ve1_1768/> the word is, according to Roth, used to indicate a measure. The feminine Pātrī occasionally occurs<ref name=fx6_ve1_1768/> in the sense of ‘vessel.’<br>

पाथ्य
<u>'''Pāthya,'''</u> a word occurring only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1769/> is either an epithet meaning ‘being in heaven’ (''pāthas''), or a patronymic, as Sāyaṇa interprets it, of '''[[वृषन्|Vṛṣan]].'''<br>

पाद
<u>'''1. Pāda'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1770/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1770/> denotes the ‘foot’ of an animal, a bird, and other creatures.<br>

पाद
<u>'''2. Pāda,'''</u> as a measure of length, denotes ‘foot’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1771/> The term is occasionally<ref name=fx2_ve1_1771/> used to express a measure of weight. As a fraction it means a ‘quarter,’ a sense derived from that of ‘foot’ of a quadruped (just as ''[[शफ|śapha]],'' the divided hoof, comes to mean an ‘eighth’).<br><br>^3) Rv. x. 90, 3. 4.<br>

पाद
<u>'''3. Pāda'''</u> is the regular expression for a ‘quarter verse’ in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1772/> This sense is merely a limitation of ‘quarter’ = the ‘foot’ of a quadruped <br>

पान
<u>'''Pāna,'''</u> ‘drink,’ occurs in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1773/> and the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1773/><br>

पान्त
<u>'''Pānta'''</u> occurs several times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1774/> apparently<ref name=fx2_ve1_1774/> meaning ‘drink,’ ‘beverage’ (''cf.'' '''[[पान|Pāna]]'''). Geldner,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1774/> however, thinks that in one passage^4 [[पान्त|Pānta]] is the name of a prince.<br>

पान्-नेजन
<u>'''Pān-nejana'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1775/> denotes a ‘vessel for washing the feet.’<br>

पाप-यक्ष्म
<u>'''Pāpa-yakṣma.'''</u> See '''[[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]].'''<br>

पाप-सम
<u>'''Pāpa-sama,'''</u> a ‘bad season,’ is in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1777/> opposed to Puṇya-sama, a ‘good season.’<br>

पामन्
<u>'''Pāman'''</u> occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1778/> as the name of a skin disease. The derivative adjective, Pāmana, ‘suffering from skin disease,’ is found in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1778/> Since it is mentioned as an accompaniment of fever, probably a cutaneous eruption or scab consequent on fever is meant.<br>

पायु
<u>'''1. Pāyu,'''</u> meaning ‘guard,’ ‘protector,’ occurs several times in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1779/> <br>

पायु
<u>'''2. Pāyu'''</u> is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1780/> as the name of a poet, a [[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]]. In the Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx2_ve1_1780/> he is credited with assisting '''[[अभ्यावर्तिन् चायमान|Abhyāvartin Cāyamāna]]''' and '''[[प्रस्तोक|Prastoka]] Sārṅjaya''' by consecrating their weapons with a hymn.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1780/><br>

पार
<u>'''Pāra,'''</u> in accordance with its derivation (''pṛ,'' ‘bring across’), denotes the ‘farther bank’ of a river or stream, in which sense<ref name=fx1_ve1_1781/> it occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1781/> and later.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1781/><br>

पारशव्य
<u>'''Pāraśavya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[परशु|Paraśu]],’ is the patronymic of '''[[तिरिन्दिर|Tirindira]]''' in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta Śūtra (xvi. 11, 20). ''Cf.'' '''[[पर्शु|Parśu]].'''<br>

पारावत
<u>'''1. Pārāvata'''</u> occurs in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’), in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1783/> meaning ‘turtle-dove.’<br>

पारावत
<u>'''2. Pārāvata'''</u> occurs in several passages of the Rigveda. Roth<ref name=fx1_ve1_1784/> thinks that in most places<ref name=fx2_ve1_1784/> it means ‘coming from a distance,’ but in two passages<ref name=fx3_ve1_1784/> he regards it as the proper name of a people on the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]''' (Jumna). It is certain that in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] the Pārāvatas are a people on that river (''cf.'' '''[[तुरश्रवस्|Turaśravas]]'''). Hillebrandt<ref name=fx4_ve1_1784/> sees in all the passages<ref name=fx5_ve1_1784/> the name of a people, comparing the  of  Ptolemy,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1784/> who apparently were settled on the northern border of Gedrosia, or the , who were found in <ref name=fx7_ve1_1784/> He suggests that they were originally ‘mountaineers’ (''Cf.'' '''[[पर्वत|Parvata]]'''). Ludwig<ref name=fx8_ve1_1784/> holds a similar view, and Geldner<ref name=fx9_ve1_1784/> recognizes a people as meant. The mention of the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' in connexion with the Pārāvatas<ref name=fx2_ve1_1784/> in the Rigveda accords generally with their position on the [[यमुना|Yamunā]] in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve1_1784/><br>

पाराशरी-कौण्डिनी-पुत्र
<u>'''Pārāśarī-[[कौण्डिनी|kauṇḍinī]]-putra'''</u> is mentioned in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhādāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 30), in the Mādhyaṃdina recension, as a pupil of '''[[गार्गीपुत्र|Gārgīputra]].'''<br>

पाराशरी-पुत्र
<u>'''Pārāśarī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of '''[[पराशर|Parāśara]],'''’ is mentioned in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] as a pupil of '''[[कात्यायनीपुत्र|Kātyāyanīputra]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1786/> of '''[[औपस्वतीपुत्र|Aupasvatīputra]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1786/> of '''[[वात्सीपुत्र|Vātsīputra]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1786/> of '''[[वार्कारुणीपुत्र|Vārkāruṇīputra]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1786/> and of '''[[गार्गीपुत्र|Gārgīputra]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve1_1786/> Different men are no doubt meant.<br>

पाराशर्य
<u>'''Pārāśarya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[पराशर|Parāśara]],'''’ is mentioned in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] as a pupil of '''[[जातूकर्ण्य|Jātūkarṇya]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1787/> or of '''[[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1787/> A [[पाराशर्य|Pārāśarya]] is also mentioned as a pupil of '''[[बैजवापायन|Baijavāpāyana]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1787/> and '''[[व्यास पाराशर्य|Vyāsa Pārāśarya]]''' is the pupil of '''[[विष्वक्सेन|Viṣvaksena]]''' according to the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] at the end of the Sāmavidhāna [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1787/> See also '''Aṣāḍha, [[जयन्त|Jayanta]], Vipaścit, Sudatta.''' <br>

पाराशर्यायण
<u>'''Pārāśaryāyaṇa'''</u> is mentioned in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1788/> as a pupil of [[पाराशर्य|Pārāśarya]].<br>

पारिकुट
<u>'''Pārikuṭa'''</u> is an obscure word--probably corrupt--occurring in a verse cited in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 22, 7), and apparently meaning ‘attendant.’<br>

पारिक्षित
<u>'''Pārikṣita,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1790/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve1_1790/> The Pārikṣitīya appear in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1790/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1790/> as performers of the horse sacrifice. In a [[गाथा|Gāthā]] there cited they are called Pārikṣitas. Apparently they were the brothers of [[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]], named '''[[उग्रसेन|Ugrasena]], [[भीमसेन|Bhīmasena]],''' and '''[[श्रुतसेन|Śrutasena]].''' In the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx5_ve1_1790/> the question whither they have gone is made the subject of a philosophical discussion. It is clear that the family had passed away before the time of the [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]], and it is also clear that there had been some serious scandal mingled with their greatness which they had, in the opinion of the Brahmins, atoned for by their horse sacrifice with its boundless gifts to the priests. Weber<ref name=fx6_ve1_1790/> sees in this the germ of the Epic stories which are recorded in the Mahābhārata.<br><br>The verses relating to [[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]] in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_1790/> are called Pārikṣityaḥ in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1790/><br>

पारि-प्लव
<u>'''Pāri-plava,'''</u> ‘cyclic,’ is a term applied to the '''[[आख्यान|Ākhyāna]],''' or ‘tale,’ which is to be recited at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse  sacrifice’), and to be repeated at intervals throughout the year. It is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1791/> and in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1791/><br>

पारी-णह्य
<u>'''Pārī-ṇahya'''</u> denotes household utensils' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1792/> where it is said that the wife (''[[पत्नी|patnī]]''), as mistress of the house, has charge of all these.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1792/><br>

पारूष्ण
<u>'''Pārūṣṇa,'''</u> occurring in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1793/> appears to mean some kind of bird.<br>

पारोवर्य-विद्
<u>'''Pārovarya-vid'''</u> in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (xiii. 12) denotes ‘knowers of tradition.’<br>

पार्ण-वल्कि
<u>'''Pārṇa-valki,'''</u> ‘descendant of Parṇavalka,’ is the patronymic of '''Nigada''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1795/><br>

पार्थव
<u>'''Pārthava,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[पृथु|Pṛthu]],'''’ occurs once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1796/> where the Pārthavas are mentioned as generous donors. The passage is somewhat obscure, as there is a reference<ref name=fx2_ve1_1796/> to a defeat of the '''Turvaśas''' and the '''Vṛcīvants''' by '''[[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]] [[दैववात|Daivavāta]],''' followed in the next verse by the praise of the bounty to the singer of '''[[अभ्यावर्तिन् चायमान|Abhyāvartin Cāyamāna]],''' who was clearly a '''[[पार्थव|Pārthava]],''' and who, in the earlier part of the hymn, has been referred to as victorious over '''[[वरशिख|Varaśikha]].''' It is uncertain whether, as Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve1_1796/> suggests, the two princes, Abhyāvartin  [[चायमान|Cāyamāna]] and [[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]] [[दैववात|Daivavāta]], are identical or not.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1796/> That [[पार्थव|Pārthava]] has any direct connexion with the Parthians, as held by Brunnhofer, is most improbable.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1796/> ''Cf.'' '''[[पर्शु|Parśu]].'''<br>

पार्थ-श्रवस
<u>'''Pārtha-śravasa,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[पृथु-श्रवस्|Pṛthu-śravas]],’ is found as the name of a demon in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1797/><br>

पार्थ्य
<u>'''Pārthya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[पृथि|Pṛthi]],’ is the patronymic of some donor in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1798/> The form of the name in the Aśvalāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1798/> is Pārtha.<br>

पार्वति
<u>'''Pārvati,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[पर्वत|Parvata]],’ is the patronymic of '''Dakṣa''' in the Śatapatha (ii. 4, 4, 6) and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] (iv. 4) Brāhmaṇas.<br>

पार्षद
<u>'''Pārṣada,'''</u> which first appears in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1800/> denotes a textbook recognized by a school of grammarians.<br>

पार्षद्-वाण
<u>'''Pārṣad-vāṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of Pṛṣadvāṇa,’ is mentioned as a wonder-worker in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1801/><br>

पार्ष्ण शैलन
<u>'''Pārṣṇa Śailana'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 4, 8).<br>

पालागल
<u>'''Pālāgala'''</u> occurs in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve1_1803/> apparently in the sense of ‘messenger,’ or ‘bearer of false news.’ <br>

पालागली
<u>'''Pālāgalī'''</u> is the name of the fourth and least respected wife of the king.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1804/> See '''Pati.'''<br>

पावमानी
<u>'''Pāvamānī'''</u> means the verses (''ṛcas'') in the ninth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda ‘relating to Soma Pavamāna’ (‘purifying itself’). The name is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1805/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1805/> possibly even in one hymn of the Rigveda itself.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1805/><br>

पाश
<u>'''Pāśa'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1806/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1806/> a ‘rope’ used for fastening or tying up. Rope and knot (''granthi'') are mentioned together in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1806/> [[पाश|Pāśa]] is in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve1_1806/> used of the rope by which Manu's ship was fastened to the mountain. It is often employed metaphorically of the ‘fetter’ of Varuṇa.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1806/><br>

पाशिन्
<u>'''Pāśin,'''</u> ‘having a noose,’ denotes a ‘hunter’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1807/> and in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1807/><br>

पाश-द्युम्न वायत
<u>'''Pāśa-[[द्युम्न|dyumna]] Vāyata'''</u> is the name of a king to whom the '''Vasiṣṭhas''' claim to have been preferred by Indra in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1808/> Apparently he was, as Sāyaṇa says, son of Vayat, who may be compared with the '''Vyat of another''' passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1808/> Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve1_1808/> sees in him a priest of the '''Pṛthus''' and '''Parśus,''' but this is most improbable.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1808/><br>

पाष्य
<u>'''Pāṣya'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1809/> with reference to the defeat of Vṛtra, and apparently denotes ‘stone bulwarks.’  In another passage<ref name=fx2_ve1_1809/> the word may mean the stones used for pressing Soma.<br>

पिक
<u>'''Pika,'''</u> the Indian ‘cuckoo,’ is mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1810/> ''Cf.'' '''[[अन्यवाप|Anyavāpa]], Koka.'''<br>

पिङ्गा
<u>'''Piṅgā'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1811/> where it is explained by the St. Petersburg Dictionary with Sāyaṇa as ‘bowstring,’ but where Hillebrandt<ref name=fx2_ve1_1811/> thinks that a musical instrument of some kind is meant.<br>

पिजवन
<u>'''Pijavana'''</u> is the name of the father of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' according to the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1812/> Probably this statement is based on a mere conjecture from the epithet [[पैजवन|Paijavana]] used of [[सुदास्|Sudās]] in a verse of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1812/> but may very well be correct.<br>

पिञ्जूल
<u>'''Piñjūla'''</u> denotes a ‘bundle’ of grass or stalks, especially of '''[[दर्भ|Darbha]].''' The word is only found in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] style.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1813/><br>

पिठीनस्
<u>'''Piṭhīnas'''</u> is the name of a man, a friend of Indra, in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1814/><br>

पिण्ड
<u>'''Piṇḍa,'''</u> denoting specifically a ball of flour offered to the Manes, especially on the evening of new moon, occurs in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx1_ve1_1815/> and repeatedly in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1815/> <br>

पिता-पुत्र
<u>'''Pitā-putra,'''</u> ‘father and son,’ is a compound of rare occurrence.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1816/><br>

पिता-पुत्रीय
<u>'''Pitā-putrīya'''</u> (‘relating to father and son’), used with Sampradāna (‘handing over’) means the ceremony by which a father, when about to die, bequeathes his bodily and mental powers to his son. It is described in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1817/><br>

पिता-मह
<u>'''Pitā-maha,'''</u> beside '''[[ततामह|Tatāmaha]],''' denotes from the Atharvaveda onwards<ref name=fx1_ve1_1818/> the ‘paternal grandfather,’ apparmtly as a ‘father in a higher sense.’<ref name=fx2_ve1_1818/> The great-grandfather is '''[[प्रपितामह|Prapitāmaha]]''' and '''[[प्रततामह|Pratatāmaha]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1818/> It is significant that there are no corrésponding Vedic words for maternal grandparents, and that the words used in the latter language, such as Mātāmaha, are imitations of the terms for paternal relations.<br><br>In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1818/> Delbrück<ref name=fx5_ve1_1818/> suggests that ''mahe pitre'' means ‘grandfather,’ a sense which would well suit the ''napātam,'' ‘grandson,’ following, but the sense of the whole passage is uncertain.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1818/><br><br>We learn very little from the texts of the position of grandparents. No doubt they were entitled to marks of respect similar to those shown to parents,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1818/> as the epic expressly testifies. A grandfather might easily be the head of the family, or be living with his eldest son, after he ceased to be able to control the family.<br><br>The grandmother (Pitāmahī) is not mentioned in the extant Vedic literature. <br>

पितु
<u>'''Pitu'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1819/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1819/> has the general sense of ‘nutriment,’ whether food or drink.<br>

पितृ
<u>'''Pitṛ,'''</u> common from the Rigveda onwards, denotes ‘father,’ not so much as the ‘begetter’ (''[[जनितृ|janitṛ]]''),<ref name=fx1_ve1_1820/> but rather as the protector of the child, this being probably also the etymological sense of the word.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1820/> The father in the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1820/> stands for all that is good and kind. Hence Agni is compared with a father,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1820/> while Indra is even dearer than a father.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1820/> The father carries his son in his arms,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1820/> and places him on his lap,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1820/> while the child pulls his garment to attract attention.<ref name=fx8_ve1_1820/> In later years the son depends on his father for help in trouble,<ref name=fx9_ve1_1820/> and greets him with joy.<ref name=fx10_ve1_1820/><br><br>It is difficult to ascertain precisely how far the son was subject to parental control, and how long such control continued. Reference is made in the Rigveda<ref name=fx11_ve1_1820/> to a father's chastising his son for gambling, and '''[[ऋज्राश्व|Ṛjrāśva]]''' is said to have been blinded by his father.<ref name=fx12_ve1_1820/> From the latter statement Zimmer<ref name=fx13_ve1_1820/> infers the existence of a developed ''patria potestas,'' but to lay stress on this isolated and semi-mythical incident would be unwise. It is, however, quite likely that the ''patria potestas'' was originally strong, for we have other support for the thesis in the Roman ''patria potestas.'' If there is no proof that a father  legally controlled his son's wedding,<ref name=fx14_ve1_1820/> and not much that he controlled his daughter's,<ref name=fx15_ve1_1820/> the fact is in itself not improbable.<br><br>There is again no evidence to show whether a son, when grown up, normally continued to stay with his father, his wife becoming a member of the father's household, or whether he set up a house of his own: probably the custom varied. Nor do we know whether the son was granted a special plot of land on marriage or otherwise, or whether he only came into such property after his father's death. But any excessive estimate of the father's powers over a son who was no longer a minor and naturally under his control, must be qualified by the fact that in his old age the sons might divide their father's property,<ref name=fx16_ve1_1820/> or he might divide it amongst them,<ref name=fx17_ve1_1820/> and that when the father-in-law became aged he fell under the control of his son's wife.<ref name=fx18_ve1_1820/> There are also obscure traces that in old age a father might be exposed, though there is no reason to suppose that this was usual in Vedic India.<ref name=fx19_ve1_1820/><br><br>Normally the son was bound to give his father full obedience.<ref name=fx20_ve1_1820/> The later Sūtras show in detail the acts of courtesy which he owed his father, and they allow him to eat the remnants of his father's food.<ref name=fx21_ve1_1820/> On the other hand, the father was expected to be kind. The story of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Brāh-  maṇa<ref name=fx22_ve1_1820/> emphasizes the horror with which the father's heartless treatment of his son was viewed. The Upaniṣads<ref name=fx23_ve1_1820/> insist on the spiritual succession from father to son. The kissing of a son<ref name=fx24_ve1_1820/> was a frequent and usual token of affection, even in mature years.<br><br>On the failure of natural children, adoption was possible.<ref name=fx25_ve1_1820/> It was even resorted to when natural children existed, but when it was desired to secure the presence in the family of a person of specially high qualifications, as in Viśvāmitra's adoption of [[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]].<ref name=fx26_ve1_1820/> It is not clear that adoption from one caste into another was possible, for there is no good evidence that [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] was, as Weber<ref name=fx27_ve1_1820/> holds, a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] who adopted a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]. Adoption was also not always in high favour: it may be accidental or not that a hymn of the [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] book of the Rigveda<ref name=fx28_ve1_1820/> condemns the usage. It was also possible for the father who had a daughter, but no sons, to appoint her to bear a son for him. At any rate the practice appears to be referred to in an obscure verse of the Rigveda<ref name=fx29_ve1_1820/> as interpreted by [[यास्क|Yāska]].<ref name=fx30_ve1_1820/> Moreover, it is possible that the difficulty of a brotherless maiden finding a husband<ref name=fx31_ve1_1820/> may have been due in part to the possibility of her father desiring to make her a [[पुत्रिका|Putrikā]], the later technical name for a daughter whose son is to belong to her father's family.<br><br>There can be no doubt that in a family the father took precedence of the mother.<ref name=fx32_ve1_1820/> Delbrück<ref name=fx33_ve1_1820/> explains away the apparent cases to the contrary.<ref name=fx34_ve1_1820/> There is no trace of the  family as a land-owning corporation.<ref name=fx35_ve1_1820/> The dual form Pitarau regularly means ‘father and mother,’ ‘parents.’<ref name=fx36_ve1_1820/><br>

पितृ-याण
<u>'''Pitṛ-yāṇa,'''</u> the ‘way of the fathers,’ mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1821/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1821/> is opposed to the Deva-[[यान|yāna]], or ‘way of the gods.’ Tilak<ref name=fx3_ve1_1821/> considers that the Devayāna corresponds with the Uttarāyaṇa, ‘northern journey’ of the sun, and the [[पितृयाण|Pitṛyāṇa]] with the [[दक्षिणायन|Dakṣiṇāyana]], its ‘southern journey.’ He concludes from a passage of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve1_1821/> where three of the seasons--spring, summer, and the rains--are ascribed to the gods, but the others to the Pitṛs, or Fathers, that the Devayāna began with the vernal equinox, and the [[पितृयाण|Pitṛyāṇa]] with the autumnal equinox. With this he connects the curious  distinction of Deva- and Yama-Nakṣatras in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_1821/> These conclusions are, however, very improbable. ''Cf.'' '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]]''' and '''[[सूर्य|Sūrya]].'''<br>

पितृ-हन्
<u>'''Pitṛ-han,'''</u> ‘parricide,’ is found in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1822/> Paippalāda recension.<br>

पित्र्य
<u>'''Pitrya'''</u> occurs in the list of sciences given in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1823/> Apparently it is to be taken as the science relating to the cult of the Manes, as explained by Śaṅkara in his commentary. As it is in that list followed by '''Rāśi,''' the St. Petersburg Dictionary is inclined to take [[पित्र्य|Pitrya]] Rāśi as one expression, but in what exact sense does not appear.<br>

पित्व
<u>'''Pitva'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve1_1824/> or '''Pidva'''<ref name=fx2_ve1_1824/> is the name of an animal included in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās. According to the commentator on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1824/> it means ‘lion.’ But it may be identical with '''[[पेत्व|Petva]].'''<br>

पिनाक
<u>'''Pināka,'''</u> ‘club,’ is found in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1825/> Later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1825/> it is used to denote the club of Rudra-[[शिव|Śiva]].<br>

पिन्वन
<u>'''Pinvana'''</u> occurs in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 1, 2, 17; 2, 1, 11; 3, 1, 22) as the name of a vessel used in the ritual.<br>

पिपील
<u>'''Pipīla,'''</u> ‘ant,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda (x. 16, 6) as eating the flesh of the dead. <br>

पिपीलिका
<u>'''Pipīlikā'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1828/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1828/> denotes an ‘ant,’ the form of the word referring doubtless not so much to the small species of ant, as it is taken in the later lexicons,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1828/> but rather to the insect's tiny size, which would naturally be expressed by a diminutive formation of the name. The form Pipīlaka<ref name=fx4_ve1_1828/> is found in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx5_ve1_1828/><br>

पिप्पका
<u>'''Pippakā'''</u> is mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] '''Saṃhitās.'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1829/> Some bird seems to be meant.<br>

पिप्पल
<u>'''Pippala,'''</u> n., is found in two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1830/> meaning ‘berry,’ used with a mystic signification, and in neither case with any certain reference to the berry of the fig-tree.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1830/> In the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1830/> the general sense of ‘berry’ is not necessary, and the special sense of ‘berry’ of the Peepal is quite possible: the latter meaning is perhaps intended in the Satapatha Brāhmana.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1830/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx5_ve1_1830/> the feminine form of the word, Pippalī, appears denoting berries used as a remedy for wounds, like '''[[अरुन्धती|Arundhatī]].'''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1830/> <br>

पिप्पलाद
<u>'''Pippalāda'''</u> (‘eater of berries’) is the name of a teacher mentioned in the [[प्रश्न|Praśna]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1831/> In the plural the name denotes a school of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1831/> Their (Paippalāda) recension of the text of the Saṃhitā has been reproduced in facsimile by Garbe and Bloomfield,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1831/> and in part published.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1831/><br>

पिप्रु
<u>'''Pipru'''</u> is the name of a foe of Indra in the Rigveda. He was repeatedly defeated by Indra for '''[[ऋजिश्वन्|Ṛjiśvan]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve1_1832/> Mentioned as possessing forts,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1832/> he is called a [[दास|Dāsa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1832/> as well as an Asura.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1832/> He is described as having a black brood,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1832/> and as being allied with blacks.<ref name=fx6_ve1_1832/> It is uncertain whether he was a demon, according to Roth's<ref name=fx7_ve1_1832/> view, which is favoured by the use of the word Asura, or a human foe, as Ludwig,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1832/> Oldenberg,<ref name=fx9_ve1_1832/> and Hillebrandt<ref name=fx10_ve1_1832/> believe. The name may mean ‘resister,’ from the root ''pṛ.''<br>

पिश
<u>'''Piśa'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1833/> where '''Sāyaṇa''' takes it to mean a deer (''ruru'').<br>

पिशङ्ग
<u>'''Piśaṅga'''</u> is the name of one of the two Unnetṛ priests officiating at the snake festival mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1834/> ''Cf.'' '''Caka.''' <br>

पिशाच
<u>'''Piśāca'''</u> is the name of a class of demon mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1835/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1835/> In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve1_1835/> they are associated with Rakṣases and Asuras, while opposed to gods, men, and fathers. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1835/> they are described as ''kravyād,'' ‘eaters of raw flesh,’ which may be the etymological sense of the word [[पिशाच|Piśāca]] itself.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1835/> It is possible that the Piśācas were, as suggested by Grierson,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1835/> really human foes, like the north-western tribes, who even in later times were reputed eaters of raw flesh (not necessarily as cannibals, but rather as eaters of human flesh in ritual). This is, however, not at all likely, the Piśācas having in all probability only meant ‘ghouls’ originally: when they appear as human tribes, they were presumably thus designated in scorn. A science called Piśācaveda<ref name=fx7_ve1_1835/> or [[पिशाच|Piśāca]]-[[विद्या|vidyā]]<ref name=fx8_ve1_1835/> is known in the later Vedic period.<br>

पिशित
<u>'''Piśita'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1836/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1836/> denotes raw flesh (''of.'' '''[[पिशाच|Piśāca]]'''). In one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve1_1836/> the sense seems to be ‘small piece,’ ‘bit,’ but the St. Petersburg Dictionary suggests that [[पिशित|Piśita]] here stands for ''piṣita,'' equivalent to ''[[पिष्ट|piṣṭa]]'' (what is ‘pounded,’ then ‘particle’).<br>

पिशील
<u>'''Piśīla'''</u> is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 5, 3, 6) as the name of a wooden vessel or dish. In the Lāṭyāyana Śrautā [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (iv. 2, 4. 5) a [[पिशील|Piśīla]]-[[वीणा|vīṇā]] is mentioned, which seems to have been a kind of guitar, with strings stretched over a body of wood. <br>

पिशुन
<u>'''Piśuna,'''</u> ‘traitor,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1838/> and occasionally later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1838/><br>

पिष्ट
<u>'''Piṣṭa'''</u> (‘pounded’), n., ‘meal,’ ‘flour,’ is mentioned in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1839/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1839/> reference is made to pounded beans (''māṣāḥ'').<br>

पीठ
<u>'''Pīṭha,'''</u> ‘stool,’ does not occur as an uncompounded word before the Sūtras, but the compound ''[[पीठ|pīṭha]]-sarpin'' (‘moving about in a little cart’) is found as the designation of a ‘cripple’ in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xxx. 21) and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 4, 17, 1) in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’).<br>

पीतु-दारु
<u>'''Pītu-dāru'''</u> is found in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1841/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1841/> denoting the Deodar (''deva-[[दारु|dāru]]'') tree, or, according to others, the '''[[खदिर|Khadira]]''' or '''[[उदुम्बर|Udumbara]]''' tree.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1841/> ''Cf.'' '''Pūtadru.'''<br>

पीयूष
<u>'''Pīyūṣa'''</u> is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1842/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1842/> in the sense of the first milk of the cow after calving, ‘biestings.’ Usually the term is applied metaphorically to the sap of the Soma plant.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1842/><br>

पीला
<u>'''Pīlā'''</u> occurs once in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1843/> as the name of an  Apsaras, being no doubt originally a name of some fragrant  plant, like '''Naladī''' and '''Guggulū,''' two other names of Apsarases given in the same verse.<br>

पीलु
<u>'''Pīlu'''</u> is the name in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1844/> of a tree (''Careya arborea'' or ''Salvadora persica'') on the fruit of which doves fed.<br>

पीलुमती
<u>'''Pīlumatī'''</u> is in the Atharvaveda (xviii. 2, 48) the name of the intermediate heaven lying between the ''udanuvatī,'' ‘watery,’ and the ''pra-dyauḥ,'' ‘farthest heaven.’ It presumably means ‘rich in '''[[पीलु|Pīlu]].'''’ ''Cf.'' '''Div.'''<br>

पुंश्-चली
<u>'''Puṃś-calī'''</u> (‘running after men’) is found in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1846/> the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1846/> and later,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1846/> to denote a ‘wanton woman.’ In the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve1_1846/> also occurs the form Puṃścalū. See also '''[[धर्म|Dharma]]''' and '''Pati.'''<br>

पुं-सवन
<u>'''Puṃ-savana'''</u> (‘male-production’ ceremony) is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1847/> in a hymn which is obviously intended to accompany a rite aiming at securing the birth of a male child and which is so applied in the ritual.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1847/><br>

पुक्लक
<u>'''Puklaka.'''</u> See '''[[पौल्कस|Paulkasa]].'''<br>

पुञ्जि-ष्ठ
<u>'''Puñji-ṣṭha'''</u> is found in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve1_1849/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1849/> apparently meaning ‘fisherman,’ though Mahīdhara<ref name=fx3_ve1_1849/> explains it as ‘bird-catcher.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[पौञ्जिष्ठ|Pauñjiṣṭha]].''' <br>

पुञ्जील
<u>'''Puñjīla'''</u> is found in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve1_1850/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve1_1850/> in the sense of a ‘bundle’ of grass, being a variant of '''[[पिञ्जूल|Piñjūla]].'''<br>

पुण्डरीक
<u>'''Puṇḍarīka'''</u> denotes the blossom of the lotus in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1851/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1851/> The [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve1_1851/> states that the lotus flower is born of the light of the Nakṣatras, and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve1_1851/> compares the human heart to the lotus.<ref name=fx5_ve1_1851/><br>

पुण्ड्र
<u>'''Puṇḍra'''</u> is the name of a people regarded as outcasts in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve1_1852/> Their name occurs in the Sūtras also.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1852/> In the Epic their country corresponds with Bengal and Bihar.<br>

पुत्र
<u>'''Putra'''</u> is, with '''[[सूनु|Sūnu]],''' the usual name for ‘son’ from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1853/> The original sense of the word was apparently ‘small,’ or something analogous.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1853/> The form Putraka<ref name=fx3_ve1_1853/> is often used with the distinct intention of an affectionate address to a younger man, not merely a son proper. Reference is frequently made to the desire for a son.<ref name=fx4_ve1_1853/> ''Cf.'' '''Pati.''' <br>

पुत्र-सेन
<u>'''Putra-sena'''</u> is the name of a man in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iv. 6, 6).<br>

पुत्रिका
<u>'''Putrikā'''</u> in the later literature<ref name=fx1_ve1_1855/> has the technical sense of the daughter of a man without sons, whom he gives in marriage on the express terms that her son shall perform the funeral rites for him, and be counted as his. The thing as well as the name is recognized by [[यास्क|Yāska]] in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx2_ve1_1855/> and traced to the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1855/> But the passages in the Rigveda are of very uncertain meaning,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1855/> and in all probability do not refer to this custom at all.<br>

पुनर्-दत्त
<u>'''Punar-datta'''</u> (‘given again’) is the name of a teacher in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (viii. 8).<br>

पुनर्-भू
<u>'''Punar-bhū'''</u> is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1857/> meaning a wife who marries again, a rite being mentioned by which she can ensure reunion with her second (not her first) husband in the next world.<br>

पुनर्-वसु
<u>'''Punar-vasu'''</u> (‘bringing goods again’), used in the dual, denotes the fifth in the series of the Vedic '''Nakṣatras,''' or ‘Lunar Mansions.’ Roth<ref name=fx1_ve1_1858/> takes the word to have this sense in its only occurrence in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1858/> but this must be regarded as decidedly doubtful. The term is, however, found in the ordinary lists of the Nakṣatras in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1858/> <br>

पुनः-सर
<u>'''Punaḥ-sara,'''</u> ‘recurrent,’ is the epithet of the barking dog in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1859/> which is told to bark at the thief. It refers, not doubt, to the dog's practice of running to and fro when it barks. It is also applied to a plant, '''[[अपामार्ग|Apāmārga]]''' (''Achyranthes aspera''), in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1859/> with the sense of ‘having revertent leaves.’<br>

पुमांस्
<u>'''Pumāṃs'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1860/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve1_1860/> man as the ‘male.’ It has no special reference to marriage like '''Pati,''' or to heroism like '''[[नृ|Nṛ]]''' or '''Nara.''' In grammar it denotes the masculine gender.<ref name=fx3_ve1_1860/><br>

पुर्
<u>'''Pur'''</u> is a word of frequent occurrence in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1861/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1861/> meaning ‘rampart,’ ‘fort,’ or ‘stronghold.’ Such fortifications must have been occasionally of considerable size, as one is called ‘broad’ (''pṛthvī'') and ‘wide’ (''urvī'').<ref name=fx3_ve1_1861/> Elsewhere<ref name=fx4_ve1_1861/> a fort ‘made of stone’ (''aśmamayī'') is mentioned. Sometimes strongholds ‘of iron’ (''āyasī'') are referred to,<ref name=fx5_ve1_1861/> but these are probably only metaphorical. A fort ‘full of kine’ (''[[गोमती|gomatī]]'') is mentioned,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1861/> showing that strongholds were used to hold cattle. ‘Autumnal’ (''śāradī'') forts are named, apparently as belonging to the '''Dāsas:''' this may refer to the forts in that season being  occupied against Āryan attacks or against inundations caused by overflowing rivers. Forts ‘with a hundred walls’ (''śatabhuji'') are spoken of.<ref name=fx7_ve1_1861/><br><br>It would probably be a mistake to regard these forts as premanently occupied fortified places like the fortresses of the mediæval barony. They were probably merely places of refuge against attack, ramparts of hardened earth with palisades and a ditch (''cf.'' '''[[देही|Dehī]]'''). Pischel and Geldner,<ref name=fx8_ve1_1861/> however, think that there were towns with wooden walls and ditches ( and) like the Indian town of Pāṭaliputra known to Megasthenes<ref name=fx9_ve1_1861/> and the Pāli texts.<ref name=fx10_ve1_1861/> This is possible, but hardly susceptible of proof, and it is not without significance that the word '''[[नगर|Nagara]]''' is of late occurrence. On the whole it is hardly likely that in early Vedic times city life was much developed. In the Epic, according to Hopkins,<ref name=fx11_ve1_1861/> there are found the [[नगर|Nagara]], ‘city’; '''[[ग्राम|Grāma]],''' ‘village’; and [[घोष|Ghoṣa]], ‘ranch.’ Vedic literature hardly seems to go beyond the village, no doubt with modifications in its later period.<br><br>The siege of forts is mentioned in the Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx12_ve1_1861/> According to the Rigveda,<ref name=fx13_ve1_1861/> fire was used. <br>

पुरं-धि
<u>'''Puraṃ-dhi'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1862/> possibly as the name of a woman, a protégée of the Aśvins, who gave her a son, '''[[हिरण्यहस्त|Hiraṇyahasta]].'''<br>

पुरय
<u>'''Puraya'''</u> is the name of a patron celebrated in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1863/><br>

पुराण
<u>'''1. Purāṇa,'''</u> denoting a tale ‘of olden times,’ is often found<ref name=fx1_ve1_1864/> in the combination [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]]-[[पुराण|Purāṇa]], which is probably a Dvandva compound meaning ‘'''[[इतिहास|Itihāsa]]''' and [[पुराण|Purāṇa]].’ It sometimes<ref name=fx2_ve1_1864/> occurs as a separate word, but beside [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]], no doubt with the same sense as in the Dvandva. Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx3_ve1_1864/> defines a [[पुराण|Purāṇa]] as a tale which deals with the primitive condition of the universe and the creation of the world, but there is no ground for supposing that this view is correct, or for clearly distinguishing [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] and [[पुराण|Purāṇa]]. See '''[[इतिहास|Itihāsa]].'''<br>

पुराण
<u>'''2. Purāṇa'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xxxix. 7). <br>

पुरीकय
<u>'''Purīkaya'''</u> is the name of a water animal in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1866/> being clearly a variant of the name that appears as [[पुलीकय|Pulīkaya]] in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1866/> and as Kulīpaya in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1866/> and as [[कुलीकय|Kulīkaya]] in the Taittirī, [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve1_1866/> What animal is meant is quite unknown.<br>

पुरीषिणी
<u>'''Purīṣiṇī'''</u> is found in a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1867/> apparently either as the name of a river,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1867/> or much more probably as an epithet of the '''[[सरयु|Sarayu]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve1_1867/> meaning, perhaps, ‘abounding in water,’ ‘swollen,’<ref name=fx4_ve1_1867/> or ‘carrying rubble.’<ref name=fx5_ve1_1867/><br>

पुरु-कुत्स
<u>'''Puru-kutsa'''</u> is the name of a king who is mentioned several times in the Rigveda. In one passage<ref name=fx1_ve1_1868/> he is mentioned as a contemporary of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' but whether as a foe, according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1868/> or merely as a contemporary, according to Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx3_ve1_1868/> is uncertain. In two other passages<ref name=fx4_ve1_1868/> he is mentioned as victorious by divine favour, and in another<ref name=fx5_ve1_1868/> he appears as a king of the '''Pūrus''' and a conqueror of the '''Dāsas.''' His son was '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]],'''<ref name=fx6_ve1_1868/> who is accordingly called '''Paurukutsya'''<ref name=fx7_ve1_1868/> or '''Paurukutsi.'''<ref name=fx8_ve1_1868/> Different conclusions have been drawn from one hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx9_ve1_1868/> in which the birth of Purukutsa's son,  [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]], is mentioned. The usual interpretation is that [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]] was killed in battle or captured, whereupon his wife secured a son to restore the fortunes of the Pūrus. But Sieg<ref name=fx10_ve1_1868/> offers a completely different interpretation. According to him the word '''daurgahe,''' which occurs in the hymn, and which in the ordinary view is rendered ‘descendant of [[दुर्गह|Durgaha]],’ an ancestor of [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]], is the name of a horse, the hymn recording the success of an [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) undertaken by [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]] for his wife, as by kings in later times, to secure a son. This interpretation is supported by the version of ''daurgahe'' given in the Śatapatha,<ref name=fx11_ve1_1868/> but is by no means certain. Moreover, if [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]] was a contemporary of [[सुदास्|Sudās]], the defeat of the Pūrus by [[सुदास्|Sudās]] in the '''[[दाशराज्ञ|Dāśarājña]]'''<ref name=fx12_ve1_1868/> might well have been the cause of the troubles from which '''[[पुरुकुत्सानी|Purukutsānī]],''' by the birth of [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]], rescued the family. In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx13_ve1_1868/> [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]] is called an [[ऐक्ष्वाक|Aikṣvāka]].<br>

पुरुकुत्सानी
<u>'''Purukutsānī,'''</u> ‘wife of '''[[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]],'''’ is mentioned as the mother of '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]]''' in one hymn of the Rigveda (iv. 42, 9).<br>

पुरु-णीथ शात-वनेय
<u>'''Puru-ṇītha Śāta-vaneya'''</u> (‘descendant of Śatavani’) is the name of a sacrificer, or perhaps a priest, a [[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]], in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve1_1870/> It is doubtful whether he is also mentioned as a singer in another passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve1_1870/> In both places Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_1870/> sees in Puru-ṇītha merely a word meaning ‘choral song.’<br>

पुरु-दम
<u>'''Puru-dama'''</u> occurs in the plural in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve1_1871/> where, according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve1_1871/> it is probably the proper name of the singers, but by Roth<ref name=fx3_ve1_1871/> and Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve1_1871/> is understood as merely an adjective meaning ‘possessed of many houses’ <br>

पुरु-पन्था
<u>'''Puru-panthā'''</u> is mentioned as a generous donor to a '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]]''' in one hymn of the Rigveda (vi. 63, 10).<br>

पुरु-माय्य
<u>'''Puru-māyya'''</u> occurs in one hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1873/> as a protégé of Indra. It is quite possible that he was the father of, or at least connected with, '''[[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]], [[ऋक्ष|Ṛkṣa]],''' and '''[[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]],''' who are celebrated in the hymn.<br>

पुरु-मित्र
<u>'''Puru-mitra'''</u> is mentioned twice in the Rigveda (i. 117, 20; x. 39, 7) as the father of a maiden who wedded '''[[विमद|Vimada]],''' apparently against her father's will.<br>

पुरु-मीळ्ह
<u>'''Puru-mīḷha'''</u> is mentioned twice in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve1_1875/> as an ancient sage, in which capacity he appears in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve1_1875/> also. Perhaps the same<ref name=fx3_ve1_1875/> [[पुरुमीळ्ह|Purumīḷha]] is intended in an obscure hymn in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1875/> where, according to the legends reported in the Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx5_ve1_1875/> and by Ṣaḍguruśiṣya in his commentary on the Sarvānukramaṇī,<ref name=fx6_ve1_1875/> and by Sāyaṇa in his commentary on the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve1_1875/> he as well as '''[[तरन्त|Taranta]]''' was a son of Vidadaśva, and a patron of the singer '''[[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]].''' The correctness of the legend has been shown to be most improbable by Oldenberg,<ref name=fx7_ve1_1875/> who points out<ref name=fx8_ve1_1875/> that the legend misinterprets the Rigveda by making [[पुरुमीळ्ह|Purumīḷha]] a [[वैदद्अश्वि|Vaidadaśvi]], for he is there only compared in generosity to one.<br><br>In another legend found in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx9_ve1_1875/> and based on a hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx10_ve1_1875/> [[पुरुमीळ्ह|Purumīḷha]] and [[तरन्त|Taranta]] appear as persons who received gifts from '''[[ध्वस्र|Dhvasra]]''' and '''[[पुरुषन्ति|Puruṣanti]],''' and as sons of Vidadaśva. The legend, which also occurs in the Śāṭyāyanaka,<ref name=fx11_ve1_1875/> is apparently best explained by  Sieg,<ref name=fx12_ve1_1875/> who says that as the two were kings they could not under the rules of caste accept gifts, unless for the nonce they became singers. The legend has no claim at all, as Oldenberg<ref name=fx13_ve1_1875/> shows, to validity. <br>

पुरुष
<u>'''Puruṣa,'''</u> or '''[[पूरुष|Pūruṣa]],''' is the generic term for ‘man’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1/> Man is composed of five parts according to the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1/> or of six according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve2_1/> or of sixteen,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1/> or of twenty,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1/> or of twenty-one,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1/> or of twenty-four,<ref name=fx8_ve2_1/> or of twenty-five,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1/> all more or less fanciful enumerations. Man is the first of animals,<ref name=fx10_ve2_1/> but also essentially an animal (see '''[[पशु|Paśu]]'''). The height of a man is given in the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx11_ve2_1/> as four Aratnis (‘cubits’) , each of two Padas (‘feet’), each of twelve Aṅgulis (‘finger's breadths’); and the term [[पुरुष|Puruṣa]] itself is found earlier<ref name=fx12_ve2_1/> as a measure of length.<br><br>[[पुरुष|Puruṣa]] is also applied to denote the length of a man's life, a ‘generation’;<ref name=fx13_ve2_1/> the ‘pupil’ in the eye;<ref name=fx14_ve2_1/> and in the grammatical literature the ‘person’ of the verb.<ref name=fx15_ve2_1/> <br>

पुरुष मृग
<u>'''Puruṣa Mṛga'''</u> the ‘man wild beast,’ occurs in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_2/> Zimmer's<ref name=fx2_ve2_2/> view that the ape is meant seems probable. According to him also, the word [[पुरुष|Puruṣa]] alone, in two passages of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_2/> refers to the ape and its cry (''[[मायु|māyu]]''); but this sense is not necessary, and it is not adopted by Bloomfield,<ref name=fx4_ve2_2/> though Whitney<ref name=fx5_ve2_2/> does not think the rendering ‘cry of a man’ satisfactory, the term ''[[मायु|māyu]]'' not being properly applicable to the noise made by human beings.<br>

पुरुष हस्तिन्
<u>'''Puruṣa Hastin'''</u> (‘the man with a hand’) is found in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_3/> It must be the ‘ape.’<br>

पुरुषन्ति
<u>'''Puruṣanti'''</u> is a name that occurs twice in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_4/> in the first passage denoting a protégé of the Aśvins, in the second a patron who gave presents to one of the Vedic singers. In both cases the name is joined with that of '''[[ध्वसन्ति|Dhvasanti]]''' or '''[[ध्वस्र|Dhvasra]].''' The presumption from the manner in which these three names are mentioned is that they designate men, but the grammatical form of the words might equally well be feminine. Females must be meant, if the evidence of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_4/> is to be taken as decisive, for the form of the first of the two names there occurring, ''Dhvasre Puruṣantī,'' ‘Dhvasrā and [[पुरुषन्ति|Puruṣanti]],’ is exclusively feminine, though '''here''' as well as elsewhere Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx3_ve2_4/> interprets the names as masculines. See also '''[[तरन्त|Taranta]]''' and '''[[पुरुमीळ्ह|Purumīḷha]].''' <br>

पुरु-हन्मन्
<u>'''Puru-hanman'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in a hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_5/> an '''[[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]],''' according to the Rigvedic Anukramaṇī (Index), but according to the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_5/> a '''[[वैखानस|Vaikhānasa]].'''<br>

पुरू-रवस्
<u>'''Purū-ravas'''</u> is the name of a hero in a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_6/> containing a curious dialogue between him and a nymph, Urvaśī, an Apsaras. He is also mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_6/> where several verses of the Rigvedic dialogue find a setting in a continuous story. In the later literature he is recognized as a king.<ref name=fx3_ve2_6/> His name is perhaps intended in one other passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx4_ve2_6/> It is impossible to say whether he is a mythical figure pure and simple, or really an ancient king. His epithet, Aiḷa,<ref name=fx5_ve2_6/> ‘descendant of Iḍā’ (a sacrificial goddess), is certainly in favour of the former alternative.<br>

पुरूरु
<u>'''Purūru'''</u> is the name of a poet, an '''[[आत्रेय|Ātreya]],''' in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_7/> according to Ludwig.<ref name=fx2_ve2_7/> But the only form of the word found, ''purūruṇā,'' seems merely an adverb meaning ‘far and wide.’<br>

पुरू-वसु
<u>'''Purū-vasu'''</u> (‘abounding in wealth’) is the name of a poet, an '''[[आत्रेय|Ātreya]],''' according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx1_ve2_8/> in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_8/> But this is very doubtful. <br>

पुरो-डाश्
<u>'''Puro-ḍāś'''</u> is the name of the sacrificial cake in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_9/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_9/><br>

पुरो-धा
<u>'''Puro-dhā'''</u> denotes the office of [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], ‘domestic priest.’ Its mention as early as the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_10/> and often later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_10/> shows that the post was a fully recognized and usual one.<br>

पुरो-'नुवाक्या
<u>'''Puro-'nuvākyā'''</u> (‘introductory verse to be recited’) is the technical term for the address to a god inviting him to partake of the offering; it was followed by the '''[[याज्या|Yājyā]],''' which accompanied the actual oblation.<ref name=fx1_ve2_11/> Such addresses are not unknown, but are rare, according to Oldenberg,<ref name=fx2_ve2_11/> in the Rigveda; subsequently they are regular, the word itself occurring in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx3_ve2_11/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx4_ve2_11/><br>

पुरो-रुच्
<u>'''Puro-ruc'''</u> is the technical description of certain '''[[निविद्|Nivid]]''' verses which were recited at the morning libation in the [[आज्य|Ājya]] and Praüga ceremonies before the hymn (''[[सूक्त|sūkta]]'') of the litany or its parts. It occurs in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_12/> <br>

पुरो-वात
<u>'''Puro-vāta,'''</u> the ‘east wind,’ is mentioned in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_13/> Geldner<ref name=fx2_ve2_13/> thinks it merely means the wind preceding the rains.<br>

पुरो-हित
<u>'''Puro-hita'''</u> (‘placed in front,’ ‘appointed’) is the name of a priest in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_14/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_14/> The office of [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] is called Purohiti<ref name=fx3_ve2_14/> and '''[[पुरोधा|Purodhā]].''' It is clear that the primary function of the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] was that of ‘domestic priest’ of a king, or perhaps a great noble; his quite exceptional position is shown by the fact that only one [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] seems ever to be mentioned in Vedic literature.<ref name=fx4_ve2_14/> Examples of Purohitas in the Rigveda are '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]'''<ref name=fx5_ve2_14/> or '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]'''<ref name=fx6_ve2_14/> in the service of the '''[[भरत|Bharata]]''' king; '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' of the '''[[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]]''' family; the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of '''Kuruśravaṇa;'''<ref name=fx7_ve2_14/> and '''Devāpi,''' the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of '''Śantanu.'''<ref name=fx8_ve2_14/> The [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] was in all religious matters the ''alter ego'' of the king. In the ritual<ref name=fx9_ve2_14/> it is laid down that a king must have a [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], else the gods will not accept his offerings. He ensures the king's safety and victory in battle by his prayers;<ref name=fx10_ve2_14/> he procures  the fall of rain for the crops;<ref name=fx11_ve2_14/> he is the flaming fire that guards the kingdom.<ref name=fx12_ve2_14/> Divodāsa in trouble is rescued by [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]];<ref name=fx13_ve2_14/> and King '''Tryaruṇa [[त्रैधात्व|Traidhātva]] [[ऐक्ष्वाक|Aikṣvāka]]''' reproaches his [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], '''[[वृश जान|Vṛśa Jāna]],''' when his car runs over a Brahmin boy and kills him.<ref name=fx14_ve2_14/> The close relation of king and [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] is illustrated by the case of '''[[कुत्स औरव|Kutsa Aurava]],''' who slew his [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], '''[[उपगु सौश्रवस|Upagu Sauśravasa]],''' for disloyalty in serving Indra, to whom [[कुत्स|Kutsa]] was hostile.<ref name=fx15_ve2_14/> Other disputes between kings and priests who officiated for them are those of '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]]''' and the '''Kaśyapas,''' and of '''Viśvantara''' and the '''Śyāparṇas;'''<ref name=fx16_ve2_14/> and between '''Asamāti''' and the '''Gaupāyanas.'''<ref name=fx17_ve2_14/> In some cases one [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] served more than one king; for example, '''[[देवभाग श्रौतर्ष|Devabhāga Śrautarṣa]]''' was the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of the '''Kurus''' and the '''Sṛṅjayas''' at the same time,<ref name=fx18_ve2_14/> and '''[[जल जातूकर्ण्य|Jala Jātūkarṇya]]''' was the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of the kings of '''[[काशि|Kāśi]], [[विदेह|Videha]],''' and '''[[कोसल|Kosala]].'''<ref name=fx19_ve2_14/><br><br>There is no certain proof that the office of [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] was hereditary in a family, though it probably was so.<ref name=fx20_ve2_14/> At any rate, it seems clear from the relations of the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] with King '''Kuruśravaṇa,''' and with his son '''[[उपमश्रवस्|Upamaśravas]],'''<ref name=fx21_ve2_14/> that a king would keep on the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of his father.<br><br>Zimmer<ref name=fx22_ve2_14/> thinks that the king might act as his own [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], as shown by the case of King Viśvantara, who sacrificed without the help of the Śyāparṇas,<ref name=fx23_ve2_14/> and that a [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] need not be a priest, as shown by the case of Devāpi and Śantanu.<ref name=fx24_ve2_14/> But neither opinion seems to be justified. It is not said that  Viśvantara sacrificed without priests, while Devāpi is not regarded as a king until the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx25_ve2_14/> and there is no reason to suppose that Yāska's view expressed in that work is correct.<br><br>According to Geldner,<ref name=fx26_ve2_14/> the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] from the beginning acted as the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] priest in the sacrificial ritual, being there the general superintendent of the sacrifice. In favour of this view, he cites the fact that [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] is mentioned both as [[पुरोहित|Purohita]]<ref name=fx27_ve2_14/> and as [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]]:<ref name=fx28_ve2_14/> at the sacrifice of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]''' he served as [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]],<ref name=fx29_ve2_14/> but he was the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of [[सुदास्|Sudās]];<ref name=fx30_ve2_14/> [[बृहस्पति|Bṛhaspati]] is called the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]]<ref name=fx31_ve2_14/> and the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]]<ref name=fx32_ve2_14/> of the gods; and the Vasiṣṭhas who are Purohitas are also the Brahmans at the sacrifice.<ref name=fx33_ve2_14/> It is thus clear that the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] was often the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]]; and it was natural that this should be the case when once the Brahman's place became, as it did in the later ritual, the most important position at the sacrifice.<ref name=fx34_ve2_14/> But the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] can hardly be said to have held this place in the earlier ritual; Oldenberg<ref name=fx35_ve2_14/> seems to be right in holding that the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] was originally the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest, the singer ''par excellence,'' when he took any part at all in the ritual of the great sacrifices with the '''Ṛtvijs.''' So Devāpi seems clearly to have  been a [[होतृ|Hotṛ]];<ref name=fx36_ve2_14/> Agni is at once [[पुरोहित|Purohita]]<ref name=fx37_ve2_14/> and [[होतृ|Hotṛ]];<ref name=fx38_ve2_14/> and the ‘two divine Hotṛs’ referred to in the Āprī litanies are also called the ‘two Purohitas.’<ref name=fx39_ve2_14/> Later, no doubt, when the priestly activity ceased to centre in the song, the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], with his skill in magic, became the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], who also required magic to undo the errors of the sacrifice.<ref name=fx40_ve2_14/><br><br>There is little doubt that in the original growth of the priesthood the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] played a considerable part. In historical times he represented the real power of the kingship, and may safely be deemed to have exercised great influence in all public affairs, such as the administration of justice and the king's conduct of business. But it is not at all probable that the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] represents, as Roth<ref name=fx41_ve2_14/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx42_ve2_14/> thought, the source which gave rise to caste. The priestly class is already in existence in the Rigveda (see '''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]]''').<br>

पुलस्ति
<u>'''Pulasti'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_15/> or '''Pulastin'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_15/> in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās denotes ‘wearing the hair plain,’ as opposed to ''kapardin,'' ‘wearing the hair in braids.’<br>

पुलिन्द
<u>'''Pulinda'''</u> is the name of an outcast tribe mentioned with the '''Andhras''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_16/> but not in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_16/> in connexion with the story of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]].''' The Pulindas again appear associated with the Andhras in the time of Aśoka.<ref name=fx3_ve2_16/> <br>

पुलीकय
<u>'''Pulīkaya.'''</u> See '''[[पुरीकय|Purīkaya]].'''<br>

पुलीका
<u>'''Pulīkā'''</u> seems to designate some kind of bird in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iii. 14, 5). The name appears in the form of [[कुलीका|Kulīkā]] in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xxiv. 24).<br>

पुलुष प्राचीन-योग्य
<u>'''Puluṣa Prācīna-yogya'''</u> (‘descendant of Prācīnayoga’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[दृति|Dṛti]] Aindroti [[शौनक|Śaunaka]],''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 2). He taught '''[[पौलुषि|Pauluṣi]] [[सत्ययज्ञ|Satyayajña]].'''<br>

पुष्कर
<u>'''Puṣkara'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_20/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_20/> of the blue lotus flower. The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_20/> mentions its sweet perfume. The lotus grew in lakes, which were thence called ''puṣkariṇī,'' ‘lotus-bearing.’<ref name=fx4_ve2_20/> That the flower was early used for personal adornment is shown by an epithet of the Aśvins, ‘lotuscrowned’ (''[[पुष्कर|puṣkara]]-sraj'').<ref name=fx5_ve2_20/><br><br>Presumably because of its likeness in shape to the flower of the lotus, the bowl of the ladle is called [[पुष्कर|Puṣkara]], perhaps already in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx6_ve2_20/> and certainly in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx7_ve2_20/> Moreover, according to the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx8_ve2_20/> [[पुष्कर|Puṣkara]] means ‘water,’ a sense actually found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx9_ve2_20/><br>

पुष्कर-साद
<u>'''Puṣkara-sāda,'''</u> ‘sitting on the lotus,’ is the name of an animal in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’)  in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_21/> It can hardly be a ‘snake,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_21/> but rather either, as Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_21/> thinks, a ‘bird,’ or perhaps, according to the commentator on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve2_21/> a ‘bee.’<br>

पुष्टि-गु
<u>'''Puṣṭi-gu'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] mentioned in a [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_22/><br>

पुष्प
<u>'''Puṣpa'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_23/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_23/> denotes a ‘flower’ generally.<br>

पुष्य
<u>'''Puṣya'''</u> is the name in the Atharvaveda (xix. 7, 2 for the '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]]''' called '''[[तिष्य|Tiṣya]]''' elsewhere.<br><br>''Cf.'' Weber, ''Naxatra,'' 2, 371. On [[तिष्य|Tiṣya]], see also ''Journal of the Royal Asatic Society,'' 1911, 514-518; 794-800.<br>

पूत-क्रता
<u>'''Pūta-kratā'''</u> is the name of a woman in a [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_25/> perhaps the wife of '''[[पूतक्रतु|Pūtakratu]],''' but this is doubtful, since the more regular form would be Pūtakratāyī,<ref name=fx2_ve2_25/> which Scheftelowitz<ref name=fx3_ve2_25/> reads in the hymn.<br>

पूत-क्रतु
<u>'''Pūta-kratu'''</u> (‘of clear insight’) is the name of a patron in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_26/> apparently the son of '''[[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]].''' <br>

पूति-रज्जु
<u>'''Pūti-rajju'''</u> is the name of a certain plant of unknown kind in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_27/> according to Roth.<ref name=fx2_ve2_27/> The [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_27/> treats it as a ‘putrid rope,’ but Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve2_27/> suggests that a snake is meant.<br>

पूतीक
<u>'''Pūtīka'''</u> is the name of a plant often mentioned<ref name=fx1_ve2_28/> as a substitute for the Soma plant. It is also given in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_28/> as a means of making milk curdle, being an alternative to the bark of the ''Butea frondosa ([[पर्ण|parṇa]]-[[वल्क|valka]]).'' It is usually identified with the ''Guilandina Bonduc,'' but Hillebrandt<ref name=fx3_ve2_28/> makes it out to be the ''Basella Cordifolia.''<br>

पूतु-द्रु
<u>'''Pūtu-dru'''</u> is another name for the Deodar (''deva-[[दारु|dāru]]'') in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_29/> and the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve2_29/> The longer form, Pūtu-[[दारु|dāru]], is found in the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_29/><br>

पूरु
<u>'''Pūru'''</u> is the name of a people and their king in the Rigveda. They are mentioned with the '''Anus, Druhyus, Turvaśas,''' and '''Yadus''' in one passage.<ref name=fx1_ve2_30/> They also occur as enemies of the '''Tṛtsus''' in the hymn of '''Sudās’''' victory.<ref name=fx2_ve2_30/> In another  hymn<ref name=fx3_ve2_30/> Agni of the '''Bharatas''' is celebrated as victorious over the Pūrus, probably a reference to the same decisive overthrow. On the other hand, victories of the Pūrus over the aborigines seem to be referred to in several passages.<ref name=fx4_ve2_30/><br><br>The great kings of the Pūrus were '''[[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]]''' and his son '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]],''' whose name bears testimony to his prowess against aboriginal foes, while a later prince was '''[[तृक्षि|Tṛkṣi]] [[त्रासदस्यव|Trāsadasyava]].'''<br><br>In the Rigveda the Pūrus are expressly<ref name=fx5_ve2_30/> mentioned as on the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].''' Zimmer<ref name=fx6_ve2_30/> thinks that the '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]''' (Indus) is meant in this passage. But Ludwig<ref name=fx7_ve2_30/> and Hillebrandt<ref name=fx8_ve2_30/> with much greater probability think that the eastern [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] in [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]] is meant. This view accords well with the sudden disappearance of the name of the Pūrus from Vedic tradition, a disappearance accounted for by Oldenberg's<ref name=fx9_ve2_30/> conjecture that the Pūrus became part of the great Kuru people, just as '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]]''' and '''[[क्रिवि|Krivi]]''' disappear from the tradition on their being merged in the '''[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]]''' nation. [[त्रासदस्यव|Trāsadasyava]], the patronymic of '''Kuruśravaṇa''' in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx10_ve2_30/> shows that the royal families of the Kurus and the Pūrus were allied by intermarriage.<br><br>Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx11_ve2_30/> admitting that the Pūrus in later times lived in the eastern country round the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]], thinks that in earlier days they were to be found to the west of the Indus with '''Divodāsa.''' This theory must fall with the theory that Divodāsa was in the far west. It might, however, be held to be supported by the fact that Alexander found a --that is, a Paurava prince on the Hydaspes,<ref name=fx12_ve2_30/> a sort of half-way locality between the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] and the West. But it is quite simple to suppose either that the Hydaspes was the earlier home of the Pūrus, where some remained after the others had  wandered east, or that the later Paurava represents a successful onslaught upon the west from the east.<br><br>In several other passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx13_ve2_30/> the Pūrus as a people seem to be meant. The [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx14_ve2_30/> recognizes the general sense of ‘man,’ but in no passage is this really necessary or even probable. So utterly, however, is the tradition lost that the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx15_ve2_30/> explains [[पूरु|Pūru]] in the Rigveda<ref name=fx16_ve2_30/> as an Asura [[रक्षस्|Rakṣas]]; it is only in the Epic that [[पूरु|Pūru]] revives as the name of a son of [[ययाति|Yayāti]] and Śarmiṣṭhā.<ref name=fx17_ve2_30/><br>

पूरुष
<u>'''Pūruṣa'''</u> has in several passages<ref name=fx1_ve2_31/> the sense of ‘menial’ or ‘dependent,’ like the English ‘man.’<br>

पूर्ण-मास
<u>'''Pūrṇa-māsa'''</u> denotes the full moon and the festival of that day, occurring frequently in the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_32/> ''Cf.'' '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

पूर्त
<u>'''Pūrta,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_33/> or '''Pūrti,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_33/> occurs in the Rigveda and later denoting the reward to the priest for his services. ''Cf.'' '''[[दक्षिणा|Dakṣiṇā]].'''<br>

पूर्-पति
<u>'''Pūr-pati,'''</u> ‘lord of the fort,’ occurring only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_34/> is of somewhat doubtful interpretation. The term-  may denote a regular office,<ref name=fx2_ve2_34/> similar to that of the '''Grāmaṇī:''' the '''Pur''' would then be a permanently occupied settlement. The expression may, however, merely mean the chief over a fort when it was actually occupied against hostile attack. The rarity of the word seems to favour the latter sense.<br>

पूर्व-पक्ष
<u>'''Pūrva-pakṣa'''</u> denotes the first half of the month. See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

पूर्व-वयस
<u>'''Pūrva-vayasa,'''</u> the ‘first period of life,’ is a term used in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_36/> to denote ‘youth.’<br>

पूर्व-वह्
<u>'''Pūrva-vah'''</u> is a term applied to the horse ('''[[अश्व|Aśva]]''') in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_37/> and elsewhere.<ref name=fx2_ve2_37/> It may either refer to a horse fastened in front as a ‘leader,’ or merely mean ‘drawing (a chariot) for the first time,’ as understood by the commentator on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<br>

पूर्वाह्ण
<u>'''Pūrvāhṇa,'''</u> ‘the earlier (part of the) day,’ ‘forenoon,’ is a common designation of time from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_38/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve2_38/> ''Cf.'' '''Ahan.'''<br>

पूल्य
<u>'''Pūlya,'''</u> or '''Pūlpa,''' in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_39/> seems to mean ‘shrivelled grain’ (''cf.'' '''Lājā'''). <br>

पृक्ष
<u>'''Pṛkṣa'''</u> (literally, perhaps ‘swift’) is the proper name of a man in an obscure verse of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_40/><br>

पृक्ष-याम
<u>'''Pṛkṣa-yāma'''</u> occurs once in the plural in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_41/> Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_41/> suggests the sense of ‘faring with swift steeds,’ and thinks a proper name is meant. Pischel<ref name=fx3_ve2_41/> holds that the word is an epithet of the '''Pajras,''' and that it means ‘performing splendid sacrifices.’<br>

पृड
<u>'''Pṛḍa.'''</u> See '''[[मृड|Mṛḍa]].'''<br>

पृत्
<u>'''Pṛt'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_43/> and Pṛtanā<ref name=fx2_ve2_43/> denote, in the Rigveda and later, ‘contest,’ whether in arms or in the chariot race. Pṛtanā has also the concrete sense of ‘army’ in some passages;<ref name=fx3_ve2_43/> in the Epic system<ref name=fx4_ve2_43/> it denotes a definite body of men, elephants, chariots, and horses. Pṛtanājya<ref name=fx5_ve2_43/> has only the sense of ‘combat.’<br>

पृथ
<u>'''Pṛtha,'''</u> the ‘palm’ of the hand in the sense of its breath, is used as a measure of length in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Brāhmaṇā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_44/><br>

पृथवान
<u>'''Pṛthavāna'''</u> is in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_45/> the name of a man, perhaps also called '''[[दुःशीम|Duḥśīma]],''' but this is uncertain. ''Cf.'' '''[[पृथि|Pṛthi]].''' <br>

पृथि
<u>'''Pṛthi,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_46/> '''Pṛthī,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_46/> or '''[[पृथु|Pṛthu]]'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_46/> is the name of a semi-mythical personage who is mentioned in the Rigveda and later as a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], and more specially as the inventor of agriculture<ref name=fx4_ve2_46/> and the lord of both worlds, of men and of animals.<ref name=fx5_ve2_46/> He bears in several passages<ref name=fx6_ve2_46/> the epithet [[वैन्य|Vainya]], ‘descendant of Vena,’ and must probably be regarded as a culture hero rather than as a real man. According to other accounts,<ref name=fx7_ve2_46/> he was the first of consecrated kings. ''Cf.'' '''Pārthiva.'''<br>

पृथिवी
<u>'''Pṛthivī'''</u> denotes the ‘earth’ as the ‘broad’ one in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_47/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_47/> being often personified as a deity<ref name=fx3_ve2_47/> both alone and with '''Div,''' ‘heaven,’ as Dyāvā-[[पृथिवी|Pṛthivī]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_47/> Mention is often made of three earths,<ref name=fx5_ve2_47/> of which the world on which we live is the highest.<ref name=fx6_ve2_47/> The earth is girdled by the ocean, according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx7_ve2_47/> The [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx8_ve2_47/> places one of the three earths in each of the worlds into which the universe is divided  (see '''Div'''). In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx9_ve2_47/> the earth is called the ‘firstborn of being,’ and its riches (''[[वित्त|vitta]]'') are referred to;<ref name=fx10_ve2_47/> hence in a late passage of the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx11_ve2_47/> the earth is styled ''vasu-matī,'' ‘full of wealth.’ The word also occurs in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx12_ve2_47/> though rarely, in the form of Pṛthvī.<ref name=fx13_ve2_47/><br>

पृथु
<u>'''Pṛthu.'''</u> See '''[[पृथि|Pṛthi]].''' Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve2_48/> also finds a mention of the Pṛthus as a tribe, allied with the '''Parśus,''' in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_48/> as opponents of the '''[[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]] Bharatas.''' But this interpretation is certainly incorrect.<ref name=fx3_ve2_48/> See '''[[पर्शु|Parśu]].'''<br>

पृथु-श्रवस्
<u>'''1. Pṛthu-śravas'''</u> (‘far-famed’) is mentioned in connexion with '''[[वश|Vaśa]]''' in two hymns<ref name=fx1_ve2_49/> of the Rigveda. In the second passage the generosity of [[पृथुश्रवस्|Pṛthuśravas]] [[कानीत|Kānīta]] to [[वश अश्व्य|Vaśa Aśvya]] is celebrated, and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_49/> refers to the episode.<br>

पृथु-श्रवस् दौरे-श्रवस
<u>'''2. Pṛthu-śravas Daure-śravasa'''</u> (‘descendant of Dūreśravas’) is the name of the Udgātṛ priest at the snake festival mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_50/><br>

पृदाकु
<u>'''Pṛdāku,'''</u> the name of a ‘snake’ in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_51/> is mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’), in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx2_ve2_51/> and occasionally else-  where.<ref name=fx3_ve2_51/> Its skin was specially valuable, according to the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx4_ve2_51/><br>

पृदाकु-सानु
<u>'''Pṛdāku-sānu,'''</u> ‘having the surface of a snake,’ is taken by Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve2_52/> and Griffith<ref name=fx2_ve2_52/> as the name of the institutor of a sacrifice in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_52/><br>

पृशन
<u>'''Pṛśana'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_53/> is considered by Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_53/> to denote a place where a battle was fought.<br>

पृश्नि-गु
<u>'''1. Pṛśni-gu'''</u> is the name of a man who is mentioned with '''[[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]]''' and '''[[शुचन्ति|Śucanti]]''' as a protégé of the Aśvins in one hymn of the Rigveda (i. 112, 7). Possibly the word is only an epithet of [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]].<br><br>''Cf.'' Geldner, ''Rigveda, Glossar,'' 114.<br>

पृश्नि-गु
<u>'''2. Pṛśni-gu,'''</u> pl., is taken in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_55/> by Geldner<ref name=fx2_ve2_55/> as denoting the name of a people. But this is not probable.<br>

पृश्नि-पर्णी
<u>'''Pṛśni-parṇī'''</u> (‘having a speckled leaf’) is the name of a plant mentioned in a hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_56/> as a protection against evil beings procuring abortion, called Kaṇvas (presumably a sign of hostility to the '''[[कण्व|Kaṇva]]''' family).<ref name=fx2_ve2_56/> It also appears in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_56/> being identified with ''Hermionitis cordifolia'' by the St. Petersburg Dictionary, but  Roth<ref name=fx4_ve2_56/> in a subsequent contribution suggests that it is the same as a plant later called ''lakṣmaṇā,'' and regarded as curing barrenness. The scholiast on the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_56/> thinks that the ''Glycine debilis'' is meant.<br>

पृषत
<u>'''Pṛṣata'''</u> is the name of an animal mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_57/> The dappled antelope or gazelle seems to be meant.<ref name=fx2_ve2_57/><br>

पृषती
<u>'''Pṛṣatī'''</u> in some passages<ref name=fx1_ve2_58/> clearly means a ‘speckled’ cow. The term is, however, generally<ref name=fx2_ve2_58/> applied to the team of the Maruts, when its sense is doubtful. The commentators usually explain it as ‘speckled antelope.’ But Mahīdhara,<ref name=fx3_ve2_58/> followed by Roth,<ref name=fx4_ve2_58/> prefers to see in it a ‘dappled mare’: it is true that the Maruts are often called<ref name=fx5_ve2_58/> ''pṛṣad-[[अश्व|aśva]],'' which is more naturally interpreted as ‘having dappled steeds,’ than as ‘having Pṛṣatīs as steeds.’<ref name=fx6_ve2_58/> In the later literature, which Grassmann<ref name=fx7_ve2_58/> prefers to follow, the word means the female of the dappled gazelle.  Aufrecht<ref name=fx8_ve2_58/> concurs in the view of Roth, but Max Müller<ref name=fx9_ve2_58/> is inclined to accept the traditional interpretation, while Muir<ref name=fx10_ve2_58/> leaves the matter open.<br>

पृषद्-आज्य
<u>'''Pṛṣad-ājya'''</u> denotes ‘sprinkled butter’--that is, butter ('''[[आज्य|Ājya]]''') mixed with sour milk, in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_59/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_59/><br>

पृषध्र
<u>'''Pṛṣadhra'''</u> occurs in a [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_60/> as the name of a man. He is also mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_60/> as a patron of '''[[प्रस्कण्व|Praskaṇva]],''' and called [[पृषध्र|Pṛṣadhra]] [[मेध्य|Medhya]] [[मातरिश्वन्|Mātariśvan]] (or Mātariśva); but for once there is a discrepancy between the statement of the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] and the text of the Rigveda, for the hymns<ref name=fx3_ve2_60/> there attributed to [[प्रस्कण्व|Praskaṇva]] as in praise of [[पृषध्र|Pṛṣadhra]] have nothing in them connected with [[पृषध्र|Pṛṣadhra]], while the Anukramaṇī (Index) ascribes to [[पृषध्र|Pṛṣadhra]] himself the authorship of one of them.<ref name=fx4_ve2_60/> On the other hand, '''[[मेध्य|Medhya]]''' and '''[[मातरिश्वन्|Mātariśvan]]''' appear as separate persons in the '''Rigveda'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_60/> along with [[पृषध्र|Pṛṣadhra]].<br>

पृषातक
<u>'''Pṛṣātaka'''</u> is the name of a mixture like '''[[पृषद्आज्य|Pṛṣadājya]],''' and consisting, according to the late Gṛhyasaṃgraha,<ref name=fx1_ve2_61/> of curds ('''[[दधि|Dadhi]]'''), honey ('''[[मधु|Madhu]]'''), and '''Ajya.''' It is mentioned in a late passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_61/> and in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx3_ve2_61/><br>

पृष्ट्या
<u>'''Pṛṣṭyā'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_62/> denotes in the Atharvaveda (vi. 102, 2) the side horse (mare). <br>

पृष्ट्य्-आमय
<u>'''Pṛṣṭy-āmaya'''</u> denotes in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_63/> a pain in the sides or ribs.<ref name=fx2_ve2_63/> It appears to be mentioned there merely as an accompaniment of fever ('''[[तक्मन्|Takman]]''').<br>

पेत्व
<u>'''Petva'''</u> is found twice in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_64/> In the first passage reference is made to its ''[[वाज|vāja]],'' which Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_64/> argues can only mean ‘strength,’ ‘swiftness,’ though naturally the sense of ‘male power’ would seem more appropriate in a spell intended to remove lack of virility. In the second passage the [[पेत्व|Petva]] is mentioned as overcoming the horse (see '''[[उभयादन्त्|Ubhayādant]]'''), a miracle which has a parallel in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_64/> where the [[पेत्व|Petva]] overcomes the female<ref name=fx4_ve2_64/> lion. The animal also occurs in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx5_ve2_64/> and occasionally elsewhere.<ref name=fx6_ve2_64/> It appears to be the ‘ram’ or the ‘wether,’ the latter<ref name=fx7_ve2_64/> being the sense given to it by the commentator on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā. But there is no conclusive evidence in favour of this meaning, while on the whole the passage of the Atharvaveda, in which ''[[वाज|vāja]]'' is found, accords best with the sense of ‘ram.’ Hopkins,<ref name=fx8_ve2_64/> however, renders the word as ‘goat,’ though for what reason is not clear. Whether it is connected in any way with '''[[पित्व|Pitva]]''' or '''Pidva''' is quite uncertain. <br>

पेदु
<u>'''Pedu'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_65/> of a protégé of the Aśvins, who gave him, in order, as it seems, to replace a bad steed, a mythical horse, hence called [[पैद्व|Paidva]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_65/> which probably represents the horse of the sun.<ref name=fx3_ve2_65/><br>

पेरुक
<u>'''Peruka'''</u> occurs in an obscure verse of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_66/> as the name of a patron of the poet.<br>

पेसस्
<u>'''Pesas'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_67/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_67/> an embroidered garment such as a female dancer would wear.<ref name=fx3_ve2_67/> The fondness of the Indians for such raiment is noted by Megasthenes<ref name=fx4_ve2_67/> and by Arrian,<ref name=fx5_ve2_67/> who refer to their . So in one passage<ref name=fx6_ve2_67/> a garment (''[[वस्त्र|vastra]]'') is called ''peśana,'' with which Roth<ref name=fx7_ve2_67/> happily compares the Roman ''vestis coloribus intexta.'' The making of such garments was a regular occupation of women, as is indicated by the Peśas-kārī, the ‘female embroiderer,’ figuring in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx8_ve2_67/> though the, commentator on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] interprets the word as ‘wife of a maker of gold.’<ref name=fx9_ve2_67/> Pischel,<ref name=fx10_ve2_67/> however, thinks that Peśas never means anything but colour or form.<br>

पेसितृ
<u>'''Pesitṛ'''</u> is the name of one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_68/> The sense is quite  uncertain. The word is rendered by the St. Petersburg Dictionary and by Weber<ref name=fx2_ve2_68/> as ‘one who cuts in pieces,’ a ‘carver,’ but Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx3_ve2_68/> thinks that it means one who causes an enmity which has been lulled to rest to break out again.<br>

पैङ्ग-राज
<u>'''Paiṅga-rāja'''</u> is the name of one of the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_69/> That a bird is meant is certain, but what particular kind is quite unknown.<br>

पैङ्गी-पुत्र
<u>'''Paiṅgī-putra'''</u> (‘son of a female descendant of Piṅga’) is the name of a teacher, pupil of '''[[शौनकीपुत्र|Śaunakīputra]],''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 30 Mādhyaṃdina).<br>

पैङ्ग्य
<u>'''Paiṅgya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Piṅga,’ is the name of a teacher who is repeatedly mentioned as an authority in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_71/> where<ref name=fx2_ve2_71/> also his doctrine is called the [[पैङ्ग्य|Paiṅgya]]. This teacher is further referred to in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_71/> which also speaks of '''Madhuka''' [[पैङ्ग्य|Paiṅgya]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_71/> It is, of course, impossible to say whether there was only one [[पैङ्ग्य|Paiṅgya]] or several Paiṅgyas. The followers of [[पैङ्ग्य|Paiṅgya]] are called Paiṅgins in the [[निदान|Nidāna]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_71/> and Anupada<ref name=fx6_ve2_71/> Sūtras. His text-book is called Paiṅga in the Anupada [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx7_ve2_71/> while the Āpastamba Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx8_ve2_71/> mentions a Paiṅgāyani [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]. It is clear that [[पैङ्ग्य|Paiṅgya]] was a teacher of a Rigveda school allied to the Kauṣītakis. Paiṅgi is a patronymic of '''[[यास्क|Yāska]]''' in the Anukramanī of the Ātreyī [[शाखा|Śākhā]].<ref name=fx9_ve2_71/> <br>

पैजवन
<u>'''Paijavana,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[पिजवन|Pijavana]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_72/> It seems most probable that [[पिजवन|Pijavana]] intervened in the line of succession between '''Divodāsa''' and [[सुदास्|Sudās]], because the two kings have, according to tradition, quite different Purohitas, the former being served by the '''Bharadvājas''' as his priests, the latter by '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]''' and '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]];'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_72/> this is more natural if they were divided by a period of time than if they had been, as is usually supposed, father and son. Geldner,<ref name=fx3_ve2_72/> however, identifies Divodāsa and [[पिजवन|Pijavana]].<br>

पैद्व
<u>'''Paidva.'''</u> See '''Pedu.'''<br>

पोतृ
<u>'''Potṛ'''</u> is the name of one of the priests ('''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]]''') of the sacrificial ritual. Already known to the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_74/> he is frequently mentioned later in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_74/> But as Oldenberg<ref name=fx3_ve2_74/> observes, the [[पोतृ|Potṛ]] is not in the later literature a priest of any importance, but is practically a mere name. Judging by the derivation of the name from the root ''pū,'' ‘purify,’ it would seem that he was properly engaged in the purification of the ''Soma [[पवमान|pavamāna]],'' ‘Soma purifying itself,’ and was perhaps employed to sing hymns to this Soma. Potra<ref name=fx4_ve2_74/> denotes both the office and the Soma vessel of the [[पोतृ|Potṛ]].<ref name=fx5_ve2_74/><br>

पौंश्चलेय
<u>'''Pauṃścaleya'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 8, 4, 2) denotes the son of a courtesan (Puṃśealī).<br>

पौंसायन
<u>'''Pauṃsāyana'''</u> is the patronymic of '''[[दुष्टरीतु|Duṣṭarītu]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xii. 9, 3, 1). <br>

पौञ्जि-ष्ठ
<u>'''Pauñji-ṣṭha'''</u> is the form in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_77/> the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve2_77/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_77/> of the word '''[[पुञ्जिष्ठ|Puñjiṣṭha]],''' denoting ‘fisherman.’ It is probably a caste name, ‘son of a [[पुञ्जिष्ठ|Puñjiṣṭha]],’ as the designation of a functional caste.<br>

पौण्डरीक
<u>'''Pauṇḍarīka'''</u> is the patronymic of '''Kṣemadhṛtvan''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxii. 18, 7).<br>

पौत-क्रत
<u>'''Pauta-krata,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[पूतक्रता|Pūtakratā]],'''’ is the metronymic of a man, apparently '''[[दस्यवे वृक|Dasyave Vṛka]],''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_79/> Scheftelowitz<ref name=fx2_ve2_79/> proposes to read [[पूतक्रतु|Pūtakratu]] with the Kashmir MS. of the Rigveda, arguing that in the same hymn Pūtakratāyī, the wife of [[पूतक्रतु|Pūtakratu]], is referred to, and that therefore [[पूतक्रतु|Pūtakratu]] is appropriate, Pūtakratāyī<ref name=fx3_ve2_79/> being the feminine, like Manāyī,<ref name=fx4_ve2_79/> for [[मनावी|Manāvī]]. But the ordinary reading in the sense of descendant is perfectly legitimate, as Oldenberg<ref name=fx5_ve2_79/> has pointed out.<br>

पौतिमाषी-पुत्र
<u>'''Pautimāṣī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Pūtimāṣa,’ is the metronymic of a teacher in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 1).<br>

पौति-माष्य
<u>'''Pauti-māṣya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Pūtimāṣa,’ is the patronymic of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[गौपवन|Gaupavana]],''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 6, 1; iv. 6, 1).<br>

पौतिमाष्यायण
<u>'''Pautimāṣyāyaṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[पौतिमाष्य|Pautimāṣya]]'''’ is the patronymic of a teacher, who, with '''[[कौण्डिन्यायन|Kauṇḍinyāyana]],''' taught '''[[रैभ्य|Raibhya]],''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 5, 20; iv. 5, 26). <br>

पौत्र
<u>'''Pautra'''</u> (‘descended from a son’) is the regular term for a ‘grandson’ from the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_83/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve2_83/> When it is used beside '''Naptṛ,'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_83/> the latter word must denote ‘great-grandson.’<br>

पौर
<u>'''Paura,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[पूरु|Pūru]],’ is the name of a man, presumably a [[पूरु|Pūru]] prince helped by Indra, in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_84/> The Greek  the name of Alexander's rival, is probably the representative of this word. Oldenberg<ref name=fx2_ve2_84/> sees the same name in another passage also.<ref name=fx3_ve2_84/><br>

पौरु-कुत्स
<u>'''Pauru-kutsa,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_85/> '''Pauru-kutsi,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_85/> '''Pauru-kutsya,'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_85/> are variant forms of the patronymic of '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]],''' the descendant of '''[[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]].'''<br>

पौरु-शिष्टि
<u>'''Pauru-śiṣṭi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Puruśiṣṭa,’ is the patronymic of '''[[तपोनित्य|Taponitya]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 9, 1 = [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka, vii. 8, 1).<br>

पौर्ण-मासी
<u>'''Paurṇa-māsī,'''</u> denoting the ‘night of the full moon,’ is celebrated in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_87/> as sacred, while it is repeatedly mentioned later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_87/> Gobhila<ref name=fx3_ve2_87/> defines it as the greatest separation (''vikarṣa'') of the sun and the moon. ''Cf.'' '''[[मास|Māsa]].''' <br>

पौलुषि
<u>'''Pauluṣi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Puluṣa,’ is the patronymic of '''[[सत्ययज्ञ|Satyayajña]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 6, 1, 1) and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (v. 11, 1). In the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 39, 1) the form is Pauluṣita, which is perhaps merely an error.<br>

पौल्कस
<u>'''Paulkasa'''</u> is the name of one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_89/> The name also occurs in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_89/> as that of a despised race of men, together with the [[चाण्डाल|Cāṇḍāla]]. The Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_89/> has the variant [[पुक्लक|Puklaka]] or Pulkaka, clearly the same as Pulkasa, of which [[पौल्कस|Paulkasa]] is a derivative form, showing that a caste is meant (''cf.'' '''[[कौलाल|Kaulāla]], [[पौञ्जिष्ठ|Pauñjiṣṭha]]'''). In the accepted theory<ref name=fx4_ve2_89/> the Pulkasa is the son of a [[निषाद|Niṣāda]] or [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] by a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] woman, but this is merely speculative; the [[पौल्कस|Paulkasa]] may either have been a functional caste, or, as Fick<ref name=fx5_ve2_89/> believes, an aboriginal clan living by catching wild beasts, and only occasionally reduced to menial tasks.<br>

पौष्कर-सादि
<u>'''Pauṣkara-sādi'''</u> (‘descendant of Puṣkarasādi’) is the name of a teacher mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx1_ve2_90/> as well as the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Prātiśākhya.<ref name=fx2_ve2_90/> A Puṣkarasādi is mentioned in the [[धर्म|Dharma]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_90/> of Āpastamba and elsewhere.<br>

पौष्पिण्ड्य
<u>'''Pauṣpiṇḍya'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[जैमिनि|Jaimini]],''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the Sāmavidhāna [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_91/><br>

प्युक्ष्ण
<u>'''Pyukṣṇa'''</u> is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 3, 1, 11) denoting the ‘covering’ for a bow ('''[[धनुस्|Dhanus]]'''), presumably made of skin. <br>

प्रौउग
<u>'''Praūga'''</u> is apparently equivalent to ''pra-yuga,'' denoting the fore part of the pole of the cart, the part in front of the yoke. It is mentioned in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_93/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_93/> where it is said to be the part of the pole behind the '''[[कस्तम्भी|Kastambhī]],''' or prop on which the pole rests.<br>

प्र-कङ्कत
<u>'''Pra-kaṅkata'''</u> is the name of some noxious insect in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_94/><br>

प्र-करितृ
<u>'''Pra-karitṛ'''</u> is the name of one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_95/> The exact sense is uncertain; the commentator Sāyaṇa on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] explains it to mean the ‘divider of dear ones by producing enmity,’ but the sense of ‘sprinkler’--that is, ‘seasoner’--is more likely.<br>

प्र-कश
<u>'''Pra-kaśa'''</u> in the Atharvaveda (ix. 1, 21) seems to mean either the ‘thong’ or the ‘lash’ of a whip.<br>

प्र-क्रम
<u>'''Pra-krama,'''</u> ‘stride,’ is mentioned as a measure of distance in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 2, 3, 1 ''et seq.''), but its exact length in unknown.<br>

प्रक्ष
<u>'''Prakṣa'''</u> is the form in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_98/> of the usual name, '''[[प्लक्ष|Plakṣa]],''' of a tree, being merely a phonetic alteration for the sake of the etymology. According to Aufrecht,<ref name=fx2_ve2_98/> the same word is found in two passages of the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_98/> the same reading occurring in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx4_ve2_98/> Oldenberg,<ref name=fx5_ve2_98/> however, questions the correctness of the reading [[प्रक्ष|Prakṣa]], both in the latter passage and in the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]]. <br>

प्रगाथ
<u>'''Pragātha'''</u> is the name given in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka (ii. 2, 2) to the poets of the eighth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda, so called because they composed [[प्रगाथ|Pragātha]] strophes (that is, verses consisting of a Bṛhatī or Kakubh followed by a Satobṛhatī).<br>

प्र-घात
<u>'''Pra-ghāta'''</u> is found in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_100/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_100/> in the sense of the closely woven ends of a cloth from which depend the loose threads of the '''[[नीवि|Nīvi]],''' or unwoven fringe.<br>

प्र-चलाका
<u>'''Pra-calākā'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vii. 5, 11, 1) and the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā ([[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]], v. 2) seems to mean a ‘cloudburst.’<br>

प्रजावन्त् प्राजापत्य
<u>'''Prajāvant Prājāpatya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Prajāpati,’ is, according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 21), the author of a hymn of the Rigveda (x. 183).<br>

प्र-णपात्
<u>'''Pra-ṇapāt'''</u> in the Rigveda (viii. 17, 13) denotes ‘greatgrandson.’<br>

प्र-णेजन
<u>'''Pra-ṇejana'''</u> is the word used in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 2, 2, 18) to denote the ‘water used for washing.’<br>

प्र-ततामह
<u>'''Pra-tatāmaha,'''</u> ‘great-grandfather,’ is found in the Atharvaveda (xviii. 4, 75).<br>

प्र-तर्दन
<u>'''Pra-tardana'''</u> is the name in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_106/> of a king who had a '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]]''' for his [[पुरोहित|Purohita]]. In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_106/> he appears as arriving at the sacrifice of the [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]] in the Naimiṣa forest, and asking them how errors in the sacrifice could be remedied; and as finding '''Alīkayu Vācaspata,''' the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] priest at the sacrifice, unable to say what was to be  done. In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_106/> it is said that [[प्रतर्दन|Pratardana]] [[दैवोदासि|Daivodāsi]] went to Indra's world through his death in battle. The patronymic connects him with '''Divodāsa,''' the ancestor or father of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' and the mention of [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]] (probably ‘a Bharadvāja’ is meant) as his priest supports the patronymic, for Divodāsa is a special favourite of the singers of the [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]] family. The name, moreover, is reminiscent of the Tṛtsus (the root ''tard'' appears in both) and of the ''Pratṛdaḥ'' (see '''[[प्रतृद्|Pratṛd]]'''). But he is not in Vedic literature a king of [[काशि|Kāśi]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_106/> Geldner<ref name=fx5_ve2_106/> regards him as Divodāsa's son, but this is not likely. ''Cf.'' '''[[प्रातर्दनि|Prātardani]].'''<br>

प्र-तिथि देव-तरथ
<u>'''Pra-[[तिथि|tithi]] Deva-taratha'''</u> is the name of a teacher, pupil of '''Devataras Śāvasāyana''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_107/><br>

प्रति-दीवन्
<u>'''Prati-dīvan'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda (x. 38, 6) and the Atharvaveda (vii. 109, 4) ‘opponent in the game of dice.’<br>

प्रति-दुह्
<u>'''Prati-duh'''</u> has the specific sense of ‘fresh milk,’ warm from the cow, in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_109/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_109/><br>

प्रति-धा
<u>'''Prati-dhā'''</u> apparently means ‘draught’ or ‘pull’ in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_110/> where Indra is said to have drunk thirty streams (''sarāṃsi'') with one [[प्रतिधा|Pratidhā]].<br>

प्रति-धि
<u>'''Prati-dhi'''</u> is mentioned in the Sūryā hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_111/> as part of the chariot on which the bride is taken home. It is  impossible to determine with certainty exactly what is meant; Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_111/> understands it to mean a cross-piece of wood fastened to the pole.<br>

प्रति-पण
<u>'''Prati-paṇa'''</u> is found in the Atharvaveda (iii. 15, 4) denoting ‘barter’ or ‘exchange.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[पण|Paṇa]].'''<br>

प्रति-प्रश्न
<u>'''Prati-praśna'''</u> occurs in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_113/> applied to Prajāpati as the decider of doubts; it may have been a technical term for an ‘arbitrator’ (''cf.'' '''[[मध्यमशी|Madhyamaśī]]''' and '''harma''').<br>

प्रति-प्र-स्थातृ
<u>'''Prati-pra-sthātṛ'''</u> is the name of a priest ('''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]]'''), one of the assistants of the [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]], in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_114/> He is not mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_114/> but mention is once made in that Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_114/> of the two Adhvaryus. These may have meant, as later, the [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]] and the [[प्रतिप्रस्थातृ|Pratiprasthātṛ]]. Oldenberg,<ref name=fx4_ve2_114/> however, thinks that the [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]] and the Agnīdh are intended, a conjecture for which there is some authority.<ref name=fx5_ve2_114/><br>

प्रति-प्राश्
<u>'''Prati-prāś.'''</u> See '''[[प्राश्|Prāś]].'''<br>

प्रतिबोधी-पुत्र
<u>'''Pratibodhī-putra'''</u> is a wrong reading for '''Prātībodhī-[[पुत्र|putra]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_116/><br>

प्रति-मित्
<u>'''Prati-mit'''</u> is found in the description of a house in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_117/> The sense must be ‘support’ of some sort, probably beams leaning up at an angle against the '''Upamits.''' <br>

प्रति-वेश
<u>'''Prati-veśa,'''</u> ‘neighbour,’ occurs, often metaphorically, from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_118/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve2_118/><br>

प्रति-वेश्य
<u>'''Prati-veśya'''</u> is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (xv. 1) as the pupil of '''[[बृहद्दिव|Bṛhaddiva]].''' ''Cf.'' '''[[प्रातिवेश्य|Prātiveśya]].'''<br>

प्रति-श्रुत्का
<u>'''Prati-śrutkā,'''</u> ‘echo,’ shows that this phenomenon had already received a name as early as the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_120/> and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 13).<br>

प्रति-ष्ठा
<u>'''Prati-ṣṭhā'''</u> is found in one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_121/> where Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_121/> thinks the word is used as a technical term of law; possibly a ‘sanctuary’ may be meant, but it is more than doubtful whether the sense of ‘home’ or ‘abode,’ as given by Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve2_121/> is not quite adequate. ''Cf.'' '''[[ज्ञातृ|Jñātṛ]].'''<br>

प्रति-सर
<u>'''Prati-sara'''</u> is used in several passages of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_122/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_122/> to denote an amulet, according to Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve2_122/> because it was a band, and so returned on itself (''prati-sṛ,'' ‘go back’). The sense is doubtful; perhaps ‘attacking’ may really be the root idea.<ref name=fx4_ve2_122/> ''Cf.'' '''[[पुनःसर|Punaḥsara]].''' <br>

प्रति-हर्तृ
<u>'''Prati-hartṛ'''</u> is the name of the assistant of the Udgātṛ in the list of the sixteen priests ('''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]]'''). It is found in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_123/> and the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve2_123/> but not in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_123/><br>

प्रती-दर्श श्वैक्न
<u>'''Pratī-[[दर्श|darśa]] Śvaikna'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_124/> as sacrificing with the [[दाक्षायण|Dākṣāyaṇa]] offering, and as teaching '''[[सुप्लन् सार्ञ्जय|Suplan Sārñjaya]],''' who thence became '''[[सहदेव|Sahadeva]] [[सार्ञ्जय|Sārñjaya]].''' In a second passage<ref name=fx2_ve2_124/> he is called Pratīdarśa [[ऐभावत|Aibhāvata]], and again brought into connexion with [[सुप्लन् सार्ञ्जय|Suplan Sārñjaya]]. According to Eggeling,<ref name=fx3_ve2_124/> he is to be deemed a king of the Śviknas; apparently, too, he was a descendant of Ibhāvant. A Pratīdarśa is also mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_124/><br>

प्रतीप प्रातिसत्वन
<u>'''Pratīpa Prātisatvana,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_125/> or '''[[प्रातिसुत्वन|Prātisutvana]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_125/> is the name of a man mentioned in a hymn of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_125/> Zimmer,<ref name=fx3_ve2_125/> with great ingenuity, compares the fact that '''[[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]]''' is mentioned as a '''Kuru''' king in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx4_ve2_125/> and that, according to the Epic genealogies, his grandson was Pratiśravas, with which name [[प्रातिसुत्वन|Prātisutvana]], as very possibly a Prākritized version of Prātiśrutvana may be compared, and his great-grandson was Pratīpa. The identification cannot, however, be regarded as at all certain, and while the Epic may have derived its genealogy from the Atharvaveda, it may have preserved an independent tradition. Bo7htlingk<ref name=fx5_ve2_125/> renders ''prātisatvanam'' as ‘in the direction opposed to the Satvans’, and this may be right. <br>

प्रती-बोध
<u>'''Pratī-bodha'''</u> is mentioned with '''[[बोध|Bodha]]''' in two passages of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_126/> apparently as the name of a very mythic [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], ‘Intelligence.’<br>

प्रतृद्
<u>'''Pratṛd'''</u> occurs once in the plural in a hymn of the [[ऋग्वेद|Ṛgveda]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_127/> where it is clearly a variant of the word '''[[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]].''' Moreover, the name of King '''[[प्रतर्दन|Pratardana]],''' a descendant of the [[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]] king, '''Divodāsa,''' confirms the identification of [[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]] and [[प्रतृद्|Pratṛd]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_127/><br>

प्र-तोद
<u>'''Pra-toda'''</u> denotes in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_128/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_128/> the ‘goad’ of the '''[[व्रात्य|Vrātya]],''' the non-Brahminical Āryan or aborigine. Later the word is regularly used for ‘goad’ in general.<br>

प्रत्यक्ष-दर्शन
<u>'''Pratyakṣa-darśana,'''</u> n., means ‘seeing with one's own eyes,’ as opposed to seeing in a vision (''[[स्वप्न|svapna]]''). A section on such visions appears in the Rigveda Āraṇyakas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_129/><br>

प्रत्य्-एनस्
<u>'''Praty-enas'''</u> is found with '''Ugra''' and '''[[सूत|Sūta]]-grāmaṇī''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_130/> clearly denoting an officer of police. The sense must be that of the humbler ‘servants’ of the king<ref name=fx2_ve2_130/> rather than ‘magistrates,’ as Max Müller, in his translation, takes it. In the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_130/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_130/> the word means, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, the next heir, who is responsible for the debts of a dead man. <br>

प्र-दर
<u>'''Pra-dara'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_131/> denotes a ‘cleft’ in the ground.<br><br>^1 [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā, iii. 4, 8, 5; v. 2, 4, 3; Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā, xxv. 7.<br>

प्र-दिव्
<u>'''Pra-div'''</u> in the Atharvaveda (xviii. 2, 48) is the third and highest heaven, in which the Fathers dwell. In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xx. 1) it is the fifth of a series of seven heavens.<br>

प्र-दिश्
<u>'''Pra-diś,'''</u> like '''[[दिश्|Diś]],''' normally designates only a ‘quarter’ of the sky, or ‘point’ of the compass. Four,<ref name=fx1_ve2_133/> five,<ref name=fx2_ve2_133/> six,<ref name=fx3_ve2_133/> and seven<ref name=fx4_ve2_133/> such points are enumerated, or more generally ‘all’ are mentioned.<ref name=fx5_ve2_133/> In some passages,<ref name=fx6_ve2_133/> on the other hand, the word has the definite sense of an ‘intermediate quarter,’ which is more precisely denoted by ''avāntara-[[दिश्|diś]].''<br>

प्र-धन
<u>'''Pra-dhana'''</u> denotes ‘contest,’ whether the real conflict of war or the competition of the chariot race, in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_134/><br>

प्र-धि
<u>'''Pra-dhi'''</u> is the name of some part of the wheel of a chariot, probably the ‘felly.’ In one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_135/> and in one of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_135/> the ‘nave’ ('''[[नभ्य|Nabhya]]''') and the ‘felly’ (''[[प्रधि|pradhi]]'') are mentioned along with the '''[[उपधि|Upadhi]],''' which must then be either a collective name for the spokes or an inner rim within the felly and binding the spokes. In the riddle hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_135/> twelve Pradhis are mentioned with three naves, one wheel, and three hundred and sixty spokes; what exactly is here meant by this particular term it would be useless to conjecture, though it is clear that the passage as a whole symbolizes  the year with three seasons, twelve months, and three hundred and sixty days. Elsewhere<ref name=fx4_ve2_135/> the nave and the [[प्रधि|Pradhi]] alone are mentioned, or the [[प्रधि|Pradhi]] occurs by itself.<ref name=fx5_ve2_135/><br>

प्र-ध्वंसन
<u>'''Pra-dhvaṃsana.'''</u> See '''[[प्राध्वंसन|Prādhvaṃsana]]'''<br>

प्र-पण
<u>'''Pra-paṇa'''</u> in the Atharvaveda (xii. 15, 4. 5) denotes ‘barter’ or ‘exchange,’ balanced by '''[[प्रतिपण|Pratipaṇa]].'''<br>

प्र-पथ
<u>'''Pra-patha'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_138/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_138/> denotes a ‘long journey.’ Wilson<ref name=fx3_ve2_138/> has seen in one passage<ref name=fx4_ve2_138/> the sense of ‘resting-place,’ where travellers can obtain food (''[[खादि|khādi]]''). Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve2_138/> shows that this is impossible, and the reading (''prapatheṣu'') in the passage in question is not improbably<ref name=fx6_ve2_138/> an error for ''prapadeṣu.'' In the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx7_ve2_138/> the word means a ‘broad road.’<br>

प्र-पथिन्
<u>'''Pra-pathin'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_139/> is the name of a patron, perhaps a Yādava, in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_139/> <br>

प्र-पा
<u>'''Pra-pā'''</u> seems to denote a ‘spring’ in the desert in the only Rigveda passage where it occurs.<ref name=fx1_ve2_140/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_140/> it has merely the sense of ‘drinking,’ or a ‘drink.’<br>

प्र-पितामह
<u>'''Pra-pitāmaha,'''</u> ‘great-grandfather,’ is found in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_141/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_141/><br>

प्र-पित्व
<u>'''Pra-pitva'''</u> is found in several passages of the Rigveda as a designation of time. In one passage<ref name=fx1_ve2_142/> the sense is made clear by the context: ‘at the rising of the sun’ (''sūra udite''), ‘at midday’ (''madhyaṃdine divaḥ''), and ‘at the [[प्रपित्व|Prapitva]], bordering on the night’ (''apiśarvare''). In another passage<ref name=fx2_ve2_142/> the sense of ‘late in the day’ also seems adequate, while the phrase<ref name=fx3_ve2_142/> ''abhipitve ahnaḥ,'' ‘at the close of day,’ also denotes the evening. According to Geldner,<ref name=fx4_ve2_142/> the sense of the word is the ‘decisive moment’ in a race or a battle, and so the ‘end of the day.’<ref name=fx5_ve2_142/> ''Cf.'' '''Ahan.'''<br>

प्र-प्रोथ
<u>'''Pra-protha'''</u> is the name in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 4, 1) of a plant used as a substitute for Soma.<br>

प्र-फर्वी
<u>'''Pra-pharvī'''</u> denotes a ‘wanton woman’ in the Rigveda (x. 85, 22), the Atharvaveda (v. 22, 7), and the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_144/><br>

प्र-बुध्
<u>'''Pra-budh,'''</u> occurring in one passage of the Rigveda (viii. 27, 19), is used in the locative parallel with ''nimruci,'' ‘at the setting (of the sun),’ and clearly means ‘at the rising (of the sun).’ <br>

प्र-मगन्द
<u>'''Pra-maganda'''</u> is the name of a prince in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_146/> where he is mentioned as the king of the '''Kīkaṭas,''' and where he seems to be designated by the epithet ''[[नैचाशाख|naicāśākha]],'' ‘belonging to a low branch or race.’ On the other hand, [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_146/> takes [[प्रमगन्द|Pramaganda]] to mean the ‘son of a usurer,’ an explanation that is hardly probable. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx3_ve2_146/> thinks that ''[[नैचाशाख|naicāśākha]]'' refers not to [[प्रमगन्द|Pramaganda]], but to the Soma plant, the plant being called ''nīcāśākha,'' ‘having shoots turned downwards,’ and that the passage refers to a raid against the Kīkaṭas, who were not observers of the milk cult or the Soma cult, with the intention of winning their lands where the Soma grew and where there were cows. Bo7htlingk,<ref name=fx4_ve2_146/> however, questions this view, which is not very probable. A place name is possibly meant by [[नैचाशाख|Naicāśākha]].<ref name=fx5_ve2_146/> The name [[प्रमगन्द|Pramaganda]] seems un-Āryan.<br>

प्र-मन्दनी
<u>'''Pra-mandanī'''</u> is the name of an Apsaras in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_147/> Probably the word primarily denoted a certain sweet-scented plant, which seems to be the sense of ''pra-manda'' in the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_147/><br>

प्र-मर
<u>'''Pra-mara'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_148/> is taken by Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_148/> to be a proper name.<br>

प्र-मोत
<u>'''Pra-mota'''</u> is the name of some sort of disease in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_149/> according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary. Zimmer,<ref name=fx2_ve2_149/> however, thinks that the word must be an adjective meaning ‘dumb.’ This view is accepted, though with doubt, by Whitney<ref name=fx3_ve2_149/> and by Bloomfield.<ref name=fx4_ve2_149/> <br>

प्र-योग
<u>'''Pra-yoga'''</u> is the name of a seer in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_150/><br>

प्र-योग्य
<u>'''Pra-yogya'''</u> denotes in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (viii. 12, 3) an animal yoked to a carriage, ‘draught animal.’<br>

प्र-लाप
<u>'''Pra-lāpa,'''</u> ‘prattle,’ is found with other words of similar import in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_152/> and in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_152/> of the Rigveda. The phrase '''[[ऐतश|Aitaśa]]-[[प्रलाप|pralāpa]],''' ‘Discourse of [[ऐतश|Aitaśa]],’ occurs as a designation of certain passages of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_152/> The name has no justification in the text itself.<br>

प्र-वचन
<u>'''Pra-vacana'''</u> means ‘oral instruction,’ ‘teaching,’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_153/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_153/><br>

प्र-वत्
<u>'''Pra-vat,'''</u> ‘height,’ is contrasted with '''[[निवत्|Nivat]],''' ‘valley,’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_154/> where it occurs several times.<ref name=fx2_ve2_154/> The word is also found later.<ref name=fx3_ve2_154/><br>

प्र-वर
<u>'''1. Pra-vara'''</u> denotes properly the ‘summons’ addressed to Agni at the beginning of the sacrifice to perform his functions. But as Agni was then invoked by the names of the ancestors of the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_155/> the term [[प्रवर|Pravara]] denotes the series of ancestors invoked.<ref name=fx2_ve2_155/> <br>

प्र-वर
<u>'''2. Pra-vara,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_156/> or '''[[प्र-वार|Pra-vāra]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_156/> denotes a ‘covering’ or ‘woollen cloth’ in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<br>

प्र-वर्त
<u>'''Pra-varta,'''</u> occurring in the description of the '''[[व्रात्य|Vrātya]]''' in the Atharvaveda (xv. 2, 1, ''et seq.''), is explained by the St. Petersburg Dictionary as a ‘round ornament.’ According to the commentator on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (2, 453 ''Bibl. Ind.''), it means an ‘ear-ring.’<br>

प्र-वल्हिका
<u>'''Pra-valhikā,'''</u> a ‘riddle,’ is the name given in the Brāhmaṇas of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_158/> to certain verses of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_158/><br>

प्र-वात
<u>'''Pra-vāta,'''</u> ‘a windy spot,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_159/> as the place where the '''[[विभीतक|Vibhītaka]]''' nuts, used as dice ('''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]]''') grow. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_159/> reference is made to the exposure of decaying matter in such a place.<br>

प्र-वार
<u>'''Pra-vāra.'''</u> See 2. '''[[प्रवर|Pravara]].'''<br>

प्र-वा¤स
<u>'''Pra-vā¤sa,'''</u> ‘dwelling abroad,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_161/> Ceremonies applicable to one who has returned from foreign residence are given in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve2_161/><br>

प्र-वाहण जैवलि
<u>'''Pra-vāhaṇa Jaivali'''</u> or '''[[जैवल|Jaivala]]''' (‘descendant of '''Jīvala'''’) is the name of a prince, contemporary with '''Uddālaka,''' who  appears in the Upaniṣads<ref name=fx1_ve2_162/> as engaged in philosophical discussions. He is probably identical with the Jaivali of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_162/><br>

प्र-शस्
<u>'''Pra-śas'''</u> in a [[मन्त्र|Mantra]] in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_163/> denotes, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, an ‘axe,’ or some similar instrument for cutting.<ref name=fx2_ve2_163/><br>

प्र-शास्तृ
<u>'''Pra-śāstṛ'''</u> is the name of one of the priests ('''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]]''') at the Vedic sacrifice. In the lesser sacrifices he plays no part at all, but he appears in the animal (''[[पशु|paśu]]'') and Soma sacrifices, in the former as the only, in the latter as the main, assistant of the '''[[होतृ|Hotṛ]]''' priest in the singing of the litanies. He is mentioned by name in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_164/> and often later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_164/> He is also in the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_164/> called '''Upavaktṛ,''' this name, like [[प्रशास्तृ|Praśāstṛ]], being derived from the fact that one of his chief functions was to issue directions (''[[प्रैष|praiṣa]]'') to the other priests. Another name for him was Maitrāvaruṇa, because his litanies were mainly addressed to [[मित्र|Mitra]] and Varuṇa, a connexion already visible in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx4_ve2_164/> The ‘two divine Hotṛs’ of the Āprī litanies denote, according to Oldenberg,<ref name=fx5_ve2_164/> the heavenly counterparts of the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] and the [[प्रशास्तृ|Praśāstṛ]].<br>

प्रश्न
<u>'''Praśna'''</u> denotes generally ‘enquiry’ or ‘disputed question,’ the phrase ''praśnam eti'' having the sense ‘he asks a person for  the decision of a disputed point’ in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_165/> and elsewhere.<ref name=fx2_ve2_165/> Thus [[प्रश्न|Praśna]] comes to have the definite meaning of ‘decision in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_165/> In the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_165/> are included the Praśnin, the [[अभि-प्रश्निन्|Abhi-praśnin]], and the [[प्रश्न|Praśna]]-vivāka; it is quite likely that here the three parties to a civil case are meant--the plaintiff, the defendant, and the arbitrator or judge ('''[[मध्यमशी|Madhyamaśī]]''').<br>

प्रष्टि
<u>'''Praṣṭi,'''</u> like '''[[पृष्ट्या|Pṛṣṭyā]],''' denotes a ‘side horse,’ which, however, possibly<ref name=fx1_ve2_166/> did not necessarily mean a horse running beside the yoke-horses, but may also have meant a third horse yoked in front as a leader. This seems to be indicated by the reference in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_166/> to the [[प्रष्टि|Praṣṭi]]--here applied to the Maruts’ team--leading (''vahati'') the team (''rohitaḥ''). In an obscure passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_166/> there is a reference to the Praṣṭis in connexion with a ''pañca-vāhī,'' ‘drawn by five,’ but it is impossible to gain any clear idea of what is meant. The [[प्रष्टि|Praṣṭi]] is not rarely referred to elsewhere.<ref name=fx4_ve2_166/> In one passage<ref name=fx5_ve2_166/> the ''dhuryau'' and the ''praṣṭyau'' are mentioned together; this probably means the two horses yoked to the pole, with two others fastened in some way one on each side. The adjectives ''praṣṭimant,''<ref name=fx6_ve2_166/> ''[[प्रष्टि|praṣṭi]]-[[वाहन|vāhana]],''<ref name=fx7_ve2_166/> ''[[प्रष्टि|praṣṭi]]-vāhin,''<ref name=fx8_ve2_166/> are all used of '''[[रथ|Ratha]],''' ‘chariot,’ meaning ‘drawn by a side horse (or horses)’ in addition to the yoke-horses. ''Cf.'' '''[[रथ|Ratha]].''' <br>

प्र-सिति
<u>'''Pra-siti'''</u> in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (ii. 19) and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 7, 13, 4) denotes a divine ‘missile,’ but does not seem to be used of human combatants.<br>

प्र-सू
<u>'''Pra-sū'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_168/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_168/> denotes the young shoots of grass or herbs used at the sacrifice.<br>

प्र-सृत
<u>'''Pra-sṛta'''</u> is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_169/> as a measure of capacity, meaning a ‘handful.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_169/><br>

प्र-स्कण्व
<u>'''Pra-skaṇva'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] who is credited by the Anukramaṇī (Index) with the authorship of certain hymns of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_170/> where<ref name=fx2_ve2_170/> he is mentioned several times. The statement in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_170/> that he obtained bounty from '''[[पृषध्र|Pṛṣadhra]] [[मेध्य|Medhya]] [[मातरिश्वन्|Mātariśvan]]''' is apparently a blunder.<ref name=fx4_ve2_170/><br>

प्र-स्तर
<u>'''Pra-stara'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_171/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_171/> denotes the grass strewn as a sacrificial seat.<br>

प्र-स्तोक
<u>'''Pra-stoka'''</u> is the name of a generous donor in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_172/> where Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_172/> identifies him with '''[[दिवोदास अतिथिग्व|Divodāsa Atithigva]]''' and  '''[[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]]''' or Aśvatha. According to the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_172/> '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]]''' obtained gifts from [[प्रस्तोक|Prastoka]] '''[[सार्ञ्जय|Sārñjaya]],''' ‘descendant of [[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]].’<br>

प्र-स्तोतृ
<u>'''Pra-stotṛ'''</u> is the name of an assistant of the Udgātṛ priest who sings the Prastāva,<ref name=fx1_ve2_173/> or prelude of the Sāman chant. His not being mentioned by name in the Rigveda is merely an accident, for he is clearly referred to in one passage,<ref name=fx2_ve2_173/> and in the later literature<ref name=fx3_ve2_173/> he is a frequent figure. Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve2_173/> erroneously thinks that '''[[प्रशास्तृ|Praśāstṛ]]''' is the earlier name of the [[प्रस्तोतृ|Prastotṛ]].<br>

प्रस्रवण
<u>'''Prasravaṇa.'''</u> See '''[[प्लक्ष|Plakṣa]].'''<br>

प्र-हा
<u>'''Pra-hā'''</u> in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_175/> the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_175/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_175/> denotes a ‘winning throw’ at dice, or, generally, any ‘gain’ or ‘advantage.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_175/><br>

प्रा-कार
<u>'''Prā-kāra'''</u> in the Śaṅkhāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xvi. 18, 14) denotes a walled mound supporting a raised platform (''[[प्रासाद|prāsāda]]'') for spectators.<br>

प्रा-काश
<u>'''Prā-kāśa'''</u> is found several times in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_177/> denoting an ornament of metal or a metal mirror. According to Geldner,<ref name=fx2_ve2_177/> [[प्रावेप|Prāvepa]] has the same sense in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx3_ve2_177/> <br>

प्रा-गहि
<u>'''Prā-gahi'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxvi. 4) according to Lindner's edition. ''Cf.'' '''[[प्रावहि|Prāvahi]].'''<br>

प्राचीन-तान
<u>'''Prācīna-tāna'''</u> denotes the ‘warp’ of a piece of cloth in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vi. 1, 1, 4). ''Cf.'' '''[[प्राचीनातान|Prācīnātāna]].'''<br>

प्राचीन-योगी-पुत्र
<u>'''Prācīna-yogī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Prācīnayoga,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[सांजीवीपुत्र|Sāṃjīvīputra]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 32).<br>

प्राचीन-योग्य
<u>'''Prācīna-yogya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Prācīnayoga,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[पाराशर्य|Pārāśarya]],''' in the first [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_181/> A [[प्राचीनयोग्य|Prācīnayogya]] is mentioned also in the Chāndogya<ref name=fx2_ve2_181/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_181/> Upaniṣads, and the same patronymic is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_181/> and in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (see '''Puluṣa, [[सत्ययज्ञ|Satyayajña]],'''<ref name=fx5_ve2_181/> '''Somaśuṣma''').<br>

प्राचीन-वंश
<u>'''Prācīna-vaṃśa'''</u> as an adjective denotes ‘having the supporting beam of the roof facing the east’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_182/> and the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve2_182/> The reference is to the central beam running from the middle of the western end of a hall to the middle of the eastern end. This beam was possibly higher than those at the side.<br>

प्राचीन-शाल औपमन्यव
<u>'''Prācīna-śāla Aupamanyava'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[उपमन्यु|Upamanyu]]'''’) is the name of a householder and theologian in the Chāndogya  [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_183/> A Prācīnaśāli appears as an Udgātṛ priest in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_183/> and the Prācīnaśālas are mentioned in the same [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_183/><br>

प्राचीनातान
<u>'''Prācīnātāna,'''</u> denoting the ‘warp’ of a piece of cloth, is found in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_184/> ''Cf.'' '''[[प्राचीनतान|Prācīnatāna]].'''<br>

प्राचीनावीत
<u>'''Prācīnāvīta'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_185/> denotes the wearing of the sacred thread of the Āryan over the right shoulder and under the left arm, Prācīnāvītin<ref name=fx2_ve2_185/> being the name for the man so wearing the thread. Tilak,<ref name=fx3_ve2_185/> however, thinks that these terms do not imply the wearing of a thread, but of a garment.<br>

प्राच्य
<u>'''Prācya'''</u> denotes in the plural ‘dwellers in the east.’ They are mentioned in the list of peoples in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_186/> It is very probable that the '''Kāśis, Kosalas, Videhas,''' and perhaps '''Magadhas,''' are meant, as Oldenberg<ref name=fx2_ve2_186/> supposes. In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_186/> the Easterns are said to call Agni by the name of Śarva, and their mode of making tombs is there<ref name=fx4_ve2_186/> referred to with disapproval. The Lāṭyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_186/> explains the '''[[विपथ|Vipatha]],''' ‘rough car,’ of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_186/> as a car of the Easterns (''[[प्राच्य|prācya]]-[[रथ|ratha]]''). In the Saṃhitopaniṣad [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve2_186/> reference is made to the PrācyaPāñcālas. <br>

प्रजापत्य
<u>'''Prajāpatya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Prajāpati,’ is only a patronymic of mythical persons like [[आरुणि|Āruṇi]] Suparṇeya (‘descendant of Suparṇā’) in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (x. 79), or of '''Prajāvant''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 21).<br>

प्राण
<u>'''Prāṇa,'''</u> properly denoting ‘breath,’ is a term of wide and vague significance in Vedic literature. It is frequently mentioned from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_188/> onwards; in the Āraṇyakas and Upaniṣads it is one of the commonest symbols of the unity of the universe.<ref name=fx2_ve2_188/> In the narrow sense [[प्राण|Prāṇa]] denotes one of the vital airs, of which five are usually<ref name=fx3_ve2_188/> enumerated--[[प्राण|Prāṇa]], '''[[अपान|Apāna]], [[व्य्आन|Vyāna]], [[उदान|Udāna]],''' and '''[[समान|Samāna]];''' but often only two, [[प्राण|Prāṇa]] and [[अपान|Apāna]],<ref name=fx4_ve2_188/> or [[प्राण|Prāṇa]] and [[व्य्आन|Vyāna]],<ref name=fx5_ve2_188/> or [[प्राण|Prāṇa]] and [[उदान|Udāna]];<ref name=fx6_ve2_188/> or three, [[प्राण|Prāṇa]], [[अपान|Apāna]], and [[व्य्आन|Vyāna]],<ref name=fx7_ve2_188/> or [[प्राण|Prāṇa]], [[उदान|Udāna]], and [[व्य्आन|Vyāna]],<ref name=fx8_ve2_188/> or [[प्राण|Prāṇa]], [[उदान|Udāna]], and [[समान|Samāna]];<ref name=fx9_ve2_188/> or four, [[प्राण|Prāṇa]], [[अपान|Apāna]], [[व्य्आन|Vyāna]], and [[समान|Samāna]],<ref name=fx10_ve2_188/> or [[प्राण|Prāṇa]], [[अपान|Apāna]], [[उदान|Udāna]], [[व्य्आन|Vyāna]].<ref name=fx11_ve2_188/> The exact sense of each of these breaths when all are mentioned cannot be determined.<ref name=fx12_ve2_188/><br>

प्राण
<u>'''Prāṇa'''</u> is also used in a wider sense to denote the organs of sense,<ref name=fx13_ve2_189/> or as Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx14_ve2_189/> puts it, the ‘orifices of the head,’ etc. These are given as six in one passage of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx15_ve2_189/> presumably the eyes, ears, and nostrils. More frequently there are stated to be seven in the head, the mouth being then included.<ref name=fx16_ve2_189/> Sometimes again they are mentioned  as nine,<ref name=fx17_ve2_189/> or as seven in the head and two below.<ref name=fx18_ve2_189/> Ten are counted in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx19_ve2_189/> and the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx20_ve2_189/> while even eleven are mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx21_ve2_189/> and twelve in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx22_ve2_189/> where the two breasts are added. Exactly what organs are taken to make up the numbers beyond seven is not certain.<ref name=fx23_ve2_189/> The tenth is the navel (''[[नाभि|nābhi]]'') in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā;<ref name=fx24_ve2_189/> when eleven are named the Brahma-[[रन्ध्र|randhra]]<ref name=fx25_ve2_189/> (suture in the crown) may be included; in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx26_ve2_189/> as interpreted by the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx27_ve2_189/> the seventh and eighth are the organs of taste and speech respectively. But usually these make one only, and the eighth and ninth are either in the breast<ref name=fx28_ve2_189/> or below (the organs of evacuation).<ref name=fx29_ve2_189/><br><br>The word [[प्राण|Prāṇa]] has sometimes merely the general sense of breath, even when opposed to [[अपान|Apāna]].<ref name=fx30_ve2_189/> But its proper sense is beyond question ‘breathing forth,’ ‘expiration,’ and not as the St. Petersburg Dictionary explains it, ‘the breath inspired,’ a version due to the desire to interpret [[अपान|Apāna]] as ‘expiration,’ a meaning suggested by the preposition ''apa,'' ‘away.’ This being clearly shown both by the native scholiasts<ref name=fx31_ve2_189/> and by other evidence,<ref name=fx32_ve2_189/> Bo7htlingk<ref name=fx33_ve2_189/> later accepted the new view. <br>

प्राण-भृत्
<u>'''Prāṇa-bhṛt'''</u> denotes a ‘living being’ or ‘man’ in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_190/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_190/> Prānin has the same sense.<ref name=fx3_ve2_190/><br>

प्रातर्
<u>'''Prātar'''</u> as a denotation of time signifies the ‘early morning’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_191/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_191/> ''Cf.'' '''Ahan.'''<br>

प्रातर्-अनुवाक
<u>'''Prātar-anuvāka'''</u> occurs in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_192/> as the name of the litany which begins the morning Soma libation.<br>

प्रातर्-अह्न कौहल
<u>'''Prātar-ahna Kauhala'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[केतु वाज्य|Ketu Vājya]],''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_193/> ''Cf.'' '''[[कौहड|Kauhaḍa]].'''<br>

प्रा-तर्दनि
<u>'''Prā-tardani,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[प्रतर्दन|Pratardana]],'''’ is the name of a prince in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_194/><br>

प्राति-पीय
<u>'''Prāti-pīya'''</u> is the patronymic of '''[[बल्हिक|Balhika]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xii. 9, 3, 3).<br>

प्राति-वेश्य
<u>'''Prāti-veśya'''</u> is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (xv. 1) as a pupil of '''[[प्रतिवेश्य|Prativeśya]].'''<br>

प्राति-सुत्वन
<u>'''Prāti-sutvana.'''</u> See '''Pratīpa.'''<br>

प्रति-बोधी-पुत्र
<u>'''Prati-bodhī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Pratī-  [[बोध|bodha]],’ is the name of a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] (iii. 1, 5) and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] (vii. 13) Āraṇyakas.<br><br>''Cf.'' Keith, ''[[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka,'' 244, 310.<br>

प्रा-तृद
<u>'''Prā-tṛda,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[प्रतृद्|Pratṛd]],'''’ is the patronymic of a teacher called '''[[भाल्ल|Bhālla]]''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 31, 4), and of another teacher in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (v. 13, 2).<br>

प्रा-देश
<u>'''Prā-deśa'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_200/> frequently occurs in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_200/> as a measure of length, a ‘span.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_200/><br>

प्रा-ध्वंसन
<u>'''Prā-dhvaṃsana,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[प्रध्वंसन|Pradhvaṃsana]],’ is the patronymic, in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_201/> of the mythical '''[[मृत्यु|Mṛtyu]],''' who is there said to be the pupil of [[प्रध्वंसन|Pradhvaṃsana]].<br>

प्रायश्-चित्त
<u>'''Prāyaś-citta'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_202/> or '''Prāyaś-citti'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_202/> denotes a ‘penance’ or ‘expiation,’ both words occurring frequently in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas. The penances are prescribed for every conceivable sort of ritual, social or moral; a complete list of them is included in the Sāmavidhāna [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_202/><br>

प्रा-वरेय
<u>'''Prā-vareya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[प्रवर|Pravara]],’ is the patronymic of the '''Gargas''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_203/><br>

प्रा-वहि
<u>'''Prā-vahi'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxvi. 4), where, however, Lindner's edition has '''[[प्रागहि|Prāgahi]].''' <br>

प्रा-वाहणि
<u>'''Prā-vāhaṇi,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Pravāhaṇa,'''’ is the patronymic of a man called '''Babara''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vii. 1, 10, 2).<br>

प्रा-वृष्
<u>'''Prā-vṛṣ'''</u> is the name of the ‘rainy season’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_206/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_206/><br>

प्रा-वेप
<u>'''Prā-vepa.'''</u> See '''[[प्राकाश|Prākāśa]].'''<br>

प्राश्
<u>'''Prāś'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_208/> denotes a ‘debater’ or a ‘debate,’ while [[प्रतिप्राश्|Pratiprāś]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_208/> denotes an ‘opponent in debate.’<br>

प्राश्नी-पुत्र
<u>'''Prāśnī-putra'''</u> (‘son of Prāśnī’) '''[[आसुरि-वासिन्|Āsuri-vāsin]]''' is mentioned in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_209/> as a pupil of '''[[आसुरायण|Āsurāyaṇa]].'''<br>

प्रा-श्रवण
<u>'''Prā-śravaṇa.'''</u> See '''[[प्रास्रवण|Prāsravaṇa]].'''<br>

प्रा-सच
<u>'''Prā-saca,'''</u> m., in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_211/> denotes a ‘cloudburst,’ while in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_211/> the adjective ''prāsacyaḥ (āpaḥ)'' means ‘(waters) produced by torrential rain.’<br>

प्रा-साद
<u>'''Prā-sāda'''</u> in the sense of ‘palace’ does not occur until the late Adbhuta [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_212/> ''Cf.'' '''[[प्राकार|Prākāra]].''' <br>

प्रा-स्रवण
<u>'''Prā-sravaṇa'''</u> occurs as part of the local name '''[[प्लक्ष प्रास्रवण|Plakṣa Prāsravaṇa]].''' It also appears as a patronymic ‘descendant of [[प्रस्रवण|Prasravaṇa]],’ applied to '''[[अवत्सार|Avatsāra]]''' in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_213/><br>

प्रियङ्गु
<u>'''Priyaṅgu'''</u> denotes ‘panic seed’ (''Panicum italicum'') in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_214/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_214/><br>

प्रिय-मेध
<u>'''Priya-medha'''</u> is the name of a seer in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_215/> where his family, the Priyamedhas, are also repeatedly alluded to.<ref name=fx2_ve2_215/> It is not probable that any hymns are really Priyamedha's own composition.<ref name=fx3_ve2_215/> See also '''[[प्रैयमेध|Praiyamedha]].'''<br>

प्रिय-रथ
<u>'''Priya-ratha'''</u> is the name of a patron of the '''Pajras''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_216/><br>

प्रिय-व्रत सोमापि
<u>'''Priya-[[व्रत|vrata]] Somāpi'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_217/> or '''[[सौमापि|Saumāpi]]''' is the name of a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_217/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx2_ve2_217/> in which he is said to be the son of '''Somapa.''' The name Priyavrata is also found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_217/> where a '''[[रौहिणायन|Rauhiṇāyana]]''' of that name is mentioned as a teacher.<br>

प्रेङ्ख
<u>'''Preṅkha,'''</u> ‘swing,’ is mentioned in the description of the Mahāvrata rite, given in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve2_218/> the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]  Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx2_ve2_218/> the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_218/> and elsewhere.<ref name=fx4_ve2_218/> As far as can be judged from the notices available,<ref name=fx5_ve2_218/> the swing was made just like a modern swing. See also '''[[प्लेङ्ख|Pleṅkha]].'''<br>

प्रेत
<u>'''Preta,'''</u> ‘departed,’ is used to denote a ‘dead man’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_219/> but not in the sense of ‘ghost,’ which only appears later, in post-Vedic literature.<br>

प्रेदि
<u>'''Predi.'''</u> See '''Proti.'''<br>

प्रेष्य
<u>'''Preṣya'''</u> (‘to be sent’ on an errand) denotes a menial servant or slave, being applied in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_221/> to the '''[[शूद्र|Śūdra]].''' In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_221/> the adjective ''praiṣya,'' ‘menial,’ occurs.<br>

प्रैय-मेध
<u>'''Praiya-medha,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[प्रियमेध|Priyamedha]],'''’ is a patronymic of the priests who sacrificed for the '''[[आत्रेय|Ātreya]] Udamaya''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_222/> They appear in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve2_222/> as priests who ‘knew all’ (sacrificial lore). Three Praiyamedhas are referred to in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_222/> In the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_222/> they are called '''Bharadvājas.'''<br>

प्रैष
<u>'''Praiṣa'''</u> is a liturgical term meaning ‘direction’ or ‘invitation,’ repeatedly found in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_223/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_223/> <br>

प्रोति कौशाम्बेय कौसुरु-बिन्दि
<u>'''Proti [[कौशाम्बेय|Kauśāmbeya]] Kausuru-bindi'''</u> (‘descendant of '''Kusurubinda'''’) is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_224/> as a pupil and contemporary of '''Uddālaka.''' In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve2_224/> on the other hand, Kusurubinda is called '''[[औद्दालकि|Auddālaki]],''' ‘descendant of Uddālaka,’ a fact which seems to indicate that little value is to be attached to these patronymics and allegations of contemporaneousness.<br>

प्रोष्ठ
<u>'''Proṣṭha,'''</u> denoting perhaps a ‘bench,’ is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_225/> in the adjective ''proṣṭhaśaya,'' ‘lying on a bench,’ used of women, and uncompounded in the Taittīriya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_225/> In the first passage it is distinguished from '''[[तल्प|Talpa]]''' and '''[[वह्य|Vahya]],''' but what the exact difference was there is not sufficient evidence to show.<br>

प्रोष्ठ-पद
<u>'''Proṣṭha-pada,'''</u> m., '''-padā,''' f. (‘foot of a bench’), is the name of a double '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

प्रोष्ठ-पाद वारक्य
<u>'''Proṣṭha-[[पाद|pāda]] Vārakya'''</u> is mentioned in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 41, 1) as a pupil of [[कंस|Kaṃsa]] [[वारकि|Vāraki]].<br>

प्लक्ष
<u>'''1. Plakṣa'''</u> is the name of the waved leaf fig-tree (''Ficus infectoria''), a large and beautiful tree with small white fruit. It is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_228/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_228/> along with the '''[[न्यग्रोध|Nyagrodha]]''' and the '''[[पर्ण|Parṇa]].''' Its name is altered in the latter Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_228/> to '''[[प्रक्ष|Prakṣa]]''' for the sake of an etymology. It is also mentioned in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx4_ve2_228/> <br>

प्लक्ष दय्यांपाति
<u>'''2. Plakṣa Dayyāṃpāti'''</u> (‘descendant of Dyāṃpati’ or Dyāṃpāta) was a contemporary of '''[[अत्य्अंहस् आरुणि|Atyaṃhas Āruṇi]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 10, 9, 3. 5).<br>

प्लक्ष प्रा-स्रवण
<u>'''3. Plakṣa Prā-sravaṇa'''</u> is the name of a locality, forty-four days’ journey from the spot where the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' disappears. It is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_230/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_230/> In the latter text it is said that the middle of the earth is only a span ('''[[प्रादेश|Prādeśa]]''') to the north of it. In the Rigveda Sūtras<ref name=fx3_ve2_230/> the locality is called Plākṣa [[प्रस्रवण|Prasravaṇa]], and is apparently meant to designate the source of the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] rather than the place of its reappearance.<br>

प्लति
<u>'''Plati'''</u> is the name of a man, the father of the seer of two hymns of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_231/><br>

प्लव
<u>'''1. Plava'''</u> (‘float’) denotes a ‘boat’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_232/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_232/><br>

प्लव
<u>'''2. Plava'''</u> is the name of an aquatic bird mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_233/> Perhaps the ‘pelican’ is meant.<br>

प्लाक्षि
<u>'''Plākṣi,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[प्लक्ष|Plakṣa]],'''’ is the name of a man mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve2_234/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]]  Prātiśākhya.<ref name=fx2_ve2_234/> In the same Prātiśākhya<ref name=fx3_ve2_234/> a Plākṣāyaṇa, or ‘descendant of Plākṣa,’ is mentioned.<br>

प्लात
<u>'''Plāta,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[प्लति|Plati]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Gaya''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 2).<br>

प्ला-योगि
<u>'''Plā-yogi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Playoga,’ is the patronymic of '''Āsaṅga''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_236/> According to the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_236/> Āsaṅga was a woman, but became a man. This version, repeated by Sāyaṇa in his commentary on the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_236/> is a mere blunder based on the fact that an additional verse, tacked on to the hymn,<ref name=fx3_ve2_236/> contains the expression ''[[शश्वती|śaśvatī]] [[नारी|nārī]],'' which has been taken to mean ‘his wife [[शश्वती|Śaśvatī]],’<ref name=fx4_ve2_236/> instead of merely ‘every woman.’<br>

प्लाशुक
<u>'''Plāśuka'''</u> is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v, 3, 3, 2) as an epithet of '''[[व्रीहि|Vrīhi]],''' ‘rice,’ in the sense of ‘shooting up rapidly.’<br>

प्लीहा-कर्ण
<u>'''Plīhā-karṇa'''</u> as an epithet of cattle in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_238/> probably denotes ‘having a spleen-shaped mark branded on the ear,’ not as Mahīdhara in his commentary on the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_238/> takes it, ‘having a disease called Plīhan in the ear.’<br>

प्लुष्
<u>'''Pluṣ'''</u> is the name of some noxious insect in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_239/> It is also included in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]]  (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx2_ve2_239/> and is mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_239/> Possibly a species of ant may be meant.<br>

प्लेङ्ख
<u>'''Pleṅkha'''</u> is a variant form of '''[[प्रेङ्ख|Preṅkha]],''' ‘swing,’ found in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vii. 5, 8, 5) and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 2, 6, 6).<br>

फण
<u>'''Phaṇa'''</u> occurs in some manuscripts of the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_241/> and is explained as meaning an ‘ornament.’ But it is merely a misreading of the correct word ''[[फल|phala]]'' in the compound ''phalahastāḥ,'' ‘bearing fruits in their hands.’<br>

फर्वर
<u>'''Pharvara,'''</u> a word occurring only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_242/> cannot be interpreted with certainty. It may mean a ‘field in bloom.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_242/> Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx3_ve2_242/> explains it as ‘filler,’ and Grassmann as perhaps a ‘sower.’<ref name=fx4_ve2_242/><br>

फल
<u>'''Phala,'''</u> denoting ‘fruit’ generally, especially the fruit of a tree, occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_243/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_243/><br>

फलक
<u>'''Phalaka'''</u> denotes ‘plank,’ as applied in the construction of a cart or chariot, or as used for pressing Soma (''adhi-ṣavaṇe phalake''),<ref name=fx2_ve2_244/> or for any other purpose.<ref name=fx3_ve2_244/><br><br>^1Pañcaviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], xvii. 1, 14 (''cf. Indische Studien,'' 1, 33, 44). <br>

फलवती
<u>'''Phalavatī,'''</u> ‘fruitful,’ is the name of a plant in the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_245/> identified by the scholiast with the '''[[प्रियङ्गु|Priyaṅgu]].'''<br>

फल्गु
<u>'''Phalgu.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

फल्गुनी
<u>'''Phalgunī.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

फाण्ट
<u>'''Phāṇṭa'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_248/> is said to denote the first particles of butter produced by churning, ‘creamy butter.’<br>

फाल
<u>'''Phāla,'''</u> ‘ploughshare,’ occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_249/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_249/> ''Cf.'' '''[[लाङ्गल|Lāṅgala]].'''<br>

बक दाल्भ्य
<u>'''Baka Dālbhya'''</u> (‘descendant of Dalbha’) is the name of a person mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] as constraining Indra for the '''Ājakeśins''' (i. 9, 2), and as a '''KuruPañcāla''' (iv. 7, 2).<br>

बकुर
<u>'''Bakura'''</u> is mentioned in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_251/> where it is said that the Aśvins made light for the Āryan by blowing their [[बकुर|Bakura]] against the '''Dasyus.''' According to the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_251/> the thunderbolt<ref name=fx1_ve2_251/> is meant; but much more probable is Roth's<ref name=fx3_ve2_251/> view, that the object blown was a musical instrument. See also '''[[बाकुर|Bākura]].''' <br>

बज
<u>'''Baja'''</u> is the name in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_252/> of a plant used against a demon of disease. Some sort of mustard plant may be meant.<ref name=fx2_ve2_252/><br>

बदर
<u>'''Badara'''</u> denoting, like '''[[कर्कन्धु|Karkandhu]]''' and '''[[कुवल|Kuvala]],''' a kind of jujube, is mentioned in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_253/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_253/><br>

बद्वन्
<u>'''Badvan'''</u> seems in one passage of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_254/> to denote a ‘causeway.’ It is said to be firmer than an ordinary road.<br>

बन्धन
<u>'''Bandhana'''</u> denotes a ‘rope’ or other fastening in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_255/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_255/><br>

बन्धु
<u>'''Bandhu,'''</u> denoting ‘relationship’<ref name=fx1_ve2_256/> in the abstract and ‘relation’<ref name=fx2_ve2_256/> in the concrete, occurs in the Rigveda and later.<br>

बबर प्रा-वाहणि
<u>'''Babara Prā-vāhaṇi'''</u> (‘descendant of '''Pravāhaṇa'''’) is the name of a man who, according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve2_257/> wished to become an orator, and obtained rhetorical power by the use of the Pañcarātra sacrifice. <br>

बभ्रु
<u>'''1. Babhru'''</u> is the name, in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_258/> of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] who received gifts from King '''[[ऋणंचय|Ṛṇaṃcaya]].''' The same [[बभ्रु|Babhru]] may be meant in another passage,<ref name=fx2_ve2_258/> where he is mentioned as a protégé of the Aśvins; but it is doubtful whether the word is a proper name at all in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_258/><br>

बभ्रु कौम्भ्य
<u>'''2. Babhru Kaumbhya'''</u> (‘descendant of Kumbha’) is the name of the seer of a Sāman or Chant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xv. 3, 13).<br>

बभ्रु दैवा-वृध
<u>'''3. Babhru Daivā-vṛdha'''</u> is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 34) as a pupil of '''[[पर्वत|Parvata]]''' and '''[[नारद|Nārada]].'''<br>

बम्ब आज-द्विष
<u>'''Bamba Āja-dviṣa'''</u> (‘descendant of Aja-dviṣ’) is mentioned as a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 7, 2). [[बिम्ब|Bimba]] is a various reading.<br>

बम्बा-विश्ववयसौ
<u>'''Bambā-Viśvavayasau'''</u> are the names, in the form of a compound, of two [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]] who, according to the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve2_262/> invented a certain rite.<br>

बरासी
<u>'''Barāsī'''</u> is found in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_263/> and the Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmana<ref name=fx2_ve2_263/> denoting a garment of some kind.<br>

बरु
<u>'''Baru'''</u> is the name of the author of a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_264/> according to the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_264/> of that Veda. <br>

बर्कु वार्ष्ण
<u>'''Barku Vārṣṇa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[वृषन्|Vṛṣan]]'''’) is the name of a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_265/><br>

बर्हिस्
<u>'''Barhis'''</u> is found repeatedly in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_266/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_266/> denoting the litter of grass strewn on the sacrificial ground on which the gods are summoned to seat themselves.<br>

बलाका
<u>'''Balākā,'''</u> ‘crane,’ is mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_267/><br>

बलाय
<u>'''Balāya'''</u> is the name of an unknown animal mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_268/><br>

बलास
<u>'''Balāsa'''</u> is the name of a disease mentioned several times in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_269/> and occasionally later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_269/> Mahīdhara<ref name=fx3_ve2_269/> and Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx4_ve2_269/> interpret the term as ‘consumption.’ Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve2_269/> supports this view on the ground that it is mentioned<ref name=fx6_ve2_269/> as a kind of '''[[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]],''' makes the bones and joints fall apart (''asthi-sraṃsa, paruḥ-sraṃsa''),<ref name=fx7_ve2_269/> and is caused by love, aversion, and the heart,<ref name=fx8_ve2_269/> characteristics which agree with the statements of the later Hindu medicine.<ref name=fx9_ve2_269/> It is in keeping with a demon of the character of consumption that [[बलास|Balāsa]] should appear as an accompaniment of [[तक्मन्|Takman]].<ref name=fx10_ve2_269/> Grohmann,<ref name=fx11_ve2_269/> however, thought  that a ‘sore’ or ‘swelling’ (in the case of fever caused by dropsy) was meant. Bloomfield<ref name=fx12_ve2_269/> considers that the question is still open. Ludwig<ref name=fx13_ve2_269/> renders the word by ‘dropsy.’<br><br>As remedies against the disease the salve ('''Āñjasa''') from '''[[त्रिककुद्|Trikakud]]'''<ref name=fx14_ve2_269/> and the '''[[जङ्गिड|Jaṅgiḍa]]'''<ref name=fx15_ve2_269/> plant are mentioned.<br>

बलि
<u>'''Bali'''</u> occurs several times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_270/> and often later<ref name=fx2_ve2_270/> in the sense of tribute to a king or offering to a god. Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_270/> thinks that the offerings were in both cases voluntary. He compares the notices of the Germans in Tacitus,<ref name=fx4_ve2_270/> where the kings of the tribes are said to receive gifts in kind as presents, but not a regular tribute. There seems to be no ground whatever for this view. No doubt in origin the prerogatives of monarchy were due to voluntary action on the part of the tribesmen,<ref name=fx5_ve2_270/> but that the Vedic peoples, who were essentially a body of conquering invaders, were in this state is most improbable, and the attitude of the Vedic Indian to his gods was at least as compatible with tribute as with voluntary gifts. Zimmer admits that in the case of hostile tribes<ref name=fx6_ve2_270/> tribute must be meant even in the Rigveda. See also '''[[राजन्|Rājan]].'''<br>

बल्कस
<u>'''Balkasa'''</u> denotes impure matter given off in the process of fermentation in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_271/> The exact sense  may be either ‘scum,’ ‘sediment,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_271/> or perhaps more probably vegetable matter in the form of ‘husks.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_271/><br>

बल्बज
<u>'''Balbaja'''</u> is the name of the grass called ''Eleusine indica.'' It is mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_272/> and is said in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve2_272/> to be produced from the excrements of cattle. In the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_272/> it is stated to be used for the sacrificial litter ('''[[बर्हिस्|Barhis]]''') and for fuel. Baskets or other products made from this grass are referred to in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_272/><br>

बल्हिक
<u>'''1. Balhika'''</u> is the name of a people in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_273/> where the fever ('''[[तक्मन्|Takman]]''') is called upon to go to the '''Mūjavants,''' the '''Mahāvṛṣas,''' and the Balhikas. The Mūjavants are quite certainly a northern tribe, and though, as Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve2_273/> suggests, the passage may contain a pun on [[बल्हिक|Balhika]] as suggesting ‘outsider’ (from ''bahis,'' ‘without’), still no doubt the name was chosen from a northern tribe. But the view of Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_273/> and Weber,<ref name=fx4_ve2_273/> which Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve2_273/> once accepted, that an Iranian tribe is referred to (''cf.'' Balkh), is not at all probable. Zimmer<ref name=fx6_ve2_273/> shows that there is no need whatever to assume Iranian influence. See also '''[[पर्शु|Parśu]].'''<br>

बल्हिक प्रातिपीय
<u>'''2. Balhika Prātipīya'''</u> is the name of a '''Kuru''' king in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_274/> where he appears as having been opposed to the restoration of '''[[दुष्टरीतु|Duṣṭarītu]] [[पौंसायन|Pauṃsāyana]]''' to his hereditary sovereignty over the '''Sṛñjayas,''' but as having failed to prevent  the restoration being carried out by '''[[रेवोत्तरस्|Revottaras]] [[पाटव|Pāṭava]] [[चाक्र|Cākra]] [[स्थपति|Sthapati]].''' The epithet [[प्रातिपीय|Prātipīya]] is curious: if it connects him with '''Pratīpa''' (whose son he is in the Epic), the form is remarkable, Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_274/> indeed tacitly altering it to Prātīpīya. In the Epic and the Purāṇas<ref name=fx3_ve2_274/> he is in the form of Vāhlīka made a brother of '''Devāpi''' and '''Śantanu,''' and a son of Pratīpa. To base chronological conclusions on this<ref name=fx4_ve2_274/> would be utterly misleading, for the facts are that Devāpi was son of [[ऋष्टिषेण|Ṛṣṭiṣeṇa]] and a priest, while Śantanu was a Kuru prince of unknown parentage, but not probably a son of Pratīpa, who seems to be a late figure in the Vedic age, later than '''[[परिक्षित्|Parikṣit]],''' being his great-grandson in the Epic. Very possibly [[बल्हिक|Balhika]] was a descendant of Pratīpa. Why he bore the name [[बल्हिक|Balhika]] must remain uncertain, for there is no evidence of any sort regarding it.<br>

बल्बूथ
<u>'''Balbūtha'''</u> is mentioned in one hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_275/> along with '''[[तरुक्ष|Tarukṣa]]''' and '''[[पृथुश्रवस्|Pṛthuśravas]],''' as a giver of gifts to the singer. He is called a '''[[दास|Dāsa]],''' but Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_275/> was inclined to amend the text so as to say that the singer received a hundred Dāsas from [[बल्बूथ|Balbūtha]]. Zimmer's<ref name=fx3_ve2_275/> suggestion that he may have been the son of an aboriginal mother, or perhaps an aboriginal himself, seems probable.<ref name=fx4_ve2_275/> If this was the case, it would be a clear piece of evidence for the establishment of friendly relations between the Āryans and the Dāsas.<br>

बस्त
<u>'''1. Basta'''</u> denotes the ‘goat’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_276/> and the later literature.<ref name=fx2_ve2_276/> <br>

बस्त रामकायन
<u>'''2. Basta Rāmakāyana'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iv. 2, 10). The patronymic is variously read Samakāyana.<br>

बहु-वचन
<u>'''Bahu-vacana'''</u> denotes in grammatical terminology the ‘plural’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_278/> and the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_278/> So ''dvivat, bahuvat,'' in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_278/> means ‘in the dual and the plural.’<br>

बह्व्-ऋच
<u>'''Bahv-ṛca'''</u> denotes an adherent of the Rigveda. The term is found in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_279/> of the Rigveda, in the Śatapatha<ref name=fx2_ve2_279/> and the Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx3_ve2_279/> and in the Āraṇyakas of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx4_ve2_279/><br>

बाकुर
<u>'''Bākura'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda (ix. 1, 8) is used as an epithet of '''[[दृति|Dṛti]],''' the combined words denoting a wind instrument of some kind. ''Cf.'' '''[[बकुर|Bakura]].'''<br>

बाडेयी-पुत्र
<u>'''Bāḍeyī-putra'''</u> (‘son of Bāḍeyī’) is mentioned in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 30) as a pupil of '''[[मौषिकीपुत्र|Mauṣikīputra]].'''<br>

बाण
<u>'''Bāṇa'''</u> denotes ‘arrow’ in the Rigveda (vi. 75, 17) and later (Av. iii. 23, 2; vi. 105, 2, etc.).<br>

बाणवन्त्
<u>'''Bāṇavant'''</u> in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iii. 8, 2) denotes an ‘arrow’ like '''[[बाण|Bāṇa]].''' Its more normal sense is ‘quiver’ (lit., ‘containing arrows’), which is its sense in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xvi. 10) and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 3, 1, 11). <br>

बादरायण
<u>'''Bādarāyaṇa'''</u> (‘descendant of Badara’) is the name of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the Sāmavidhāna [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_284/><br>

बाध्योग
<u>'''Bādhyoga'''</u> (‘descendant of Badhyoga’) is the patronymic of '''Jihvāvant,''' a pupil of '''[[असित|Asita]] [[वार्षगण|Vārṣagaṇa]],''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 33).<br>

बाध्व
<u>'''Bādhva'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka (iii. 2, 3). The reading in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (viii. 3) is '''[[वात्स्य|Vātsya]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_286/><br>

बाभ्रव
<u>'''Bābhrava,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[बभ्रु|Babhru]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Vatsanapāt''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_287/> In the legend of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_287/> the '''Kāpileyas''' and the Bābhravas are enumerated as the descendants of [[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]] under his adoptive name of '''[[देवरात|Devarāta]] [[वैश्वामित्र|Vaiśvāmitra]].''' A Sāman, or Chant, of [[बभ्रु|Babhru]] is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_287/><br>

बाभ्रव्य
<u>'''Bābhravya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[बभ्रु|Babhru]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Girija''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 1), and of '''[[शङ्ख|Śaṅkha]]''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 41, 1; iv. 17, 1).<br>

बार्हत्-सामा
<u>'''Bārhat-sāmā'''</u> is an anomalously formed word meaning ‘daughter of Bṛhatsāman’ in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_289/> where her name occurs in a hymn for easy conception. <br>

बार्हस्-पत्य
<u>'''Bārhas-patya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[बृहस्पति|Bṛhaspati]],’ is the patronymic of the mythical '''[[शंयु|Śaṃyu]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_290/><br>

बाल
<u>'''Bāla'''</u> denotes ‘boy,’ ‘young child,’ in the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx1_ve2_291/> The later definition<ref name=fx2_ve2_291/> makes childhood extend to the sixteenth year.<br>

बालन्दन
<u>'''Bālandana'''</u> is a variant of '''[[भालन्दन|Bhālandana]],''' the patronymic of '''Vatsaprī.'''<br><br>^1 See Weber, ''Indische Studien,'' 3, 459, 478.<br>

बालाकि
<u>'''Bālāki, Bālākyā.'''</u> See '''Dṛpta-[[बालाकि|bālāki]]''' and '''Kāśyapī-bālākyāmāṭharī-[[पुत्र|putra]].'''<br>

बालेय
<u>'''Bāleya'''</u> is a patronymic (‘descendant of Bali’) of '''Gandharvāyaṇa''' in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xx. 25).<br>

बाष्कल
<u>'''Bāṣkala.'''</u> See '''[[वार्कलि|Vārkali]].'''<br>

बाष्किह
<u>'''Bāṣkiha,'''</u> ‘descendant of Baṣkiha,’ is the patronymic of '''[[शुनस्कर्ण|Śunaskarṇa]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_296/> In the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_296/> he is a descendant of '''[[शिबि|Śibi]].'''<br>

बाहीक
<u>'''Bāhīka'''</u> is applied in the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_297/> to the people of the west, of the Panjab,<ref name=fx2_ve2_297/> as opposed to the '''Prācyas''' or easterns. They are said to have called Agni by the name of Bhava. <br>

बाहु
<u>'''Bāhu,'''</u> ‘arm,’ as a measure of length, is found in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vi. 2, 11, 1) and often in the Sūtras.<br>

बाहु-वृक्त
<u>'''Bāhu-vṛkta'''</u> is the name of a man, apparently a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], who overcame foes in battle, according to the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_299/><br>

बिदल-कारी
<u>'''Bidala-kārī,'''</u> ‘female splitter of bamboos,’ is the name of one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_300/> Eggeling<ref name=fx2_ve2_300/> renders the word as ‘basket-maker.’<br>

बिम्ब
<u>'''Bimba'''</u> appears in one passage of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 5, 6) to denote the plant ''Momordica monadelpha.''<br>

बिल्व
<u>'''Bilva'''</u> is the name of the wood-apple tree (''Aigle marmelos''). It is mentioned in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_302/> and in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_302/> where a reference to its valuable fruit may be intended. According to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve2_302/> the sacrificial post was made of [[बिल्व|Bilva]] wood in some cases. The [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx4_ve2_302/> contains a hymn in praise of the virtues of an amulet of [[बिल्व|Bilva]] (''irā-[[मणि|maṇi]] bailva'').<ref name=fx5_ve2_302/><br>

बिस
<u>'''Bisa'''</u> denotes the radical fibres of the lotus, which seem to have been eaten as a delicacy as early as the times of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_303/> It is mentioned also in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_303/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx3_ve2_303/> <br>

बीज
<u>'''Bīja'''</u> denotes ‘seed,’ the operation of sowing seed (''vap'') being several times referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_304/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_304/> In a metaphorical sense the term is used in the Upaniṣads of the classes of beings according to origin, of which the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_304/> enumerates three, the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_304/> four. The former list includes ''aṇḍa-ja,'' ‘egg-born,’ ''[[जीव-ज|jīva-ja]],'' ‘born alive,’ and ''udbhij-ja,'' ‘produced from sprouts,’ ‘germinating,’ while the latter adds ''[[स्वेद-ज|sveda-ja]],'' ‘sweat-born’--that is, ‘generated by hot moisture,’ an expression which is glossed to comprise flies, worms, etc. ''Cf.'' '''[[कृषि|Kṛṣi]].'''<br>

बुडिल आश्वतराश्वि
<u>'''Buḍila Āśvatarāśvi'''</u> or '''Āśvatara Āśvi''' is mentioned several times in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] literature as a teacher. According to the Chāndogya<ref name=fx1_ve2_305/> and the Bṛhadāraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve2_305/> Upaniṣads, he was a contemporary of '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' of '''[[विदेह|Videha]],''' and, according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_305/> of '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]],''' the '''[[केकय|Kekaya]]''' king. He is also mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].^4<br>

बुध सौमायन
<u>'''Budha Saumāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Soma,'''’ is the name of a teacher mentioned in a verse in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_306/><br>

बुन्द
<u>'''Bunda'''</u> means ‘arrow’ in a few passages of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_307/><br>

बृबु
<u>'''Bṛbu'''</u> is mentioned in a hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_308/> where he is described as a most generous giver (''sahasra-dātama''), and as at the head of the '''Paṇis.''' According to the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_308/> '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]]''' received gifts from [[बृबु|Bṛbu]] '''[[तक्षन्|Takṣan]]''' and  '''[[प्रस्तोक|Prastoka]] [[सार्ञ्जय|Sārñjaya]],''' a fact alluded to in the [[मानव|Mānava]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] Śāstra,<ref name=fx3_ve2_308/> where ''[[तक्षन्|takṣan]]'' is treated as a descriptive attribute, ‘a carpenter.’ Apparently [[बृबु|Bṛbu]] was a [[पणि|Paṇi]], though the words of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_308/> might be taken to mean that he was one who had overthrown them entirely. If so, [[पणि|Paṇi]] must here certainly mean a merchant in a good sense, [[बृबु|Bṛbu]] being then a merchant prince.<ref name=fx4_ve2_308/> According to Weber,<ref name=fx5_ve2_308/> the name suggests connexion with Babylon, but this conjecture must be regarded as quite improbable. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx6_ve2_308/> sensibly expresses no opinion as to [[बृबु|Bṛbu]], while Brunnhofer's<ref name=fx7_ve2_308/> attempt to recognize a people named , and to connect them with the Vedic word ''[[तक्षन्|takṣan]],'' is valueless, especially considering the fact that [[तक्षन्|Takṣan]] is not found as an epithet of [[बृबु|Bṛbu]] in the Rigveda.<br>

बृसय
<u>'''Bṛsaya'''</u> is mentioned twice in the Rigveda, being in the first passage<ref name=fx1_ve2_309/> connected with the '''Paṇis,''' and in the second<ref name=fx2_ve2_309/> with the '''Pārāvatas''' and the Paṇis. According to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, the word is the name of a demon,<ref name=fx3_ve2_309/> but is in the second passage<ref name=fx2_ve2_309/> used as an appellative, perhaps meaning ‘sorcerer.’<ref name=fx4_ve2_309/> Hillebrandt<ref name=fx5_ve2_309/> thinks that a people is meant locating them in Arachosia or Drangiana with the Pārāvatas and the Paṇis, and comparing , satrap of Arachosia and Drangiana in the time of Darius.<ref name=fx6_ve2_309/> But this theory is not probable. <br>

बृसी
<u>'''Bṛsī,'''</u> denoting a ‘cushion’ of grass, is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve2_310/> and the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve2_310/> The incorrect forms Vṛśī and Vṛṣī also occur occasionally.<br>

बृहच्-छन्दस्
<u>'''Bṛhac-chandas'''</u> is found in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_311/> as an epithet of '''[[शाला|Śālā]],''' ‘house.’ It is apparently<ref name=fx2_ve2_311/> an error for ''bṛhad-[[छदिस्|chadis]],'' ‘broad-roofed,’ which in any case is the sense.<ref name=fx3_ve2_311/><br>

बृहत्-सामन्
<u>'''Bṛhat-sāman'''</u> is mentioned in the Atharvaveda (v. 19, 2) as an '''[[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]]''' who was oppressed by Kṣatriyas. The latter are said to have been ruined in consequence. ''Cf.'' '''[[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]]''' and '''[[बार्हत्सामा|Bārhatsāmā]].'''<br>

बृहद्-उक्थ
<u>'''Bṛhad-uktha'''</u> is mentioned in an obscure hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_313/> as a priest; in two hymns of the tenth Maṇḍala<ref name=fx2_ve2_313/> he is definitely a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]]. He is also mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_313/> as having consecrated '''[[दुर्मुख|Durmukha]] [[पाञ्चाल|Pāñcāla]],''' and is called '''Vāmadeva's''' son in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_313/> In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_313/> he appears as '''Vāmneya,''' ‘descendant of Vāmnī.’ Hopkins<ref name=fx6_ve2_313/> suggestion that he may have been there thought of as Vāmadevya also is quite probable.<ref name=fx7_ve2_313/><br>

बृहद्-गिरि
<u>'''Bṛhad-giri'''</u> is said in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 1, 4) to have been one of the three '''Yatis''' who survived the slaughter of them by Indra. A Sāman, or Chant, of his is mentioned in the same [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 4, 15-17). <br>

बृहद्-दिव
<u>'''Bṛhad-diva'''</u> appears in a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_315/> as its author, calling himself an [[अथर्वन्|Atharvan]]. He is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_315/> and is named in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx3_ve2_315/> as a pupil of '''[[सुम्नयु|Sumnayu]].'''<br>

बृहद्-रथ
<u>'''Bṛhad-ratha'''</u> is mentioned twice in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_316/> in both cases beside '''[[नववास्त्व|Navavāstva]].''' The name may thus be an epithet of [[नववास्त्व|Navavāstva]].<br>

बृहद्-वसु
<u>'''Bṛhad-vasu'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_317/><br>

बृहस्पति
<u>'''Bṛhaspati,'''</u> ‘lord of prayer,’ is the name of a god in the Vedic texts. The view of Thibaut,<ref name=fx1_ve2_318/> that the name designates the planet Jupiter, is certainly not supported by good evidence. Oldenberg<ref name=fx2_ve2_318/> seems clearly right in rejecting it.<br>

बृहस्पति-गुप्त शायस्थि
<u>'''Bṛhaspati-[[गुप्त|gupta]] Śāyasthi'''</u> is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_319/> as a pupil of '''[[भवत्रात शायस्थि|Bhavatrāta Śāyasthi]].'''<br>

बृहस्पति-सव
<u>'''Bṛhaspati-sava'''</u> is the name of a sacrifice by which, according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_320/> the priest who desired to become a '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]]''' obtained that office. According to the Āśvalāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_320/> it was the sacrifice to be performed by a priest after the '''[[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]],''' while the king performed the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]].''' In  the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_320/> on the other hand, the [[बृहस्पतिसव|Bṛhaspatisava]] is identified with the [[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]]; but such identity is clearly not primitive.<ref name=fx4_ve2_320/><br>

बेकनाट
<u>'''Bekanāṭa'''</u> occurs only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_321/> when Indra is said to overcome all the Bekanāṭas and the Paṇis. The natural sense, therefore, seems to be ‘usurer,’ the explanation given by [[यास्क|Yāska]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_321/> The word has a foreign appearance, but its provenance can hardly be determined: it might just as well be aboriginal as Babylonian.<ref name=fx3_ve2_321/> Hillebrandt<ref name=fx4_ve2_321/> thinks Brunnhofer is right in identifying [[बेकनाट|Bekanāṭa]] with Bikanir.<br>

बेकुरा
<u>'''Bekurā'''</u> occurs in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_322/> where it may mean ‘voice’ or ‘sound,’ the sense assigned to the word in the Naighaṇṭuka.<ref name=fx2_ve2_322/> It is, however, possibly, like '''[[बकुर|Bakura]],''' the name of a musical instrument. In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_322/> and the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_322/> Saṃhitās the words Bekuri and Vekuri occur as epithets of Apsarases, or celestial nymphs, meaning, perhaps, ‘melodious’; in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx5_ve2_322/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_322/> the variations Bhakuri and [[भाकुरि|Bhākuri]] are found.<br>

बैज-वाप
<u>'''Baija-vāpa,'''</u> ‘descendant of Bījavāpa,’ is the name of a teacher in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 5, 20; iv. 5, 26).<br>

बैज-वापायन
<u>'''Baija-vāpāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[बैजवाप|Baijavāpa]],'''’ is the name of a teacher in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 5, 20; iv. 5, 26). The name is also spelt Vaijavāpāyana. <br>

बैज-वापि
<u>'''Baija-vāpi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Bījavāpa, or Bījavāpin,’ is the name of a teacher in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (i. 4, 7).<br>

बैन्द
<u>'''Bainda'''</u> is the name of one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_326/> According to the commentator Mahīdhara, the word denotes a [[निषाद|Niṣāda]], but according to Sāyaṇa a catcher of fish. See '''[[मृगयु|Mṛgayu]].'''<br>

बोध
<u>'''Bodha'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the [[मन्त्र|Mantra]] Pāṭha.<ref name=fx1_ve2_327/> He is mentioned with '''Pratibodha''' in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_327/> but Whitney<ref name=fx3_ve2_327/> thinks that in the second passage, at least, the word is an ordinary noun meaning ‘the wakeful one.’<br>

बौधायन
<u>'''Baudhāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Budha''' or '''[[बोध|Bodha]],'''’ is the name of a teacher who is mentioned in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_328/> and under whose name are current a Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] described<ref name=fx2_ve2_328/> and in part edited by Caland,<ref name=fx3_ve2_328/> and a [[धर्म|Dharma]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] which has been edited<ref name=fx4_ve2_328/> and translated,<ref name=fx5_ve2_328/> while the [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] is still unedited.<br>

बौधी-पुत्र
<u>'''Baudhī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of '''[[बोध|Bodha]],'''’ is the name of a pupil of '''[[शालङ्कायनीपुत्र|Śālaṅkāyanīputra]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāranyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 31).<br>

ब्रह्म-चर्य
<u>'''Brahma-carya'''</u> denotes the condition of life of the '''Brahmacārin'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_330/> or religious student. The technical sense is first found in  the last Maṇḍala of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_330/> The practice of studentship doubtless developed, and was more strictly regulated by custom as time went on, but it is regularly assumed and discussed in the later Vedic literature, being obviously a necessary part of Vedic society<br><br>The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_330/> has in honour of the Brahmacārin a hymn which already gives all the characteristic features of religious studentship. The youth is initiated (''upa-nī'') by the teacher<ref name=fx4_ve2_330/> into a new life; he wears an antelope skin, and lets his hair grow long;<ref name=fx5_ve2_330/> he collects fuel,<ref name=fx6_ve2_330/> and begs,<ref name=fx7_ve2_330/> learns, and practises penance. All these characteristics appear in the later literature. The student lives in the house of his teacher (''ācārya-kula-vāsin;''<ref name=fx8_ve2_330/> ''[[अन्ते-वासिन्|ante-vāsin]]'');<ref name=fx9_ve2_330/> he begs,<ref name=fx10_ve2_330/> looks after the sacrificial fires,<ref name=fx11_ve2_330/> and tends the house.<ref name=fx12_ve2_330/> His term of studentship might be long extended: it was normally fixed at twelve years,<ref name=fx13_ve2_330/> but much longer periods, such as thirty-two years, are mentioned.<ref name=fx14_ve2_330/> The  age at which studentship began varied.<ref name=fx15_ve2_330/> '''[[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]]''' commenced at twelve and studied for twelve years.<ref name=fx16_ve2_330/><br><br>It is assumed in the [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] Sūtras that the three Āryan castes were all required to pass through a period of studentship. But that this is much more than priestly schematism is uncertain. No doubt individuals of the '''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]''' or '''[[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]''' caste might go through part of the period of studentship, just as Burmese boys of all classes now pass some time in a monastery as students. This is borne out by the reference in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx17_ve2_330/> to the king guarding his country by [[ब्रह्मचर्य|Brahmacarya]]--though that is susceptible of a different interpretation--and more clearly by the reference in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx18_ve2_330/> to a rite intended to benefit one who, although not a Brahmin, had studied (''vidyām anūcya''), but had not gained renown, and by references in the Upaniṣads to kings who like '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' studied the Vedas and the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx19_ve2_330/> Normally, however, the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] studied the art of war.<ref name=fx20_ve2_330/><br><br>One of the duties of the Brahmacārin was chastity. But reference is in several places<ref name=fx21_ve2_330/> made to the possibility of misconduct between a student and the wife of his preceptor, nor is any very severe penance imposed in early times--later it is different--for such a sin. In certain cases the ritual required a breach of chastity, no doubt as a magic spell to secure fertility.<ref name=fx22_ve2_330/><br><br>Even an old man might on occasion become a pupil, as the story of '''[[आरुणि|Āruṇi]]''' shows.<ref name=fx23_ve2_330/> <br>

ब्रह्म-ज्य
<u>'''Brahma-jya,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_331/> ‘oppressor of a Brahmin,’ and '''Brahma-jyeya,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_331/> ‘oppression of a Brahmin,’ are terms mentioned several times in the Atharvaveda as expressing a heinous crime which involves its perpetrator in ruin. See '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].'''<br>

ब्रह्म-दत्त चैकितानेय
<u>'''Brahma-datta Caikitāneya'''</u> (‘descendant of Cekitāna’) is the name of a teacher in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 3, 26). He is mentioned also in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 38, 1; 59, 1) as patronized by '''Abhipratārin,''' the Kuru king.<br>

ब्रह्मन्
<u>'''1. Brahman'''</u> (neut.) denotes the priestly class as opposed to the warrior class and the people ('''[[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]]''' and '''[[विश्|Viś]]'''). The term is found in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_333/> and repeatedly later on.<ref name=fx2_ve2_333/> For the position, etc., of this class, see '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].'''<br>

ब्रह्मन्
<u>'''2. Brahman'''</u> is found in many passages of the Rigveda and later in the sense of ‘priest.’ In many passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_334/> he is referred to as praising the gods; in others<ref name=fx2_ve2_334/> the sense of ‘priest’ is adequate. In not a few cases<ref name=fx3_ve2_334/> the priesthood as a profession is clearly alluded to, nor is there any reason to doubt<ref name=fx4_ve2_334/> that in all cases the word has the technical sense of a member of the priesthood. There is, however, considerable doubt as to the number of cases in the Rigveda, where it has the technical  sense of the priest who guides the sacrifice generally. It is undoubtedly found in that sense, both Muir<ref name=fx5_ve2_334/> and Roth<ref name=fx6_ve2_334/> recognizing instances of its being used thus. Geldner,<ref name=fx7_ve2_334/> however, is anxious to find that sense in a large number of passages, and insists that the '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]]''' was normally a [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] in the narrower sense. Oldenberg,<ref name=fx8_ve2_334/> on the other hand, holds with greater probability that in most of the passages adduced [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] means simply ‘priest,’ and that the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], who was essentially not a member of the ordinary body of sacrificing priests ('''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]]'''), was, when he officiated at the sacrifice, more usually the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest, and only later became the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]]. This change he regards as having taken place when the importance of the hymns declined, and most weight was laid on the functions of the priest who superintended the sacrifice as a whole, and by his magic repaired the flaws in the sacrifice.<ref name=fx9_ve2_334/> In the later literature both senses of the word are quite common.<ref name=fx10_ve2_334/><br>

ब्रह्म-पुत्र
<u>'''Brahma-putra'''</u> in a few passages is used in the sense of a ‘priest's son.’<br><br>^1 Rv. ii. 43, 2; Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], xi. 4, 1, 2. 9. ''Cf.'' Weber, ''Indische Studien,'' 10, 43, 69; Muir, ''Sanskrit Texts,'' 12, 252. <br>

ब्रह्म-पुरोहित
<u>'''Brahma-purohita'''</u> is found in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_336/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_336/> where the St. Petersburg Dictionary gives the sense as ‘having the priesthood as its [[पुरोहित|Purohita]].’ This seems rather doubtful; more probably the sense should be ‘having a [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] priest as [[पुरोहित|Purohita]],’ unless the word merely means ‘having the priesthood superior to it,’ as an epithet of '''[[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]],''' the ‘warrior caste,’ which seems to be Weber's view.<ref name=fx3_ve2_336/><br>

ब्रह्म-बन्धु
<u>'''Brahma-bandhu'''</u> (‘priest fellow’) denotes, in a deprecatory sense, an ‘unworthy priest,’ ‘priest in name only,’ in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_337/> and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_337/> ''Cf.'' '''[[राजन्यबन्धु|Rājanyabandhu]].'''<br>

ब्रह्मर्षि-देश
<u>'''Brahmarṣi-deśa.'''</u> See '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]].'''<br>

ब्रह्म-वद्य
<u>'''Brahma-vadya.'''</u> See '''[[ब्रह्मोद्य|Brahmodya]].'''<br>

ब्रह्म-वादिन्
<u>'''Brahma-vādin'''</u> (‘expounder of the Veda’) in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_340/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_340/> denotes a ‘theologian.’ Brahma-vid (‘knowing what is sacred’) has the same sense.<ref name=fx3_ve2_340/><br>

ब्रह्म-विद्या
<u>'''Brahma-vidyā,'''</u> ‘knowledge of the Absolute,’ is the name of one of the sciences enumerated in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_341/> It is also mentioned elsewhere.<ref name=fx2_ve2_341/><br>

ब्रह्म-वृद्धि
<u>'''Brahma-vṛddhi'''</u> is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_342/> as a pupil of '''Mitravarcas.''' <br>

ब्रह्म-हत्या
<u>'''Brahma-hatyā,'''</u> the ‘murder of a Brahmin,’ is mentioned in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_343/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_343/> as a heinous crime. The murderer is called Brahma-han.<ref name=fx3_ve2_343/><br>

ब्रह्मावर्त
<u>'''Brahmāvarta.'''</u> See '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]].'''<br>

ब्रह्मोद्य
<u>'''Brahmodya'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_345/> denotes a ‘theological riddle,’ such as formed an essential part of various ceremonies in the Vedic ritual, as at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] or the Daśarātra. [[ब्रह्म-वद्य|Brahma-vadya]] is the form found in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_345/> and Brahma-vādya in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_345/> probably has the same sense.<br>

ब्रह्मोपनिषद्
<u>'''Brahmopaniṣad,'''</u> a ‘secret doctrine regarding the Absolute,’ is the name of a discussion in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iii. 11, 3).<br>

ब्रह्मौदन
<u>'''Brahmaudana'''</u> denotes in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_347/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_347/> the ‘rice boiled ('''[[ओदन|Odana]]''') for the priests’ officiating at the sacrifice.<br>

ब्राह्मण
<u>'''1. Brāhmaṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of a Brahman’ (''i.e.,'' of a priest), is found only a few times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_348/> and mostly in its latest  parts. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_348/> and later<ref name=fx3_ve2_348/> it is a very common word denoting ‘priest,’ and it appears in the quadruple division of the castes in the [[पुरुष|Puruṣa]]-[[सूक्त|sūkta]] (‘hymn of man’) of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx4_ve2_348/><br><br>It seems certain that in the Rigveda this [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], or Brahmin, is already a separate caste, differing from the warrior and agricultural castes.<ref name=fx5_ve2_348/> The texts regularly claim for them a superiority to the '''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]''' caste,<ref name=fx6_ve2_348/> and the Brahmin is able by his spells or manipulation of the rite to embroil the people and the warriors<ref name=fx7_ve2_348/> or the different sections of the warriors.<ref name=fx8_ve2_348/> If it is necessary to recognize, as is sometimes done, that the Brahmin does pay homage to the king at the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]],'''<ref name=fx9_ve2_348/> nevertheless the unusual fact is carefully explained away so as to leave the priority of the Brahmin unaffected. But it is expressly recognized that the union of the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] and the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] is essential for complete prosperity.<ref name=fx10_ve2_348/> It is admitted<ref name=fx11_ve2_348/> that the king or the nobles might at times oppress the Brahmins, but it is indicated that ruin is then certain swiftly to follow. <br><br>The Brahmins are gods on earth,<ref name=fx12_ve2_348/> like the gods in heaven, but this claim is hardly found in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx13_ve2_348/><br><br>In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx14_ve2_348/> the Brahmin is said to be the ‘recipient of gifts’ (''ādāyī'') and the ‘drinker of the offering’ (''āpāyī''). The other two epithets applied, ''āvasāyī'' and ''yathākāma-prayāpya,'' are more obscure; the former denotes either ‘dwelling everywhere’<ref name=fx15_ve2_348/> or ‘seeking food’;<ref name=fx16_ve2_348/> the latter is usually taken as ‘moving at pleasure,’ but it must rather allude to the power of the king to assign a place of residence to the Brahmin.<br><br>In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx17_ve2_348/> the prerogatives of the Brahmin are summed up as (1) [[अर्चा|Arcā]], ‘honour’; (2) [[दान|Dāna]], ‘gifts’; (3) [[अज्येयता|Ajyeyatā]], ‘freedom from oppression’; and (4) [[अवध्यता|Avadhyatā]], ‘freedom from being killed.’ On the other hand, his duties are summed up as (5) Brāhmaṇya, ‘purity of descent’; (6) Pratirūpa-caryā, ‘devotion of the duties of his caste’; and (7) Loka-[[पक्ति|pakti]], ‘the perfecting of people’ (by teaching).<br><br>1. ''Respect paid to Brahmins.''--The texts are full<ref name=fx18_ve2_348/> of references to the civilities to be paid to the Brahmin. He is styled ''bhagavant,''<ref name=fx19_ve2_348/> and is provided with good food<ref name=fx20_ve2_348/> and entertainment wherever he goes. Indeed, his sanctity exempts him from any close inquiry into his real claim to Brahminhood according to the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx21_ve2_348/><br><br>2. ''Gifts to Brahmins.''--The Dānastuti (‘Praise of gifts’) is a recognized feature of the Rigveda, and the greed of the poets for '''Dakṣiṇās,''' or sacrificial fees, is notorious. Vedic texts<ref name=fx22_ve2_348/> themselves recognize that the literature thence resulting ('''Nārā-  śaṃsī''') was often false to please the donors. It was, however, a rule<ref name=fx23_ve2_348/> that Brahmins should not accept what had been refused by others; this indicates a keen sense of the danger of cheapening their wares. So exclusively theirs was the right to receive gifts that the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx24_ve2_348/> has to explain how '''[[तरन्त|Taranta]]''' and '''[[पुरुमीळ्ह|Purumīḷha]]''' became able to accept gifts by composing a Rigvedic hymn.<ref name=fx25_ve2_348/> The exaggerations in the celebration of the gifts bestowed on the priests has the curious result of giving us a series of numerals of some interest ('''[[दशन्|Daśan]]'''). In some passages<ref name=fx26_ve2_348/> certain gifts--those of a horse or sheep--are forbidden, but this rule was not, it is clear, generally observed.<br><br>3. ''Immunities of Brahmins.''--The Brahmin claimed to be exempt from the ordinary exercise of the royal power. When a king gives all his land and what is on it to the priests, the gift does not cover the property of the Brahmin according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx27_ve2_348/> The king censures all, but not the Brahmin,<ref name=fx28_ve2_348/> nor can he safely oppress any Brahmin other than an ignorant priest.<ref name=fx29_ve2_348/> An arbitrator (or a witness) must decide (or speak) for a Brahmin against a non-Brahmin in a legal dispute.<ref name=fx30_ve2_348/><br><br>The Brahmin's proper food is the '''Soma,'''<ref name=fx31_ve2_348/> not '''[[सुरा|Surā]]'''<ref name=fx32_ve2_348/> or '''[[परिस्रुत्|Parisrut]],'''<ref name=fx33_ve2_348/> and he is forbidden to eat certain forms of flesh.<ref name=fx34_ve2_348/> On the other hand, he alone is allowed to eat the remains of the sacrifice,<ref name=fx35_ve2_348/> for no one else is sufficiently holy to consume food which the gods have eaten. Moreover, though he cannot be a physician,<ref name=fx36_ve2_348/> he helps the physician by being beside him  while he exercises his art.<ref name=fx37_ve2_348/> His wife<ref name=fx38_ve2_348/> and his cow<ref name=fx39_ve2_348/> are both sacred.<br><br>4. ''Legal Position of Brahmins.''--The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx40_ve2_348/> lays down a penalty of a hundred (the unit meant is unknown) for an insult to a Brahmin, and of a thousand for a blow; but if his blood is drawn, the penalty is a spiritual one. The only real murder is the slaying of a Brahmin according to the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx41_ve2_348/> The crime of slaying a Brahmin ranks above the sin of killing any other man, but below that of killing an embryo (''bhrūṇa'') in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]];<ref name=fx42_ve2_348/> the crime of slaying an embryo whose sex is uncertain is on a level with that of slaying a Brahmin.<ref name=fx43_ve2_348/> The murder of a Brahmin can be expiated only by the horse sacrifice,<ref name=fx44_ve2_348/> or by a lesser rite in the late [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx45_ve2_348/> The ritual slaying of a Brahmin is allowed in the later ceremonial,<ref name=fx46_ve2_348/> and hinted at in the curious legend of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]];'''<ref name=fx47_ve2_348/> and a [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] might be punished with death for treachery to his master.<ref name=fx48_ve2_348/><br><br>5. ''Purity of Birth.''--The importance of pure descent is seen in the stress laid on being a descendant of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] (''ārṣeya'').<ref name=fx49_ve2_348/> But, on the other hand, there are clear traces of another doctrine, which requires learning, and not physical descent, as the true criterion of Ṛṣihood.<ref name=fx50_ve2_348/> In agreement with this is the fact that '''[[सत्यकाम|Satyakāma]] [[जाबाल|Jābāla]]''' was received as a pupil, though his parentage was unknown, his mother being a slave girl who had been connected with several men,<ref name=fx51_ve2_348/> and that in the Śatapatha  [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx52_ve2_348/> the ceremony on acceptance as a pupil required merely the name of the pupil. So '''[[कवष|Kavaṣa]]''' is taunted in the Rigveda Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx53_ve2_348/> as being the son of a female slave ('''Dāsī'''), and '''[[वत्स|Vatsa]]''' cleared himself of a similar imputation by a fire ordeal.<ref name=fx54_ve2_348/> Moreover, a very simple rite was adequate to remove doubts as to origin.<ref name=fx55_ve2_348/> In these circumstances it is doubtful whether much value attaches to the '''[[प्रवर|Pravara]]''' lists in which the ancestors of the priest were invoked at the beginning of the sacrifice by the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] and the [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]] priests.<ref name=fx56_ve2_348/> Still, in many parts of the ritual the knowledge of two or more generations was needed,<ref name=fx57_ve2_348/> and in one ceremony<ref name=fx58_ve2_348/> ten ancestors who have drunk the Soma are required, but a literal performance of the rite is excused. Moreover, there are clear traces of ritual variations in schools, like those of the '''Vasiṣṭhas''' and the '''Viśvāmitras.'''<br><br>6. ''The Conduct of the Brahmin.''--The Brahmin was required to maintain a fair standard of excellence.<ref name=fx59_ve2_348/> He was to be kind to all<ref name=fx60_ve2_348/> and gentle,<ref name=fx61_ve2_348/> offering sacrifice and receiving gifts.<ref name=fx62_ve2_348/> Especial stress was laid on purity of speech;<ref name=fx63_ve2_348/> thus '''Viśvantara's''' excuse for excluding the '''Śyāparṇas''' from his retinue was their impure (''apūtā'') speech.<ref name=fx64_ve2_348/> Theirs was the craving for knowledge<ref name=fx65_ve2_348/> and the life of begging.<ref name=fx66_ve2_348/> False Brahmins are those who do not fulfil their duties<ref name=fx67_ve2_348/> (''cf.'' '''[[ब्रह्मबन्धु|Brahmabandhu]]''') .  But the penances for breach of duty are, in the Sūtras, of a very light and unimportant character.<ref name=fx68_ve2_348/><br><br>7. ''Brahminical Studies.''--The aim of the priest is to obtain pre-eminence in sacred knowledge (''brahma-varcasam''), as is stated in numerous passages of Vedic literature.<ref name=fx69_ve2_348/> Such distinction is not indeed confined to the Brahmin: the king has it also, but it is not really in a special manner appropriate to the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]].<ref name=fx70_ve2_348/> Many ritual acts are specified as leading to Brahmavarcasa,<ref name=fx71_ve2_348/> but more stress is laid on the study of the sacred texts: the importance of such study is repeatedly insisted upon.<ref name=fx72_ve2_348/><br><br>The technical name for study is [[स्वाध्याय|Svādhyāya]]: the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] is eloquent upon its advantages,<ref name=fx73_ve2_348/> and it is asserted that the joy of the learned [[श्रोत्रिय|Śrotriya]], or ‘student,’ is equal to the highest joy possible.<ref name=fx74_ve2_348/> '''[[नाक|Nāka]] [[मौद्गल्य|Maudgalya]]''' held that study and the teaching of others were the true penance (''[[तपस्|tapas]]'').<ref name=fx75_ve2_348/> The object was the ‘threefold knowledge’ (''trayī [[विद्या|vidyā]]''), that of the Ṛc, [[यजुस्|Yajus]], and Sāman,<ref name=fx76_ve2_348/> a student of all three Vedas being called ''tri-śukriya''<ref name=fx77_ve2_348/> or ''tri-[[शुक्र|śukra]],''<ref name=fx78_ve2_348/> ‘thrice pure.’ Other objects of study are enumerated in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx79_ve2_348/> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx80_ve2_348/> the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx81_ve2_348/> etc. (See '''[[इतिहास|Itihāsa]], [[पुराण|Purāṇa]]; [[गाथा|Gāthā]], [[नाराशंसी|Nārāśaṃsī]]; [[ब्रह्मोद्य|Brahmodya]]; [[अनुशासन|Anuśāsana]], [[अनुव्याख्यान|Anuvyākhyāna]], [[अन्वाख्यान|Anvākhyāna]], [[कल्प|Kalpa]],''' 2. '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]; [[विद्या|Vidyā]], [[क्षत्रविद्या|Kṣatravidyā]], [[देवजनविद्या|Devajanavidyā]], [[नक्षत्रविद्या|Nakṣatravidyā]], [[भूतविद्या|Bhūtavidyā]], [[सर्पविद्या|Sarpavidyā]]; [[अथर्वाङ्गिरसः|Atharvāṅgirasaḥ]], [[दैव|Daiva]], [[निधि|Nidhi]], [[पित्र्य|Pitrya]], Rāśi; [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],''' etc.) <br><br>Directions as to the exact place and time of study are given in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx82_ve2_348/> and in the Sūtras. If study is carried on in the village, it is to be done silently (''manasā''); if outside, aloud (''vācā'').<br><br>Learning is expected even from persons not normally competent as teachers, such as the '''Carakas,''' who are recognized in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx83_ve2_348/> as possible sources of information. Here, too, may be mentioned the cases of Brahmins learning from princes, though their absolute value is doubtful, for the priests would naturally represent their patrons as interested in their sacred science: it is thus not necessary to see in these notices any real and independent study on the part of the Kṣatriyas.<ref name=fx84_ve2_348/> '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]]''' learnt from '''[[जनक|Janaka]],'''<ref name=fx85_ve2_348/> '''[[उद्दालक आरुणि|Uddālaka Āruṇi]]''' and two other Brahmins from '''[[प्रवाहण जैवलि|Pravāhaṇa Jaivali]],'''<ref name=fx86_ve2_348/> '''[[दृप्तबालाकि गार्ग्य|Dṛptabālāki Gārgya]]''' from '''[[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]],'''<ref name=fx87_ve2_348/> and five Brahmins under the lead of Aruṇa from '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]] [[कैकेय|Kaikeya]].'''<ref name=fx88_ve2_348/> A few notices show the real educators of thought: wandering scholars went through the country<ref name=fx89_ve2_348/> and engaged in disputes and discussions in which a prize was staked by the disputants.<ref name=fx90_ve2_348/> Moreover, kings like [[जनक|Janaka]] offered rewards to the most learned of the Brahmins;<ref name=fx91_ve2_348/> [[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]] was jealous of his renown, and imitated his generosity. Again, learned women are several times mentioned in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx92_ve2_348/><br><br>A special form of disputation was the '''[[ब्रह्मोद्य|Brahmodya]],''' for which there was a regular place at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’)<ref name=fx93_ve2_348/> and at the Daśarātra (‘ten-day festival’).<ref name=fx94_ve2_348/> The reward of learning was the gaining of the title of Kavi or [[विप्र|Vipra]], ‘sage.’<ref name=fx95_ve2_348/> <br><br>8. ''The Functions of the Brahmin.''--The Brahmin was required not merely to practise individual culture, but also to give others the advantage of his skill, either as a teacher or as a sacrificial priest, or as a [[पुरोहित|Purohita]].<br><br>As a teacher the Brahmin has, of course, the special duty of instructing his own son in both study and sacrificial ritual.<ref name=fx96_ve2_348/> The texts give examples of this, such as [[आरुणि|Āruṇi]] and '''[[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]],'''<ref name=fx97_ve2_348/> or mythically Varuṇa and [[भृगु|Bhṛgu]].<ref name=fx98_ve2_348/> This fact also appears from some of the names in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx99_ve2_348/> of the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]] and the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx100_ve2_348/> On the other hand, these Vaṃśas and the Vaṃśas of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] show that a father often preferred to let his son study under a famous teacher. The relation of pupil and teacher is described under '''[[ब्रह्मचर्य|Brahmacarya]].''' A teacher might take several pupils,<ref name=fx101_ve2_348/> and he was bound to teach them with all his heart and soul.<ref name=fx102_ve2_348/> He was bound to reveal everything to his pupil, at any rate to one who was staying with him for a year (''[[संवत्सर|saṃvatsara]]-vāsin''),<ref name=fx103_ve2_348/> an expression which shows, as was natural, that a pupil might easily change teachers. But, nevertheless, certain cases of learning kept secret and only revealed to special persons are enumerated.<ref name=fx104_ve2_348/> The exact times and modes of teaching are elaborately laid down in the Sūtras,<ref name=fx105_ve2_348/> but not in the earlier texts.<br><br>As priest the Brahmin operated in all the greater sacrifices; the simple domestic (''[[गृह्य|gṛhya]]'') rites could normally be performed without his help, but not the more important rites (''śrauta'').  The number varied: the ritual literature requires sixteen priests to be employed at the greatest sacrifices (see '''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]]'''), but other rites could be accomplished with four,<ref name=fx106_ve2_348/> five,<ref name=fx107_ve2_348/> six,<ref name=fx108_ve2_348/> seven,<ref name=fx109_ve2_348/> or ten<ref name=fx110_ve2_348/> priests. Again, the Kauṣītakins<ref name=fx111_ve2_348/> had a seventeenth priest beside the usual sixteen, the [[सदस्य|Sadasya]], so called because he watched the performance from the [[सदस्|Sadas]], ‘seat.’ In one rite, the Sattra (‘sacrificial session’) of the serpents, the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx112_ve2_348/> adds three more to the sixteen, a second Unnetṛ, an Abhigara, and an Apagara. The later ritual places the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] at the head of all the priests, but this is probably not the early view (see '''[[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]]''').<br><br>The sacrifice ensured, if properly performed, primarily the advantages of the sacrificer (''yajamāna''),<ref name=fx113_ve2_348/> but the priest shared in the profit, besides securing the '''Dakṣiṇās.''' Disputes between sacrificers and the priests were not rare, as in the case of '''Viśvantara''' and the '''Śyāparṇas,'''<ref name=fx114_ve2_348/> or '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]]''' and the '''Asitamṛgas;'''<ref name=fx115_ve2_348/> and the '''Aiṣāvīras''' are referred to as undersirable priests.<ref name=fx116_ve2_348/> Moreover, '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' once held the post of [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] to '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' but gave place to '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]].''' <br><br>The position of '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]]''' differed considerably from that of the ordinary priest, for the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] not merely might officiate at the sacrifice, but was the officiator in all the private sacrifices of his king. Hence he could, and undoubtedly sometimes did, obtain great influence over his master in matters of secular importance; and the power of the priesthood in political as opposed to domestic and religious matters, no doubt rested on the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]].<br><br>There is no recognition in Vedic literature of the rule later prevailing by which, after spending part of his life as a Brahmacārin, and part as a householder, the Brahmin became an ascetic<ref name=fx117_ve2_348/> (later divided into the two stages of Vānaprastha, ‘forest-dweller,’ and Saṃnyāsin, ‘mystic’). Yājñavalkya's case<ref name=fx118_ve2_348/> shows that study of the Absolute might empty life of all its content for the sage, and drive him to abandon wife and family. In Buddhist times the same phenomenon is seen<ref name=fx119_ve2_348/> applying to other than Brahmins. The Buddhist texts are here confirmed in some degree by the Greek authorities.<ref name=fx120_ve2_348/> The practice bears a certain resemblance to the habit of kings, in the Epic tradition,<ref name=fx121_ve2_348/> of retiring to the forest when active life is over.<br><br>From the Greek authorities<ref name=fx122_ve2_348/> it also appears--what is certainly the case in the Buddhist literature<ref name=fx123_ve2_348/> --that Brahmins practised the most diverse occupations. It is difficult to say how far this was true for the Vedic period. The analogy of the Druids<ref name=fx124_ve2_348/> --in some respects very close--suggests that the Brahmins may have been mainly confined to their professional tasks, including all the learned professions such as astronomy<ref name=fx125_ve2_348/>  and so forth. This is not contradicted by any Vedic evidence, for instance, the poet of a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx126_ve2_348/> says he is a poet, his father a physician ('''[[भिषज्|Bhiṣaj]]'''), and his mother a grinder of corn ('''[[उपल-प्रक्षिणी|Upala-prakṣiṇī]]'''). This would seem to show that a Brahmin could be a doctor, while his wife would perform the ordinary household duties. So a [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] could perhaps take the field to assist the king by prayer, as [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]],<ref name=fx127_ve2_348/> and later on [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]<ref name=fx128_ve2_348/> do, but this does not show that priests normally fought. Nor do they seem normally to have been agriculturists or merchants. On the other hand, they kept cattle: a Brahmacārin's duty was to watch his master's cattle.<ref name=fx129_ve2_348/> It is therefore needless to suppose that they could not, and did not, on occasion turn to agricultural or mercantile pursuits, as they certainly did later. But it must be remembered that in all probability there was more purity of blood, and less pressure of life, among the Brahmins of the Vedic age than later in Buddhist times, when the Vedic sacrificial apparatus was falling into grave disrepute.<br><br>It is clear that the Brahmins, whatever their defects, represented the intellectual side of Vedic life, and that the Kṣatriyas, if they played a part in that life, did so only in a secondary degree, and to a minor extent. It is natural to suppose that the Brahmins also composed ballads, the precursors of the epic; for though none such have survived, a few stanzas of this character, celebrating the generosity of patrons, have been preserved by being embedded in priestly compositions. A legend in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx130_ve2_348/> shows clearly that the Brahmins regarded civilization as being spread by them only:  '''[[कोसल|Kosala]]''' and '''[[विदेह|Videha]],''' no doubt settled by Āryan tribes, are only rendered civilized and habitable by the influence of pious Brahmins. We need not doubt that the non-Brahminical tribes (see '''[[व्रात्य|Vrātya]]''') had attained intellectual as well as material civilization, but it is reasonable to assume that their civilization was inferior to that of the Brahmins, for the history of Hinduism is the conquest by the Brahmins--not by arms, but by mind--of the tribes Āryan and non-Āryan originally beyond the pale.<br>

ब्राह्मण
<u>'''2. Brāhmaṇa,'''</u> ‘religious explanation,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_349/> is the title of a class of books which as such are only mentioned in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_349/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx3_ve2_349/> and then in the Sūtras, where the names of the Brāhmaṇas occur, showing that literary works were in existence.<br>

ब्राह्मण
<u>'''3. Brāhmaṇa'''</u> is taken by Roth in the St. Petersburg Dictionary<ref name=fx1_ve2_350/> to mean the ‘Soma cup of the Brahman’ in two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_350/> and one of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_350/><br>

ब्राह्मणाच्-छंसिन्
<u>'''Brāhmaṇāc-chaṃsin'''</u> (‘reciting after the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]--''i.e.,'' Brahman’) is the name of a priest in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_351/> In the technical division of the sacrificial priests ('''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]]''') he is classed with the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_351/> but it is clear that he was really a [[होत्रक|Hotraka]] or assistant of the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_351/> According to Oldenberg,<ref name=fx4_ve2_351/> he was known to the Rigveda as '''[[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]].''' This is denied by Geldner,<ref name=fx5_ve2_351/> who sees in [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] merely the ‘superintending priest’ or the ‘priest.’ <br>

ब्लेष्क
<u>'''Bleṣka'''</u> in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_352/> denotes a rope or noose for strangling. It is spelt [[व्लेष्क|Vleṣka]] in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_352/><br>

भग
<u>'''Bhaga'''</u> denotes a part of the chariot in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_353/> according to Hillebrandt.<ref name=fx2_ve2_353/><br>

भगिनी
<u>'''Bhaginī,'''</u> ‘sister,’ literally the ‘fortunate one’ in so far as she has a brother, occurs in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (iii. 6).<br>

भगी-रथ ऐक्ष्वाक
<u>'''Bhagī-[[रथ|ratha]] Aikṣvāka'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[इक्ष्वाकु|Ikṣvāku]]'''’) is the name of a king in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iv. 6, 1. 2). It is important to note that he is regarded as being on friendly terms with the '''Kuru-Pañcālas,''' which points to the Ikṣvākus being allied to that people, and not belonging (as is the case in the Buddhist books) to the east of India.<br>

भङ्ग
<u>'''Bhaṅga,'''</u> ‘hemp,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_356/> In the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_356/> it is an epithet of Soma, presumably<ref name=fx3_ve2_356/> in the sense of ‘intoxicating,’ which then came to designate hemp.<ref name=fx4_ve2_356/><br>

भङ्गाश्विन
<u>'''Bhaṅgāśvina'''</u> is the name of the father of '''Ṛtuparna''' in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_357/> In the Mahābhārata<ref name=fx2_ve2_357/> he is called Bhāṅgāsuri. In the Āpastamba Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_357/> mention is made of [[ऋतुपर्ण|Ṛtuparṇa]]-Kayovadhī as the Bhaṅgyaśvinau. <br>

भङ्ग्य-श्रवस्
<u>'''Bhaṅgya-śravas'''</u> is the name of a man in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve2_358/><br>

भजे-रथ
<u>'''Bhaje-ratha'''</u> is mentioned in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_359/> where Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_359/> thinks a place-name is meant. Griffith<ref name=fx3_ve2_359/> is doubtful whether the word is the name of a place or a man. Roth<ref name=fx4_ve2_359/> was inclined to see a corruption of the text.<ref name=fx5_ve2_359/> ''Cf.'' '''Bhagīratha.'''<br>

भद्र-पदा
<u>'''Bhadra-padā.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

भद्र-सेन आजातशत्रव
<u>'''Bhadra-sena Ājātaśatrava'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]]'''’) is the name of a man, presumably a prince, whom '''Uddālaka''' is said in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 5, 5, 14) to have bewitched.<br>

भय-द आसमात्य
<u>'''Bhaya-da Āsamātya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''Asamāti'''’) is the name of a king in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_362/> Oertel,<ref name=fx2_ve2_362/> however, seems to take the name as Abhayada, but this is not probable, for Bhayada is a name in the Purāṇas.<br>

भयमान
<u>'''Bhayamāna'''</u> is, according to Sāyaṇa, the name of a man in one hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_363/> which is ascribed by the Anukramaṇī (Index) to his authorship. The interpretation is, however, uncertain.<br>

भरत
<u>'''Bharata'''</u> is the name of a people of great importance in the Rigveda and the later literature. In the Rigveda they appear prominently in the third and seventh Maṇḍalas in connexion  with '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' and the '''Tṛtsus,'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_364/> while in the sixth Maṇḍala they are associated with '''Divodāsa.'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_364/> In one passage<ref name=fx3_ve2_364/> the Bharatas are, like the Tṛtsus, enemies of the '''Pūrus:''' there can be little doubt that Ludwig's view of the identity of the Bharatas and and Tṛtsus is practically correct. More precisely Oldenberg<ref name=fx5_ve2_364/> considers that the Tṛtsus are the '''Vasiṣṭhas,''' the family singers of the Bharatas; while Geldner<ref name=fx6_ve2_364/> recognizes, with perhaps more probability, in the Tṛtsus the royal family of the Bharatas. That the Tṛtsus and Bharatas were enemies, as Zimmer<ref name=fx7_ve2_364/> holds, is most improbable even on geographical grounds, for the Tṛtsus in Zimmer's view<ref name=fx8_ve2_364/> occupied the country to the east of the '''[[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]]''' (Ravi), and the Bharatas must therefore be regarded as coming against the Tṛtsus from the west, whereas the Rigveda<ref name=fx9_ve2_364/> recognizes two [[भरत|Bharata]] chiefs on the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]], [[आपया|Āpayā]],''' and '''[[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]]'''--that is, in the holy land of India, the '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]].''' Hillebrandt<ref name=fx10_ve2_364/> sees in the connexion of the Tṛtsus and the Bharatas a fusion of two tribes; but this is not supported by any evidence beyond the fact that in his opinion some such theory is needed to explain Divodāsa's appearing in connexion with the '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]]''' family, while [[सुदास्|Sudās]], his son,<br><br>^4 Translation of the Rigveda, 3, 172 ''et seq.''  or perhaps grandson (''cf.'' '''[[पिजवन|Pijavana]]'''), is connected with the Vasiṣṭhas and the '''Viśvāmitras.'''<br><br>In the later literature the Bharatas appear as especially famous. The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx11_ve2_364/> mentions [[भरत|Bharata]] [[दौःषन्ति|Dauḥṣanti]] as a king, sacrificer of the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) and '''[[शतानीक सात्राजित|Śatānīka Sātrājita]],''' as another [[भरत|Bharata]] who offered that sacrifice. The [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx12_ve2_364/> mentions [[भरत|Bharata]] [[दौःषन्ति|Dauḥṣanti]] as receiving the kingly coronation from '''[[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]] [[मामतेय|Māmateya]],''' and Śatānīka as being consecrated by '''[[सोमशुष्मन् वाजरत्नायन|Somaśuṣman Vājaratnāyana]],''' a priest whose name is of quite late origin. The geographical position of the [[भरत|Bharata]] people is clearly shown by the fact that the [[भरत|Bharata]] kings win victories over the '''Kāśis,''' and make offerings on the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]''' (Jumna) and '''[[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]]''' (Ganges).<ref name=fx13_ve2_364/> Moreover, in the formula of the king's proclamation for the people, the variants recorded<ref name=fx14_ve2_364/> include ''Kuravaḥ, Pañcālāḥ, Kuru-Pañcālāḥ,'' and ''Bharatāḥ;'' and the Mahābhārata consistently recognizes the royal family of the '''Kurus''' as a [[भरत|Bharata]] family.<ref name=fx15_ve2_364/> It is therefore extremely probable that Oldenberg<ref name=fx16_ve2_364/> is right in holding that the Bharatas in the times of the Brāhmaṇas were merging in the Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] people.<br><br>The ritual practices of the Bharatas are repeatedly mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx17_ve2_364/> the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx18_ve2_364/> the  Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx19_ve2_364/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx20_ve2_364/> Already in the Rigveda<ref name=fx21_ve2_364/> there is mention made of Agni [[भारत|Bhārata]] (‘of the Bharatas’). In the Āprī hymns<ref name=fx22_ve2_364/> occurs a goddess Bhāratī, the personified divine protective power of the Bharatas: her association in the hymns with [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] reflects the connexion of the Bharatas with the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx9_ve2_364/> Again, in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx23_ve2_364/> Agni is referred to as ''[[ब्राह्मण|brāhmaṇa]] [[भारत|Bhārata]],'' ‘priest of the Bharatas,’ and is invited to dispose of the offering ''Manuṣvat Bharatavat,'' ‘like Manu,’ ‘like [[भरत|Bharata]].’<ref name=fx24_ve2_364/><br><br>In one or two passages<ref name=fx25_ve2_364/> [[सुदास्|Sudās]] or Divodāsa and, on the other hand, [[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]] or [[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] appear in a friendly relation. Possibly this points, as Oldenberg<ref name=fx26_ve2_364/> suggests, to the union of Bharatas and Pūrus with the Kurus.<br><br>A [[भरत|Bharata]] is referred to in the fifth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda:<ref name=fx27_ve2_364/> who he was is uncertain.<br>

भरद्-वाज
<u>'''Bharad-vāja'''</u> is the name of the reputed<ref name=fx1_ve2_365/> author of the sixth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda. The attribution is so far correct that [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_365/> and the Bharadvājas<ref name=fx3_ve2_365/> are repeatedly mentioned as singers in that Maṇḍala. Judging by the tone of the references to [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]], he can hardly be deemed to have been a contemporary of any of the hymns.<ref name=fx4_ve2_365/> According to the Pañcaviṃśa  [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx5_ve2_365/> he was the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of '''Divodāsa.''' This interpretation is to be preferred to that of Roth,<ref name=fx6_ve2_365/> who suggests that he and Divodāsa were identical. His connexion with the house of Divodāsa also appears from the statement of the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx7_ve2_365/> that [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]] gave '''[[प्रतर्दन|Pratardana]]''' the kingdom. It is unnecessary to suppose that the same [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]] was meant in both cases, and that [[प्रतर्दन|Pratardana]] was a son of Divodāsa: the later Saṃhitās refer to [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]], like the other great sages, irrespective of chronology.<br><br>The Bharadvājas in their poems mention '''[[बृबु|Bṛbu]], [[बृसय|Bṛsaya]],''' and the '''Pārāvatas.'''<ref name=fx8_ve2_365/> Hillebrandt<ref name=fx9_ve2_365/> has pointed out that they are also connected with the '''Sṛñjayas.''' In particular, the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx10_ve2_365/> mentions that [[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]] gained largesse from '''[[प्रस्तोक|Prastoka]] [[सार्ञ्जय|Sārñjaya]]''' and [[बृबु|Bṛbu]]. But it is very doubtful if it is correct to place all these people and Divodāsa in Arachosia and Drangiana.<br><br>[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]] as an author and a seer is frequently referred to in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx11_ve2_365/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx12_ve2_365/><br>

भरन्त्
<u>'''Bharant,'''</u> ‘bearing,’ in the plural denotes in one passage of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_366/> according to Bo7htlingk,<ref name=fx2_ve2_366/> following Sāyaṇa, ‘the warrior caste,’ but the sense is not certain. Weber<ref name=fx3_ve2_366/> was inclined to see a reference to the Bharatas, though the form of the word is that of the present participle.<ref name=fx4_ve2_366/><br>

भरूजी
<u>'''Bharūjī'''</u> in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_367/> may denote, according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_367/> a noxious animal. <br>

भर्तृ
<u>'''Bhartṛ,'''</u> besides having the literal sense of ‘bearer,’ means ‘supporter’ or ‘master’ in the older literature;<ref name=fx1_ve2_368/> but it is doubtful whether the sense of ‘husband’ is ever found there. In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_368/> ‘husband’ is certainly the most natural sense, but, as Delbrück<ref name=fx3_ve2_368/> correctly remarks, even there ‘father’ may be meant, since ‘mother’ is here and there<ref name=fx4_ve2_368/> called Bhartrī.<br>

भलानस्
<u>'''Bhalānas,'''</u> plural, is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_369/> of one of the five tribes, '''Pakthas,''' Bhalānases, '''Alinas, Viṣāṇins,''' and '''Śivas,''' who are mentioned as ranged on the side<ref name=fx2_ve2_369/> of the enemies of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' in the battle of the ten kings ('''[[दाशराज्ञ|Dāśarājña]]'''), not opposed to them, as Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve2_369/> and at one time Zimmer,<ref name=fx4_ve2_369/> thought. Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve2_369/> suggests as their original home East Kabulistan, comparing the name of the Bolan pass. This seems a reasonably probable view.<br>

भव-त्रात शायस्थि
<u>'''Bhava-trāta Śāyasthi'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_370/><br>

भस्त्रा
<u>'''Bhastrā'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 1, 2, 7; 6, 3, 16) denotes a leathern bottle or pouch.<br>

भाकुरि
<u>'''Bhākuri.'''</u> See '''[[बेकुरा|Bekurā]].''' <br>

भाग-दुघ
<u>'''Bhāga-dugha,'''</u> ‘dealer out of portions,’ ‘distributor,’ is the name of one of the king's ‘jewels’ ('''[[रत्निन्|Ratnin]]''') in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_373/> and Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_373/> What his functions exactly were is uncertain. Sāyaṇa in some places<ref name=fx3_ve2_373/> renders the word by ‘tax-collector’ but in others<ref name=fx4_ve2_373/> as ‘carver,’ thus making this functionary either a revenue officer or a mere court official.<br>

भाग-वित्ति
<u>'''Bhāga-vitti'''</u> (‘descendant of Bhagavitta’) is the patronymic of a teacher called Cūḍa<ref name=fx1_ve2_374/> or Cūla<ref name=fx2_ve2_374/> in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<br>

भाडितायन
<u>'''Bhāḍitāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Bhaḍita,’ is the patronymic of '''Śākadāsa''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_375/><br>

भानुमन्त् औपमन्यव
<u>'''Bhānumant Aupamanyava'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[उपमन्यु|Upamanyu]]'''’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''Ānandaja,''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_376/><br>

भाय-जात्य
<u>'''Bhāya-jātya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Bhayajāta,’ is the patronymic of '''Nikothaka''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_377/><br>

भारत
<u>'''Bhārata.'''</u> See '''[[भरत|Bharata]].'''<br>

भारद्-वाज
<u>'''Bhārad-vāja,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]],'''’ is the patronymic of many teachers. In the Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]], Bhāradvājas are mentioned as  pupils of [[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_379/> '''[[पाराशर्य|Pārāśarya]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_379/> '''Balākākauśika,'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_379/> '''[[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]],'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_379/> '''[[आसुरायण|Āsurāyaṇa]],'''<ref name=fx5_ve2_379/> and '''[[बैजवापायन|Baijavāpāyana]].'''<ref name=fx6_ve2_379/> A [[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]] occurs in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx7_ve2_379/> and '''[[शूष वाह्नेय|Śūṣa Vāhneya]]''' is mentioned as a [[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]] in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx8_ve2_379/><br>

भारद्वाजायन
<u>'''Bhāradvājāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]],'''’ is the patronymic of a teacher in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_380/><br>

भारद्वाजी-पुत्र
<u>'''Bhāradvājī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]],'''’ is the metronymic of several teachers in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]], pupils of '''Pāraśarīputra,'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_381/> '''[[पैङ्गीपुत्र|Paiṅgīputra]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_381/> and '''[[वात्सीमाण्डवीपुत्र|Vātsīmāṇḍavīputra]]'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_381/> respectively.<br>

भार्गव
<u>'''Bhārgava,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[भृगु|Bhṛgu]],'''’ is the patronymic of several teachers, including '''[[च्यवन|Cyavana]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_382/> and '''[[गृत्समद|Gṛtsamada]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_382/> Other Bhārgavas are also mentioned without dication of their personal names.<ref name=fx3_ve2_382/><br>

भार्गायण
<u>'''Bhārgāyaṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of Bharga,’ is the patronymic of '''Sutvan''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 28).<br>

भार्म्य्-अश्व
<u>'''Bhārmy-aśva,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[भृम्य्अश्व|Bhṛmyaśva]],’ is the patronymic of '''[[मुद्गल|Mudgala]]''' in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (ix. 23) and the Brhaddevatā (vi. 46; viii. 12). <br>

भार्या
<u>'''Bhāryā,'''</u> later a common expression for ‘wife,’ does not occur in that sense at all in the Saṃhitās. It first appears, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_385/> where, however, Delbrück<ref name=fx2_ve2_385/> suggests that merely a member of the household (‘who is to be maintained’) may be meant. In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_385/> however, the two wives of [[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]] are so designated.<br>

भालन्दन
<u>'''Bhālandana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Bhalandana,’ is the patronymic of '''Vatsaprī''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,’ the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve2_386/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_386/><br><br>^1 v. 2, 1, 6.<br>

भालुकी-पुत्र
<u>'''Bhālukī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of Bhālukī,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[क्रौञ्चिकीपुत्र|Krauñcikīputra]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_387/> or of '''[[प्राचीनयोगीपुत्र|Prācīnayogīputra]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_387/> in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<br>

भाल्ल
<u>'''Bhālla'''</u> is the name or patronymic of a teacher who bears the patronymic [[प्रातृद|Prātṛda]] in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 31, 4).<br>

भाल्लवि
<u>'''Bhāllavi'''</u> is the name of a school mentioned as authorities in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 2, 4).<br>

भाल्लविन्
<u>'''Bhāllavin,'''</u> ‘pupil of Bhallavin,’ is the name of a school of teachers mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_390/> <br>

भाल्लवेय
<u>'''Bhāllaveya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[भाल्लवि|Bhāllavi]],'''’<ref name=fx1_ve2_391/> is the patronymic of '''Indradyumna''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_391/> and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_391/> Probably the same person is meant by the [[भाल्लवेय|Bhāllaveya]], who is cited frequently as an authority in the same [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_391/><br>

भावयव्य
<u>'''Bhāvayavya.'''</u> See '''[[भाव्य|Bhāvya]].'''<br>

भाव्य
<u>'''Bhāvya'''</u> is the name of a patron, as it seems, in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_393/> In the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_393/> the form given is [[भावयव्य|Bhāvayavya]], being a patronymic of '''Svanaya,''' who is the patron of '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]].''' This combination is borne out by the Rigveda, where [[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]] and Svanaya are mentioned in the same verse,<ref name=fx3_ve2_393/> while Svanaya must be meant in the verse of the same hymn,<ref name=fx4_ve2_393/> where [[भाव्य|Bhāvya]] is mentioned as ‘living on the Sindhu’ (Indus). Roth's<ref name=fx5_ve2_393/> view that [[भाव्य|Bhāvya]] here is perhaps a gerundive meaning to be ‘reverenced’ is not probable. Ludwig<ref name=fx6_ve2_393/> thinks Svanaya was connected with the '''Nahuṣas.'''<br>

भाषा
<u>'''Bhāṣā'''</u> in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_394/> and Pāṇini<ref name=fx2_ve2_394/> denotes the ordinary speech of the day as opposed to Vedic language. ''Cf.'' '''[[वाच्|Vāc]].'''<br>

भास
<u>'''Bhāsa'''</u> is the name of a bird of prey in the Adbhuta [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_395/> and often in the Epic. <br>

भिक्षा
<u>'''Bhikṣā,'''</u> ‘begging,’ is one of the duties of the '''Brahmacārin''' according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_396/> The word has also the sense of ‘alms,’ as that which is obtained by begging, in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_396/> According to the St. Petersburg Dictionary,<ref name=fx3_ve2_396/> it has this sense in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_396/> also, but the correct reading there is probably '''[[आमिक्षा|Āmikṣā]].'''<br>

भिक्षु
<u>'''Bhikṣu,'''</u> ‘beggar,’ is a term not found in Vedic literature. The begging of the '''Brahmacārin''' is quite a different thing from the duties of the [[भिक्षु|Bhikṣu]] in the later system of the Āśramas (religious stages of life), when the Brahmin in the last stage of his life, after leaving his home and family, lives on alms alone. See 1. '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].'''<br>

भित्ति
<u>'''Bhitti'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_398/> denotes a mat made of split reeds.<br>

भिषज्
<u>'''Bhiṣaj,'''</u> ‘physician,’ is a word of common occurrence in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_399/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_399/> There is no trace whatever in the former text of the profession being held in disrepute: the Aśvins,<ref name=fx3_ve2_399/> Varuṇa,<ref name=fx4_ve2_399/> and Rudra<ref name=fx5_ve2_399/> are all called physicians. On the other hand, in the [[धर्म|Dharma]] literature<ref name=fx6_ve2_399/> this profession is utterly  despised. This dislike is found as early as the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx7_ve2_399/> where the Aśvins are condemned because of their having to do with the practice of medicine (''[[भेषज|bheṣaja]]''), on the ground that it brings them too much among men, an allusion to the caste dislike of promiscuous contact.<br><br>The Rigveda<ref name=fx8_ve2_399/> contains a hymn in which a physician celebrates his plants and their healing powers. Moreover, wonderful cures are referred to as performed by the Aśvins: the healing of the lame<ref name=fx9_ve2_399/> and of the blind;<ref name=fx10_ve2_399/> the rejuvenation of the aged '''[[च्यवन|Cyavana]]'''<ref name=fx11_ve2_399/> and of '''Puraṃdhi's''' husband;<ref name=fx12_ve2_399/> the giving of an iron leg (''jaṅghā āyasī'') to '''[[विश्पला|Viśpalā]],'''<ref name=fx13_ve2_399/> a deed only more wonderful if we assume that [[विश्पला|Viśpalā]] was a mare, as has been suggested by Pischel.<ref name=fx14_ve2_399/> It would in all probability be a mistake to assume<ref name=fx15_ve2_399/> that the Vedic Indians had any surgical skill: they no doubt applied simples to wounds,<ref name=fx16_ve2_399/> but both their medicien and their surgery must have been most primitive. All that the Atharvaveda shows in regard to medicine is the use of herbs combined with spells,<ref name=fx17_ve2_399/> and of water (''cf.'' '''Jalāṣa'''), remedies Indo-European in character, but not of much scientific value. On the other hand, the knowledge of anatomy shown (see '''[[शरीर|Śarīra]]'''), though betraying grave inaccuracies, is not altogether insignificant; but that was due no doubt mainly to the practice of dissecting animals at the sacrifice.<br><br>There is some evidence in the Rigveda<ref name=fx18_ve2_399/> that the practice of medicine was already a profession; this is supported by the inclusion of a physician in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx19_ve2_399/> According to  Bloomfield,<ref name=fx20_ve2_399/> a hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx21_ve2_399/> contains a physician's deprecation of the use of home-made remedies instead of reliance on his professional training.<br>

भिषज् आथर्वण
<u>'''2. Bhiṣaj Ātharvaṇa'''</u> is the name of a mythic physician mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_400/><br>

भीम वैदर्भ
<u>'''Bhīma Vaidarbha'''</u> (‘prince of Vidarbha’) is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 34) as having received instruction regarding the substitute for the Soma juice, through a succession of teachers, from '''[[पर्वत|Parvata]]''' and '''[[नारद|Nārada]].'''<br>

भीम-सेन
<u>'''Bhīma-sena'''</u> is the name of one of the brothers of '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]],''' the '''Pārikṣitīyas,''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_402/><br>

भुज्यु
<u>'''1. Bhujyu'''</u> denotes, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, an ‘adder’ in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_403/> and one of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_403/> But the sense is uncertain in all these passages.<br>

भुज्यु
<u>'''2. Bhujyu'''</u> is the name of a man, son of '''[[तुग्र|Tugra]],''' who is repeatedly mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_404/> as saved from the deep by the Aśvins. According to Bühler,<ref name=fx2_ve2_404/> the passages refer to  [[भुज्यु|Bhujyu]] being saved from shipwreck during a voyage in the Indian Ocean, but the evidence is inadequate to support this conclusion. ''Cf.'' '''[[सम्उद्र|Samudra]].'''<br>

भुज्यु लाह्यायनि
<u>'''Bhujyu Lāhyāyani'''</u> (‘descendant of Lahyāyana’) is the name of a teacher, a contemporary of '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]],''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iii. 3, 1).<br>

भुरिज्
<u>'''Bhurij'''</u> (used in the dual only) is a word of somewhat doubtful sense. Roth<ref name=fx1_ve2_406/> regarded it as meaning in some passages<ref name=fx2_ve2_406/> ‘scissors,’ and in others<ref name=fx3_ve2_406/> an apparatus consisting of two arms used by the chariot-maker for fixing the wood at which he worked, being of the nature of a carpenter's vice. See also '''Ksura'''<br>

भूत-विद्या
<u>'''Bhūta-vidyā'''</u> is one of the sciences enumerated in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_407/> It seems to mean the ‘science of creatures’ that trouble men, and of the means of warding them off, ‘demonology.’<br>

भूत-वीर
<u>'''Bhūta-vīra'''</u> is the name of a family of priests who, according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_408/> were employed by '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]]''' to the exclusion of the '''Kaśyapas.''' A family of the latter, the '''Asitamṛgas,''' however, won back the favour of [[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]], and ousted the Bhūtavīras. <br>

भूतांश
<u>'''Bhūtāṃśa'''</u> is in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_409/> the name of a poet, a descendant of [[कश्यप|Kaśyapa]].<br>

भूति
<u>'''Bhūti'''</u> is the term used in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_410/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_410/> for ‘prosperity.’<br>

भूमि
<u>'''Bhūmi'''</u> or '''Bhūmī''' is a common word for ‘earth’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_411/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_411/> being practically a synonym of '''[[पृथिवी|Pṛthivī]].''' It is also used of the land given by the god to the Āryan,<ref name=fx3_ve2_411/> and of grants of land.<ref name=fx4_ve2_411/><br>

भूमि-दुन्दुभि
<u>'''Bhūmi-dundubhi,'''</u> ‘earth drum,’ denotes a pit covered with a hide used at the Mahāvrata rite, and mentioned in the Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_412/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_412/><br>

भूमि-पाश
<u>'''Bhūmi-pāśa,'''</u> ‘earth net,’ is the name of a plant in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], probably some sort of creeper.<br><br>^1 xiii. 8, 1, 16. ''Cf.'' Eggeling, ''Sacred Books of the East,'' 44, 427, n. 1.<br>

भृगवाण
<u>'''Bhṛgavāṇa'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_414/> apparently<ref name=fx2_ve2_414/> as a name of a man who is called '''Śobha.''' Ludwig,<ref name=fx3_ve2_414/> however, thinks that his name was '''[[घोष|Ghoṣa]].''' Elsewhere the word appears as an epithet of Agni, doubtless in allusion to his cult by the '''Bhṛgus.''' <br>

भृगु
<u>'''Bhṛgu'''</u> is a sage of almost entirely mythical character in the Rigveda and later. He counts as a son of Varuṇa,<ref name=fx1_ve2_415/> bearing the patronymic [[वारुणि|Vāruṇi]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_415/> In the plural the Bhṛgus are repeatedly<ref name=fx3_ve2_415/> alluded to as devoted to the fire cult. They are clearly<ref name=fx4_ve2_415/> no more than a group of ancient priests and ancestors with an eponymous [[भृगु|Bhṛgu]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_415/> in the Rigveda, except in three passages,<ref name=fx6_ve2_415/> where they are evidently regarded as an historic family. It is not clear, however, whether they were priests or warriors: in the battle of the ten kings the Bhṛgus appear with the '''Druhyus,''' perhaps as their priests, but this is not certain.<ref name=fx7_ve2_415/><br><br>In the later literature the Bhṛgus are a real family, with subdivisions like the '''Aitaśāyana,''' according to the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx8_ve2_415/> The Bhṛgus are mentioned as priests in connexion with various rites, such as the Agnisthāpana<ref name=fx9_ve2_415/> and the Daśapeyakratu.<ref name=fx10_ve2_415/> In many passages they are conjoined with the '''Aṅgirases.'''<ref name=fx11_ve2_415/> the close association of the two families is shown  by the fact that [[च्यवन|Cyavana]] is called either a [[भार्गव|Bhārgava]] or an [[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]] in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx12_ve2_415/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx13_ve2_415/> the name of [[भृगु|Bhṛgu]] is selected to exemplify the dangers incurred by the oppressors of Brahmans: the '''[[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]] Vaitahavyas''' perish in consequence of an attack on [[भृगु|Bhṛgu]]. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx14_ve2_415/> also [[भृगु|Bhṛgu]] has this representative character. ''Cf.'' '''[[भृगवाण|Bhṛgavāṇa]]''' and '''[[भार्गव|Bhārgava]].'''<br>

भृङ्गा
<u>'''Bhṛṅgā'''</u> is the name of a species of bee, later specified as large and black, in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_416/> and the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx2_ve2_416/> which include it in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’).<br>

भृम्य्-अश्व
<u>'''Bhṛmy-aśva'''</u> is the name of the father of '''[[मुद्गल|Mudgala]]''' in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (ix. 24).<br>

भेकुरि
<u>'''Bhekuri.'''</u> See '''[[बेकुरा|Bekurā]].'''<br>

भेद
<u>'''1. Bheda,'''</u> one of the enemies of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' and the '''TṛtsuBharatas,''' was defeated by the former in the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]''' (Jumna),<ref name=fx1_ve2_419/> apparently in a second conflict fought after the battle of the ten kings, in which [[सुदास्|Sudās]] successfully defended his western frontier against the confederate foes. The '''Ajas, Śigrus,''' and '''Yakṣus,''' who are mentioned as also defeated, may have been united under his leadership if he was a king; or the Bhedas may have been a separate people, as Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_419/> thinks. Hopkins'<ref name=fx3_ve2_419/> opinion that the defeat was on the '''[[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]],''' [[यमुना|Yamunā]] being another  name of that stream, is most improbable; nor is the view that [[भेद|Bheda]] was one of the ten kings essential.<ref name=fx4_ve2_419/> ''Cf.'' '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]].'''<br>

भेद
<u>'''2. Bheda'''</u> is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_420/> as having come to a bad end because he refused a cow (''[[वशा|vaśā]]'') to Indra when asked for it. That he is different from the preceding [[भेद|Bheda]], as Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_420/> assumes, is not certain. Indeed, it may very well be that his defeat led to his being chosen as the representative of the evil end of the wicked man. Moreover, the irreligious character of [[भेद|Bheda]] may be ascribed to his being a leader of non-Āryan folk, if the '''Ajas''' and '''Śigrus,''' with whom in the Rigveda he is connected or associated were, as is possible, though by no means certain, un-Āryan tribes of totemists.<ref name=fx3_ve2_420/><br>

भेषज
<u>'''1. Bheṣaja,'''</u> denoting a ‘remedial agent,’ ‘medicine,’ is often mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_421/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_421/> being also used in a figurative sense.<ref name=fx3_ve2_421/> Plants,<ref name=fx4_ve2_421/> waters,<ref name=fx5_ve2_421/> and spells<ref name=fx6_ve2_421/> are repeatedly enumerated as medicines. Most of the medical practices of the Atharvaveda are merely examples of sympathetic magic. For example, in one hymn<ref name=fx7_ve2_421/> the yellow of jaundice is entreated to pass into yellow birds. In another<ref name=fx8_ve2_421/> fever is to be banished by means of a frog; for the frog, being a potent means of cooling fire<ref name=fx9_ve2_421/> (because of its association with water), is regarded as analogously effective in banishing the fire of fever. See '''[[भिषज्|Bhiṣaj]].''' <br>

भेषज
<u>'''2. Bheṣaja'''</u> in the plural is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_422/> and in the Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve2_422/> denoting the hymns of the Atharvaveda in so far as they are regarded as having ‘healing’ powers.<br>

भैम-सेन
<u>'''Bhaima-sena,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[भीमसेन|Bhīmasena]],'''’ is the name of a man in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iv. 6, 6).<br>

भैम-सेनि
<u>'''Bhaima-seni,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[भीमसेन|Bhīmasena]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Divodāsa''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_424/><br>

भैषज्य
<u>'''Bhaiṣajya'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xii, 7. 1, 12) and the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (x. 7. 25) denotes ‘healing remedy’ or ‘medicine,’ like '''[[भेषज|Bheṣaja]].'''<br>

भोग
<u>'''Bhoga'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_426/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_426/> denotes the ‘coil’ of a serpent.<br>

भोज
<u>'''Bhoja'''</u> in several passages of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 12. 14. 17) seems to be used as a king's title.<br>

भौज्य
<u>'''Bhaujya'''</u> in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_428/> denotes the rank of a prince bearing the title of '''[[भोज|Bhoja]].'''<br>

भौमक
<u>'''Bhaumaka'''</u> is the name of some animal in the late Adbhuta [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_429/><br>

भौमी
<u>'''Bhaumī'''</u> is the name of an animal in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_430/> <br>

भौवन
<u>'''Bhauvana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Bhuvana,’ is the patronymic of the mythical '''Viśvakarman''' in the Śatapatha (xiii. 7, 1, 15) and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] (viii. 21, 8. 10) Brāhmaṇas, and the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (x. 26).<br>

भौवायन
<u>'''Bhauvāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Bhuva,’ is the patronymic of '''Kapivana''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_432/> It is also found in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve2_432/><br>

भ्रातृ
<u>'''Bhrātṛ'''</u> is the common designation of ‘brother’ from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_433/> onwards. The word is also applied to a relation or close friend generally,<ref name=fx2_ve2_433/> but here the persons concerned are, it should be noted, in the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_433/> deities, who are brothers of one another or of the worshipper. Thus in the early literature the word has not really lost its precise sense. The derivation from the root ''bhṛ,'' ‘support,’ is probably correct, designating the brother as the support of his sister. This harmonizes with the fact that in Vedic literature the brother plays the part of protector of his sister when bereft of her father, and that maidens deprived of their brothers (''abhrātṛ'') meet an evil fate.<ref name=fx4_ve2_433/> The gradation of the relations in the home is shown by the order in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx5_ve2_433/> where father, mother, brother, and sister are successively mentioned. Strife between brothers is occasionally referred to.<ref name=fx6_ve2_433/> <br>

भ्रातृव्य
<u>'''Bhrātṛvya'''</u> is found in one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_434/> where, being named with brother and sister, it must be an expression of relationship. The sense appears to be ‘(father's) brother's son,’ ‘cousin,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_434/> this meaning alone accounting for the sense of ‘rival,’ ‘enemy,’ found elsewhere in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_434/> and repeatedly in the other Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx4_ve2_434/> In an undivided family the relations of cousins would easily develop into rivalry and enmity. The original meaning may, however, have been ‘nephew,’<ref name=fx5_ve2_434/> as the simple etymological sense would be ‘brother's son’; but this seems not to account for the later meaning so well. The [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx6_ve2_434/> prescribes the telling of a falsehood to a [[भ्रातृव्य|Bhrātṛvya]], who, further, is often given the epithets ‘hating’ (''dviṣan'') and ‘evil’ (''apriya, pāpman'') in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx7_ve2_434/> The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx8_ve2_434/> also contains various spells, which aim at destroying or expelling one's ‘rivals.’<br>

भ्रूण-हन्
<u>'''Bhrūṇa-han,'''</u> ‘slaying an embryo’; '''Bhrūṇa-hatyā,''' ‘the slaying of an embryo,’ are terms expressing a crime which is repeatedly and severely censured in the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve2_435/> where it is said to be the greatest of all crimes, and one of which the  guilt cannot be removed. In many later passages<ref name=fx2_ve2_435/> the same crime is referred to, always with reprobation: this fact alone shows the erroneousness of the theory<ref name=fx3_ve2_435/> that daughters could be allowed, once born, to die if their fathers so desired.<br>

मकक
<u>'''Makaka,'''</u> a word occurring once in the Atharvaveda (viii. 6, 12), may be the name of some unknown animal; but it is possibly an adjective having some such sense as ‘bleating.’<br>

मकर
<u>'''Makara'''</u> is the name of an animal, probably the ‘crocodile,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_437/> which is included in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve2_437/><br>

मक्ष
<u>'''Makṣa,'''</u> ‘fly,’ is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_438/> and the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_438/> where its fondness for sweet things is alluded to. ''Cf.'' '''[[अद्मसद्|Admasad]]'''<br>

मक्षा
<u>'''Makṣā, Makṣikā,'''</u> denote both ‘fly’<ref name=fx1_ve2_439/> and ‘bee’<ref name=fx2_ve2_439/> in the Rigveda and later. <br>

मख
<u>'''Makha'''</u> appears to designate a person in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_440/> but in neither passage does the context explain who he was. Probably a demon of some kind is meant. In the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve2_440/> mention is also made of the ‘head of [[मख|Makha]],’ an expression which has become unintelligible to the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx3_ve2_440/><br>

मगध
<u>'''Magadha'''</u> is the name of a people who appear throughout Vedic literature as of little repute. Though the name is not actually found in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_441/> it occurs in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_441/> where fever is wished away to the '''Gandhāṛis''' and '''Mūjavants,''' northern peoples, and to the '''Aṅgas''' and Magadhas, peoples of the east. Again, in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_441/> the [[मागध|Māgadha]], or man of [[मगध|Magadha]], is included as dedicated to ''ati-kruṣṭa,'' ‘loud noise’(?), while in the '''[[व्रात्य|Vrātya]]''' hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_441/> the [[मागध|Māgadha]] is said to be connected with the [[व्रात्य|Vrātya]] as his [[मित्र|Mitra]], his [[मन्त्र|Mantra]], his laughter, and his thunder in the four quarters. In the Śrauta Sūtras<ref name=fx5_ve2_441/> the equipment characteristic of the [[व्रात्य|Vrātya]] is said to be given, when the latter is admitted into the Āryan Brahminical community, to a bad Brahmin living in [[मगध|Magadha]] (''[[ब्रह्म-बन्धु|brahma-bandhu]] [[मागध-देशीय|Māgadha-deśīya]]''), but this point does not occur in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx6_ve2_441/> On the other hand, respectable Brahmins sometimes lived there, for the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx7_ve2_441/> mentions '''Madhyama, Prātībodhī-[[पुत्र|putra]],''' as ''[[मगध|Magadha]]-vāsin,'' ‘living in [[मगध|Magadha]].’ Oldenberg,<ref name=fx8_ve2_441/> however, seems clearly right in regarding this as unusual. <br><br>The Magadhas are evidently a people in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] and other Sūtras,<ref name=fx9_ve2_441/> possibly also in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx10_ve2_441/> It is therefore most improbable that Zimmer<ref name=fx11_ve2_441/> can be right in thinking that in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_441/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_441/> the [[मागध|Māgadha]] is not a man of [[मगध|Magadha]], but a member of the mixed caste produced by a '''[[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]''' marrying a '''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]''' woman.<ref name=fx12_ve2_441/> But the theory of mixed castes, in any case open to some doubt, cannot be accepted when used to explain such obviously tribal names as [[मागध|Māgadha]]. The fact that the [[मागध|Māgadha]] is often in later times a minstrel is easily accounted for by the assumption that the country was the home of minstrelsy and that wandering bards from [[मगध|Magadha]] were apt to visit the more western lands. This class the later texts recognize as a caste, inventing an origin by intermarriage of the old-established castes.<br><br>The dislike of the Magadhas, which may be Rigvedic, since the '''Kīkaṭas''' were perhaps the prototype of the Magadhas, was in all probability due, as Oldenberg<ref name=fx13_ve2_441/> thinks, to the fact that the Magadhas were not really Brahminized. This is entirely in accord with the evidence of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx14_ve2_441/> that neither '''[[कोसल|Kosala]]''' nor '''[[विदेह|Videha]]''' were fully Brahminized at an early date, much less [[मगध|Magadha]]. Weber<ref name=fx15_ve2_441/> suggests two other grounds that may have influenced the position--the persistence of aboriginal blood and the growth of Buddhism. The latter consideration is hardly applicable to the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] or the Atharvaveda; but the imperfect Brahminization of the land, if substituted for it in accordance with Oldenberg's suggestion,  would have some force. The former motive, despite Oldenberg's doubt, seems fully justified. Pargiter<ref name=fx16_ve2_441/> has gone so far as to suggest that in [[मगध|Magadha]] the Āryans met and mingled with a body of invaders from the east by sea. Though there is no evidence for this view in the Vedic texts, it is reasonable to suppose that the farther east the Āryans penetrated, the less did they impress themselves upon the aborigines. Modern ethnology confirms this ''a priori'' supposition in so far as it shows Āryan types growing less and less marked as the eastern part of India is reached, although such evidence is not decisive in view of the great intermixture of peoples in India.<br>

मगुन्दी
<u>'''Magundī'''</u> is the name of some pest occurring in a verse of an Atharvaveda hymn<ref name=fx1_ve2_442/> employed to exorcise evil influences. By that verse the ‘daughters of the Magundī’ are to be expelled from the cowstall, the wagon, and the house. It is uncertain whether an animal, insect, or demoness is meant.<ref name=fx2_ve2_442/><br>

मघ
<u>'''Magha'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_443/> denotes ‘bounty,’ and Maghavan<ref name=fx2_ve2_443/> is the regular Vedic name for the ‘generous giver’ of bounties to priests. It is doubtful whether the Maghavans were more than this, or had any special rank as a class in Vedic society. See '''[[सभा|Sabhā]].'''<br>

मघा
<u>'''Maghā.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]]''' and '''[[अघा|Aghā]].'''<br>

मङ्गल
<u>'''Maṅgala'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xxvi. 2). <br>

मङ्गीर
<u>'''Maṅgīra'''</u> is found in an obscure verse in the Vaitāna<ref name=fx1_ve2_446/> and other<ref name=fx2_ve2_446/> Sūtras with reference to cows. It is quite uncertain whether a river or a man<ref name=fx3_ve2_446/> is meant. The [[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]] (Ganges) and the [[यमुना|Yamunā]] (Jumna) are mentioned in the same verse. The correct form of the word is doubtful.<ref name=fx4_ve2_446/><br>

मञ्जिष्ठा
<u>'''Mañjiṣṭhā,'''</u> ‘madder,’ is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] (iii. 2, 4) and [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] (viii. 7) Āraṇyakas.<br>

मटची
<u>'''Maṭacī'''</u> occurs in a passage of the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_448/> where reference is made to the '''Kurus''' being overwhelmed by Maṭacīs.<ref name=fx2_ve2_448/> Śaṅkara interprets the word by ‘thunderbolts’ (''aśanayaḥ''), while Ānandatīrtha in his commentary gives, as an alternative rendering, ''pāṣāṇa-vṛṣṭayaḥ--i.e.,'' ‘hailstones,’ which may be the sense. The Śabdakalpadruma,<ref name=fx3_ve2_448/> agreeing with Ānandatīrtha,<ref name=fx4_ve2_448/> says that [[मटची|Maṭacī]] means, ‘a kind of small red bird’ (''rakta-[[वर्ण|varṇa]]-kṣudra-pakṣi-viśeṣa,'' reading ''-pakṣī-''), and Jacob<ref name=fx5_ve2_448/> suggests that the ‘locust’ is meant.<br>

मणि
<u>'''Maṇi'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_449/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_449/> of a ‘jewel’ used as an amulet against all kinds of evil. That either ‘pearl’<ref name=fx3_ve2_449/> or ‘diamond’<ref name=fx4_ve2_449/> is denoted is not clear.<ref name=fx5_ve2_449/> It is evident that the  [[मणि|Maṇi]] could be strung on a thread (''[[सूत्र|sūtra]]''), which is referred to in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_449/> and elsewhere;<ref name=fx7_ve2_449/> the [[मणि|Maṇi]] was certainly also worn round the neck, for in the Rigveda<ref name=fx8_ve2_449/> occurs the epithet ''[[मणि|maṇi]]-grīva,'' ‘having a jewel on the neck.’ An amulet of [[बिल्व|Bilva]] is celebrated in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx9_ve2_449/> and many varieties of amulet are there enumerated.<ref name=fx10_ve2_449/> The ‘jeweller’ (''[[मणि|maṇi]]-kāra'') is mentioned in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx11_ve2_449/><br>

मणिक
<u>'''Maṇika'''</u> in the late Adbhuta [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_450/> and the Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve2_450/> denotes a large ‘water bottle.’<br>

मण्ड
<u>'''Maṇḍa,'''</u> n., is found in the compound ''nau-[[मण्ड|maṇḍa]]'' (du.), denoting the two ‘rudders’ of a ship in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_451/><br>

मण्डूक
<u>'''Maṇḍūka'''</u> is the name of ‘frog’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_452/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_452/> the feminine Maṇḍūkī also occurring.<ref name=fx3_ve2_452/> The famous frog hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_452/> compares with Brahmins the frogs croaking  as they awake to activity at the beginning of the rains. It has been explained by Max Müller<ref name=fx5_ve2_452/> as a satire on the Brahmins. Geldner,<ref name=fx6_ve2_452/> agreeing with this view, thinks that it is directed by its '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]''' composer against rival Brahmins, probably the '''Viśvāmitras.'''<ref name=fx7_ve2_452/> The view, however, which interprets the hymn as a rain charm<ref name=fx8_ve2_452/> seems on the whole more likely. The frog, from its connexion with water, was considered to have cooling properties. Thus after the burning of the dead body the frog is invited to come to the spot where the cremation has taken place in order to cool it down.<ref name=fx9_ve2_452/> Similarly the frog is invoked in the Atharvaveda against the fire of fever.<ref name=fx10_ve2_452/><br>

मत्स्य
<u>'''1. Matsya,'''</u> ‘fish,’ is mentioned only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_453/> but frequently later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_453/><br>

मत्स्य
<u>'''2. Matsya'''</u> appears to be the name of a people in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_454/> where they are ranged with the other enemies of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' although it is possible to see merely the sense of ‘fish’ in that passage. In the list of Aśvamedhins, ‘offerers of the horse sacrifice,’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_454/> '''[[ध्वसन् द्वैतवन|Dhvasan Dvaitavana]]''' is mentioned as a [[मत्स्य|Matsya]] king ('''[[मात्स्य|Mātsya]]'''). The Matsyas as a people occur also in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_454/> in  connexion with the '''Vaśas,'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_454/> and in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_454/> in connexion with '''Śālvas.''' In Manu<ref name=fx6_ve2_454/> the '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]],''' the Matsyas, the '''Pancālas,''' and the '''Śūrasenakas''' comprise the land of the Brahmin [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]] (''[[ब्रह्मर्षि-देश|brahmarṣi-deśa]]''). There is no reason to doubt that the Matsyas occupied much the same territory as in Epic times, say Alwar, Jaipur, Bharatpur.<ref name=fx7_ve2_454/><br>

मदा-वती
<u>'''Madā-vatī,'''</u> ‘intoxicating,’ is the name of a plant in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_455/><br>

मदुघ
<u>'''Madugha,'''</u> ‘honey-plant,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_456/> is the name of a sweet herb in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_456/> The spelling is somewhat uncertain, since many manuscripts read Madhugha.<ref name=fx3_ve2_456/><br>

मद्गु
<u>'''Madgu,'''</u> ‘diver’ (from the root ''majj,''<ref name=fx1_ve2_457/> ‘dive’), is the name of some aquatic bird which is included in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx2_ve2_457/> and is occasionally mentioned elsewhere.<ref name=fx3_ve2_457/> <br>

मद्य
<u>'''Madya,'''</u> ‘intoxicating liquor,’ is not mentioned until the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_458/> where it occurs in the compound ''[[मद्य|madya]]-pā,'' ‘drinking intoxicating liquor.’<br>

मद्र
<u>'''Madra'''</u> denotes a people who are mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]];<ref name=fx1_ve2_459/> '''[[काप्य|Kāpya]] Patañcala''' was then living among them. Their name appears elsewhere in Vedic literature, only in that of a branch, the '''Uttara Madras,''' the ‘northern Madras,’ who are referred to in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_459/> as living beyond the Himālaya (''pareṇa Himavantam'') in the neighbourhood of the '''Uttara Kurus,''' probably, as Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_459/> conjectures, in the land of Kaśmīr. The Madras mentioned in the [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] were, like the '''Kurus,''' probably settled somewhere in '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]]''' in the '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]]''' or ‘Middle Land.’ ''Cf.'' '''Madragāra.'''<br>

मद्र-गार शौङ्गायनि
<u>'''Madra-gāra Śauṅgāyani'''</u> (‘descendant of Śuṅga’) is the name of a teacher, whose pupil was '''[[काम्बोज|Kāmboja]] [[औपमन्यव|Aupamanyava]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_460/> Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_460/> concludes, with probability, that these names point to a connexion of the Kambojas and the Madras.<br>

मधु
<u>'''Madhu'''</u> denotes anything sweet used as food, and especially drink, ‘mead,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_461/> a sense often found in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_461/> More precisely it denotes either ‘Soma’<ref name=fx3_ve2_461/> or ‘milk,’<ref name=fx4_ve2_461/> or less often  ‘honey,’<ref name=fx5_ve2_461/> which, however, is the most definite sense in the later literature. Taboos against the use of honey are recorded.<ref name=fx6_ve2_461/><br>

मधुक पैङ्ग्य
<u>'''Madhuka Paiṅgya'''</u> (‘descendant of Piṅga’) is the name of a teacher mentioned in the Śatapatha<ref name=fx1_ve2_462/> and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_462/> Brāhmaṇas.<br>

मधु-कशा
<u>'''Madhu-kaśā,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_463/> or '''Madhoḥ Kasā,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_463/> is the name in the Rigveda of the Aśvins’ ‘honey-whip,’ by which they impart sweetness to the sacrifice. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_463/> ingeniously conjectures that the idea was derived from an instrument provided with thongs for whipping milk, a ‘milk-whip.’<br>

मधु-कृत्
<u>'''Madhu-kṛt,'''</u> ‘honey-maker,’ denotes ‘bee’ in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_464/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_464/><br>

मधु-छन्दस्
<u>'''Madhu-chandas,'''</u> the reputed author of the first ten hymns of the first Maṇḍala of the Rigveda, is mentioned as a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_465/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx2_ve2_465/> In the  [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_465/> he counts as the fifty-first son of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]],''' and his Praüga (hymn at the morning service) is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_465/><br>

मधु-ब्राह्मण
<u>'''Madhu-brāhmaṇa,'''</u> ‘the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] of the Honey,’ is the designation of a certain mystical doctrine in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_466/><br>

मध्य-देश
<u>'''Madhya-deśa,'''</u> the ‘Middle Country,’ is, according to the [[मानव|Mānava]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] Śāstra,<ref name=fx1_ve2_467/> the land between the Himālaya in the north, the Vindhya in the south, '''[[विनशन|Vinaśana]]''' in the west, and Prayāga (now Allahabad) in the east--that is, between the place where the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' disappears in the desert, and the point of the confluence of the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]''' (Jumna) and the '''[[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]]''' (Ganges). The same authority<ref name=fx2_ve2_467/> defines [[ब्रह्मर्षि-देश|Brahmarṣi-deśa]] as denoting the land of '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]],''' the '''Matsyas, Pañcālas,''' and '''Śūrasenakas,''' and [[ब्रह्मावर्त|Brahmāvarta]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_467/> as meaning the particularly holy land between the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] and the '''[[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]].''' The [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_467/> defines Āryāvarta as the land east of [[विनशन|Vinaśana]]; west of the Kālaka-vana, ‘Black Forest,’ or rather Kanakhala, near Hardvār; south of the Himālaya; and north of the Pāriyātra or the Pāripātra Mountains; adding that, in the opinion of others,<ref name=fx5_ve2_467/> it was confined to the country between the [[यमुना|Yamunā]] and the [[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]], while the '''Bhāllavins'''<ref name=fx6_ve2_467/> took it as the country between the boundary-river (or perhaps the [[सरस्|Saras]]-  vatī)<ref name=fx7_ve2_467/> and the region where the sun rises. The [[मानव|Mānava]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] Śāstra,<ref name=fx8_ve2_467/> in accord with the [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx9_ve2_467/> defines Āryāvarta as the region between the Vindhya and the Himālaya, the two ranges which seem to be the boundaries of the Āryan world in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] also.<ref name=fx10_ve2_467/><br><br>The term [[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]] is not Vedic, but it is represented in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx11_ve2_467/> by the expression ''madhyamā [[प्रतिष्ठा|pratiṣṭhā]] [[दिश्|diś]],'' ‘the middle fixed region,’ the inhabitants of which are stated to be the Kurus, the Pañcālas, the '''Vaśas,''' and the '''Uśīnaras.''' The latter two peoples practically disappear later on, the [[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]] being the country of the Kuru-Pañcālas, the land where the Brāhmaṇas and the later Saṃhitās were produced, bounded on the east by the '''[[कोसल|Kosala]]-Videhas,''' and on the west by the desert. The western tribes are mentioned with disapproval both in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx12_ve2_467/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx13_ve2_467/> while the tradition of the Brahminization of the Kosalas and the Videhas from the Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]] country is preserved in the former [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx14_ve2_467/> <br>

मध्यं-दिन
<u>'''Madhyaṃ-dina,'''</u> ‘mid-day,’ is a frequent designation of time in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_468/> the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx2_ve2_468/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx3_ve2_468/> ''Cf.'' '''Ahan.'''<br>

मध्यम-वह्
<u>'''Madhyama-vah'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_469/> as an epithet of the chariot. The exact interpretation is doubtful. Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_469/> assigns to it the expression the sense of ‘driving with a single horse between the shafts.’ According to Sāyana's explanation, it means ‘driving with middling speed.’ It might mean ‘driving in the middle’--that is, ‘only half-way.’^3<br>

मध्यम-शी
<u>'''Madhyama-śī'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_470/> where Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_470/> assigns to the word the meaning of ''intercessor,'' which Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_470/> accepts, in the sense of ‘mediator’ or ‘arbiter,’ as a legal term, but which Roth may, as Lanman<ref name=fx4_ve2_470/> suggests, have intended to express ‘adversary’ or ‘preventer’ of the disease referred to in the hymn. Whitney<ref name=fx5_ve2_470/> thinks that it means ‘mid-  most man’ or ‘chief’ as the one round whom his followers encamp.<ref name=fx6_ve2_470/> Geldner,<ref name=fx7_ve2_470/> however, thinks that a third king, who is ‘neutral’ between two enemies, is intended.<br>

मध्यम-स्थ
<u>'''Madhyama-stha,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_471/> '''Madhyame-ṣṭha,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_471/> in the later Saṃhitās denotes the chief in his relation to his followers ''([[सजात|sajāta]]). Cf.'' '''[[मध्यमशी|Madhyamaśī]].'''<br>

मध्या-वर्ष
<u>'''Madhyā-varṣa,'''</u> the ‘middle of the rains,’ is specially mentioned as a time of the year in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_472/> and in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx2_ve2_472/><br>

मनस
<u>'''Manasa,'''</u> occurring in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_473/> seems clearly to be the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], in accordance with Sāyaṇa's interpretation.<br>

मना
<u>'''Manā'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_474/> in an enumeration of gifts, where it is described as ‘golden’ (''sacā [[मना|manā]] hiraṇyayā''). It therefore seems to designate some ornament, or possibly a weight, and has accordingly been compared<ref name=fx2_ve2_474/> with the Greek  (Herodotus has ), the Latin ''mina.'' All three words have been considered Semitic in origin, as borrowed from the Phœnicians<ref name=fx3_ve2_474/> in the case of Greece, from Carthage by way  of Etruria or Sicily in the case of Rome, and from Babylon in the case of India. The identification as regards [[मना|Manā]] is very conjectural, depending merely on the probabilities of Babylonian borrowing<ref name=fx4_ve2_474/> seen--''e.g.,'' in the legend of the flood, and in the system of the '''Nakṣatras.''' On the other hand, Mahā may very well be identical with the word ''[[मना|manā]]'' which occurs several times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx5_ve2_474/> in the sense of ‘desire’ (from the root ''man,'' ‘think’), and which may have in this one passage the concrete sense of ‘desirable object.’ It is to be noted that in Bo7htlingk's Dictionary a single word [[मना|Manā]] appears, to which the only senses assigned are ‘wish,’ ‘desire,’ ‘jealousy.’<br>

मनावी
<u>'''Manāvī,'''</u> ‘wife of Manu,’ is mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_475/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_475/> See '''Manu.'''<br>

मनु
<u>'''Manu'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_476/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_476/> has no claim to historical reality. He is simply the first man, father of the race, and its guide in all matters, sacrificial and other. Hence the views of the texts on inheritance are foisted on Manu and his youngest son, '''[[नाभानेदिष्ठ|Nābhānediṣṭha]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_476/> He also plays the part of the hero in the Vedic legend of the flood.<ref name=fx4_ve2_476/> <br><br>Manu is called Vivasvan<ref name=fx5_ve2_476/> or Vaivasvata,<ref name=fx6_ve2_476/> ‘son of Vivasvant’ (the god); [[सावर्णि|Sāvarṇi]],<ref name=fx6_ve2_476/> ‘descendant of Savarṇā’ (the substitute of Saraṇyū in the legend of her wedding); and [[सांवरणि|Sāṃvaraṇi]],<ref name=fx7_ve2_476/> ‘descendant of [[संवरण|Saṃvaraṇa]].’ The first name is, of course, mythical. The other two have been regarded as historical, [[सावर्णि|Sāvarṇi]] being taken by Ludwig<ref name=fx8_ve2_476/> as a king of the '''Turvaśas,''' but this is very doubtful.<br>

मनोर् अवसर्पण
<u>'''Manor Avasarpaṇa'''</u> is the name, in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_477/> of the mountain on which the vessel of '''Manu''' rested. In the Epic the name is Naubandhana, but the view<ref name=fx2_ve2_477/> that it is alluded to as '''[[नावप्रभ्रंशन|Nāvaprabhraṃśana]]''' in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_477/> is now abandoned.<ref name=fx4_ve2_477/><br>

मनुष्य-राज
<u>'''Manuṣya-rāja'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_478/> and '''Manuṣya-[[राजन्|rājan]]'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_478/> denote in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas a ‘king of men.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[राजन्|Rājan]].'''<br>

मनुष्य-विश्
<u>'''Manuṣya-viś,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_479/> '''Manuṣya-viśa,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_479/> and '''Manuṣya-viśā'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_479/> denote ‘mankind,’ ‘the human race,’ in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas. <br>

मन्त्र
<u>'''Mantra'''</u> (from the root ''man,'' ‘think’) denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_480/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_480/> the ‘hymn’ as the product of the singer's creative thought. In the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx3_ve2_480/> the word is regularly used of the poetic and prose utterances of the [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]], including not merely the verse parts of the Saṃhitās, but also the prose formulæ that betray by their style their special and archaic character.<ref name=fx4_ve2_480/><br>

मन्त्र-कृत्
<u>'''Mantra-kṛt'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_481/> and the '''Brāhmaṇas'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_481/> denotes a poet as a ‘maker of Mantras.’<br>

मन्थ
<u>'''Mantha'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_482/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_482/> denotes a drink in which solid ingredients are mixed with a fluid by stirring, usually parched barley-meal ('''[[सक्तु|Saktu]]''') with milk.<ref name=fx3_ve2_482/> All sorts of mixed beverages of this type are mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx4_ve2_482/><br>

मन्था
<u>'''Manthā'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_483/> seems to mean a ‘churn.’ So the root ''math'' denotes to ‘churn’ in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_483/> In one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_483/> the word is used to denote a drink like '''[[मन्थ|Mantha]].''' <br>

मन्थावल
<u>'''Manthāvala'''</u> is the name of an animal in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_484/> a sort of snake according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary. Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx2_ve2_484/> understands it to be a kind of animal which hangs head downwards from the branches of trees, meaning, presumably, the flying fox.<ref name=fx3_ve2_484/> ''Cf.'' '''[[मान्थाल|Mānthāla]], Mānthīlava.'''<br>

मन्थिन्
<u>'''Manthin'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_485/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_485/> denotes Soma juice mixed with meal ('''[[सक्तु|Saktu]]''') by stirring.<br>

मन्दीर
<u>'''Mandīra'''</u> is perhaps the name of a man whose cattle, according to a [[मन्त्र|Mantra]] in the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xiii. 3, 21), did not drink the water of the '''[[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]]''' (Ganges). See '''[[मङ्गीर|Maṅgīra]].'''<br>

मन्धातृ
<u>'''1. Mandhātṛ'''</u> occurs in several passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_487/> in all of which Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_487/> takes the word as merely an adjective used substantively, ‘the pious man.’ In one passage<ref name=fx3_ve2_487/> the word, being applied to Agni, is thus used, but in another<ref name=fx4_ve2_487/> ''Mandhātṛvat'' being parallel with ''Aṅgirasvat,'' ‘like [[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]],’ is naturally to be understood as a proper name, which is probably also the sense of the word in the preceding hymn.<ref name=fx5_ve2_487/> A different [[मन्धातृ|Mandhātṛ]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_487/> may be meant in the first Maṇḍala,<ref name=fx6_ve2_487/> where he is mentioned as a protégé of the Aśvins, and evidently as a king. To equate these persons, and make a Rājarṣi out of [[मन्धातृ|Mandhātṛ]], as Ludwig<ref name=fx7_ve2_487/> and Griffith<ref name=fx8_ve2_487/> do, is unnecessary and improbable. <br>

मन्धातृ यौवनाश्व
<u>'''2. Mandhātṛ Yauvanāśva'''</u> (‘descendant of Yuvanāśva’) is in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_488/> the name of an emperor who was instructed by '''Vicārin,''' son of '''[[कबन्ध आथर्वण|Kabandha Ātharvaṇa]].'''<br>

मन्या
<u>'''Manyā'''</u> (plur.), ‘nape of the neck,’ occurs in a passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_489/> directed against a disease which Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve2_489/> regards as scrofulous swellings on the neck. He compares the disease Manskunder, ‘tumours of the neck’ (which looks like a combination of the words ''[[मन्या|manyā]]'' and ''[[स्कन्ध्या|skandhyā]],'' ‘pains of the neck and shoulders,’ both occurring in verses 1 and 3 of the [[अथर्वन्|Atharvan]] hymn), mentioned by Wise.<ref name=fx3_ve2_489/><br>

ममता
<u>'''Mamatā'''</u> is, according to Sāyaṇa, in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_490/> the wife of Ucathya and the mother of '''[[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]].''' But the word may be merely an abstract noun meaning ‘selfinterest,’ a sense which it often has in the later language. Oldenberg<ref name=fx2_ve2_490/> finds a mention of Mamata (masc.) in a verse of the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_490/> as the name of a '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]].'''<br>

मय
<u>'''Maya'''</u> is found once in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xxii. 19) in the sense of ‘horse.’<br>

मयु
<u>'''Mayu'''</u> occurs in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_492/> The commentator on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_492/> explains the word as meaning either an ‘ape’ (''[[किंपुरुष|kiṃpuruṣa]]'') or a ‘forest peacock’ (''āraṇya-[[मयूर|mayūra]]'').  The former sense is supported by another passage of the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve2_492/> where the Mayu, being a substitute for the man, must be an ape. This sense also suits the word in the other passage<ref name=fx3_ve2_492/> where it occurs.<br>

मयूख
<u>'''Mayūkha'''</u> denotes, from the Rigveda onwards,<ref name=fx1_ve2_493/> a ‘peg,’ especially as used for keeping a web stretched.<ref name=fx2_ve2_493/> ''Cf.'' '''Otu.'''<br>

मयूर
<u>'''Mayūra,'''</u> ‘peacock,’ occurs in the Rigveda in the compounds describing Indra's horses, ''[[मयूर|mayūra]]-roman,''<ref name=fx1_ve2_494/> ‘with hair like peacocks’ feathers,’ and ''[[मयूर|mayūra]]-śepya,''<ref name=fx2_ve2_494/> ‘with tails like those of peacocks.’ The peacock also appears in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx3_ve2_494/> The pea-hen, Mayūrī, is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_494/> and the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx5_ve2_494/> in both cases with reference to the bird's efficacy against poison, a curious superstition to be compared with the modern dislike of peacocks' feathers.<br>

मरीचि
<u>'''Marīci'''</u> in the plural denotes according to Weber,<ref name=fx1_ve2_495/> the ‘particles of light’ or ‘shining motes’ that fill the air, as opposed to rays of light (''[[रश्मि|raśmi]]''). This meaning adequatelysuits the passages in the early Vedic literature<ref name=fx2_ve2_495/> where the  word occurs; but the sense of ‘ray’ is quite clearly found in the Upaniṣads,<ref name=fx3_ve2_495/> as well as the older sense.<ref name=fx4_ve2_495/><br>

मरु
<u>'''Maru,'''</u> in the plural, is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx1_ve2_496/> as the ''utkara'' (‘mound of earth thrown up’ from the excavation of the altar<ref name=fx2_ve2_496/> ) of '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]].''' This seems to mean that the Maru deserts (the later Maru-sthala)<ref name=fx3_ve2_496/> were so called because they stood to the ‘altar,’ [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]], in the same relation as the waste earth of the ''utkara'' to the altar at the sacrifice.<br>

मरुत्त आवि-क्षित
<u>'''Marutta Āvi-kṣita'''</u> (‘descendant of Avikṣit’) '''[[काम-प्रि|Kāma-pri]]''' (‘descendant of Kāmapra’) is the name of a king who was anointed by '''[[संवर्त|Saṃvarta]]''' according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_497/> In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_497/> account of the same king he is called '''[[आयोगव|Āyogava]].'''<br>

मरुद्-वृधा
<u>'''Marud-vṛdhā'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_498/> is the name of a stream mentioned in the Nadīstuti (‘Praise of Rivers’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_498/> along with the '''[[असिक्नी|Asiknī]]''' (Akesines) and the '''[[वितस्ता|Vitastā]]''' (Hydaspes). Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_498/> considers that the [[मरुद्वृधा|Marudvṛdhā]] denotes the stream formed by the combined waters of these two rivers down to its junction with the '''[[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]]''' (Ravi), a view accepted by Zimmer.<ref name=fx4_ve2_498/> On the other hand, Ludwig<ref name=fx5_ve2_498/> thinks that the [[मरुद्वृधा|Marudvṛdhā]] designates  the stream formed by the junction of the [[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]] with the combined waters of the [[असिक्नी|Asiknī]] and [[वितस्ता|Vitastā]], a view which seems less likely.<br>

मर्क
<u>'''1. Marka'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_499/> where Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_499/> sees in the expression ''sūro markaḥ'' the ‘eclipse of the sun.’ Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx3_ve2_499/> thinks the meaning is ‘purifying.’<ref name=fx4_ve2_499/><br>

मर्क
<u>'''2. Marka'''</u> is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_500/> and elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve2_500/> as the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], along with '''[[शण्ड|Śaṇḍa]],''' of the Asuras, while [[बृहस्पति|Bṛhaspati]] is, of course, the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of the gods. [[मर्क|Marka]] is mentioned elsewhere also.<ref name=fx3_ve2_500/> The name may quite possibly have Iranian affinities, as believed by Hillebrandt<ref name=fx4_ve2_500/> and by Hopkins.<ref name=fx5_ve2_500/> Hillebrandt<ref name=fx6_ve2_500/> also sees in a [[गृध्र|Gṛdhra]] mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx7_ve2_500/> and elsewhere<ref name=fx8_ve2_500/> a prototype of [[मर्क|Marka]].<br>

मर्कट
<u>'''Markaṭa,'''</u> ‘ape,’ is enumerated in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_501/> It is classified in the same Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve2_501/> with man and the elephant as ‘taking hold by the hand’ (''[[हस्तादान|hastādāna]]'') instead of ‘taking hold by the mouth’ (''mukhādāna''). The animal is mentioned several times elsewhere also.<ref name=fx3_ve2_501/> ''Cf.'' '''[[पुरुष हस्तिन्|Puruṣa Hastin]], Mayu.''' <br>

मर्य
<u>'''1. Marya'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_502/> denotes a ‘man’ especially regarded as young and a lover, being constantly mentioned as in company with maidens (''yuvatī'').<br>

मर्य
<u>'''2. Marya'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_503/> in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_503/> denotes a ‘stallion.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_503/> It is once<ref name=fx3_ve2_503/> described as ''[[पस्त्यावन्त्|pastyāvant]],'' ‘a stalled horse’--that is, one carefully tended, and not allowed out to graze.<br>

मर्यक
<u>'''Maryaka,'''</u> occurring only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_504/> seems to denote the bull which is described as separated from the cows.<br>

मर्यादा
<u>'''Maryādā,'''</u> ‘boundary,’ is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_505/> referring to the boundary between the '''Kosalas''' and the '''Videhas.''' Usually the word is metaphorically employed.<ref name=fx2_ve2_505/><br>

मल
<u>'''Mala'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_506/> is used of the garments of the Munis. The St. Petersburg Dictionary takes it to mean a ‘leathern garment,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_506/> but Ludwig and Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_506/> think it means only ‘soiled’ raiment, which, of course, suits the ordinary sense of the word (‘dirt’) in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx4_ve2_506/> and the character of the long-haired (''[[केशिन्|keśin]]'') hermit ('''Muni'''). ''Cf.'' '''[[मलग|Malaga]].''' <br>

मल-ग
<u>'''Mala-ga'''</u> in one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_507/> denotes a cleanser of clothes, a ‘washerman,’ but the origin of the word is somewhat uncertain.<ref name=fx2_ve2_507/><br>

मलिम्लु
<u>'''Malimlu'''</u> in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_508/> denotes a ‘robber,’ specifically, according to the commentator Mahīdhara, a burglar or housebreaker. ''Cf.'' '''[[तायु|Tāyu]], [[तस्कर|Taskara]], [[स्तेन|Stena]],''' and '''[[देवमलिम्लुच्|Devamalimluc]].'''<br>

मलिम्लुच
<u>'''Malimluca'''</u> is the name of an intercalary month in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_509/> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

मशक
<u>'''1. Maśaka'''</u> denotes a ‘biting fly’ or ‘mosquito,’ being described in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_510/> as ‘quickly(?) biting’ (''tṛpradaṃśin''), and as having a poisonous sting. The elephant is mentioned<ref name=fx2_ve2_510/> as particularly subject to its stings. The insect is often referred to elsewhere.<ref name=fx3_ve2_510/> ''Cf.'' '''[[दंश|Daṃśa]].'''<br>

मशक गार्ग्य
<u>'''2. Maśaka Gārgya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[गर्ग|Garga]]'''’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[स्थिरक गार्ग्य|Sthiraka Gārgya]],''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_511/> He is also mentioned in the Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve2_511/> of the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]], and is the reputed author of an extant [[कल्प|Kalpa]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]. <br>

मशर्शार
<u>'''Maśarśāra'''</u> is the name of a king, according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx1_ve2_512/> of the '''Nahuṣas,''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_512/><br>

मष्णार
<u>'''Maṣṇāra'''</u> is the name of a locality, the scene of the victory of a '''Kuru''' king, in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_513/><br>

मसूर
<u>'''Masūra'''</u> is the name of a kind of lentil (''Ervum hirsutum'') in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_514/> and the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_514/><br>

मसूस्य
<u>'''Masūsya,'''</u> occurring in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 8, 14, 6), is, according to the commentator, the name of a grain of the north country.<br>

मस्तु
<u>'''Mastu'''</u> in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_516/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_516/> denotes ‘sour curds.’<br>

मह-र्त्विज्
<u>'''Maha-rtvij,'''</u> ‘great priest,’ is the collective name of the four chief priests--[[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]], [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], [[होतृ|Hotṛ]], and Udgātṛ--in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_517/><br>

मह-र्षभ
<u>'''Maha-rṣabha,'''</u> a ‘great bull,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda (iv. 15, 1).<br>

मह-र्षि
<u>'''Maha-rṣi,'''</u> a ‘great [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]],’ is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (i. 9, 6). ''Cf.'' '''[[महाब्राह्मण|Mahābrāhmaṇa]].''' <br>

महा-कुल
<u>'''Mahā-kula,'''</u> ‘sprung from a great family,’ is the designation of a bowl or cup ('''[[चमस|Camasa]]''') in the Rigveda (i. 161, 1). The metaphorical use of this word shows that the high position of certain families was already recognized in the times of the Rigveda.<br>

महा-कौषीतक
<u>'''Mahā-kauṣītaka,'''</u> the ‘Great Kauṣītaka ([[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]),’ is the name of a Vedic text in the Rigveda [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] Sūtras.<ref name=fx1_ve2_521/><br>

महाज
<u>'''Mahāja,'''</u> a ‘great goat’ ('''Aja''') is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 4, 1, 2).<br>

महा-धन
<u>'''Mahā-dhana'''</u> in the Rigveda denotes either a ‘great fight’<ref name=fx1_ve2_523/> or a ‘great prize’<ref name=fx2_ve2_523/> as the result of a fight. In many cases the fight may mean merely the contest of the chariot race.<br>

महा-नग्नी
<u>'''Mahā-nagnī'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_524/> denotes a ‘courtesan.’ The masculine, Mahā-nagna,<ref name=fx2_ve2_524/> ‘paramour,’ is probably secondarily. derived from the feminine [[महानग्नी|Mahānagnī]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_524/><br>

महा-नाग
<u>'''Mahā-nāga,'''</u> a ‘great snake,’ is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xi. 2, 7, 12), where it is plainly mythical.<br>

महा-निरष्ट
<u>'''Mahā-niraṣṭa,'''</u> a ‘great castrated’ ox, is mentioned as the '''[[दक्षिणा|Dakṣiṇā]],''' or ‘sacrificial fee,’ in the house of the '''[[सूत|Sūta]]''' at the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]]''' (‘royal consecration’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_526/> ''Cf.'' '''[[अनड्वाह्|Anaḍvāh]]''' and '''Go.''' <br>

महा-पथ
<u>'''Mahā-patha'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_527/> denotes the ‘high road’ between two villages.<br>

महा-पुर
<u>'''Mahā-pura'''</u> in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_528/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_528/> denotes a great fortress.<ref name=fx1_ve2_528/> Probably the only difference between the '''Pur''' and the [[महापुर|Mahāpura]] was size.<br>

महा-ब्राह्मण
<u>'''Mahā-brāhmaṇa,'''</u> a ‘great Brahmin,’ is found in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 1, 19. 22) denoting a Brahmin of great consequence. ''Cf.'' '''[[महर्षि|Maharṣi]].'''<br>

महाभिषेक
<u>'''Mahābhiṣeka,'''</u> ‘great consecration,’ is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_530/> and described as a ceremony performed for great kings, a list of whom is given. It is equivalent to the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]].'''<br>

महा-भूत
<u>'''Mahā-bhūta'''</u> in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (xiv. 5, 10) and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iii. 2, 3) denotes the ‘gross elements’ (earth, water, fire, air, ether).<br>

महा-मत्स्य
<u>'''Mahā-matsya,'''</u> a ‘great fish,’ is mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 3, 18).<br>

महा-मेरु
<u>'''Mahā-meru,'''</u> ‘great Meru,’ is the name of a mountain in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve2_533/> <br>

महा-रथ
<u>'''Mahā-ratha,'''</u> ‘having a great car’--''i.e.,'' ‘a great chariot fighter,’ is an epithet of the hero who is prayed for in the ritual of the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_534/><br>

महा-राज
<u>'''Mahā-rāja,'''</u> a ‘great king,’ is frequently referred to in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_535/> It seems to mean no more than a king, or rather perhaps a reigning and powerful king, as opposed to a mere prince, who would also be called '''[[राजन्|Rājan]].'''<br>

महा-रात्र
<u>'''Mahā-rātra,'''</u> ‘advanced night,’ is a phrase found in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_536/> and the Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve2_536/> to denote the latter part of the night, after midnight and before dawn.<br>

महार्णव
<u>'''Mahārṇava,'''</u> a ‘great ocean,’ is a phrase not found before the late Maitrāyaṇī [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 4), where the drying up of ‘great oceans’ is one of the marvels enumerated. ''Cf.'' '''[[सम्उद्र|Samudra]].'''<br>

महा-वीर
<u>'''Mahā-vīra'''</u> (‘great hero’) is the name in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_538/> of a large earthenware pot which could be placed on the fire, and which was especially employed at the introductory Soma ceremony called Pravargya.<br>

महा-वृक्ष
<u>'''Mahā-vṛkṣa'''</u> a ‘great tree,’ is mentioned sometimes in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 6, 15; xiv. 1, 12) and in the Sūtras.<br>

महा-वृष
<u>'''Mahā-vṛṣa'''</u> is the name of a tribe mentioned along with the '''Mūjavants''' in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_540/> as a locality to which fever is to be relegated. It is reasonable to suppose that they were  northerners, though Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve2_540/> suggests that the name may be chosen more for its sound and sense (as ‘of mighty strength’ to resist the disease) than for its geographical position. In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_540/> the place '''[[रैक्वपर्ण|Raikvaparṇa]]''' is said to be in the [[महावृष|Mahāvṛṣa]] country. The king of the Mahāvṛṣas in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_540/> is said to be '''Hṛtsvāśaya.''' The Mahāvṛṣas are also known from a [[मन्त्र|Mantra]] in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx5_ve2_540/><br>

महा-शाल
<u>'''1. Mahā-śāla'''</u> (lit., ‘having a great house’), a ‘great householder,’ is an expression applied in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (v. 11, 1) to the Brahmins who were instructed by '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]],''' no doubt to emphasize their importance. ''Cf.'' '''[[महाब्राह्मण|Mahābrāhmaṇa]].'''<br>

महा-शाल जाबाल
<u>'''2. Mahā-śāla Jābāla'''</u> is the name of a teacher twice mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], once as instructing '''[[धीर शातपर्णेय|Dhīra Śātaparṇeya]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_542/> and once as one of the Brahmins who received instruction from '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_542/> In the parallel passage of the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_542/> the name is '''[[प्राचीनशाल औपमन्यव|Prācīnaśāla Aupamanyava]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_542/> The word must be considered a proper name rather than an adjective (1. '''[[महाशाल|Mahāśāla]]'''), as it is taken in the St. Petersburg Dictionary.<ref name=fx5_ve2_542/><br>

महा-सुपर्ण
<u>'''Mahā-suparṇa'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xii. 2, 3, 7) denotes a ‘great bird’ or ‘great eagle.’<br>

महा-सुहय
<u>'''Mahā-suhaya,'''</u> a ‘great (''i.e.,'' high-spirited) horse,’ is the description in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_544/> of the steed from  the Indus (''[[सैन्धव|saindhava]]'') which tears away the peg of its hobble (''[[पड्बीश|paḍbīśa]]-śaṅkhu'').<br>

महा-सूक्त
<u>'''Mahā-sūkta,'''</u> m. plur., the ‘composers of the long hymns’ of the tenth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_545/> are mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve2_545/> and the Sūtras.<ref name=fx3_ve2_545/> ''Cf.'' '''Kṣudra-[[सूक्त|sūkta]].'''<br>

महाह्न
<u>'''Mahāhna'''</u> in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 9) denotes the ‘advanced (time of the) day’--that is, ‘afternoon.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[महारात्र|Mahārātra]].'''<br>

महि-दास ऐतरेय
<u>'''Mahi-[[दास|dāsa]] Aitareya'''</u> (‘descendant of Itara or Itarā’) is the name of the sage from whom the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] and Āraṇyaka take their names. He is several times referred to in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx1_ve2_547/> but not as its author. He is credited with a life of 116 years in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_547/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_547/><br>

महिष
<u>'''Mahiṣa,'''</u> the ‘strong,’ with<ref name=fx1_ve2_548/> or without<ref name=fx2_ve2_548/> '''[[मृग|Mṛga]],''' ‘wild beast,’ denotes the ‘buffalo’ in the Rigveda and the later texts. The feminine, [[महिषी|Mahiṣī]], is found in the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx3_ve2_548/><br>

महिषी
<u>'''1. Mahiṣī.'''</u> See '''[[महिष|Mahiṣa]].'''<br>

महिषी
<u>'''2. Mahiṣī,'''</u> ‘the powerful one,’ the name of the first of the four wives (see '''Pati''') of the king, is mentioned frequently in  the later literature.<ref name=fx1_ve2_550/> Perhaps even in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_550/> the technical sense of ‘first wife’ is present.<br>

महैतरेय
<u>'''Mahaitareya'''</u> is the title of a Vedic text according to the [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] Sūtras of the [[ऋग्वेद|Ṛgveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_551/><br>

महोक्ष
<u>'''Mahokṣa,'''</u> a ‘great bull,’ is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 4, 1, 2).<br>

मांस
<u>'''Māṃsa,'''</u> ‘flesh.’ The eating of flesh appears as something quite regular in the Vedic texts, which show no trace of the doctrine of Ahiṃsā, or abstaining from injury to animals. For example, the ritual offerings of flesh contemplate that the gods will eat it, and again the Brahmins ate the offerings.<ref name=fx1_ve2_553/> Again, the slaying of a ‘great ox’ (''[[महोक्ष|mahokṣa]]'') or a ‘great goat’ (''[[महाज|mahāja]]'') for a guest was regularly prescribed;<ref name=fx2_ve2_553/> and the name '''[[अतिथिग्व|Atithigva]]''' probably means ‘slaying cows for guests.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_553/> The great sage '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]]''' was wont to eat the meat of milch cows and bullocks (''dhenv-anaḍuha'') if only it was ''aṃsala'' (‘firm’ or ‘tender’).<ref name=fx4_ve2_553/> The slaughter of a hundred bulls (''[[उक्षन्|ukṣan]]'') was credited to one sacrificer, '''[[अगस्त्य|Agastya]].'''<ref name=fx5_ve2_553/> The marriage ceremony was accompanied by the slaying of oxen, clearly for food.<ref name=fx6_ve2_553/> <br><br>That there was any general objection to the eating of flesh is most improbable. Sometimes it is forbidden, as when a man is performing a vow,<ref name=fx7_ve2_553/> or its use is disapproved, as in a passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx8_ve2_553/> where meat is classed with '''[[सुरा|Surā]],''' or intoxicating liquor, as a bad thing. Again, in the Rigveda<ref name=fx9_ve2_553/> the slaying of the cows is said to take place in the '''Aghās,''' a deliberate variation for '''[[मघास्|Maghās]];''' but this may be the outcome merely of a natural association of death with gloom, even when cows alone are the victims in question. The Brāhmaṇas also contain the doctrine of the eater in this world being eaten in the next,<ref name=fx10_ve2_553/> but this is not to be regarded as a moral or religious disapproval of eating flesh, though it no doubt contains the germ of such a view, which is also in harmony with the persuasion of the unity of existence, which becomes marked in the Brāhmaṇas. But Ahiṃsā as a developed and articulate doctrine would seem to have arisen from the acceptance of the doctrine of transmigration, which in its fundamentals is later than the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] period.<ref name=fx11_ve2_553/><br><br>On the other hand, it is to be noted that the cow was on the road to acquire special sanctity in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx12_ve2_553/> as is shown by the name ''[[अघ्न्या|aghnyā]],''<ref name=fx13_ve2_553/> ‘not to be slain,’ applied to it in several passages. But this fact cannot be regarded as showing that  meat eating generally was condemned. Apart from mythical considerations, such as the identification of the cow with earth or Aditi (which are, of course, much more than an effort of priestly ingenuity), the value of the cow for other purposes than eating was so great as to account adequately for its sanctity, the beginnings of which can in fact be traced back to Indo-Iranian times.<ref name=fx14_ve2_553/> Moreover, the ritual of the cremation of the dead required the slaughter of a cow as an essential part, the flesh being used to envelope the dead body.<ref name=fx15_ve2_553/><br><br>The usual food of the Vedic Indian, as far as flesh was concerned, can be gathered from the list of sacrificial victims: what man ate he presented to the gods--that is, the sheep, the goat, and the ox. The horse sacrifice was an infrequent exception: it is probably not to be regarded as a trace of the use of horseflesh as food, though the possibility of such being the case cannot be overlooked in view of the widespread use of horseflesh as food in different countries and times. It is, however, more likely that the aim of this sacrifice was to impart magic strength, the speed and vigour of the horse, to the god and his worshippers, as Oldenberg<ref name=fx16_ve2_553/> argues.<br>

मांसौदन
<u>'''Māṃsaudana'''</u> denotes in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_554/> a dish consisting of ‘meat cooked with rice.’<br>

माक्षव्य
<u>'''Mākṣavya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Makṣu,’ is the patronymic of a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve2_555/> <br>

मागध
<u>'''Māgadha.'''</u> See '''[[मगध|Magadha]].'''<br>

मागध-देशीय
<u>'''Māgadha-deśīya,'''</u> ‘belonging to the district of '''[[मगध|Magadha]],'''’ is the description in the Sūtras<ref name=fx1_ve2_557/> of a Brahmin of [[मगध|Magadha]].<br>

माचल
<u>'''Mācala,'''</u> mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_558/> apparently denotes some sort of dog found in '''[[विदर्भ|Vidarbha]].'''<br>

माठरी
<u>'''Māṭharī,'''</u> ‘female descendant of Maṭhara,’ occurs in the curious name, '''[[काश्यपी-बालाक्या-माठरी-पुत्र|Kāśyapī-bālākyā-<a class="pada_vei" href="माठरी">māṭharī]]-putra»,''' of a teacher in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 31 Mādhyaṃdina).<br>

माण्टि
<u>'''Māṇṭi'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[गौतम|Gautama]],''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_560/><br>

माण्डवी
<u>'''Māṇḍavī,'''</u> ‘female descendant of Maṇḍu,’ occurs in the name of a teacher, '''[[वात्सी-माण्डवी-पुत्र|Vātsī-<a class="pada_vei" href="माण्डवी">māṇḍavī]]-putra»,''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 30 Mādhyaṃdina).<br>

माण्डव्य
<u>'''Māṇḍavya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Maṇḍu,’ is mentioned as a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_562/> in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx2_ve2_562/> and in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx3_ve2_562/> He is also mentioned as a pupil of '''[[कौत्स|Kautsa]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_562/><br>

माण्डूकायनि
<u>'''Māṇḍūkāyani,'''</u> ‘descendant of Māṇḍūka,’ is mentioned as a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_563/> <br>

माण्डूकायनी-पुत्र
<u>'''Māṇḍūkāyanī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Māṇḍūka,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[माण्डूकीपुत्र|Māṇḍūkīputra]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Brhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_564/><br>

माण्डूकी-पुत्र
<u>'''Māṇḍūkī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of [[मण्डूक|Maṇḍūka]],’ is mentioned as a teacher, a pupil of '''[[शाण्डिलीपुत्र|Śāṇḍilīputra]],''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_565/><br>

माण्डूकेय
<u>'''Māṇḍūkeya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Māṇḍūka,’ is the patronymic of several teachers in the Rigveda Āraṇyakas--viz., '''Śūravīra,'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_566/> '''Hrasva,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_566/> '''Dīrgha,'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_566/> '''Madhyama Prātībodhīputra.'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_566/> The Māṇḍūkeyas also occur as a school in the Āraṇyakas:<ref name=fx5_ve2_566/> a special form of the text of the Rigveda evidently appertained to them.<ref name=fx6_ve2_566/><br>

मातरिश्वन्
<u>'''Mātariśvan'''</u> is mentioned in a [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_567/> as a sacrificer along with '''[[मेध्य|Medhya]]''' and '''[[पृषध्र|Pṛṣadhra]].''' He seems to be mentioned also in one other passage, possibly in two.<ref name=fx2_ve2_567/> In the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_567/> a patron, '''[[पृषध्र|Pṛṣadhra]] [[मेध्य|Medhya]] [[मातरिश्वन्|Mātariśvan]]''' or '''Mātariśva''' is created by a misunderstanding of the Rigvedic text. <br>

मातुर्-भ्रात्र
<u>'''Mātur-bhrātra'''</u> is a curiously formed compound, occurring once in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_568/> as a designation of the ‘maternal uncle,’ who in the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period bears the name of '''[[मातुल|Mātula]].''' Thus little is heard of the maternal uncle in the Vedic period: it is not till the Epic<ref name=fx2_ve2_568/> that traces appear of his prominence as compared with the paternal uncle (''pitṛvya''). This fact is significant for the ‘patriarchal’ character of the early Indian family organization.<ref name=fx3_ve2_568/><br>

मातुल
<u>'''Mātula,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_569/> ‘maternal uncle,’ is found only in the Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve2_569/> and later.<br>

मातृ
<u>'''Mātṛ'''</u> is the regular word for ‘mother’ from the Rigveda onwards,<ref name=fx1_ve2_570/> being a formation probably developed under the influence of an onomatopœtic word ''mā,''<ref name=fx2_ve2_570/> used like Ambā<ref name=fx3_ve2_570/> and '''[[नना|Nanā]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_570/><br><br>The relations of wife and husband, as well as of mother and children, are treated under '''Pati.''' It remains only to add that details are given in the Sūtras<ref name=fx5_ve2_570/> of the respectful attention paid to a mother, and of the ceremonies in which she is concerned. The mother also appears interested in the fate of her children as in the story of the sale of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]''' for adoption by '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx6_ve2_570/> <br><br>In the household the mother ranked after the father (see '''[[पितृ|Pitṛ]]'''). Occasionally ''mātarā'' is used for ‘parents,’ as are also ''pitarā'' and ''mātarā pitarā''<ref name=fx7_ve2_570/> and ''mātā-pitaraḥ.''<ref name=fx8_ve2_570/><br>

मातृ-वध
<u>'''Mātṛ-vadha,'''</u> ‘matricide,’ is mentioned as a very grave crime in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iii. 1), but as one that can be expiated by the knowledge of the truth.<br>

मातृ-हन्
<u>'''Mātṛ-han,'''</u> ‘mother-killer,’ ‘matricide,’ occurs in a Vedic quotation mentioned by the commentator on Pāṇini.<ref name=fx1_ve2_572/><br>

मात्रा
<u>'''Mātrā'''</u> in the Upaniṣads<ref name=fx1_ve2_573/> denotes a mora, the length of a short vowel.<br>

मात्स्य
<u>'''1. Mātsya,'''</u> ‘prince of the [[मत्स्य|Matsya]] people.’ See '''[[मत्स्य|Matsya]].'''<br>

मात्स्य
<u>'''2. Mātsya'''</u> occurs in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_575/> as the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] skilled in sacrifice. Possibly,<ref name=fx2_ve2_575/> but not probably, he may also be meant in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_575/><br>

माथव
<u>'''Māthava,'''</u> ‘descendant of Mathu,’ is the patronymic of '''[[विदेघ|Videgha]],''' perhaps ‘king of [[विदेह|Videha]],’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_576/> <br>

माधुकि
<u>'''Mādhuki,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Madhuka,''' is the patronymic of a teacher mentioned with disapproval in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_577/><br>

माध्यंदिनायन
<u>'''Mādhyaṃdināyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[मध्यंदिन|Madhyaṃdina]],’ is the patronymic of a teacher mentioned in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 6, 2).<br>

माध्यम
<u>'''Mādhyama'''</u> (‘relating to the middle’) is a term applied in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_579/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve2_579/> to denote the ‘authors of the middle books’ (ii.-vii.) of the Rigveda.<br>

मान
<u>'''1. Māna'''</u> as a measure of weight is said to be the equivalent of the '''[[कृष्णल|Kṛṣṇala]]''' or Raktikā--that is, the berry of the Guñjā (''Abrus precatorius''). It occurs in compounds in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_580/><br>

मान
<u>'''2. Māna'''</u> is the name of a man occurring in several passages of the Rigveda. In one place<ref name=fx1_ve2_581/> express mention is made of his son (''[[सूनु|sūnu]]''), by whom, despite Bergaigne's view to the contrary,<ref name=fx2_ve2_581/> '''[[अगस्त्य|Agastya]]''' must be meant. In another passage,<ref name=fx3_ve2_581/> apparently the same meaning applies to [[मान|Māna]]--that is, [[अगस्त्य|Agastya]] as ‘a [[मान|Māna]].’ In a third passage<ref name=fx4_ve2_581/> the expression ''sūnave Mānena'' has been held by Sieg<ref name=fx5_ve2_581/> to be an inversion of ''Mānasya sūnunā,'' ‘by the son of Māna’--''i.e.,'' [[अगस्त्य|Agastya]]; but it seems more likely<ref name=fx6_ve2_581/> that either ''sūnor [[मान|Māna]]'' is the fuller form of Agastya's name (‘pride  of the son,’ with reference to his high ancestry), or that the son<ref name=fx7_ve2_581/> of [[मान|Māna]] (= [[अगस्त्य|Agastya]]) is alluded to as interested in '''[[विश्पला|Viśpalā]].'''<br><br>The Mānas--that is, the descendants of [[मान|Māna]], are in several passages alluded to as singers.<ref name=fx8_ve2_581/> ''Cf.'' '''[[मान्य|Mānya]], Māndārya.'''<br>

मानव
<u>'''Mānava,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Manu,'''’<ref name=fx1_ve2_582/> is the patronymic of '''[[नाभानेदिष्ठ|Nābhānediṣṭha]]''' and of '''[[शार्यात|Śāryāta]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_582/><br>

मानवी
<u>'''Mānavī,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Manu,'''’ is the patronymic of the mythical Iḍā (‘oblation’) in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_583/> and of a woman named '''[[पर्शु|Parśu]]''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_583/><br>

मानु-तन्तव्य
<u>'''Mānu-tantavya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Manutantu,’ is the patronymic of '''Aikādaśākṣa''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 30, 15). The Saumāpau Mānutantavyau, ‘two Saumāpas, descendants of Manutantu,’ are mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 5, 3, 2).<br>

मान्थाल
<u>'''Mānthāla'''</u> is the form in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 5, 8, 4) of the next name.<br>

मन्थालव
<u>'''Manthālava,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_586/> '''Mānthīlava'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_586/> are the names in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās of a victim at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’). What it was is unknown: the commentator Mahīdhara<ref name=fx3_ve2_586/> thinks it was a kind of mouse; Sāyaṇa explains it as a ‘water-cock’  (''jala-[[कुक्कुट|kukkuṭa]]''). Possiby, if Sāyaṇa's<ref name=fx4_ve2_586/> version of the parallel word '''[[मन्थावल|Manthāvala]]''' is to be trusted, the ‘flying fox’ may be meant.<ref name=fx5_ve2_586/><br>

मान्दार्य मान्य
<u>'''Māndārya Mānya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[मान|Māna]],'''’ is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_587/> It seems most probable that '''[[अगस्त्य|Agastya]]''' himself is meant.<ref name=fx2_ve2_587/><br>

मान्य
<u>'''Mānya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[मान|Māna]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Māndārya''' in several passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_588/> being also found alone in others.<ref name=fx2_ve2_588/> It probably denotes '''[[अगस्त्य|Agastya]].'''<br>

मान्यमान
<u>'''Mānyamāna'''</u> occurs with the word '''Devaka''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_589/> The word seems to be a patronymic from Manyamāna, meaning ‘son of the proud one.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_589/> Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_589/> renders the two words ‘the godling, the proudling (hast thou smitten).’<br>

मामतेय
<u>'''Māmateya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[ममता|Mamatā]],’ is the metronymic of '''[[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]]''' in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_590/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_590/><br>

मायव
<u>'''Māyava,'''</u> ‘descendant of Mayu or [[मायु|Māyu]],’ is the patronymic of a patron in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_591/> perhaps of '''[[राम|Rāma]],''' as Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_591/> thinks. <br>

माय
<u>'''Māya'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 4, 3, 11) corresponds to '''[[असुरविद्या|Asuravidyā]],''' ‘magic.’<br>

मायु
<u>'''Māyu'''</u> denotes the ‘lowing’ of a cow and the ‘bleating’ of a sheep or goat in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_593/> as well as the ‘chattering’ of a monkey in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_593/><br>

मारुत
<u>'''Māruta,'''</u> ‘descendant of Marut,’ is the patronymic of '''Dyutāna''' and of '''Nitāna.'''<br>

मारुताश्व
<u>'''Mārutāśva,'''</u> ‘descendant of Marutāśva,’ is, according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx1_ve2_595/> the patronymic of a patron in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_595/> The word may, however, be merely an adjective ‘having windswift horses.’<br>

मार्गवेय
<u>'''Mārgaveya'''</u> is the patronymic or metronymic of '''[[राम|Rāma]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 27, 3. 4), where he is mentioned as a '''Śyāparṇa.'''<br>

मार्गार
<u>'''Mārgāra'''</u> is the name of one of the victims at the Paruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_597/> The sense of the word is apparently ‘hunter,’ or possibly ‘fisherman,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_597/> as a patronymic from ''mṛgāri,'' ‘enemy of wild beasts.’<br>

माल्य
<u>'''1. Mālya,'''</u> ‘garland,’ is found in the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx1_ve2_598/><br>

माल्य
<u>'''2. Mālya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Māla,’ is the patronymic of '''[[आर्य|Ārya]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 4, 11). <br>

माष
<u>'''Māṣa'''</u> is the name of a kind of bean (''Phaseolus radiatus'') in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_600/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_600/> It is still one of the most valuable of similar plants in India. The seeds<ref name=fx3_ve2_600/> were pounded (''[[पिष्ट|piṣṭa]]'') according to the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx4_ve2_600/> These beans ripened in the winter (''[[हेमन्त|hemanta]]'').<ref name=fx5_ve2_600/> In the ritual the human head for the sacrifice is bought for twenty-one Māṣas<ref name=fx6_ve2_600/> : it does not appear that the word here means a weight of metal, as it often does later.<ref name=fx7_ve2_600/> A taboo on beans is found in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx8_ve2_600/><br>

मास्
<u>'''Mās'''</u> denotes rarely ‘moon,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_601/> and often ‘month’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_601/> and later.<ref name=fx3_ve2_601/> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

मास
<u>'''Māsa'''</u> denotes a ‘month,’ a period of time repeatedly mentioned in the Rigveda and later.<br><br>The characteristic days (or rather nights) of the month were those of the new moon, Amā-vasyā, ‘home-staying (night),’ and ‘of the full moon,’ [[पौर्ण-मासी|Paurṇa-māsī]]. Two hymns of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_602/> celebrate these days respectively. A personification of the phases of the moon is seen in the four names [[सिनीवाली|Sinīvālī]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_602/>  the day before new moon; [[कुहू|Kuhū]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_602/> also called Guṅgū,<ref name=fx4_ve2_602/> the new moon day; [[अनुमति|Anumati]],<ref name=fx5_ve2_602/> the day before full moon; and [[राका|Rākā]],<ref name=fx6_ve2_602/> the day of new moon. The importance of the new and full moon days is seen in the [[दर्श|Darśa]]-pūrṇamāsau, or festivals of the new and full moon days respectively.<br><br>One special day in the month, the '''[[एकाष्टका|Ekāṣṭakā]],''' or eighth day after full moon, was important. In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve2_602/> there are stated to be in the year twelve such, mentioned between the twelve days of full moon and the twelve days of new moon. But one [[एकाष्टका|Ekāṣṭakā]] is referred to in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās and elsewhere<ref name=fx8_ve2_602/> as of quite special importance. This was, in the accordant opinion of most commentators, the eighth day after the full moon of '''Māgha.''' It marked the end of the year, or the beginning of the new year. Though the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx9_ve2_602/> places the winter solstice in the new moon of Māgha, the latter date probably means the new moon preceding full moon in Māgha,<ref name=fx10_ve2_602/> not the new moon following  full moon; but it is perhaps possible to account adequately for the importance of the [[एकाष्टका|Ekāṣṭakā]] as being the first [[अष्टका|Aṣṭakā]] after the beginning of the new year.<br><br>It is not certain exactly how the month was reckoned, whether from the day after new moon to new moon--the system known as ''amānta,'' or from the day after full moon to full moon--the ''pūrṇimānta'' system, which later, at any rate, was followed in North India, while the other system prevailed in the south. Jacobi<ref name=fx11_ve2_602/> argues that the year began in the full moon of Phālguna, and that only by the full moon's conjunction with the [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] could the month be known. Oldenberg<ref name=fx12_ve2_602/> points to the fact that the new moon is far more distinctively an epoch than the full moon; that the Greek, Roman, and Jewish years began with the new moon; and that the Vedic evidence is the division of the month into the former (''pūrva'') and latter (''apara'') halves, the first being the bright (''[[शुक्ल|śukla]]''), the second the dark (''[[कृष्ण|kṛṣṇa]]'') period. Thibaut<ref name=fx13_ve2_602/> considers that to assume the existence of the ''pūrṇimānta'' system for the Veda is unnecessary, though possible. Weber<ref name=fx10_ve2_602/> assumes that it occurs in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] as held by the scholiasts. But it would probably be a mistake to press that passage, or to assume that the ''amānta'' system was rigidly accepted in the Veda: it seems at least as probable that the month was vaguely regarded as beginning with the new moon day, so that new moon preceded full moon, which was in the middle, not the end or the beginning of the month.<br><br>That a month regularly had 30 days is established by the conclusive evidence of numerous passages in which the year is given 12 months and 360 days. This month is known from the earliest records, being both referred to directly and alluded to.<ref name=fx14_ve2_602/>  It is the regular month of the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx15_ve2_602/> and must be regarded as the month which the Vedic Indian recognized. No other month is mentioned as such in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] literature; it is only in the Sūtras that months of different length occur. The [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]] Sūtras<ref name=fx16_ve2_602/> refer to (1) years with 324 days--''i.e.,'' periodic years with 12 months of 27 days each; (2) years with 351 days--''i.e.,'' periodic years with 12 months of 27 days each, plus another month of 27 days; (3) years with 354 days--''i.e.,'' 6 months of 30 days, and 6 with 29 days, in other words, lunar synodic years; (4) years with 360 days, or ordinary civil (''sāvana'') years; (5) years with 378 days, which, as Thibaut<ref name=fx17_ve2_602/> clearly shows, are third years, in which, after two years of 360 days each, 18 days were added to bring about correspondence between the civil year and the solar year of 366 days. But even the Sāmasūtras do not mention the year of 366 days, which is first known to the [[ज्योतिष|Jyotiṣa]]<ref name=fx18_ve2_602/> and to [[गर्ग|Garga]].<ref name=fx19_ve2_602/><br><br>That the Vedic period was acquainted with the year of 354 days cannot be affirmed with certainty. Zimmer,<ref name=fx20_ve2_602/> indeed, thinks that it is proved by the fact that pregnancy is estimated at ten months, or sometimes a year.<ref name=fx21_ve2_602/> But Weber<ref name=fx22_ve2_602/> may be right in holding that the month is the periodic month of 27 days, for the period is otherwise too long if a year is taken. On the other hand, the period of ten months quite well suits the period of gestation, if birth takes place in the tenth month, so that in this sense the month of 30 days may well be meant. <br><br>The year of 12 months of 30 days each being admittedly quite unscientific, Zimmer<ref name=fx23_ve2_602/> is strongly of opinion that it was only used with a recognition of the fact that intercalation took place, and that the year formed part of a greater complex, normally the five your Yuga or cycle. This system is well known from the Jyotṣa: it consists of 62 months of 29(16/31) days each = 1, 830 days (two of these months being intercalary, one in the middle and one at the end), or 61 months of 30 days, or 60 months of 30(1/2) days, the unit being clearly a solar year of 366 days. It is not an ideal system, since the year is too long;<ref name=fx24_ve2_602/> but it is one which cannot be claimed even for the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] period, during which no decision as to the true length of the year seems to have been arrived at. The references to it seen by Zimmer in the Rigveda<ref name=fx25_ve2_602/> are not even reasonably plausible, while the ''pañcaka yuga,'' cited by him from the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx26_ve2_602/> occurs only in a quotation in a commentary, and had no authority for the text itself.<br><br>On the other hand, there was undoubtedly some attempt to bring the year of 360 days--a synodic lunar year--roughly into connexion with reality. A Sāmasūtra<ref name=fx27_ve2_602/> treats it as a solar year, stating that he sun perambulates each Naxatra in 13(1/3) days, while others again evidently interpolated 18 days every third year, in order to arrive at some equality. But Vedic literature, from the Rigveda<ref name=fx28_ve2_602/> downwards,<ref name=fx29_ve2_602/> teems with the assertion of the difficulty of ascertaining the month. The length is variously given as 30 days,<ref name=fx30_ve2_602/> 35 days,<ref name=fx31_ve2_602/> or  36 days.<ref name=fx32_ve2_602/> The last number possibly indicates an intercalation after six years (6×6 = 36, or for ritual purposes 35), but for this we have no special evidence. There are many references<ref name=fx33_ve2_602/> to the year having 12 or 13 months.<br><br>The names of the months are, curiously enough, not at all ancient. The sacrificial texts of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] give them in their clearest form where the Agnicayana, ‘building of the fire-altar,’ is described.<ref name=fx34_ve2_602/> These names are the following: (1) [[मधु|Madhu]], (2) Mādhava (spring months, ''vāsantikāv ṛtū''); (3) [[शुक्र|Śukra]], (4) Śuci (summer months, ''graiṣmāv ṛtū''); (5) Nabha (or Nabhas),<ref name=fx35_ve2_602/> (6) Nabhasya (rainy months, ''vārṣikāv ṛtū''); (7) Iṣa, (8) Ūrja (autumn months, ''śāradāv ṛtū''); (9) Saha (or Sahas),<ref name=fx35_ve2_602/> (10) Sahasya (winter months, ''haimantikāv ṛtū''); (11) Tapa (or [[तपस्|Tapas]]),<ref name=fx35_ve2_602/> (12) Tapasya (cool months, ''śaiśirāv ṛtū'').<br><br>There are similar lists in the descriptions of the Soma sacrifice<ref name=fx36_ve2_602/> and of the horse sacrifice,<ref name=fx37_ve2_602/> all of them agreeing in essentials. There are other lists of still more fanciful names,<ref name=fx38_ve2_602/> but these have no claim at all to represent actual divisions in popular use. It is doubtful if the list given above is more than a matter of priestly invention. Weber points out that [[मधु|Madhu]] and Mādhava later appear as names of spring, and that these two are mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx39_ve2_602/> as if actually  employed; but the evidence is very inadequate to show that the other names of the months given in the list were in ordinary use.<ref name=fx40_ve2_602/><br><br>In some of these lists the intercalary month is mentioned. The name given to it in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx41_ve2_602/> is [[अंहसस्पति|Aṃhasaspati]], while that given in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]]<ref name=fx42_ve2_602/> and Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitās<ref name=fx43_ve2_602/> is [[संसर्प|Saṃsarpa]]. The [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx44_ve2_602/> gives it the name of [[मलिम्लुच|Malimluca]], which also occurs elsewhere, along with [[संसर्प|Saṃsarpa]], in one of the lists of fanciful names.<ref name=fx45_ve2_602/> The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx46_ve2_602/> describes it as ''[[सनिस्रस|sanisrasa]],'' ‘slipping,’ owing no doubt to its unstable condition.<br><br>The other method of naming the months is from the '''Nakṣatras.''' It is only beginning to be used in the Brāhmaṇas, but is found regularly in the Epic and later. The [[ज्योतिष|Jyotiṣa]]<ref name=fx47_ve2_602/> mentions that Māgha and Tapa were identical: this is the fair interpretation of the passage, which also involves the identification of [[मधु|Madhu]] with [[चैत्र|Caitra]], a result corresponding with the view frequently found in the Brāhmaṇas, that the full moon in [[चित्रा|Citrā]], and not that in [[फल्गुनी|Phalgunī]], is the beginning of the year.<ref name=fx48_ve2_602/><br><br>In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx49_ve2_602/> are found two curious expressions, ''yava'' and ''ayava,'' for the light and dark halves of the month, which is clearly considered to begin with the light half. Possibly the words are derived, as Eggling<ref name=fx50_ve2_602/> thinks, from ''yu,'' ‘ward off,’ with reference to evil spirits. The word '''[[पर्वन्|Parvan]]'''  (‘joint’ = division of time) probably<ref name=fx51_ve2_602/> denotes a half of the month, perhaps already in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx52_ve2_602/> More precisely the first half, the time of the waxing light, is called ''[[पूर्व-पक्ष|pūrva-pakṣa]],''<ref name=fx53_ve2_602/> the second, that of the waning light, ''apara-[[पक्ष|pakṣa]],''<ref name=fx54_ve2_602/> Either of these might be called a half-month (''ardha-[[मास|māsa]]'').<ref name=fx55_ve2_602/><br>

मासर
<u>'''Māsara'''</u> is mentioned as a beverage in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_603/> Its composition is described fully in the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_603/> It seems to have been a mixture of rice and '''[[श्यामाक|Śyāmāka]]''' with grass, parched barley, etc.<br>

माहकि
<u>'''Māhaki,'''</u> ‘descendant of Mahaka,’ is the patronymic of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_604/><br>

माहा-चमस्य
<u>'''Māhā-camasya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Mahācamasa,'''’ is the patronymic of a teacher to whom the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve2_605/> ascribes the addition of Mahas to the triad Bhūr '''Bhuvas''' Svar.<ref name=fx2_ve2_605/><br>

माहा-रजन
<u>'''Māhā-rajana,'''</u> ‘dyed with saffron’ (''mahā-rajana''), is applied to a garment ('''[[वासस्|Vāsas]]''') in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 3, 10). <br>

माहा-राज्य
<u>'''Māhā-rājya,'''</u> ‘the dignity of a great king’ (''[[महा-राज|mahā-rāja]]''), is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 6, 5; 12, 4; 15, 3).<br>

माहित्थि
<u>'''Māhitthi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Mahittha,’ is the patronymic of a teacher mentioned several times in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_608/> He is said to be a pupil of '''[[वामकक्षायण|Vāmakakṣāyaṇa]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_608/><br>

माहीन
<u>'''Māhīna'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_609/> which celebrates '''Asamāti''' as a king. The word, used in the plural, may be a patronymic referring to the priests who praised Asamāti, or it may be an adjective of uncertain meaning.<br>

मित्र
<u>'''Mitra'''</u> denotes ‘friend’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_610/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_610/> According to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_610/> a wife is a man's friend, and in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_610/> the value of a friend is insisted upon. Treachery to a friend is reprobated.<ref name=fx5_ve2_610/><br>

मित्र-भू काश्यप
<u>'''Mitra-bhū Kāśyapa'''</u> (‘descendant of Kaśyapa’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[विभण्डक काश्यप|Vibhaṇḍaka Kāśyapa]],''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_611/><br>

मित्र-भूति लौहित्य
<u>'''Mitra-[[भूति|bhūti]] Lauhitya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]''' (iii. 42, 1) as a pupil of '''Kṛṣṇadatta [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]].''' <br>

मित्र-वर्चस् स्थैरकायण
<u>'''Mitra-varcas Sthairakāyaṇa'''</u> (‘descendant of Sthiraka’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[सुप्रतीत औलुण्ड्य|Supratīta Auluṇḍya]],''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_613/><br>

मित्र-विन्द काश्यप
<u>'''Mitra-vinda Kāśyapa'''</u> (‘descendant of Kaśyapa’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''Sunītha,''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_614/><br>

मित्रातिथि
<u>'''Mitrātithi'''</u> is mentioned in one hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_615/> as the father of '''Kuruśravaṇa''' and the grandfather of '''[[उपमश्रवस्|Upamaśravas]],''' all being evidently kings.<br>

मुक्षीजा
<u>'''Mukṣījā'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_616/> where the sense seems clearly to be ‘net’ for catching animals. ''Cf.'' '''Padi.'''<br>

मुञ्ज
<u>'''1. Muñja'''</u> denotes a grass, the ''Saccharum [[मुञ्ज|Muñja]],'' which is of luxuriant growth, attaining to a height of ten feet. It is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_617/> along with other kinds of grasses as the lurking-place of venomous creatures. In the same text<ref name=fx2_ve2_617/> the [[मुञ्ज|Muñja]] grass is spoken of as purifying, apparently being used as the material of a filter for Soma. The grass is often mentioned in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx3_ve2_617/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx4_ve2_617/> It is in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_617/> said to be ‘hollow’ (''suṣira'') and to be used for the plaited part of the throne ('''[[आसन्दी|Āsandī]]''').<ref name=fx6_ve2_617/> <br>

मुञ्ज साम-श्रवस
<u>'''2. Muñja Sāma-śravasa'''</u> (‘descendant of Sāmaśravas’) is the name of a man, possibly a king, mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_618/> and the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_618/><br>

मुण्डिभ औदन्य
<u>'''Muṇḍibha Audanya'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_619/> or '''Audanyava'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_619/> is the name of a man in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_619/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_619/><br>

मुद्ग
<u>'''Mudga,'''</u> denoting a kind of bean (''Phascolus Mungo''), occurs in a list of vegetables in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_620/> A ‘soup of rice with beans’ (''mudgaudana'') is mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve2_620/> and the Sūtras. ''Cf.'' perhaps '''[[मुद्गल|Mudgala]].'''<br>

मुद्गल
<u>'''Mudgala'''</u> and '''Mudgalanī,''' ‘Mudgala's wife,’ both figure in a hopelessly obscure hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_621/> variously interpreted by Pischel<ref name=fx2_ve2_621/> and Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve2_621/> and von Bradke<ref name=fx4_ve2_621/> as telling of a real chariot race in which, despite difficulties, [[मुद्गल|Mudgala]] won by his wife's aid. The Indian tradition is as variant as the interpretations of modern authorities. Ṣaḍguruśiṣya<ref name=fx5_ve2_621/> explains that Mudgala's oxen were stolen, that he pursued the thieves with the one old ox he had left, and that hurling his hammer (''[[द्रु-घण|dru-ghaṇa]]'') he caught the marauders. [[यास्क|Yāska]],<ref name=fx6_ve2_621/> on the other hand, says that [[मुद्गल|Mudgala]] won a race with a ''[[द्रुघण|drughaṇa]]'' and an ox instead of with two oxen. It is pretty clear that, as Roth<ref name=fx7_ve2_621/> observed, the tradition is merely a guess, and a bad one, at the meaning of an obscure hymn, and this view is  accepted by Oldenberg.<ref name=fx8_ve2_621/> Bloomfield<ref name=fx9_ve2_621/> has interpreted the legend as one of heavenly, not of human, events. [[मुद्गल|Mudgala]], probably a variant form of Mudgara,<ref name=fx10_ve2_621/> which in the later language means a hammer or a similar weapon, may be meant as a personfication of the thunderbolt of Indra, rather than a real man.<ref name=fx11_ve2_621/> Later<ref name=fx12_ve2_621/> [[मुद्गल|Mudgala]] is a mythical sage.<br>

मुनि
<u>'''Muni'''</u> occurs in one hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_622/> where it seems to denote an ascetic of magic powers with divine afflatus (''deveṣita''), the precursor of the strange ascetics of later India. This agrees with the fact that '''[[ऐतश|Aitaśa]],''' the Muni, is in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_622/> regarded by his son as deranged, a view not unjustified if the nonsense which passes as the Aitaśapralāpa.<ref name=fx3_ve2_622/> ‘Chatter of [[ऐतश|Aitaśa]],’ was really his. The Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_622/> calls Indra the ‘friend of Munis,’ and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx5_ve2_622/> refers to a ‘divine Muni’ (''deva muni''), by whom a similar ascetic may be meant.<br><br>In the Upaniṣads<ref name=fx6_ve2_622/> the Muni is of a more restrained type: he is one who learns the nature of the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], the Absolute, by study, or sacrifice, or penance, or fasting, or faith (''śraddhā''). It must not of course be thought that there is any absolute distinction between the older Muni and the later: in both cases the man is in a peculiar ecstatic condition, but the ideal of the Upaniṣads is less material than the earlier picture of the Muni, who is more of a ‘medicine man’ than a sage. Nor would it be wise to conclude from the comparative rareness  of the mention of the Muni in the Vedic texts that he was an infrequent figure in Vedic times: he was probably not approved by the priests who followed the ritual, and whose views were essentially different from the ideals of a Muni, which were superior to earthly considerations, such as the desire for children and '''Dakṣiṇās.'''<ref name=fx7_ve2_622/><br>

मुनि-मरण
<u>'''Muni-maraṇa,'''</u> ‘Saints’ Death,’ is the name of the place where, according to the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 4, 7), the '''Vaikhanasas''' were slain.<br>

मुलालिन्
<u>'''Mulālin'''</u> (masc.) or '''Mulālī''' (fem.) is the name of some part of an edible lotus (perhaps the ''Nymphaea esculenta'') in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_624/><br>

मुषीवन्
<u>'''Muṣīvan'''</u> denotes ‘robber’ in one passage of the Rigveda (i. 42, 3).<br>

मुष्कर
<u>'''Muṣkara'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_626/> possibly in the sense of a small animal or insect, as suggested by Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_626/> who, however, thought the passage corrupt. Bloomfield<ref name=fx3_ve2_626/> suggests that the reading of the Paippalāda text ''puṣkaram,'' (‘blue lotus’) is the correct form.<br>

मुष्टि-हन्
<u>'''Muṣṭi-han,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_627/> '''Muṣṭi-hatyā,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_627/> in the Rigveda and the Atharvaveda denote. respectively, the ‘hand to hand fighter’--that is, the ordinary warrior as opposed to the charioteer, and the  ‘fight’ itself. So also in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_627/> the charioteer (''[[रथिन्|rathin]]'') is opposed to the foot-soldier (''[[पत्ति|patti]]''), and in the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_627/> the chariots are opposed to the troops (''[[ग्राम|grāma]]'') of the infantry. The parallel of the Greek and other Āryan races shows that the Kṣatriyas were the fighters from chariots, while the ordinary host fought on foot.<br>

मुसल
<u>'''Musala'''</u> denotes a ‘pestle’ in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_628/> and in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_628/><br>

मुहूर्त
<u>'''Muhūrta'''</u> denotes a division of time, one-thirtieth of a day, or an hour of forty-eight minutes, in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_629/> In the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_629/> the sense of ‘moment’ only is found. ''Cf.'' '''Ahan.'''<br>

मूचीप
<u>'''Mūcīpa'''</u> or '''Mūvīpa''' is the variant in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xv. 26, 6) of the '''[[मूतिब|Mūtiba]]''' of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] as the name of a barbarian tribe.<br><br>''Cf.'' Weber, ''Indische Studien,'' 10, 67, n. 1.<br>

मूजवन्त्
<u>'''Mūjavant'''</u> is the name of a people who, along with the '''Mahāvṛṣas,''' the '''Gandhāris,''' and the '''Balhikas,''' are mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_631/> as dwelling far away, and to whom fever is to be banished. Similarly in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve2_631/> the Mūjavants are chosen as a type of distant folk, beyond  which Rudra with his bow is entreated to depart. In the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_631/> Soma is described as [[मौजवत|Maujavata]], ‘coming from the Mūjavants,’ or, as [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_631/> takes it, ‘from Mount [[मूजवन्त्|Mūjavant]].’ The Indian commentators<ref name=fx5_ve2_631/> agree with [[यास्क|Yāska]] in taking [[मूजवन्त्|Mūjavant]] as the name of a mountain, and though Hillebrandt<ref name=fx6_ve2_631/> is justified in saying that the identification of [[मूजवन्त्|Mūjavant]] by Zimmer<ref name=fx7_ve2_631/> with one of the lower hills on the south-west of Kaśmīr lacks evidence, it is not reasonable to deny that [[मूजवन्त्|Mūjavant]] was a hill from which the people took their name. [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx8_ve2_631/> suggests that [[मूजवन्त्|Mūjavant]] is equivalent to Muñjavant, which actually occurs later, in the Epic,<ref name=fx9_ve2_631/> as the name of a mountain in the Himālaya.<br>

मूत
<u>'''Mūta'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_632/> denotes a ‘woven basket.’ Mūtaka means a ‘small basket.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_632/><br>

मूतिब
<u>'''Mūtiba'''</u> appears in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_633/> as the name of one of the barbarous peoples enumerated as nominally '''Viśvāmitra's''' outcast offspring. The [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_633/> gives the name as '''[[मूचीप|Mūcīpa]]''' or '''Mūvīpa.'''<br>

मूल
<u>'''Mūla, Mūlabarhaṇa.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

मूस्
<u>'''Mūs,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_635/> '''Mūṣikā,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_635/> are the names of ‘mouse’ occurring in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_635/> and the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve2_635/> <br>

मृग
<u>'''1. Mṛga'''</u> has the generic sense of ‘wild beast’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_636/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_636/> Sometimes it is qualified by the epithet ‘terrible’ (''bhīma''),<ref name=fx3_ve2_636/> which indicates that a savage wild beast is meant. Elsewhere the buffalo is shown to be denoted by the epithet ''[[महिष|mahiṣa]],''<ref name=fx4_ve2_636/> ‘powerful,’ which later becomes the name of the buffalo. More particularly the word has the sense of an animal of the gazelle type.<ref name=fx5_ve2_636/> In some passages<ref name=fx6_ve2_636/> Roth<ref name=fx7_ve2_636/> sees the sense of ‘bird.’ See also '''[[मृग हस्तिन्|Mṛga Hastin]], [[पुरुष हस्तिन्|Puruṣa Hastin]].'''<br>

मृग
<u>'''2. Mṛga'''</u> in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_637/> denotes, according to Sāyaṇa's commentary, the constellation '''[[मृगशिरस्|Mṛgaśiras]].''' But it seems more probable<ref name=fx2_ve2_637/> that [[मृग|Mṛga]] there really covers the whole of Orion, not merely the inconspicuous group of stars in the head of Orion that make up the [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] [[मृगशिरस्|Mṛgaśiras]], but also the star ''a'' in his shoulder, which is reckoned as [[आर्द्रा|Ārdrā]], and  in his left shoulder. Tilak,<ref name=fx3_ve2_637/> however, makes [[मृग|Mṛga]] or [[मृगशिरस्|Mṛgaśiras]] into a different group, consisting of the belt of Orion, with two stars in the knees and one in the left shoulder, which he deems to resemble a deer's head with an arrow through it, an implausible and unlikely theory. ''Cf.'' '''[[मृगव्याध|Mṛgavyādha]].'''<br>

मृग हस्तिन्
<u>'''3. Mṛga Hastin,'''</u> the ‘animal with a hand,’ is mentioned in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_638/> in which Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_638/> recognizes that the elephant is meant, but concludes that the compound name  is a proof of the newness of the elephant to the Vedic Indians.<ref name=fx3_ve2_638/> Later the adjective [[हस्तिन्|Hastin]] alone became the regular name of the animal (like '''[[महिष|Mahiṣa]]''' of the ‘buffalo’). The elephant is also denoted in the Rigveda by the descriptive term [[मृग|Mṛga]] [[वारण|Vāraṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve2_638/> the ‘wild or dangerous animal,’ the adjective ''[[वारण|vāraṇa]]'' similarly becoming one of the names for ‘elephant’ in the later language. Pischel's view<ref name=fx5_ve2_638/> that the catching of elephants by the use of tame female elephants is already alluded to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve2_638/> seems very doubtful. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve2_638/> elephants are described as ‘black, white-toothed, adorned with gold.’<br>

मृगय
<u>'''Mṛgaya'''</u> occurs in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_639/> as defeated by Indra. That he was a human foe, as Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_639/> thinks, seems unlikely: more probably he was a demon, as [[मृग|Mṛga]] unquestionably is.<ref name=fx3_ve2_639/><br>

मृगयु
<u>'''Mṛgayu,'''</u> ‘hunter,’ occurs in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_640/> and the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve2_640/> but not very often. The Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_640/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve2_640/> however, in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) include a number of names which seem to be those of persons who make a livelihood by fishing or by hunting, such as the '''[[मार्गार|Mārgāra]],''' ‘hunter,’  the '''[[कैवर्त|Kaivarta]]''' or '''[[केवर्त|Kevarta]], [[पौञ्जिष्ठ|Pauñjiṣṭha]], Daśa, [[मैनाल|Maināla]],''' ‘fisher man,’ and perhaps the '''[[बैन्द|Bainda]]''' and the Ānda,<ref name=fx5_ve2_640/> who seem to have been some sort of fishermen.<br><br>It is not probable that even in the earliest Vedic period hunting formed the main source of livelihood for any of the Vedic tribes: pastoral pursuits and agriculture ('''[[कृषि|Kṛṣi]]''') were, no doubt, the mainstay of their existence. But it would be unreasonable to suppose that not much hunting was done, both for recreation and for purposes of food, as well as for protection of flocks from wild beasts. The Rigveda is naturally our chief source of information in regard to hunting. The arrow was sometimes employed,<ref name=fx6_ve2_640/> but, as is usual with primitive man, the normal instruments of capture were nets and pitfalls. Birds were regularly caught in nets ('''[[पाश|Pāśa]],'''<ref name=fx7_ve2_640/> '''[[निधा|Nidhā]],'''<ref name=fx8_ve2_640/> '''[[जाल|Jāla]]'''),<ref name=fx9_ve2_640/> The bird-catcher being called ''[[निधा|nidhā]]-pati,''<ref name=fx10_ve2_640/> ‘master of snares.’ The net was fastened on pegs<ref name=fx11_ve2_640/> (as is done with modern nets for catching birds). Another name of net is apparently '''[[मुक्षीजा|Mukṣījā]].'''<br><br>Pits were used for catching antelopes ('''[[ऋश्य|Ṛśya]]'''), and so were called ''[[ऋश्य|ṛśya]]-da,''<ref name=fx12_ve2_640/> ‘antelope-catching.’ Elephants were captured as in Greek times, perhaps through the instrumentality of tame females (see '''[[मृग हस्तिन्|Mṛga Hastin]]'''). Apparently the boar was captured in the chase, dogs being used,<ref name=fx13_ve2_640/> but the passage from which this view is deduced is of uncertain mythological content. There is also an obscure reference<ref name=fx14_ve2_640/> to the capture of the buffalo ('''[[गौर|Gaura]]'''), but it is not clear whether the reference is to shooting with an arrow or capturing by means of ropes, perhaps a lasso, or a net. The lion was captured in pitfalls,<ref name=fx15_ve2_640/> or was surrounded by the hunters and slain;<ref name=fx16_ve2_640/> one very obscure passage refers to the lion being caught by ambuscade, which perhaps merely alludes to the use of the hidden pit.<ref name=fx17_ve2_640/><br><br>The modes of catching fish are little known, for the only evidence available are the explanations of the various names  mentioned in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]. Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx18_ve2_640/> says that '''[[धैवर|Dhaivara]]''' is one who takes fish by netting a tank on either side; [[दाश|Dāśa]] and '''[[शौष्कल|Śauṣkala]]''' do so by means of a fish-hook (''baḍiśa''); [[बैन्द|Bainda]], [[कैवर्त|Kaivarta]], and [[मैनाल|Maināla]] by means of a net (''[[जाल|jāla]]''); [[मार्गार|Mārgāra]] catches fish in the water with his hands; Ānda by putting in pegs at a ford (apparently by building a sort of dam); '''[[पर्णक|Parṇaka]]''' by putting a poisoned leaf on the water. But none of these explanations can claim much authority.<br>

मृग-व्याध
<u>'''Mṛga-vyādha,'''</u> ‘the hunter,’ is the name of Sirius in the legned of Prajāpati's daughter in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_641/> Prajāpati (Orion) pursues his daughter ([[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]]), and is shot by the archer Sirius. The transference of the legend of Prajāpati to the sky is no doubt secondary, caused by the obvious similarity of the constellation in question to the idea of an archer.<br>

मृग-शिरस्
<u>'''Mṛga-śiras, [[मृग|Mṛga]]-śīrṣa.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]],''' 1. and 2. '''[[मृग|Mṛga]].'''<br>

मृगाखर
<u>'''Mṛgākhara'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vii. 5, 21, 1) and [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 9, 17, 3) denotes the ‘lair of wild beasts.’<br>

मृड
<u>'''Mṛḍa'''</u> is found only in compounds in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve2_644/> where it seems to denote a small weight of gold. It is uncertain whether the reading should not be Pṛda, as in the grammatical tradition.<ref name=fx2_ve2_644/><br>

मृत्तिका
<u>'''Mṛttikā,'''</u> ‘clay,’ is mentioned in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_645/> ''Cf.'' '''[[मृद्|Mṛd]].''' <br>

मृत्यु
<u>'''Mṛtyu,'''</u> ‘death,’ is repeatedly mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_646/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_646/> as a thing of terror. There are a hundred and one forms of death, the natural one by old age<ref name=fx3_ve2_646/> (''jarā''), and a hundred others, all to be avoided.<ref name=fx4_ve2_646/> To die before old age (''purā jarasaḥ'')<ref name=fx5_ve2_646/> is to die before the allotted span (''purā āyuṣaḥ''),<ref name=fx6_ve2_646/> the normal length of life being throughout Vedic literature spoken of as a hundred years.<ref name=fx7_ve2_646/> On the other hand, the evils of old age in the loss of physical strength were clearly realized.<ref name=fx8_ve2_646/> one of the feats of the Aśvins was to restore old '''Cyavāna''' to his former youth and powers, and another was the rejuventation of '''Kali.'''<ref name=fx9_ve2_646/> The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx10_ve2_646/> is full of charms of all sorts to avert death and secure length of years (''āyuṣya'').<br><br>The modes of disposing of the dead were burial and cremation (see '''[[अग्निदग्ध|Agnidagdha]]'''). Both existed in the early Vedic period,<ref name=fx11_ve2_646/> as in Greece;<ref name=fx12_ve2_646/> but the former method was on the whole less favoured, and tended to be regarded with disapproval. The bones of the dead, whether burned or not, were marked by the erection of a tumulus ('''[[श्मशान|Śmaśāna]]'''): the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx13_ve2_646/> preserves traces of strong differences of opinion as to the mode in which these tumuli should be constructed. There is little or no trace<ref name=fx14_ve2_646/> of the custom common in northern lands of sending the dead man to sea in a burning ship: the reference  to a ship<ref name=fx15_ve2_646/> seems to point to mythical perils after death, not to the mode of burial.<br><br>The life after death was to the Vedic Indian a repetition of the life in this world. He passed into the next world ''sarvatanuḥ sāṅgaḥ,'' ‘with whole body and all his members,’<ref name=fx16_ve2_646/> enjoying there the same pleasures as he had enjoyed on earth. Even in the Rigveda<ref name=fx17_ve2_646/> there are hints of evil awaiting evil-doers, but it is not until the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx18_ve2_646/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx19_ve2_646/> that a hell of punishment is set out, and it is in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx20_ve2_646/> that good and evil deeds are said to produce happiness or hell hereafter. But there is no hint of extinction<ref name=fx21_ve2_646/> in the Rigveda as the fate of the wicked, as Roth<ref name=fx22_ve2_646/> inclined to think. The Vedic poet not being deeply moral, his verses do not convey, as would those of a man convinced of sin, warnings of future judgment.<br>

मृद्
<u>'''Mṛd'''</u> denotes ‘clay’ in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_647/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_647/> (''cf.'' '''[[मृत्तिका|Mṛttikā]]'''). A ‘lump of clay’ also occurs in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx3_ve2_647/> and a Mṛt-paca, ‘potter,’ in the Maitrāyaṇī [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_647/> A ‘clay vessel,’ Mṛtpātra,<ref name=fx5_ve2_647/> and vessels (''[[पात्र|pātra]]'') made of clay (''mṛn-maya''),<ref name=fx6_ve2_647/> are mentioned, and the grave is called the ‘house of clay.’<ref name=fx7_ve2_647/> <br>

मृध्
<u>'''Mṛdh'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_648/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_648/> denotes ‘enemy.’<br>

मृध्र-वाच्
<u>'''Mṛdhra-vāc.'''</u> See '''[[दस्यु|Dasyu]]''' and '''[[दास|Dāsa]].'''<br>

मेक्षण
<u>'''Mekṣaṇa'''</u> is the name in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_650/> of a wooden ladle used for stirring up the oblation ('''Caru''').<br>

मेखला
<u>'''Mekhalā'''</u> denotes ‘girdle’ in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_651/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_651/> The '''Brahmacārin''' wore a girdle.<ref name=fx3_ve2_651/><br>

मेघ
<u>'''Megha'''</u> denotes ‘cloud’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_652/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_652/><br>

मेथि
<u>'''Methi'''</u> is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_653/> denoting ‘post.’ The word is also found in the marriage ritual,<ref name=fx2_ve2_653/> when the sense is, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, a post to support the pole of a chariot. In one passage of the Rigveda it is perhaps used of posts forming a palisade.<ref name=fx3_ve2_653/> In the Pañcaviṃśa  [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_653/> it appears in the form of Methī to denote the post to which the sacrificial cow is tied. The word is very variously spelt, Medhi and Meṭhī also being found.<br>

मेध
<u>'''Medha'''</u> is a word of uncertain sense occurring in a [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_654/> According to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, the proper name of a sacrificer may be meant.<br>

मेधातिथि
<u>'''Medhātithi,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_655/> '''[[मेध्यातिथि|Medhyātithi]]'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_655/> (‘having a guest at the sacrifice’) appear to be the names of one and the same man, a descendant of '''[[कण्व|Kaṇva]]''' and a famous Vedic '''[[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]],''' to whom the authorship of various hymns<ref name=fx3_ve2_655/> is attributed in the Anukramaṇī (Index). To him Indra is said in the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_655/> to have come in the form of a ram: this myth is perpetuated in the Subrahmaṇyā formula<ref name=fx5_ve2_655/> recited by the priest while the Soma is being carried within the sacrificial enclosure, when Indra is hailed as ‘ram of [[मेधातिथि|Medhātithi]].’ He appears also as a rival of '''[[वत्स|Vatsa]],''' whom he accused of low birth, but who convinced him of his error by undergoing a fire ordeal (''cf.'' '''[[दिव्य|Divya]]''').<ref name=fx6_ve2_655/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx7_ve2_655/> he is mentioned with many other sages, and occurs elsewhere<ref name=fx8_ve2_655/> also as a sage. <br>

मेध्य
<u>'''Medhya'''</u> is the name of a man, an ancient sacrificer, in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_656/> In the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_656/> he is erroneously transmuted into '''[[पृषध्र|Pṛṣadhra]] [[मेध्य|Medhya]] [[मातरिश्वन्|Mātariśvan]],''' the patron of '''[[प्रस्कण्व|Praskaṇva]] [[काण्व|Kāṇva]].'''<br>

मेध्यातिथि
<u>'''Medhyātithi.'''</u> See '''[[मेधातिथि|Medhātithi]].'''<br>

मेनका
<u>'''Menakā.'''</u> See 2. '''[[मेना|Menā]].'''<br>

मेना
<u>'''1. Menā'''</u> in a few passages of the Rigveda denotes ‘woman.’<ref name=fx1_ve2_659/> The word is also used in the sense of the ‘female’ of an animal, either mare<ref name=fx2_ve2_659/> or cow.<ref name=fx3_ve2_659/><br>

मेना
<u>'''2. Menā'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_660/> or '''[[मेनका|Menakā]]'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_660/> is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_660/> and in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx4_ve2_660/> as the daughter, or perhaps wife, of '''[[वृषण्अश्व|Vṛṣaṇaśva]].''' The meaning of the legend connected with her is quite unknown. ''Cf.'' '''[[मैनाक|Maināka]]''' or '''Mainaga.'''<br>

मेष
<u>'''Meṣa'''</u> denotes ‘ram’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_661/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_661/> while Meṣī means ‘sheep.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_661/> Both words are also used to denote the  ‘wool’<ref name=fx4_ve2_661/> of the sheep, '''especially''' as employed for the Soma filter. A wild (''āraṇya'') '''ram is''' mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx5_ve2_661/><br>

मेहत्नू
<u>'''Mehatnū'''</u> is the name of a stream in the Nadīstuti (‘Praise of Rivers’) in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_662/> It must apparently have been a tributary of the '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]''' (Indus), entering that river before the '''[[क्रुमु|Krumu]]''' (Kurum) and '''[[गोमती|Gomatī]]''' (Gomal). It may conceivably have been a tributary of the '''[[क्रुमु|Krumu]].'''<br>

मैत्रायणीय ब्राह्मण
<u>'''Maitrāyaṇīya Brāhmaṇa'''</u> is the name of a text mentioned in the Śulba [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] of [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_663/><br>

मैत्रेय
<u>'''Maitreya'''</u> is the patronymic or metronymic<ref name=fx1_ve2_664/> of '''[[कौषारव|Kauṣārava]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_664/> It is also applied to '''Glāva''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_664/><br>

मैत्रेयी
<u>'''Maitreyī'''</u> is the name of one of the wives of '''Yājṅavalkya''' according to the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 4, 1 ''et seq.;'' iv. 5, 2 ''et seq.'').<br>

मैनाक
<u>'''Maināka,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[मेनका|Menakā]],'''’ is the name of a mountain among the Himālayas in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve2_666/> There is a various reading Maināga. <br>

मैनाल
<u>'''Maināla'''</u> occurs in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_667/> It seems clearly to mean ‘fisherman’ from Mīna, ‘fish,’ as Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx2_ve2_667/> and Mahīdhara<ref name=fx3_ve2_667/> explain it.<br>

मौजवत
<u>'''Maujavata.'''</u> See '''[[मूजवन्त्|Mūjavant]].'''<br>

मौद्गल्य
<u>'''Maudgalya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[मुद्गल|Mudgala]],'''’ is the patronymic of several persons, '''[[नाक|Nāka]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_669/> '''Śatabalākṣa,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_669/> and '''[[लाङ्गलायन|Lāṅgalāyana]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_669/> '''A Brahmacārin''' of the name is mentioned in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_669/> as disputing with '''[[ग्लाव मैत्रेय|Glāva Maitreya]].'''<br>

मौन
<u>'''Mauna,'''</u> ‘descendant of Muni,’ is the patronymic of '''Aṇīcin''' in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxiii. 5).<br>

मौषिकी-पुत्र
<u>'''Mauṣikī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Mūṣikā,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[हारिकर्णीपुत्र|Hārikarṇīputra]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 30).<br>

म्लेच्छ
<u>'''Mleccha'''</u> occurs in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_672/> in the sense of a barbarian in speech. The Brahmin is there forbidden to use barbarian speech. The example<ref name=fx2_ve2_672/> given of such speech is ''lie 'lavo,'' explained by Sāyaṇa as ''he 'rayaḥ,'' ‘ho, foes.’ If this is correct--the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension has a different reading<ref name=fx3_ve2_672/> --the barbarians referred to were Āryan speakers, though not speakers of Sanskrit, but of a Prākṛta form of speech.<ref name=fx4_ve2_672/> ''Cf.'' '''[[वाच्|Vāc]].''' <br>

यक्ष
<u>'''Yakṣa'''</u> is found several times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_673/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_673/> in passages in which Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve2_673/> sees the meaning of a feast or holy practice in accordance with the native commentators. It is, however, very doubtful whether this sense ever occurs.<ref name=fx4_ve2_673/><br>

यक्षु
<u>'''Yakṣu'''</u> is mentioned, once in the singular and once in the plural, in the hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_674/> which celebrates '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' battle with the ten kings. Who they were and what part they played in that conflict is quite uncertain. They seem, from the wording of the text, to have taken part in two conflicts, as Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_674/> says--one on the '''[[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]]''' (Ravi), and one on the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]''' (Jumna)--with the aid of the '''Ajas''' and '''Śigrus,''' under the leadership of '''Bḥeda.''' It is, however, at least possible that in the former passage '''Yadu''' should be read for [[यक्षु|Yakṣu]], or, at any rate, [[यक्षु|Yakṣu]] be deemed a contemptuous substitute of the name of a possibly un-Āryan or unimportant tribe (as their allies, the Ajas and Śigrus, clearly were) for the name of the certainly famous Yadus, as is suggested by Hopkins.<ref name=fx3_ve2_674/> ''Cf.'' '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]].'''<br>

यक्ष्म
<u>'''Yakṣma'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_675/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_675/> frequently denotes ‘illness,’ in general, perhaps as rendering the body emaciated. A hundred kinds of [[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]] are referred to in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve2_675/> and ''a-[[यक्ष्म|yakṣma]]'' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx4_ve2_675/>  denotes ‘free from disease.’ In the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx5_ve2_675/> an account is given of the origin of [[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]], which is distinguished as of three kinds--'''[[राज-यक्ष्म|Rāja-yakṣma]],''' ‘royal [[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]],’ [[पाप-यक्ष्म|Pāpa-yakṣma]], ‘evil [[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]],’ and '''Jāyenya,''' most probably ‘syphilis.’ The second of the series is elsewhere unknown, and can hardly be defined, for it merely means ‘serious or deadly disease.’ ''Cf.'' also '''[[अज्ञातयक्ष्म|Ajñātayakṣma]].'''<br>

यजत
<u>'''Yajata'''</u> occurs in a hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_676/> where he is apparently a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] or a sacrificer.<br>

यजुर्-वेद
<u>'''Yajur-veda,'''</u> the ‘Veda of the sacrificial utterance’ ('''[[यजुस्|Yajus]]'''), is mentioned frequently in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_677/> and Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx2_ve2_677/><br>

यजुस्
<u>'''Yajus'''</u> is repeatedly distinguished from the Ṛc and the '''Sāman''' in Vedic literature.<ref name=fx1_ve2_678/> The [[यजुस्|Yajus]] is the utterance accompanying the sacrifice, and may have the form of verse or prose, the tern covering both. <br>

यज्ञ-गाथा
<u>'''Yajña-gāthā'''</u> denotes a verse ('''[[गाथा|Gāthā]]''') containing a maxim as to the sacrifice of any kind or sort,<ref name=fx1_ve2_679/> or, as it is expressed in the Mahābhārata,<ref name=fx2_ve2_679/> a ‘verse sung regarding the sacrifice’ (''[[गाथा|gāthā]] yajña-gītā'').<br>

यज्ञ-वचस् राजस्तम्बायन
<u>'''Yajña-vacas Rājastambāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Rājastamba,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[तुर कावषेय|Tura Kāvaṣeya]],''' according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_680/> He is also mentioned in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_680/><br>

यज्ञ-सेन
<u>'''Yajña-sena'''</u> is the name of a teacher with the patronymic '''[[चैत्र|Caitra]]''' or '''[[चैत्रियायण|Caitriyāyaṇa]]''' mentioned in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_681/><br>

यज्ञेषु
<u>'''Yajñeṣu'''</u> is the name of a man in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_682/> He was made to prosper by his priest '''[[मात्स्य|Mātsya]],''' who knew the exact moment of sacrificing.<br>

यज्ञोपवीत
<u>'''Yajñopavīta'''</u> denotes the ‘wearing of the Brahminical thread over the left shoulder at the sacrifice,’ and is mentioned as early as the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_683/> Tilak,<ref name=fx2_ve2_683/> however, urges that it was not originally a thread that was worn, but a garment of cloth ('''[[वासस्|Vāsas]]''') or of deerskin ('''[[अजिन|Ajina]]'''). This seems quite probable. <br>

यति
<u>'''Yati'''</u> is the name of an ancient clan which is connected with the '''Bhṛgus''' in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_684/> where the Yatis certainly seem to be real persons. In another hymn,<ref name=fx2_ve2_684/> however, they already appear as almost mythical. In the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx3_ve2_684/> and elsewhere,<ref name=fx4_ve2_684/> the Yatis are a race whom Indra, in an evil moment, gave over to the hyænas ('''[[सालावृक|Sālāvṛka]]'''): exactly what is referred to is uncertain. Yati is mentioned with [[भृगु|Bhṛgu]] in a verse of the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_684/><br>

यदु
<u>'''Yadu'''</u> is the name of a tribe and of the king of the tribe. They are mentioned repeatedly in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_685/> normally in conjunction with '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]].''' They seem to have taken part in the great battle against '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]:'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_685/> the Yadu and the [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] kings seem to have escaped with their lives, while the '''Anu''' and the '''[[द्रुह्यु|Druhyu]]''' kings perished. This is at least the most natural explanation of several passages,<ref name=fx3_ve2_685/> though these passages possibly refer to a successful raid across the '''[[सरयु|Sarayu]],''' and a defeat of two princes, Arṇa and [[चित्ररथ|Citraratha]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_685/> That [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] was the Yadu king, as Hopkins<ref name=fx5_ve2_685/> holds, is most improbable.<br>

यन्तृ
<u>'''Yantṛ'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_686/> and in the Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve2_686/> denotes a ‘driver’ of horses or ‘charioteer.’ <br>

यम
<u>'''Yama'''</u> denotes ‘twins,’ the birth of which is frequently alluded to in Vedic literature.<ref name=fx1_ve2_687/> Twins of different sex seem to be indicated by the expression ''yamau mithunau.''<ref name=fx2_ve2_687/> There are traces of the belief--widely spread among negro and other races--that twins are uncanny and of evil omen,<ref name=fx3_ve2_687/> but there are also vestiges of the opposite opinion, that twins are lucky.<ref name=fx4_ve2_687/><br>

यम-नक्षत्र
<u>'''Yama-nakṣatra.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

यम-सू
<u>'''Yama-sū,'''</u> a ‘bearer of twins,’ is one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_689/><br>

यमुना
<u>'''Yamunā,'''</u> ‘twin,’ the name of a river, so called as running parallel with the Ganges, is mentioned thrice in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_690/> and not rarely later. According to the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_690/> the '''Tṛtsus''' and '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' won a great victory against their foes on the [[यमुना|Yamunā]]; there is no reason<ref name=fx3_ve2_690/> whatever to accept Hopkins'<ref name=fx4_ve2_690/> view that the [[यमुना|Yamunā]] here was another name of the '''[[परुष्णी|Paruṣṇī]]''' (Ravi). In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx5_ve2_690/> the salve ('''[[आञ्जन|Āñjana]]''') of the [[यमुना|Yamunā]] (''Yāmuna'') is mentioned along with that of '''[[त्रिककुद्|Trikakud]]''' (''[[त्रैककुद|Traikakuda]]'') as of value. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_690/> and the Śatapatha<ref name=fx7_ve2_690/> Brāhmaṇas the '''Bharatas''' are famed as victorious on the [[यमुना|Yamunā]]. Other Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx8_ve2_690/>  also mention this river. In the Mantrapāṭha<ref name=fx9_ve2_690/> the '''Sālvas''' are spoken of as dwelling on its banks.<br>

ययाति
<u>'''Yayāti'''</u> is mentioned twice in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_691/> once as an ancient sacrificer, and once as Nahuṣya, ‘descendant of '''Nahuṣa,'''’ apparently a king. There is no trace whatever of his connexion with '''[[पूरु|Pūru]],''' as in the Epic,<ref name=fx2_ve2_691/> the tradition of which must be deemed to be inaccurate.<br>

यव
<u>'''1. Yava'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_692/> appears to be a generic term for any sort of ‘grain,’ and not merely ‘barley.’ The latter sense is probably found in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_692/> and is regular later. The barley harvest came after spring,<ref name=fx3_ve2_692/> in the summer.<ref name=fx4_ve2_692/> That barley was cultivated in the period of the Rigveda<ref name=fx5_ve2_692/> is not certain, but on the whole very probable.<ref name=fx6_ve2_692/><br>

यव
<u>'''2. Yava.'''</u> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

यवस
<u>'''Yavasa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_694/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_694/> denotes the ‘grass’ on which animals feed, and which is burned by the forest fire.<ref name=fx3_ve2_694/> <br>

यवागू
<u>'''Yavāgū'''</u> means ‘barley-gruel,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_695/> but is also used of weak decoctions of other kinds of grain.<ref name=fx2_ve2_695/><br>

यवाशिर्
<u>'''Yavāśir'''</u> is used in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_696/> as an epithet of '''Soma,''' meaning ‘mixed with grain.’<br>

यवाष
<u>'''Yavāṣa.'''</u> See '''[[येवाष|Yevāṣa]].'''<br>

यव्य
<u>'''Yavya'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 7, 2, 46) denotes ‘month’ (lit., ‘containing a first half,’ see 2. '''Yava''').<br>

यव्यावती
<u>'''Yavyāvatī'''</u> is the name of a river in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_699/> and in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_699/> Hillebrandt<ref name=fx3_ve2_699/> thinks that the river is one in Iran, the Djob (Zhobe), near the Iryāb (Haliāb), but there is no reason to accept this identification.<br>

यशस्विन् जयन्त लौहित्य
<u>'''Yaśasvin [[जयन्त|Jayanta]] Lauhitya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''Kṛṣṇarāta Triveda [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1).<br>

यष्टि
<u>'''Yaṣṭi,'''</u> ‘staff,’ is mentioned in the latest parts of the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_701/> <br>

यस्क
<u>'''Yaska'''</u> is the name of a man. The Yaskas, descendants of Girikṣit (''Gairikṣitāḥ'') are mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_702/> ''Cf.'' '''[[यास्क|Yāska]].'''<br>

याज्ञ-तुर
<u>'''Yājña-tura,'''</u> ‘descendant of Yajñatura,’ is the patronymic of 2. '''[[ऋषभ|Ṛṣabha]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_703/><br>

याज्ञ-वल्क्य
<u>'''Yājña-valkya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Yajñavalkya,’ is repeatedly mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_704/> as an authority on questions of ritual. He is, however, also given as an authority on questions of philosophy in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_704/> but Oldenberg<ref name=fx3_ve2_704/> is, no doubt, right in thinking that no possible importance can be attached to the mention of [[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]] in the latter capacity. He is said to have been a pupil of '''[[उद्दालक आरुणि|Uddālaka Āruṇi]],'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_704/> whom he opposed successfully in a dispute.<ref name=fx5_ve2_704/> His two wives, '''[[मैत्रेयी|Maitreyī]]''' and '''[[कात्यायनी|Kātyāyanī]],''' are mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx6_ve2_704/> which concludes<ref name=fx7_ve2_704/> with a passage ascribing to [[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]] [[वाजसनेय|Vājasaneya]] the ‘white Yajus’ (''śuklāni yajūṃṣi''). It is remarkable that [[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]] is never mentioned in any other Vedic text outside the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] except the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx8_ve2_704/> where, however, both reference are merely transcripts from the Śatapatha.<ref name=fx9_ve2_704/> It has  been supposed by Oldenberg<ref name=fx10_ve2_704/> and others that [[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]] belonged to '''[[विदेह|Videha]],''' but despite the legend of Janaka's patronage of him, his association with '''Uddālaka,''' the '''Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]],''' renders this doubtful.<br>

याज्या
<u>'''Yājyā'''</u> (scil. ṛc, ‘verse’) denotes the words uttered at the moment of offering the sacrifice, ‘consecrating sacrificial formula,’ in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_705/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_705/><br>

यातु-धान
<u>'''Yātu-dhāna'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_706/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_706/> denotes a ‘sorcerer,’ ‘wizard,’ or ‘magician.’ The sense of the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_706/> is clearly unfavourable to sorcery. The feminine, Yātudhānī, is also found in the Rigveda and later.<ref name=fx4_ve2_706/><br>

यातु-विद्
<u>'''Yātu-vid,'''</u> denoting in the plural ‘those who know sorcery,’ designates the Atharvaveda in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_707/><br>

याद्व
<u>'''Yādva,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Yadu,'''’ is used of the Yadu prince in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_708/> while the largesse of the Yādvas<ref name=fx2_ve2_708/> is alluded to elsewhere. In another passage a beast (''[[पशु|paśu]]'') of the Yadus or Yādvas is mentioned.<ref name=fx3_ve2_708/> ''Cf.'' '''Yadu.''' <br>

यान
<u>'''Yāna'''</u> denotes ‘vehicle’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_709/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_709/><br>

याम
<u>'''Yāma,'''</u> used in the plural, denotes in one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_710/> according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_710/> the planets among which the sun (''[[भग|bhaga]]'') wanders. But both Bloomfield<ref name=fx3_ve2_710/> and Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve2_710/> accept the sense--the regular one in the later language--of ‘night watches.’<br>

यामन्
<u>'''Yāman'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_711/> a ‘march’ or ‘expedition’ in war.<br>

यायावर
<u>'''Yāyāvara'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_712/> denotes a person of no fixed abode in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve2_712/><br>

याव
<u>'''Yāva.'''</u> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

यास्क
<u>'''Yāska'''</u> (‘descendant of Yaska’) is mentioned in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_714/> as a contemporary of '''[[आसुरायण|Āsurāyaṇa]]''' and a teacher of '''[[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]].''' Whether [[यास्क|Yāska]], author of the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_714/> was the same person, it is, of course, impossible to say.<br>

यु
<u>'''Yu,'''</u> appearing in the dual in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 7, 4, 10), seems to mean ‘yoke animals.’ <br>

युक्त
<u>'''Yukta'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vi. 7, 4, 8; xii. 4, 1, 2) denotes a ‘yoke’ of oxen. ''Cf.'' 1. '''Yuga.'''<br>

युक्ताश्व
<u>'''Yuktāśva'''</u> is the name of a man who is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_717/> as the seer of a Sāman, or chant. He is said to have exposed a pair of twins,<ref name=fx2_ve2_717/> but Hopkins<ref name=fx3_ve2_717/> thinks that the reference is only to an exchange of children.<br>

युग
<u>'''1. Yuga'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_718/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_718/> denotes ‘yoke.’ ''Cf.'' [[रथ|Ratha]].<br>

युग
<u>'''2. Yuga'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_719/> frequently denotes a ‘generation’; but the expression ''daśame yuge'' applied to '''[[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]]''' in one passage<ref name=fx2_ve2_719/> must mean ‘tenth decade’ of life.<br><br>There is no reference in the older Vedic texts to the five-year cycle (see '''[[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]]'''). The quotation from the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_719/> given in the St. Petersburg Dictionary, and by Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve2_719/> and others, is merely a citation from a modern text in the commentary on that work.<br><br>Nor do the older Vedic texts know of any series of Yugas or ages such as are usual later. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx5_ve2_719/> there are mentioned in order a hundred years, an ''ayuta'' (10,000?), and then two, three, or four Yugas: the inference from this seems to be that a Yuga means more than an ''ayuta,'' but is not very  certain. Zimmer<ref name=fx6_ve2_719/> adduces a passage from the Rigveda,<ref name=fx7_ve2_719/> but the reference there, whatever it may be,<ref name=fx8_ve2_719/> is certainly not to the four ages (''cf.'' also '''[[त्रियुग|Triyuga]]''').<ref name=fx9_ve2_719/> The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx10_ve2_719/> recognizes long periods of time--''e.g.,'' one of 100,000 years.<br><br>To the four ages, Kali, [[द्वापर|Dvāpara]], Tretā, and [[कृत|Kṛta]], there is no certain reference in Vedic literature, though the names occur as the designations of throws at dice (see '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]]'''). In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx11_ve2_719/> the names occur, but it is not clear that the ages are really meant. Haug<ref name=fx12_ve2_719/> thought that the dice were meant: this view is at least as probable as the alternative explanation, which is accepted by Weber,<ref name=fx13_ve2_719/> Roth,<ref name=fx14_ve2_719/> Wilson,<ref name=fx15_ve2_719/> Max Müller,<ref name=fx16_ve2_719/> and Muir.<ref name=fx17_ve2_719/> Roth, indeed, believes that the verse is an interpolation; but in any case it must be remembered that the passage is from a late book of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]. Four ages--[[पुष्य|Puṣya]], [[द्वापर|Dvāpara]], Khārvā, and [[कृत|Kṛta]]--are mentioned in the late Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx18_ve2_719/> and the [[द्वापर|Dvāpara]] in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx19_ve2_719/> <br>

युद्ध
<u>'''Yuddha'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_720/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_720/> denotes ‘battle.’ The more usual word earlier<ref name=fx3_ve2_720/> is Yudh.<br>

युधां-श्रौष्टि औग्र-सैन्य
<u>'''Yudhāṃ-śrauṣṭi Augra-sainya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[उग्रसेन|Ugrasena]]'''’) is the name, in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_721/> of a king who was anointed by '''[[पर्वत|Parvata]]''' and '''[[नारद|Nārada]].'''<br>

युध्यामधि
<u>'''Yudhyāmadhi'''</u> is apparently the name of a king who was defeated by '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]].''' The mention of him occurring only in the verses added at the end of the hymn celebrating the victory of [[सुदास्|Sudās]] over the ten kings<ref name=fx1_ve2_722/> can claim little authenticity as a notice of [[सुदास्|Sudās]].<br>

युवति
<u>'''Yuvati'''</u> is the ordinary expression for a ‘young woman’ or ‘maiden’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_723/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_723/><br>

यूथ
<u>'''Yūtha'''</u> is the word for ‘herd’ of cows in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_724/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_724/><br>

यूप
<u>'''Yūpa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_725/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_725/> means a ‘post,’ usually that to which the sacrificial victim was tied. It also designates the post to which the door of the house was attached ('''[[दुर्य|Durya]]''').<ref name=fx3_ve2_725/> <br>

यूषन्
<u>'''Yūṣan,'''</u> occurring in the description of the horse-sacrifice in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_726/> and the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx2_ve2_726/> denotes the ‘broth’ which was made from the flesh of the sacrificial animal, and was no doubt used as food. Vessels employed for holding it, '''[[पात्र|Pātra]]''' and '''[[आसेचन|Āsecana]],''' are mentioned. Another form of the word, found in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve2_726/> is Yūs, which corresponds to the Latin ''jus.''<br>

येवाष
<u>'''Yevāṣa'''</u> is the name of a destructive insect in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_727/> The form [[यवाष|Yavāṣa]] is found in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_727/> ''Cf.'' '''[[वृष|Vṛṣa]].'''<br>

योक्त्र
<u>'''Yoktra'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_728/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_728/> denotes the ‘thongs’ used for yoking the chariot or cart.<br>

योग
<u>'''Yoga'''</u> denotes the yoke of oxen or horses drawing a car in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_729/> and the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_729/><br>

योजन
<u>'''Yojana'''</u> occurs frequently in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_730/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_730/> as a measure of distance,<ref name=fx3_ve2_730/> but there is no reference defining its real  length. Later it is reckoned at four '''Krośas,''' or about nine miles.<ref name=fx4_ve2_730/><br>

योध
<u>'''Yodha'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_731/> means ‘fighter,’ ‘warrior,’ ‘soldier.’<br>

योषन्
<u>'''Yoṣan, Yoṣaṇā, Yoṣā, Yoṣit.'''</u> all denote ‘young woman,’ ‘maiden,’ as an object of affection, and as meet for wedlock.<ref name=fx1_ve2_732/> So these terms are often opposed in the Brāhmaṇas to '''[[वृषन्|Vṛṣan]],''' ‘male,’ in the general sense of ‘female,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_732/> but they also occur in the sense of ‘wife,’<ref name=fx3_ve2_732/> or ‘daughter,’<ref name=fx4_ve2_732/> or merely ‘girl.’<ref name=fx5_ve2_732/> See '''[[स्त्री|Strī]].'''<br>

यौगं-धरि
<u>'''Yaugaṃ-dhari,'''</u> ‘descendant of Yugaṃdhara,’ is the name of a king of the '''Sālvas''' in the Mantrapāṭha (ii. 11, 12).<br>

यौवन
<u>'''Yauvana,'''</u> ‘youth,’ is found in the Atharvaveda (xviii. 4, 50), where it is opposed to ‘old age.’<br>

रक्षितृ
<u>'''Rakṣitṛ,'''</u> ‘protector,’ ‘guardian,’ occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_735/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_735/> usually in a metaphorical sense.<br>

रघट्
<u>'''Raghaṭ'''</u> occurs once in the plural in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_736/> where the Paippalāda recension reads ''vaghaṭah.'' Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_736/> once con-  jectured ''raghavaḥ,'' ‘swift,’ as the correct reading. Bloomfield,<ref name=fx3_ve2_736/> who in his translation explains the word as ‘falcons,’ in his notes inclines to think Roth's conjecture likely. Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve2_736/> suggests ‘bees’ as the meaning. Possibly some kind of bird may be intended.<ref name=fx5_ve2_736/><br>

रजत
<u>'''Rajata'''</u> as an adjective with '''[[हिरण्य|Hiraṇya]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_737/> designates ‘silver,’ and ornaments ('''[[रुक्म|Rukma]]'''),<ref name=fx2_ve2_737/> dishes ('''[[पात्र|Pātra]]'''),<ref name=fx3_ve2_737/> and coins ('''[[निष्क|Niṣka]]''')<ref name=fx4_ve2_737/> ‘made of silver’ are mentioned. The word is also used alone as a substantive to denote ‘silver.’<ref name=fx5_ve2_737/><br>

रजन कोणेय
<u>'''Rajana Koṇeya,'''</u> or '''[[कौणेय|Kauṇeya]],''' is the name of a teacher mentioned in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_738/> It is said in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_738/> that '''[[क्रतुजित् जानकि|Kratujit Jānaki]]''' successfully sacrificed for him when he desired to obtain eyesight. He is also mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_738/> where the name of his son, '''[[उग्रदेव|Ugradeva]] [[राजनि|Rājani]],''' also occurs.<ref name=fx4_ve2_738/><br>

रजनी
<u>'''Rajanī'''</u> is found in one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_739/> where it denotes some sort of plant, probably so called because of its  power of ‘colouring’ (from ''rañj,'' ‘to colour’). The species cannot be identified owing to the untrustworthiness of the later authorities who attempt its identification.<br>

रजयित्री
<u>'''Rajayitrī,'''</u> a ‘female dyer,’ is included in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_740/><br>

रजस्
<u>'''1. Rajas'''</u> denotes the region of the atmosphere between heaven and earth in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_741/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_741/> The atmosphere, like the sky ('''Div'''), is divided into three regions,<ref name=fx3_ve2_741/> but more normally into two, the ‘earthly’ (''pārthiva'')<ref name=fx4_ve2_741/> and the ‘heavenly’ (''[[दिव्य|divya]]'' or ''divaḥ'').<ref name=fx5_ve2_741/> In some passages<ref name=fx6_ve2_741/> the word refers in the plural to the dusty fields on earth.<br>

रजस्
<u>'''2. Rajas'''</u> in one passage of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_742/> clearly means ‘silver,’ like '''[[रजत|Rajata]].''' It is also taken in this sense in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_742/> by Zimmer,<ref name=fx3_ve2_742/> but this interpretation is doubtful.<br>

रजस
<u>'''Rajasa'''</u> occurs once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_743/> apparently as the name of a kind of ‘fish.’ Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_743/> however, understood it as an adjective meaning ‘impure.’ <br>

रजि
<u>'''Raji'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_744/> seemingly as the name of a king, or perhaps demon, slain by Indra for '''[[पिठीनस्|Piṭhīnas]].'''<br>

रज्जव्य
<u>'''Rajjavya'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vi. 7, 1, 28) den ‘cord’ or ‘rope.’<br>

रज्जु
<u>'''Rajju'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_746/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_746/> denotes ‘rope.’ In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_746/> the serpent is called the ‘toothed rope’ (''[[रज्जु|rajju]] datvatī'').<br>

रज्जु-दाल
<u>'''Rajju-dāla'''</u> is the name of a tree (''Cordia myxa'' or ''latifolia'') the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_747/><br>

रज्जु-सर्ज
<u>'''Rajju-sarja,'''</u> ‘rope-maker,’ is one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_748/><br>

रण
<u>'''Raṇa'''</u> denotes properly the ‘joy’ of battle, then ‘battle,’ ‘combat’ itself in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_749/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_749/><br>

रत्न
<u>'''Ratna'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_750/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_750/> denotes a precious object, not specifically a ‘jewel,’ as in post-Vedic literature.<br>

रत्नि
<u>'''Ratni,'''</u> ‘ell,’ occurring in the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iv. 4) is a corruption of '''[[अरत्नि|Aratni]].'''<br>

रत्निन्
<u>'''Ratnin,'''</u> ‘receiving gifts,’ is the term applied to those people of the royal entourage in whose houses the [[रत्न|Ratna]]-[[हविस्|havis]], a  special rite, was performed in the course of the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]]''' or ‘royal consecration.’ The list given in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_752/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_752/> consists of the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] (''i.e.,'' the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]]), the [[राजन्य|Rājanya]], the [[महिषी|Mahiṣī]] (the first wife of the king), the '''Vāvāta''' (the favourite wife of the king), the Parivṛktī (the discarded wife), the [[सेनानी|Senānī]], ‘commander of the army’; the [[सूत|Sūta]], ‘charioteer’; the Grāmaṇī, ‘village headman’; the [[क्षत्तृ|Kṣattṛ]], ‘chamberlain’; the [[संग्रहीतृ|Saṃgrahītṛ]], ‘charioteer’ or ‘treasurer’; the [[भागदुघ|Bhāgadugha]], ‘collector of taxes’ or ‘divider of food’; and the Akṣāvāpa, ‘superintender of dicing’ or ‘thrower of dice.’ In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_752/> the order is [[सेनानी|Senānī]]; [[पुरोहित|Purohita]]; Mahisī; [[सूत|Sūta]]; Grāmaṇī; [[क्षत्तृ|Kṣattṛ]]; Saṃgrahitṛ; [[भागदुघ|Bhāgadugha]]; Akṣāvāpa; Go-nikartana, ‘slayer of cows’ or ‘huntsman’; and [[पालागल|Pālāgala]], ‘courier’; the ‘discarded wife’ being mentioned as forbidden to stay at home<ref name=fx4_ve2_752/> on the day of the ceremony of offering a pap for Nirṛti in her house. In the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx5_ve2_752/> the list is [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] (''i.e.,'' [[पुरोहित|Purohita]]); [[राजन्|Rājan]]; [[महिषी|Mahiṣī]]; Parivṛktī; [[सेनानी|Senānī]]; [[संग्रहीतृ|Saṃgrahītṛ]]; [[क्षत्तृ|Kṣattṛ]]; [[सूत|Sūta]]; Vaiśyagrāmaṇī; [[भागदुघ|Bhāgadugha]]; Takṣa-Rathakārau, ‘carpenter and chariot-maker’; Akṣāvāpa; and Go-vikarta. The [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx6_ve2_752/> substitutes Go-[[व्यछ|vyacha]] for Govikarta, and omits Takṣa-Rathakārau.<br><br>It will be seen that the list is essentially that of the royal household, and of the king's servants in the administration of the country, though the exact sense of '''[[संग्रहीतृ|Saṃgrahītṛ]], [[भागदुघ|Bhāgadugha]], [[सूत|Sūta]], Grāmaṇī, [[क्षत्तृ|Kṣattṛ]],''' is open to reasonable doubt, mainly as to whether public officers or private servants<ref name=fx7_ve2_752/> are meant, for the names are of uncertain significance. A briefer list of eight '''Vīras,''' ‘heroes,’ as among the friends of the king,  is given in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]:<ref name=fx8_ve2_752/> brother, son, [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], [[महिषी|Mahiṣī]], [[सूत|Sūta]], Grāmaṇī, [[क्षत्तृ|Kṣattṛ]], and [[संग्रहीतृ|Saṃgrahītṛ]].<br>

रथ
<u>'''Ratha'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_753/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_753/> denotes ‘chariot’ as opposed to '''Anas,''' ‘cart,’ though the distinction is not absolute. Of differences in the structure of the two we have no information, except that the '''Kha,''' or nave hole, in the wheel of the chariot was greater than in that of the cart.<ref name=fx3_ve2_753/><br><br>The chariot has, as a rule, two wheels ('''[[चक्र|Cakra]]'''), to which reference is frequently made.<ref name=fx4_ve2_753/> The wheel consisted of a rim ('''Pavi'''), a felly ('''[[प्रधि|Pradhi]]'''), spokes ('''Ara'''),<ref name=fx5_ve2_753/> and a nave ('''[[नभ्य|Nabhya]]'''). The rim and the felly together constitute the '''Nemi.''' The hole in the nave is called '''Kha:''' into it the end of the axle was inserted; but there is some uncertainty whether '''[[आणि|Āṇi]]''' denotes the extremity of the axle that was inserted in the nave, or the lynch-pin used to keep that extremity in the wheel. Sometimes a solid wheel was used.<ref name=fx6_ve2_753/><br><br>The axle ('''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]]''') was, in some cases, made of '''[[अरटु|Araṭu]]''' wood;<ref name=fx7_ve2_753/> round its ends the wheels revolved. To the axle was attached the body of the chariot ('''[[कोश|Kośa]]'''). This part is also denoted by the word '''[[वन्धुर|Vandhura]],''' which more precisely means the ‘seat’ of the chariot. The epithet ''tri-[[वन्धुर|vandhura]]'' is used of the chariot of the Aśvins, seemingly to correspond with another of its epithets, ''tri-[[चक्र|cakra]]:'' perhaps, as Weber<ref name=fx8_ve2_753/> thinks, a chariot with three seats and three wheels was a real form of vehicle; but Zimmer<ref name=fx9_ve2_753/> considers that the vehicle was purely mythical. '''[[गर्त|Garta]]''' also denotes the seat of the warrior. <br><br>At right angles to the axle was the pole of the chariot ('''[[ईषा|Īṣā]], Praüga'''). Normally there was, it seems, one pole, on either side of which the horses were harnessed, a yoke ('''Yuga''') being laid across their necks; the pole was passed through the hole in the yoke (called Kha<ref name=fx10_ve2_753/> or [[तर्द्मन्|Tardman]]),<ref name=fx11_ve2_753/> the yoke and the pole then being tied together.<ref name=fx12_ve2_753/><br><br>The horses were tied by the neck (''grīvā''), where the yoke was placed, and also at the shoulder, presumably by traces fastened to a bar of wood at right angles to the pole, or fastened to the ends of the pole, if that is to be regarded, as it probably should, as of triangular shape, wide at the foot and coming to a point at the tip.<ref name=fx13_ve2_753/> The traces seem to be denoted by '''[[रश्मि|Raśmi]]''' and '''[[रशना|Raśanā]].''' These words also denote the ‘reins,’ which were fastened to the bit (perhaps ''[[शिप्रा|śiprā]]'') in the horse's mouth. The driver controlled the horses by reins, and urged them on with a whip (''Kaśā'').<ref name=fx14_ve2_753/> The girths of the horse were called Kakṣyā.<ref name=fx15_ve2_753/><br><br>The normal number of horses seems to have been two, but three or four<ref name=fx16_ve2_753/> were often used. It is uncertain whether, in these cases, the extra horse was attached in front or at the side; possibly both modes were in use. Even five steeds could be employed.<ref name=fx17_ve2_753/> Horses were normally used for chariots, but the ass (''[[गर्दभ|gardabha]]'')<ref name=fx18_ve2_753/> or mule (''aśvatarī'')<ref name=fx19_ve2_753/> are also mentioned. The ox was employed for drawing carts, and in fact derived its  name, '''[[अनड्वाह्|Anaḍvāh]],''' from this use. Sometimes a poor man had to be content with a single steed, which then ran between two shafts.<ref name=fx20_ve2_753/><br><br>In the chariot the driver stood on the right, while the warrior was on the left, as indicated by his name, '''Savyeṣṭha''' or '''[[सव्यष्ठा|Savyaṣṭhā]],'''<ref name=fx21_ve2_753/> He could also sit when he wanted, for the chariot had seats, and an archer would naturally prefer to sit while shooting his arrows.<br><br>The dimensions of the chariot are given in the Śulba [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx22_ve2_753/> of Āpastamba at 188 Aṅgulis (finger-breadths) for the pole, 104 for the axle, and 86 for the yoke. The material used in its construction was wood, except for the rim of the wheel.<ref name=fx23_ve2_753/><br><br>Many other parts of the chariot are mentioned, their names being often obscure in meaning: see '''[[अङ्क|Aṅka]], [[न्य्अङ्क|Nyaṅka]], [[उद्धि|Uddhi]], [[पक्षस्|Pakṣas]], [[पातल्य|Pātalya]], [[भुरिज्|Bhurij]], [[रथोपस्थ|Rathopastha]], [[रथवाहन|Rathavāhana]].'''<br>

रथ-कार
<u>'''Ratha-kāra,'''</u> ‘chariot-maker,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_754/> as one of those who are to be subject to the king, seeming to stand generally as an example of the industrial population. He is also referred to in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx2_ve2_754/> and in the Brāhmaṇas:<ref name=fx3_ve2_754/> in all these passages, as well a probably in the Atharvaveda also, the [[रथकार|Rathakāra]] already forms a caste. The  later system<ref name=fx4_ve2_754/> regards the [[रथकार|Rathakāra]] as the offspring of a Māhiṣya (the son of a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] husband and a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] wife) and a Karaṇī (the daughter of a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] husband and a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] wife), but it is unreasonable to suppose that such an origin is historically accurate. The Rathakāras must rather be deemed to have been a functional caste. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx5_ve2_754/> suggests that the '''Anu''' tribe formed the basis of the [[रथकार|Rathakāra]] caste, referring to their worship of the Ṛbhus, who are, of course, the chariotmakers ''par excellence.'' But there is little ground for this view.<br>

रथ-गृत्स
<u>'''Ratha-gṛtsa'''</u> in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xv. 15) and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 48, 9) denotes a ‘skilled charioteer.’<ref name=fx1_ve2_755/><br>

रथ-चक्र
<u>'''Ratha-cakra,'''</u> ‘chariot wheel,’ is often mentioned in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_756/> See '''[[रथ|Ratha]]''' and '''[[चक्र|Cakra]].'''<br>

रथ-चर्षण
<u>'''Ratha-carṣaṇa'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_757/> where the sense is doubtful. Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_757/> thought that some part of the chariot was meant, but the sense is perhaps only the ‘pathway of the chariot.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_757/><br>

रथ-जूति
<u>'''Ratha-jūti'''</u> in the Atharvaveda (xix. 44, 3) is either an adjective meaning ‘driving swiftly in a chariot,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_758/> or a proper name, as Roth in the St. Petersburg Dictionary suggests. <br>

रथ-नाभि
<u>'''Ratha-nābhi,'''</u> the ‘nave of the chariot-wheel,’ is mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_759/> and in the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx2_ve2_759/><br>

रथ-प्रोत दार्भ्य
<u>'''Ratha-prota Dārbhya'''</u> (‘descendant of Darbha’) is mentioned in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (ii. 1, 3) perhaps as a king, but possibly as a priest.<br>

रथ-प्रोष्ठ
<u>'''Ratha-proṣṭha'''</u> occurs as the name of a princely family in the Rigveda (x. 60, 5). See '''[[सुबन्धु|Subandhu]].'''<br>

रथ-मुख
<u>'''Ratha-mukha'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_762/> denotes the fore-part of a chariot. ''Cf.'' '''[[रथशीर्ष|Rathaśīrṣa]].'''<br>

रथर्वी
<u>'''Ratharvī'''</u> is the name of a snake in the Atharvaveda (x. 4, 5).<br>

रथ-वाहन
<u>'''Ratha-vāhana'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_764/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_764/> for a movable stand to hold the chariot. According to Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve2_764/> it corresponds to the Greek , on which the chariot rested when out of use. The word [[रथवाहन|Rathavāhana]]-[[वाह|vāha]] is employed in the sense of the two horses that draw the stand.<ref name=fx4_ve2_764/> Weber<ref name=fx5_ve2_764/> thinks it was used to convey the war chariot to the scene of action. <br>

रथवीति दार्भ्य
<u>'''Rathavīti Dārbhya'''</u> (‘descendant of Darbha’) is mentioned once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_765/> as residing in places abounding in kine (''gomatīr anu'') far away among the hills, possibly the Himālayas, and as the patron of the singer of the hymn. Later the tradition<ref name=fx2_ve2_765/> makes him the king, whose daughter '''Śyāsvāśva''' won for his wife by his father's and the Maruts' aid.<br>

रथ-शीर्ष
<u>'''Ratha-śīrṣa,'''</u> the ‘head of the chariot’--that is, its fore-part-is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ix. 4. 1, 13).<br>

रथ-सङ्ग
<u>'''Ratha-saṅga'''</u> in the Rigveda (ix. 53, 2) denotes the hostile encounter of chariots.<br>

रथाक्ष
<u>'''Rathākṣa'''</u> in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_768/> denotes the ‘axle of the chariot.’ Its length is given by the scholiast on the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_768/> as 104 Aṅgulas (‘finger-breadths’), which agrees with the statement in the Āpastamba Śulba [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_768/> See '''[[रथ|Ratha]].'''<br>

रथाह्न्य
<u>'''Rathāhnya'''</u> in the Śatapatha Brāhmana (xii. 2, 3, 12) denotes a ‘day's journey by chariot.’<br>

रथिन्
<u>'''Rathin'''</u> and '''Rathī''' in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_770/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_770/> denote ‘one who goes in a chariot,’ an expression which includes both the driver and the warrior who accompanied him. <br>

रथीतर
<u>'''Rathītara'''</u> (‘good charioteer’) is the name of a teacher mentioned in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_771/> and the Bṛhaddevatā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_771/><br>

रथे-ष्ठा
<u>'''Rathe-ṣṭhā,'''</u> ‘standing on the chariot,’ denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_772/> the warrior who fights from the chariot, ‘car-fighter.’<br>

रथोपस्थ
<u>'''Rathopastha,'''</u> ‘lap of the chariot,’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_773/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_773/> seems to denote the ‘bottom’ or lower part on which the driver and the fighter stand.<br>

रन्ध्र
<u>'''Randhra'''</u> seems, in the phrase Ukṣṇo [[रन्ध्र|Randhra]] occurring in one passage of the Rigveda (viii. 7, 26), to be the name of a place, but the sense is very doubtful. In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 9, 13) Ukṣṇo [[रन्ध्र|randhra]] is the name of a man.<br>

रभि
<u>'''Rabhi,'''</u> occurring once in the Rigveda (viii. 5, 29), designates some part of the chariot. The term perhaps means ‘supporting shaft.’<br>

रम्भ
<u>'''Rambha'''</u> seems to mean a ‘staff’ or ‘support’ in one passage of the Rigveda (viii. 45, 20). In another place (ii. 15, 9) a man is described as Rambhin, apparently as carrying a staff to support himself in old age; Sāyaṇa explains this word as ‘door-keeper’ (like one of the senses of ''daṇḍin,'' ‘staff-bearer,’ in later Sanskrit).<br>

रम्भिणी
<u>'''Rambhiṇī'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_777/> as being on the shoulders of the Maruts. A ‘spear’ seems to be meant, perhaps conceived as clinging (''rambh = rabk,'' ‘clasp’) to the shoulders of a man. <br>

रयि
<u>'''Rayi'''</u> is the common word for ‘wealth’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_778/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_778/> Special mention is often made of wealth in ‘heroes’ ''([[वीर|vīra]])--i.e.,'' in ‘good sons,’<ref name=fx3_ve2_778/> in horses,<ref name=fx4_ve2_778/> in cattle,<ref name=fx5_ve2_778/> etc.<br>

रशना
<u>'''Raśanā'''</u> means generally ‘cord’ or ‘rope.’ In the Rigveda the word ofter refers to various fastenings of a horse. In one passage<ref name=fx1_ve2_779/> the expression ''śīrṣaṇyā [[रशना|raśanā]],'' ‘head rope,’ perhaps means not so much ‘reins’ as ‘headstall.’ In others<ref name=fx2_ve2_779/> the sense of ‘traces’ seems certain, though sometimes<ref name=fx3_ve2_779/> ‘reins’ or ‘traces’ may equally well be intended. Elsewhere the more general sense of ‘rope’ for stening is meant.<ref name=fx4_ve2_779/><br>

रश्मि
<u>'''1. Raśmi'''</u> is not rarely found in the sense of ‘rope’<ref name=fx1_ve2_780/> generally; but more usually it denotes either the ‘reins’ or the ‘traces’<ref name=fx2_ve2_780/> of a chariot, either sense being equally good in most passages.<br>

रश्मि
<u>'''2. Raśmi'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_781/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_781/> regularly denotes a ‘ray’ of the sun. <br>

रसा
<u>'''Rasā'''</u> is found in three passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_782/> clearly as the name of a real stream in the extreme north-west of the Vedic territory. Elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve2_782/> it is the name of a mythic stream at the ends of the earth, which as well as the atinosphere it encompasses. It is reasonable to assume that, as in the case of the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],''' the literal is the older sense, and to see in the river a genuine stream, perhaps originally the Araxes or Jaxartes, because the Vendidad mentions the Raṅhā, the Avestan form of [[रसा|Rasā]]. But the word seems originally to allude merely to the ‘sap’ or ‘flavour’ of the waters,<ref name=fx3_ve2_782/> and so could be applied to every river, like [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].<br>

रसाशिर्
<u>'''Rasāśir'''</u> as an epithet of Soma in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_783/> means ‘mixed with juice’--''i.e.,'' with milk.<br>

रह-सू
<u>'''Raha-sū,'''</u> ‘bearing in secret,’ is a term applied in one passage of the Rigveda (ii. 29, 1) to an unmarried mother. ''Cf.'' '''Pati''' and '''[[धर्म|Dharma]].'''<br>

रहस्यु देव-मलिम्लुच्
<u>'''Rahasyu Deva-malimluc'''</u> is the name, in the Pañcavimśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 4, 7), of a mythical person who at '''[[मुनिमरण|Munimaraṇa]]''' slew the saintly '''Vaikhānases.'''<br>

रहू-गण
<u>'''Rahū-gaṇa'''</u> is the name of a family mentioned in the plural in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_786/> According to Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve2_786/> they were connected with the '''Gotamas,''' as is shown by the name '''[[गोतम|Gotama]] [[राहूगण|Rāhūgaṇa]].''' <br>

राका
<u>'''Rākā'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_787/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_787/> denotes the full moon day as a personification. ''Cf.'' '''Candramās.'''<br>

राज-कर्तृ
<u>'''Rāja-kartṛ,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_788/> or '''Rāja-kṛt,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_788/> ‘king-maker,’ is the term applied in the Atharvaveda and the Brāhmaṇas to those who, ‘not themselves kings,’<ref name=fx3_ve2_788/> aid in the consecration of the king. In the Śatapatha<ref name=fx2_ve2_788/> the persons meant and specified are the '''[[सूत|Sūta]],''' ‘charioteer,’ and the '''Grāmaṇī,''' ‘village chief,’ probably a representative chief from the village nearest to the place of consecration, as Eggeling<ref name=fx4_ve2_788/> suggests. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_788/> according to the commentator's explanation, the father, brother, etc., are meant; in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_788/> also, the meaning of the expression is not stated in the text.<br>

राज-कुल
<u>'''Rāja-kula,'''</u> a ‘kingly family,’ is mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 28, 4), where, it is to be noted, such a family is ranked after, not before, a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] Kula, a ‘Brahmin family.’<br>

राजन्
<u>'''1. Rājan,'''</u> ‘king,’ is a term repeatedly occurring in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_790/> and the later literature.<ref name=fx2_ve2_790/> It is quite clear that the normal, though not universal form of government, in early India was that by kings, as might be expected in view of the fact that the Āryan Indians were invaders in a hostile territory: a situation which, as in the case of the Āryan invaders of Greece and of the German invaders of England, resulted almost necessarily in strengthening the monarchic element of the constitution.<ref name=fx3_ve2_790/> The mere patriarchal organization of society is not sufficient, as Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve2_790/> assumes, to explain the Vedic kingship. <br><br>''Tenure of Monarchy.''--Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve2_790/> is of opinion that while the Vedic monarchy was sometimes hereditary, as is indeed shown by several cases where the descent can be traced,<ref name=fx6_ve2_790/> yet in others the monarchy was elective, though it is not clear whether the selection by the people was between the members of the royal family only or extended to members of all the noble clans. It must, however, be admitted that the evidence for the elective monarchy is not strong. As Geldner<ref name=fx7_ve2_790/> argues, all the passages cited<ref name=fx8_ve2_790/> can be regarded not as choice by the cantons ('''[[विश्|Viś]]'''), but as acceptance by the subjects (''[[विश्|viś]]''): this seems the more probable sense. Of course this is no proof that the monarchy was not sometimes elective: the practice of selecting one member of the family to the exclusion of another less well qualified is exemplified by the legend in [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx9_ve2_790/> of the Kuru brothers, '''Devāpi''' and '''Śantanu,''' the value of which, as evidence of contemporary views, is not seriously affected by the legend itself being of dubious character and validity.<br><br>Royal power was clearly insecure: there are several references to kings being expelled from their realms, and their efforts to recover their sovereignty,<ref name=fx10_ve2_790/> and the Atharvaveda contains spells in the interest of royalty.<ref name=fx11_ve2_790/><br><br>''The King in War.''--Naturally the Vedic texts, after the Rigveda, contain few notices of the warlike adventures that no doubt formed a very considerable proportion of the royal functions. But the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx12_ve2_790/> contains the statement that the '''Kuru-[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]]''' kings, who, like the Brahmins of  those tribes, stand as representatives of good form, used to make their raids in the dewy season. The word '''[[उद्आज|Udāja]],''' too, with its variant Nirāja, records that kings took a share of the booty of war. The Rigveda<ref name=fx13_ve2_790/> has many references to Vedic wars: it is clear that the Kṣatriyas were at least as intent on fulfilling their duty of war as the Brahmins on sacrificing and their other functions. Moreover, beside offensive war, defence was a chief duty of the king: he is emphatically the ‘protector of the tribe’ (''[[गोपा|gopā]] janasya''), or, as is said in the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]]''' (‘royal consecration’), ‘protector of the Brahmin.’<ref name=fx14_ve2_790/> His '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]]''' was expected to use his spells and charms to secure the success of his king's arms. The king no doubt fought in person: so '''[[प्रतर्दन|Pratardana]]''' met death in war according to the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]];<ref name=fx15_ve2_790/> and in the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]] the king is invoked as ‘sacker of cities’ (''purāṃ bhettā'').<br><br>''The King in Peace.''--In return for his warlike services the king received the obedience<ref name=fx16_ve2_790/> --sometimes forced<ref name=fx17_ve2_790/> --of the people, and in particular their contributions for the maintenance of royalty. The king is regularly<ref name=fx18_ve2_790/> regarded as ‘devouring  the people,’ but this phrase must not be explained as meaning that he necessarily oppressed them. It obviously has its origin in a custom by which the king and his retinue were fed by the people's contributions, a plan with many parallels. It is also probable that the king could assign the royal right of maintenance to a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]], thus developing a nobility supported by the people. Taxation would not normally fall on [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] or Brahmin; the texts contam emphatic assertions of the exemption of the goods of the latter from the royal bounty.<ref name=fx19_ve2_790/>In the people, however, lay the strength of the king.<ref name=fx20_ve2_790/> See also '''Bali.'''<br><br>In return the king performed the duties of judge. Himself immune from punishment (''a-daṇḍya''), he wields the rod of punishment ('''[[दण्ड|Daṇḍa]]''').<ref name=fx21_ve2_790/> It is probable that criminal justice remained largely in his actual administration, for the Sūtras<ref name=fx22_ve2_790/> preserve clear traces of the personal exercise of royal criminal jurisdiction. Possibly the jurisdiction could be exercised by a royal officer, or even by a delegate, for a [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] is mentioned as an overseer (''adhyakṣa'') of the punishment of a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx23_ve2_790/> In civil justice it may be that the king played a much less prominent part, save as a court of final appeal, but evidence is lacking on this head. The '''[[मध्यमशी|Madhyamaśī]]''' of the Rigveda was probably not a royal, but a private judge or arbitrator. A wide criminal jurisdiction is, however, to some extent supported<ref name=fx24_ve2_790/> by the frequent mention of Varuṇa's spies, for Varuṇa is the divine counterpart of the human king.<ref name=fx25_ve2_790/> Possibly such spies could be used in war also.<ref name=fx26_ve2_790/><br><br>There is no reference in early Vedic literature to the exercise of legislative activitv by the king, though later it is an essential  part of his duties.<ref name=fx27_ve2_790/> Nor can we say exactly what executive functions devolved on the king.<br><br>In all his acts the king was regularly advised by his '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]];''' he also had the advantage of the advice of the royal ministers and attendants (see '''[[रत्निन्|Ratnin]]'''). The local administration was entrusted to the '''Grāmaṇī,''' or village chief, who may have been selected or appointed by the king. The outward signs of the king's rank were his palace<ref name=fx28_ve2_790/> and his brilliant dress.<ref name=fx29_ve2_790/><br><br>''The King as Landowner.''--The position of the king with regard to the land is somewhat obscure. The Greek notices,<ref name=fx30_ve2_790/> in which, unhappily, it would be dangerous to put much trust, since they were collected by observers who were probably little used to accurate investigations of such matters, and whose statements were based on inadequate information, vary in their statements. In part they speak of rent being paid, and declare that only the king and no private person could own land, while in part they refer to the taxation of land. Hopkins<ref name=fx31_ve2_790/> is strongly of opinion that the payments made were paid for protection-''i.e.,'' in modern terminology as a tax, but that the king was recognized as the owner of all the land, while yet the individual or the joint family also owned the land. As against BadenPowell,<ref name=fx32_ve2_790/> who asserted that the idea of the king as a landowner was later, he urges for the Vedic period that the king, as we have seen, is described as devouring the people, and that, according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx33_ve2_790/> the '''[[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]''' can be devoured at will and maltreated (but, unlike the '''[[शूद्र|Śūdra]],''' not killed); and for the period of the legal Sūtras and Śāstras he cites [[बृहस्पति|Bṛhaspati]] and [[नारद|Nārada]] as clearly recognizing the king's overlordship, besides a passage of the [[मानव|Mānava]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] Śāstra<ref name=fx34_ve2_790/> which describes the king as ‘lord of all,’ a phrase which  Bühler<ref name=fx35_ve2_790/> was inclined to interpret as a proof of landowning. The evidence is, however, inadequate to prove what is sought. It is not denied that gradually the king came to be vaguely conceived--as the English king still is--as lord of all the land in a proprietorial sense, but it is far more probable that such an idea was only a gradual development than that it was primitive. The power of devouring the people is a political power, not a right of ownership; precisely the same feature can be traced in South Africa,<ref name=fx36_ve2_790/> where the chief can deprive a man arbitrarily of his land, though the land is really owned by the native. The matter is ultimately to some extent one of terminology, but the parallel cases are in favour of distinguishing between the political rights of the crown, which can be transferred by way of a grant, and the rights of ownership. Hopkins<ref name=fx37_ve2_790/> thinks that the gifts of land to priests, which seems to be the first sign of land transactions in the Brāhmaṇas, was an actual gift of land; it may have been so in many cases, but it may easily also have been the grant of a superiority: the Epic grants are hardly decisive one way or the other.<br><br>For the relations of the king with the assembly, see '''[[सभा|Sabhā]];''' for his consecration, see '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]].''' A-rāja-tā, ‘lack of a king,’ means ‘anarchy.’<ref name=fx38_ve2_790/><br>

राजन्
<u>'''2. Rājan'''</u> in several passages-means no more than a ‘noble of the ruling house,’ or perhaps even merely a ‘noble,’ there being(**  1 ''Cf.'' Rv. i. 40, 8; 108, 7; x. 42, 10; 97, 6; [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā, iv. 6, 8, 3; v. 7, 6, 4; [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā, xl. 13; Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā, xviii. 48; xxvi. 2; Av. xix. 62, 1, and possibly ii. 6, 4, etc.; Ludwig, Translation of the Rigveda, 3, 236, 237. Possibly ''rājñaḥ'' in Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], i. 4, 5, may be taken in this sense. The king there is said to be a non-Āryan, but the reading is corrupt, and Oertel's conjecture is not probable. ''Cf.'' '''[[राज्य|Rājya]],''' n. 2.  no decisive passage. Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_791/> sees traces in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_791/> that in times of peace there was no king in some states, the members of the royal family holding equal rights. He compares this with the state of affairs in early Germany.<ref name=fx4_ve2_791/> But the passage merely shows that the nobles could be called [[राजन्|Rājan]], and is not decisive for the sense ascribed to it by Zimmer. Of course this state of affairs is perfectly possible, and is exemplified later in Buddhist times.<ref name=fx5_ve2_791/><br>

राजनि
<u>'''Rājani,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Rajana,'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[उग्रदेव|Ugradeva]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 3, 17; xxiii. 16, 11) and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (v. 4. 12).<br>

राजन्य
<u>'''Rājanya'''</u> is the regular term in Vedic literature<ref name=fx1_ve2_793/> for a man of the royal family, probably including also those who were not actually members of that family, but were nobles, though it may have been originally restricted to members of the royal family. This, however, does not appear clearly from any passage; the term may originally have applied to all the nobles irrespective of kingly power. In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_793/> the [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] is different from the [[राजपुत्र|Rājaputra]], who is literally a son of the king. The functions and place of the [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] are described under '''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]],''' which expression later normally takes the place of [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] as a designation for the ruling class. His high place is shown by the fact that in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_793/> he is ranked with the learned Brahmin and the  '''Grāmaṇī''' (who was a '''[[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]''') as having reached the height of prosperity (''gata-[[श्री|śrī]]'').<br>

राजन्य-बन्धु
<u>'''Rājanya-bandhu'''</u> denotes a [[राजन्य|Rājanya]], but usually with a depreciating sense. Thus in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_794/> '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' is called by the Brahmins, whom he defeated in disputation, ‘a fellow of a Rājanya’; the same description is applied to '''[[प्रवाहण जैवलि|Pravāhaṇa Jaivali]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_794/> for a similar reason. On the other hand, in one passage<ref name=fx3_ve2_794/> where reference is made to men eating apart from women, princes are said to do so most of all: the term [[राजन्यबन्धु|Rājanyabandhu]] cannot here be deemed to be contemptuous, unless, indeed, it is the expression of Brahmin contempt for princes, such as clearly appears in the treatment of '''[[नग्नजित्|Nagnajit]]''' in another passage.<ref name=fx4_ve2_794/> Again, in a passage<ref name=fx5_ve2_794/> in which the four castes are mentioned, the '''[[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]''' precedes the [[राजन्यबन्धु|Rājanyabandhu]], a curious inversion of the order of the second and third castes.<ref name=fx6_ve2_794/><br>

राजन्य-र्षि
<u>'''Rājanya-rṣi,'''</u> ‘royal sage,’ is a term applied to '''[[सिन्धुक्षित्|Sindhukṣit]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_795/> The story about him is, however, purely mythical.<br>

राज-पति
<u>'''Rāja-pati,'''</u> ‘lord of kings,’ is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xi. 4, 3, 9) as an epithet of Soma. It is not used elsewhere as a title of imperial temporal supremacy: see '''[[राज्य|Rājya]].''' <br>

राज-पितृ
<u>'''Rāja-pitṛ'''</u> is one of the titles given to the king in the rite of the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]]''' (‘royal consecration’) according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 12, 5; 17, 5). It probably designates the king as ‘father of a king,’ and indicates the hereditary character of the monarchy. Possibly the later plan<ref name=fx1_ve2_797/> of associating the king's son in the monarchy prevailed in earlier times also.<br>

राज-पुत्र
<u>'''Rāja-putra,'''</u> ‘king's son,’ ‘prince,’ seems to be capable of being interpreted literally in every passage of the older literature<ref name=fx1_ve2_798/> in which it is found, though it may also be capable of a wider interpretation.<ref name=fx2_ve2_798/> Later the [[राजपुत्र|Rājaputra]] degenerates into a mere ‘landowner.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_798/><br>

राज-पुरुष
<u>'''Rāja-puruṣa'''</u> denotes a ‘royal servant’ in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (ii. 3). ''Cf.'' '''[[पूरुष|Pūruṣa]].'''<br>

राज-भ्रातृ
<u>'''Rāja-bhrātṛ,'''</u> the ‘brother of the king,’ is mentioned as one of the eight '''Vīras,''' or supporters of the monarchy, in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_800/> He is also alluded to elsewhere.<ref name=fx2_ve2_800/><br>

राज-मात्र
<u>'''Rāja-mātra'''</u> is found in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxvii. 6) and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xvii. 5, 3. 4; 15, 3), where it seems to include ‘the whole class of persons (who could be called) Rājan’--''i.e.,'' the '''Rājaputras''' and the '''Rājanyas.''' <br>

राज-यक्ष्म
<u>'''Rāja-yakṣma,'''</u> ‘royal sickness,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_802/> and several times later on.<ref name=fx2_ve2_802/> Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_802/> identifies it with consumption: this identification seems certain, being supported by the later view of the disease.<ref name=fx4_ve2_802/> Bloomfield<ref name=fx5_ve2_802/> suggests ‘king's evil,’ or syphilis, as the sense, but this is not probable.<br>

राज-सूय
<u>'''Rāja-sūya'''</u> is the name in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_803/> and the later literature<ref name=fx2_ve2_803/> of the ceremony of the ‘royal consecration.’ The rite is described at great length in the Sūtras,<ref name=fx3_ve2_803/> but its main features are clearly outlined in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx4_ve2_803/> while the verses used in the ceremony are preserved in the Saṃhitās of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx5_ve2_803/> Besides much mere priestly elaboration, the ritual contains traces of popular ceremonial. For example, the king is clothed in the ceremonial garments of his rank, and provided with bow and arrow as emblems of sovereignty. He is formally anointed; he performs a mimic cow raid against a relative of his;<ref name=fx6_ve2_803/> or engages in a sham fight with a '''[[राजन्य|Rājanya]].'''<ref name=fx7_ve2_803/> A game of dice is played in which he is made to be the victim;<ref name=fx8_ve2_803/> he symbolically ascends the quarters of the sky as an indication of his universal rule; and steps on a tiger skin, thus gaining the strength and the pre-eminence of the tiger. <br><br>A list of the consecrated kings is given in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx9_ve2_803/> where the royal inauguration is called the ‘great unction’ (''[[महाभिषेक|mahābhiṣeka]]'') connected with Indra. It corresponds generally with a list of Aśvamedhins, ‘performers of the horse sacrifice,’ given in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx10_ve2_803/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx11_ve2_803/><br>

राज-स्तम्बायन
<u>'''Rāja-stambāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Rājastamba,’ is the patronymic of '''Yajñavacas''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_804/><br>

राजाधिराज
<u>'''Rājādhirāja,'''</u> ‘king of kings,’ later a title of paramount sovereignty, is only found in Vedic literature in the late [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (i. 31, 6) as a divine epithet.<br>

राजाश्व
<u>'''Rājāśva'''</u> (‘king's horse’) in the Atharvaveda (vi. 102, 2) seems merely to denote a powerful horse.<br>

राज्ञी
<u>'''Rājñī,'''</u> ‘queen,’ is found in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_807/> and in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_807/><br>

राज्य
<u>'''Rājya'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_808/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_808/> regularly denotes ‘sovereign power,’ from which, as the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_808/> notes, the Brahmin is excluded.<br><br>In addition to [[राज्य|Rājya]], the texts give other expressions of sovereign power. Thus the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_808/> contends  that the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]] sacrifice is that of a king, the '''[[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]]''' that of a [[सम्राज्|Samrāj]] or emperor, the status of the latter ([[साम्राज्य|Sāmrājya]]) being superior to that of the former ([[राज्य|Rājya]]). The sitting on a throne ('''[[आसन्दी|Āsandī]]''') is given in the same text<ref name=fx5_ve2_808/> as one of the characteristics of the [[सम्राज्|Samrāj]]. Elsewhere<ref name=fx6_ve2_808/> [[स्वाराज्य|Svārājya]], ‘uncontrolled dominion,’ is opposed to [[राज्य|Rājya]]. In the ritual of the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]]''' the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve2_808/> gives a whole series of terms: [[राज्य|Rājya]], [[साम्राज्य|Sāmrājya]], [[भौज्य|Bhaujya]], [[स्वाराज्य|Svārājya]], [[वैराज्य|Vairājya]], Pārameṣṭhya, and [[माहाराज्य|Māhārājya]], while Ādhipatya, ‘supreme power,’ is found elsewhere.<ref name=fx8_ve2_808/> But there is no reason to believe that these terms refer to essentially different forms of authority. A king might be called a '''[[महाराज|Mahārāja]]''' or a '''[[सम्राज्|Samrāj]],''' without really being an overlord of kings; he would be so termed if he were an important sovereign, or by his own entourage out of compliment, as was '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' of '''[[विदेह|Videha]].'''<ref name=fx9_ve2_808/> That a really great monarchy of the Aśoka or [[गुप्त|Gupta]] type ever existed in the Vedic period seems highly improbable.<ref name=fx10_ve2_808/><br>

रात्री
<u>'''Rātrī'''</u> is the most usual word in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_809/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_809/> for ‘night.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

राथीतर
<u>'''Rāthītara,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[रथीतर|Rathītara]],’ is the patronymic of '''[[सत्यवचस्|Satyavacas]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 9, 1), and occurs several times as the name of a teacher in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (vii. 4, etc.).<br>

राथीतरी-पुत्र
<u>'''Rāthītarī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of [[रथीतर|Rathītara]],’ is the name of a teacher in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]], the pupil of '''[[भालुकी-पुत्र|Bhālukī-putra]],''' according to the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension (vi. 5, 1), of the '''Krauñcikīputras''' according to the Mādhyaṃdina (vi. 4, 32). <br>

राध गौतम
<u>'''Rādha Gautama'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[गोतम|Gotama]]'''’) is the name of two teachers in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_812/><br>

राधेय
<u>'''Rādheya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Rādhā,’ is the metronymic of a teacher in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (vii. 6).<br><br>''Cf.'' Keith, ''Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society,'' 1908, 372.<br>

राम
<u>'''1. Rāma'''</u> is the name of a man in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_814/> Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_814/> thinks that he bore the patronymic '''[[मायव|Māyava]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_814/> but this is doubtful.<br>

राम औप-तस्विनि
<u>'''2. Rāma Aupa-tasvini'''</u> (‘descendant of Upatasvina’) is the name of a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iv. 6, 1, 7).<br>

राम क्रातु-जातेय
<u>'''3. Rāma Krātu-jāteya'''</u> (‘descendant of Kratu-jāta’) '''[[वैयाघ्र-पद्य|Vaiyāghra-padya]]''' (‘descendant of Vyāghrapad’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[शङ्ग शाट्यायनि|Śaṅga Śāṭyāyani]] [[आत्रेय|Ātreya]],''' who is mentioned in two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 1; iv. 16, 1).<br>

राम मार्ग-वेय
<u>'''4. Rāma Mārga-veya'''</u> is the name of a man of the priestly family of the '''Śyāparṇas''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_817/><br>

रामकायन
<u>'''Rāmakāyana.'''</u> See '''[[बस्त|Basta]].'''<br>

रामा
<u>'''Rāmā'''</u> in a few passages<ref name=fx1_ve2_819/> seems to have the sense of a ‘hetaera.’<br>

रायो-वाज
<u>'''Rāyo-vāja'''</u> is the name of a seer of Sāmans or chants in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 1, 4; xiii. 4, 17; ''cf.'' xxiv. 1, 7). <br>

राष्ट्र
<u>'''Rāṣṭra'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_821/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_821/> denotes ‘kingdom’ or ‘royal territory.’<br>

राष्ट्र-गोप
<u>'''Rāṣṭra-gopa,'''</u> ‘protector of the realm,’ is the epithet applied, in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 25), to the '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]],''' whose special charge it was to preserve the king and realm from harm by his spells and rites.<br>

रासभ
<u>'''Rāsabha'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_823/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_823/> denotes an ‘ass.’<br>

रास्ना
<u>'''Rāsnā'''</u> in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_824/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] denotes ‘girdle’ or ‘band,’ like '''[[रशना|Raśanā]]''' and '''[[रश्मि|Raśmi]].'''<br><br>vi. 2, 2, 25; 5, 2, 11, 13. ''Cf. rāsnāva,'' ‘girdled,’ iv. 1, 5, 19.<br>

राहु
<u>'''Rāhu,'''</u> the demon that eclipses the sun, seems to be referred to in one passage of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_825/> The reading here is somewhat uncertain, but [[राहु|Rāhu]] is probably meant.<br>

राहू-गण
<u>'''Rāhū-gaṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[रहू-गण|Rahū-gaṇa]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[गोतम|Gotama]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_826/> <br>

रिक्थ
<u>'''Riktha'''</u> is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_827/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_827/> denoting ‘inheritance.’<ref name=fx1_ve2_827/><br>

रिपु
<u>'''Ripu'''</u> is a common word for ‘foe,’ ‘enemy,’ in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_828/> It occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_828/> also.<br>

रुक्म
<u>'''Rukma'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_829/> denotes an ornament, probably of gold, usually worn on the breast. Being in several passages used of the sun, it probably had the form of a disk. In the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_829/> it designates a gold plate. See also '''[[रजत|Rajata]].'''<br>

रुक्म-पाश
<u>'''Rukma-pāśa'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_830/> denotes the ‘cord’ on which ‘the gold plate’ is hung.<br>

रुद्र-ब्नुति द्राह्यायण
<u>'''Rudra-bnuti Drāhyāyaṇa'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''Trāta''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_831/><br>

रुम
<u>'''Ruma'''</u> is mentioned in one hymn of the Rigveda (viii. 4, 2) with '''[[रुशम|Ruśama]], [[श्यावक|Śyāvaka]],''' and '''[[कृप|Kṛpa]]''' as a favourite of Indra. <br>

रुरु
<u>'''Ruru'''</u> is one of the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_833/> A kind of deer is meant. The Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_833/> mentions ‘deer-headed’ (''ruru-śīrṣan'') arrows, meaning such as have points made of deer's horn.<br>

रुशम
<u>'''Ruśama'''</u> is mentioned three times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_834/> as a protégé of Indra. The Ruśamas occur in another passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_834/> with their generous king '''[[ऋणंचय|Ṛṇaṃcaya]];''' they are also referred to, with their king '''[[कौरम|Kaurama]],''' in a passage of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_834/><br>

रुशमा
<u>'''Ruśamā'''</u> is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxv. 13, 3), where she is said to have run round '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]],''' and so to have defeated Indra, who understood her challenge to refer to the earth proper. The story indicates the connexion of the Ruśamas with the '''Kurus.'''<br>

रुषती
<u>'''Ruṣatī'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_836/> denotes, according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve2_836/> a maiden who was married to '''[[श्याव|Śyāva]].''' On the other hand, Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_836/> treats the word as ''ruśatī,'' ‘white,’ and ''ruśatīm'' seems clearly to be the reading of the text. It is doubtful what the meaning is, and whether [[श्याव|Śyāva]] is a proper name at all.<ref name=fx4_ve2_836/><br>

रेक्णस्
<u>'''Rekṇas'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_837/> denotes ‘inherited property,’ and then ‘property’ in general. <br>

रेणु
<u>'''Reṇu'''</u> is the name of a son of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 17, 7) and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xv. 26, 1).<br>

रेभ
<u>'''1. Rebha'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_839/> denotes a ‘singer’ of praise, a ‘panegyrist.’<br>

रेभ
<u>'''2. Rebha'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_840/> as the name of a protégé of the Aśvins, who saved him from the waters and from imprisonment.<ref name=fx1_ve2_840/><br>

रेवा
<u>'''Revā,'''</u> a name of the Narmadā (Nerbudda) river, otherwise occurring only in post-Vedic literature, is seen by Weber<ref name=fx1_ve2_841/> in the word '''[[रेवोत्तरस्|Revottaras]],''' which is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_841/> and is certainly a man's name.<br>

रेवती
<u>'''Revatī.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

रेवोत्तरस्
<u>'''Revottaras'''</u> is the name of '''[[पाटव|Pāṭava]] [[चाक्र|Cākra]] [[स्थपति|Sthapati]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_843/> who was expelled, with '''[[दुष्टरीतु|Duṣṭarītu]] [[पौंसायन|Pauṃsāyana]],''' by the '''Sṛnjayas,''' and who was in part instrumental in the restoration of his master to power, despite the opposition of '''[[बल्हिक प्रातिपीय|Balhika Prātipīya]],''' the '''Kuru''' king.<br>

रेष्मन्
<u>'''Reṣman'''</u> in the Atharvaveda (vi. 102, 2; xv. 2, 1), the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iii. 15, 2), and the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xxv. 2) denotes a ‘whirlwind.’<br>

रैक्व
<u>'''Raikva'''</u> is the name of a man who is mentioned several times in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 1, 3. 5. 8; 2, 2. 4). <br>

रैक्व-पर्ण
<u>'''Raikva-parṇa,'''</u> masc. plur., is the name of a locality in the '''[[महावृष|Mahāvṛṣa]]''' country according to the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_846/><br>

रैभी
<u>'''Raibhī,'''</u> fem. plur., occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_847/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve2_847/> together with '''[[गाथा|Gāthā]]''' and '''[[नाराशंसी|Nārāśaṃsī]],''' as a form of literature. Later on<ref name=fx3_ve2_847/> the [[रैभी|Raibhī]] verses are identified with certain verses of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx4_ve2_847/> but that this identification holds<ref name=fx5_ve2_847/> in the Rigveda and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā seems very doubtful.<ref name=fx6_ve2_847/><br>

रैभ्य
<u>'''Raibhya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[रेभ|Rebha]],'''’ is the name of a teacher in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 5, 20; iv. 5, 26), where he is said to be a pupil of '''[[पौतिमाष्यायण|Pautimāṣyāyaṇa]]''' and '''[[कौण्डिन्यायन|Kauṇḍinyāyana]].'''<br>

रोग
<u>'''Roga'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_849/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_849/> denotes ‘disease’ generally.<br>

रोपणाका
<u>'''Ropaṇākā'''</u> is the name of a bird mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_850/> and the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_850/> The ‘thrush’ seems to be meant;<ref name=fx3_ve2_850/> but Keśava, the commentator on the [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx4_ve2_850/> is inclined to understand the word to mean a sort of wood. <br>

रोमशा
<u>'''Romaśā'''</u> is mentioned in the Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx1_ve2_851/> as the wife of king '''[[भावयव्य|Bhāvayavya]],''' and is credited with the authorship of a Rigvedic verse.<ref name=fx2_ve2_851/> But in reality the word ''[[रोमशा|romaśā]]'' in that verse, which is the source of the legend, is merely an adjective meaning ‘hairy.’<br>

रोहिणी
<u>'''1. Rohiṇī'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_852/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_852/> denotes a ‘red cow.’<br>

रोहिणी
<u>'''2. Rohiṇī.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

रोहित्
<u>'''Rohit'''</u> in some passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_854/> denotes, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, a ‘red mare,’ while later<ref name=fx2_ve2_854/> it denotes a ‘red doe.’<br>

रोहित
<u>'''1. Rohita'''</u> denotes a ‘red horse’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_855/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_855/><br>

रोहित
<u>'''2. Rohita'''</u> is a son of '''Hariścandra''' in the famous tale of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 14) and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xv. 18, 8).<br>

रोहितक
<u>'''Rohitaka'''</u> occurs in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iii. 9, 3) with a variant [[रोहीतक|Rohītaka]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_857/> as the name of the tree ''Andersonia [[रोहितक|Rohitaka]].''<br>

रोहितक-कूल
<u>'''Rohitaka-kūla'''</u> is in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_858/> the name of a locality after which a Sāman or chant was called. <br>

रोहीतक
<u>'''Rohītaka.'''</u> See '''[[रोहितक|Rohitaka]].'''<br>

रौहिण
<u>'''1. Rauhiṇa'''</u> is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_860/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_860/> as a demon foe of Indra's. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx3_ve2_860/> is inclined to see in the word the name of a planet (''cf.'' '''[[रोहिणी|Rohiṇī]]'''), but without any clear reason.<br>

रौहिण
<u>'''2. Rauhiṇa'''</u> (‘born under the [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] Rohiṇī’) '''[[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]'''’), is the name of a man in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (i. 12, 5).<br>

रौहिणायन
<u>'''Rauhiṇāyana'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[रौहिण|Rauhiṇa]]'''’) is the patronymic of '''Priyavrata''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 3, 5, 14). It is also in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 5, 20; iv. 5, 26) the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[शौनक|Śaunaka]]''' and others.<br>

लक्ष
<u>'''Lakṣa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_863/> denotes the ‘prize’ at dicing.<br>

लक्षण
<u>'''Lakṣaṇa'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_864/> or '''[[लक्ष्मन्|Lakṣman]]'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_864/> denotes the ‘mark’ made on cattle by branding to distinguish ownership. According to the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx3_ve2_864/> it was to be made under the '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]] [[रेवती|Revatī]],''' clearly because of the property indicated in the name (‘wealthy’) of that [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]]. See '''[[अष्टकर्णी|Aṣṭakarṇī]].''' <br>

लक्ष्मण्य
<u>'''Lakṣmaṇya'''</u> in one verse of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_865/> seems to be a patronymic of '''[[ध्वन्य|Dhvanya]],''' ‘son of Lakṣmaṇa.’<br>

लक्ष्मन्
<u>'''Lakṣman.'''</u> See '''[[लक्षण|Lakṣaṇa]].'''<br>

लब
<u>'''Laba,'''</u> ‘quail’ (''Perdix chinensis'') is one of the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_867/><br>

लम्बन
<u>'''Lambana'''</u> is the reading in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension (v. 10, 1) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] for '''[[आडम्बर|Āḍambara]],''' ‘drum,’ in the Mādhyaṃdina recension (v. 12, 1).<br>

लवण
<u>'''Lavaṇa,'''</u> ‘salt,’ is never mentioned in the Rigveda, only once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_869/> and not after that until the latest part of the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx2_ve2_869/> where it is regarded as of extremely high value.<ref name=fx3_ve2_869/> This silence in the early period is somewhat surprising if the regions then occupied by the Indians were the Panjab and the Indus valley, where salt abounds; it would at first sight seem less curious if the home of the early Vedic Indian is taken to be '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_869/> It is, however, quite conceivable that a necessary commodity might happen to be passed over without literary mention in a region where it is very common, but to be referred to in a locality where it is not found, and consequently becomes highly prized. <br>

लवन
<u>'''Lavana'''</u> in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (ii. 2) denotes the ‘mowing’ or ‘reaping’ of corn.<br>

लाक्षा
<u>'''Lākṣā'''</u> occurs once in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_871/> as the name of a plant.<br>

लाङ्गल
<u>'''Lāṅgala'''</u> is the regular word for ‘plough’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_872/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_872/> It is described in a series of passages<ref name=fx3_ve2_872/> as ‘lancepointed’ (''pavīravat'' or ''pavīravam''), ‘well-lying’ (''susīmam''),<ref name=fx4_ve2_872/> and ‘having a well-smoothed handle’ (see '''[[त्सरु|Tsaru]]'''). See also '''[[सीर|Sīra]].'''<br>

लाङ्गलायन
<u>'''Lāṅgalāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[लाङ्गल|Lāṅgala]],’ is the patronymic of '''[[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] [[मौद्गल्य|Maudgalya]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[मुद्गल|Mudgala]]'''’) in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 3, 8).<br>

लाज
<u>'''Lāja,'''</u> masc. plur., in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_874/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_874/> denotes ‘fried or parched grain.’<br>

लाजि
<u>'''Lāji'''</u> in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xxiii. 8) and the Taittīrīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 9, 4, 8) is a word of uncertain meaning; according to Sāyaṇa, it is a vocative of Lājin, ‘having parched grain’; according to Mahīdhara, it denotes a ‘quantity of parched grain.’ <br>

लातव्य
<u>'''Lātavya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Latu,’ is the patronymic of '''Kūśāmba [[स्वायव|Svāyava]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_876/><br>

लामकायन
<u>'''Lāmakāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Lamaka,’ is often mentioned as an authority in the Lāṭyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_877/> the [[निदान|Nidāna]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_877/> and the Drāhyāyaṇa Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]];<ref name=fx3_ve2_877/> also with the name '''Saṃvargajit''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_877/><br>

लाह्यायन
<u>'''Lāhyāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Lahya,’ is the patronymic of '''[[भुज्यु|Bhujyu]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 5, 1. 2).<br>

लिबुजा
<u>'''Libujā'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_879/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_879/> denotes a creeping plant that climbs trees.<br>

लुश
<u>'''Luśa'''</u> is represented in a series of passages in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_880/> as a rival of '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]]''' for the favour of Indra. To [[लुश|Luśa]] Dhānāka the authorship of certain hymns<ref name=fx2_ve2_880/> is ascribed by the Anukramaṇī (Index) of the Rigveda.<br>

लुशाकपि खार्गलि
<u>'''Luśākapi Khārgali'''</u> (‘descendant of Khṛgala’) is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_881/> as having cursed '''[[कुषीतक|Kuṣītaka]]''' and the '''Kauṣītakins.''' He was a contemporary of '''[[केशिन्|Keśin]] [[दाल्भ्य|Dālbhya]]''' according to the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_881/> <br>

लोक
<u>'''Loka'''</u> denotes ‘world’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_882/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_882/> Mention is often made of the three worlds,<ref name=fx3_ve2_882/> and ''ayaṃ lokaḥ,'' ‘this world,’<ref name=fx4_ve2_882/> is constantly opposed to ''asau lokaḥ,''<ref name=fx5_ve2_882/> ‘yonder world’-''i.e.,'' ‘heaven.’ Loka itself sometimes means ‘heaven,’<ref name=fx6_ve2_882/> while in other passages several different sorts of world are mentioned.<ref name=fx7_ve2_882/><br>

लोध
<u>'''Lodha'''</u> occurs in a very obscure verse of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_883/> where Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_883/> conjectures that some sort of ‘red’ animal is meant, and Oldenberg<ref name=fx3_ve2_883/> shows some reason for thinking that a ‘red goat’ is intended.<br>

लोपा
<u>'''Lopā'''</u> is mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve2_884/> where Sāyaṇa explains it as a kind of bird, perhaps the carrion crow (''śmaśānaśakuni''). <br>

लोपा-मुद्रा
<u>'''Lopā-mudrā'''</u> appears in one hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_885/> where she is seemingly the wife of '''[[अगस्त्य|Agastya]],''' whose embraces she solicits.<ref name=fx2_ve2_885/><br>

लोपाश
<u>'''Lopāśa'''</u> is the name of an animal, probably the ‘jackal’ or ‘fox,’ which is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_886/> and is included in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve2_886/><br>

लोह
<u>'''Loha,'''</u> primarily an adjective meaning ‘red,’ is used as a neuter substantive to designate a metal, probably ‘copper,’ but possibly ‘bronze.’ It is mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_887/> and the Taittīriya Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_887/> as distinguished from '''[[श्याम|Śyāma]].''' It also occurs several times in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx3_ve2_887/> See Ayas.<br>

लोह-मणि
<u>'''Loha-maṇi'''</u> in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 2, 5) denotes a ‘copper amulet,’ as Bo7htlingk<ref name=fx1_ve2_888/> renders it, rather than a ‘lump of gold,’ as translated by Max Müller following the scholiast.<br>

लोहायस
<u>'''Lohāyasa,'''</u> ‘red metal,’ is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_889/> where it is distinguished from '''Ayas''' and gold. In the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_889/> the contrast is with Kārṣṇā-  yasa, ‘iron,’ and in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_889/> with [[कृष्णायस|Kṛṣṇāyasa]], ‘iron.’ ‘Copper’ seems to be meant.<br>

लोहित
<u>'''Lohita,'''</u> often occurring as an adjective meaning ‘red,’ is used as a neuter substantive in the Atharvaveda (xi. 3, 7) to denote a metal, presumably ‘copper.’ As a proper name it is found in Āpastamba Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], xxiv. 9, 7.<br>

लोहितायस
<u>'''Lohitāyasa,'''</u> ‘red metal,’ ‘copper,’ is the variant of '''Loha''' in the Maitrāyaṇī (ii. 11, 5; iv. 4, 4) and [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] (xviii. 10) Saṃhitās.<br>

लोहिताहि
<u>'''Lohitāhi,'''</u> ‘red snake,’ is the name of a variety of serpent mentioned in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_892/><br>

लौहित्य
<u>'''Lauhitya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[लोहित|Lohita]],’ is the patronymic of a large number of teachers in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], which clearly must have been the special object of study of the [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]] family. See '''Kṛṣṇadatta, Kṛṣṇarāta, Jayaka, Triveda Kṛṣṇarāta, Dakṣa [[जयन्त|Jayanta]], Palligupta, Mitrabhūti, Yaśasvin [[जयन्त|Jayanta]], Vipaścit [[दृढजयन्त|Dṛḍhajayanta]], [[वैपश्चित|Vaipaścita]] [[दार्ढजयन्ति|Dārḍhajayanti]], [[वैपश्चित|Vaipaścita]] [[दार्ढजयन्ति|Dārḍhajayanti]] [[दृढजयन्त|Dṛḍhajayanta]], Śyāmajayanta, Śyāmasujayanta, [[सत्यश्रवस्|Satyaśravas]].''' A [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]] or Lauhikya is also mentioned as a teacher in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve2_893/> The form of name ([[जयन्त|Jayanta]]) affected by the family, and the silence of the older texts, proves that they were modern. <br>

वंश
<u>'''1. Vaṃśa,'''</u> denoting the ‘rafters’ or ‘beams’ of the house as made of bamboo cane, is found in this sense from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_894/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve2_894/> ''Cf.'' '''[[तिरश्चीनवंश|Tiraścīnavaṃśa]], [[प्राचीनवंश|Prācīnavaṃśa]],''' and see '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].'''<br>

वंश
<u>'''2. Vaṃśa'''</u> (lit. ‘bamboo’) in the sense of ‘spiritual genealogy,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_895/> ‘list of teachers,’ is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_895/> the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_895/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx4_ve2_895/><br>

वंश-नर्तिन्
<u>'''Vaṃśa-nartin'''</u> is mentioned as one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_896/> A ‘poledancer’ or ‘acrobat’ seems to be meant.<br>

वंसग
<u>'''Vaṃsaga'''</u> is in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_897/> a common name of the ‘bull’ that leads the herds.<br>

वक दाल्भ्य
<u>'''Vaka Dālbhya'''</u> (‘descendant of Dalbha’) is the name of a teacher in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_898/> According to the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve2_898/> he was engaged in a ritual dispute with '''[[धृतराष्ट्र|Dhṛtarāṣṭra]].'''<br>

वकल
<u>'''Vakala'''</u> denotes in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_899/> the ‘inner bark’ of a tree, ‘bast.’ <br>

वक्षणा
<u>'''Vakṣaṇā,'''</u> fem. plur. denotes in one passage of the '''Rigveda'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_900/> the bed of a stream.<br>

वघा
<u>'''Vaghā'''</u> is the name of a noxious animal the '''Atharvaveda.'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_901/><br>

वङ्ग
<u>'''Vaṅga,'''</u> the designation of Bengal proper is not found in the earlier Vedic literature unless it is to be recognized in the curious word ''Vaṅgāvagadhāḥ,'' which occurs in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx1_ve2_902/> and which suggests amendment to ''[[वङ्ग|Vaṅga]]-Magadhāḥ,'' ‘the Vaṅgas and the Magadhas,’ two neighbouring peoples. The name is certainly found in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_902/><br>

वङ्गृद
<u>'''Vaṅgṛda'''</u> is the name of a demon or a human foe in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_903/><br>

वज्र
<u>'''Vajra'''</u> in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_904/> denotes, according to Geldner,<ref name=fx2_ve2_904/> the ‘handle,’ while '''[[कूट|Kūṭa]]''' means the ‘head’ of the hammer.<br>

वडव
<u>'''Vaḍava'''</u> is a common name for a ‘mare’ in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_905/><br>

वणिज्
<u>'''Vaṇij'''</u> denotes ‘merchant’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_906/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_906/> See '''[[पणि|Paṇi]]''' and '''[[क्रय|Kraya]];''' ''cf.'' also '''[[वाणिज|Vāṇija]].''' <br>

वणिज्या
<u>'''Vaṇijyā'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_907/> denotes the business of a merchant ('''[[वणिज्|Vaṇij]]''') ‘trade.’<br>

वत्स
<u>'''1. Vatsa'''</u> is often found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_908/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_908/> in the sense of ‘calf.’ Reference is made to the use of a calf to induce the cow to give milk,<ref name=fx3_ve2_908/> and to the separation of the cows from the calves at certain times.<ref name=fx4_ve2_908/><br>

वत्स
<u>'''2. Vatsa'''</u> occurs several times in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_909/> as the name of a singer, a son or descendant of '''[[कण्व|Kaṇva]].''' In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_909/> he is said to have passed successfully through a fire ordeal to which he resorted for the purpose of proving to his rival, '''[[मेधातिथि|Medhātithi]],''' the purity of his descent. He is also mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_909/> as the recipient of bounty from '''Tirindara [[पारशव्य|Pāraśavya]].'''<br>

वत्सतर
<u>'''Vatsatara, Vatsatari,'''</u> denotes a ‘young calf’ in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_910/><br>

वत्स-नपात् बाभ्रव
<u>'''Vatsa-[[नपात्|napāt]] Bābhrava'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[बभ्रु|Babhru]]'''’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[पथिन् सौभर|Pathin Saubhara]],''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_911/><br>

वत्स-प्री भालन्दन
<u>'''Vatsa-prī Bhālandana'''</u> (‘descendant of Bhalandana’) is the name of a sage who ‘saw’ the Vātsapra Sāman (chant). He  is mentioned in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_912/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_912/><br>

वधक
<u>'''Vadhaka'''</u> is the name of some sort of ‘reed’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_913/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_913/><br>

वधर्
<u>'''Vadhar'''</u> means a ‘weapon’ generally; it is used not merely of a divine,<ref name=fx1_ve2_914/> but also of a human<ref name=fx2_ve2_914/> weapon in the Rigveda.<br>

वधू
<u>'''1. Vadhū'''</u> is a frequent word for ‘woman’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_915/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_915/> It denotes, according to Delbrück,<ref name=fx3_ve2_915/> the woman as either married or as seeking a husband, or as a bride in the wedding ceremony. The word appears to be derived from a form of the root ''vah,'' ‘to carry,’ as is ''[[वहतु|vahatu]],'' ‘the bridal procession,’ thus meaning ‘she who is to be or has been conducted home.’ Zimmer,<ref name=fx4_ve2_915/> however, objects to this explanation, regarding ''[[वधू|vadhū]]'' as a derivative from a different root meaning ‘to marry.’<br>

वधू
<u>'''2. Vadhū'''</u> is in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_916/> taken by Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_916/> to denote a ‘female animal,’ while Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_916/> urges that it means a ‘female slave.’ As far as the use of [[वधू|Vadhū]] goes, either meaning is abnormal, for if [[वधू|Vadhū]] never elsewhere  means a female animal (from ''vah,'' to ‘draw’ a cart), neither does it denote a slave: as the passage refers to a gift of fifty Vadhūs by '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]] Paurukutsya''' to the singer, the latter must have been a polygamist of an advanced type to require fifty wives. The same doubt arises in the case of ''vadhūmant,'' which is used in the Rigveda and Atharvaveda as an epithet of the chariot ('''[[रथ|Ratha]]'''),<ref name=fx4_ve2_916/> of horses ('''[[अश्व|Aśva]]'''),<ref name=fx5_ve2_916/> and of buffaloes ('''Uṣṭra''').<ref name=fx6_ve2_916/> Zimmer sees in all cases a reference to slaves in the chariots or with the horses: this interpretation has the support of the Bṛhaddevatā.<ref name=fx7_ve2_916/> Roth's version of the references to horses or buffaloes as ‘suitable for draught’ is not very happy; if ''[[वधू|vadhū]]'' is really a female animal ''vadhūmant'' means rather ‘together with mares,’ or ‘together with female buffaloes,’ which makes reasonable sense.<ref name=fx8_ve2_916/><br>

वध्रिमती
<u>'''Vadhrimatī,'''</u> ‘having an impotent man as a husband,’ seems in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_917/> to be the name of a woman who owed the restoration of her husband's virility to the Aśvins, and obtained a son, '''[[हिरण्यहस्त|Hiraṇyahasta]].''' The word is, however, possibly only descriptive.<br>

वध्र्य्-अश्व
<u>'''1. Vadhry-aśva,'''</u> ‘having castrated horses,’ is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_918/> of a prince, the father of '''Divodāsa,''' and an energetic supporter of the fire cult, as was his son after him. He is mentioned in a long list of names in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_918/><br>

वध्र्य्-अश्व आनूप
<u>'''2. Vadhry-[[अश्व|aśva]] Ānūpa'''</u> (‘descendant of Anūpa’) is the name of the seer of a Sāman, or chant, in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 3, 17). <br>

वन
<u>'''Vana'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_920/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_920/> denotes the ‘forest,’ not necessarily of trees only, but, like [[अरण्य|Araṇya]], the wild uninhabited land.<ref name=fx3_ve2_920/> It also means ‘wooden cup’ used in the Soma ritual,<ref name=fx4_ve2_920/> and in one passage perhaps a part of the chariot.<ref name=fx5_ve2_920/><br>

वन-प
<u>'''Vana-pa,'''</u> ‘forest-guardian,’ is included in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_921/> ''Cf.'' '''Dāvapa.'''<br>

वनर्-गु
<u>'''Vanar-gu,'''</u> ‘forest-goer,’ is used in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_922/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_922/> to designate robbers who haunt the forests. In the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_922/> the term is more generally opposed to civilized men (''kavayaḥ,'' ‘sages’; ''vanargavaḥ,'' ‘savages’).<br>

वनस्-पति
<u>'''Vanas-pati,'''</u> ‘lord of the forest,’ primarily denotes ‘tree,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_923/> and then ‘post’ or ‘pole.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_923/> In some passages it is applied either to a part of the chariot or to the chariot as a whole.<ref name=fx3_ve2_923/> It also means a ‘wooden drum’<ref name=fx4_ve2_923/> and a ‘wooden amulet,’<ref name=fx5_ve2_923/> while in some passages<ref name=fx6_ve2_923/> it denotes the plant ''par excellence,'' Soma.<br>

वन्दन
<u>'''1. Vandana'''</u> is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_924/> as the name of a disease, apparently some sort of eruption spreading over the body. <br>

वन्दन
<u>'''2. Vandana'''</u> is the name of a protégé of the Aśvins in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_925/><br>

वन्धुर
<u>'''Vandhura'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_926/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_926/> the ‘seat’ of the chariot. See '''[[रथ|Ratha]].'''<br>

वप
<u>'''Vapa,'''</u> ‘sower,’ is mentioned in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_927/><br>

वपन
<u>'''Vapana'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_928/> denotes the process of ‘shaving.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[क्षुर|Kṣura]]''' and '''[[केश|Keśa]].'''<br>

वपा
<u>'''Vapā'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_929/> denotes an ant-hill.<br>

वप्तृ
<u>'''Vaptṛ'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_930/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_930/> denotes a ‘shaver,’ ‘barber.’<br>

वप्र
<u>'''Vapra,'''</u> ‘rampart,’ is a conjectural reading in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_931/> <br>

वम्र
<u>'''1. Vamra,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_932/> '''Vamrī,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_932/> are the names of the male and female ‘ant’ in the Rigveda and later. ''Cf.'' '''[[वपा|Vapā]].'''<br>

वम्र
<u>'''2. Vamra'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the '''Rigveda.'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_933/> ''Cf.'' '''[[वम्रक|Vamraka]].'''<br>

वम्रक
<u>'''Vamraka'''</u> is mentioned in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_934/> where Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_934/> thinks that an ‘ant’ is meant. But Pischel,<ref name=fx3_ve2_934/> with more probability, thinks that it is a proper name, perhaps equivalent to '''[[वम्र|Vamra]],''' and denoting the child of a maiden who was saved from being devoured by ants.<ref name=fx4_ve2_934/><br>

वयस्
<u>'''1. Vayas'''</u> is a common name for ‘bird’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_935/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_935/><br>

वयस्
<u>'''2. Vayas'''</u> denotes in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_936/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_936/> the ‘age of animals or men.’<br>

वया
<u>'''Vayā'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_937/> denotes the ‘branch’ of a tree.<br>

वयित्री
<u>'''Vayitrī'''</u> in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 8, 9) denotes a ‘female weaver.’ <br>

वय्य
<u>'''Vayya'''</u> occurs in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_939/> in connexion with '''[[तुर्वीति|Turvīti]],''' of whom the word is, according to Sāyaṇa,<ref name=fx2_ve2_939/> a patronymic in one passage. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_939/> is inclined to think that the sense of ‘companion’ would suit all passages.<br>

वर
<u>'''Vara'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_940/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_940/> regularly denotes a ‘wooer.’<br>

वरण
<u>'''Varaṇa'''</u> is the name of a tree (''Crataeva Roxburghii'') in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_941/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_941/><br>

वरणावती
<u>'''Varaṇāvatī'''</u> is found in one passage of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_942/> It seems to be, as Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_942/> thought, the name of a stream, and is regarded by Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve2_942/> as the Ganges. Bloomfield,<ref name=fx4_ve2_942/> while considering that a plant may, as Sāyaṇa thinks, be meant, yet regards a reference to a river as probable. ''Cf.'' '''[[काशि|Kāśi]].'''<br>

वरत्रा
<u>'''Varatrā'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_943/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_943/> denotes a ‘thong’ or ‘strap.’ It was used to fasten the oxen to the yoke,<ref name=fx3_ve2_943/> or perhaps to fasten the yoke to the pole.<ref name=fx4_ve2_943/> Or, again, it denotes<ref name=fx5_ve2_943/> the strap which was used in drawing up water from the well ('''[[अवत|Avata]]'''). <br>

वरशिख
<u>'''Varaśikha'''</u> is the name of a leader whose tribe is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_944/> as being defeated by '''[[अभ्यावर्तिन् चायमान|Abhyāvartin Cāyamāna]]'''<br>

वराह
<u>'''Varāha,'''</u> ‘boar,’ is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_945/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_945/> The god Rudra is described as the ‘boar of heaven.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_945/> The use of dogs to hunt the boar is once alluded to.<ref name=fx4_ve2_945/> The variant form of the word, Varāhu, is not used except metaphorically of divinities.<ref name=fx5_ve2_945/><br>

वरु
<u>'''Varu'''</u> is held by Sāyaṇa to be a proper name in several passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_946/> where it is accented as a vocative followed by ''suṣāmṇe.'' Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_946/> considers that the name must be Varosuṣāman, despite its doubtful formation.<br>

वरुण-गृहीत
<u>'''Varuṇa-gṛhīta,'''</u> ‘seized by Varuṇa,’ is found in several passages<ref name=fx1_ve2_947/> as a description of a man afflicted with dropsy, which is the disease sent by Varuṇa as a punishment for sin.<ref name=fx2_ve2_947/> <br>

वर्चिन्
<u>'''Varcin'''</u> is the name of a foe of Indra in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_948/> Being called a '''[[दास|Dāsa]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_948/> and coupled with [[शम्बर|Śambara]], he is probably to be regarded as a terrestrial foe, though he is also spoken of as an Asura.<ref name=fx3_ve2_948/> He may possibly have been connected with the '''Vṛcīvants.'''<br>

वर्ण
<u>'''1. Varṇa,'''</u> ‘colour,’ is a common word in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_949/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_949/> A large number of colours are enumerated in Vedic literature, but it is not possible to deduce any clear information as to the accuracy with which the Vedic Indian distinguished colours, or as to the principle on which his distinctions were based. The Rigveda seems to show that red or yellow colours were the most noticed, but this may be accidental.<ref name=fx3_ve2_949/> ‘Black’ or ‘dark’ is denoted by ''[[कृष्ण|kṛṣṇa]],'' ‘white’ or ‘light-coloured’ by ''[[शुक्ल|śukla]]'' or ''śveta.'' ‘Black’ seems to be meant in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_949/> by ''śyenī'' also. ‘Dark-grey’ or ‘dusky’ is expressed by ''[[श्याम|śyāma]].''<ref name=fx5_ve2_949/> The sense of ''nīla''<ref name=fx6_ve2_949/> is doubtful, perhaps ‘dark-blue,’ ‘bluish-black.’ The series of words ''hari, [[हरिण|hariṇa]], harit, [[हरित|harita]],'' seems, on the whole, to denote ‘yellow,’ but ‘green’ is also a possible rendering, since the epithet is used of the frog.<ref name=fx7_ve2_949/> ‘Brown’ is certainly the meaning of ''[[बभ्रु|babhru]],'' which is used of the '''[[विभीतक|Vibhītaka]]''' nut (see '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]]'''). ‘Reddish-brown’ seems to be the tinge implied by ''[[कपिल|kapila]]''<ref name=fx8_ve2_949/> (‘monkey-coloured’), while ''piṅgala'' appears to denote a shade of brown in which yellow pre-  dominates, ‘tawny.’<ref name=fx9_ve2_949/> ‘Yellow’ is expressed by ''pīta'' as well as ''pāṇḍu.''<ref name=fx10_ve2_949/> A garment of saffron (''[[माहारजन|māhārajana]]'') is mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx11_ve2_949/> ''Rudhira'' and ''[[लोहित|lohita]]'' are red, while ''aruṇa'' is ‘ruddy.’ ''Kalmāṣa'' means ‘spotted,’<ref name=fx12_ve2_949/> and ''[[शिल्प|śilpa]]'' ‘dappled,’<ref name=fx13_ve2_949/> while mingled shades like ''aruṇa-[[पिशङ्ग|piśaṅga]],'' ‘reddish brown,’ also occur.<ref name=fx14_ve2_949/><br>

वर्ण
<u>'''2. Varṇa'''</u> (lit. ‘colour’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_950/> is applied to denote classes of men, the '''[[दास|Dāsa]]''' and the Āryan [[वर्ण|Varṇa]] being contrasted, as other passages<ref name=fx2_ve2_950/> show, on account of colour. But this use is confined to distinguishing two colours: in this respect the Rigveda differs fundamentally from the later Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx3_ve2_950/> where the four castes (''varṇāḥ'') are already fully recognized.<br><br>''(a) Caste in the Rigveda.''--The use of the term [[वर्ण|Varṇa]] is not, of course, conclusive for the question whether caste existed in the Rigveda. In one sense it must be admitted to have existed: the [[पुरुष|Puruṣa]]-[[सूक्त|sūkta]], ‘hymn of man,’ in the tenth  Maṇḍala<ref name=fx4_ve2_950/> clearly contemplates the division of mankind into four classes--the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], [[राजन्य|Rājanya]], [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]], and [[शूद्र|Śūdra]]. But the hymn being admittedly late,<ref name=fx5_ve2_950/> its evidence is not cogent for the bulk of the Rigveda. Zimmer<ref name=fx6_ve2_950/> has with great force combatted the view that the Rigveda was produced in a society that knew the caste system. He points out that the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx7_ve2_950/> show us the Vedic Indians on the Indus as unbrahminized, and not under the caste system; he argues that the Rigveda was the product of tribes living in the Indus region and the Panjab; later on a part of this people, who had wandered farther east, developed the peculiar civilization of the caste system. He adopts the arguments of Muir,<ref name=fx8_ve2_950/> derived from the study of the data of the Rigveda, viz.: that (''a'') the four castes appear only in the late Puruṣasūkta; (''b'') the term [[वर्ण|Varṇa]], as shown above, covers the three highest castes of later times, and is only contrasted with [[दास|Dāsa]]; (''c'') that [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] is rare in the Rigveda, [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] occurs seldom,<ref name=fx9_ve2_950/> [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] only in the Puruṣasūkta, where too, alone, [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] and [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] are found; (''d'') that [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] denotes at first ‘poet,’ ‘sage,’ and then ‘officiating priest,’ or still later a special class of priest; (''e'') that in some only of the passages<ref name=fx10_ve2_950/> where it occurs does [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] denote a ‘priest by profession,’ while in others it denotes something peculiar to the individual, designating a person distinguished for genius or virtue, or specially chosen to receive divine inspiration.<ref name=fx11_ve2_950/> [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], on the other hand, as Muir admits,<ref name=fx12_ve2_950/> already denotes a hereditary professional priesthood.<br><br>Zimmer connects the change from the casteless system of the Rigveda to the elaborate system of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] with the  advance of the Vedic Indians to the east, comparing the Germanic invasions that transformed the German tribes into monarchies closely allied with the church. The needs of a conquering people evoke the monarch; the lesser princes sink to the position of nobles; for repelling the attacks of aborigines or of other Āryan tribes, and for quelling the revolts of the subdued population, the state requires a standing army in the shape of the armed retainers of the king, and beside the nobility of the lesser princes arises that of the king's chief retainers, as the Thegns supplemented the Gesiths of the Anglo-Saxon monarchies.<ref name=fx13_ve2_950/> At the same time the people ceased to take part in military matters, and under climatic influences left the conduct of war to the nobility and their retainers, devoting themselves to agriculture, pastoral pursuits, and trade. But the advantage won by the nobles over the people was shared by them with the priesthood, the origin of whose power lies in the Purohitaship, as Roth first saw.<ref name=fx14_ve2_950/><br><br>Originally the prince could sacrifice for himself and the people, but the Rigveda<ref name=fx15_ve2_950/> itself shows cases, like those of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' and '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]''' illustrating forcibly the power of the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], though at the same time the right of the noble to act as [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] is seen in the case of '''[[देवापि आर्ष्टिषेण|Devāpi Ārṣṭiṣeṇa]].'''<ref name=fx16_ve2_950/> The Brahmins saw their opportunity, through the Purohitaship, of gaining practical power during the confusion and difficulties of the wars of invasion, and secured it, though only after many struggles, the traces of which are seen in the Epic tradition.<ref name=fx17_ve2_950/> The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx18_ve2_950/> also preserves relics of these conflicts in its narration of the ruin of the '''Sṛñjayas''' because of oppressing Brahmins, and besides other hymns of the Atharvaveda (viiixii), the [[शतरुद्रिय|Śatarudriya]] litany of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx19_ve2_950/> reflects the period of storm and stress when the aboriginal population was  still seething with discontent, and Rudra was worshipped as the patron god of all sorts of evil doers.<ref name=fx20_ve2_950/><br><br>This version of the development of caste has received a good deal of acceptance in its main outlines, and it may almost be regarded as the recognized version.<ref name=fx21_ve2_950/> It has, however, always been opposed by some scholars, such as Haug,<ref name=fx22_ve2_950/> Kern,<ref name=fx23_ve2_950/> Ludwig,<ref name=fx24_ve2_950/> and more recently by Oldenberg<ref name=fx25_ve2_950/> and by Geldner.<ref name=fx26_ve2_950/> The matter may be to some extent simplified by recognizing at once that the caste system is one that has progressively developed, and that it is not legitimate to see in the Rigveda the full caste system even of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]; but at the same time it is difficult to doubt that the system was already well on its way to general acceptance. The argument from the nonbrahminical character of the '''Vrātyas''' of the Indus and Panjab loses its force when it is remembered that there is much evidence in favour of placing the composition of the bulk of the Rigveda, especially the books<ref name=fx27_ve2_950/> in which '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' appears with [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] and [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]], in the east, the later '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]],''' a view supported by Pischel,<ref name=fx28_ve2_950/> Geldner,<ref name=fx29_ve2_950/> Hopkins,<ref name=fx30_ve2_950/> and Macdonell.<ref name=fx31_ve2_950/> Nor is it possible to maintain that [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] in the Rigveda merely means a ‘poet’ or ‘sage.’ It is admitted by Muir that in some passages it must mean a hereditary profession; in fact, there is not a single passage in which it occurs where the sense of ‘priest’ is not allowable, since the priest was of course the singer. Moreover, there are traces in the Rigveda of the threefold<ref name=fx32_ve2_950/> or fourfold<ref name=fx33_ve2_950/> division of the people  into ''brahma, kṣatram,'' and ''viśaḥ,'' or into the three classes and the servile population. Nor even in respect to the later period, any more than to the Rigveda, is the view correct that regards the Vaiśyas as not taking part in war. The Rigveda evidently<ref name=fx34_ve2_950/> knows of no restriction of war to a nobility and its retainers, but the late Atharvaveda<ref name=fx35_ve2_950/> equally classes the folk with the ''bala,'' ‘power,’ representing the [[विश्|Viś]] as associated with the '''[[सभा|Sabhā]], [[सम्इति|Samiti]],''' and '''[[सेना|Senā]],''' the assemblies of the people and the armed host. Zimmer<ref name=fx36_ve2_950/> explains these references as due to tradition only; but this is hardly a legitimate argument, resting, as it does, on the false assumption that only a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] can fight. But it is (see '''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]''') very doubtful whether [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] means anything more than a member of the nobility, though later, in the Epic, it included the retainers of the nobility, who increased in numbers with the growth of military monarchies, and though later the ordinary people did not necessarily take part in wars, an abstention that is, however, much exaggerated if it is treated as an absolute one. The Kṣatriyas were no doubt a hereditary body; monarchy was already hereditary (see '''[[राजन्|Rājan]]'''), and it is admitted that the Śūdras were a separate body: thus all the elements of the caste system were already in existence. The [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], indeed, was a person of great importance, but it is clear, as Oldenberg<ref name=fx37_ve2_950/> urges, that he was not the creator of the power of the priesthood, but owed his position, and the influence he could in consequence exert, to the fact that the sacrifice required for its proper performance the aid of a hereditary priest in whose possession was the traditional sacred knowledge.<br><br>Nor can any argument for the non-existence of the caste system be derived from cases like that of '''Devāpi.''' For, in the first place, the Upaniṣads show kings in the exercise of the priestly functions of learning and teaching, and the Upaniṣads are certainly contemporaneous with an elaborated caste system. In the second place the Rigvedic evidence is very weak, for Devāpi, who certainly acts as [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], is not stated in the  Rigveda to be a prince at all, though [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx38_ve2_950/> calls him a [[कौरव्य|Kauravya]]; the hymns attributed to kings and others cannot be vindicated for them by certain evidence, though here, again, the Brāhmaṇas do not scruple to recognize Rājanyarṣis, or ‘royal sages’; and the famous [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] shows in the Rigveda no sign of the royal character which the Brāhmaṇas insist on fastening on him in the shape of royal descent in the line of '''[[जह्नु|Jahnu]].'''<ref name=fx39_ve2_950/><br><br>''(b) Caste in the later Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas.''--The relation between the later and the earlier periods of the Vedic history of caste must probably be regarded in the main as the hardening of a system already formed by the time of the Rigveda.<br><br>1. ''The Names of the Castes.''--The most regular names are [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], [[राजन्य|Rājanya]], [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]], and [[शूद्र|Śūdra]],<ref name=fx40_ve2_950/> or later [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]], [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]], and [[शूद्र|Śūdra]].<ref name=fx41_ve2_950/> There are many other variants: [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], [[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]], Śūdrāryau;<ref name=fx42_ve2_950/> [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], [[राजन्य|Rājanya]], [[शूद्र|Śūdra]], [[आर्य|Ārya]];<ref name=fx43_ve2_950/> [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], [[राजन्य|Rājanya]], [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]], [[शूद्र|Śūdra]];<ref name=fx44_ve2_950/> [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], [[राजन्|Rājan]], Viśya, [[शूद्र|Śūdra]];<ref name=fx45_ve2_950/> Deva, [[राजन्|Rājan]], [[शूद्र|Śūdra]], [[आर्य|Ārya]];<ref name=fx46_ve2_950/> and [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], [[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]], [[विश्|Viś]], and [[शूद्र|Śūdra]].<ref name=fx47_ve2_950/> In other cases the fourth class is represented by a special member: [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]], [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]], and [[चाण्डाल|Cāṇḍāla]].<ref name=fx48_ve2_950/> Often only the three upper classes are mentioned, as [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], [[राजन्य|Rājanya]], [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]];<ref name=fx49_ve2_950/> [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], Kṣatram, [[विश्|Viś]],<ref name=fx50_ve2_950/>  etc.<ref name=fx51_ve2_950/> Three castes--[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], [[राजन्|Rājan]], [[शूद्र|Śūdra]]--are mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx52_ve2_950/> and two castes are repeatedly mentioned together, either [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] and [[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]], or [[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]] and [[विश्|Viś]].<ref name=fx53_ve2_950/><br><br>2. ''The Relation of the Castes.''--The ritual literature is full of minute differences respecting the castes. Thus, for example, the Śatapatha prescribes different sizes of funeral mounds for the four castes,<ref name=fx54_ve2_950/> Different modes of address are laid down for the four castes,<ref name=fx55_ve2_950/> as ''ehi,'' ‘approach’; ''āgaccha,'' ‘come’; ''ādrava,'' ‘run up’; ''ādhāva,'' ‘hasten up,’ which differ in degrees of politeness. The representatives of the four castes are dedicated at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) to different deities.<ref name=fx56_ve2_950/> The Sūtras have many similar rules.<ref name=fx57_ve2_950/><br><br>But the three upper castes in some respects differ markedly from the fourth, the Śūdras. The latter are in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx58_ve2_950/> declared not fit to be addressed by a Dīkṣita, ‘consecrated person,’ and no [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] is to milk the cow whose milk is to be used for the Agnihotra<ref name=fx59_ve2_950/> (‘fire-oblation’). On the other hand, in certain passages, the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] is given a place in the Soma sacrifice,<ref name=fx60_ve2_950/> and in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx61_ve2_950/> there are given formulæ for the placing of the sacrificial fire not only for the three upper castes, but also for the '''[[रथकार|Rathakāra]],'''  ‘chariot-maker.’ Again, in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx62_ve2_950/> the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] is opposed as ‘eater of the oblation’ to the members of the other three castes.<br><br>The characteristics of the several castes are given under '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]''' and '''[[राजन्|Rājan]], [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]], [[शूद्र|Śūdra]]:''' they may be briefly summed up as follows: The [[विश्|Viś]] forms the basis of the state on which the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] and [[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]] rest;<ref name=fx63_ve2_950/> the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] and [[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]] are superior to the [[विश्|Viś]];<ref name=fx64_ve2_950/> while all three classes are superior to the Śūdras. The real power of the state rested with the king and his nobles, with their retainers, who may be deemed the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] element. Engaged in the business of the protection of the country, its administration, the decision of legal cases, and in war, the nobles subsisted, no doubt, on the revenues in kind levied from the people, the king granting to them villages (see '''[[ग्राम|Grāma]]''') for their maintenance, while some of them, no doubt, had lands of their own cultivated for them by slaves or by tenants. The states were seemingly small:<ref name=fx65_ve2_950/> there are no clear signs of any really large kingdoms, despite the mention of '''Mahārājas.''' The people, engaged in agriculture, pastoral pursuits, and trade ('''[[वणिज्|Vaṇij]]'''), paid tribute to the king and nobles for the protection afforded them. That, as BadenPowell suggests,<ref name=fx66_ve2_950/> they were not themselves agriculturists is probably erroneous; some might be landowners on a large scale, and draw their revenues from [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] tenants, or even Āryan tenants, but that the people as a whole were in this  position is extremely unlikely.<ref name=fx67_ve2_950/> In war the people shared the conflicts of the nobles, for there was not yet any absolute separation of the functions of the several classes. The priests may be divided into two classes--the Purohitas of the kings, who guided their employers by their counsel, and were in a position to acquire great influence in the state, as it is evident they actually did, and the ordinary priests who led quiet lives, except when they were engaged on some great festival of a king or a wealthy noble.<ref name=fx68_ve2_950/><br><br>The relations and functions of the castes are well summed up in a passage of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx69_ve2_950/> which treats of them as opposed to the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]. The [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] is a receiver of gifts (''ā-dāyī''), a drinker of Soma (''ā-pāyī''), a seeker of food (''āvasāyī''),<ref name=fx70_ve2_950/> and liable to removal at will (''yathākāma-prayāpyaḥ'').<ref name=fx71_ve2_950/> The [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] is tributary to another (''anyasya balikṛt''), to be lived on by another (''anyasyādyaḥ''), and to be oppressed at will (''yathākāma-jyeyaḥ'').<ref name=fx72_ve2_950/> The [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] is the servant of another (''anyasya preṣyaḥ''), to be expelled at will (''kāmotthāpyaḥ''), and to be slain  at pleasure (''yathākāma-vadhyaḥ'').<ref name=fx73_ve2_950/> The descriptions seem calculated to show the relation of each of the castes to the [[राजन्य|Rājanya]]. Even the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] he can control, whilst the [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] is his inferior and tributary, whom he can remove without cause from his land,<ref name=fx74_ve2_950/> but who is still free, and whom he cannot maim or slay without due process. The [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] has no rights of property or life against the noble, especially the king.<br><br>The passage is a late one, and the high place of the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] is to some extent accounted for by this fact. It is clear that in the course of time the [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] fell more and more in position with the hardening of the divisions of caste. Weber<ref name=fx75_ve2_950/> shows reason for believing that the [[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]] sacrifice, a festival of which a chariot race forms an integral part,<ref name=fx76_ve2_950/> was, as the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx77_ve2_950/> says, once a sacrifice for a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]], as well as for a priest or king. But the king, too, had to suffer diminution of his influence at the hands of the priest: the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] texts<ref name=fx78_ve2_950/> show that the [[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]] was originally a lesser sacrifice which, in the case of a king, was followed by the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]], or consecration of him as an overlord of lesser kings, and in that of the Brahmin by the [[बृहस्पतिसव|Bṛhaspatisava]], a festival celebrated on his appointment as a royal [[पुरोहित|Purohita]]. But the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx79_ve2_950/> exalts the [[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]], in which a priest could be the sacrificer, over the [[राजसूय|Rājasūya]], from which he was excluded, and identifies it with the [[बृहस्पतिसव|Bṛhaspatisava]], a clear piece of juggling in the interests of the priestly pretentions. But we must not overestimate the value of such passages, or the exaltation of the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] in the later books of the Śatapatha  and [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Brāhmaṇas as evidence of a real growth in the priestly power: these books represent the views of the priests of what their own powers should be, and to some extent were in the [[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]]. Another side of the picture is presented in the Pāli literature,<ref name=fx80_ve2_950/> which, belonging to a later period than the Vedic, undoubtedly underestimates the position of the priests; while the Epic,<ref name=fx81_ve2_950/> more nearly contemporaneous with the later Vedic period, displays, despite all priestly redaction, the temporal superiority of the nobility in clear light.<br><br>Although clear distinctions were made between the different castes, there is little trace in Vedic literature of one of the leading characteristics of the later system, the impurity communicated by the touch or contact of the inferior castes,<ref name=fx82_ve2_950/> which is seen both directly in the purification rendered necessary in case of contact with a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]], and indirectly in the prohibition of eating in company with men of lower caste.<ref name=fx83_ve2_950/> It is true that prohibition of eating in company with others does appear,<ref name=fx84_ve2_950/> but not in connexion with caste: its purpose is to preserve the peculiar sanctity of those who perform a certain rite or believe in a certain doctrine; for persons who eat of the same food together, according to primitive thought, acquire the same characteristics and enter into a sacramental communion. But Vedic literature does not yet show that to take food from an inferior caste was forbidden as destroying  purity.<ref name=fx85_ve2_950/> Nor, of course, has the caste system developed the constitution with a head, a council, and common festivals which the modern caste has; for such an organization is not found even in the Epic or in the Pāli literature.<ref name=fx86_ve2_950/> The Vedic characteristics of caste are heredity, pursuit of a common occupation, and restriction on intermarriage.<br><br>3. ''Restrictions on Intermarriage.''--Arrian, in his ''Indica,''<ref name=fx87_ve2_950/> probably on the authority of Megasthenes, makes the prohibition of marriage between , no doubt ‘castes,’ a characteristic of Indian life. The evidence of Pāli literature<ref name=fx88_ve2_950/> is in favour of this view, though it shows that a king could marry whom he wished, and could make his son by that wife the heir appearent. But it equally shows that there were others who held that not the father's but the mother's rank determined the social standing of the son. Though Manu<ref name=fx89_ve2_950/> recognizes the possibility of marriage with the next lower caste as producing legitimate children, still he condemns the marriage of an Āryan with a woman of lower caste. The Pāraskara [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx90_ve2_950/> allows the marriage of a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] with a wife of his own caste or of the lower caste, of a Brahmin with a wife of his own caste or of the two lower classes, and of a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] with a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] wife only. But it quotes the opinion of others that all of them can marry a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] wife, while other authorities condemn the marriage with a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] wife in certain circumstances, which implies that in other cases it might be justified.<ref name=fx91_ve2_950/> The earlier  literature bears out this impression: much stress is laid on descent from a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], and on purity of descent;<ref name=fx92_ve2_950/> but there is other evidence for the view that even a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] need not be of pure lineage. '''[[कवष|Kavaṣa]]''' [[ऐलूष|Ailūṣa]] is taunted with being the son of a Dāsī, ‘slave woman,’<ref name=fx93_ve2_950/> and '''[[वत्स|Vatsa]]''' was accused of being a Śūdrā's son, but established his purity by walking unhurt through the flames of a fire ordeal.<ref name=fx94_ve2_950/> He who is learned (''śuśruvān'') is said to be a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], descended from a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] (''ārṣeya''), in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā;<ref name=fx95_ve2_950/> and '''[[सत्यकाम|Satyakāma]],''' son of '''[[जबाला|Jabālā]],''' was accepted as a pupil by '''[[हारिद्रुमत|Hāridrumata]]''' [[गौतम|Gautama]], though he could not name his father.<ref name=fx96_ve2_950/> The [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx97_ve2_950/> says that knowledge is all-important, not descent. But all this merely goes to show that there was a measure of laxity in the hereditary character of caste, not that it was not based on heredity. The [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx98_ve2_950/> recognize the illicit union of [[आर्य|Ārya]] and [[शूद्रा|Śūdrā]], and ''vice versa:'' it is not unlikely that if illicit unions took place, legal marriage was quite possible. The [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx99_ve2_950/> indeed, recognizes such a case in that of '''[[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]],''' son of the slave girl Uśij, if we may adopt the description of Uśij given in the Bṛhaddevatā.<ref name=fx100_ve2_950/><br><br>In a hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx101_ve2_950/> extreme claims are put  forward for the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], who alone is a true husband and the real husband, even if the woman has had others, a [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] or a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]: a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] husband is not mentioned, probably on purpose.<ref name=fx102_ve2_950/> The marriage of Brāhmaṇas with [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] women is illustrated by the cases of '''[[सुकन्या|Sukanyā]],''' daughter of king '''[[शर्यात|Śaryāta]],''' who married '''[[च्यवन|Cyavana]],'''<ref name=fx103_ve2_950/> and of '''Rathavīti's''' daughter, who married '''[[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]].'''<ref name=fx104_ve2_950/><br><br>4. ''Occupation and Caste.''--The Greek authorities<ref name=fx105_ve2_950/> and the evidence of the Jātakas<ref name=fx106_ve2_950/> concur in showing it to have been the general rule that each caste was confined to its own occupations, but that the Brāhmaṇas did engage in many professions beside that of simple priest, while all castes gave members to the Śramaṇas, or homeless ascetics. The Jātakas<ref name=fx107_ve2_950/> recognize the Brahmins as engaged in all sorts of occupations, as merchants, traders, agriculturists, and so forth. Matters are somewhat simpler in Vedic literature, where the Brāhmaṇas and Kṣatriyas appear as practically confined to their own professions of sacrifice and military or administrative functions. Ludwig<ref name=fx108_ve2_950/> sees in '''[[दीर्घश्रवस्|Dīrghaśravas]]''' in the Rigveda<ref name=fx109_ve2_950/> a Brahmin reduced by indigence to acting as a merchant, as allowed even later by the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] literature; but this is not certain, though it is perfectly possible. More interesting is the question how far the Kṣatriyas practised the duties of priests; the evidence here is conflicting. The best known case is, of course, that of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]].''' In the Rigveda he appears merely as a priest who is attached to the court of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' king of the '''Tṛtsus;''' but in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx110_ve2_950/> he is called a king, a descendant of '''[[जह्नु|Jahnu]],''' and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx111_ve2_950/> refers to '''Śunaḥśepa's'''  succeeding, through his adoption by [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]], to the divine lore (''[[दैव|daiva]] veda'') of the '''Gāthins''' and the lordship of the Jahnus. That in fact this tradition is correct seems most improbable, but it serves at least to illustrate the existence of seers of royal origin. Such figures appear more than once in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx112_ve2_950/> which knows the technical terms '''[[राजन्यर्षि|Rājanyarṣi]]''' and '''[[देवराजन्|Devarājan]]''' corresponding to the later Rājarṣi, ‘royal sage.’ The Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx113_ve2_950/> says of one who knows a certain doctrine, ‘being a king he becomes a seer’ (''rājā sann ṛṣir bhavati''), and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx114_ve2_950/> applies the term [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] to a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]. Again, it is argued that '''[[देवापि आर्ष्टिषेण|Devāpi Ārṣṭiṣeṇa]],''' who acted as [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], according to the Rigveda,<ref name=fx115_ve2_950/> for '''Śantanu,''' was a prince, as [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx116_ve2_950/> says or implies he was.<ref name=fx117_ve2_950/> But this assumption seems to be only an error of Yāska's. Since nothing in the Rigveda alludes to any relationship, it is impossible to accept Sieg's view<ref name=fx118_ve2_950/> that the Rigveda recognizes the two as brothers, but presents the fact of a prince acting the part of [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] as unusual and requiring explanation. The principle, however, thus accepted by Sieg as to princes in the Rigveda seems sound enough. Again, Muir<ref name=fx119_ve2_950/> has argued that Hindu tradition, as shown in Sāyaṇa,<ref name=fx120_ve2_950/> regards many hymns of the Rigveda as composed by royal personages, but he admits that in many cases the ascription is wrong; it may be added that in the case of '''Pṛthī [[वैन्य|Vainya]],''' where the hymn<ref name=fx121_ve2_950/> ascribed to him seems to be his, it is not shown in the hymn itself that he is other than a seer; the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx122_ve2_950/> calls him a king, but that is probably of no more value than the later tradition as to [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]. The case of '''Viśvantara'''  and the '''Śyāparṇas''' mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx123_ve2_950/> has been cited<ref name=fx124_ve2_950/> as that of a king sacrificing without priestly aid, but the interpretation is quite uncertain, while the parallel of the '''Kaśyapas, Asitamṛgas,''' and '''Bhūtavīras''' mentioned in the course of the narrative renders it highly probable that the king had other priests to carry out the sacrifice.<br><br>Somewhat different are a series of other cases found in the Upaniṣads, where the Brahma doctrine is ascribed to royal persons. Thus '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' is said in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx125_ve2_950/> to have become a [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]]; '''[[अजातशत्रु|Ajātaśatru]]''' taught '''[[गार्ग्य|Gārgya]] [[बालाकि|Bālāki]];'''<ref name=fx126_ve2_950/> '''[[प्रवाहण जैवलि|Pravāhaṇa Jaivali]]''' instructed '''[[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]] [[आरुणेय|Āruṇeya]],'''<ref name=fx127_ve2_950/> as well as '''[[शिलक शालावत्य|Śilaka Śālāvatya]]'''<ref name=fx128_ve2_950/> and '''[[चैकितायन|Caikitāyana]] [[दाल्भ्य|Dālbhya]];''' and '''[[अश्वपति|Aśvapati]] [[कैकेय|Kaikeya]]''' taught Brahmins.<ref name=fx129_ve2_950/> It has been deduced<ref name=fx130_ve2_950/> from such passages that the Brahma doctrine was a product of the Kṣatriyas. This conclusion is, however, entirely doubtful,<ref name=fx131_ve2_950/> for kings were naturally willing to be flattered by the ascription to them of philosophic activity, and elsewhere<ref name=fx132_ve2_950/> the opinion of a [[राजन्य|Rājanya]] is treated with contempt.<br><br>It is probably a fair deduction that the royal caste did not much concern itself with the sacred lore of the priests, though it is not unlikely that individual exceptions occurred. But that warriors became priests, that an actual change of caste took place, is quite unproved by a single genuine example. That it was impossible we cannot say, but it seems not to have taken place. To be distinguished from a caste change, as Fick<ref name=fx133_ve2_950/> points out, is the fact that a member of any caste could, in the later period at least, become a [[श्रमण|Śramaṇa]], as is recorded in effect  of many kings in the Epic.<ref name=fx134_ve2_950/> Whether the practice is Vedic is not clear: [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx135_ve2_950/> records it of Devāpi, but this is not evidence for times much anterior to the rise of Buddhism.<br><br>On the other hand, the Brahmins, or at least the Purohitas, accompanied the princes in battle, and probably, like the mediæval clergy, were not unprepared to fight,<ref name=fx136_ve2_950/> as [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] and [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] seem to have done, and as priests do even in the Epic from time to time.<ref name=fx137_ve2_950/> But a priest cannot be said to change caste by acting in this way.<br><br>More generally the possibility of the occurrence of change of caste may be seen in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx138_ve2_950/> where '''[[श्यापर्ण सायकायन|Śyāparṇa Sāyakāyana]]''' is represented as speaking of his offspring as if they could have become the nobles, priests, and commons of the Śalvas; and in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx139_ve2_950/> where Viśvantara is told that if the wrong offering were made his children would be of the three other castes. A drunken [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] of the Rigveda<ref name=fx140_ve2_950/> talks as if he could be converted into a king. On the other hand, certain kings, such as '''[[पर आट्णार|Para Āṭṇāra]],''' are spoken of as performers of Sattras, ‘sacrificial sessions.’<ref name=fx141_ve2_950/> As evidence for caste exchange all this amounts to little; later a Brahmin might become a king, while the [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the Rigveda is represented as speaking in a state of intoxication; the great kings could be called sacrificers if, for the nonce, they were consecrated (''dīkṣita''), and so temporarily became Brahmins.<ref name=fx142_ve2_950/> The hypothetical passages, too, do not help much. It would be unwise to deny the possibility of caste exchange, but it is not clearly indicated by any record. Even cases like that of [[सत्यकाम|Satyakāma]] [[जाबाल|Jābāla]] do not go far; for ''ex hypothesi'' that teacher  did not know who his father was, and the latter could quite well have been a Brahmin.<br><br>It may therefore be held that the priests and the nobles practised hereditary occupations, and that either class was a closed body into which a man must be born. These two Varṇas may thus be fairly regarded as castes. The Vaiśyas offer more difficulty, for they practised a great variety of occupations (see '''[[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]'''). Fick<ref name=fx143_ve2_950/> concludes that there is no exact sense in which they can be called a caste, since, in the Buddhist literature, they were divided into various groups, which themselves practised endogamy such as the ''gahapatis,'' or smaller landowners, the ''setthis,'' or large merchants and members of the various guilds, while there are clear traces<ref name=fx144_ve2_950/> in the legal textbooks of a view that [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] and [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] stand opposed to all the other members of the community. But we need hardly accept this view for Vedic times, when the [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]], the ordinary freeman of the tribe, formed a class or caste in all probability, which was severed by its free status from the Śūdras, and which was severed by its lack of priestly or noble blood from the two higher classes in the state. It is probably legitimate to hold that any [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] could marry any member of the caste, and that the later divisions within the category of Vaiśyas are growths of divisions parallel with the original process by which priest and noble had grown into separate entities. The process can be seen to day when new tribes fall under the caste system: each class tries to elevate itself in the social scale by refusing to intermarry with inferior classes on equal terms--hypergamy is often allowed--and so those Vaiśyas who acquired wealth in trade ('''[[श्रेष्ठिन्|Śreṣṭhin]]''') or agriculture (the Pāli Gahapatis) would become distinct, as sub-castes, from the ordinary Vaiśyas. But it is not legitimate to regard [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] as a theoretic caste; rather it is an old caste which is in process of dividing into innumerable sub-castes under influences of occupation, religion, or geographical situation.<br><br>Fick<ref name=fx145_ve2_950/> denies also that the Śūdras ever formed a single  caste: he regards the term as covering the numerous inferior races and tribes defeated by the Āryan invaders, but originally as denoting only one special tribe. It is reasonable to suppose that [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] was the name given by the Vedic Indians to the nations opposing them, and that these ranked as slaves beside the three castes--nobles, priests, and people--just as in the Anglo-Saxon and early German constitution beside the priests, the ''nobiles'' or eorls, and the ''ingenui,'' ordinary freemen or ceorls, there was a distinct class of slaves proper; the use of a generic expression to cover them seems natural, whatever its origin (see '''[[शूद्र|Śūdra]]'''). In the Āryan view a marriage of Śūdras could hardly be regulated by rules; any [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] could wed another, if such a marriage could be called a marriage at all, for a slave cannot in early law be deemed to be capable of marriage proper. But what applied in the early Vedic period became no doubt less and less applicable later when many aboriginal tribes and princes must have come into the Āryan community by peaceful means, or by conquest, without loss of personal liberty, and when the term [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] would cover many sorts of people who were not really slaves, but were freemen of a humble character occupied in such functions as supplying the numerous needs of the village, like the '''Caṇḍālas,''' or tribes living under Āryan control, or independent, such as the '''Niṣādas.'''<br><br>But it is also probable that the Śūdras came to include men of Āryan race, and that the Vedic period saw the degradation of Āryans to a lower social status. This seems, at any rate, to have been the case with the '''Rathakāras.''' In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx146_ve2_950/> the [[रथकार|Rathakāra]] is placed as a special class along with the Brāhmaṇas, Rājanyas, and Vaiśyas: this can hardly be interpreted except to mean that the Rathakāras were not included in the Āryan classes, though it is just possible that only a subdivision of the Vaiśyas is meant. There is other evidence<ref name=fx147_ve2_950/> that the Rathakāras were regarded as Śūdras. But in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx148_ve2_950/> the Rathakāras and the '''Karmāras''' appear in a position of importance in connexion with the  selection of the king; these two classes are also referred to in an honourable way in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā;<ref name=fx149_ve2_950/> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx150_ve2_950/> too, the [[रथकार|Rathakāra]] is mentioned as a a person of high standing. It is impossible to accept the view suggested by Fick<ref name=fx151_ve2_950/> that these classes were originally nonĀryan; we must recognize that the Rathakāras, in early Vedic times esteemed for their skill, later became degraded because of the growth of the feeling that manual labour was not dignified. The development of this idea was a departure from the Āryan conception; it is not unnatural, however undesirable, and has a faint parallel in the class distinctions of modern Europe. Similarly, the [[कर्मार|Karmāra]], the '''[[तक्षन्|Takṣan]],'''<ref name=fx152_ve2_950/> the Carmamna, or ‘tanner,’ the weaver and others, quite dignified occupations in the Rigveda, are reckoned as Śūdras in the Pāli texts.<ref name=fx153_ve2_950/><br><br>The later theory, which appears fully developed in the [[धर्म|Dharma]] Sūtras,<ref name=fx154_ve2_950/> deduces the several castes other than the original four from the intermarriage of the several castes. This theory has no justification in the early Vedic literature. In some cases it is obviously wrong; for example, the '''[[सूत|Sūta]]''' is said to be a caste of this kind, whereas it is perfectly clear that if the Sūtas did form a caste, it was one ultimately due to occupation. But there is no evidence at all that the Sūtas, Grāmaṇīs, and other members of occupations were real castes in the sense that they were endogamic in the early Vedic period. All that we can say is that there was a steady progress by which caste after caste was formed, occupation being an important determining feature, just as in modern times there are castes bearing names like Gopāla (‘cowherd’) [[कैवर्त|Kaivarta]] or Dhīvara (‘fisherman’), and [[वणिज्|Vaṇij]] (‘merchant’).<ref name=fx155_ve2_950/> <br><br>Fick<ref name=fx156_ve2_950/> finds in the Jātakas mention of a number of occupations whose members did not form part of any caste at all, such as the attendants on the court, the actors and dancers who went from village to village, and the wild tribes that lived in the mountains, fishermen, hunters, and so on. In Vedic times these people presumably fell under the conception of [[शूद्र|Śūdra]], and may have included the '''[[पर्णक|Parṇaka]], [[पौल्कस|Paulkasa]], [[बैन्द|Bainda]],''' who are mentioned with many others in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’). The slaves also, whom Fick<ref name=fx157_ve2_950/> includes in the same category, were certainly included in the term [[शूद्र|Śūdra]].<br><br>5. ''Origin of the Castes.''--The question of the origin of the castes presents some difficulty. The ultimate cause of the extreme rigidity of the caste system, as compared with the features of any other Āryan society, must probably be sought in the sharp distinction drawn from the beginning between the Āryan and the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]]. The contrast which the Vedic Indians felt as existing between themselves and the conquered population, and which probably rested originally on the difference of colour between the upper and the lower classes, tended to accentuate the natural distinctions of birth, occupation, and locality which normally existed among the Āryan Indians, but which among other Āryan peoples never developed into a caste system like that of India. The doctrine of hypergamy which marks the practical working of the caste system, seems clearly to point to the feeling that the Āryan could marry the [[शूद्रा|Śūdrā]], but not the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] the Āryā. This distinction probably lies at the back of all other divisions: its force may be illustrated by the peculiar state of feeling as to mixed marriages, for example, in the Southern States of America and in South Africa, or even in India itself, between the new invaders from Europe and the mingled population which now peoples the country. Marriages between persons of the white and the dark race are disapproved in principle, but varying degrees of condemnation attach to (1) the marriage of a man of the white race with a woman of the dark race;  (2) an informal connexion between these two; (3) a marriage between a woman of the white race and a man of the dark race; and (4) an informal connexion between these two. Each category, on the whole, is subject to more severe reprobation than the preceding one. This race element, it would seem, is what has converted social divisions into castes. There appears, then, to be a large element of truth in the theory, best represented by Risley,<ref name=fx158_ve2_950/> which explains caste in the main as a matter of blood, and which holds that the higher the caste is, the greater is the proportion of Āryan blood.<br><br>The chief rival theory is undoubtedly that of Senart,<ref name=fx159_ve2_950/> which places the greatest stress on the Āryan constitution of the family. According to Senart the Āryan people practised in affairs of marriage both a rule of exogamy, and one of endogamy. A man must marry a woman of equal birth, but not one of the same ''gens,'' according to Roman law as interpreted by Senart and Kovalevsky;<ref name=fx160_ve2_950/> and an Athenian must marry an Athenian woman, but not one of the same . In India these rules are reproduced in the form that one must not marry within the '''[[गोत्र|Gotra]],''' but not without the caste. The theory, though attractively developed, is not convincing; the Latin and Greek parallels are not even probably accurate;<ref name=fx161_ve2_950/> and in India the rule forbidding marriage within the [[गोत्र|Gotra]] is one which grows; in strictness as the evidence grows later in date.<ref name=fx162_ve2_950/><br><br>On the other hand, it is not necessary to deny that the development of caste may have been helped by the family traditions of some ''gentes,'' or , or Gotras. The Patricians of Rome for a long time declined intermarriage with the plebeians; the Athenian Eupatridai seem to have kept their pure from contamination by union with lower blood; and there may well have been noble families among the Vedic Indians who intermarried only among themselves. The  Germans known to Tacitus<ref name=fx163_ve2_950/> were divided into ''nobiles'' and ''ingenui,'' and the Anglo-Saxons into eorls and ceorls, noble and non-noble freemen.<ref name=fx164_ve2_950/> The origin of nobility need not be sought in the Vedic period proper, for it may already have existed. It may have been due to the fact that the king, whom we must regard as originally elected by the people, was as king often in close relation with, or regarded as an incarnation of, the deity;<ref name=fx165_ve2_950/> and that hereditary kingship would tend to increase the tradition of especially sacred blood: thus the royal family and its offshoots would be anxious to maintain the purity of their blood. In India, beside the sanctity of the king, there was the sanctity of the priest. Here we have in the family exclusiveness of king and nobles, and the similar exclusiveness of a priesthood which was not celibate, influences that make for caste, especially when accompanying the deep opposition between the general folk and the servile aborigines.<br><br>Caste, once created, naturally developed in different directions. Nesfield<ref name=fx166_ve2_950/> was inclined to see in occupation the one ground of caste. It is hardly necessary seriously to criticize this view considered as an ultimate explanation of caste, but it is perfectly certain that gilds of workers tend to become castes. The carpenters ('''[[तक्षन्|Takṣan]]'''), the chariot-makers ('''[[रथकार|Rathakāra]]'''), the fishermen ('''[[धैवर|Dhaivara]]''') and others are clearly of the type of caste, and the number extends itself as time goes on. But this is not to say that caste is founded on occupation pure and simple in its first origin, or that mere difference of occupation would have produced the system of caste without the interposition of the fundamental difference between Āryan and [[दास|Dāsa]] or [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] blood and colour. This difference rendered increasingly important what the history of the Āryan peoples shows us to be declining, the distinction between the noble and the non-noble  freemen, a distinction not of course ultimate, but one which seems to have been developed in the Āryan people before the separation of its various branches.<br><br>It is well known that the Iranian polity presents a division of classes comparable in some respects<ref name=fx167_ve2_950/> with the Indian polity. The priests (Atharvas) and warriors (Rathaesthas) are unmistakably parallel, and the two lower classes seem to correspond closely to the Pāli Gahapatis, and perhaps to the Śūdras.<ref name=fx168_ve2_950/> But they are certainly not castes in the Indian sense of the word. There is no probability in the view of Senart<ref name=fx169_ve2_950/> or of Risley<ref name=fx170_ve2_950/> that the names of the old classes were later superimposed artificially on a system of castes that were different from them in origin. We cannot say that the castes existed before the classes, and that the classes were borrowed by India from Iran, as Risley maintains, ignoring the early [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] evidence for the four Varṇas, and treating the transfer as late. Nor can we say with Senart that the castes and classes are of independent origin. If there had been no [[वर्ण|Varṇa]], caste might never have arisen; both colour and class occupation are needed for a plausible account of the rise of caste.<ref name=fx171_ve2_950/> <br>

वर्त
<u>'''Varta.'''</u> See '''[[वर्त्र|Vartra]].'''<br>

वर्तनि
<u>'''Vartani'''</u> as a part of a chariot seems to denote the ‘felly’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_952/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_952/><br>

वर्तिका
<u>'''Vartikā,'''</u> a ‘quail,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_953/> as having been saved by the Aśvins from a wolf's jaws. It is also included in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the Yajurvedas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_953/><br>

वर्त्र
<u>'''Vartra'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_954/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_954/> denote the ‘dam’ of a tank. In the former passage the commentator and some manuscripts have [[वर्त|Varta]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_954/><br>

वर्ध्र
<u>'''Vardhra'''</u> denotes a ‘thong’ or ‘strap’ with which a woven couch is fastened. It is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_955/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_955/><br>

वर्मन्
<u>'''Varman'''</u> denotes ‘body armour,’ ‘coat of mail,’ ‘corselet,’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_956/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_956/> Of what material it was made is  uncertain; there are references to sewing (''syūta'')<ref name=fx3_ve2_956/> which may be reckoned in favour of the use of linen corselets such as those recorded by Herodotus,<ref name=fx4_ve2_956/> but there is a later reference<ref name=fx5_ve2_956/> to corselets of '''Ayas, Loha,''' or '''[[रजत|Rajata]],''' on which it is doubtful whether much stress can be laid. They may, however, have been either of metal or of leather covered with metal.<br>

वर्ष
<u>'''Varṣa'''</u> denotes primarily ‘rain,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_957/> then ‘rainy season’<ref name=fx2_ve2_957/> and ‘year.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_957/><br>

वलग
<u>'''Valaga'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_958/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_958/> seems to denote a ‘secret spell.’<br>

वल्क
<u>'''Valka'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_959/> denotes ‘bark’ of a tree.<br>

वल्मीक
<u>'''Valmīka'''</u> denotes an ‘ant-hill’ in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_960/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_960/><br>

वल्श
<u>'''Valśa'''</u> denotes ‘twig,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_961/> usually in the compounds ''śata-[[वल्श|valśa]],'' ‘having a hundred twigs,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_961/> or ''sahasra-[[वल्श|valśa]],'' ‘having a thousand twigs,’<ref name=fx3_ve2_961/> which is applied metaphorically of ‘offspring.’<ref name=fx4_ve2_961/> <br>

वश अश्व्य
<u>'''1. Vaśa Aśvya'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_962/> of a protégé of the Aśvins. He is also mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_962/> as having received bounty from '''[[पृथुश्रवस्|Pṛthuśravas]] [[कानीत|Kānīta]].''' He is the reputed author of a Rigvedic hymn,<ref name=fx3_ve2_962/> which is repeatedly referred to by his name [[वश|Vaśa]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_962/> ''Cf.'' also '''[[व्य्अश्व|Vyaśva]].'''<br>

वश
<u>'''2. Vaśa,'''</u> plur., is the name of a tribe mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_963/> as being in '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]]''' along with the '''Kurus,''' the '''Pañcālas,''' and the '''Uśīnaras.''' They are also connected with the '''Matsyas''' according to the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_963/> The Vaśas and Uśīnaras are spoken of as united in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]:<ref name=fx3_ve2_963/> the names<ref name=fx4_ve2_963/> seem to indicate that the Vaśas and Uśīnaras were connected.<br>

वशा
<u>'''Vaśā'''</u> denotes ‘cow’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_964/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_964/> According to the commentators, the word means a ‘barren cow,’ but this is not a necessary sense except in a few passages.<ref name=fx3_ve2_964/> <br>

वसति
<u>'''Vasati'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_965/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_965/> ‘abode,’ ‘house.’<br>

वसन
<u>'''Vasana'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_966/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_966/> denotes ‘dress.’<br>

वसन्त
<u>'''Vasanta,'''</u> ‘spring,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_967/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_967/> It is regularly identified with the first of the months. See '''[[ऋतु|Ṛtu]].'''<br>

वसावि
<u>'''Vasāvi'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_968/> denotes, according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_968/> a ‘treasure house.’<br>

वसिष्ठ
<u>'''Vasiṣṭha'''</u> is the name of one of the most prominent priestly figures of Vedic tradition. The seventh Maṇḍala of the Rigveda is ascribed to him; this ascription is borne out by the fact that the Vasiṣṭhas<ref name=fx1_ve2_969/> and [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_969/> are frequently mentioned in that Maṇḍala, besides being sometimes referred to elsewhere. That by the name [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] a definite individual is always meant is most improbable, as Oldenberg<ref name=fx3_ve2_969/> shows; [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] must normally mean simply ‘a [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]].’ But it is not necessary to deny that a real [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] existed, for one hymn<ref name=fx4_ve2_969/> seems to show clear traces of his authorship, and of his assistance to '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' against the ten kings.<br><br>The most important feature of Vasiṣṭha's life was apparently  his hostility to '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]].''' The latter was certainly<ref name=fx5_ve2_969/> at one time the '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]]''' (‘domestic priest’) of [[सुदास्|Sudās]], but he seems to have been deposed from that post, to have joined Sudās' enemies, and to have taken part in the onslaught of the kings against him, for the hymn of Sudās' triumph<ref name=fx4_ve2_969/> has clear references to the ruin [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] brought on his allies.<ref name=fx6_ve2_969/> Oldenberg,<ref name=fx7_ve2_969/> however, holds that the strife of [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] and [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] is not to be found in the Rigveda. On the other hand, Geldner<ref name=fx8_ve2_969/> is hardly right in finding in the Rigveda<ref name=fx9_ve2_969/> a compressed account indicating the rivalry of '''[[शक्ति|Śakti]],''' Vasiṣṭha's son, with [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]], the acquisition by [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] of special skill in speech, and the revenge of [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]], who secured the death of [[शक्ति|Śakti]] by Sudās' servants, an account which is more fully related by Ṣaḍguruśiṣya,<ref name=fx10_ve2_969/> which appeared in the Śāṭyāyanaka,<ref name=fx11_ve2_969/> and to which reference seems to be made in the brief notices of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx12_ve2_969/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx13_ve2_969/> regarding Vasiṣṭha's sons having been slain, and his overcoming the Saudāsas. But it is important to note that no mention is made in these authorities of [[सुदास्|Sudās]] himself being actually opposed to [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]], while in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx14_ve2_969/> [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] appears as the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] and consecrator of [[सुदास्|Sudās]] [[पैजवन|Paijavana]]. [[यास्क|Yāska]]<ref name=fx15_ve2_969/> recognizes [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] as the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of [[सुदास्|Sudās]]; this accords with what seems to have been the fact  that [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] originally held the post. Probably, however, with the disappearance of [[सुदास्|Sudās]], [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] recovered his position, whereupon [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] in revenge for the murder of his sons secured in some way unspecified the defeat of the Saudāsas.<ref name=fx16_ve2_969/><br><br>At any rate it is hardly necessary to suppose that the enmity of the Saudāsas and Vasiṣṭhas was permanent. There is evidence<ref name=fx17_ve2_969/> that the Bharatas had the Vasiṣṭhas as Purohitas, while other versions<ref name=fx18_ve2_969/> regard them as Purohitas for people (''prajāḥ'') generally. It seems that the Vasiṣṭhas were pioneers in adopting the rule that Purohitas should act as [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] priest<ref name=fx19_ve2_969/> at the sacrifice: the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx20_ve2_969/> states that the Vasiṣṭhas were once the only priests to act as Brahmans, but that later any priest could serve as such.<ref name=fx21_ve2_969/> A rivalry with Jamadgni and [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] is reported in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx22_ve2_969/> [[पराशर|Parāśara]] and [[शतयातु|Śatayātu]] are associated with [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx23_ve2_969/> being apparently, as Geldner<ref name=fx24_ve2_969/> thinks, the grandson and a son of [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]. According to Pischel,<ref name=fx25_ve2_969/> in another hymn,<ref name=fx26_ve2_969/> [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] appears as attempting to steal the goods of his father Varuṇa; Geldner<ref name=fx27_ve2_969/> also shows that the Rigveda<ref name=fx28_ve2_969/> contains a clear reference to Vasiṣṭha's being a son of Varuṇa and the nymph Urvaśī. Perhaps this explains the fact that the Vasiṣṭhas are called the '''Tṛtsus''' in one passage  of the Rigveda;<ref name=fx29_ve2_969/> for being of miraculous parentage, [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] would need adoption into a [[गोत्र|Gotra]], that of the princes whom he served, and to whom [[अगस्त्य|Agastya]] seems to have introduced him.<br><br>There are numerous other references to [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] as a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in Vedic literature,<ref name=fx30_ve2_969/> in the Sūtras,<ref name=fx31_ve2_969/> and in the Epic, where he and [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] fight out their rivalry.<ref name=fx32_ve2_969/><br>

वसु
<u>'''Vasu'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_970/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_970/> denotes ‘wealth,’ ‘property.’<br>

वसुक्र
<u>'''Vasukra'''</u> and his wife are the reputed composers of certain hymns of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_971/> The ascription goes back to the Rigveda Āraṇyakas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_971/><br>

वसु-रोचिस्
<u>'''Vasu-rocis'''</u> is a name occurring only once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_972/> in a form which may be interpreted as either plural or singular. In the former alternative it denotes a family of singers;<ref name=fx2_ve2_972/> in the latter a patron.<ref name=fx3_ve2_972/><br>

वस्तु
<u>'''Vastu'''</u> as a designation of time is the ‘early morning’ in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_973/> <br>

वस्त्र
<u>'''Vastra'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_974/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_974/> denotes ‘dress,’ ‘clothing.’ See '''Yāsas.'''<br>

वस्न
<u>'''Vasna'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_975/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_975/> denotes the ‘price’ paid for anything or its ‘value,’ or the thing itself as an object of purchase, ‘ware.’<br>

वहतु
<u>'''Vahatu'''</u> is the regular name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_976/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_976/> for the ceremonial conducting of the bride from the house of her parents to that of her husband.<br>

वह्नि
<u>'''Vahni,'''</u> ‘carrier,’ denotes any draught animal--''e.g.,'' a ‘horse,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_977/> a ‘goat,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_977/> or an ‘ox.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_977/><br>

वह्य
<u>'''Vahya'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_978/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_978/> a ‘couch’ or ‘bed’ of a comfortable kind used by women.<br>

वाको-वाक्य
<u>'''Vāko-vākya,'''</u> ‘dialogue,’ is the name given in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_979/> to certain portions of the Vedic texts. In one place<ref name=fx2_ve2_979/> the '''[[ब्रह्मोद्य|Brahmodya]]''' is said to be a dialogue; very probably in all the passages the [[ब्रह्मोद्य|Brahmodya]] is meant by this term. Geldner's  view<ref name=fx3_ve2_979/> is different: he sees in the [[वाकोवाक्य|Vākovākya]] an essential part of the '''[[इतिहास|Itihāsa]]-[[पुराण|Purāṇa]],''' the dialogue or dramatic element as opposed to the narrative portion.<br>

वाच्
<u>'''Vāc,'''</u> ‘speech,’ plays a great part in Vedic speculation, but only a few points are of other than mythological significance. Speech is in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_980/> divided into four kinds-that of men, of animals, of birds (''vayāṃsi''), and of small creeping things (''kṣudraṃ sarīsṛpam''). The discrimination or making articulate of speech is ascribed to Indra by the Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve2_980/> The ‘speech’ of the following musical instruments-'''[[तूणव|Tūṇava]], [[वीणा|Vīṇā]], [[दुन्दुभि|Dundubhi]]'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_980/> --is mentioned, and in one Saṃhitā<ref name=fx4_ve2_980/> also that of the axle of a chariot. The speech of the '''Kuru-Pañcālas''' was especially renowned,<ref name=fx5_ve2_980/> as well as that of the northern country, according to the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx6_ve2_980/> so that men went there to study the language. On the other hand, barbarisms in speech were known, and were to be avoided.<ref name=fx7_ve2_980/> <br><br>One division of speech referred to<ref name=fx8_ve2_980/> is that of the divine (''daivī'') and the human (''mānuṣī''), of which some specimens are given, such as ''om,'' the divine counterpart of ''tathā,'' and so forth. The Brahmin is said to know both;<ref name=fx9_ve2_980/> it seems best to regard the distinction not as between Sanskrit and Apabhraṃśa, as Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx10_ve2_980/> suggests, but as between the Sanskrit of the ritual and the hymns and that of ordinary life.<br><br>Reference is also made to Āryan<ref name=fx11_ve2_980/> and to Brahmin<ref name=fx12_ve2_980/> speech, by which Sanskrit, as opposed to non-Āryan tongues, seems to be meant. The '''Vrātyas''' are described as speaking the language of the initiated (''dīkṣita-[[वाच्|vāc]]''), though not themselves initiated (''a-dīkṣita''), but as calling that which is easy to utter (''a-durukta''), difficult to utter.<ref name=fx13_ve2_980/> This may mean that the non-Brahminical Indians were advancing more rapidly than the Brahminical tribes to Prākrit speech, especially if it is legitimate to connect the Vrātyas with the barbarians in speech alluded to in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx7_ve2_980/><br>

वाचक्नवी
<u>'''Vācaknavī,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vacaknu,’ is the patronymic of a woman with the further patronymic of '''Gārgī,''' who appears as a student of '''[[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_981/><br>

वाज
<u>'''Vāja'''</u> from the meaning of ‘strength,’ ‘speed,’ in its application to horses derives the sense of ‘race’<ref name=fx1_ve2_982/> and ‘prize,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_982/> or  merely ‘prosperity.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_982/> That it ever means ‘horse’ is most improbable, that sense being given by '''[[वाजिन्|Vājin]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_982/><br>

वाजपेय
<u>'''Vājapeya'''</u> is the name of a ceremony which, according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_983/> and later authorities,<ref name=fx2_ve2_983/> is only performed by a Brahmin or a [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]. The same [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_983/> insists that this sacrifice is superior to the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]],''' but the consensus of other authorities<ref name=fx4_ve2_983/> assigns to it merely the place of a preliminary to the '''[[बृहस्पतिसव|Bṛhaspatisava]]''' in the case of a priest, and to the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]]''' in the case of a king, while the Śatapatha<ref name=fx5_ve2_983/> is compelled to identify the [[बृहस्पतिसव|Bṛhaspatisava]] with the [[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]]. The essential ceremony is a chariot race in which the sacrificer is victorious. There is evidence in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_983/> showing that once the festival was one which any Āryan could perform. Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx7_ve2_983/> indeed, goes so far as to compare it with the Olympic games; but there is hardly much real ground for this: the rite seems to have been developed round a primitive habit of chariot racing, transformed into a ceremony which by sympathetic magic secures the success of the sacrificer. In fact<ref name=fx8_ve2_983/> Eggeling seems correct in holding that the [[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]] was a preliminary rite performed by a Brahmin prior to his formal installation as a [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], or by a king prior to his consecration. The Kuru [[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]] was specially well known.<ref name=fx9_ve2_983/><br>

वाज-बन्धु
<u>'''Vāja-bandhu'''</u> in one verse of the Rigveda (viii. 68, 19) may be a proper name. It may, however, merely be an adjective meaning ‘ally in conflict.’ <br>

वाज-रत्नायन
<u>'''Vāja-ratnāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vājaratna,’ is the patronymic of '''Somaśuṣman''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 21, 5).<br>

वाज-श्रवस्
<u>'''Vāja-śravas'''</u> is mentioned in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_986/> as a pupil of '''[[जिह्वावन्त् बाध्योग|Jihvāvant Bādhyoga]].'''<br>

वाज-श्रवस
<u>'''Vāja-śravasa,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[वाजश्रवस्|Vājaśravas]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Kuśri''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_987/> It is also the patronymic of the father of '''[[नचिकेतस्|Naciketas]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_987/> where the name is apparently Uśant, though it is understood by Sāyaṇa as a participle in the sense of ‘desiring.’ The Vājaśravases are in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] said to have been sages.<ref name=fx3_ve2_987/> They were '''Gotamas.'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_987/><br>

वाजसनेय
<u>'''Vājasaneya'''</u> is the patronymic of '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_988/> and the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_988/> His school, the Vājasaneyins, are mentioned in the Sūtras.<ref name=fx3_ve2_988/><br>

वाजिन्
<u>'''Vājin'''</u> in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_989/> denotes ‘steed’ with reference to its swiftness and strength. In one passage<ref name=fx2_ve2_989/> it is perhaps, as Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve2_989/> thinks, a proper name, that of a son of '''[[बृहद्उक्थ|Bṛhaduktha]],''' but this view seems forced.<br>

वाजिन
<u>'''Vājina'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_990/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_990/> denotes a mixture of hot fresh milk with sour milk. <br>

वाज्य
<u>'''Vājya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[वाज|Vāja]],’ is the patronymic of '''Ketu''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_991/><br>

वाडेयी-पुत्र
<u>'''Vāḍeyī-putra.'''</u> See '''[[बाडेयीपुत्र|Bāḍeyīputra]].'''<br>

वाण
<u>'''Vāṇa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_993/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_993/> denotes ‘instrumental music’ according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary; but in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx3_ve2_993/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx4_ve2_993/> a ‘harp’ or ‘lyre’ with a hundred strings (''śata-[[तन्तु|tantu]]''), used at the Mahāvrata ceremony. The Rigveda<ref name=fx5_ve2_993/> clearly refers to the seven ‘notes’ (''dhātu'') of the instrument, which are called elsewhere<ref name=fx6_ve2_993/> the seven Vāṇīs, unless the latter expression be taken as referring to the metres.<ref name=fx7_ve2_993/><br>

वाणिज
<u>'''Vāṇija'''</u> denotes a ‘merchant’ as a hereditary profession (‘son of a '''[[वणिज्|Vaṇij]]'''’) in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_994/><br>

वाणी
<u>'''Vāṇī.'''</u> See '''[[वाण|Vāṇa]].'''<br>

वाणीची
<u>'''Vāṇīcī'''</u> occurs in a verse of the Rigveda (v. 75, 4), where the St. Petersburg Dictionary ascribes to it the sense of ‘musical instrument.’ <br>

वात
<u>'''Vāta'''</u> is the regular word for ‘wind’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_997/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_997/> Five winds are mentioned.<ref name=fx3_ve2_997/> In one passage<ref name=fx4_ve2_997/> Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve2_997/> sees a reference to the north-east monsoon. ''Cf.'' '''[[सलिलवात|Salilavāta]].'''<br>

वात-पान
<u>'''Vāta-pāna'''</u> (‘wind guard’) apparently means some sort of garment as protecting against wind in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vi. 1, 1, 3).<br>

वात-रशन
<u>'''Vāta-raśana,'''</u> ‘wind-girt,’ is applied to the '''Munis''' in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_999/> and to the [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]] in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx2_ve2_999/> Naked ascetics, such as are known throughout later Indian religious history, are evidently meant<br>

वातवन्त्
<u>'''Vātavant'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxv. 3, 6). He and '''[[दृति|Dṛti]]''' performed a certain Sattra or sacrificial session, but by stopping at a particular time he came to grief, and his descendants, the Vātavatas, were less prosperous than the '''Dārteyas.'''<br>

वातवत
<u>'''Vātavata,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[वातवन्त्|Vātavant]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Vṛṣaśuṣma''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1001/> The [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1001/> has the same form with a variant [[वाधावत|Vādhāvata]].<br>

वात्सि
<u>'''Vātsi,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[वत्स|Vatsa]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Sarpi''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vi. 24, 16).<br>

वात्सी-पुत्र
<u>'''Vātsī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of '''[[वत्स|Vatsa]],'''’ as the name of a teacher mentioned in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers)  of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] as a pupil of '''[[पाराशरीपुत्र|Pārāśarīputra]]''' according to the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension (vi, 5, 2), as a pupil of '''[[भारद्वाजीपुत्र|Bhāradvājīputra]]''' according to the Mādhyaṃdina (vi. 4, 31).<br>

वात्सी-माण्डवी-पुत्र
<u>'''Vātsī-[[माण्डवी|Māṇḍavī]]-putra'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[पाराशरीपुत्र|Pārāśarīputra]],''' according to the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 30).<br>

वात्स्य
<u>'''Vātsya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[वत्स|Vatsa]],'''’ is the name of one or more teachers. One is mentioned in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1005/> where the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve2_1005/> in the parallel passage has '''[[बाध्व|Bādhva]].''' Others occur in the Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] as pupils of '''Kuśri,'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1005/> '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]],'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1005/> or another [[वात्स्य|Vātsya]],<ref name=fx5_ve2_1005/> while a [[वात्स्य|Vātsya]] is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx6_ve2_1005/><br>

वात्स्यायन
<u>'''Vātsyāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[वात्स्य|Vātsya]],'''’ is the name of a teacher in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (i. 7, 2).<br>

वादन
<u>'''Vādana'''</u> denotes the plectrum of a harp in the Āraṇyakas of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1007/><br>

वादित
<u>'''Vādita'''</u> is found denoting ‘music’ in the compound ''gītavādita,'' ‘song and music,’ in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (viii. 2, 8), and uncompounded in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxix. 5) along with '''Nṛtya,''' ‘dance,’ and Gīta, ‘song.’ See '''[[शिल्प|Śilpa]].'''<br>

वाधावत
<u>'''Vādhāvata'''</u> is a various reading in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1009/> for '''[[वातावत|Vātāvata]].''' <br>

वाधूय
<u>'''Vādhūya'''</u> denotes the garment of the bride worn at the marriage ceremony and afterwards given to a Brahmin.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1010/><br>

वाध्र्यश्व
<u>'''Vādhryaśva,'''</u> ‘connected with '''[[वध्र्य्अश्व|Vadhryaśva]],'''’ is apparently the epithet of Agni in a hymn of the Rigveda (x. 69, 5).<br>

वानस्पत्य
<u>'''Vānaspatya'''</u> (as a masculine) in one or two passages of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1012/> seems to denote a ‘small tree.’ Elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve2_1012/> (as a neuter) it has the sense of the ‘fruit of a tree’ ('''[[वनस्पति|Vanaspati]]''').<br>

वाम-कक्षायण
<u>'''Vāma-kakṣāyaṇa'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[वात्स्य|Vātsya]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1013/> or '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]]'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1013/> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<br>

वाम-देव
<u>'''Vāma-deva'''</u> is credited<ref name=fx1_ve2_1014/> by tradition with the authorship of the fourth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda, and he is once mentioned in that Maṇḍala.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1014/> He is, moreover, credited with the authorship of the fourth hymn of the Maṇḍala by the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1014/> He there appears as a son of '''[[गोतम|Gotama]],''' while in one hymn of the fourth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_1014/> [[गोतम|Gotama]] is mentioned as the father of the singer, and in another<ref name=fx5_ve2_1014/> the Gotamas occur as praising Indra. In the Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx6_ve2_1014/> two absurd legends are narrated of [[वामदेव|Vāmadeva]]. One describes Indra as revealing himself in the form of an eagle to the seer as he cooked the entrails of a dog; the other tells of his successful conflict with Indra, whom he sold among the seers. Sieg<ref name=fx7_ve2_1014/> has endeavoured to trace these tales in the  Rigveda,<ref name=fx8_ve2_1014/> but without any success. Moreover, though [[वामदेव|Vāmadeva]] is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx9_ve2_1014/> and often in the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx10_ve2_1014/> he never figures there as a hero of these legends.<br>

वायत
<u>'''Vāyata,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vayant,’ is the patronymic of '''Pāśadyumna''' in the Rigveda (vii. 33, 2). ''Cf.'' '''Vyant.'''<br>

वायस
<u>'''Vāyasa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1016/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1016/> denotes a ‘large bird.’ The sense of ‘crow’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1016/> occurs in the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] only.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1016/><br>

वायो-विद्यिक
<u>'''Vāyo-vidyika,'''</u> ‘bird-catcher,’ is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1017/><br>

वाय्य
<u>'''Vāyya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[वय्य|Vayya]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[सत्यश्रवस्|Satyaśravas]]''' in the Rigveda (v. 79, 1. 2).<br>

वार्
<u>'''Vār'''</u> is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1019/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1019/> denoting ‘water.’ In some passages<ref name=fx3_ve2_1019/> ‘stagnant water,’ ‘pond,’ is meant.<br>

वारकि
<u>'''Vāraki,'''</u> ‘descendant of Varaka,’ is the patronymic of '''[[कंस|Kaṃsa]]''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 41, 1). <br>

वारक्य
<u>'''Vārakya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Varaka,’ is the patronymic, in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], of '''[[कंस|Kaṃsa]], Kubera, [[जनश्रुत|Janaśruta]], [[जयन्त|Jayanta]],''' and '''Proṣṭhapad.'''<br>

वारण
<u>'''Vāraṇa'''</u> in two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1022/> is taken by Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1022/> as an adjective with '''[[मृग|Mṛga]],''' meaning ‘wild beast.’ But the sense intended must have been ‘elephant,’ the usual sense of [[वारण|Vāraṇa]] in the classical literature. Probably the feminine Vāraṇī in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1022/> likewise denotes a ‘female elephant.’<br>

वारुणि
<u>'''Vāruṇi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Varuṇa,’ is the patronymic of '''[[भृगु|Bhṛgu]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1023/><br>

वार्कलि
<u>'''Vārkali,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vṛkalā,’ is the metronymic of a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1024/> The name in the form of Vārkalin has been seen in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1024/> but wrongly.<br>

वार्कारुणी-पुत्र
<u>'''Vārkāruṇī-putra'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[आर्तभागीपुत्र|Ārtabhāgīputra]],''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1025/><br>

वार्ध्रा-णस
<u>'''Vārdhrā-ṇasa,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1026/> '''Vārdhrī-nasa'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1026/> is the name of an animal in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the  [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās. The meaning seems to be, as taken by Sāyaṇa,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1026/> ‘rhinoceros.’ Bo7htlingk<ref name=fx4_ve2_1026/> quotes as other interpretations ‘an old white he-goat’ or ‘a kind of crane.’<br>

वार्ष-गण
<u>'''Vārṣa-gaṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[वृषगण|Vṛṣagaṇa]],’ is the patronymic of '''[[असित|Asita]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1027/><br>

वार्षगणी-पुत्र
<u>'''Vārṣagaṇī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of [[वृषगण|Vṛṣagaṇa]],’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[गौतमी-पुत्र|Gautamī-putra]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 31).<br>

वार्ष-गण्य
<u>'''Vārṣa-gaṇya,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[वृषगण|Vṛṣagaṇa]],’ is the name of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1029/><br>

वार्षा-गिर
<u>'''Vārṣā-gira,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vṛṣāgir,’ is the patronymic of '''[[अम्बरीष|Ambarīṣa]], [[ऋज्राश्व|Ṛjrāśva]], [[भयमान|Bhayamāna]]. [[सहदेव|Sahadeva]],''' and '''[[सुराधस्|Surādhas]],''' in the Rigveda (i. 100, 17).<br><br>''Cf.'' Ludwig, Translation of the Rigveda, 3, 113.<br>

वार्ष्ण
<u>'''Vārṣṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[वृषन्|Vṛṣan]] or Vṛṣṇi or Vṛṣṇa,’ is the patronymic of '''[[गोबल|Gobala]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1031/> and '''Barku,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1031/> and of '''[[ऐक्ष्वाक|Aikṣvāka]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1031/><br>

वार्ष्णि-वृद्ध
<u>'''Vārṣṇi-vṛddha,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vṛṣṇivṛddha,’ is the patronymic of '''Ula''' in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 4).<br>

वार्ष्णेय
<u>'''Vārṣṇeya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vṛṣṇi,’ is the patronymic of '''Śūṣa''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 10, 9, 15). <br>

वार्ष्ण्य
<u>'''Vārṣṇya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vṛṣṇi, is the patronymic of a man in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1034/><br>

वार्ष्म
<u>'''Vārṣma.'''</u> See '''[[वार्ष्ण|Vārṣṇa]].'''<br>

वाल
<u>'''Vāla'''</u> denotes a ‘hair sieve’ in the later Saṃhitās and he Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1036/><br>

वाल-खिल्य
<u>'''Vāla-khilya'''</u> is the term applied in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1037/> to the supplementary hymns inserted after Rigveda viii. 48. The [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]] of these hymns are so named in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1037/> ''Cf.'' 2. '''[[खिल|Khila]].'''<br>

वाल-दामन्
<u>'''Vāla-dāman'''</u> denotes a ‘horse-hair strap’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 3, 1, 10).<br>

वालिशिखायनि
<u>'''Vāliśikhāyani'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1039/><br>

वावाता
<u>'''Vāvātā'''</u> is in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1040/> the name of the king's ‘favourite’ wife. inferior to the '''[[महिषी|Mahiṣī]]''' only. <br>

वाशिता
<u>'''Vāśitā'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1041/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1041/> denotes a cow desiring the bull.<br>

वाशी
<u>'''Vāśī'''</u> is mentioned in the Rigveda both as a weapon of the Maruts<ref name=fx1_ve2_1042/> and as held by the god [[त्वष्टृ|Tvaṣṭṛ]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1042/> as well as in other mythical surroundings.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1042/> It is used, however, in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_1042/> of the carpenter's knife; here it may mean ‘awl,’ in accordance with Sāyaṇa's view.(**  5 Zimmer, ''Altindisches Leben,'' 301.<br>

वासः-पल्पूली
<u>'''Vāsaḥ-palpūlī,'''</u> ‘washer of clothes,’ is the name of one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1043/><br>

वासस्
<u>'''Vāsas'''</u> is the most usual word in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1044/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1044/> for ‘clothing.’ Clothes were often woven of sheep's wool (''cf.'' '''[[ऊर्णा|Ūrṇā]]'''); the god Pūṣan is called a ‘weaver of garments’ (''vāsevāya'')<ref name=fx3_ve2_1044/> because of his connexion with the fashioning of forms. The garments worn were often embroidered (''cf.'' '''Peśas'''), and the Maruts are described as wearing mantles adorned with gold.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1044/> When the ‘giver of garments’ (''vāso-dā'')<ref name=fx5_ve2_1044/> is mentioned along with the giver of horses and gold, ornamental garments are probably meant. There are several references in the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve2_1044/> to the Indians' love of ornament, which is attested by Megas-  thenes for his day.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1044/> The Rigveda also presents epithets like ''[[सु-वसन|su-vasana]]''<ref name=fx8_ve2_1044/> and ''su-[[रभि|rabhi]],''<ref name=fx9_ve2_1044/> implying that garments were becoming or well-fitting.<br><br>The Vedic Indian seems often to have worn three garments-an undergarment (''cf.'' '''[[नीवि|Nīvi]]'''),<ref name=fx10_ve2_1044/> a garment,<ref name=fx11_ve2_1044/> and an overgarment (''cf.'' '''Adhīvāsa'''),<ref name=fx12_ve2_1044/> which was presumably a mantle, and for which the names '''Atka''' and '''[[द्रापि|Drāpi]]''' also seem to be used. This accords with the description of the sacrificial garments given in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx13_ve2_1044/> which comprise a '''[[तार्प्य|Tārpya]],''' perhaps a ‘silken undergarment’; secondly, a garment of undyed wool, and then a mantle, while the ends of the turban, after being tied behind the neck, are brought forward and tucked away in front. The last point would hardly accord with the usual practice in ordinary life, but seems to be a special sacrificial ritual act. A similar sort of garments in the case of women appears to be alluded to in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx14_ve2_1044/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx15_ve2_1044/> There is nothing to show exactly what differences there were between male and female costume, nor what was exactly the nature of the clothes in either case.<br><br>It is important to note that the Vedic Indian evidently assumed that all civilized persons other than inspired Munis would wear clothing of some sort.<ref name=fx16_ve2_1044/><br><br>See also '''[[वसन|Vasana]], [[वस्त्र|Vastra]], Otu, [[तन्तु|Tantu]].''' For the use of skin garments, see '''Mala.'''<br>

वासिष्ठ
<u>'''Vāsiṣṭha,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[सात्यहव्य|Sātyahavya]],''' a teacher mentioned several times in the later  Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1045/> of '''Rauhina''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1045/> and of '''[[चैकितानेय|Caikitāneya]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1045/> Moreover, reference is made to the claim of the Vāsiṣṭhas to be [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] priest at the sacrifice.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1045/> A [[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]] is mentioned as a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1045/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx6_ve2_1045/><br>

वास्तु-पश्य
<u>'''Vāstu-paśya,'''</u> according to Bo7htlingk<ref name=fx1_ve2_1046/> a name of a [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], is a mere error for ''Vāstupasya''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1046/> in the Jaiminiya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1046/><br>

वाह
<u>'''Vāha'''</u> is found in the Rigveda (iv. 57, 4. 8) and the Atharvaveda (vi. 102, 1) apparently denoting an ox for ‘drawing’ the plough. See also '''[[रथवाहन|Rathavāhana]].'''<br>

वाहन
<u>'''Vāhana'''</u> (neut.) in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1048/> denotes a ‘beast of burden,’ or occasionally<ref name=fx2_ve2_1048/> a ‘cart.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[रथवाहन|Rathavāhana]].'''<br>

वाहस
<u>'''Vāhasa,'''</u> ‘boa constrictor,’ is included in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1049/> <br>

वि
<u>'''Vi'''</u> in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1050/> and sometimes later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1050/> denotes ‘bird.’<br>

वि-ककर
<u>'''Vi-kakara'''</u> is the name of some bird, a victim at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) according to the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1051/><br>

वि-कङ्कत
<u>'''Vi-kaṅkata'''</u> is the name of a tree (''Flacourtia sapida''), often mentioned in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1052/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1052/><br>

वि-क्रय
<u>'''Vi-kraya'''</u> is found in the Atharvaveda (iii. 15, 4) and the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (iii. 4) denoting ‘sale.’ See '''[[क्रय|Kraya]].'''<br>

वि-क्लिन्दु
<u>'''Vi-klindu'''</u> is the name of a disease in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1054/> Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve2_1054/> suggests ‘catarrh.’<br>

वि-घन
<u>'''Vi-ghana'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1055/> seems to denote ‘club.’<br>

वि-चक्षण ताण्ड्य
<u>'''Vi-cakṣaṇa Tāṇḍya'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[गर्दभीमुख|Gardabhīmukha]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1056/><br>

वि-चारिन् काबन्धि
<u>'''Vi-cārin Kābandhi'''</u> (‘descendant of '''Kabandha'''’) is the name of a mythical teacher in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1057/> <br>

वि-चृत्
<u>'''Vi-cṛt'''</u> in the dual is found in three passages of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1058/> where Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1058/> sees in the term the name of two stars, while in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_1058/> he thinks they mean the '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]]''' called [[मूल|Mūla]]. There can, however, be no doubt that the asterism is intended in all the passages.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1058/><br>

विज्
<u>'''Vij.'''</u> See 2. '''[[अक्ष|Akṣa]].'''<br>

वि-जामातृ
<u>'''Vi-jāmātṛ.'''</u> See '''[[जामातृ|Jāmātṛ]].'''<br>

वितस्ता
<u>'''Vitastā,'''</u> the most westerly of the five rivers of the Panjab, is only mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1061/> in the Nadīstuti (‘Praise of Rivers’).<ref name=fx2_ve2_1061/> It is the Hydaspes of Alexander's historians, more correctly reproduced by Ptolemy as Bidaspes. The name appears in the Mohammedan historians corrupted to Bihat or Wihat, and survives in the modern Kashmīrī form of Veth.<br>

वित्त
<u>'''Vitta'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1062/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1062/> denotes ‘wealth,’ ‘possessions.’ The earth is referred to in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1062/> as full of riches (''vittasya pūrṇā''). The doctrine that a man's greatness depends on his wealth is found as early as the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_1062/> The striving after wealth (''vittaiṣaṇā'') is mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1062/> as one of the things abandoned by the sage. <br>

विदग्ध शाकल्य
<u>'''Vidagdha Śākalya'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a contemporary and rival of '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]]''' at the court of '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' of '''[[विदेह|Videha]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1063/> the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1063/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1063/><br>

विदथ
<u>'''Vidatha'''</u> is a word of obscure sense, confined mainly to the Rigveda. According to Roth,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1064/> the sense is primarily ‘order,’ then the concrete body which gives orders, then ‘assembly’ for secular<ref name=fx2_ve2_1064/> or religious ends,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1064/> or for war.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1064/> Oldenberg<ref name=fx5_ve2_1064/> once thought that the main idea is ‘ordinance’ (from ''vi-dhā,'' ‘dispose,’ ‘ordain’), and thence ‘sacrifice.’ Ludwig<ref name=fx6_ve2_1064/> thinks that the root idea is an ‘assembly,’ especially of the '''Maghavans''' and the Brahmins. Geldner<ref name=fx7_ve2_1064/> considers that the word primarily means ‘knowledge,’ ‘wisdom,’ ‘priestly lore,’ then ‘sacrifice’ and ‘spiritual authority.’ Bloomfield,<ref name=fx8_ve2_1064/> on the other hand, insists that [[विदथ|Vidatha]] refers to the ‘house’<ref name=fx9_ve2_1064/> in the first place (from ''vid,'' ‘acquire’), and then to the ‘sacrifice,’ as connected with the house; this interpretation, at any rate, appears to suit all the passages. The term ''vidathya,'' once<ref name=fx10_ve2_1064/> applied to the king (''samrāṭ''), might seem to be against this view, but it may refer to his being ‘rich in homesteads’; and the connexion of the woman with the [[विदथ|Vidatha]], as opposed to  the '''[[सभा|Sabhā]],''' tells in favour<ref name=fx11_ve2_1064/> of Bloomfield's explanation. That the word ever denotes an asylum, like the house of the Brahmin,<ref name=fx12_ve2_1064/> as Ludwig<ref name=fx13_ve2_1064/> suggests, is doubtful.<ref name=fx14_ve2_1064/><br>

विदन्वन्त् भार्गव
<u>'''Vidanvant Bhārgava'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[भृगु|Bhṛgu]]'''’) is mentioned as the seer of a Sāman or chant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1065/> and in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1065/><br>

विदर्भ
<u>'''Vidarbha'''</u> occurs in the earlier Vedic literature as the name of a place only in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1066/> where its '''Mācalas''' (perhaps a species of dog) are said to kill tigers.<br>

विदर्भी-कौण्डिनेय
<u>'''Vidarbhī-Kauṇḍineya'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''Vatsanapāt''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1067/><br>

वि-दिश्
<u>'''Vi-diś'''</u> denotes<ref name=fx1_ve2_1068/> an ‘intermediate quarter.’ See '''[[दिश्|Diś]].'''<br>

विदीगय
<u>'''Vidīgaya'''</u> is the name of an animal in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1069/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1069/> The commentary on the former takes it as a kind of cock (''[[कुक्कुट|kukkuṭa]]-viśeṣa''), that on the latter as a white heron (''śveta-baka''). <br>

विदेघ
<u>'''Videgha'''</u> is the name of a man, '''[[माथव|Māthava]],''' in the Śatapatha Brāhmana.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1070/> It is legitimate to assume<ref name=fx2_ve2_1070/> that it is a name given to him as king of the Videghas who are the later '''Videhas.'''<br>

विदेह
<u>'''Videha'''</u> is the name of a people who are not mentioned before the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] period. In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1071/> the legend of '''[[विदेघ|Videgha]] [[माथव|Māthava]]''' preserves clearly a tradition that in [[विदेह|Videha]] culture came from the Brahmins of the West, and that '''[[कोसल|Kosala]]''' was brahminized before [[विदेह|Videha]]. The Videhas, however, derived some fame later from the culture of their king '''[[जनक|Janaka]],''' who figures in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1071/> as one of the leading patrons of the [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]] doctrine. In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1071/> the Videhas are joined with the '''Kāśis;''' in the list of peoples in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_1071/> the Videhas are passed over, probably because, with [[कोसल|Kosala]] and [[काशि|Kāśi]], they are included in the term '''Prācyas,''' ‘easterners.’ Again, in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1071/> it is recorded that the [[काशि|Kāśi]], [[कोसल|Kosala]], and [[विदेह|Videha]] kingdoms had each the one [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], '''[[जल जातूकर्ण्य|Jala Jātūkarṇya]];''' and in another passage of the same text<ref name=fx6_ve2_1071/> the connexion between the [[विदेह|Videha]] king, '''[[पर आट्णार|Para Āṭṇāra]],''' and the [[कोसल|Kosala]] king, '''[[हिरण्यनाभ|Hiraṇyanābha]],''' is explained, while the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve2_1071/> speaks of [[पर आट्णार|Para Āṭṇāra]] as the [[कोसल|Kosala]] king, descendant of [[हिरण्यनाभ|Hiraṇyanābha]].<br><br>Another king of [[विदेह|Videha]] was '''[[नमी साप्य|Namī Sāpya]],''' mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx8_ve2_1071/> In the Saṃhitās of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx9_ve2_1071/> ‘cows of Videha’ seem to be alluded to, though the commentator on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā merely takes the adjective ''vaidehī'' as ‘having a splendid body’ (''viśiṣṭa-deha-sambandhinī''), and the point of a place name in the expression is not very obvious. The Videhas also occur in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx10_ve2_1071/> in [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]-like passages.<br><br>The boundary of [[कोसल|Kosala]] and [[विदेह|Videha]] was the '''[[सदानीरा|Sadānīrā]],'''  probably the modern Gandak<ref name=fx11_ve2_1071/> (the Kondochates of the Greek geographers), which, rising in Nepal, flows into the Ganges opposite Patna. [[विदेह|Videha]] itself corresponds roughly to the modern Tirhut.<br>

विद्या
<u>'''Vidyā'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1072/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1072/> denotes ‘knowledge,’ especially that of the three Vedas, which are called the ''trayī [[विद्या|vidyā]],'' ‘the threefold knowledge,’ as early as the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1072/> In a more special sense [[विद्या|Vidyā]] occurs in lists of objects of study in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_1072/> What exactly the expression here means is uncertain: Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx5_ve2_1072/> suggests the philosophic systems; Geldner<ref name=fx6_ve2_1072/> the first Brāhmaṇas; and Eggeling,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1072/> more probably, special sciences like the '''[[सर्पविद्या|Sarpavidyā]]''' or the '''[[विषविद्या|Viṣavidyā]].'''<br>

विद्रध
<u>'''Vidradha'''</u> denotes a disease, ‘abscesses,’ in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1073/> According to Zimmer,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1073/> it was a symptom accompanying '''[[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]].''' Later it is called Vidradhi. Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve2_1073/> compares the obscure [[विद्रध|Vidradha]] of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1073/> where, however, the sense of the word is very uncertain.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1073/><br>

विधवा
<u>'''Vidhavā'''</u> denotes ‘widow’ as the ‘desolate one,’ from the root ''vidh,'' ‘be bereft.’ The masculine ''vidhava'' is conjectured  by Roth<ref name=fx1_ve2_1074/> in a difficult passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1074/> where the received text presents the apparent false concord ''vidhantaṃ vidhavām,'' in which he sees a metrical lengthening for ''vidhavam,'' ‘the sacrificing widower.’ Ludwig in his version takes ''vidhantam'' as equivalent to a feminine, while Delbrück<ref name=fx3_ve2_1074/> prefers ‘the worshipper and the widow.’ Possibly ‘the widower and the widow’ may be meant; but we know nothing of the mythological allusion in question, the feat being one of those attributed to the Aśvins, and the natural reference to '''[[घोषा|Ghoṣā]]''' as ‘husbandless’ being rendered unlikely because their feat in regard to her has already been mentioned a few verses before in the same hymn.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1074/> The word [[विधवा|Vidhavā]] is not of common occurrence.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1074/><br>

विधु
<u>'''Vidhu'''</u> seems clearly to mean (as it does in the post-Vedic language) the ‘moon’ in a passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1075/> where it is alluded to as ‘wandering solitary in the midst of many’ (''vidhuṃ dadrāṇaṃ samane bahūnām'').<br>

वि-नशन
<u>'''Vi-naśana,'''</u> ‘disappearance,’ is the name of the place where the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' is lost in the sands of the desert. It is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1076/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1076/> The locality is the Patiala district of the Panjab.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1076/> ''Cf.'' '''[[प्लक्ष प्रास्रवण|Plakṣa Prāsravaṇa]].'''<br>

विप्
<u>'''Vip'''</u> in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1077/> refers, according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1077/> to the rods which form the bottom of the Soma filter,  and on which the straining cloth is stretched. But this explanation is very doubtful.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1077/><br>

वि-पथ
<u>'''Vi-patha,'''</u> in the description of the '''[[व्रात्य|Vrātya]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1078/> denotes a vehicle suited for rough roads. ''Cf.'' '''Anas.'''<br>

विपश्चित् दृढ-जयन्त लौहित्य
<u>'''1. Vipaścit [[दृढ-जयन्त|Dṛḍha-jayanta]] Lauhitya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1) as the pupil of '''[[दक्ष जयन्त लौहित्य|Dakṣa <a class="pada_vei" href="जयन्त">Jayanta]] Lauhitya».'''<br>

विपश्चित् शकुनि-मित्र पाराशर्य
<u>'''2. Vipaścit [[शकुनि-मित्र|Śakuni-mitra]] Pārāśarya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[पराशर|Parāśara]]'''’) is the name of a teacher, pupil of [[अषाढ उत्तर पाराशर्य|Aṣāḍha Uttara Pārāśarya]], in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] Brāhmana (iii. 41, 1).<br>

वि-पाश्
<u>'''Vi-pāś'''</u> (‘fetterless’) is the name of a river mentioned twice in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1081/> It is the modern Beās in the Panjab, the Hyphasis, Hypanis or Bipasis of the Greeks. Its small importance for the Vedic Indians is indicated by the fact that it is never mentioned in the earlier Vedic literature except in two hymns of the Rigveda. The [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1081/> preserves the notice that its earlier name was '''[[उरुञ्जिरा|Uruñjirā]],''' while the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1081/> places in the middle of it the ''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]-śilāḥ.'' Pāṇinī<ref name=fx4_ve2_1081/> mentions the name, which otherwise in post-Vedic literature appears as Vipāśā. This river has changed its course considerably since ancient times.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1081/> <br>

वि-पूजन शौराकि
<u>'''Vi-pūjana Śaurāki'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1082/> or Saurāki<ref name=fx2_ve2_1082/> is the name of a teacher in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<br>

विपृथु
<u>'''Vipṛthu'''</u> in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xiv. 72, 3) is apparently equivalent to the '''[[विपथ|Vipatha]],''' ‘rough cart,’ of other texts. It is probably a mere blunder.<br>

विप्र
<u>'''Vipra'''</u> seems to mean ‘inspired singer’ (from ''vip,'' ‘quiver’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1084/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1084/> More especially in the later texts<ref name=fx3_ve2_1084/> it denotes a ‘learned Brahmin.’ In the epic style it comes to mean no more than ‘Brahmin.’<br>

विप्र-चित्ति
<u>'''Vipra-citti'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1085/> or '''[[विप्र|Vipra]]-jitti'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1085/> is the name of a teacher in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<br>

विप्र-जन सौराकि
<u>'''Vipra-jana Saurāki'''</u> is the form of the name of '''Vipūjana''' given by the St. Petersburg Dictionaries for the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1086/><br>

विबाली
<u>'''Vibālī'''</u> is found once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1087/> apparently as the name of an unknown stream.<br>

विभण्डक काश्यप
<u>'''Vibhaṇḍaka Kāśyapa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[कश्यप|Kaśyapa]]'''’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[ऋष्यशृङ्ग|Ṛṣyaśṛṅga]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1088/> <br>

वि-भिन्दु
<u>'''Vi-bhindu'''</u> is the name of a sacrificer in the Rigveda (viii. 2, 91).<br><br>''Cf.'' Hopkins. ''Journal of the American Oriental Society,'' 19, 59.<br>

विभिन्दुक
<u>'''Vibhinduka'''</u> occurs in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1090/> as the name of a man or a demon<ref name=fx2_ve2_1090/> from whom '''[[मेधातिथि|Medhātithi]]''' drove away the cows. Hopkins<ref name=fx3_ve2_1090/> is inclined to read Vaibhinduka as a patronymic of [[मेधातिथि|Medhātithi]]. ''Cf.'' '''[[विभिन्दुकीय|Vibhindukīya]].'''<br>

विभिन्दुकीय
<u>'''Vibhindukīya'''</u> is the name of a group of priests whose Sattra is mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1091/><br>

विभीतक
<u>'''Vibhītaka'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1092/> and '''Vibhīdaka,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1092/> the latter being the old form, denote a large tree, the ''Terminalia bellerica,'' the nut of which was used in dicing.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1092/> The wood was also used for making the<ref name=fx4_ve2_1092/> sacrificial fire burn.<br>

वि-मद
<u>'''1. Vi-mada'''</u> is credited by the Anukramaṇī (Index) with the authorship of a number of hymns of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1093/> This attribution is supported by the occurrence in this group of the name of the seer,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1093/> and once of his family, the Vimadas,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1093/> besides the repeated refrain<ref name=fx4_ve2_1093/> ''vi vo made,'' ‘in your carouses.’ [[विमद|Vimada]] is occasionally alluded to later.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1093/> <br>

विमद
<u>'''2. Vimada'''</u> is mentioned in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1094/> as a protégé of the Aśvins, who gave him a wife, '''[[कमद्यू|Kamadyū]].''' His identity with the preceding is improbable.<br>

वि-मुक्ता
<u>'''Vi-muktā'''</u> (lit., ‘secreted’), ‘pearl,’ is found in the late Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 6).<br>

वि-मोक्तृ
<u>'''Vi-moktṛ'''</u> in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha<ref name=fx1_ve2_1096/> (‘human sacrifice’) denotes one who unharnesses horses from the chariot, as opposed to Yoktṛ, ‘one who yokes.’ The corresponding verbal noun Vimocana, ‘unyoking,’ is often found.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1096/><br>

वि-राज्
<u>'''Vi-rāj'''</u> as a title of royalty is mentioned several times in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1097/> but only in a metaphorical sense. As an actual title, it is asserted in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1097/> to be used by the '''Uttara Kurus''' and the '''Uttara Madras.'''<br>

वि-रूप
<u>'''Vi-rūpa'''</u> is the name of an Aṅgirasa who is twice mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1098/> and to whom certain hymns are attributed by the Anukramaṇī (Index).<br><br>^2 viii. 43 ''et seq.;'' 64.<br>

विलिगी
<u>'''Viligī'''</u> denotes a kind of snake in the Atharvaveda (v. 13, 7).<br>

विलिष्ट-भेषज
<u>'''Viliṣṭa-bheṣaja'''</u> in the Atharvaveda (Paippalāda, xx. 5, 2) denotes a remedy for a dislocation or a sprain. <br>

वि-लोहित
<u>'''Vi-lohita'''</u> is the name of a disease mentioned in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1101/> Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve2_1101/> thinks that ‘flow of blood from the nose’ is meant; Henry<ref name=fx3_ve2_1101/> renders it ‘decomposition of the blood’; and Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve2_1101/> has ‘anæmia.’<br>

वि-वध
<u>'''Vi-vadha'''</u> or '''Vī-vadha''' seems to denote a yoke borne on the shoulders to enable one to carry a weight. But it is found in the Brāhmaṇas used only metaphorically in such phrases as ''vi-[[विवध|vivadha]],''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1102/> ‘with the weight unequally distributed,’ and ''savīvadhatā,''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1102/> ‘equality of burden.’<br>

वि-वयन
<u>'''Vi-vayana'''</u> denotes in the Brāhmaṇas ‘plaited work,’ such as that used in a couch ('''Asandī''').<br><br>^1 [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], viii. 5, 3; Śatapatha Brāhmaṇā, xii. 8, 3, 6. In the Sūtras ''vivāna'' has the same sense; Lāṭyāyana Srauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], iii, 12, 1, etc.<br>

वि-वाह
<u>'''Vi-vāha,'''</u> ‘marriage,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1104/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1104/> See '''Pati.'''<br>

विश्
<u>'''Viś'''</u> is an expression of somewhat doubtful significance. In many passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1105/> the sense of ‘settlement’ or ‘dwelling’ is adequate and probable, since the root ''[[विश्|viś]]'' means to ‘enter’ or ‘settle.’ In other passages, where the Viśaḥ  stand in relation to a prince, the term must mean ‘subject’;<ref name=fx2_ve2_1105/> so, for example, when the people of '''[[तृणस्कन्द|Tṛṇaskanda]]'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1105/> or of the '''Tṛtsus''' are mentioned.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1105/> Again, in some passages<ref name=fx5_ve2_1105/> the general sense of ‘people’ is adequate; as when the Rigveda speaks of the ‘Āryan people,’<ref name=fx6_ve2_1105/> or the ‘divine people,’<ref name=fx7_ve2_1105/> or the ‘Dāsa people,’ and so on.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1105/><br><br>Sometimes,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1105/> however, the [[विश्|Viś]] appear in a more special sense as a subdivision of the '''Jana''' or whole people. This is, however, not common, for in most passages one or other of the senses given above is quite possible. Moreover, it is very difficult to decide whether the [[विश्|Viś]] as a subdivision of the Jana is to be considered as being a local subdivision (canton) or a blood kinship equivalent to a clan in the large sense of the word, while the relation of the [[विश्|Viś]] to the '''[[ग्राम|Grāma]]''' or to the '''[[गोत्र|Gotra]]''' is quite uncertain. In one passage of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx10_ve2_1105/> the Viśaḥ are mentioned along with the ''sabandhavaḥ'' or relatives, but no definite conclusion can be drawn from that fact. Nor does the analogy of the Roman ''curia'' or the Greek  throw much light, as these institutions are themselves of obscure character, and the parallelism need not be cogent. It is, at any rate, possible that the [[विश्|Viś]] may in some cases have been no more than a [[गोत्र|Gotra]] or clan, or different clans may sometirnes  have made up a [[विश्|Viś]], while [[ग्राम|Grāma]] is more definitely, perhaps, a local designation. But the Vedic evidence is quite inconclusive.<ref name=fx11_ve2_1105/> ''Cf.'' '''[[विश्पति|Viśpati]].'''<br><br>In the later period the sense of [[विश्|Viś]] is definitely restricted in some cases<ref name=fx12_ve2_1105/> to denote the third of the classes of the Vedic polity, the people or clansmen as opposed to the nobles ('''[[क्षत्र|Kṣatra]], [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]''') and the priests ('''[[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]'''). For the position of this class, see '''Vaiśva.'''<br>

वि-शर
<u>'''Vi-śara'''</u> is found as the name of a disease, perhaps ‘tearing pains,’ in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1106/> Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_1106/> thinks that the pains in the limbs attendant on fever ('''[[तक्मन्|Takman]]''') are alluded to. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_1106/> sees in the word the name of a demon. The view of Zimmer is supported by the use of ''viśarīka,'' ‘rending,’ beside '''[[बलास|Balāsa]]''' in another passage.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1106/> <br>

वि-शाखे
<u>'''Vi-śākhe.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]]'''<br>

विश्-पति
<u>'''Viś-pati'''</u> is a word of somewhat uncertain signification, reflecting in this respect the nature of '''[[विश्|Viś]].''' Zimmer holds that in its strict sense it denotes the head of a canton, but he admits that there is no passage requiring this sense, the only one quoted by him<ref name=fx2_ve2_1108/> being certainly indecisive. In the great majority of passages the word simply means the ‘lord of the dwelling,’ whether used of a man or of the god Agni as the householder ''par excellence,'' or possibly as the fire of the '''[[सभा|Sabhā]]''' or assembly house of the people. This sense suits even the passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_1108/> in which the [[विश्पति|Viśpati]], as well as the father and the mother of a maiden,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1108/> are to be lulled to sleep in order to allow her lover to approach her, for the household may well be deemed to have been a joint family, in which the [[विश्पति|Viśpati]] could easily be different from the father of the girl--''e.g.,'' a grandfather or uncle. In other passages<ref name=fx6_ve2_1108/> the [[विश्पति|Viśpati]] is the king as ‘lord of the subject-people’ (''viśām''), though here Zimmer<ref name=fx7_ve2_1108/> thinks reference is made to the election of a king.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1108/> Or again,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1108/> the [[विश्पति|Viśpati]] is the chief of the [[विश्|Viś]], probably in the sense of ‘subjects.’(**  1) ''Altindisches Leben,'' 171.(**  9) ''E.g.,'' [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā, ii. 3, 1, 3, where [[विश्|Viś]] must clearly be the people or subject class, and the [[विश्पति|Viśpati]] their chief representative; we cannot from such a passage infer a formal office of [[विश्पति|Viśpati]] even as head of the [[विश्|Viś]].<br>

विश्पला
<u>'''Viśpalā'''</u> is, according to the tradition in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1109/> the name of a woman to whom the Aśvins gave an iron (''āyasī'')  limb to replace one lost by her in a contest. Pischel<ref name=fx2_ve2_1109/> considers that a racing horse miraculously cured of a broken limb by the Aśvins is meant, but this is no more than an improbable conjecture.<br>

विश्वक
<u>'''Viśvaka,'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1110/> called Kṛṣṇiya (possibly ‘son of '''[[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]]'''’) is a protégé of the Aśvins, who restored to him his lost son, '''[[विष्णापु|Viṣṇāpu]].''' See 2. '''[[कृष्ण|Kṛṣṇa]].'''<br>

विश्व-कर्मन् भौवन
<u>'''Viśva-karman Bhauvana'''</u> (‘descendant of Bhuvana’) is the name of a quite mythical king. He is said in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] to have been consecrated by '''[[कश्यप|Kaśyapa]],''' to whom he offered the earth (''i.e.,'' presumably a piece of land) as a sacrificial fee; in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1111/> he performed the Sarvamedha (‘universal sacrifice’), and made a similar offer; in both cases the earth refused to be given. The story seems to contain a reference to the early dislike of gifts of land,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1111/> but it cannot be stated with certainty that this is the meaning.<br><br>^1 viii. 21, 8.<br>

विश्वन्-तर सौ-षद्मन
<u>'''Viśvan-tara Sau-ṣadmana'''</u> (‘descendant of Suṣadman’) is the name in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1112/> of a prince who set aside the '''Śyāparṇas,''' his priests, and performed a sacrifice without their help, presumably with the aid of others. '''[[राम मार्गवेय|Rāma Mārgaveya]],''' one of the Śyāparṇas, however, succeeded in inducing the king to reinstate the Śyāparṇas, and to give him a thousand cows.<br>

विश्व-मनस्
<u>'''Viśva-manas'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] mentioned in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1113/> and as a frined of Indra in the Pañcaviṃśa  [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1113/> According to the Anukramaṇī (Index), he was a descendant of '''[[व्य्अश्व|Vyaśva]],''' and the author of certain hymns.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1113/><br>

विश्व-मानुष
<u>'''Viśva-mānuṣa'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1114/> may be a proper name, but more probably merely means ‘all mankind.’<br>

विश्व-वार
<u>'''Viśva-vāra'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1115/> apparently as the name of a sacrificer.<br>

विश्वा-सामन्
<u>'''Viśvā-sāman'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], an '''Atreya,''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1116/><br>

विश्व-सृज्
<u>'''Viśva-sṛj'''</u> is the name of certain mythical beings to whom, however, a Sattra, or sacrificial session, is ascribed in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxv. 18, 1 ''et seq.'').<br>

विश्वा-मित्र
<u>'''Viśvā-mitra'''</u> (‘friend of all’) is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] who is mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1118/> and to whom the third Maṇḍala is attributed by tradition. In one hymn<ref name=fx2_ve2_1118/> which appears to be his own composition, he praises the rivers '''[[विपाश्|Vipāś]]''' (Beas) and '''[[शुतुद्री|Śutudrī]]''' (Sutlej). There he calls himself the son of '''[[कुशिक|Kuśika]],''' and seems unquestionably to be the helper of the '''Bharatas,''' whom he mentions. The tribe, engaged in a raid, apparently came to the rivers from the east.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1118/> Anxious to cross them, they<br><br>^3 Rv. iii. 33, 5.  found them in high flood, but [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] by prayer induced the waters to subside. The same feat appears to be referred to in another passage of the same book of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1118/> Curiously enough, Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx6_ve2_1118/> quite misunderstands the situation: according to him, [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] having obtained wealth by the exercise of his office, went off with it to the rivers, pursued by others. Yāska's<ref name=fx7_ve2_1118/> version of the tale merely seems to mean that the king paid [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] to act as his '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]],''' or domestic priest. For the relations of [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] to [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]] connected with their service of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]], see [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]].'''<br><br>The Viśvāmitras are mentioned in several other passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx8_ve2_1118/> and are also designated as a family by the term '''Kuśikas.'''<ref name=fx9_ve2_1118/><br><br>In the later literature [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] becomes, like [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]], a mythical sage, usually<ref name=fx10_ve2_1118/> mentioned in connection with '''[[जमद्अग्नि|Jamadagni]];''' he was [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest at the sacrifice of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]],''' whom he adopted, and to whom he gave the name of '''[[देवरात|Devarāta]].'''<ref name=fx11_ve2_1118/> He was a protégé of Indra, with whom he had an interview according to the Rigveda Āraṇyakas.<ref name=fx12_ve2_1118/> He is also often mentioned as a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]].<ref name=fx13_ve2_1118/><br><br>In the Epic<ref name=fx14_ve2_1118/> [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] is represented as a king, who becomes a Brahmin. There is no trace of his kingship in the Rigveda, but the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx15_ve2_1118/> calls his father, [[कुशिक|Kuśika]], a king; the  [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx16_ve2_1118/> refers to [[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]] as succeeding to the lordship of the '''Jahnus,''' as well as the ‘divine lore’ (''[[दैव|daiva]] veda'') of the '''Gāthins;''' and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx17_ve2_1118/> mentions [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] as a king. But there is no real-trace of this kingship of [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]: it may probably be dismissed as a mere legend, with no more foundation at most than that [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]] was of a family which once had been royal. But even this is doubtful.<br>

विष
<u>'''Viṣa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1119/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1119/> regularly denotes ‘poison’ as an antidote, for which the Atharvaveda supplies spells.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1119/><br>

विष-विद्या
<u>'''Viṣa-vidyā,'''</u> the ‘science of poison,’ is enumerated with other sciences in the Āśvalāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (x. 75). ''Cf.'' '''[[विद्या|Vidyā]].'''<br>

विषाणा
<u>'''Viṣāṇā'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1121/> and later^2 denotes an animal's ‘horn.’<br>

विषाणका
<u>'''Viṣāṇakā'''</u> is the name of a plant in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1122/> Bloomfield,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1122/> however, thinks that the word may merely mean ‘horn.’ It is used as a remedy against the disease Vātīkāra.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1122/> That  disease is of doubtful character: Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve2_1122/> thinks that it is one ‘caused by wounds,’ comparing the adjective ''a-[[वात|vāta]],'' ‘uninjured,’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1122/> but Bloomfield<ref name=fx6_ve2_1122/> shows that ‘wind’ in the body is meant as causing the disease.<br>

विषाणिन्
<u>'''Viṣāṇin'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1123/> as the name of a tribe in the list of the enemies of the '''Tṛtsus,''' not as Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1123/> thought, of their allies. The word seems to mean ‘having horns,’ but in what sense is unknown; perhaps their helmets were horn-shaped or ornamented with horns. They may, like their allies, the '''Alinas, [[भलानस्|Bhalānas]], Śivas,''' and '''Pakthas,''' be reckoned as belonging to the tribes of the north-west.<br>

विषूवन्त्
<u>'''1. Viṣūvant'''</u> denotes in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1124/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1124/> the middle day in the Sattra or sacrificial session of a year's duration. Tilak<ref name=fx3_ve2_1124/> argues that the [[विषूवन्त्|Viṣūvant]] literally means the day when night and daylight are equal--''i.e.,'' the equinoctial day--and that this is the true sense of the word. But the theory is without probability.<br><br>^4 ''Cf.'' Whitney, ''Journal of the American Oriental Society,'' 16, ixxxiii. ''et seq.''<br>

विषूवन्त्
<u>'''2. Viṣūvant'''</u> occurs in the description of the house in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1125/> The meaning seems to be tha ‘ridge of the roof.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1125/> <br>

विषूचिका
<u>'''Viṣūcikā'''</u> is the name of a disease mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1126/> as a result of over-indulgence in '''Soma''' drinking. It seems clearly to be ‘dyser ery,’ or, as Wise calls it, ‘sporadic cholera.’ The term apparently means ‘causing evacuations in both directions.’(**  2) ''Hindu System of Medicine,'' 330.<br><br>''Cf.'' Zimmer, ''Altindisches Leben,'' 275, 392.<br>

वि-ष्कन्ध
<u>'''Vi-ṣkandha'''</u> occurs severai times in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1127/> as the name of a disease. As rem dies against it a lead amulet,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1127/> or hemp,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1127/> or a salve,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1127/> or the '''Ja giḍa''' plant are recommended for use.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1127/> Weber<ref name=fx6_ve2_1127/> suggests that the disease meant is ‘rheumatism,’ because it draws the shoulders apart (''vi-skandha''), but Bloomfield<ref name=fx7_ve2_1127/> thinks that it is rather the name of a demon, like the Rigvedic Vyaṃśa<ref name=fx8_ve2_1127/> and Vigrīva,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1127/> both of which are similarly formed and are names of demons. Possibly Karśapha and Viśapha mentioned in one hymn<ref name=fx10_ve2_1127/> are plants used to cure the disease.<br>

वि-ष्टारिन्
<u>'''Vi-ṣṭārin'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1128/> denotes a special sort of '''[[ओदन|Odana]]''' or porridge.<br>

विष्ठा-व्राजिन्
<u>'''Viṣṭhā-vrājin'''</u> is a word of doubtful significance in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1129/> According to Sāyaṇa, it means ‘remaining in one and the same place’; if this is right, the rendering of the  St. Petersburg Dictionary and of Bo7htlingk's Dictionary, ‘one whose herd is stationary,’ seems legitimate. But, as Eggeling<ref name=fx2_ve2_1129/> points out, the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] in another passage<ref name=fx3_ve2_1129/> seems to treat the word as denoting a disease: thus [[विष्ठाव्राजिन्|Viṣṭhāvrājin]] may mean ‘one afflicted by dysentery.’<br>

विष्णापु
<u>'''Viṣṇāpu'''</u> is the son of '''[[विश्वक|Viśvaka]]''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1130/> When lost he was restored to his father by the Aśvins.<br>

विष्फुलिङ्ग
<u>'''Viṣphuliṅga'''</u> denotes a ‘spark’ of fire in the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1131/><br>

विष्वक्-सेन
<u>'''Viṣvak-sena'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[नारद|Nārada]],''' mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the Sāmavidhāna [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<br>

विसल्य
<u>'''Visalya'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1133/> and '''Visalyaka'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1133/> are names of a disease in the Atharvaveda. Since Shaṅkar Paṇḍit's reciters<ref name=fx3_ve2_1133/> pronounced the word as Visalpaka in all the passages, that should probably be adopted as the right reading.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1133/> Some sort of pain is meant, perhaps ‘neuralgia,’ in connexion with fever.<br>

वि-स्रस्
<u>'''Vi-sras'''</u> denotes the ‘decay’ of old age, ‘decrepitude,’ ‘senility.’<ref name=fx1_ve2_1134/> <br>

विहल्ह
<u>'''Vihalha'''</u> is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1135/> apparently as the name of a plant. The forms Vihaṃla and Vihahla occur as variants.<br>

वीणा
<u>'''Vīṇā'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1136/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_1136/> denotes a ‘lute.’ A [[वीणा-वाद|Vīṇā-vāda]], ‘lute-player,’ is included in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1136/> and is also mentioned elsewhere.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1136/> The [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1136/> which states that the instrument was once covered with a hairy skin, enumerates its parts as Śiras, ‘head’ (''i.e.,'' neck); Udara, ‘cavity’; Ambhaṇa, ‘sounding board’; [[तन्त्र|Tantra]], ‘string’; and [[वादन|Vādana]], ‘plectrum.’ In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_1136/> the Uttaramandrā is either a tune or a kind of lute. ''Cf.'' '''[[वाण|Vāṇa]].'''<br>

वीणा-गाथिन्
<u>'''Vīṇā-gāthin'''</u> denotes ‘lute-player’ in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1137/> In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] Vīṇāgaṇagin denotes the ‘leader of a band.’(**  2) xiii. 4, 3, 3; 4, 2; [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], xvi. 1, 29.<br>

वीणा-वाद
<u>'''Vīṇā-vāda.'''</u> See '''[[वीणा|Vīṇā]].'''<br>

वीत-हव्य
<u>'''Vīta-havya'''</u> is the name of a prince who is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1139/> along with '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]],''' and as a contemporary of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1139/> though in both passages it is possible to understand the  word as a mere adjective. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1139/> [[वीतहव्य|Vītahavya]] appears as connected with '''[[जमद्अग्नि|Jamadagni]]''' and '''[[असित|Asita]],''' but it is clear that the legend there has no value. It is possible, though not certain, that he was a king of the '''Sṛṇjayas.'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1139/> In the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx5_ve2_1139/> a [[वीतहव्य|Vītahavya]] '''[[श्रायस|Śrāyasa]]''' appears as a king: he may be identical with the [[वीतहव्य|Vītahavya]] of the Rigveda, or belong to the same line. ''Cf.'' '''[[वैतहव्य|Vaitahavya]].'''<br>

वीर
<u>'''Vīra'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1140/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1140/> denotes ‘man’ as the strong and heroic. Collectively in the singular<ref name=fx3_ve2_1140/> the word denotes ‘male offspring,’ an object of great desire (''cf.'' '''[[पुत्र|Putra]]''') to the Vedic Indian. The [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_1140/> gives a list of eight Vīras of the king, constituting his supporters and entourage.<br>

वीरण
<u>'''Vīraṇa'''</u> is the form in the late Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 2) of the name of the plant '''[[वीरिण|Vīriṇa]].'''<br>

वीर-हत्या
<u>'''Vīra-hatyā,'''</u> ‘murder of a man,’ is one of the crimes referred to in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1142/> The [[वीर|Vīra]]-han, ‘man-slayer,’ is often mentioned in the older texts.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1142/> ''Cf.'' '''[[वैर|Vaira]].''' <br>

वीरिण
<u>'''Vīriṇa'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1143/> denotes a kind of grass (''Andropogon muricatus''). See '''[[वैरिण|Vairiṇa]].'''<br>

वीरुध्
<u>'''Vīrudh'''</u> means ‘plant’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1144/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1144/> As contrasted with '''[[ओषधि|Oṣadhi]],''' it denotes the inferior order of plants, but it often has practically the same sense as [[ओषधि|Oṣadhi]].<br>

वृक
<u>'''1. Vṛka,'''</u> ‘wolf,’ is mentioned frequently in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1145/> and also later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1145/> It was an enemy of sheep<ref name=fx3_ve2_1145/> and of calves,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1145/> being dangerous even to men.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1145/> Its colour is stated to be reddish (''aruṇa'').<ref name=fx6_ve2_1145/> The ‘she-wolf,’ Vṛkī, is also mentioned several times in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1145/><br>

वृक
<u>'''2. Vṛka'''</u> in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1146/> denotes ‘plough.’<br>

वृक-द्वरस्
<u>'''Vṛka-dvaras'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1147/> which Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_1147/> interprets as referring to a battle against [[वृकद्वरस्|Vṛkadvaras]], king of the '''Śaṇḍikas.''' But this is quite uncertain. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_1147/> and Oldenberg<ref name=fx4_ve2_1147/> incline to read ''vṛkadhvaras.'' Hillebrandt<ref name=fx5_ve2_1147/> suggests Iranian connections, but without any clear reason. <br>

वृक्ष
<u>'''Vṛkṣa'''</u> is the ordinary term for tree' in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1148/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1148/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1148/> it denotes the coffin made from a tree, no doubt by hollowing it out. The Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_1148/> refers to the portent of a tree secreting blood.<br>

वृक्ष-सर्पी
<u>'''Vṛkṣa-sarpī,'''</u> ‘tree-creeper,’ is the name of a species of worm or female serpent in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1149/><br>

वृक्ष्य
<u>'''Vṛkṣya'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 1, 1, 10) denotes the ‘fruit of a tree.’<br>

वृचया
<u>'''Vṛcayā'''</u> is referred to once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1151/> as the spouse given by the Aśvins to '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]].'''<br>

वृचीवन्त्
<u>'''Vṛcīvant'''</u> is the name of a tribe referred to once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1152/> where it is clearly stated that the '''[[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]]''' king, '''[[दैववात|Daivavāta]],''' conquered the '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]]''' king and the Vṛcīvants. Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_1152/> thinks that the Vṛcīvants and the [[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]] people should be identified, but this is both unnecessary and improbable; it is adequate to assume that they were allied against<ref name=fx3_ve2_1152/> the Sṛñjayas. The Vṛcīvants appear again only in the strange legend in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve2_1152/> according to which the '''Jahnus''' and the Vṛcīvants contended for sovereignty, '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]],''' the [[जह्नु|Jahnu]] king, winning it by his knowledge of a certain rite. See also '''[[हरियूपीया|Hariyūpīyā]].''' <br>

वृजन
<u>'''Vṛjana,'''</u> according to Roth,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1153/> denotes in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1153/> the ‘settlement’ or ‘village,’ the German ‘Mark’ and its inhabitants. Zimmer,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1153/> accepting this view, sees in [[वृजन|Vṛjana]] the ‘secure abode’ (''[[क्षिति|kṣiti]] [[ध्रुवा|dhruvā]]'') where the clan lives,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1153/> the clan itself as a village community (like '''[[ग्राम|Grāma]]'''), and the clan in war.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1153/> Geldner,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1153/> on the other hand, takes the literal sense of [[वृजन|Vṛjana]] ṭo be ‘net,’ developing all the other senses from that idea, but the traditional view seems more natural.<br>

वृत्र-घ्न
<u>'''Vṛtra-ghna'''</u> occurs in a passage of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1154/> where in a '''[[गाथा|Gāthā]]''' reciting the prowess of '''[[भरत|Bharata]]''' it is said that he bound horses on the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]]''' (Jumna) and '''[[गङ्गा|Gaṅgā]]''' (Ganges) ''Vṛtraghne,'' which Sāyaṇa renders ‘at [[वृत्रघ्न|Vṛtraghna]],’ as the name of a place. Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1154/> however, seems right in interpreting the form as a dative, ‘for the slayer of Vṛtra’--''i.e.,'' Indra.<br>

वृत्र-शङ्कु
<u>'''Vṛtra-śaṅku,'''</u> literally ‘Vṛtra-peg,’ found in one passage of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1155/> is said by the scholiast on the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1155/> to denote a stone pillar. This improbable interpretation is based on another passage in the same [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1155/><br>

वृद्ध-द्युम्न आभिप्रतारिण
<u>'''Vṛddha-[[द्युम्न|dyumna]] Ābhipratāriṇa'''</u> (‘descendant of Abhipratārin’) is the name of a prince (''[[राजन्य|rājanya]]'') in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 48, 9), where his priest, '''Śucivṛkṣa Gaupalāyana,''' is praised. In the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xv, 16, 10-13), on the contrary, he is said to have erred in the '''sacrifice,''' when a Brahmin prophesied that the result would be the expulsion of the '''Kurus''' from '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]], an event which''' actually came to pass. <br>

वृद्ध-वाशिनी
<u>'''Vṛddha-vāśinī'''</u> in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (v. 21) denotes the ‘female jackal.’<br><br>^1. '''Vṛśa.''' See '''[[वृष|Vṛṣa]].'''<br>

वृश जान
<u>'''2. Vṛśa Jāna'''</u> (‘descendant of Jana’) is the name of a famous [[पुरोहित|Purohita]], who was unfortunate enough, while with his royal master, '''Tryaruṇa,''' to see a boy killed by the chariot which the king drove too fast. He thereupon recalled the boy to life. The story is told briefly in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1158/> the Śāṭyāyanaka,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1158/> the Tāṇḍaka,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1158/> was also narrated in the [[भाल्लवि|Bhāllavi]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve2_1158/> and is preserved in the Bṛhaddevatā,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1158/> Sieg<ref name=fx6_ve2_1158/> has endeavoured to trace the story in part in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1158/> but there is a consensus of opinion<ref name=fx8_ve2_1158/> against the correctness of such a view.<br>

वृश्चिक
<u>'''Vṛścika'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1159/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1159/> denote ‘scorpion.’ Its poison was feared<ref name=fx3_ve2_1159/> like that of serpents. It is described as lying torpid in the earth during winter.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1159/><br>

वृष
<u>'''Vṛṣa'''</u> is the name of a plant of some kind in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1160/> Later the ''Gendarussa vulgaris'' is so styled. Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_1160/> has Vṛśa, which Bo7htlingk<ref name=fx3_ve2_1160/> takes to mean a small animal, a quite possible sense. ''Cf.'' '''[[येवाष|Yevāṣa]].''' <br>

वृष-खादि
<u>'''Vṛṣa-khādi'''</u> is used as an epithet of the Maruts in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1161/> The sense is doubtful: Bollensen<ref name=fx2_ve2_1161/> thought the expression referred to the wearing of rings in the ears; Max Müller<ref name=fx3_ve2_1161/> renders it ‘strong rings,’ comparing the later [[चक्र|Cakra]] or discus.<br>

वृष-गण
<u>'''Vṛṣa-gaṇa'''</u> is the name of a family of singers mentioned in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1162/><br>

वृषण्-अश्व
<u>'''Vṛṣaṇ-aśva'''</u> is the name of a man referred to in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1163/> where Indra is called '''[[मेना|Menā]],''' perhaps his ‘wife’ or ‘daughter.’ The same legend is alluded to in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1163/> the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1163/> the Ṣaḍviṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx4_ve2_1163/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1163/> but it is clear that all of these texts had no real tradition of what was referred to.<br>

वृष-दंश
<u>'''Vṛṣa-daṃśa,'''</u> ‘strong-toothed,’ is the name of the cat in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1164/> where it figures as a victim at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’). It also appears in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]];<ref name=fx2_ve2_1164/> the fact that the sneeze of the cat is here referred to renders it likely that the animal was already tamed. Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve2_1164/> sees a house cat in the animal alluded to in a hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_1164/> by a set of curious epithets, including ''vṛṣadatī,'' ‘strong-toothed,’ but Whitney<ref name=fx5_ve2_1164/> decisively rejects the idea that the hymn refers to the domestic cat. <br>

वृषन्
<u>'''Vṛṣan'''</u> in two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1165/> seems to denote a man, with the patronymic '''[[पाथ्य|Pāthya]]''' in one of them.<br>

वृषभ
<u>'''Vṛṣabha'''</u> regularly denotes a ‘bull’ in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1166/> but usually in a metaphorical sense.<br>

वृषल
<u>'''Vṛṣala'''</u> in the dicing hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1167/> denotes an ‘outcast’; the same sense appears in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1167/> where the touch of either a [[वृषल|Vṛṣala]] or a Vṛṣalī is to be avoided.<br>

वृष-शुष्म वातावत
<u>'''Vṛṣa-śuṣma Vātāvata'''</u> (‘descendant of Vātāvant’) '''[[जातूकर्ण्य|Jātūkarṇya]]''' is the name of a priest in the Brāhmaṇas of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1168/> Vṛṣaśuṣma in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1168/> is probably intended for the same name.<br>

वृषा-रव
<u>'''Vṛṣā-rava,'''</u> ‘roaring like a bull,’ is the name of some animal in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1169/> In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1169/> the word occurs in the dual, meaning perhaps ‘mallet’ or ‘drumstick.’<br>

वृष्टि
<u>'''Vṛṣṭi'''</u> is the regular word for ‘rain’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1170/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1170/> <br>

वृष्टि-हव्य
<u>'''Vṛṣṭi-havya'''</u> is in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1171/> the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], whose sons were the '''Upastutas.'''<br>

वेणु
<u>'''Veṇu'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1172/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1172/> denotes a ‘reed’ of bamboo, It is described in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_1172/> as ‘hollow’ (''su-ṣira''). In the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_1172/> it occurs only in a [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymn in a Dānastuti (‘praise of gifts’), where Roth<ref name=fx5_ve2_1172/> thinks that ‘flutes of reed’ are meant, a sense which [[वेणु|Veṇu]] has in the later texts. The [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_1172/> couples [[वेणु|Veṇu]] with '''[[सस्य|Sasya]],''' stating that they ripen in [[वसन्त|Vasanta]], ‘spring.’ Apparently bamboo reeds are meant.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1172/><br>

वेतस
<u>'''Vetasa'''</u> is the name of the water plant ''Calamus Rotang,'' or a similar reed, in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1173/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1173/> It is called ‘golden’ (''hiraṇyaya'') and ‘water-born’ (''apsuja'').<ref name=fx4_ve2_1173/><br><br>^3 Rv. ''loc. cit.;'' Av. x. 7, 41.<br>

वेतसु
<u>'''Vetasu'''</u> is a name occurring in the singular in two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1174/> and once in the plural.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1174/> It seems that he was defeated by Indra, but there is no reason to assume that he was a demon. Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_1174/> thinks that the Vetasus were probably the tribe of which '''[[दशद्यु|Daśadyu]]''' was a member, and that they defeated the '''Tugras.''' The passages are too obscure to render any version probable. <br>

वेतस्वन्त्
<u>'''Vetasvant,'''</u> ‘abounding in reeds,’ is the name of a place in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1175/> not, as Weber<ref name=fx2_ve2_1175/> once took it, a part of the name of '''Ekayāvan [[गांदम|Gāṃdama]].'''<br>

वेद
<u>'''Veda'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1176/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1176/> denotes ‘sacred lore.’ In the plural<ref name=fx3_ve2_1176/> it more definitely refers to the Vedas of the Ṛc, [[यजुस्|Yajus]], and Sāman. ''Cf.'' '''[[विद्या|Vidyā]].'''<br>

वेदाङ्ग
<u>'''Vedāṅga,'''</u> as the name of a text subsidiary to the study of the Rigveda, is first found in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1177/> and the Rigveda Prātiśākhya.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1177/><br>

वेन
<u>'''1. Vena'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1178/> as a generous patron. '''[[पृथवान|Pṛthavāna]],''' found in the same passage, may or may not be another name of his, and '''[[पार्थ्य|Pārthya]]''' in the following stanza of the hymn is perhaps his patronymic.<br>

वेन
<u>'''2. Vena'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1179/> is thought by Tilak<ref name=fx2_ve2_1179/> to be the planet Venus. But this is certainly impossible. <br>

वेश
<u>'''1. Veśa'''</u> is a term of somewhat doubtful sense, apparently denoting ‘vassal,’ ‘tenant,’ in a few passages,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1180/> and, according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1180/> ‘dependent neighbour.’<br>

वेश
<u>'''2. Veśa'''</u> may be a proper name in two passages of the Rigveda;<ref name=fx1_ve2_1181/> if so, it is quite uncertain whether a demon is meant or not.<br>

वेशन्ता
<u>'''Veśantā,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1182/> '''Veśantī,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1182/> '''[[वेशान्ता|Veśāntā]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1182/> all denote a ‘pond’ or ‘tank.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[वैशन्त|Vaiśanta]].'''<br>

वेशस्
<u>'''Veśas.'''</u> See 1. '''[[वेश|Veśa]].'''<br>

वेशान्ता
<u>'''Veśāntā.'''</u> See '''[[वेशन्ता|Veśantā]].'''<br>

वेशी
<u>'''Veśī'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1185/> seems to denote a ‘needle.’<br>

वेश्मन्
<u>'''Veśman,'''</u> ‘house,’ occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1186/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1186/> It denotes the house as the place where a man is ‘settled’ (''[[विश्|viś]]''). <br>

वेश्य
<u>'''Veśya'''</u> in two passages of the Rigveda (iv. 26, 3; vi. 61, 14) seems to denote the relation of ‘dependence’ rather than ‘neighbourhood.’ ''Cf.'' 1. '''[[वेश|Veśa]].'''<br>

वेष्क
<u>'''Veṣka'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 8, 1, 15) denotes the ‘noose’ for strangling the sacrificial animal. See '''[[ब्लेष्क|Bleṣka]].'''<br>

वेहत्
<u>'''Vehat'''</u> seems to mean a ‘cow that miscarries.’ It is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1189/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1189/><br>

वैकर्ण
<u>'''Vaikarṇa'''</u> occurs but once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1190/> in the description of the '''[[दाशराज्ञ|Dāśarājña]],''' where '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' is stated to have overthrown the twenty-one tribes (''janān'') of the kings or folk of the two Vaikarṇas. Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_1190/> conjectures that they were a joint people, the '''Kuru-Krivis:''' this is quite possible, and even probable. Vikarṇa as the name of a people is found in the Mahābhārata,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1190/> and a lexicographer<ref name=fx4_ve2_1190/> places the Vikarṇas in Kaśmīr, a reminiscence probably of a real settlement of the Kurus in that country. ''Cf.'' '''[[उत्तर कुरु|Uttara Kuru]].'''<br>

वैखानस
<u>'''Vaikhānasa'''</u> is the name of a mythical group of [[ऋषिस्|Ṛṣis]] who are said in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1191/> to have been slain at '''[[मुनिमरण|Munimaraṇa]]''' by '''[[रहस्यु देवमलिम्लुच्|Rahasyu Devamalimluc]],''' and who are mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka also.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1191/> An individual [[वैखानस|Vaikhānasa]] is '''[[पुरुहन्मन्|Puruhanman]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1191/> <br>

वैजान
<u>'''Vaijāna,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vijāna,’ is Sāyaṇa's version of the patronymic of '''Vṛśa''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1192/> The real reading is ''vai Jānaḥ,'' as pointed out by Weber.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1192/><br>

वैट्टभटी-पुत्र
<u>'''Vaiṭṭabhaṭī-putra'''</u> is the name in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 2) of a teacher, a pupil of '''Kāraśakeyīputra,''' ''Cf.'' '''[[वैदभृतीपुत्र|Vaidabhṛtīputra]].'''<br>

वैडव
<u>'''Vaiḍava,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Vīḍu,'''’ is the patronymic of a '''Vaisiṣṭha''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xi. 8, 14), where he is said to have been the seer of a Sāman or Chant.<br>

वैदूर्य
<u>'''Vaidūrya,'''</u> ‘beryl,’ is first '''found in''' the late Adbhuta [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1195/><br>

वैतरण
<u>'''Vaitaraṇa'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1196/> Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1196/> thinks the word is a patronymic, but it seems rather<ref name=fx3_ve2_1196/> to be an adjective in the sense of ‘belonging to Vitaraṇa’ used of Agni, like Agni of '''[[भरत|Bharata]]''' or of '''[[वध्र्य्अश्व|Vadhryaśva]].'''<br>

वैतहव्य
<u>'''Vaitahavya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[वीतहव्य|Vītahavya]],'''’ is the name of a family who are said in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1197/> to have come to ruin because they devoured a Brahmin's cow. They are said to be '''Sṛñjayas,''' but as the exact form of the legend here referred to does not occur elsewhere, its authenticity is open to some doubt.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1197/> According to Zimmer,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1197/> [[वैतहव्य|Vaitahavya]] is a mere epithet of the Sṛñjayas, but this is not probable<ref name=fx4_ve2_1197/> in view of the existence of a [[वीतहव्य|Vītahavya]]. <br>

वैद
<u>'''Vaida,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vida,’ is the patronymic of '''[[हिरण्यदन्त्|Hiraṇyadant]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1198/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1198/> The word is also written Baida.<br>

वैदथिन
<u>'''Vaidathina,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vidathin,’ is the patronymic of '''[[ऋजिश्वन्|Ṛjiśvan]]''' in the Rigveda (iv. 16, 11; v. 29, 13).<br>

वैदद्-अश्वि
<u>'''Vaidad-aśvi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vidadaśva,’ is the patronymic of [[तरन्त|Taranta]] in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1200/> In the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1200/> and the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1200/> the Vaidadaśvis are [[तरन्त|Taranta]] and '''Purumīlha.''' The latter is not a [[वैदद्अश्वि|Vaidadaśvi]] in the Rigveda, a clear sign of the worthlessness of the legends relative to these two men in the Brāhmaṇas.<br>

वैदभृती-पुत्र
<u>'''Vaidabhṛtī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Vedabhṛt,’ is the name of a teacher in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 32). ''Cf.'' '''[[वैट्टभटीपुत्र|Vaiṭṭabhaṭīputra]].'''<br>

वैदर्भ
<u>'''Vaidarbha,'''</u> ‘prince of [[विदर्भ|Vidarbha]],’ is applied to '''Bhīma''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 34, 9).<br>

वैदर्भि
<u>'''Vaidarbhi,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[विदर्भ|Vidarbha]],'''’ is the patronymic of a '''[[भार्गव|Bhārgava]]''' in the [[प्रश्न|Praśna]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 1; ii. 1).<br>

वैदेह
<u>'''Vaideha,'''</u> ‘prince of [[विदेह|Videha]],’ is the title of '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' and of '''[[नमी साप्य|Namī Sāpya]].'''<br>

वैधस
<u>'''Vaidhasa,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vedhas,’ is the patronymic of '''Hariścandra''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Brāhmana (vii. 13, 1) and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xv. 17. 1). <br>

वैन्य
<u>'''Vainya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Vena,'''’ is the patronymic of the mythic '''[[पृथि|Pṛthi]], Pṛthī,''' or '''[[पृथु|Pṛthu]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1206/><br>

वैपश्चित
<u>'''Vaipaścita'''</u> (‘descendant of '''Vipaścit'''’) '''[[दार्ढ-जयन्ति|Dārḍha-jayanti]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[दृढजयन्त|Dṛḍhajayanta]]'''’) '''[[गुप्त|Gupta]] [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[लोहित|Lohita]]'''’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[वैपश्चित|Vaipaścita]] [[दार्ढजयन्ति|Dārḍhajayanti]] [[दृढजयन्त|Dṛḍhajayanta]] [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]],''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1).<br>

वैपश्चित
<u>'''Vaipaścita'''</u> (‘descendant of '''Vipaścit'''’) '''[[दार्ढजयन्ति|Dārḍhajayanti]]''' (‘descendant of '''Dṛdhajayanta'''’) '''[[दृढजयन्त|Dṛḍhajayanta]] [[लौहित्य|Lauhitya]]''' (‘descendant of Lohita’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[विपश्चित् दृढजयन्त लौहित्य|Vipaścit <a class="pada_vei" href="दृढजयन्त">Dṛḍhajayanta]] Lauhitya»,''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1).<br>

वैयश्व
<u>'''Vaiyaśva,'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[व्य्अश्व|Vyaśva]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[विश्वमनस्|Viśvamanas]]''' in the Rigveda (viii. 23, 24, 24, 23; 26, 11).<br>

वैयाघ्रपदी-पुत्र
<u>'''Vaiyāghrapadī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Vyāghrapad,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[काण्वी-पुत्र|Kāṇvī-putra]],''' in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension of the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 5, 1).<br>

वैयाघ्र-पद्य
<u>'''Vaiyāghra-padya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Vyāghrapad,’ is the patronymic of '''Indradyumna [[भाल्लवेय|Bhāllaveya]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1211/> and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1211/> of '''[[बुडिल आश्वतराश्वि|Buḍila Āśvatarāśvi]]''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1211/> and of '''Gośruti''' in that [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_1211/> and in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1211/> In the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_1211/> the patronymic is applied to '''[[राम क्रातुजातेय|Rāma Krātujāteya]].''' <br>

वैयास्क
<u>'''Vaiyāska'''</u> is read in one passage of the Rigveda Prātiśākhya,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1212/> as the name of an authority on the metres of the Rigveda. Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1212/> is clearly right in thinking that '''[[यास्क|Yāska]]''' is meant.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1212/><br>

वैर
<u>'''Vaira'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1213/> and '''[[वैर|Vaira]]-deya'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1213/> seem to have in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas the definite and technical sense of ‘wergeld,’ the money to be paid for killing a man as a compensation to his relatives. This view is borne out by the Sūtras of Āpastamba<ref name=fx3_ve2_1213/> and [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_1213/> Both prescribe the scale of 1,000 cows for a '''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]],'''<ref name=fx5_ve2_1213/> 100 for a '''[[वैश्य|Vaiśya]],''' 10 for a '''[[शूद्र|Śūdra]],''' and a bull over and above in each case. Āpastamba leaves the destination of the payment vague, but [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] assigns it to the king. It is reasonable to suppose that the cows were intended for the relations, and the bull was a present to the king for his intervention to induce the injured relatives to abandon the demand for the life of the offender. The Āpastamba [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_1213/> allows the same scale of wergeld for women, but the [[गौतम|Gautama]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx7_ve2_1213/> puts them on a level with men of the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] caste only, except in one special case. The payment is made for the purpose of ''[[वैर|vaira]]-yātana'' or ''[[वैर|vaira]]-niryātana,'' ‘requital of enmity,’ ‘expiation.’<br><br>The Rigveda<ref name=fx8_ve2_1213/> preserves, also, the important notice that a man's wergeld was a hundred (cows), for it contains the epithet ''śata-[[दाय|dāya]],'' ‘one whose wergeld is a hundred.’ No doubt the values varied, but in the case of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]''' the amount is a hundred (cows) in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx9_ve2_1213/> In the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx10_ve2_1213/> ''śata-[[दाय|dāya]]'' again appears. <br><br>The fixing of the price shows that already public opinion, and perhaps the royal authority, was in Rigvedic times diminishing the sphere of private revenge; on the other hand, the existence of the system shows how weak was the criminal authority of the king (''cf.'' '''[[धर्म|Dharma]]''').<br><br>''Cf.'' Roth, ''Zeitschrift der Deutschen Morgenländischen Gesellschaft,'' 41, 672676; Bühler and von Schroeder, ''Festgruss an Roth,'' 44-52; Bühler, ''Sacred Books of the East,'' 2, 78, 79; 14, 201 Schrader, ''Prehistoric Antiquities,'' 402 Jolly, ''Recht und Sitte,'' 131, 132; Delbrück in Leist, ''Altarisches Jus Gentium,'' 297.<br>

वैर-हत्य
<u>'''Vaira-hatya,'''</u> ‘manslaughter,’ is mentioned in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xxx. 13) and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 5, 9, 5). ''Cf.'' '''Vīrahan.'''<br>

वै-राज्य
<u>'''Vai-rājya.'''</u> See '''[[राज्य|Rājya]].'''<br>

वैरूप
<u>'''Vairūpa,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[विरूप|Virūpa]],’ is the patronymic of '''Aṣṭādaṃṣṭra''' in the Pañcavimśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 9, 21).<br>

वैशन्त
<u>'''Vaiśanta'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1217/> of a prince whose offering Indra is said to have deserted for that of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' through the aid of the '''Vasiṣṭhas.''' Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_1217/> thinks that the name is Veśanta, and that he was a priest of the '''[[पृथु|Pṛthu]]-Parśus;''' Griffith<ref name=fx3_ve2_1217/> says that probably a river is meant, but neither of these views is plausible.<br>

वैशंपायन
<u>'''Vaiśaṃpāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Viśaṃpa,’ is the name of a teacher, famous later, but in the earlier Vedic literature known only to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (i. 7, 5) and the [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] Sūtras.<br>

वै-शालेय
<u>'''Vai-śāleya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Viśāla,’ is the patronymic of the mythic '''Takṣaka''' in the Atharvaveda (viii. 10, 29).<br>

वैशी-पुत्र
<u>'''Vaiśī-putra,'''</u> ‘the son of a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] wife,’ is mentioned in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1220/> <br>

वैश्य
<u>'''Vaiśya'''</u> denotes a man, not so much of the people, as of the subject class, distinct from the ruling noble ('''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]''') and the '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],''' the higher strata of the Āryan community on the one side, and from the aboriginal '''[[शूद्र|Śūdra]]''' on the other. The name is first found in the [[पुरुष|Puruṣa]]-[[सूक्त|sūkta]] (‘hymn of man’) in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1221/> and then frequently from the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1221/> onwards,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1221/> sometimes in the form of Viśya.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1221/><br><br>The [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] plays singularly little part in Vedic literature, which has much to say of [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] and Brahmin. His characteristics are admirably summed up in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1221/> in the adjectives ''anyasya bali-kṛt,'' ‘tributary to another’; ''anyasyādya,'' ‘to be lived upon by another’; and ''yathākāmajyeyaḥ,'' ‘to be oppressed at will.’ He was unquestionably taxed by the king ('''[[राजन्|Rājan]]'''), who no doubt assigned to his retinue the right of support by the people, so that the Kṣatriyas grew more and more to depend on the services rendered to them by the Vaiśyas. But the [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] was not a slave: he could not be killed by the king or anyone else without the slayer incurring risk and the payment of a wergeld ('''[[वैर|Vaira]]'''), which even in the Brahmin books extends to 100 cows for a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]. Moreover, though the [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] could be expelled by the king at pleasure, he cannot be said to have been without property in his land. Hopkins<ref name=fx6_ve2_1221/> thinks it is absurd to suppose that he could really be a landowner when he was subject to removal at will, but this is to ignore the fact that normally the king could not remove the landowner, and that kings were ultimately dependent on the people, as the tales of exiled kings show.<br><br>On the other hand, Hopkins<ref name=fx7_ve2_1221/> is clearly right in holding that the [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] was really an agriculturist, and that Vedic society was not merely a landholding aristocracy, superimposed upon an agricultural aboriginal stock, as Baden Powell<ref name=fx8_ve2_1221/> urged. Without ignoring the possibility that the Dravidians were agriculturists, there is no reason to deny that the Āryans were  so likewise, and the goad of the plougher was the mark of a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] in life<ref name=fx9_ve2_1221/> and in death.<ref name=fx10_ve2_1221/> It would be absurd to suppose that the Āryan Vaiśyas did not engage in industry and commerce (''cf.'' '''[[पणि|Paṇi]], [[वणिज्|Vaṇij]]'''), but pastoral pursuits and agriculture must have been their normal occupations.<br><br>In war the Vaiśyas must have formed the bulk of the force under the [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]] leaders (see '''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]'''). But like the Homeric commoners, the Vaiśyas may well have done little of the serious fighting, being probably ill-provided with either body armour or offensive weapons.<br><br>That the Vaiśyas were engaged in the intellectual life of the day is unlikely; nor is there any tradition, corresponding to that regarding the Kṣatriyas, of their having taken part in the evolution of the doctrine of [[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]], the great philosophic achievement of the age. The aim of the Vaiśya's ambition was, according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx11_ve2_1221/> to become a '''Grāmaṇī,''' or village headman, a post probably conferred by the king on wealthy Vaiśyas, of whom no doubt there were many. It is impossible to say if in Vedic times a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] could attain to nobility or become a Brahmin. No instance can safely be quoted in support of such a view,<ref name=fx12_ve2_1221/> though such changes of status may have taken place (see '''[[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]]''' and '''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]]''').<br><br>It is denied by Fick<ref name=fx13_ve2_1221/> that the Vaiśyas were ever a caste, and the denial is certainly based on good grounds if it is held that a caste means a body within which marriage is essential, and which follows a hereditary occupation (''cf.'' '''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]]'''). But it would be wrong<ref name=fx14_ve2_1221/> to suppose that the term [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] was merely applied by theorists to the people who were not nobles or priests. It must have been an early appellation of a definite class which was separate from the other classes, and properly to be compared with them. Moreover, though there were differences among Vaiśyas, there were equally differences among Kṣatriyas and Brāhmanas, and it is impossible to deny  the Vaiśyas' claim to be reckoned a class or caste it the other two are such, though at the present day things are different.<br><br>''Cf.'' Zimmer, ''Altindisches Leben,'' 213 ''et seq.;'' Weber, ''Indische Studien,'' 10, 1 ''et seq.;'' Muir, ''Sanskrit Texts,'' 1^2, 7 ''et seq.;'' Ludwig, Translation of the Rigveda, 3, 242, 243; Hopkins, ''Journal of the American Oriental Society,'' 13, 76 ''et seq.'' (for the Epic [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]).<br>

वैश्वा-मित्र
<u>'''Vaiśvā-mitra,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]],'''’ is the term by which that famous priest's line is referred to in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 17 ''et seq.'').<br>

वैष्ठ-पुरेय
<u>'''Vaiṣṭha-pureya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Viṣṭhapura,’ is the name of a teacher in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] in the Mādhyaṃdina recension (ii. 5, 20; iv. 5, 25). He was a pupil of '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]]''' and '''[[रौहिणायन|Rauhiṇāyana]].'''<br>

व्यछ
<u>'''Vyacha'''</u> in ''go-[[व्यछ|vyacha]],'' the name of one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1224/> is of uncertain signification. According to Sāyaṇa,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1224/> the compound denotes a ‘driver out of cows.’ Perhaps it means a ‘tormentor of cows,’ as the St. Petersburg Dictionary takes it. Weber<ref name=fx3_ve2_1224/> renders it as ‘knacker of cows,’ Eggeling as ‘one who approaches cows.’<br><br>^4 ''Sacred Books of the East,'' 44, 416.<br>

व्य्-अद्वर
<u>'''Vy-advara,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1225/> '''Vy-advarī,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1225/> are the names of a ‘gnawing’ (''ad,'' ‘eat’) animal in the Atharvaveda and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]. ''Cf.'' also '''[[व्यध्वर|Vyadhvara]],''' which the St. Petersburg Dictionary would read throughout. <br>

व्यध्वर
<u>'''Vyadhvara,'''</u> ‘perforating,’ designates a worm in one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1226/> where there seems to be no good reason to alter the reading to [[व्य्अद्वर|Vyadvara]], though Whitney<ref name=fx2_ve2_1226/> thinks that it may rather be connected with ''vi-adhvan''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1226/> than with the root ''vyadh,'' ‘pierce.’<ref name=fx4_ve2_1226/> The term occurs with '''[[मशक|Maśaka]],''' ‘fly,’ in the Hiraṇyakeśi [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx5_ve2_1226/> and perhaps also in another passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1226/> where, however, both Whitney<ref name=fx7_ve2_1226/> and Shaṅkar Paṇḍit read '''[[व्य्अद्वर|Vyadvara]].'''<br>

व्यल्कशा
<u>'''Vyalkaśā'''</u> is the name of a plant in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1227/><br>

व्य्-अश्व
<u>'''Vy-aśva'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]], a protégé of the Aśvins,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1228/> mentioned in several hymns of the eighth Maṇḍala,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1228/> which may have been the composition of a descendant of his, '''[[विश्वमनस्|Viśvamanas]].''' In two other passages<ref name=fx3_ve2_1228/> he is referred to only as a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] of the past, and Oldenberg<ref name=fx4_ve2_1228/> points out that none of his own work appears in the Saṃhitā. The Rigveda also mentions<ref name=fx5_ve2_1228/> the Vyaśvas, with whom Ludwig<ref name=fx6_ve2_1228/> is inclined to connect '''[[वश अश्व्य|Vaśa Aśvya]].''' An '''[[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]]''' [[व्य्अश्व|Vyaśva]] occurs as a seer of Sāmans or Chants in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx7_ve2_1228/><br>

व्य्-अष्टि
<u>'''Vy-aṣṭi'''</u> is the name of a mythical teacher in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka '''[[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1229/> <br>

व्या-ख्यान
<u>'''Vyā-khyāna'''</u> in one passage of the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1230/> clearly denotes a ‘narrative’ merely--viz., that of the dispute of [[कद्रू|Kadrū]] and Suparṇī. In other passages<ref name=fx2_ve2_1230/> the word means simply ‘commentary.’ In the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1230/> used in the plural, it signifies a species of writing, apparently ‘commentaries,’ though its exact relation to '''[[अनुव्याख्यान|Anuvyākhyāna]]''' must remain obscure. Sieg<ref name=fx4_ve2_1230/> thinks that the Vyākhyānas were forms of narrative like '''[[अन्वाख्यान|Anvākhyāna]]''' and [[अनुव्याख्यान|Anuvyākhyāna]].<br>

व्याघ्र
<u>'''Vyāghra,'''</u> ‘tiger,’ is never found in the Rigveda, but frequently occurs in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1231/> as well as the lion This fact is legitimately regarded as an indication that the Atharvaveda belongs to a period when the Vedic Indian had approached and entered the territory of Bengal. Later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1231/> also, mention of the tiger is quite common. The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_1231/> preserves a reference to the danger of waking a sleeping tiger. The destructive character of the animal is often alluded to,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1231/> the man-eater (''puruṣād'')<ref name=fx5_ve2_1231/> being also mentioned. Like the lion, the tiger passes as a symbol of strength.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1231/> This idea is illustrated by the fact that the king at the '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]]''' (‘royal consecration’) steps<ref name=fx7_ve2_1231/> on a tiger's skin to win himself the strength of the animal. ''Cf.'' also '''[[शार्दूल|Śārdūla]], [[पेत्व|Petva]].'''<br>

व्याघ्र-पद्य
<u>'''Vyāghra-padya'''</u> is a false reading in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (v. 16, 1) for '''[[वैयाघ्रपद्य|Vaiyāghrapadya]].''' <br>

व्याधि
<u>'''Vyādhi,'''</u> ‘disease,’ occurs several times in Vedic literature.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1233/> The specific diseases are dealt with under the separate names, but the Vedic texts also mention innumerable bodily defects. The list of victims<ref name=fx2_ve2_1233/> at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) includes a ‘dwarf’ (''vāmana, kubja''), a ‘bald’ person (''khalati''),<ref name=fx3_ve2_1233/> a ‘blind’ man (''andha''),<ref name=fx4_ve2_1233/> a ‘deaf’ man (''badhira''),<ref name=fx5_ve2_1233/> a ‘dumb’ man (''mūka''),<ref name=fx6_ve2_1233/> a ‘fat’ man (''pīvan''), a ‘leper’ (''[[सिध्मल|sidhmala]], [[किलास|kilāsa]]''),<ref name=fx7_ve2_1233/> a ‘yellow-eyed’ man (''hary-[[अक्ष|akṣa]]''), a ‘tawny-eyed’ man (''piṅgākṣa''), a ‘cripple’ (''[[पीठ|pīṭha]]-sarpin''), a ‘lame’ man (''srāma''), a ‘sleepless’ man (''jāgaraṇa''), a ‘sleepy’ man (''svapana''), one<ref name=fx8_ve2_1233/> ‘too tall’ (''ati-dīrgha''), one ‘too short’ (''ati-hrasva''), one ‘too stout’ (''ati-sthāla'' or ''aty-aṃsala''), one ‘too thin’ (''ati-[[कृश|kṛśa]]''), one ‘too white’ (''ati-[[शुक्ल|śukla]]''), one ‘too dark’ (''ati-[[कृष्ण|kṛṣṇa]]''), one ‘too bald’ (''ati-kulva''), and one ‘too hairy’ (''ati-lomaśa'').<br><br>In the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx9_ve2_1233/> the man with bad nails and the man with brown teeth are mentioned along with sinners like the '''[[दिधिषूपति|Didhiṣūpati]].''' The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx10_ve2_1233/> mentions a ‘white-spotted (''[[शुक्ल|śukla]]''), bald-headed man, with projecting teeth (''viklidha'') and reddish-brown eyes.’ Interesting is Zimmer's<ref name=fx11_ve2_1233/> suggestion that ''kirmira'' found in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx12_ve2_1233/> means ‘spotty’ as an intermixture of races, but it is only a conjecture, apparently based on a supposed connexion of the word with ''kṛ,'' ‘mix.’ In the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx13_ve2_1233/> and the  [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx14_ve2_1233/> various epithets are applied to women, some of which seem to denote disease, and in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx15_ve2_1233/> the feminine adjectives, ‘antelope-footed’ (''[[ऋश्य|ṛśya]]-padī'') and ‘bulltoothed’ (''[[वृष|vṛṣa]]-datī''), probably refer to bodily defects.<br>

व्य्-आन
<u>'''Vy-āna'''</u> is the name of one of the vital airs. See '''[[प्राण|Prāṇa]].'''<br>

व्याम
<u>'''Vyāma'''</u> in the Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1235/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_1235/> denotes the ‘span’ of the outstretched arms as a measure of length. It may be estimated at six feet or equivalent to a fathom.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1235/><br>

व्यास पाराशर्य
<u>'''Vyāsa Pārāśarya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[पराशर|Parāśara]]'''’) is the name of a mythical sage who in the Vedic period is found only as a pupil of '''[[विष्वक्सेन|Viṣvaksena]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teacheres) at the end of the Sāmavidhāna [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] and in the late [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1236/><br>

व्र
<u>'''Vra,'''</u> according to Roth,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1237/> means ‘troop’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1237/> and the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1237/> Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve2_1237/> sees in the word (in the feminine form of ''vrā'') a designation in one passage of the village host which formed part of the '''[[विश्|Viś]],''' and was composed of relations (''[[सु-बन्धु|su-bandhu]]''). On the other hand, Pischel<ref name=fx5_ve2_1237/> thinks that in all the passages Vrā means ‘female,’ used either of animals<ref name=fx6_ve2_1237/> or of  women who go to the feast ('''[[समन|Samana]]'''),<ref name=fx7_ve2_1237/> or courtezans (''viśyā,'' ‘of the people’),<ref name=fx8_ve2_1237/> or, metaphorically,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1237/> the hymns compared with courtezans; these senses are perhaps adequate.<br>

व्रज
<u>'''Vraja'''</u> denotes in the first instance, in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1238/> the place to which the cattle resort (from ''vraj,'' ‘go’), the ‘feeding ground’ to which the milk-giving animals go out<ref name=fx2_ve2_1238/> in the morning from the village ('''[[ग्राम|Grāma]]'''), while the others stay in it all day and night.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1238/> Secondarily it denotes the ‘herd’<ref name=fx4_ve2_1238/> itself. This is Geldner's view,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1238/> which seems clearly better than that of Roth<ref name=fx6_ve2_1238/> who regards [[व्रज|Vraja]] as primarily the ‘enclosure’ (from ''vṛj''), and only thence the ‘herd’; for the [[व्रज|Vraja]] does not normally mean an ‘enclosure’ at all: the Vedic cattle were not stall-fed as a general rule. In some passages, however, ‘pen,’<ref name=fx7_ve2_1238/> in others ‘stall,’<ref name=fx8_ve2_1238/> is certainly meant. The word is often used in the myth of the robbing of the kine.<ref name=fx9_ve2_1238/> It occasionally denotes a ‘cistern.’<ref name=fx10_ve2_1238/> <br>

व्रत
<u>'''Vrata'''</u> (‘vow’) in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1239/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_1239/> has the peculiar sense of the ‘milk’ used by one who is living on that beverage alone as a vow or penance.<br>

व्रतति
<u>'''Vratati'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1240/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1240/> denotes a ‘creeping plant.’<br>

व्राज-पति
<u>'''Vrāja-pati'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1241/> where it is said that comrades attend Indra, as the '''Kulapas''' the [[व्राजपति|Vrājapati]], when he goes about. Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_1241/> thinks that this refers to the heads of families being subordinate in war to the village headman ('''Grāmaṇī'''), but Whitney<ref name=fx3_ve2_1241/> seems to be right in seeing merely the chieftain surrounded by the leading men, the family heads, not necessarily merely a village headman. Vrāja alone occurs in one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1241/> adverbially in the sense of ‘in troops.’<br>

व्राज-बाहु
<u>'''Vrāja-bāhu'''</u> is used in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 9) of the ‘encompassing arms’ of death, Vrāja here apparently meaning a ‘pen,’ like '''[[व्रज|Vraja]].''' ''Cf.'' '''[[विष्ठा-व्राजिन्|Viṣṭhā-vrājin]].'''<br>

व्रात
<u>'''Vrāta'''</u> is found in several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1243/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1243/> in the sense of ‘troop.’ In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1243/> the troops of the Maruts are referred to by three different terms--''[[शर्ध|śardha]], [[व्रात|vrāta]],'' and ''gaṇa.'' From this fact Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve2_1243/> has  deduced that a Vedic host fought according to clan ('''[[विश्|Viś]]'''), village ('''[[ग्राम|Grāma]]'''), and family, but this conclusion is hardly warranted, there being nothing to show that there is any intention to present a distinct series of divisions. It is not probable that the word ever has the technical sense of ‘guild,’ as Roth<ref name=fx5_ve2_1243/> thinks. ''Cf.'' '''Vrātapati.'''<br>

व्रात-पती
<u>'''Vrāta-patī,'''</u> ‘lord of troops,’ is an epithet included in the names of Rudra in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1244/> along with the epithet Gaṇa-pati, ‘lord of groups.’ The exact sense is quite uncertain, but the term may allude to the chief of a band of robbers, as Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_1244/> thinks.<br>

व्रात्य
<u>'''Vrātya'''</u> is included in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1245/> where, however, no further explanation of the name is given. Fuller information is furnished by the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1245/> the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1245/> and the Sūtras.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1245/> which describe at length a certain rite intended for the use of Vrātyas. According to the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]], there are four different kinds of ‘outcasts’--viz., the ''hīna,'' who are merely described as ‘depressed’; those who have become outcasts for some sin (''nindita''); those who become outcasts at an early age, apparently by living among outcasts; and those old men who, being impotent (''śama-nīcameḍhra''), have gone to live with outcasts. The last three categories are by no means of the same importance as the first. The motive of the fourth is hard to understand: according to Rājārām Rām-  krishṇa Bhāgavat,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1245/> they were men who had enfeebled their constitutions by undue intercourse with women in the lands of the outcasts, and returned home in a debilitated state. But this is not stated in the text.<br><br>It seems probable that the really important Vrātyas were those referred to as ''hīna,'' and that the other classes were only subsidiary. According to Rājārām,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1245/> there were two categories of the first class: (''a'') The depressed (''hīna''), who were nonĀryan; and (''b'') degraded Āryans (''gara-gir''). This, however, is a mere guess, and devoid of probability. There seems to have been but one class of Vrātyas. That they were non-Āryan is not probable, for it is expressly said<ref name=fx7_ve2_1245/> that, though unconsecrated, they spoke the tongue of the consecrated: they were thus apparently Āryans. This view is confirmed by the statement that ‘they call what is easy of utterance, difficult to utter’: probable they and already a somewhat Prakritic form of speech (''cf.'' '''[[वाच्|Vāc]]'''). The Sūtras mention their Arhants (‘saints’) and Yaudhas (‘warrioes’), corresponding to the Brahminical [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] and [[क्षत्रिय|Kṣatriya]].<br><br>Other particulars accord with the view that they were Āryans outside the sphere of Brahmin culture. Thus they are said<ref name=fx8_ve2_1245/> not to practise agriculture or commerce (an allusion to a nomadic life), not to observe the rules of '''[[ब्रह्मचर्य|Brahmacarya]]'''--''i.e.,'' the principle regulating the Brahminic order of life. They were also allowed to become members of the Brahminical community by performance of the ritual prescribed, which would hardly be so natural in the case of non-Āryans.<br><br>Some details are given of the life and dress of the Vrātyas. Their principles were opposed to those of the Brahmins: they beat those unworthy of correction.<ref name=fx9_ve2_1245/> Their leder (Gṛhapati) or householder wore a turbrn ('''[[उष्णीष|Uṣṇīṣa]]'''), carried a whip ('''[[प्रतोद|Pratoda]]'''), a kind of bow ('''[[ज्याह्रोड|Jyāhroḍa]]'''), was clothed in a black (''kṛṣṇaśa'') garment and two skins ('''[[अजिन|Ajina]]'''), black and white (''[[कृष्ण|kṛṣṇa]]-valakṣa''), and owned a rough vagon ('''[[विपथ|Vipatha]]''') covered with planks  (''phalakāstīrṇa''). The others,<ref name=fx10_ve2_1245/> subordinate to the leader, had garments with fringes of red (''valūkāntāni dāmatūṣāṇi''), two fringes on each, skins folded double (''dviṣaṃhitāny ajināni''), and sandals ('''[[उपानह्|Upānah]]'''). The leader wore also an ornament ('''[[निष्क|Niṣka]]''') of silver, which Rājārām<ref name=fx11_ve2_1245/> converts into a silver coinage. The Vrātyas, on becoming consecrated, were expected to hand over their goods to the priest. Many other details are given in the Sūtras (''e.g.,'' that the shoes or sandals were of variegated black hue and pointed), but these are not authenticated by the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<br><br>The locality in which the Vrātyas lived cannot be stated with certainty, but their nomad life<ref name=fx12_ve2_1245/> suggests the western tribes beyond the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]. But they may equally well have been in the east: this possibility is so far supported by the fact that the Sūtras make the Brahmin receiving the gift of the Vrātya's outfit an inhabitant of '''[[मगध|Magadha]].''' The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx13_ve2_1245/> does not help, for it treats the [[व्रात्य|Vrātya]] in so mystical a way that he is represented as being in all the quacters. Indeed, Roth<ref name=fx14_ve2_1245/> believed that it was here not a case of the [[व्रात्य|Vrātya]] of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] at all, but of a glorification of the [[व्रात्य|Vrātya]] as the type of the pious vagrant or wandering religious mendicant ('''[[परिव्राजक|Parivrājaka]]'''). This view is clearly wrong, as the occurrence of the words ''uṣṇīsa, [[विपथ|vipatha]],'' and ''pratoaa'' shows. It is probable that the 15th Book of the Atharvaveda, which deals with the [[व्रात्य|Vrātya]], and is of a mystical character, exalts the converted [[व्रात्य|Vrātya]] as a type of the perfect '''Brahmicārin,''' and, in so far, of the divinity.<ref name=fx15_ve2_1245/> <br>

व्रीहि
<u>'''Vrīhi,'''</u> ‘rice,’ is never mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1246/> but is frequently alluded to in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1246/> and later.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1246/> Rice seems to be indigenous in the south-east of India:<ref name=fx4_ve2_1246/> this fact accounts well for the absence of any mention of it in the Rigveda. Black and white rice is contrasted in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1246/> where also<ref name=fx6_ve2_1246/> the distinctions of dark, swift-growing (''[[आशु|āśu]]''), and large rice (''mahā-[[व्रीहि|vrīhi]]'') are found. Probably the swift-growing variety is that later known as ''ṣaṣṭika,'' ‘ripening in sixty days.’ [[व्रीहि|Vrīhi]] and '''Yava,''' ‘barley,’ are normally conjoined in the texts.^7 ''Cf.'' '''[[प्लाशुक|Plāśuka]].'''<br>

व्लेष्क
<u>'''Vleṣka.'''</u> See '''[[ब्लेष्क|Bleṣka]].'''<br>

शंयु
<u>'''Śaṃyu'''</u> is the name of a mythical son of [[बृहस्पति|Bṛhaspati]]. He is quoted as a teacher in the texts of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1248/><br>

शकट
<u>'''Śakaṭa,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1249/> '''Śakaṭī,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1249/> are rare words in the older literature for a ‘cart.’ The creaking of a cart is referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1249/> as like the sound heard by night in the forest. <br>

शक-धूम
<u>'''Śaka-dhūma'''</u> is found in one hymn of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1250/> where it is celebrated as the king of the asterisms. The word seems to mean the ‘smoke of (burning) cow-dung,’ or else the ‘smoke (rising) from (fresh) cow-dung’: it may well be, as Weber<ref name=fx2_ve2_1250/> thinks, that this was deemed to be significant of the weather. Bloomfield,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1250/> however, considers that the word is to be rendered as ‘weather prophet,’ that is, one who foretells the weather by means of the smoke of a fire. Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve2_1250/> objects to this view with reason. It is not at all improbable that, as Roth<ref name=fx5_ve2_1250/> believed, an asterism of some sort is meant, probably the ‘milky way.’<br>

शकन्
<u>'''Śakan.'''</u> See '''[[शकृत्|Śakṛt]].'''<br>

शक-पूत
<u>'''Śaka-pūta'''</u> (‘purified by cow-dung’) is the name, apparently, of a prince, in one hymn of the Rigveda (x. 132, 5).<br>

शकं-भर
<u>'''Śakaṃ-bhara,'''</u> ‘bearer of dung,’ is found in one passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1253/> where the sense is doubtful. Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_1253/> and Grill<ref name=fx3_ve2_1253/> see in it a tribal name, Bloomfield<ref name=fx4_ve2_1253/> the personification of excessive evacuation (diarrhœa), while Whitney<ref name=fx5_ve2_1253/> considers that it may refer to the '''Mahāvṛṣas,''' despised as having to collect dung for fuel in the absence of wood in their country.<br>

शका
<u>'''Śakā'''</u> is the name of one of the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1254/> It is uncer-  tain whether a kind of bird<ref name=fx2_ve2_1254/> or fly,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1254/> or long-eared beast<ref name=fx4_ve2_1254/> is intended.<br>

शकुन
<u>'''Śakuna,'''</u> ‘bird,’ is mentioned frequently in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1255/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1255/> It usually denotes a large bird,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1255/> or a bird which gives omens.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1255/> Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve2_1255/> compares  which also is a bird of omen.<br>

शकुनि
<u>'''Śakuni,'''</u> ‘bird,’ is used practically like '''[[शकुन|Śakuna]],''' but with a much clearer reference to divination. It was smaller than the '''[[श्येन|Śyena]]''' or '''[[सुपर्ण|Suparṇa]],'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1256/> gave signs,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1256/> and foretold ill-luck.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1256/> When it is mentioned<ref name=fx4_ve2_1256/> in the list of sacrificial victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’), a special species must be meant: later the falcon is so called, but the ‘raven’ may be intended; the commentator on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā thinks that it is the ‘crow.’ It is mentioned several times elsewhere.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1256/><br>

शकुनि-मित्र
<u>'''Śakuni-mitra'''</u> is one of the names of '''Vipaścit [[पाराशर्य|Pārāśarya]]''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 41, 1).<br>

शकुन्त
<u>'''Śakunta'''</u> is a name for ‘bird’ in the Atharvaveda (xi. 6, 8). <br>

शकुन्तक
<u>'''Śakuntaka,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1259/> '''Śakuntikā,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1259/> are diminutives, meaning ‘little bird’ in the Saṃhitās.<br>

शकुन्तला
<u>'''Śakuntalā'''</u> is the name of an Apsaras who bore '''[[भरत|Bharata]],''' according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1260/> at '''[[नाडपित्|Nāḍapit]].''' Weber<ref name=fx2_ve2_1260/> doubtfully reads the latter word as Nāḍapitī, an epithet of [[शकुन्तला|Śakuntalā]].<br>

शकुन्ति
<u>'''Śakunti'''</u> is found in the Rigveda (ii. 42, 3; 43, 1) denoting a ‘bird’ of omen.<br>

शकुल
<u>'''Śakula'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1262/> denotes an unknown species of fish.<br>

शकृत्
<u>'''Śakṛt,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1263/> '''[[शकन्|Śakan]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1263/> denotes ‘dung’ in the Rigveda and later. It is clear that the value of manure was early appreciated (see '''[[करीष|Karīṣa]]'''). For the use of the smoke of dung or of a dung fire for prognosticating the weather, see '''[[शकधूम|Śakadhūma]].'''<br>

शक्ति
<u>'''1. Śakti'''</u> is said in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1264/> to have been the son of '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]],''' and to have been cast into the fire by the '''Viśvāmitras.''' According to Ṣaḍguruśiṣya,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1264/> who appears to follow the Śāṭyāyanaka,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1264/> the story of [[शक्ति|Śakti]] is as follows: [[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]], being defeated in a contest by [[शक्ति|Śakti]], had recourse  to '''[[जमद्अग्नि|Jamadagni]],''' who taught him the '''[[ससर्परी|Sasarparī]];''' later he revenged himself on [[शक्ति|Śakti]] by having him burnt in the forest. The Bṛhaddevatā<ref name=fx4_ve2_1264/> relates the first part of the tale only. Geldner<ref name=fx5_ve2_1264/> sees in the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve2_1264/> a description of the death struggle of [[शक्ति|Śakti]], but this interpretation is more than doubtful.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1264/><br>

शक्ती आङ्गिरस
<u>'''2. Śaktī Āṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]'''’) is the name of a seer of a Sāman or Chant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1265/><br>

शक्वरी
<u>'''Śakvarī,'''</u> fem. plur., denotes the [[शक्वरी|Śakvarī]] verses, known also as the Mahānāmnī verses, to which the [[शाक्वर|Śākvara]] Sāman (chant) is sung. This sense seems to occur in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1266/> and is certain later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1266/><br>

शङ्कु
<u>'''Śaṅku'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1267/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1267/> denotes a ‘wooden peg.’ Thus the '''term''' is used of the pags by which a skin is stretched out in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1267/> and of the pin of hobbles ('''[[पड्बीश|Paḍbīśa]]''').<ref name=fx4_ve2_1267/> '''In''' the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1267/> it may mean ‘stalk’<ref name=fx6_ve2_1267/> or ‘fibre of a '''leaf.'''’<ref name=fx7_ve2_1267/> <br>

शङ्ख
<u>'''1. Śaṅkha'''</u> in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1268/> with the epithet '''[[कृशन|Kṛśana]],''' denotes a pearl-shell used as an amulet. In the later literature<ref name=fx2_ve2_1268/> it denotes a ‘shell’ or ‘conch’ used for blowing as a wind instrument.<br>

शङ्ख कौष्य
<u>'''2. Śaṅkha Kauṣya'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher whom '''[[जात शाकायन्य|Jāta Śākāyanya]]''' criticized in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xxii. 7; ''cf.'' 6).<br>

शङ्ख बाभ्रव्य
<u>'''3. Śaṅkha Bābhravya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[बभ्रु|Babhru]]'''’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[राम|Rāma]],''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 41, 1; iv. 17, 1).<br>

शङ्ख-धम
<u>'''Śaṅkha-dhama,'''</u> a ‘conch-blower,’ is enumerated among the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1271/> and is mentioned in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1271/><br>

शङ्ग शाट्यायनि
<u>'''Śaṅga Śāṭyāyani'''</u> (‘descendant of Śāṭyāyana’) '''[[आत्रेय|Ātreya]]''' (‘descendant of '''Atri'''’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''Nagarin,''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 1).<br>

शचीवन्त्
<u>'''Śacīvant'''</u> is apparently the name of a man in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1273/> where the vocative ''Śacīvaḥ'' occurs. But Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1273/> perfers to read ''Śacī ca'' instead.<br>

शण
<u>'''Śaṇa'''</u> denotes a kind of ‘hemp’ (''Cannabis sativa'' or ''Crotolaria juncea''). It is mentioned in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1274/> as growing in the forest, and as used like the '''[[जङ्गिड|Jaṅgiḍa]]''' as a remedy against '''[[विष्कन्ध|Viṣkandha]].''' It also occurs in the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1274/> <br>

शण्ड
<u>'''Śaṇḍa'''</u> is joined with '''[[मर्क|Marka]]''' as a [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of the Asuras in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1275/> and Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1275/><br>

शण्डिक
<u>'''Śaṇḍika'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1276/> in the plural. According to Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1276/> the hymn is a prayer for victory over the Śaṇḍikas and their king.<br>

शत-द्युम्न
<u>'''Śata-dyumna'''</u> (‘possessing a hundred glories’) is the name of a man who, along with '''[[यज्ञेषु|Yajñeṣu]],''' was made prosperous by the priest '''[[मात्स्य|Mātsya]]''' through his knowledge of the exact moment for sacrifice, according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 5, 2, 1).<br>

शत-पति
<u>'''Śata-pati'''</u> occurs in a verse of the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1278/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1278/> as an epithet of Indra, who is described as alone the ‘lord of a hundred’ among men. To interpret the expression as ‘lord of a hundred gods,’ as does the commentary on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], is obviously impossible. It seems clear that there is a reference to an analogous human functionary--viz., the lord of a hundred villages, known in the later law<ref name=fx3_ve2_1278/> --who was probably at once a judicial deputy of the sovereign and a revenue collector, an ancient magistrate and collector.<br>

शत-बलाक्ष मौद्गल्य
<u>'''Śata-balākṣa Maudgalya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[मुद्गल|Mudgala]]'''’) is the name of a grammarian in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (xi. 6).<br>

शत-मान
<u>'''Śata-māna.'''</u> See '''[[मान|Māna]]''' and '''Kṛṣṇaia.''' <br>

शत-यातु
<u>'''Śata-yātu'''</u> (‘having a hundred magic powers’) is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1281/> He is enumerated after '''[[पराशर|Parāśara]]''' and before '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]].''' Geldner<ref name=fx2_ve2_1281/> thinks he may have been a son of [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]].<br>

शत-रुद्रिय
<u>'''Śata-rudriya,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1282/> '''Śata-rudrīya'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1282/> (hymn ‘relating to the hundred Rudras’), is the name of a section of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1282/> which celebrates the god Rudra in his hundred aspects, enumerating his many epithets.<br>

शत-शारद
<u>'''Śata-śārada'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1283/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1283/> denotes a ‘period of a hundred autumns’ or years.<br>

शतानीक सात्राजित
<u>'''Śatānīka Sātrājita'''</u> is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Brāhmana<ref name=fx1_ve2_1284/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1284/> as a great king who defeated '''[[धृतराष्ट्र|Dhṛtarāṣṭra]],''' the prince of '''[[काशि|Kāśi]],''' and took away his sacrificial horse. He was clearly a '''[[भरत|Bharata]].''' He is also alluded to in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1284/><br>

शत्रि आग्नि-वेशि
<u>'''Śatri Āgni-veśi'''</u> (‘descendant of Agniveśa’) is the name of a generous patron in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1285/><br>

शत्रु
<u>'''Śatru'''</u> denotes ‘enemy’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1286/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1286/> <br>

शं-तनु
<u>'''Śaṃ-tanu'''</u> is the hero of a tale told by [[यास्क|Yāska]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1287/> and often found later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1287/> He supersedes his elder brother '''Devāpi''' as king of the '''Kurus.''' When his improper deed brings on a prolonged drought in his realm, he is compelled to ask his brother to assume the kingship; Devāpi, however, refuses, but instead performs a sacrifice which produces rain. Sieg<ref name=fx3_ve2_1287/> endeavours to trace this story in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1287/> but all that is there stated is that Devāpi '''Ārṣṭiṣeṇa''' obtained (no doubt as priest) rain for [[शंतनु|Śaṃtanu]] (no doubt a king). There is no hint of relationship at all.<br>

शपथ
<u>'''Śapatha'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1288/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1288/> denotes a ‘curse,’ not an ‘oath,’ as a judicial process. But that an oath of such a kind was possible as it was later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1288/> is shown by at least one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1288/> where the speaker, possibly '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]],''' imprecates death on himself if he is a wizard, and death on his foes if he is not.<br>

शफ
<u>'''1. Śapha,'''</u> ‘hoof,’ comes to be used to denote the fraction ‘one-eighth,’ because of the divided hoofs of the cow, just as '''[[पाद|Pāda]],''' the ‘foot’ of a quadruped, also means a ‘quarter.’ This sense in found as early as the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1289/> and is not rare later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1289/><br>

शफ
<u>'''2. Śapha'''</u> in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1290/> is the name (used in the dual) of a wooden implement, acting like a pair of tongs, for lifting an iron pot from the fire. It is probably so called because it resembled a hoof in being divided. <br>

शफक
<u>'''Śaphaka'''</u> is the name of some plant in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1291/> It is also mentioned in the Āpastamba Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1291/> where it seems to denote an edible water plant or fruit, perhaps a water nut. It may be so called from its leaves being shaped like hoofs ('''[[शफ|Śapha]]''').<br>

शफाल
<u>'''Śaphāla'''</u> is the name of '''Ṛtuparṇa's''' kingdom in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta Sātra.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1292/><br>

सबर
<u>'''Sabara'''</u> is the name of a wild tribe who in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1293/> are classed as '''Dasyus,''' with the '''Andhras, Pulindas, Mūtibas,''' and '''Puṇḍras.'''<br>

शमितृ
<u>'''Śamitṛ'''</u> denotes the ‘man who cuts up’ the slaughtered animal in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1294/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1294/> sometimes having merely the sense of ‘cook.’<br>

शमी
<u>'''Śamī'''</u> is the name of a tree in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1295/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1295/> It is described in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1295/> as destructive to the hair,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1295/> as producing intoxication, and as broad-leaved. These characteristics are totally wanting in the two trees, ''Prosopis spicigera'' or ''Mimosa suma,'' with which the [[शमी|Śamī]] is usually identified.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1295/>  From the soft wood of the [[शमी|Śamī]] was formed the lower of the two sticks (''[[अरणी|araṇī]]'') used for kindling the sacred fire,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1295/> the upper one (the drill) being of '''[[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]].''' The fruit of the tree is called Śamīdhānya.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1295/><br>

शम्बर
<u>'''Śambara'''</u> is the name of an enemy of Indra in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1296/> He is mentioned along with '''Śuṣṇa, [[पिप्रु|Pipru]],''' and '''[[वर्चिन्|Varcin]],''' being in one passage called a '''[[दास|Dāsa]],''' son of Kulitara.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1296/> In another passage<ref name=fx3_ve2_1296/> he is said to have deemed himself a godling (''devaka''). His forts, ninety,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1296/> ninety-nine,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1296/> or a hundred<ref name=fx6_ve2_1296/> in number, are alluded to, the word itself in the neuter plural once<ref name=fx7_ve2_1296/> meaning the ‘forts of [[शम्बर|Śambara]].’ His great foe was '''[[दिवोदास अतिथिग्व|Divodāsa Atithigva]],''' who won victories over him by Indra's aid.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1296/><br><br>It is impossible to say with certainty whether [[शम्बर|Śambara]] was a real person or not. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx9_ve2_1296/> is strongly in favour of the theory that he was a real chief as enemy of Divodāsa: he relies on the statistics<ref name=fx10_ve2_1296/> of the mention of the name to show that, where as he was conceived as a real foe in the hymns of the time of Divodāsa, later texts, like those of the seventh Maṇḍala, make him into a demon, as a result of the change of scene from Arachosia to India. As a matter of fact, apart from this theory, [[शम्बर|Śambara]] was quite possibly an aboriginal enemy in India, living in the mountains.<ref name=fx11_ve2_1296/> <br>

शम्बिन्
<u>'''Śambin,'''</u> a word occurring only once, appears to mean ‘ferryman’ in the Atharvaveda (ix. 2, 6). The literal sense is probably ‘pole-man’ (from ''śamba,'' a word of doubtful signification found in the Rigveda, x. 42, 7).<br>

शंमद् आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Śaṃmad Āṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]'''’) is the name of the seer of a Sāman or Chant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xv. 5, 11).<br><br>''Cf.'' Hillebrandt, ''Vedische Mythologic.'' 2, 160.<br>

शम्या
<u>'''Śamyā'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1299/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1299/> a ‘peg,’ more particularly one on the millstone;<ref name=fx3_ve2_1299/> and on the yoke,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1299/> where it seems to mean the pin of wood attached to either end so as to keep the yoke in place on the ox's neck.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1299/> The [[शम्या|Śamyā]] was also used as a measure of length.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1299/><br>

शयण्डक
<u>'''Śayaṇḍaka.'''</u> See '''[[शयाण्डक|Śayāṇḍaka]].'''<br>

शयन
<u>'''Śayana'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1301/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1301/> denotes a ‘couch.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[तल्प|Talpa]], [[वह्य|Vahya]].'''<br>

शयाण्डक
<u>'''Śayāṇḍaka'''</u> is the form in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1302/> of the name of an animal which in the Maitrāyaṇī<ref name=fx2_ve2_1302/> and Vājasaneyi Saṃhitās<ref name=fx3_ve2_1302/> is written as [[शयण्डक|Śayaṇḍaka]]. Some sort of bird is meant according to Roth,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1302/> but the commentator on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā equates the word with '''[[कृकलास|Kṛkalāsa]],''' ‘chameleon.’ <br>

शयु
<u>'''Śayu'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1303/> of a protégé of the Aśvins, who made his cow to give milk.<br>

शर
<u>'''1. Śara'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1304/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1304/> denotes a kind of ‘reed’ (''Saccharum Sara''). Its use for arrow shafts,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1304/> and its brittleness,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1304/> are expressly referred to in the Atharvaveda. ''Cf.'' '''[[शर्य|Śarya]].'''<br>

शर अर्चत्क
<u>'''2. Śara Arcatka'''</u> (‘descendant of Ṛcatka’) is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1305/> It is very doubtful, however, whether Ārcatka is really a patronymic.<br>

शर शौर-देव्य
<u>'''3. Śara Śaura-devya'''</u> (‘descendant of Śūradeva’) is the name of a generous prince in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1306/> who gave one calf to three singers. That this Dānastuti (‘praise of gifts’) is ironical seems certain.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1306/><br>

शरद्
<u>'''Śarad.'''</u> See '''[[ऋतु|Ṛtu]].'''<br>

शरभ
<u>'''1. Śarabha'''</u> is the name of some wild animal in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1308/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1308/> In the '''classical''' literature it is a fabulous, eight-legged beast, dwelling in the snowy mountains, a foe of lions and elephants: the commentator Mahīdhara sees this sense, but without reason, in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā. The  animal is spoken of as akin to the goat;<ref name=fx3_ve2_1308/> it was probably a kind of deer.<br>

शरभ
<u>'''2. Śarabha'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1309/><br>

शरव्या
<u>'''Śaravyā,'''</u> ‘arrow-shot,’ is an expression found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1310/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1310/><br>

शराव
<u>'''Śarāva'''</u> is a measure of corn in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1311/><br>

शरीर
<u>'''Śarīra,'''</u> ‘body,’ is a word of frequent occurrence in Vedic literature.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1312/> The interest of the Vedic Indians seems early to have been attracted to the consideration of questions connected with the anatomy of the body. Thus a hymn of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1312/> enumerates many parts of the body with some approach to accuracy and orderly arrangement.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1312/> It mentions the heels (''pārṣṇī''), the flesh (''[[मांस|māṃsa]]''), the ankle-bones (''gulphau''), the fingers (''aṅgulīḥ''), the apertures (''kha''), the two metatarsi (''uchlakau''), the tarsus (''[[प्रतिष्ठा|pratiṣṭhā]]''), the two knee-caps (''aṣṭhīvantau''), the two legs (''jaṅghe''), the two knee-joints (''jānunoḥ sandhī''). Then comes above the two kness (''jānū'') the foursided (''catuṣṭaya''), pliant (''śithira'') trunk (''kabandha''). The two hips (''śroṇī'') and the two thighs (''ārū'') are the props of the frame  (''kusindha''). Next come the breast-bone (''uras''), the cervical cartilages (''grīvāḥ''), the two breast pieces (''stanau''), the two shoulder-blades (''kaphoḍau''), the neck-bones (''skandhau''), and the backbones (''pṛṣṭīḥ''), the collar-bones (''aṃsau''), the arms (''bāhū''), the seven apertures in the head (''sapta khāni śīrṣaṇi''), the ears (''karṇau''), the nostrils (''nāsike''), the eyes (''cakṣaṇī''), the mouth (''mukha''), the jaws (''hanū''), the tongue (''jihvā''), the brain (''mastiṣka''), the forehead (''lalāṭa''), the facial bone (''kakāṭikā''), the cranium (''kapāla''), and the structure of the jaws (''cityā hanvoḥ'').<br><br>This system presents marked similarities with the later system of [[चरक|Caraka]] and Suśruta,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1312/> which render certain the names ascribed to the several terms by Hoernle. ''Kaphoḍau,'' which is variously read in the manuscripts,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1312/> is rendered ‘collar-bone’ by Whitney, but ‘elbow’ in the St. Petersburg Dictionary. ''Skandha'' in the plural regularly<ref name=fx6_ve2_1312/> denotes ‘neck-bones,’ or, more precisely, ‘cervical vertebræ,’ a part denoted also by ''uṣṇihā'' in the plural.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1312/> ''Pṛṣṭī''<ref name=fx8_ve2_1312/> denotes not ‘rib,’ which is ''[[पर्शु|parśu]],''<ref name=fx9_ve2_1312/> but a transverse process of a vertebra, and so the vertebra itself, there being in the truncal portion of the spinal column seventeen vertebræ and thirty-four transverse processes. The vertebræ are also denoted by ''kīkasā'' in the plural,<ref name=fx10_ve2_1312/> which sometimes<ref name=fx11_ve2_1312/> is limited to the upper portion of the vertebral column, sometimes<ref name=fx12_ve2_1312/> to the thoracic portion of the spine. ''Anūka'' also denotes the vertebral column,<ref name=fx13_ve2_1312/> or more specially the lumbar<ref name=fx14_ve2_1312/> or thoracic<ref name=fx15_ve2_1312/> portion of the spine; it is said in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx15_ve2_1312/>  that there are twenty transverse processes in the lumbar spine (''udara'') and thirty-two in the thoracic, which gives twenty-six vertebræ, the true number (but the modern division is seven cervical, twelve thoracic, five lumbar, and two false--the sacrum and the coccyx). The vertebral column is also denoted by ''karūkara,''<ref name=fx16_ve2_1312/> which, however, is usually found in the plural<ref name=fx17_ve2_1312/> denoting the transverse processes of the vertebræ, a sense expressed also by ''kuntāpa.''<ref name=fx18_ve2_1312/><br><br>''Grīvā,'' in the plural, denotes cervical vertebræ, the number seven being given by the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx19_ve2_1312/> but usually<ref name=fx20_ve2_1312/> the word simply means windpipe, or, more accurately, the cartilaginous rings under the skin. '''Jatru,''' also in the plural, denotes the cervical cartilages,<ref name=fx21_ve2_1312/> or possibly the costal cartilages, which are certainly so called in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx22_ve2_1312/> where their number is given as eight.<br><br>''Bhaṃsas,'' which occurs thrice in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx23_ve2_1312/> seems to denote the pubic bone or arch rather than the ‘buttocks’ or ‘fundament,’ as Whitney<ref name=fx24_ve2_1312/> takes it.<br><br>In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx25_ve2_1312/> the number of bones in the the human body is given as 360. The number of the bones of the head and trunk are given in another passage<ref name=fx26_ve2_1312/> as follows: The head is threefold, consisting of skin (''tvac''), bone (''asthi''), brain (''matiṣka''); the neck has 15 bones: 14 transverse processes (''karūkara'') and the strength (''vīrya'')--''i.e.,'' the bone of the centre regarded as one--as the 15th; the breast has 17: 16 cervical cartilages (''jatru''), and the sternum (''uras'') as the 17th; the abdominal portion of the spine has 21: 20 trans-  verse processes (''kuntāpa''), and the abdominal portion (''udara'') as the 21st; the two sides have 27: 26 ribs (''[[पर्शु|parśu]]''), and the two sides as the 27th; the thoracic portion of the spine (''anūka'') has 33: 32 transverse processes, and the thoracic portion as 33rd.<br><br>There are several enumerations of the parts of the body, not merely of the skeleton, in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx27_ve2_1312/> They include the hair (''lomāni''), skin (''tvac''), flesh (''[[मांस|māṃsa]]''), bone (''asthi''), marrow (''majjan''), liver (''yakṛt''), lungs (''kloman''), kidneys (''matasne''), gall (''pitta''), entrails (''āntrāṇi''), bowels (''gudāḥ''), spleen (''plīhan''), navel (''[[नाभि|nābhi]]''), belly (''udara''), rectum (''vaniṣṭhu''), womb (''yoni''), penis (''plāśi'' and ''śepa''), face (''mukha''), head (''śiras''), tongue (''jihvā''), mouth (''āsan''), rump (''[[पायु|pāyu]]''), leech (''[[वाल|vāla]]''), eye (''[[चक्षुस्|cakṣus]]''), eyelashes (''pakṣmāṇi''), eyebrows (''utāni''), nose (''nas''), breath (''[[व्य्आन|vyāna]]''), nose-hairs (''nasyāni''), ears (''karṇau''), brows (''bhrū''), body or trunk (''ātman''), waist (''upastha''), hair on the face (''śmaśrūṇi''), and on the head (''keśāḥ''). Another enumeration<ref name=fx28_ve2_1312/> gives ''śiras, mukha, keśāḥ, śmaśrūṇi, [[प्राण|prāṇa]]'' (breath), ''[[चक्षुस्|cakṣus]], śrotra'' (ear), ''jihvā, [[वाच्|vāc]]'' (speech), ''manas'' (mind), ''aṅgulīḥ, aṅgāni'' (limbs), ''bāhū, hastau'' (hands), ''karṇau, ātmā, uras'' (sternum), ''pṛṣṭīḥ'' (vertebræ), ''udara, aṃsau, grīvāḥ, śroṇī, ūrū, aratnī'' (elbows), ''jānūni, [[नाभि|nābhi]], [[पायु|pāyu]], bhasat'' (fundament), ''āṇḍau'' (testicles), ''pasas'' (membrum virile), ''jaṅghā, pad'' (foot), ''lomāni, tvac, [[मांस|māṃsa]], asthi, majjan.'' Another set of names<ref name=fx29_ve2_1312/> includes ''vaniṣṭhu, purītat'' (pericardium), ''lomāni, tvac, [[लोहित|lohita]]'' (blood), ''medas'' (fat), ''māṃsāni, snāvāni'' (sinews), ''asthīni, majjānaḥ, retas'' (semen), ''[[पायु|pāyu]], kośya'' (flesh near the heart), ''pārśvya'' (intercostal flesh), etc.<br><br>The bones of the skeleton of the horse are enumerated in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx30_ve2_1312/><br><br>In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx31_ve2_1312/> the human body is regarded as made up of one hundred and one items; there are four parts,  each of twenty-five members, with the trunk as one hundred and first. In the two upper parts there are five four-jointed<ref name=fx32_ve2_1312/> fingers, two ''kakṣasī'' (of uncertain meaning),<ref name=fx33_ve2_1312/> the arm (''dos''), the collar-bone (''[[अक्ष|akṣa]]''), and the shoulder-blade (''aṃsa-[[फलक|phalaka]]''). In the two lower portions there are five four-jointed toes, the thigh, the leg, and three articulations, according to Sāyaṇa's commentary.<br><br>The [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx34_ve2_1312/> enumerates three bones in the head,<ref name=fx35_ve2_1312/> three joints (''parvāṇi'') in the neck,<ref name=fx36_ve2_1312/> the collar-bone (''[[अक्ष|akṣa]]''),<ref name=fx37_ve2_1312/> three joints in the fingers,<ref name=fx38_ve2_1312/> and twenty-one transverse processes in the spine (''anūka'').<ref name=fx39_ve2_1312/> The Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx40_ve2_1312/> enumerates four constituents in the head (''[[प्राण|prāṇa]], [[चक्षुस्|cakṣus]], śrotra, [[वाच्|vāc]]''), but there are many variations, the number going up to twelve on one calculation.<ref name=fx41_ve2_1312/> In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx42_ve2_1312/> an enumeration is given consisting of ''carma'' (skin), ''[[मांस|māṃsa]], snāvan, asthi,'' and ''majjan;'' and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx43_ve2_1312/> has ''lomāni, [[मांस|māṃsa]], tvac, asthi, majjan,'' and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx44_ve2_1312/> couples ''majjānaḥ, snāvāni,'' and ''asthīni.'' Other terms relating to the body are ''kaṅkūṣa,''<ref name=fx45_ve2_1312/> perhaps a part of the ear,<ref name=fx46_ve2_1312/> ''yoni'' (female organ), ''[[कक्ष|kakṣa]]''<ref name=fx47_ve2_1312/> (armpit), '''Danta''' (tooth), ''[[नख|nakha]]'' (nail), ''prapada''<ref name=fx48_ve2_1312/> (forepart of the foot), ''halīkṣṇa''<ref name=fx49_ve2_1312/> (gall). <br>

शरु
<u>'''Śaru'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1313/> and Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1313/> a missile weapon, often certainly an ‘arrow,’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1313/> but perhaps sometimes a ‘dart’ or ‘spear.’<ref name=fx4_ve2_1313/><br>

शर्करा
<u>'''Śarkarā,'''</u> fem. plur., denotes in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1314/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_1314/> ‘grit’ or ‘gravel.’<br>

शर्कराख्य
<u>'''Śarkarākhya.'''</u> See '''[[शार्कराक्ष|Śārkarākṣa]].'''<br>

शर्कोट
<u>'''Śarkoṭa'''</u> is the name of an animal in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1316/> either a ‘serpent,’ as Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1316/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_1316/> held, or a ‘scorpion,’ as Grill,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1316/> Henry,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1316/> and Bloomfield<ref name=fx6_ve2_1316/> think.<br>

शर्ध
<u>'''Śardha.'''</u> See '''[[व्रात|Vrāta]].'''<br>

शर्ध्य
<u>'''Śardhya'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1318/> is taken by Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1318/> as perhaps denoting a part of the chariot. The sense is, however, quite uncertain.<br>

शर्य
<u>'''Śarya,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1319/> '''Śaryā,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1319/> seem in the Rigveda to denote an ‘arrow.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1319/> Perhaps, also, Śaryā<ref name=fx4_ve2_1319/> and [[शर्य|Śarya]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1319/> (neut.) mean the ‘wicker-  work’ in the Soma sieve, but the exact sense of the passages is doubtful.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1319/><br>

शर्यणावन्त्
<u>'''Śaryaṇāvant'''</u> occurs in several passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1320/> in all of which Sāyaṇa sees a local name. According to his account, Śaryaṇāḥ (masc. plur.) is a district in '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]],''' [[शर्यणावन्त्|Śaryaṇāvant]] being a lake not far from it in the back part (''jaghanārdhe'') of [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]]. The unusual consistency of his statements on this point is in favour of the word being a place name; it is also to be noted that [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]] contained the lake '''[[अन्यतःप्लक्षा|Anyataḥplakṣā]].''' Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1320/> however, thought that in two passages<ref name=fx3_ve2_1320/> the word denoted merely a ‘lake,’ literally ‘(water) covered with a thicket of reeds’ (''śaryaṇa''), and in the others a Soma vessel. Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve2_1320/> inclines to this rendering. On the other hand, Pischel<ref name=fx5_ve2_1320/> accepts Sāyaṇa's view. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx6_ve2_1320/> also sees in the word a place name, but he is inclined to locate it among the ‘five tribes,’<ref name=fx7_ve2_1320/> which is not quite inconsistent with its being in [[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]], for the connexion of the '''Pūrus''' with the later '''Kurus''' is known;<ref name=fx8_ve2_1320/> or perhaps, he suggests, [[शर्यणावन्त्|Śaryaṇāvant]] is an old name for the Wular sea of Kaśmīr, which was only a reminiscence in Vedic times. This is not probable; still less so is Ludwig's hypothesis<ref name=fx9_ve2_1320/> that the [[शर्यणावन्त्|Śaryaṇāvant]] is the later eastern '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].''' Bergaigne<ref name=fx10_ve2_1320/> regards the name as that of a celestial preparer of Soma.<br>

शर्यात
<u>'''Śaryāta'''</u> is mentioned once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1321/> as a protégé of the Aśvins. Of him in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]^2 and the  Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1321/> is told a story how '''[[च्यवन|Cyavana]]''' was annoyed by the '''Śāryātas,''' and appeased by the gift of '''[[सुकन्या|Sukanyā]],''' Śaryāta's daughter, as a wife, and how [[च्यवन|Cyavana]] was then restored to youth by the Aśvins. He is there called '''[[मानव|Mānava]]''' (‘descendant of Manu’). He appears also as [[शर्यात|Śaryāta]] [[मानव|Mānava]], a sacrificer, in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_1321/><br>

शर्व-दत्त
<u>'''Śarva-datta'''</u> (‘given by the god Śarva’) '''[[गार्ग्य|Gārgya]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[गर्ग|Garga]]'''’) is the name of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1322/><br>

शल
<u>'''Śala'''</u> is explained by the St. Petersburg Dictionary as a measure of length in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1323/> [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1323/> and [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1323/> Whitney<ref name=fx4_ve2_1323/> objects that the sense in all<ref name=fx5_ve2_1323/> these passages is not suited by this meaning.<br>

शलभ
<u>'''Śalabha,'''</u> ‘locust,’ appears in the Paippalāda recension of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1324/> for '''[[शरभ|Śarabha]],''' the reading of the received text, and is regarded by Whitney<ref name=fx2_ve2_1324/> as making better sense.<br>

शलली
<u>'''Śalalī'''</u> denotes the ‘quill’ of the porcupine, used for parting the hair and anointing the eyes.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1325/> <br>

शलुन
<u>'''Śaluna'''</u> is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1326/> denoting a ‘worm.’ The Paippalāda recension reads Śalūla, and Sāyaṇa Śalga.<br>

शल्क
<u>'''Śalka'''</u> denotes in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1327/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_1327/> chip' or ‘shaving’ used for kindling a fire, etc.<br>

शल्मल्ल्
<u>'''Śalmall'''</u> is the name of the ‘silk cotton tree’ (''Salmalia Malabarica''). Its fruit is regarded as poisonous in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1328/> but the car of the bridal procession is made of its wood.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1328/> It is described as the tallest of trees.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1328/><br>

शल्य
<u>'''Śalya.'''</u> See '''[[इषु|Iṣu]].'''<br>

शल्यक
<u>'''Śalyaka'''</u> denotes in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1330/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1330/> the ‘porcupine.’<br>

शवर्त
<u>'''Śavarta'''</u> is the name of a species of ‘worm’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1331/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1331/><br>

शवस्
<u>'''Śavas'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[अग्निभू काश्यप|Agnibhū Kāśyapa]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1332/> <br>

शवस
<u>'''Śavasa'''</u> occurs only in the false reading ''[[शवस|Śavasa]]-Uśinareṣu'' in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i, 2, 9) for ''sa-Vaśośīnareṣu.'' See '''[[वश|Vaśa]].'''<br>

शविष्ठ
<u>'''Śaviṣṭha'''</u> is, according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1334/> the name of a generous patron in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1334/><br>

शश
<u>'''Śaśa,'''</u> ‘hare,’ is found once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1335/> where it is said to have swallowed a razor. The animal is occasionally mentioned later also.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1335/><br>

शशयु
<u>'''Śaśayu,'''</u> ‘pursuing the hare,’ is the epithet of some animal ('''[[मृग|Mṛga]]''') in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1336/> Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_1336/> thinks the tiger is meant, but this is not likely. Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_1336/> considers that a bird of prey is intended, while Whitney,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1336/> following the commentator, renders the word by ‘lurking.’<br>

शश्वती
<u>'''Śaśvatī.'''</u> See '''Āsaṅga.'''<br>

शष्प
<u>'''Śaṣpa'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1338/> denotes ‘young or sprouting grass.’<br>

शस्तृ
<u>'''Śastṛ'''</u> in the Rigveda (i. 162, 5) and the Atharvaveda (ix. 3, 3) denotes the slaughterer of an animal. <br>

शस्त्र
<u>'''Śastra'''</u> is the technical term<ref name=fx1_ve2_1340/> for the ‘recitation’ of the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] priest, as opposed to the '''[[स्तोत्र|Stotra]]''' of the Udgātṛ. The recitations at the morning offering of Soma are called the [[आज्य|Ājya]] and Praüga; at the midday offering, the Marutvatīya and the Niṣkevalya; at the evening offering, the Vaiśvadeva and the Āgnimāruta.<br>

शाकटायन
<u>'''Śākaṭāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[शकट|Śakaṭa]],’ is the patronymic of a grammarian referred to by '''[[यास्क|Yāska]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1341/> and in the Prātiśākhyas,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1341/> as well as often later.<br>

शाक-दास भाडितायन
<u>'''Śāka-[[दास|dāsa]] Bhāḍitāyana'''</u> (‘descendant of Bhaḍita’) is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1342/> as the pupil of '''[[विचक्षण ताण्ड्य|Vicakṣaṇa Tāṇḍya]].'''<br>

शाक-पूणि
<u>'''Śāka-pūṇi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śakapūṇa,’ is the name of a grammarian often mentioned in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1343/><br>

शाकल
<u>'''Śākala'''</u> in the Aitaṛeya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1344/> denotes the ‘teaching of '''[[शाकल्य|Śākalya]]'''’ according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary. But Bo7htlingk<ref name=fx2_ve2_1344/> seems right in taking it as a kind of snake in that passage.<br>

शाकल्य
<u>'''Śākalya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śakala,’ is the patronymic of '''Vidagdha''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1345/> and of '''[[स्थविर|Sthavira]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1345/> and [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyakas.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1345/> An undefined [[शाकल्य|Śākalya]]  is mentioned in the same Āraṇyakas,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1345/> in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]],<ref name=fx5_ve2_1345/> and often later, as a teacher dealing with the text of the Rigveda. Weber<ref name=fx6_ve2_1345/> is inclined to identify Vidagdha with the [[शाकल्य|Śākalya]] who is known as the maker of the Pada Pāṭha of the Rigveda, but Oldenberg<ref name=fx7_ve2_1345/> thinks that the latter was later than the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] period. Geldner<ref name=fx8_ve2_1345/> identifies the two; this view, however, is not very probable.<ref name=fx9_ve2_1345/><br>

शाकायनिन्
<u>'''Śākāyanin,'''</u> in the plural, denotes the followers of '''[[शाकायन्य|Śākāyanya]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 4, 5, 1).<br>

शाकायन्य
<u>'''Śākāyanya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śāka,’ is the patronymic of '''Jāta''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1347/><br>

शाकिन्
<u>'''Śākin,'''</u> plur., is believed by Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve2_1348/> to designate a group of generous donors in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1348/><br>

शाक्त्य
<u>'''Śāktya,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[शक्ति|Śakti]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Gaurivīti.'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1349/><br>

शाक्वर
<u>'''Śākvara.'''</u> See '''[[शक्वरी|Śakvarī]].'''<br>

शाखा
<u>'''Śākhā'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1351/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1351/> denotes the ‘branch’ of a tree. '''[[वया|Vayā]]''' is more often used in this sense in the Rigveda. <br>

शाङ्खायन
<u>'''Śāṅkhāyana'''</u> as the name of a teacher is not mentioned in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], but it occurs in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1352/> where Guṇākhya is given as the authority for that work. In the Śrauta Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve2_1352/> the name of [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] never occurs, but the [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] Sūtras<ref name=fx3_ve2_1352/> seem to recognize as teacher '''Suyajña [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]].''' In later times<ref name=fx4_ve2_1352/> the school flourished in Northern Gujarat. [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] appears in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Prātiśākhya<ref name=fx5_ve2_1352/> along with Kāṇḍamāyana.<br>

शाट्यायन
<u>'''Śāṭyāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śāṭya,’ is the patronymic of a teacher mentioned twice in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1353/> and often in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1353/> In a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the latter work<ref name=fx3_ve2_1353/> he is called a pupil of '''[[ज्वालायन|Jvālāyana]],''' while in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] at the end of the Sāmavidhāna [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] he appears as a pupil of '''[[बादरायण|Bādarāyaṇa]].''' The Śāṭyāyanins, his followers, are frequently mentioned in the Sūtras,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1353/> the Śāṭyāyani [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1353/> and the Śāṭyāyanaka<ref name=fx6_ve2_1353/> being also referred to in them. It has been shown by Oertel<ref name=fx7_ve2_1353/> that this [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] bore a close resemblance to, and probably belonged to the same period as, the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]. <br>

शाण्ड
<u>'''Śāṇḍa,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[शण्ड|Śaṇḍa]],'''’ is the name of a man in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1354/> who is praised for his generosity. It is not likely that he is identical with '''[[पुरुपन्था|Purupanthā]]''' mentioned in the next verse.<br>

शाण्डिल
<u>'''Śāṇḍila,'''</u> masc. plur., is the term applied to the ‘descendants of '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]]'''’ in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (i. 22, 10).<br>

शाण्डिली-पुत्र
<u>'''Śāṇḍilī-putra,'''</u> ‘pupil of a female descendant of Śaṇḍila,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[राथीतरीपुत्र|Rāthītarīputra]],''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1356/><br>

शाण्डिल्य
<u>'''Śāṇḍilya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śaṇḍila,’ is the patronymic of several teachers (see '''Udara''' and '''Suyajña'''). The most important [[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]] is the one cited several times as an authority in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1357/> where his Agni, or ‘sacrificial fire,’ is called [[शाण्डिल|Śāṇḍila]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1357/> From this it appears clearly that he was one of the great teachers of the fire ritual which occupies the fifth and following books of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]. In the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the tenth book<ref name=fx3_ve2_1357/> he is given as a pupil of '''Kuśri''' and a teacher of '''[[वात्स्य|Vātsya]];''' another list at the end of the last book in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension<ref name=fx4_ve2_1357/> gives him as a pupil of [[वात्स्य|Vātsya]], and the latter as a pupil of Kuśri. In the confused and worthless<ref name=fx5_ve2_1357/> lists of teachers at the end of the second and fourth books of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] he is said to be the pupil of various persons--'''[[कैशोर्य|Kaiśorya]] [[काप्य|Kāpya]],'''<ref name=fx6_ve2_1357/> '''Vaiṣṭapureya,'''<ref name=fx7_ve2_1357/> '''[[कौशिक|Kauśika]],'''<ref name=fx8_ve2_1357/> '''[[गौतम|Gautama]],'''<ref name=fx9_ve2_1357/> '''[[बैजवाप|Baijavāpa]],'''<ref name=fx10_ve2_1357/> and '''Āṇa-  bhimlāta.'''<ref name=fx11_ve2_1357/> No doubt different Śāṇḍilyas may be meant, but the lists are too confused to claim serious consideration.<br>

शाण्डिल्यायन
<u>'''Śāṇḍilyāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]],'''’ is the patronymic of a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1358/> Apparently he is identical with '''Celaka,''' also mentioned in that text;<ref name=fx2_ve2_1358/> it is thus reasonable to suppose that '''[[चैलकि|Cailaki]] Jīvala'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1358/> was his son. It is much more doubtful whether he was<ref name=fx4_ve2_1358/> the grandfather of '''Pravāhaṇa [[जैवल|Jaivala]],''' who was a prince rather than a Brahmin.<br>

शात-पर्णेय
<u>'''Śāta-parṇeya'''</u> ‘descendant of Śataparṇa,’ is the patronymic of '''Dhīra''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 3, 3, 1).<br>

शाद
<u>'''Śāda'''</u> denotes ‘grass’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1360/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1360/> and later.<br>

शाप
<u>'''Śāpa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1361/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1361/> denotes the ‘drift’ brought down by streams, possibly conceived as the ‘curse’ of the waters.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1361/><br>

शामुल्य
<u>'''Śāmulya'''</u> in the marriage hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1362/> denotes a collen garment’ worn at night. <br>

शमूल
<u>'''Śamūla'''</u> in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1363/> seems to have much the same sense as '''[[शामुल्य|Śāmulya]],''' ‘a '''woollen''' shirt,’ generally. Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1363/> emends to ''śamīla,'' ‘pieces of [[शमी|Śamī]] wood.’<br>

शाम्ब
<u>'''Śāmba.'''</u> See '''[[शार्कराक्ष|Śārkarākṣa]].'''<br>

शाम्बर
<u>'''Śāmbara,'''</u> properly an adjective in the sense of ‘relating to '''[[शम्बर|Śambara]],'''’ appears in one passage of the Rigveda (iii. 47, 4) to be used as a substantive denoting ‘the contest with [[शम्बर|Śambara]].’<br>

शाम्बु
<u>'''Śāmbu'''</u> occurs in the plural with the '''Aṅgirases''' in a passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1366/> no doubt as the name of a family of ancient teachers. There is extant in manuscript a [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] of the Śāmbavyas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1366/><br>

शायस्थि
<u>'''Śāyasthi'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1367/><br>

शारद
<u>'''Śārada.'''</u> See '''Pur.'''<br>

शारि
<u>'''1. Śāri'''</u> occurs in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1369/> It seems clear, since it is described as ‘of human speech’ (''[[पुरुष|puruṣa]]-[[वाच्|vāc]]''), that it was some kind of bird, possibly the later Sārikā (‘starling’), as Zimmer<ref name=fx2_ve2_1369/> suggests. See also '''[[शारिशाका|Śāriśākā]].''' <br>

शारि
<u>'''2. Śāri,'''</u> occurring in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1370/> is said by Sāyaṇa to mean ‘arrow.’ This is uncertain, but connexion with '''[[शर|Śara]]''' or 1. '''[[शारि|Śāri]]''' is quite possible.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1370/><br>

शारिशाका
<u>'''Śāriśākā'''</u> is an utterly obscure expression found in one passage of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1371/> Weber<ref name=fx2_ve2_1371/> thinks it means ‘dung (''[[शकन्|śakan]]'') of the [[शारि|Śāri]] bird’; Grill<ref name=fx3_ve2_1371/> sees in the word the ''śārikā,'' ‘the hooded crow’; Roth<ref name=fx4_ve2_1371/> suggests the emendation (''śāriḥ (= śāliḥ) śaka iva,'' ‘like rice in manure’; and Bloomfield<ref name=fx5_ve2_1371/> emends ''[[शारि|śāri]]-śukeva,'' ‘like starlings and parrots.’<br>

शार्कराक्ष
<u>'''Śārkarākṣa'''</u> is found in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1372/> as the patronymic of a teacher, '''[[शाम्ब|Śāmba]],''' perhaps by a blunder for '''[[शार्कराक्ष्य|Śārkarākṣya]],''' ‘descendant of Śarkarākṣa.’ In the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_1372/> a teacher, [[शर्कराख्य|Śarkarākhya]], occurs, again probably a blunder, in this case for Śarkarākṣa himself. The patronymic Śārkarākṣi is found in the Āśvalāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1372/><br>

शार्कराक्ष्य
<u>'''Śārkarākṣya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śarkarākṣa,’ is the patronymic of '''Jana''' in the Śatapatha Brāhmana<ref name=fx1_ve2_1373/> and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1373/> In the plural they occur in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx3_ve2_1373/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1373/> It is not necessary to assume that the form is incorrect for [[शार्कराक्ष|Śārkarākṣa]].<br>

शार्ग
<u>'''Śārga'''</u> is the name of a bird in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1374/> Sāyana on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā calls it the ‘wild Caṭaka.’ <br>

शार्ङ्ग
<u>'''Śārṅga.'''</u>--The Anukramaṇī<ref name=fx1_ve2_1375/> (Index) of the Rigveda ascribes a hymn of that text<ref name=fx2_ve2_1375/> to the Śārṅgas, [[जरितृ|Jaritṛ]], [[द्रोण|Droṇa]], Sārisṛkva, and Stambamitra. The Mahābhārata<ref name=fx3_ve2_1375/> contains a tale describing how the four Śārṅgas, sons of the [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] Mandapāla, were saved from the great fire in the [[खाण्डव|Khāṇḍava]] forest by means of prayers. Sieg<ref name=fx4_ve2_1375/> has attempted to use this tale for the elucidation of the hymn in question, but without substantial success. As Oldenberg<ref name=fx5_ve2_1375/> says, the tale is based on the hymn rather than ''vice versa.''<br>

शार्दूल
<u>'''Śārdūla,'''</u> ‘tiger,’ is mentioned in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1376/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1376/> ''Cf.'' '''[[व्याघ्र|Vyāghra]].'''<br>

शार्यात
<u>'''Śāryāta,'''</u> perhaps ‘descendant of '''[[शर्यात|Śaryāta]],'''’ is the name of a singer in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1377/> A [[शार्यात|Śāryāta]] appears also in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1377/> with the patronymic '''[[मानव|Mānava]]''' as the seer of a Rigvedic hymn,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1377/> and as having been anointed by '''[[च्यवन|Cyavana]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1377/> The same man is evidently meant by [[शर्यात|Śaryāta]] in the story of [[च्यवन|Cyavana]] in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1377/> and the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx6_ve2_1377/> In both these passages the Śāryātas are mentioned as his descendants, and his daughter is called Śāryātī.<br>

शालङ्कायन
<u>'''Śālaṅkāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śalaṅku,’ is the patronymic of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1378/> <br>

शालङ्कायनी-पुत्र
<u>'''Śālaṅkāyanī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Śalaṅku,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[वार्षगणीपुत्र|Vārṣagaṇīputra]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 31).<br>

शाला
<u>'''Śālā'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1380/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1380/> denotes a ‘house’ in the wide sense of the word, including such meanings as ‘stall’ for cattle, ‘shed’ for corn, etc.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1380/> See '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].''' The householder is called [[शाला|Śālā]]-pati, ‘lord of the house,’ in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1380/><br>

शालावत्य
<u>'''Śālāvatya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śalāvant,’ is the patronymic of '''Śilaka''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 8, 1), and of '''[[गलूनस आर्क्षाकायण|Galūnasa Ārkṣākāyaṇa]]''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 38, 4).<br>

सालि
<u>'''Sāli,'''</u> a later word for ‘rice,’ is conjectured by Roth to be the equivalent of [[शारि|Śāri]] in the word '''[[शारिशाका|Śāriśākā]]''' in the Atharvaveda.<br>

शालूक
<u>'''Śālūka'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1383/> denotes the edible roots of the lotus.<br>

शाल्व
<u>'''Śālva'''</u> as the name of a people is found in the Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1384/> coupled with that of the '''Matsyas.'''<br>

सावसायन
<u>'''Sāvasāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[शवस्|Śavas]],’ is the patronymic of '''Devataras''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1385/><br>

शास
<u>'''Śāsa'''</u> denotes in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1386/> a ‘sword’ or ‘knife.’ <br>

शिंशपा
<u>'''Śiṃśapā'''</u> is the name of a tree (''Dalbergia Sisu'') in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1387/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1387/> It is a sately and beautiful tree.<br>

शिंशु-मार
<u>'''Śiṃśu-māra,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1388/> or '''Śiśu-māra,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1388/> is the name of an aquatic creature in the Rigveda and the later Saṃhitās. It is either the ‘crocodile,’ the ‘alligator,’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1388/> or the ‘porpoise’<ref name=fx4_ve2_1388/> (''Delphinus Gangeticus'').<br>

शिक्य
<u>'''Śikya'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1389/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1389/> seems to mean a carrying ‘sling’ of rope.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1389/><br>

शिख
<u>'''Śikha'''</u> and '''[[अनुशिख|Anuśikha]]''' are the names of two priests who served as '''[[नेष्टृ|Neṣṭṛ]]''' and '''[[पोतृ|Potṛ]]''' at the snake festival in the '''Pañca-''' viṃśa [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1390/><br>

शिखण्ड
<u>'''Śikhaṇḍa'''</u> denotes a ‘tuft’ or ‘lock,’ as a mode of wearing the hair, in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1391/> <br>

शिखण्डिन् याज्ञसेन
<u>'''Śikhaṇḍin Yājñasena'''</u> (‘descendant of Yajñasena’) is mentioned in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 4) as a priest of '''[[केशिन्|Keśin]] [[दाल्भ्य|Dālbhya]].'''<br>

शिखर
<u>'''Śikhara'''</u> as a ‘peak’ of a mountain is found in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxvi. 1), and often in the Epic.<br>

शिखा
<u>'''Śikhā'''</u> denotes in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1394/> the ‘knot of hair’ worn on the top of the head. Wearing the top-knot unloosened was the sign of mourning in the case of women and men alike.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1394/><br>

शिग्रु
<u>'''Śigru'''</u> is the name of a tribe occurring in the passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1395/> in which they are mentioned with the '''Ajas''' and the '''Yakṣus''' as having been defeated by the '''Tṛtsus''' and King '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]].''' It is impossible to say whether they were or were not under the leadership of '''[[भेद|Bheda]],''' as Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_1395/> plausibly suggests. If Sigru is connected with the later ''[[शिग्रु|śigru]],'' ‘horse-radish’ (''Moringa pterygosperma''), which is quite probable, it is possible that the tribe was totemistic and non-Āryan, but this is a mere matter of conjecture.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1395/> The '''Matsyas''' (‘Fishes’) were probably Āryan.<br>

शिञ्जार
<u>'''Śiñjāra'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] twice mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1396/> along with '''[[कण्व|Kaṇva]], [[प्रियमेध|Priyamedha]], [[उपस्तुत|Upastuta]],''' and '''Atri.''' Geldner<ref name=fx2_ve2_1396/> takes the word either as a name of Atri or an adjective. <br>

शिति-कक्षी
<u>'''Śiti-kakṣī'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1397/> is explained by Sāyaṇa as a ‘white-breasted’ (''pāṇḍarodara'') vulture. The word may, however, well be only an adjective.^2<br>

शिति-पृष्ठ
<u>'''Śiti-pṛṣṭha'''</u> (‘white-backed’) is the name of the Maitrāvaruṇa priest at the snake festival in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1398/><br>

शिति-बाहु ऐषकृत नैमिशि
<u>'''Śiti-[[बाहु|bāhu]] [[ऐषकृत|Aiṣakṛta]] Naimiśi'''</u> is mentioned as a sacrificer in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1399/> where it is recorded that a monkey an off with his sacrificial cake.<br>

शित्पुट
<u>'''Śitpuṭa'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1400/> denotes, according to the commentator, a kind of cat.<br>

शिपद
<u>'''Śipada'''</u> occurs only in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1401/> in the negative form ''a-[[शिपद|śipada]],'' together with ''a-[[शिमिद|śimida]].'' Both [[शिपद|Śipada]] and [[शिमिद|Śimida]] are perhaps names of unknown diseases.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1401/><br>

शिपवित्नुक
<u>'''Śipavitnuka'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1402/> seems to denote a species of worm.<br>

शिप्रा
<u>'''Śiprā'''</u> is a word of somewhat uncertain sense: it seems to mean ‘cheeks’ in several passages;<ref name=fx1_ve2_1403/> in others<ref name=fx2_ve2_1403/> it appears to  designate the ‘cheek-pieces’ of a helmet, or of the ‘bit’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1403/> of a horse. In ''ayaḥ-śipra,'' used of the Aśvins,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1403/> and the other compounds, ''[[हिरण्य|hiraṇya]]-śipra,''<ref name=fx5_ve2_1403/> ''hari-śipra,''<ref name=fx6_ve2_1403/> and ''hiri-śipra,''<ref name=fx7_ve2_1403/> the word probably has the extended sense of ‘helmet,’ described as ‘of iron,’ ‘of gold,’ or ‘yellow,’ Similarly ''śiprin''<ref name=fx8_ve2_1403/> would mean ‘wearing a helmet.’<br>

शिफा
<u>'''Śiphā'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1404/> where Sāyaṇa explains the word as the name of a river, quite a possible interpretation.<br>

शिबि
<u>'''Śibi,'''</u> son of '''[[उशीनर|Uśīnara]],''' is mentioned in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1405/> as a protégé of Indra, who sacrificed for him on the Varṣiṣṭhīya plain, and saved him from fear of foreign invasion.<br>

शिमिद
<u>'''Śimida,'''</u> occurring in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1406/> in the compound ''a-śinida,'' perhaps denotes a disease. The feminine form, Śimidā, is found as the name of a demoness in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1406/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1406/> ''Cf.'' '''[[शिपद|Śipada]].'''<br>

शिम्बल
<u>'''Śimbala'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1407/> denotes, according to Sāyaṇa, the flower of the Śālmali (= '''Śalmali'''), ‘silk-cotton tree.’ <br>

शिम्यु
<u>'''Śimyu'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1408/> as the name of one of the peoples or kings who were defeated by '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' in the '''[[दाशराज्ञ|Dāśarājña]]''' (‘battle of the ten kings’). Since in another passage<ref name=fx2_ve2_1408/> the Śimyus are coupled with the '''Dasyus,''' Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_1408/> plausibly concludes that they were non-Āryans.<br>

शिरिम्बिठ
<u>'''Śirimbiṭha'''</u> occurs in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1409/> where the name of a man may possibly be meant, the Anukramaṇī (Index) ascribing the hymn in which the word occurs to his authorship. [[यास्क|Yāska]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1409/> however, renders the term by ‘cloud.’<br>

शिलक शालावत्य
<u>'''Śilaka Śālāvatya'''</u> (‘descendant of Śalāvant’) is the name of a teacher, a contemporary of '''Calkitāyana [[दाल्भ्य|Dālbhya]]''' and '''Pravāhaṇa [[जैवल|Jaivala]],''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 8, 1).<br>

शिल्प
<u>'''1. Śilpa'''</u> means ‘art,’ of which three kinds--''nṛtya,'' ‘dance’; ''gīta,'' ‘song’; and ''[[वादित|vādita]],'' ‘instrumental music,’ are enumerated in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xxix. 5).<br>

शिल्प कश्यप
<u>'''2. Śilpa Kaśyapa'''</u> is named in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1412/> as a teacher, a pupil of '''[[कश्यप नैध्रुवि|Kaśyapa Naidhruvi]].'''<br>

शिव
<u>'''Śiva'''</u> as the name of a people occurs once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1413/> where they share with the '''Alinas, Pakthas, Bhalānases,''' and '''Viṣāṇins''' the honour of being defeated by '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],''' not of being, as Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1413/> thought, his allies. There can hardly be any doubt  of their identity with the <ref name=fx3_ve2_1413/> or <ref name=fx4_ve2_1413/> of the Greeks, who dwelt between the Indus and the Akesines ('''[[असिक्नी|Asiknī]]''') in Alexander's time. The village of [[शिव|Śiva]]-pura, mentioned by the scholiast on Pāṇini<ref name=fx5_ve2_1413/> as situated in the northern country, may also perserve the name. ''Cf.'' '''[[शिबि|Śibi]].'''<br>

शिशिर
<u>'''Śiśira.'''</u> See '''[[ऋतु|Ṛtu]].'''<br>

शिशु आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Śiśu Āṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]'''’) is the name of the seer of a Sāman or Chant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1415/><br>

शिशुक
<u>'''Śiśuka'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1416/> seems to be an adjective meaning ‘young,’ but according to Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve2_1416/> it has the sense of ‘foal.’ The commentator, Sāyaṇa, reads [[शुशुक|Śuśuka]], which he explains as a ‘wild animal so called.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[आशुंग|Āśuṃga]].'''<br>

शिशुमार
<u>'''1. Śiśumāra.'''</u> See '''[[शिंशुमार|Śiṃśumāra]].'''<br>

शिशुमार
<u>'''2. Śiśumāra'''</u> is a term applied to '''Śarkara''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 5, 15), where he is called a Śiśumārarṣi, explained by the commentator to mean a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the form of a Siśumāra.<br>

सिश्न-देव
<u>'''Siśna-deva,'''</u> occurring twice in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1419/> in the plural, means ‘those who have the phallus for a deity.’ The term most probably refers to the phallus worship of the aborigines. <br>

शीपाल
<u>'''Śīpāla'''</u> is the name of a water plant (''Blyxa Octandra'') mentioned in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1420/> Its later name is Śaivala.<br>

शीपाला
<u>'''Śīpālā'''</u> is found once in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1421/> where it may mean either a ‘pool abounding in '''[[शीपाल|Śīpāla]]''' plants’ or the proper name of a river or lake.<br>

शीपुद्रु
<u>'''Śīpudru'''</u> is merely an incorrect reading in the text of the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1422/> for '''[[चीपुद्रु|Cīpudru]].'''<br>

शीर्षक्ति
<u>'''Śīrṣakti'''</u> is a common word for ‘headache’ in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1423/><br>

शीर्षण्य
<u>'''Śīrṣaṇya'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1424/> denotes the ‘head’ of a couch ('''Asandī''').<br>

शीर्षामय
<u>'''Śīrṣāmaya,'''</u> ‘disease of the head,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda (v. 4, 10; ix. 8, 1).<br>

शीष्ट
<u>'''Śīṣṭa'''</u> occurs only in a [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymn of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1426/> where the word seems to be the name of an unimportant clan. <br>

शुक
<u>'''Śuka,'''</u> ‘parrot,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1427/> where a desire is expressed to transfer to the [[शुक|Śuka]] and the '''[[रोपणाका|Ropaṇākā]]''' the yellowness of jaundice. The bird is included in the list of sacrificial victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1427/> It is described as yellow and as ‘of human speech’ (''[[पुरुष|puruṣa]]-[[वाच्|vāc]]'').<ref name=fx3_ve2_1427/> According to Bloomfield,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1427/> this word is the correct reading for the second half of the obscure '''[[शारिशाका|Śāriśākā]]''' of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1427/><br>

शुक्ति आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Śukti Āṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]'''’) is the name of the seer of a Sāman or Chant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xii. 5, 16).<br>

शुक्र
<u>'''1. Śukra,'''</u> according to Tilak,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1429/> has in two passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1429/> the sense of a planet. This is most improbable. ''Cf.'' '''[[मन्थिन्|Manthin]].'''<br>

शुक्र जाबाल
<u>'''2. Śukra Jābāla'''</u> (‘descendant of Jabālā’) is the name of a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 7, 7).<br>

शुक्ल
<u>'''Śukla.'''</u> See '''[[यजुस्|Yajus]].'''<br>

शुक्ल-दन्त्
<u>'''Śukla-dant,'''</u> ‘white-tusked,’ is applied as an epithet to '''[[मृग|Mṛga]],''' ‘wild beast,’ in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 23, 3). ‘Elephants’ must be meant.<br>

शुच
<u>'''Śuca'''</u> and '''Śucā''' occur in an obscure verse of the Rigveda (x. 26, 6), where a man and a woman may be meant. <br>

शुचन्ति
<u>'''Śucanti'''</u> is the name of a protégé of the Aśvins in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1434/><br>

शुचि-वृक्ष गौपालायन
<u>'''Śuci-[[वृक्ष|vṛkṣa]] Gaupālāyana'''</u> (‘descendant of Gopāla’) is the name of the priest of '''Vṛddhadyumna Abhipratāriṇa''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1435/> He is also mentioned in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1435/><br>

शुतुद्री
<u>'''Śutudrī,'''</u> twice mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1436/> is the name of the most easterly river of the Panjab, the modern Sutlej, the Zaradros of Ptolemy and Arrian.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1436/> In the post-Vedic period the name of this river appears transformed to Śatadru (‘flowing in a hundred channels’). The Sutlej has changed its course very considerably within historical times.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1436/><br>

शुनः-पुच्छ
<u>'''Śunaḥ-puccha,'''</u> ‘Dog’s tail,’ is the name of a brother of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1437/><br>

शुनः-शेप
<u>'''Śunaḥ-śepa,'''</u> ‘Dog’s tail,’ is the name of a man with the patronymic '''[[आजीगर्ति|Ājīgarti]].''' According to a tale told in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1438/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1438/> he was purchased as a victim by '''[[रोहित|Rohita]],''' King '''Hariścandra's''' son, who had been promised by his father to Varuṇa as a sacrifice. He was actually bound to the stake, but was released in time through his supplications, supposed to be preserved in certain hymns of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1438/> He was adopted by '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]],''' to whose advice he owed the inspiration to ask the gods to release him, and became his son as '''[[देवरात|Devarāta]],''' much to the annoyance  of some of Viśvāmitra's sons, who in consequence were cursed by their father. The Rigveda, however, contains merely the statement of Śunaḥśepa's deliverance from peril of death by the divine help, and the Yajurvedas<ref name=fx4_ve2_1438/> simply say that he was seized by Varuṇa (perhaps with dropsy),<ref name=fx5_ve2_1438/> but saved himself from Varuṇa's bonds.<br>

शुनस्-कर्ण
<u>'''Śunas-karṇa,'''</u> ‘Dog-ear,’ is the name of a king,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1439/> son of '''[[शिबि|Śibi]]''' or of Baṣkiha,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1439/> who performed a certain rite, the Sarvasvāra, and so died without disease.<br>

सुन-होत्र
<u>'''Suna-hotra,'''</u> in the plural, denotes a family of seers in the Rigveda (ii. 18, 6; 41, 14. 17).<br>

शुना-सीर
<u>'''Śunā-sīra,'''</u> in the dual, occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1441/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1441/> as the names of two agricultural deities, the personifications, probably, of ‘the share and the plough,’ as Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_1441/> thinks.<br>

शुनो-लाङ्गूल
<u>'''Śuno-lāṅgūla,'''</u> ‘Dog’s tail,’ is the name of a brother of '''[[शुनः-शेप|Śunaḥ-śepa]].'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1442/> <br>

सुम्बल
<u>'''Sumbala'''</u> is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1443/> The meaning of the word is uncertain: Harisvāmi in his commentary takes it to be ‘straw’; Eggeling<ref name=fx2_ve2_1443/> suggests that dried cotton fibre or pods may be meant. In any case, some substance that easily catches fire is intended.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1443/><br>

शुल्क
<u>'''Śulka'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1444/> clearly means ‘price.’ In the [[धर्म|Dharma]] Sūtras<ref name=fx2_ve2_1444/> it denotes a ‘tax,’ a sense which is found by Muir<ref name=fx3_ve2_1444/> in a passage of the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1444/> where ''[[शुक्ल|śukla]]'' is read in the edition with great detriment to the sense. This correction is accepted by Bloomfield<ref name=fx5_ve2_1444/> and by Whitney.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1444/> In another passage the same change made by Weber<ref name=fx7_ve2_1444/> is not accepted by Whitney,<ref name=fx8_ve2_1444/> and doubtfully by Bloomfield.<ref name=fx9_ve2_1444/><br>

शुशुक
<u>'''Śuśuka.'''</u> See '''Aśuṃga''' and '''[[शिशुक|Śiśuka]].'''<br>

शुशुलूक
<u>'''Śuśulūka'''</u> is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1446/> in the compound ''śuśulūkayātu,'' the name of a demon. According to Sāyaṇa, the word means a ‘small owl.’ It appears in the feminine form, Śuśulūkā, in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1446/><br>

शुष्क-भृङ्गार
<u>'''Śuṣka-bhṛṅgāra'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the Kauṣitaki [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1447/><br>

सुश्मिण
<u>'''Suśmiṇa'''</u> is a name of '''Amitratapana,''' a king of the '''Śibis,''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 23, 10). <br>

शूद्र
<u>'''Śūdra'''</u> is the designation of the fourth caste in the Vedic state (see '''[[वर्ण|Varṇa]]'''). It is quite unknown in the Rigveda except in the Puruṣasūkta<ref name=fx1_ve2_1449/> (‘hymn of man’) in the tenth Maṇḍla, where is the earliest version of the origin of the castes the Śudra for the first time appears. The Rigveda, on the other hand, knows '''[[दस्यु|Dasyu]]''' and '''[[दास|Dāsa]],''' both as aborigines independent of Āryan control and as subjugated slaves: it is reasonable to reckon the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] of the later texts as belonging to the aborigines who had been reduced to subjection by the Āryans. Strictly speaking, the defeated aborigines must have been regarded as slaves, but it is obvious that, except on occasions when most of the men were slain, which may have occurred quite often, there must have remained too many of them to be used as slaves of individual owners. The villages of the aborigines must have continued to subsist, but under Āryan lordship and control: there may be this amount of truth in Baden Powell's theory, which practically traced all the early cultivating villages in India to Dravidian origin. On the other hand, the term [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] would also cover the wild hill tribes which lived by hunting and fishing, and many of which would acknowledge the superiority of their Āryan neighbours: it could, in fact, be applied to all beyond the pale of the Āryan state.<br><br>This view of the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] suits adequately the Vedic references to his condition, which would not apply adequately to domestic slaves only. The [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] is continually opposed to the Āryan,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1449/> and the colour of the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] is compared with that of the Āryan,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1449/> just as his ways are so contrasted.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1449/> The [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx5_ve2_1449/> in its account of the castes, declares that the  [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] is ''anyasya [[प्रेष्य|preṣya]],'' ‘the servant of another’; ''kāmotthāpya,'' ‘to be expelled at will’; and ''yathākāmavadhya,'' ‘to be slain at will.’ All these terms well enough describe the position of the serf as the result of a conquest: the epithets might have been applied to the English serf after the Norman Conquest with but slight inaccuracy, especially if his master had received a grant of jurisdiction from the Crown. The [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_1449/> explains that even if prosperous (''bahu-[[पशु|paśu]],'' ‘having many cows’) a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] could not be other than a servant: his business was ''pādāvanejya,'' ‘the washing of the feet’ of his superiors. The Mahābhārata<ref name=fx7_ve2_1449/> says out and out that a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] has no property (''na hi svam asti śūdrasya,'' ‘the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] has nothing he can call his own’). On the other hand, just as in England the royal justice would protect the serf in life and limb,<ref name=fx8_ve2_1449/> so it appears that the slaying of a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] involved a wergeld of ten cows according to both [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]]<ref name=fx9_ve2_1449/> and Āpastamba.<ref name=fx10_ve2_1449/> It may, indeed, be held that this wergeld was only due in case of murder by another than the master, but such limitation is nowhere stated.<br><br>In sacred matters the distinction between Āryan and '''[[शूद्र|Śūdra]]''' was, of course, specially marked. The texts<ref name=fx11_ve2_1449/> do not hesitate to declare that the upper castes were ‘all,’ ignoring the Śūdras; the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] is prohibited<ref name=fx12_ve2_1449/> from milking the cow for the milk required at the Agnihotra (‘oblation to Agni’); and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx13_ve2_1449/> forbids a man who has been consecrated (''dīkṣita'') for a sacrifice to speak to a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] at all for the time, though the Śāṭyāyanaka<ref name=fx14_ve2_1449/> seems to have relaxed this rule by confining it to cases in which the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] was guilty of some sin.  At the sacrifice itself the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] could not be present in the ''[[शाला|śālā]],'' ‘hall’; he is definitely classed in the Śatapatha Brāhmáṇa<ref name=fx15_ve2_1449/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx16_ve2_1449/> as unfit for ‘sacrifice’ (''ayajñiya''); and declared in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx17_ve2_1449/> not to be admitted to drink Soma. At the Pravargya (introductory Soma) rite the performer is not allowed to come in contact with a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]],<ref name=fx18_ve2_1449/> who here, as in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx17_ve2_1449/> is reckoned as excluded from a share in the Soma-draught. On the other hand, the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] is one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]],<ref name=fx19_ve2_1449/> and a fight between an Āryan and a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]], in which, of course, the former wins, forms a part of the Mahāvrata rite, being perhaps a precursor of the Indian drama.<ref name=fx20_ve2_1449/><br><br>Other indications, however, exist, showing that it would be undesirable to ignore the real importance of the [[शूद्र|Śūdra]], which again reminds us of the condition of the serf, who, though legally restrained, still gradually won his way to the rank of a free man. Rich Śūdras are mentioned in the early texts,<ref name=fx21_ve2_1449/> just as [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] ''gahapatis,'' ‘householders,’ occur in the Buddhist texts, and [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] kings in the legal literature.<ref name=fx22_ve2_1449/> Sin against [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] and Āryan is mentioned;<ref name=fx23_ve2_1449/> prayers for glory on behalf of Śūdras, as well as of the other castes<ref name=fx24_ve2_1449/> occur; and the desire to be dear to [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] as well as to Āryan is expressed.<ref name=fx25_ve2_1449/> <br><br>The Sūtras also, while they emphasize as general rules points earlier not insisted on, such as their inferiority in sitting, etc.,<ref name=fx26_ve2_1449/> their exclusion from the study of the Vedas,<ref name=fx27_ve2_1449/> the danger of contact with them<ref name=fx28_ve2_1449/> or their food,<ref name=fx29_ve2_1449/> still recognize that Śūdras can be merchants,<ref name=fx30_ve2_1449/> or even exercise any trade.<ref name=fx31_ve2_1449/><br><br>Moreover, the Sūtras<ref name=fx32_ve2_1449/> permit the marriage of a [[शूद्रा|Śūdrā]] woman with members of all castes. Though it was a reproach to '''[[वत्स|Vatsa]]'''<ref name=fx33_ve2_1449/> and to '''[[कवष|Kavaṣa]]'''<ref name=fx34_ve2_1449/> that they were the sons of a [[शूद्रा|Śūdrā]] and a Dāsī respectively, still the possibility of such a reproach shows that marriages of this kind did take place. Moreover, illicit unions of [[आर्य|Ārya]] and [[शूद्रा|Śūdrā]], or [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] and Āryā, are referred to in the Saṃhitās of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx35_ve2_1449/><br><br>The origin of the term [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] is quite obscure, but Zimmer<ref name=fx36_ve2_1449/> points out that Ptolemy<ref name=fx37_ve2_1449/> mentions  as a people, and he thinks that the Brāhui may be meant. Without laying any stress on this identification,<ref name=fx38_ve2_1449/> it is reasonable to accept the  view<ref name=fx39_ve2_1449/> that the term was originally the name of a large tribe opposed to the Āryan invasion. See also '''[[निषाद|Niṣāda]].'''<br>

शूद्रा
<u>'''Śūdrā'''</u> denoted a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] woman in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1450/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1450/><br>

शूर
<u>'''Śūra'''</u> is the regular word in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1451/> and occasionally later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1451/> to denote a ‘hero’ or ‘brave warrior.’<br>

शूर-वीर माण्डूक्य
<u>'''Śūra-[[वीर|vīra]] Māṇḍūkya'''</u> (‘descendant of Maṇḍūka’) is the name of a teacher in the Āraṇyakas of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1452/><br>

शूर्प
<u>'''Śūrpa'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1453/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1453/> denotes a wickerwork basket for winnowing grain. It is called ''[[वर्ष|varṣa]]-vṛddha,'' ‘swollen by rain,’ in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1453/> which shows, as Zimmer<ref name=fx4_ve2_1453/> says, that it was sometimes made of reeds, not of dry wood. <br>

शूल
<u>'''Śūla,'''</u> denoting the ‘spit,’ used for roasting flesh on, is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1454/> and the later Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1454/><br>

सुष वार्ष्ण
<u>'''1. Suṣa Vārṣṇa'''</u> (‘descendant of Vṛṣṇi’) is mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Brāhmaṇ (iii. 10, 9, 15) as having been honoured by a consecration with Āditya.<br>

शूष वाह्नेय
<u>'''2. Śūṣa Vāhneya'''</u> (‘descendant of Vahni’) '''[[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]]'''’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of Arāḍa [[दात्रेय|Dātreya]] '''[[शौनक|Śaunaka]],''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1456/> ''Cf.'' '''Śruṣa.'''<br>

शृङ्ग
<u>'''Śṛṅga'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1457/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1457/> denotes the ‘horn’ of any sort of animal. Hence the ‘barb’ of the arrow is called its horn in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1457/><br>

शृङ्ग-वृष्
<u>'''Śṛṅga-vṛṣ'''</u> is the name of a man in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1458/> According to Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1458/> he is father of '''[[पृदाकुसानु|Pṛdākusānu]].'''<br>

शेरभ
<u>'''Śerabha'''</u> and '''Śerabhaka''' are names of snakes or demons in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1459/><br>

शेव-धि
<u>'''Śeva-dhi'''</u> denotes ‘treasure’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1460/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1460/> <br>

शेवृध
<u>'''Śevṛdha'''</u> and '''Śevṛdhaka''' are the names of snakes or demons in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1461/><br>

शेषण
<u>'''Śeṣaṇa'''</u> in the Atharvaveda (vii. 109, 5), means the ‘leaving’ of the dice as opposed to Glahana (''grahaṇa''), the ‘taking up’ of them for the throw. ''Cf.'' '''[[ग्लह|Glaha]].'''<br>

शेषस्
<u>'''Śeṣas'''</u> denotes ‘offspring’ in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1463/><br>

शैब्य
<u>'''Śaibya,'''</u> ‘belonging to the '''Śibis,'''’ is a designation of king Amitratapana Śuṣmiṇa in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 23, 10). In the [[प्रश्न|Praśna]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 1; v. 1) [[शैब्य|Śaibya]] is the patronymic of a teacher, '''[[सत्यकाम|Satyakāma]].'''<br>

शैलन
<u>'''Śailana,'''</u> in the plural, is the name of a school of teachers in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 2, 3; ii. 4, 6).<br>

सैलालि
<u>'''Sailāli,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śilālin,’ is the name of a ritual teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1466/> A Śailāli [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] is mentioned in the Āpastamba Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1466/> and the school of the Śailālins often occurs in the Śūtras.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1466/><br>

शैलिन
<u>'''Śailina'''</u> or '''Śailini,''' ‘descendant of Śilina,’ is the patronymic of '''Jitvan''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1467/> Perhaps '''[[शैलन|Śailana]]''' should be compared. <br>

शैलूष
<u>'''Śailūṣa'''</u> is included in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1468/> An ‘actor’ or ‘dancer’ may be meant. Sāyaṇa says it is a man who lives on the prostitution of his wife.<br>

शोण सात्रासाह
<u>'''Śoṇa Sātrāsāha,'''</u> king of '''[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]]''' and father of '''Koka,''' is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1469/> as having offered the horse sacrifice, which was attended by the '''Turvaśas''' also.<br>

शौङ्गायनि
<u>'''Śauṅgāyani,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śauṅga,’ is the name of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1470/><br>

शौङ्गी-पुत्र
<u>'''Śauṅgī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Śuṅga,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[सांकृती-पुत्र|Sāṃkṛtī-putra]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1471/><br>

शौच
<u>'''Śauca'''</u> (‘descendant of Śuci’) is the patronymic of a man, called also '''[[आह्नेय|Āhneya]],''' who is mentioned as a teacher in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (ii. 12).<br>

शौचद्-रथ
<u>'''Śaucad-ratha'''</u> (‘descendant of Śucad-ratha’) is the patronymic of '''Sunītha''' in the Rigveda (v. 79, 2).<br>

शौचेय
<u>'''Śauceya'''</u> (‘descendant of Śuci’) '''[[प्राचीनयोग्य|Prācīnayogya]]''' (‘descendant of Prācīnayoga’) is the name of a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xi. 5, 3, 1. 8). [[शौचेय|Śauceya]] is also the patronymic of '''[[सार्वसेनि|Sārvaseni]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vii. 1, 10, 2). <br>

शौनक
<u>'''Śaunaka,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śunaka,’ is a common patronymic. It is applied to '''[[इन्द्रोत|Indrota]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1475/> and '''[[स्वैदायन|Svaidāyana]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1475/> A [[शौनक|Śaunaka]] appears as a teacher of '''[[रौहिणायन|Rauhiṇāyana]]''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1475/> A [[शौनक|Śaunaka]]-yajña, or [[शौनक|Śaunaka]] sacrifice, occurs in the Kauṣitaki [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_1475/> In the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1475/> '''Atidhanvan''' [[शौनक|Śaunaka]] appears as a teacher. That [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_1475/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve2_1475/> mention a [[शौनक|Śaunaka]] [[कापेय|Kāpeya]] who was a contemporary of '''[[अभिप्रतारिन् काक्षसेनि|Abhipratārin Kākṣaseni]],''' whose [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] [[शौनक|Śaunaka]] was according to another passage<ref name=fx8_ve2_1475/> of the latter [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]. In the Sūtras, the Bṛhaddevatā, etc., a [[शौनक|Śaunaka]] appears as a great authority on grammatical, ritual, and other matters.<ref name=fx9_ve2_1475/><br>

शौनकी-पुत्र
<u>'''Śaunakī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Śunaka,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[काश्यपीबालाक्यामाठरीपुत्र|Kāśyapībālākyāmāṭharīputra]]''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 30. 31).<br>

शौर्प-णाय्य
<u>'''Śaurpa-ṇāyya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śūrpaṇāya,’ is the patronymic of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[गौतम|Gautama]],''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 5, 20; iv. 5, 26).<br>

शौल्बायन
<u>'''Śaulbāyana'''</u> or '''Śaulvāyana,''' ‘descendant of Śulba,’ is the patronymic of a teacher, '''Udaṅka.'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1478/> According to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1478/> a [[शौल्बायन|Śaulbāyana]] was the [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]], or sacrificing priest, of those who had '''[[अयस्थूण|Ayasthūṇa]]''' as Gṛhapati (‘householder,’ the title of the sacrificer who has precedence at a ''sattra,'' or sacrificial session). <br>

शौष्कल
<u>'''Śauṣkala'''</u> is the name of one of the sacrificial victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1479/> It means, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, ‘living on dried fish or flesh,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1479/> or, according to the native lexicographers, ‘selling dried fish,’ while, Sāyaṇa's commentary on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] explains the meaning to be one who catches fish with a hook, ‘angler.’<br>

श्रुष्टि आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Śruṣṭi Āṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]'''’) is the name of the seer of a Sāman or Chant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1480/><br>

श्मशान
<u>'''Śmaśāna'''</u> is the name of the ‘burial mound’ in which the bones of the dead man were laid to rest (''cf.'' '''[[अन्अग्निदग्ध|Anagnidagdha]]'''). It is mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1481/> and often later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1481/> The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1481/> prescribes a four-cornered mound facing the south-east, on ground inclined to the north, out of sight of the village, in a peaceful spot amid beautiful surroundings, or on barren ground. For an Agni-cit (‘builder of a fire-latar’) a funeral mound like a fire-altar is prescribed. The Easterners (''Prācyāḥ'') made their mounds round.<br>

श्मश्रु
<u>'''Śmaśru'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1482/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1482/> means ‘beard’ and ‘moustache,’ being sometimes contrasted with '''[[केश|Keśa]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1482/> ‘hair of the head.’ Shaving was known (see '''[[वप्तृ|Vaptṛ]]''' and '''[[क्षुर|Kṣura]]'''). The  wearing of a beard was a sign of manhood according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1482/> with which agrees the notice of Megasthenes<ref name=fx5_ve2_1482/> that the Indians carefully tended their beards up to the day of their death.<br>

श्यापर्ण सायकायन
<u>'''Śyāparṇa Sāyakāyana'''</u> is the name of a man, the last for whom five victims were slain at the building of the sacrificial altar according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1483/> The same text<ref name=fx2_ve2_1483/> again mentions him as a builder of the fire-altar. He must have been connected in some way with the '''Salvas.'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1483/> His family, the Śyāparṇas, appear in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_1483/> as a self-assertive family of priests whom king '''Viśvantara''' excluded from his sacrifice, but whose leader, '''[[राम मार्गवेय|Rāma Mārgaveya]],''' induced him to take them back. In some way Śyāparṇa was connected with the defeat of the '''Pañcālas''' by the '''Kuntis.'''<ref name=fx5_ve2_1483/><br>

श्याम
<u>'''Śyāma'''</u> (‘swarthy’) with '''Ayas''' (‘metal’) in all probability denotes ‘iron’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1484/> [[श्याम|Śyāma]] alone has the same sense in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1484/> and later.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1484/><br>

श्याम-जयन्त लौहित्य
<u>'''Śyāma-[[जयन्त|jayanta]] Lauhitya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[जयन्त|Jayanta]] [[पाराशर्य|Pārāśarya]],''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Jiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1). Another man of the same name occurs in the same place as a pupil of '''[[मित्रभूति लौहित्य|Mitrabhūti Lauhitya]].'''<br>

श्याम-पर्ण
<u>'''Śyāma-parṇa'''</u> is, in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1486/> and Maitrāyaṇī<ref name=fx2_ve2_1486/> Saṃhitās, the name of a man who was instructed by '''[[सोमदक्ष कौश्रेय|Somadakṣa Kauśreya]].''' <br>

श्याम-सुजयन्त लौहित्य
<u>'''Śyāma-sujayanta Lauhitya'''</u> (‘descendant of Lohita’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[कृष्णधृति सात्यकि|Kṛṣṇadhṛti Sātyaki]],''' in a [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 42, 1).<br>

श्यामाक
<u>'''Śyāmāka'''</u> is the name of a cultivated millet (''Panicum frumentaceum'') in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1488/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1488/> The lightness of its seed is alluded to in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1488/> where it is spoken of as blown away by the wind. There it is also mentioned as the food of pigeons.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1488/> The [[श्यामाक|Śyāmāka]] and its seed ('''[[तण्डुल|Taṇḍula]]''') are referred to as very small in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx5_ve2_1488/> where Max Müller<ref name=fx6_ve2_1488/> renders it as ‘canary seed.’<br>

श्याव
<u>'''1. Śyāva'''</u> is the name of a protégé of the Aśvins in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1489/> He may be identical with '''[[हिरण्यहस्त|Hiraṇyahasta]].'''<br>

श्याव
<u>'''2. Śyāva'''</u> is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1490/> as a generous donor on the '''[[सुवास्तु|Suvāstu]]''' river.<br>

श्याव
<u>'''3. Śyāva'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda (v. 61, 9) seems clearly, as Sāyaṇa thinks, to denote '''[[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]].'''<br>

श्यावक
<u>'''Śyāvaka'''</u> is mentioned as a sacrificer and friend of Indra in the Rigveda (viii. 3, 12; 4, 2). He may be identical with 2. '''[[श्याव|Śyāva]].'''<br>

श्यावसायन
<u>'''Śyāvasāyana'''</u> is the patronymic of '''Devataras''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 2). The form is perhaps an error for '''Śāvasāyana.''' <br>

श्यावाश्व
<u>'''Śyāvāśva'''</u> is the name of a man mentioned several times in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1494/> The Anukramaṇī (Index) assigns to him a series of hymns in the fifth, eight, and ninth books.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1494/> In one of the hymns<ref name=fx3_ve2_1494/> [[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]] mentions, apparently as his patrons, '''[[तरन्त|Taranta]]''' (a son of '''Vidadaśva''') and '''Purumīlha,''' as well as '''Rathavīti.''' On this hymn is based a legend found in the Bṛhaddevatā,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1494/> that he was the son of '''[[अर्चनानस्|Arcanānas]],''' who was sacrificing for Rathavīti [[दाल्भ्य|Dālbhya]]. The father was anxious to obtain the king's daughter for his son in marriage; but though the father was willing, his wife insisted on her son-in-law being a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]]. The father and son, repulsed, were returning home, when they met on the way [[तरन्त|Taranta]] and Purumīḍha, former patrons of the father. These showed him respect, while Taranta's wife, Śaśīyasī, presented [[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]] with much wealth. The son was then fortunate enough to meet the Maruts in the forest, and praised them, thus becoming a seer. As a result the king himself ultimately offered his daughter to [[श्यावाश्व|Śyāvāśva]]. Sieg<ref name=fx5_ve2_1494/> seeks to show that this legend is presupposed in the Rigveda; but it is difficult to accept this view, since the references in the Rigveda are very obscure, and Śaśīyasī is probably no more than an epithet.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1494/> That there is some [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] at the back of the hymn is clear: what it is can hardly now be determined.<br><br>Śyāvāśva's obtaining gifts from [[वैदद्अश्वि|Vaidadaśvi]] is referred to also in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx7_ve2_1494/> His name occurs in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx8_ve2_1494/> in two lists of persons, of which the former includes Purumīḍha, the latter also [[अर्चनानस्|Arcanānas]] and Atri. A Sāman is ascribed to him in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx9_ve2_1494/> and he is perhaps referred to in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx10_ve2_1494/> In the  [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx11_ve2_1494/> he is styled Ārcanānasa, ‘son of [[अर्चनानस्|Arcanānas]],’ and later<ref name=fx12_ve2_1494/> he is called [[आत्रेय|Ātreya]], ‘descendant of Atri.’<br>

श्येन
<u>'''Śyena'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1495/> of a strong bird of prey, most probably the ‘eagle’; later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1495/> (as in post-Vedic Sanskrit) it seems to mean the ‘falcon’ or ‘hawk.’ It is the swiftest of birds,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1495/> and a source of terror to smaller birds.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1495/> It is the strongest of birds,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1495/> and even attacks herds.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1495/> It watches over men (''[[नृ|nṛ]]-cakṣas''),<ref name=fx7_ve2_1495/> a reference, no doubt, to its lofty flight in air. It brings the Soma from heaven.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1495/><br>

श्रपयितृ
<u>'''Śrapayitṛ,'''</u> ‘cook,’ is a term mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i, 2, 2, 14).<br>

श्रमण
<u>'''Śramaṇa'''</u> ‘mendicant monk,’ is first found in the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1497/> According to Fick,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1497/> anyone could become a [[श्रमण|Śramaṇa]]. For the time of Megasthenes this seems indicated by his evidence, which, however, refers only to the east of India, beyond the '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]]''' proper.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1497/> The Vedic evidence is merely the name and the fact that '''[[तापस|Tāpasa]],''' ‘ascetic,’ follows it in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka. <br>

श्रवण
<u>'''Śravaṇa.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

श्रवण-दत्त
<u>'''Śravaṇa-datta'''</u> (‘given by '''[[श्रवण|Śravaṇa]]'''’) '''Kauhala''' (‘descendant of Kohala’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[सुशारद शालङ्कायन|Suśārada Śālaṅkāyana]]''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1499/><br>

श्रविष्ठ
<u>'''Śraviṣṭha.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

श्रायस
<u>'''Śrāyasa'''</u> is the patronymic of '''[[कण्व|Kaṇva]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1501/> and the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1501/> where he appears as a teacher, and of '''[[वीतहव्य|Vītahavya]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx3_ve2_1501/> and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx4_ve2_1501/><br>

श्री
<u>'''Śrī'''</u> is the regular word for ‘prosperity,’ found once in the '''Rigveda'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1502/> and often later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1502/> '''[[श्रेष्ठिन्|Śreṣṭhin]].'''<br>

श्रुत-कक्ष
<u>'''Śruta-kakṣa'''</u> is mentioned once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1503/> as the [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] of a hymn, the authorship of which the Anukramaṇī (Index) ascribes to him. A Sāman or chant of his is mentioned in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1503/><br>

श्रुत-रथ
<u>'''Śruta-ratha'''</u> is the name of a young king in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1504/> He is also the patron of the '''[[पज्र|Pajra]]''' family, including '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1504/> <br>

श्रुतर्य
<u>'''Śrutarya'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda (i. 112, 9) as the name of a protégé of the Aśvins.<br>

श्रुतर्वन् आर्क्ष
<u>'''Śrutarvan Ārkṣa'''</u> (‘descendant of Ṛkṣa’) is the name of a prince whose liberality is celebrated in one hymn of the Rigveda (viii. 74, 4. 13), and whose victory over '''[[मृगय|Mṛgaya]]''' is mentioned in another (x. 49, 5).<br>

श्रुतर्-विद्
<u>'''Śrutar-vid'''</u> is the name of a man in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1507/><br>

श्रुत-सेन
<u>'''Śruta-sena'''</u> is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 5, 4, 3) and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xvi. 9, 4) as one of the brothers of '''[[जनम्एजय|Janamejaya]].'''<br>

श्रुष वाह्नेय
<u>'''Śruṣa Vāhneya'''</u> (‘descendant of Vahni’) '''Kāśyapa''' (‘descendant of '''[[कश्यप|Kaśyapa]]'''’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''Devataras,''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 1). It is much more likely that Śruṣa is a mere misreading for '''Śūṣa.'''<br>

श्रुष्टि-गु
<u>'''Śruṣṭi-gu'''</u> (‘possessing obedient oxen’) is the name of a man in a [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1510/><br>

श्रेणि
<u>'''Śreṇi'''</u> means a ‘row’ or ‘line’ of birds,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1511/> or horses,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1511/> or chariots,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1511/> and so forth.<br>

श्रेष्ठिन्
<u>'''Śreṣṭhin'''</u> occurs in several passages of the Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1512/> where the St. Petersburg Dictionary assigns to the word the sense of ‘a man of consequence.’ It is, however, possible that  the word may already have the sense of the ‘headman of a guild,’ the modern Seth.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1512/> There is a similar doubt in the use of ''śraiṣṭhya,''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1512/> which is perhaps not merely ‘the foremost place,’ as usually assumed, but definitely ‘the presidency of a guild.’<br><br>Guilds are referred to in the [[धर्म|Dharma]] Sūtras,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1512/> and they play a considerable part in the Buddhist texts<ref name=fx5_ve2_1512/> and the Epic.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1512/> But the Vedic evidence is inadequate to afford ground for positive assertion or denial of their existence or organization in Vedic times.<br>

श्रोत्रिय
<u>'''Śrotriya'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1513/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1513/> denotes a ‘Brahmin learned in holy lore,’ ‘theologian.’<br>

श्रौत-ऋषि
<u>'''Śrauta-ṛṣi'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1514/> or '''Śrautarṣi,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1514/> ‘descendant of Srutaṛṣi or Śrutarṣi,’ is the patronymic of '''[[देवभाग|Devabhāga]].'''<br>

श्रौमत्य
<u>'''Śraumatya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Śrumant,’ is the name of a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 4, 5, 1).<br>

श्लेष्मन्
<u>'''Śleṣman'''</u> means generally that with which parts of a thing are joined together (from ''śliṣ,'' ‘join’): with reference to a hide,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1516/>  ‘laces’ of some sort may be intended; to a chariot,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1516/> ‘bonds’ or ‘cords’ are probably meant; and to wood,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1516/> ‘glue’ is perhaps the sense.<br>

श्लोक
<u>'''Śloka,'''</u> in the plural, is found enumerated after the '''Upaniṣads,''' and before the '''Sūtras,''' in the list of literary types given in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1517/> In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1517/> the [[श्लोक|Śloka]]-kṛt appears: he is rather the ‘poet,’ as Max Müller<ref name=fx3_ve2_1517/> renders it, than merely one who ‘calls aloud,’ as the St. Petersburg Dictionary explains the term.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1517/> Exactly what is meant cannot be said: ‘verses’ generally may be intended, several kinds being preserved in the Brāhmaṇas and called Ślokas.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1517/><br>

श्लोण्य
<u>'''Śloṇya'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1518/> denotes ‘lameness,’ not ‘skin disease’ (''tvag-doṣa''), as explained by the commentator.<br>

श्व-घ्निन्
<u>'''Śva-ghnin'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1519/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1519/> clearly means a ‘gamester’ or ‘professional gambler.’ It may originally have denoted a ‘hunter.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1519/><br>

श्वन्
<u>'''Śvan'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1520/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1520/> is the word for ‘dog,’ the feminine being Śunī.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1520/> The dog was a tame animal,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1520/> and used  to guard the house from thieves or other intruders.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1520/> He was also employed in hunting the boar (''[[वराह|varāha]]-yu''),<ref name=fx6_ve2_1520/> but was no match for the lion.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1520/> A hundred dogs are mentioned as a gift in a Dānastuti (‘Praise of Gifts’) in a [[वालखिल्य|Vālakhilya]] hymn.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1520/> Elsewhere the dog is regarded as unfit for sacrifice, as being unclean,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1520/> and is driven away from the sacrifice.<ref name=fx10_ve2_1520/> To eat dog's flesh was a last resort of despair and hunger.<ref name=fx11_ve2_1520/> The bones of the feast were given to the dog.<ref name=fx12_ve2_1520/> Saramā figures in legend as Indra's faithful dog<ref name=fx13_ve2_1520/> searching for the cows. Rudra is lord of dogs (''śva-pati'') in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]];<ref name=fx14_ve2_1520/> the ‘dog-keeper’ (''śvanin'') is mentioned in the list of sacrificial victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the same Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx15_ve2_1520/> The four-eyed (''catur-[[अक्ष|akṣa]]'') dogs of certain texts<ref name=fx16_ve2_1520/> are, of course, mythological.<ref name=fx17_ve2_1520/> ''Cf.'' '''[[कुर्कुर|Kurkura]].'''<br>

स्व-पद्
<u>'''Sva-pad'''</u> denotes a ‘savage animal,’ ‘beast of prey,’ in the Atharvaveda (viii. 5, 11; xix. 39, 4).<br>

श्वयथ
<u>'''Śvayatha'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1522/> means ‘swelling.’ Possibly ''śīyathu,'' the disease prevalent in '''[[विदेह|Videha]]''' according to the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta Sutra,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1522/> was a kind of ‘swelling’ (? goitre). <br>

श्व-वर्त
<u>'''Śva-varta,'''</u> ‘found in dogs,’ is, according to some manuscripts, the name of a species of worm in the Atharvaveda (ix. 4, 16). See '''[[शवर्त|Śavarta]].'''<br>

श्वशुर
<u>'''Śvaśura'''</u> from the Rigveda onwards<ref name=fx1_ve2_1524/> denotes the ‘father-inlaw’ of the wife; not till the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period does it include the ‘father-in-law’ of the husband.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1524/> The daughter-in-law ('''[[स्नुषा|Snuṣā]]'''), in the normal case when the father-in-law was the head of the family to which her husband belonged in fact as well as in age, was bound to pay him all respect.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1524/> When the old man had ceased to exercise control, she became mistress (''samrājñī'') over him and his wife.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1524/> In the plural<ref name=fx5_ve2_1524/> the word denotes the ‘parents-in-law.’<br>

श्वश्रू
<u>'''Śvaśrū'''</u> denotes ‘mother-in-law’ of the husband<ref name=fx1_ve2_1525/> as well as of the wife.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1525/> She, together with her husband, if he became unable to manage the family,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1525/> fell under the daughter-in-law's sway, but otherwise was entitled to regard.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1525/> The gambler in the Rigveda<ref name=fx5_ve2_1525/> complains of his having lost the favour of his wife's mother as one of the misfortunes brought upon him by dicing.<br>

श्वाजनि
<u>'''Śvājani'''</u> is the name of a [[वैश्य|Vaiśya]] in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 5, 2). <br>

श्वापद
<u>'''Śvāpada,'''</u> like '''Śvapad,''' denotes a ‘savage animal’ or ‘beast of prey.’ It is mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1527/> in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1527/> and occasionally later.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1527/><br>

श्वा-विध्
<u>'''Śvā-vidh'''</u> (‘dog-piercing’) is the name of the ‘porcupine’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1528/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1528/> It is called ‘long-eared’ (''karṇa'').<ref name=fx3_ve2_1528/> See also '''[[शल्यक|Śalyaka]].'''<br>

श्विक्न
<u>'''Śvikna'''</u> is the name of a people twice mentioned in the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1529/> in connexion with their king, '''[[ऋषभ|Ṛṣabha]] [[याज्ञतुर|Yājñatura]].''' ''Cf.'' '''[[श्वैक्न|Śvaikna]].'''<br>

श्वित्र
<u>'''1. Śvitra'''</u> (‘white’) is the name of a species of serpent in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1530/> and the later Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1530/><br>

श्वित्र
<u>'''2. Śvitra'''</u> is found as an adjective in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xii. 11, 11) in the sense of ‘afflicted with white leprosy.’<br>

श्वित्र्य
<u>'''Śvitrya.'''</u> See '''[[श्वैत्रेय|Śvaitreya]].''' <br>

श्वेत-केतु
<u>'''Śveta-ketu'''</u> Aruṇeya<ref name=fx1_ve2_1533/> (‘descendant of '''Aruṇa'''’) or '''[[औद्दालकि|Auddālaki]]'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1533/> (‘son of '''Uddālaka'''’) is mentioned repeatedly in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]. In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1533/> he appears as [[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]], son of '''[[आरुणि|Āruṇi]],''' and as a '''[[गौतम|Gautama]].''' In the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_1533/> he is quoted as an authority on the vexed question of the duty of the '''[[सदस्य|Sadasya]],''' or the seventeenth priest, at the ritual of the Kauṣītakins, to notify errors in the sacrifice; [[आरुणि|Āruṇi]], his father, is also cited. He was a person of some originality, for he insisted on eating honey despite the general prohibition of the use of that delicacy by Brahmacārins or religious students.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1533/> He was a contemporary of, and was instructed by the '''[[पञ्चाल|Pañcāla]]''' king '''Pravāhaṇa [[जैवल|Jaivala]].'''<ref name=fx6_ve2_1533/> He was also a contemporary of '''[[जनक|Janaka]],''' of '''[[विदेह|Videha]],''' and figured among the Brahmin disputants at his court.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1533/> A story is told of him in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]:<ref name=fx8_ve2_1533/> '''[[जल जातूकर्ण्य|Jala Jātūkarṇya]]''' was lucky enough to become the [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of three peoples or kings, of '''[[काशि|Kāśi]], [[कोसल|Kosala]],''' and '''[[विदेह|Videha]].''' Seeing this, [[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]] felt annoyed and reproached his father with his excessive devotion to sacrifice, which merely enriched and glorified others, not himself. His father replied, forbidding him to speak thus: he had learned the true method of sacrificing, and his ambition in life had been to discuss it with every Brahmin.<br><br>All the references to [[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]] belong to the latest period of Vedic literature. It is, therefore, not surprising that the Āpastamba [[धर्म|Dharma]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx9_ve2_1533/> should refer to him as an Avara, or  person of later days, who still became a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] by special merit. His date, however, must not be fixed too low, because the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] in which he plays so marked a part is certainly earlier than Pāṇini, and was apparently even in that grammarian's time believed to be an ancient work: hence 500 B.C. is probably rather too late than too early a period for [[श्वेतकेतु|Śvetaketu]] as a rough approximation to a date.<ref name=fx10_ve2_1533/><br>

श्वेत्या
<u>'''Śvetyā'''</u> appears in the [[नदी|Nadī]]-[[स्तुति|stuti]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1534/> (‘praise of rivers’) to be a stream, probably a tributary of the Indus.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1534/><br>

श्वैक्न
<u>'''Śvaikna,'''</u> ‘king of the '''Śviknas,'''’ is the title of '''Pratīdarśa,''' who was, according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1535/> one of those who offered the [[दाक्षायण|Dākṣāyaṇa]] sacrifice. He also taught '''[[सुप्लन् सार्ञ्जय|Suplan Sārñjaya]]''' the sacrifice: hence Weber<ref name=fx2_ve2_1535/> has inferred a connexion of the Śviknas and the '''Sṛñjayas.'''<br>

श्वैत्रेय
<u>'''Śvaitreya'''</u> occurs in two passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1536/> where Sāyaṇa sees in the word the name of a man, a ‘descendant of Śvitrā.’ The first passage is almost identical with one in the sixth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1536/> where, however, '''[[दशद्यु|Daśadyu]]''' appears alone without [[श्वैत्रेय|Śvaitreya]]. Ludwig<ref name=fx3_ve2_1536/> identifies [[दशद्यु|Daśadyu]] with [[श्वैत्रेय|Śvaitreya]] (‘son of Śvitrī’), and considers him a son of '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1536/> Bergaigne<ref name=fx5_ve2_1536/> and Baunack<ref name=fx6_ve2_1536/> think he is really '''[[भुज्यु|Bhujyu]].''' Geldner<ref name=fx7_ve2_1536/> considers that he was a bull used for fighting, the son  of a Śvitrā cow,<ref name=fx8_ve2_1536/> but this is very doubtful, though the term ''[[श्वैत्रेय|śvaitreya]]'' is elsewhere applied to a bull.<ref name=fx9_ve2_1536/> [[श्वित्र्य|Śvitrya]]<ref name=fx10_ve2_1536/> seems to have the same sense as [[श्वैत्रेय|Śvaitreya]].<br>

षण्ड
<u>'''Ṣaṇḍa'''</u> is the name of a priest at the snake festival described in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1537/> ''Cf.'' '''[[कुषण्ड|Kuṣaṇḍa]].'''<br>

षण्डिक
<u>'''Ṣaṇḍika'''</u> is mentioned in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1538/> as a contemporary of '''[[केशिन्|Keśin]].''' Probably '''Khaṇḍika''' should be read as usual elsewhere.<br>

सं-रुध्
<u>'''Saṃ-rudh'''</u> and '''Saṃ-likhita''' occur in the Atharvaveda (vii. 50, 5) as two technical terms, of unknown sense, used in dicing.<br>

सं-वत्सर
<u>'''Saṃ-vatsara,'''</u> ‘year,’ is repeatedly mentioned from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1540/><br><br>It duration was, according to the concurrent evidence of the Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas, 360 days, divided into 12 months, being, no doubt, roughly a lunar synodic year, which, however, it exceeded in length by 6 days.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1540/> As a solar year it appears only in the [[निदान|Nidāna]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1540/> of the [[सामवेद|Sāmaveda]], where the sun is stated to spend 13(1/3) days in each of the 27 Nakṣatras. <br><br>The year being obviously out of harmony with the solar year (whether sidereal or tropical), efforts were certainly made to effect an assimilation of the natural and the accepted year. As has been seen (see '''[[मास|Māsa]]'''), the evidence goes strongly to show that the intercalation was not an easy matter in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] period, though there are traces of what may be regarded as a five-yearly or six-yearly intercalation. But there is no conclusive evidence that these periods were really observed.<br><br>Zimmer,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1540/> indeed, considers that the evidence required is afforded by the lists of the years, which are sometimes enumerated as five: [[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]], [[परिवत्सर|Parivatsara]], Idāvatsara, Idvatsara, and Vatsara;<ref name=fx5_ve2_1540/> or [[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]], [[परिवत्सर|Parivatsara]], Idāvatsara, Iduvatsara, Vatsara;<ref name=fx6_ve2_1540/> or [[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]], Idāvatsara, Iduvatsara, Idvatsara, Vatsara;<ref name=fx7_ve2_1540/> or [[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]], [[परिवत्सर|Parivatsara]], Idāvatsara, Anuvatsara, Udvatsara;<ref name=fx8_ve2_1540/> or [[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]], [[परिवत्सर|Parivatsara]], Idāvatsara, Anuvatsara, Idvatsara.<ref name=fx9_ve2_1540/> But it must be noted not merely that the names vary considerably, but that four only are mentioned in some places,<ref name=fx10_ve2_1540/> in others<ref name=fx11_ve2_1540/> three, in others<ref name=fx12_ve2_1540/> two, and in yet others<ref name=fx13_ve2_1540/> six. Moreover, in none of these enumerations is there any reference to the names being connected with a system of intercalation. It is most probable that here we have no more that a mere series of priestly variations of Vatsara, based on the older and more genuine [[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]] and [[परिवत्सर|Parivatsara]] as variants of the simple Vatsara, ‘year.’ The key to the invention of the series is probably to be found in passages like that of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx14_ve2_1540/> where the several '''[[चातुर्मास्य|Cāturmāsya]]''' (‘four-monthly’) sacrifices are equated  with the different years.<ref name=fx15_ve2_1540/> Particularly unjustifiable is the attempt of Zimmer to see in the two-year series a series of two years of 354 days each, with an intercalary month in the second; for the year of 354 days, as such, is not known to have existed before the [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] period.<br><br>Zimmer<ref name=fx16_ve2_1540/> also finds an attempt at intercalation in the famous 12 days in which the Ṛbhus are said to have slept in the house of Agohya.<ref name=fx17_ve2_1540/> He thinks that they represent twelve days added at the winter solstice to equate the lunar year of 354 days and the solar year of 366 days; and from the reverence paid in German antiquity to the ‘12 nights,’ he infers that this mode of intercalation is Indo-Germanic.<ref name=fx18_ve2_1540/> There can be little doubt that this view is wrong, and that the 12 days are merely the ‘reflexion of the year’ (''saṃvatsarasya pratimā'')<ref name=fx19_ve2_1540/> in the sense that they represent the twelve months, and have no relation to chronology at all.<br><br>A reference to the use of [[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]] alone as the fifth year of the cycle is seen by Shamasastry<ref name=fx20_ve2_1540/> in the peculiar dating of certain notices in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx21_ve2_1540/> but this view is improbable.<ref name=fx22_ve2_1540/><br>

संवरण
<u>'''Saṃvaraṇa'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] mentioned in one passage of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1541/> <br>

संवर्ग-जित् लामकायन
<u>'''Saṃvarga-jit Lāmakāyana'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''Śākadāsa''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1542/><br>

सं-वर्त
<u>'''1. Saṃ-varta'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1543/> with '''[[कृश|Kṛśa]]''' as an ancient sacrificer. He may be identical with the next.<br>

सं-वर्त आङ्गिरस
<u>'''2. Saṃ-[[वर्त|varta]] Āṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]'''’) is said in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1544/> to have consecrated '''Marutta.'''<br>

सं-श्रवस् सौवर्चनस
<u>'''Saṃ-śravas Sauvarcanasa'''</u> is the name of a teacher who, according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (i. 7, 2, 1), discussed a point of ritual with '''Tumiñja.'''<br>

सं-श्रावयितृ
<u>'''Saṃ-śrāvayitṛ'''</u> in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (ii. 1) denotes the attendant who announces visitors, the ‘doorkeeper.’<br>

सं-श्लिष्टका
<u>'''Saṃ-śliṣṭakā'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1547/> or '''Saṃśviṣṭikā'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1547/> is the name of an animal mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] and the Śāṭyāyanaka along with the '''[[गोधा|Godhā]].'''<br>

सं-सर्प
<u>'''Saṃ-sarpa.'''</u> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

सं-स्कन्ध
<u>'''Saṃ-skandha'''</u> (‘having the shoulders together’) is the name of a disease mentioned with '''[[विष्कन्ध|Viṣkandha]]''' in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1549/> Whitney,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1549/> however, thinks it is intended as an adjective implying the sense of ‘counteracting the disease [[विष्कन्ध|Viṣkandha]].’ <br>

सं-होत्र
<u>'''Saṃ-hotra'''</u> occurs once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1550/> where Geldner<ref name=fx2_ve2_1550/> thinks the sense of ‘school,’ referring to a school of pupils of the ritual, is most appropriate.<br>

सक्तु
<u>'''Saktu'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1551/> denotes ‘coarsely ground meal,’ ‘groats,’ especially ‘barley meal.’ In the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1551/> where the word occurs only once, it seems rather to mean grain before it is winnowed by the '''[[तितü|Titaü]].''' If the latter word, however, designates a ‘sieve,’ [[सक्तु|Saktu]] might still mean ‘groats,’ as opposed to fine meal.<br>

सखि
<u>'''Sakhi,'''</u> ‘friend,’ is common from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1552/> onwards,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1552/> both literally and metaphorically.<br>

सघन्
<u>'''Saghan'''</u> is the name of a bird, perhaps ‘eagle’ or ‘vulture,’ in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1553/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1553/><br>

सङ्ग प्रयोगि
<u>'''Saṅga Prayogi'''</u> seems to be mentioned as a teacher in the Maitrāyaṇi Saṃhitā (iii. 1, 9).<br>

सं-गति
<u>'''Saṃ-gati'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda (x. 141, 4) seems to have the sense of '''[[सम्इति|Samiti]],''' ‘assembly of the people.’ <br>

सं-गव
<u>'''Saṃ-gava'''</u> denotes the time when the grazing cows are driven together for milking. In the division of the day the word denotes the period before midday, ‘forenoon.’ It is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1556/> and often later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1556/> ''Cf.'' '''Go''' and '''Ahan.'''<br>

सं-गविनी
<u>'''Saṃ-gavinī'''</u> is found in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1557/> where it is said that the animals of the '''Bharatas''' in the evening were at the '''[[गोष्ठ|Goṣṭha]],''' ‘pasture,’ but at midday came to the [[संगविनी|Saṃgavinī]], apparently a shed or an enclosure in which during the heat of the day they were milked.<br>

सं-ग्रहीतृ
<u>'''Saṃ-grahītṛ'''</u> is found in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1558/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1558/> He is an official who figures among the '''Ratnins''' of the king. The sense of ‘charioteer’ seems adequate for every passage, but Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx3_ve2_1558/> in some passages inclines to think that the meaning is ‘treasurer’ of the king.<br>

सं-ग्राम
<u>'''Saṃ-grāma'''</u> denotes primarily, it seems, ‘assembly’ either in peace<ref name=fx1_ve2_1559/> or in war,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1559/> when it means an ‘armed band.’ Its normal sense in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1559/> and later<ref name=fx4_ve2_1559/> is ‘war,’ ‘battle.’ <br><br>Little is known of Vedic warfare, but it seems to have been simple. A body of foot soldiers with charioteers composed every army, the two going together,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1559/> and the foot soldiers being often overthrown by the charioteers,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1559/> who were doubtless the Kṣatriyas and their foremost retainers. Probably the foot soldiers bore little armour, and used only the bow for offence, as is suggested by the account that Herodotus gives of the Indian contingent of the army with which Xerxes invaded Greece.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1559/> The nobles, on the other hand, may have had cuirass ('''[[वर्मन्|Varman]]'''), helmet ('''[[शिप्रा|Śiprā]]'''), and hand-guard ('''[[हस्तघ्न|Hastaghna]]''') as a protection from the friction of the bowstring. On the car was the charioteer, and on his left the warrior ('''[[सारथि|Sārathi]], [[सव्यष्ठा|Savyaṣṭhā]]'''). Riding is never mentioned in war,<ref name=fx8_ve2_1559/> and would hardly have been suited to Vedic ideas, for the warrior mainly depended on his bow, which he could not have used effectively from horseback. The offensive weapon ('''[[आयुध|Āyudha]]''') was practically the bow; spear and sword and axe were very seldom used.<br><br>Whether there was a strict tribal organization of the host, such as is once alluded to in the Homeric poems,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1559/> and is also recognized in Germany by Tacitus,<ref name=fx10_ve2_1559/> is uncertain (''cf.'' '''[[व्रात|Vrāta]]'''), but in the Epic relations ('''[[ज्ञाति|Jñāti]]''') fight together,<ref name=fx11_ve2_1559/> and this rule, no doubt, applied more or less in Vedic times also.<br><br>Cities were besieged and invested (''upa-sad, pra-bhid''),<ref name=fx12_ve2_1559/> probably as a rule by blockade, since the ineffective means of assault of the time would have rendered storming difficult and expensive. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx13_ve2_1559/> thinks that the ''pur cariṣṇū'' of the Rigveda<ref name=fx14_ve2_1559/> was a kind of chariot; it may--like the Trojan horse--have been an Indian anticipation of the Roman means of assaulting a town.<br><br>Besides ordinary wars of defence and conquest, raids into  neighbouring territory seem to have been frequent and normal,<ref name=fx15_ve2_1559/> no doubt because of the booty ('''[[उद्आज|Udāja]], Nirāja''') which was to be won, and which the king had to share with the people.<br><br>Banners ('''[[ध्वज|Dhvaja]]''') were borne in war, and musical instruments ('''[[दुन्दुभि|Dundubhi]], [[बकुर|Bakura]]''')<ref name=fx16_ve2_1559/> were used by the combatants.<br>

सं-घात
<u>'''Saṃ-ghāta'''</u> seems in a few passages<ref name=fx1_ve2_1560/> to have the sense of ‘battle.’<br>

सचिव
<u>'''Saciva'''</u> ‘companion,’ ‘attendant’ (from ''sac,'' ‘follow’), later a common word for the comrade of a king, his minister, is found in Vedic literature in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 20, 1), where it is used by Indra of the Maruts. It seems to correspond in sense to the German ''comes'' or the English ''gesith.''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1561/><br>

स-जात
<u>'''Sa-jāta'''</u> (‘born together’) is found once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1562/> and very often later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1562/> The word must clearly mean a ‘relative,’ and then more widely a man of the same position or rank, but the senses cannot be distinguished, so much do they merge into each other. The Sajātas of a king are of course princes;<ref name=fx3_ve2_1562/> of an  ordinary man, Vaiśyas;<ref name=fx4_ve2_1562/> of a military man, Kṣatriyas. But there is no clear reference to caste as in the later Sajāti<ref name=fx5_ve2_1562/> (‘man of the same caste’). The disputes of Sajātas were notorious.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1562/><br>

सं-चर
<u>'''Saṃ-cara'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1563/> has the sense of the ‘path’ of animals. Normally it is the term designating the ‘passage’ or ‘space’ on the sacrificial ground used or occupied by the several persons taking part in the rite.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1563/><br>

सं-ज्ञान
<u>'''Saṃ-jñāna,'''</u> ‘concord,’ ‘harmony,’ is mentioned from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1564/> onwards<ref name=fx2_ve2_1564/> as a matter of great consequence; the Atharvaveda contains many spells to bring it about. The lack of peace in the Vedic village was almost inevitable in view of its small size and the economic interdependence of its inhabitants. ''Cf.'' '''[[भ्रातृव्य|Bhrātṛvya]].'''<br>

सत
<u>'''Sata'''</u> is the name of a vessel of some kind mentioned in the ritual.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1565/><br>

सतीन-कङ्कत
<u>'''Satīna-kaṅkata'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1566/> is, in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1566/> the name of some animal, according to Sāyaṇa an ‘aquatic snake.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1566/> <br>

सत्य-काम
<u>'''Satya-kāma'''</u> (‘lover of truth’) '''[[जाबाल|Jābāla]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[जबाला|Jabālā]]''') is the name of a teacher, the son of a slave girl by an unknown father. He was initiated as a '''Brahmacārin,''' or religious student, by '''[[गौतम|Gautama]] [[हारिद्रुमत|Hāridrumata]]''' according to the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1567/> He is often cited as an authority in that [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1567/> and in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1567/> where he learns a certain doctrine from '''[[जानकि|Jānaki]] Āyasthūṇa.'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1567/> He is also mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1567/> and the Śatapatha Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1567/><br>

सत्य-यज्ञ
<u>'''Satya-yajña'''</u> (‘true sacrificer’) '''[[पौलुषि|Pauluṣi]]''' (‘descendant of '''Puluṣa'''’) '''[[प्राचीनयोग्य|Prācīnayogya]]''' (‘descendant of Prācīnayoga’) is the name of a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1568/> the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1568/> and the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1568/> In the latter text he is said to have been the pupil of '''[[पुलुष प्राचीनयोग्य|Puluṣa Prācīnayogya]].'''<br>

सत्य-वचस्
<u>'''Satya-vacas'''</u> (‘true-speaking’) '''[[राथीतर|Rāthītara]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[रथीतर|Rathītara]]'''’) is, in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 9, 1), the name of a teacher who insisted on the importance of truth.<br>

सत्य-श्रवस्
<u>'''Satya-śravas'''</u> (‘of true renown’) '''[[वाय्य|Vāyya]]''' (‘descendant of Vayya’) is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1570/> Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_1570/> thinks that he was the son of '''[[सुनीथ शौचद्रथ|Sunītha Śaucadratha]].'''<br>

सत्य-हविस्
<u>'''Satya-havis'''</u> is the name of a mythical [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]], or sacrificial priest, in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (i. 9, 1, 5).<br>

सत्याधिवाक चैत्ररथि
<u>'''Satyādhivāka Caitrarathi'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[चित्ररथ|Citraratha]]'''’) is the name of a man in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 39, 1). <br>

सत्वन्
<u>'''Satvan'''</u> in the '''Rigveda,'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1573/> and occasionally later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1573/> has the sense of ‘warrior.’<br>

सत्वन्त्
<u>'''Satvant'''</u> is the name of a people who are stated in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1574/> to belong to the south. In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1574/> the defeat by '''[[भरत|Bharata]]''' of the Satvants, and his taking away the horse which they had prepared for an [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’), are referred to: this reference clearly shows that in another passage of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1574/> the text must be altered from ''satvanām'' to ''Satvatām,'' ‘of the Satvants,’ against whom it seems the Bharatas made regular raids. The name has also been found by the St. Petersburg Dictionary, Cowell, and Max Müller in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]],<ref name=fx4_ve2_1574/> but it is certain<ref name=fx5_ve2_1574/> that the reading there is not ''[[सत्वन्|Satvan]]-Matsyeṣu,'' but ''sa-[[वश|Vaśa]]-Matsyeṣu.''<br>

सदन
<u>'''Sadana.'''</u> See '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].'''<br>

सदंदि
<u>'''Sadaṃdi.'''</u> See '''[[तक्मन्|Takman]].'''<br>

सदस्
<u>'''Sadas.'''</u> See '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].'''<br>

सदस्य
<u>'''Sadasya.'''</u> See '''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]].'''<br>

सदा-नीरा
<u>'''Sadā-nīrā,'''</u> ‘having water always’ (‘perennial’), is the name of a stream which, according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1579/> was the boundary between the '''Kosalas''' and the '''Videhas.''' The river is identified by the native lexicographers with the Karatoyā,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1579/> but this seems to be too far east. Weber's<ref name=fx3_ve2_1579/> identification  of it with the Gaṇḍakī<ref name=fx4_ve2_1579/> is probably correct; for though the Mahābhārata<ref name=fx5_ve2_1579/> distinguishes the two rivers, there is nothing to show that this is due to any good tradition.<br>

सदा-पृण
<u>'''Sadā-pṛṇa'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1580/><br>

सद्यन्
<u>'''Sadyan'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 8, 6, 1) is a misreading of '''[[सघन्|Saghan]].'''<br>

सध्रि
<u>'''Sadhri'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1582/><br>

सनक
<u>'''Sanaka'''</u> occurs as the name of one of the two '''Kāpyas''' (the other being '''[[नवक|Navaka]]''') who took part in the sacrifice of the '''Vibhindukīyas,''' which is mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1583/> Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_1583/> thinks that the Sanakas are referred to as non-sacrificers in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1583/> but this is very doubtful.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1583/><br>

सनग
<u>'''Sanaga.'''</u> See '''[[सनातन|Sanātana]].'''<br>

सनत्-कुमार
<u>'''Sanat-kumāra'''</u> is the name of a mythical sage in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vii. 1, 1; 26, 2).<br>

सन-श्रुत
<u>'''Sana-śruta'''</u> (‘famed of old’) '''Ariṃdama''' (‘tamer of foes’) is mentioned as a [[महाराज|Mahārāja]] in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 34, 9).<br>

सनाच्-छव
<u>'''Sanāc-chava'''</u> is perhaps the proper name of a teacher in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1587/> The Kapiṣṭhala Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_1587/> has ''Śahanāśchiva.'' Very probably the reading of both texts is bad. <br>

सनातन
<u>'''Sanātana'''</u> is the name of a mythical [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā. In the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1588/> he appears in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) as the pupil of '''[[सनग|Sanaga]]''' and the teacher of '''[[सनारु|Sanāru]],''' both equally mythical persons.<br><br>^1 iv. 3, 3, 1.<br>

सनारु
<u>'''Sanāru.'''</u> See '''[[सनातन|Sanātana]].'''<br>

सनिस्रस
<u>'''Sanisrasa.'''</u> See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

सं-दंश
<u>'''Saṃ-daṃśa.'''</u> See '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].'''<br>

सं-दान
<u>'''Saṃ-dāna'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1592/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1592/> denotes a ‘bond,’ ‘halter,’ or ‘fetter.’<br>

सं-धा
<u>'''Saṃ-dhā'''</u> denotes in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1593/> an ‘agreement’ or ‘compact.’<br>

सं-धि
<u>'''Saṃ-dhi'''</u> denotes the ‘juncture’ of heaven and earth, the ‘horizon,’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1594/> It also has the sense of ‘twilight’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1594/> as the juncture of light and dark.<br>

सं-नहन
<u>'''Saṃ-nahana'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1595/> denotes a ‘band’ or ‘rope.’ <br>

स-पत्न
<u>'''Sa-patna,'''</u> ‘rival,’ is a common word in the later Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1596/> being also found in the tenth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1596/> It is a curious masculine formed by analogy from '''[[स-पत्नी|Sa-patnī]],''' ‘co-wife,’ and so ‘female rival.’<br>

स-पत्नी
<u>'''Sa-patnī'''</u> occurs in the Rigveda in the sense of ‘co-wife’;<ref name=fx1_ve2_1597/> in the first and the last Maṇḍalas it means co-wife as a ‘rival.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1597/> In post-Vedic Sanskrit the word becomes a synonym for ‘rival.’<br>

सप्त-गु
<u>'''Sapta-gu'''</u> is the reputed author of a Rigvedic hymn in a verse of which he is mentioned.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1598/><br>

सप्त सिन्धवः
<u>'''Sapta Sindhavaḥ,'''</u> ‘the seven rivers,’ occur only once in the Rigveda as the designation of a definite country,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1599/> while elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve2_1599/> the seven rivers themselves are meant. Max Müller<ref name=fx3_ve2_1599/> thinks that the five streams of the Panjab, with the Indus and the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],''' are intended; others<ref name=fx4_ve2_1599/> hold that the '''[[कुभा|Kubhā]]''' should be substituted for the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]], or that perhaps the Oxus<ref name=fx5_ve2_1599/> must originally have been one of the seven. Zimmer<ref name=fx6_ve2_1599/> is probably right in laying no stress at all on any identifications; ‘seven’ being one of the favourite numbers in the Rigveda and later. <br>

सप्त सूर्याः
<u>'''Sapta Sūryāḥ,'''</u> the ‘seven suns’ referred to in the Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1600/> are named in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx2_ve2_1600/> as Āroga, Bhrāja, Paṭara, [[पतङ्ग|Pataṅga]], [[स्वर्णर|Svarṇara]], Jyotiṣīmant, and Vibhāsa, but these occur very rarely even later.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1600/> Weber at one time<ref name=fx4_ve2_1600/> thought that the seven planets (see '''[[ग्रह|Graha]]''') were meant by the phrase, but later he abandoned the idea.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1600/> Probably the ‘seven rays’ of the Rigveda<ref name=fx6_ve2_1600/> are meant.<br>

सप्त-मानुष
<u>'''Sapta-mānuṣa'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1601/> as an epithet of Agni, ‘belonging to the seven tribes.’ Hopkins<ref name=fx2_ve2_1601/> thinks that this is a reference to the seven ‘family’ books of the Rigveda (ii.-viii.), but this seems less likely than the view of Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1601/> that ''[[सप्तमानुष|saptamānuṣa]]'' is equivalent to ''vaiśvānara.''<br>

सप्त-वध्रि
<u>'''Sapta-vadhri'''</u> is the name of a protégé of the Aśvins, who appear from several passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1602/> to have rescued him from a tree in which he had got fastened. He is mentioned in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1602/> According to Geldner,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1602/> he is identical with '''Atri.'''<br>

सप्ति
<u>'''Sapti'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1603/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1603/> denotes a ‘swift steed.’ <br>

सप्त्य
<u>'''Saptya'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda (viii. 41, 4) seems to denote a ‘racecourse.’<br>

स-बन्धु
<u>'''Sa-bandhu'''</u> (‘of the same kin’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1605/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1605/> denotes ‘related.’<br>

सभा
<u>'''Sabhā'''</u> is the name of an ‘assembly’ of the Vedic Indians as well as of the ‘hall’ where they met in assembly. It is often mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1606/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1606/> but its exact character is not certain. The hall was clearly used for dicing,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1606/> presurnably when the assembly was not transacting public business: a dicer is called ''[[सभा-स्थाणु|sabhā-sthāṇu]],'' ‘pillar of the assembly hall,’ doubtless because of his constant presence there.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1606/> The hall also served, like the Homeric , as a meeting-place for social intercourse and general conversation about cows and so forth,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1606/> possibly for debates and verbal contests.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1606/><br><br>According to Ludwig,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1606/> the [[सभा|Sabhā]] was an assembly not of all the people, but of the Brahmins and '''Maghavans''' (‘rich patrons’). This view can be supported by the expressions  ''[[सभेय|sabheya]],'' ‘worthy of the assembly,’ applied to a Brahmin,<ref name=fx8_ve2_1606/> ''rayiḥ sabhāvān,'' ‘wealth fitting for the assembly,’<ref name=fx9_ve2_1606/> and so on. But Bloomfield<ref name=fx10_ve2_1606/> plausibly sees in these passages a domestic use of [[सभा|Sabhā]], which is recognized by the St. Petersburg Dictionary in several passages<ref name=fx11_ve2_1606/> as relating to a house, not to the assembly at all. Zimmer<ref name=fx12_ve2_1606/> is satisfied that the [[सभा|Sabhā]] was the meetingplace of the village council, presided over by the '''Grāmaṇī.''' But of this there is no trace whatever. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx13_ve2_1606/> seems right in maintaining that the [[सभा|Sabhā]] and the '''[[सम्इति|Samiti]]''' cannot be distinguished, and that the reference to well-born (''[[सु-जात|su-jāta]]'')<ref name=fx14_ve2_1606/> men being there in session is to the Āryan as opposed to the [[दास|Dāsa]] or [[शूद्र|Śūdra]], not to one class of Āryan as opposed to the other. Hillebrandt also sees in Agni ‘of the hall’ (''sabhya'') a trace of the fire used in sacrifice on behalf of the assembly when it met.<ref name=fx15_ve2_1606/><br><br>Women did not go to the [[सभा|Sabhā]],<ref name=fx16_ve2_1606/> for they were, of course, excluded from political activity. For the [[सभा|Sabhā]] as a courthouse, ''cf.'' '''[[ग्राम्यवादिन्|Grāmyavādin]].''' There is not a single notice of the work done by the [[सभा|Sabhā]].<br>

सभा-चर
<u>'''Sabhā-cara'''</u> is one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1607/> The St. Petersburg  Dictionary thinks it is an adjective equivalent in sense to ''[[सभा|sabhā]]-ga,''’ ‘going to the assembly.’ As he is dedicated to [[धर्म|Dharma]], ‘Justice,’ it is difficult not to see in him a member of the [[सभा|Sabhā]] as a law court, perhaps as one of those who sit to decide cases: there is nothing to show whether the whole assembly did so, or only a chosen body. The special use of [[सभाचर|Sabhācara]] suggests the latter alternative. See also '''[[सभासद्|Sabhāsad]].'''<br>

सभा-पति
<u>'''Sabhā-pati,'''</u> ‘lord of the assembly,’ is an epithet in the [[शतरुद्रिय|Śatarudriya]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1608/><br>

सभा-पाल
<u>'''Sabhā-pāla'''</u> is found in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 7, 4, 6), where the sense may be ‘guardian of an assembly hall.’<br>

सभाविन्
<u>'''Sabhāvin'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 4, 16, 1) denotes, according to the commentator Sāyaṇa, the ‘keeper of a gambling hall.’<br>

सभा-सद्
<u>'''Sabhā-sad,'''</u> ‘sitter in the assembly,’ is probably a technical description of the assessors who decided legal cases in the assembly (''cf.'' '''[[सभाचर|Sabhācara]]'''). The term, which is found in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1611/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1611/> cannot well merely denote any member of the assembly. It is also possible that the Sabhāsads, perhaps the heads of families, were expected to be present at the [[सभा|Sabhā]] oftener than the ordinary man: the meetings of the assembly for justice may have been more frequent than for general discussion and decision.<br>

सभा-स्थाणु
<u>'''Sabhā-sthāṇu.'''</u> See '''[[सभा|Sabhā]].'''<br>

सभेय
<u>'''Sabheya.'''</u> See '''[[सभा|Sabhā]].''' <br>

सम्-अङ्क
<u>'''Sam-aṅka'''</u> is a word of obscure sense occurring in two passages of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1614/> Bloomfield<ref name=fx2_ve2_1614/> renders it ‘hook’ in the first, and takes it to mean an insect destructive of grain in the other.<br>

समन
<u>'''Samana'''</u> is a word of somewhat doubtful sense in the Rigveda. Roth<ref name=fx1_ve2_1615/> renders it either ‘battle’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1615/> or ‘festival.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1615/> Pischel<ref name=fx4_ve2_1615/> thinks that it was a general popular festivity to which women went to enjoy themselves,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1615/> poets to win fame,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1615/> bowmen to gain prizes at archery,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1615/> horses to run races;<ref name=fx8_ve2_1615/> and which lasted until morning<ref name=fx9_ve2_1615/> or until a conflagration, caused by the fires kept burning all night, scattered the celebrators.<ref name=fx10_ve2_1615/> Young women,<ref name=fx11_ve2_1615/> elderly women,<ref name=fx12_ve2_1615/> sought there to find a husband, and courtezans to make profit of the occasion.<ref name=fx13_ve2_1615/><br>

समर
<u>'''Samara'''</u> in the sense of ‘battle’ is found in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1616/> and, according to Geldner,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1616/> in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1616/><br>

समा
<u>'''Samā'''</u> appears originally to have denoted ‘summer,’ a sense which may be seen in a few passages of the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1617/>  Hence it also denotes more generally ‘season,’ a rare use.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1617/> More commonly it is simply ‘year’;<ref name=fx3_ve2_1617/> but in one place the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_1617/> interprets it in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx5_ve2_1617/> as meaning ‘month,’ a doubtful sense.<br>

समान
<u>'''Samāna.'''</u> See '''[[प्राण|Prāṇa]].'''<br>

समान-गोत्र
<u>'''Samāna-gotra'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1619/> and '''[[समान|Samāna]]-jana'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1619/> mean ‘belonging to the same family’ and ‘class’ respectively in the Brāhmaṇas. '''[[समान|Samāna]]-[[बन्धु|bandhu]],''' ‘having the same kin,’ is found in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1619/><br>

समान्त
<u>'''Samānta'''</u> (‘having the same boundary’), ‘neighbour,’ and therefore ‘foe,’ occurs in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (ii. 1, 24).<br>

सम्-इति
<u>'''Sam-iti'''</u> denotes an ‘assembly’ of the Vedic tribe. It is already mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1621/> and often later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1621/> sometimes in connexion with '''[[सभा|Sabhā]].'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1621/> Ludwig<ref name=fx4_ve2_1621/> considers that the [[सम्इति|Samiti]] included all the people, primarily the ''viśaḥ,'' ‘subjects,’ but also the '''Maghavans''' and Brahmins if they desired, though the [[सभा|Sabhā]] was their special assembly. This view is not probable, nor is that of Zimmer,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1621/> that the [[सभा|Sabhā]] was the village assembly. Hillebrandt appears to be right in holding that [[सम्इति|Samiti]] and [[सभा|Sabhā]] are much the same, the one being the assembly, the other primarily the place of assembly.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1621/> <br><br>The king went to the assembly<ref name=fx7_ve2_1621/> just as he went to the [[सभा|Sabhā]]. That he was elected there, as Zimmer<ref name=fx8_ve2_1621/> thinks, is as uncertain as whether he was elected at all (see '''[[राजन्|Rājan]]'''). But there are clear signs that concord between king and assembly were essential for his prosperity.<ref name=fx9_ve2_1621/><br><br>It is reasonable to assume that the business of the assembly was general deliberation on policy of all kinds, legislation so far as the Vedic Indian cared to legislate, and judicial work (''cf.'' '''[[सभासद्|Sabhāsad]]'''). But of all these occupations there is, perhaps as a result of the nature of the texts, little or no evidence directly available.<br><br>The gods had a [[सम्इति|Samiti]], hence called ''daivī,'' ‘divine,’<ref name=fx10_ve2_1621/> just as they had a [[सभा|Sabhā]].<ref name=fx11_ve2_1621/><br><br>The assembly disappears as an effective part of government in the Buddhist texts,<ref name=fx12_ve2_1621/> the Epic,<ref name=fx13_ve2_1621/> and the law-books.<ref name=fx14_ve2_1621/><br>

सम्-इध्
<u>'''Sam-idh'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1622/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1622/> denotes the ‘fuel’ for kindling fire. Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve2_1622/> inclines to see in one passage<ref name=fx4_ve2_1622/> the name of a priest, the later Agnidh.<br>

सम्-उद्र
<u>'''Sam-udra'''</u> (literally ‘gathering of waters’), ‘ocean,’ is a frequent word in the Rigveda and later. It is of importance in  so far as it indicates that the Vedic Indians knew the sea. This is, indeed, denied by Vivien de Saint Martin,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1623/> but not only do Max Müller<ref name=fx2_ve2_1623/> and Lassen<ref name=fx3_ve2_1623/> assert it, but even Zimmer,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1623/> who is inclined to restrict their knowledge of the sea as far as possible, admits it in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1623/> and of course later.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1623/> He points out that the ebb and flow of the sea are unknown, that the mouths of the Indus are never mentioned, that fish is not a known diet in the Rigveda (''cf.'' '''[[मत्स्य|Matsya]]'''), and that in many places [[सम्उद्र|Samudra]] is metaphorically used, as of the two oceans,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1623/> the lower and the upper oceans,<ref name=fx8_ve2_1623/> etc. In other passages he thinks that [[सम्उद्र|Samudra]] denotes the river Indus when it receives all its Panjab tributaries.<ref name=fx9_ve2_1623/> It is probable that this is to circumscribe too narrowly the Vedic knowledge of the ocean, which was almost inevitable to people who knew the Indus. There are references to the treasures of the ocean,<ref name=fx10_ve2_1623/> perhaps pearls or the gains of trade,<ref name=fx11_ve2_1623/> and the story of '''[[भुज्यु|Bhujyu]]''' seems to allude to marine navigation.<br><br>That there was any sea trade with Babylon in Vedic times cannot be proved: the stress Iaid<ref name=fx12_ve2_1623/> on the occurrence in the Hebrew Book of Kings<ref name=fx13_ve2_1623/> of ''qof'' and ''tukhiīm,'' ‘monkey’ (''kapi'') and ‘peacock,’ is invalidated by the doubtful date of the Book of Kings. There is, besides, little reason to assume an early date for the trade that no doubt developed later, perhaps about 700 B.C.<ref name=fx14_ve2_1623/> <br><br>In the later texts [[सम्उद्र|Samudra]] repeatedly means the sea.<ref name=fx15_ve2_1623/><br>

सम्राज्
<u>'''Samrāj'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1624/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1624/> means ‘superior ruler, ‘sovereign,’ as expressing a greater degree of power than ‘king’ ('''[[राजन्|Rājan]]'''). In the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1624/> in accordance with its curious theory of the '''[[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]]''' and '''[[राजसूय|Rājasūya]],''' the [[सम्राज्|Samrāj]] is asserted to be a higher authority than a king, and to have become one by the sacrifice of the [[वाजपेय|Vājapeya]]. There is, however, no trace of the use of the word as ‘emperor’ in the sense of an ‘overlord of kings,’ probably because political conditions furnished no example of such a status, as for instance was attained in the third century B.C. by Aśoka. At the same time [[सम्राज्|Samrāj]] denotes an important king like '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' of '''[[विदेह|Videha]].'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1624/> It is applied in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1624/> as the title of the eastern kings. ''Cf.'' '''[[राज्य|Rājya]].'''<br>

सरघ्
<u>'''Saragh,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1625/> '''Saraghā,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1625/> both denote ‘bee’ in the Brāhmaṇas. See also '''[[सरह्|Sarah]].'''<br>

सरयु
<u>'''Sarayu'''</u> is mentioned thrice in the Rigveda as the name of river. '''[[चित्ररथ|Citraratha]]''' and Arṇa are said to have been defeated apparently by the '''Turvaśas''' and '''Yadus''' who crossed the  [[सरयु|Sarayu]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1626/> [[सरयु|Sarayu]] appears in one passage with '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]''' and '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1626/> and in another with '''[[रसा|Rasā]], [[अनितभा|Anitabhā]],''' and '''Kubha.'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1626/> Later, in the post-Vedic period, Sarayū, rarely [[सरयु|Sarayu]], is the name of a river in Oudh, the modern Sarjū.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1626/> Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve2_1626/> regards this as the river meant in all the Vedic passages, seeing in the last,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1626/> which may be used as an argument for locating the [[सरयु|Sarayu]] in the Panjab, a reference to the north-east monsoon as well as to the usual monsoon from the west. Hopkins<ref name=fx6_ve2_1626/> thinks that the [[सरयु|Sarayu]] is to be found in the west, and Ludwig<ref name=fx7_ve2_1626/> identifies it with the Kurum ('''[[क्रुमु|Krumu]]'''). Vivien de St. Martin considered it to be probably identical with the united course of the '''[[शुतुद्री|Śutudrī]]''' (Sutlej) and '''[[विपाश्|Vipāś]]''' (Beas).<br>

सरस्
<u>'''Saras'''</u> denotes ‘lake’ in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1627/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1627/><br>

सरस्वती
<u>'''Sarasvatī'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1628/> is the name of a river frequently mentioned in the Rigveda and later. In many passages<ref name=fx2_ve2_1628/> of the later texts it is certain the river meant is the modern [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]], which loses  itself in the sands of Patiala (see '''[[विनशन|Vinaśana]]'''). Even Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_1628/> admits that this river is intended in some passages of the Rigveda. With the '''[[दृषद्वती|Dṛṣadvatī]]'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1628/> it formed the western boundary of [[ब्रह्मावर्त|Brahmāvarta]] (see '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]]'''). It is the holy stream of early Vedic India. The Sūtras<ref name=fx5_ve2_1628/> mention sacrifices held on its banks as of great importance and sanctity.<br><br>In many other passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1628/> and even later,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1628/> Roth held that another river, the '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]''' (Indus), was really meant: only thus could it be explained why the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] is called the ‘foremost of rivers’ (''nadītamā''),<ref name=fx8_ve2_1628/> is said to go to the ocean,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1628/> and is referred to as a large river, on the banks of which many kings,<ref name=fx10_ve2_1628/> and, indeed, the five tribes, were located.<ref name=fx11_ve2_1628/> This view is accepted by Zimmer<ref name=fx12_ve2_1628/> and others.<ref name=fx13_ve2_1628/><br><br>On the other hand, Lassen<ref name=fx14_ve2_1628/> and Max Müller<ref name=fx15_ve2_1628/> maintain the identity of the Vedic [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] with the later [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].<ref name=fx16_ve2_1628/> The latter is of opinion that in Vedic times the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] was as large a stream as the Sutlej, and that it actually reached the  sea either after union with the Indus or not, being the ‘iron citadel,’ as the last boundary on the west, a frontier of the Panjab against the rest of India. There is no conclusive evidence of there having been any great change in the size or course of the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]], though it would be impossible to deny that the river may easily have diminished in size. But there are strong reasons to accept the identification of the later and the earlier [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] throughout. The insistence on the divine character of the river is been in the very hymn<ref name=fx17_ve2_1628/> which refers to it as the support of the five tribes, and corresponds well with its later sacredness. Moreover, that hymn alludes to the '''Pārāvatas,''' a people shown by the later evidence of the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx18_ve2_1628/> to have been in the east, a very long way from their original home, if [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] means the Indus. Again, the '''Pūrus,''' who were settled on the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],<ref name=fx19_ve2_1628/> could with great difficulty be located in the far west. Moreover, the five tribes might easily be held to be on the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]], when they were, as they seem to have been, the western neighbours of the '''Bharatas''' in '''[[कुरुक्षेत्र|Kurukṣetra]],''' and the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]] could easily be regarded as the boundary of the Panjab in that sense. Again, the ‘seven rivers’ in one passage<ref name=fx20_ve2_1628/> clearly designate a district: it is most probable that they are not the five rivers with the Indus and the '''[[कुभा|Kubhā]]''' (Cabul river), but the five rivers, the Indus and the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]]. Nor is it difficult to see why the river is said to flow to the sea: either the Vedic poet had never followed the course of the river to its end, or the river did actually penetrate the desert either completely or for a long distance, and only in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] period was its disappear-  ance in the desert found out. It is said, indeed, in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx21_ve2_1628/> that the five rivers go to the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]], but this passage is not only late (as the use of the word '''[[देश|Deśa]]''' shows), but it does not say that the five rivers meant are those of the Panjab. Moreover, the passage has neither a parallel in the other Saṃhitās, nor can it possibly be regarded as an early production; if it is late it must refer to the later [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].<br><br>Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx22_ve2_1628/> on the whole, adopts this view of the [[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],<ref name=fx23_ve2_1628/> but he also sees in it, besides the designation of a mythical stream, the later Vaitaraṇī,<ref name=fx24_ve2_1628/> as well as the name of the Arghandab in Arachosia.<ref name=fx25_ve2_1628/> This opinion depends essentially on his theory that the sixth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda places the scene of its action in Iranian lands, as opposed to the seventh Maṇḍala: it is as untenable as that theory itself.<ref name=fx26_ve2_1628/> Brunnhofer<ref name=fx27_ve2_1628/> at one time accepted the Iranian identification, but later<ref name=fx28_ve2_1628/> decided for the Oxus, which is quite out of the question. See also '''[[प्लक्ष प्रास्रवण|Plakṣa Prāsravaṇa]].'''<br>

सरह्
<u>'''Sarah'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1629/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1629/> denotes ‘bee.’ ''Cf.'' '''Saragha.'''<br>

सरित्
<u>'''Sarit'''</u> denotes ‘stream’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1630/> and later.^2 <br>

सरीसृप
<u>'''Sarīsṛpa'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1631/> and often later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1631/> any ‘creeping animal’ or ‘reptile.’<br>

सर्प
<u>'''Sarpa,'''</u> ‘serpent,’ occurs once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1632/> where '''Ahi''' is the usual word, but often later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1632/><br>

सर्प-राज्ञी
<u>'''Sarpa-rājñī,'''</u> ‘serpent-queen,’ is the alleged authoress of a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1633/> according to the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1633/><br>

सर्प-विद्या
<u>'''Sarpa-vidyā,'''</u> the ‘science of snakes,’ is enumerated in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] among branches of learning. It must have been reduced to fixed rules, since a section (''[[पर्वन्|parvan]]'') of it is referred to as studied. The Gopatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1634/> has the form [[सर्प|Sarpa]]-veda.<br><br>^1 xiii. 4, 3, 9. ''Cf.'' Śānkhāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], xvi. 2, 25. The Āśvalāyana Srauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], x. 7, 5, has '''[[विष-विद्या|Viṣa-vidyā]],''' and the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vii. 1. 2. 4; 2, 1; 4, 1; 7, 1) has ''sarpadevajana-[[विद्या|vidyā]].''<br>

सर्पि वात्सि
<u>'''Sarpi Vātsi'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[वत्स|Vatsa]]'''’) is the name of a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1635/><br>

सर्पिस्
<u>'''Sarpis'''</u> denotes ‘melted butter,’ whether in a liquid or solidified condition, and not differing from '''[[घृत|Ghṛta]]''' according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary. Roth there rejects the definition cited by Sāyaṇa in his commentary on the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1636/> which discriminates [[सर्पिस्|Sarpis]] as the liquid and [[घृत|Ghṛta]] as the solid condition of the butter. The word is repeatedly mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1636/> and later.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1636/> <br>

सर्व-चरु
<u>'''Sarva-caru'''</u> is found in a passage of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1637/> and of the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1637/> where the gods are referred to as holding a sacrifice ''sarvacarau.'' The word is the name of a man according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary; the name of a place<ref name=fx3_ve2_1637/> seems possible, or even a mere adjective may be meant.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1637/><br>

सर्व-वेदस
<u>'''Sarva-vedasa'''</u> denotes in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas either a sacrifice in which the sacrificer gives his all to the priests,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1638/> or the whole property of a man.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1638/><br>

सर्षप
<u>'''Sarṣapa,'''</u> denoting ‘mustard’ or ‘mustard seed,’ occurs only a few times in later Vedic texts.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1639/><br>

सला-वृकी
<u>'''Salā-vṛkī.'''</u> See '''[[सालावृक|Sālāvṛka]].'''<br>

सलिल-वात
<u>'''Salila-vāta'''</u> occurs in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1641/> as an adjective meaning ‘favoured with a wind from the water.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1641/> It probably refers to the wind from the ocean, the south-west monsoon.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1641/> <br>

सल्व
<u>'''Salva'''</u> is the name of a people mentioned in a passage of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1642/> which records a boast by '''[[श्यापर्ण सायकायन|Śyāparṇa Sāyakāyana]]''' that if a certain rite of his had been completed, his race would have been the nobles, Brahmins, and peasants of the Salvas, and even as it was his race would surpass the Salvas. This people appears also to be alluded to as ''Sālvīḥ (prajāḥ)'' in the [[मन्त्र|Mantra]] Pāṭha,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1642/> where they are said to have declared that their king was '''Yaugandhari''' when they stayed their chariots<ref name=fx3_ve2_1642/> on the banks of the '''[[यमुना|Yamunā]].''' There is later evidence<ref name=fx4_ve2_1642/> indicating that the Sālvas or Śālvas were closely connected with the '''Kuru-Pañcālas,''' and that apparently some of them, at least, were victorious near the banks of the [[यमुना|Yamunā]]. There is no good evidence to place them in the north-west in Vedic times.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1642/><br>

सव्य-ष्ठा
<u>'''Savya-ṣṭhā,'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1643/> '''Savya-ṣṭhṛ,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1643/> '''Savye-ṣṭha,'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1643/> and '''Savya-stha'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1643/> are all various forms of the word for ‘car-fighter,’ as opposed to '''[[सारथि|Sārathi]],''' ‘charioteer,’ showing that, as was natural, the fighter stood on the left of the driver. The commentators<ref name=fx5_ve2_1643/> are inclined to see in the [[सव्यष्ठा|Savyaṣṭhā]] merely another ‘charioteer,’ but this is quite unjustifiable,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1643/> and is perhaps due to later caste prejudice against a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]] charioteer.<br>

सस
<u>'''Sasa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1644/> denotes ‘herb’ or ‘grass.’<ref name=fx1_ve2_1644/> The word is also applied to the Soma plant<ref name=fx2_ve2_1644/> and the sacrificial straw.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1644/> <br>

ससर्परी
<u>'''Sasarparī'''</u> is a word occurring in two curious verses of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1645/> According to a later interpretation,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1645/> it designates a particular kind of skill in speech which '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' obtained from '''[[जमद्अग्नि|Jamadagni]].''' What it was is quite uncertain.<br>

सस्य
<u>'''Sasya'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1646/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1646/> regularly denotes ‘corn’ generally. It corresponds to the Avestan ''hahya.'' See '''[[कृषि|Kṛṣi]].'''<br>

सह
<u>'''Saha'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1647/> is, according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1647/> the name of a plant, but Bloomfield<ref name=fx3_ve2_1647/> thinks the word is only an adjective meaning ‘mighty.’<br>

सह-देव
<u>'''Saha-deva'''</u> is the name of a prince in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1648/> where he is victorious over the '''Śimyus''' and '''Dasyus.''' It is quite probable that he is identical with King [[सहदेव|Sahadeva]] [[सार्ञ्जय|Sārñjaya]], who is mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1648/> as having once been called '''[[सुप्लन् सार्ञ्जय|Suplan Sārñjaya]],''' and as having changed his name because of his success in performing the [[दाक्षायण|Dākṣāyaṇa]] sacrifice. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1648/> he is mentioned with '''Somaka Sahadevya,''' who also appears in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1648/><br>

सह-देवी
<u>'''Saha-devī'''</u> is the name of a plant in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1649/> according to the reading of the commentary. <br>

सहमान
<u>'''Sahamāna'''</u> is the name of a plant in the Atharvaveda (ii. 25, 2; iv. 17, 2; viii. 2, 6; 7, 5).<br>

सहो-जित्
<u>'''Saho-jit.'''</u> See '''Jaitrāyaṇa.'''<br>

सांवरणि
<u>'''Sāṃvaraṇi'''</u> is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1652/> in one passage, where it naturally seems to be a patronymic (‘descendant of Saṃvaraṇa’) of Manu. According to Bloomfield,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1652/> it is a corruption for '''[[सावर्णि|Sāvarṇi]],''' a reference to Manu's birth from the ''savarṇā,'' ‘similar’ female who was substituted for Saraṇyū according to the legend (see '''Manu'''). This is possible, but not certain. Scheftelowitz<ref name=fx3_ve2_1652/> thinks that the reading of the Kaśmir manuscript of the Rigveda, which has ''sāṃvaraṇam,'' ‘found on the sacrificial ground,’ as an epithet of Soma, is to be preferred. But this seems quite improbable.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1652/> We must either recognize a real man called Manu [[सांवरणि|Sāṃvaraṇi]]; or take Manu as one name, [[सांवरणि|Sāṃvaraṇi]] as another; or admit that Manu [[सांवरणि|Sāṃvaraṇi]] is simply Manu with a patronymic derived from an unknown legend.<br>

साकम्-अश्व देवरात
<u>'''Sākam-[[अश्व|aśva]] Devarāta'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]],''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) which concludes the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (xv. 1).<br>

सांकृती-पुत्र
<u>'''Sāṃkṛtī-putra'''</u> (‘son of a female descendant of Saṃkṛta’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[आलम्बायनीपुत्र|Ālambāyanīputra]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1654/> or '''[[आलम्बीपुत्र|Ālambīputra]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1654/> in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<br>

सांकृत्य
<u>'''Sāṃkṛtya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Saṃkṛti,’ is the name of a teacher whose pupil was '''[[पाराशर्य|Pārāśarya]]''' in the first two Vaṃśas (lists of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1655/> <br>

साची-गुण
<u>'''Sācī-guṇa'''</u> is mentioned, apparently as a place in the territory of the '''Bharatas,''' in a verse occurring in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1656/> Leumann,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1656/> however, thinks an epithet of Indra, Śācīgu, may be meant.<br>

सांजीवी-पुत्र
<u>'''Sāṃjīvī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of Sāṃjīvī,’ is the name of a teacher who appears in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the tenth Kāṇḍa of the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1657/> and at the end of the fourteenth Kāṇḍa in the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] recension,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1657/> as a pupil of '''[[माण्डूकायनि|Māṇḍūkāyani]].''' In the Vaṃśas at the end of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] in both recensions<ref name=fx3_ve2_1657/> he is given as a pupil of '''[[प्राश्नीपुत्र|Prāśnīputra]] [[आसुरिवासिन्|Āsurivāsin]].''' It seems clear that he united in himself two lines of teachers--that of the tradition of the firecult from '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]],''' and that of the tradition of '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]].'''<br>

साति औष्ट्राक्षि
<u>'''Sāti Auṣṭrākṣi'''</u> (‘descendant of Uṣṭrākṣa’) is the name of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1658/><br>

सात्य-कामि
<u>'''Sātya-kāmi'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[सत्यकाम|Satyakāma]]'''’) is the patronymic of '''[[केशिन्|Keśin]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (ii. 6, 2, 3).<br>

सात्य-कीर्त
<u>'''Sātya-kīrta'''</u> is the name of a school of teachers mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 32, 1).<br>

सात्य-यज्ञ
<u>'''Sātya-yajña'''</u> (‘descendant of Saryayajña’) is the name of a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 1, 1, 4).<br>

सात्य-यज्ञि
<u>'''1. Sātya-yajñi'''</u> (‘descendant of Satyayajña’) is the patronymic of '''Somaśuṣma''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xi. 6, 2, 1. 3; xiii. 4, 2, 4; 5, 3, 9). <br>

सात्य-यज्ञि
<u>'''2. Sātya-yajñi'''</u> is the name of a school of teachers mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 4, 5) with the '''Śailanas''' and the '''Kārīradis.'''<br>

सात्य-हव्य
<u>'''Sātya-havya'''</u> (‘descendant of Satyahavya’) is the patronymic of a '''[[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]]''' who is mentioned as a contemporary of '''[[अत्य्अराति जानंतपि|Atyarāti Jānaṃtapi]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 23, 9), and of '''[[देवभाग|Devabhāga]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vi. 6, 2, 2).<br>

सात्राजित
<u>'''Sātrājita'''</u> (‘descendant of Satrājit’) is the patronymic of '''Śatānīka.'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1665/><br>

सात्रा-साह
<u>'''Sātrā-sāha'''</u> (‘descendant of Satrāsāha’) is the patronymic of '''Śoṇa.'''<br><br>^1 Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], xiii. 5, 4, 16, 18.<br>

सादिन्
<u>'''Sādin'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1667/> denotes the ‘rider’ of a horse as opposed to ''a-sāda,'' ‘pedestrian.’ An ''[[अश्व|aśva]]-[[सादिन्|sādin]],'' ‘horse-rider,’ is known to the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1667/> The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1667/> and the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_1667/> itself contain clear references to horse-riding, while the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx5_ve2_1667/> refers to mounting a horse sideways. Āśvalāyana<ref name=fx6_ve2_1667/> knows ''sādya'' as a ‘riding horse’ opposed to ''[[वह्य|vahya]],'' a ‘draught animal.’<br>

साधारणी
<u>'''Sādhāraṇī'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1668/> seems to refer not so much to an ''uxor communis,'' like Draupadī in the Epic, as Max Müller<ref name=fx2_ve2_1668/> suggests, but to a courtezan. <br>

साप्त
<u>'''Sāpta'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1669/> may be a proper name, but the sense is quite uncertain.<br>

साप्तरथ-वाहनि
<u>'''Sāptaratha-vāhani'''</u> (‘descendant of Saptarathavāhana’) is the patronymic of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[शाण्डिल्य|Śāṇḍilya]],''' in the '''Śatapatha''' [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1670/><br>

साप्य
<u>'''Sāpya'''</u> or '''[[साय्य|Sāyya]]''' is the patronymic of '''Namī''' in the Rigveda (vi. 20, 6).<br>

साम-वेद
<u>'''Sāma-veda,'''</u> ‘the Veda of the Sāman chants,’ is the name of a collection of verses for chanting, often mentioned in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1672/> The Sāman itself is repeatedly referred to in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1672/> and the triad Ṛc, [[यजुस्|Yajus]], and Sāman is common from the Atharvaveda onwards.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1672/> These texts know also the Sāma-ga, the ‘Sāman-chanter,’<ref name=fx4_ve2_1672/> who occurs later.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1672/><br>

साम-श्रवस्
<u>'''Sāma-śravas'''</u> (‘famed for chants’) occurs in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1673/> According to Max Müller,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1673/> the word is an epithet of '''[[याज्ञवल्क्य|Yājñavalkya]],''' but Bo7htlingk<ref name=fx3_ve2_1673/> takes it as the name of a pupil of that teacher.<br>

साम-श्रवस
<u>'''Sāma-śravasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[सामश्रवस्|Sāmaśravas]]'''’) is the patronymic of '''[[कुषीतक|Kuṣītaka]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xvii. 4, 3). <br>

सामुद्रि
<u>'''Sāmudri'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[सम्उद्र|Samudra]]'''’) is the name of a mythical sage, [[अश्व|Aśva]], in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 2, 2, 14).<br>

सांमद
<u>'''Sāṃmada'''</u> (‘descendant of Saṃmada’) is the patronymic of the mythical [[मत्स्य|Matsya]] in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 4, 3, 12).<br>

साम्राज्य
<u>'''Sāmrājya.'''</u> See '''[[सम्राज्|Samrāj]]''' and '''[[राज्य|Rājya]].'''<br>

साय
<u>'''Sāya'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1678/> denotes ‘evening’ in the Rigveda and later, usually appearing in the adverbial form Sāyam,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1678/> ‘in the evening.’ ''Cf.'' '''Ahar.'''<br>

सायक
<u>'''1. Sāyaka'''</u> denotes ‘arrow’ in the '''Rigveda''' (ii. 33, 10; iii. 53, 23; x. 48, 4).<br>

सायक जान-श्रुतेय
<u>'''2. Sāyaka [[जान|Jāna]]-śruteya'''</u> (‘descendant of Janaśruta’) '''[[काण्ड्विय|Kāṇḍviya]]''' is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[जनश्रुत|Janaśruta]] [[काण्ड्विय|Kāṇḍviya]],''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 2).<br>

सायकायन
<u>'''Sāyakāyana'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[सायक|Sāyaka]]'''’) is the patronymic of '''Śyāparṇa''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1681/> and also of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[कौशिकायनि|Kauśikāyani]]''' in the second [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1681/><br>

साय्य
<u>'''Sāyya.'''</u> See '''[[साप्य|Sāpya]].'''<br>

सारथि
<u>'''Sārathi'''</u> denotes the ‘charioteer’ as opposed to the warrior ('''[[सव्यष्ठा|Savyaṣṭhā]]''') in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1683/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1683/> <br>

सारमेय
<u>'''Sārameya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Saramā,’ Indra's mythical dog, is applied to a dog on earth in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1684/> as also to the dogs of Yama.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1684/><br>

सार्ञ्जय
<u>'''Sārñjaya'''</u> is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1685/> in a Dānastuti (‘praise of gifts’) where the word probably denotes the ‘'''[[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]]''' king’ rather than a ‘descendant of [[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]].’ According to the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1685/> he was '''[[प्रस्तोक|Prastoka]],''' mentioned, in the same hymn, but this conclusion is not very cogent. He was clearly a patron of the '''Bharadvājas.''' The same epithet belongs to '''[[सहदेव|Sahadeva]],''' ''alias'' '''Suplan.'''<br><br>^3 Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], ii. 4, 4, 4; xii. 8, 2, 3.<br><br>''Cf.'' Hillebrandt, ''Vedische Mythologie,'' 1, 104, 105.<br>

सार्प-राज्ञी
<u>'''Sārpa-rājñī'''</u> in the Pañcaviṃśa (iv. 9, 4) and the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] (xxvii. 4) Brāhmaṇas is identical with '''[[सर्पराज्ञी|Sarparājñī]].'''<br>

सार्व-सेनि
<u>'''Sārva-seni'''</u> (‘descendant of Sarvasena’) is the patronymic of '''[[शौचेय|Śauceya]]''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vii. 1, 10, 3).<br>

साला-वृक
<u>'''Sālā-vṛka'''</u> is found twice in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1688/> apparently denoting the ‘hyæna’ or ‘wild dog.’ This sense also seems appropriate in the later narrative of the destruction of the '''Yatis''' by Indra,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1688/> who is said to have handed them over to the Sālāvṛkas. Sālāvṛkeya<ref name=fx3_ve2_1688/> is a variant form of the same word, meaning literally ‘descendant of a [[सालावृक|Sālāvṛka]].’ The feminine is Sālāvṛkī,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1688/> but in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx5_ve2_1688/> it appears as [[सलावृकी|Salāvṛkī]]. ''Cf.'' '''[[तरक्षु|Tarakṣu]].''' <br>

सावयस
<u>'''Sāvayasa'''</u> (‘descendant of Savayasa’) is the patronymic of Aṣāḍha, or Āṣāḍha, in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 1, 1, 7).<br>

सा-वर्णि
<u>'''Sā-varṇi'''</u> is found as a patronymic in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1690/> together with Sāvarṇya.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1690/> It is clear that no man called Savarṇa ever existed, though Roth<ref name=fx3_ve2_1690/> accepted that view, and that the reference is to the mythical '''Manu''' [[सावर्णि|Sāvarṇi]], the descendant of the ''sa-varṇā'' female, who, according to the legend,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1690/> took the place of Saraṇyū.<br>

सिंह
<u>'''Siṃha'''</u> denotes the ‘lion’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1691/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1691/> The roaring (''nad'') of the lion is often alluded to,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1691/> and is called thundering (''stanatha'').<ref name=fx4_ve2_1691/> He wanders about (''ku-cara'') and lives in the hills (''giri-ṣṭha''),<ref name=fx5_ve2_1691/> and is clearly the ‘dread wild beast that slays’ (''mṛgo bhīma upahatnuḥ'')<ref name=fx6_ve2_1691/> to which Rudra is compared. When Agni, who has entered the waters, is compared to a lion,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1691/> the reference may be to the lion's habit of springing on animals at drinking places. That a jackal should defeat the lion is spoken of as a marvel.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1691/> The lion, being dangerous to men,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1691/> was trapped,<ref name=fx10_ve2_1691/> lain in wait for in ambush,<ref name=fx11_ve2_1691/> or chased by hunting bands.<ref name=fx12_ve2_1691/> But dogs were terrified of lions.<ref name=fx13_ve2_1691/> The liones (''siṃhī'') was also famous for her courage: the aid given by Indra to '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]]''' against the vast host of his enemies is compared to the defeat of a lioness by a ram ('''[[पेत्व|Petva]]''').<ref name=fx14_ve2_1691/> The gaping jaws of the lioness when attacking men are alluded to in  the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx15_ve2_1691/> The lioness is also mentioned in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx16_ve2_1691/> See also '''Halīkṣṇa.'''<br>

सिच्
<u>'''1. Sic'''</u> denotes the ‘border’ of a garment. The Rigveda refers to a son clutching the hem of his father's robe to attract his attention,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1692/> and to a mother's covering her son with the edge of her garment.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1692/> The word also occurs later.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1692/><br>

सिच्
<u>'''2. Sic'''</u> denotes, in the dual, the ‘wings’ of an army,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1693/> or, in the plural, the ‘lines.’(**  2) Av. xi. 9, 18; 10, 20.<br><br>''Cf.'' Pischel, ''Vedische Studien,'' 2, 65; Geldner, ''ibid.,'' 3, 31.<br>

सिच्
<u>'''3. Sic'''</u> seems in one passage of the Rigveda (i. 95, 7), where it is used in the dual, to denote the ‘horizon’ (meaning literally the ‘two borders’; ''i.e.,'' of heaven and of earth).<br>

सिध्मल
<u>'''Sidhmala,'''</u> ‘leprous,’ is found in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xxx. 17) and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 4, 14, 1) as a designation of one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’). ''Cf.'' '''[[किलास|Kilāsa]].'''<br>

सिनीवाली
<u>'''Sinīvālī'''</u> denotes the day of new moon and its presiding spirit, which, in accordance with widespread ideas concerning the connexion of the moon and vegetation, is one of fertility and growth. It occurs very frequently from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1696/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1696/> <br>

सिन्धु
<u>'''Sindhu'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1697/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1697/> often means ‘stream’ merely (''cf.'' '''[[सप्त सिन्धवः|Sapta Sindhavaḥ]]'''), but it has also<ref name=fx3_ve2_1697/> the more exact sense of ‘the stream’ ''par excellence,'' ‘the Indus.’ The name is, however, rarely mentioned after the period of the Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1697/> always then occurring in such a way as to suggest distance. The horses from the Indus (''[[सैन्धव|saindhava]]'') were famous.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1697/> See '''[[सैन्धव|Saindhava]].''' ''Cf.'' also '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].'''<br>

सिन्धु-क्षित्
<u>'''Sindhu-kṣit'''</u> is the name of a long-banished but finally restored '''[[राजन्यर्षि|Rājanyarṣi]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1698/> probably quite a mythical personage.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1698/><br>

सिरी
<u>'''Sirī'''</u> in the Rigveda (x. 71, 9) seems to denote a ‘female weaver.’<br>

सिलाची
<u>'''Silācī'''</u> is, in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1700/> the name of a healing plant, also called '''[[लाक्षा|Lākṣā]].'''<br>

सिलाञ्जाला
<u>'''Silāñjālā,'''</u> which the commentator reads as Śalāñjālā, is the name of a plant, perhaps a ‘grain creeper,’ in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1701/> The [[कौशिक|Kauśika]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1701/> reads the word as Śilāñjālā. ''Cf.'' '''Silāeī.''' <br>

सीचापू
<u>'''Sīcāpū'''</u> in the list of victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1702/> seems to denote a kind of bird.<br>

सीता
<u>'''Sītā,'''</u> ‘furrow,’ occurs in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1703/> and often later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1703/><br>

सीमन्
<u>'''Sīman'''</u> denotes the ‘parting’ of the hair in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1704/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1704/><br>

सीर
<u>'''Sīra,'''</u> ‘plough,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1705/> and often later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1705/> It was large and heavy, as is shown by the fact that six oxen,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1705/> or eight,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1705/> or twelve,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1705/> or even twenty-four,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1705/> were used to drag it. The animals which drew the plough were oxen, which were, no doubt, yoked and harnessed with traces.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1705/> The ox was guided by the '''[[अष्ट्रा|Aṣṭrā]],''' or ‘goad,’ of the ploughman (''cf.'' '''[[वैश्य|Vaiśya]]''').<ref name=fx8_ve2_1705/> Little is known of the parts of the plough. See '''[[लाङ्गल|Lāṅgala]]''' and '''[[फाल|Phāla]].'''<br>

सील
<u>'''Sīla,'''</u> ‘plough,’ is found in the Kapiṣṭhala Saṃhitā (xxviii. 8). <br>

सीलमावती
<u>'''Sīlamāvatī'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1707/> is, according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1707/> the name of a river; but this is most improbable.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1707/> Sāyaṇa thinks the word means ‘rich in hemp.’<br>

सीस
<u>'''Sīsa,'''</u> ‘lead,’ occurs first in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1708/> where it is mentioned as used for amulets.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1708/> The word is then quite common.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1708/> The use of lead by the weaver as a weight is perhaps also referred to.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1708/><br>

सु-कन्या
<u>'''Su-kanyā'''</u> is the name of '''Śaryāta's''' daughter, who married '''[[च्यवन|Cyavana]]''' according to the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1709/><br>

सु-कपर्द
<u>'''Su-kaparda.'''</u> See '''[[कपर्द|Kaparda]].'''<br>

सु-करीर
<u>'''Su-karīra'''</u> in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (ii. 7, 5) is a misreading of ''[[सु-कुरीर|su-kurīra]].'' See '''[[कुरीर|Kurīra]].'''<br>

सु-कीर्ति काक्षीवत
<u>'''Su-kīrti Kākṣīvata'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]]'''’) is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] to whom the Brāhmaṇas of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1712/> ascribe the authorship of a Vedic hymn.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1712/><br>

सु-केशिन् भारद्वाज
<u>'''Su-[[केशिन्|keśin]] Bhāradvāja'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[भरद्वाज|Bharadvāja]]'''’) is the name of a teacher in the [[प्रश्न|Praśna]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (i. 1). <br>

सु-कुरीर
<u>'''Su-kurīra.'''</u> See '''[[कुरीर|Kurīra]].'''<br>

सु-ख
<u>'''Su-kha.'''</u> See '''Kha.'''<br>

सुगन्धि-तेजन
<u>'''Sugandhi-tejana'''</u> in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1716/> and the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx2_ve2_1716/> denotes a kind of fragrant grass.<br>

सु-चित्त शैलन
<u>'''Su-citta Śailana'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 14, 4).<br>

सु-जात
<u>'''Su-jāta,'''</u> ‘well-born,’ is an epithet found applied to men in a few passages of the Rigveda. It would probably be a mistake to press the sense so as to denote ‘nobles’ as compared with the people. See '''[[सभा|Sabhā]].'''<br><br>^1 ii. 2, 11; v. 6, 2; vii. 1, 4. 15; viii. 20, 8.<br>

सुतं-भर
<u>'''Sutaṃ-bhara'''</u> is credited by the '''Anukramaṇī''' (Index) with the authorship of certain hymns of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1719/> The word does not occur in those hymns, but it appears as an adjective (‘carrying away Soma’) elsewhere,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1719/> and may, in a second passage,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1719/> by a conjecture<ref name=fx4_ve2_1719/> be taken as a man's name.<br>

सुत्वन् कैरिशि भार्गायण
<u>'''Sutvan [[कैरिशि|Kairiśi]] Bhārgāyaṇa'''</u> is, in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 28, 18), the name of a king who, being taught a spell by '''[[मैत्रेय|Maitreya]] [[कौषारव|Kauṣārava]],''' slew five kings and became great.<br>

सु-दक्षिण क्षैमि
<u>'''Su-dakṣiṇa Kṣaimi'''</u> (‘descendant of Kṣema’) is the name of a teacher in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 6, 3; 7, 1 ''et seq.;'' 8, 6). <br>

सु-दत्त पाराशर्य
<u>'''Su-datta Pārāśarya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[पराशर|Parāśara]]'''’) is in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 41, 1; iv. 17, 1) the name of a teacher who was a pupil of '''[[जनश्रुत|Janaśruta]] [[वारक्य|Vārakya]].'''<br>

सु-दामन्
<u>'''Su-dāman'''</u> is the name of a river in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxii. 18, 1).<br>

सु-दास्
<u>'''Su-dās'''</u> is the name of the '''[[तृत्सु|Tṛtsu]]''' king who won a famous victory over the ten kings, as described in a hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1724/> At one time '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]]''' was his '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]],''' and accompanied him in his victorious raids over the '''[[विपाश्|Vipāś]]''' (Beās) and '''[[शुतुद्री|Śutudrī]]''' (Sutlej).<ref name=fx2_ve2_1724/> The Aśvins gave him a queen, '''[[सुदेवी|Sudevī]],'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1724/> and also helped him on another occasion.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1724/> He appears with '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]]''' in a late hymn without hint of rivalry,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1724/> but elsewhere he seems to be referred to as defeated by '''[[पुरुकुत्स|Purukutsa]],''' Trasadasyu's father.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1724/> In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve2_1724/> he is recognized as a great king, with '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]]''' as his Puro hita, and similarly in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]],<ref name=fx8_ve2_1724/> where his generosity to his priest is related.<br><br>His exact ancestry is a little uncertain, because he is called '''[[पैजवन|Paijavana]],''' ‘son of [[पिजवन|Pijavana]],’ as [[यास्क|Yāska]] explains the patronymic. If this explanation is correct, '''Divodāsa''' must have been his grandfather. If he was the son of Divodāsa, [[पिजवन|Pijavana]] must be understood as a more remote ancestor. The former alternative seems the more probable. ''Cf.'' '''[[तुर्वश|Turvaśa]], [[दाशराज्ञ|Dāśarājña]]. [[पैजवन|Paijavana]], [[भरत|Bharata]], [[सौदास|Saudāsa]].'''<br>

सु-देव
<u>'''1. Su-deva'''</u> is, according to Ludwig,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1725/> the proper name of a sacrificer in one hymn of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1725/> <br>

सु-देव काश्यप
<u>'''2. Su-deva Kāśyapa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[कश्यप|Kaśyapa]]'''’) is the name of a teacher in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve2_1726/> who set forth the expiation for lack of chastity.<br>

सु-देवला
<u>'''Su-devalā'''</u> was the name of '''[[ऋतुपर्ण|Ṛtuparṇa]]''' as a woman according to the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xx. 12).<br>

सु-देवी
<u>'''Su-devī.'''</u> See '''Sudas.'''<br>

सु-धन्वन् आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Su-[[धन्वन्|dhanvan]] Āṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]'''’) is the name of a teacher in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iii. 3, 1).<br>

सु-नीथ शौचद्-रथ
<u>'''1. Su-[[नीथ|nītha]] Śaucad-ratha'''</u> (‘descendant of Śucadratha’) is the name of a man in the Rigveda (v. 79, 2). ''Cf.'' '''[[सत्यश्रवस्|Satyaśravas]].'''<br>

सु-नीथ कापटव
<u>'''2. Su-[[नीथ|nītha]] Kāpaṭava'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1731/><br>

सु-पर्ण
<u>'''1. Su-parṇa,'''</u> ‘well-winged,’ designates a large bird of prey, the ‘eagle’ or the ‘vulture,’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1732/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1732/> In the passages in which it appears as an eater of carrion<ref name=fx3_ve2_1732/> it must be the vulture. The Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_1732/> mentions an eagle which separates milk from water like the '''[[क्रुञ्च्|Kruñc]].''' In the Rigveda<ref name=fx5_ve2_1732/> the [[सुपर्ण|Suparṇa]] is said to be the child of the '''[[श्येन|Śyena]],''' and is distinguished from the latter in another passage:<ref name=fx6_ve2_1732/> this led Zimmer<ref name=fx7_ve2_1732/> to think that the falcon is probably meant.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1732/> The Atharvaveda alludes to its cry,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1732/> and describes it as living in the hills.<ref name=fx10_ve2_1732/> <br>

सुपर्ण
<u>'''2. Suparṇa'''</u> is personified in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1733/> as a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]].<br>

सु-पित्र्य
<u>'''Su-pitrya,'''</u> a word occurring once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1734/> is probably an adjective (‘maintaining his paternal character well’). Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1734/> however, regards it, but without any great probability, as a proper name.<br>

सु-प्रतीत औलुण्ड्य
<u>'''Su-pratīta Auluṇḍya'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''Bṛhaspatigupta,''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1735/><br>

सुप्लन् सार्ञ्जय
<u>'''Suplan Sārñjaya'''</u> is the name of a prince of the '''Sṛñjayas''' who was taught the [[दाक्षायण|Dākṣāyaṇa]] sacrifice by '''Pratīdarśa,''' and took the name of '''[[सहदेव|Sahadeva]]''' as a token of his success.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1736/><br>

सु-बन्धु
<u>'''Su-bandhu'''</u> in the hymns of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1737/> is taken by Sāyaṇa to be a proper name; but this is not certain, Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1737/> seeing in the passages only an ordinary noun meaning ‘a good friend.’ The later tradition<ref name=fx3_ve2_1737/> explains that [[सुबन्धु|Subandhu]] and his brothers, called '''Gaupāyanas,''' were priests of '''Asamāti,''' who cast them off and took two others, '''[[किरात|Kirāta]]''' and '''[[आकुलि|Ākuli]].''' By these two in pigeon form [[सुबन्धु|Subandhu]] was caused to swoon, but was revived by his three brothers, who recited certain hymns.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1737/><br>

सु-ब्रह्मण्य
<u>'''Su-brahmaṇya'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1738/> denotes a priest who officiates as one of the three assistants of the Udgātṛ (see '''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]]'''). His office is Subrahmaṇyā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1738/> <br>

सु-भगा
<u>'''Su-bhagā,'''</u> in the vocative ''subhage,'' is a frequent form of courteous address to women from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1739/><br>

सु-भद्रिका
<u>'''Su-bhadrikā'''</u> occurs in the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) section of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1740/> as in some way connected with the rite. Weber<ref name=fx2_ve2_1740/> thinks that a proper name, that of the wife of the king of '''[[काम्पील|Kāmpīla]],''' is intended, but Mahīdhara<ref name=fx3_ve2_1740/> explains the word merely as a lady with many lovers or a courtezan, a view followed by Roth.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1740/> Since the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]]<ref name=fx5_ve2_1740/> and [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_1740/> Saṃhitās have no [[सुभद्रिका|Subhadrikā]], but a vocative ''subhage'' (see '''[[सुभगा|Subhagā]]'''), the sense remains very doubtful.<br>

सुमति-त्सरु
<u>'''Sumati-tsaru.'''</u> See '''[[त्सरु|Tsaru]].'''<br>

सु-मन्त्र बाभ्रव
<u>'''Su-[[मन्त्र|mantra]] Bābhrava'''</u> (‘descendant of Babhru’) '''[[गौतम|Gautama]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[गोतम|Gotama]]'''’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[शूष वाह्नेय|Śūṣa Vāhneya]] [[भारद्वाज|Bhāradvāja]],''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1742/><br>

सु-मित्र वाध्र्यस्व
<u>'''Su-[[मित्र|mitra]] Vādhryasva'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[वध्र्य्अश्व|Vadhryaśva]]'''’) is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1743/> where also<ref name=fx2_ve2_1743/> the '''Sumitras,''' his family, are mentioned.<br>

सु-मीळ्ह
<u>'''Su-mīḷha'''</u> is the name of a patron in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1744/> <br>

सु-मेध
<u>'''Su-medha'''</u> occurs in an obscure hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1745/> either as an adjective (‘of good understanding’) or a proper name, perhaps identical with '''[[नृमेध|Nṛmedha]]''' or his brother.<br>

सुम्न-यु
<u>'''Sumna-yu'''</u> is mentioned in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (xv. 1) as a pupil of '''Uddālaka.'''<br>

सु-यज्ञ शाण्डिल्य
<u>'''Su-yajña Śāṇḍilya'''</u> is the name of a pupil of '''[[कंस|Kaṃsa]] [[वारक्य|Vārakya]]''' in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iv. 17, 1). Another Suyajña is a '''[[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]],''' author of the [[गृह्य|Gṛhya]] [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<br>

सु-यवस
<u>'''Su-yavasa'''</u> denotes a ‘good pasture’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1748/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1748/><br>

सुरा
<u>'''Surā'''</u> is the name of an intoxicating ‘spirituous liquor,’ often mentioned in Vedic literature. In some passages<ref name=fx1_ve2_1749/> it is referred to favourably, in others with decided disapproval.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1749/> It is classed with the use of meat and with dicing as an evil in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1749/> and often with dicing.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1749/> It was, as opposed to '''Soma,''' essentially a drink of ordinary life.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1749/> It was the drink of men in the '''[[सभा|Sabhā]],'''<ref name=fx6_ve2_1749/> and gave rise to broils.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1749/><br><br>Its exact nature is not certain. It may have been a strong spirit prepared from fermented grains and plants, as Eggeling<ref name=fx8_ve2_1749/>  holds, or, as Whitney<ref name=fx9_ve2_1749/> thought, a kind of beer or ale. Geldner<ref name=fx10_ve2_1749/> renders it ‘brandy.’ It is sometimes mentioned in connexion with '''[[मधु|Madhu]].'''<ref name=fx11_ve2_1749/> It was kept in skins.<ref name=fx12_ve2_1749/><br>

सुरा-कार
<u>'''Surā-kāra,'''</u> ‘maker of '''[[सुरा|Surā]],'''’ is included in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1750/><br>

सु-राधस्
<u>'''Su-rādhas'''</u> is the name of a man in the Rigveda (i. 100, 17). where he is mentioned with '''[[अम्बरीष|Ambarīṣa]]''' and others.<br>

सुराम
<u>'''Surāma'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1752/> refers to the illness caused by drinking '''[[सुरा|Surā]]''' to excess. Indra is described as suffering from it in the Namuci legend.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1752/> Later [[सुराम|Surāma]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1752/> was treated as an epithet of '''Soma,''' meaning ‘delightful.’<br>

सु-वर्ण
<u>'''Su-varṇa,'''</u> ‘beautiful coloured,’ is an epithet of gold ('''[[हिरण्य|Hiraṇya]]'''), and then comes to be used as a substantive denoting ‘gold.’<br><br>^1) [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], i. 4, 7, 4; 8, 9, 1, etc.<br><br>^2) Av. xv. 1, 2; [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], iii. 12, 6, 6; Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], xi. 4, 1, 8, etc.; Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]], i. 6, 6; iii. 19, 1; iv. 17, 7, etc.<br>

सु-वसन
<u>'''Su-vasana'''</u> in the Rigveda denotes a ‘splendid garment,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_1754/> and is also used adjectivally, ‘clothing well.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1754/> Su-[[वासस्|vāsas]], ‘welldressed,’ is a common adjective.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1754/> See '''[[वासस्|Vāsas]].''' <br>

सु-वास्तु
<u>'''Su-vāstu'''</u> (‘having fair dwellings’) is the name of a river in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1755/> It is clearly the Soastos of Arrian<ref name=fx2_ve2_1755/> and the modern Swāt, a tributary of the '''[[कुभा|Kubhā]]''' (Kabul river) which is itself an affluent of the Indus.<br>

सु-शारद शालङ्कायन
<u>'''Su-[[शारद|śārada]] Śālaṅkāyana'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[ऊर्जयन्त् औपमन्यव|Ūrjayant Aupamanyava]],''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1756/><br>

सु-श्रवस्
<u>'''1. Su-śravas'''</u> is the name of a man in the Rigveda (i. 53, 9) according to Sāyaṇa.<br>

सु-श्रवस्
<u>'''2. Su-śravas'''</u> is the name of the father of '''[[उपगु सौश्रवस|Upagu Sauśravasa]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 6, 8).<br>

सु-श्रवस् कौष्य
<u>'''3. Su-śravas Kauṣya'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a contemporary of '''[[कुश्रि वाजश्रवस|Kuśri Vājaśravasa]],''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 5, 5, 1 ''et seq.'').<br>

सु-श्रवस् वार्ष-गण्य
<u>'''4. Su-śravas Vārṣa-gaṇya'''</u> (‘descendant of Vṛṣagaṇa’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[प्रातर्अह्न कौहल|Prātarahna Kauhala]],''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1760/><br>

सु-षामन्
<u>'''Su-ṣāman'''</u> is the name of a man in one verse of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1761/> and probably forms part of the strange name, Varo [[सुषामन्|Suṣāman]], in other passages.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1761/> ''Cf.'' '''Varu.'''<br>

सु-षोमा
<u>'''Su-ṣomā'''</u> occurs certainly as the name of a river in the Nadīstuti (‘praise of rivers’) in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1762/> In two other passages it would seem to be a proper name, once masculine,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1762/> perhaps  the people, and once feminine,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1762/> though Roth<ref name=fx4_ve2_1762/> sees in the word the designation of a Soma vessel. Its identification is quite uncertain, though it has been thought to be the  of Megasthenes,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1762/> the modern Suwan.<br>

सु-सर्तु
<u>'''Su-sartu'''</u> is the name of a river in the [[नदी|Nadī]]-[[स्तुति|stuti]] (‘praise of rivers’) in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1763/> That it was a tributary of the Indus is certain, but which one is unknown.<br>

सु-हविस् आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Su-[[हविस्|havis]] Āṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]'''’) is the name of the seer of a Sāman or chant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 3, 25).<br>

सू-कर
<u>'''Sū-kara'''</u> ‘wild-boar,’ has the appearance of being an onomatopoetic word (‘making the sound ''sū''’); it is more probably a very old word going back to the Indo-European period, and cognate with the Latin ''su-culus'' (‘little pig’), being transformed in sense by popular etymology.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1765/> It occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1765/> and later.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1765/> It appears once in the Atharvaveda accompanied by ''[[मृग|mṛga]],''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1765/> the combined words apparently meaning ‘wild hog,’ as opposed to '''[[वराह|Varāha]],''' ‘boar.’ <br>

सूक्त
<u>'''Sūkta,'''</u> ‘well uttered,’ is the regular term for a ‘hymn’ as part of the [[शस्त्र|Śastra]] in the later Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1766/> and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1766/> The sense of ‘hymn’ must also be recognized in several passages of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1766/><br>

सूची
<u>'''Sūcī,'''</u> ‘needle,’ is found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1767/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1767/><br>

सूचीक
<u>'''Sūcīka'''</u> is the name of a stinging insect in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1768/><br>

सूत
<u>'''Sūta'''</u> is the name of a court official who is often mentioned with the '''Grāmaṇī.''' He is one of the eight '''Vīras''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1769/> and of the eleven '''Ratnins''' in other texts.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1769/> He also appears in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1769/> among the kingmakers ('''Rājakṛt''') and in the Śatrarudriya<ref name=fx4_ve2_1769/> (‘section dealing with the hundred Rudras’) of the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]. The commentators are agreed in seeing in him the ‘charioteer’ ('''[[सारथि|Sārathi]]''') or ‘master of the horse,’ of the king; this sense is accepted by Roth,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1769/> by Whitney,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1769/> and by Bloomfield.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1769/> But the fact that the '''Saṃ-  grahītṛ,''' who occurs in several passages beside the [[सूत|Sūta]], is the ‘charioteer,’ renders this version improbable. Eggeling<ref name=fx8_ve2_1769/> thinks that he was, in the Brāhmaṇas at least, a minstrel and court poet, while Weber<ref name=fx9_ve2_1769/> considers that his name denotes him as ‘consecrated’--that is, one who has constant access to the king. In the Epic the [[सूत|Sūta]] serves as a royal herald and bard:<ref name=fx10_ve2_1769/> it may be that the curious words ''ahanti,''<ref name=fx11_ve2_1769/> ''ahantya,''<ref name=fx12_ve2_1769/> or ''ahantva''<ref name=fx13_ve2_1769/> applied to him<ref name=fx14_ve2_1769/> in the [[शतरुद्रिय|Śatarudriya]] denote his sacred character at once as minstrel and as herald--a combination of functions not unknown elsewhere.<br>

सूत-वशा
<u>'''Sūta-vaśā'''</u> denotes in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1770/> a cow barren after having one calf.<br>

सूत्र
<u>'''Sūtra'''</u> has the sense of ‘thread’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1771/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1771/> In the sense of a ‘book of rules’ for the guidance of sacrificers and so forth, the word occurs in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1771/><br>

सूद
<u>'''Sūda,'''</u> according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, means ‘well’<ref name=fx1_ve2_1772/> and the ‘mud of a dried-up pool.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1772/> Pischel,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1772/> however, shows clearly that [[सूद|Sūda]] denotes what is added to Soma to  make it fit for use, especially the warm milk, and this sense suits all the passages. Eggeling<ref name=fx4_ve2_1772/> renders it ‘well,’ and Grassmann ‘sweet drink.’<br>

सूद-दोहस्
<u>'''Sūda-dohas'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1773/> denotes ‘milking '''[[सूद|Sūda]]'''’--''i.e.,'' what is requisite to mix with Soma, according to Pischel.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1773/> According to Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1773/> it means ‘yielding milk like a well.’<br>

सूना
<u>'''Sūnā'''</u> means, in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1774/> and the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1774/> apparently a ‘woven (from ''sīv,'' ‘sew’) wickerwork basket’ for holding flesh.<br>

सूनु
<u>'''Sūnu'''</u> is a common word for ‘son’ from the Rigveda onwards.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1775/> The etymological sense seems to be ‘he who is borne,’ and then ‘the begotten.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1775/> But the use of [[सूनु|Sūnu]] in the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1775/> is predominantly in relation to the father, and only rarely in its connexion with words for mother.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1775/> Thus a father is ‘easy of access’ (''sāpāyana'') to his son (''[[सूनु|sūnu]]'');<ref name=fx5_ve2_1775/> but in another passage,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1775/> where the same term is applied to earth as a mother, the word used for son is '''[[पुत्र|Putra]].''' No conclusion as to matriarchy can of course be drawn from the etymology. On the relation of son and father, see '''[[पितृ|Pitṛ]].''' <br>

सूरि
<u>'''Sūri'''</u> is the regular word in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1776/> for the sacrificer, the later Yajamāna--that is, the man who pays the priests for performing the rite, and reaps the benefit of that service. The Sūris are often coupled with the '''Maghavans,'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1776/> described as heroes or warriors,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1776/> and as related to the priests by their patronage<ref name=fx3_ve2_1776/> or as companions.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1776/><br>

सूर्मि
<u>'''Sūrmi'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1777/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1777/> according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, a kind of ‘tube’ serving as a lamp. In one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1777/> it means a ‘pipe’ for conveying water. ''Cf.'' '''[[अवत|Avata]].'''<br>

सूर्य
<u>'''Sūrya,'''</u> the ‘sun,’ plays a great part in Vedic mythology and religion,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1778/> corresponding with the importance of the sun as a factor in the physical life of the peninsula. In the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1778/> the sun is normally regarded as a beneficent power, a not unnatural view in a people which must apparently have issued from the cold regions of the Himālaya mountains. Its heat is, however, alluded to in some passages of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1778/> as well as referred to in the Atharvaveda and the literature of the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1778/><br><br>In one myth Indra is said to have vanquished [[सूर्य|Sūrya]] and to have stolen his wheel:<ref name=fx5_ve2_1778/> this is possibly a reference to the  obscuration of the sun by a thunderstorm.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1778/> The [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx7_ve2_1778/> presents a naive conception of the course of the sun, which it regards as bright on one side only, and as returning from west to east by the same road, but with the reverse side turned towards the earth, thus at night illumining the stars in heaven.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1778/> In the Rigveda<ref name=fx9_ve2_1778/> wonder is expressed that the sun does not fall.<br><br>There are several references to eclipses in the Rigveda. In one passage<ref name=fx10_ve2_1778/> Svarbhānu, a demon, is said to have eclipsed the sun with darkness, while '''Atri''' restores the light of the sun, a similar feat being elsewhere attributed to his family, the Atris.<ref name=fx11_ve2_1778/> In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx12_ve2_1778/> '''[[राहु|Rāhu]]''' appears for the first time in connexion with the sun. Indra's defeat of [[सूर्य|Sūrya]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_1778/> may also be explained as alluding to an eclipse; in two other passages<ref name=fx13_ve2_1778/> such an interpretation seems at least probable. Ludwig<ref name=fx14_ve2_1778/> not only argues that the Rigveda knows the theory of eclipses caused by an occultation of the sun by the moon, and regards the sun as going round the earth,<ref name=fx15_ve2_1778/> but even endeavours to identify an eclipse referred to in the Rigveda with one that occurred in 1029 B.C. These views are completely refuted by Whitney.<ref name=fx16_ve2_1778/><br><br>The sun as a maker of time<ref name=fx17_ve2_1778/> determines the year of 360 days, which is the civil year and the usual year ('''[[संवत्सर|Saṃvatsara]]''') of  Vedic literature. This solar year is divided into two halves-the Uttarāyaṇa,<ref name=fx18_ve2_1778/> when the sun goes north, and the [[दक्षिणायन|Dakṣiṇāyana]],<ref name=fx19_ve2_1778/> when it goes south. There can be no doubt that these periods denote the time when the sun turns north from the winter solstice, and when it turns south from the summer solstice, for the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx20_ve2_1778/> says so in perfectly clear language. The alternative theory is to regard the periods as those when the sun is in the north--''i.e.,'' when it is north of the equator, and when it is in the south, taking as points of departure the equinoxes, not the solstices; but this view has no support in Vedic literature, and is opposed to the fact that the equinoxes play no part in Vedic astronomical theory.<ref name=fx21_ve2_1778/> There are only doubtful references to the solstices in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx22_ve2_1778/><br><br>The Brāhmaṇas,<ref name=fx23_ve2_1778/> and perhaps the Rigveda,<ref name=fx24_ve2_1778/> regard the moon as entering the sun at new moon. According to Hillebrandt,<ref name=fx25_ve2_1778/> the Rigveda<ref name=fx26_ve2_1778/> recognizes that the moon shines by the borrowed light of the sun, but this seems very doubt-  ful. See also '''[[अर्यम्णः पन्था|Aryamṇaḥ Panthā]],'''<ref name=fx27_ve2_1778/> '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]],''' and '''[[सप्त सूर्याः|Sapta Sūryāḥ]].'''<br>

सूर्य-नक्षत्र
<u>'''Sūrya-nakṣatra'''</u> is found in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1779/> in a passage where Sāyaṇa takes it as denoting a '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]],''' which gives out rays of light like the sun. But the real sense (as the [[काण्व|Kāṇva]] text helps to show) is that the sacrificer may take the sun for his [[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]]--''i.e.,'' he may neglect the Nakṣatras altogether and rely on the sun.<br>

सूर्य-चन्द्रमसा
<u>'''Sūrya-candramasā'''</u> or '''[[सूर्य|Sūrya]]-candramasau''' denotes ‘sun and moon’ as a pair of luminaries in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1780/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1780/><br>

सृक
<u>'''Sṛka'''</u> in a couple of passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1781/> denotes a weapon of Indra, perhaps a ‘lance.’<br>

सृगाल
<u>'''Sṛgāla'''</u>, ‘jackal,’ is not found until the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] xii. 5, 2, 5), but is common in the Epic. <br>

सृजय
<u>'''Sṛjaya'''</u> is the name of one of the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1783/> What it was is unknown: Mahīdhara on the Vājasaneyi passage calls it a kind of bird; Sāyaṇa on the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā gives the alternatives ‘black fly’ (when ''sṛjayā'' must be read), ‘white serpent,’ and ‘black buffalo.’<br>

सृञ्जय
<u>'''Sṛñjaya'''</u> is the name of a people mentioned as early as the Rigveda. [[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]] (that is, the king of this people) '''[[दैववात|Daivavāta]]''' is celebrated as victorious over the '''Turvaśas''' and the '''Vṛcīvants,'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1784/> and his sacrificial fire is referred to.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1784/> In connexion with [[दैववात|Daivavāta]] is also mentioned '''Sāhadevya Somaka,'''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1784/> no doubt another prince; for in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_1784/> we find [[सोमक साहदेव्य|Somaka Sāhadevya]] and his father, [[सहदेव|Sahadeva]] (originally '''Suplan''') [[सार्ञ्जय|Sārñjaya]], as kings who were anointed by '''[[पर्वत|Parvata]]''' and '''[[नारद|Nārada]].''' The Rigveda<ref name=fx5_ve2_1784/> has also a Dānastuti (‘praise of gifts’) of '''[[प्रस्तोक|Prastoka]],'''<ref name=fx6_ve2_1784/> a [[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]], who is lauded along with '''Divodāsa.''' Moreover, '''[[वीतहव्य|Vītahavya]]'''<ref name=fx7_ve2_1784/> seems to have been a [[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]], though Zimmer<ref name=fx8_ve2_1784/> prefers to take the derivative word, '''[[वैतहव्य|Vaitahavya]],''' not as a patronymic, but as an epithet.<br><br>It seems probable that the Sṛñjayas and the '''Tṛtsus''' were closely allied, for Divodāsa and a [[सृञ्जय|Sṛñjaya]] prince are celebrated together,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1784/> and the Turvaśas were enemies of both.<ref name=fx10_ve2_1784/> This view is borne out by the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx11_ve2_1784/> which recognizes '''[[देवभाग श्रौतर्ष|Devabhāga Śrautarṣa]]''' as [[पुरोहित|Purohita]] of the '''Kurus''' and the Sṛñjayas. <br><br>On the other hand, some disaster certainly befel the Sṛñjayas, at least the Vaitahavyas, for they are said in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx12_ve2_1784/> to have offended the '''Bhṛgus''' and to have ended miserably. There is, it is true, no precise confirmation of this notice, but both the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx13_ve2_1784/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx14_ve2_1784/> in independent passages, refer to the Sṛñjayas having sustained some serious loss, though the notice is in each case coupled with a ritual error, much as in the Old Testament the fate of kings depends on their devotion to Jahve or their disobedience. It is justifiable to recognize some disaster in this allusion.<br><br>The geographical position of the Sṛñjayas is uncertain. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx15_ve2_1784/> suggests that in early times they must be looked for west of the Indus with Divodāsa; he also mentions, though he does not definitely adopt, the suggestion of Brunnhofer that the Sṛñjayas are to be compared with the <ref name=fx16_ve2_1784/> of the Greeks, and to be located in Drangiana. Zimmer<ref name=fx17_ve2_1784/> is inclined to locate them on the upper Indus; but it is difficult to decide definitely in favour of any particular location. They may well have been a good deal farther east than the Indus, since their allies, the Tṛtsus, were in the '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]],''' and were certainly absorbed in the Kurus.<br><br>Of the history of this clan we have one notice.<ref name=fx18_ve2_1784/> They expelled '''[[दुष्टरीतु|Duṣṭarītu]] [[पौंसायन|Pauṃsāyana]],''' one of their kings, from the hereditary monarchy--of ten generations--and also drove out '''[[रेवोत्तरस्|Revottaras]] [[पाटव|Pāṭava]] [[चाक्र|Cākra]] [[स्थपति|Sthapati]],''' probably his minister, who, however, succeeded in effecting the restoration of the king, despite the opposition of the Kuru prince, '''[[बल्हिक|Balhika]] Prātīpya.''' Very probably this Kuru prince may have been at the bottom of the movement which led to the expulsion of the king and his minister. But the restoration of the king can  hardly be regarded, in accordance with Bloomfield's view,<ref name=fx19_ve2_1784/> as a defeat of the Sṛñjayas.<br>

सृणी¤
<u>'''Sṛṇī¤'''</u> is found certainly in one,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1785/> and probably also in two other<ref name=fx2_ve2_1785/> passages of the Rigveda. The sense appears to be ‘sickle.’ In one other passage [[सृण्य|Sṛṇya]] is coupled with ''jetā:''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1785/> the sense is doubtful, Roth<ref name=fx4_ve2_1785/> conjecturing ''cetā,'' and Oldenberg<ref name=fx5_ve2_1785/> pointing out that ''chettā'' is also possible. Hopkins<ref name=fx6_ve2_1785/> thinks that a ‘hook’ is here meant.<br>

सृण्य
<u>'''Sṛṇya.'''</u> See '''Sṛṇī.'''<br>

सृबिन्द
<u>'''Sṛbinda'''</u> is the name of a foe of Indra<ref name=fx1_ve2_1787/> in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1787/> The word may denote a real foe, since it has no obvious '''Āryan''' derivation.<br>

सृमर
<u>'''Sṛmara'''</u> is the name of an unknown animal at the '''[[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]]''' (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1788/> <br>

सेतु
<u>'''Setu'''</u> appears in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1789/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1789/> to denote merely a raised bank for crossing inundated land,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1789/> a ‘causeway,’ such as are common all the world over. This sense explains best the later meaning of ‘boundary.’ The word in Vedic literature is probably always metaphorical.<br>

सेना
<u>'''Senā'''</u> denotes primarily a ‘missile,’ a sense found in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1790/> and the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1790/> and then a ‘host’ or ‘army,’ which is its normal meaning.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1790/> See '''[[संग्राम|Saṃgrāma]].'''<br>

सेना-नी
<u>'''Senā-nī,'''</u> ‘leader of an army,’ is the title of the royal ‘general.’ He is mentioned in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1791/> where also<ref name=fx2_ve2_1791/> the word is used metaphorically. He is also referred to in the [[शतरुद्रिय|Śatarudriya]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1791/> as well as elsewhere in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās and Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1791/> He is one of the '''Ratnins''' of the king.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1791/> Presumably he was appointed by the king, not by the people, to command in war when the king became too important to lead every little fray in person. In the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_1791/> this official is called [[सेना|Senā]]-pati. <br>

सेलग
<u>'''Selaga'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1792/> appears to denote ‘robber.’ See '''[[सैलग|Sailaga]].'''<br>

सेहु
<u>'''Sehu'''</u> occurs in a comparison in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1793/> where it must denote a very sapless (''arasa'') substance.<br>

सैतव
<u>'''Saitava,'''</u> ‘descendant of Setu,’ is the name of a teacher in the first two Vaṃśas (list of teachers) in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1794/> He is described as a pupil of '''[[पाराशर्य|Pārāśarya]]''' or of '''[[पाराशर्यायण|Pārāśaryāyaṇa]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1794/><br>

सैन्धव
<u>'''Saindhava,'''</u> ‘coming from the Indus,’ is a term applied to water in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1795/> to '''[[गुग्गुलु|Guggulu]]''' in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1795/> to a horse in the Śatapatha, [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1795/> and to salt in the same text.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1795/><br>

सैर्य
<u>'''Sairya'''</u> is the name in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1796/> of some species of grass infested by insects.<br>

सैलग
<u>'''Sailaga'''</u> is found in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1797/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1797/> as the name of one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’). ‘Robber’ seems to be the sense of this word, as of '''[[सेलग|Selaga]].''' <br>

सोभरि
<u>'''Sobhari'''</u> is the name of a [[ऋषि|Ṛṣi]] frequently mentioned in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1798/> The family is also referred to,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1798/> and a father, Sobharī.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1798/><br>

सोम
<u>'''Soma'''</u> was the famous plant which was used for the preparation of the libation of Soma made at the Vedic sacrifice. Its importance is sufficiently shown by the fact that the whole of the ninth Maṇḍala of the Rigveda, and six hymns in other Maṇḍalas, are devoted to its praise.<br><br>Nevertheless, little is actually known of the plant. Its twigs or shoots are described as brown (''[[बभ्रु|babhru]]''),<ref name=fx1_ve2_1799/> ruddy (''aruṇa''),<ref name=fx2_ve2_1799/> of tawny (''hari'').<ref name=fx3_ve2_1799/> Possibly its twigs hang down if the epithet '''[[नैचाशाख|Naicāśākha]]'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1799/> refers to the plant as Hillebrandt<ref name=fx5_ve2_1799/> thinks. The shoot is called ''[[अंशु|aṃśu]],''<ref name=fx6_ve2_1799/> while the plant as a whole is called ''andhas,''<ref name=fx7_ve2_1799/> which also denotes the juice.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1799/> ''[[पर्वन्|Parvan]]''<ref name=fx9_ve2_1799/> is the stem. ''Kṣip,''<ref name=fx10_ve2_1799/> ‘finger,’ is used as a designation of the shoots, which may therefore have resembled fingers in shape; ''[[वक्षणा|vakṣaṇā]]''<ref name=fx11_ve2_1799/> and ''[[वाण|vāṇa]]''<ref name=fx12_ve2_1799/> also seem to have the sense of the shoot. There is some slight. evidence to suggest that the stem was not round, but angular.<ref name=fx13_ve2_1799/>  The plant grew on the mountains,<ref name=fx14_ve2_1799/> that of '''Müjavant''' being specially renowned.<br><br>These notices are inadequate to identify the plant. It has been held<ref name=fx15_ve2_1799/> to be the ''Sarcostemma viminale'' or the ''Asclepias acida (= Sarcostemma brevistigma).'' Roth<ref name=fx16_ve2_1799/> held that the ''Sarcostemma acidum'' more nearly met the requirements of the case. Watt<ref name=fx17_ve2_1799/> suggested the Afghan grape as the real Soma, and Rice<ref name=fx18_ve2_1799/> thought a sugar-cane might be meant, while Max Müller and Rājendralāla [[मित्र|Mitra]] suggested that the juice was used as an ingredient in a kind of beer--''i.e.,'' that the Soma plant was a species of hop. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx19_ve2_1799/> considers that neither hops nor the grape can explain the references to Soma. It is very probable that the plant cannot now be identified.<ref name=fx20_ve2_1799/><br><br>In the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]]<ref name=fx21_ve2_1799/> the plant is purchased ere it is pressed. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx22_ve2_1799/> considers that the sale must be assumed for the Rigveda. It grew on a mountain, and could not be obtained by ordinary people: perhaps some special tribe or prince owned it, like the '''Kīkaṭas.'''<ref name=fx23_ve2_1799/> As it stands, the ritual performance is clearly an acquisition of the Soma from the Gandharvas (represented by a [[शूद्र|Śūdra]]), a ritual imitation of the action which may have been one of the sources of the drama. Owing to the difficulty of obtaining the real plant from a great  distance, several substitutes were allowed in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] period.<ref name=fx24_ve2_1799/><br><br>The plant was prepared for use by being pounded with stones or in a mortar. The former was the normal method of procedure, appearing in the Rigveda as the usual one. The stones are called ''grāvan''<ref name=fx25_ve2_1799/> or ''adri,''<ref name=fx26_ve2_1799/> and were, of course, held in the hands.<ref name=fx27_ve2_1799/> The plant was laid on boards one beside the other ('''Adhiṣavana'''), and, according at least to the later ritual,<ref name=fx28_ve2_1799/> a hole was dug below, so that the pounding of the plant by means of the stones resulted in a loud noise, doubtless a prophylactic against demoniac influences.<br><br>The plant was placed on a skin and on the Vedi<ref name=fx29_ve2_1799/> --which was no longer done in the later ritual--'''[[धिषणा|Dhiṣaṇā]]''' in some passages denoting the Vedi.<ref name=fx30_ve2_1799/><br><br>Sometimes the mortar and pestle were used in place of the stones.<ref name=fx31_ve2_1799/> This use, though Iranian, was apparently not common in Vedic times.<br>

चमू
<u>'''Camū'''</u> denotes the vessel used for the offering to the god,<ref name=fx32_ve2_1800/> '''[[कलश|Kalaśa]]''' and '''[[चमस|Camasa]]''' those used for the priests to drink from. Sometimes<ref name=fx33_ve2_1800/> the [[चमू|Camū]] denotes the mortar and pestle. Perhaps the vessel was so called because of its mortar-like shape.<br><br>The skin on which the shoots were placed was called '''Tvac,'''<ref name=fx34_ve2_1800/> or twice ''go'' (‘cow-hide’).<ref name=fx35_ve2_1800/> '''[[कोश|Kośa]],'''<ref name=fx36_ve2_1800/> Sadhastha,<ref name=fx37_ve2_1800/> '''Dru,'''<ref name=fx38_ve2_1800/>  '''Vana,'''<ref name=fx39_ve2_1800/> '''[[द्रोण|Droṇa]],'''<ref name=fx40_ve2_1800/> are all terms used for Soma vessels, while '''[[स्रुव|Sruva]]'''<ref name=fx41_ve2_1800/> denotes the ‘ladle.’<br><br>Apparently the plant was sometimes steeped in water to increase its yield of juice.<ref name=fx42_ve2_1800/><br><br>It is not possible to describe exactly the details of the process of pressing the Soma as practised in the Rigveda. It was certainly purified by being pressed through a sieve<ref name=fx43_ve2_1800/> ('''[[पवित्र|Pavitra]]'''). The Soma was then used unmixed (''[[शुक्र|śukra]],''<ref name=fx44_ve2_1800/> ''śuci'')<ref name=fx45_ve2_1800/> for Indra and '''Vāyu,''' but the '''Kaṇvas''' seem to have dropped this usage.<ref name=fx46_ve2_1800/> The juice is described as brown (''[[बभ्रु|babhru]]''),<ref name=fx47_ve2_1800/> tawny (''hari''),<ref name=fx48_ve2_1800/> or ruddy (''aruṇa''),<ref name=fx49_ve2_1800/> and as having a fragrant smell,<ref name=fx50_ve2_1800/> at least as a rule.<ref name=fx51_ve2_1800/><br><br>Soma was mixed with milk ('''[[गवाशिर्|Gavāśir]]'''),<ref name=fx52_ve2_1800/> curd or sour milk ('''[[दध्य्आशिर्|Dadhyāśir]]'''),<ref name=fx53_ve2_1800/> or grain ('''[[यवाशिर्|Yavāśir]]''').<ref name=fx54_ve2_1800/> The admixtures are  alluded to with various figurative expressions, as '''Atka,''' ‘armour’;<ref name=fx55_ve2_1800/> '''[[वस्त्र|Vastra]]'''<ref name=fx56_ve2_1800/> or '''[[वासस्|Vāsas]],'''<ref name=fx57_ve2_1800/> ‘garment’; '''[[अभिश्री|Abhiśrī]],'''<ref name=fx58_ve2_1800/> ‘admixture’; ''rūpa,''<ref name=fx59_ve2_1800/> ‘beauty’; ''[[श्री|śrī]],''<ref name=fx60_ve2_1800/> ‘splendour’; ''rasa,''<ref name=fx61_ve2_1800/> ‘flavour’; ''prayas,''<ref name=fx62_ve2_1800/> ‘dainty’; and perhaps ''nabhas,''<ref name=fx63_ve2_1800/> ‘fragrance.’ The adjective ''tīvra''<ref name=fx64_ve2_1800/> denotes the ‘pungent’ flavour of Soma when so mixed. The Soma shoots, after the juice has been pressed out, are denoted by ''ṛjīṣa,'' ‘residue.’<ref name=fx65_ve2_1800/><br><br>It seems probable that in some cases honey was mixed with Soma: perhaps the ''[[कोश|kośa]] [[मधु|madhu]]-ścut,'' ‘the pail distilling sweetness,’ was used for the mixing.<ref name=fx66_ve2_1800/> It seems doubtful if [[सुरा|Surā]] was ever so mixed.<ref name=fx67_ve2_1800/><br><br>There were three pressings a day of Soma, as opposed to the two of the Avesta.<ref name=fx68_ve2_1800/> The evening pressing was specially connected with the Ṛbhus, the midday with Indra, the morning with Agni, but the ritual shows that many other gods also had their share.<ref name=fx69_ve2_1800/> The drinker of Soma and the nondrinker are sharply discriminated in the texts.<ref name=fx70_ve2_1800/> Localities where Soma was consumed were '''[[आर्जीक|Ārjīka]], [[पस्त्यावन्त्|Pastyāvant]], [[शर्यणावन्त्|Śaryaṇāvant]], [[सुषोमा|Suṣomā]],''' the territory of the '''[[पञ्चजनाः|Pañcajanāḥ]]''' or ‘five  peoples,’ and so on.<ref name=fx71_ve2_1800/> The effects of Soma in exhilarating and exciting the drinkers are often alluded to.<ref name=fx72_ve2_1800/><br><br>It is difficult to decide if Soma was ever a popular, as opposed to a hieratic drink. The evidence for its actual popularity is very slight,<ref name=fx73_ve2_1800/> and not decisive.<br>

सोम प्राति-वेश्य
<u>'''2. Soma Prāti-veśya'''</u> (‘descendant of Prativeśya’) is the name of a teacher, a pupil of [[प्रतिवेश्य|Prativeśya]], in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) at the end of the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (xv. 1).<br>

सोमक साह-देव्य
<u>'''Somaka Sāha-devya'''</u> (‘descendant of Sahadeva’) is the name of a king of the '''Sṛnjayas''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1802/> He is mentioned in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1802/> as having '''[[पर्वत|Parvata]]''' and '''[[नारद|Nārada]]''' as his priests.<br>

सोम-दक्ष कौश्रेय
<u>'''Soma-dakṣa Kauśreya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''Kuśri'''’) is the name of a teacher in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1803/> and the Maitrāyaṇī<ref name=fx2_ve2_1803/> Saṃhitās. <br>

सोमपि-त्सरु
<u>'''Somapi-tsaru.'''</u> See '''[[त्सरु|Tsaru]].'''<br>

सोम-शुष्म सात्य-यज्ञि
<u>'''Soma-śuṣma Sātya-yajñi'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[सत्ययज्ञ|Satyayajña]]'''’) is the name in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xi. 6, 2, 1. 3) of a travelling Brahmin who met '''[[जनक|Janaka]]''' of '''[[विदेह|Videha]].''' He may be identical with the man of the same name with the additional patronymic '''[[प्राचीनयोग्य|Prācīnayogya]]''' (‘descendant of Prācīnayoga’), who is mentioned as a pupil of [[सत्ययज्ञ|Satyayajña]] in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 2).<br>

सोम-शुष्मन् वाज-रत्नायन
<u>'''Soma-śuṣman [[वाज|Vāja]]-ratnāyana'''</u> (‘descendant of Vājaratna’) is the name in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 21, 5) of the priest who consecrated '''Śatānīka.'''<br>

सौकरायण
<u>'''Saukarāyaṇa'''</u> is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[काषायण|Kāṣāyaṇa]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1807/> or '''[[त्रैवणि|Traivaṇi]],'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1807/> in the second [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<br>

सौ-जात आराढि
<u>'''Sau-jāta Ārāḍhi'''</u> is the name of a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 22, 1).<br>

सौत्रामणी
<u>'''Sautrāmaṇī.'''</u> See '''Soma.'''<br>

सौ-दन्ति
<u>'''Sau-danti'''</u> (‘descendant of Sudanta’) occurs in the plural in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xiv. 3, 13), apparently as the name of priests who were contemporaries of '''[[विश्वामित्र|Viśvāmitra]].'''<br>

सौदास
<u>'''Saudāsa'''</u> in the plural designates the ‘descendants of '''[[सुदास्|Sudās]],'''’ who are referred to in the Jaiminīya [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1811/> as having cast '''[[शक्ति|Śakti]],''' the son of '''[[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]],''' into the fire. Other texts<ref name=fx2_ve2_1811/> relate  that [[वसिष्ठ|Vasiṣṭha]], his son being slain, desired to avenge himself on the Saudāsas, and eventually succeeded. Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve2_1811/> sees a reference to the story in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1811/> but without cause.<br>

सौ-द्युम्नि
<u>'''Sau-dyumni'''</u> (‘descendant of Sudyumna’) is the patronymic of king '''[[भरत|Bharata]] [[दौःषन्ति|Dauḥṣanti]]''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 5, 4, 12).<br>

सौ-बल
<u>'''Sau-bala,'''</u> ‘descendant of Subala,’ is the name of a pupil of '''[[सर्पि वात्सि|Sarpi Vātsi]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vi. 24, 16).<br>

सौभर
<u>'''Saubhara,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[सोभरि|Sobhari]],’ is the patronymic of '''Pathin''' in the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1814/><br>

सौमाप
<u>'''Saumāpa'''</u> ‘descendant of Somāpa,’ is the patronymic of the two '''Mānutantavyas,''' teachers in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1815/><br>

सौमापि
<u>'''Saumāpi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Somāpa,’ is the patronymic of a teacher called '''Priyavrata''' in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka (xv. 1).<br>

सौमायन
<u>'''Saumāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Soma,’ is the patronymic of '''Budha''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xxiv. 18, 6).<br>

सौम्य
<u>'''Saumya'''</u> is a term of affectionate address (‘my dear’) in the Upaniṣads.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1818/><br>

सौ-यवसि
<u>'''Sau-yavasi,'''</u> ‘descendant of [[सुयवस|Suyavasa]],’ is the patronymic of '''Ajīgarta.'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1819/> <br>

सौरी
<u>'''Saurī'''</u> is given by Zimmer<ref name=fx1_ve2_1820/> as the name of an unknown animal at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1820/> But this is an error: ''[[सौरी|saurī]]'' means ‘dedicated to the sun.’<br>

सौ-वर्चनस
<u>'''Sau-varcanasa'''</u> is the patronymic of '''Saṃśravas''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (i. 7, 2, 1).<br>

सौ-श्रवस
<u>'''Sau-śravasa,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[सुश्रवस्|Suśravas]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''Upagu''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1822/> and the '''[[कण्व|Kaṇva]]''' Sauśravasas are mentioned in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1822/><br>

सौ-श्रोमतेय
<u>'''Sau-śromateya,'''</u> ‘descendant of Suśromatā,’ is the metronymic of '''Aṣāḍhi''' in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1823/> ''Cf.'' '''Āṣādhi.'''<br>

सौ-षद्मन
<u>'''Sau-ṣadmana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Suṣadman,’ is the patronymic of '''Viśvantara''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (vii. 27, 1; 34, 7).<br>

स्कन्ध्या
<u>'''Skandhyā,'''</u> fem. plur., is used in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1825/> of a disease ‘of the shoulders,’ probably tumours of some kind.<br>

स्तनयित्नु
<u>'''Stanayitnu,'''</u> sing. and plur., denotes ‘thunder’ from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1826/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1826/><br>

स्तम्ब
<u>'''Stamba'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1827/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1827/> denotes a ‘tuft of grass,’ or more generally a ‘bunch’ or ‘cluster.’ <br>

स्तम्भ
<u>'''Stambha,'''</u> ‘pillar,’ is found in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1828/> and often in the Sūtras. Earlier Skambha<ref name=fx2_ve2_1828/> is used, but only metaphorically.<br>

स्तरी
<u>'''Starī'''</u> denotes a ‘barren cow’ in the Rigveda (i. 101, 3; 116, 22; 117, 20, etc.).<br>

स्ति
<u>'''Sti.'''</u> See '''[[उपस्ति|Upasti]].'''<br>

स्ति-पा
<u>'''Sti-pā.'''</u> See '''[[उपस्ति|Upasti]].'''<br>

स्तुका
<u>'''Stukā'''</u> denotes a ‘tuft’ of hair or wool in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1832/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1832/><br>

स्तुति
<u>'''Stuti'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1833/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1833/> denotes a ‘song of praise.’<br>

स्तुप
<u>'''Stupa'''</u> means ‘tuft of hair’ in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (ii. 2; xxv. 2) and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (i. 3, 3, 5; iii. 5, 3, 4). See '''[[स्तुका|Stukā]].'''<br>

स्तूप
<u>'''Stūpa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1835/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1835/> denotes the ‘top-knot’ of hair as designating the upper part of the head.<br>

स्तृ
<u>'''Stṛ'''</u> (used in the instrumental plural only) denotes the ‘stars’ of heaven.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1836/> <br>

स्तेग
<u>'''Stega'''</u> in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās<ref name=fx1_ve2_1837/> seems to denote a species of ‘worm.’ The word occurs in the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1837/> also, where its sense is unknown, but may possibly be ‘ploughshare.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1837/><br>

स्तेन
<u>'''Stena'''</u> is a common word for ‘thief’ from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1838/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1838/> See '''[[तस्कर|Taskara]].'''<br>

स्तेय
<u>'''Steya'''</u> denotes ‘theft’ in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1839/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1839/> ''Cf.'' '''[[धर्म|Dharma]].'''<br>

स्तोतृ
<u>'''Stotṛ'''</u> denotes ‘praiser’ or ‘panegyrist’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1840/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1840/> The word often<ref name=fx3_ve2_1840/> occurs in connexion with patrons, the '''Maghavan''' or '''[[सूरि|Sūri]].'''<br>

स्तोत्र
<u>'''Stotra'''</u> denotes the ‘song’ of the Udgātṛ and his assistant priests (see '''[[ऋत्व्इज्|Ṛtvij]]'''), just as '''[[शस्त्र|Śastra]]''' denotes the ‘recitation’ of the '''[[होतृ|Hotṛ]]''' and his assistants. The word has this technical sense quite frequently in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1841/> <br>

स्तोम
<u>'''Stoma'''</u> denotes ‘song of praise’ in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1842/> Later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1842/> the term has the technical sense of the typical forms in which the '''Stotras''' are chanted.<br>

स्त्री
<u>'''Strī'''</u> is the ordinary word in poetry and prose for ‘woman,’ without special reference to her as a wife or as a maiden. '''[[नारी|Nārī]]''' has the same sense, but disappears in later prose, while '''Gnā''' refers only to the wives of the gods, and '''Yoṣit,''' with its cognate words, denotes the young woman as ripe for marriage.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1843/> In the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1843/> [[स्त्री|Strī]] stands opposed to '''[[पुमांस्|Pumāṃs]],''' ‘man,’ and once to ''[[वृषन्|vṛṣan]],'' ‘male person’; not until the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1843/> does it mean ‘wife’ as opposed to '''Pati,''' ‘husband,’ and even in the Sūtras it is sharply opposed to '''[[जाया|Jāyā]].'''<br><br>In Vedic India by far the greater part of a woman's life was taken up in her marriage and marital relations (see Pati and '''[[मातृ|Mātṛ]]'''). There is no trace in the Rigveda of the seclusion of women, which was practically complete in all but the earliest Epic:<ref name=fx4_ve2_1843/> the maiden may be assumed to have grown up in her father's house, enjoying free intercourse with the youth of the village, and sharing in the work of the house. Education<ref name=fx5_ve2_1843/> was not denied to them, at any rate in certain cases, for we hear in the Upaniṣads of women who could take no unimportant part in disputations on philosophical topics. Moreover, women were taught to dance and sing, which were unmanly accomplishments.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1843/><br><br>Of the exact legal position of daughters the notices are few and meagre. The Rigveda,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1843/> however, shows that in the place  of a father the brother was looked to for aid, and that brotherless maidens were apt to be ruined, though religious terrors were believed to await the man who took advantage of their defencelessness.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1843/> Moreover, women could not take an inheritance,<ref name=fx9_ve2_1843/> and were not independent persons in the eyes of the law, whether married or not. Presumably before marriage they lived on their parents or brothers, and after that on their husbands, while in the event of their husbands predeceasing them, their relatives took the property, burdened with the necessity of maintaining the wife.<ref name=fx10_ve2_1843/> Their earnings would be appropriated by their nearest relative--usually father or brother-in the few cases in which unmarried women could earn anything, as in the case of courtezans.<br>

स्थ-पति
<u>'''Stha-pati'''</u> is the name of a royal official mentioned in the Atharvaveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1844/> and often later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1844/> '''[[रेवोत्तरस्|Revottaras]] [[चाक्र|Cākra]]''' was the [[स्थपति|Sthapati]] of the exiled '''[[दुष्टरीतु|Duṣṭarītu]] [[पौंसायन|Pauṃsāyana]],''' a king of the '''Sṛñjayas,''' and succeeded in restoring him to his royal dignity.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1844/> The exact sense of the term is not certain: ‘governor’<ref name=fx4_ve2_1844/> is possible, but perhaps ‘chief judge’<ref name=fx5_ve2_1844/> is more likely; as in the case of the early English judges, his functions may have been both executive and judicial. He is inferior in position to the king's brother.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1844/> <br>

स्थविर
<u>'''Sthavira,'''</u> literally ‘elder,’ is used as a sort of epithet of several men; [[स्थविर|Sthavira]] '''[[शाकल्य|Śākalya]]''' occurs in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx1_ve2_1845/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1845/> and [[स्थविर|Sthavira]] '''[[जातूकर्ण्य|Jātūkarṇya]]''' in the [[कौषीतकि|Kauṣītaki]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1845/> ''Cf.'' the names '''Hrasva''' and '''Dīrgha.'''<br>

स्थागर
<u>'''Sthāgara'''</u> in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1846/> is applied to an ornament (''alaṃkāra'') meaning ‘made of the fragrant substance Sthagara,’ which elsewhere<ref name=fx2_ve2_1846/> appears as Sthakara.<br>

स्थाणु
<u>'''Sthāṇu'''</u> in the '''Rigveda'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1847/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1847/> denotes a ‘stump’ or ‘post’ of wood.<br>

स्थातृ
<u>'''Sthātṛ'''</u> (‘he who stands’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1848/> denotes the ‘driver’ of horses or a car.<br>

स्था-पत्य
<u>'''Sthā-patya'''</u> denotes in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (xvii. 11, 6. 7) the ‘rank or status of a '''[[स्थपति|Sthapati]].'''’<br>

स्थाली
<u>'''Sthālī'''</u> denotes a ‘cooking pot,’ usually of earthenware, in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1850/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1850/><br>

स्थिरक गार्ग्य
<u>'''Sthiraka Gārgya'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[गर्ग|Garga]]'''’) is the name of a teacher in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1851/><br>

स्थिवि
<u>'''Sthivi'''</u> occurs once (used in the plural) in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1852/> probably meaning ‘bushel.’ The word is also found once in the adjective ''sthivimant,''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1852/> ‘provided with bushels.’ <br>

स्थूणा
<u>'''Sthūṇā'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1853/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1853/> denotes the ‘pillar’ or ‘post’ of a house.<br>

स्थूरि
<u>'''Sthūri'''</u> has in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1854/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1854/> the sense of ‘drawn by one animal’ instead of the usual two (see '''[[रथ|Ratha]]'''), and always with an implication of inferiority.<br>

स्थैरकायण
<u>'''Sthairakāyaṇa,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Sthiraka,'''’ is the patronymic of '''Mitravarcas''' in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1855/><br>

स्थौलाष्ठीवि
<u>'''Sthaulāṣṭhīvi,'''</u> ‘descendant of Sthūlāṣṭhīva,’ is the patronymic of a grammarian in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]] (vii. 14; x. 1).<br>

स्नातक
<u>'''Snātaka,'''</u> the designation of the student ‘who has taken the bath,’ marking the termination of his studentship under a religious teacher, occurs in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xii. 1, 1, 10), and repeatedly in the Sūtras. ''Cf.'' '''Brahmacārin.'''<br>

स्नावन्य
<u>'''1. Snāvanya,'''</u> used in the plural, denotes particular parts of the body of a horse in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (v. 7, 23, 1).<br>

स्नावन्य
<u>'''2. Snāvanya'''</u> appears to be the name of a people in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1859/><br>

स्नुषा
<u>'''Snuṣā'''</u> denotes the ‘daughter-in-law’ in relation primarily to her father-in-law, but also to her mother-in-law. In the latter sense the word appears in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1860/> in the epithet ''su-[[स्नुषा|snuṣā]],''  ‘having a good daughter-in-law,’ used of Vṛṣākapāyī, while in the former it occurs in several passages, where the daughterin-law's respect for her father-in-law is mentioned,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1860/> a respect which spirituous liquor alone causes to be violated.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1860/> See also '''[[श्वशुर|Śvaśura]]''' and '''Pati.'''<br>

स्पन्दन
<u>'''Spandana'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1861/> denotes a certain tree. Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1861/> however, reads ''[[स्यन्दन|syandana]],'' ‘chariot.’<br>

स्पर्शु
<u>'''Sparśu'''</u> is apparently the name of a western people in the [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xxi. 13).<br>

स्पश्
<u>'''Spaś.'''</u> See '''[[राजन्|Rājan]].'''<br>

स्फूर्जक
<u>'''Sphūrjaka'''</u> denotes a tree (''Diospyros embryopteris'') mentioned in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 8, 1, 16).<br>

स्मद्-इभ
<u>'''Smad-ibha'''</u> is found once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1865/> where Roth<ref name=fx2_ve2_1865/> takes the word as perhaps the name of an enemy of '''[[कुत्स|Kutsa]].''' ''Cf.'' '''Ibha.'''<br>

स्यन्दन
<u>'''Syandana,'''</u> ‘chariot,’ is found in the earlier literature only, if at all, in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1866/> where '''[[स्पन्दन|Spandana]]''' is the received reading. <br>

स्याल
<u>'''Syāla,'''</u> a word occurring in only one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1867/> appears to denote the brother of a man's wife, who is regarded as willing to protect her, and so secure a marriage for her.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1867/><br>

स्यूम-गभस्ति
<u>'''Syūma-gabhasti.'''</u> See '''[[गभस्ति|Gabhasti]].'''<br>

स्यूम-गृभ्
<u>'''Syūma-gṛbh,'''</u> used of a horse in the Rigveda (vi. 36, 2) seems to mean ‘grasping the bit between his teeth,’ as a horse does when anxious to break away from control.<br>

स्यूमन्
<u>'''Syūman'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1870/> denotes, according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1870/> the strap fastening the door of a house, the Homeric.<br>

स्यूम-रश्मि
<u>'''Syūma-raśmi'''</u> is the name of a protégé of the Aśvins in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1871/><br>

स्रक्ति
<u>'''Srakti'''</u> is found in the description of the '''[[दाशराज्ञ|Dāśarājña]]''' in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1872/> where Hopkins<ref name=fx2_ve2_1872/> thinks the sense of ‘spears’ essential.<br>

स्रज्
<u>'''Sraj,'''</u> ‘garland,’ is mentioned in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1873/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1873/> as often worn by men when anxious to appear handsome, as at a wedding and so on. The Aśvins are described as ‘lotuswreathed’ (''[[पुष्कर|puṣkara]]-sraj'').<ref name=fx3_ve2_1873/> <br>

स्राक्त्य
<u>'''Srāktya'''</u> is an adjective describing an amulet ('''[[मणि|Maṇi]]''') in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1874/> According to Weber,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1874/> it designates a crystal (literally ‘many-cornered’). The commentators,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1874/> however, agree in explaining the word to mean ‘derived from the Sraktya’--''i.e.,'' from the Tilaka tree (''Clerodendrum phlomoides'').<br>

स्रुच्
<u>'''Sruc'''</u> denotes a ‘large wooden sacrificial ladle’ (used for pouring clarified butter on the fire) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1875/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1875/> It is of the length of an arm, with a bowl of the size of a hand and a beaklike spout.<br>

स्रुव
<u>'''Sruva,'''</u> as opposed to '''Sruc,''' denotes in the ritual literature<ref name=fx1_ve2_1876/> a small ladle used to convey the offering ('''[[आज्य|Ājya]]''') from the cookingpot ('''[[स्थाली|Sthālī]]''') to the large ladle ('''[[जुहू|Juhū]]'''). In the Rigveda,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1876/> however, it was clearly used for the actual Soma libation.<br>

स्रेक-पर्ण
<u>'''Sreka-parṇa'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1877/> seems to mean ‘like the oleander leaf.’<br>

स्वज
<u>'''Svaja'''</u> in the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1878/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1878/> denotes the ‘viper.’ The word is explained by the commentators as ''sva-ja,'' ‘self-  born,’ but Roth,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1878/> Weber,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1878/> and Zimmer<ref name=fx5_ve2_1878/> prefer to derive it from the root ''svaj,'' ‘clasp,’ ‘encircle.’ In the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā<ref name=fx6_ve2_1878/> the '''[[हरिण|Hariṇa]]''' is said to kill the viper.<br>

स्वधिति
<u>'''1. Svadhiti'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1879/> denotes the ‘axe’ or ‘knife’ used for dissecting the sacrificial horse. In all the other passages in that Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_1879/> the sense of ‘axe’ for cutting wood is adequate; reference is made in one place<ref name=fx3_ve2_1879/> to sharpening the axe on the whetstone (''kṣṇotra''). In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_1879/> the term seems once to denote the copper (''[[लोहित|lohita]]'')<ref name=fx5_ve2_1879/> knife used to mark the ears of cattle; the carpenter's knife or axe is also twice referred to there.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1879/> Later the word means ‘axe’ generally.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1879/> As a weapon it does not appear at all.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1879/><br>

स्वधिति
<u>'''2. Svadhiti'''</u> in certain passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1880/> denotes, according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, a great tree with hard wood. This interpretation seems probable.<br>

स्वनद्-रथ
<u>'''Svanad-ratha'''</u> (‘having a rattling car’) is taken by Ludwig<ref name=fx1_ve2_1881/> as a proper name of '''Āsaṅga''' in the Rigveda.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1881/> But the word is most probably only an epithet. <br>

स्वनय भाव्य
<u>'''Svanaya Bhāvya'''</u> is the name of a prince on the '''[[सिन्धु|Sindhu]]''' (Indus) who bestowed gifts on '''[[कक्षीवन्त्|Kakṣīvant]],''' according to the Rigveda (i. 126, 1. 3). He is called Svanaya [[भावयव्य|Bhāvayavya]] in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xvi. 11, 5).<br>

स्वप्न
<u>'''Svapna,'''</u> ‘dream,’ is referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1883/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1883/> Evil dreams<ref name=fx3_ve2_1883/> are often mentioned. The Āraṇyakas of the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_1883/> contain a list of dreams with their signification, as well as of ''pratyakṣa-darśanāni,'' ‘sights seen with one's own eyes.’<br>

स्वर्
<u>'''Svar'''</u> denotes the ‘sun’<ref name=fx1_ve2_1884/> and the ‘heaven of light’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1884/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1884/><br>

स्वर
<u>'''Svara'''</u> denotes in the Upaniṣads<ref name=fx1_ve2_1885/> the sound of a vowel: these are described<ref name=fx2_ve2_1885/> as being ''[[घोषवन्त्|ghoṣavant]],'' ‘sonant,’ and also as ''balavant,'' ‘uttered with force.’ The precise word for a mute is ''sparśa,''<ref name=fx3_ve2_1885/> ‘contact,’ while ''ūṣman'' denotes a ‘sibilant,’ and ''[[स्वर|svara]]'' a ‘vowel,’ in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1885/> and [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyakas.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1885/> The semivowels are there denoted by ''anta-sthā'' (‘intermediate’)<ref name=fx5_ve2_1885/> or ''akṣara.''<ref name=fx6_ve2_1885/> Another division in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx7_ve2_1885/> is into ''[[घोष|ghoṣa]], ūṣman,'' and ''vyañjana,'' apparently ‘vowels,’ ‘sibilants,’ and ‘consonants’ respectively. ''[[घोष|Ghoṣa]]'' elsewhere in that Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx8_ve2_1885/> seems to have the general sense of ‘sounds.’ The [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]]<ref name=fx9_ve2_1885/> refers to ''[[मात्रा|mātrā]],'' a ‘mora’;<ref name=fx10_ve2_1885/> ''bala,'' ‘force’ of utterance, and ''[[वर्ण|varṇa]],'' ‘letter,’ an expression found elsewhere<ref name=fx11_ve2_1885/> in the explanation of ''om,'' as compacted of ''a + u + m.'' <br><br>The [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx12_ve2_1885/> and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Āraṇyaka<ref name=fx13_ve2_1885/> recognize the three forms of the Rigveda text as ''pratṛṇṇa, nirbhuja,'' and ''ubhayam-antareṇa,'' denoting respectively the Saṃhitā, Pada, and Krama Pāṭhas of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx14_ve2_1885/> The same authorities<ref name=fx15_ve2_1885/> recognize the importance of the distinction of the cerebral and dental ''n'' and ''s,'' and refer<ref name=fx16_ve2_1885/> to the '''Māṇḍūkeyas'''' mode of recitation. They also discuss<ref name=fx17_ve2_1885/> Sandhi, the euphonic ‘combination’ of letters.<br><br>The Prātiśākhyas of the several Saṃhitās develop in detail the grammatical terminology, and Yāska's [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]]<ref name=fx18_ve2_1885/> contains a good deal of grammatical material. The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx19_ve2_1885/> distinguishes the genders, and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx20_ve2_1885/> the division of words in the Sāman recitation.<br>

स्व-राज्
<u>'''Sva-rāj,'''</u> ‘self-ruler,’ ‘king,’ is found frequently in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1886/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1886/> It is the technical term for the kings of the west according to the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1886/><br>

स्वरु
<u>'''Svaru'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1887/> or later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1887/> denotes a ‘post,’ or more precisely in the ritual a splinter of the [[यूप|Yūpa]], or sacrificial post.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1887/> <br>

स्वर्-जित् नाग्न-जित
<u>'''Svar-jit Nāgna-jita'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[नग्न-जित्|Nagna-jit]]'''’) is the name of a royal personage in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1888/> a '''[[गन्धार|Gandhāra]]''' prince, whose views on the ritual are referred to with contempt.<br>

स्वर्-णर
<u>'''Svar-ṇara'''</u> appears to be the proper name of a sacrificer in two verses of the Rigveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1889/> According to Geldner,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1889/> it everywhere<ref name=fx3_ve2_1889/> means a specially sacred lake and the Soma-producing district around it.<br>

स्वर्-भानु असुर
<u>'''Svar-bhānu Asura'''</u> is the name, in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1890/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1890/> of a demon supposed to have eclipsed the sun. See '''[[सूर्य|Sūrya]].'''<br>

स्व-सर
<u>'''Sva-sara,'''</u> according to the St. Petersburg Dictionary, denotes ‘cattle stall,’<ref name=fx1_ve2_1891/> and more generally ‘dwelling-place,’ ‘house,’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1891/> and then ‘nest of birds.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1891/> Geldner,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1891/> however, shows that the real sense is the ‘wandering at will’ of cattle, more precisely their ‘grazing in the morning,’<ref name=fx5_ve2_1891/> and in the case of birds their ‘early flight’ from the nest,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1891/> while metaphorically it is applied first to the morning pressing of Soma and then to all three pressings.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1891/><br>

स्वसृ
<u>'''Svasṛ'''</u> is the regular word from the Rigveda onwards<ref name=fx1_ve2_1892/> for ‘sister.’ Like the word '''[[भ्रातृ|Bhrātṛ]],''' the term sister can be applied  to things not precisely so related. For example, in the Rigveda the fingers and the seasons are ‘sisters,’ and night is the sister of dawn, for whom, as the elder, she makes way.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1892/> The '''Paṇis''' offer to adopt Saramā as their sister;<ref name=fx3_ve2_1892/> but this use is not applied--any more than in the case of [[भ्रातृ|Bhrātṛ]]--to ordinary human beings.<br><br>The sister stood in a close relation to her brother. If the father was dead or feeble, the sister was dependent on her brother and on his wife, as appears from the Rigveda<ref name=fx4_ve2_1892/> and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx5_ve2_1892/> Moreover, maidens without brothers were apt to find marriage difficult, and to degenerate into Hetairai;<ref name=fx6_ve2_1892/> but it is not certain whether this was due, as Zimmer<ref name=fx7_ve2_1892/> thinks, to brothers being required to arrange marriages for orphan girls, or because sonless fathers were anxious to make their daughters '''Putrikās,''' in order that they themselves, instead of the husbands, should count the daughters' sons as their own.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1892/> See also '''[[जामि|Jāmi]].'''<br>

स्वस्रीय
<u>'''Svasrīya'''</u> occurs in the sense of ‘sister's son’ in the description of Viśvarūpa's ancestry in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1893/><br>

स्वाती
<u>'''Svātī.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

स्वाध्याय
<u>'''Svādhyāya'''</u> (‘reciting to oneself’) in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1895/> denotes the study or repetition of the Vedic texts. The Sūtras give rules for it in great detail. ''Cf.'' '''[[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].''' <br>

स्वायव
<u>'''Svāyava,'''</u> ‘descendant of Svāyu,’ is the patronymic of '''Kūśāmba [[लातव्य|Lātavya]]''' in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]] (viii. 6, 8).<br>

स्वा-राज्य
<u>'''Svā-rājya.'''</u> See '''[[राज्य|Rājya]].'''<br>

स्वेद-ज
<u>'''Sveda-ja,'''</u> ‘born of sweat’--that is, ‘engendered by hot moisture’--is used in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iii. 3, 3) as a term designating a class of creatures comprising vermin of all sorts. The [[मानव|Mānava]] [[धर्म|Dharma]] Śāstra (i. 45) explains it as ‘flies, mosquitoes, lice, bugs, and so forth.’<br><br>''Cf.'' Keith, ''[[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka,'' 235.<br>

स्वैदायन
<u>'''Svaidāyana,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''Sveda,'''’ is the patronymic of a '''[[शौनक|Śaunaka]]''' in the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1899/><br>

स्वौपश
<u>'''Svaupaśa.'''</u> See '''[[ओपश|Opaśa]].'''<br>

हंस
<u>'''Haṃsa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1901/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1901/> denotes the ‘gander.’ These birds are described as dark in colour on the back (''nīlapṛṣṭha'');<ref name=fx3_ve2_1901/> they fly in troops,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1901/> swim in the water (''uda-prut''),<ref name=fx5_ve2_1901/> make loud noises,<ref name=fx6_ve2_1901/> and are wakeful at night.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1901/> The [[हंस|Haṃsa]] is credited with the power of separating Soma from water (as later milk from water) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx8_ve2_1901/> It is also mentioned as one of the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’).<ref name=fx9_ve2_1901/> <br>

हंस-साचि
<u>'''Haṃsa-sāci'''</u> is the name of an unknown bird mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx1_ve2_1902/> as one of the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’).<br>

हय
<u>'''Haya'''</u> denotes ‘horse’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1903/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1903/><br>

हर-याण
<u>'''Hara-yāṇa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1904/> is clearly the name of a man mentioned along with '''[[उक्षण्यायन|Ukṣaṇyāyana]]''' and '''[[सुषामन्|Suṣāman]].'''<br>

हरिण
<u>'''Hariṇa'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1905/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1905/> denotes a ‘gazelle.’ It is at once a type of speed<ref name=fx3_ve2_1905/> and terror.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1905/> Its horns are used as amulets.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1905/> It is fond of eating barley ('''Yava''').<ref name=fx6_ve2_1905/> In the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1905/> it is said to kill vipers ('''[[स्वज|Svaja]]'''). ''Cf.'' '''[[कुलुङ्ग|Kuluṅga]], [[न्यङ्कु|Nyaṅku]].''' The feminine is Hariṇī.<ref name=fx8_ve2_1905/><br>

हरित
<u>'''1. Harita'''</u> seems to mean ‘gold’ in a few passages of the Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1906/><br>

हरित कश्यप
<u>'''2. Harita Kaśyapa'''</u> is mentioned as a teacher, a pupil of '''[[शिल्प कश्यप|Śilpa Kaśyapa]],''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) of the Bṛhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1907/> <br>

हरि-द्रु
<u>'''Hari-dru'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 8, 1, 16) is the name of a tree (''Pinus deodora'').<br>

हरिमन्
<u>'''Hariman'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1909/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1909/> denotes ‘yellowness’ as a disease, ‘jaundice.’<br>

हरि-यूपीया
<u>'''Hari-yūpīyā'''</u> is mentioned in a hymn of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1910/> as the scene of the defeat of the '''Vṛcīvants''' by '''Abhyāvartin Cāyamana.''' It may denote either a place or a river, since many battles seem to have been fought on the banks of rivers. Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_1910/> took it as the name of a town on the river '''[[यव्यावती|Yavyāvatī]],''' which is identified with it in Sāyaṇa's commentary on the passage. Hillebrandt<ref name=fx3_ve2_1910/> thinks that it is the river Iryāb (Haliāb), a tributary of the Kurum ('''[[क्रुमु|Krumu]]'''), but this is not at all probable.<br>

हरि-वर्ण अङ्गिरस
<u>'''Hari-[[वर्ण|varṇa]] Aṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of Aṅgiras’) is the name of the seer of a Sāman or chant in the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1911/><br>

हरि-श्चन्द्र वैधस
<u>'''Hari-ścandra Vaidhasa'''</u> (‘descendant of Vedhas’) '''[[ऐक्ष्वाक|Aikṣvāka]]''' (‘descendant of '''[[इक्ष्वाकु|Ikṣvāku]]'''’) is the name of a probably mythical king whose rash vow to offer up his son '''[[रोहित|Rohita]]''' to Varuṇa is the source of the tale of '''[[शुनःशेप|Śunaḥśepa]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Brāhmana (vii. 14, 2) and the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xv. 17).<br>

हर्म्य
<u>'''Harmya'''</u> denotes the Vedic ‘house’ as a unity including the stabling<ref name=fx1_ve2_1913/> and so forth, and surrounded by a fence or wall of  some sort.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1913/> It is several times referred to in the Rigveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_1913/> and later.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1913/> ''Cf.'' '''[[गृह|Gṛha]].'''<br>

हलिक्ष्ण
<u>'''Halikṣṇa'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1914/> or '''Halīkṣṇa'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1914/> is mentioned as one of the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās. The commentator Mahīdhara<ref name=fx3_ve2_1914/> thinks that it is a kind of lion, Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx4_ve2_1914/> that a green Caṭaka bird or a lion (''[[तृण|tṛṇa]]-hiṃsa'')<ref name=fx5_ve2_1914/> is meant. In the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx6_ve2_1914/> Halīkṣṇa seems to be some particular intestine, but Weber<ref name=fx7_ve2_1914/> thinks it may mean ‘gall.’<br>

हविर्-धान
<u>'''Havir-dhāna'''</u> (‘oblation receptacle’) denotes primarily the cart on which the Soma plants are conveyed to be pressed,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1915/> then the shed in which these Soma vehicles were kept.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1915/><br>

हविष्-कृत् आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Haviṣ-kṛt Āṅgirasa'''</u> (‘descendant of '''[[अङ्गिरस्|Aṅgiras]]'''’) is the name of the seer of a Sāman or chant according to the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1916/> and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1916/> See the following.<br>

हविष्मन्त् आङ्गिरस
<u>'''Haviṣmant Āṅgirasa'''</u> is mentioned along with '''Haviṣkṛt,''' in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā and the [[पञ्चविंश ब्राह्मण|Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx2_ve2_1917/> as the seer of a Sāman or chant.<br><br>^1) vii. 1, 4, 1. <br>

हविस्
<u>'''Havis'''</u> is the general term for an offering to the gods, ‘oblation,’ whether of grain, or Soma, or milk, or clarified butter, etc. It is common from the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1918/> onwards.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1918/><br>

हस्त
<u>'''Hasta.'''</u> See '''[[नक्षत्र|Nakṣatra]].'''<br>

हस्त-घ्न
<u>'''Hasta-ghna'''</u> denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1920/> a ‘hand-guard,’ a covering used as a protection of the hand and arm from the impact of the bowstring. The word is of remarkable and still unexplained formation.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1920/> Lāṭyāyana<ref name=fx3_ve2_1920/> has ''[[हस्त|hasta]]-tra'' and the Epic ''hastāvāpa''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1920/> as its equivalent in sense.<br>

हस्तादान
<u>'''Hastādāna.'''</u> See '''[[पशु|Paśu]].'''<br>

हस्तिन्
<u>'''Hastin,'''</u> ‘having a hand,’ with '''[[मृग|Mṛga]],''' ‘beast,’ denotes in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1922/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_1922/> the ‘elephant.’ Later the adjective alone comes to mean ‘elephant.’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1922/> The animal was famed for its strength<ref name=fx4_ve2_1922/> as well as its virility.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1922/> It is mentioned with man and monkey as one of the beasts that take hold by the hand (''[[हस्तादान|hastādāna]]''), as opposed to those that take hold by the mouth (''mukhādāna'').<ref name=fx6_ve2_1922/> It was tamed, as the expression '''[[हस्तिप|Hastipa]],''' ‘elephant-keeper,’ shows, and tame elephants were used to catch others (see '''[[वारण|Vāraṇa]]'''). But there is no trace of its use in war, though Ktesias and Megasthenes both record such use for  their times.<ref name=fx7_ve2_1922/> The Atharvaveda<ref name=fx8_ve2_1922/> alludes to its being pestered by mosquitoes.<br>

हस्ति-प
<u>'''Hasti-pa,'''</u> ‘elephant-keeper,’ is mentioned as one of the victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1923/><br>

हस्रा
<u>'''Hasrā'''</u> (‘laughing woman’) in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1924/> denotes a courtesan according to Pischel.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1924/><br>

हायन
<u>'''Hāyana'''</u> denotes a ‘year,’ usually in compounds.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1925/> In the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā<ref name=fx2_ve2_1925/> and the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_1925/> the term appears as a designation of a species of red rice. As an adjective in the sense of ‘lasting a year’ or ‘recurring every year,’ it is applied to fever in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1925/><br>

हारिकर्णी-पुत्र
<u>'''Hārikarṇī-putra,'''</u> ‘son of a female descendant of Harikarṇa,’ is the name of a teacher, a pupil of '''[[भारद्वाजी-पुत्र|Bhāradvājī-putra]],''' in the last [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) in the Mādhyaṃdina recension of the Brhadāraṇyaka [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 4, 30).<br>

हारिद्रव
<u>'''Hāridrava'''</u> is the name of a yellow bird in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1927/> perhaps the ‘yellow water-wagtail.’<ref name=fx2_ve2_1927/> Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve2_1927/> compares the Greek  <br>

हारिद्रविक
<u>'''Hāridravika'''</u> is the title of a work by Hāridravin mentioned in the [[निरुक्त|Nirukta]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1928/><br>

हारि-द्रुमत
<u>'''Hāri-drumata,'''</u> ‘descendant of Haridrumant,’ is the patronymic of a '''[[गौतम|Gautama]]''' in the Chāndogya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (iv. 4, 3).<br>

हालिङ्गव
<u>'''Hāliṅgava,'''</u> ‘descendant of Haliṅgu,’ is the name of a teacher in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (x. 4, 5, 1).<br>

हिता
<u>'''Hitā'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1931/> is the name of certain ‘veins.’ ''Cf.'' '''[[हिरा|Hirā]].'''<br>

हिम
<u>'''Hima,'''</u> denoting ‘cold,’ ‘cold weather,’ is quite common in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1932/> but less frequent later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1932/> As ‘snow’ the word appears as a masculine in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1932/> and often later as a neuter.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1932/> ''Cf.'' '''[[हेमन्त|Hemanta]].'''<br>

हिमवन्त्
<u>'''Himavant,'''</u> ‘snowy,’ appears as an epithet of mountains in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1933/> It is also used both there<ref name=fx2_ve2_1933/> and in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1933/> as well as later,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1933/> as a noun. There seems no reasen to deny that in all the passages the word refers vaguely to the mountains now called Himālaya, though it is possible that the name may include mountains not strictly in that system, like the Suleiman hills.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1933/> See also '''[[मूजवन्त्|Mūjavant]]''' and '''Trikakubh.''' <br>

हिमा
<u>'''Himā'''</u> denotes ‘winter’ in the combination a ‘hundred winters’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1934/> and elsewhere.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1934/><br>

हिरणिन्
<u>'''Hiraṇin,'''</u> ‘rich in gold,’ is apparently an epithet of '''[[त्रसदस्यु|Trasadasyu]]''' in one verse of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1935/> referring to the golden raiment or possessions of the king. Ludwig,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1935/> however, thinks the word is a proper name, possibly of Trasadasyu's son.<br>

हिरणिन
<u>'''Hiraṇina'''</u> is found in one passage of the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1936/> where Ludwig<ref name=fx2_ve2_1936/> takes the word as a name of '''[[शाण्ड|Śāṇḍa]].''' But it seems to be an adjectival form of ''[[हिरणिन्|hiraṇin]],'' ‘golden.’<br>

हिरण्य
<u>'''Hiraṇya'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1937/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1937/> denotes ‘gold.’ It is hardly possible to exaggerate the value attached to gold by the Vedic Indians. The metal was, it is clear, won from the bed of rivers. Hence the Indus is called ‘golden’<ref name=fx3_ve2_1937/> and ‘of golden stream.’<ref name=fx4_ve2_1937/> Apparently the extraction of gold from the earth was known,<ref name=fx5_ve2_1937/> and washing for gold is also recorded.<ref name=fx6_ve2_1937/><br><br>Gold is the object of the wishes of the Vedic singer,<ref name=fx7_ve2_1937/> and golden treasures (''hiraṇyāni'') are mentioned as given by patrons<ref name=fx8_ve2_1937/> along with cows and horses. Gold was used for ornaments for neck and breast ('''[[निष्क|Niṣka]]'''), for ear-rings ('''[[कर्ण-शोभन|Karṇa-śobhana]]'''), and even for cups.<ref name=fx9_ve2_1937/> Gold is always associated with the gods.<ref name=fx10_ve2_1937/> <br><br>In the plural [[हिरण्य|Hiraṇya]] denotes ‘ornaments of gold.’<ref name=fx11_ve2_1937/><br><br>A gold currency was evidently beginning to be known in so far as definite weights of gold are mentioned: thus a weight, ''aṣṭā-prūḍ,'' occurs in the Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx12_ve2_1937/> and the golden ''[[शतमान|śatamāna]],'' ‘weight of a hundred ('''Kṛṣṇalas''')’ is found in the same texts.<ref name=fx13_ve2_1937/> In several passages,<ref name=fx14_ve2_1937/> moreover, ''[[हिरण्य|hiraṇya]]'' or ''hiraṇyāni'' may mean ‘pieces of gold.’<br><br>Gold is described sometimes as ''[[हरित|harita]],''<ref name=fx15_ve2_1937/> ‘yellowish,’ sometimes as ''[[रजत|rajata]],''<ref name=fx16_ve2_1937/> ‘whitish,’ when probably. ‘silver’ is alluded to. It was obtained from the ore by smelting.<ref name=fx17_ve2_1937/> Megasthenes<ref name=fx18_ve2_1937/> bears testimony to the richness in gold of India in his time.<br>

हिरण्य-कशिपु
<u>'''Hiraṇya-kaśipu'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_1938/> denotes a ‘golden seat,’ probably one covered with cloth of gold.<br>

हिरण्य-कार
<u>'''Hiraṇya-kāra'''</u> denotes a ‘worker in gold’ mentioned in the list of victims at the Puruṣamedha (‘human sacrifice’) in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1939/> <br>

हिरण्य-दन्त्
<u>'''Hiraṇya-dant'''</u> (‘gold-toothed’) '''[[वैद|Vaida]]''' (‘descendant of Veda’) is the name of a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 6, 3) and the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka (ii. 1, 5). The name presumably refers to the use of gold to stop the teeth; see '''Dant.'''<br>

हिरण्य-नाभ
<u>'''Hiraṇya-nābha'''</u> is the name of a '''[[कौसल्य|Kausalya]]''' or [[कोसल|Kosala]] prince, whose horse sacrifice appears to be alluded to in the [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]] Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xvi. 9, 13). He is also referred to in the [[प्रश्न|Praśna]] [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] (vi. 1), and may have been connected with '''[[पर आट्णार|Para Āṭṇāra]].''' ''Cf.'' '''[[हैरण्य-नाभ|Hairaṇya-nābha]].'''<br>

हिरण्य-स्तूप
<u>'''Hiraṇya-stūpa'''</u> is the name of a man in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1942/> and in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx2_ve2_1942/> He is called an '''[[आङ्गिरस|Āṅgirasa]]''' in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]],<ref name=fx3_ve2_1942/> which credits him with the authorship of a Rigvedic hymn.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1942/> The Anukramaṇī (Index) ascribes to him several other hymns.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1942/><br>

हिरण्य-हस्त
<u>'''Hiraṇya-hasta'''</u> is in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1943/> the name of a son given by the Aśvins to '''[[वध्रिमती|Vadhrimatī]]''' (who, as her name denotes, was the wife of a eunuch).<br>

हिरा
<u>'''Hirā'''</u> in the '''Atharvaveda'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1944/> denotes ‘vein,’ like '''[[हिता|Hitā]].'''<br>

हृत्स्व्-आशय आल्लकेय
<u>'''Hṛtsv-āśaya Āllakeya'''</u> is mentioned in the Jaiminīya [[उपनिषद्|Upaniṣad]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (iii. 40, 2) in the [[वंश|Vaṃśa]] (list of teachers) as a pupil of '''[[सोमशुष्म सात्ययज्ञि|Somaśuṣma Sātyayajñi]] [[प्राचीनयोग्य|Prācīnayogya]].'''<br>

हृदयामय
<u>'''Hṛdayāmaya,'''</u> ‘disease of the heart,’ is mentioned in the Atharvaveda in connexion with '''[[यक्ष्म|Yakṣma]]'''<ref name=fx1_ve2_1946/> and with '''[[बलास|Balāsa]].'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1946/>  Zimmer,<ref name=fx3_ve2_1946/> who thinks that '''[[बलास|Balāsa]]''' is consumption, connects the name with the later view of the medical Saṃhitās,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1946/> that love is one of the causes of the disease. But it would be more natural to see in it a disease affecting the heart.<br>

हृद्-योत
<u>'''Hṛd-yota'''</u><ref name=fx1_ve2_1947/> (for '''Hṛd-dyota''') and '''Hṛd-roga,'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1947/> ‘heart disease,’ are mentioned in the Atharvaveda and the Rigveda respectively. Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_1947/> identifies the disease in the Atharvaveda with '''[[हृदयामय|Hṛdayāmaya]],''' ‘consumption caused by love.’ In the Rigveda this is not at all likely: later in the medical Saṃhitās the word probably denotes ''angina pectoris.''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1947/><br>

हेमन्
<u>'''Heman'''</u> (used only in the locative singular) denotes ‘winter’ in the later Saṃhitās and the Brāhmaṇas.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1948/><br>

हेमन्त
<u>'''Hemanta,'''</u> ‘winter,’ occurs only once in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1949/> but often in the later texts.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1949/> Zimmer<ref name=fx3_ve2_1949/> is inclined to trace differences of climate in the Rigveda: he thinks that certain hymns,<ref name=fx4_ve2_1949/> which ignore winter and insist on the rains, indicate a different place and time of origin from those which refer to the snowy mountains.<ref name=fx5_ve2_1949/> It is, however, quite impossible to separate parts of the Rigveda on this basis. It is probable that that text owes its composition in the main to residents in the later '''[[मध्यदेश|Madhyadeśa]];''' hence the references to cold and snow are rather a sign of local than of temporal differences. It is otherwise with the later expansion of the three into four seasons,  which represents clearly the earlier advance of the Indians (see '''[[ऋतु|Ṛtu]]''').<br><br>The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx6_ve2_1949/> describes winter as the time when the plants wither, the leaves fall from the trees, the birds fly low and retire more and more.<br>

हैत-नामन
<u>'''Haita-nāmana,'''</u> ‘descendant of Hitanāman,’ is the patronymic of a teacher apparently called Āhṛta in the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā,<ref name=fx1_ve2_1950/> though the verse is a strange one.<br>

हैरण्य-नाभ
<u>'''Hairaṇya-nābha,'''</u> ‘descendant of '''[[हिरण्यनाभ|Hiraṇyanābha]],'''’ is the patronymic of '''[[पर आट्णार|Para Āṭṇāra]],''' the '''[[कोसल|Kosala]]''' king, in a '''[[गाथा|Gāthā]]''' occurring in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (xiii. 5, 4, 4).<br>

होतृ
<u>'''Hotṛ'''</u> is the name of one of the oldest and most important priests of the Vedic ritual, the counterpart of the Zaotar of the Avestan priesthood.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1952/> The word must be derived from ''hu,'' ‘sacrifice,’ as was held by '''[[और्णवाभ|Aurṇavābha]];'''<ref name=fx2_ve2_1952/> this indicates a time when the [[होतृ|Hotṛ]] was at once sacrificer (the later [[अध्वर्यु|Adhvaryu]]) and singer. But the functions were already clearly divided in the Rigveda, where the Hotṛ's chief duty was the recitation of the '''Śastras.''' He was also in the older period often the '''[[पुरोहित|Purohita]]''' of the king, an office later filled by the '''[[ब्रह्मन्|Brahman]]''' priest.<br>

होत्रक
<u>'''Hotraka'''</u> in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx1_ve2_1953/> denotes ‘assistant of the Hotṛ’ priest. <br>

ह्यस्
<u>'''Hyas'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1954/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1954/> denotes ‘yesterday.’<br>

ह्रद
<u>'''Hrada'''</u> in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1955/> and later<ref name=fx2_ve2_1955/> denotes a ‘lake’ or ‘pond.’<br>

ह्रदे-चक्षुस्
<u>'''Hrade-cakṣus'''</u> in one passage of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1956/> is thought by Jackson<ref name=fx2_ve2_1956/> to mean ‘will of the wisp.’<br>

ह्रस्व माण्डूकेय
<u>'''Hrasva Māṇḍūkeya'''</u> (‘descendant of Maṇḍūka’) is the name of a teacher in the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] Āraṇyaka.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1957/><br>

ह्रादुनि
<u>'''Hrāduni'''</u> denotes ‘hail’ in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1958/> and later.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1958/><br>

ह्रूडु
<u>'''Hrūḍu'''</u> is a word of unknown meaning applied to '''[[तक्मन्|Takman]]''' in the Atharvaveda.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1959/> It is variously spelled in the manuscript as ''hruḍa, hūḍu, rūḍu,'' and so forth; the Paippalāda recension reads ''huḍu,'' ‘ram.’ Henry<ref name=fx2_ve2_1959/> has conjectured that the word is the equivalent of a proto-Semitic ''ḥarāḍu,'' ‘gold’ (Assyrian ''huraçu'' and Hebrew ''ḥarāç''), while Halévy<ref name=fx3_ve2_1959/> suggests that it may be the Greek  ‘greenish-yellow’; but both conjectures are highly improbable.<ref name=fx4_ve2_1959/> Weber<ref name=fx5_ve2_1959/> thinks ‘cramp’ is meant. <br>

ह्वरस्
<u>'''Hvaras'''</u> in three passages of the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1960/> denotes, according to Roth,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1960/> a part of the Soma sieve, perhaps the part through which the Soma juice flowed. But Geldner<ref name=fx3_ve2_1960/> thinks that in all these cases the sense is merely ‘hindrance.’ <br>

अङ्गुलि
<u>'''Aṅguli,'''</u> ‘finger-breadth,’ is mentioned as the ‘lowest measure’ in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]].<ref name=fx1_ve2_1961/><br>

अनस्
<u>'''Anas.'''</u>--In the Sūtras<ref name=fx1_ve2_1962/> mention is made of a part of the cart called Gadhā, which in Garbe's<ref name=fx2_ve2_1962/> opinion means ‘roof.’<br>

अरणी
<u>'''Araṇī'''</u> is the designation, in the Rigveda<ref name=fx1_ve2_1963/> and later,<ref name=fx2_ve2_1963/> of the two pieces of wood used in producing the sacrificial fire by friction. The upper (''uttarā'') and the lower (''adharā'') are distinguished.<ref name=fx3_ve2_1963/> The upper, in the form of a drill, is made of the hard wood of the '''[[अश्वत्थ|Aśvattha]],'''<ref name=fx4_ve2_1963/> the lower, in the form of a slab, of the soft wood of the '''[[शमी|Śamī]].'''<ref name=fx5_ve2_1963/> The drill is twirled forcibly (''sahasā'')<ref name=fx6_ve2_1963/> backwards and forwards with the arms (''bāhubhyām'')<ref name=fx7_ve2_1963/> by means of cords (''raśanābhiḥ'').<ref name=fx8_ve2_1963/> The action doubtless resembled that by which butter is separated from milk in India  at the present day, the same verb (''math,'' ‘twirl,’ ‘churn’)<ref name=fx9_ve2_1963/> being used for both processes. This method of producing the sacrificial fire still survives in India. Specimens of the modern apparatus may be seen in the Indian Institute and in the PittRivers Museum at Oxford.<br>

अरत्नि
<u>'''Aratni,'''</u> ‘cubit.’ According to the Śulvasūtra of [[बौधायन|Baudhāyana]],<ref name=fx1_ve2_1964/> this measure is equal to 24 Aṅgulas or ‘finger-breadths.’ The Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx2_ve2_1964/> also mentions 24 Aṅgulis or ‘fingerbreadths’ as a measure, but without reference to the [[अरत्नि|Aratni]].<ref name=fx3_ve2_1964/><br>

अर्क
<u>'''Arka'''</u> (''Calotropis gigantea'') is often referred to in the Satapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ix. 1, 1, 4. 9; its leaf: ''arka-[[पर्ण|parṇa]],'' 42; ''arkapalāśa,'' i. 2, 3, 12. 13).<br>

आधान
<u>'''Ādhāna'''</u> denotes ‘bridle,’ and especially the ‘bit’ of the bridle in the [[यजुर्वेद|Yajurveda]] Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_1966/><br>

इतिहास
<u>'''Itihāsa.'''</u>--The question of the nature of the Vedic [[इतिहास|Itihāsa]] has been further considered by Keith, ''Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society,'' 1911, 979-995; 1912, 429-438; and by Oldenberg, ''Nachrichten der ko7niglichen Gesellschaft der Wissenschaften zu Go7ttingen,'' 1911, 441-468.<br>

ऐक्ष्वाक
<u>'''Aikṣvāka.'''</u> For ‘Vārṣṇi’ read ‘Vārṣṇa.’<br>

कक्ष
<u>'''Kakṣa,'''</u> 1, 131, should be 2. '''[[कंस|Kaṃsa]],''' coming before '''[[ककर|Kakara]],''' 1, 130, and after '''[[कंस|Kaṃsa]],''' ‘pot or vessel of metal,’ which should be 1. '''[[कंस|Kaṃsa]].'''<br>

कम्बोज
<u>'''Kamboja.'''</u>--For these Iranian connexions, see Kuhn, ''Avesta, Pehlvi and Ancient Persian Studies in Honour of the late Shamsul-ulema Dastur Peshotanji Behramji Sanjana'' (Strassburg und Leipzig, 1904), 213 ''et seq.;'' Grierson, ''Journal of the Royal  Asiatic Society,'' 1911, 801, 802; 1912, 255; G. K. Nariman, ''ibid,'' 255-257; Muir, ''Sanskrit Texts,'' 2^2, 355, 356.<br>

काण्डा-विष
<u>'''Kāṇḍā-viṣa,'''</u> 1, 148, should be '''Kāndā-[[विष|viṣa]].'''<br>

काण्वी-पुत्र
<u>'''Kāṇvī-putra,'''</u> 1, 147, should come after '''[[काण्वायन|Kāṇvāyana]].'''<br>

कुमार-हारित
<u>'''Kumāra-hārita,'''</u> 1, 172, should come after '''[[कुभ्र|Kubhra]],''' 1, 162.<br>

कुमल बर्हिस्
<u>'''Kumala barhis,'''</u> 1, 172, should be '''[[कुल्मल|Kulmala]]-[[बर्हिस्|barhis]].'''<br>

कुषुम्भक
<u>'''Kuṣumbhaka,'''</u> according to Egerton (''Journal of the American Oriental Society,'' 31, 134), denotes ‘poison-bag’ in both passages of the Rigveda.<br>

कृष्णल
<u>'''Kṛṣṇala,'''</u> line 1 and note^4, read ‘seed’ for ‘berry.’<br>

क्रैव्य
<u>'''Kraivya.'''</u>--For ‘on the '''[[परिवक्रा|Parivakrā]]'''’ read ‘at '''[[परिवक्रा|Parivakrā]].'''’<br>

क्रोश
<u>'''Krośa.'''</u>--In note<ref name=fx1_ve2_1978/> for ‘about two miles’ read ‘1(1/8) miles.’ See Fleet, ''Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society,'' 1912, 237.<br>

ग्राम
<u>'''Grāma.'''</u>--The phrase Grāmin, ‘possessing a village,’ occurs often in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (ii. 1, 3, 2; 6, 7; 2, 8, 1; 11, 1; 3, 3, 5; 9, 2), usually in connexion with various rites for acquiring a village. Since in these cases repeated mention is made of obtaining pre-eminence over '''Sajātas''' and Samānas, ‘equals,’ it is probable that allowance must also be made for the control over his fellow-villagers which an ambitious man could obtain (''e.g.,'' by loans), and which might end by giving him the position of a great landlord, even without the intervention of the king.<br>

चण्डातक
<u>'''Caṇḍātaka'''</u> in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (v. 2, 1, 8) and the Kātyāyana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]] (xiv. 5, 3) denotes an undergarment worn by women.<br>

चमू
<u>'''Camū.'''</u>--Oldenberg<ref name=fx1_ve2_1981/> considers that even in the dual the word denotes two vessels into which the Soma, often mixed with water in the '''[[कोश|Kośa]]''' and purified with the sieve, was poured, and that, in the plural, reference is made to these and other vessels into which the Soma was put at the various stages of the  process. '''[[कलश|Kalaśa]]''' similarly denoted either one (sing.) or several (plur.) of the vessels, the dual not being used, since the dual of '''[[चमू|Camū]]''' was reserved for the two vessels ''par excellence.'' In the later ritual the Camūs are replaced by the [[द्रोण|Droṇa]]-[[कलश|Kalaśa]] and the Pūtabhṛt, which was, however, assimilated in form and material (being made of clay, not of wood) to the Ādhāvanīya, the later name of the [[कोश|Kośa]]. The main difficulty of this theory is that it is hard to explain why [[कलश|Kalaśa]] never occurs in the dual. Geldner<ref name=fx2_ve2_1981/> falls back on the older view that in [[चमू|Camū]] (dual) the two boards of the Soma press are meant.<br>

चाण्डाल
<u>'''Cāṇḍāla,'''</u> 1, 258, should come after '''[[चाक्षुष|Cākṣuṣa]].'''<br>

जाबाल
<u>'''Jābāla.'''</u>--For ‘descendant of '''Jabāla'''’ read ‘descendant of '''[[जबाला|Jabālā]].'''’<br>

तलव
<u>'''Talava,'''</u> 1, 302, should come after '''[[तर्य|Tarya]],''' 1, 301.<br>

दृषद्वती
<u>'''Dṛṣadvatī.'''</u>--The identification of this river with the Ghaggar (Macdonell, ''History of Sanskrit Literature,'' 142) seems to be wrong. It is almost certainly the modern Chitang (which is the correct spelling according to Raverty, ''Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal,'' 61, 422), or Chitrung (Oldham, ''Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society,'' 25, 58; ''cf.'' the sketch map opposite p. 49). See '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]],''' 2, 435, note^4.<br>

देवभाग
<u>'''Devabhāga,'''</u> is also mentioned in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vi. 6, 2, 2) as having ruined the '''Sṛñjayas''' by an error in the sacrifice, and as a contemporary of '''[[वासिष्ठ|Vāsiṣṭha]] Sātahavya.'''<br>

नक्षत्र
<u>'''Nakṣatra.'''</u>--In note ^137, 1, 424, supply ‘of’ before ‘the criticisms made,’ and in the following lines read ‘''Journal''’ and ‘466.’<br>

निषाद
<u>'''Niṣāda.'''</u>--The Niṣādas, according to the Mahābhārata (iii. 10 538), are situated beyond '''[[विनशन|Vinaśana]],''' the ‘place of disappear ance’ of the '''[[सरस्वती|Sarasvatī]].'''<br>

नृमेध
<u>'''Nṛmedha.'''</u>--For '''Sumedhas''' read '''[[सुमेध|Sumedha]].'''<br>

पति
<u>'''Pati,'''</u> 1, 489, note 145, line 7, after ‘ritual’ delete ‘of.’<br>

परावृज्
<u>'''Parāvṛj,'''</u> 1, 493, headline, for ‘49,’ read ‘493.’ <br>

पष्ठवाह्
<u>'''Paṣṭhavāh'''</u> in the later literature appears sometimes as Praṣṭhavāḥ: if Bloomfield's view<ref name=fx1_ve2_1992/> that '''[[प्रष्टि|Praṣṭi]]''' is from ''pra'' and ''as,'' ‘be,’ is correct, this may be the older form. Against this, however, is to be set the constant earlier tradition.<ref name=fx2_ve2_1992/> Macdonell<ref name=fx3_ve2_1992/> connects the word with ''pṛṣṭhavāh,'' ‘carrying on the back.’<br>

प्रतिष्ठा
<u>'''Pratiṣṭhā.'''</u>--For the succour of a fugitive offender may be compared the phrase in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (vi. 5, 6, 3; 8, 4. 5), ‘men do not deliver up even one deserving death (''vadhya'') who has come to them for protection (''prapanna'').’ ''Cf.'' '''[[परिदा|Paridā]].'''<br>

प्रवर्त
<u>'''Pravarta.'''</u>--The sense of ‘ear-ornament’ is justified by Āpastamba Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], xix. 23, 11; 24, 10. ''Cf.'' Baudhāvana Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], xiii. 31.<br>

प्रष्टि
<u>'''Praṣṭi'''</u> is considered by Bloomfield<ref name=fx1_ve2_1995/> to refer to a horse yoked in front to guide the team, a sense clearly occurring in some places, and to be derived from ''pra'' and ''as,'' ‘be,’ as in '''[[उपस्ति|Upasti]].''' The word is usually<ref name=fx2_ve2_1995/> considered to be connected with ''[[पर्शु|parśu]],'' ‘rib.’<br>

बल्बूथ
<u>'''Balbūtha,'''</u> 2, 64, should come after '''[[बल्बज|Balbaja]],''' 2, 63.<br>

बाहीक
<u>'''Bāhīka.'''</u>--For the later traditions, see Muir, ''Sanskrit Texts,'' 2^2, 482 ''et seq.;'' Grierson, ''Zeitschrift der Deutschen Morgenländischen Gesellschaft,'' 66, 68, 73.<br>

ब्रह्मचर्य
<u>'''Brahmacarya.'''</u>--The later rules are exhaustively given by O{??}aser, ''Zeitschrift der Deutschen Morgenländischen Gesellschaft,'' 66, 1 ''et seq.''<br>

भङ्ग-श्रवस्
<u>'''Bhaṅga-śravas'''</u> is the form of a man's name found in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xxxviii. 12) in the parallel to the passage of the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Āraṇyaka (vi. 5, 2), which has '''[[भङ्ग्यश्रवस्|Bhaṅgyaśravas]].'''<br>

भिषज्
<u>'''Bhiṣaj,'''</u> 2, 104, should be 1. '''[[भिषज्|Bhiṣaj]].''' <br>

मत्य
<u>'''Matya,'''</u> ‘harrow’ or ‘roller,’ is found in the [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] portions of the Saṃhitās.<ref name=fx1_ve2_2001/> Sāyaṇa<ref name=fx2_ve2_2001/> takes it as ‘manure.’<br>

माय
<u>'''Māya,'''</u> 2, 155, should be '''Māyā.'''<br>

मास
<u>'''Māsa,'''</u> 2, 157, note ^10, add: according to [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Samhitā, iii. 5, 1, 3, the new moon begins the month.<br>

युग
<u>'''Yuga.'''</u>--Tilak<ref name=fx1_ve2_2004/> has pressed this word into his theory of the reminiscence in the Vedas of an arctic home. He finds in it the sense of ‘month,’ interpreting the legend of '''[[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]]''' (= the sun) as an allusion to the arctic summer of ten months, followed by a night of two, traces of which he thinks exist in the notices of the seasons. This theory is, however, most improbable, as is his explanation<ref name=fx2_ve2_2004/> of the [[ऐतरेय|Aitareya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx3_ve2_2004/> reference by the theory that it portrays the various stages of the life of the Āryans.<br>

योजन
<u>'''Yojana.'''</u>--From the attribution of thirty Yojanas to the dawn in the Rigveda,<ref name=fx1_ve2_2005/> Tilak<ref name=fx2_ve2_2005/> has argued that the dawns of the arctic regions in the interglacial period must be meant. But the reference is apparently to the thirty dawns of the thirty days which constitute the Vedic month. See '''[[मास|Māsa]].'''<br>

रक्षस्
<u>'''Rakṣas'''</u> in the early Vedic literature normally refers to demons, and is only metaphorically<ref name=fx1_ve2_2006/> applied to human foes. No definite tribe is meant.<ref name=fx2_ve2_2006/><br>

राजसूय
<u>'''Rājasūya.'''</u>--Read ‘victor’ for ‘victim’ in line 12.<br>

लह्यायन
<u>'''Lahyāyana,'''</u> 2, 232, should be '''Lāhyāyani,''' and the reference, iii. 3, 1, 2. <br>

वर्षा-हू
<u>'''1. Varṣā-hū,'''</u> ‘frog’ (‘calling in the rains’), is one of the victims at the [[अश्वमेध|Aśvamedha]] (‘horse sacrifice’) in the Vājasaneyi Saṃhitā (xxiv. 38).<br>

वर्षा-हू
<u>'''2. Varṣā-hū'''</u> (‘produced in the rains’) is the name<ref name=fx1_ve2_2010/> of a plant (''Boerhavia procumbens'') in the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (iii. 4, 10, 3).<br>

वशा
<u>'''Vaśā'''</u> is frequently qualified by ''anūbandhyā''<ref name=fx1_ve2_2011/> (‘to be bound for slaughtering’); the economy of killing a barren cow probably tended to produce the sense of ‘barren’ in the word.<br>

वाच्
<u>'''Vāc.'''</u>--Grierson, in his discussion<ref name=fx1_ve2_2012/> of the Paiśācī speech, holds that the passage cited as the speech of the Asuras in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]], ''he 'lavo (= he 'rayaḥ),''<ref name=fx2_ve2_2012/> can be regarded as in Paiśācī just as much as in Māgadhī, since the change of ''r'' to ''l,'' and of ''y'' to ''v,'' is found in Paiśācī also. Sten Konow,<ref name=fx2_ve2_2012/> however, considers that Paiśācī was the speech used in the Vindhya region. It would be unwise, as a matter of fact, to lay stress on the phrase ''he 'lavo,'' because both the reading and the sense are by no means certain.<ref name=fx3_ve2_2012/> But it should be noted that the easterners and the Asuras are elsewhere in the Śatapatha [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]]<ref name=fx4_ve2_2012/> connected: this tells against Dr. Grierson's view.<br>

वातावत
<u>'''Vātāvata'''</u> and '''Vātāvant,''' 2, 284, should be read for '''[[वातवत|Vātavata]]''' and '''[[वातवन्त्|Vātavant]].'''<br>

वासस्
<u>'''Vāsas.'''</u>--In the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] Saṃhitā (ii. 2, 11, 4) ''upādhāyyapūrvaya,'' as an epithet of [[वासस्|Vāsas]], appears to denote ‘fringed (''citrānta'') according to Āpastamba Śrauta [[सूत्र|Sūtra]], xix. 20, 2.<br>

विषाणका
<u>'''Viṣāṇakā,'''</u> 2, 313, headline, for ‘31,’ read ‘313.’ <br>

वेहत्
<u>'''Vehat'''</u> occurs in conjunction with '''[[वशा|Vaśā]]''' in the [[काठक|Kāṭhaka]] Saṃhitā (xxxviii. 10), the Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā (iii. 11, 11), the Vājasaneyī Saṃhitā (xxi. 21), and the [[तैत्तिरीय|Taittirīya]] [[ब्राह्मण|Brāhmaṇa]] (ii. 6, 18, 4).<br>

वैरिण
<u>'''Vairiṇa,'''</u> 2, 318, should be '''[[वीरण|Vīraṇa]].'''<br>

व्यत्
<u>'''Vyat,'''</u> 1, 523, should be Vyant.<br>

शम्या
<u>'''Śamyā'''</u> in the Brāhmaṇas<ref name=fx1_ve2_2019/> frequently denotes the wooden support on which the lower of the two millstones ('''[[दृषद्|Dṛṣad]]''') is placed.<br>

स्यामैअजयन्त
<u>'''Syāmaiajayanta,'''</u> 1, 185, should be '''Śyāmasujayanta.'''<br>

श्रुष्टि
<u>'''Śruṣṭi'''</u> (more correctly '''Śnuṣṭi''') '''Aṅgirasa,''' 2, 397, should come on p. 403, before '''[[श्रुष्टिगु|Śruṣṭigu]]; and [[सुकुरीर|Sukurīra]]''' before '''Sukeśin,''' 2, 453.<br>

संवत्सर
<u>'''Saṃvatsara.'''</u>--Tilak<ref name=fx1_ve2_2022/> argues that the Rigveda<ref name=fx2_ve2_2022/> and the Atharvaveda<ref name=fx3_ve2_2022/> contain signs of a dating by season and day, but neither of the passages adduced by him is at all probably so taken.<br>

सायकायन
<u>'''Sāyakāyana,'''</u> 1, 155, '''[[सोभरि|Sobhari]],''' 1, 261, '''[[सौकरायण|Saukarāyaṇa]],''' 1, 155, should be read for [[सायकायन|Sāyakāyana]], [[सोभरि|Sobhari]], and [[सौकरायण|Saukarāyaṇa]] respectively.<br><br>Several misprints are due to the loss of diacritical marks: thus for Ajya read [[आज्य|Ājya]], 2, 20; for Arcatka, Ārcatka, 2, 357; for Artava, [[आर्तव|Ārtava]], 1, 63; for Apayā, [[आपया|Āpayā]], 1, 218; for Amikṣā, [[आमिक्षा|Āmikṣā]], 1, 250; for Aśuṃga, [[आशुंग|Āśuṃga]], 2, 387; for Asandī, [[आसन्दी|Āsandī]], 2, 383; for Dirghatamas, [[दीर्घतमस्|Dīrghatamas]], 1, 366; for Satapatha, Śatapatha, 1, 18, 34, 55, 67, 111, 119, 157, 242, 291, 371, 463, 516, 523; 2, 24, 80, 220, 221, 358, 362, 433; for Srauta, Śrauta, 1, 18, 55, 281, 282, 373; 2, 34, 71, 281, 301; for Sāṅkhāyana, [[शाङ्खायन|Śāṅkhāyana]], 1, 257, 281, 400, 469; 2, 34, 87, 281, 383; for Sāṭyāyanaka, Śātyāyanaka, i. 407; for [[सावसायन|Sāvasāyana]], Śāvasāyana, 2, 376. <br>

